INSERT INTO `tbl_mock_test_questions` VALUES (1,1,'Question: 1 A frivolous income tax return is one that does not include enough information to figure the correct tax or that contains certain information clearly showing that the tax that was reported is substantially incorrect. If a taxpayer files a frivolous return, which penalty applies specifically to the taxpayer for the frivolous return?','[\"$5,000 frivolous return penalty, applied in addition to any other applicable penalty or penalties\",\"$50 for failure to supply the taxpayer\'s Social Security number\",\"$100 for the failure to furnish the tax shelter registration number\",\"20% of the underpayment, reduced for those items for which there was adequate disclosure made\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(2,1,'Question: 2 John Bright recently passed the Special Enrollment Examination and is advertising for his business. Which of the following presentations will violate the Circular 230 rules for advertising?','[\"John Bright, admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"John Bright, Certified Enrolled Agent\",\"John Bright, enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"John Bright, enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\"]',1,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(3,1,'Question: 3 The IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue in a court proceeding if the taxpayer has:','[\"cooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the return.\",\"cooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the return.\",\"provided credible evidence relating to the issue in a court proceeding.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(4,1,'Question: 4 Ray was suspended from practice for 4 months by the Internal Revenue Service. Which of the following is Ray permitted to do during the period of suspension?','[\"Sign a consent to extend the statute of limitations for the assessment and collection of tax\",\"Sign closing agreements regarding tax liabilities\",\"Represent taxpayers before the IRS with respect to returns Ray did not prepare\",\"Appear as a witness for the taxpayer\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(5,1,'Question: 5 What is the penalty if you understate your income tax because you show negligence (i.e., failure to keep adequate books and records) or disregard of the rules or regulations?','[\"25% of the underpayment\",\"20% of the underpayment\",\"$500\",\"$50\"]',1,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(6,1,'Question: 6 After assessment, as a general rule, the Internal Revenue Service has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for:','[\"20 years.\",\"20 years.\",\"5 years.\",\"10 years.\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(7,1,'Question: 7 Which of the following statements is correct concerning adequate proof for establishing an expense of a business purpose for income tax purposes?','[\"A canceled check of a hotel is adequate proof.\",\"An itinerary of a business meeting is adequate proof.\",\"Both a canceled check of a hotel and an itinerary of a business meeting are necessary.\",\"Either a canceled check of a hotel or an itinerary of a business meeting is adequate.\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(8,1,'Question: 8 How many years in the future can an authorization on a Form 2848 be recorded to the Centralized Authentication File (CAF)?','[\"Current year +3\",\"Current year +3\",\"Current year +1\",\"Current year +2\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(9,1,'Question: 9 George is a truck driver who is also a licensed return preparer and specializes in preparing income tax returns claiming the American opportunity tax credit (AOTC). George will not be subject to a preparer penalty for an erroneously claimed AOTC if he complies with which one of the following?','[\"Knowledge or reason to know that the information used to determine eligibility for an amount of the AOTC is correct\",\"All of the responses are correct.\",\"Completion of Form 8867, Paid Preparer\\u2019s Due Diligence Checklist, based upon information provided by the client and filed with the tax return or claim for refund\",\"Completion of the computation worksheet for the AOTC based upon information provided by the client\"]',1,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(10,1,'Question: 10 A paid preparer must: 1. give the taxpayer a copy of his or her tax return.n2. give the taxpayer a copy of his or her tax return that has a claim for refund.n3. sign the tax return after the taxpayer signs the tax return.n','[\"1 and 3\",\"2 and 3\",\"1, 2, and 3\",\"1 and 2\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(11,1,'Question: 11 Under Treasury Circular 230, a practitioner may be:','[\"censured\",\"suspended\",\"censured, suspended, or disbarred.\",\"disbarred.\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(12,1,'Question: 12 The following statements are given to you as an enrolled agent: 1. The filing of Form 8821 will revoke any Form 2848 that is in effect.n2. The filing of Form 2848 will revoke any Form 8821 that is in effect.n','[\"Both items 1 and 2 are incorrect.\",\"Both items 1 and 2 are correct.\",\"Item 2 is correct.\",\"Item 1 is correct.\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(13,1,'Question: 13 A practitioner can be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service for incompetence and/or disreputable conduct. Which one of the following is considered disreputable conduct?','[\"Willfully preparing all or substantially all of, or signing, a tax return or claim for refund when the practitioner does not possess a current or otherwise valid preparer tax identification number\",\"Willfully representing a taxpayer before an officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service unless the practitioner is authorized to do so\",\"Willfully failing to file on electronic media a tax return prepared by the practitioner that is required by federal law to be filed unless due to reasonable cause\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(14,1,'Question: 14 How is a proceeding for a violation of the regulations in Circular 230 instituted against an attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary?','[\"The Commissioner of the IRS files a complaint against the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary with the U.S. Tax Court.\",\"An aggrieved taxpayer files a petition with the U.S. Tax Court stating a claim against the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary.\",\"The authorized representative of the Internal Revenue Service signs a complaint naming the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary and fairly informs them of the charges brought so that the respondent is able to prepare a defense.\",\"The Secretary of the Treasury files a complaint against the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia.\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(15,1,'Question: 15 Which of the following is covered under Circular 230\'s requirement that a practitioner exercise due diligence?','[\"In preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters\",\"In determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury\",\"C In determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service\",\"All of the answer choices are covered.\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(16,1,'Question: 16 To whom may a summons for information be issued by the Service to determine the taxpayer\'s financial situation?','[\"To a financial institution\",\"Any person with information that may be relevant to the case\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\",\"To a third-party record keeper\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(17,1,'Question: 17 The examination of Greta\'s tax return for 2020 resulted in adjustments creating a tax liability in the amount of $30,000. Greta does not believe she owes anything. A Notice of Proposed Income Tax Deficiency is issued to Greta, who wants to appeal the Revenue Agent\'s adjustments to the IRS Office of Appeals. Greta must file a written protest letter no later than which of the following periods?','[\"10 days\",\"90 days\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\",\"30 days\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(18,1,'Question: 18 Rich, an enrolled agent, is currently representing Dana before the Internal Revenue Service. Mike, Dana\'s former business partner, asks Rich to represent him before the Internal Revenue Service. Notwithstanding the existence of a conflict of interest between Dana and Mike, Rich may still represent Mike before the Internal Revenue Service if certain requirements are met. Which of the following is not a requirement that Rich has to satisfy before he can represent Mike?','[\"Rich must immediately notify the Internal Revenue Service in writing that he is representing both Dana and Mike.\",\"Dana and Mike must each give informed consent, confirmed in writing, to Rich.\",\"Rich must reasonably believe that he will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to both Dana and Mike.\",\"The representation is not prohibited by law.\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(19,1,'Question: 19 Which of the following statements is correct concerning documentation for a taxpayer?','[\"A checkbook cannot be used to keep records of income or expenses.\",\"A checkbook can be used to keep records of income but not expenses.\",\"A checkbook can be used to keep records of both income and expenses.\",\"A checkbook can be used to keep records of expenses but not income.\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(20,1,'Question: 20 The IRS has begun an examination of Mark\'s income tax return. The IRS would like to ask Mark\'s neighbors questions with respect to that examination. There is no pending criminal investigation into the matter and there is no evidence that such contact will result in reprisals against the neighbors or jeopardize collection of the tax liability. Before the IRS contacts the neighbors, the IRS must:','[\"mail Mark a statutory notice of deficiency.\",\"make an assessment of Mark\'s tax liability.\",\"provide Mark with reasonable notice of the contact.\",\"ask the court for a third-party record keeper subpoena.\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(21,1,'Question: 21 A practitioner can be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service for incompetence and/or disreputable conduct. Which one of the following is considered disreputable conduct?','[\"Giving false or misleading information or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information to the Department of the Treasury or any officer or employee thereof\",\"Conviction of any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United States\",\"Conviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(22,1,'Question: 22 Who can enroll and use EFTPS?','[\"Any individual or business taxpayer\",\"Only individual taxpayers\",\"Only authorized tax preparers\",\"Only business taxpayers\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(23,1,'Question: 23 In some cases, a spouse will be relieved of the tax, interest, and penalties on a joint return. Which of the following types of relief is not relief from a joint tax return?','[\"Equitable relief\",\"Innocent spouse relief\",\"Injured spouse relief\",\"Separation of liability relief\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(24,1,'Question: 24 The IRS began an examination of Mr. Jones\' 2024 income tax return. Mr. Jones hired Tyler, an enrolled agent and former IRS employee, to represent him before the IRS. Tyler wrote a memorandum to Mr. Jones outlining the issues that might be raised by the IRS and how to address these issues. Tyler correctly marked this memorandum as confidential and privileged under Section 7525 of the Internal Revenue Code. During the examination, the Revenue Officer assigned to the case asked Tyler for a copy of the memorandum. Mr. Jones, invoking the Section 7525 privilege, told Tyler not to disclose it to the Revenue Officer. Tyler is not required to provide the Revenue Officer with a copy of the memorandum because:','[\"Section 7525 extends the attorney client privilege to federally authorized tax practitioners.\",\"Circular 230 does not authorize officers or employees of the IRS to request any documents other than a tax return.\",\"the Revenue Officer did not issue a summons requesting it.\",\"the IRS cannot request documents during an examination.\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(25,1,'Question: 25 What action may a taxpayer take when the taxpayer and the IRS do not reach agreement on proposed audit changes?','[\"The taxpayer may take the case directly to the Tax Court.\",\"The IRS decision is final and cannot be appealed.\",\"The taxpayer must seek settlement by an Appeals Office before going to the Tax Court.\",\"The taxpayer may request the case be handled under the small tax case procedures if the tax liability is less than $100,000.\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(26,1,'Question: 26 Which of the following courts hears only tax cases and its rulings can be cited as precedent?','[\"U.S. Court of Federal Claims\",\"Small Case Division\",\"Tax Court\",\"District Court\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(27,1,'Question: 27 Which of the following statements is incorrect with respect to signing a taxpayer\'s income tax return?','[\"Taxpayers can use an electronic signature to sign their tax return when e-filing a return.\",\"Both spouses must sign the return when filing a joint tax return.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct. (There are no incorrect statements.)\",\"A child (or parent or guardian) must sign the return when a child is required to file a tax return.\"]',2,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(28,1,'Question: 28 Under Treasure Department Circular No. 230, all of the following are considered to be incompetence and disreputable conduct EXCEPT:','[\"willfully disclosing tax return information with the consent of the taxpayer.\",\"conviction of any criminal offense under the Federal tax laws.\",\"willfully failing to sign a tax return prepared by the tax practitioner as required by Federal tax laws, unless the failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect.\",\"conviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust.\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(29,1,'Question: 29 Sara Birch became an enrolled agent on March 12, 2024. Sara is ordering business cards and advertising for her accounting and tax practice. Of the following presentations listed below, which one will violate the Circular 230 rules for advertising?','[\"Sara Birch, enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service\",\" Sara Birch, Enrolled Agent, certified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Sara Birch, EA, admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Sara Birch, Enrolled Agent, representing taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service\"]',1,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(30,1,'Question: 30 The Internal Revenue Service notified Sally in February 2024 that she passed the Special Enrollment Examination. She submitted her application for enrollment and received the initial enrollment on June 15, 2024. Her continuing professional education requirements until the first full renewal cycle are that:','[\"she must complete a minimum of 72 hours of continuing professional education unless she is within less than a year before the end of the current cycle.\",\"she does not have to complete any continuing professional education requirements until the first full renewal cycle.\",\"she must complete 2 hours of credit for only each full month left in the current renewal cycle.\",\"she must complete 2 hours of credit for each full month and each part of a month left in the current renewal cycle.\"]',3,'',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:16','2026-04-23 02:34:16'),(31,2,'Which of the following is covered under Circular 230\'s requirement that a practitioner exercise due diligence?','[\"In preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters\",\"In determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury\",\"In determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service\",\"All of the answer choices are covered.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides the general rule for a practitioner and due diligence as to accuracy. That is, a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service.nHence, all of the above statements are listed in this problem.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(32,2,'Which of the following statements presumes that a practitioner has exercised due diligence as to accuracy?nn1. If the practitioner relies on the work product of another personn2. If the practitioner takes proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner being relied on and another person doing the work','[\"Item 1\",\"Item 2\",\"Either item 1 or 2\",\"Both items 1 and 2\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22(b), provides that a practitioner will be presumed to have exercised due diligence for purposes of this section if:nnthe practitioner relies on the work product of another person andnthe practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(33,2,'A practitioner must exercise due diligence:','[\"in determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"in preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters.\",\"in determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides the general rule for a practitioner and due diligence as to accuracy. That is, a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service.nHence, all of the answer choices in this problem are true.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(34,2,'While all providers must be on the lookout for fraud and abuse in IRS e-file, Electronic Return Originators (EROs) must be particularly diligent while acting in their capacity as the first contact with taxpayers filing a return. Which of the following actions should an ERO take when preparing a tax return for a new taxpayer?','[\"Confirm the taxpayer identification number of the taxpayer, spouse, and dependents listed on the tax return being prepared\",\"Confirm identities, if the taxpayer is unknown to the preparer, by means of two forms of picture identification\",\"Report only altered Forms W-2 to the IRS if the provider observes or becomes aware of them\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Safeguarding of IRS e-file from fraud and abuse is the shared responsibility of the IRS and Authorized IRS e-file Providers (\"Providers\"). Providers must be diligent in recognizing and preventing fraud and abuse in IRS e-file.nnPublication 1345, pages 9–10, provides information relevant to EROs in safeguarding IRS e-file from fraud and abuse. The ERO should confirm the identities and TINs (tax identification numbers) of taxpayers, spouses, and dependents listed on returns prepared by its firm. To confirm identities, an ERO should ask taxpayers not known to them to provide two forms of identification (picture IDs are preferable but are not required) that include the taxpayer\'s name and current address. Also, seeing Social Security cards, ITIN (individual TIN) letters, and other documents avoids including incorrect TINs for taxpayers, spouses, and dependents on returns. Providers should take care to ensure that they transcribe all TINs correctly.nnThe IRS has identified questionable Forms W-2 as a key indicator of potentially abusive and fraudulent returns. An ERO should be on the lookout for suspicious or altered Forms W-2, W-2G, and 1099-R, and forged or fabricated documents. EROs must always enter the “non-standard form” code in the electronic record of individual income tax returns for Forms W-2, W-2G, or 1099-R that are altered, handwritten, or typed. An alteration includes any pen-and-ink change. Providers must never alter the information after the taxpayer has given the forms to them.nnProviders should report questionable (not only altered) Forms W-2 if they observe or become aware of them.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(35,2,'Which of the following conditions would not prevent an individual from qualifying for the earned income credit (EIC) for the year 2024?','[\"Married filing separately filing status\",\"Being a qualifying child of another person\",\"Being age 25\",\"Investment income of more than $12,000\"]',2,'Table 1, which appears on page 2 of Publication 596, provides a capsule presentation on the qualification rules for the earned income credit.nnFrom the information given in Table 1, the only condition that would not prevent an individual from qualifying for the EIC is being age 25. nnChapter 1 of Table 1 (“Rules for Everyone”) states that the filing status cannot be married filing separately (rule 3). Chapter 1 (rule 6) also states that your “investment income must be $11,600 or less.” Chapter 3 (rule 13) of Table 1 (“Rules If You Do Not Have a Qualifying Child”) says that you “cannot be the qualifying child of another person.”nnNote: Although the subject matter of this question is not included in the content outline of Part 3 of the examination, there is a possibility that such a question may appear on the Part 3 exam (graded or ungraded).',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(36,2,'Which of the following is a taxpayer\'s responsibility when filing Form 8878?','[\"To verify the accuracy of the prepared application for an extension\",\"To check the appropriate box in Part II of the form to authorize the ERO to enter the taxpayer\'s PIN\",\"To return the completed Form 8878 to the ERO by hand delivery, U.S. mail, private delivery service, or fax\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'As provided on page 2 of Form 8878, IRS e-file Signature Authorization for Form 4868 or Form 2350, the taxpayer has the responsibility to do all of the following when filing Form 8878:nnVerify the accuracy of the prepared application for an extensionnCheck the appropriate box in Part II of Form 8878, to authorize the Electronic Return Originator (ERO) to enter or generate the taxpayer\'s PIN (personal identification number) or to do it themselvesnIndicate or verify the taxpayer\'s PIN (five numbers other than all zeros) when authorizing the ERO to enter or generate itnSign and date Form 8878nReturn the completed Form 8878 to the ERO by hand delivery, U.S. mail, private delivery service, fax, e-mail, or an Internet websitenA taxpayer\'s application for extension of time to file will not be transmitted to the IRS until the ERO receives the signed Form 8878.nnIt should be noted that the ERO has responsibilities listed on Form 8878.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(37,2,'Which of the following should an ERO do when e-filing for taxpayers?','[\"Exercise care in inputting tax return data into tax return preparation software\",\"Exercise care not to ask a taxpayer if she or he had any problems with a prior tax return filing\",\"Use software that does not permit the taxpayer to e-pay\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, page 11, provides several suggestions on how an Electronic Return Originator (ERO) can assist a taxpayer in avoiding refund delays. One of the items listed is to exercise care in inputting tax return data into tax return preparation software. Another item listed is to ask a taxpayer whether he or she had any problems with the prior tax filing or refund.nnPublication 1345, page 15, addresses a number of issues associated with credit card payments. In particular, taxpayers can e-file and, at the same time, pay the balance due by credit or debit card if the tax software used includes this option. Taxpayers who choose this option must provide the Authorized IRS e-file Provider with the credit card number, expiration date, and possibly the cardholder\'s address information. The credit card service provider will charge the taxpayer a convenience fee based on the amount of the tax payment. Taxpayers should be informed of the convenience fee before the return is filed. IRS e-file Providers should caution taxpayers to ensure, before they e-file, that the necessary line of credit is available.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(38,2,'During 2024, Jennifer received $32,000 W-2 income, $64,000 inheritance from her deceased Uncle Ben, $300 interest from her bank account, and $5,000 in combat pay. Jennifer is a staff sergeant in the reserves who was called to active duty. What amount would Jennifer report in gross income for the year?','[\"$32,300\",\"$37,300\",\"$96,300\",\"$101,300\"]',0,'In general, gross income includes, but is not limited to, income reported on Forms W-2, 1099-INT, and 1099-DIV.nnSome forms of income are excluded from gross income. Examples of nontaxable income include the following:nnProperty received as a gift, bequest, or inheritance generally is not included in gross income. (Publication 17, page 76)nAmounts received from passengers for driving a car in a car pool to and from work are not included in income; they are considered reimbursement for expenses. (Publication 525, page 32)nCompensation for active service while in a combat zone is excluded from gross income for non-officers and for a limited amount for officers. (Publication 3, pages 7 and 14–17)nAs a result, Jennifer would include $32,300, which is the sum of her W-2 income ($32,000) and Form 1099-INT income ($300).nnNote: A taxpayer does not actually need to show the exclusion on his or her tax return because income that qualifies for the combat zone exclusion is not included in the wages reported on the taxpayer\'s Form W-2.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(39,2,'Louie is the sole shareholder of a perfume manufacturing corporation. The corporation\'s tax return was examined, resulting in unagreed adjustments which were appealed and sustained at the IRS Appeals Office. Louie still believes that the adjustments are erroneous and wants a judge to hear his reasons. The corporation files a timely petition in the U.S. Tax Court contesting the adjustments. At the beginning of the trial, the attorney for the corporation files a motion requesting the judge order that the IRS has the burden to prove that its adjustments are not erroneous. Which of the following criteria must be satisfied before the burden of proof shifts to the IRS?','[\"The corporation must have maintained all records required and complied with all substantiation requirements under the Internal Revenue Code.\",\"The corporation must have cooperated with all reasonable requests by the revenue agent for information regarding the items being questioned on its return.\",\"The corporation had a net worth of $7 million or less at the time the petition was filed in the Tax Court.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 9, provides information on burden of proof. For court proceedings resulting from examinations started after July 22, 1998, the IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue if the taxpayer has introduced credible evidence relating to the issue. The taxpayer, however, also must have:nnintroduced credible evidence relating to the issues,ncomplied with all substantiation requirements of the Internal Revenue Code,nmaintained all records required by the Internal Revenue Code,ncooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the taxpayer\'s tax return, andnhad a net worth of $7 million or less and not more than 500 employees at the time the taxpayer\'s tax liability is contested in any court proceeding if the taxpayer\'s tax return is for a corporation, partnership, or trust.nMore importantly, the taxpayer must still keep and maintain records needed by the IRS to verify that all taxes have been properly determined and computed, even if the IRS has the burden of proof on disputed factual issues.nnHence, all of the statements given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(40,2,'If a taxpayer uses an electronic storage system for recordkeeping, she must have all electronic storage systems provide a complete and accurate record of her data that is accessible to the IRS. In addition to the computerized records, she must:','[\"keep proof of payment to prove the amounts shown on her tax return.\",\"keep proof of receipts to prove the amounts shown on her tax return.\",\"keep proof of receipts and other documents to prove the amounts shown on her tax return.\",\"keep any other books and records that are required to be retained.\"]',3,'Publication 583, page 12, provides that all requirements that apply to hardcopy books and records also apply to electronic storage systems that maintain tax books and records. When a taxpayer replaces hardcopy books and records, the taxpayer must maintain the electronic storage systems for as long as they are material to the administration of tax law.nnIn addition, if a taxpayer uses an electronic storage system, the taxpayer must have all electronic storage systems provide a complete and accurate record of the taxpayer\'s data that is accessible to the IRS. Electronic storage systems are also subject to the same controls and retention guidelines as those imposed on your original hard copy books and records. That is, the taxpayer must keep any other books and records that are required to be retained.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(41,2,'How long should a taxpayer keep a copy of Form W-2?','[\"2 years after filing the tax return\",\"3 years after filing the tax return\",\"7 years after filing the tax return\",\"Until the taxpayer begins receiving Social Security benefits\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 18, states that a taxpayer should keep Copy C of Form W-2 until the taxpayer begins receiving Social Security benefits. This will help protect the taxpayer’s benefits in case there is a question about the taxpayer\'s work record or earnings in a particular year.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(42,2,'As a general rule, if you receive property in a nontaxable exchange, your basis in that property is the same as the basis of the property you gave up. Which of the following is correct about this transaction?','[\"You\\u00a0must\\u00a0keep the records on the old property until the period of limitations expires for the year in which you dispose of the new property in a taxable disposition.\",\"You\\u00a0must\\u00a0keep the records on the new property until the period of limitations expires for the year in which you dispose of the new property in a taxable disposition.\",\"You\\u00a0must\\u00a0keep the records on the old property, as well as the new property, until the period of limitations expires for the year in which you dispose of the new property in a taxable disposition.\",\"You\\u00a0must\\u00a0keep the records on the old property, as well as the new property, for a minimum of 7 years from which you dispose of the new property in a taxable disposition.\"]',2,'Publication 17, pages 17 and 18, provides that a taxpayer must keep records as long as they may be needed for the administration of any provision of the Internal Revenue Code. Generally, this means the taxpayer must keep records that support items shown on his or her return until the period of limitations for that return runs out.nnIn the case of property transactions, a taxpayer keeps records until the period of limitations expires for the year in which the taxpayer disposes of the property in a taxable disposition. That is, the taxpayer must keep these records to figure his or her basis for computing gain or loss when the taxpayer sells or otherwise disposes of the property.nnGenerally, if the taxpayer received property in a nontaxable exchange, his or her basis in that property is the same as the basis of the property he or she gave up. The taxpayer must keep the records on the old property, as well as the new property, until the period of limitations expires for the year in which the taxpayer disposes of the new property in a taxable disposition.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(43,2,'The IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue in a court proceeding if the taxpayer has:','[\"provided credible evidence relating to the issue in a court proceeding.\",\"complied with all substantiation requirements and maintained all required records.\",\"cooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the return.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 9, provides information on burden of proof. That is, for court proceedings resulting from examinations started after July 22, 1998, the IRS generally has the burden of proof for any factual issue if the taxpayer has:nnintroduced credible evidence relating to the issue,ncomplied with all substantiation requirements of the Internal Revenue Code,nmaintained all records required by the Internal Revenue Code,ncooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the taxpayer\'s tax return, andnhad a net worth of $7 million or less and not more than 500 employees at the time the taxpayer\'s tax liability is contested in any court proceeding if the taxpayer\'s tax return is for a corporation, partnership, or trust.nMore importantly, the taxpayer must still keep and maintain records needed by the IRS to verify that all taxes have been properly determined and computed even if the IRS has the burden of proof on disputed factual issues.nnHence, all of the statements given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(44,2,'Martha and Max are married with two children. Martha and Max each have earned income of $12,000 in 2024. Even though they live together, they choose to file separate returns, with each one of them claiming one child as a dependent. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to claiming the earned income credit (EIC)?','[\"Either Martha or Max can claim the EIC, but not both spouses.\",\"Only Martha can claim the EIC.\",\"Only Max can claim the EIC.\",\"Neither Martha nor Max can claim the EIC.\"]',3,'As found in Rule 3 in Table 1 appearing on page 2 of Publication 596, a taxpayer who is married is required to file a joint return in order to claim the EIC.nnThere is an exception to this rule as given in the explanation for Rule 3 appearing on page 24 of Publication 17. That is, the taxpayer cannot file as married filing separately unless the taxpayer\'s spouse did not live in the taxpayer\'s home at any time during the last 6 months of the year. In this case, the taxpayer may be able to file as head of household, instead of married filing separately and as such may be able to claim the EIC.nnFor more details on this issue, you should consult Publication 596.nnNote: Although the subject matter of this question is not included in the content outline of Part 3 of the examination, there is a possibility that such a question may appear on the Part 3 exam (graded or ungraded).',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(45,2,'In general, what must a tax practitioner do if a client wants her tax records back?','[\"Return any and all records\",\"Return any and all records necessary for the client to comply with her federal tax obligations\",\"Return any and all records necessary for the client to comply with her federal tax obligations and internal memoranda of tax strategies for future transactions\",\"Return any and all records necessary for the client to comply with her federal tax obligations but only after she has paid all outstanding statements from the practitioner\"]',1,'In general, a practitioner must promptly return any and all records necessary for a client to comply with federal tax obligations. The practitioner can make and keep copies. If applicable state law allows for retention of records because of a fee dispute, the practitioner must return only records that need to be attached to the client’s return.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(46,2,'If your clients keep their records on a computer, they are required to keep:nn1. all of their receipts.n2. all of their checks.n3. all of their other documents.','[\"1 only\",\"1 and 2 only\",\"2 and 3 only\",\"1, 2, and 3\"]',3,'Publication 583, pages 12 through 15, provides in part that a taxpayer can use a checkbook to keep a record of his or her income and expenses. If this system is used, the taxpayer should record amounts, sources of deposits, and types of expenses. In addition, the taxpayer needs to keep documents such as receipts and sales slips that can help prove a deduction.nnIf a taxpayer uses an electronic storage system, all requirements that apply to hard copy books and records also apply to the electronic storage systems that maintain tax books and records. Thus, the system must index, store, preserve, retrieve, and reproduce the electronically stored books and records in a legible, readable format.nnHence, if your clients keep their records on a computer, they are required to keep all three of the items listed.nnAs an aside, the original hardcopy books and records may be destroyed provided that the electronic storage system has been tested to establish that the hardcopy books and records are being reproduced in compliance with IRS requirements for an electronic storage system and procedures are established to ensure continued compliance with all applicable rules and regulations. Since no mention is made in this question about the electronic storage system, one must assume that it has not been tested.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(47,2,'How long should you keep Copy C of your W-2 after you have filed your return?','[\"2 years\",\"3 years\",\"7 years\",\"Until the taxpayer begins receiving Social Security benefits\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 18, states that a taxpayer should keep Copy C of Form W-2 until the person begins receiving Social Security benefits. This will help protect the taxpayer’s benefits in case there is a question about the taxpayer\'s work record or earnings in a particular year.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(48,2,'What information must paid preparers that file a taxpayer\'s tax return electronically disclose about themselves on the copies they supply to taxpayers?','[\"Their Social Security number\",\"Their employer identification number\",\"Their Social Security number or employer identification number\",\"None of these answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 1345, pages 25 and 26, states the ERO (Electronic Return Originator) must provide a complete copy of the return to the taxpayer. The return may be provided in any media, including electronic, that is acceptable to both the taxpayer and the ERO. IRC Section 1.6107-1(a)(2) states: \"the copy provided to the taxpayer must include all information submitted to the IRS to enable the taxpayer to determine what schedules, forms, electronic files, and other supporting materials have been filed with the return. The copy, however, need not contain the identification number of the paid tax return preparer.\" Therefore, paid preparers that file a taxpayer\'s tax return electronically need not disclose their Social Security number or employer identification number on the copies they supply to taxpayers.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(49,2,'Pursuant to Treasury Circular 230, which of the following statements about the return of a client\'s records is correct?','[\"The client\'s records are to be destroyed upon submission of a tax return.\",\"The practitioner may retain copies of the client\'s records.\",\"The existence of a dispute over fees generally relieves the practitioner of responsibility to return the client\'s records.\",\"The practitioner does not need to return any client records that are necessary for the client to comply with the client\'s federal tax obligations.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.28(a) advises that the taxpayer may request and receive any and all records that are necessary to comply with the taxpayer\'s federal tax obligation. The practitioner may retain a copy of the records returned to the client.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(50,2,'John Jones, an enrolled agent, prepared the 2024 tax return for Mr. William Smith. The return of Mr. Smith contained a Schedule C, wages (Form W-2), retirement income (Form 1099-R), and Form 8453, U.S. Individual Income Tax Transmittal for an IRS e-file Return. Based upon the information in the 2024 tax return of Mr. Smith, which statement below describes the documents that Mr. Jones is required to maintain for Mr. Smith\'s 2024 electronically filed tax return?','[\"Mr. Jones must only maintain a paper copy of the tax return and W-2.\",\"Mr. Jones must only retain a copy of Form 8453.\",\"Mr. Jones must retain a copy of Form 8453 and paper copies of Forms W-2 and 1099-R, as well as any supporting documents that are not included in the electronic return data.\",\"Mr. Jones does not have to retain any of the documents used in the preparation of Mr. Smith\'s return. Mr. Jones should secure a signed statement from Mr. Smith that lists all the documents used in the preparation of the return, and that they were all returned to Mr. Smith.\"]',2,'Electronic Return Originators (EROs) must retain and make available to the IRS upon request, until the end of the calendar year in which a return was filed, the following material at the business address from which the return was originated. An ERO may retain the required records at the business address of the Responsible Official during any period of time the office is closed:nnA copy of Form 8453, any supporting documents that are not included in the electronic records submitted to the IRSnCopies of Forms W-2, W-2G, and 1099-RnA copy of signed IRS e-file consent to disclosure formsnA complete copy of the electronic portion of the return that can be readily and accurately converted into an electronic transmission that the IRS can processnThe acknowledgment file for IRS accepted returnsnForms 8879 and 8878 must be available to the IRS in the same manner described above, for 3 years from the due date of the return or the IRS received date, whichever is later.nnGiven such, Mr. Jones must retain a copy of the Form 8453 and paper copies of Forms W-2 and 1099-R, as well as any supporting documents that are not included in the electronic return data.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(51,2,'Which of the following statements is correct about an ERO\'s responsibilities when preparing tax returns?','[\"An ERO needs to confirm identities and Social Security numbers of taxpayers and spouses but\\u00a0not\\u00a0the dependents listed on returns.\",\"An ERO needs to confirm Social Security numbers\\u00a0only\\u00a0of taxpayers, spouses, and the dependents listed on returns.\",\"An ERO needs to confirm identities and Social Security numbers of taxpayers, spouses, and dependents listed on returns.\",\"An ERO does\\u00a0not\\u00a0need to confirm identities and Social Security numbers of taxpayers, spouses, and dependents listed on returns.\"]',2,'Publication 1345, pages 9–10, provides that while all Authorized IRS e-file Providers must be on the lookout for fraud and abuse in IRS e-file, EROs (Electronic Return Originators) must be particularly diligent while acting in their capacity as the first contact with taxpayers filing a return. An ERO must be diligent in recognizing fraud and abuse, reporting it to the IRS, and preventing it when possible. Providers must cooperate with the IRS\'s investigations by making available to the IRS, upon request, information and documents related to returns with potential fraud or abuse. Additional information regarding reporting fraud and abuse in IRS e-file is available at the IRS website.nnIndicators of abusive or fraudulent returns may be unsatisfactory responses to filing status questions, multiple returns with the same address, and missing or incomplete Schedules A and C income and expense documentation. A “fraudulent return” is a return in which the individual is attempting to file using someone else\'s name or Social Security number (SSN) on the return, or the taxpayer is presenting documents or information that have no basis in fact. A “potentially abusive return” is a return that the taxpayer is required to file but contains inaccurate information that may lead to an understatement of a liability or the overstatement of a credit resulting in a refund to which the taxpayer may not be entitled.nnAn ERO that is also the paid preparer should exercise due diligence in the preparation of returns involving the earned income tax credit (EITC), as it is a popular target for fraud and abuse. IRC Section 6695(g) requires paid preparers to exercise due diligence in the preparation of returns involving EITC. Paid preparers must complete all required worksheets and meet all recordkeeping requirements.nnPublication 1345, page 10, further states that an ERO should confirm identities and taxpayer identification numbers of taxpayers, spouses, and dependents listed on returns prepared by its firm.nnTo prevent filing returns with stolen identities, an ERO should ask taxpayers not known to them to provide two forms of identification (picture IDs are preferable) that include the taxpayer\'s name and current address. Also, seeing Social Security cards, ITIN letters, and other documents for taxpayers, spouses and dependents avoids including incorrect TINs on returns. Providers should take care to ensure that they transcribe all TINs correctly.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(52,2,'Under Treasury Circular 230, the IRS requires that certain records be returned to a client by the tax practitioner even though no payment for services has been received. Records of the client for this purpose do not include:','[\"materials prepared by a client\'s actuary and provided to the practitioner with respect to tax preparation.\",\"a schedule prepared by the practitioner that provides mathematical details of a particular amount included in a client\'s tax return.\",\"electronic materials provided to the practitioner that existed before the client retained the practitioner.\",\"written records given to the practitioner at the beginning of the engagement.\"]',1,'A practitioner must, at the request of the client, promptly return any and all records of the client that are necessary for the client to comply with his or her federal tax obligations, even if the client has not yet paid for the practitioner’s services. Generally, these would be client-prepared documents. The practitioner may retain copies of the records returned to a client (Circular 230, Section 10.28).nnRecords of the client for this purpose would not include a schedule prepared by the practitioner that provides mathematical details of a particular amount included in a client\'s tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(53,2,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to a client\'s request for records of the client that are necessary for the client to comply with his or her federal tax obligations?','[\"The practitioner may never return records of the client to the client even if the client requests prompt return of the records.\",\"The existence of a dispute over fees always relieves the practitioner of his or her responsibility to return records of the client to the client.\",\"The practitioner must, at the request of the client, promptly return the records of the client to the client unless applicable state law provides otherwise.\",\"The practitioner must, at the request of the client, return the records of the client to the client within 3 months of receiving the request.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.28, provides that, in general, a practitioner must, at the request of a client, promptly return any and all records of the client that are necessary for the client to comply with his or her federal tax obligations.nnThe practitioner may retain copies of the records returned to a client. The existence of a dispute over fees generally does not relieve the practitioner of his or her responsibility under this section. Nevertheless, if applicable state law allows or permits the retention of a client\'s records by a practitioner in the case of a dispute over fees for services rendered, the practitioner need only return those records that must be attached to the taxpayer\'s return.nnThe practitioner, however, must provide the client with reasonable access to review and copy any additional records of the client retained by the practitioner under state law that are necessary for the client to comply with his or her federal tax obligations.nnThus, the correct response to this problem is the practitioner must, at the request of the client, promptly return the records of the client to the client unless applicable state law provides otherwise.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(54,2,'Leslie Oak, an enrolled agent, prepared the 2024 tax return for Ms. Barbara Smith. The Form 1040 tax return of Ms. Smith contained capital gains and losses (Schedule D), wages (Form W-2), rental income (Schedule E), and Form 8453, U.S. Individual Income Tax Transmittal for an IRS e-file Return. Based upon the information in the 2024 tax return of Ms. Smith, which statement below best describes the documents that Leslie Oak is required to maintain for Ms. Smith\'s 2024 electronically filed tax return?','[\"Leslie Oak must retain two copies of Form 8453.\",\"Leslie Oak does not have to retain any of the documents used in preparation of Ms. Smith\'s return. Leslie should secure from Ms. Smith a list of all the documents used in preparation of the return and that they were all returned to Ms. Smith (Form 8454,\\u00a0Return of Documents Used in Preparation of Electronically Filed Returns).\",\"Leslie Oak must retain a copy of Form 8453 and paper copies of all Forms W-2.\",\"Leslie Oak must only retain one copy of Form 8453.\"]',2,'Electronic Return Originators (EROs) must retain and make available to the IRS upon request, until the end of the calendar year in which a return was filed, the following material at the business address from which the return was originated. An ERO may retain the required records at the business address of the Responsible Official during any period of time the office is closed.nnA copy of Form 8453, any supporting documents that are not included in the electronic records submitted to the IRSnCopies of Forms W-2, W-2G, and 1099-RnA copy of signed IRS e-file consent to disclosure formsnA complete copy of the electronic portion of the return that can be readily and accurately converted into an electronic transmission that the IRS can processnThe acknowledgment file for IRS accepted returnsnForms 8879 and 8878 must be available to the IRS, in the same manner described above, for 3 years from the due date of the return or the IRS received date, whichever is later.nnGiven such, Leslie Oak must retain a copy of Form 8453 and paper copies of Forms W-2.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(55,2,'Sandy is an Electronic Return Originator. Which of the following is she not required to maintain a copy of until the end of the calendar year in which a return was filed?','[\"Any signed Forms 8453 (U.S. Individual Income Tax Transmittal for an IRS e-file Return)\",\"Any signed IRS\\u00a0e-file\\u00a0consent to disclosure forms for taxpayers who provided an electronic signature\",\"Any Forms W-2, W-2G, and 1099-R\",\"An electronic photo of the taxpayer\"]',3,'Publication 1345, page 25, provides that an ERO (Electronic Return Originator) must retain and make available to the Service upon request the following material at the business address from which a return was originated:nnA copy of any signed Forms 8453 and supporting documents that are not included in the electronic return data;nCopies of Forms W-2, W-2G, and 1099-R;nA copy of any signed IRS e-file consent to disclosure forms for taxpayers who provided an electronic signature;nA complete copy of the electronic portion of the return that can be readily and accurately converted into an electronic transmission that the Service can process; andnThe acknowledgment file for IRS-accepted returnsnAn ERO must also retain this material until the end of the calendar year in which a return was filed and make available to the Service upon request at either the business address from which the origination of the electronic submission occurred or at the business address of the Responsible Official during any period of time the office is closed.nnForms 8879 and 8878 must be available to the IRS in the same manner described above for 3 years from the due date of the return or the IRS received date, whichever is later.nnHence, Sandy is not required to maintain an electronic photo of the taxpayer; however, it might be a wise move to have such a photo for future reference.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(56,2,'How long should you keep your tax records?','[\"3 years if you owe additional tax\",\"7 years if you file a claim for a loss from worthless securities\",\"No limit if you do not file a return\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 18, provides a listing of time that a taxpayer must keep tax records. The basic rule is that a taxpayer must keep tax records as long as they may be needed for the administration of any provision of the Code.nnIn general, a taxpayer must keep records that support items shown on his or her tax return until the period of limitations for that return runs out. The period of limitations is the period in which a taxpayer can amend the return to claim a credit or refund or the IRS can assess additional tax.nnThe following is taken from Table 1-7 (Publication 17, page 18), which provides a listing of the periods of limitations that apply to income tax returns. Unless otherwise stated, the years refer to the period beginning after the return was filed. Returns filed before the due date are treated as being filed on the due date.nn3 years when a taxpayer owes additional tax and none of the next three items applyn6 years when a taxpayer does not report income that he or she should and it is more than 25% of the gross income shown on the taxpayer\'s returnnNo limit when a taxpayer files a fraudulent return or does not file a returnnThe later of 3 years or 2 years after tax was paid when a taxpayer files a claim for credit or refund after filing a returnn7 years when a taxpayer files a claim for a loss from worthless securitiesnIn this problem, all three situations that are given are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(57,2,'Which of the following are due diligence requirements for a tax preparer when claiming the earned income credit for a taxpayer on a 2024 tax return?','[\"All of the responses are correct.\",\"The preparer has complied with the knowledge requirements.\",\"The preparer keeps the checklist for his or her files.\",\"The checklist is based on information reasonably obtained by the preparer.\"]',0,'Form 8867 is a paid preparer\'s (not a taxpayer\'s) due diligence checklist that should be completed by a tax preparer. It is required to be filed when a taxpayer is claiming the earned income tax credit (EIC), the child tax credit/additional child tax credit (CTC/ACTC), and/or the American opportunity tax credit (AOTC). Beginning in 2018, the form is also required for those tax returns where the taxpayer is claiming head of household status.nnThe first section is the Due Diligence Requirements section. It provides a checklist that contains eight questions and it is broken into four columns: one column for each of the three tax credits and one column for the head of household filing status.nnThe first question asks whether the tax preparer completed the return based on information for tax year 2024 provided by the taxpayer or reasonably obtained by the tax preparer.nThe second question asks whether the tax preparer completed the EIC and/or CTC/ACTC worksheet found in the Form 1040, 1040-SR, 1040-NR, 1040-PR, or 1040-SS Instructions, and/or AOTC worksheet found in the Form 8863 Instructions or their own worksheets that provide the same information.nThe third question asks whether the tax preparer satisfied the knowledge requirement by interviewing the taxpayer and asking adequate questions.nThe fourth question asks whether any of the information provided by the taxpayer or third-party or information reasonably known by the tax preparer appears to be incorrect, incomplete, or inconsistent.nThe fifth question asks whether the tax preparer satisfied the record retention requirement.nThe sixth question asks if the tax preparer asked the taxpayer whether they could provide documentation to substantiate eligibility for and the amount of the credit(s) claimed and/or HOH filing status.nThe seventh question asks whether the tax preparer asked if any of these credits were disallowed or reduced in the previous year.nFinally, the eighth question asks if the taxpayer is reporting self-employment income and whether the tax preparer asked adequate questions for prepare a complete and correct Form 1040, Schedule C.nAs a result, all of the responses given for this question are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(58,2,'Michael Young, an Authorized Internal Revenue Service e-file Provider, prepared and electronically transmitted the Form 1040 return of Vivian Blue to the Internal Revenue Service. The Internal Revenue Service notified Michael that the electronic portion of Vivian\'s return was rejected for processing. Which statement listed below best explains what Michael must do?','[\"Michael must advise the taxpayer that the return may never be filed electronically. Vivian must return to the office, sign a paper copy of Form 1040, and mail it to the Service.\",\"If Michael cannot correct the error with the information in his possession, he must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 24 hours and provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation.\",\"Michael must mail a paper copy of the return to the IRS with the original Form 8453 that Vivian signed.\",\"If Michael cannot correct the error with the information in his possession, he must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection by the return due date or within 1 week, whichever date is earlier.\"]',1,'Publication 1345, pages 26 and 27, provides that if the Service rejects the electronic portion of a taxpayer\'s return for processing and the reason for the rejection cannot be rectified, the Electronic Return Originator (ERO) must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 24 hours.nnWhen the ERO advises the taxpayer that the return has not been filed, the ERO must provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation. If the taxpayer chooses not to have the electronic portion of the return corrected and transmitted to the Service or if it cannot be accepted for processing by the Service, the taxpayer must file a paper return.nnAs a side note, Form 8453 is not signed by the taxpayer.nnIn order to be filed timely, the paper return must be filed by the later of the due date of the return or 10 calendar days after the date the Service gives notification that the electronic portion of the return is rejected or that it cannot be accepted for processing. The paper return should include an explanation of why the return is being filed after the due date.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:18','2026-04-23 02:34:18'),(59,2,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to an Electronic Filing Identification Number (EFIN)?','[\"It may be transferred to a provider that purchases an existing IRS\\u00a0e-file\\u00a0business.\",\"It may be gifted from an existing IRS\\u00a0e-file\\u00a0business to a family member.\",\"The IRS assigns an EFIN to those applicants accepted for participation in IRS\\u00a0e-file.\",\"Online providers are assigned EFINs with prefix codes of 10, 15, and 20.\"]',2,'An Authorized IRS e-file Provider (Provider) is a business or organization authorized by the IRS to participate in IRS e-file. It may be a sole proprietorship, partnership, corporation, or other entity. The firm submits an e-file application, meets the eligibility criteria, and must pass a suitability check before the IRS assigns an Electronic Filing Identification Number (EFIN). Applicants accepted for participation in IRS e-file are Authorized IRS e-file Providers. (Publication 3112, page 2)nnPursuant to Publication 3112, page 11, providers that acquire an existing IRS e-file business by purchase, transfer, or gift must submit a new IRS e-file application and receive new Electronic Filing Identification Numbers (EFINs). The Provider must submit an e-file application and proof of sale, transfer, or gift during the period beginning 45 days before and ending 30 days after the acquisition date.nnThe IRS assigns Electronic Identification Filing Numbers (EFINs) to all Providers and assigns Electronic Identification Transmission Numbers (ETINs) to Transmitters, Software Providers, and Online Providers. The IRS assigns EFINs with prefix codes 10, 21, 32, 44, and 53 to Online Providers (Publication 3112, page 9).',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(60,2,'Which of the following methods are the primary payment methods for EFTPS?','[\"EFTPS online and EFTPS by phone\",\"EFTPS\\u2013Through a Financial Institution and Same Day Payment\",\"EFTPS-Direct and EFTPS\\u2013Through a Financial Institution\",\"EFTPS online and EFTPS\\u2013Through a Financial Institution\"]',0,'Publication 966, page 2, provides that the Electronic Federal Tax Payment System (EFTPS) is a tax payment system provided free by the U.S. Department of the Treasury. The EFTPS enables businesses and taxpayers to conveniently pay all their federal taxes either online or by phone from anywhere, 24/7 (24 hours a day, 7 days a week), 365 days a year.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(61,2,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning authorized electronic filing providers?','[\"They may base their fees on a percentage of the refund amount.\",\"They may compute their fees using any figure from tax returns.\",\"They may assist a taxpayer in applying for a Refund Anticipation Loan.\",\"They may accept a fee from a financial institution for any service connected with a Refund Anticipation Loan.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.27, provides that a practitioner (which would include an Authorized IRS e-file Provider) may not base their fees on a percentage of the refund amount or compute their fees using any figure from tax returns. Separate fees may not be charged for direct deposits.nnAn Authorized IRS e-file Provider may assist a taxpayer in applying for a RAL (Refund Anticipation Loan) or other tax refund-related product and may charge a flat fee for that assistance. nnAdditionally, the e-file Provider is not allowed to accept a fee from a financial institution for any service connected with a RAL that is contingent upon the amount of the refund or a RAL. In addition, the Service has no responsibility for the payment of any fees associated with the preparation of a return, the transmission of the electronic portion of a return, or a RAL.nnThus, the best response to this question is the authorized e-file provider may assist a taxpayer in applying for Refund Anticipation Loan.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(62,2,'Authorized electronic filing providers must notify the Internal Revenue Service of all changes to the information they originally submitted with the e-file Application. You may update certain information by letter, using the firm\'s official letterhead. Which of the following revisions listed below may be submitted by letter?','[\"Adding an additional principal of a firm, such as a partner or a corporate officer, that was not included in the original\\u00a0e-file\\u00a0Application\",\"Making a change to the Responsible Official listed in the original\\u00a0e-file\\u00a0Application\",\"Adding federal\\/state electronic filing to the list of services\",\"Deleting a principal that was included in the original\\u00a0e-file\\u00a0Application\"]',2,'Providers should ensure that the IRS has current information by reviewing and either updating or revising their IRS e-file Applications. Providers may review and update or revise, as necessary, their IRS e-file Application information electronically on the IRS website via e-services. A Principal, Responsible Official, or Delegated User authorized to revise an IRS e-file Application may submit all revisions.nnProviders must submit updates within 30 days of a change of any information. It is important to provide updates such as changes to business structure, Principals, Responsible Officials, addresses, and telephone numbers, and to remove individuals no longer associated with the firm, including deceased individuals. The IRS needs current information to be able to contact Providers and obtain or provide important information.nnMoreover, providers that are unable to revise their IRS e-file Application electronically may update the below information by letter, using the firm\'s official letterhead:nnAll addressesnAll phone and fax numbersnE-mail addressesnContact personsnForm types to be e-filednTransmission protocolsnAdding federal/state e-filenChanges to Foreign Filer informationnAdd or remove Provider OptionsnThe following situations are changes that cannot be made by letter or telephone, but require revision using the IRS e-file Application:nnThe Authorized IRS e-file Provider is functioning solely as a Software Developer or Reporting Agent and intends to do business as an ERO, Intermediate Service Provider, or Transmitter.nAn additional Principal of the firm, such as a partner or a corporate officer, is being added.nA Principal or Responsible Official is changed.nA Principal or Responsible Official must be deleted.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(63,2,'Warren and Ruthmary desperately needed their tax refund and decided to electronically file their year 2024 return. Which of the following provides the most accurate information regarding a Refund Anticipation Loan?','[\"The IRS states that it will guarantee a refund within 2 weeks for an electronically filed return.\",\"Electronic Return Originators may charge a separate fee for direct deposit to a temporary account when a Refund Anticipation Loan is involved.\",\"Electronic Return Originators must charge the same identical flat fee for all Refund Anticipation Loan clients.\",\"Electronic Return Originators may charge a double fee because it is a joint return.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.27, provides that a practitioner (which would include an Authorized IRS e-file Providers) may not base their fees on a percentage of the refund amount or compute their fees using any figure from tax returns. Separate fees may not be charged for direct deposits.nnPublication 1345, page 38, further provides that a tax refund-related product (sometimes referred to as a Refund Anticipation Loan (RAL)) is money borrowed by a taxpayer from a lender that is based on the taxpayer\'s anticipated income tax refund. Furthermore, a Refund Anticipation Check (RAC) directs the refund to a financial institution, which disburses fees and the balance to the taxpayer. Financial institutions also offer a variety of other financial products to taxpayers based on their refunds. The IRS is in no way involved in or responsible for tax refund-related products or other financial products.nnMoreover, there are no guarantees that the Department of the Treasury deposits refunds within a specified time or in their entirety. For example, it may delay a refund due to processing problems, or it may offset some or all of the refund. The Department of the Treasury is not liable for any loss suffered by taxpayers, Authorized IRS e-file Providers, or financial institutions resulting from reduced refunds or not-honored Direct Deposits, causing it to issue refunds by check.nnAn Authorized IRS e-file Provider may assist a taxpayer in applying for a tax refund-related product and may charge a flat fee for that assistance. However, the fee must not be related to the amount of the refund or a tax refund-related product (or RAL) therefore, it must be identical for all customers. nnThus, the best response regarding a Refund Anticipation Loan for Warren and Ruthmary is that the ERO (Electronic Return Originator) must charge the same identical flat fee for all Refund Anticipation Loan clients.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(64,2,'Some returns are not eligible for the Internal Revenue Service electronic filing program. Which item listed below is generally eligible to be filed through the Internal Revenue Service electronic filing program?','[\"Form 1040 returns for the previous tax year\",\"Tax returns with a TIN of 900-00-0000 or higher\",\"Fiscal-year tax periods\",\"Amended tax returns (prior to 2019)\"]',0,'Filing individual income tax returns using IRS e-file is limited to tax returns with prescribed due dates in the current and previous 2 tax years.nnThe following individual income tax returns and related return conditions cannot be processed using IRS e-file:nnTax returns with fiscal-year tax periodsnReturns containing forms or schedules that cannot be processed by IRS e-file other than those forms and schedules that are required to be submitted with Form 8453nTax returns with TINs (taxpayer identification numbers) within the range of 900-00-0000 through 999-99-9999, with a few exceptionsnTherefore, the only item qualified to be filed through the Internal Revenue Service\'s electronic filing program is Form 1040 returns for the current and previous 2 tax years.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(65,2,'An Electronic Return Originator (ERO) should:','[\"advise his or her clients of the option to receive their refund by direct deposit or paper check.\",\"advise his or her clients of the requirement to receive their refund by direct deposit only when electronically filing.\",\"advise his or her clients of the requirement to receive their refund by paper check only when electronically filing.\",\"not\\u00a0provide any advice about the manner in which a refund can be received when filing electronically.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, pages 12–13, states that EROs should advise taxpayers of the option to receive their refund by direct deposit or paper check; apply it to next year\'s estimated tax; or split the refund so that a portion is applied to next year\'s estimated tax and the rest received as a direct deposit or paper check.nnTaxpayers often elect the Direct Deposit option because it is the fastest way of receiving refunds. Providers must accept any direct deposit election to any eligible financial institution designated by the taxpayer. The taxpayer may designate refunds for direct deposit to qualified accounts in the taxpayer\'s name. Qualified accounts include savings, checking, share draft, or consumer asset accounts (for example, IRA or money market accounts). Taxpayers should not request a deposit of their refund to an account that is not in their own name (such as their tax preparer\'s own account). The taxpayer may not designate refunds for direct deposit to credit card accounts. Qualified accounts are accounts held by financial institutions within the United States and established primarily for personal, family, or household purposes. Qualifying institutions may be national banks, state banks (including the District of Columbia and political subdivisions of the 50 states), savings and loan associations, mutual savings banks, and credit unions.nnTaxpayers should be cautioned that some financial institutions do not permit the deposit of joint individual income tax refunds into individual accounts. The IRS is not responsible if direct deposits are refused for this reason.nnAdditionally, an Authorized IRS e-file Provider must never charge a separate fee for direct deposit and must accept any direct deposit election by a taxpayer to any eligible financial institution. The e-file Provider must advise the taxpayer that a direct deposit election cannot be rescinded and that changes cannot be made to routing numbers of financial institutions or to the taxpayer\'s account numbers after the IRS has accepted the return.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(66,2,'Which of the following tax credits being claimed by a taxpayer on their 2024 tax return requires the paid tax preparer to file Form 8867, Paid Preparer’s Due Diligence Checklist, with the taxpayer’s tax return?','[\"Head of Household\",\"Earned income tax credit\",\"Child tax credit\",\"All of the listed items\"]',3,'Regulation Sections 1.6695-2 and 1.6695-2T provide guidance on satisfying the due diligence requirement for a paid tax return preparer claiming the earned income tax credit, the child tax credit/additional child tax credit, and/or the American opportunity tax credit for a client. Beginning in 2018, this form is required whenever a taxpayer files as the Head of Household. In particular, Form 8867 is required whenever a taxpayer is claiming any one of the three tax credits or claiming Head of Household filing status.nnFailure to comply with the due diligence regulations results in a penalty for each failure on a tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(67,2,'Which of the following statements is true regarding rejected electronic filed returns?','[\"The ERO must notify the taxpayer within 48 hours if they can\'t fix the reason for the rejection.\",\"The ERO only needs to provide an explanation of the rejection.\",\"To timely file the return, the taxpayer must file the paper returns by the later of the due date of the return or ten calendar days after the notification of rejection.\",\"Taxpayers do not need to include any explanation with the paper return, as to why it is being filed after the due date.\"]',2,'According to IRS Publication 1345, if an Electronic Return Originator (ERO) cannot correct the reason for a rejected return, the taxpayer must file a paper return by the later of the due date of the return or ten calendar days after the notification of rejection to be considered timely filed. An explanation should be included with the paper return to explain why it is being filed after the due date if applicable. Additionally, the ERO needs to notify the taxpayer within 24 hours of a reject with the business rule(s)and an explanation of the reject.nnThe correct answer is to timely file a return, the taxpayer must file the paper return by the later of the due date of the return or ten calendar days after the notification of the rejection.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(68,2,'E-file providers are required to advise their clients that:','[\"once an electronically filed return is accepted, a direct deposit option\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0be rescinded.\",\"once an electronically filed return is accepted, a direct deposit option can be rescinded within 3 working days only.\",\"once an electronically filed return is accepted, a direct deposit option can be rescinded within 7 working days only.\",\"once an electronically filed return is accepted, a direct deposit option can be rescinded within 10 working days only.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, pages 12–13, notes that the Electronic Return Originators (EROs) should advise taxpayers that they have several options, such as applying the tax refund to next year\'s estimated tax, receiving their refund by direct deposit or paper check, or splitting it between next year\'s estimated tax and receiving the rest as a direct deposit or paper check.nnTaxpayers, however, often elect the Direct Deposit option because it is the fastest way of receiving refunds.nnAs noted on page 13 of Publication 1345, the ERO has some responsibilities to the taxpayer. First, the ERO should caution taxpayers that some financial institutions do not permit the deposit of joint individual income tax refunds into individual accounts and the IRS is not responsible if the financial institution refuses direct deposits for this reason.nnSecond, the ERO must advise the taxpayer that a direct deposit election cannot be rescinded and that changes cannot be made to routing numbers of financial institutions or to the taxpayer\'s account numbers. The Authorized e-file Provider, likewise, must not alter the direct deposit information in the electronic record after taxpayers have signed the tax return. (Publication 1345, page 13)nnHence, the correct response is that a direct deposit election cannot be rescinded once the return is filed.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(69,2,'Which of the following is an acceptable method of computation for an Electronic Return Originator fee?','[\"Fees based on time required for preparation\",\"Fees based on AGI from the tax return\",\"Fees based on percent of refund\",\"Flat fee identical for all customers\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.27, provides that a practitioner (which would include an Authorized IRS e-file Provider) may not base their Electronic Return Originator fees on a percentage of the refund amount or compute their fees using any figure from tax returns. Contingent fees are prohibited and the fees related to preparation do not apply to the Electronic Return Originator fees. Separate fees may not be charged for direct deposits.nnAs a result, the flat fee identical for all customers is an acceptable method for an ERO (Electronic Return Originator).',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(70,2,'The Internal Revenue Service e-file Program allows taxpayers to schedule the payment for withdrawal on a future date. Scheduled payments must be effective on or before the return due date. Which of the following is correct concerning when the taxpayer must specify the withdrawal be made if the provider transmits an individual income tax return in February?','[\"The taxpayer must specify that the withdrawal be made on or before the return due date.\",\"The taxpayer must specify that the withdrawal be made when the tax return is being filed.\",\"The taxpayer must specify that the withdrawal be made within 15 days of the tax return filing.\",\"The taxpayer must specify that the withdrawal be made within 45 days of the tax return filing.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, page 14, provides that taxpayers can e-file and, at the same time, authorize an electronic funds withdrawal (EFW). Taxpayers who choose this option must provide account numbers and routing transit numbers for qualified savings, checking, or share draft accounts to the Authorized e-file Provider.nnLikewise, taxpayers can schedule the payment for withdrawal on a future date. Scheduled payments must be effective on or before the return due date.nnFor example, the provider may transmit an individual income tax return in March and the taxpayer can specify that the withdrawal be made on any day on or before the return due date. The taxpayer does not have to remember to do anything at a later date. For returns transmitted after the due date, the payment date must be the same as the date the return is transmitted. Electronic funds withdrawal payments must be authorized at the time the balance due return or form is e-filed.nnPayments can be made by EFW for the following:nnCurrent-year Form 1040 series returnnForm 4868, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax ReturnnForm 2350, Application for Extension of Time to File U.S. Income Tax Return for U.S. Citizens and Resident Aliens Abroad Who Expect to Qualify for Special Tax TreatmentnForm 1040-ES, Estimated Tax for Individuals (Taxpayers can make up to four estimated tax payments at the time that the Form 1040 is electronically filed.)nProviders should be careful to ensure that all the information needed for the electronic funds withdrawal request is included with the return.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(71,2,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the EFTPS?','[\"Taxpayers can make a tax payment using EFTPS without enrolling in the system.\",\"Only tax preparers can make a tax payment using EFTPS without enrolling in the system.\",\"Taxpayers can make a tax payment using EFTPS if they are enrolled in the system.\",\"Only tax preparers can make a tax payment using EFTPS if they are enrolled in the system.\"]',2,'Publication 966, page 2, provides that the Electronic Federal Tax Payment System (EFTPS) is a tax payment system provided free by the U.S. Department of the Treasury that enables business and individual taxpayers to make all their federal tax payments electronically, 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year, using the Internet or phone.nnWhen a taxpayer enrolls in EFTPS, the taxpayer will receive by mail a personal identification number (PIN) and instruction on obtaining an Internet password. After enrolling in the program, the taxpayer can select how he or she wants the payments to be made; that is, the taxpayer may choose to make his or her tax payment online or by phone (page 2).nnNotice the key word in the prior paragraph: “enrolls.” So, it is incorrect to say that taxpayers can use these methods if they do not enroll. Moreover, EFTPS is available to any business or individual taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(72,2,'When must the signature on an electronically filed individual tax return be signed?','[\"Any time\\u00a0after\\u00a0the electronic data portion of the return is submitted\",\"Within 24 hours\\u00a0after\\u00a0the electronic data portion of the return is submitted\",\"Before\\u00a0the electronic data portion of the return is submitted\",\"Before\\u00a0or within 24 hours after the electronic data portion of the return is submitted\"]',2,'As with an income tax return submitted to the IRS on paper, the taxpayer and paid preparer (if applicable) must sign an electronic income tax return. Taxpayers must sign individual income tax returns electronically. There are currently two methods for signing individual income tax returns electronically, as noted below.nnTaxpayers must sign and date the Declaration of Taxpayer to authorize the origination of the electronic submission of the return to the IRS prior to the transmission of the return to the IRS. The Declaration of Taxpayer includes the taxpayer\'s declaration under penalties of perjury that the return is true, correct, and complete, as well as the taxpayer\'s Consent to Disclosure. The Consent to Disclosure authorizes the IRS to disclose information to the taxpayer\'s Providers. Taxpayers authorize Intermediate Service Providers (ISPs), Transmitters, and Electronic Return Originators (EROs) to receive from the IRS an acknowledgement of receipt or reason for rejection of the electronic return, an indication of any refund offset, the reason for any delay in processing the return or refund, and the date of the refund.nnThere are two methods of signing individual income tax returns with an electronic signature available for use by taxpayers. Both methods allow taxpayers to use a personal identification number (PIN) to sign the return and the Declaration of Taxpayer. Self-select PIN is one of these methods. Practitioner PIN is the other method and it does not require the taxpayer to provide their prior-year AGI amount or prior-year PIN.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(73,2,'Gail files her return electronically. What responsibility does her Electronic Return Originator (ERO) have if the return is rejected?','[\"No responsibility once the return is filed\",\"Notify her if her return is rejected and results in a change of more than $25 total tax.\",\"Take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 10 calendar days.\",\"Provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation.\"]',3,'Publication 1345, page 26, provides that if the Internal Revenue Service rejects the electronic portion of a taxpayer\'s return for processing, and the reason for the rejection cannot be rectified, the ERO must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 24 hours.nnWhen the ERO advises the taxpayer that the return has not been filed, the ERO must provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation. If the taxpayer chooses not to have the electronic portion of the return corrected and transmitted to the Service or if it cannot be accepted for processing by the Service, the taxpayer must file a paper return.nnIn order to be filed timely, the paper return must be filed by the later of the due date of the return or 10 calendar days after the date the Service gives notification that the electronic portion of the return is rejected or that it cannot be accepted for processing. The paper return should include an explanation of why the return is being filed after the due date.nnThe ERO is obligated to notify Gail that her return is rejected regardless of the reason.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(74,2,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to rejected electronic return data?','[\"They can be corrected and retransmitted but new signatures or authorizations are required regardless of the change in amount.\",\"They can generally be corrected and retransmitted without new signatures or authorization if changes are not more than $50 to total income or AGI.\",\"They can generally be corrected and retransmitted without new signatures or authorization if changes are not more than $100 to total income or AGI.\",\"They can be corrected but they cannot be retransmitted; they must be submitted in paper form.\"]',1,'Publication 1345, page 26, states that rejected electronic return data can be corrected and retransmitted without new signatures or authorizations if changes are not more than $50 to “Total income” or “AGI” or more than $14 to “Total tax,” “Federal income tax withheld,” “Refund,” or “Amount you owe.”nnTaxpayers, however, must be given paper copies of the new electronic return data. If new signatures are required, the taxpayer must be given copies (either paper or electronic).nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBe aware that if federal electronic return data rejects due to errors, the state electronic return data also rejects. The converse is also true.nn',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(75,2,'Tunica Blake is an enrolled agent who participates in the Internal Revenue Service e-file Program as an Electronic Return Originator and Transmitter. Which of the following individual returns can be e-filed?','[\"Delinquent tax returns\",\"Amended tax returns (2018 and prior)\",\"Tax returns with fiscal-year tax periods\",\"None of the responses are eligible for e-filing.\"]',3,'Publication 1345, pages 6–7, provides, in part, that filing individual income tax returns using IRS e-file is limited to tax returns with prescribed due dates in the current and 2 previous tax years.nnThe following individual income tax returns and related return conditions cannot be processed using IRS e-file:nnTax returns with fiscal-year tax periodsnAmended tax returns (2018 and prior)nReturns containing forms or schedules that cannot be processed by IRS e-file other than those forms and schedules that are required to be submitted with Form 8453nTax returns with TINs (taxpayer identification numbers) within the range of 900-00-0000 through 999-99-9999, with a few exceptionsnTherefore, none of the responses (delinquent tax returns, amended tax returns, or tax returns with fiscal-year tax periods) are eligible for e-filing per Publication 1345.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(76,2,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the fee charged for an Electronic Return Originator (ERO)?','[\"An ERO may not charge a different fee for those who select direct deposits into their own accounts.\",\"An ERO may charge different fees for customers that are related to the amount of the refund or a Refund Anticipation Loan (RAL).\",\"EROs are permitted to base their fees on a percentage of the refund amount or compute their fees using any figure from tax returns.\",\"An ERO is allowed to accept a fee from a financial institution for any service connected with a Refund Anticipation Loan (RAL) that is contingent upon the amount of the refund or a RAL.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, page 13 provides that a provider is not allowed to charge a separate fee for a taxpayer using direct deposit.nnCircular 230, Section 10.27 provides that a practitioner may not charge an unconscionable fee in connection with any matter before the IRS. Moreover, a practitioner may not charge a contingent fee for services rendered in connection with any matter before the IRS.nnA contingent fee:nnIs any fee that is based, in whole or part, on whether or not a position taken on a tax return or other filing avoids challenge by the IRS or is sustained either by the IRS or in litigation; ornIncludes a fee that is based on a percentage of the refund reported on a return that is based on a percentage of the taxes saved, or that otherwise depends on the specific result attained.nThere are exceptions to charging a contingency fee. Specifically, a practitioner may charge a contingent fee for services rendered in connection with:nnThe Service\'s examination of, or challenge to:nAn original tax return; ornAn amended return or claim for refund or credit where the amended return or claim for refund or credit was filed within 120 days of the taxpayer receiving a written notice of the examination of, or a written challenge to the original tax return.nA claim for credit or refund filed solely in connection with the determination of statutory interest or penalties assessed by the IRSnAny judicial proceeding arising under the IRSnTherefore, the best response to this question is an ERO is not allowed to charge a different fee for those who select direct deposits into their own accounts.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(77,2,'Mandy files Maureen\'s 2024 tax return electronically. The return is rejected and the errors are corrected. As a result of the correction, Maureen owes an additional tax of $13. Which of the following statements are correct with respect to the signing and dating of the Declaration of Taxpayer on the refiling of the tax return?','[\"Rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted and must also include a newly signed Declaration of Taxpayer to authorize the origination of the electronic submission.\",\"Rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted without a newly signed Declaration of Taxpayer to authorize the origination of the electronic submission if changes do not differ from the amount on the original electronic return by more than $75 to \\u201cTotal income\\u201d or \\u201cAGI.\\u201d\",\"Rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted without a newly signed Declaration of Taxpayer to authorize the origination of the electronic submission if changes do not differ from the amount on the original electronic return by more than $14 to \\u201cTotal tax,\\u201d \\u201cFederal income tax withheld,\\u201d \\u201cRefund,\\u201d or \\u201cAmount you owe.\\u201d\",\"The taxpayer needs to sign a new declaration to authorize the origination of the electronic submission.\"]',2,'Publication 1345, page 26, provides that taxpayers must sign a new declaration if the electronic return data on individual income tax returns is changed after taxpayers signed the Declaration of Taxpayer and the amounts differ:nnby more than either $50 to “Total income” or “AGI,” ornby more than $14 to “Total tax,” “Federal income tax withheld,” “Refund,” or “Amount you owe.”nTherefore, Mandy can correct and retransmit Maureen’s tax return without a newly signed Declaration of Taxpayer to authorize the origination of the electronic submission because the tax error is less than $14.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(78,2,'Taxpayers often elect the direct deposit option because it is the fastest way of receiving refunds. The Electronic Return Originator should advise the taxpayer of the option to receive his/her refund by direct deposit or paper check. Select the statement below that is correct with respect to direct deposit.','[\"The Electronic Return Originator does not have to accept a direct deposit election to a financial institution designated by the taxpayer.\",\"Refunds may be direct deposited to credit card accounts.\",\"The Electronic Return Originator may make a separate charge of only $15, or less, as a processing fee if the taxpayer elects direct deposit.\",\"The Electronic Return Originator should caution taxpayers that some financial institutions do not permit the deposit of joint refunds into individual accounts.\"]',3,'When taxpayers are entitled to refunds, providers should inform taxpayers that they have several options:nnAn individual income tax refund may be:nnapplied to next year\'s estimated tax,nreceived as a direct deposit or paper check, ornbe split so that a portion is applied to next year\'s estimated tax and the rest received as a direct deposit or paper check.nTaxpayers often elect the Direct Deposit option because it is the fastest way of receiving refunds. Yet taxpayers should be cautioned that some financial institutions do not permit the deposit of joint individual income tax refunds into individual accounts. Furthermore, the IRS is not responsible if direct deposits are refused for this reason.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(79,2,'The Internal Revenue Service monitors and performs annual suitability checks on authorized Internal Revenue Service electronic filing providers for compliance with the revenue procedure and program requirements. Violations may result in a variety of sanctions. Which statement is correct with respect to sanctions the Internal Revenue Service may impose on an electronic filing provider?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service may issue a letter of reprimand or a 1-year suspension as a sanction for a Level One Infraction in the electronic filing program.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service may impose a period of suspension for 2 calendar years for a Level Two Infraction in the electronic filing program.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service may suspend or expel an authorized Internal Revenue Service electronic filing provider prior to administrative review for a Level Three Infraction in the electronic filing program.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service may not impose a sanction that is greater than a 1-year suspension from the electronic filing program.\"]',2,'Violations of IRS e-file requirements may result in warning or sanctioning Principals, Responsible Officials, and the Authorized IRS e-file Provider (Provider). The IRS may sanction any Provider when the firm or any of its Principals or Responsible Officials fails to comply with any requirement or any provision of IRS Publication 3112 (IRS e-file Application and Participation), as well as other publications and notices that govern IRS e-file. The IRS may also sanction for the same reasons that it denies an application to participate in IRS e-file. (See the \"Denial to Participate in IRS e-file\" page on the IRS website (www.irs.gov).) Before sanctioning, the IRS may issue a warning letter that describes specific corrective action the Provider must take. The IRS may also sanction without issuance of a warning letter.nnSanctioning may be a written reprimand, suspension, or expulsion from participation from IRS e-file, or other sanctions, depending on the seriousness of the infraction. The IRS categorizes the seriousness of infractions as Level One, Level Two, and Level Three. The Provider, Principal, or Responsible Official may appeal sanctions through the Administrative Review Process. Suspended Providers and individuals are usually ineligible to participate in IRS e-file for a period of either 1 or 2 years from the effective date of the sanction, but they may reapply after resolution of suitability issues. Individuals of firms expelled from participation may be eligible for reconsideration after a 5-year waiting period.nnIn most circumstances, a sanction is effective 30 days after the date of the letter informing of the sanction or the date the reviewing offices or the Office of Appeals affirms the sanction, whichever is later. In certain circumstances, the IRS can immediately suspend or expel a Provider, Principal, or Responsible Official without warning or notice. If a Provider, Principal, or Responsible Official is suspended or expelled from participation in IRS e-file, every related entity, including those that listed the suspended or expelled Principal or Responsible Official on its IRS e-file Application, may also be suspended or expelled.nnLevel One Infractions are violations of IRS e-file rules and requirements that, in the opinion of the IRS, have little or no adverse impact on the quality of electronically filed returns or on IRS e-file. The IRS may issue a written reprimand for a Level One Infraction.nnLevel Two Infractions are violations of IRS e-file rules and requirements that, in the opinion of the IRS, have an adverse impact upon the quality of electronically filed returns or on IRS e-file. Level Two Infractions include continued Level One Infractions after the IRS has brought the Level One Infraction to the attention of the Authorized IRS e-file Provider. Depending on the infractions, the IRS may either restrict participation in IRS e-file or suspend the Authorized IRS e-file Provider from participation in IRS e-file for a period of 1 year beginning with the effective date of suspension.nnLevel Three Infractions are violations of IRS e-file rules and requirements that, in the opinion of the IRS, have a significant adverse impact on the quality of electronically filed returns or on IRS e-file. Level Three Infractions include continued Level Two Infractions after the IRS has brought the Level Two Infraction to the attention of the Authorized IRS e-file Provider. A Level Three Infraction may result in suspension from participation in IRS e-file for 2 years beginning with the effective date of the suspension year. Depending on the severity of the infraction, such as fraud or criminal conduct, a Level Three Infraction may result in expulsion without the opportunity for future participation. The IRS reserves the right to suspend or expel an Authorized IRS e-file Provider prior to administrative review for Level Three Infractions.nnGiven the above, the only correct statement is, “The Internal Revenue Service may suspend or expel an authorized Internal Revenue Service electronic filing provider prior to administrative review for a Level Three Infraction in the electronic filing program.”',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(80,2,'What must the ERO, at the request of the taxpayer, provide?','[\"The Submission ID\",\"The date the electronic return data was accepted by the IRS\",\"The electronic postmark if one was provided by the Transmitter\",\"All of the answer choices are required to be supplied if requested.\"]',3,'Publication 1345, pages 25–26, provides that the ERO (Electronic Return Originator) must, at the request of the taxpayer, provide the Submission ID and the date the electronic return data was accepted by the IRS. Form 9325, Acknowledgment and General Information for Taxpayers Who File Returns Electronically, may be used for this purpose.nnThe ERO must also, if requested, supply the electronic postmark if one was provided by the Transmitter.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(81,2,'Which of the following must all authorized IRS e-file Providers adhere to in order to continue participating in the IRS e-file program?','[\"Revenue Procedure 2005-60\",\"Revenue Procedure 2007-40\",\"Revenue Procedure 2011-40\",\"Revenue Procedure 2012-30\"]',1,'Publication 1345, pages 36–37, provides that Authorized IRS e-file Providers (Providers) must adhere to applicable IRS e-file rules and requirements to continue participation in IRS e-file. The IRS e-file rules and requirements are included in Revenue Procedure 2007-40, throughout Publication 3112 (IRS e-file Application and Participation), and in other IRS e-file publications and notices on the IRS website.nnAll Providers must adhere to all rules and requirements, regardless of where published. Some rules and requirements are specific to the activities performed by the Provider and are included in appropriate chapters of Publication 1345. The following list, while not all inclusive, applies to all Providers of individual income tax returns, except software developers that do not engage in any other IRS e-file activity other than software development. A Provider must:nnmaintain an acceptable cumulative error or reject rate.nadhere to the requirements for ensuring that tax returns are properly signed.nproperly use the standard/nonstandard Form W-2 indicator.nproperly use the Refund Anticipation Loan (RAL) indicator.ninclude the Electronic Return Originator’s (ERO’s) Electronic Filing Identification Number (EFIN) as the return EFIN for returns the ERO submits to an Intermediate Service Provider or Transmitter.ninclude the Intermediate Service Provider’s EFIN in the designated Intermediate Service Provider field in the electronic return record.nsubmit an electronic return to the IRS with information that is identical to the information provided to the taxpayer on the copy of the return.nAs an aside:nnRevenue Procedure 2007-40 informs Authorized IRS e-file Providers of their obligations to the IRS, taxpayers, and other participants in the IRS e-file Program. It supersedes Revenue Procedure 2005-60 and has not been superseded.nRevenue Procedure 2011-40 provides the specifications for e-filing 2011 tax forms; it was superseded by Revenue Procedure 2012-30.nRevenue Procedure 2012-30 provides the specifications for e-filing 2012 tax forms; it has not been superseded. Hence, it provides the most recently published specifications for electronic filing of Forms 1042-S, 1097, 1098, 1099, 3921, 3922, 5498, 8027, 8935, 8955-SSA, and W-2G through the IRS FIRE (Filing Information Returns Electronically) system (supersedes Revenue Procedure 2011-40).nProviders should familiarize themselves with these revenue procedures, the e-file publications, and e-file information on the IRS website (www.IRS.gov) to ensure compliance with requirements for participation in IRS e-file. Therefore, the correct response for this question is that all providers must adhere to Revenue Procedure 2007-40 to continue participating in the IRS e-file program.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(82,2,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the Direct Deposit option?','[\"Taxpayers have been hesitant to elect the Direct Deposit option because it is the slowest way of receiving refunds.\",\"The Electronic Return Originator (ERO) must accept any direct deposit election to any eligible financial institution designated by the taxpayer.\",\"Refunds may be designated for direct deposit to any individual\'s account (not just the taxpayer).\",\"Refunds may be designated for direct deposit to credit card accounts.\"]',1,'As provided on pages 12 and 13 of Publication 1345, taxpayers often elect the Direct Deposit option because it is the fastest way of receiving refunds. Providers must accept any direct deposit election to any eligible financial institution designated by the taxpayer. Refunds may be designated for direct deposit to qualified accounts in the taxpayer\'s name. Qualified accounts include savings, checking, share draft, or consumer asset accounts (for example, IRA or money market accounts).nnRefunds, however, may not be designated for direct deposit to an account that is not in the taxpayer\'s own name or credit card accounts. Qualified accounts must be held by financial institutions within the United States and established primarily for personal, family, or household purposes. Qualifying institutions may be national banks, state banks (including the District of Columbia and political subdivisions of the 50 states), savings and loan associations, mutual savings banks, and credit unions.nnHence, the Electronic Return Originator (ERO) must accept any direct deposit election to any eligible financial institution designated by the taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(83,2,'Vivian Blake is an enrolled agent who participates in the Internal Revenue Service e-file Program as an Electronic Return Originator and Transmitter. Fred Birch has not filed his Form 1040 for tax years 2015 and 2016. Fred hires Vivian in March 2024 to prepare and file the delinquent returns. Which of the following statements about the delinquent returns is correct?','[\"Vivian will be able to electronically file the delinquent 2015 and 2016 returns after April 15, 2024, and before January 1, 2025.\",\"Vivian will be able to electronically file the delinquent 2015 and 2016 returns after April 15, 2024, and before October 15, 2024.\",\"Vivian will be able to electronically file the delinquent 2015 and 2016 returns as long as it is before April 15, 2024.\",\"Vivian will\\u00a0not\\u00a0be able to electronically file the delinquent 2015 and 2016 returns.\"]',3,'Publication 1345, pages 9–10, provides, in part, that filing individual income tax returns using IRS e-file is limited to tax returns with prescribed due dates in the current and 2 previous tax years.nnThe following individual income tax returns and related return conditions cannot be processed using IRS e-file:nnTax returns with fiscal-year tax periodsnAmended tax returns (for individual returns for tax years 2018 and prior)nReturns containing forms or schedules that cannot be processed by IRS e-file other than those forms and schedules that are required to be submitted with Form 8453nTax returns with TINs (taxpayer identification numbers) within the range of 900-00-0000 through 999-99-9999, with a few exceptionsnTherefore, Vivian will not be able to electronically file the delinquent 2015 and 2016 returns because they are not current-year or the 2 previous tax years’ returns.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(84,2,'Which of the following tax returns can be filed electronically?','[\"Amended tax returns for periods prior to 2019\",\"Fiscal-year tax returns\",\"Current-year tax returns and 2 previous years\' tax returns\",\"Current-year tax returns only\"]',2,'Publication 1345, page 9, provides that filing individual income tax returns using IRS e-file is limited to tax returns with prescribed due dates in the current and previous 2 years. A taxpayer can electronically file an individual tax return all year except for a short cutover period at the end of the calendar year.nnPublication 1345, page 10, provides a list of returns that are not eligible for the e-file program of the IRS. The following is a list of some of the returns and return conditions that cannot be processed:nnTax returns with fiscal-year tax periodsnReturns containing forms or schedules that cannot be processed by IRS e-filenTax returns with Taxpayer Identification Numbers within the range of 900-00-0000 through 999-99-9999nHence, the current year’s and 2 previous years’ tax returns are the only returns listed that can be filed electronically. Starting with 2019, individual amended tax returns can be filed electronically.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(85,2,'Which of the following statements is correct regarding electronically filed returns?','[\"A return for a deceased taxpayer may not be electronically filed.\",\"U.S. Individual Income Tax Returns\\u00a0may not be electronically filed after April 15, 2024.\",\"For tax year 2024, current-year tax returns may be electronically filed.\",\"For tax year 2024, all electronically filed returns require a separate signature document to be submitted to the appropriate Internal Revenue Service Center.\"]',2,'Publication 1345, pages 6 and 7, provides the basic rule for e-filing. Specifically, filing a return through the IRS e-file Program is limited to tax returns with prescribed due dates in the current and 2 previous tax years. A taxpayer can electronically file an individual income tax return year-round except for a short cutover period at the end of the calendar year.nnPublication 1345, page 7, provides a list of returns that are not eligible for the IRS e-file Program. The following is a list of some of the returns and return conditions that cannot be processed by the IRS e-file Program:nnTax returns with fiscal-year tax periodsnReturns containing forms or schedules that cannot be processed by IRS e-filenTax returns with TINs (taxpayer identification numbers) within the range of 900-00-0000 through 999-99-9999. There are a few exceptions within this range.nThe IRS cannot electronically process tax returns with rare or unusual processing conditions or that exceed the specifications for returns allowable in IRS e-file.nHence, current-year tax returns may be electronically filed.nnTreasury Regulations Section 301.6011-3(a) provides that if a partnership with more than 100 partners is required to file a partnership return, the information required by the applicable forms and schedules must be filed electronically, unless a waiver from the electronic filing requirement has been granted. Returns filed electronically must be prepared in accordance with applicable revenue procedures or publications. nnBe aware that certain partnerships with more than 100 partners are required to file Form 1065, Schedules K-1, and related forms and schedules electronically. Other partnerships generally have the option to file electronically (Form 1065 Instructions, page 4) and estate and trust returns may be able to file Form 1041 and related schedules electronically.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(86,2,'Which of the following is incorrect concerning an Electronic Return Originator (ERO)?','[\"An ERO may charge a separate fee for direct deposit.\",\"An ERO must accept any direct deposit election by a taxpayer to any eligible financial institution.\",\"An ERO should advise the taxpayer that a direct deposit election cannot be rescinded.\",\"An ERO should advise the taxpayer that changes cannot be made to routing numbers of financial institutions or to the taxpayer\'s account numbers.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, pages 12 and 13 provides that Electronic Return Originators (EROs) should advise taxpayers of the option to receive their refund by direct deposit or paper check, or be split so that a portion is applied to next year\'s estimated tax and the rest received as a direct deposit or paper check.nnPublication 1345, page 13, further provides that an ERO must advise taxpayers that they cannot rescind a Direct Deposit election and they cannot make changes to routing transit numbers of financial institutions or to their account numbers after the IRS has accepted the return. Providers must not alter the Direct Deposit information in the electronic record after taxpayers have signed the tax return.nnProviders must never charge a separate fee for Direct Deposit.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(87,2,'Which of the following is correct about an ERO (Electronic Return Originator)?','[\"They may originate the electronic submission of income tax returns they prepared but\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0electronically submit returns collected from taxpayers.\",\"They may originate the electronic submission of income tax returns they prepared or returns collected from taxpayers.\",\"They may originate the electronic submission of returns collected from taxpayers but\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0electronically submit income tax returns they prepared.\",\"They may\\u00a0not\\u00a0originate the electronic submission of income tax returns they prepared or returns collected from taxpayers.\"]',1,'According to Publication 1345, an ERO (Electronic Return Originator) originates the electronic submission of either income tax returns they prepared or returns collected from taxpayers who want to e-file their returns.nnAn ERO originates the electronic submission of a return after the taxpayer authorizes the filing of the return via IRS e-file. The ERO must have either prepared the return or collected it from a taxpayer. An ERO originates the electronic submission by:nnelectronically sending the return to a Transmitter that transmits the return to the IRS,ndirectly transmitting the return to the IRS, ornproviding a return to an Intermediate Service Provider for processing prior to transmission to the IRS.nThe ERO must always identify the paid preparer (if any) in the appropriate field of the electronic record of returns it originates. EROs may either transmit returns directly to the IRS or arrange with another e-file Provider to transmit the electronic return to the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(88,2,'Jenny files Lester\'s 2024 tax return electronically. The return is rejected, and the errors are corrected. As a result of the correction, Lester owes an additional tax of $12. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to the refiling of the tax return?','[\"Rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted, but only with new electronic signatures in all cases.\",\"Rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted without new signatures if changes do not differ from the amount on the original electronic return by more than $150 to \\u201cTotal income\\u201d or \\u201cAGI.\\u201d\",\"Rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted without new signatures or authorizations if changes do not differ from the amount on the original electronic return by more than $14 to \\\"Total tax,\\\" \\\"Federal income tax withheld,\\\" \\\"Refund,\\\" or \\\"Amount you owe.\\\"\",\"The ERO does not need to give the taxpayer copies of the new electronic return data.\"]',2,'Publication 1345, page 26, provides that rejected electronic individual income tax return data can be corrected and retransmitted without new signatures or authorizations if changes do not differ from the amount on the original electronic return:nnby more than $50 (not $150) to \"Total income\" or \"AGI,\" ornby more than $14 to \"Total tax,\" \"Federal income tax withheld,\" \"Refund,\" or \"Amount you owe.\"nIn addition, the Electronic Return Originator (ERO) must give taxpayers copies of the new electronic return data.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(89,2,'Which of the following is correct if an authorized Internal Revenue Service electronic filing provider uses radio, television, Internet, signage, or other methods of communication to advertise Internal Revenue Service electronic filing?','[\"The provider must keep a copy and provide the text to the Internal Revenue Service upon request.\",\"The provider is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to keep the recorded advertisement, if it is prerecorded.\",\"The provider must keep a copy and provide the text to the Internal Revenue Service upon request and, if prerecorded, the recorded advertisement.\",\"The provider is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to keep a copy of the text or, if prerecorded, the recorded advertisement.\"]',2,'“IRS e-file” is a brand name. Firms accepted for participation in IRS e-file as EROs, Transmitters, Intermediate Service Providers, Reporting Agents and Software Developers are “Authorized IRS e-file Providers.” Acceptance to participate in IRS e-file does not imply endorsement of the software or quality of services provided by the IRS, Financial Management Service, or Treasury. All Providers must abide by the following advertising standards. (Publication 3112, page 17)nnAn Authorized IRS e-file Provider must comply with the advertising and solicitation provisions of 31 CFR Part 10 (Treasury Department Circular 230). This circular prohibits the use or participation in the use of any form of public communication containing a false, fraudulent, misleading, deceptive, unduly influencing, coercive, or unfair statement or claim. Additionally, a Provider must adhere to all relevant federal, state, and local consumer protection laws that relate to advertising and soliciting. (Publication 3112, page 17)nnSpecific to this question, if an Authorized IRS e-file Provider uses radio, television, Internet, signage, or other methods of communication to advertise IRS e-file, the Provider must keep a copy of the text or, if prerecorded, the recorded advertisement. A Provider must retain copies until the end of the calendar year following the last transmission or use (Publication 3112, page 18).',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(90,2,'Which of the following is a taxpayer\'s responsibility when filing Form 8879?','[\"To verify the accuracy of the prepared income tax return, including direct deposit information\",\"To check the appropriate box in Part II of the form to authorize the ERO to enter the taxpayer\'s PIN\",\"To return the completed Form 8879 to the ERO by hand delivery, U.S. mail, private delivery service, or fax\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'As provided on page 2 of Form 8879, IRS e-file Signature Authorization, the taxpayer has the responsibility to do all of the following when filing Form 8879:nnVerify the accuracy of the prepared income tax return, including direct deposit informationnCheck the appropriate box in Part II of Form 8879 to authorize the Electronic Return Originator (ERO) to enter or generate the taxpayer\'s PIN (personal identification number) or to do it themselvesnIndicate or verify the taxpayer\'s PIN (five numbers other than all zeros) when authorizing the ERO to enter or generate itnSign and date Form 8879, and the taxpayer must sign Form 8879 by handwritten signaturenReturn the completed Form 8879 to the ERO by hand delivery, U.S. mail, private delivery service, fax, e-mail, or an Internet websitenThe ERO must notify the taxpayer that their return will not be transmitted to the IRS until the ERO receives the signed Form 8879.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(91,2,'What action must an ERO take if the Internal Revenue Service rejects the electronic portion of a taxpayer\'s return for processing and the reason for the rejection cannot be rectified with the information already provided to the ERO?','[\"The ERO must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 48 hours.\",\"The ERO must provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation.\",\"The ERO must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 48 hours and provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation.\",\"\\n\\nNone of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 1345, page 26, provides that if the Service rejects the electronic portion of a taxpayer\'s return for processing and the reason for the rejection cannot be rectified, the Electronic Return Originator (ERO) must take reasonable steps to inform the taxpayer of the rejection within 24 hours.nnWhen the ERO advises the taxpayer that the return has not been filed, the ERO must provide the taxpayer with the reject code(s) accompanied by an explanation. If the taxpayer chooses not to have the electronic portion of the return corrected and transmitted to the Service or if it cannot be accepted for processing by the Service, the taxpayer must file a paper return.nnIn order to be filed timely, the paper return must be filed by the later of the due date of the return or 10 calendar days after the date the Service gives notification that the electronic portion of the return is rejected or that it cannot be accepted for processing. The paper return should include an explanation of why the return is being filed after the due date.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(92,2,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a Refund Anticipation Loan (RAL)?','[\"It is money borrowed by a taxpayer from a lender based on the taxpayer\'s anticipated income tax refund.\",\"The IRS is involved and responsible for the Refund Anticipation Loan.\",\"It is money borrowed by a taxpayer from a lender based on the taxpayer\'s anticipated income tax refund, and the IRS is involved and responsible for the Refund Anticipation Loan.\",\"It is money borrowed by a taxpayer from the government based on the taxpayer\'s anticipated income tax refund, and the IRS is involved and responsible for the Refund Anticipation Loan.\"]',0,'Publication 1345, pages 38–39, states that a tax refund-related product (aka, Refund Anticipation Loan (RAL)) is money borrowed by a taxpayer from a lender based on the taxpayer\'s anticipated income tax refund. Financial institutions also offer a variety of other financial products to taxpayers based on their refunds. The IRS is in no way involved in or responsible for RALs.nnAuthorized IRS e-file Providers that assist taxpayers in applying for a RAL or other tax refund-related product have additional responsibilities and may be sanctioned by the IRS if they failed to adhere to the below requirements. Specifically, the e-file Provider must:nnensure taxpayers understand that by agreeing to a RAL or other financial product, they will not receive their refund from the IRS, as the IRS will send their refund to the financial institution;nadvise taxpayers that RALs are interest-bearing loans and not a quicker way of receiving their refunds from the IRS;nadvise taxpayers that if a direct deposit is not received within the expected time frame for whatever reason, the taxpayers may be liable to the lender for additional interest and other fees, as applicable for the RAL or other financial product;nadvise taxpayers of all fees and other known deductions to be paid from their refund and the remaining amount the taxpayers will actually receive;nsecure the taxpayer\'s written consent as specified in Regulation Section 301.7216-3(a) to disclose tax information to the lending financial institution in connection with an application for a RAL or other financial product;nensure that, if it is also the return preparer, that it is not a related taxpayer to the financial institution or other lender that makes a RAL or other financial product agreement within the meaning of Section 267 or 707A; andnadhere to the fee restrictions and advertising standards described in Publication 1345.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(93,2,'A Form 1065, U.S. Return of Partnership Income, must be filed electronically if the number of partners exceeds:','[50,75,100,250]',2,'Treasury Regulations Section 301.6011-3(a) provides that if a partnership with more than 100 partners is required to file a partnership return, the information required by the applicable forms and schedules must be filed electronically, unless a waiver from the electronic filing requirement has been granted. Returns filed electronically must be prepared in accordance with applicable revenue procedures or publications.n',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(94,2,'Who can enroll and use EFTPS?','[\"Only individual taxpayers\",\"Only business taxpayers\",\"Any individual or business taxpayer\",\"Only authorized tax preparers\"]',2,'The Electronic Federal Tax Payment System (EFTPS) is a tax payment system provided free by the U.S. Department of the Treasury, for use by any business taxpayer or individual taxpayer.nnA taxpayer may enroll online. (See the About EFTPS/General page or the FAQ page at www.eftps.gov.)',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(95,2,'Taxpayers who have their returns filed electronically may elect to pay any taxes owed on their tax returns by which of the following?nn1. Electronic Funds Withdrawaln2. Credit or Debit Card Paymentsn3. Pay by checkn4. Installment Agreement Requests','[\"2 or 3 only\",\"1, 2, or 3 only\",\"2, 3, or 4 only\",\"1, 2, 3, or 4\"]',3,'Taxpayers who owe additional tax must pay their balances due by the original due date of the return or be subject to interest and penalties. An extension of time to file may be filed electronically by the original return due date, but it is an extension of time to file the return, not an extension of time to pay a balance due. Providers should inform taxpayers of their obligations and options for paying balances due.nnWhen submitting their returns electronically, the taxpayers have the option of having their balance due withdrawn by providing their banking information (electronic funds withdrawal). The taxpayer’s payment submission thus occurs at the same time as the tax return filing. However, sometimes taxpayers prefer having control of the payment process as opposed to relying on the payment to happen automatically. In this case, they have several other choices for paying any taxes owed, such as: IRS Direct Pay, Credit Card/Debit Card Payment, EFTPS, cash, check, money order, or installment agreement.nnTherefore, all statements in the above question are correct options for payment of taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19'),(96,2,'Mr. Jones is filing his 2022 return in the year 2024. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Mr. Jones cannot file this return electronically with the IRS if it is an amended return.\",\"Mr. Jones can file this return electronically with the IRS if it is a fiscal-year return.\",\"Mr. Jones cannot file this return electronically with the IRS if it is a return for a decedent.\",\"Mr. Jones can file this return electronically with the IRS.\"]',3,'Publication 1345, pages 6–7, provides that filing individual income tax returns using IRS e-file is limited to tax returns with prescribed due dates in the current (2024) and 2 previous tax years (2022 and 2023). In addition, the following is a list of some of the returns and return conditions that cannot be processed by the IRS e-file Program:nnTax returns with fiscal-year tax periodsnReturns containing forms or schedules that cannot be processed by the IRS e-filenTax returns with Taxpayer Identification Numbers (TIN) within the range of 900-00-0000 through 999-99-9999.nHence, Mr. Jones can e-file his 2022 return (due by April 15) in 2024 because it is within 2 two previous tax years\' windows.',1,'2026-04-23 02:34:19','2026-04-23 02:34:19');
