INSERT INTO `tbl_unit_questions` VALUES (1,2,'Don and Joyce have adjusted gross income of $85,000. Both children (Mary, age 14, and David, age 20, who completed his education in the prior year) lived with them all year. Mary had interest income of $300. David had interest income of $600 and wages of $6,500. The parents provided over 50% of the support of both children. How many dependents, not including Don and Joyce, would they list on their Form 1040 as dependents?n','[1,4,3,2]',0,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits. Therefore, the following rules are provided:nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nTo be a qualifying child, the individual must be under age 19 (24 if a full-time student) and must satisfy both tests 2 and 4 above. In addition, a qualifying child is exempt from all of the above tests except the gross income test. But, be aware there are a number of exceptions to the above tests for a qualifying child as provided in Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17.nnIf a person is a qualifying relative or a qualifying child, the person still must satisfy three additional tests as provided on pages 26 and 27 of Publication 17:nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnThe exemption and dependency rules are covered in chapter 3 of Publication 17.nnIn this case, one dependent would be listed on Don and Joyce\'s Form 1040. Their daughter (Mary, age 14) qualifies as a dependent (meets the qualifying child test). David, on the other hand, does not qualify under qualifying child (he is 20 and not a full-time student). He can still qualify as a qualifying relative (no age test), but his gross income of $7,100 ($600 + $6,500) exceeds the gross income test limit of $5,050 for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(2,2,'Which of the following is the green card test?','[\"Whether or not a taxpayer is a U.S. citizen at any time during calendar year 2024\",\"Whether or not a taxpayer is a lawful permanent resident of the United States at any time during calendar year 2024\",\"Whether or not income tax returns are filed using Certified Mail Return Receipt Requested (the green cards at the U.S. Post Office)\",\"None of the answer choices describe the green card test.\"]',1,'A person is a resident alien of the United States for tax purposes if they meet either the green card test or the substantial presence test for the calendar year. Even if the person does not meet either test, they may be able to choose to be treated as a U.S. resident for part of the year.nnA person is a resident for tax purposes if they are a lawful permanent resident of the United States at any time during the calendar year. This is known as the “green card” test per page 4 of Publication 519. A taxpayer is a lawful permanent resident of the United States at any time if they have been given the privilege, according to the immigration laws, of residing permanently in the United States as an immigrant. A taxpayer has this status if the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) (or its predecessor organization) has issued the taxpayer an alien registration card, also known as a “green card.”nnPer page 11 of Publication 519, a resident alien’s income is generally subject to tax in the same manner as a U.S. citizen. Resident aliens must report all income from sources within and outside the United States. A nonresident alien usually is subject to U.S. income tax only on U.S. source income.nnIn this case, whether or not a taxpayer is a lawful permanent resident of the United States at any time during calendar year 2024 is the green card test. Mailing income tax returns to the Internal Revenue Service using the Certified Mail Return Receipt Requested at the U.S. Post Office is a good idea to prove timely filing and receipt of the income tax returns, but it is not the green card test.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(3,2,'Mr. and Mrs. Rose are both over 65. Their adjusted gross income is $100,000. During the year their 35-year-old single son, Tom, lived with them while attending college and earned $5,500. Mr. Rose\'s mother, Ivy, lived with them until June 1 when she was placed in a nursing home for an indefinite period to receive medical care. Ivy received no income and was supported solely by Mr. and Mrs. Rose. Determine the number of individuals (excluding themselves) that Mr. and Mrs. Rose can list on their Form 1040 as dependents on their 2024 joint return.','[\"None\",4,1,2]',2,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits. Therefore, the following rules are provided.nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see page 27 (Table 3-1) of Publication 17):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nTo be a qualifying child, the child must be under age 19 (24 if a full-time student) and must satisfy both tests 2 and 4 above. In addition, a qualifying child is exempt from all of the above tests except the gross income test, but be aware there are a number of exceptions to the above tests for a qualifying child as provided in Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17.nnThe dependency rules are covered in chapter 3 of Publication 17.nnIn this case, only Mr. Rose\'s mother, who is totally supported by the couple can be listed on the taxpayer\'s tax return. Mr. Rose\'s mother is one of the relatives that does not need to live with the taxpayer to satisfy the relationship test. Hence, she qualifies as a dependent.nnAlthough Tom is a student, he does not qualify as a dependent under the qualifying child rules (age limit is exceeded). However, he may still qualify as a qualified relative. Since his gross income of $4,500 exceeds the gross income test limit of $5,050, he does not meet the requirements for a qualified relative either. Hence, he cannot be claimed as a dependent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(4,2,'Milton is 39 years old. He has been divorced from his wife since March 1 of the tax year. They have two minor children. One child lives with Milton, and the other child lives with the mother. The children have been with their respective parents from March through December of the tax year. Milton provides all of the support for the minor child living with him. The filing status with the lowest rate that Milton qualifies for is:','[\"head of household.\",\"married filing separately.\",\"married filing jointly.\",\"single.\"]',0,'Milton will qualify as head of household because he satisfies all of the requirements (as given on page 24 of Publication 17):nnunmarried or considered unmarried (generally, the taxpayer’s spouse did not live in the taxpayer’s home during the last 6 months of the tax year) on the last day of the year,npaid more than half the cost of keeping up a home for the year, andna qualifying person lived with the taxpayer in the home for more than half the year (except for temporary absences, such as school).nThere is another exception to the third requirement; a taxpayer\'s dependent parents do not need to live with the taxpayer. Of course, this exception is not relevant to this problem.nnA taxpayer is considered unmarried if they satisfy all five tests given on page 24, which are:nnfile a separate return,npaid more than half the cost of keeping up the taxpayer\'s home for the tax year,nthe taxpayer\'s spouse did not live in the taxpayer\'s home during the last 6 months of the tax year,nthe taxpayer\'s home is the main home for the taxpayer\'s child, stepchild, or foster child for more than half the year, andnthe taxpayer must be able to claim an exemption for the child. (However, the taxpayer meets this test if they cannot claim the exemption only because the noncustodial parent can claim the child.)nSince Milton is considered unmarried at year-end (i.e., divorced), has one child living with him, and paid more than half of the cost of keeping up a home for the year, he has satisfied all three conditions for claiming head of household filing status.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(5,2,'Joe is 37 years old. His wife died during the tax year, and he has not remarried. His deceased wife had no income. He has two minor children living with him. Joe paid all of the costs for keeping up his home for the tax year, and he has paid for all of the support of his wife and these children. The filing status with the lowest tax rate that Joe qualifies for is:','[\"married filing jointly.\",\"head of household.\",\"qualifying surviving spouse.\",\"married filing separately.\"]',0,'Publication 17, pages 22–23, states, in part, that a taxpayer is considered married for the whole year if, on the last day of the taxpayer\'s tax year, the taxpayer and the taxpayer\'s spouse meet any one of the following four tests:nnmarried and living together,nliving together in a common-law marriage that is recognized in the state where the taxpayer now lives or in the state where the common-law marriage began,nmarried and living apart, but not legally separated under a decree of divorce or separate maintenance, ornseparated under an interlocutory (not final) decree of divorce.nIn the case where a spouse died during the year, the taxpayer is considered married for the whole year for filing status purposes.nnHence, Joe is able to file as married filing jointly since his wife died in the current tax year.nnIt should also be mentioned that Joe will likely be able to claim qualifying surviving spouse status for the 2 years following his wife\'s death unless he remarries during either of those years.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(6,2,'Charles Moore had a $2,000 tax liability in 2023. In 2024, Charles expects to owe at least $1,500 in federal taxes. For 2024, he has not withheld income taxes. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Charles must pay estimated taxes because his withholdings are smaller than 100% of his expected tax in 2024.\",\"Charles does\\u00a0not\\u00a0need to pay estimated taxes because his tax in 2024 is less than his 2023 tax.\",\"Charles must pay estimated taxes because his withholdings are smaller than 90% of his tax in 2023.\",\"Charles must pay estimated taxes because his tax in 2024 is greater than $1,000.\"]',3,'In general, a taxpayer must pay estimated tax if both of the following apply:nnThe taxpayer expects to owe at least $1,000 in tax for 2024 after subtracting his or her withholdings and refundable credits.nThe taxpayer expects his or her withholdings and credits to be less than the smaller of 90% of the tax to be shown on the 2024 tax return or 100% of the tax shown on the 2023 tax return. Moreover, the 2023 tax return must cover all 12 months.nIn this case, Charles satisfies both tests. He expects to owe $1,500, which is greater than $1,000. In addition, his withholdings of $0 are less than the smaller of $1,350 (90% of $1,500, which is the expected tax for 2024) or $2,000, which is 100% of his 2023 tax liability.nnSee Publication 17, pages 41–42, for a discussion on who does and does not need to pay estimated taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(7,2,'Which of the following filing statuses is correct if you did not live with your spouse at any time during the year and you file a separate return (being legally separated) for determining the deduction phaseout for a traditional IRA?','[\"Single\",\"Married filing separate\",\"Married filing jointly\",\"Head of household\"]',0,'Publication 590-A, page 13, provides, in part, that a taxpayer\'s filing status depends primarily on his or her marital status. For this purpose, a taxpayer needs to know if his or her filing status is single or head of household, married filing jointly or qualifying surviving spouse, or married filing separately.nnPublication 590-A, Table 1-2, footnote 2, page 13 provides that if a taxpayer does not live with his or her spouse at any time during the year and the taxpayer is qualified to file a separate return, the taxpayer\'s filing status, for this purpose, is single.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nIf you have a same-gender spouse whom you legally married in a state (or foreign country), you and your spouse must use the married filing jointly or married filing separately filing status on your 2024 return.nn n nnFor more information on taxpayer\'s filing status, see pages 21 through 26 in Publication 17.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(8,2,'Which one of the following criteria is used to determine a taxpayer\'s “tax home,” if the taxpayer does not have a regular or main place of business or work?','[\"The taxpayer performs part of his business in the area surrounding his main home and uses that home for lodging while doing business in the area.\",\"The taxpayer has living expenses at his main home that are duplicated because his business requires him to be away from that home.\",\"The taxpayer has not abandoned the area in which both his traditional place of lodging and his main home are located; members of his family live at his main home; or he often uses that home for lodging.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'There are three factors that are stipulated in Publication 463, pages 4 and 5, that are used to determine the person\'s tax home if the taxpayer does not have a regular or main place of business or work:nnThe taxpayer performs part of his or her business in the area of his or her main home and uses that home for lodging while doing business in the area.nThe taxpayer has living expenses at his or her main home that the taxpayer duplicates because the taxpayer\'s business requires the taxpayer to be away from that home.nThe taxpayer has not abandoned the area in which both the taxpayer\'s historical place of lodging and claimed main home are located; the taxpayer has a member or members of his or her family living at the main home; or the taxpayer often uses that home for lodging.nIn this problem, all three responses correspond to the above listed factors.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(9,2,'Denise worked for 3 months in Russia and earned foreign income. Denise is a U.S. citizen and, except for the 3 months spent in Russia, resides in Mobile, Alabama. Denise did not receive either a Form W-2 or a Form 1099 for her earnings while in Russia. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Because Denise resides in the United States, is a U.S. citizen, and did not receive any tax reporting forms, she does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to report any of the income she earned in Russia.\",\"Because Denise did not receive any tax reporting forms, she does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to report any of the income she earned in Russia.\",\"Because Denise resides in the United States and did not receive any tax reporting forms, she does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to report any of the income she earned in Russia.\",\"Denise must report all of the income she earned in Russia even though she did not receive any tax reporting forms.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 3, provides that if a taxpayer is a U.S. citizen with income from sources outside the United States (foreign income), the taxpayer must report all such income on his or her tax return unless it is exempt by U.S. law.nnThis is true whether the taxpayer resides inside or outside the United States and whether or not the taxpayer receives a Form W-2 or Form 1099 from the foreign payer. This applies to earned income (such as wages and tips) as well as unearned income (such as interest, dividends, capital gains, pensions, rents, and royalties).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(10,2,'Brian is preparing his 2024 income tax return. He has gathered all of his records together for the current year, including a copy of the 2023 income tax return that he filed last year to assist with his preparation. While reviewing all of the forms he received for 2023 (i.e., Form W-2s and Form 1099s) he observes that his 2023 income tax return included dividends for ABC Corporation of $1,000 as reported on a 2023 Form 1099-DIV, but he does not have a 2024 Form 1099-DIV showing ABC Corporation dividends. Brian recalls that ABC Corporation has been paying an annual dividend for several years. Which of the following reasons could be why there is no Form 1099-DIV for ABC Corporation for 2024?','[\"Brian may have sold all of his shares in ABC Corporation in 2023 or 2024 after he was entitled to the 2023 dividend payment and before he was entitled to the 2024 dividend payment.\",\"ABC Corporation may not have paid a dividend for 2024.\",\"ABC Corporation may have paid a dividend in 2024 and the Form 1099-DIV is lost in the mail or the delivery has been delayed.\",\"All of the reasons listed could be why there is no Form 1099-DIV for ABC Corporation for 2024.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 12, Table 1-6, lists six steps for preparing a tax return. The first two steps advise the taxpayer to get records together for income and expenses and to get the forms, schedules, and publications that are needed. These steps should be done before the income tax return is filled in.nnIn this case, Brian has made a useful observation while preparing his income tax return for 2024 that may not have occurred if he had not reviewed his 2024 income tax return and his basic records. ABC Corporation may not have paid a dividend in 2024, may have paid a dividend but the Form 1099-DIV is missing, or Brian may have sold it before he was entitled to a dividend in 2023. All of these reasons are possible. Thus, Brian should look further into why he did not receive the Form 1099-DIV. He may need to report dividends for 2024 or a sale or exchange of ABC stock in 2024 so that he can render a complete and accurate income tax return (as noted in \"What Records Should I Keep?\" on page 18 of Publication 17).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(11,2,'Who would not be a qualifying person for purposes of filing as head of household in 2024?','[\"Your aunt, related to you by blood. She does not live with you but is your dependent.\",\"Your adopted child who lives with you, is married, and can be claimed as your dependent\",\"Your foster child who lived with you all year and is your dependent\",\"Your mother, whom you can claim as a dependent\"]',0,'For a person to be able to file as head of household, the taxpayer must meet all of the following requirements:nnBe unmarried or “considered unmarried” on the last day of the year,nPay more than half the cost of keeping up a home for the year, andnHave a “qualifying person” live with the taxpayer in the home for more than half the year (except for temporary absences, such as school).nDependent parents, however, are not required to live with the taxpayer.nnIn this case, the aunt is related by blood to and is a dependent of the taxpayer, but she does not live with the taxpayer and is not a parent; thus, she is not a qualifying person for filing as head of household.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(12,2,'George is preparing his income tax return for 2024 and believes that his itemized deductions will exceed his standard deduction. To what sources could George turn to see which deductions are applicable to him and how much he can deduct?','[\"Cash receipts\",\"Financial account statements, checkbooks, canceled checks, and substitute checks\",\"Credit card statements\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Taxpayers should itemize deductions if their total deductions are more than their standard deduction amount, as discussed on page 94 of Publication 17. Generally, a taxpayer may benefit from itemizing their deductions if they have such items as large uninsured medical and dental expenses, interest and taxes on their home, or large contributions to qualified charities.nnBasic records for taxpayers include proof of payment to substantiate itemized deductions (see page 18 of Publication 17). Generally, payment is proved with a cash receipt, financial account statement, credit card statement, canceled check, or substitute check. If payments are made in cash, a dated and signed receipt showing the amount and the reason for the payment should be obtained. If payments are made by electronic funds transfer, payment may be proved by an account statement. Information for itemized deductions may also be found on IRS forms such as Form 1098 or Form K-1 that are received by the taxpayer.nnSince all of the items listed in the answer choices can help George determine and substantiate his itemized deductions, all of these sources should be reviewed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(13,2,'Jill and John, married filing jointly, have provided more than 50% of the support for two minor children and Jill\'s mother. The children each had interest income of less than $1,000. Jill\'s mother received a taxable pension of $3,500, dividends of $1,500 and interest of $1,000. How many dependents can the taxpayers, excluding themselves, list on their 2024 tax return?','[\"None\",1,2,3]',2,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits. Therefore, the following rules are provided.nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nGross income is all income in the form of money, property, and services that is not exempt from tax. (Publication 17, page 7)nnTo be a qualifying child, the child must be under age 19 (24 if a full-time student) and must satisfy both tests 2 and 4 above. In addition, a qualifying child is exempt from all of the above tests except the gross income test, but be aware there are a number of exceptions to the above tests for a qualifying child as provided in Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17.nnIf a person is a qualifying relative or a qualifying child, the person still must satisfy three additional tests:nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnMore specifically, the gross income test generally will not allow a taxpayer to claim a dependent if that person had gross income of $5,050 or more for 2024. Given that Jill\'s mother\'s gross income ($6,000) is greater than the $5,050 limit (see Publication 17, page 27), Jill and John are unable to claim her as a dependent.nnGross income calculation for Jill\'s mother:nn  Pension:            $3,500n  Dividends:           1,500n  Interest:            1,000 n  Gross Income:       $6,000n  Limit               (5,050)n  Exceeds limit by    $  950nThus, the couple would only claim two dependents, one for each minor child.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(14,2,'Ted and Sharon (husband and wife) are the sole support of their 27-year-old son Tom, who lives with them. Tom was unable to work in 2024 because of a medical condition but received $5,500 from a charitable foundation for a speaking engagement. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to claiming Tom as a dependent on their tax return?','[\"Ted and Sharon may claim Tom as a dependent on their 2024 federal income tax return.\",\"Tom cannot be claimed as a dependent on his parents\' 2024 federal income tax return and will need to file his own return.\",\"Ted and Sharon may claim Tom as a dependent on their 2024 federal income tax return or Tom may claim an exemption for himself on his 2024 federal income tax return.\",\"Tom\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0be claimed by either himself or his parents.\"]',1,'A taxpayer can claim one dependent for each person that satisfies the qualifying child or qualifying relative tests. There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see pages 34–36 and Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nTo be a qualifying child, the child must be under age 19 (24 if a full-time student) and must satisfy both tests 2 and 4 above. In addition, a qualifying child is exempt from all of the above tests except the gross income test, but be aware there are a number of exceptions to the above tests for a qualifying child as provided in Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17.nnIf a person is a qualifying relative, he or she still must satisfy three additional tests (Publication 17, page 28):nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnIn this case, Tom is not a qualifying child because he is over the age of 19. He is not a qualified relative as his income of $5,500 exceeds the gross income test limit of $5,050 in 2024 (Publication 17, pages 29 and 34). Hence, he cannot be claimed as a dependent by Ted and Sharon. If Tom chooses to file, he will need to file his own return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(15,2,'John and Joanne are the sole support of the following individuals, all U.S. citizens, none of whom lives with them. None of these individuals files a joint return or has any gross income:nnJennie, John\'s mothernJulie, Joanne\'s stepmothernJonathan, father of John\'s first wifenHow many individuals, excluding John and Joanne, are listed on their tax return for 2024 as dependents?','[2,3,1,0]',1,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits (Publication 17, page 27). Therefore, the following rules are provided:nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see Table 3-1, Publication 17, page 28):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nIf a person is a qualifying relative or a qualifying child, the person must satisfy three additional tests (Publication 17, page 27) to claim an exemption for him or her:nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnThe exemption and dependency rules are covered in chapter 3 of Publication 17.nnAn exception exists to the Member of the Household rule. In particular, a person related to the taxpayer in any of the following ways does not have to live with the taxpayer for the entire year as a member of the taxpayer\'s household to meet this test (see Publication 17, page 34):nnChild, grandchild, great-grandchild, etc. (a legally adopted child is considered your child),nStepchild, foster child,nBrother, sister, half-brother, half-sister, stepbrother, or stepsister,nParent, grandparent, or other direct ancestor, but not foster parent,nStepfather or stepmother,nBrother or sister of the taxpayer\'s father or mother,nSon or daughter of the taxpayer\'s brother or sister, ornFather-in-law, mother-in-law, son-in-law, daughter-in-law, brother-in-law, or sister-in-law.nBetter yet, any of these relationships that were established by marriage are not ended by death or divorce.nnAs a result of the new tax, John and Joanne can claim three dependents on their return because the three individuals do not need to live with the taxpayer in order to be claimed as a dependent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(16,2,'Lisa was married with two dependent children in 2024. Her husband died in April and she did not remarry before the end of 2024. Which filing status should Lisa use for her tax return in 2024?','[\"Married filing jointly\",\"Qualifying surviving spouse\",\"Head of household\",\"Single\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 22, states, in part, that a taxpayer is considered married for the whole year if, on the last day of the taxpayer\'s tax year, the taxpayer and the taxpayer\'s spouse meet any one of the following tests:nnmarried and living together,nliving together in a common-law marriage that is recognized in the state where the taxpayer now lives or in the state where the common-law marriage began,nmarried and living apart, but not legally separated under a decree of divorce or separate maintenance, ornseparated under an interlocutory (not final) decree of divorce.nIn the case where a spouse died during the year, the taxpayer is considered married for the whole year for filing status purposes.nnHence, Lisa is able to file as married filing jointly since her husband died during the current tax year. It should be noted that although Lisa may qualify under another filing status, married filing jointly is the most favorable tax filing status. Hence, Lisa should elect it, and that is the question here.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(17,2,'What is the filing status of a taxpayer if their spouse died during the year?','[\"Qualifying surviving spouse\",\"Head of household\",\"Married filing jointly\",\"Single\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 22, states, in part, that a taxpayer is considered married for the whole year if, on the last day of the taxpayer\'s tax year, the taxpayer and the taxpayer\'s spouse meet any one of the following tests:nnmarried and living together,nliving together in a common-law marriage that is recognized in the state where the taxpayer now lives or in the state where the common-law marriage began,nmarried and living apart, but not legally separated under a decree of divorce or separate maintenance, ornseparated under an interlocutory (not final) decree of divorce.nIn the case where a spouse died during the year, the taxpayer is considered married for the whole year for filing status purposes. Hence, the taxpayer would have a filing status of married jointly.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(18,2,'John is the sole support of his mother. To claim her as a dependent on his Form 1040-SR for 2024, she must be a resident of which of the following countries for some part of calendar year 2024?','[\"Canada\",\"United States, Mexico, or Canada\",\"United States\",\"Mexico\"]',1,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits (Publication 17, page 27). Therefore, the following rules are provided:nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative (see Table 3-1, page 27, of Publication 17). There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative:nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nIf a person is a qualifying relative, the person still must satisfy three additional tests:nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnThe exemption and dependency rules are covered in chapter 3 of Publication 17.nnPublication 17, page 28, expands on the citizen or residency test by stating, in part, that a taxpayer cannot claim an exemption for a dependent unless that person is a U.S. citizen, U.S. resident alien, U.S. national, or resident of Canada or Mexico. There is an exception for certain adopted children, which is not relevant to this problem.nnIn this problem, John\'s mother can be a resident of any one of the three countries (United States, Mexico, or Canada) to qualify as his dependent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(19,2,'Which of the following is the correct deadline for a taxpayer to obtain an automatic extension of time to file an individual tax return for 2024?','[\"File Form 4868,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, by June 1, 2025.\",\"File Form 4868,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, by April 15, 2025.\",\"File Form 4868,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, by April 1, 2025.\",\"File Form 4868,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, by March 15, 2025.\"]',1,'According to Publication 17, page 11, an automatic 6-month extension can be obtained by filing Form 4868 in paper form or by e-file by the due date for filing the taxpayer\'s tax return (generally, April 15).nnForm 4868 can be filed by mail up through April 15 by mailing it to the address shown in the form instructions. An extension does not abate any interest that is accruing for underpaying a person\'s income tax by the filing date.nnAn extension also can be obtained by e-file by means of a person\'s personal computer or a tax professional providing certain information from the prior year’s tax form. An extension by e-file can be obtained by paying part or all of the taxpayer\'s estimated tax by use of a credit or debit card. The taxpayer can accomplish this by phone or over the Internet.nnFor more information on the ways to e-file Form 4868, see Publication 17, page 11.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(20,2,'All of the following are correct for Anthony, filing single, who has one household employee in 2024, except:','[\"He is required to attach Schedule H to his individual tax return if he pays $2,700 in wages to his employee.\",\"He may use his W-2 withholdings to offset the Schedule H tax liabilities.\",\"He is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to pay employment taxes on wages paid unless the wages are $2,900 or more.\",\"He may make estimated tax payments to offset the Schedule H tax liabilities.\"]',2,'If a taxpayer employs household employees, he or she may need to withhold and pay Social Security and Medicare taxes, federal unemployment tax, or both. The taxpayer, however, does not need to withhold federal income tax from the household employee\'s wages. However, if the employee requests the taxpayer to withhold it, the taxpayer can comply. (Publication 926, page 4)nnFor 2024, employment taxes must be paid if the taxpayer pays to the household employee cash wages of $2,700 (not $2,900) or more during 2024 or total cash wages of $1,000 or more in any calendar quarter of 2024 (see Table 1 in Publication 926, page 4).nnPursuant to Publication 926, pages 6 through 9, if the taxpayer needs to pay Social Security, Medicare, or federal unemployment tax or chooses to withhold federal income tax, then Schedule H (Form 1040) is utilized in calculating the amount of employer tax due, and must be attached to the taxpayer\'s tax return. A taxpayer can avoid owing tax with the filing of their tax return by using the following methods to cover any tax liability created through the use of household employees:nnHave the taxpayer\'s employer withhold more federal income taxes from the taxpayer\'s wages;nHave the payer of the taxpayer\'s pension or annuity withhold additional federal income taxes from the taxpayer\'s distributions;nMake estimated tax payments for 2024 to the IRS; ornIncrease existing estimated payments.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(21,2,'Which of the following is true regarding the filing of Form 4868, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return?','[\"Interest is charged on tax not paid by the due date of the return even if an extension is obtained.\",\"Any U.S. citizen who is out of the country on April 18, 2025, is allowed an automatic 6-month extension of time to file his\\/her 2024 return and pay any federal income tax due.\",\"Electronic filing cannot be used to get an extension of time to file.\",\"Filing Form 4868 provides an automatic 2-month extension of time to file and pay income tax.\"]',0,'According to Publication 17, page 11, an automatic 6-month (not 2-month) extension can be obtained by filing Form 4868 in paper form or e-filing.nnForm 4868 can be filed using e-filing up through April 15 by providing certain information from the prior year\'s tax form.nnA taxpayer can get an extension by paying part or all of their estimate of tax due by using a credit or debit card or by direct transfer from their bank account. A taxpayer can do this by phone or over the Internet. Under this method, a taxpayer does not file Form 4868.nnIf an extension is obtained by the taxpayer, the return that was due on April 15, 2025, is now due on October 15, 2025. However, if the taxpayer does not pay the tax due by the regular due date (generally, April 15), the taxpayer will owe interest and may also be charged penalties.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(22,2,'Phil is unmarried and his dependent daughter, Susan, lived with him all year. Property taxes of $2,500 and mortgage interest of $5,000 on the home where he and Susan live are divided equally with his ex-wife. Phil paid the utilities of $200 per month. What amount may Phil use as the costs of keeping up a home to qualify for head of household filing status?','[\"$6,150\",\"$4,950\",\"$3,750\",\"$9,900\"]',0,'To qualify for head of household status, a taxpayer must pay more than half of the cost of keeping up a home for the year. Publication 17, page 25, provides the rules and a “Cost of Keeping Up a Home” worksheet to determine if a taxpayer satisfies this rule.nnCosts that are included are items in the cost of keeping up a home such as rent, mortgage interest, real estate taxes, home insurance, repairs, utilities, and food eaten in the home.nCosts that are not included are items such as clothing, education, medical treatment, vacations, life insurance, or transportation. In addition, a taxpayer does not include the rental value of a home owned by the taxpayer, or the value of the taxpayer\'s services or those of a member of the taxpayer\'s household.nIn this case, Phil has upkeep costs of $6,150, which is the sum of his share of the property taxes ($1,250) and the mortgage interest ($2,500), and the full cost of the utilities ($2,400, or $200 per month times 12 months).nnNote: This question is tricky because the utilities are a monthly cost and the mortgage and taxes are given as an annual cost. Thus, you need to read carefully.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(23,2,'Which of the following statements regarding extensions of time to file is correct?','[\"An automatic 4-month extension can be obtained by filing Form 4868,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return.\",\"An extension request for a 2024 individual income tax return must be filed by August 15, 2025.\",\"A penalty for late payment may still be charged even if an extension is granted.\",\"An automatic 2-month extension can be obtained for individuals living outside the United States by filing Form 4868,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return.\"]',2,'Although a taxpayer is required to file his or her tax return by the taxpayer\'s due date (usually April 15), there are exceptions that may permit the taxpayer to file at a later time by applying for an extension. nnA taxpayer can get the automatic extension by using IRS e-file (electronic filing) or filing a paper form. (See Publication 17, pages 11–12, for more detailed information.)nnIndividuals are allowed an automatic 2-month extension to file their tax return and pay any federal income tax due if the taxpayer is either a U.S. citizen or resident living outside the United States and the taxpayer\'s main place of business or post of duty is outside the United States and Puerto Rico, or the taxpayer is in military or naval service on duty outside the United States and Puerto Rico. No form is filed for this extension. (See Publication 17, pages 11–12, for more detailed information.)nnIf a taxpayer does not file his or her tax return by the due date, the taxpayer may have to pay a failure-to-file penalty as well as interest. The penalty is usually 5% for each month or part of a month that a return is late, but not more than 25% (page 20, Publication 17). The penalty is based on the tax not paid by the due date (without regard to extensions).nnInterest is charged on the failure-to-file penalty, the accuracy-related penalty, and the fraud penalty from the due date of the return (including extensions) to the date of payment. There are some reasons whereby the Service can forgive all or part of the interest. (See page 16 of Publication 17 for more on this issue.)nnPublication 17, page 20, also provides a failure-to-pay penalty for paying tax late of one-half of 1% of the unpaid taxes for each month, or part of a month, after the due date that the tax is not paid. This penalty does not apply during the automatic 6-month extension of time to file period if the taxpayer paid at least 90% of the actual tax liability on or before the due date of the return and pays the balance when the return is filed.nnIn this problem, the correct statement is that a penalty for late payment may still be charged even if an extension is granted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(24,2,'In meeting the gross income test for claiming his father as a dependent, Doug considered the income received by his father. This income included gross rents of $4,000 (expenses were $2,000), municipal bond interest of $1,200, dividends of $1,400, and Social Security of $4,000. What is Doug\'s father\'s gross income for dependency test purposes?','[\"$9,400\",\"$8,600\",\"$5,400\",\"$3,400\"]',2,'To meet the gross income test, a person\'s gross income for the year must be less than $5,050 in 2024. Gross income is defined as all income in the form of money, property, and services that is not exempt from tax. In a manufacturing, merchandising, or mining business, gross income is the total net sales minus the cost of goods sold, plus any miscellaneous income from the business. In the case of rental property, gross receipts are gross income. Do not deduct taxes, repairs, etc. to determine the gross income from rental property.nnGross income also includes all taxable unemployment compensation, taxable social security benefits, and certain scholarship and fellowship grants. Scholarships received by degree candidates that are used for tuition, fees, supplies, books, and equipment required for particular courses generally are not included in gross income.nnTax-exempt income, such as certain Social Security payments, is not included in gross income. (See Publication 17, page 34.)nnIn this case, Doug\'s father has gross income for the dependency test purpose of $5,400, which is the sum of the rents ($4,000) and the dividend income ($1,400).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(25,2,'Rev. Elvin Snider is the ordained minister at Crossroads United Methodist Church. His salary on his Form W-2 is $20,000. He also receives a $12,000 housing allowance. His housing costs for the year are $14,000. What is Rev. Snider\'s self-employment income?','[\"$20,000\",\"$32,000\",\"$34,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Per Publication 517, page 2, all wages and self-employment income are subject to either SECA (Self-employment Contribution Act) or FICA (Federal Insurance Contribution Act). Per Table 1, on page 2, a minister is not covered by FICA, but is covered under SECA – meaning is subject to self-employment taxes. Page 3 further provides: “if you are a member of a church, your earnings for the services you perform in your capacity as a minister are subject to SE tax, even if you perform these services as an employee of that church.” Ministers are individuals who are duly ordained, commissioned, or licensed by a religious body constituting church or church denomination. Furthermore, even though all of the income from performing ministerial services is subject to self-employment tax for social security purposes, you may be an employee for income tax or retirement plan purposes, in which case your income is considered wages and not self-employed income.nnPublication 517 provides that a member of the clergy (minister, member of a religious order etc.) can request an exemption from self-employed tax. Provided that the clergy member meets the conditions prescribed in the publication (page 5), they would start by filing Form 4361.nnPublication 17, pages 51 and 52, states, in part, that a member of the clergy must include in income offerings and fees received for marriages, baptisms, funerals, masses, etc., in addition to the taxpayer\'s salary. If the offering is made to the religious institution and not the minister, the amount is not taxable to the minister.nnIn addition to salary, special rules for housing apply to members of the clergy. Under these rules, a minister does not include in income the rental value of a home (including utilities) or a designated housing allowance that is provided to the minister. The exclusion, however, cannot be more than the lesser of the following amounts:nnThe amount actually used to provide or rent a home;nThe fair market rental value of the home (including furnishings, utilities, garage, etc.);nThe amount officially designated (in advance of payment) as a rental or housing allowance; ornAn amount that represents reasonable pay for the taxpayer\'s service.nThe home or allowance must be provided as compensation for the minister\'s services as an ordained, licensed, or commissioned minister. However, the taxpayer must include the rental value of the home or the housing allowance as earnings from self-employment on Schedule SE (Form 1040) if the minister is subject to the self-employment tax.nnRev. Snyder in this case would include $32,000, which is the sum of his W-2 income of $20,000 and his housing allowance of $12,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(26,2,'Which of the following situations will disqualify a single individual from claiming the premium tax credit?','[\"Marriage to an individual enrolled in a qualified health plan\",\"Becoming eligible as a dependent on their parent\'s joint tax return\",\"Inheritance of $1,100,000 received during the tax year\",\"Increase in household income to 390% of the federal poverty line\"]',1,'Publication 974, page 4, states that a taxpayer can take the premium tax credit (PTC) for 2024 if the taxpayer for at least 1 month of the year, meets all of the following:nnAn individual in the taxpayer’s tax family was enrolled in a qualified health plan offered through the Marketplace on the first day of the month; andnThat individual was not eligible for minimum eligible coverage (MEC) for the month, other than individual market coverage; andnThe portion of the enrollment premiums for the month for which the taxpayer is responsible was paid by the due date of their tax return (not including extensions).nIn addition,nnThe applicable taxpayer’s household income is at least 100% but no more than 400% of the poverty line for their family; andnNo one can claim the taxpayer as a dependent on a tax return for 2024; andnIf married by the end of the year, they must generally file a joint tax return.nSince cash inheritances are not counted, the correct response for this question is that the individual cannot become eligible as a dependent on their parent’s tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(27,2,'In April 2024, 2 months after Tory and Wendy finished constructing a silo on their property, it was completely destroyed by a tornado. Their adjusted basis in the silo was its cost, $40,000. It was not covered by insurance. The entire community has been declared a qualified federal disaster area by the President. Tory and Wendy may elect to do which of the following?','[\"Deduct $40,000 in 2023, 2024, or 2025\",\"Deduct $40,000 in either 2023 or 2024\",\"Deduct $40,000 in either 2024 or 2025\",\"No deduction in any year because the loss is personal\"]',1,'Publication 547, page 3 states, in part, that there are three types of casualty losses:nnA federal casualty loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a federally declared disaster.nA disaster loss is a loss that is attributable to a federally declared disaster and that occurs in an area eligible for assistance pursuant to the Presidential declaration.nA qualified disaster loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a major disaster declared by the President under section 401 of the Stafford Act in 2016, as well as other specified events. If you suffered a qualified disaster loss, you are eligible to claim a casualty loss deduction, to elect to claim the loss in the preceding tax year, and to deduct the loss without itemizing other deductions on Schedule A (Form 1040).nIf a taxpayer suffered a qualified disaster loss, they are eligible to claim the loss on the current tax year or amended return for the preceding tax year. (Publication 547, page 16)nnIn such situations, the taxpayer is able to deduct the loss on the taxpayer\'s return or amended return for the tax year immediately preceding the tax year in which the disaster happened. If the person files an amended return, the loss is treated as having occurred in the preceding year. (Publication 547, page 16)nnIn this case, Tory and Wendy can deduct the entire loss of $40,000 in the current year or in the prior year by filing an amended tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(28,2,'Filing Form 4868, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, gives you:','[\"an extension of time to pay the amount of taxes due.\",\"no interest on the amount due from the original due date of the return, which for most taxpayers is April 15.\",\"a 6-month extension to file the tax return.\",\"a penalty-free period of 6 months if you cannot pay the taxes due by the filing date.\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 11, states, in part, that if a taxpayer cannot file his or her tax return by the due date, the taxpayer may be able to get an automatic 6-month extension of time to file. However, failure to pay the tax due by the regular due date (generally, April 15) will result in the taxpayer owing interest on the tax liability and may also result in penalty charges for failing to file the return when due.nnA taxpayer can get the automatic extension by:nnUsing IRS e-file (electronic filing), ornFiling a paper form (i.e., Form 4868)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(29,2,'Which of the following items does not appear on Schedule 3 (Form 1040) as a reduction in a person\'s tax liability?','[\"Credit for child and dependent care\",\"Self-employment tax\",\"Retirement savings contributions credit\",\"Foreign tax credit\"]',1,'One way to reduce a taxpayer\'s income tax liability is to claim tax credits that a person is qualified to claim. There are a number of tax credits that a person may be eligible to claim on Schedule 3 (Form 1040), including the child and dependent care credit, foreign tax credit, education credit, and retirement savings contribution credit (to name a few).nnThe self-employment tax, on the other hand, appears on Schedule 2 (Form 1040), line 4. The self-employment tax is an increase in a person\'s tax liability and not a reduction to a person’s tax liability. (Form 1040 Instructions, page 3)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(30,2,'Which of the following actions does not provide a taxpayer with an automatic 6-month extension of time to file an individual return?','[\"Individual does\\u00a0not\\u00a0need to do anything.\",\"Individual files Form 4868 electronic form.\",\"Individual makes the required tax payment by credit card online.\",\"Individual files Form 4868 in paper form.\"]',0,'According to Publication 17, page 11, an automatic 6-month extension can be obtained by filing Form 4868 in paper form or by means of using IRS e-file. If a person elects to e-file Form 4868, they do not also send a paper copy of the form.nnForm 4868 can be filed by mail up through the due date by providing certain information from the prior year\'s tax form.nnE-file can be done by using a taxpayer\'s personal computer or a tax professional. In addition, an extension can be obtained by paying part or all of the taxpayer\'s estimated tax by use of a credit or debit card. This extension can be done by phone or over the Internet.nnFor more information on the two ways to e-file Form 4868, see Publication 17, page 11.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(31,2,'Mary and Fred filed a joint tax return for 2024. They have a son, Fred Jr. (age 15), and a daughter, Joan (age 13), who live at home. Fred Jr. has interest income of $400 and Joan has interest income of $600. Mary\'s widowed mother has lived with them for the entire year. Mary\'s mother receives a pension of $3,000, interest income of $2,000, and dividends of $1,000. Mary and Fred fully support Mary\'s mother with the exception of her clothing; the balance of her income she invests. How many dependents can Mary and Fred, not including themselves, list on their joint tax return?','[4,3,5,2]',3,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits (Publication 17, page 27). Therefore, the following rules are provided:nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are four tests as noted in Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17 that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative:nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nTo be a qualifying child, the child must be under age 19 (24 if a full-time student) and must satisfy both tests 2 and 4 above. In addition, a qualifying child is exempt from the gross income test, but be aware there are a number of exceptions to the above tests for a qualifying child as provided in Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17.nnIf a person is a qualifying relative or a qualifying child, the person still must satisfy three additional tests as noted on page 27 of Publication 17 to claim an exemption for him or her:nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnThe exemption and dependency rules are covered in chapter 3 of Publication 17.nnIn this case, two dependents would be listed on their joint tax return: two for the children (Fred Jr. and Joan). Because both children are less than 19 years of age, they are not subject to the gross income test. Mary\'s mother, on the other hand, has gross income of $6,000 ($3,000 + $2,000 + $1,000), which exceeds the gross income limit of $5,050 for 2024. Hence, she does not qualify since she is unable to satisfy all of the tests for a qualifying relative.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(32,2,'Holly and Harp Oaks were divorced in 2023. The divorce decree was silent regarding the exemption for their 12-year-old daughter, June, as a dependent on their 2024 tax return. Holly has legal custody of her daughter and did not sign a statement releasing the exemption. Holly earned $8,000 and Harp earned $80,000. June had a paper route and earned $3,000. June lived with Harp 4 months of the year and with Holly 8 months. Who may claim June as a dependent in 2024?','[\"Since June lived with both Holly and Harp during the year, they both may claim her as a dependent.\",\"June may, since she had gross income over $3,000 and files her own return.\",\"Holly may, since she has legal custody and physical custody for more than half the year.\",\"Harp may, since he earned more than Holly and, therefore, is presumed to have provided more than 50% of June\'s support.\"]',2,'Publication 17, pages 28–29, states, in part, that a child will be treated as the qualifying child of his or her custodial parent. However, the child will be treated as the qualifying child of the noncustodial parent if all of the following apply:nnThe parents:nare divorced or legally separated under a decree of divorce or separate maintenance,nare separated under a written separation agreement, ornlived apart at all times during the last 6 months of the year.nThe child received over half of his or her support for the year from the parents.nThe child is in the custody of one or both parents for more than half of the year.nThe custodial parent signs a written declaration that he or she will not claim the child as a dependent for the year and the noncustodial parent attaches the waiver to his or her return for pre-2009 divorce decrees or separations; or in the case of a post-2008 divorce decree or separation, the noncustodial parent must attach Form 8332 if the decree or agreement went into effect after 2008. Form 8332 or a similar statement is signed by the custodial parent and is a release of the claim to the exemption.nAs a result of the general rule, Holly may claim June as a dependent because she had legal custody and physical custody for more than half of the year, and she did not provide Form 8332 or similar documentation to Harp releasing her claim to the exemption.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(33,2,'Which of the following changes must a taxpayer report to the Marketplace when re-enrolling in health coverage or during the year?','[\"Changes in household income\",\"Changes in employment\",\"Change in marital status\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 974, page 2, states that a taxpayer should report changes in circumstances when they re-enroll in health coverage and during the year so that the Marketplace can adjust their advance payments of the premium tax credit for 2024. Changes that should be reported include, but are not limited to, changes in household income; moving to a different address; gaining, losing, or other changes in employment; births or adoptions; marriage or divorce; and other changes affecting the composition of the taxpayer’s family.nnAs a result, all of the responses given are applicable. Moreover, an enrolled agent should remember to ask the taxpayer if any of these issues pertain to them to determine if they qualify for the premium tax credit (PTC).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(34,2,'Form 4868, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, will provide the individual taxpayer with the following:','[\"An automatic extension of 8 months to file the return\",\"An automatic extension of 2 months for taxpayers out of the country on April 15\",\"An automatic extension of 6 months to file the return\",\"An automatic extension of 6 months to pay the taxes due\"]',2,'If Form 4868, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, is properly filed by the normal due date of the return, a taxpayer is granted an automatic extension of 6 months for filing the return. This extension, however, does not extend the time for payment of tax, should there be tax due.nnAlso, individuals are allowed an automatic 2-month extension to file their 2024 tax return and pay any federal income tax due if the taxpayer is either a U.S. citizen or resident living outside the United States and the taxpayer\'s main place of business or post of duty is outside the United States and Puerto Rico, or the taxpayer is in military or naval service on duty outside the United States and Puerto Rico. No form is filed for this extension. However, if the taxpayer pays the tax due after the regular due date (April 15 for most taxpayers) interest will be charged from that date until the date the tax is paid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(35,2,'Michele is a member of the U.S. Armed Forces and served in an active status in a combat zone declared by executive order of the President from January 25, 2024, through March 17, 2024. She returned to the United States and received her regular duty pay for the rest of 2024. What portion of Michele\'s income is excluded on her Form W-2?','[\"January 25, 2024, through March 17, 2024, only\",\"January 1, 2024, through December 31, 2024\",\"January 1, 2024, through March 31, 2024, only\",\"All of the income is taxable.\"]',2,'Publication 3, pages 14–15, provides that gross income does not include compensation a person received for active service in the Armed Forces for any month during any part of which they served in a combat zone or qualified hazardous duty area. The exclusion available to person as a member of the Armed Forces may depend on their rank.nnAn enlisted member, warrant officer, or commissioned warrant officer, can exclude the following amounts from income:nnActive duty pay earned in any month served in a combat zone.nImminent danger/hostile fire pay.nA reenlistment bonus if the voluntary extension or reenlistment occurs in a month served in a combat zone.nPay for accrued leave earned in any month served in a combat zone. The DoD must determine that the unused leave was earned during that period.nPay received for duties as a member of the Armed Forces in clubs, messes, post and station theaters, and other non-appropriated fund activities. The pay must be earned in a month served in a combat zone.nAwards for suggestions, inventions, or scientific achievements for submission made in a month served in a combat zone.nThe month for which the taxpayer received the pay must be a month in which the taxpayer either served in a combat zone or was hospitalized as a result of wounds, disease, or injury incurred while serving in the combat zone. The taxpayer does not have to receive the pay while in a combat zone, while he or she is hospitalized, or in the same year of service in a combat zone.nnFinally, if a person serves in a combat zone for any part of 1 or more days during a particular month, he or she is entitled to exclude the amount for that entire month.nnSo, in this case, Michele could exclude from tax the income she earned in January, February, and March. The income she earned the rest of the year is not excludable as combat pay.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(36,2,'Which of the following items is an adjustment to income for a taxpayer in 2024?','[\"State and local taxes\",\"Rent and royalty expense\",\"IRA contribution\",\"Trade or business expenses\"]',2,'Schedule 1 (Form 1040) provides a list of expenses that are Adjustments to Income. Some of those items include educator expenses, health savings account (HSA) deductions, moving expenses for members of the Armed Forces, SEP and SIMPLE contributions, IRA deductions, and student loan interest deductions. (Schedule 1 (Form 1040), page 1)nnIn addition, the net amounts from rent and royalties, and trade and business are part of the total income calculation. Hence, they are Additional Income (or Losses). (Schedule 1 (Form 1040), page 1)nnState and local tax, on the other hand, is an itemized deduction that a taxpayer may claim if they itemize instead of taking the standard deduction. Thus, it is a deduction from, adjusted gross income. (Schedule A (Form 1040), page 1)nnHence, the only item that is an adjustment to income on Schedule 1(Form 1040) is an IRA contribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(37,2,'There are five tests that must be met for you to claim a qualifying relative as a dependent. Which of the following is not a requirement?','[\"Citizen or resident test\",\"Disability test\",\"Joint return test\",\"Member of household or relationship test\"]',1,'A taxpayer can claim one dependent for each person that satisfies the qualifying child or qualifying relative tests. (Publication 17, page 27) There are four basic tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see pages 33 through 36 and Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nIf a person satisfies the above four tests under qualifying relative, he or she still must satisfy three additional tests (Publication 17, page 28):nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnThe dependency rules are covered in chapter 3 of Publication 17.nnThe disability test is not one of the tests that must be met by a taxpayer to claim a qualifying relative as a dependent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(38,2,'Johan spends his weekends painting outdoor scenes to relax. Some people passing by admire his work and offer to purchase the painting. As a result, Johan begins selling his paintings for a nominal amount. Although Johan has not made a profit since he began painting a few years ago, he made sales of $3,000 and had expenses of $5,400 during 2024. What advice can you give Johan concerning his income and expenses?','[\"Report $5,400 as an itemized deduction\",\"Report a business loss of $2,400\",\"Johan does not report the income or expenses.\",\"Report $3,000 as income\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 74, provides the proper treatment of income from not-for-profit activities (also referred to as activities that are not entered into for profit). Activities such as hobbies, or activities mainly for sport or recreation, are often not entered into for profit.nnIn determining whether a person is carrying on an activity for profit, several factors are considered (no single factor is decisive). For example, a taxpayer should show that he is carrying on the activity in a businesslike manner, significant time and effort is put into the activity to make it profitable, and he is dependent on the income for his livelihood.nnIf a taxpayer makes a profit in at least 3 out of the last 5 years (Johan did not), then an activity is presumed to be carried on for profit in the current year.nnIf a taxpayer cannot demonstrate that the activity is one for profit, then the gross income may be determined by subtracting the cost of goods sold from the gross receipts. The other expenses are taken on Schedule A and would be limited to the income from the activity. Hence, the taxpayer cannot have a loss from the activity. Beginning in 2018, expenses for not-for-profit activities are not deductible because miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% limitation are suspended.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(39,2,'All of the following are requirements to claim head of household filing status, except:','[\"you paid more than half of the cost of keeping up your house for the entire year.\",\"your parent must live in your home at least 6 months.\",\"your spouse did not live in your home during the last 6 months of the tax year.\",\"you are unmarried or considered unmarried on the last day of the year.\"]',1,'To qualify as head of household, a taxpayer must meet all of the following requirements:nnunmarried or considered unmarried (generally, the taxpayer’s spouse did not live in the taxpayer’s home during the last 6 months of the tax year) on the last day of the year,npaid more than half the cost of keeping up a home for the year, andna qualifying person lived with the taxpayer in the home for more than half the year (except for temporary absences, such as school).nThere is another exception to qualifying as head of household; a taxpayer\'s dependent parents do not need to live with the taxpayer.nnThus, in this question, all of the responses are correct except the one stating that the taxpayer\'s parent must live in the taxpayer\'s home.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(40,2,'Mary\'s spouse, John, died in an auto accident in 2023. She has not remarried, and she supported their 5-year-old son all year. What is Mary\'s filing status for year 2024?','[\"Married filing separately\",\"Married filing jointly\",\"Single\",\"Qualifying surviving spouse\"]',3,'In the case where a spouse dies, the surviving spouse has a filing status of married joint for the year of death. Thus, Mary would have a filing status of married joint for her 2023 tax year. (Publication 17, pages 22–23)nnFor the 2 years following the death of the spouse (2024 and 2025), the surviving spouse may be eligible to use the qualifying surviving spouse status. This filing status entitles the surviving spouse to use the joint return tax rates and the highest standard deduction amount (if the taxpayer elects not to itemize deductions). This status does not entitle the surviving spouse to file a joint return. (See Publication 17, page 25.)nnA taxpayer must meet all of the following tests in order to file their 2024 return as a qualifying surviving spouse:nnThe taxpayer was entitled to file a joint return with their spouse for the year their spouse died. It does not matter whether the taxpayer actually filed a joint return.nThe taxpayer’s spouse died in 2022 or 2023 and the taxpayer did not remarry before the end of 2024.nThe taxpayer had a child or stepchild (not a foster child) whom they can claim as a dependent or could claim as a dependent except that for 2024:nthe child had gross income of $5,050 or more,nthe child filed a joint return, ornthe taxpayer could be claimed as a dependent on someone else’s return.nThis child lived in the taxpayer\'s home all year, except for temporary absences.nThe taxpayer paid more than half of the cost of keeping up a home for the year.nMary, in this case, has a filing status of qualifying surviving spouse because she has met all the tests listed above in 2024, which is the year following John\'s death.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(41,2,'John is an unmarried dependent child; he earns $15,000 wages during the summer, has no tips, has $200 in interest/dividends, and has no income tax withheld. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to him being required to file a tax return for 2024?','[\"He is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return.\",\"He is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return because his total income exceeded the minimum amount.\",\"He is required to file a tax return because his gross income exceeded the minimum amount.\",\"He is required to file a tax return because his unearned income exceeded the minimum amount.\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 9, Table 1-2, states that a single dependent that is not age 65 or older or blind is required to file a tax return if any of the following apply:nnHis or her unearned income was more than $1,300.nHis or her earned income was more than $14,600.nHis or her gross income was more than the larger of:n$1,300 ornhis or her earned income (up to $14,600) plus $400.nJohn is required to file a tax return for 2024 because he is an unmarried dependent child with gross income ($15,200) that exceeds $14,600.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(42,2,'April is 18 years old and single. Her only income in 2024 was $600 of self-employment income from selling cosmetics. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"April is required to file a tax return in 2024 because she exceeded the gross income level for a single filer.\",\"April is required to file a tax return in 2024 because she exceeded the minimum self-employment income level.\",\"April is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return in 2024 because she did not exceed the minimum self-employment income level.\",\"April is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return in 2024 because she did not exceed the gross income level for a single filer.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 17, page 8, a self-employed person must file a return if the taxpayer\'s gross income is at least as much as the filing requirement amount for his or her filing status and age (shown in Table 1-1 on page 8 of Publication 17). In April\'s case, she is required to file a tax return if her gross income was equal to or greater than $14,600. Although her gross income does not reach this plateau, there is another rule to consider for a self-employed taxpayer.nnA self-employed taxpayer must file Form 1040 and Schedule SE (Form 1040), Self-Employment Tax, if:nnthe taxpayer\'s net earnings from self-employment (excluding church employee income) were $400 or more, ornthe taxpayer had church employee income of $108.28 or more. (Publication 17, page 10)nAs a result of the above rules, April is required to file a tax return in 2024 because her minimum self-employment income exceeded the minimum reporting level.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(43,2,'Kathy, a U.S. citizen, is 22 years old and correctly files as single. In 2024, she had net self-employment income of $550 after expenses. She had no other income or any tax payments. Which of the following statements is correct concerning Kathy\'s requirement to file a federal income tax return for the year 2024?','[\"Kathy is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required because she has does not have net earnings from self-employment in excess of the minimum filing amount.\",\"Kathy is required because she has net earnings from self-employment in excess of the minimum filing amount.\",\"Kathy is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required because she can be claimed on her parents\' return as a child.\",\"There is not enough information to respond to the question.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 17, page 7, a taxpayer must file a return if the taxpayer\'s gross income is at least as much as the filing requirement amount for his or her filing status and age (shown in Table 1-1 on page 7 of Publication 17).nnIn the case of a self-employed taxpayer, a second rule also applies for determining when to file. Specifically, a self-employed taxpayer must file Form 1040 and Schedule SE (Form 1040), Self-Employment Tax, if:nnthe taxpayer\'s net earnings from self-employment (excluding church employee income) were $400 or more, ornthe taxpayer had church employee income of $108.28 or more. (Publication 17, page 8)nAs a result, Kathy is required to file because she has net earnings from self-employment of $550, which exceeds the minimum filing amount of $400.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(44,2,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the Additional Medicare Tax?','[\"A taxpayer may claim a credit for any withheld Additional Medicare Tax against the total tax liability on their tax return by filing Form 8959.\",\"A taxpayer may be subject to a penalty for failure to make estimated tax payments if they owe Additional Medicare Tax.\",\"A nonresident alien is required to pay Additional Medicare Tax if their wages exceed the threshold amount.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'As provided in the instructions for Form 8959, page 1, all wages that are subject to Medicare tax are subject to Additional Medicare Tax to the extent they exceed the threshold amount for a person’s filing status. The threshold for a married taxpayer filing jointly is $250,000 and for all other taxpayers is $200,000. However, the rules further state that employers must withhold Additional Medicare Tax on wages it pays to their employee in excess of $200,000 for the calendar year, regardless of the employee’s filing status and regardless of wages or compensation paid by another employer.nnAs a result, an employee who has wages between $200,000 and $250,000 has Additional Medicare Tax withheld from their wages even though they are not subject to this tax if they file married jointly with their spouse who does not have any wages in that year. In this case, the taxpayer may claim a credit for any withheld Additional Medicare Tax against the total tax liability on their tax return by filing Form 8959.nnSecond, a taxpayer may be subject to a penalty for failure to make estimated tax payments if they owe Additional Medicare Tax and wait to pay the tax with their tax return. (Form 8959, page 2)nnThird, a nonresident alien or a U.S. citizen living abroad is required to pay Additional Medicare Tax on Medicare wages, railroad retirement (RRTA) compensation, and self-employment income that exceed the threshold amount for the person\'s filing status. There are no special rules for nonresident aliens and U.S. citizens living abroad.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(45,2,'To meet the dependency test of “gross income,” the taxpayer had to consider the following income received by his mother, who was 81 years of age: Social Security $3,600, municipal bond interest $2,200, corporate bond interest $1,300, stock dividends $900, rental income $1,500, rental expenses $200, and wages $600. The mother lived with the taxpayer the entire year. What is the correct gross income of the mother for this test?','[\"$3,000\",\"$4,100\",\"$10,100\",\"$4,300\"]',3,'To meet the gross income test, a person\'s gross income for the year must be less than $5,050 in 2024 (which is the exemption amount) even though the personal and dependent exemptions are zero for years 2018 through 2025. Gross income is defined on page 35 of Publication 17 as all income in the form of money, property, and services that is not exempt from tax.nnIn a manufacturing, merchandising, or mining business, gross income is the total net sales minus the cost of goods sold, plus any miscellaneous income from the business. In the case of rental property, gross receipts are gross income. Do not deduct taxes, repairs, etc. to determine the gross income from rental property.nnGross income also includes all taxable unemployment compensation, taxable Social Security benefits, and certain scholarship and fellowship grants.nnTax-exempt income, such as tax-exempt income or untaxable Social Security payments, is not included in gross income. To determine whether Social Security benefits are taxable, the sum of one half of Social Security benefits ($1,800) and all the other income, including tax exempt income ($6,500) must not exceed $25,000 for a single person (Publication 915, page 3). Since the amount of $8,300 does not exceed $25,000, none of the Social Security benefits are taxable. As such, they will not be included in the computation of gross income for purposes of income testing associated with a qualifying relative.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer\'s mother\'s gross income consisted of corporate bond interest, stock dividends, gross rental income, and wages or $4,300 ($1,300 + $900 + $1,500 + $600). Note that, the $200 of rental expenses does not reduce the gross income figure.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(46,2,'Which statement pertaining to estimated tax payments is not correct?','[\"Estimated tax is used to pay not only income tax, but self-employment tax and alternative minimum tax as well.\",\"If insufficient tax is paid through withholding, estimated payments may be necessary.\",\"An individual whose only income is from self-employment will have to pay estimated payments.\",\"Estimated tax payments are required when the withholding taxes are greater than the overall tax liability.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 41, provides that estimated tax is the method used to pay tax on income that is not subject to withholdings. This includes income from self-employment, interest, dividends, alimony, rent, gains from the sale of assets, prizes, and awards.nnEstimated tax is used to pay both income tax and self-employment tax, as well as other taxes and amounts reported on a tax return. If a taxpayer does not pay enough through withholding or estimated tax payments, a taxpayer may have to pay a penalty. If a taxpayer does not pay enough by the due date of each payment period, a taxpayer may be charged a penalty even if the taxpayer is due a refund when he or she files his or her tax return.nnIn general, a taxpayer must pay estimated tax if both of the following apply:nnThe taxpayer expects to owe at least $1,000 in tax for 2025 after subtracting his or her withholdings and refundable credits.nThe taxpayer expects his or her withholdings and credits to be less than the smaller of 90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 tax return or 100% of the tax shown on the 2024 tax return. Moreover, the 2024 tax return must cover all 12 months.nAs a result, a taxpayer would not be required to make estimated tax payments if the withholding taxes are greater than the overall tax liability. The taxpayer in this case would be getting a tax refund.nnRemember, if a taxpayer\'s AGI for 2024 was more than $150,000 ($75,000 if married filing separately for 2024), then 110% is substituted for the 100% in the rule above.nnSee Publication 17 (pages 41–42) and Publication 505 for discussions on who does and does not need to pay estimated taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(47,2,'What action can a tax preparer take when the taxpayer has been audited for the same items in either of the 2 preceding years, had no change proposed on his or her tax liability, and receives notice that his or her return has been selected for examination?','[\"The tax preparer must submit to the examination.\",\"The tax preparer can disregard the notice under the repeat examination rule.\",\"The tax preparer must submit to the examination because the repeat examination rule pertains to the 3 preceding years.\",\"The tax preparer may contact the Internal Revenue Service and request that the examination be discontinued under the repeat examination rule.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight into the issue of repeat examinations. In particular, the IRS tries to avoid repeat examinations of the same items, but sometimes this happens. If a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer should contact the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(48,2,'Sue must make estimated tax payments of $4,000 for the tax year. She makes the following payments:nn1st Payment—credit of $1,000 from her previous year refundn2nd Payment—$500 on April 20n3rd Payment—$500 on May 31n4th Payment—$1,000 on August 15n5th Payment—$500 on October 15n6th Payment—$500 on December 30nWhich of the following statements is correct?','[\"She has\\u00a0not\\u00a0made timely payments because her second and third payments were not made by April 15.\",\"She has\\u00a0not\\u00a0made any timely payments because none of the payments were made by the required IRS schedule.\",\"She has made timely estimated payments.\",\"She has\\u00a0not\\u00a0made timely payments because her fourth payment was not made by June 15.\"]',2,'For estimated tax purposes, the tax year is divided into four payment periods for taxpayers that are required to make estimated tax payments. Each period has a specific payment due date and if the taxpayer does not pay enough tax by the due date of each of the payment periods, then a penalty may be charged even if the taxpayer is due a refund when the income tax return is filed (Publication 17, pages 42 and 43).nnThe specific payment dates for estimated tax payments are as follows: April 15, June 15, September 15, and finally January 15 of the following year. Per Publication 505, page 26, the regular installment method provides: \"if your first estimated tax payment is due April 15, you can figure your required payment for each period by dividing your annual estimated tax due by 4. (...) However, use this method only if your income is basically the same throughout the year.\"nnIn this case, Sue made at least a $1,000 payment ($4,000 ÷ 4 periods) by each payment date. Hence, she has made timely estimated payments.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(49,2,'Which of the following statements is true regarding the filing of a Form 4868, Application for an Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return?','[\"Interest is not assessed on any income tax due if a Form 4868 is filed.\",\"Even though you file Form 4868, you will owe interest, but you will not be charged a late payment penalty on the amount you owe.\",\"A U.S. citizen who is out of the country on April 15 will be allowed an additional 2 months to file.\",\"Form 4868 provides the taxpayer with an automatic additional 4-month extension to file.\"]',2,'If Form 4868, Application for an Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, is properly filed before the normal due date of the return, a taxpayer is granted an automatic extension of 6 (not 4) months for filing the return. This extension, however, does not extend the time for payment of tax, should there be tax due.nnA taxpayer is allowed an automatic 2-month extension (until June 15 in 2025, if the taxpayer uses the calendar year) to file his or her 2024 return and pay any federal income tax due if:nnthe taxpayer is a U.S. citizen or resident andnon the due date of the taxpayer\'s return:nthe taxpayer is living outside the United States and Puerto Rico, and the taxpayer\'s main place of business or post of duty is outside the United States and Puerto Rico, ornthe taxpayer is in military or naval service on duty outside the United States and Puerto Rico.nTo use this automatic extension, the taxpayer must attach a statement to the tax return explaining what situation qualified for the extension.nnAn individual taxpayer residing outside the United States who files Form 4868 and checks box 8 on the form for \"out of the country\" can request a discretionary 2-month additional extension of time to file their returns (to December 15 for calendar year taxpayers). To request this extension, the taxpayer must send the IRS a letter explaining the reasons why you need the additional 2 months. The letter must be sent by the extended due date (October 15). (Publication 54, pages 4 and 5)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(50,2,'Which of the following information does not appear on a paper Form 1040?','[\"Dependent\'s relationship to taxpayer\",\"Dependent\'s date of birth\",\"Dependent\'s Social Security number\",\"All of the answer choices appear on Form 1040.\"]',1,'Form 1040 requires certain information concerning those individuals for whom a taxpayer is claiming them as dependents. In particular, a taxpayer must provide the dependent\'s first and last name, Social Security number, and the relationship to the taxpayer. In addition, a checkbox is given to indicate if the child qualifies for the child tax credit or a credit for other dependents.nnAlthough the date of birth for a dependent is not provided on Form 1040, it is necessary for a tax advisor to inquire about and obtain reasonable evidence about all dependents\' ages. Otherwise, it is questionable as to whether the person qualifies as a child or relative.nnHence, in this case, the dependent\'s date of birth is not a line on a taxpayer\'s Form 1040. It is required to e-file a return as the computer determines what the taxpayer qualifies for based on the dependents\' age.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(51,2,'Tyler is single and is 18 years old. He works part-time and is going to school. His total income for 2024 was $8,000. Tyler lives with his parents. He qualifies as their dependent and they are claiming him as a dependent on their 2024 tax return. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to claiming Tyler?','[\"Only Tyler\'s parents can claim him as a dependent.\",\"Only Tyler can claim himself as a dependent.\",\"Either Tyler can claim himself as a dependent or Tyler\'s parents can claim him as a dependent.\",\"Neither Tyler can claim himself as a dependent nor can Tyler\'s parents claim him as a dependent.\"]',0,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits (Publication 17, page 27). Therefore, the following rules are provided.nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are five tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying child (see pages 27 to 29 and Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17):nnRelationshipnAgenResidencynSupportnJoint returnnBe aware that Table 3-1 gives the basic definitions for the tests given above.nnA qualifying child does not need to satisfy the gross income test (as in the case of a qualifying relative) unless the child fails to satisfy the age test. A child satisfies the age test (see page 28 of Publication 17) if the child is:nnunder age 19 at the end of the year,na full-time student under age 24 at the end of the year, ornpermanently and totally disabled at any time during the year, regardless of age.nAs stated in Table 3-1, a person cannot claim any dependents, including themselves, if they can be claimed as a dependent by another person. Therefore, since Tyler qualified as a dependent to his parents, he cannot claim himself as a dependent. Only his parents can claim him as a dependent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(52,2,'In which of the following situations is no return required to be filed in 2024?','[\"Married, joint filing status, both spouses under age 65, gross income $30,000\",\"Single, filing status single, under age 65, gross income $15,000\",\"Single, filing status single, age 70, gross income $14,500\",\"Married, separate filing status, age 65, gross income $6,000\"]',2,'Table 1-1, which appears in Publication 17, page 7, provides the most comprehensive presentation on when a taxpayer must file a tax return. In this problem:nnThe single person with a single filing status and age 65 or older (age 70 in this case) with gross income of $14,500 is not required to file a tax return because gross income is under $16,100.nThe single person with a single filing status and under age 65 with gross income of $15,000 is required to file a tax return because gross income is over $14,600.nThe married couple with a joint filing status and both spouses under age 65 with gross income of $30,000 is required to file a tax return because gross income is over $29,200.nThe married person with a separate filing status and any age (age 65 in this case) with gross income of $6,000 is required to file a tax return because gross income is over $5 in 2024. (Note the $5 threshold is not a typo!)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(53,2,'John is an unmarried dependent child; he earns $4,500 wages during the summer, has no tips, has $200 in interest/dividends, and has no income tax withheld. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to him being required to file a tax return for 2024?','[\"He is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return.\",\"He is required to file a tax return because his earned income exceeded the minimum amount.\",\"He is required to file a tax return because his unearned income exceeded the minimum amount.\",\"He is required to file a tax return because his total income exceeded the minimum amount.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 9, Table 1-2, states that a single dependent that is not age 65 or older or blind is required to file a tax return if any of the following apply:nnHis or her unearned income was more than $1,300.nHis or her earned income was more than $14,600.nHis or her gross income was more than the larger of:n$1,300 ornhis or her earned income plus $400 up to the regular standard deduction.nJohn is not required to file a tax return for 2024 because he is an unmarried dependent child with earned income ($4,500) that does not exceed $14,600 and unearned income ($200) that does not exceed $1,300.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(54,2,'Form 4868, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, will provide the taxpayer with the following:','[\"An automatic extension of 2 months for taxpayers out of the country on April 15\",\"An automatic extension of 4 months to pay the taxes due\",\"An automatic extension of 4 months to file the return\",\"An automatic extension of 6 months to file the return\"]',3,'According to Publication 17, page 11, an automatic 6-month extension can be obtained by filing Form 4868 in paper form or e-filing. In addition, an extension can be obtained by paying part or all of the taxpayer\'s estimated tax by use of a credit or debit card. This can be accomplished by phone or over the Internet.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(55,2,'Mary\'s spouse died in 2021. Her son Bob is her dependent and has lived in her house since his birth in 2014. What is Mary\'s filing status in 2024 if she has not remarried?','[\"Married filing jointly\",\"Head of household\",\"Qualifying surviving spouse\",\"Single\"]',1,'In general, if a taxpayer\'s spouse died in 2021, he or she can use the married filing jointly filing status for 2021. However, for the 2024 tax year and thereafter, the surviving spouse if not remarried is required to file as single unless he or she can qualify as a head of household.nnA surviving spouse may be eligible to file as a qualifying surviving spouse for 2 tax years following the year of death of their spouse, if the surviving spouse remains unmarried and maintains a household that, for the entire tax year, is the principal home of a son or daughter, adopted child, or stepchild for whom the taxpayer is entitled to the dependency exemption or could claim as a dependent except that for 2024 the child had gross income of $5,050 or more, the child filed a joint return, or the child could be claimed as a dependent on someone else’s return. A foster child does not make the surviving spouse eligible for the qualifying surviving spouse, but that does not mean that a surviving spouse cannot claim the foster child as a dependent. This benefit is afforded to a surviving spouse only if he or she was entitled to file a joint return with the deceased spouse during the year of death (Publication 17, page 25).nnAs a result, in 2021, Mary was entitled to file a joint return for herself and her deceased husband. For 2022 and 2023, she was eligible to file as qualifying surviving spouse.nnFor 2024 and thereafter, Mary would be eligible to file as head of household because she is unmarried on the last day of the year, paid more than half the cost of keeping up a home for the year, and has a qualifying person living with her in the home for more than half of the year (see pages 24 and 25 of Publication 17).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(56,2,'Reba, age 88, and Charles, age 90, are married, live together, and file jointly. During 2024, they received interest income of $3,000, dividend income of $1,500, a pension of $12,000, and Social Security of $17,000. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Reba and Charles are\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return.\",\"The couple must include $8,500 of their Social Security benefits in gross income.\",\"The couple does\\u00a0not\\u00a0include any Social Security benefits in gross income because they are over age 80.\",\"Reba and Charles are required to file a tax return.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 7, Table 1-1, states for 2024 that a couple with a married joint filing status is not required to file a tax return where both spouses are 65 or older and gross income is less than $32,200, where one spouse is age 65 or older and gross income is less than $30,700, or where neither spouse is 65 or older and gross income is less than $29,200.nnPublication 17, pages 63 and 64, states that some Social Security benefits become taxable if one-half of the benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest, exceed the base amount of $32,000 in the case of a couple filing married ($25,000 if filing single or head of household and $0 if married, filing separate, and living with one\'s spouse at any time during 2024).nnReba, age 88, and Charles, age 90, are married, live together, and file jointly. None of the Social Security benefits are included in gross income because the sum of AGI without the Social Security ($16,500) and one-half of the Social Security ($8,500) equals $25,000, which is less than the starting point of $32,000 for including Social Security income in gross income (Publication 17, pages 63 and 64). Furthermore, the couple is not required to file a tax return because they had an AGI of $16,500, which is less than $32,200, in 2024 (Publication 17, page 7).nnThus, the correct response is the couple is not required to file a tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(57,2,'No estimated tax payments are required if enough tax is paid through withholding to keep the amount owed with the return:','[\"to be under $1,000.\",\"to be $2,000 or less.\",\"to be under $2,000.\",\"to be $1,000 or less.\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer must pay estimated tax if both of the following apply:nnThe taxpayer expects to owe at least $1,000 in tax for 2025 after subtracting his or her withholdings and refundable credits.nThe taxpayer expects his or her withholdings and credits to be less than the smaller of 90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 tax return or 100% of the tax shown on the 2024 tax return. Moreover, the 2024 tax return must cover all 12 months.nSee Publication 17, pages 41 and 42, for a discussion on who does and who does not need to pay estimated taxes.nnRemember, if a taxpayer\'s AGI for 2024 was more than $150,000 ($75,000 if married filing separately for 2024), then 110% is substituted for the 100% in the rule above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(58,2,'Peter\'s unmarried daughter lived with him in his house for the entire year 2024. Peter owns the home and pays all the costs of upkeep for that home. His ex-wife did not live in the home at any time during the year. What is Peter\'s filing status for tax year 2024?','[\"Single\",\"Married filing separate\",\"Head of household\",\"Married filing jointly\"]',2,'In order to qualify for head of household status, a taxpayer must meet all of the following requirements (Publication 17, pages 24 and 25):nnis unmarried or “considered unmarried” as of the last day of the year,npaid more than half of the cost of maintaining a home for the year, andna qualifying person lived with the taxpayer in the home for more than half of the year (except for temporary absences, such as school).nA taxpayer is considered unmarried if they satisfy all five tests given on page 24 of Publication 17, which are:nnfile a separate return,npaid more than half the cost of keeping up the taxpayer\'s home for the tax year,nthe taxpayer\'s spouse did not live in the taxpayer\'s home during the last 6 months of the tax year,nthe taxpayer\'s home is the main home for the taxpayer\'s child, stepchild, or foster child for more than half the year, andnthe taxpayer must be able to claim an exemption for the child. (However, the taxpayer meets this test if they cannot claim the exemption only because the noncustodial parent can claim the child.)nGiven that Peter is unmarried and paid for all of the costs of maintaining the home, and his unmarried daughter lived with him for the entire year, he is eligible to file as head of household for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(59,2,'Julie celebrated her 18th birthday on January 1, 2025. She attends college on a part-time basis and has a part-time job. Julie lived with her parents throughout 2024 and had dividend income of $700, interest income of $2,000, and wages of $20,500. She provided 60% of her support during the year. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Julie\'s investment income is taxed at her own tax rate because she is considered to be 18 in 2024 and does not meet the support test.\",\"Julie\'s investment income is taxed at the tax rate of Julie\'s parents because she is under 24 in 2024 and is a student.\",\"Julie\'s investment income is taxed at her parent\'s tax rate because she is considered to be 18 in 2024 and her investment income exceeds the minimum threshold amount.\",\"Julie\'s investment income is taxed at the tax rate of Julie\'s parents because she is under 18 in 2024 and her investment income exceeds the minimum threshold amount.\"]',0,'Special tax rules apply to certain dependent children under age 18 (and certain older children) with $2,600 of unearned income or more.nnIf the parent doesn\'t or can\'t choose to include the child\'s income on the parent\'s return, Form 8615 is used to figure the child\'s tax, which is attached to the child\'s Form 1040.nnForm 8615 must be filed for a child instead of the child\'s tax rate if all of the following occur:nnThe child had more than $2,600 of investment income and has to file a tax return.nAt least one of the child\'s parents was alive at the end of 2024.nThe child is:nunder age 18 at the end of the year (A child born on January 1, 2007—celebrates her 18th birthday on January 1, 2025—is considered to be age 18 at the end of 2024);nage 18 at the end of the year and did not have earned income that was more than half of the child\'s support; orna full-time student over age 18 and under age 24 at the end of 2024 and did not have earned income that was more than half of the child\'s support; andnthe child doesn’t file a joint tax return for 2024.nIn this case, Julie is 18 (not under 18), provides more than half of her own support, and is not a full-time student. Thus, her investment income is taxed at her own rate.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(60,2,'In meeting the “gross income” test for claiming his father as a dependent, the taxpayer had to consider the income received by his father. This income included gross rents of $4,000 (expenses were $2,000), mutual fund municipal bond interest of $1,200, corporate bond interest of $1,000, dividends of $1,400, wages of $2,000, and Social Security of $4,000. What is the father\'s gross income for dependency test purposes?','[\"$2,000\",\"$8,400\",\"$9,600\",\"$11,600\"]',1,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits. Therefore, the following rules are provided.nnThe term “dependent” means a qualifying child or a qualifying relative. There are four tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying relative (see Table 3-1 on page 27 of Publication 17):nnNot a qualifying childnMember of the household or satisfies the relationship testnGross income test (less than $5,050 in 2024)nSupport test (more than half of the person\'s total support for the year)nIf a person is a qualifying relative or a qualifying child, the person still must satisfy three additional tests as provided in Publication 17, page 28:nnDependent taxpayer testnJoint return testnCitizen or resident testnPursuant to Publication 17, pages 34 through 35, gross income for the dependency test is all income in the form of money, property, and services that is not exempt from tax. In determining the gross income from rental property, the taxes, repairs, etc. are not deducted to determine the gross income from rental property, i.e., gross receipts are gross income. nnGross income also includes all taxable unemployment, taxable Social Security benefits, and certain scholarship and fellowship grants.nnTo determine whether Social Security benefits are taxable, the sum of one half of Social Security benefits ($2,000) and all the other income, including tax exempt income ($9,600) must not exceed $25,000 for a single person (Publication 915, page 3). Since the amount of $11,600 does not exceed $25,000, none of the Social Security benefits are taxable. As such, they will not be included in the computation of gross income for purposes of income testing associated with a qualifying relative.nnTherefore, the father\'s gross income in the above question is computed as follows:nn  Gross rents:               $4,000n  Corporate bond interest     1,000n  Dividends:                  1,400n  Wages:                      2,000n  Gross Income:              $8,400',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(61,2,'Thomas and Rebecca are the parents of four children, ages 10, 12, 15, and 22. Their 22-year-old child is a full-time student with income of $5,600. Thomas and Rebecca provided more than 50% of the support for all their children. If they file a joint return, how many of the children can they list on their Form 1040 as dependents?','[1,2,3,4]',3,'For 2024, a taxpayer cannot claim a personal exemption deduction for themselves, their spouse, or their dependents. However, dependents are still listed on Form 1040 in order to claim appropriate tax credits. Therefore, the following rules are provided.nnA taxpayer is allowed to claim one dependent for each person that satisfies the qualifying child or qualifying relative tests (Publication 17, page 27). There are five tests that must be met for a person to be a qualifying child (see pages 26 through 28 and Table 3-1 on page 26 of Publication 17):nnRelationshipnAgenResidencynSupportnJoint returnnBe aware that Table 3-1 gives the basic definitions for the tests given above.nnA child satisfies the age test (see Publication 17, page 28) if the child is:nnunder age 19 at the end of the year,na full-time student under age 24 at the end of the year, ornpermanently and totally disabled at any time during the year, regardless of age.nA qualifying child can include one\'s brother, sister, half-brother, half-sister, or descendant of any of them as well as an adopted or foster child.nnIn this case, four dependents are permitted: one for each of the couple\'s children. Although their 22-year-old child has income of $5,600, which exceeds the gross income test limit of $5,050 for 2024, he or she still qualifies as a dependent. The gross income test does not apply to a taxpayer\'s child if the child is a full-time student and is younger than 24 years of age at the end of the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(62,2,'Robin is preparing her 2024 income tax return. She has figured her income tax and is now ready to see if she is entitled to any tax credits to reduce her income tax liability. Which of the following items could be a source of tax credits that she should gather more information on to see if she is entitled to the credit?','[\"Education\",\"Foreign tax\",\"Child and dependent care\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 17, pages 109–111, lists possible credits that taxpayers may be entitled to and where to find the eligibility information for those tax credits in Publication 17. As an example, the following credits may apply, and more information is found in the following publications:nnChild and dependent care in Publication 503nEducation in Publication 970nForeign tax in Publication 17nBasic records for taxpayers include proof of payment to substantiate tax credits (see pages 17 and 18 of Publication 17). Generally, payment is proved with a cash receipt, financial account statement, credit card statement, canceled check, or substitute check. If payments are made in cash, a dated and signed receipt showing the amount and the reason for the payment should be obtained. If payments are made by electronic funds transfer, payment may be able to be proved by an account statement. Information for tax credits may also be found on IRS forms such as Form 1098 or Form K-1 that are received by the taxpayer.nnSince all of the items listed in the answer choices for Robin are possible tax credits, she should review her basic records to see which tax credits are available for her and to calculate the amount she may be entitled to reduce her tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(63,6,'Which of the following statements concerning the deduction for estate taxes by individuals is true?','[\"Individuals may claim the deduction for estate tax whether or not they itemize deductions.\",\"The estate tax deduction is a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% limitation.\",\"The deduction for estate tax can be claimed only for the same tax year in which the income in respect of a decedent must be included in the recipient\'s income.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Income that a decedent had a right to receive is included in the decedent\'s gross estate and is subject to estate tax. This income in respect of a decedent is also taxed when received by the recipient (estate or beneficiary). However, an income tax deduction is allowed to the recipient for the estate taxes paid on this income.nnThe deduction for estate tax can be claimed only for the same tax year in which the income in respect of a decedent must be included in the recipient\'s income. (This is also true for income in respect of a prior decedent.)nnIndividuals can claim this deduction only as an itemized deduction on line 16 of Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), which is a miscellaneous deduction that is not subject to the 2% limitation.nnHence, the only correct response is the deduction for estate tax can be claimed only for the same tax year in which the income in respect of a decedent must be included in the recipient\'s income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(64,6,'Lace gave the following gifts during 2024:nn  Cash to her sister         $15,000n  Stocks to her brother       19,000n  Cash to United Way          21,000n  A car to her cousin         23,000nBased on this information, what is the amount of taxable gifts given?','[\"$0\",\"$63,000\",\"$6,000\",\"$9,000\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. Gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date. For 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000. (Form 709 Instructions, pages 2–3)nnAdditionally, there are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions.nnFurthermore, as provided on page 12 of the instructions for line 7 of Form 709, a deduction from the total gifts made during the calendar year is permitted for all gifts made to or for the use of:nnThe United States, a state or political subdivision of a state or the District of Columbia, for exclusively public purposes;nAny corporation, trust, community chest, fund, or foundation organized and operated only for religious, charitable, scientific, literary, or educational purposes, or to prevent cruelty to children or animals, or to foster national or international amateur sports competition (if none of its activities involve providing athletic equipment unless it is a qualified amateur sports organization), as long as no part of the earnings benefits any one person, no substantial propaganda is produced, and no lobbying or campaigning for any candidate for public office is done;nA fraternal society, order, or association operating under a lodge system, if the transferred property is to be used only for religious, charitable, scientific, literary, or educational purposes, including the encouragement of art and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals; ornAny war veterans\' organization organized in the United States (or any of its possessions), or any of its auxiliary departments or local chapters or posts, as long as no part of any of the earnings benefits any one person.nFinally, if the only gifts made during the year are deductible as charitable gifts, then no gift tax return is required to be filed. However, if a return is required to be filed to report noncharitable gifts and gifts were made to charities, all gifts made to charities must be included on the form. Hence, if the question asked for total amount of gifts given, the response would be $63,000 ($19,000 + $21,000 + $23,000).nnIn this question, however, based on the above information, the total amount of taxable gifts given is $6,000, which is the sum of $1,000 ($19,000 − $18,000) from the stock and $5,000 ($23,000 − $18,000). The cash gift of $15,000 is below the exclusion amount and the gift to United Way is not a taxable gift.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(65,6,'Which of the following is not a characteristic of a skip person as it pertains to the GST tax?','[\"A natural person\",\"A person only one generation below the generation of the donor\",\"A person two or more generations below the generation of the donor\",\"A donee of a gift\"]',1,'A donee, who is a natural person, is a skip person if that donee is assigned to a generation that is two or more generations below the generation assignment of the donor.rnrnA donee that is a trust is a skip person if all the interests in the property transferred to the trust are held by skip persons. A trust will also be a skip person if there are no interests in the property transferred to the trust held by any person, and future distributions or terminations from the trust can be made only to skip persons.rnrnA nonskip person is any donee who is not a skip person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(66,6,'For purposes of Form 8865, which of the following cases would be a Category 3 filer?','[\"Michael Smith is a 25% partner in Supplies for All, LLC, a U.S. partnership. Supplies for All, LLC contributed $400,000 in its 100%-owned Indian subsidiary, Supplies India Partners. Supplies for All, LLC does not file Form 8865 with its own tax return (Form 1065).\",\"Kelly Peterson, who owned 12% of a foreign partnership, disposed of 4% of her ownership during the year, with an ending interest of 8% by the end of the foreign partnership\\u2019s tax year.\",\"Marcy Delong, who was a 60% profit interest partner in a foreign partnership.\",\"Patrick Pratt, who is a 5% owner in XYZ, a partnership in Poland.\"]',0,'IRS Code section 1.6038B-2(a)(2), “Reporting of certain transfers to foreign partnerships,” states: “For purposes of this section, if a domestic partnership transfers property to a foreign partnership in a section 721 transaction, the domestic partnership’s partners shall be considered to have transferred a proportionate share of the property to the foreign partnership. However, if the domestic partnership properly reports all of the information required under this section with respect to the contribution, no partner of the transferor partnership, whether direct or indirect, is also required to report under this section.”nnSince Form 8865 is not filed by Supplies for All, LLC, Michael Smith is considered to have contributed 25% of the partnership’s $400,000 contribution to the Indian partnership, or $100,000. The indirect amount contributed creates a filing requirement for Michael, who is thus deemed to be a Category 3 filer.nnKelly is a Category 4 filer, so that answer choice is incorrect. Marcy is a Category 1 filer since she controlled the partnership (over 50% interest) and Patrick does not need to file Form 8865.nnVarious categories of filers are described in the instructions to Form 8865, revised December 18, 2020, under “Categories of Filers.”',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(67,6,'Who of the following individuals must disclose their interest in their foreign financial assets on Form 8938?','[\"Jeane is married and files a joint return with her husband, Alan. Jeane resides in the United States, but 10 years ago she worked in the UK and contributed $25,000 to her UK employer\\u2019s pension plan. Her interest in the pension plan has a current market value of $55,000.\",\"Tom is a pilot who spends more than 330 days per year abroad. He maintains a foreign bank account with a balance of $55,000.\",\"Jay, a single U.S. person residing in the United States, who owns 2% of foreign corporation, FCO. His FCO stock is valued at $35,000.\",\"Manuel, a single individual, who currently resides in Argentina is the holder of a U.S. issued green card. Manuel has a vested interest in his Argentinian employer\\u2019s stock option plan with a fair market value of $100,000.\"]',0,'Presence abroad and reporting thresholds are defined in the instructions to Form 8938, under “Types of Reporting Threshold”. Even though Tom spends more than 330 days abroad, he does not do so on a continuous basis. He is not a bona-fide resident of another country. Therefore, for purposes of Form 8938, the single, U.S. resident thresholds apply ($50,000/$75,000). Since his foreign bank account balance is higher than $50,000, he is required to disclose his interest on Form 8938. (He also needs to file Form 114.)nnJeane’s interest in a foreign pension account constitutes an interest in a foreign financial asset but as a joint filer she is under the filing threshold; therefore, she does not need to disclose her interest on Form 8938.nnBecause Manuel resides abroad, the filing thresholds that are applicable in his case are those for single individuals residing abroad: $200,000 on the last day of the tax year or more than $300,000 at any time during the year. Since his interest does not meet the filing threshold, he has no 8938-filing requirement.nnJay’s interest does meet the filing threshold.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(68,6,'Which of the following is true regarding the Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR) requirements?','[\"The FinCEN Form 114 (FBAR) is filed online with the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network.\",\"The due date for the FBAR filing is generally July 15 of the current tax year for individuals.\",\"The FinCEN Form 114 (FBAR) must be filed with the current tax year individual income tax return.\",\"FinCEN will not grant an automatic extension if unable to meet the FBAR annual due date.\"]',0,'The Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR) is filed on FinCen Form 114 if any financial interest or signature authority was held in a bank, securities, or other financial account in a foreign country with assets of $10,000 or more at any point in the year.nnPublication 54, pages 10–11, provides that the FBAR must be filed electronically with FinCEN. The due date is April 15th, and an automatic extension is granted until October 15th if unable to meet the April 15th deadline. Although some tax software does allow filing of the FBARs in conjunction with the tax returns, it is not a requirement, and they can be filed separately.nnThe correct answer is that the FBAR is filed online with FinCEN.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(69,6,'Which of the following items is not provided on a separate schedule of Form 706?','[\"Funeral expenses\",\"Authorization of more than one person to represent the estate\",\"Generation-skipping transfer tax\",\"Stocks and bonds\"]',1,'For decedents who died in 2024, Form 706 must be filed by the executor of the estate whose gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemptions, is more than $13,610,000. An estate, therefore, will arrive at the taxable estate by subtracting related deductions against their gross estate. (Form 706 Instructions, page 2)rnrnAs applicable in this question, a taxpayer must file the first four pages of Form 706 and all required schedules (Form 706 Instructions, page 5). The separate schedules of Form 706 are given on page 1 of the instructions for Form 706 and include but are not limited to the following:rnrnFuneral expenses (Schedule J, Form 706)rnGeneration-skipping transfer tax (Schedules R and R-1, Form 706)rnStocks and bonds (Schedule B, Form 706)rnAs provided in Part 4 on pages 15–16 of the instructions for Form 706, completing the authorization (on page 2 of Form 706) will authorize one attorney, accountant, or enrolled agent to represent the estate and receive confidential tax information. However, if a taxpayer wishes more than one person to be authorized, then Form 2848 must be completed and attached to Form 706.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(70,6,'John, who was not married, died on October 12, 2024. He did not leave any of his assets to charity. Given the following information, may the executor of the estate make the alternate valuation election, and if so, what is the value of the gross estate on the alternate valuation date?nn                      FMV Date of Death      FMV Alternate Valuationn  Residence              $3,000,000                 $3,010,000n  Installment note            5,000                        500n  Stock                     600,000                    350,000n  Expenses                 (450,000)                  (300,000)','[\"No, the election cannot be made.\",\"Yes, the election can be made. The alternate value of the gross estate is $3,350,500.\",\"Yes, the election can be made. The alternate value of the gross estate is $3,360,500.\",\"Yes, the election can be made. The alternate value of the gross estate is $3,060,500.\"]',2,'The election for alternate valuation may not be made unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the total net estate and GST (generation-skipping transfer) taxes due after application of all allowable credits. Once made, the election may not be revoked.nnAdditionally, if the alternate valuation method is used the value of the property that is included in the gross estate must agree with the following applicable dates:nnany property distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of or separated or passed from the gross estate by any method within 6 months after the decedent\'s death is valued on the date of distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition,nany property not distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of within the 6-month period is valued on the date 6 months after the date of the decedent\'s death, andnany property, interest, or estate that is “affected by mere lapse of time” is valued as of the date of decedent\'s death or on the date of its distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition, whichever occurs first.nAlternate valuation cannot be applied to only a part of the property in the estate. The election for alternate valuation may not be made unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the total net estate and GST taxes due after application of all allowable credits. Once made, the election may not be revoked.nnTherefore, the value of the gross estate on the alternate valuation date is $3,360,500, which is the residence of $3,010,000 plus the installment note of $500 plus the stock of $350,000. The value of the gross estate on the date of death is $3,605,000, which is greater than the gross estate on the alternate valuation date. Hence, the alternate valuation date election can be made. Please note the gross estate does not include expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(71,6,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Forms FinCEN 114 and 8938 report essentially the same information.\",\"Form 8938 is filed separately from the individual\\/entity\\u2019s tax returns.\",\"A $250,000 direct interest in the stock of a foreign corporation would be disclosed on Form 8938, but not on Form FinCEN 114.\",\"Only individuals are required to file Form FinCEN 114.\"]',2,'Outright, direct ownership of foreign stock is disclosed on Form 8938, but not on FinCEN Form 114. If the stock were held through a foreign investment account, then it would be reportable on FinCEN Form 114 as well. Although, at times Forms 8938 and FinCEN 114 may report the same information, they have different purposes and report different types of financial assets. Form 8938 is filed with the entity’s tax return (1040, 1065, 1041, etc.). Trusts, corporations, or partnerships may also need to file FinCEN Form 114 provided they meet the filing requirements. A comprehensive comparison between FinCEN Form 114 and Form 8938 is compiled by the IRS. A copy of the report can be accessed here: https://www.irs.gov/businesses/comparison-of-form-8938-and-fbar-requirements.nnForm FinCEN 114 (online only)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(72,6,'What disclosure does a taxpayer need to make if he/she owns one foreign bank with a balance of less than $10,000?','[\"No disclosure is needed.\",\"File FinCEN 114 disclosing the foreign bank account to make sure all penalties are avoided\",\"File Form 8938, but not FinCEN 114\",\"Do not file FinCEN 114, but answer \\u201cyes\\u201d to question 7a on Form 1040, Schedule B, Part III.\"]',3,'Since the aggregate balance is below the filing threshold, the taxpayer does not have to file FinCEN 114. However, they are still required to answer “yes” to question 7a of Form 1040, Schedule B, Part III. Disclosure has a general meaning here, not focused necessarily on one form in particular but anywhere on the return to ensure completeness and accuracy. The 2024 Instructions to Form 1040 Schedule B, Part III state: “Line 7A – Question 1. Check the “yes” box if at any time during 2024 you had a financial interest in or signature authority over a financial account located in a foreign country. (…) Check the “yes” box even if you aren’t required to file FinCEN 114.”nnForm FinCEN 114 (online only)n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(73,6,'When must Form 706-GS(T) be filed by a trustee for a trust that has a taxable termination?','[\"By the 15th day of the 4th month following the date of termination\",\"By April 15 of the year following the calendar year of termination\",\"By September 15 of the year following the calendar year of termination\",\"By December 31 of the year following the calendar year of termination\"]',1,'In general, the trustee of any trust that has a taxable termination must file Form 706-GS(T) for the tax year in which the termination occurred.rnrnPursuant to Form 706-GS(T) Instructions, page 1, the trustee must file Form 706-GS(T) by April 15 of the year following the calendar year of termination. However, if the due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the filing is due on the next business day.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(74,6,'During calendar year 2024, Mary gave several gifts to relatives. Which of the following gifts must be reported in an annual gift tax return?nn1. $25,000 to her mother to help pay for medical expensesn2. A $20,000 federal tax-exempt municipal bond to her sistern3. 100 shares of stock to her daughter (Mary\'s basis in the stock was $10,000 and the fair market value at the date of gift was $20,000.)n4. $20,000 to a qualified university for her son\'s dormitory fees','[\"2 and 4 only\",\"2, 3, and 4 only\",\"3 only\",\"1, 2, 3, and 4\"]',3,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. For 2024 the annual exclusion is $18,000.nnThere are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. More specific to this question, to qualify for the educational exclusion the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition (not dormitory fees) for the education or training of the individual. Furthermore, for a transfer to qualify for the medical exclusion the amounts must be paid directly to the person or institution that provided the medical care (not the person receiving the medical care). Please note that even though the expenses are paid directly to the university, they are not for tuition and as such they do not qualify for the exception above.nnFinally, bonds that are exempt from federal income taxes are not exempt from federal gift taxes.nnTherefore, all of the above gifts must be reported in an annual gift tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(75,6,'John made several transfers during 2024. In January, he paid $11,000 of tuition directly to State University for his friend, Sam. He gave his niece, Sally, $7,000 for her school tuition. In addition, in May, he also gave the following graduation gifts:nn  Cash to his friend, Sam      $12,000n  Cash to his niece, Sally      10,000nHe gave no other gifts during the year. From the information above, must John file a gift tax return, and why?','[\"No, total gifts to any one individual during the year do not exceed $18,000.\",\"No, each transfer was under $18,000.\",\"Yes, total gifts given during the year exceed $18,000.\",\"Yes, total gifts to Sam exceed $18,000.\"]',0,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. Gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date.nnFor 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000. Given that John\'s total gifts to any one individual during the year did not exceed $18,000, he is not required to file a gift tax return. In Sam\'s case, the $11,000 of tuition was paid directly to State University; hence, Sam only received a gift of $12,000, which is less than the $18,000. In Sally’s case, she received two gifts that totaled $17,000 ($7,000 and $10,000), which also is less than $18,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(76,6,'Which of the following items are included in calculating a decedent\'s gross estate?nn* The decedent\'s IRA, where the decedent\'s spouse is the named beneficiaryn* A checking account with the decedent\'s daughter as joint tenants and the daughter\'s funds were used to set up the accountn* Assets held in the decedent\'s revocable grantor trust','[\"All of the assets are included in the decedent\'s estate.\",\"The IRA and checking account are included in the decedent\'s estate.\",\"The IRA and the assets in the revocable grantor trust are included in the decedent\'s estate.\",\"None of the assets are included in the decedent\'s estate.\"]',2,'The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States).nnIt also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nPursuant to the general instructions given on pages 30 through 32 of the instructions for Form 706, the general rules for including the value of any annuity in the gross estate include pension plans, IRAs, purchased commercial annuities, and private annuities. Accordingly, the IRA and the assets in the revocable grantor trust are included in the decedent\'s estate.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(77,6,'Which of the following statements is true regarding allowable deductions on Form 706, United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return?','[\"Penalties incurred as the result of a federal estate tax deficiency are deductible administrative expenses.\",\"Attorney fees paid incidental to litigation incurred by the beneficiaries are a deductible administrative expense.\",\"Executor\'s commissions may be deducted if they have actually been paid or if it is expected that they will be paid.\",\"Funeral expenses are not an allowable expense.\"]',2,'In general, an estate will arrive at the taxable estate by subtracting related deductions from the gross estate. As applicable in this question, the following expenses are permitted as deductions for an estate:nnFuneral expenses (net any reimbursements)nExecutor\'s commissions (have been paid or are expected to be paid)nExecutors’ commissions may be deducted that have actually been paid or that will be paid. Commissions are not deducted if none will be collected.nnInterest incurred as the result of a federal estate tax deficiency is a deductible administrative expense. Penalties, on the other hand, are not deductible even if they are allowable under local law.nnLikewise, attorney fees incidental to litigation incurred by the beneficiaries are not deductible. These expenses are charged against the beneficiaries personally and are not administrative expenses.nnTherefore, the only statement that is true regarding allowable deductions on Form 706 is that executor\'s commissions may be deducted if they have actually been paid or if it is expected that they will be paid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(78,6,'The requirement to file the FinCEN Form 114 applies to U.S. persons with a financial interest in or signature authority over any foreign financial account(s), if the aggregate value of these accounts, at any time during the calendar year, exceeds:','[\"$10,000.\",\"$75,000.\",\"$50,000.\",\"$100,000.\"]',0,'Publication 4261, page 1, states that any United States person who has a financial interest in or signature authority over any financial account(s) located outside of the United States is required to electronically file a FinCEN Form 114, Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR), if the aggregate value of these accounts exceeds $10,000 at any time during the calendar year.nnNote: This question appears in different forms, but the key issue is recognizing the aggregate value of these accounts must EXCEED (not be equal to) $10,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(79,6,'Which of the following statements is incorrect?','[\"The deemed intangible income considers a routine 10% rate of return on the adjusted tax basis of its intangible assets.\",\"Eligible income for FDII purposes does not include Subpart F income.\",\"FDII (foreign derived intangible income deduction) is available to U.S. corporations that sell products on foreign markets.\",\"The formula for FDII includes comparing the foreign portion of sales relative to the total amount of sales recorded at the company level.\"]',0,'IRS Code Section 250(b)(1)(A) and (B) defines deemed intangible income as the difference between deduction-eligible income less the deemed tangible income return. Deemed tangible income return “means, with respect to any corporation, an amount equal to 10 percent of the corporation’s qualified business asset investment as defined in section 951(A)(d)….” In a simplified approach, deemed intangible income is calculated as a “residual” from total eligible income (as defined per Code Section 250) less a return on investment in fixed assets.nnThe statement \"the deemed intangible income considers a routine 10% rate of return on the adjusted tax basis of its intangible assets\" is false because the 10% rate of return is considered for the adjusted tax basis of fixed assets rather than intangible assets.nnAll the other statements are true because they meet the definitions of IRS Code Section 250 and 951A.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(80,6,'Margaret\'s 2024 Form 709, page 1, has the following entries:nn  Tax on current-year gifts       $3,036,000n  Maximum applicable credit        5,389,800n  Credit used in prior years       2,897,800nBased on this information, what is the balance due on Margaret\'s Form 709 gift tax return this year?','[\"$0\",\"$513,200\",\"$544,000\",\"$414,200\"]',2,'The gift tax presently payable is determined by applying the applicable tax rate to the sum of all prior years\' taxable gifts and then subtracting that from the tentative tax. The tentative tax is then reduced by the amount of applicable credit. The basic credit (formerly the unified credit) amount in 2024 is $5,389,800. (Form 709 Instructions, page 1)nnThus, the balance of tax due on Margaret\'s Form 709 gift tax return this year is $544,000, which is the tax on current-year gifts of $3,036,000 less the applicable credit of $2,492,000. (The applicable credit is calculated as $5,389,800 − $2,897,800.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(81,6,'Ralph gave his aunt an antique clock during tax year 2024. He had purchased the clock for $16,000 in 2020. The fair market value at the date of the transfer was $21,000. What amount should be recorded on Form 709 as the value of this gift?','[\"$16,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$21,000\",\"$0\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee (Form 709 Instructions, page 2).nnFurthermore, the value of a gift is the fair market value of the property on the date the gift was made (valuation date) (Form 709 Instructions, page 10).nnThus, Ralph will report an amount of $21,000 of gifts on his 2024 Form 709, which is the fair market value at the date of transfer (i.e., the value of the gift). The taxable portion of the gift is $3,000 ($21,000 − $18,000 annual gift exclusion for 2024); you must be careful to answer the question being asked (i.e., gift amount) and not the one you think is being asked (i.e., taxable portion).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(82,6,'How is a carryover NOL that is passed through to a beneficiary deducted on the beneficiary\'s return?','[\"As a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% floor\",\"As an adjustment to adjusted gross income\",\"As an adjustment to capital gains income\",\"As a miscellaneous itemized deductionu00a0notu00a0subject to the 2% floor\"]',1,'Any unused net operating loss carryover or capital loss carryover existing upon the termination of an estate is passed through to the beneficiaries of the estate. The carryovers will be claimed on the beneficiary\'s tax return. This treatment is allowable only if the carryover would have been allowed to the estate in a later tax year if the estate had not been terminated.rnrnBoth types of carryovers generally keep their same character for the beneficiary as they had for the estate. The net operating loss carryover and the capital loss carryover are used in figuring the beneficiary\'s adjusted gross income and taxable income. Hence, it is an adjustment to AGI.rnrnIf the beneficiary of a capital loss carryover is a corporation, the corporation will treat the carryover as a short-term capital loss regardless of its status in the estate.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(83,6,'John, who is not married, made the following transfers during 2024:nn$13,000 to his son Bradleyn$19,000 to his daughter Alexandrian$9,000 political contributionn$7,000 charitable contributionnCar to his son Bradley ($24,000 basis; $18,000 FMV)nWhat is the gross amount of gifts that John will report on his 2024 Form 709 (before deductions)?','[\"$18,000\",\"$0\",\"$57,000\",\"$48,000\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. Additionally, there are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. More specific to this question, transfers to a political organization as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) for the use of the organization is not subject to the gift tax and are not reported on Form 709. (Form 709 Instructions, page 2)nnFurthermore, the value of a gift is the fair market value (FMV) of the property on the date the gift was made (valuation date). That is, the FMV is the price at which the property would change hands between a willing buyer and a willing seller, when neither is forced to buy or to sell, and when both have reasonable knowledge of all relevant facts. (Form 709 Instructions, page 10)nnIf the taxpayer is required to file a return to report noncharitable gifts and the taxpayer made gifts to charities, the taxpayer must include all of his or her gifts to charities on the return. (Form 709 Instructions, page 2)nnThus, John will report a gross amount of $57,000 of gifts on his 2024 Form 709, which is the sum of $31,000 to his son Bradley ($13,000 plus $18,000 (FMV of car)), $19,000 to his daughter Alexandria, and $7,000 to charities.nnBe aware: This question is somewhat tricky in that it gave two gifts to Bradley, where one is below the $18,000 threshold. When some gifts are below the $18,000 threshold and others are more than the threshold, all gifts have to be disclosed on the tax return. The $18,000 will be applied to each gift to determine the taxable portion of the gift. For instance, if the taxpayer gifts three gifts: $19,000, $7,000, $23,000, he/she will have taxable gifts of $7,000 calculated as follows: $19,000 - $18,000 = $1,000, $7,000 - $18,000 = no taxable gift, $23,000 - $18,000 = $5,000. Total taxable gifts = $6,000. Beware that the unused exclusion from one gift is lost and cannot be used against other gifts that are over the threshold. In our example, the unused $11,000 from the $7,000 gift cannot be used against the other gifts.nnAlso, in determining the taxability of gifts for gift tax purposes, various gifts will not be aggregated. In our example earlier, the taxpayer is not allowed to sum up the gifts of $49,000 ($19,000 + $7,000 + $23,000) and exclude $18,000 × 3 = $54,000 to conclude there are no taxable gifts. The exclusion must be applied on a gift-by-gift basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(84,6,'John made the following transfers during tax year 2024:nnTo his neighbor in the amount of $19,000nTo his nephew in the amount of $15,000nTo his uncle in the amount of $19,000nAll of the transfers are gifts that qualify for the annual exclusion. John files one Form 709 for tax year-end December 31, 2024. What is the total annual exclusion amount for gifts that will be listed on John\'s 2024 Form 709 filing?','[\"$34,000\",\"$53,000\",\"$36,000\",\"$18,000\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, a taxpayer is allowed an exclusion for a gift of a present interest to each donee. For 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000.nnTherefore, John\'s annual exclusion amount for gifts listed on his 2024 Form 709 is $36,000, which is the exclusion allowable for the gift to his neighbor of $19,000 (limited to $18,000) and $19,000 (limited to $18,000) gift to his uncle. All of the gifts made during the calendar year to a donee are fully excluded under the annual exclusion if they are gifts of present interest and they total $18,000 or less (i.e., are not reported on Form 709). The total of the exclusions permitted for the two gifts that are reported on Form 709 is $36,000 ($18,000 + $18,000). The gift to his nephew was not more than $18,000, and therefore it is not included in the exclusion.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(85,6,'Given the following information, determine the value of Sam\'s gross estate. (Sam is single.)nn                                                         FMV at Daten                                                          of Death  n  Cash                                                    $ 15,000n  Life Insurance on Sam\'s Life (payable to his estate)     200,000n  Jointly Owned Property (percentage includible: 100%)     100,000','[\"$315,000\",\"$115,000\",\"$265,000\",\"$65,000\"]',0,'The gross estate is valued at the date of death, unless the alternate valuation method is elected. The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nAccordingly, the gross value of Sam\'s estate is $315,000, determined as follows:nn  Cash              $ 15,000n  Life Insurance     200,000n  Property           100,000n  Gross Estate      $315,000nAlthough no estate tax return is filed in this case for 2024 because the gross estate plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemption is not more than $13,610,000, the question only asks for the gross estate value. Thus, carefully read what is required by a question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(86,6,'Following the death of her husband, the executrix of his estate paid the following:nn1. Medical expenses of the decedent, paid within 6 months of the date of death and not claimed on the decedent\'s final income tax returnn2. Funeral expenses of her husbandn3. State inheritance taxesn4. Qualified charitable contributions, as a bequest dictated by the will of her husbandnWhich of the preceding generally would be allowable deductions in determining the taxable estate on the 2024 federal estate tax return (Form 706)?','[\"1 and 3 only\",\"1, 2, and 4 only\",\"1, 2, 3, and 4\",\"2 and 3 only\"]',2,'For 2024, an estate will arrive at the taxable estate by subtracting related deductions against their gross estate. As applicable in this question, the following expenses appearing on Form 706, Part 5, are permitted as deductions:nnFuneral expenses (Schedule J, Form 706)nCharitable bequest (Schedule O, Form 706)nAdditionally, if the taxpayer chooses to deduct medical expenses only on the estate tax return, they are fully deductible as claims against the gross estate (Form 706 Instructions, page 33). That is, the full medical expense amount is deductible. However, if the taxpayer chooses to deduct the medical expenses on the final return, the percent limitation will apply. Moreover, a taxpayer may not deduct on the estate tax return any amounts that were not deductible on the income tax return because of the percentage limitations.nnLastly, a deduction for state death taxes may be taken for estate, inheritance, legacy, or succession taxes paid as the result of the decedent\'s death to any state or the District of Columbia on line 3b of Part 2 (Form 706 Instructions, pages 5 and 6).nnAs a result, all of the above would be allowable deductions in determining the taxable estate on the federal estate tax return (Form 706).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(87,6,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a gift of property that is an inter vivos direct skip?','[\"It is a transfer that is subject to gift taxes.\",\"It is a transfer that is of an interest in property.\",\"It is a transfer that is made to a skip person.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The generation-skipping tax that must be reported on Form 709 is that imposed only on inter vivos direct skips. An “inter vivos direct skip” is a transfer that is:nnsubject to gift tax,nof an interest in property, andnmade to a skip person.nAll three requirements must be met before the gift is subject to the generation-skipping transfer tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(88,6,'Which of the following transfers are subject to the gift tax?','[\"Transfer of municipal bonds by parent to child\",\"Transfer by taxpayer to political organization for the use of that organization\",\"Transfer by taxpayer to organization where the payment qualifies for the educational exclusion\",\"Transfer by taxpayer to organization where the payment qualifies for the medical exclusion\"]',0,'In general, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that a taxpayer made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee.nnThere are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions.nnQualifying transfers to political organizations must be to political organizations as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) and must be for the use of the organization.nnAmounts paid on behalf of an individual to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual is a qualifying transfer.nnFinally, amounts paid on behalf of an individual to a person or institution that provided medical care for the individual are a qualifying transfer.nnAs a result, the transfer of municipal bonds by parent to child is subject to the gift tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(89,6,'Mr. Brown died on September 30, 2024. His gross estate was valued at $12,670,000. Unless an extension is granted, a federal estate tax return (Form 706) must be filed on or before:','[\"April 15, 2024.\",\"A federal estate tax return does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to be filed.\",\"January 15, 2025.\",\"June 30, 2025.\"]',0,'For decedents dying in 2024, Form 706 must be filed by the executor for the estate of every U.S. citizen or resident whose gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemption, is more than $13,610,000. However, Form 706 must be filed if an executor wants to make the election to permit the decedent\'s surviving spouse to use the decedent\'s unused exclusion amount, regardless of the size of the decedent\'s gross estate.nnGiven that Mr. Brown\'s gross estate was valued at $12,670,000 (less than $13,610,000), a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed in 2024. If the amount were greater than $13,610,000, then the return would need to be filed no later than June 15, 2025, which is 9 months after September 30, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(90,6,'Jack, a single individual, made the following gifts in 2024:nn  Payment directly to sister\'s qualifyingn     college for tuition                      $17,000n  Payment directly to sister\'s qualifyingn     college for room and board                25,000n  Cash to nephew                               16,000n  Cash to brother                              30,000nWhat is the gross amount of gifts that Jack must include on his 2024 Form 709, United States Gift (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return?n','[\"$88,000\",\"$45,000\",\"$70,000\",\"$55,000\"]',3,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee.nnAdditionally, there are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions.nnMore specific to this question, for transfers to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual. Moreover, to qualify the payment must be made directly to the institution.nnNo educational exclusion is allowed for amounts paid for books, supplies, room and board, or other similar expenses that do not constitute direct tuition costs. To the extent that the payment to the educational institution was for something other than tuition, it is a gift to the individual for whose benefit it was made and may be offset by the annual exclusion if it is otherwise available.nnThus, Jack will report a gross gift amount of $55,000 on his 2024 Form 709, which is the sum of $30,000 to his brother and $25,000 for his sister\'s room and board. The cash to his nephew is not reported because it is not greater than $18,000 (annual exclusion amount) and the payment made to the qualifying college for tuition is not reported.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(91,6,'On June 30, 2024 John Smith made a gift of $2,000 to his daughter. John will need to file a gift tax return (Form 709) on or after January 1, 2025, but no later than:','[\"March 15, 2025.\",\"April 15, 2025.\",\"March 31, 2025.\",\"John will\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to file Form 709 for the year ending December 31, 2024.\"]',3,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. The annual exclusion is $18,000 for 2024.nnGiven that John\'s gift falls under the exclusion amount, he will not have to file Form 709 for the year ending December 31, 2024.nnIf, however, John\'s gifts exceeded the applicable exclusion amount, Form 709 should be filed on or after January 1 but not later than April 15.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(92,6,'Alberta, who had not given taxable gifts in any prior year, gave her five children the following gifts in 2024:nn   A car to Richard         $22,000n   Cash to Elizabeth         21,000n   Stock to John             18,500n   Stock to Jane             17,500n   Cash to Robert            12,000nFrom the information above, determine the amount, if any, of taxable gifts given by Alberta.','[\"$0\",\"$43,000\",\"$7,500\",\"$61,000\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. Gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date.nnFor 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000 per person.nnTherefore, Alberta\'s total taxable gifts are $7,500, which is:nn  $4,000 for Richard ($22,000 gift - $18,000 exclusion), plusn   3,000 for Elizabeth ($21,000 gift - $18,000 exclusion), plusn     500 for John ($18,500 gift - $18,000 exclusion)n  $7,500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(93,6,'U.S. Co. is a 25% owner of an Irish corporation. The Irish corporation reported $8,500,000 in sales and $3,500,000 in general expenses. It paid $500,000 in taxes to the Irish government (10%). The adjusted taxable bases of the Irish company’s assets are $2,000,000. Assume U.S. Co. makes an election under IRC Section 250. What is the tax liability associated with its GILTI inclusion for U.S. Co.?','[\"$0\",\"$252,000\",\"$152,000\",\"$26,000\"]',3,'The net U.S. tax liability is calculated as follows:nnControlled foreign corporation’s (CFC) net income = $8,500,000 sales − $3,500,000 expenses = $5,000,000nQualified business asset investment (QBAI) = 10% × $2,000,000 = $200,000nIndirect foreign tax credit available = 25% × ($500,000 × 80%) = $100,000nGlobal intangible low taxed income (GILTI) inclusion for U.S. Co. = 25% × ($5,000,000 − $200,000) = $1,200,000nGILTI inclusion after electing IRC Section 250 = $1,200,000 × 50% = $600,000nU.S. tax liability before indirect foreign tax credit = $600,000 × 21% = $126,000nNet U.S. tax liability = $126,000 – $100,000 Indirect foreign tax credit = $26,000nIRC Section 951(A) governs GILTI tax. Final and temporary regulations were issued on June 14, 2019.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(94,6,'Which of the following statements regarding the annual exclusion for gift taxes in 2024 is true?','[\"A gift made by a spouse is always split between the spouses if they are married and filing jointly.\",\"A gift of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion.\",\"The annual exclusion amount for 2024 is $17,000.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee.rnrnA gift of a present interest may be excluded, whereas gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date.rnrnThe annual exclusion for 2024 is $18,000. rnrnA married couple can elect to gift splitting, but it is not an automatic election.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(95,6,'Which of the following is a correct statement regarding Form 8938, Statement of Specified Foreign Financial Assets?','[\"Form 8938 is attached to your annual return and filed by the due date, including extensions\",\"If an income tax return is not required to be filed for the tax year, you are still required to file Form 8938 when specified foreign financial assets is more than the appropriate reporting threshold\",\"If you are required to file Form 8938, you must report the specified foreign financial assets in which you have an interest only if the assets affect your tax liability for the year\",\"Filing Form 8938 relieves you of the requirement to file FinCEN Form 114,\\u00a0Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR)\\u00a0if you are otherwise required to file the FBAR\"]',0,'Form 8938 must be filed by all specified persons who have an interest in specified foreign assets with values exceeding their applicable filing threshold. The report must be filed even if the items do not affect tax liability, along with the applicable annual tax return by the due date (including extensions) for that return. If no return is required, Form 8938 is not necessary. Form 8938 does not replace the FBAR, which must be filed if certain thresholds are met.nnThe correct answer is that Form 8938 is attached to the annual return and filed by the due date, including extensions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(96,6,'A calendar-year estate came into existence November 12, 2024. It had a tax balance due of $15,000 on the 2024 return. The estate executor expects to have a $10,000 balance due on the 2025 tax return. The estate will not be finalized until 2025. Income is received evenly throughout the year, and there is no withholding. The executor is required to make estimated payments on:','[\"April 15, 2025; June 15, 2025; September 15, 2025; and January 15, 2026.\",\"December 31, 2025, if the return is filed on or before February 28, 2026.\",\"either April 15, 2025; June 15, 2025; September 15, 2025; January 15, 2026; or December 31, 2025, if the return is filed on or before February 28, 2026.\",\"No estimated payments are required.\"]',3,'Generally, estimated tax must be paid if the estate is expected to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least $1,000 in tax for 2025. You will not, however, have to pay estimated tax if you expect the withholding and credits to be at least:nn90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 return orn100% of the tax shown on the 2024 return. (The percentage is 110% if the estate\'s 2024 adjusted gross income (AGI) was more than $150,000.) This exception does not apply if there was no return filed for 2024 or if the 2024 return did not cover a full 12 months.nIf the estate has adopted a calendar year as its tax year, it must file under the rules set forth for trusts (Form 1041-ES, page 2). That is, the estate can either pay all of the estimated tax on April 15 or pay it in four equal installment amounts (i.e., April 15, June 15, September 15, and January 15).nnThere are three exceptions to this general rule. One of the exceptions pertains to the first 2 years following the death of the taxpayer. During this period, no estimated payments are necessary. Estates, therefore, with tax years ending 2 or more years after the date of the decedent\'s death must pay estimated tax in the same manner as individuals.nnSince the return being filed in 2025 is within the 2-year period, no estimated payments are required.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(97,6,'Mary Smith made only the following transfers of interest in personal property during the 2024 tax year:nn$40,000 cash to the Republican Party, a political organization (as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1))n$25,000 cash to Good Care Health Inc. for medical care (as defined in IRC Section 213(d)) of her ailing resident fathern100 shares of common stock of ABC Inc. with a basis to Mary of $5,000 and a fair market value (FMV) of $10,000 to Save the Walnut Foundation, a Section 501(c)(3) organizationnWhat is the total amount of gifts that must be reported on Mary\'s gift tax return for 2024?','[\"$75,000\",\"$70,000\",\"$50,000\",\"Mary does not need to file Form 709 for the 2024 tax year.\\n\"]',3,'There are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. Qualifying transfers to political organizations must be to political organizations as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) and must be for the use of the organization.nnFor transfers to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual. Furthermore, for a transfer to qualify for the medical exclusion, the amounts must be paid directly to the person or institution that provided the medical care.nnIf the only gifts the taxpayer made during the year are deductible as gifts to charities, the taxpayer does not need to file a return as long as the taxpayer transferred his or her entire interest in the property to qualifying charities. If the taxpayer is required to file a return to report noncharitable gifts and the taxpayer made gifts to charities, the taxpayer must include all of his or her gifts to charities on the return.nnGiven that Mary\'s transfers qualify as transfers not subject to the gift tax, she is not required to file Form 709 for the 2024 tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(98,6,'According to the IRS, which of the following is NOT an option for addressing failure to comply with U.S. tax and information return obligations with respect to non-U.S. investments?','[\"Streamlined filing compliance procedures\",\"Delinquent FBAR submission procedures\",\"Amending the prior year\'s tax return and including the missing information (\\u201cquiet disclosure\\u201d)\",\"Delinquent International Information Return submission procedures\"]',2,'Amending the prior year\'s tax return to include information not reported on the original return is not “endorsed” by the IRS, nor does it provide any audit or further examination protection.nnThe IRS lists and describes various amnesty programs for offshore compliance options on their webpage “Delinquent FBAR submission procedures.\"',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(99,6,'All of the following statements are correct, except:','[\"a married couple may not file a joint gift tax return.\",\"a married couple is able to gift split.\",\"consent to gift split may be signed up to December 31 of the year following the gift.\",\"the executor for a deceased spouse may sign the consent form.\"]',2,'The IRS does not permit a married couple to file a joint gift tax return. However, spouses can gift split.nnA spouse must sign the consent for the gift-splitting election to be valid. The consent to gift split may generally be signed after the end of the calendar year, but there are two exceptions. Specifically, the consent may not be signed after April 15 following the end of the year in which the gift was made, and not after a notice of deficiency for the tax year has been issued to either spouse.nnIn addition, the executor for a deceased spouse or the guardian of a legally incompetent spouse may sign the consent form.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(100,6,'All of the following are correct, except:','[\"consent to gift split may be signed up to the end of the calendar year following the gift.\",\"a married couple is able to gift split.\",\"a married couple may\\u00a0not\\u00a0file a joint gift tax return.\",\"the executor for a deceased spouse may sign the consent form.\"]',0,'The IRS does not permit a married couple to file a joint gift tax return. However, spouses are able to gift split. The consent to gift split can be signed after the end of the calendar year, but generally not after April 15 following the end of the year in which the gift was made, and not after a notice of deficiency for the tax year has been issued to either spouse.nnIn addition, the executor for a deceased spouse or the guardian of a legally incompetent spouse may sign the consent form.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThis question or versions of it have appeared periodically on the exam.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(101,6,'Which of the following entities are required to file Form 709, United States Gift (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return?','[\"An estate or trust\",\"An individual\",\"A corporation\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'A series of situations is provided in the instructions for Form 709 for who must file a gift tax form. In general, the following are required to file gift tax returns:rnrnonly individuals,rna taxpayer who gives gifts to someone in 2024 totaling more than $18,000 (other than the taxpayer\'s spouse); andrnif a trust, estate, partnership, or corporation makes a gift, the individual beneficiaries, partners, or stockholders are considered donors and may be liable for the gift and GST (generation-skipping transfer) taxes.rnThus, the best response to this question is an individual.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(102,6,'Meg Griffin holds the following: a French savings account holding $8,000, an investment account at UBS Switzerland holding securities with a value of $3,500, an undeveloped tract of land purchased for $12,000 with a fair market value of $14,000 in the Bahamas, and an interest in an UK Social Security payment program valued at $50,000 (based on life expectancy, using a discounted present value of future payments method). Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Meg has a FinCEN Form 114-filing requirement for the French savings account and the Swiss investment account, and a Form 8938 filing requirement for interest in the UK Social Security account.\",\"Meg is not required to file FinCEN Form 114 because the French and the Swiss account balances are individually below $10,000.\",\"Meg should file FinCEN Form 114 only because the aggregated values of her French and Swiss accounts exceed $10,000. She need not file Form 8938 since the interest in a foreign government\\u2019s Social Security program does not constitute a financial interest.\",\"All of Meg\\u2019s foreign assets should be disclosed on Form 8938 since in aggregate, they exceed $50,000.\"]',2,'Meg is required to file FinCEN Form 114 because the aggregated values of her accounts exceed $10,000. However, the aggregated value of the two accounts $11,500 does not meet the filing threshold for Form 8938. As such, Form 8938 is not required to be filed. Meg’s interest in a foreign government’s Social Security program is not considered a financial interest. The tract of land does not represent a financial asset and, as such, it will not be considered for any of the two filing requirements. Foreign financial assets excepted from reporting are defined in “Assets Not Required to be Reported” in the instructions to Form 8938. Types of specified foreign financial assets are defined in the instructions to Form 8938 under the section “Specified Foreign Financial Assets.”nnFinCEN From 114 (online only)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(103,6,'Mark died on December 22, 2023. The executor of his estate chose a calendar year. In 2024, the estate had a tax liability of $2,000. It is expected that the estate will have an adjusted gross income of $43,000 and a tax liability of $3,000 in 2025. All of the income is from interest and dividends from which no tax was withheld. Which of the following statements regarding estimated tax payments for this estate is true?','[\"The executor does not need to make estimated tax payments because the estate is only in its 3rd year of existence.\",\"The executor should make equal estimated payments totaling at least $2,000 (last year\'s tax liability) to avoid a penalty for underpayment of tax.\",\"The executor should make equal estimated payments totaling at least $3,000 to avoid the penalty for underpayment of tax.\",\"Because the 2025 tax liability is no more than $1,000 greater than the prior-year liability, no estimated tax payments are required.\"]',0,'Generally, estimated tax must be paid if the estate is expected to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least $1,000 in the current tax year. You will not, however, have to pay estimated tax if you expect the withholding and credits to be at least (Form 1041 Instructions, page 10):nn90% of the tax to be shown on the current-year return orn100% of the tax shown on the prior-year return. (The percentage is 110% if the estate\'s prior-year return\'s adjusted gross income (AGI) was more than $150,000.)nThere are three exceptions to paying estimated taxes. One of the exceptions to making estimated tax payments, as given on page 1 of Form 1041-ES, is if the decedent\'s estate for any tax year is ending before the date that is 2 years after the decedent\'s death. This exception does not apply here because the 2-year period ended on December 22, 2025, which precedes December 31, 2025.nnAccording to page 2 of Form 1041-ES, if the estate has adopted a calendar year as its tax year, it must file under the rules set forth for trusts (which also appear on page 2 of Form 1041-ES). That is, the estate can either pay all of the estimated tax on April 15, 2025, for tax year 2024 or pay it in four equal installment amounts.nnTherefore, the executor should make equal estimated payments totaling at least $2,000 (last year\'s tax liability) to avoid a penalty for underpayment of tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(104,6,'Which of the following amounts paid may be claimed as a credit on the estate tax return?','[\"Charitable contributions\",\"Generation-skipping transfer tax\",\"State death taxes paid\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Under current law, a taxpayer may take a deduction on line 3b of Form 706 (Part 2) for estate, inheritance, legacy, or succession taxes paid as the result of the decedent\'s death to any state or the District of Columbia.nnBetter yet, the taxpayer may claim an anticipated amount of deduction and figure the federal estate tax on the return before the state death taxes have been paid. However, the deduction cannot be finally allowed unless the taxpayer pays the state death taxes and claims the deduction within 4 years after the return is filed or later under certain conditions. (Form 706 Instructions, page 6)nnCharitable contributions deductions can be claimed on Schedule O and filed with the taxpayer’s Form 706. A person can claim the charitable contributions allowed under IRC Section 2055 for the value of property in the decedent’s gross estate that was transferred by the decedent during life or by will to or for the use of specific organizations as provided on pages 38 and 39 of the instructions for Form 706.nnIn addition, the generation-skipping transfer tax is computed on Schedule R, but it is not an allowable deduction appearing in Part 5 of Form 706. (Form 706 Instructions, page 43) Please note the distinction between a deduction and a credit. Whereas the answer choices include items that qualify as deductions, they cannot be claimed as credits.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(105,6,'Mr. Alexis died April 30, 2024. His gross estate totaled $12.6 million. Assuming that no extension is granted, the executor must file Form 706, United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return, on or before:','[\"August 15, 2024.\",\"January 30, 2025.\",\"October 31, 2025.\",\"No estate tax return is filed.\"]',3,'For decedents dying in 2024, Form 706 must be filed by the executor for the estate of every U.S. citizen or resident:nnwhose gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemption, is more than $13,610,000 ornwhose executor elects to transfer the decedent’s unused exclusion (DSUE) amount to the surviving spouse, regardless of the size of the decedent\'s gross estate.nIf the executor must file Form 706 to report estate and/or generation-skipping transfer tax, it is due within 9 months after the date of the decedent\'s death unless an extension of time to file has been granted. An automatic 6-month extension of time to file is requested by filing Form 4768.nnIn this case, January 30 of the following year is the 9-month limit.nnForm 706, however, is not filed in this case because the value of the estate is below $13,610,000, which is the threshold amount for requiring the filing of an estate form.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(106,6,'The following transfers were made by Ed during 2024. What is the gross amount of gifts to be included on Ed\'s 2024 Form 709 filing?nn$18,000 to the United Wayn$14,000 to a political organizationn$22,000 paid directly to his nephew\'s college for tuitionn$19,000 paid directly to his niece for her college tuition','[\"$73,000\",\"$18,000\",\"$37,000\",\"$59,000\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. Additionally, there are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions.nnMore specific to this question, transfers to a political organization as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) for the use of the organization are not subject to the gift tax.nnFor transfers to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual. Moreover, to qualify the payment must be made directly to the institution.nnFinally, if the only gifts made during the year are deductible as charitable gifts then no gift tax return is required to be filed. However, if a return is required to be filed to report noncharitable gifts and gifts were made to charities, all gifts made to charities must be included on the form.nnThus, Ed will report a gross amount of $37,000 of gifts on his 2024 Form 709, which is the sum of $18,000 to United Way and $19,000 paid directly to his niece for her college tuition. If the $19,000 were paid directly to the niece\'s educational institution, Ed would not have to file a gift tax return since he would not have to report any noncharitable gifts, as noted in the paragraph above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(107,6,'George and Helen are husband and wife. During 2024, George gave $44,000 to his brother and Helen gave $36,000 to her niece. George and Helen both agree to split the gifts they made during the year. What is the taxable amount of gifts, after the annual exclusion, each must report on Form 709?','[\"George and Helen each have taxable gifts of $22,000.\",\"George has a taxable gift of $26,000 and Helen has a taxable gift of $18,000.\",\"George and Helen each have taxable gifts of $4,000.\",\"George has a taxable gift of $8,000 and Helen has a taxable gift of zero.\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. An exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. The annual exclusion is $18,000 for 2024.nnAdditionally, married couples may not file a joint gift tax return, but IRC Section 2513 does permit spouses to split gifts. If both spouses agree, all gifts during the calendar year will be considered as made one-half by each spouse.nnAs such, George and Helen have a taxable gift of $8,000 that is split between them. The taxable gift amount is computed as follows:nn  George\'s brother   $44,000n  Helen\'s niece       36,000n  Gross gifts        $80,000n  Exclusions          72,000 (($18,000 x 2) + ($18,000 x 2))n  Taxable gifts      $ 8,000 ($4,000 to each)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(108,6,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning (the value of the) bonds that are specifically exempt from federal income tax?','[\"They are reported on the\\u00a0United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return\\u00a0(Form 706) but\\u00a0not\\u00a0on the final income tax return.\",\"They are\\u00a0not\\u00a0reported on the\\u00a0United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return\\u00a0(Form 706) or on the final income tax return.\",\"They are\\u00a0not\\u00a0reported on the\\u00a0United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return\\u00a0(Form 706) but\\u00a0are\\u00a0reported on the final income tax return.\",\"They are reported on the\\u00a0United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return\\u00a0(Form 706) and on the final income tax return.\"]',0,'Bonds that are exempt from federal income tax are not exempt from estate tax unless specifically exempted by an estate tax provision of the Internal Revenue Code. Therefore, bonds exempted from federal income tax need to be reported on the United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return (Form 706).nnExempt bonds are not reported on the final income tax form, but the tax-exempt interest is reported on Form 1040 although it is not subject to tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(109,6,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a $20,000 gift to an unrelated individual who is 40 years younger than the donor?','[\"The gift is subject to gift tax only.\",\"The gift is subject to generation-skipping tax only.\",\"The gift is subject to the gift tax and generation-skipping tax.\",\"The gift is\\u00a0not\\u00a0subject to either the gift tax or the generation-skipping tax.\"]',2,'The federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. Additionally, for 2024 an exclusion of $18,000 is allowed for a gift of a present interest. (Form 709 Instructions, page 2)nnFurthermore, the generation-skipping transfer tax also will apply only on inter vivos direct skips when a transfer is subject to the gift tax, is of an interest in property, and is made to a “skip” person. All three conditions must be met for both taxes to apply. As applicable to this question, a “skip” person is a person who is two or more generations younger than the transferor (more than 37.5 years between the donor and donee birthdates). (Form 709 Instructions, pages 8 and 9)nnGiven that the gift exceeds the $18,000 exclusion, and the gift was made to a “skip” person, both the gift tax and generation-skipping transfer tax apply.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(110,6,'Which of the following is NOT a reportable event for purposes of Form 3520?','[\"Peter Johnson, a U.S. resident, contributes $10,000 to fund the Peter Johnson Marital Offshore Trust \\u2013 a foreign trust located in the Bahamas.\",\"Cindy Krauss\\u2019 grandmother from Denmark gifts Cindy, who is a U.S. resident, $50,000 to help her with the down payment for Cindy\\u2019s first residence.\",\"Olivia Ricardo received a $25,000 trust distribution from a Swiss trust account.\",\"Jane Moneypenny, who is a U.S. resident, receives a lumpsum distribution of $500,000 from her UK pension account. Her UK pension is deemed to be a foreign trust that does\\u00a0not\\u00a0meet the reporting exemption as described in Rev. Proc. 2020-17, 2020-12, I.R.B 539.\"]',0,'Cindy Krauss is not required to report a direct, outright gift from a foreign person (Danish grandmother) in an amount less than $100,000.nnAll the other instances are examples of reportable events on Form 3520: setting up an offshore trust, receiving a distribution from a foreign trust, and receiving a distribution from a foreign pension account deemed to be a trust that does not meet the exemption tests from reporting as described in Revenue Procedure 2020-17. Reportable events and responsible parties are described in the instructions to Form 3520, under the “Who Must File” section. IRC Section 6039F defines non-U.S. persons and the filing thresholds.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(111,6,'Which of the following values of property is not eligible for the marital deduction?','[\"Value of property passed on to the surviving spouse\",\"Value of property interest not included in the decedent\'s gross estate\",\"Value of property not disclaimed by the surviving spouse\",\"Neither the value of property interest not included in the decedent\'s gross estate nor the value of property not disclaimed by the surviving spouse is eligible for the marital deduction.\"]',0,'Generally, a taxpayer may list on Schedule M all property interests that pass from the decedent to the surviving spouse and are included in the gross estate. However, the instructions for Form 706, page 38, provide that certain property interests are listed on Schedule M and that other property interests that are not listed on Schedule M and therefore are not eligible for the marital deduction, such as:nnthe value of any property that does not pass from the decedent to the surviving spouse;nproperty interests that are not included in the decedent\'s gross estate;nthe full value of a property interest for which a deduction is claimed on Schedules J through L (The value of the property interest should be reduced by the deductions claimed with respect to it.);nthe full value of a property interest that passes to the surviving spouse subject to a mortgage or other encumbrance or an obligation of the surviving spouse (Include on Schedule M only the net value of the interest after reducing it by the amount of the mortgage or other debt.);nnondeductible terminable interests (as further described on pages 35 and 36 of the Form 706 Instructions); ornany property interest disclaimed by the surviving spouse.nBased on the list provided above, the correct response is the value of property interest not included in the decedent\'s gross estate is not eligible for the marital deduction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(112,6,'John is a single taxpayer who died during the current tax year. Based on the following information, determine the value of John\'s gross estate.nn                                     FMV on Date of DeathnLife insurance on John\'s lifen  (payable to John\'s estate)              $7,250,000nJohn\'s revocable grantor trust             1,900,000nStock given to John\'s son in 2024 n  (no gift tax was paid)                      50,000n','[\"$7,250,000\",\"$7,300,000\",\"$9,150,000\",\"$9,200,000\"]',2,'The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nAccordingly, John\'s gross estate is $9,150,000, computed as follows:nn  Gross estatenn    Life insurance             $7,250,000n    Revocable grantor trust     1,900,000n  John\'s gross estate          $9,150,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(113,6,'The terms of John\'s will require annual payments of $30,000 and $10,000 to his widow and daughter, respectively, out of the estate\'s income, during each year of his estate\'s administration. The estate\'s distributable net income (DNI) for the year ending December 31, 2024, was $20,000. Calculate the amount of income each of the beneficiaries will receive on their annual K-1 from the estate.','[\"Widow: $10,000 and Daughter: $10,000\",\"Widow: $15,000 and Daughter: $5,000\",\"Widow: $20,000 and Daughter: $-0-\",\"Widow: $-0- and Daughter: $-0-\"]',1,'Beneficiaries of a simple trust must include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI.rnrnGiven that the estate had $20,000 of distributable net income to distribute, the amount of income on each of the K-1s will be as follows:rnrnWidow\'s K-1 is $15,000, which is 75% ($30,000 ÷ $40,000) of the DNI amount of $20,000.rnDaughter\'s K-1 is $5,000, which is 25% ($10,000 ÷ $40,000) of the DNI amount of $20,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(114,6,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning U.S. persons electronically filing a Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) 114, Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (the \"FBAR\")?','[\"A U.S. person that has a financial interest in a foreign financial account with a balance of $10,000 must file an FBAR.\",\"The FBAR must be filed on or before June 30 of the year immediately following the calendar year being reported.\",\"A U.S. person that has signature authority over foreign financial account with a balance of $20,000 must file an FBAR.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Beginning on September 30, 2013, a taxpayer that has a financial interest in or signature authority over a foreign financial account, including a bank account, brokerage account, mutual fund, trust, or other type of foreign financial account, exceeding certain thresholds is required by the Bank Secrecy Act to report the account yearly to the Internal Revenue Service by filing electronically a Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) Form 114, Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR).nnThe FBAR must be received by the Department of the Treasury on or before April 15 of the year immediately following the calendar year being reported. FinCEN will grant filers failing to meet the FBAR annual due date of April 15 an automatic extension to October 15 each year. Accordingly, specific requests for this extension are not required. This date change was mandated by the Act § 2006(b)(11) of the Surface Transportation and Veterans Health Care Choice Improvement Act of 2015, Public Law 114-41.nnThe following individuals are required to file an FBAR:nnA United States person that has a financial interest in or signature authority over at least one financial account located outside of the United States; andnthe aggregate value of the foreign financial accounts exceeds $10,000 (not equal to $10,000) at any time during the calendar year. https://bsaefiling.fincen.treas.gov/FFBARHelp.htmlnThus, the correct response is a U.S. person that has signature authority over a foreign financial account with a balance of $20,000 must file an FBAR.nnFinCEN Form 114 (only available online)nnFinCEN Form 114a (only available online)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(115,6,'Richard Devins owns 4% of foreign corporation, ABC Ltd. During the year, Richard acquires an additional interest of 7% in ABC. ABC is neither a specified foreign company (SFC), nor a controlled corporation (CFC). Should Richard file Form 5471 and if yes, what category should he file under?','[\"Richard does not have a Form 5471 filing requirement since his interest was less than 10%.\",\"Richard should file Form 5471 as a Category 1 filer since cumulatively he owns more than 10% of ABC.\",\"Richard should file Form 5471 as a Category 3 filer since he purchased sufficient stock that added to the existing stock, he was over the 10% ownership requirement.\",\"Richard should not file Form 5471 since ABC is neither a CFC, nor an SFC.\"]',2,'Richard should file Form 5471 as a Category 3 filer. His newly acquired interest of 7% when added to his existing interest of 4% brings him over 10% ownership requirement. The category that describes best this type of filer is Category 3.nnThe other answer choices are incorrect:nnRichard does have a filing requirement. His interest is considered cumulatively.nRichard is not a Category 1 filer since ABC is not an SFC.nThe filing requirement of Form 5471 is not limited only to controlled foreign corporations and/or specified foreign corporations.nVarious categories of 5471 filers are described in the instructions to Form 5471, under the section “Categories of Filers.” A Category 3 filer includes a U.S. person who acquires stock in a foreign corporation which, when added to any stock owned on the date of the acquisitions, meets the 10% stock ownership requirement with respect to the foreign corporation. Controlled foreign corporations and United States persons are defined IRC Section 957.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(116,6,'Which of the following tax credits are allowed when an estate tax return (Form 706) is filed?','[\"Credit for foreign death taxes\",\"Credit for federal gift taxes (pre-1977)\",\"Credit for tax on prior transfers\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'As applicable to the above question and according to the IRS instructions for line 15 of Form 706, page 10, the following credits are allowed on an estate tax return: credit for foreign death taxes (Schedule P), and credit for tax on prior transfers as discussed on pages 40–42. In addition, line 10 provides an exemption for decedent made gifts.nnAs a result, all of the answer choices are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(117,6,'Mrs. Flame passed away on March 15, 2024. The assets, included in her estate, were properly valued as follows:nn                         3-15-24         7-15-24         9-15-24 n Personal residence    $  500,000      $  600,000      $  700,000n Stocks held            2,000,000       1,400,000       1,500,000nThe executor sold the home on July 15, 2024, for $600,000. The alternate valuation date was properly elected. What is the value of the estate reported for estate tax purposes?','[\"$1,900,000\",\"$2,500,000\",\"$2,100,000\",\"$2,200,000\"]',2,'For 2024, the gross estate is valued at the date of death, unless the alternate valuation method is elected. The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nUnder the alternate valuation method, the value used to determine the basis of the property is not the value at the date of the decedent\'s death, but it is the value at the date 6 months after the death if the property is not sold, distributed, or otherwise disposed of within 6 months after the decedent\'s death. If the property is sold, the value that is used in determining basis is the value of the property at the date of sale. (Form 706 Instructions, page 10)nnAs an aside, the alternate valuation date cannot be elected unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the sum (reduced by allowable credits) of the estate and GST (generation-skipping transfer) taxes payable by reason of the decedent\'s death for the property includible in the decedent\'s gross estate.nnAccordingly, if the executor makes the special election, the gross value of Mrs. Flame\'s estate is $2,100,000, determined as follows:nn  Personal residence   $  600,000 (Date of sale value)n  Stocks                1,500,000 (Alternate valuation date value)n  Gross estate         $2,100,000nNote: As given above, the personal residence is valued at the date of sale because it precedes the alternate valuation date election. Also, Form 706 is not filed because the estate is valued at less than $13,610,000 in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(118,6,'Which of the following items is not an allowable deduction on a decedent\'s estate tax return?','[\"Bequest to a surviving ex-spouse\",\"Property taxes accrued before death but not paid until after death\",\"Executor\'s fees for administering the estate\",\"None of the items are allowed as a deduction against the decedent\'s estate\\n\"]',0,'In figuring taxable income, an estate is generally allowed the same deductions as an individual. Special rules, however, apply to some deductions for an estate (Publication 559, pages 18–19).nnAs applicable in this question, the following expenses would be permitted as deductions:nnExecutor\'s feesnThe deduction for property taxes is limited to the taxes accrued before the date of the decedent\'s death (Form 706 Instructions, page 34).nPublication 559, page 23, provides, in part, that a bequest is the act of giving or leaving property to another through the last will and testament. Generally, any distribution of income (or property in kind) to a beneficiary is an allowable deduction to the estate and is includible in the beneficiary\'s gross income to the extent of the estate\'s distributable net income. However, a distribution will not be an allowable deduction to the estate and will not be includible in the beneficiary\'s gross income if the distribution meets the following requirements: it is required by the terms of the will, it is a gift or bequest of a specific sum of money or property, and it is paid out in three or fewer installments under the terms of the will.nnTherefore, a bequest to a surviving ex-spouse would not be an allowable deduction because it meets the above requirements.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(119,6,'Which of the following items generally is included in a person\'s estate?nn1. The transfer of title to property to another individual whereby the decedent retains the right to the use of the property during his or her lifetimen2. The receipt of annuity income by the decedentn3. The interest in community property ownership by the decedent','[\"1 only\",\"2 only\",\"2 and 3 only\",\"1, 2, and 3\"]',3,'The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nSee pages 30 through 32 of the instructions for Form 706 for a more detailed discussion of the conditions necessary for including annuity income in the gross estate. If the conditions are not satisfied, annuity income would not be included. However, the general rule is that the amount is included. Hence, the correct response for this question would be that items 1, 2, and 3 are includible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(120,6,'What type of provision is available for requesting an extension of time to pay the tax liability associated with Form 706-GS(D), Generation-Skipping Transfer Tax Return for Distributions?','[\"An automatic 2-month extension is available.\",\"An automatic 4-month extension is available.\",\"An automatic 6-month extension is available.\",\"No\\u00a0extension is available.\"]',2,'Form 706-GS(D) is used by a skip person distributee to calculate and report the tax due on distributions from a trust that are subject to the generation-skipping transfer (GST) tax.nnThe GST tax on distributions is figured and reported on a calendar-year basis, regardless of the taxpayer\'s income tax accounting period. The taxpayer, generally, must file the form on or after January 1 but not later than April 15 of the year following the calendar year when the distributions were made.nnIf a taxpayer is unable to file the return by the due date, the taxpayer may request an automatic 6-month extension of time by filing Form 7004. Since the extension is automatic, the taxpayer does not need to sign the form or provide a reason. However, Form 7004 must be filed on or before the regular due date of Form 706-GS(D).nnNow, most tax people would argue that no extension is available for paying the tax, only for filing the return. However, if you look at Form 4768, you will see that the heading for this form, which is the way to request an extension, is Application for Extension of Time to File a Return and/or Pay U.S. Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(121,6,'Which of the following transfers are subject to the gift tax?','[\"A $20,000 transfer of municipal bonds by parent to child\",\"A $20,000 contribution to a political organization for the use of that organization\",\"A $20,000 contribution to an organization where the payment qualifies for the educational exclusion\",\"A $20,000 contribution to an organization where the payment qualifies for the medical exclusion\"]',0,'In general, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property.nnThere are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. Qualifying transfers to political organizations must be to political organizations as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) and must be for the use of the organization.nnTransfers of this type are not deemed “gifts.” Accordingly, Form 709 is not required to be filed and, additionally, the transfers should not be listed on Schedule A of Form 709 if a return is filed.nnTherefore, the $20,000 transfer of municipal bonds by a parent to a child exceeds the $18,000 exclusion amount for 2024 and therefore it must be reported on Form 709, United States Gift (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(122,6,'Which of the following individuals qualifies under the marital deduction rules under IRC Section 2056?','[\"A surviving spouse that is a U.S. citizen\",\"Surviving children that are U.S. citizens\",\"A surviving spouse that is not a U.S. citizen\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Pursuant to the instructions for Form 706, page 38, the marital deduction is authorized by IRC Section 2056 for certain property interests that pass from the decedent to the surviving spouse (not children). The estate may claim the deduction only for property interests that are included in the decedent\'s gross estate (Schedules A through I).nnIn addition, the marital deduction is generally not allowed if the surviving spouse is not a U.S. citizen. The marital deduction is allowed for property passing to such a surviving spouse in a qualified domestic trust (QDOT) or if such property is transferred or irrevocably assigned to such a trust before the estate tax return is filed. The executor must elect QDOT status on this return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(123,6,'Which of the following persons has a FinCEN 114 filing requirement in 2024?','[\"A nonresident alien with a $20,000 bank account who was present in the United States for 120 days in 2024 but was not present in the United States for any of the previous years.\",\"A U.S citizen residing abroad with a foreign bank account balance of $8,000. The U.S. person does not have other foreign bank accounts.\",\"A U.S. citizen who is the officer of a foreign company and has signature authority over the foreign company\'s bank accounts in the foreign country. The highest balance in the bank account was recorded in June at $12,000, but in December the balance was $6,000.\",\"A U.S. person who purchased French real estate for $20,000 using a direct wire transfer from a US bank to the seller\\u2019s bank.\"]',2,'The nonresident alien does not have a filing requirement since they do not meet the residency test described in 26 U.S.C. section 7701(b). The U.S. citizen residing abroad would have a filing requirement only if their bank account balance exceeded $10,000; since their bank account balance is below $8,000, they do not have a filing requirement.nnA U.S. person having signature authority in a foreign bank account would have to file Form 114 and indicate (by checking the box) they do not have a financial interest in the account. The foreign account reached the filing threshold during the year, so a filing requirement exists regardless of the end-of-the-year balance. Real estate assets do not constitute financial assets and, as such, there is no filing requirement. For purposes of Form 114 filing, IRS Code Section 1010.350 (b) defines a United States person and Code Section 1010.350 (c) defines the reportable accounts.nnFinCEN 114 (Online only)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(124,6,'Jim has elected to treat transfers (on behalf of his son) made by him during tax year 2024 to a qualified state tuition program as made ratably over 5 years. His total contribution to this plan, which he made during 2024, is $85,000. He makes no other transfers during tax year 2024. What amount will be treated as a taxable gift in tax year 2024?','[\"$85,000\",\"$72,000\",\"$18,000\",\"$0\"]',3,'A citizen or resident of the United States generally must file a gift tax return (whether or not any tax is ultimately due) in a number of situations that are given on page 2 of the instructions for Form 709. The following is a short list of those situations:nnif gifts were given to someone in 2024 totaling more than $18,000 (other than to your spouse), ncertain gifts, called future interests, are not subject to the $18,000 annual exclusion and Form 709 must be filed even if the gift was under $18,000, and na gift tax return must be filed to split gifts with a spouse (regardless of the amount).nMoreover, if more than $18,000 is contributed to a qualified tuition program (QTP) on behalf of any one person, an election may be made to treat up to $90,000 (which is $18,000 multiplied by 5 years) of the contribution as if it had been made ratably over a 5-year period. This election allows the annual exclusion to apply to a portion of the contribution in each of the 5 years. (Form 709 Instructions, page 7)nnTherefore, given the above, Jim will not have any taxable gifts for 2024 because his gift is $85,000, which is not more than $90,000.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(125,6,'Cassy is single and has not been required to file a gift tax return in any prior year. In 2024, Cassy paid $19,000 tuition directly to State University for her sister, Andrea. She gave her brother $13,000 to pay medical bills for his daughter. She also donated $23,000 to the United Way. Must Cassy file a gift tax return?','[\"No\",\"Yes, because the gift to her sister exceeded $18,000\",\"Yes, because the United Way donation exceeded $18,000\",\"Yes, because the total gifts she gave during the year exceeded $18,000\"]',0,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. Gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date. For 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000.nnAdditionally, there are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. More specific to this question, for the transfer to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual. Furthermore, for a transfer to qualify for the medical exclusion, the amounts must be paid directly to the person or institution that provided the medical care.nnIf the only gifts the taxpayer made during the year are deductible as gifts to charities, the taxpayer does not need to file a return as long as the taxpayer transferred his or her entire interest in the property to qualifying charities. If the taxpayer is required to file a return to report noncharitable gifts and the taxpayer made gifts to charities, the taxpayer must include all of his or her gifts to charities on the return.nnGiven that Cassy\'s gifts either fall under the applicable exclusion ($18,000) or are transfers not subject to the gift tax, she is not required to file a gift tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(126,6,'Lois, a cash basis taxpayer, died on September 30, 2024. Assume the following details regarding the assets of her estate:nnLois\' home was appraised for $2,000,000 at the date of her death and sold on March 15, 2025, for $1,950,000.nLois had a time certificate in the amount of $100,000. The certificate was redeemed for funeral expenses on October 1, 2024. (Ignore interest for purposes of this question.)nLois had common stock valued at $1,850,000 at the date of death. On the alternate valuation date, the stock was valued at $1,750,000.nLois had personal and household furnishings that were appraised at $25,000 as of the date of death. The executor gave all of the items to a charity on November 1, 2024.nIf the alternate valuation date is elected, what is the gross value of the estate if it were to be reported?n','[\"$3,825,000\",\"$3,875,000\",\"$3,925,000\",\"$3,975,000\"]',0,'Unless the election to adopt an alternate valuation is made at the time the return is filed, the value of all property included in the gross estate will be the value on the date of the decedent\'s death. Alternate valuation cannot be applied to only a part of the property.nnThe election for alternate valuation may not be made unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the total net estate and GST (generation-skipping transfer) taxes due after application of all allowable credits. Once made, the election may not be revoked.nnAdditionally, if the alternate valuation method is used, the value of the property that is included in the gross estate must be in agreement with the following applicable dates:nnAny property distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of or separated or passed from the gross estate by any method within 6 months after the decedent\'s death is valued on the date of distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition.nAny property not distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of within the 6-month period is valued on the date 6 months after the date of the decedent\'s death.nAny property, interest, or estate that is “affected by mere lapse of time” is valued as of the date of decedent\'s death or on the date of its distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition, whichever occurs first.nIn this case, the alternate valuation election is made and, as such, the gross value if it had to be reported is determined as follows:nn                           Fair Market Value (FMV)n                             Alternate Valuation  n  Home                           $1,950,000n  Certificate of Deposit            100,000n  Stock                           1,750,000n  Personal Items                     25,000n  Gross Estate Value             $3,825,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(127,6,'In general, on Form 709, you can claim a marital deduction for gifts to your spouse. Generally, you cannot take the marital deduction if the gift to your spouse is a terminal interest.nnYou may elect to deduct a gift of a terminal interest (QTIP) if it meets four requirements. Which of the following is not a necessary requirement?','[\"No part of the entire interest is subject to another person\'s power of appointment.\",\"Your spouse is entitled for life to all of the income from the entire interest.\",\"The income is paid yearly or more often.\",\"Your spouse does not have the unlimited power, while he or she is alive or by will, to appoint the entire interest in all circumstances.\"]',3,'A taxpayer\'s ability to deduct a gift of a terminable interest, without an election, is permitted if it meets all four of the following requirements:nnYour spouse is entitled for life to all of the income from the entire interest.nThe income is paid yearly or more often.nYour spouse has the unlimited power, while he or she is alive or by will, to appoint the entire interest in all circumstances.nNo part of the entire interest is subject to another person\'s power of appointment (except to appoint it to your spouse).nIf either the right to income or the power of appointment given to the spouse pertains only to a specific portion of a property interest, the marital deduction is allowed only to the extent that the rights of the spouse meet all four of the above conditions. For example, if the spouse is to receive all of the income from the entire interest, but only has a power to appoint one-half of the entire interest, then only one-half qualifies for the marital deduction.nnThe election is made by listing the qualified terminable interest property on Schedule A and deducting its value on line 4, Part 4 of Schedule A.nnThus, a necessary requirement does not include the case where the spouse does not have the unlimited power, while he or she is alive or by will, to appoint the entire interest in all circumstances.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(128,6,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to filing Form 706, United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return, in 2024 if the executor does not make the special election?','[\"An automatic 6-month extension of time can be requested by filing Form 4868.\",\"Form 706 does not need to be filed.\",\"Form 706 must be filed when the gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts, is more than $13,610,000.\",\"Form 706 figures the estate tax on the share received by each beneficiary.\"]',2,'With respect to 2024, the instructions for Form 706, page 2, provide, in part, that an executor can request an automatic 6-month extension of time by filing Form 4768 (not Form 4868, which is for individuals seeking an extension). Moreover, a taxpayer is not required to provide an explanation when requesting a filing extension for Form 706.nnForm 706 must be filed in 2024 when the gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts, is more than $13,610,000. In addition, it figures the estate tax on the entire estate, not just the share received by each beneficiary. (Form 706 Instructions, pages 1–2)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:16'),(129,6,'Which of the following situations would require the filing of Form 709?','[\"You and your spouse agree to split your gifts, which total $35,000.\",\"You gave more than $18,000 during the year to any one donee.\",\"Any of the gifts you made were of a future interest.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Specific to this question, a citizen or resident of the United States generally must file a gift tax return (whether or not any tax is ultimately due) in the following situations:nnif gifts were given to someone in 2024 totaling more than $18,000 (other than to your spouse), na gift of community property, because it is considered made one-half by each spouse,ncertain gifts, called future interests, are not subject to the $18,000 annual exclusion and Form 709 must be filed even if the gift was under $18,000, and na gift tax return must be filed to split gifts with a spouse (regardless of the amount).nTherefore, in the above question, all of the situations would require the filing of Form 709.nnFor a detailed list of \"who must file\" situations requiring Form 709 to be filed, refer to page 2 of the IRS instructions for Form 709.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(130,6,'Andrew has an AGI amount of $300,000. During the year, he gave several taxable gifts to friends and relatives. In addition, he gave a future interest with an FMV of $51,000 to a qualified charity. When he files his 2024 Form 709, what taxable gift amount will Andrew enter?','[\"There is no gift tax on a future interest.\",\"$13,000\",\"$38,000\",\"$51,000\"]',3,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that a taxpayer made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. The first $18,000 of gifts of present interest to each donee during the calendar year is subtracted from total gifts in figuring the amount of taxable gifts.nnThere are exceptions to the general rule. Specifically, a gift of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion and Form 709 must be filed even if the gift is less than $18,000.nnHence, Andrew would include the entire gift amount of $51,000 in this case. (Form 709 Instructions, pages 2 and 3) Although gifts to public charities usually enjoy 100% exclusion, IRC Section 2522(c)(2) indicates that where a donor transfers an interest in property but retains an interest in the same property or the property is transferred for less than adequate consideration in money from the donor to the person, no deduction shall be allowed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(131,6,'Laura\'s gross estate equals $10 million. Given the following information, determine Laura\'s taxable estate for 2024 prior to consideration of the estate exemption amount.nn  Charitable contribution specified in Laura\'s will     $100,000n  Funeral expenses                                        10,000n  Medical expenses claimed on Laura\'s Form 1040           20,000','[\"$0\",\"$9,870,000\",\"$9,890,000\",\"$10,000,000\"]',2,'For 2024, an estate will arrive at the taxable estate by subtracting related deductions against their gross estate. A taxpayer must file the first four pages of Form 706 and all required schedules (such as A through PC—see page 1 of the Form 706 Instructions for a complete listing). As applicable in this question, the following expenses are permitted as deductions:nnFuneral expenses (Schedule J, Form 706)nCharitable bequest (Schedule O, Form 706)nAdditionally, if the taxpayer chooses to deduct medical expenses only on the estate tax return, they are fully deductible as claims against the gross estate. That is, the full medical expense amount is deductible. However, if the taxpayer chooses to deduct the medical expenses on the final income tax return, the percent limitation will apply. Moreover, a taxpayer may not deduct on the estate tax return any amounts that were not deductible on the income tax return because of the percentage limitations. (Form 706 Instructions, page 33)nnTherefore, Laura\'s taxable estate is $9,890,000, determined as follows:nn  Gross estate               $10,000,000n  Less:n    Charitable contribution     (100,000)n    Funeral expenses             (10,000)n  Taxable estate              $9,890,000nThere is no estate tax where the gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemption, is equal to or less than $13,610,000. This question involves determining the amount of the taxable estate prior to considering the estate tax exemption amount. (If the gross estate equaled $14.5 million, then the taxable estate would be $14,390,000, which is over the $13,610,000 threshold.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(132,6,'Generally, in which of the following scenarios must a gift tax return be filed?','[\"You gave gifts to an individual (other than your spouse) totaling more than $18,000.\",\"You gave a gift of a future interest that was less than $18,000.\",\"You wish to split gifts with your spouse.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Specific to this question, a citizen or resident of the United States generally must file a gift tax return (whether or not any tax is ultimately due) in the following situations:nnif gifts were given to someone in 2024 totaling more than $18,000 (other than to your spouse),ncertain gifts, called future interests, are not subject to the $18,000 annual exclusion, and Form 709 must be filed even if the gift was under $18,000, orna gift tax return must be filed to split gifts with a spouse (regardless of the amount).nFor a detailed list of situations requiring Form 709 to be filed, refer to pages 1 through 3 of the IRS instructions for Form 709.Therefore, in the above question, all of the above situations would require the filing of Form 709.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(133,6,'Which of the following is not a credit against gross estate tax in determining net estate tax?','[\"Foreign death taxes\",\"Qualified charitable contributions\",\"Unified credit (applicable credit amount)\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Form 706, Part 2, line 3a, provides that an estate will arrive at the tentative taxable estate by subtracting total allowable deductions (not credits) from Part 5 (Form 706, line 2) against their gross estate. As applicable in this question, the following expense (Form 706, Part 5) is permitted as a deduction:nnCharitable bequest (Schedule O, Form 706)nAdditionally, estates are allowed to take certain credits (Part 2, lines 9a to 9e and line 15 of Form 706) against the gross estate which include but are not limited to foreign death taxes, the credit for tax on prior transfers (Form 706 Instructions, page 10), and the unified credit (applicable credit amount) on line 11.nnAs such, the charitable contribution is a deduction and not a credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(134,6,'Johnny died on May 1, 2024. When must the executor file Form 706, assuming that an extension of time to file is not being requested?','[\"April 15, 2025\",\"November 1, 2025\",\"August 15, 2024\",\"February 1, 2025\"]',3,'The estate tax return (Form 706) must be filed within 9 months after the date of the decedent\'s death. If the taxpayer is unable to file this form by the due date, an extension of time to file may be requested by filing Form 4768.nnForm 4768 provides an automatic 6-month extension.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(135,6,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Mary, a U.S. person, is a partner in Foreign Partnership FPA. Her interest in the partnership is 25%. Mary does not have signature authority over the partnership\\u2019s bank accounts and does not serve as an officer or director. The highest balance registered during the year by FPA in its bank account was $60,000. Mary has a filing requirement for FinCEN Form 114 because her share of FPA\\u2019s cash is $15,000 which is above the filing threshold.\",\"Robert Smith is the U.S. beneficiary of a Generous Grandma Trust FBO Robert Smith. The trust maintains a bank account in the Cayman Islands with a balance of $20,000. The trust files and submit FinCEN Form 114 disclosing the interest in the Cayman Island account. Robert, as the sole beneficiary of the trust should also file FinCEN Form 114 to disclose his indirect interest in the Cayman Island account.\",\"Alice and Bob are a married couple who file a joint return. Alice and Bob have a joint interest in a foreign account held in the United Kingdom with a dollar equivalent balance of $14,000. Bob has two more foreign accounts in France for which he is the sole owner. Bob prepares and submits FinCEN Form 114 including all 3 accounts. Alice signs the e-file authorization form. Alice does not have a separate FinCEN Form 114 filing requirement.\",\"Joanna, a U.S. resident, decides to invest her savings in a mutual fund managed by a U.S. bank within the United States. The mutual fund contains foreign stock only valued at $25,000. Joanna should disclose her ownership of foreign stock on FinCEN Form 114.\"]',2,'Mary is not considered to have a financial interest in FPA’s foreign bank account since her ownership interest is below 50%. Robert meets one of the exceptions from filing FinCEN Form 114 since the information is disclosed and filed at the trust level. Joanna does not have a filing requirement since her investment account is managed and maintained within the United States.nnAlice meets all the requirements for a non-filing spouse to be excepted from filing. However, Bob is required to file a FinCEN Form 114. Code Section 1010.350(c) defines the reportable accounts. Form 114 instructions define the exceptions from filing an FBAR.nnFinCEN 114 (online only)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(136,6,'Which of the following statements regarding gift splitting is correct?','[\"The couple must have been married at the time the gift was given, but either or both spouses may be remarried during the year.\",\"The couple must have been married at the time the gift was given and the spouse who gave the gift mayu00a0notu00a0be remarried during the year.\",\"The couple needu00a0notu00a0be married at the time of the gift, but must be married by the end of the year.\",\"The couple must be married at all times during the year.\"]',1,'While a married couple may not file a joint gift tax return, the IRS permits spouses to split gifts under certain conditions. If both spouses agree, all gifts during the calendar year will be considered as made one-half by each spouse if:rnrnboth spouses were married to one another at the time of the gift,rndivorced or widowed after the gift, the spouse did not remarry during the rest of the calendar year,rnneither of the spouses was a nonresident alien at the time of the gift, andrna spouse was not given a general power of appointment over the property interest transferred.rnAccordingly, the only correct statement in this question regarding gift splitting is that the couple must have been married at the time the gift was given and the spouse who gave the gift may not be remarried during the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(137,6,'In general, which of the following items are allowable deductions against a decedent\'s estate (Form 706)?','[\"Funeral expenses\",\"Mortgages (decedent\'s liability)\",\"Charitable bequests\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'An estate will arrive at the taxable estate by subtracting related deductions from the gross estate. As applicable in this question, the following expenses as given in Part 5 of Form 706 are permitted as deductions for an estate: funeral expenses, mortgages (decedent\'s liability), and charitable bequests.nnTherefore, all of the above listed expenses are allowable deductions against a decedent\'s estate.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(138,6,'When Lisa\'s husband died in 2021, he set up a qualified terminable interest property (QTIP) trust, naming Lisa as the beneficiary for her life. What is the value of Lisa\'s gross estate if she should die, given the following information?nn                                   FMV on Date of Deathn  Lisa\'s revocable grantor trust        $3,750,000n  QTIP trust                             1,000,000','[\"$0\",\"$1,000,000\",\"$3,750,000\",\"$4,750,000\"]',3,'The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nAdditionally, any “QTIP” property received from a pre-deceased spouse must be included in the gross estate.nnAccordingly, Lisa\'s gross estate is $4,750,000, computed as follows:nn  Gross estaten    Revocable grantor trust   $3,750,000n    QTIP trust                 1,000,000n  Lisa\'s gross estate         $4,750,000nThe estate of Lisa would not file an estate tax return because the gross estate is $13,610,000 or less.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(139,6,'Which of the following statements regarding the annual exclusion for gift taxes is true?','[\"The gift of a present interest to more than one donee as joint tenants qualifies for only one annual exclusion.\",\"A gift of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion.\",\"The annual exclusion amount for 2024 is $17,000.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. (Form 709 Instructions, page 2)nnA gift of a present interest may be excluded, whereas gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date. (Form 709 Instructions, page 3)nnThe annual exclusion for 2024 is $18,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(140,6,'All of the following items can be claimed as deductions against a decedent\'s estate, except:','[\"specific bequest to son.\",\"executor\'s fees.\",\"legal fees to settle estate.\",\"charitable bequests.\"]',0,'In figuring taxable income, an estate is generally allowed the same deductions as an individual.nnA bequest is the act of giving or leaving property to another through the last will and testament. Generally, any distribution of income (or property in kind) to a beneficiary is an allowable deduction to the estate and is includible in the beneficiary\'s gross income to the extent of the estate\'s distributable net income. However, a distribution will not be an allowable deduction to the estate and will not be includible in the beneficiary\'s gross income if the distribution meets the following requirements:nnit is required by the terms of the will,nit is a gift or bequest of a specific sum of money or property, andnit is paid out in three or fewer installments under the terms of the will.nTherefore, a “specific” bequest to a son would not be an allowable deduction because it meets the above requirements.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(141,6,'Which of the following items is provided on a separate schedule of Form 706, United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return, if filed in 2024?nn1. Funeral expensesn2. Generation-skipping transfer taxn3. Charitable, public, and similar gifts and bequests','[\"2 and 3 only\",\"2 only\",\"1 only\",\"1, 2, and 3\"]',3,'For 2024, an estate will arrive at the taxable estate by subtracting related deductions against their gross estate. A taxpayer must file the first four pages of Form 706 and all required schedules (such as A through PC—see page 1 of the Form 706 Instructions for a complete listing). As applicable in this question, the following items are provided on a separate schedule of Form 706 (see, for example, Form 706 Instructions, page 1):nnFuneral expenses (Schedule J, Form 706)nGeneration-skipping transfer tax (Schedule R and R-1, Form 706)nCharitable, public, and similar gifts and bequests (Schedule O, Form 706)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(142,6,'For calendar-year 2024, if a gift tax return is required to be filed and the donor is not deceased, what is the due date of the return excluding extensions?','[\"Within 75 days of making the gift\",\"On or before December 31, 2024\",\"No earlier than January 1, 2024, and no later than April 15, 2025\",\"Within 180 days of making the gift\"]',2,'For 2024, Form 709 must be filed on or after January 1 but not later than April 15, 2024. However, in instances when April 15 falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, Form 709 will be due on the next business day. See IRC Section 7503.nnIf the donor died during 2024, the executor must file the donor\'s 2024 Form 709 not later than the earlier of:nnthe due date (with extensions) for filing the donor\'s estate tax return ornApril 15 or the extended due date granted for filing the donor’s gift tax return.nIf no estate tax return is required to be filed, the due date for the 2024 Form 709 (without extensions) is April 15, 2025. For more details, see Regulation Section 25.6075-1.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(143,6,'Which of the following statements concerning the alternate valuation election is correct for 2024?','[\"The alternate valuation election may be made even if no estate tax will be paid if the election is not made.\",\"If the alternate valuation election is made, it is possible for some but not all of the assets to be included in the decedent\'s estate at a higher FMV than on the date of death.\",\"If the alternate valuation election is made, assets that are disposed of within 6 months of the decedent\'s death are generally valued on the date of death.\",\"None of the statements are correct.\"]',0,'Unless the election to adopt an alternate valuation is made at the time the return is filed, the value of all property included in the gross estate will be the value on the date of the decedent\'s death. Alternate valuation cannot be applied to only a part of the property.nnThe election for alternate valuation may not be made unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the total net estate and GST (generation-skipping transfer) taxes due after application of all allowable credits. Once made, the election may not be revoked.nnAdditionally, if the alternate valuation method is used, the value of the property that is included in the gross estate must be in agreement with the following applicable dates:nnany property distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of or separated or passed from the gross estate by any method within 6 months after the decedent\'s death is valued on the date of distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition,nany property not distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of within the 6-month period is valued on the date 6 months after the date of the decedent\'s death, andnany property, interest, or estate that is “affected by mere lapse of time” is valued as of the date of decedent\'s death or on the date of its distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition, whichever occurs first.nTherefore, if the alternate valuation election is made, it is possible for some but not all of the assets to be included in the decedent\'s estate at a higher FMV than on the date of death. The key issue is that the election for alternate valuation may not be made unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the total net estate and GST taxes. If all the assets increased in value, the key rule would be violated.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(144,6,'John died on June 1, 2024. After determining that an estate tax return will be required, his executor decided to use the alternate valuation date for valuing the gross estate. Which of the following dates will be the alternate valuation date?','[\"April 15, 2025\",\"December 31, 2024\",\"December 1, 2024\",\"On or before the due date of the federal estate tax return\"]',2,'If the alternate valuation method is used to value property that is included in the gross estate, it must be in agreement with the following applicable dates:nnAny property distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of or separated or passed from the gross estate by any method within 6 months after the decedent\'s death is valued on the date of distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition.nAny property not distributed, sold, exchanged, or otherwise disposed of within the 6-month period is valued on the date 6 months after the date of the decedent\'s death.nAny property, interest, or estate that is “affected by mere lapse of time” is valued as of the date of decedent\'s death or on the date of its distribution, sale, exchange, or other disposition, whichever occurs first.nAs an aside, once the election is made for the alternate valuation date, it may not be revoked.nnTherefore, if John\'s executor decided to use the alternate valuation date for valuing the gross estate, the assets would be valued 6 months from the date of death, December 1, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(145,6,'Anil is a U.S. resident. His grandfather resides in Canada. Unbeknownst to Anil, when Anil turned 21, his grandfather opened a certificate of deposit account in Canada with Anil as the transfer-on-death beneficiary of the account. His grandfather passed away in 2022. The highest balance in the Canadian account for each year was $8,000 (in 2022), $12,000 (2023) and $15,000 (2024). Anil found out about the account and his FBAR filing requirement in 2023. What is Anil’s best option to disclose his beneficiary interest in the Canadian account? In considering your answer, assume the IRS has not commenced any civil action or sent any examination notices to Anil.','[\"Anil should just amend his 2022 and 2023 tax returns and include his FBAR information.\",\"Anil should submit his delinquent FBAR forms under the streamlined filing compliance procedures program.\",\"Anil is not required to file an FBAR since he did not know about the existence of this account.\",\"Anil should file a current FBAR for the year 2024 listing the Canadian account on his 2024 FBAR submission with the highest balance of $15,000. Anil should also submit his 2023 FBAR as a late filer and amend his 2023 and 2022 tax returns to include any interest he may have accrued from the certificate of deposit.\"]',3,'Since Anil’s failure to file was not due to negligence and was not willful, he can submit a late FBAR filing for 2023, and select “did not know I had to file\" as the reason why he is filing late. For 2022, he did not have a filing requirement. To the extent he earned interest in 2022 and 2023, Anil should amend his tax returns to include the additional income.nnThe streamlined filing compliance is for taxpayers who were negligent, but non-willful, which is not Anil’s case. Amending the returns without any FBAR filing would make Anil delinquent on his foreign asset reporting. Even though Anil did not know about the existence of the account, he needs to show he took steps to remedy the situation as soon as he received pertinent information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(146,6,'Which of the following is true regarding the Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR) requirements?','[\"The FinCEN Form 114 (FBAR) must be filed by anyone with any type of foreign bank accounts.\",\"The due date for the FBAR filing is generally July 15 of the current tax year for individuals.\",\"The FinCEN Form 114 (FBAR) must be filed with the current tax year\'s individual income tax return.\",\"The FinCEN Form 114 (FBAR) is filed online with the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network.\"]',3,'Publication 54, page 8, provides that a taxpayer must file Form 114, Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR), if they had any financial interest in, or signature or other authority over, a bank, securities, or other financial account in a foreign country.nnAlso, a taxpayer does not need to file the report if the assets are with a U.S. military banking facility operated by a financial institution or if the combined assets in the account(s) are $10,000 or less during the entire year.nnFinally, Form 114 is filed electronically with the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN). See the filing instructions at the BSA (Bank Secrecy Act) e-filing system web page at www.bsaefiling.fincen.treas.gov.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(147,6,'On December 15, 2024, Kyle received a $10,000 distribution from his father\'s estate. On March 30, 2025, Kyle was issued Schedule K-1 for the estate\'s first fiscal year (February 1, 2024, through January 31, 2025). The Schedule K-1 from the estate showed taxable interest income of $200 and had no other entries. Based on the information above, which of the following statements is true?','[\"Kyle must report income of $10,000 on his 2025 return.\",\"Kyle must report $200 interest income on his 2025 return.\",\"Kyle may claim a deduction on Schedule A for a pro rata share of the estate tax that was paid by the estate.\",\"Kyle must report $200 interest income on his 2025 return, and Kyle may claim a deduction on Schedule A for a pro rata share of the estate tax that was paid by the estate.\"]',0,'If income from the estate is credited or must be distributed to a beneficiary for a tax year, he or she reports that income (even if not distributed) on his or her return for that year. Other income from the estate is reported on his or her return for the year in which it was received. However, if the beneficiary\'s tax year is different from the estate\'s tax year, the amounts must be reported on the beneficiary\'s return for the tax year in which the last day of the estate\'s tax year falls.nn nn 	Different Tax Years\' Example	 n 	 	 n 	nIf the tax year of the estate is a fiscal year ending on June 30, 2024, and the beneficiary\'s tax year is the calendar year, the beneficiary will include in gross income for the tax year ending December 31, 2024, his or her share of the estate\'s distributable net income distributed or required to be distributed during the fiscal year ending the previous June 30.nn n nnEach beneficiary (or nominee of a beneficiary) who receives a distribution from the estate for the tax year, or to whom any item is allocated must receive a Schedule K-1 or substitute.nnAs a result, Kyle must report $200 interest income on his 2025 return, the tax year in which the last day of the estate\'s tax year falls, January 31, 2025',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(148,6,'Bob and Mary were divorced on July 1, 2024. Prior to their divorce, on June 20, they agreed to gift a jointly held income property to their only son. What is the last day on which the transfer must be completed so that the couple may elect to split the gift on their Forms 709, United States Gift (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return?','[\"December 31, 2023\",\"April 15, 2024\",\"June 30, 2024\",\"December 31, 2024\"]',2,'While a married couple may not file a joint gift tax return, the IRS permits spouses to split gifts under certain conditions. If both spouses agree, all gifts during the calendar year will be considered as made one-half by each spouse if:nnboth spouses were married to one another at the time of the gift,ndivorced or widowed after the gift, the spouse did not remarry during the rest of the calendar year,nneither of the spouses was a nonresident alien at the time of the gift, andna spouse was not given a general power of appointment over the property interest transferred.nHence, Bob and Mary must complete the transfer before the divorce is finalized. In this case, June 30, 2024, would be the best response for the couple to be able to “split” the gift.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(149,6,'A decedent\'s estate may be allowed a credit for estate taxes previously paid on the property if a decedent\'s estate includes property that was received from a person who died:','[\"within 10 years before or 4 years after the decedent received the gift.\",\"within 8 years before or 4 years after the decedent received the gift.\",\"within 10 years before or 2 years after the decedent received the gift.\",\"within 12 years before or 2 years after the decedent received the gift.\"]',2,'If a decedent received property from a person (transferor) who died within 10 years before or 2 years after the decedent, a credit is allowable for all or part of the federal estate tax paid by the transferor\'s estate with respect to the transfer. There is no requirement that the property be identified in the estate of the decedent or that it exists on the date of the decedent\'s death. It is sufficient for the allowance of the credit that the transfer of the property was subject to federal estate tax in the estate of the transferor and that the specified period of time has not elapsed.nnIf the transferee was the transferor\'s surviving spouse, no credit is allowed for property received from the transferor to the extent that a marital deduction was allowed to the transferor\'s estate for the property. There is no credit for tax on prior transfers for federal gift taxes paid in connection with the transfer of the property to the transferee. (Form 706 Instructions, page 44)nn(See the instructions for Form 706 for further details on spousal transactions.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(150,6,'When must a Form 706, United States Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Tax Return, be filed after the date of the decedent\'s death, unless an extension of time to file is received?','[\"3 months\",\"3 months and 15 days\",\"6 months\",\"9 months\"]',3,'The Form 706 to report estate and/or generation-skipping transfer tax must be filed within 9 months after the date of the decedent\'s death unless an extension of time to file has been approved. Form 4768, Application for Extension of Time to File a Return and/or Pay U.S. Estate (and Generation-Skipping Transfer) Taxes, is used to apply for an automatic 6-month extension of time to file.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(151,6,'For a decedent dying in 2024, Form 706 must be filed by the executor for the estate of every U.S. citizen whose gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemption:','[\"exceeds $12,920,000.\",\"exceeds $12,060,000.\",\"exceeds $13,610,000.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Pursuant to the instructions for Form 706, page 1, Form 706 must be filed by the executor for the estate of every U.S. citizen whose gross estate, plus adjusted taxable gifts and specific exemption, exceeds $13,610,000 for a decedent dying in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(152,6,'Which of the following statements is not correct concerning the gross estate?','[\"It includes only property that was owned and in the possession of the decedent at the time of death.\",\"It includes dower or curtesy of the surviving spouse.\",\"It includes real property outside the United States in which the decedent had an interest.\",\"It includes property over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment.\"]',0,'The gross estate is valued at the date of death and includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). (Form 706 Instructions, page 2)nnIt also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);ndigital assets;nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(153,6,'Which of the following is correct concerning the executor of an estate and the alternate valuation date election?','[\"The executor can change his\\/her mind and use the date of death as the valuation date by amending the estate tax return (Form 706) within 1 year of the date of death.\",\"The election to adopt an alternate valuation can be made after the date in which the return is filed.\",\"The alternate valuation date election is\\u00a0not\\u00a0revocable.\",\"The election for alternate valuation may be made if it will increase both the value of the gross estate and the total net estate and GST taxes due after application of all allowable credits.\"]',2,'Unless the election to adopt an alternate valuation is made at the time the return is filed, the value of all property included in the gross estate will be the value on the date of the decedent\'s death. Alternate valuation cannot be applied to only a part of the property.nnThe election for alternate valuation may not be made unless the election will decrease both the value of the gross estate and the sum (reduced by allowable credits) of the estate and GST (generation-skipping transfer) taxes payable by reason of the decedent\'s death for property includible in the decedent\'s gross estate.nnOnce the election for alternate valuation is made, the election may not be revoked.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(154,6,'What character does income that is distributed to an estate beneficiary retain when reported on the beneficiary\'s income tax return?','[\"The same character for the beneficiary that it had for the estate\",\"Ordinary income\",\"Capital income\",\"It depends on the election made by the executor or executrix.\"]',0,'An amount distributed to a beneficiary for inclusion in gross income retains the same character for the beneficiary that it had for the estate.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(155,6,'Edwin gave his grandson, Todd, $32,000. Todd is 15 years old and lives with his parents. Which of the following statements regarding the generation-skipping transfer tax is true?','[\"Because the gift is subject to the generation-skipping transfer tax, it is\\u00a0not\\u00a0subject to the regular gift tax.\",\"The gift is subject to both the regular gift tax and the generation-skipping transfer tax.\",\"The gift is\\u00a0not\\u00a0subject to the generation-skipping transfer tax because Todd\'s parents are still alive.\",\"If Edwin had transferred the funds into a trust solely for his grandson\'s benefit, the gift would\\u00a0not\\u00a0be subject to the generation-skipping transfer tax.\"]',0,'The federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, in 2024 an exclusion of $18,000 is allowed for a gift of a present interest. (Form 709 Instructions, page 2)nnAdditionally, the generation-skipping transfer (GST) tax will apply when a transfer is subject to the gift tax, is of an interest in property, and is made to a “skip” person. A GST must be reported on Form 709 when it is imposed only on inter vivos direct skips. An inter vivos direct skip is a transfer that satisfies all three conditions: subject to the gift tax, of an interest in property, and made to a skip person. A “skip” person is a person (e.g., grandson) who is assigned to a generation that is two or more generations below the generation assignment of the donor (Edwin). (Form 709 Instructions, page 8) Please note the Internal Revenue Code also provides for an annual exclusion, just as it does for gift taxes. A taxpayer can give away up to $18,000 per person per year as of 2024 without incurring the GST.nnGiven that the gift exceeds the $18,000 exclusion, and the gift was made to a “skip” person, $14,000 of the gift ($32,000 − $18,000) is subject to both the regular gift tax and the generation-skipping transfer tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(156,6,'The annual gift tax exclusion amount is allowed on which of the following gifts?','[\"$36,000 cash to Friend A\",\"$36,000 car to Friend B\",\"$36,000 remainder interest to Friend C\",\"$36,000 cash to Friend A and $36,000 car to Friend B\"]',3,'The annual gift tax exclusion is allowed for gifts of present interest only. Gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. A gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date. Future interests include reversions, remainders, and other similar interests or estates.nnThus, the annual gift tax exclusion ($18,000 per person in 2024) is allowed for both the $36,000 gift of cash and $36,000 gift of a car but disallowed for the future gift, the $36,000 remainder interest to Friend C.nnBe aware that although there are three correct responses for this question, the best of the three responses is the correct answer. The best response is \"$36,000 cash to Friend A and $36,000 car to Friend B\" and hence the correct answer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(157,6,'Tom, who is married, gave a vase worth $40,000 to his sister, Julie. Tom\'s basis in the vase is $10,000. What amount will Tom report as the value of the gift on Form 709?','[\"$10,000\",\"$28,000\",\"$30,000\",\"$40,000\"]',3,'The value of a gift is the fair market value (FMV) of the property on the date the gift is made (valuation date). The FMV is the price at which the property would change hands between a willing buyer and a willing seller, when neither is forced to buy or to sell, and when both have reasonable knowledge of all relevant facts.nnTherefore, Tom will report a value of $40,000 for the gift on Form 709.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(158,6,'Under which of the following conditions is gift splitting not permitted even if both spouses agree to gift splitting?','[\"Divorced after the gift\",\"Widowed before the gift and the surviving spouse does not remarry during the rest of the calendar year\",\"Neither of the spouses was a nonresident alien at the time of the gift.\",\"A spouse was not given a general power of appointment over the property interest transferred.\"]',0,'While a married couple may not file a joint gift tax return, the IRS permits spouses to split gifts under certain conditions. If both spouses agree, all gifts during the calendar year will be considered as made one-half by each spouse if:nnboth spouses were married to one another at the time of the gift,ndivorced or widowed after the gift, the spouse did not remarry during the rest of the calendar year,nneither of the spouses was a nonresident alien at the time of the gift, andna spouse was not given a general power of appointment over the property interest transferred.nAccordingly, if a husband and wife elect gift splitting, then both spouses must file their own, individual gift tax return. As such, the liability for the entire gift tax of each spouse is joint and several.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(159,6,'Forrester gave his son $20,000 in stock that he had inherited from his father. His wife, Martha, gave no gifts during the year. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"No\\u00a0gift tax return is filed because the gift amount is less than the annual exclusion amount under gift splitting.\",\"A gift tax return is filed no matter what the gift amount is.\",\"A gift tax return is filed because the gift amount is greater than the annual exclusion amount for Forrester.\",\"No\\u00a0gift tax return is filed because the gift was inherited by Forrester.\"]',2,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, a gift of a present interest may be excluded. Gifts of a future interest cannot be excluded under the annual exclusion. (Form 709 Instructions, page 2)nnA gift is considered a present interest if the donee has immediate rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property. A gift is considered a future interest if the donee\'s rights to the use, possession, and enjoyment of the property or income from the property will not begin until some future date. (Form 709 Instructions, page 3)nnWhile a married couple may not file a joint gift tax return, the IRS permits spouses to split gifts under certain conditions. If both spouses agree, all gifts (including gifts of property held with the spouse as joint tenants or tenants by the entirety) during the calendar year will be considered as made one-half by each spouse. In this case, no mention is made of gift splitting; hence, we must assume that one is not considered. However, for tax purposes, we should advise the client that such an opportunity may be possible. (Form 709 Instructions, page 6)nnFor 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000.nnGiven that Forrester\'s gift to his son during the year exceeded the $18,000 exclusion and, apparently, the couple did not elect or are not qualified to split the gift, he is required to file a gift tax return. If, on the other hand, gift splitting was permitted and elected by the couple, a gift tax return would be needed regardless of the gift amount.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(160,6,'During calendar-year 2024, John made the following payments:nn$18,000 to a qualified political partyn$20,000 to a local hospital for his mother\'s recent operationn$25,000 to the state university for his nephew\'s tuition expensen$18,000 to his favorite qualified charitynWhat is the gross amount that John must report on his gift tax return (Form 709)?','[\"John does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to file a gift tax return for the calendar year 2024.\",\"$81,000\",\"$63,000\",\"$18,000\"]',0,'There are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. Qualifying transfers to political organizations must be to political organizations as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) and must be for the use of the organization.nnFor transfers to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual. Furthermore, for a transfer to qualify for the medical exclusion, the amounts must be paid directly to the person or institution that provided the medical care.nnIf the only gifts the taxpayer made during the year are deductible as gifts to charities, the taxpayer does not need to file a return as long as the taxpayer transferred his or her entire interest in the property to qualifying charities. If the taxpayer is required to file a return to report noncharitable gifts and the taxpayer made gifts to charities, the taxpayer must include all of his or her gifts to charities on the return.nnGiven that John\'s transfers qualify as transfers not subject to the gift tax, he is not required to file a gift tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(161,6,'Which of the following statements is incorrect concerning the election to split gifts?','[\"It may be made on an amended Form 709 if it is filed within 3 years after the due date of the original return.\",\"It may be signed after April 15 following the end of the year in which the gift was made.\",\"It may be signed after a notice of deficiency for the gift tax for the year has been sent to either the taxpayer or the taxpayer\'s spouse.\",\"All of the answer choices are incorrect.\"]',3,'In order for the gift-splitting election to be valid, a spousal consent must be signed. Generally, the consent may be signed at any time after the end of the calendar year.nnHowever, there are two exceptions:nnThe consent may not be signed after April 15 following the end of the year in which the gift was made.nThe consent may not be signed after a notice of deficiency for the gift tax for the year has been sent to either the taxpayer or the taxpayer\'s spouse.nGiven the above rules, an election to split gifts may not be made on an amended Form 709. Therefore, all of the answer choices are incorrect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(162,6,'During 2024, Rebecca made the following potentially taxable gifts:nn$1,000 to the Democratic Partyn$5,000 to a local university for her nephew\'s tuitionn$10,000 to a local university for her nephew\'s room and boardn$21,000 to a local hospital for her sister\'s surgerynSold land with a fair market value of $22,000 to her brother for $100nWhat is the total of Rebecca\'s taxable gifts for the year 2024','[\"$36,000\",\"$28,900\",\"$22,000\",\"$3,900\"]',3,'Generally, the federal gift tax applies to any transfer by gift of real or personal property, whether tangible or intangible, that is made directly or indirectly, in trust, or by any other means to a donee. However, an exclusion is allowed for a gift of a present interest. For 2024, the annual exclusion is $18,000.nnThere are four types of transfers that are not subject to the gift tax. These are transfers to political organizations, transfers to certain exempt organizations, and payments that qualify for the educational and medical exclusions. Qualifying transfers to political organizations must be to political organizations as defined in IRC Section 527(e)(1) and must be for the use of the organization.nnFor transfers to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amount paid on behalf of an individual must be paid to a qualifying domestic or foreign educational organization as tuition for the education or training of the individual. Furthermore, for a transfer to qualify for the educational exclusion, the amounts must be paid directly to the qualifying educational organization and it must be for tuition. In addition, the gift tax does not apply to an amount paid on behalf of an individual to a person or institution that provided the medical care for the individual. (Form 709 Instructions, pages 1–3)nnMoreover, if property is sold or exchanged for less than fair market value with the intent of making a gift, the transaction is partly a sale or exchange and partly a gift. (Publication 544, page 4)nnTherefore, Rebecca\'s total taxable gifts for the year 2024 are $3,900, calculated as follows:nn                        Gift  -  Exclusion = Taxable Giftn  Room and Board     $ 10,000     $18,000            0n  Land                 21,900      18,000        3,900n  Total Taxable Gifts                           $3,900',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(163,6,'When e-filing a taxpayer’s federal return, which of the following is correct in the case where the taxpayer meets the requirements to file both Form 8938, Statement of Specified Foreign Financial Assets, and Form 114, Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts?','[\"Send both forms in separately to the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Attach only the Form 114 as it contains the Form 8938 information\",\"Attach only the Form 8938 and file the Form 114 separately\",\"Attach both forms to their federal return\"]',2,'The Form 8938 Instructions, page 1, provide that the purpose of this form is to report specified foreign financial assets if the total value of all the specified foreign financial assets in which the taxpayer has an interest is more than the appropriate reporting threshold. The threshold amounts vary by the taxpayer’s filing status and are given on pages 3 and 4 of the Form 8938 Instructions.nnForm 8938 is attached to a taxpayer’s annual return (or an amended return) and is filed by the due date (including extensions) for that return.nnPublication 54, page 8, provides that a taxpayer must file Fin CEN Form 114, Report of Foreign Bank and Financial Accounts (FBAR), if they had any financial interest in, or signature or other authority over, a bank, securities, or other financial account in a foreign country.nnAlso, a taxpayer does not need to file the report if the assets are with a U.S. military banking facility operated by a financial institution or if the combined assets in the account(s) are $10,000 or less during the entire year.nnFinally, Form 114 is filed electronically with the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN). See the filing instructions at the BSA (Bank Secrecy Act) e-filing system web page at www.bsaefiling.fincen.treas.gov.nnThus, the taxpayer needs to file Form 8938 with their tax return and Form 114 is electronically submitted separately with the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(164,7,'Which of the following situations is reported on Form 1099-MISC?','[\"Payment of non-employee compensation of $600 or more\",\"Payments of rent of $400\",\"Payments of $5 in royalty income\",\"Payments made to a physician or other supplier or provider of medical or healthcare services of $600 or more made in your trade or business\"]',3,'x`Form 1099-MISC is used for:nnAt least $10 in royalties or broker payments in lieu of dividends or tax-exempt interestnAt least $600 in rents, prizes and awards, other income payments, the cash paid from a specific interval contract to individuals, partnerships or estates, fishing boat proceeds, medical and health care payments, crop insurance proceeds, gross proceeds paid to an attorney, IRC Section 409A deferrals, or non-qualified deferred compensation.nPayments from which federal taxes are withheld due to backup withholding.nBased on the information provided above, payments made to a physician or other supplier or provider of medical or healthcare services of $600 or more made in your trade or business.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(165,7,'Which of the following items is not an adjustment or tax preference item for computing alternative minimum tax?','[\"Subtraction of any refund of state and local taxes\",\"Standard deduction\",\"Interest income\",\"Itemized deduction for state and local taxes\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 108, provides a list of the more common adjustments and tax preference items in computing the alternative minimum tax (AMT). The list includes:nnaddition of the standard deduction (if claimed),naddition of itemized deductions claimed for state and local taxes, certain interest, most miscellaneous deductions, and part of medical expenses,nsubtraction of any refund of state and local taxes included in gross income,nchanges to accelerated depreciation of certain property,ndifference between gain and loss on the sale of property reported for regular tax purposes and AMT purposes,naddition of certain income from incentive stock options,nchange in certain passive activity loss deductions,naddition of certain depletion that is more than the adjusted basis of the property,naddition of part of the deduction for certain intangible drilling costs, andnaddition of tax-exempt interest on certain private activity bonds.nAdditional information about the alternative minimum tax can be found in the instructions for Form 6251, Alternative Minimum Tax—Individuals.nnGiven the information above, interest income is not a tax preference item or adjustment to taxable income for AMT purposes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(166,7,'Joyce and Arron are married and file a joint tax return in 2024. Joyce has $150,000 in wages and Arron has $130,000 in wages. Neither employer withheld Additional Medicare Tax from the couple\'s wages. What amount is subject to the Additional Medicare Tax for the couple on their 2024 tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$30,000\",\"$80,000\",\"$280,000\"]',1,'As provided in the instructions for Form 8959, page 1, all wages that are currently subject to Medicare tax are subject to Additional Medicare Tax to the extent they exceed the threshold amount for the taxpayer\'s filing status. Thus, Medicare wages and self-employment income are combined to determine if a taxpayer\'s income exceeds the threshold amount. Since Joyce and Arron\'s wages of $280,000 exceed the threshold amount of $250,000 for a married couple filing jointly, the couple is subject to the Additional Medicare Tax on $30,000, which is the excess amount ($280,000 − $250,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(167,7,'What is the total amount a sole proprietor is obligated to report on Form 1099-NEC based on the following expenses claimed on Schedule C?Attorneys\' fees to incorporated law firm: $600Sign painter: $800 ($600 labor and $200 materials)Web page designer: $500Incorporated janitorial company: $800Consultant A: $1,000 ($400 paid in cash and $600 paid by check)Consultant B: $500 paid in cashConsultant C: $400 paid by check','[\"$1,400\",\"$1,600\",\"$2,000\",\"$2,400\"]',3,'Form 1099-NEC is used to report compensation of $600 or more to non-employees. Compensation can include fees, commissions, prizes, awards, and other forms of payment.rnrnAdditionally, the Instructions for Form 1099-MISC and 1099-NEC, page 2, states that proceeds paid to an attorney are to be included in box 10 of Form 1099-NEC provided the following conditions are met:rnrnPayments are made to an attorney in the course of your trade or business in connection with legal services;rnTotal $600 or more; and rnAre not reportable in box 1 of Form 1099-NEC.rnThe correct answer is $2,400, which is computed as follows:rnrn$600 to the law firm + $800 to the sign painter + $1,000 to Consultant A = $2,400.Form 1099-NEC is used to report compensation of $600 or more to non-employees. Compensation can include fees, commissions, prizes, awards, and other forms of payment.rnrnAdditionally, the Instructions for Form 1099-MISC and 1099-NEC, page 2, states that proceeds paid to an attorney are to be included in box 10 of Form 1099-NEC provided the following conditions are met:rnrnPayments are made to an attorney in the course of your trade or business in connection with legal services;rnTotal $600 or more; and rnAre not reportable in box 1 of Form 1099-NEC.rnThe correct answer is $2,400, which is computed as follows:rnrn$600 to the law firm + $800 to the sign painter + $1,000 to Consultant A = $2,400.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(168,7,'The tax law gives special treatment to certain types of income and allows special deductions and credits for certain types of expenses. Taxpayers who benefit from the law in these ways may have to calculate the alternative minimum tax (AMT). A review of Jamie’s past 5 years of tax returns shows he paid AMT for 2023 and had a minimum tax credit carryforward to 2024. Which of the following statements is applicable to Jamie for his 2024 tax return?','[\"He may be eligible to take a credit for the prior-year minimum tax.\",\"He may be eligible to take a refundable credit for the prior-year minimum tax.\",\"He may be eligible to take both a refundable and nonrefundable credit for the prior-year minimum tax.\",\"He is not eligible to take a credit for the prior-year minimum tax.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 108, states, in part, that the tax law gives special treatment to some kinds of income and allows special deductions and credits for some kinds of expenses. Taxpayers who benefit from the law in these ways may have to pay at least a minimum amount of tax through an additional tax (not a tax credit). This additional tax is called the alternative minimum tax (AMT).nnThe special treatment of some items of income and expenses only allows taxpayers to postpone paying tax until a later year. If in prior years the taxpayer paid alternative minimum tax because of these tax postponement items, they may be able to take a credit for prior-year minimum tax against their current year\'s regular tax. The taxpayer may be able to take a credit against their regular tax if for 2024 they had:nnan alternative minimum tax liability and adjustments or preferences other than exclusion items,na minimum tax credit that they are carrying forward to 2025, ornan unallowed qualified electric vehicle credit.nIn this case, Jamie may be eligible to claim a nonrefundable credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(169,7,'Richard has $180,000 in self-employment income and $100,000 in retirement income. His employer does not withhold Additional Medicare Tax. What amount is subject to the Additional Medicare Tax for Richard on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$80,000\",\"$180,000\",\"$280,000\"]',0,'As provided in the instructions for Form 8959, page 1, all wages that are currently subject to Medicare tax are subject to Additional Medicare Tax to the extent they exceed the threshold amount for the taxpayer\'s filing status. Thus, Medicare wages and self-employment income are combined to determine if a taxpayer\'s income exceeds the threshold amount. Retirement income is not considered Medicare wages; as such, James\' retirement income is not added to his Medicare wages. Since James\' Medicare wages of $180,000 are below the threshold amount of $200,000 for a single taxpayer, he is not subject to this tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(170,7,'Which of the following early distributions from an IRA is not an exception to the early distribution excise tax?','[\"An early distribution caused by an IRS levy of the qualified plan\",\"An early distribution due to the taxpayer being totally and permanently disabled\",\"An early distribution that is not more than the taxpayer\'s qualified higher education expenses\",\"None of the answer choices are subject to the early distribution excise tax.\"]',3,'Publication 590-B, page 25, provides the general exceptions to the early distribution excise tax penalty. The following are some exceptions to this excise tax:nnThe taxpayer has unreimbursed medical expenses that are more than 7.5% of the taxpayer\'s AGI.nThe distributions are not more than the cost of the taxpayer\'s medical insurance due to a period of unemployment.nThe taxpayer is totally and permanently disabled.nThe taxpayer is the beneficiary of a deceased IRA owner.nThe taxpayer is receiving distributions in the form of an annuity.nThe distributions are not more than the taxpayer\'s qualified higher education expenses.nThe taxpayer uses the distributions to buy, build, or rebuild a first home.nThe distribution is due to an IRS levy of the qualified plan.nThe distribution is a qualified reservist distribution.nAs given in the listing above, all three distributions are exceptions to the early distribution penalty.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThis question is worded quite oddly, with a negative question and a negative correct response.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(171,7,'Donna has $145,000 in self-employment income and $140,000 in wages. Her employer does not withhold Additional Medicare Tax. Which of the following statements is correct for Donna\'s 2024 tax return?','[\"She is not required to pay the Additional Medicare Tax because neither income amount exceeds the threshold amount of $200,000.\",\"She is not required to pay the Additional Medicare Tax because her employer failed to withhold the tax on her behalf.\",\"She is required to pay the Additional Medicare Tax because her total Medicare wages are greater than $200,000.\",\"None of the responses are correct.\"]',2,'As provided in the instructions for Form 8959, page 1, all wages that are currently subject to Medicare tax are subject to Additional Medicare Tax to the extent they exceed the threshold amount for the taxpayer\'s filing status. Thus, Medicare wages and self-employment income are combined to determine if a taxpayer\'s income exceeds the threshold amount. In the case of a single taxpayer, the threshold amount is $200,000.nnIn Donna’s case, she is required to pay the Additional Medicare Tax because her total Medicare wages are $285,000 ($145,000 + $140,000), which is greater than $200,000.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nCarl, a single filer, has $145,000 in self-employment income and $130,000 in wages. Carl\'s wages do not exceed $200,000. Therefore, Carl\'s employer did not withhold Additional Medicare Tax. However, the $130,000 of wages reduces the self-employment income threshold to $70,000 ($200,000 threshold minus the $130,000 of wages). Carl is liable to pay Additional Medicare Tax on $75,000 of self-employment income ($145,000 in self-employment income minus the reduced threshold of $70,000). Carl must file Form 8959.nnInstructions for Form 8959, Example 3, page 2',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(172,7,'Maria has a traditional IRA, from which she has taken a taxable distribution of $8,000. Under which of the following circumstances will the distribution be subject to the 10% penalty for premature distributions?','[\"Maria\'s AGI is $30,000, and she had $13,000 in unreimbursed deductible medical expenses which exceed 10% of her adjusted gross income.\",\"Maria\'s granddaughter is a sophomore in college, and Maria paid her tuition expenses of $10,000.\",\"Maria is age 57, the distribution is not part of a series of equal periodic payments, and she has no qualifying expenses or conditions.\",\"The distribution was made pursuant to an IRS levy on Maria\'s IRA.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 590-B, page 25, distributions before the taxpayer is age 59-1/2 are called early distributions. Most early distributions from a traditional IRA result in a 10% additional tax on the distribution of any assets (money or other property).nnThere are several exceptions to the age 59-1/2, which means some early distributions are not subject to the 10% additional tax. A list of these exceptions is given below and can be found in Publication 590-B, beginning on page 25:nnThe taxpayer has unreimbursed medical expenses that are more than 7.5% of the taxpayer\'s AGI.nThe distributions are not more than the cost of the taxpayer\'s medical insurance due to a period of unemployment.nThe taxpayer is totally and permanently disabled.nThe person is the beneficiary of a deceased IRA owner.nThe taxpayer is receiving distributions in the form of an annuity.nThe distributions are not more than the taxpayer\'s qualified higher education expenses.nThe taxpayer uses the distributions to buy, build, or rebuild a first home.nThe distribution is due to an IRS levy of the qualified plan.nThe distribution is a qualified reservist distribution.nIn Maria\'s case, she cannot avoid the excise tax penalty because she is age 57 (under age 59-1/2), the distribution is not a series of equal periodic payments, and she has no qualifying expenses or conditions.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(173,7,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to unused alternative minimum tax credits?','[\"They may be carried back 2 years and then forward 20 years.\",\"They may be carried forward and used against other income.\",\"They may be carried forward and used against other deferral-type preferences.\",\"They may\\u00a0not\\u00a0be carried back or forward.\"]',2,'The tax laws give special treatment to some kinds of income and allow special deductions and credits for some kinds of expenses. If a taxpayer benefits from these laws, they may have to pay at least a minimum amount of tax in addition to any other tax on their tax return. This is called the alternative minimum tax.nnThe special treatment of some items of income and expenses only allows a taxpayer to postpone paying tax until a later year. If in prior years a taxpayer paid alternative minimum tax (AMT) because of these tax postponement items, the taxpayer may be able to take a credit for prior-year minimum tax against his or her current-year regular tax.nnThe AMT is attributable to two types of adjustments and preferences—deferral items and exclusion items. Deferral items (for example, depreciation) generally do not cause a permanent difference in taxable income over time. Exclusion items (for example, the standard deduction), on the other hand, do cause a permanent difference. The minimum tax credit is allowed only for the AMT attributable to deferral items (Form 8801 Instructions, page 1).nnMore specifically, a taxpayer may be able to take a credit against his or her regular tax if for 2024 the taxpayer had:nnan alternative minimum tax liability and adjustments or preferences other than exclusion items,na minimum tax credit that is being carried forward to 2024, ornan unallowed qualified electric vehicle credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(174,7,'Randy Lee is an ordained minister of a tax-exempt church. Randy receives a salary plus a housing allowance for rent and utilities. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Randy must claim as income on his return all of his salary and all of his housing allowance. The salary is subject to income tax and self-employment tax, but his housing allowance is subject to income tax only.\",\"Randy has to pay both income tax and self-employment tax on his salary, but only self-employment tax for the housing allowance. The housing allowance is not subject to income tax.\",\"Randy does not have to report any income received from the church because the church is tax-exempt.\",\"Randy only has to pay the self-employment tax on both his salary and the housing allowance. Neither is subject to income tax.\"]',1,'Publication 517, page 9, states, in part, that a member of the clergy must include in income offerings and fees received for marriages, baptisms, funerals, masses, etc. in addition to the taxpayer\'s salary. If the offering is made to the religious institution and not the minister, the amount is not taxable to the minister.nnSpecial rules for housing apply to members of the clergy. Under these rules, they don’t include in income the rental value of a home (including utilities) or a designated housing allowance provided to them as part of their pay. However, the exclusion can’t be more than the reasonable pay for their services. If the minister pays for the utilities, they can exclude any allowance designated for utility cost, up to the actual cost. The home or allowance must be provided as compensation for their services as an ordained, licensed, or commissioned minister.nnHowever, the minister must include the rental value of the home or the housing allowance as earnings from self-employment on Schedule SE (Form 1040) if they are subject to the self-employment tax. (Publication 517, page 9).nnServices include ministerial services, administrative duties and teaching at theological seminaries, and the ordinary duties of a minister performed as an employee of the United States (other than as a chaplain in the Armed Forces), a state, a possession, a political subdivision, or the District of Columbia. This exclusion applies only for income tax purposes. It does not apply for self-employment tax purposes. (Publication 517, page 9)nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nRev. Joanna Baker is a full-time minister. The church allows her to use a parsonage that has an annual fair rental value of $24,000. The church pays her an annual salary of $67,000, of which $7,500 is designated for utility costs. Her actual utility costs during the year were $7,000.nnFor income tax purposes, Rev. Baker excludes $31,000 from gross income ($24,000 for fair rental value of the parsonage plus $7,000 from the allowance for utility costs). She will report $60,000 ($59,500 salary plus $500 of unused utility allowance). Her income for self-employment tax purposes, however, is $91,000 ($67,000 salary plus $24,000 fair rental value of the parsonage).nn n nnFor more information, see Publication 517, Social Security and Other Information for Members of the Clergy and Religious Workers.nnMinister Lee in this case would pay both income tax and self-employment tax on his salary, but only self-employment tax for the housing allowance. His housing allowance would not be included in gross income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(175,7,'The Net Investment Income Tax may apply to which of the following?','[\"Alimony\",\"Traditional IRA distribution\",\"Taxable mutual fund distribution\",\"Tax exempt municipal bond interest\"]',2,'Net investment income is subject to an additional 3.8% Medicare tax for modified adjusted gross incomes over $250,000 for MFJ (Married Filing Jointly) and QSS (Qualifying Surviving Spouse), $125,000 for MFS (Married Filing Separately), and $200,000 for Single and HOH (Head of Household). This tax does not apply to wages, non-passive business income, alimony, retirement distributions, Social Security benefits, unemployment, tax-exempt interest, and Alaska Permanent Dividend funds.nnTherefore, the correct answer is taxable mutual fund distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(176,7,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the ABLE account?','[\"Distributions to pay for qualified disability expenses are not included in gross income.\",\"The earnings portion of a distribution in excess of qualified disability is included in gross income.\",\"Any distribution amount included in taxable income from an ABLE account is assessed an additional tax of 10%.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 907, pages 7–9, provides the general rules for the taxing of distributions from ABLE accounts. In general, a person can take distributions from their ABLE account to pay for any qualified disability expenses such as expenses for maintaining or improving their health, independence, or quality of life. Qualified disability expenses include those for education; housing; transportation; employment training and support; assistive technology; personal support services; health, prevention and wellness; financial management; administrative services; legal fees; expenses for oversight and monitoring; and funeral and burial.nnIf distributions from a person’s ABLE account during a year are not more than their qualified disability expenses for that year, no amount is taxable for that year. If the total amount distributed during a year is more than their qualified disability expenses for that year, the earnings portion of the distribution is included in their income for that year. The includible portion is calculated as follows:nn(Qualified portion of distribution ÷ Total distribution) × Earnings portion of distribution = Nontaxable earnings amountnIn addition, the tax on any distribution included in a person\'s taxable income is increased by 10%. This tax is figured on Form 5329, Part II, and is filed even if the taxpayer is not otherwise required to file a federal income tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(177,7,'Which of the following is correct regarding a personal casualty loss?','[\"Loss of property due to progressive deterioration is not deductible.\",\"It is reduced by the amount of your standard deduction.\",\"It must be less than 10% of your adjusted gross income.\",\"It is deducted over a three-year consecutive period.\"]',0,'Publication 547, page 5, states that damage resulting from a normal process rather than a sudden event is not deductible as a casualty loss. Page 15 explains that you must reduce federal casualty losses by $100, then by 10% of your adjusted gross income, but it does not have to be less than 10% of your adjusted gross income. The standard deduction is not part of the calculation, and the deduction is not spread over a three-year period.nnTherefore, the correct answer is that the loss of property due to progressive deterioration is not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(178,7,'All of the following items are an adjustment or tax preference item for computing alternative minimum tax, except:','[\"most itemized miscellaneous deductions.\",\"interest income.\",\"standard deduction.\",\"passive activity loss deductions.\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 108, provides a list of the more common adjustments and tax preference items in computing the alternative minimum tax (AMT). The list includes:nnaddition of the standard deduction (if claimed),naddition of itemized deductions claimed for state and local taxes, certain interest, most miscellaneous deductions, and part of medical expenses,nsubtraction of any refund of state and local taxes included in gross income,nchanges to accelerated depreciation of certain property,ndifference between gain and loss on the sale of property reported for regular tax purposes and AMT purposes,naddition of certain income from incentive stock options,nchange in certain passive activity loss deductions,naddition of certain depletion that is more than the adjusted basis of the property,naddition of part of the deduction for certain intangible drilling costs, andnaddition of tax-exempt interest on certain private activity bonds.nAdditional information about the nonrefundable credit for prior-year alternative minimum tax can be found in Form 6251, Alternative Minimum Tax—Individuals.nnGiven the information above, interest income is not a tax preference item or adjustment to taxable income for AMT purposes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(179,7,'Violet made no estimated tax payments for 2024 because she thought she had enough tax withheld from her wages. In January 2025, she realized that her withholding was $2,000 less than the amount needed to avoid a penalty for the underpayment of estimated tax, so she made an estimated tax payment of $2,500 on January 10. Violet filed her 2024 return on March 1, 2025, showing a refund due her of $100. Which of the following statements is not true regarding the estimated tax penalty?','[\"Violet will\\u00a0not\\u00a0owe a penalty for the quarter ending December 31, 2024, because she made sufficient payment before January 15, 2025.\",\"Violet will\\u00a0not\\u00a0owe a penalty for any quarter because her total payments exceed her tax liability.\",\"Violet could owe a penalty for 1 or all of the first 3 quarters even though she is due a refund for the year.\",\"If Violet owes a penalty for any quarter, the underpayment will be computed from the date the amount was due to the date the payment is made.\"]',1,'An underpayment of tax either through withholding or by making estimated tax payments may cause a penalty to be imposed. Generally, a taxpayer will not be subject to a penalty for 2024 if any of the following situations apply:nnTotal withholding and estimated tax payments are at least as much as the 2023 tax (or 110% of 2023 tax if adjusted gross income was more than $150,000, more than $75,000 if the taxpayer\'s filing status is married filing separately) and all required estimated tax payments were paid on time,nThe tax balance due is no more than 10% of the total 2024 tax, and all required estimated tax payments were paid on time,nTotal tax minus withholding is less than $1,000,nThere was not a tax liability for 2023 and the taxpayer\'s 2023 tax year was 12 months, ornThe taxpayer did not have any withholding taxes and current-year tax less any household employment taxes is less than $1,000.nIn addition, a penalty is figured separately for each installment due date. Therefore, a taxpayer may owe a penalty for an earlier due date even if the taxpayer paid enough tax later to make up the underpayment. This is true even if the taxpayer is due a refund when he or she files the tax return.nnThe statement that “Violet will not owe a penalty for any quarter because her total payments exceed her tax liability” is not covered by any of the above situations. Hence, it is the incorrect statement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(180,7,'Joyce and Eric are married and file a joint tax return in 2024. The couple have a son (age 24) who lives with them because he is totally disabled. The couple wish to establish an ABLE account on behalf of their son. Which of the following statements is correct concerning their ability to establish an ABLE account on behalf of their son in 2024?','[\"The maximum contribution the couple can make to the ABLE account is $36,000 ($18,000 each).\",\"An ABLE account can be established for the son because he is disabled.\",\"Contributions to an ABLE account are tax deductible for the person making the contribution.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',1,'As provided on pages 7–8 of Publication 907, contributions to an ABLE account are not tax deductible and must be in cash equivalents. Anyone, including the designated beneficiary, can contribute to an ABLE account. In addition, a person may establish an ABLE account if their blindness or disability occurred before age 26. As a disabled individual, a person may be eligible if either of the following applies:nnThe person is entitled to benefits based on blindness or disability under Title II or XVI of the Social Security Act, ornThe person files a disability certification with their qualified ABLE program, including their diagnosis relating to their relevant impairment or impairments signed by a physician (as defined in section 1861(r) of the Social Security Act). In addition, the person must certify one of the following:nThe person has a medically determinable physical or mental impairment, which results in marked and severe functional limitations, which can be expected to result in death or lasted or can be expected to last for a continuous period of not less than 12 months; ornThe person is blind (within the meaning of section 1614(a)(2) of the Social Security Act).nThe total annual contributions to an ABLE account (including those rolled over from a Section 529 account, but not other amounts received in rollovers and/or program-to-program transfers) are limited to the annual gift tax exclusion amount ($18,000 for 2024, not $18,000 per person), plus certain employed ABLE account beneficiaries may make an additional contribution up to the lesser of these amount:nnthe designated beneficiary\'s compensation for the tax year, ornthe poverty the continental United States of $15,060, $17,310 in Hawaii, and $18,810 in Alaska. (Publication 907, page 8)nTherefore, the only correct response is an ABLE account can be established for the couple’s son because he is disabled.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(181,7,'Which of the following is not a tax preference item or an adjustment to taxable income for alternative minimum tax purposes?','[\"Addition of personal exemptions\",\"Addition of the standard deduction (if claimed)\",\"Addition of all itemized deductions (if claimed)\",\"Subtraction of any refund of state and local taxes included in gross income\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 108, provides a list of the more common adjustments and tax preference items in computing the alternative minimum tax (AMT). The list includes the following items:nnAddition of the standard deduction (if claimed)nAddition of itemized deductions claimed for state and local taxes, certain interest, most miscellaneous deductions, and part of medical expensesnSubtraction of any refund of state and local taxes included in gross incomenChanges to accelerated depreciation of certain propertynDifference between gain and loss on the sale of property reported for regular tax purposes and AMT purposesnAddition of certain income from incentive stock optionsnChange in certain passive activity loss deductionsnAddition of certain depletion that is more than the adjusted basis of the propertynAddition of part of the deduction for certain intangible drilling costsnAddition of tax-exempt interest on certain private activity bondsnAdditional information about the alternative minimum tax can be found in the instructions for Form 1040 or 1040-SR, Schedule 2, line 1, and Form 6251, Alternative Minimum Tax—Individuals.nnGiven the information above, the addition of all itemized deductions, if claimed, is not a tax preference item or adjustment to taxable income for AMT purposes. The addition is limited to a select few itemized deductions as given above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(182,7,'What action should a taxpayer take regarding the repayment of Social Security benefits received in a prior year if the total figure shown in box 5 for all of the taxpayer’s current-year Forms SSA-1099 and RRB-1099 is a negative amount and the portion of the negative amount that represents benefits the taxpayer included in gross income in the prior year is $3,000 or less?','[\"The taxpayer must amend the prior-year return to claim a deduction on Schedule A (Form 1040), and it is\\u00a0not\\u00a0subject to the 2%-of-AGI limit that applies to certain miscellaneous itemized deductions.\",\"The taxpayer must amend the prior-year return to claim a deduction on Schedule A (Form 1040), and it is subject to the 2%-of-AGI limit that applies to certain miscellaneous itemized deductions.\",\"The taxpayer can claim a deduction on Schedule A (Form 1040) for the portion of the negative amount that represents benefits included in gross income in the prior year, and it is subject to the 2%-of-AGI limit that applies to certain miscellaneous itemized deductions.\",\"The taxpayer cannot claim a deduction because it is a miscellaneous itemized deduction and can no longer be deducted.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 17, pages 66 and 67, there are some situations where a taxpayer’s Form SSA-1099 or Form RRB-1099 will show that the total benefits repaid (box 4) are more than the gross benefits (box 3) received. If this occurred, the taxpayer’s net benefits in box 5 will be a negative figure (a figure in parentheses) and none of their benefits will be taxable.nnIf the total amount shown in box 5 of all the taxpayer’s Forms SSA-1099 and RRB-1099 is a negative figure, a taxpayer may be able to deduct the part of this negative figure that represents benefits they included in gross income in an earlier year if the figure is more than $3,000. If the figure is $3,000 or less, it is a miscellaneous itemized deduction and can no longer be deducted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(183,7,'A child may be subject to kiddie tax in the current year if:','[\"neither parent of the child is alive at the end of the year.\",\"the child is under age 18 at the end of the tax year.\",\"the child has only nontaxable income of more than $2,300.\",\"the child is required to file a tax return and he or she files a joint return for the year.\"]',1,'The kiddie tax was enacted to prevent parents from shifting income to their children in lower tax brackets. The kiddie tax applies if a child under age 18 has unearned income over $2,600. It may also apply to students ages 19–23 if their earned income is not more than half of their support. Any amount over $2,600 for 2024 is taxed at the parent’s rate.rnrnThe only correct answer is that the child is under 18. There is not enough information to determine if the child had sufficient income, but the other options are either incorrect or irrelevant. It is possible for a child under 18 to be subject to kiddie tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(184,7,'Which of the following statements is correct if a taxpayer files his 2024 Form 1040 by January 31, 2025, and pays the balance due with the return?','[\"He will\\u00a0not\\u00a0receive an underpayment of estimated tax penalty for the 4th-quarter estimated tax payment that was due on January 15, 2025.\",\"He may receive an underpayment of estimated tax penalty for the 4th-quarter estimated tax payment that was due on January 15, 2025.\",\"He is required to make the estimated tax payment that is due on January 15, 2025.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 42, provides a special rule for the January estimated tax payment. Specifically, if a taxpayer files his or her Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR by January 31 of the year the tax return is due and pays the rest of the tax owed, the taxpayer does not need to make the payment due on January 15, 2025.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(185,7,'Ted is an ordained minister. He owns his own home and receives a housing allowance. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"If the housing allowance is less than the fair rental value of the home, Ted\\u00a0must\\u00a0include the housing allowance as income for self-employment tax and\\u00a0may\\u00a0exclude it for income tax.\",\"If the housing allowance is less than the fair rental value of the home, Ted\\u00a0must\\u00a0include the housing allowance as income for income tax and self-employment tax.\",\"If the housing allowance is less than the fair rental value of the home, Ted\\u00a0must\\u00a0include the housing allowance as income for income tax and\\u00a0may\\u00a0exclude it for self-employment tax.\",\"If the housing allowance is less than the fair rental value of the home, Ted\\u00a0may\\u00a0exclude the housing allowance as income for self-employment tax and income tax.\"]',0,'Ministerial services, in general, are the services a taxpayer performs in the exercise of their ministry, in the exercise of their duties as required by their religious order, or in the exercise of their profession as a Christian Science practitioner or reader. Income the taxpayer receives for performing ministerial services is subject to self-employment tax unless the taxpayer has an exemption (as explained later). Even if the taxpayer has an exemption, only the income the taxpayer receives for performing ministerial services is exempt. The exemption does not apply to any other income. (Publication 517, page 4)nnPublication 517, page 9, goes on to provide that if the taxpayer owns his or her home and they receive as part of their salary a housing or rental allowance (including an amount to pay utility costs), the taxpayer may exclude from their gross income the smallest of:nnthe amount actually used to provide a home;nthe amount officially designated as a rental allowance; ornthe fair rental value of the home, including furnishings, utilities, garage, etc.nIn addition, the amount excluded cannot be more than the fair rental value of the home, including furnishings, plus the cost of utilities.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nRev. Joanna Baker is a full-time minister. The church allows her to use a parsonage that has an annual fair rental value of $24,000. The church pays her an annual salary of $67,000, of which $7,500 is designated for utility costs. Her actual utility costs during the year were $7,000.nnFor income tax purposes, Rev. Baker excludes $31,000 from gross income ($24,000 for fair rental value of the parsonage plus $7,000 from the allowance for utility costs). She will report $60,000 ($59,500 salary plus $500 of unused utility allowance). Her income for self-employment tax purposes, however, is $91,000 ($67,000 salary plus $24,000 fair rental value of the parsonage).nn n nnTherefore, Ted as an ordained minister who is receiving a housing allowance that is less than the fair rental value may exclude the allowance from income for income tax purposes, but he must include the amount for self-employment tax purposes (see above example, Publication 517, page 9).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(186,7,'In which situation would Janice not be required to file Schedule H, Household Employment Taxes, for the year 2024?','[\"Paid $2,500 wages to Cynthia for babysitting in Janice\'s home\",\"Withheld $100 federal income tax from payments to her yard worker\",\"Paid $2,500 to her mother for housekeeping\",\"Paid household help, other than her mother, $2,500 for the period July, August, and September\"]',2,'Publication 926 addresses issues associated with household employment. In particular, Schedule H is used to report household employment taxes and is necessary if the taxpayer pays any of the following wages to the employee (Publication 926, page 11):nnSocial Security and Medicare wagesnFUTA wagesnWages from which a taxpayer withholds federal income taxnAs provided in Table 1 on page 5 of Publication 926, a person needs to pay employment taxes if they:nnPay cash wages of $2,700 or more in 2024 to any one household employee. But wages are not counted if they are paid to a taxpayer’s spouse, child under the age of 21, parent, or any employee under the age of 18 at any time in 2024; ornPay cash wages of $1,000 or more in any calendar quarter of 2023 or 2024 to any household employee.  Wages are not counted if they are paid to a taxpayer’s spouse, child under the age of 21, or parent.nSchedule H is filed with a taxpayer\'s federal income tax return by April 15. If the taxpayer gets an extension to file his or her tax return, the extension also will apply to the Schedule H filing.nnIn this case, Janice does not need to file a Schedule H for her mother since she satisfies the exception given above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(187,7,'James has $180,000 in self-employment income and $100,000 in retirement income. His employer does not withhold Additional Medicare Tax. What amount is subject to the Additional Medicare Tax for James on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$80,000\",\"$180,000\",\"$280,000\"]',0,'As provided in the instructions for Form 8959, page 1, all wages that are currently subject to Medicare tax are subject to Additional Medicare Tax to the extent they exceed the threshold amount for the taxpayer\'s filing status. Thus, Medicare wages and self-employment income are combined to determine if a taxpayer\'s income exceeds the threshold amount. Retirement income is not considered Medicare wages; as such, James\' retirement income is not added to his Medicare wages. Since James\' Medicare wages of $180,000 are below the threshold amount of $200,000 for a single taxpayer, he is not subject to this tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(188,7,'Jennifer expects to owe $1,500 in tax for 2025. Her tax liability for 2024 was $0. Which of the following statements is correct concerning Jennifer\'s requirement to pay estimated tax for 2025?','[\"Jennifer is required to pay estimated tax for 2025.\",\"Jennifer should pay estimated taxes for 2025.\",\"Jennifer is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to pay estimated tax for 2025.\",\"There is insufficient information to respond to the question.\"]',2,'Publication 17 (pages 41 and 42) provides the general rule regarding when a taxpayer is not required to pay estimated taxes for the coming year. In general, a taxpayer must satisfy all three of the following conditions to be excluded from paying estimated tax for 2025:nnthe taxpayer had no tax liability for 2024,nthe taxpayer was a U.S. citizen or resident for the whole year, andnthe taxpayer\'s 2024 tax year covered a 12-month period.nIn this case, the first exception applies (i.e., no tax liability in 2024), and one must assume that the second and third exceptions apply.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(189,7,'A taxpayer has total tax in the previous year of $21,000. In this year, the taxpayer received a bonus and his tax increased $4,500. The taxpayer has long-term capital gain of $4,000 with a tax of $600. The taxpayer\'s withholding was increased to $23,700. To avoid a penalty for underpayment of estimated tax, the taxpayer must:','[\"do nothing, since the withholding exceeds 100% of last year\'s tax.\",\"pay an additional $5,300 to equal 100% of tax due.\",\"do nothing, since the withholding exceeds 90% of the tax due this year.\",\"do nothing, since the withholding exceeds 100% of last year\'s tax\\u00a0or\\u00a0exceeds 90% of the tax due this year.\"]',3,'Publication 17, pages 41–42, provides the general rule for determining the amount of estimated tax that must be paid to avoid the underestimated tax penalty. Specifically, a taxpayer must pay estimated tax if both of the following apply:nnthe taxpayer expects to owe at least $1,000 in tax after subtracting any amounts withheld and credits, andnthe taxpayer expects withholding and credits to be less than the smaller of 90% of the tax to be shown on the current tax return or 100% of the tax shown on the previous tax return. Also, the taxpayer\'s previous tax return must cover all 12 months.nIn this case, the taxpayer\'s withholding for the current year ($23,700) exceeds 100% of last year\'s total tax liability of $21,000 and exceeds 90% of this year\'s tax liability of $23,490 (0.90 × ($21,000 + $4,500 + $600)). Hence, both rules are covered.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nIf the taxpayer had an adjusted gross income in excess of $150,000 ($75,000 if married filing a separate return), the taxpayer will have to deposit the smaller of 90% of the expected tax for 2024 or 110% of the tax shown on the person\'s 2023 return to avoid an estimated tax penalty (see chapter 2 of Publication 505).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(190,7,'Which of the following statements is not correct concerning the filing of an amended tax return?','[\"If the last day for filing falls on a weekend, the return must be filed by the Friday preceding the weekend.\",\"Form 1040-X is used to file an amended tax return.\",\"An amended return can be filed within 3 years after the date of filing the original return.\",\"All of the statements are correct.\"]',0,'With respect to filing an amended tax return, Publication 17, pages 19–20, provides that a taxpayer should file an amended tax return (Form 1040-X) if they did not report some income, claimed deductions or credits that should have been claimed, claimed deductions or credits that should not have been claimed, or claimed a different filing status.nnIn addition, a person must file their claim within 3 years after the date the original return was filed or within 2 years after the date the taxes were paid, whichever is later. Also, if the last day for claiming a credit or refund is a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the taxpayer can file the claim on the next business day. (Publication 17, pages 19–20)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(191,7,'Which of the following items could be subject to the Net Investment Income Tax?','[\"Interest from a tax-exempt municipal bond\",\"Distribution from a traditional IRA\",\"Alimony income\",\"Distribution from a taxable mutual fund\"]',1,'Generally, net investment income includes gross income from interest, dividends, annuities, royalties, and rents, unless they are derived from the ordinary course of a trade or business that is not (a) a passive activity or (b) a trade or business of trading in financial instruments or commodities, or unless it is specifically excluded.nnExcluded income includes but is not limited to the following:nnIncome excluded from gross income in Chapter 1 of the Internal Revenue Code (IRC)nIncome not included in net investment incomenGross income and net gain specifically excluded by IRC Section 1411, related regulations, or other guidance published in the Internal Revenue BulletinnExamples of excluded items are:nnwages,nunemployment compensation,nAlaska Permanent Fund Dividends,nalimony,nSocial Security benefits,ntax-exempt interest income,nincome from certain qualified retirement plan distributions, andnincome subject to self-employment taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(192,5,'Rick, an electrician, needed a new service van. He was a frequent customer of Eldon\'s Grill. Eldon wanted to remodel his kitchen. Eldon offered to sell his catering van, fair market value $10,000, to Rick for $8,000 and pay $1,000 cash in return for Rick\'s rewiring his kitchen. If Rick agrees to do the work under these terms, what will be his basis in the van received?n','[\"$10,000\\n\",\"$11,000\\n\",\"$8,000\\n\",\"$9,000\\n\"]',0,'Bartering is an exchange of property or services, which is discussed and illustrated on page 67 of Publication 17. In general, a taxpayer must include in income, at the time received, the fair market value of property or services the person receives in bartering. If the person exchanges services with another person, and the taxpayers both have agreed ahead of time as to the value of the services, that value will be accepted as fair market value unless the value can be shown to be otherwise.nnGenerally, you report this income on Schedule C, Profit or Loss From Business, or Schedule C-EZ, Net Profit From Business (Form 1040 or 1040-SR). However, if the barter involves an exchange of something other than services, then another schedule may be required (e.g., free rent would be reported on Schedule E, Supplemental Income and Loss (Form 1040 or 1040-SR)).nnIn this situation, Rick would have income of $3,000, which is the $2,000 difference between the FMV of the van ($10,000) and the cash Rick paid Eldon ($8,000) plus the cash of $1,000 received by Rick from Eldon.nnThe basis of the van, on the other hand, would be $10,000, which is the FMV of the van at the time of the trade.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(193,5,'Megan, an engineer, maintains a residence for herself in Phoenix, Arizona, where her employer maintains a satellite office. In 2024, Megan\'s employer enrolls her in a 12-month executive training program at their corporate offices in Santa Clara, California. Megan will attend classroom training in Santa Clara and temporary work assignments throughout the United States, but does expect to return to work in Phoenix after she completes her training. Every Monday morning, she takes a commuter flight to Santa Clara. She maintains a small, one-bedroom apartment in Santa Clara and incurs all the ordinary and necessary expense in the upkeep of a home. Her grandparents live in a separate residence in Phoenix, so she returns to Arizona on weekends to spend time with them and also attend to her personal affairs from her Phoenix residence. Where can Megan consider her “tax home” to be for the year 2024?','[\"Santa Clara, California\",\"Phoenix, Arizona\\n\",\"Neither because Megan is a transient\",\"Both because Megan spends time in both places\\n\"]',1,'Generally, the taxpayer\'s tax home is the taxpayer\'s regular place of business or post of duty, regardless of where he or she maintains his or her family home. It includes the entire city or general area in which the taxpayer\'s business or work is located. (Publication 463, page 3)nnIf a taxpayer has more than one regular place of business, the taxpayer\'s tax home is his or her main place of business. If a taxpayer does not have a regular or main place of business because of the nature of his or her work, then the taxpayer\'s tax home may be the place where he or she regularly lives.nnIf a taxpayer’s assignment or job away from their main place of work is temporary, their tax home doesn’t change. In fact, the taxpayer is away from home for the whole period they are away from their main place of work. Generally, a temporary assignment in a single location is one that is realistically expected to last (and does in fact last) for 1 year or less. (Publication 463, page 4)nnIn this case, Megan has no regular place of employment and her temporary assignment is not expected to last for more than 1 year. Hence, her tax home is considered to be Phoenix, Arizona.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(194,5,'Morris, a single taxpayer is not covered by a qualified plan at his place of employment. He wishes to establish an IRA and contribute $7,000 for 2024. An IRA may be invested in all of the following accounts, except:','[\"Bank CD.\",\"Mutual Fund.\",\"Annuity.\",\"Artwork.\"]',3,'If a traditional IRA invests in collectibles, the amount invested is considered distributed to the taxpayer in the year invested. The taxpayer may be required to pay a 10% additional tax on “early” distribution.nnCollectibles for this purpose include stamps, coins, artworks, rugs, antiques, metals, gems, alcoholic beverages, and certain other tangible personal property.nnTherefore, Morris may establish his IRA by contributing to all of the above items except the artwork.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(195,5,'Which of the following penalties is likely to be assessed a taxpayer when filing a claim for the earned income tax credit and not including the Social Security number when required?','[\"$50 per tax return\",\"$50 per omission\",\"$100 per omission\",\"$100 per tax return\"]',1,'A taxpayer that fails to include his or her Social Security number (SSN) or that of another person where required on a return, statement, or other document is subject to a $50 penalty for each failure. The penalty can be waived if the taxpayer can show that the failure was due to reasonable cause and not willful neglect.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(196,5,'What information should an Enrolled Agent pass onto a taxpayer concerning the options available for direct deposit of their refund?','[\"The taxpayer can elect to have part, or all, of the refund deposited into their checking or savings account.\",\"The taxpayer can elect to have part, or all, of the refund deposited into the EA\'s personal bank account.\",\"The taxpayer can elect to split the refund and have it deposited among as many as four accounts.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 15, provides the general rules for a taxpayer electing to use direct deposit of their tax refund amount. The current tax rules permit a taxpayer to have their refund deposited directly into their checking or savings account, including an individual retirement arrangement.nnIf the taxpayer chooses direct deposit, they can split the refund and have it deposited among two or three accounts or buy up to $5,000 in paper series I savings bonds (not four accounts). To make a direct deposit, Form 8888, Allocation of Refund (Including Savings Bond Purchases), must be completed and attached to their tax return.nnThus, the only correct response for this question is the taxpayer can elect to have part, or all, of the refund deposited into their checking or savings account.nnCircular 230, Section 10.30 prohibits an enrolled agent or any other tax preparer to endorse, negotiate, electronically transfer, or direct the deposit of any government check relating to a Federal tax liability issued to a client. Any person subject to Treasury Circular 230 is prohibited from directing or accepting payment from the government into an account owned or controlled by that person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(197,5,'At age 50, Yolanda began taking distributions from her IRA as part of a series of substantially equal periodic payments. In 2024, at age 62, Yolanda took out a one-time additional distribution of $20,000. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Yolanda does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to pay a recapture tax on any amount received due to a change in distribution method.\",\"Yolanda pays a recapture tax on the $20,000 amount that was received due to a change in distribution method.\",\"Yolanda pays a recapture tax on the amount that was received prior to her reaching age 59-1\\/2 due to a change in distribution method.\",\"Yolanda pays a recapture tax on the amount that has been received to date due to a change in distribution method.\"]',0,'Publication 590-B, page 26, provides the general rules for an annuity type distribution from an IRA. In general, a taxpayer can receive distributions from his or her traditional IRA that are part of a series of substantially equal payments over the taxpayer\'s life (or the taxpayer\'s life expectancy), or over the lives (or the joint life expectancies) of the taxpayer and the taxpayer\'s beneficiary, without having to pay the 10% additional tax, even if the taxpayer received such distributions before the taxpayer is age 59-1/2.nnThe payments under the above exception must generally continue until at least 5 years after the date of the first payment, or until the taxpayer reaches age 59-1/2, whichever is later. If a change from an approved distribution method is made before the end of the appropriate period, any payments the taxpayer receives before the taxpayer reaches age 59-1/2 will be subject to the 10% additional tax. This is true even if the change is made after the taxpayer reaches age 59-1/2. The payments will not be subject to the 10% additional tax if another exception applies or if the change is made because of the taxpayer\'s death or disability.nnSince Yolanda has been receiving the annuity distribution for over 10 years, the additional distribution that she takes at age 62 is not subject to the 10% early distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(198,5,'All of the following may be deducted by a taxpayer as a transportation expense, except:','[\"getting from one workplace to another in the course of your business or profession.\",\"commuting expenses if you work during the commuting trip using your telephone to make business calls or have business associates ride with you to and from work and you have a business discussion in the car.\",\"visiting clients or customers after going to your office.\",\"going to a business meeting away from your regular workplace.\"]',1,'Publication 463, page 6, states there are some expenses a taxpayer can deduct for business transportation when not traveling away from home. These expenses include the cost of transportation by air, rail, bus, taxi, etc., and the cost of driving and maintaining the taxpayer\'s car.nnTransportation expenses include the ordinary and necessary costs of all of the following:nnGetting from one workplace to another in the course of your business or profession when you are traveling within the area of your tax home nVisiting clients or customersnGoing to a business meeting away from your regular workplacenGetting from your home to a temporary workplace when you have one or more regular places of work (These temporary workplaces can be either within the area of the taxpayer\'s tax home or outside that area.)nPublication 463, page 20, gives an example under “Commuting expenses” which states that a taxpayer uses his cell phone to make business calls while commuting to and from work. In addition, sometimes business associates rode with the taxpayer to and from work, where business discussions were held in the car. These activities do not change the trip from personal to business. Hence, the taxpayer still cannot deduct commuting expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(199,5,'With respect to an employer\'s reimbursement of employee business expenses, all of the following are requirements of an accountable plan, except:','[\"the expenses incurred by the employee must have a business purpose.\",\"the reimbursement of meal expenditures is limited to 50% of the amount incurred.\",\"the employee must provide an accounting to the employer within a reasonable period of time.\",\"the employee must return any excess reimbursement or allowance to the employer within a reasonable period of time.\"]',1,'Publication 463, page 36, states, in part, that an accountable plan is one whereby the reimbursement or allowance arrangement by the employer must include all three of the following rules:nnYour expenses must have a business connection—that is, you must have paid or incurred deductible expenses while performing services as an employee of your employer,nYou must adequately account to your employer for these expenses within a reasonable period of time, andnYou must return any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period of time.nA “reasonable period of time” for accounting to your employer is 60 days from the date of the expenditure. A “reasonable period of time” for returning an excess reimbursement is 120 days after the expense is paid or incurred. If an employee meets the rules for accountable plans, the employer excludes the payments from the employee\'s W-2 income.nnIn addition, an exception to the 50% cutback rule is where an employee is reimbursed under an accountable plan and the employer is only able to deduct up to 50% for meals. In this case, the 50% rule doesn\'t apply to the employee but rather shifts from the employee to the employer (refer to Table 6-1, page 16, Publication 463).nnThus, in this question, it is incorrect to say that the reimbursement of meal and entertainment expenditures is limited to 50% of the amount incurred.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(200,5,'Which of the following is not an example of minimum essential insurance coverage to avoid the penalty for not having insurance?','[\"Individual health coverage such as health insurance purchased directly from an insurance company or the Health Insurance Marketplace\",\"Coverage under government-sponsored programs such as Medicare Part A coverage, Medicare Advantage Plans, and most Medicaid coverage\",\"Employer-sponsored coverage such as a self-insured group health plan for employees, retirees, and COBRA coverage\",\"Certain insurance coverage that may provide limited benefits such as stand-alone dental and vision, accident or disability income, or workers\\u2019 compensation\"]',3,'Publication 974, page 8, provides that under the health care law, certain health coverage is called minimum essential coverage (MEC). A taxpayer generally cannot take the premium tax credit (PTC) for an individual in their tax family for any month that the individual is eligible for minimum essential coverage, except for coverage in the individual market. Minimum essential coverage includes the following:nnIndividual market coverage (including qualified health plans)nMost coverage through government-sponsored programs (including Medicaid coverage, Medicare parts A or C, the Children\'s Health Insurance Program (CHIP), certain benefits for veterans and their families, TRICARE, and health coverage for Peace Corps volunteers)nMost types of employer-sponsored coveragenGrandfathered health plansnOther health coverage designated by the Department of Health and Human Services as minimum essential coveragenMinimum essential coverage does not include coverage consisting solely of excepted benefits. Excepted benefits include vision and dental coverage not part of a comprehensive health insurance plan, workers’ compensation coverage, and coverage limited to a specified disease or illness.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(201,5,'Which of the following statements is not true regarding tax benefits for education?','[\"The American Opportunity Credit may be claimed for tuition expenses incurred in the first 4 years of postsecondary education.\",\"The dollar limitations for the American Opportunity Credit are calculated on a per student basis.\",\"The Lifetime Learning Credit is allowed for tuition paid for graduate program studies.\",\"Room and board are qualifying expenses for the American Opportunity Credit.\"]',3,'Table 1 on page 11 of Publication 970 provides some of the general information for the American Opportunity Credit. The American Opportunity Credit can be claimed for up to $2,500 per eligible student for no more than 4 years. The Lifetime Learning Credit, on the other hand, has no limit on the number of years for which it can be claimed on the same student\'s expenses, but it is limited to $2,000 per tax return.nnNeither the American Opportunity Credit nor the Lifetime Learning Credit is adjusted for inflation.nnIn addition, qualified education expenses for both education credits include tuition and required enrollment fees. Books, supplies, and equipment qualify for the American Opportunity Credit even if they are not purchased from the educational institution. Books, supplies, and equipment qualify for the Lifetime Learning Credit only if they are required to be paid to the educational institution. (Publication 970, pages 13–14)nnQualified education expenses do not include amounts paid for insurance, medical expenses (including student health fees), room and board, transportation, or similar personal, living, or family expenses. (Publication 970, page 17)nnIn this case, the room and board do not qualify as expenses for the American Opportunity Credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(202,5,'The state condemned Joe\'s property. Joe did not hold the property for use in a trade or business or for investment. The adjusted basis of the property was $26,000. The state paid Joe $36,000 in 2024. Joe realized a gain of $10,000. He bought like-kind property for $35,000 in 2024 for the purpose of replacing the condemned property. Joe also made a proper Internal Revenue Code Section 1033 election to defer gain from the condemnation on his 2024 tax return. In 2024, what is the net taxable gain and where must Joe report it?','[\"$36,000 on Form 8949 and transfer to Schedule D\",\"$10,000 on line 21 of Form 1040\",\"$1,000 on Form 8949 and transfer to Schedule D\",\"$26,000 on Form 4797 (Sales of Business Property)\"]',2,'In the case where property is condemned or disposed of under the threat of condemnation, the gain or loss is determined by comparing the adjusted basis of the condemned property with the net condemnation award. (Publication 544, pages 6 and 7)nnBecause this question deals with a gain situation, there are two parts to the question: amount of gain and reporting of gain. The first part is addressed in Publication 544, page 9, which provides that a taxpayer can postpone reporting all the gain if the taxpayer buys replacement property costing at least as much as the amount realized for the condemned property. If the cost of the replacement property is less than the amount realized, the taxpayer must report the gain up to the unspent part of the amount realized.nnThe second part is addressed in Publication 544, page 11, which provides that a taxpayer reports a gain from a condemnation of property held for personal use (other than excluded gain from a condemnation of the taxpayer\'s main home or postponed gain) on Form 8949 and transfers to Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR).nnIn this case, Joe has a reportable gain of $1,000, which is the amount of the condemnation award not used on the replacement property ($36,000 less $35,000). The gain would be reported on Form 8949 or Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), as applicable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(203,5,'Which of the following is correct if Jonathan files his 2024 Form 1040 by January 31, 2025, and pays the rest of the tax due?','[\"Jonathan is required to make the estimated tax payment that would have been due on January 15, 2025.\",\"Jonathan is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to pay estimated taxes for 2025.\",\"Jonathan is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to make the estimated tax payment that would have been due on January 15, 2025.\",\"Jonathan is required to make the estimated tax payment that would have been due on January 15, 2025, as part of his June 15, 2025, payment.\"]',2,'Publication 505, page 26, provides a special rule for the January estimated tax payment. Specifically, if you file your 2024 Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR by January 31, 2025, and pay the rest of the tax you owe, you do not need to make the payment due on January 15, 2025.nnFor more information on filing estimated taxes, see page 26 of Publication 505.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(204,5,'Mr. and Mrs. Black purchased their primary residence in 2016 and lived in it until they sold it in 2024. They purchased the home for $250,000 and sold it for $650,000. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"They are required to report the gain of $150,000 from the sale of their home on their 2024 tax return.\",\"They are required to report the gain of $400,000 from the sale of their home on their 2024 tax return.\",\"They are\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to report the sale of their home on their 2024 tax return.\",\"They are required to report the sale of their home on their 2024 tax return even though there is no gain.\"]',2,'Publication 523, page 2, states that if the taxpayer sold his or her main home in 2023, the taxpayer may be able to exclude from income any gain up to a limit of $250,000 ($500,000 on a joint return in most cases). If the taxpayer can exclude all of the gain, the taxpayer does not need to report the sale on his or her tax return.nnIf, on the other hand, the taxpayer cannot exclude all of the gain (i.e., the taxpayer has a gain beyond $250,000 or $500,000, if applicable), then the taxpayer must report the gain on Form 8949, Sales and Other Dispositions of Capital Assets, and Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR). A taxpayer may need to complete Form 4797, Sales of Business Property.nnPursuant to Publication 523, pages 3–6, the $250,000 exclusion is applicable if the taxpayer is able to satisfy the ownership test and use test, and the primary residence has been held for more than 2 out of the last 5 years.nnSimilarly, if a taxpayer has a loss on the sale, the loss cannot be deducted on the tax return. (Publication 523, page 13).nnSince the gain on the sale of the taxpayer\'s home is $400,000 ($650,000 − $250,000), which is less than the $500,000, no gain is recognized and, therefore, the gain is not reported.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(205,5,'Joe had a taxable gain on the sale of his main home, which could not be totally excluded on his 2024 tax return. He had no business use of the home. Which schedule does he need to submit to report the gain?','[\"Schedule C, for sole proprietors\",\"Schedule A, for itemized deductions\",\"Schedule D, for capital gains\",\"Schedule SE, for self-employment income\"]',2,'In the case of a sale of a personal residence, the sale is not reported on a taxpayer\'s tax return unless the taxpayer:nnhas a gain and the taxpayer does not qualify to exclude all of it,nhas a gain and the taxpayer chooses not to exclude it, ornreceives Form 1099-S.nIf, on the other hand, the taxpayer has a taxable gain of any amount on the sale of the personal residence that cannot be excluded, the entire gain realized is reported on Form 8949 and the details on how to report the gain or loss are found in the instructions for Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) and the instructions for Form 8949.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(206,5,'In 2024, Jerry was required to use his car for his employer. His employer\'s mileage reimbursement was $0.15 per mile. Which of the following statements is correct if Jerry\'s actual expenses are more than the reimbursement?','[\"He can deduct the excess amount on Schedule C only.\",\"He can deduct the excess amount on Form 2106 and Schedule A.\",\"He can deduct the excess amount on Schedule A only.\",\"He\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0deduct any of the excess amounts.\"]',3,'When an employee uses his or her car in the performance of the taxpayer\'s job as an employee and the allowance is less than or equal to the federal rate, the allowance would not be included in box 1 of the employee’s Form W-2. (See Publication 463, page 28.)nnHowever, if the employee’s actual expenses are more than the allowance, the unreimbursed amount (i.e., the excess expense) are not deductible by a regular employee between 2018 and 2025 per TCJA. (See Publication 17, page 102) The only individuals who can deduct excess expenses by completing Form 2106 and deducting the excess amount as an itemized deduction on Schedule A are Armed Forces reservist, fee-based state or local government officials, qualified performing artists, or disabled employees with impairment-related work expenses.nnSince Jerry doesn’t qualify under any of these exceptions, he cannot deduct the excess amount on Form 2106 and Schedule A.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(207,5,'Arthur lived and worked in Florida for 8 months and earned $30,000. He then worked in California at a seasonal job at a racetrack the last 4 months of the year and earned $12,000 before returning to Florida. What is Arthur\'s “tax home”?','[\"Since he does not have a regular place of business, he is considered a transient and his tax home is wherever he works.\",\"Since Arthur was working in California at the end of the year, it is his tax home.\",\"Since Arthur had significant earnings at two locations, it is impossible to determine his tax home.\",\"Since most of his time and income were from the job in Florida, it is considered his tax home.\"]',3,'Publication 463 addresses many questions associated with travel and entertainment expenses, including the determination of one\'s tax home. On page 5, it states in the temporary assignment section that a taxpayer may regularly work at a person\'s tax home and also work at another location. It may not be practical to return to the person\'s tax home from this other location at the end of each workday. In such cases, the taxpayer\'s tax home does not change. Rather, the taxpayer is considered to be temporarily away from home for the whole period that the person is away from the main place of work.nnIf a person has more than one place of work, consider the following (as given on page 4 of Publication 463) when determining which one is your main place of business or work:nnThe total time you ordinarily spend in each placenThe level of your business activity in each placenWhether your income from each place is significant or insignificantnExample: You live in Cincinnati where you have a seasonal job for 8 months each year and earn $40,000. You work the other 4 months in Miami, also at a seasonal job, and earn $15,000. Cincinnati is your main place of work because you spend most of your time there and earn most of your income there.nnAs a result of the above example, Arthur would claim Florida as his tax home because he spends most of his time and earns most of his income from the job in Florida.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(208,5,'Debra, age 30, had established a traditional IRA at her local bank several years earlier. In September 2024, Debra told the custodian to use the amount in her account to buy an annuity contract. The bank sent the annuity contract payment to her in October. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Debra will be taxed on the annuity contract beginning in 2024.\",\"Debra will be taxed on the annuity amount received in 2024.\",\"Debra will be excluded from tax because she has opted for an annuity distribution.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 590-B, page 35, provides the rules for a distribution of an annuity contract from a taxpayer\'s IRA. In general, a taxpayer can tell the trustee or custodian of his or her traditional IRA account to use the amount in the account to buy an annuity contract for the taxpayer. The taxpayer, however, is not taxed when the annuity contract is received. Rather, the taxpayer is taxed when he or she starts receiving payments under that annuity contract.nnIf only deductible contributions were made to the traditional IRA, then the entire annuity payments would be included in gross income. If, on the other hand, any of the contributions included both deductible and nondeductible contributions to the traditional IRA, then only part of the annuity payments would be included in gross income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(209,5,'Frederick (age 48) changed jobs in 2024. During the year, he had elective deferrals of $12,700 for his 401(k) plan at the old job and elective deferrals of $11,000 for his 401(k) plan at his new job. Which of the following statements is correct about Frederick?','[\"Frederick does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have an excess deferral.\",\"Frederick has an excess deferral of $700.\",\"Frederick has an excess deferral of $1,200.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 560, page 16, provides the limits on the amount an employee can defer each year under 401(k) plans. In general, this limit applies without regard to community property laws. The employer\'s plan must provide that the employees cannot defer more than the limit that applies for a particular year. The basic limit on elective deferrals is $23,000 for 2024.nnSince Frederick made contributions of $23,700 in total ($12,700 and $11,000) in 2024 between the two plans, he has an excess deferral of $700 ($23,700 less $23,000) for the year.nnAs an aside, if Frederick was 50 or older, he also could make a catch-up contribution, which has a limit of $8,000 for 2024. In this case, he is able to make a maximum contribution of $31,000 ($23,000 + $8,000) in 2024, which would mean that he did not have an excess deferral.nnIn addition, if, in conjunction with other plans, the deferral limit is exceeded, the employee can have the difference (called an excess deferral) paid out of any of the plans that permit these distributions. He or she must notify the plan by April 15, 2025, (or an earlier date specified in the plan) of the amount to be paid from each plan. (See Publication 560, page 17.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(210,5,'A taxpayer has both short-term capital loss and nondividend distribution from an investment. The following statements are correct, except:','[\"the basis of the investment is reduced by the nondividend distribution.\",\"nondividend distribution is a return of capital invested.\",\"short-term capital loss reduces the basis of the investment.\",\"short-term capital losses have no effect on basis.\"]',2,'A nondividend distribution is a distribution that is not paid out of the earnings and profits of a corporation or a mutual fund. Hence, a nondividend distribution is treated as a return of capital; it reduces the basis of the taxpayer\'s stock. Hence, it is not taxed until the taxpayer\'s basis in the stock is fully recovered. Once the basis is reduced to zero, any additional return of capital that is received by the taxpayer is treated as a capital gain. The reporting of the capital gain as long-term or short-term capital gain depends on how long the taxpayer held the stock. See Publication 550, page 80, for more discussion on this topic.nnIf a taxpayer\'s capital losses exceed the capital gains, the taxpayer can claim a capital loss deduction (not a basis reduction). It should be remembered, however, that the allowable capital loss deduction is the lesser of (1) $3,000 ($1,500 if married and filing a separate return), or (2) the total net loss. See Publication 550, page 100, for more details on this topic.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(211,5,'Carleen paid $1,000 U.S. dollar equivalent in euros to Germany on income earned while working there. She qualified for the income earned abroad exclusion on the $40,000 wages she earned. Which of the following statements is correct for 2024?','[\"Carleen can take a tax credit for the $1,000 or she can take an exclusion from income for the $40,000.\",\"Carleen only can take a tax credit for the $1,000.\",\"Carleen only can take an exclusion from income for the $40,000.\",\"Carleen can take both a tax credit for the $1,000 and an exclusion from income for the $40,000.\"]',0,'In order to lessen the potential for double taxation, United States taxpayers are allowed to take an amount of qualified foreign taxes paid or accrued during the year as a credit or a deduction. You can change from a credit to deduction or vice versa from year to year. Claiming the credit requires a taxpayer to complete and attach Form 1116. In order to claim the deduction, the taxpayer must itemize the deductions and therefore take the deduction on Schedule A of Form 1040 (Publication 54, page 24).nnThere is no rule to determine whether it is to a taxpayer\'s advantage to take a deduction or a credit for foreign income taxes. In most cases, the credit is preferable to a deduction in figuring taxable income. A taxpayer must treat all foreign income taxes the same way. That is, if the taxpayer takes a credit for any foreign income taxes, the taxpayer cannot deduct any foreign income taxes.nnIn addition, U.S. taxpayers who work “abroad” are permitted (if they qualify) to exclude from gross income up to $126,500 of foreign earned income for 2024 (Publication 54, page 2). However, a taxpayer is not permitted to take the credit or deduction for foreign income taxes paid on income that can be excluded from the U.S. tax (Publication 54, page 24).nnGiven that Carleen qualified for the foreign earned income exclusion, she is permitted to take a credit or deduction on the U.S. $1,000 of tax she paid on the foreign earned income or she can exclude up to the $40,000 of foreign earned income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(212,5,'Which of the following statements is correct if you inherited a traditional IRA from someone other than your spouse?','[\"You can treat the traditional IRA as your own.\",\"You cannot convert it to a Roth IRA.\",\"You can roll over any amounts into or out of the inherited IRA.\",\"You can change the name on the inherited IRA to your own name.\"]',1,'Publication 590-B, page 6, states that if a taxpayer inherits a traditional IRA from anyone other than the taxpayer\'s deceased spouse, the taxpayer cannot treat the inherited IRA as his or her own. This means that the taxpayer cannot roll over any amounts into or out of the inherited IRA. The taxpayer, however, can make a trustee-to-trustee transfer as long as the new IRA is set up and maintained in the name of the deceased IRA owner for the benefit of taxpayer as beneficiary.nnThus, an inherited IRA cannot be converted to a Roth IRA.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(213,5,'Which of the following penalties is a taxpayer likely to be assessed if they fail to keep adequate books and records when claiming the earned income credit?','[\"Accuracy-related penalty\",\"Fraud penalty\",\"Frivolous tax submission\",\"There is no penalty.\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer may have to pay an accuracy-related penalty if they underpay their tax because they show negligence or disregard of the rules or regulations, substantially understate their income tax, claim tax benefits for a transaction that lacks economic substance, or fail to disclose a foreign financial asset.nnThe term “negligence” includes a failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the tax law or to exercise ordinary and reasonable care in preparing a return. Negligence also includes failure to keep adequate books and records.nnHence, a taxpayer is negligent if they fail to keep adequate books and records when claiming the earned income credit and may be subject to an accuracy-related penalty.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(214,5,'Which of the following is correct concerning the basis of property received by a person as a gift?','[\"The basis is always the donor\'s basis plus any gift taxes paid.\",\"The basis depends on the donor\'s basis and the fair market value of the gift on the date received plus any gift taxes paid.\",\"The basis depends on the donor\'s basis and the fair market value of the gift on the date received.\",\"The basis is always the fair market value of the gift on the date received plus any gift taxes paid.\"]',1,'Publication 551, page 9, provides the general rules for computing a person\'s adjusted basis for property received as a gift. In general, the basis of property received as a gift requires the taxpayer to know the property\'s adjusted basis to the donor just before it was given to the taxpayer, the property\'s FMV at the time it was received, and any gift tax paid by the donor.nnMore specifically, if the FMV of the property at the time of the gift is less than the donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis depends on whether the taxpayer has a gain or a loss when the taxpayer disposes of the property. That is, the taxpayer\'s basis for figuring gain is the same as the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustments to basis while the property is held. Likewise, the taxpayer\'s basis for figuring loss is its FMV when the taxpayer received the gift plus or minus any required adjustments to basis while the property is held.nnIf the FMV of the property is equal to or greater than the donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis is the donor\'s adjusted basis at the time the gift is received, increased by all or part of any gift tax paid, depending on the date of the gift (i.e., pre-1977 or post-1976).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(215,5,'All of the following are correct statements about the balance that is maintained in the Coverdell education savings account, except:','[\"it generally must be distributed within 30 days after the beneficiary reaches age 30.\",\"it generally must be distributed within 30 days after the beneficiary\'s death.\",\"it generally does\\u00a0not\\u00a0need to be distributed within 30 days after the special needs beneficiary reaches age 30.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct statements.\"]',3,'According to Publication 970, page 48, the balance in the Coverdell education savings account generally must be distributed within 30 days after the earlier of the following events:nnThe beneficiary reaches age 30, unless the beneficiary is a special needs beneficiarynThe beneficiary dies before reaching age 30',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(216,5,'Which of the following statements is correct for individuals who pay AMT (alternative minimum tax) in the current year?','[\"Taxpayers may take a credit against regular income tax in future years for only the portion of the AMT that is attributable to deferral items, such as depreciation.\",\"Taxpayers may take a credit against regular income tax in future years for only the portion of the AMT that is attributable to exclusion items.\",\"Taxpayers may take a credit against regular income tax in future years for up to $3,000 per year for only the portion of the AMT that is attributable to deferral items, such as depreciation.\",\"Taxpayers may\\u00a0not\\u00a0take a credit against regular income tax in the past or future.\"]',0,'The special treatment of some items of income and expense only allows a taxpayer to postpone paying tax until a later year. If in prior years a taxpayer paid alternative minimum tax (AMT) because of these tax postponement items, the taxpayer may be able to take a credit for prior-year minimum tax against the current year\'s regular tax. (Form 8801 Instructions, page 1)nnA credit against regular tax is possible if for 2023 the taxpayer had an AMT liability and adjustments or preferences other than exclusion items, a minimum tax credit that was carried forward to 2024, or an unallowed qualified electric vehicle credit.nnIn general, the AMT preference items and adjustments may provide a permanent reduction of or only a deferral of tax liability. Deferral items (for example, depreciation) generally do not cause a permanent difference in taxable income over time. Exclusion items (for example, the standard deduction) do cause a permanent difference. The minimum tax credit is allowed only for the AMT caused by deferral items. (Form 8801 Instructions)nnFor more discussion on AMT and the credit against regular income tax in future years, see page 1 in the instructions for Form 8801.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(217,5,'Vivian, who lives in Cleveland, Ohio, took a job in Buffalo, New York. Her employer required her to move, with the understanding that she would keep the job only if her work was satisfactory during a 1-year probationary period. Which of the following is correct?','[\"Vivian has a temporary job during the probationary period.\",\"Vivian can deduct her traveling expenses between Cleveland and Buffalo.\",\"Vivian has a temporary job during the probationary period and therefore she can deduct her traveling expenses between Cleveland and Buffalo.\",\"Vivian does not have a temporary job during the probationary period and therefore she\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0deduct her traveling expenses between Cleveland and Buffalo.\"]',3,'Publication 463, page 4, states, in part, that if a taxpayer takes a job that requires the person to move, with the understanding that the taxpayer will keep the job if the person\'s work is satisfactory during a probationary period, the job is indefinite. As a result, the taxpayer cannot deduct any expenses for meals and lodging during the probationary period.nnWhen a job or assignment is expected to last for 1 year or less, it is considered temporary unless there are facts and circumstances that indicate otherwise. (Publication 463, page 4)nnIn this case, Vivian is deemed to have a job that is indefinite. The probationary issue is not a relevant factor.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(218,5,'Which of the following rules requires a person to make estimated tax payments for year 2025 if the taxpayer had a tax liability for year 2024?nnThe taxpayer expects to owe at least $1,000 in tax for 2025 after subtracting withholding and credits.nThe taxpayer expects withholding and credits to be less than the smaller of (1) 90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 tax return or (2) 100% of the tax shown on the 2024 tax return (110% if AGI over $150,000) and the 2024 tax return must cover all 12 months.','[\"The taxpayer only needs to satisfy item 1 to be required to pay estimated taxes.\",\"The taxpayer only needs to satisfy item 2 to be required to pay estimated taxes.\",\"The taxpayer must satisfy both items 1 and 2 to be required to pay estimated taxes.\",\"The taxpayer must satisfy some other rule to be required to pay estimated taxes.\"]',2,'In general, a taxpayer must pay estimated tax if both of the following apply:nnThe taxpayer expects to owe at least $1,000 in tax for 2025 after subtracting his or her withholdings and credits.nThe taxpayer expects his or her withholdings and credits to be less than the smaller of 90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 tax return or 100% of the tax shown on the 2024 tax return. Moreover, the 2024 tax return must cover all 12 months.nIf a taxpayer is considered a higher-income taxpayer, the percentages in the above general rule change. Specifically, if the taxpayer\'s AGI for 2023 is more than $150,000 ($75,000 if filing married separate), 110% is substituted for the 100% in the general rule.nnSee Publication 17, page 41, or Publication 505 for a discussion on who does and who does not need to pay estimated taxes.nnAssuming that this is not a higher-income taxpayer, both rules would apply in this question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(219,5,'What is the base amount used by a taxpayer to determine the taxable portion of their Social Security benefits if they are 62, are married filing separately, and live apart from their spouse for the entire year?','[\"$0\",\"$16,000\",\"$25,000\",\"$32,000\"]',2,'To find out whether any of a taxpayer’s Social Security benefits may be taxable, compare the base amount for their filing status with the total of:nnone-half of their benefits plusnall their other income, including tax-exempt interest.nWhen making this comparison, do not reduce the taxpayer’s other income by any exclusions for:nninterest from qualified U.S. savings bonds,nemployer-provided adoption benefits,nforeign earned income or foreign housing, ornincome earned by bona fide residents of American Samoa or Puerto Rico.nThe base amount for the various filing statuses is:nn$25,000 if the taxpayer is single, head of household, or a qualifying widow(er);n$25,000 if the taxpayer is married filing separately and lived apart from their spouse for the entire year;n$32,000 if the taxpayer is married filing jointly; orn$0 if the taxpayer is married filing separately and lived with their spouse at any time during the year.nThe correct response is $25,000, as highlighted above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(220,5,'Alice and Mike file a joint return for 2024 on April 15, 2025. Alice, who is a nonworking spouse, is 49. Both Alice and Mike contributed $2,000 each to a traditional IRA although they qualified to contribute the maximum amount. They filed their return timely. On June 1, 2025, Mike\'s mother gave each of them $1,000. What additional amount of the gift may Alice and Mike contribute to each of their IRAs for the year 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$1,000\",\"$4,500\",\"$4,000\"]',0,'Publication 590-A, page 10, provides the basic rules for the due date in making IRA contributions. Specifically, contributions can be made to a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA for a year at any time during the year or by the due date for filing the person\'s return for that year, not including extensions. For most people, this means that contributions for 2024 must be made by April 15, 2025 and contributions for 2025 must be made by April 15, 2026.nn nn 	Caution	 n 	 	 n 	nIf April 15, falls on a Sunday, and Emancipation Day, a legal holiday in the District of Columbia, then the due date for making contributions is the following day, even if the taxpayer does not live in the District of Columbia. Although this oddity is not likely to appear in the exam, one never knows.nn n nnFurthermore, if contributions to a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA for a year were less than the limit, the taxpayer cannot contribute more after the due date of their return for that year to make up the difference. (Publication 590-A, page 9)nnIn general, the last day for Alice and Mike to contribute to their IRA for tax year 2024 is April 15, 2025. Since June 1, 2025, is beyond April 15, the couple cannot make any additional contributions to their IRAs for 2024. However, assuming they qualify they can make an IRA contribution for 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(221,5,'A taxpayer had adjusted gross income of $98,000 and a total tax liability in 2023 of $20,000. In 2024, the taxpayer has a tax liability of $25,000. The taxpayer\'s withholding was increased to $23,500. He will file his tax return for 2024 on April 10, 2025. To avoid the underpayment of estimated tax penalty, the taxpayer must:','[\"pay the additional $1,500 due by April 15, 2025.\",\"pay an additional $1,500 by January 15, 2025.\",\"file an annualized estimated tax computation.\",\"do nothing, as he has satisfied the minimum tax payment requirements.\"]',3,'An underpayment of tax either through withholding or by making estimated tax payments may cause a penalty to be imposed. Generally, a taxpayer will not be subject to a penalty for 2024 if any of the following situations apply:nnTotal withholding and estimated tax payments are at least as much as the 2023 tax (or 110% of 2023 tax if adjusted gross income was more than $150,000—$75,000 if the taxpayer\'s filing status is married filing separately) and all required estimated tax payments were paid on time.nThe tax balance due is no more than 10% of the taxpayer\'s total 2024 tax, and all required estimated tax payments were paid on time.nTotal 2024 tax minus withholding is less than $1,000.nThere was not a tax liability for 2023 and the taxpayer\'s 2023 tax year was 12 months.nThe taxpayer did not have any withholding taxes and the current-year tax less any household employment taxes is less than $1,000.nTherefore, in the above, two of the following situations apply:nn1. Total withholding and estimated tax payments are at least as much as the 2023 tax:nn  2023 Tax × 110%     $22,000n  2024 Withholding:    23,500 n                      $(1,500)n                      ========nn nn2. Total tax balance due is not more than 10% of the taxpayer\'s total 2024 tax:nn  2024 Tax:          $25,000n                         .10n  10% of 2024 Tax:   $ 2,500n  Balance Due:       $ 1,500 (Less than $2,500)nnTherefore, the taxpayer does not need to do anything since the 2024 withholdings exceed their 2023 tax liability and their total tax balance is less than 10% of their tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(222,5,'If a taxpayer has capital gains dividends, but has no other capital gain:','[\"capital gain distributions must be put on Schedule B.\",\"no Schedule D is required, and the amount is put directly on the Form 1040.\",\"dividends and capital gains dividends may be added together on Schedule B.\",\"it must be combined with interest on the Schedule B.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Exception 1 as given in Publication 550, page 95, the taxpayer that receives only capital gain distributions does not need to file Form 8949 or Schedule D if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer has no capital losses and the only amounts the taxpayer would have to report on Schedule D are capital gain distributions from box 2a of Form 1099-DIV (or substitute statement).nThe taxpayer does not have an amount in box 2b, 2c, or 2d of any Form 1099-DIV (or substitute statement).nIf both of the above statements are true, the taxpayer satisfies the exceptions to filing Form 8949 and Schedule D, reports the capital gain distributions directly on line 7 of Form 1040, and checks the box on line 7. (See Publication 550, page 95.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(223,5,'Jack received $3,000 in educational assistance benefits from his employer during 2024 to reimburse him for the cost of course tuition and fees for him to earn a degree. The benefits were paid under an accountable plan and were not included in Jack\'s W-2. He has a modified adjusted gross income of $20,000 and he files single. A list of Jack\'s 2024 expenses follows. What is Jack\'s deductible tuition and fee expense?nn$500 for a bowling class not required for his degreen$2,000 for accounting courses required for his degreen$1,000 for room and boardn$500 for textbooksn$500 for lab fees for courses required for his degree','[\"$0\",\"$4,500\",\"$4,000\",\"$3,000\"]',0,'If a taxpayer receives educational assistance benefits from his or her employer under an educational assistance program, they can exclude up to $5,250 of those benefits each year. This means the taxpayer’s employer should not include those benefits with their wages, tips, and other compensation shown in box 1 of the taxpayer\'s Form W-2. This also means that the taxpayer does not need to include the benefits on their income tax return. (Publication 970, page 59)nnPublication 970, page 59, states, in part, that tax-free educational assistance benefits include payments for tuition, fees and similar expenses, books, supplies, and equipment to enroll at or attend an educational institution.nnEducation generally includes any form of instruction or training that improves or develops the person’s capabilities. The payments do not have to be for work-related courses or courses that are part of a degree program.nnEducation assistance benefits do not include payments for meals, lodging, or transportation. Hence, amounts used for room and board would not qualify for the exclusion.nnIn this case, Jack incurred $3,000 in educational expenses ($2,000 + $500 + $500), which is the same amount that he received from his employer under an accountable plan. Jack would have no income from the reimbursement, and he would have no deductible educational expenses. Also, the tuition and fee deduction is no longer available, the only credits are the Lifetime Learning and American Opportunity Tax Credit. He is not able to take either of those.nnFor additional information on qualified scholarships and fellowship grants, see Publication 970, Tax Benefits for Education.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(224,5,'Which of the following is not a payment deductible as alimony?','[\"Payments for life insurance premiums required by the divorce decree\",\"Payments for medical expenses of your spouse under the terms of the divorce decree\",\"Half of the mortgage payment on a home jointly owned with your ex-spouse when required by the divorce decree\",\"Payments for child support required by the divorce decree\"]',3,'For pre-2019, alimony is deductible by the payer and must be included in the spouse\'s or former spouse\'s income. However, not all payments under a divorce or separation instrument are alimony. Alimony does not include any of the following:nnChild supportnNoncash property settlementsnPayments that are the spouse\'s part of community income (See “Community Property” in Publication 504.)nPayments to keep up the payer\'s propertynUse of payer\'s propertyn(See Publication 504, page 13.)nnAs a result of the above rules, the child support payment that is required by the divorce degree is not deductible as alimony.nnNote: For divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, you may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(225,5,'Leslie claimed the earned income credit (EIC) on her 2023 tax return, which was filed in April 2024. The IRS determined that she was not entitled to the EIC and that her error was due to reckless or intentional disregard of the EIC rules. In May 2025, she received a notice that her EIC was denied because she failed to follow up after receiving the statutory notice of deficiency in December 2024. Which of the following statements is correct concerning Leslie if she filed her 2024 tax return in April 2025?','[\"She must file an amended 2024 tax return withdrawing her EIC claim.\",\"She cannot claim the EIC until she files her 2027 tax return, and only then if she attaches Form 8862.\",\"She cannot claim the EIC until she files her 2025 tax return, and only then if she attaches Form 8862.\",\"She cannot claim the EIC until she files her 2026 tax return, and only then if she attaches Form 8862.\"]',1,'If the IRS determined that a taxpayer was not entitled to the EIC and that the taxpayer error was due to reckless or intentional disregard of the EIC rules, then they are unable to claim the credit for 2 years. The date on which the EIC was denied and the date on which the taxpayer filed their 2024 return affect the years for which they are prohibited from claiming the EIC.nnIf the error is due to fraud, then the taxpayer cannot claim the EIC for 10 years.nnIn this case, the taxpayer does not file an amended return because she filed her 2024 tax return claiming the EIC before she received the notice of denial in May 2025. The controlling item is the notice of denial, not the notice of deficiency. The taxpayer will be able to claim the EIC again on her 2027 tax return, but only if she attaches Form 8862 to that return. Thus, the penalty that the taxpayer has suffered is the loss of the tax credit for 2 years.nnPublication 596 provides several timing examples on pages 23 and 24',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(226,5,'You may receive a return of capital or a tax-free distribution in shares of stock or stock rights. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"These distributions are treated the same as ordinary dividends or capital gain distributions.\",\"These distributions are treated the same as ordinary dividends but\\u00a0not\\u00a0treated the same as capital gain distributions.\",\"These distributions are\\u00a0not\\u00a0treated the same as capital gain distributions but are treated the same as ordinary dividends.\",\"These distributions are\\u00a0not\\u00a0treated the same as ordinary dividends or capital gain distributions.\"]',3,'As given on pages 30 and 31 of Publication 550, a nondividend distribution is a distribution that is not paid out of the earnings and profits of a corporation or a mutual fund. When a taxpayer receives a nondividend (also known as a return of capital) or a tax-free distribution of more shares of stock or stock rights, these distributions are not treated the same as ordinary dividends or capital gain distributions.nnTo begin with, amounts received as a return of capital are not included in gross income. It is treated as a reduction in the basis of the taxpayer\'s stock. Thus, it is not taxed until the taxpayer\'s basis is totally recovered.nnWhen the basis of the stock has been reduced to zero, any additional nondividend distribution received as a capital gain is reported. Whether the amount received is reported as a long-term or short-term capital gain depends on how long the stock has been held.nnFurther, distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire the corporation\'s stock. Generally, stock dividends and stock rights are not taxable to the taxpayer, and as such they are not reported on the taxpayer\'s return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(227,5,'Which of the following is necessary for the 60-day rollover requirement to be waived automatically?','[\"The financial institution receives the funds on the taxpayer\'s behalf before the end of the 60-day rollover period.\",\"It would have been a valid rollover if the financial institution had deposited the funds as instructed.\",\"The funds are deposited into an eligible retirement plan within 1 year from the beginning of the 60-day rollover period.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The rules for the automatic waiver to apply are found in Publication 590-A, pages 22 and 23. In general, the 60-day rollover requirement is waived automatically only if all of the following apply:nnThe financial institution receives the funds on the taxpayer\'s behalf before the end of the 60-day rollover period.nThe taxpayer followed all the procedures set by the financial institution for depositing the funds into an eligible retirement plan within the 60-day period (including giving instructions to deposit the funds into an eligible retirement plan).nThe funds are not deposited into an eligible retirement plan within the 60-day rollover period solely because of an error on the part of the financial institution.nThe funds are deposited into an eligible retirement plan within 1 year from the beginning of the 60-day rollover period.nIt would have been a valid rollover if the financial institution had deposited the funds as instructed.nBeginning in 2016, if a taxpayer does not qualify for an automatic waiver, they can use the self-certification procedure to make a late rollover contribution or they can apply to the IRS for a waiver of the 60-day rollover requirement. Revenue Procedure 2016-47 provides the rules associated with the procedures for a taxpayer to self-certify. However, it should be realized that this is not a waiver; it is only a written certification to a plan administrator or an IRA trustee that the taxpayer missed the 60-day rollover contribution deadline because of one or more of the 11 reasons listed in Revenue Procedure 2016-47.nnIn this problem, all of the responses are needed to satisfy the automatic waiver rules for the 60-day rollover rules.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(228,5,'What penalty will most likely be assessed a taxpayer that erroneously claims the earned income credit but is able to show a reasonable basis for claiming it?','[0,0.200000000000000011102230246251565404236316680908203125,0.5,0.75]',0,'In general, a taxpayer may have to pay a penalty if he or she files an erroneous claim for refund or credit. The penalty is equal to 20% of the disallowed amount of the claim, unless the taxpayer can show a reasonable basis for the way they treated the item.nnAny disallowed amount due to a transaction that lacks economic substance will not be treated as having a reasonable basis. The penalty will not be figured on any part of the disallowed amount of the claim that relates to the earned income credit or on which the accuracy-related or fraud penalties are charged.nnIn the case of fraud, the taxpayer will be subject to a 75% penalty.nnSince this taxpayer shows a reasonable basis for claiming the credit, the penalty will most likely be zero.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(229,5,'Sally, age 38, converted $14,000 from her traditional IRA to a Roth IRA in 2024. When she had her tax return prepared for 2024, her tax professional informed her that the taxable portion of the conversion:','[\"was included entirely in her taxable income for 2024.\",\"was included half in her taxable income for 2024 and half in her taxable income for 2025.\",\"is excludable as long as she leaves it in the Roth IRA for 5 years.\",\"Sally can elect to include it entirely in her taxable income for 2024\\u00a0or\\u00a0include half in her taxable income for 2025 and half in her taxable income for 2026.\"]',0,'Starting in 2010, a taxpayer can convert amounts from a person\'s traditional IRA to a Roth IRA in any of the following three ways regardless of their AGI amount:nnRollovernTrustee-to-trustee transfernSame-trustee transfernTherefore, a taxpayer can withdraw all or part of the assets from a traditional IRA and reinvest them (within 60 days) in a Roth IRA. The amount that they withdraw and timely contribute (convert) to the Roth IRA is called a conversion contribution. If properly (and timely) rolled over, the 10% additional tax on early distributions will not apply. However, a part or all of the conversion contribution from the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA is included in their gross income.nnA taxpayer must roll over into the Roth IRA the same property they received from the traditional IRA. They can roll over part of the withdrawal into a Roth IRA and keep the rest of it. The amount kept will generally be taxable (except for the part that is a return of nondeductible contributions) and may be subject to the 10% additional tax on early distributions.nnUnder current rules, the entire rollover amount is taxable in 2024 since there is no mention of any return of capital in the distributed amount.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(230,5,'The use of IRA funds in prohibited transactions can result in additional taxes and penalties. Which of the following is not a prohibited transaction in a traditional IRA?','[\"Borrowing money from the IRA\",\"Selling property to an IRA\",\"Inheriting your spouse\'s IRA\",\"Using an IRA as security for a loan\"]',2,'Publication 590-A, pages 31 and 32, provides that a prohibited transaction is any improper use of a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA account or annuity by the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s beneficiary, or any disqualified person. Disqualified persons include the taxpayer\'s fiduciary and members of the taxpayer\'s family (spouse, ancestor, lineal descendant, and any spouse of a lineal descendant).nnThe following are examples of prohibited transactions with a traditional IRA:nnBorrowing money from itnSelling property to itnReceiving unreasonable compensation for managing itnUsing it as security for a loannBuying property for personal use (present or future) with IRA fundsnA prohibited transaction does not include inheriting an IRA from one\'s spouse.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(231,5,'Which of the following statements is correct regarding Form 1095-A, Health Insurance Marketplace Statement?','[\"Taxpayers do\\u00a0not\\u00a0need Form 1095-A to complete Form 8962,\\u00a0Premium Tax Credit (PTC),\\u00a0to reconcile advance payments of the premium tax credit or claim the premium tax credit on their tax return.\",\"Taxpayers will receive Form 1095-A to complete Form 8962,\\u00a0Premium Tax Credit (PTC),\\u00a0if they have been covered by an employer insurance plan for the entire year.\",\"Taxpayers will use Form 1095-A to complete Form 8962,\\u00a0Premium Tax Credit (PTC),\\u00a0to reconcile advance payments of the premium tax credit or claim the premium tax credit on their tax return.\",\"Taxpayers will attach a Form 1095-A with their return to reconcile advance payments of the premium tax.\"]',2,'Form 8962 Instructions, pages 2 and 3, provide that a taxpayer will need Form 1095-A to complete Form 8962. The Marketplace uses Form 1095-A to report certain information to the IRS about individuals who enrolled in a qualified health plan through the Marketplace. The Marketplace sends copies to individuals to allow them to accurately file a tax return taking the premium tax credit (PTC) and reconciling the advanced PTC (APTC).nnThe Marketplace is required to provide or send Form 1095-A to the individual(s) identified in the Marketplace enrollment application by January 31. If the taxpayer is expecting to receive Form 1095-A for a qualified health plan and they do not receive it by early February, they should contact the Marketplace.nnUnder certain circumstances, for example, where two spouses enroll in a qualified health plan and divorce during the year, the Marketplace will provide Form 1095-A to one taxpayer, but another taxpayer will also need the information from that form to complete Form 8962. The recipient of Form 1095-A should provide a copy to other taxpayers as needed.nnTherefore, the correct response is taxpayers will use Form 1095A to complete Form 8962, Premium Tax Credit (PTC), to reconcile advance payments of the PTC or claim the PTC on their tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(232,5,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"If you hold a capital asset 1 year or less, the gain or loss from its disposition is short term.\",\"If you hold a capital asset less than 1 year, the gain or loss from its disposition is long term.\",\"If you hold a capital asset 1 year and a day, the gain or loss from its disposition is short term.\",\"If you hold a capital asset less than 1 year and a day, the gain or loss from its disposition is long term.\"]',0,'Publication 550, page 80, essentially states that if a capital asset is held more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss.nnTo determine how long the taxpayer held the investment property, the taxpayer begins counting on the date after the day the property is acquired and includes the day the property is disposed of.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(233,5,'If you purchase stock of a small corporation meeting the requirements of Section 1244 (small business) stock, and you sell that stock at a loss, the loss from that stock will be reported as:','[\"long-term loss.\",\"ordinary loss.\",\"short-term loss.\",\"ordinary loss subject to limitations.\"]',3,'A taxpayer can deduct as an ordinary loss, rather than as a capital loss, his or her loss on the sale, trade, or worthlessness of a small business investment company (also known as Section 1244 stock or a SBIC stock). The loss is reported on Form 4797, Part II, line 10. Any gain on this stock is capital gain and is reported on Form 8949 if the stock is a capital asset in the taxpayer\'s hands (Publication 550, page 65).nnFor more information on losses on Section 1244 (small business) stock, see chapter 4 of Publication 550.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(234,5,'All of the following statements about a Coverdell education savings account are correct for 2024, except:','[\"the maximum contributions on behalf of a beneficiary per year are $2,000.\",\"the maximum number of accounts that a beneficiary can have is three.\",\"contributions to the account are not deductible.\",\"earnings on the account may be taxable when distributed.\"]',1,'Publication 970, page 41, states that a taxpayer may be able to establish a Coverdell Education Savings Account (ESA) to finance the qualified education expenses of a designated beneficiary if the taxpayer\'s modified adjusted gross income is less than $110,000 ($220,000 if filing a joint return).nnFurthermore, there is no limit on the number of separate Coverdell ESAs that can be established for a designated beneficiary. However, contributions must be in cash and cannot be made after the beneficiary reaches age 18, unless the beneficiary is a special-needs beneficiary. In addition, the total contributions for the beneficiary in any year cannot be more than $2,000, no matter how many accounts have been established. (Publication 970, page 42)nnContributions to a Coverdell account are not deductible, but the earnings on the account are not taxable until distributed. Better yet, the distribution may be tax-free, depending on the situation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(235,5,'Marge Godfrey sold her investment property March 30, 2024, at a gain of $50,000. Marge expects to owe $10,000 in additional income taxes on this sale. She had a tax liability of $900 for 2024 and will have no withholding for 2024. Marge\'s first estimated tax payment is due on what date?','[\"April 30, 2024\",\"April 15, 2024\",\"June 15, 2024\",\"January 15, 2025\"]',1,'Estimated tax is the method used to pay tax on income that is not subject to withholdings, which is discussed beginning on page 41 of Publication 17.nnThe tax year is divided into four payment periods for taxpayers that are required to make estimated tax payments. Each period has a specific payment due date, and if the taxpayer does not pay enough tax by the due date of each of the payment periods, then a penalty may be charged even if the taxpayer is due a refund when the income tax return is filed. (Publication 17, page 41)nnThe specific payment dates for estimated tax payments are as follows: April 15, June 15, September 15 of the tax year, and finally January 15 of the following year. Each payment is equal to one-quarter of the total estimated payment. Be aware, the payment date may differ from year to year due to the 15th falling on a Saturday, Sunday, or holiday. If the due date for an estimated tax payment falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the payment will be on time if made on the next day that is not a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday. (Publication 17, page 42) nnA taxpayer is responsible for making estimated tax payments after the taxpayer has income on which a tax amount is owed. In such a case, if the taxpayer has income subject to estimated tax during the first payment period, the taxpayer must make the first payment by the due date for the first payment period (i.e., January 1 through March 31). The taxpayer has the option of paying all of the estimated tax at that time or paying it in installments. If the installment method is chosen, the taxpayer must make the first payment by the due date for the first payment period and the proper payments for each successive payment due date (Publication 17, page 42).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(236,5,'Jerry has two dependent children, Greg and Mandy, who are attending an accredited, qualified college in 2024. Greg is a senior who spent $7,000 for tuition and fees. Mandy, a freshman with no prior postsecondary education, had tuition expenses of $5,000 and transportation expenses of $400. Jerry meets all the income and filing status requirements for the education credits. Which of the following statements is correct for 2024?','[\"Jerry cannot claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit on the room and board expenses of Mandy.\",\"Jerry can claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit on the educational cost of Greg.\",\"Jerry cannot claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit on the transportation expenses of Mandy.\",\"All of these statements are correct.\"]',3,'Taxpayers are able to claim an American Opportunity Tax Credit if the taxpayers can satisfy all three of the following requirements (Publication 970, pages 11–12):nnthe taxpayer pays qualified education expenses of higher education,nthe taxpayer pays the qualified education expenses for an eligible student, andnthe eligible student is the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s spouse, or a dependent for which the taxpayer claims an exemption on his or her tax return.nThe American Opportunity Credit is available for qualified education expenses, which include tuition and certain related expenses required for enrollment or attendance at an eligible educational institution. Qualified education expenses do not include amounts paid for insurance, medical expenses, room and board, and transportation, to name a few items. (Publication 970, pages 13 and 17)nnAs a result, all the responses given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(237,5,'In computing the gain or loss from a sale or trade of property, which statement below best describes the amount you realize?','[\"The money you actually receive\",\"The fair market value of the property on the transaction date\",\"Everything you receive for the property\",\"The value of any services you received\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property (Publication 550, page 65).nnIf the amount realized from a sale or trade is more than the adjusted basis of the property the taxpayer transferred, the difference is a gain.nIf the adjusted basis of the property transferred is more than the amount realized, the difference is a loss.nThe amount realized from a sale or trade of property is everything received for the property minus expenses related to sale. This includes the money received plus the fair market value of any property or services received. Hence, the best response to this question is everything you receive for the property. (Publication 550, page 65)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(238,5,'Sam uses his personal vehicle to make business deliveries. He submits the number of miles he drives to his employer and is reimbursed an amount per mile which exceeds the federal rate. Sam\'s actual expenses are more than the federal rate. His employer includes the amount up to the federal rate in box 12 of Form W-2 where it is not taxable to Sam. The excess allowance is included in box 1 of the Form W-2 as wages. How should Sam report or claim this mileage in 2024?','[\"File Form 2106 to deduct the excess expenses.\",\"Repay the excess to his employer.\",\"He cannot claim any of the unreimbursed expenses on Form 2106.\",\"If he files Form 2106, he need not reduce his mileage expense by his reimbursed amount.\"]',2,'If a taxpayer\'s allowance is more than the federal rate, the employer must include the allowance amount up to the federal rate under Code L in box 12 and the excess allowance in box 1 of the employee\'s W-2:nnIf the employee\'s actual expenses are less than or equal to the federal rate, he or she does not need to complete Form 2106 because the allowance should not be included in box 1 of Form W-2.nIf the employee\'s actual expenses are greater than the federal rate and they are eligible to file Form 2106, he or she needs to complete Form 2106 to deduct the excess expenses. However, the employee must report on Form 2106 their reimbursements up to the federal rate (as shown under code L in box 12 of your Form W-2) and all their expenses. The employee should be able to prove these amounts to the IRS.nIf the employee\'s actual expenses are greater than the federal rate and they are not eligible to file Form 2106 (do not meet the exceptions listed in Publication 17, page 102), he or she cannot deduct the unreimbursed employee expenses.nExample: Joe, a performing artist, lives and works in Austin. In May, his employer sent him to San Diego for 4 days and paid the hotel directly for Joe\'s hotel bill. The employer reimbursed Joe $75 a day for his meals and incidental expenses. The federal rate for San Diego is $71 a day.nnJoe can prove that his actual non-entertainment-related meal expenses totaled $380. His employer\'s accountable plan won’t pay more than $75 a day for travel to San Diego, so Joe doesn’t give his employer the records that prove that he actually spent $380. However, he does account for the time, place, and business purpose of the trip. This is Joe\'s only business trip this year.nnJoe was reimbursed $300 ($75 × 4 days), which is $16 more than the federal rate of $284 ($71 × 4 days). His employer includes the $16 as income on Joe\'s Form W-2 in box 1. His employer also enters $284 under code L in box 12 of Joe\'s Form W-2.nnUnless Joe meets one of the exceptions under Publication 17, page 102, Joe may not file Form 2106 to claim a deduction for his unreimbursed business expenses.nnTherefore, the correct response for this situation is he cannot claim any of the unreimbursed expenses on Form 2106.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(239,5,'For 8 months of each year, George lives in Ocala, Florida, training horses for several owners and earning approximately $20,000. He rents an apartment for the 8 months. He stays in motels or rented rooms at various racetracks in other states for the other 4 months of the year during horse racing season and earns approximately $10,000. What part of George\'s travel expenses can be deducted?','[\"All meals and lodging for the entire year\",\"Only his meals and lodging for the 4 months he is away from his tax home, Ocala\",\"None of his meals or lodging because he has no tax home\",\"1\\/3rd of his total meals and lodging because he is away from his tax home 1\\/3rd of the year\"]',1,'Publication 463 addresses many questions associated with travel and entertainment expenses. On page 6, it states that a taxpayer may regularly work at a person\'s tax home and also work at another location. It may not be practical to return to the person\'s tax home from this other location at the end of each workday. In such cases, the taxpayer\'s tax home does not change. Rather, the taxpayer is considered to be temporarily away from home for the whole period that the person is away from the main place of work. During this travel period, the taxpayer is able to deduct travel expenses if they otherwise qualify for deduction. Generally, a temporary assignment in a single location is one that is realistically expected to last (and does in fact last) for 1 year or less.nnTravel expenses are deductible if they are ordinary and necessary expenses that are incurred while traveling away from home on business. The type of expenses that can be deducted depends on the taxpayer\'s facts and circumstances. Table 1-1 on page 7 of Publication 463 summarizes travel expenses; they include, in general, transportation, car, lodging and meals, cleaning, telephone, and tips.nnIn this case, George is able to deduct his meals and lodging for the 4 months that he is away from his tax home of Florida because he is self-employed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(240,5,'Dr. Steve and Joyce are married and have a tax liability of $16,835 in 2024. Their withholding was $14,337 during the year. Their AGI has exceeded $200,000 for the past three years. The couple had a tax liability of $16,700 on their 2023 tax return. For 2024, they would need to make:n','[\"estimated payments of $2,498.\",\"estimated payments of $815.\",\"estimated payments of $2,363.\",\"no estimated tax payments since they have withholding taxes.\"]',1,'Publication 505, pages 19 through 22, provides the estimated tax safe harbor rules (i.e., special rules) for higher income taxpayers. Specifically, if the taxpayer\'s adjusted gross income in 2023 is more than $150,000 ($75,000 if married filing a separate return), the person will have to deposit the smaller of:nn90% of the expected tax for 2024 orn110% of the tax shown on the person\'s 2023 return to avoid an estimated tax penalty. (This replaces the 100% of the tax shown that applies to regular taxpayers with less than $150,000 AGI).nIn this case, 90% of $16,835 is $15,152, which means the taxpayer would need to make an additional payment of $815 ($15,152 – $14,337).nnAlternatively, 110% of $16,700 is $18,370, which means the taxpayer would need to make an additional payment of $4,033 ($18,370 − $14,337).nnSince $815 is the lesser amount, the taxpayer would satisfy the rule by making that payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(241,5,'In 2024, Jonathan Smith paid his educational expenses at a community college where he completed his freshman year and began his sophomore year. His father, John Smith, provides more than half of the support for Jonathan and claims an exemption for him on his tax return. Which of the following is correct?','[\"Jonathan is eligible to take the American Opportunity Tax Credit on his 2024 tax return.\",\"John is eligible to take the American Opportunity Tax Credit on his 2024 tax return.\",\"Jonathan and John may split the American Opportunity Tax Credit between their 2024 tax returns.\",\"Neither may take the American Opportunity Tax Credit.\"]',1,'In general, a taxpayer can claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit of up to $2,500 for qualified educational expenses paid for each eligible student. A taxpayer can claim the credit if all three of the following conditions are satisfied (Publication 970, page 11):nnThe taxpayer pays qualified education expenses of higher education.nThe taxpayer pays the qualified educational expenses for an eligible student.nThe eligible student is the taxpayer, spouse, or a dependent for which the taxpayer claims an exemption on the taxpayer\'s tax return.nIf the taxpayer claims an exemption for a dependent who is an eligible student, only the taxpayer can include any expenses paid when figuring the amount of an education credit. If neither the taxpayer nor anyone else claims an exemption for the dependent, only the dependent can include any expenses paid by the taxpayer when figuring an education credit (Publication 970, page 20). Please refer to summarizing table on page 20 of Publication 970 that covers other examples of when the dependent himself or a third party pays for education expenses.nnIn our case, although the son (Jonathan) paid the expenses, the father (John) is claiming the son (Jonathan) as a dependent on his return, and so the father (John) is entitled to the American Opportunity Credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(242,5,'All of the following statements are correct if you have started taking equal periodic distributions from a traditional IRA and you convert the amounts in the traditional IRA to a Roth IRA and then continue the periodic payments, except:','[\"the taxpayer has a failed conversion.\",\"the 10% additional tax on early distributions will not apply.\",\"the rule that conversion is permitted if the taxpayer is not a married individual filing a separate return will not apply.\",\"the rule that the taxpayer\'s modified AGI for Roth IRA purposes is not more than $100,000 will not apply.\"]',0,'According to Publication 590-A, page 29, if a taxpayer has started taking substantially equal periodic payments from a traditional IRA, the taxpayer may convert the amounts in the traditional IRA to a Roth IRA and then continue the periodic payments. The 10% additional tax on early distributions will not apply even if the distributions are not qualified distributions (as long as they are part of a series of substantially equal periodic payments).nnFurthermore, starting in 2010 the $100,000 modified AGI limit and filing status requirements were eliminated. Therefore, the taxpayer does not have a failed conversion.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(243,5,'What action should a taxpayer take if she gets married in October but made estimated tax payments during the year under her maiden name?','[\"Attach a statement to the front of the paper tax return\",\"File amended estimated tax forms\",\"File any remaining estimated tax forms under her maiden name\",\"No action is necessary.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Form 1040-ES, page 3, if a taxpayer changes his or her name because of marriage, divorce, etc. and they made estimated tax payments using their former name, the taxpayer should attach a statement to the front of the paper tax return. On the form, the following information should be given: all of the estimated tax payments the taxpayer (and the taxpayer\'s spouse, if filing jointly) made for the current tax year and the name(s) and SSN(s) under which the taxpayer made the payments.nnIn addition, the taxpayer should be advised to report the change, if they have not already, to their local Social Security Administration office before filing the tax return to prevent delays in processing the tax return.nnHence, the correct response for this question is to attach a statement to the front of the tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(244,5,'An individual taxpayer has capital gain distributions only, and no other capital gains. Which of the following satisfies the reporting requirements?','[\"All capital gain distributions must be entered on Schedule B.\",\"No Schedule D is required and the amount is entered directly on Form 1040.\",\"Dividends and capital gains distributions are totaled on Schedule B and carried to the front page of Form 1040.\",\"If there are no other capital gains, capital gain distributions must be combined with interest on the Schedule B.\"]',1,'If a taxpayer does not have any capital losses and only receives capital gain distributions, they are not required to complete and file a Form 8949 and/or Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) if both of the following are true (per “Exception 1” on pages 64 and 65 of Publication 550):nnThe amounts that would be reported on Schedule D would be the capital gain distributions from box 2a of Form 1099-DIV.nThe 1099-DIV received does not include any amounts in boxes 2b, 2c, or 2d of any Form 1099-DIV.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(245,5,'To meet your employer\'s reimbursement or allowance arrangement accountable plan, which of the following are the requirements of his accountable plan?','[\"Your expenses must have a business connection.\",\"You must adequately account to your employer for these expenses within a reasonable period of time.\",\"You must return any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period of time.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 463, page 42, states an accountable plan is one where the employer\'s reimbursement or allowance arrangement must include all three of the following rules:nnThe taxpayer\'s expenses must have a business connection—that is, the taxpayer must have paid or incurred deductible expenses while performing services as an employee of the employer.nThe taxpayer must adequately account to the employer for these expenses within a reasonable period of time.nThe taxpayer must return any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period of time.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(246,5,'Jim and Tammy, husband and wife, were both employed and filed a joint return, which showed they were entitled to a refund of $1,000. Rather than receiving the refund of $1,000, they received a notice advising them that the entire refund was applied to an amount due that Jim owed from a prior year, which was before they were married. What is the likely outcome if Tammy files Form 8857, Request for Innocent Spouse Relief?','[\"Tammy will receive a refund of $500 and Jim will still owe $500 in back taxes.\",\"Tammy will receive a refund of $1,000 and Jim will still owe $1,000 in back taxes.\",\"Tammy is\\u00a0not\\u00a0an innocent spouse and therefore she will receive no refund.\",\"Tammy is an innocent spouse, but she will\\u00a0not\\u00a0qualify for any refund.\"]',2,'When taxpayers file a joint income tax return, the law makes both spouses responsible for the entire tax liability. This is called joint and several liability. In some cases, a spouse (or former spouse) will be relieved of the tax, interest, and penalties on a joint return. Three types of relief are available to married persons who filed joint returns: innocent spouse relief, separation of liability relief, and equitable relief. (Publication 971, pages 1 and 2)nnAs provided on page 5 of Publication 971, a taxpayer requests innocent spouse relief by filing Form 8857, Request for Innocent Spouse Relief, which relieves the taxpayer of paying tax, interest, and penalties if the taxpayer\'s spouse (or former spouse) improperly reported items or omitted items on the taxpayer\'s tax return. Generally, the tax, interest, and penalties that qualify for relief can only be collected from a taxpayer\'s spouse (or former spouse). However, a taxpayer is jointly and individually responsible for any tax, interest, and penalties that do not qualify for relief.nnA taxpayer must meet all of the following conditions to qualify for innocent spouse relief:nnThe taxpayer must have filed a joint return.nThere is an understatement of tax due to erroneous items of the taxpayer\'s spouse (or former spouse).nThe taxpayer must establish that, at the time the taxpayer signed the joint return, the taxpayer did not know, and had no reason to know, that there was an understatement of tax.nTaking into account all the facts and circumstances, it would be unfair to hold the spouse liable for the understatement of tax.nPursuant to Publication 971, page 2, a taxpayer can be an injured spouse if the taxpayer\'s share of the overpayment was, or is expected to be, applied (offset) against the other taxpayer\'s past-due federal tax, child or spousal support, federal nontax debt (such as a student loan), or state income tax. In this case, the taxpayer completes Form 8379, Injured Spouse Allocation, if the taxpayer wants his or her share of the overpayment shown on the joint return refunded to the taxpayer.nnPublication 971, pages 4 and 5, provides that if the taxpayer\'s residence is in a community property state, the taxpayer may file Form 8379 if only he or she is not legally obligated to pay the past-due amount.nnFurthermore, the taxpayer is an injured spouse if the taxpayer:nnis not legally obligated to pay the past-due amount andnsatisfies any one of the following conditions: made and reported tax payments; had earned income such as wages, salaries, or self-employment income and claimed the earned income credit or the additional child tax credit; or claimed a refundable tax credit, such as the health coverage tax credit or the refundable credit for prior-year minimum tax.nGiven the above rules, Tammy does not meet the requirements for innocent spouse because the overpayment is being applied against her husband’s past-due federal taxes, and therefore she cannot file Form 8857. On the other hand, she may qualify for relief due as an injured spouse and, as such, she can file Form 8379 to obtain her portion of the refund.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(247,5,'In order to qualify as an accountable plan for reimbursement of travel expenses, the employer plan must satisfy all of the following, except:','[\"the expenses have a business connection.\",\"the employee must make an adequate and timely accounting to the employer.\",\"the employer must pay a per diem for meals.\",\"the employee must timely return any excess reimbursements.\"]',2,'In order for an employer\'s reimbursement or allowance arrangements to qualify as an accountable plan the arrangements must include all three of the following rules:nnYour expenses must have a business connection—that is, you must have paid or incurred deductible expenses while performing services as an employee of your employer.nYou must adequately account to your employer for these expenses within a reasonable period of time.nYou must return any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period of time.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(248,5,'Under which of the following conditions may the substantial understatement of income tax penalty be assessed a taxpayer whose earned income tax credit is disallowed?','[\"All of the taxpayers listed would be subject to the substantial understatement of income tax penalty.\",\"A taxpayer whose understatement is greater than 10% of the correct tax and the amount owed is less than $5,000\",\"A taxpayer whose understatement is greater than 10% of the correct tax and the amount owed is greater than $5,000\",\"A taxpayer whose understatement is less than 10% of the correct tax but the amount owed is greater than $5,000\"]',0,'The substantial understatement of income tax penalty may be assessed a taxpayer if the tax shown on their tax return is less than the correct tax. In particular, the understatement is substantial if it is more than the larger of:nn10% of the correct tax orn$5,000.nThis amount of the understatement may be reduced to the extent the understatement is due to (1) substantial authority or (2) adequate disclosure and a reasonable basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(249,5,'What is the excise tax rate if distributions from a traditional IRA are less than the minimum required distribution in 2024?','[0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625,0.5,0.25,\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'A taxpayer cannot keep funds in a traditional IRA (including SEP and SIMPLE IRAs) indefinitely. Required minimum distributions must be taken annually. If there are no distributions, or if the distributions are not large enough, the taxpayer may have to pay a 25% excise tax on the amount not distributed as required. This amount decreased from 50% in 2023. It can be reduced to 10% if other conditions are met.nnAs an aside, the 10% penalty is assessed on those taxpayers that take early distribution (e.g., before age 59-1/2).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(250,5,'What action should a taxpayer take if they receive a Form 1099-MISC with the wrong dollar amount in box 7?','[\"Contact the payer for a corrected Form 1099-MISC\",\"Disregard the Form 1099-MISC since it is incorrect\",\"Contact the IRS for a corrected Form 1099-MISC\",\"Report the income as stated on the Form 1099-MISC\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 44, provides that if a taxpayer receives a form that shows an incorrect amount (or other incorrect information), they should ask the payer for a corrected form. The new Form W-2G or Form 1099 will be marked with an “X” in the “Corrected” box. A special form, Form W-2c, Corrected Wages and Tax Statement, is used to correct a Form W-2.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(251,5,'Which of the following income types is not reported on Form 1099-MISC?','[\"Nonemployee compensation over $600\",\"Rents of $600 of more\",\"Crop insurance proceeds of $600 or more\",\"Medical and health care payments of $600 or more made in the course of the taxpayer\\u2019s trade of business\"]',0,'Due to the creation of Form 1099-NEC, Form 1099-MISC, Miscellaneous Income, has been redesigned and box numbers rearranged for reporting certain income (Form 1099-MISC Instructions, page 1). File Form 1099-MISC for each person in the course of your business to whom you have paid the following during the year:nnrents (box 1);nprizes and awards (box 3);nother income payments (box 3);ngenerally, the cash paid from a notional principal contract to an individual, partnership, or estate (box 3);nany fishing boat proceeds (box 5);nmedical and health care payments (box 6);ncrop insurance proceeds (box 9);npayments to an attorney (box 10);nsection 409A deferrals (box 12); ornnonqualified deferred compensation (box 14)nOn the other hand, the reintroduced Form 1099-NEC will be used to report nonemployee compensation (NEC) for each person in the course of your business to whom you have paid the following during the year:nnServices performed by someone who is not your employee (box 1)nCash payments for fish (or other aquatic life) you purchase from anyone engaged in the trade or business of catching fishnPayments to an attorney (box 1)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(252,5,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to a person\'s 2024 federal tax return?','[\"There is\\u00a0no\\u00a0difference in the tax treatment of short-term capital gains, dividends, and long-term capital gains.\",\"There is\\u00a0no\\u00a0difference in the tax treatment of short-term capital gains and dividends.\",\"There is\\u00a0no\\u00a0difference in the tax treatment of short-term capital gains and long-term capital gains.\",\"There is a difference in the tax treatment of short-term capital gains, dividends, and long-term capital gains.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 544, page 36, the tax rates that apply to a net capital gain are generally lower than the tax rates that apply to other income. These lower rates are called the maximum capital gain rates.nnThe term “net capital gain” means the amount by which the net long-term capital gain for the year exceeds the net short-term capital loss. For 2024, the maximum capital gains rates are 0%, 15%, 20%, 25%, or 28%, depending on the assets. (See page 36 of Publication 544.)nnIn this case, the correct response is that there is a difference in the tax treatment of short-term capital gains, dividends, and long-term capital gains.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(253,5,'John bought a condominium and lived in it as his principal residence for $250,000 on May 1, 2022. He sold it on May 3, 2024, for $400,000. What is the amount and character of his gain to be reported?','[\"No gain on sale\",\"Long-term, capital gain of $150,000\",\"Long-term, ordinary gain of $650,000\",\"Short-term, capital gain of $150,000\"]',0,'Pages 14 through 15 of Publication 523 provide that the gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary residence, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 15)nA condominium (as well as houseboat, mobile home, or cooperative apartment) qualifies as a main home as provided in Publication 523, page 3. Therefore, John satisfied the special rule for excluding up to $250,000. In this case, the gain from the sale is $150,000, which is the amount received of $400,000 less the property\'s basis of $250,000. Since $150,000 is less than the excludable amount, the correct answer is no gain on sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(254,5,'John failed to take required minimum distributions from his traditional IRA. The excess accumulation is subject to a penalty of:','[\"6%.\",\"25%.\",\"10%.\",\"50%.\"]',1,'A taxpayer cannot keep funds in a traditional IRA (including SEP and SIMPLE IRAs) indefinitely. Required minimum distributions must be taken annually. If there are no distributions, or if the distributions are not large enough, the taxpayer may have to pay a 25% excise tax on the amount not distributed as required.nnDue to the fact that John failed to take required minimum distributions from his traditional IRA, the excess accumulation (also known as minimum distribution) is subject to a penalty of 25%',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(255,5,'Which of the following is not a deductible transportation expense?','[\"Cost of round-trip transportation between an individual\'s office and his client\'s place of business\",\"Cost of round-trip transportation between an individual\'s home and a temporary training site in the same city\",\"Cost of round-trip transportation between an individual\'s home and office while conducting business on his car phone\",\"Cost of round-trip transportation between an individual\'s office in the home and his client\'s place of business\"]',2,'Transportation expenses are deductible as business transportation when a taxpayer is not traveling away from home. They include costs such as air, rail, bus, taxi, and the cost of driving and maintaining the taxpayer\'s car. In addition, the following costs are ordinary and necessary costs (Publication 463, page 18):nnBetween one workplace and another in the course of a person\'s business or professionnBetween an office and a “client\'s” businessnBetween one\'s workplace and a business meeting at another locationnBetween home and a temporary work or training site, either in the same city or outside the taxpayer\'s citynIf a taxpayer has an office in their home that qualifies as a principal place of business, the taxpayer can deduct their daily transportation costs between their home and another work location in the same trade or business. Publication 463, page 19)nnCommuting expenses, on the other hand, are not deductible; they are personal expenses. Publication 463, page 19, gives the following example to further clarify the fact that commuting expenses are not deductible: You sometimes use your cell phone to make business calls while commuting to and from work. Sometimes business associates ride with you to and from work, and you have a business discussion in the car. These activities do not change the trip\'s expenses from commuting to business. You cannot deduct your commuting expenses.nnAs a result, using a cell phone does not make commuting expense deductible. Likewise, putting an advertising display on a taxpayer\'s car or hauling tools or instruments to and from work does not make commuting expenses deductible. However, going between two business locations is deductible as described in the other answer choices.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(256,5,'Each month Betsy\'s employer gives her $600 for her business expenses. Sometimes Betsy spends more than the $600. Once a year, she negotiates the amount of expense money with her employer but she is not required to submit any proof of how she spends the $600 per month. How should Betsy report her expenses on her return?','[\"No reporting required\",\"Deduct all of her expenses on Schedule C,\\u00a0Profit or Loss From Business\",\"Deduct all of her expenses on Form 2106,\\u00a0Employee Business Expenses\",\"Deduct her expenses in excess of $600 per month on Form 2106\"]',0,'The treatment of reimbursements depends on the type of plan maintained by the employer; there are two basic types of reimbursement arrangements: accountable plans and nonaccountable plans.nnAccountable plans are ones whereby the employer\'s reimbursement or allowance arrangement includes all three of the following rules (Publication 463, page 29):nnThe employee\'s expenses must have a business connection—that is, the employee must have paid or incurred deductible expenses while performing services as an employee of the employer,nThe employee must adequately account to the employer for these expenses within a reasonable period of time, andnThe employee must return any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period of time.nIf the plan is not an accountable plan, then it is a nonaccountable plan by default.nnEmployees generally must complete Form 2106 to deduct travel, transportation, and entertainment expenses incurred in a nonaccountable plan. However, for tax years beginning after 2017, the only taxpayers that can use Form 2106 are Armed Forces reservists, government officials who are paid on a fee basis, performing artists, and disabled employees with impairment-related work expenses. (Publication 17, page 102)nnIn this case, Betsy\'s employer does not maintain an accountable plan and she doesn\'t fall into one of the taxpayer classes listed above. Hence, she cannot deduct her excess expenses on Form 2106. However, her W-2 wages at the end of year will be increased by the total amount of employer reimbursements she has received throughout the year. Not having an accountable plan is disadvantageous to Betsy since she has to report higher wages with no counterbalance in a deduction for the business related expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(257,5,'Generally, which of the following expenses paid by Kathy, a salesperson, are deductible as entertainment expenses?','[\"Chamber of commerce dues\",\"Cover charges and cost of meals for taking a client to a nightclub\",\"Country club dues where she entertains clients\",\"None of the listed items are deductible as entertainment expenses.\"]',3,'In order to answer this question, one must understand what is meant by “entertainment expenses.” Publication 463, page 10, states, in part, that entertainment expenses include any activity that is considered to provide entertainment, amusement, or recreation. Entertainment expenses include but are not limited to entertaining guest at nightclubs; at social, athletic, and sporting clubs; at theaters; at sporting events; on yachts; or on hunting, fishing, vacation, and similar trips.nnBeginning in 2018, a taxpayer can no longer take a deduction for any expense related to activities generally considered entertainment, amusement, or recreation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(258,12,'Max, a fiduciary, pledged his client\'s traditional IRA of $300,000 as security for a loan. If Max is found liable for engaging in a prohibited transaction, what is the minimum penalty he is most likely to pay if the transaction is corrected?','[\"$45,000\",\"$30,000\",\"$36,000\",\"$300,000\"]',0,'The tax issue on a prohibited transaction is a complex one. First, the minimum additional penalty that Max (as the fiduciary) would incur by engaging in a prohibited transaction is $45,000, which is 15% of the IRA value. Second, if Max fails to correct the transaction, then he can be subject to a penalty of $300,000, which is a 100% penalty.nnThe issues of taxes on prohibited transactions by someone other than the owner is addressed on page 24 in Publication 590-B. If someone other than the owner or beneficiary of a traditional IRA engages in a prohibited transaction, that person may be liable for certain taxes. In general, there is a 15% tax on the amount of the prohibited transaction and a 100% additional tax if the transaction is not corrected.nnNote: If the taxpayer (and not someone other than the taxpayer) uses part of their traditional IRA account as security for a loan, that part is treated as a distribution and is included in their gross income. In addition, they may be subject to a 10% additional tax on the early distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(259,12,'Mr. and Mrs. Clark are both 72 years of age, married, filing jointly. They received Social Security benefits of $7,500 each. Additional income is a taxable pension of $12,000 for Mr. Clark and $6,000 for Mrs. Clark. What is the taxable portion of the Social Security benefits received by the Clarks?','[\"$15,000\",\"$7,500\",\"$3,750\",\"$0\"]',3,'Some Social Security benefits become taxable if total income (one-half of the benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest) exceeds the base amount of $25,000 in the case of a person filing single or head of household ($32,000 if married filing jointly and $0 if married and filing separate). (Publication 17, pages 61 and 62)nnIn this case, Mr. and Mrs. Clark have total income for determining if Social Security benefits are taxable of $25,500, which is the sum of the couple\'s pension of $18,000 ($12,000 + $6,000) and one-half of Social Security benefits of $7,500 (50% of $15,000). Since $25,500 is less than the $32,000 limit, none of the couple\'s Social Security benefits are included in AGI.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(260,12,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a traditional IRA that is involved in a prohibited transaction?','[\"It is treated as distributing its assets at fair market value on the last day of the year.\",\"It is treated as distributing its assets at fair market value on the day the prohibited transaction occurs.\",\"It is treated as distributing its assets at fair market value on the first day of the year.\",\"It is treated as distributing its assets at average market value for the year in which the prohibited transaction occurs.\"]',2,'Publication 590-B, pages 23 and 24, and Publication 17, page 87, provide the general rules for an IRA account when the owner engages in a prohibited transaction. Generally, if the taxpayer or taxpayer\'s beneficiary engages in a prohibited transaction in connection with the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA account at any time during the year, the account stops being an IRA as of the first day of that year.nnIf the account stops being an IRA because the taxpayer or the taxpayer\'s beneficiary engaged in a prohibited transaction, the account is treated as distributing all of its assets to the taxpayer at their fair market value on the first day of the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(261,12,'Antonio is an ordained minister. As a minister, Antonio is a common-law employee of the church where he works, but his earnings and parsonage allowance are treated as self-employment income on which he pays self-employment tax. If the church had no retirement plan under which Antonio was covered, which of the following would Antonio be permitted to establish for himself?','[\"Traditional IRA\",\"Savings incentive match plan for employees (SIMPLE) IRA\",\"Simplified employee pension (SEP)\",\"Either a traditional IRA or a SIMPLE IRA\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer can set up and contribute to a traditional IRA if the taxpayer (or, if filing a joint return, the taxpayer\'s spouse) received taxable compensation during the year.nnGenerally, compensation is the amount that the taxpayer earns from working. This includes wages and salaries, commissions, self-employment income, and alimony. Compensation includes earnings from self-employment even if they are not subject to self-employment tax because of religious beliefs. (Publication 590-A, page 6)nnSIMPLE and SEP plans are tax-favored retirement plans that certain small employers (including self-employed individuals) can set up for the benefit of their employees. If a congregation pays a salary for a minister to perform qualified services, the minister is subject to the congregation\'s control and, as such, the person is a common-law employee. Thus, the person is not self-employed for purposes of setting up a retirement plan. Even though Antonio has self-employment income, he is a common-law employee (not a small business). Hence, he is not eligible to establish either of these plans (Publication 517, page 12).nnAs an aside, amounts received directly from members of the congregation, such as fees for performing marriages, baptisms, or other personal services that are reported on Schedule C, are earnings from self-employment for all tax purposes. That is, this income is eligible for a contribution to a SIMPLE or SEP plan.nnBecause Antonio has taxable compensation during the year Antonio can establish a traditional IRA for himself.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(262,12,'Joe Smith never married and had no children. When he died, he left all of his assets, including his traditional IRA, to his nephew, David. What is David allowed to do with the inherited IRA?','[\"He could make additional direct contributions to the IRA, treating it as his own.\",\"He could roll over amounts out of the inherited IRA to another IRA with his name as owner tax-free.\",\"He could make additional contributions, which were rollovers from Roth IRAs.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 590-A, page 20, provides the general rules for an inherited IRA from someone other than a spouse. If a taxpayer inherits a traditional IRA from anyone other than the taxpayer\'s deceased spouse, he or she cannot treat the inherited IRA as his or her own. However, the taxpayer can make a trustee-to-trustee transfer to another IRA as long as the new IRA is maintained in the name of the deceased owner.nnThis means that the person cannot make any contributions to the IRA. It also means the taxpayer cannot roll over any amounts into or out of the inherited IRA. The taxpayer, however, can make a trustee-to-trustee transfer as long as the IRA into which amounts are being moved is set up and maintained in the name of the deceased IRA owner for the benefit of the taxpayer as beneficiary.nnSince David is the nephew of Joe Smith, he cannot contribute to or rollover to the inherited IRA, and he cannot rollover from the inherited IRA to his IRA. Thus, none of the items suggested in this problem are permitted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(263,12,'When must distributions from a Roth IRA begin?','[\"No later than December 31 of the year the account owner reaches age 73\",\"No later than April 1 of the year following the year the account owner reaches age 73\",\"No later than December 31 of the year following the year the account owner reaches age 73\",\"Distributions are\\u00a0not\\u00a0required during the taxpayer\'s life.\"]',3,'Publication 590-B, page 36, provides the general rule that a taxpayer is not required to take distributions from his or her Roth IRA at any age.nnThe minimum distribution rules that apply to traditional IRAs do not apply to Roth IRAs while the owner is alive. However, after the death of a Roth IRA owner, the minimum distribution rules that apply to traditional IRAs also apply to Roth IRAs.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(264,12,'Which of the following investments, if made by a traditional IRA, is not a distribution?','[\"Stamps that have been issued by the U.S. Postal Service\",\"An oil painting certified by an art expert as being an authentic original by a Dutch master artist\",\"One-ounce silver coins minted by the U.S. Treasury Department\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'If a traditional IRA invests in collectibles, the amount invested is considered distributed to the taxpayer in the year invested. The taxpayer may be required to pay a 10% additional tax on “early” distribution.nnCollectibles for this purpose include stamps, coins, artworks, rugs, antiques, metals, gems, alcoholic beverages, and certain other tangible personal property.nnThere is an exception to this rule. A traditional IRA can invest in one, one-half, one-quarter, or 1/10th ounce U.S. gold coins, or one-ounce silver coins minted by the Treasury Department, without the investment being a distribution. It also can invest in certain platinum coins and certain gold, silver, palladium, and platinum bullion.nnTherefore, a traditional IRA could invest in one-ounce silver coins minted by the U.S. Treasury Department without the investment being a distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(265,12,'Dave, age 40, had a traditional IRA with a $40,000 balance at the beginning of 2024. All of Dave\'s contributions have been tax-deductible. On July 1, 2024, Dave withdraws $20,000 from the IRA account. Which of the following would be a correct statement regarding the effects of this transaction?','[\"Dave would not have to include the $20,000 in income if it is returned to the IRA within 90 days from the day of withdrawal.\",\"Dave would be required to include $20,000 in income as a distribution in 2024.\",\"Dave would be required to include $40,000 in income as a distribution in 2024.\",\"Dave would not have to include the $20,000 in income if it were used for qualified higher education expenses.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 590-B, page 14, distributions from a traditional IRA generally are taxable in the year the taxpayer receives them. Exceptions to distributions from traditional IRAs being taxable in the year the taxpayer receives them are:rnrnrollovers (i.e., 60 days),rnqualified charitable distributions,rntax-free withdrawals of contributions, andrnthe return of nondeductible contributions.rnAs a result, Dave would be required to include $20,000 in income as a distribution in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(266,12,'Which of the following would be an allowable investment for a traditional IRA?','[\"Stamps which have been issued by the U.S. Postal Service\",\"An oil painting certified by an art expert as being an authentic original by a Dutch Master\",\"One-ounce silver coins minted by the Treasury Department\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'If a traditional IRA invests in collectibles, the amount invested is considered distributed to the taxpayer in the year invested. The taxpayer may be required to pay a 10% additional tax on “early” distribution.nnCollectibles for this purpose include stamps, coins, artworks, rugs, antiques, metals, gems, alcoholic beverages, and certain other tangible personal property.nnThere is an exception to this rule. A traditional IRA can invest in one, one-half, one-quarter, or 1/10th ounce U.S. gold coins, or one-ounce silver coins minted by the Treasury Department, without the investment being a distribution.nnTherefore, a traditional IRA could invest in one-ounce silver coins minted by the U.S. Treasury Department without the investment being a distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(267,12,'When must excess contributions to IRAs for tax year 2024 be withdrawn so that the contributions are not subject to a penalty?','[\"If the excess contributions only are withdrawn before December 31, 2025.\",\"If both the excess contributions and earnings are withdrawn before April 15, 2025 (excluding extensions).\",\"If both the excess contributions and earnings are withdrawn before April 15, 2025 (including extensions).\",\"If both the excess contributions and earnings are withdrawn before December 31, 2025.\"]',2,'Publication 590-A, pages 34 and 35, states, in part, that if any part of a taxpayer\'s contributions is an excess contribution for 2024, it is subject to a 6% excise tax. The taxpayer will not have to pay the 6% tax if any 2024 excess contributions including earnings on those contributions were withdrawn by April 15, 2025 (plus extensions).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(268,12,'Larry, age 35, made an excess contribution to his traditional IRA in 2024 of $1,000, which he withdrew by April 15, 2025. At the same time, he withdrew the $50 income that was earned on the $1,000. Which of the following statements is true?','[\"Larry must include the $50 in his gross income in 2025.\",\"Larry would have to pay the 6% excise tax on the $1,050.\",\"Larry must include the $50 in his gross income in 2024 and would have to pay the 10% additional tax on the $50 as an early distribution.\",\"Larry must include the $50 in his gross income in 2024.\"]',2,'A taxpayer will not have to pay the 6% tax if the taxpayer withdraws an excess contribution and any interest earned on the excess contribution by the date the tax return for that year is due, including extensions.rnrnAccording to Publication 590-A, page 34, a taxpayer includes in income the interest or other income that was earned on the excess contribution and that the taxpayer timely withdraws for the tax year in which the contributions are made, not the tax year in which it is withdrawn.rnrnBeginning on December 29, 2022, the 10% additional tax on early distributions will not apply to a corrective IRA distribution, which consists of an excessive contribution (a contribution greater than the IRA contribution limit) and any earnings allocable to the excessive contribution, as long as the corrective distribution is made on or before the due date (including extensions) of the income tax return.rnrnHence, the correct response is that Larry must include the $50 in his gross income in 2024 (not 2025, when he withdrew the $50).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(269,12,'Vernon, age 73, had compensation of $4,000 in 2024. He made a $4,000 contribution to his traditional IRA during 2024. The balance of the IRA account at the end of the 2024 was $10,000. Vernon did not withdraw any amount of the contribution by the due date of the 2024 return. What would be the tax because of an excess contribution for 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$90\",\"$240\",\"$150\"]',0,'The general rule for 2024 as given in Publication 590-A, page 8, is that the maximum annual contribution to a person\'s traditional IRA is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if you are 50 or older) or the person\'s taxable compensation for the year.rnrnGiven that Vernon is permitted to make contributions to his traditional IRA (the age limit was removed in 2020), all $4,000 of his contribution is no longer deemed to be an excess contribution. Hence, Vernon would owe no excise tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(270,12,'Joe has a traditional IRA with a basis of $8,800. This was his only IRA. On December 31, 2024, he converted $44,000 of the $88,000 total value of the IRA to a Roth IRA. He files as head of household and his AGI, without the conversion, is $62,000. What amount of income will be included on Joe\'s 2024 return as the result of this conversion?','[\"$8,800\",\"$35,200\",\"$39,600\",\"$44,000\"]',2,'A taxpayer is permitted to convert amounts from a traditional IRA into a Roth IRA, except for any amounts that must be distributed from the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA for that year under the required minimum distribution rules. (Publication 590-A, page 28)nnPublication 590-A, page 28, provides that a taxpayer must include in his or her gross income distributions from a traditional IRA that the taxpayer would have had to include in income if the taxpayer had not converted them into a Roth IRA. Therefore, a taxpayer would need to include the portion of the distribution that is attributable to the deductible portion of the contributions made to the traditional IRA.nnGenerally, if a taxpayer ever made a nondeductible contribution or rolled over after-tax amounts to any of their traditional IRAs, Form 8606 must be filed with their return to determine the taxable and nontaxable portions of the distribution or conversion. (Publication 590-B, page 6)nnIn this problem, Joe converted $44,000, which is half of his traditional IRA with a basis of $8,800 into a Roth IRA. As a result, Joe must include $39,600 of the converted amount into gross income. The $39,600 is the $44,000 (amount converted) less the recovered basis of $4,400 (50% of $8,800). (Note: Since the taxpayer converted 50% of their account total, 50% of the basis would be attributable to this conversion.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(271,12,'Which of the following is NOT included when calculating if any social security benefits are taxable?','[\"Interest that is tax-exempt\",\"Foreign earned income exclusion\",\"Meals excluded from gross income under Section 119\",\"Employer provided adoption benefits\"]',2,'To determine if Social Security benefits are taxable, compare the base amount for the filing status with one-half of the benefits plus other income, including tax-exempt interest. The following items do not reduce the other income:nnInterest from qualified U.S. savings bondsnEmployer-provided adoption benefitsnInterest on education loansnForeign earned income on foreign housingnIncome earned by bona fide residents of American Samoa or Puerto RiconSince meals excluded from gross income are not listed, that is the correct answer. All other exclusions cannot be used to reduce other income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(272,12,'On which of the following dates is a traditional IRA treated as distributing its assets when it is involved in a prohibited transaction?','[\"On the first day of the tax year involving the prohibited transaction\",\"On the day of the prohibited transaction\",\"On the last day of the tax year involving the prohibited transaction\",\"On the last day of the tax year preceding the prohibited transaction\"]',0,'Publication 590-B, pages 23 and 24, and Publication 17, page 87, provide the general rules for an IRA account when the owner engages in a prohibited transaction. Generally, if the taxpayer or taxpayer\'s beneficiary engages in a prohibited transaction in connection with the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA account at any time during the year, the account stops being an IRA as of the first day of that year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(273,12,'Generally, which of the following is a prohibited transaction concerning your traditional IRA?','[\"Withdraw funds for qualified higher education expenses\",\"Pledge your IRA account as security for your mortgage\",\"Withdraw funds for qualified medical expenses\",\"Withdraw funds to purchase your first home\"]',1,'Publication 590-B, pages 23 through 24, and Publication 17, page 87, provide that a prohibited transaction is any improper use of a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA account or annuity by the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s beneficiary, or any disqualified person. Disqualified persons include the taxpayer\'s fiduciary and members of the taxpayer\'s family (spouse, ancestor, lineal descendant, and any spouse of a lineal descendant).rnrnThe following are examples of prohibited transactions with a traditional IRA:rnrnBorrowing money from itrnSelling property to itrnUsing it as security for a loanrnBuying property for personal use (present or future) with IRA fundsrnIn this problem, a prohibited transaction is pledging your IRA as security for a loan.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(274,12,'Jackie 72 years old. She is required to take a minimum distribution of $39,000 from her IRA in 2024, which is all taxable, but decides to make a qualified charitable distribution from her IRA of $50,000 on March 31, 2024. What amount is included in gross income if Jackie instructs the trustee of the IRA to transfer the $50,000 to a qualified charity?','[\"$0\",\"$11,000\",\"$39,000\",\"$50,000\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 86, states, in part, that in general, distributions from a traditional IRA are taxable in the year the taxpayer receives them. The following are exceptions to the above rule: rollovers, qualified charitable distributions (QCDs), tax-free withdrawals of contributions, and return of nondeductible contributions.nnA qualified charitable distribution (QCD) is generally a nontaxable distribution made directly by the trustee of a taxpayer\'s IRA to an organization eligible to receive tax-deductible contributions. The taxpayer must have been at least age 70-1/2 when the distribution was made and the total QCD cannot be more than $105,000. In addition, the amount of the QCD is limited to the amount of the distribution that would otherwise be included in income. (Publication 590-B, pages 13–14)nnIn this case, Jackie would exclude the entire $50,000 because she satisfies all three of the conditions: the amount is less than $105,000, she is over 70-1/2 when the gift is given, and the entire amount would otherwise be taxable income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(275,12,'Martin, age 35, made an excess contribution to his traditional IRA in 2024 of $1,000, which he withdrew by April 15, 2025. At the same time, he withdrew the $50 income that was earned on the $1,000. Which of the following statements is true?','[\"Martin must include the $50 in his gross income in 2025.\",\"Martin would have to pay the 6% excise tax on the $1,050.\",\"Martin must include the $50 in his gross income in 2024 and Martin would have to pay the 10% additional tax on the $50 as an early distribution.\",\"Martin must include the $50 in his gross income in 2024.\"]',2,'According to Publication 590-A, page 34, A taxpayer includes in income the interest or other income that was earned on the excess contribution that the taxpayer timely withdraws for the tax year in which the contributions are made, not the tax year in which it is withdrawn.rnIn addition, excess contributions generally are subject to a 6% excise tax. A taxpayer, however, can avoid the 6% excise tax on the 2024 excess contribution if withdrawn by April 15, 2025 (plus extensions).rnFinally, the 10% additional tax on early distributions (i.e., before reaching age 59-1/2) does not apply to the tax-free withdrawals of the taxpayer\'s contributions, but it does apply to the taxable distribution of interest.rnHence, the correct response is that Martin must include the $50 in his gross income in 2024 and Martin would have to pay the 10% additional tax on the $50 as an early distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(276,12,'Donovan established a Roth IRA in 2021 at age 58 and has contributed $3,000 each year up through 2023. In 2024, at age 60, Donovan received a distribution of his entire account balance from the Roth IRA. Which of the following statements would be correct concerning the distribution amount?','[\"None of the distribution would be included in his gross income.\",\"Only the earnings would be included in his gross income.\",\"Only the contribution amounts would be included in his gross income.\",\"The entire distribution would be included in his gross income.\"]',0,'Publication 590-B, page 31, provides that a taxpayer generally does not include in their gross income qualified distributions or distributions that are a return of the regular contributions from a Roth IRA(s). Additionally, a rollover distribution from one Roth IRA into another Roth IRA is not included in gross income.nnIf, however, a taxpayer receives a distribution from a Roth IRA that is not a qualified distribution (i.e., within the first 5-year period), part of it may be taxable and it may be subject to the 10% additional tax on an early distribution.nnA qualified distribution is any payment or distribution from a Roth IRA that meets the following requirements:nnIt is made after the 5-year period beginning with the first taxable year for which a contribution was made to a Roth IRA set up for your benefit, andnthe payment or distribution is:nmade on or after the date you reach age 59-1/2,nmade because you are disabled,nmade to a beneficiary or to your estate after your death, ornto buy, build or rebuild a new home that meets the requirements listed under “First home” under “Exceptions” in Chapter 1 of Publication 590-B, page 27 (up to a $10,000 lifetime limit).nSince the distribution was not made after the 5th year, it is not a qualified one. Hence, the earnings on the investment would be included in gross income and the taxable amount would not be subject to the 10% early distribution excise tax because the taxpayer is over age 59-1/2.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(277,12,'Mrs. Domino made deductible contributions to traditional individual retirement accounts for several years. She decides to withdraw $10,000 from one of her accounts in 2024. Mrs. Domino is 61 years old. How does this transaction affect Mrs. Domino\'s 2024 tax return?','[\"Mrs. Domino must report the entire amount of $10,000.\",\"Mrs. Domino does not have to report anything because she is older than 59-1\\/2 years.\",\"Mrs. Domino does not have to report any amount because this was not withdrawn from a Roth IRA.\",\"Mrs. Domino must report all of the distribution received but can elect to use the 10-year option.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 83, provides that, in general, distributions from a traditional IRA are taxable in the year the taxpayer receives them. There are some exceptions to the general rule, as one would expect. Exceptions to distributions from traditional IRAs being taxable in the year a taxpayer receives them are:nnrollovers,nqualified charitable distributions from an IRA,ntax-free withdrawals of contributions, andnthe return of nondeductible contributions.nDistributions from traditional IRAs may be fully or partly taxable, depending on whether the taxpayer\'s IRA includes any nondeductible contributions. If only deductible contributions were made to the traditional IRA, the taxpayer has no basis in the investment and thus the taxpayer includes the full amount in gross income, which means that the amount is taxed as ordinary income.nnMrs. Domino, therefore, must report the entire amount of $10,000 in gross income in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(278,12,'In 2024, Ivan was over age 72. The balance at the beginning of 2024 of his traditional IRA was $41,000. All of his IRA contributions had been tax-deductible. The required minimum distribution for 2024 will be $3,000. If Ivan takes a distribution of only $1,000, what is the amount of excise tax that Ivan would have to pay on the excess accumulation?','[\"$1,000\",\"$200\",\"$500\",\"$2,400\"]',2,'A taxpayer cannot keep funds in a traditional IRA indefinitely. Required minimum distributions must be taken annually. If there are no distributions, or if the distributions do not equal or exceed the minimum required distribution amount, the taxpayer incurs a 25% excise tax (reduced from 50%) on the amount not distributed as required.nnIn this problem, failure to take the minimum distribution amount results in an excise tax of $1,000, calculated as follows:nn  Required Minimum Distribution:   $3,000n  Less amount distributed:          1,000n  Deficiency:                      $2,000n  Excise Tax Rate:                     25%n  Excise Tax:                      $  500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(279,12,'To recharacterize a contribution from a Roth IRA that was made in 2023 back to a traditional IRA in 2024, you must do the following:','[\"Withdraw the earnings, as only the principal investment is eligible\",\"A trustee-to-trustee transfer by October 15, 2024, including the income earned, if any\",\"Request written permission from the IRS\",\"File Form 5329 to pay the penalty on the earnings\"]',1,'A taxpayer may be able to treat a contribution made to one type of IRA as having been made to a different type of IRA. This is called recharacterizing the contribution.rnrnIn order to recharacterize a contribution, the contribution and any net income allocable to the contribution must be transferred from the first IRA (the one to which it was made) to the second IRA in a trustee-to-trustee transfer. If the transfer is made by the due date (including extensions) for the taxpayer\'s tax return for the year during which the contribution was made, an election to treat the contribution as having been originally made to the second IRA instead of to the first IRA can be made.rnrnA conversion of a traditional IRA to a Roth IRA, and a rollover from any other eligible retirement plan to a Roth IRA, made in tax years beginning after December 31, 2017, cannot be recharacterized as having been made to a traditional IRA.  To recharacterize a Roth IRA contribution made in 2023 back to a Traditional IRA in 2024, the IRS requires:rnrnA trustee-to-trustee transfer (you can’t just withdraw and redeposit the funds yourself).rnThe transfer must include the original contribution plus or minus any earnings (or losses).rnIt must be completed by your tax filing deadline for 2023, including extensions — typically October 15, 2024 if you filed an extension.rnrnIn this case, the contribution made to the Roth IRA is not a conversion; hence, it can be recharacterized by October 15, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(280,12,'Which of the following is an example of prohibited transactions with a traditional IRA?','[\"Selling property to it\",\"Using it as security for a loan\",\"Buying property for personal use with your IRA funds\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 590-B, pages 23 and 24, and Publication 17, page 87, provide that a prohibited transaction is any improper use of a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA account or annuity by the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s beneficiary, or any disqualified person. Disqualified persons include the taxpayer\'s fiduciary and members of the taxpayer\'s family (spouse, ancestor, lineal descendant, and any spouse of a lineal descendant).nnThe following are examples of prohibited transactions with a traditional IRA:nnBorrowing money from itnSelling property to itnUsing it as security for a loannBuying property for personal use (present or future) with IRA fundsnAs given in the list above, all the transactions given in this problem qualify as prohibited transactions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(281,12,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning excess contribution to a traditional IRA and the 6% excise tax?','[\"The contribution and any earnings on it must be withdrawn by the date the taxpayer\'s return is due (or within 6 months of the due date, excluding extensions) to avoid the 6% excise tax.\",\"The contribution and any earnings on it must be withdrawn by the date the taxpayer\'s return is due (or within 6 months of the due date, including extensions) to avoid the 6% excise tax.\",\"The contribution only must be withdrawn by the date the taxpayer\'s return is due (including extension) to avoid the 6% excise tax.\",\"The contribution only must be withdrawn by the date the taxpayer\'s return is due (excluding extension) to avoid the 6% excise tax.\"]',0,'Publication 590-A, pages 33 and 34, provides the general rules for the tax when making an excess contribution to an IRA. In general, if the excess contributions for a year and the interest or other income that was earned on the excess contribution are not withdrawn by the date the taxpayer\'s return for the year is due (within 6 months of the due date of your return, including extensions), the taxpayer is subject to a 6% tax.nnThe taxpayer must pay the 6% tax each year on excess amounts that remain in the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA at the end of the tax year. The tax cannot be more than 6% of the value of the taxpayer\'s IRA as of the end of the taxpayer\'s tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(282,12,'Which of the following is not a prohibited transaction for a person\'s traditional IRA?','[\"Using it as security for a loan\",\"Selling property to it\",\"Receiving unreasonable compensation for managing it\",\"All of the answer choices are prohibited transactions.\"]',3,'Publication 590-B, pages 23 and 24, and Publication 17, page 87, provide that a prohibited transaction is any improper use of a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA account or annuity by the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s beneficiary, or any disqualified person. Disqualified persons include the taxpayer\'s fiduciary and members of the taxpayer\'s family (spouse, ancestor, lineal descendant, and any spouse of a lineal descendant).nnThe following are examples of prohibited transactions with a traditional IRA:nnBorrowing money from itnSelling property to itnUsing it as security for a loannBuying property for personal use (present or future) with IRA fundsnAs a result, all of the responses are prohibited transactions for a person\'s traditional IRA.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(283,12,'Adam, a single taxpayer, converted $40,000 from his traditional IRA into a Roth IRA in 2024. His AGI for 2024, including the conversion income, was $120,000. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Adam has a successful conversion.\",\"Adam has a failed conversion and must recharacterize $20,000 to his traditional IRA.\",\"Adam has a failed conversion and must recharacterize $40,000 to his traditional IRA.\",\"Adam has a failed conversion and must withdraw the $40,000 from his Roth IRA.\"]',0,'A taxpayer can withdraw all or part of the assets from a traditional IRA and reinvest them within 60 days in a Roth IRA. The amount withdrawn and timely contributed (converted) to the Roth IRA is called a conversion contribution. However, a part or all of the distribution from the traditional IRA may be included in gross income and subject to ordinary income tax. (Publication 590-A, page 28)nnAs a result, Adam has a successful conversion.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(284,12,'Which of the following is a true statement regarding a rollover distribution from a qualified plan to a traditional IRA?','[\"To be an eligible rollover, you must rollover the entire distribution from the qualified plan.\",\"You can deduct the distribution rolled over, up to the amount of the allowable deductible contribution limit for the year.\",\"If you chose the direct rollover option, the payer must generally withhold 20% of it for income tax.\",\"A hardship distribution from a qualified plan is not an eligible rollover distribution.\"]',3,'Publication 575, page 28, provides the general rules for an eligible rollover distribution. An eligible rollover distribution is any distribution of all or any part of the balance to the taxpayer\'s credit in a qualified retirement plan except:nnany of a series of substantially equal distributions paid at least once a year over the taxpayer\'s lifetime or life expectancy, the joint lives or life expectancies of the taxpayer and beneficiary, or a period of 10 years or more,na required minimum distribution,nhardship distributions,ncorrective distributions of excess contributions or excess deferrals,na loan treated as a distribution,ndividends on employer securities, andnthe cost of life insurance coverage.nTherefore, a hardship distribution from a qualified plan is not an eligible rollover distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(285,12,'Maggie is 73 years of age. She received Social Security benefits of $8,000, which includes $500 for Medicare premiums. Withdrawals from her IRA were $16,000 and she received $22,000 from a pension. She also had other income of $14,000. How much is Maggie\'s adjusted gross income?','[\"$59,225\",\"$58,800\",\"$60,000\",\"$60,500\"]',1,'The first issue to be addressed in this problem is whether the taxpayer\'s Social Security benefits are taxable and, if so, to what extent: 50% or 85%. In general, the higher the income amount of the taxpayer, the more likely the benefits will be taxable. Because this taxpayer has income (ignoring Social Security benefits) of $52,000, the 85% rule is the better starting point. In particular, 85% of a person\'s Social Security benefits are taxable if either of the following situations applies (Publication 17, pages 62–63):rnrnThe total of one-half of the person\'s benefits and all other income is more than $34,000 ($44,000 if the taxpayer is married filing jointly) orrnThe taxpayer is married filing separately and lived with his or her spouse at any time during the tax year.rnIn this case, the taxpayer satisfies the first situation with a total dollar amount of $56,000 ($52,000 plus one-half of $8,000). Hence, the taxpayer has an AGI amount of $58,800, which is her other income of $52,000 plus 85% of her Social Security benefits of $8,000 ($6,800).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(286,12,'George (age 42) is a single taxpayer and has W-2 income of $61,000. During the 2024 tax year, he contributed $7,500 to his traditional IRA in addition to $7,000 to his 401(k) at work. How much is his excess contribution?','[\"$7,500\",\"$7,000\",\"$500\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 590-A, page 10, the most that a taxpayer can contribute to his or her traditional IRA is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if the taxpayer is 50 or older) or the taxpayer\'s taxable compensation for the year.nnSince George is not 50 or older, his maximum contribution amount for 2024 is $7,000. Any amount over $7,000 is considered to be an excess contribution amount. As a result, George has an excess contribution of $500 ($7,500 − $7,000). The 401(k) contribution does not limit the IRA contribution. George can contribute to both. His maximum 401(k) contribution is $23,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(287,12,'Diane, single and age 49, made a $4,000 contribution to her traditional IRA in 2024. Her compensation for 2024 was $3,000. She filed a Form 4868 for an extension until October 15, 2025, to file her 2024 return. In order to avoid the 6% additional tax on excess contributions, Diane must do which of the following?','[\"Withdraw the $1,000 excess contribution and all interest earned on the $1,000 by December 31, 2024.\",\"Withdraw the $1,000 excess contribution and all interest earned on the $1,000 by April 15, 2025.\",\"Withdraw the $1,000 excess contribution and all interest earned on the $1,000 by October 15, 2025.\",\"File an election to deduct the $1,000 on her 2025 return by attaching a statement to her 2024 return.\"]',2,'Publication 590-A, page 33, provides the general rules for the tax when making an excess contribution to an IRA. In general, the taxpayer is subject to a 6% tax if the excess contributions (including interest earned) for a year are not withdrawn by the date the taxpayer\'s return for the year is due (including extensions).nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nFor 2024, a taxpayer is 45 years old and single, his compensation is $31,000, and he contributed $7,000 to his traditional IRA. The taxpayer has made an excess contribution to his IRA of $500 ($7,000 minus the $6,500 limit). The contribution earned $5 interest in 2024 and $6 interest in 2025 before the due date of the return, including extensions. He does not withdraw the $500 or the interest it earned by the due date of his return, including extensions.nnThe taxpayer figures his additional tax for 2024 by multiplying the excess contribution ($500) by 6%, giving him an additional tax liability of $30.nn n nnTo avoid the 6% additional tax on excess contributions, Diane must withdraw the $1,000 excess contribution and all interest earned on the $1,000 by October 15, 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(288,12,'John and Mary, a married couple, have a wide variety of investments and are cash basis taxpayers. Because their self-employment earnings are considerable, they reinvested the following: $4,000 of mutual fund dividends and $5,000 of certificate of deposit interest. They also earned dividends on corporate stock of $12,000 that they received and spent. Interest of $2,000 that had accrued on a loan to a friend was not paid until the following year. What is the amount of interest and dividends currently taxable to them?','[\"$21,000\",\"$14,000\",\"$16,000\",\"$23,000\"]',0,'In general, any interest that is received or that is credited to an account and can be withdrawn is taxable income. (For exceptions to this, see chapter 6 in Publication 17.) If a taxpayer uses the cash method, interest income is reported in the year in which it was actually or constructively received. (Publication 17, pages 53 and 59)nnAs provided on page 30 of Publication 550, a number of corporations have a dividend reinvestment plan, whereby the taxpayer may choose to use his or her dividends to buy (through an agent) more shares of stock in the corporation instead of receiving the dividends in cash. If the taxpayer makes this election and stock is bought at a price equal to its fair market value, the taxpayer must report the dividends as income.nnGiven that John and Mary are cash basis taxpayers they are not required to report the accrued loan interest income of $2,000 until the year of actual receipt. Therefore, the amount of interest and dividends taxable to them is $21,000, computed as follows:nn  Mutual fund dividends               $ 4,000n  Certificate of deposit interest       5,000n  Corporate stock dividends            12,000n  Taxable interest and dividends      $21,000n nn 	Caution	 n 	 	 n 	nThe inclusion of mutual fund interest, which is taxable, is oftentimes mistaken for municipal fund interest, which is tax exempt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(289,12,'Ms. Winter owns an apartment complex. She received $5,000 in December 2024 to cover the January rents for tenants who will be on vacation January 15, 2025, when the rent is due. Although she is a cash basis taxpayer for purposes of filing her return, she uses the accrual method of accounting to maintain her books on the rental property. What amount should Ms. Winter report if she uses the accrual method of accounting?','[\"$0 in 2024 and $0 in 2025\",\"$0 in 2024 and $5,000 in 2025\",\"$5,000 in 2024 and $0 in 2025\",\"$5,000 in 2024 and $5,000 in 2025\"]',2,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in general in Publication 527. In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts that are received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property.nnIn addition to amounts received as normal rent payments, there are other amounts that may be rental income and as such are included in rental income. Advance rent, for example, is any amount received before the period that it covers. These payments are included in rental income in the year received regardless of the period covered or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer includes the $5,000 of advance rent as rental income in the year received (i.e., 2024). It does not matter what period the payment is for or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using. (See Publication 527, pages 3–4.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(290,12,'Jennifer works for Joyce and received a parcel of land as payment for her services. Joyce\'s basis in the land was $6,000 and the land had an FMV of $10,000. Jennifer\'s basis in the land is:','[\"$0.\",\"$6,000.\",\"$10,000.\",\"$4,000.\"]',2,'In general, gross income includes all income that the taxpayer receives in the form of money, goods, property, and services that is not exempt from tax. It also includes income from sources outside the United States or from the sale of a person\'s main home (even if the person can exclude all or part of it). (See Publication 17, pages 47–48.)nnWhen a taxpayer receives property for services, the taxpayer must include its fair market value in income in the year the property is received. The amount included in income becomes the taxpayer\'s basis in the property. If the services were performed for a price agreed on beforehand, it is accepted as the fair market value of the property IF there is no evidence to the contrary. (See Publication 551, pages 2–4.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(291,12,'Clyde is a degree candidate at a local college. During the fall semester, he received a $3,000 scholarship from a local foundation. Clyde spent the entire $3,000 and another $1,500 from a student loan during this semester. He paid the following expenses: tuition $2,000, books $500, and room and board $2,000. How much of the $3,000 scholarship should Clyde report as income?','[\"$500\",\"$0\",\"$3,000\",\"$1,000\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 77, states, in part, that a candidate for a degree can exclude amounts received as a qualified scholarship or fellowship. A qualified scholarship or fellowship is any amount received by a taxpayer that is for:rnrntuition and fees to enroll at or attend an educational institution, orrnfees, books, supplies, and equipment required for courses at the educational institution.rnAmounts used for room and board do not qualify for the exclusion.rnrnClyde would report $500 of the $3,000 scholarship that he received. The $500 is the difference between the amount received of $3,000 and the qualified excluded expenses of $2,000 for tuition and $500 for books.rnrnFor additional information on qualified scholarships and fellowship grants, see Publication 970, Tax Benefits for Education.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(292,12,'Mr. Brown is a college student working on a degree in accounting. He received the following in 2024:   n1. A $4,000 scholarship used for tuition at State Universityn2. A $1,000 scholarship used for fees and booksn3. An $8,000 fellowship used for his room and boardnCompute the amount Mr. Brown must include in income for 2024.','[\"$8,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$9,000\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 74, states, in part, that a candidate for a degree can exclude amounts received as a qualified scholarship or fellowship. A qualified scholarship or fellowship is any amount received by a taxpayer that is for:nntuition and fees to enroll at or attend an educational institution, ornfees, books, supplies, and equipment required for courses at the educational institution.nAmounts used for room and board do not qualify for the exclusion.nnMr. Brown would report $8,000 of the $13,000 in scholarships and fellowships that he received. The $5,000 received for tuition, fees, and books is excludable and the $8,000 for room and board is includible.nnFor additional information on qualified scholarships and fellowship grants, see Publication 970, Tax Benefits for Education.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(293,12,'Martha invested in a mutual fund. This year the mutual fund declared a dividend which Martha elected to leave in the fund. Which of the following statements is correct about the dividend?','[\"The dividend is reportable this year.\",\"Martha has the option to report or not report the dividend this year.\",\"The dividend is\\u00a0not\\u00a0reportable this year if Martha has the agent purchase additional shares with the dividend.\",\"The dividend is\\u00a0not\\u00a0reportable this year because Martha did not receive the money yet.\"]',0,'Most corporations sponsor a dividend reinvestment plan for those shareholders owning stock in the corporation. In these cases, a taxpayer may elect to use dividends paid by the corporation to buy (through an agent) more shares of stock in the corporation instead of receiving the dividends in cash. Most mutual funds also permit shareholders to automatically reinvest distributions in more shares in the fund, instead of receiving cash. When this election is made, the reinvested dividend amount is still reported as dividend income by the taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(294,12,'A 62-year-old, married taxpayer files Married Filing Separately, and lives apart from the spouse for an entire taxable year. What is the taxpayer’s base amount for computing taxable Social Security benefits?','[\"Zero\",\"$25,000\",\"$32,000\",\"$44,000\"]',1,'Social Security benefits are includible if one-half of the Social Security benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest, are more than the base amount of $25,000 for a single taxpayer ($32,000 for a married filing jointly taxpayer). (Publication 17, page 63)nnSee Publication 17, pages 63 through 66, to review the rules for determining the taxable portion of a person\'s Social Security benefits.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(295,12,'During 2024, Mr. French received state unemployment benefits of $4,900 and $700 of supplemental unemployment benefits from an employer-financed fund. The union paid Mr. French an additional $2,000 as strike benefits. What amount must Mr. French include in income for 2024?','[\"$2,500\",\"$5,200\",\"$6,900\",\"$7,600\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 73, states that a taxpayer must include in income all unemployment compensation received by him or her. The person should receive a Form 1099-G showing the unemployment compensation paid to him or her. nnPublication 17, page 73 states that benefits (or supplemental unemployment benefits) received from an employer-financed fund (to which the employees did not contribute) are not unemployment compensation. They are taxable as wages. Report these payments on line 1 of Form 1040 or Form 1040.nnPublication 17, page 77, states, in part, that benefits paid to a taxpayer by a union as strike or lockout benefits, including both cash and the fair market value of other property, are usually included in the person\'s income as compensation. The taxpayer can exclude these benefits from his or her income only when the facts show that the union intended them as gifts to the person.nnMr. French, therefore, must report $7,600 in income, which is the sum of the state unemployment benefits of $4,900, the supplemental unemployment benefits of $700 from a company financed fund, and the union strike benefits of $2,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(296,12,'The interest on qualified U.S. savings bonds may not be taxable if you pay:','[\"a reduced rent that is government subsidized.\",\"qualified higher education expenses in the same year.\",\"household employee wages in excess of $1,000.\",\"mortgage interest for a rental property.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 17, page 57, a taxpayer may be able to exclude from income all or part of the interest they receive on the redemption of qualified U.S. savings bonds during the year if the taxpayer pays qualified higher educational expenses during the same year. This exclusion is known as the Education Savings Bond Program.nnMoreover, a taxpayer doesn’t qualify for this exclusion if their filing status is married filing separately.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(297,12,'You own a vacation home on Amelia Island, Florida, which you rented for 10 days in 2024. In 2024, rental expenses were $2,000 and rental income was $5,000. How much of the rental income should be reported on the tax return?','[\"$5,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$0\",\"$7,000\"]',2,'Generally, a person must include in gross income all amounts received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. If the taxpayer has any personal use of the dwelling unit (including vacation home) that is rented, the taxpayer must divide the total expenses between rental use and personal use.nnThere is an exception for minimal rental use by the taxpayer. Specifically, if the taxpayer uses the dwelling unit as a home and it is rented for fewer than 15 days during the year, none of the rent is included in income and none of the rental expenses are deductible. See pages 18–19 in Publication 527 for more information on rental income and expense.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(298,12,'How much income should Devin, who uses the cash method of accounting, report on his 2024 return from the following transactions?1. $300 was garnished from his wages to pay his debts2. $500 (gross) paycheck received December 28, 2024,    but not cashed until January 2, 20253. $900 (gross) wages paid directly to his mother at his request','[\"$1,200\",\"$1,700\",\"$1,400\",\"$800\"]',1,'As a cash basis taxpayer, a person is required to include all items of income in the year in which the taxpayer actually or constructively received them. Generally, a taxpayer deducts all expenses in the year that the taxpayer actually pays them. This is the method most individual taxpayers use.rnrnA taxpayer constructively receives income when it is credited to the taxpayer\'s account or set apart in any way that makes it available to the taxpayer. The taxpayer does not need to have physical possession of it. For example, interest credited to a taxpayer\'s bank account on December 31 is taxable income to the taxpayer in the current year even if the taxpayer does not withdraw it until the following year.rnrnIf a taxpayer\'s wages are held by the employer to pay the taxpayer\'s debts, or if the taxpayer\'s wages are attached or garnished, the full amount is constructively received by the taxpayer and therefore is included in gross income.rnrnAs a result of the constructive receipt rules, Devin must report on his tax return $1,700, which is the sum of the garnishment ($300), gross wages received but not cashed ($500), and wages paid to his mother ($900). For more information on this issue, see page 13 in Publication 17.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(299,12,'Mr. and Mrs. Black received the following income for 2024. How much income should be reported on their 2024 joint return?n1. W-2 income for Mrs. Black for wages of $30,000n2. Payment of $2,000 for Mrs. Black, the value of fringe benefits not included in the above W-2. Mrs. Black did not pay for the fringe benefits.n3. Benefits of $5,000 paid to Mr. Black from a health and accident plan for which the premiums were paid by his employer but included in his income','[\"$30,000\",\"$32,000\",\"$37,000\",\"$35,000\"]',1,'Fringe benefits received in connection with the performance of a taxpayer\'s services are included in income as compensation unless the taxpayer pays fair market value (FMV) for them or they are specifically excluded by law. In this case, there is no information to suggest that the fringe benefit is excluded by law; so the $2,000 must be included. (Publication 17, pages 47–48)nnPursuant to Publication 17, page 53, a taxpayer must report as income any amounts received for personal injury or sickness through an accident or health plan that is paid for by their employer. If both the taxpayer and employer pay for the plan, only the amount received that is due to the employer\'s payments is reported as income..nnThere are, however, some other sickness and injury benefits that are not taxable. These include the following amounts (Publication 17, page 53):nnCompensatory damages received by the taxpayer for physical injury or physical sickness, whether paid in a lump sum or in periodic paymentsnBenefits received by the taxpayer under an accident or health insurance policy on which either the taxpayer or the taxpayer\'s employer paid the premiums, but the taxpayer had to include them in his or her incomenDisability benefits received by the taxpayer for loss of income or earning capacity as a result of injuries under a no-fault car insurance policynAs a result of the above information, Mr. and Mrs. Black would include $32,000 in income on their 2024 tax return, which is Mrs. Black\'s W-2 income and her $2,000 in fringe benefits that are not included in the W-2 income. Mr. Black\'s $5,000 in disability income, on the other hand, is not included because the cost of the policy was included in his pay.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(300,12,'John, who is 63 years of age and single, has wages of $10,000, interest income of $3,000, dividends of $2,000, municipal bond interest of $3,000, state unemployment compensation of $4,000, and Social Security benefits of $4,000. What is John\'s adjusted gross income?','[\"$26,000\",\"$22,400\",\"$22,000\",\"$19,000\"]',3,'Three issues must be addressed to resolve this problem. First, interest on a bond used to finance government operations generally is not taxable if the bond is issued by a state, the District of Columbia, a possession of the United States, or any of their political subdivisions. As a result, the municipal bond interest in this problem ($3,000) is excludable (Publication 17, pages 59–60).nnSecond, Social Security benefits are includible if total income (one-half of benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt income) exceeds $25,000 for a person that is not married filing jointly. In this case, the total income equals $24,000 and is computed as AGI ($19,000) + municipal bond interest ($3,000) + one-half of Social Security income ($2,000). Since the total income does not exceed $25,000, none of the Social Security benefits are includible. (Publication 17, page 62)nnThird, Publication 17, page 73, states that a taxpayer must include in income all unemployment compensation that is received by the taxpayer. The taxpayer should receive a Form 1099-G showing the unemployment compensation paid to him or her.nnAs a result of the above information, John\'s AGI is $19,000, which is the sum of his wages ($10,000), interest income ($3,000), dividends ($2,000), and unemployment compensation ($4,000).nnSee Publication 17, pages 62 through 65, to review the rules for determining the taxable portion of a person\'s Social Security benefits.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(301,12,'How does Pam report a gift valued at $60 that she received from a savings institution for opening a savings account?','[\"$60 as dividend income\",\"$60 as interest income\",\"$60 as other income\",\"Not reportable since it is less than $100\"]',1,'When a taxpayer receives noncash gifts or services for making deposits or for opening an account in a savings institution, the taxpayer may have to report the value as interest.nnMore specifically, for deposits of less than $5,000, gifts or services valued at more than $10 must be reported as interest. For deposits of $5,000 or more, gifts or services valued at more than $20 must be reported as interest. The value is determined by the cost to the financial institution. See Publication 17, page 56, for more details on this issue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(302,12,'Zenith Mortgage Co. offered John a 10% discount on his $100,000 mortgage on his principal residence if he would pay the mortgage in full. John paid Zenith Mortgage Co. $90,000 in 2024 and his mortgage was canceled. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"John reports the $10,000 as other income.\",\"John reports the $10,000 as interest income.\",\"John treats the $10,000 as a gift and therefore reports nothing.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 68, states, in part, that if a taxpayer\'s financial institution offers a discount for the early payment of the taxpayer\'s mortgage loan, the amount of the discount is canceled debt and, as such, the amount is included in gross income of the taxpayer unless it qualifies for exclusion under excluded debt.nnPublication 4681, page 9, provides a series of examples illustrating the qualified principal residence indebtedness exclusion. This provision was extended as a result of the Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Relief Act of 2019, which is included in the Further Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2019.nnTo show that all or part of a taxpayer\'s  canceled debt is excluded from income because it is qualified residence indebtedness, attach Form 982 to the taxpayer\'s federal income tax return and check the box on line 1e. On line 2 of Form 982, include the amount of canceled qualified principal indebtedness, but not more than the amount of the exclusion limit (explained earlier).nnIf the taxpayer continues to own their home after a cancellation of qualified principal residence indebtedness, the taxpayer must reduce their basis in the home as explained under Reduction of Tax Attributes appearing on page 10 of Publication 4681.nnHence, John would not be required to include the forgiven amount in gross income. Rather, he would include Form 982 with his tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(303,12,'The following statements about dividends received from a dividend reinvestment plan are correct, except:','[\"reinvested dividends are not taxable if not removed from the plan.\",\"reinvested dividends are taxable in the year paid.\",\"reinvested dividends are taxable and are added to the basis of the stock or mutual fund.\",\"reinvested dividends are treated as ordinary dividends.\"]',0,'Some corporations allow stockholders to participate in the company\'s dividend reinvestment plan rather than accept the cash dividend. When a taxpayer elects to buy (through an agent) more shares of stock in the corporation instead of receiving the dividends in cash from the corporation, the reinvested dividend amount is reported as dividend income by the taxpayer. Moreover, the reinvested dividends are taxable in the year paid and are added to the basis of the stock or mutual fund.nnPublication 550, page 30, provides additional information on this issue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(304,12,'Which of the following is not rental income in the year received?','[\"Security deposit, equal to 1 month\'s rent, to be refunded at the end of the lease if the building passes inspection\",\"Payment to cancel the remaining lease\",\"Repairs paid by the tenant in lieu of rent\",\"January 2024 rent received December 2023\"]',0,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in general on pages 3 and 4 of Publication 527. In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts that are received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. Similarly, any amounts received from a tenant to cancel a lease are treated as rent and therefore are included in income.nnIn addition to amounts received as normal rent payments, there are other amounts that may be rental income and as such are included in rental income. Advance rent, for example, is any amount received before the period that it covers. These payments are included in rental income in the year received regardless of the period covered or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using.nnIf a tenant pays any of the taxpayer\'s expenses, the payments are rental income and therefore are included in income.nnSecurity deposits, on the other hand, are not included in rental income when it is received if the amount is to be returned to the tenant at the end of the lease. If the taxpayer keeps part or all of the security deposit during any year because the tenant does not live up to the terms of the lease, the amount retained becomes income for that year.nnIf an amount called a security deposit is to be used as a final payment of rent, it is advance rent, and as such, it is included as rental income in the year that it is received.nnIn this problem, all the items listed are included as rental income with one exception. That is, the taxpayer does not include the security deposit because it is to be refunded at the end of the lease if the property passes final inspection, and therefore, it is not an advanced rent payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(305,12,'Roger Brown, who is single, owns a rental apartment building property. This is the only rental property that Roger owns. He \"actively participates\" in this rental activity, as he collects the rents and performs ordinary and necessary repairs. In 2024, Roger had a loss of $30,000 on this rental activity and had no reportable passive income. His adjusted gross income, without regard to this rental loss, is $60,000. How much of the rental loss may Roger deduct on his 2024 return?','[\"$30,000\",\"$25,000\",\"$0\",\"$6,000\"]',1,'Rental real estate activities are generally considered passive activities, and the amount of loss a taxpayer can deduct is limited.nnIf a taxpayer or a taxpayer\'s spouse actively participated in a passive rental real estate activity, the taxpayer can deduct up to $25,000 of loss from the activity from the nonpassive income. This special allowance is an exception to the general rule disallowing losses in excess of income from passive activities. Similarly, a taxpayer can offset credits from the activity against the tax on up to $25,000 of nonpassive income after considering any losses allowed under this exception.nnIf the taxpayer is married, is filing a separate return (which is not the case here), and lived apart from his or her spouse for the entire tax year, the taxpayer\'s special allowance cannot be more than $12,500. If the taxpayer lived with his or her spouse at any time during the year and is filing a separate return, the taxpayer cannot use the special allowance to reduce his or her nonpassive income or tax on nonpassive income.nnThe maximum amount of the special allowance is reduced if the taxpayer\'s modified adjusted gross income is more than $100,000 ($50,000 if married filing separately) and totally phased out if it equals or exceeds $150,000.nnSince Roger is single, he is an active participant in this case, and his AGI is below $100,000, he is able to claim a maximum loss of $25,000 on this year\'s tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(306,12,'Heather spent $2,500 for lottery tickets during the year. She saved all her tickets. She won $2,000 in November on a $1 ticket. Heather\'s adjusted gross income is $50,000. How much of her lottery ticket costs can she deduct as an itemized deduction?','[\"$1\",\"$0\",\"$2,500\",\"$2,000\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 76, provides that a taxpayer must report the full amount of a person\'s gambling winnings for the year on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 8. If the taxpayer itemizes their deductions on Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), they can deduct gambling losses they had during the year, but only up to the amount of the taxpayer\'s winnings.nnIf the taxpayer is in the trade or business of gambling, use Schedule C (Form 1040 or 1040-SR).nnIn addition, the taxpayer is able to deduct any gambling losses for the year on line 16, Schedule A (Form 1040) as an other itemized deduction. However, a taxpayer cannot deduct gambling losses that are more than the winnings. If the taxpayer cannot or does not itemize, then the taxpayer has gambling income but cannot deduct any gambling losses. (Publication 17, pages 101–102)nnHeather is able to deduct up to $2,000 of her gambling losses ($2,500), which is the amount of her gambling winnings for the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(307,12,'Susan is a waitress and earned $15,000 in wages, not including any tips she received in 2024. She received tips of $17 in March, which she did not report to her employer. Because she became ill in February and did not return to work until late March, she also forgot to report the $58 for tips that she received in February. She did report the $7,000 she received as tips for the rest of the year. How much income must she report as wages, tips, and other compensation for tax year 2024?','[\"$22,185\",\"$22,075\",\"$15,260\",\"$15,183\"]',1,'All tips received by a taxpayer are income and are subject to federal income tax. A taxpayer must include in gross income all tips received directly from customers, tips from charge customers, and any amounts under a “tip-splitting” or “tip-pooling” arrangement.nnThis question has a tricky part in that the waitress received less than $20 in tips in March and as such, Publication 531, page 3, provides that if total tips for any one month from any one job are less than $20, the amount need not be reported for that month to the employer. However, that does not mean the amount is not included in gross income. All tips are included in gross income. (See the example on pages 5 and 6 of Publication 531.)nnSince Susan is responsible for reporting all tips, the total income that she must report as wages, tips, and other compensation for 2024 is $22,075, which is determined as follows:nn  Wages:               $15,000n  Tips, February            58n  Tips, March               17n  Tips, Rest of year     7,000n  Total                $22,075',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(308,12,'Maria had municipal bond interest of $6,000, certificate of deposit interest of $4,000, reinvested corporate bond interest of $2,000, mutual fund municipal bond interest of $7,000, and savings account interest of $1,000. What is Maria\'s taxable interest?','[\"$3,000\",\"$7,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$16,000\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 17, page 54, all interest received or accrued that can be withdrawn from the taxpayer\'s account is fully taxable except interest on:nninterest on bonds issued by states and other municipalities and used to finance government operations (Publication 17, page 58) andninterest on qualified U.S. savings bonds used to pay for qualified educational expenses (Publication 17, page 57).nTherefore, Marie\'s taxable interest is as follows:nn  Certificate of deposit interest        $4,000n  Reinvested corporate bond interest      2,000n  Savings account interest                1,000n    Total taxable interest               $7,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(309,12,'Pat is the 100% shareholder of a corporation. He did not pay himself any salary or any dividends during 2024 from the corporation, thus there may not be any taxable income for him from the corporation. However, which of the following transactions could result in a constructive distribution for Pat and thus taxable income to him from the corporation?','[\"A loan from the corporation to Pat at a zero-interest rate\",\"Sale of a truck from Pat to the corporation at FMV\",\"Rents received from the corporation to Pat at the same rate that a stranger would be charged\",\"None of the answer choices would be considered constructive dividends.\"]',0,'Publication 542, page 17, provides that a corporate distribution to a shareholder is generally treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Any part of a distribution from either current or accumulated earnings and profits is reported to the shareholder as a dividend. Any part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder.nnThere are, however, certain transactions between corporations and shareholders that may be treated as distributions (also known as constructive distributions), hence taxable dividend income if there is enough earnings and profits (see page 17 of Publication 542):nnBelow-market loansnCorporation cancels shareholder\'s debtnTransfers of property to shareholder for less than fair market value (FMV)nUnreasonable rentsnUnreasonable salariesnSo, in this case, Pat would probably not have any taxable income from his corporation except for the loan from the corporation to Pat at a zero-interest rate. If the interest rate had been set at the market rate that would be typical for this type of loan, then Pat may not have had a taxable dividend. The rental income at the same rate a stranger would pay would probably be considered rental income for Pat, but the amount taxable to him would depend on Pat\'s rental expenses, such as depreciation or repairs. The sale of the truck would not be considered a constructive dividend since it was sold at FMV. Again, Pat may have income from the sale, but the amount taxable depends on his basis for determination of the gain or loss on the sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(310,12,'Some mutual funds and REITs keep their long-term capital gains and pay tax on them. How must the taxpayer treat his or her share of these gains?','[\"As a dividend that is reported as a dividend on Schedule B\",\"As a long-term capital gain on Schedule D\",\"As a short-term capital gain on Schedule D\",\"The taxpayer does\\u00a0not\\u00a0report the dividend since the taxpayer did not actually receive it.\"]',1,'Publication 550, page 30, (“Capital Gain Distributions”) states that even when mutual funds and REITs elect to keep their long-term capital gains and pay tax on them, the taxpayer is required to treat his or her share of these gains as distributions, even though the taxpayer did not actually receive them.nnIn addition, the undistributed gains are not included on Form 1099-DIV. Instead, they are reported to the taxpayer on Form 2439, Notice to Shareholder of Undistributed Long-Term Capital Gains. In this case, the reported undistributed capital gains shown in box 1a of Form 2439 is placed in the long-term capital gains on line 11 of Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR).nnThe tax paid on these gains by the mutual fund or REIT is shown in box 2 of Form 2439 and the taxpayer takes credit for this tax by including it on Schedule 3 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), Part II, line 13, and following the instructions there.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(311,12,'The following fringe benefits are nontaxable, except:','[\"a nonstatutory option to buy or sell stock or other property as payment for your services when you receive the option or when you exercise the option.\",\"the value of accident or health plan coverage provided to you by your employer.\",\"long-term care coverage contributions made by your employer to provide coverage for long-term care services.\",\"contributions by your employer to your medical savings account.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 51, states, in part, that if a taxpayer receives a nonstatutory option to buy or sell stock or other property as payment for the taxpayer\'s services, the taxpayer will usually have income when he or she receives the option, when the taxpayer exercises the option (use it to buy or sell the stock or other property), or when the taxpayer sells or otherwise disposes of the option.nnHowever, if the taxpayer\'s option is a statutory stock option, the taxpayer will not have any income until the person sells or exchanges the taxpayer\'s stock.nnFor additional details on this issue and statutory stock options, see Publication 525, pages 11 to 13.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(312,12,'Which of the following costs incurred on rental property should be classified as a capital improvement?','[\"Replacing a 20-year-old roof\",\"Repainting all of the interior walls\",\"Refinishing the existing wood floors\",\"Replacing a broken windowpane\"]',0,'Publication 527, pages 5–6, states, in part, a taxpayer can deduct the cost of repairs to rental property if the taxpayer is not required to capitalize the expense. A taxpayer must capitalize any expense they pay to improve their rental property. An expense is for an improvement if it results in a betterment to the taxpayer\'s property, restores the property, or adapts the property to a new or different use.nnA repair keeps the taxpayer\'s property in good operating condition. It does not materially add to the value of the taxpayer\'s property or substantially prolong its life (Publication 550, page 58–59).nnImprovements, on the other hand, have a useful life of more than 1 year, add to the value of the property, prolong its useful life, or adapt it to new uses. (See pages 58–59 of Publication 550 for examples of increases to basis.) Improvements include:nnputting a recreation room in an unfinished basement,nadding a bathroom or bedroom,nputting up a new fence,nputting in new plumbing or wiring,nputting on a new roof, andnpaving an unpaved driveway.nFurthermore, if a taxpayer makes an improvement to the property, the cost of the improvement must be capitalized and depreciated as if the improvement were separate property.nnIn this case, replacing a 20-year-old roof would be classified as a capital improvement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(313,12,'Sandy received the following income in 2024: wages (Box 1 of W-2) $50,000, money won at weekly poker games $1,000, Christmas ham from her employer (fair market value) $22, dependent care benefits (Box 10 of W-2) $2,000 (spent $3,000 for childcare), and group-term life insurance ($40,000 death benefit) $50. How much gross income must be reported by Sandy for tax year 2024?','[\"$50,022\",\"$53,000\",\"$51,000\",\"$53,072\"]',2,'A taxpayer must include for federal income tax purposes all income received from money, goods, property, and services, unless specifically excluded by the code (Publication 17, page 7).nnFringe benefits received in connection with the performance of the taxpayer\'s services are included in gross income unless the taxpayer pays the fair market value (FMV) for them or the benefit is specifically excluded by law. (Publication 17, pages 47–48)nnIf an employer provides a taxpayer with a product or service and the cost of it is so small (i.e., a de minimis benefit) that it would be unreasonable for the employer to account for it, the value is not included in the taxpayer\'s income (e.g., turkey or a ham). In relation to the above question, the Christmas ham that Sandy received is considered to be a de minimis (minimal) benefit and not includible in gross income (Publication 17, page 46).nnAdditionally, the employer-provided dependent care benefits under a qualified plan would not generally be includible in gross income, to the extent that they do not exceed the total amount of dependent care benefits received the total amount of qualified expenses incurred, earned income, spouse\'s earned income, or $6,000 ($3,000 for married filing separately) (Publication 503, page 2).  Employer-provided amounts that are used to cover qualified child care expenses will not be included in gross income but will also be excluded from qualifying expense for purposes of calculating the qualified child and dependent care credit (no double benefit).nnFurthermore, group-term life insurance coverage paid by an employer is not taxable because it is below $50,000 of coverage (Publication 17, page 49).nnTherefore, Sandy\'s gross income for 2024 would include only her wages and winnings as follows:nn  Wages        $50,000n  Winnings       1,000n  Total        $51,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(314,12,'Ms. Red, age 28, is single and received $10,000 in unemployment benefits from the state for 2024. She also received $3,000 from the state to reduce the costs of her winter fuel bill. What amount of income should Ms. Red report for 2024?','[\"$7,600\",\"$13,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$0\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 73, states that a taxpayer must include in income all unemployment compensation received by the taxpayer. The person should receive a Form 1099-G showing the unemployment compensation paid to him or her.nnWelfare and other public assistance benefits from a public welfare fund based upon need, such as payments due to blindness, generally are not included in gross income. Payments made by a state to qualified people to reduce their cost of winter energy use, for example, are not taxable pursuant to Publication 17, page 73.nnMs. Red, therefore, must report only $10,000, which are her state unemployment benefits for the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(315,12,'Matthew Kennedy received a dividend from Mayflow Corporation. Matthew has elected, using Mayflow\'s dividend reinvestment plan, to purchase additional stock at FMV with the dividend received. The dividend was $1,500 and the FMV of the stock purchased was $1,475. A $25 service charge was applied to this transaction. What must Matthew report as dividend income on his tax return for 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$1,500\",\"$1,525\",\"$1,475\"]',1,'When a taxpayer elects to buy (through an agent) more shares of stock in the corporation instead of receiving the dividends in cash from the corporation, the reinvested dividend amount is reported as dividend income by the taxpayer. Moreover, the reinvested dividends are taxable in the year paid and are added to the basis of the stock or mutual fund.nnFurthermore, the taxpayer must report as dividend income any service charge subtracted from the cash dividends before the dividends are used to buy the additional stock. Hence, the full dividend amount is taxable, but the taxpayer may be able to deduct the service charge.nnPublication 550 (pages 27–28) provides additional information on this issue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(316,12,'Cheryl inherited 200 digital assets from her grandfather when her grandfather died on December 10, 2023; the fair market value of the digital assets was $4 per coin. Her grandfather paid $3 per coin when he purchased the coins on July 1, 2023. If Cheryl sells all 200 coins for $6 per coin on May 30, 2024, how should she report the sale on her 2024 return?','[\"$400 short-term capital gain\",\"$600 short-term capital gain\",\"$400 long-term capital gain\",\"$600 long-term capital gain\"]',2,'The character of the gain or loss generally depends on whether the virtual currency is a capital asset in the hands of the taxpayer. A taxpayer generally realizes capital gain or loss on the sale or exchange of virtual currency that is a capital asset in the hands of the taxpayer. For example, stocks, bonds, and other investment property are generally capital assets. A taxpayer generally realizes ordinary gain or loss on the sale or exchange of virtual currency that is not a capital asset in the hands of the taxpayer. Inventory and other property held mainly for sale to customers in a trade or business are examples of property that is not a capital asset. See Publication 544, Sales and Other Dispositions of Assets, for more information about capital assets and the character of gain or loss. (IRS Notice 2014-21)nnThe gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. As provided in Publication 551, page 9, the basis of property that is received from a decedent is:nnthe fair market value (FMV) of the property at the date of the individual\'s death ornthe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation.nIf a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance taxes.nnOnce the amount of the gain or loss is determined, the taxpayer must determine whether it is long term or short term. If the investment property is held for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. When investment property is inherited, the capital gain or loss on any later disposition of that property is treated as a long-term capital gain or loss. This is true regardless of how long the taxpayer actually held the property. (Publication 550, page 43)nnIn this problem, the gain on the sale for Cheryl is long-term capital gain, and it equals $400, which is the selling price of $1,200 ($6 × 200 coins) less the adjusted basis of $800 ($4 × 200 coins).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(317,12,'Which of the following situations exempts the earnings of a taxpayer that is a minister of a church for the services he performs as a minister, whether he is an employee of his church or a self-employed person under the common-law rules, from self-employment taxes?','[\"The taxpayer has requested an exemption from the IRS.\",\"The taxpayer has taken a vow of poverty.\",\"The taxpayer is subject to the social security laws of a foreign country.\",\"All of the answer choices are exempt from self-employment taxes.\"]',3,'Publication 517, page 3, states, in part, that the services performed in the exercise of one\'s ministry, of duties required by one\'s religious order, or of one\'s profession as a Christian Science practitioner or reader are covered by Social Security and Medicare under SECA. Hence, these earnings for ministerial services are subject to self-employment (SE) tax unless one of the following exceptions applies:nnThe person is a member of a religious order who has taken a vow of poverty,nthe person has asked the IRS for an exemption from SE tax for one\'s services and the IRS approves the request, ornthe person is subject only to the social security laws of a foreign country under the provisions of a social security agreement between the United States and that country.nPublication 517, page 4 further provides that a member of a religious order who has taken a vow of poverty is already exempt from paying SE tax on earnings for ministerial services performed as a member of a church or its agencies. However, services performed outside the order are still subject to SE tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(318,12,'Mr. Barley, an accountant, accepted a painting for his office from his client in lieu of payment of his customary fee of $400 for preparation of a tax return. What action must Mr. Barley take as a result of his acceptance of the painting?','[\"He must include the $400 in income.\",\"He must include the $400 in income when he sells the painting.\",\"He must have the painting appraised and include the appraisal amount in income.\",\"He treats the $400 as a gift being received.\"]',0,'Publication 551, page 7, states that if a taxpayer receives property for his services, the property\'s FMV is taxable. The taxable amount becomes the taxpayer\'s basis. If the services were performed for a price agreed on beforehand, the price will be accepted as the FMV of the property if there is no evidence to the contrary.nnIn this case, Mr. Barley would report the $400 as income, which is his customary fee for preparing a tax return.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(319,12,'Kathy rented out her summer home for 80 days and used it personally for 20 days. She paid $1,000 for utilities and $2,000 for repairs. Rental income was $8,000. What was Kathy\'s net rental income?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$5,600\",\"$8,000\"]',2,'If a taxpayer uses a dwelling unit (including a vacation home) for both rental and personal purposes, the expenses for such must be divided between the rental use and the personal use based on the number of days used for each purpose. (Publication 527, pages 26–28)nnThe following rules should be regarded when dividing expenses (Publication 527, page 27):nnAny day that the unit is rented at a fair rental price is a day of rental use even if the unit was used for personal purposes that day.nAny day that the unit is available for rent but not actually rented is not a day of rental use.nAdditionally, rental deductions are limited if a taxpayer rents property for 15 or more days during the tax year and uses it for the greater of (a) more than 14 days or (b) more than 10% of the number of days during the year for which the home is rented. Under this limitation, the amount of rental activity deductions may not exceed the amount by which the gross income derived from such activity exceeds the deductions otherwise allowable for the property, such as interest and taxes (similar to hobby loss rules). (Publication 527, page 27)nnGiven that Kathy\'s rental income was $8,000, her applicable deductions are limited to that extent. The rental property was used 100 days, which is the sum of 80 days (rental) and 20 days (personal use). All expenses are based on 80% (80 days rented ÷ 100 days used) and the deductible expense would be calculated as follows:nn  Utilities, etc.      $  800 of the $1,000n  Repairs               1,600 of the $2,000n  Maximum deductible   $2,400 which does not exceed the rentaln                              income amount of $8,000nSee Worksheet 5-1 of Publication 527 (pages 30–31) for figuring the limit on rental deductions.nnAs a result, Kathy\'s net rental income is $5,600, which is the rental income of $8,000 less the maximum deductible rental expenses of $2,400.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(320,12,'nMr. and Mrs. Beet own a house which they rent to non-related parties. They had some major expenses during 2024 as follows:n1. $2,000 to replace the cabinets in the kitchenn2. $500 to replace the stoven3. $600 to replace the built-in dishwashern4. $400 to resurface the tub in the master bathroomnWhat is the amount and character of their expenses?','[\"$2,000 capital improvements and $1,500 repairs expense\",\"$2,600 capital improvements and $900 repairs expense\",\"$400 capital improvements and $3,100 repairs expense\",\"$3,100 capital improvements and $400 repairs expense\"]',3,'In 2013, the IRS issued TD 9636 (Tangible Property Final Regulations), applicable to tax year beginning on or after January 1, 2014 which finalized the guidance on Sections 162(a) and 263(a).nnAn expense is for an improvement if it results in a betterment to the taxpayer’s property, restores the taxpayer’s property, or adapts the property to a new or different use. Table 1-1 of Publication 527, page 5, shows examples of many improvements.nnIn general, improvements add to the value of the property, prolong its useful life, or adapt it to new uses. (See also pages 4–5 of Publication 551 for examples of increases to basis.) Improvements include but are not limited to:nnputting a recreation room in an unfinished basement,nadding a bathroom or bedroom,nputting up a new fence,nputting in new plumbing or wiring,nputting on a new roof, andnpaving an unpaved driveway.nFurthermore, if a taxpayer makes improvements to the property, the cost of the improvement must be capitalized and depreciated as if the improvement were separate property. Replacement of old assets with new assets are generally considered improvements and as such, must be capitalized. However, if the taxpayer qualifies and makes a de minimis safe harbor election, the taxpayer may immediately deduct repairs and maintenance costs up to $2,500 per invoice per item.nnIn this case, there is no indication Mr. and Mrs. Beet made the de minimis safe harbor election and as such they are required to capitalize the costs associated with the new appliances.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(321,12,'The Becks own and operate an assisted-living facility. They provide maid service and meals in a common dining room. Where should they report the income and expenses from this activity?','[\"Other income on Form 1040 and expenses as itemized deductions on Schedule A\",\"Income and expenses on Schedule E,\\u00a0Supplemental Income and Loss\",\"Income and expenses on Schedule C,\\u00a0Profit or Loss From Business\",\"Short-term capital gain on Schedule D\"]',2,'If a taxpayer rents a building, room, or an apartment and provides limited additional services, such as heat, light, and trash collection, the rental income and expenses of renting such property would be reported on Schedule E. On the other hand, if a taxpayer provides significant services that are predominantly for the convenience of the tenant, such as regular cleaning, changing of linen, and maid service, the rental income and expenses would be reported on Schedule C.nnGiven that the Becks own and operate an assisted-living facility and provide maid service and meals in a common dining room, limited services that are primarily for the convenience of the tenants, the income and expenses associated with this activity should be reported on Schedule C, Profit or Loss From Business.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(322,12,'Dr. Jay purchased an apartment building as an investment in 2024 and the property is available to rent. The apartments are fully furnished. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"He can depreciate the purchase price of the apartment building.\",\"He can elect to deduct, as a Section 179 deduction, up to $500,000 of the portion of the cost allocable to the furnishings and depreciate the remaining amount.\",\"He can elect to deduct, as a Section 179 deduction, the purchase price of the apartment building.\",\"He must capitalize the purchase price of the apartment building.\"]',0,'As stated on page 6 of Publication 527, a taxpayer recovers the cost of income-producing property through yearly tax deductions, which is known as depreciating the property. The three basic factors that are needed to determine the depreciation amount are basis of property, recovery period for the property, and depreciation method selected.nnThe IRC Section 179 deduction is a means of recovering part or all of the cost of certain qualifying property in the year it is placed in service (Publication 527, page 6). Residential rental property is defined in Publication 527, page 9, as real property that is a rental building or structure (including a mobile home), if 80% or more of its annual gross rental income for the year is from dwelling units. Per Publication 946, pages 15 and 16, residential rental property is not eligible property for purposes of Section 179 depreciation.nnNote: Residential rental property does not include a unit in a hotel, motel, inn, or other establishment where more than half of the units are used on a transient basis.nnThe capitalization response is incorrect because it assumes that the taxpayer capitalizes the cost of the property without claiming annual depreciation expense on the property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(323,12,'A regulated investment company (mutual fund) or real estate investment trust (REIT) declares a dividend (including any exempt-interest dividend) in October, November, or December that is payable to shareholders of record on a date in one of those months but actually pays the dividend during January of the next calendar year. When is the taxpayer considered to have received the dividend?','[\"On the date that the dividend is declared\",\"On December 31\",\"On January 1\",\"In the year the dividend is received\"]',1,'Publication 550, page 28, specifically states that if a regulated investment company (mutual fund) or real estate investment trust (REIT) declares a dividend (including any exempt-interest dividend or capital gain distribution) in October, November, or December payable to shareholders of record on a date in one of those months but actually pays the dividend during January of the next calendar year, the taxpayer is considered to have received the dividend on December 31.nnThat is to say, a taxpayer must report the dividend in the year it was declared if it is declared in the 4th quarter and not the year it was received.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(324,12,'Gordon, age 70, is retired and works part-time as a security guard earning $8,000. He received $5,000 interest from a savings account and $2,500 interest from tax-exempt municipal bonds. His Social Security benefits were $12,000 and his taxable pension was $6,000. To determine if any of his Social Security is taxable, Gordon should compare how much of his income to the $25,000 base amount?','[\"$27,500\",\"$21,500\",\"$19,000\",\"$25,000\"]',0,'Social Security benefits are includible if one-half of the Social Security benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest, are more than the base amount of $25,000 for a single taxpayer. To find out whether any of a person\'s benefits are taxable, the base amount is compared to total income, which is one-half of the person\'s benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest. In this case, the total income equals $27,500 and is the sum of the earnings ($8,000), interest from the savings account ($5,000), municipal bond interest ($2,500), taxable pension ($6,000), and one-half of the taxpayer\'s Social Security income ($6,000).nnSee Publication 17, pages 62 through 67, to review the rules for determining the taxable portion of a person\'s Social Security benefits.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(325,12,'The taxpayer earned $1,000 in interest in 2023. The taxpayer withdrew $700 in 2023 and $300 in 2024. How much of the original $1,000 should taxpayer report as interest earned in 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$300\",\"$700\",\"$1,000\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 54, provides the basic concept to the tax treatment of interest income. In general, any interest that a taxpayer receives or that is credited to his or her account and can be withdrawn is taxable income. (It does not have to be entered in the taxpayer\'s passbook or bankbook.) There are some exceptions to this general statement, but they are not applicable in this problem.nnMost individual taxpayers use the cash method. If a taxpayer uses this method, they generally report their interest income in the year in which they actually or constructively receive it. (Publication 17, page 60)nnThe taxpayer earned interest in 2023 and, as such, the taxpayer pays taxes on the earnings in that year. A later withdrawal of that income does not trigger another taxable event.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(326,12,'Pastor Green received an annual salary of $20,000 as a full-time minister in 2024. The church also paid him $1,000 designated as a housing allowance to pay for his utilities. His church owns a parsonage that has a fair rental value of $6,000 in which he lives rent-free. Neither the rental allowance nor the rental value of the parsonage is included in his W-2. All amounts are considered provided for services he renders as a licensed pastor. He is not exempt from self-employment tax. Compute the amount of Pastor Green\'s income that is subject to income tax on his 2024 return.','[\"$19,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$27,000\",\"$26,000\"]',1,'Publication 517, page 9, states, in part, that a member of the clergy must include in income offerings and fees received for marriages, baptisms, funerals, masses, etc., in addition to the taxpayer\'s salary. If the offering is made to the religious institution and not the minister, the amount is not taxable to the minister.nnAs provided in Publication 517, page 9, the value of “housing” provided in exchange for services is generally taxed as compensation; however, there is an exception to the rule for parsonages. Under this exception, ordained, commissioned, or licensed ministers of the gospel may be able to exclude the rental allowance or fair rental value of a parsonage that is provided to them as pay for services.nnServices include ministerial services, administrative duties and teaching at theological seminaries, and the ordinary duties of a minister performed as an employee of the United States (other than as a chaplain in the Armed Forces), a state, a possession, a political subdivision, or the District of Columbia. This exclusion applies only for income tax purposes. It does not apply for self-employment tax purposes (Publication 517, page 9).nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nRev. Joanna Baker is a full-time minister. The church allows her to use a parsonage that has an annual fair rental value of $24,000. The church pays her an annual salary of $67,000, of which $7,500 is designated for utility costs. Her actual utility costs during the year were $7,000.nnFor income tax purposes, Rev. Baker excludes $31,000 from gross income ($24,000 for fair rental value of the parsonage plus $7,000 from the allowance for utility costs). She will report $60,000 ($59,500 salary plus $500 of unused utility allowance). Her income for self-employment tax purposes, however, is $91,000 ($67,000 salary plus $24,000 fair rental value of the parsonage).nn n nnFor more information, see Publication 517, Social Security and Other Information for Members of the Clergy and Religious Workers.nnPastor Green in this case would include only the $20,000, which is his annual salary. His housing allowance and free rent would not be included in gross income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(327,12,'A regulated investment company (mutual fund) or real estate investment trust (REIT) declares a dividend in November 2024 payable to shareholders of record on November 15. When are the dividends regarded as being received if the dividends are actually paid on January 5, 2025?','[\"November 15, 2024\",\"December 31, 2024\",\"January 1, 2025\",\"January 5, 2025\"]',1,'According to Publication 550, page 28, states, in part, if a regulated investment company (mutual fund) and a real estate investment trust (REIT) declares a dividend (including any exempt-interest dividend or capital gain dividend) in October, November, or December payable to shareholders of record on a date in one of those months but actually pays the dividend during January of the next calendar year, the dividend is regarded as being received on December 31. Therefore, the dividend is taxable in the year it was declared.nnGiven that the dividend was declared in November 2024 to shareholders of record in November 2024, and actually paid in January 2025, the dividend is taxed in 2024, not 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(328,12,'Mr. and Mrs. Garden filed a joint return for 2024. Mr. Garden received $8,000 in Social Security benefits and Mrs. Garden received $4,000. Their income also included $10,000 taxable pension income and interest income of $2,000. What part of their Social Security benefits will be taxable for 2024? (The base amount for married filing jointly is $32,000 for 2024.)','[\"$0\",\"$6,000\",\"$24,000\",\"$12,000\"]',0,'Social Security benefits are includible if total income exceeds $32,000 in the case of a couple filing a married joint tax return ($25,000 for single and head of household filing). Total income is one-half of the taxpayer\'s benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest. In this case, the total income equals $18,000 and is sum of the interest from savings account ($2,000), taxable pension ($10,000), and one-half of the taxpayer\'s Social Security income ($6,000). Since the total income is below the $32,000 limit, the couple would not include any Social Security benefits in gross income.nnSee Publication 17, pages 62 through 63 to review the rules for determining the taxable portion of a person\'s Social Security benefits.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(329,12,'John, a single taxpayer, received interest income of $40,000 consisting of the following: certificate of deposit $6,000 (which is reinvested), savings account $4,000, City of Glendale Municipal Bond $8,000, mortgage note $12,000, Cobb County Municipal Bond $7,000, and corporate bond $3,000. What is the amount of taxable interest income he will report on his Form 1040?','[\"$40,000\",\"$25,000\",\"$19,000\",\"$33,000\"]',1,'In general, any interest that a taxpayer receives or that is credited to the taxpayer\'s account and can be withdrawn is taxable income unless stated otherwise (Publication 17, page 54). Examples of interest income include but are not limited to savings accounts, CD interest, and U.S. treasury bills, notes, and bonds (Publication 17 pages 54–59). Hence, the CD interest is taxable when credited to the account, even if it is subsequently reinvested.nnIn addition, interest earned on a bond used to finance government operations generally is not taxable if issued by a state or its municipalities (generally referred to as municipal income; i.e., $8,000 and $7,000). (Publication 17, pages 58–59)nnThe amount of taxable interest income to be reported is $25,000, which is the sum of all taxable interest earned by the taxpayer. Therefore, the taxable income items are $6,000, $4,000, $12,000, and $3,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(330,12,'Peter owned a cottage on the lake that he bought in 2023. In 2024, he rented the cottage for 10 days to a stranger and used the cottage for 20 days for his own personal use. The cottage was not used the rest of the year. Peter had rental income of $1,000 and he paid $600 for repairs. How should Peter report these activities on his 2024 return?','[\"$1,000 income, $600 expense\",\"$333 income, $200 expense\",\"$0 income, $0 expense\",\"$667 income, $400 expense\"]',2,'In general, a person must include in gross income all amounts received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. (Publication 527, page 3)nnIf the taxpayer has any personal use of the dwelling unit (including vacation home) that is rented, the taxpayer must divide the total expenses between rental use and personal use. Also, the rental expense deductions may be limited. (Publication 527, pages 3–5)nnAre you ready for some good news? There is an exception for minimal rental use by the taxpayer. Specifically, if the taxpayer uses the dwelling unit as a home and it rented for fewer than 15 days during the year, none of the rent is included in income and none of the rental expenses are deductible. See page 19 in Publication 527 for more information on rental income and expenses.nnPeter in this problem would include $0 in income and would have $0 in expenses since it was rented for less than 15 days.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(331,12,'Which of the following statements is correct if a discount is received for early payment of a mortgage loan?','[\"The discount amount is reported as interest income.\",\"The discount amount is reported as income.\",\"The discount amount is reported as nontaxable interest income.\",\"The discount amount is\\u00a0not\\u00a0reported.\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 68, states, in part, that if a taxpayer\'s financial institution offers a discount for the early payment of the taxpayer\'s mortgage loan, the amount of the discount is canceled debt, and as such, the amount is included in gross income of the taxpayer.nnBe careful, however; there are several exceptions to the inclusion of canceled debt in income. (See Publication 17, page 68 and Publication 525, page 21, and Publication 4681, page 9 for more details on excluded debt.) Since the facts in this question do not indicate that there is an exception, you cannot assume that is the case.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(332,12,'Cory owns an apartment building. In addition to providing the utilities for his tenants, he also cleans the halls and utility room and picks up the trash. On what tax form must Cory report the rentals if he is not a real estate professional?','[\"Form 1040 as other income\",\"Schedule C,\\u00a0Profit or Loss From Business\",\"Schedule E,\\u00a0Supplemental Income and Loss\",\"None of the rent payments are taxable.\"]',2,'If a taxpayer rents a building, room, or an apartment and provides limited additional services, such as heat, light, and trash collection, etc., the rental income and expenses of renting such property would be reported on Schedule E.nnOn the other hand, if a taxpayer provides significant services that are predominantly for the convenience of the tenant, such as regular cleaning, changing of linen, and maid service, the rental income and expenses would be reported on Schedule C.nnGiven that Cory, who rents his apartment building out, also provides limited services such as the utilities, cleaning of the halls and utility room, and picking up trash, he may report the rental income and expenses on a Schedule E. Cory is not required to file Schedule C, Profit or Loss From Business, because he does not provide significant services that are primarily for the convenience of the tenants.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(333,12,'Elizabeth received an appointment to the U.S. Naval Academy at Annapolis. As such, she did not incur any qualified higher education expenses. Which of the following statements is correct if Elizabeth withdraws an amount greater than her qualified education expenses each year from her Coverdell education savings account while she is attending the academy?','[\"The distributed amount is tax-free.\",\"The distributed amount up to the qualified education expenses is tax-free.\",\"The distributed amount in excess of the qualified education expenses is tax-free.\",\"The distributed amount is taxable.\"]',3,'The designated beneficiary of a Coverdell ESA (education savings account) can take a distribution at any time. Whether the distributions are tax-free depends, in part, on whether the distributions are equal to, or less than, the amount of adjusted qualified education expenses that the beneficiary has in the same tax year. A portion of the distribution is generally taxable to the beneficiary if the distributions are more than the adjusted qualified education expenses of the beneficiary for the year. (Publication 970, pages 51–52)nnGiven that Elizabeth did not incur any qualified education expense, her distributions from her Coverdell education savings account would be taxable.nnNote: See Publication 970, pages 52 and 53, for a discussion on the coordination with both a QTP (qualified tuition program) and a Coverdell ESA in the same year.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(334,12,'Debby broke her leg this past year and was unable to work for 3 months. During this time she received $2,500 in sick pay from her employer. She also received $1,000 from her personally purchased accident policy. How much of these benefits is taxable income to Debby?','[\"$0\",\"$2,500\",\"$1,000\",\"$3,500\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 48, states, in part, that sick pay is a payment to a taxpayer that they receive from their employer while the person is sick or injured. It is part of the person\'s salary or wages. In addition, the taxpayer must include in their income sick pay benefits received from any of the following payers:nnA welfare fund.nA state sickness or disability fund.nAn association of employers or employees.nAn insurance company, if their employer paid for the plan.nHowever, if the taxpayer paid the premiums on an accident or health insurance policy, the benefits they receive under the policy are not taxable. For more information, see Publication 525.nnDebby, in this case, would include in gross income the sick pay from her employer\'s plan of $2,500 and not the benefits from her own plan of $1,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(335,12,'Paul owns a second home at the lake. During 2024, he spent 3 weeks (21 days) at the lake home, rented it to his daughter for three 3-day weekends for a total of $220, and rented it to friends for 10 weeks (70 days) at fair rental value of $300 per week. His expenses for the year include the following:n  Depreciation           $2,000n  Insurance                 100n  Mortgage interest       1,000n  Real estate taxes       2,000n  Utilities               1,000nWhat amount may he deduct for expenses on his Schedule E, Supplemental Income and Loss?','[\"$2,100\",\"$3,000\",\"$3,220\",\"$4,620\"]',2,'If a taxpayer uses a dwelling unit for both rental and personal purposes, the expenses for such must be divided between the rental use and the personal use based on the number of days used for each purpose.nnThe following rules (as given on page 17 of Publication 527) should be regarded when dividing expenses:nnAny day that the unit is rented at a fair rental price is a day of rental use even if the unit was used for personal purposes that day, andnAny day that the unit is available for rent but not actually rented is not a day of rental use.nAdditionally, rental deductions are limited if a taxpayer rents property for 15 or more days during the tax year and uses it for the greater of (a) more than 14 days or (b) more than 10% of the number of days during the year for which the home is rented. Under this limitation the amount of rental activity deductions may not exceed the amount by which the gross income derived from such activity exceeds the deductions otherwise allowable for the property such as interest and taxes (similar to hobby loss rules). (See Publication 527, pages 17 and 18.)nnGiven that Paul\'s rental income was $3,220, his applicable deductions are limited to that extent. The rental property was used 100 days, which is the sum of 70 days (rental), 21 days (personal use), and 9 days (daughter\'s use). All expenses are based on 70% (70 days rented ÷ 100 days used) and the deductible expense would be calculated as follows:nn  Interest             $  700 of the $1,000n  Taxes                 1,400 of the $2,000n  Insurance                70 of the $100n  Utilities, etc.         700 of the $1,000n  Depreciation          1,400 of the $2,000n  Maximum deductible   $4,270 which exceeds the rental incomen                              amount of $3,220nSee Worksheet 9-1 for figuring the limit on rental deductions (Publication 527, pages 20 and 21).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(336,12,'John, a cash basis taxpayer, had a $5,000 loan from his local credit union. He lost his job and was unable to make the payments on this loan. The credit union determined that the legal fees to collect might be higher than the amount John owed, so they canceled the $3,000 remaining amount due on the loan. John did not file bankruptcy nor was he insolvent. How much must John include in his income as a result of this occurrence?','[\"$5,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$0\",\"$8,000\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 68, addresses this issue by stating that in general, if a debt owed by the taxpayer is canceled or forgiven, other than as a gift or bequest, the taxpayer must include the canceled amount in gross income. If the debt, on the other hand, is intended as a gift, then the taxpayer has no income from the canceled debt. A debt includes any indebtedness for which the taxpayer is liable, or which attaches to property held by the taxpayer.nnThere are several exceptions to the inclusion of canceled debt in income. Some examples include certain student loans, deductible debt, or certain taxpayer situations (none of which apply here).nnHence, John should report the $3,000 on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 8c.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(337,12,'Mr. and Mrs. Apple received the following income during 2024:nn$200 in interest credited to their bank account but not withdrawn or used by them during the yearn$2,000 in interest received as a beneficiary in a trust established by Mr. Apple\'s father and included on Schedule K-1 from the trustn$100 in interest on a bond issued by the state of Georgian$1,000 bond interest, City of Atlanta municipal bondnHow much taxable interest income must Mr. and Mrs. Apple report on their 2024 tax return?','[\"$3,300\",\"$0\",\"$2,200\",\"$1,300\"]',2,'In general, any interest that a taxpayer receives or that is credited to the taxpayer\'s account and can be withdrawn is taxable income unless stated otherwise (Publication 17, pages 54–55). Examples of interest income include but are not limited to saving accounts, CD interest, and U.S. Treasury bills, notes, and bonds issued by any agency or instrumentality of the United States that are taxable for federal income tax purposes. (See Publication 17, pages 55.)nnInterest on a bond used to finance government operations generally is not taxable if the bond is issued by a state, the District of Columbia, a possession of the United States, or any of their political subdivisions. These bonds are better known as municipal bonds (or munis or muni bonds for short). (See Publication 17, pages 57–58.)nnThe amount of taxable interest income to be reported by Mr. and Mrs. Apple is $2,200, which is the sum of all taxable interest earned by the taxpayers (i.e., $2,000 plus $200). Municipal bond income (i.e., $1,000 and $100), on the other hand, is excludable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(338,12,'Sherwood received disability income of $6,000 for 2024. All premiums on the health and accident policy were paid by his employer and included in Sherwood\'s income. In addition, he received compensatory damages of $10,000 as a result of inadvertent poisoning at a local restaurant. He received no other income this year. How much income must Sherwood include on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$16,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$6,000\",\"$0\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 17, pages 52–53, amounts that are received by a taxpayer as compensation for sickness or injury through an accident or health plan that is paid for by the taxpayer’s employer are generally taxable. There are, however, some other sickness and injury benefits that are not taxable. These include the following amounts:nnCompensatory damages received by the taxpayer for physical injury or physical sickness, whether paid in a lump sum or in periodic paymentsnBenefits received by the taxpayer under an accident or health insurance policy on which either the taxpayer or the taxpayer\'s employer paid the premiums, but the taxpayer had to include them in his or her incomenDisability benefits received by the taxpayer for loss of income or earning capacity as a result of injuries under a no-fault car insurance policynAs a result of the above information, Sherwood would include $0 in income on his 2024 tax return. The $6,000 in disability income premiums was included in income, and the $10,000 in compensatory damages is not taxable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(339,12,'How are repainting and fixing leaks in a rental property treated if they are part of an extensive remodeling of the property?','[\"The costs of repainting and fixing leaks are\\u00a0not\\u00a0currently deductible as repairs.\",\"The cost of repainting, but not the cost of fixing leaks, is currently deductible as repairs.\",\"The cost of fixing leaks, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0the cost of repainting, is currently deductible as repairs.\",\"The costs of repainting and fixing leaks are currently deductible as repairs.\"]',0,'In 2013, the IRS issued TD 9636 (Tangible Property Final Regulations), applicable to tax year beginning on or after January 1, 2014 which finalized the guidance on Sections 162(a) and 263(a).nnThe “plan of rehabilitation” doctrine provided that a taxpayer must capitalize otherwise deductible repair or maintenance costs if they were incurred as part of a general rehabilitation, modernization and improvement to property (Moss v. Commissioner, United States v. Wehrli). The 2011 temporary regulations provided that a taxpayer must capitalize both the direct costs of an improvement as well as the indirect costs that directly benefit or are incurred by reason of improvement. The exception to this provision allowed a taxpayer to capitalize repair and maintenance costs incurred with connection with a personal residence if the costs were incurred at the time of a substantial residential remodel. The final regulations retain the rules from the 2011 temporary regulations and continue to provide that indirect costs, such as repair and maintenance costs, that do not directly benefit and that are not incurred by reason of an improvement are not required to be capitalized under section 263(a), regardless of whether they are incurred at the same time as an improvement.nnSince these expenses are direct costs intended to restore the property (i.e., repainting and fixing existing leaks), the expenses cannot be treated as repairs but rather as capital improvements, per the above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(340,12,'How are taxable disability payments reported?','[\"As pension income both before and after reaching the minimum retirement age\",\"As nontaxable income before and pension income after reaching the minimum retirement age\",\"As wages before and pension income after reaching the minimum retirement age\",\"As wages both before and after reaching the minimum retirement age\"]',2,'Publication 17, pages 52–53, states that if a taxpayer retired on disability, then the taxpayer must include in income any disability pension received under a plan that is paid for by the employer. Moreover, the taxpayer must report the taxable disability payments as wages, until the taxpayer reaches minimum retirement age. Minimum retirement age generally is the age at which the taxpayer can first receive a pension or annuity if the taxpayer is not disabled.nnBeginning on the day after the taxpayer reaches minimum retirement age, payments received by the taxpayer are taxable as a pension or annuity.nnFor information concerning the reporting of pension income, refer to Publication 575.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(341,12,'Ms. Miller set up a computer system for Mr. Town\'s business. In return, Mr. Town gave Ms. Miller a storage facility. Ms. Miller plans to use this facility for business purposes and plans to depreciate it. The fair market value of Ms. Miller\'s services and the storage facility was $50,000. Mr. Town\'s basis in the storage facility was $30,000. How should Ms. Miller treat the transaction, and what is her depreciable basis for the property?','[\"Ms. Miller should include the $50,000 in income and use $30,000 as the depreciable basis for the storage facility she received.\",\"Mr. Town should include the $30,000 in his income and use the $50,000 as the depreciable basis for the storage facility.\",\"Ms. Miller should include $30,000 in income and $50,000 as the depreciable basis for the storage facility.\",\"Ms. Miller should include $50,000 in income and use $50,000 as the basis for the storage facility.\"]',3,'In general, when property is received for services, the taxpayer includes the property\'s FMV in income, and the amount included in income becomes the basis of the property received.nnIf the services were performed for a price agreed on beforehand, it will be accepted as the FMV of the property if there is no evidence to the contrary.nnIn this case, Ms. Miller should include $50,000 in income and use the same amount as the basis for the storage facility.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(342,12,'Interest was credited to Jane\'s savings account on December 31, 2024. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The interest becomes taxable after Jane removes the interest from her account.\",\"The interest becomes taxable in 2025 because interest is taxable the day after it is credited to a person\'s account, which is January 1, 2025.\",\"The interest becomes taxable in 2024 because it was credited to her account in 2024, even though it was December 31, 2024.\",\"There isn\'t enough information to respond to the question.\"]',2,'Most individual taxpayers use the cash method. Under this method, taxpayers generally report any interest as interest income in the year that they receive or constructively receive the interest.nnThe interest is constructively received if it is credited to his or her account or is made available to the taxpayer. Moreover, the taxpayer does not need to have physical possession of it. For example, the taxpayer is considered to receive interest, dividends, or other earnings on any deposit or account in a bank, savings and loan, or similar financial institution, or interest on life insurance policy dividends left to accumulate, when they are credited to the person\'s account and can be withdrawn by the person. This is true even if they are not yet entered in the taxpayer\'s passbook or bankbook.nnOne exception to this rule is municipal bond interest, which is excludable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(343,12,'Joan and Jim had income from investments in 2024. They also earned a substantial amount in wages. Most of their dividends and interest are reinvested. The reinvested income included $2,000 in dividends from mutual funds, interest from savings account of $3,000, and interest from certificates of deposit of $4,000. Dividends from stocks of $5,000 were received and spent. Interest of $1,000 earned in 2024 on a loan from a friend was not received until the following year. How much interest and dividend income must Joan and Jim report on their tax return for 2024?','[\"$6,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$14,000\",\"$5,000\"]',2,'In general, any interest that a taxpayer receives or that is credited to his or her account and can be withdrawn is taxable income. It does not have to be entered in the taxpayer\'s passbook or bankbook. (Publication 17, pages 54–55)nnOne exception to the general rule is interest on a bond used to finance government operations generally is not taxable if the bond is issued by a state, the District of Columbia, a possession of the United States, or any of their political subdivisions. This type of interest is known as municipal bond interest and is excludable. (Publication 17, page 58)nnPublication 550, page 30, states that dividend reinvestment plans permit taxpayers to use the dividends to buy (through an agent) more shares of stock in the corporation instead of receiving the dividends in cash. In such cases, if the taxpayer reinvests the dividends to buy more stock at a price equal to its fair market value, the taxpayer still must report the dividends as income. If, on the other hand, the taxpayer is a member of a dividend reinvestment plan that lets the person buy more stock at a price less than its fair market value, the taxpayer must report as dividend income the fair market value of the additional stock on the dividend payment date.nnOrdinary (taxable) dividends are the most common type of distribution from a corporation. They are paid out of the earnings and profits of a corporation and are ordinary income to the taxpayer. (Publication 550, page 28)nnJoan and Jim would report interest and dividend income of $14,000, which is the sum of reinvested dividend income ($2,000), interest from savings account ($3,000), interest from a CD ($4,000), and dividend income spent ($5,000). The interest earned on a loan from a friend is taxable in the year received and not the year earned since the couple are cash basis taxpayers (refer to the example on page 23 of Publication 550, \"When To Report Interest Income\").',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(344,12,'John frequently pays for repairs in his apartment and gives the receipts to his landlord in lieu of part of his rental payment. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The landlord does\\u00a0not\\u00a0deduct the repair expenses and does\\u00a0not\\u00a0report the repair expense amounts as rental income.\",\"The landlord is entitled to deduct the repair expenses (noncapital improvements) on his tax return.\",\"The landlord must report the repair expense amounts as rental income.\",\"The landlord is entitled to deduct the repair expenses (noncapital improvements) on his tax return but must also report these amounts as rental income.\"]',3,'Publication 527, page 4, states in part that expenses paid by a tenant are considered rental income by the landlord or owner of the rent property. That means the taxpayer must include the amount spent by the tenant in gross income.nnIn addition, the taxpayer (i.e., property owner) can deduct the expenses paid by the tenant if they are deductible rental expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(345,12,'Ms. Flyer owns a house and rents it to a painter. The painter lost his job in April and volunteered to paint the outside of the house in lieu of rent for the months of May and June. Ms. Flyer determines the $1,000 rent due from her renter is approximately the amount she would have to pay someone else to paint the house. She decides to accept his offer. How should she handle the situation since she did not receive any cash rent for the months of May and June?','[\"Include $0 in rent income\",\"Include $1,000 in rent income\",\"Include $1,000 in interest income\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 551, page 7, states that if a taxpayer receives property for his or her services, the property\'s FMV is taxable. The taxable amount becomes the taxpayer\'s basis. If the services were performed for a price agreed on beforehand, the price will be accepted as the FMV of the property if there is no evidence to the contrary.nnLikewise, Publication 527, page 3, states that if a taxpayer receives property or services, instead of money, as rent, the FMV of the property or services should be included as rent income. If the services are provided at an agreed-upon or specified price, that price is the FMV unless there is evidence to the contrary.nnIn this case, Ms. Flyer would report the $1,000 as income, which is the approximate cost that she would have paid someone to paint her house.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(346,12,'When Joe\'s financial institution offered a substantial discount of $5,000 for early payment of his home mortgage, he borrowed from a family member to take advantage of this offer. The mortgage is the original debt from when he purchased his home and it is the only debt on his home. How should Joe treat this discount transaction?','[\"File Form 982 to claim the exclusion\",\"Report $5,000 on Schedule 1 (Form 1040)\",\"Reduce his home mortgage interest deduction by $5,000\",\"Report $5,000 original issue discount as interest income\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 68, states, in part, that if a taxpayer\'s financial institution offers a discount for the early payment of the taxpayer\'s mortgage loan, the amount of the discount is canceled debt and, as such, the amount is included in gross income of the taxpayer unless it qualifies for exclusion under excluded debt.nnPublication 4681, pages 3–4, provides, a series of examples illustrating the qualified principal residence indebtedness exclusion. This provision was extended as a result of the Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Relief Act of 2019, which is included in the Further Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2019 (Consolidated Appropriation Act of 2021, under Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Tax Relief Act of 2020 extended the exclusion from income of discharge of indebtedness but modified the limits of how much indebtedness taxpayers may exclude).nnTo show that all or part of a taxpayer’s canceled debt is excluded from income because it is qualified principal residence indebtedness, attach Form 982 to the taxpayer’s federal income tax return and check the box on line 1e. On line 2 of Form 982, include the amount of canceled qualified principal residence indebtedness, but not more than the amount of the exclusion limit (explained earlier).nnIf the taxpayer continues to own their home after a cancellation of qualified principal residence indebtedness, the taxpayer must reduce their basis in the home as explained under Reduction of Tax Attributes appearing on pages 3 and 4 of Publication 4681',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(347,12,'John and Mary moved into your rental property and paid a $10,000 security deposit. You agreed to use this security deposit as their last month\'s rent. Additionally, they paid a painting contractor $2,500 to paint the interior. How much of these payments should be reported as rental income for this year?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$12,500\"]',3,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in Publication 527, Residential Rental Income (Including Rental of Vacation Homes). In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts received as rent.nnRental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. In addition to amounts received as normal rent payments, there are other amounts that may be rental income and as such are included in rental income. Advance rent, for example, is any amount received before the period that it covers. These payments are included in rental income in the year received regardless of the period covered or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using. (See page 2 of Publication 527.)nnSecurity deposits, on the other hand, are not included in rental income when it is received if the amount is to be returned to the tenant at the end of the lease. If the taxpayer keeps part or all of the security deposit during any year because the tenant does not live up to the terms of the lease, the amount retained becomes income for that year.nnIf an amount called a security deposit is to be used as a final payment of rent, it is advance rent and as such, it is included as rental income in the year that it is received.nnIf a tenant pays any of the rental property expenses, the payments are treated as rental income by the property owner and may be deducted as an expense by the property owner if they are deductible rental expenses.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer includes the entire $12,500 ($10,000 as advanced rent and $2,500 as tenant-paid expenses on the property) as rental income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(348,12,'The standard deduction is increased for individuals who are age 65 and older and/or:','[\"Receiving unemployment compensation\",\"Retired from the military\",\"A beneficiary of a trust\\u00a0 \\u00a0\",\"Blind\"]',3,'Publication 17, pages 93–94 provides, in part, that if a taxpayer is age 65 or older on the last day of the year and don\'t itemize deductions, the taxpayer is entitled to a higher standard deduction. A taxpayer is considered 65 on the day before their 65th birthday.nnLikewise, if a taxpayer is blind on the last day of the year and they don\'t itemize deductions, the taxpayer is entitled to a higher standard deduction.nnThe standard deduction amounts for most people are shown in Table 10-1 (Publication 17, pages 93–94).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(349,12,'Ms. Cross owns a house that she rents to non-related parties. She incurred the following costs during 2024:nn$400 to resurface a tub in the master bathroomn$500 to paint the kitchen after installing new cabinetsn$2,000 to replace cabinets in the kitchenn$600 to replace the built-in dishwashernHow should these costs be characterized and in what amounts?','[\"$3,100 as improvements to be capitalized and $400 as repairs\",\"$400 as improvements to be capitalized and $3,100 as repairs\",\"$3,500 as improvements to be capitalized\",\"$2,000 as improvements to be capitalized and $1,500 as repairs\"]',0,'Publication 527, page 5, provides that a taxpayer can deduct the cost of repairs to the taxpayer\'s rental property. The taxpayer cannot deduct the cost of improvements; rather, the taxpayer recovers the cost of improvements by taking depreciation.nnA repair keeps the property in good operating condition. It does not materially add to the value of the property or substantially prolong its life. In general, an expense for repairing or maintaining rental property may be deducted if the expense is not required to be capitalized. Repainting the property inside or out, fixing gutters or floors, fixing leaks, plastering, and replacing broken windows are examples of repairs. (Publication 527, page 5)nnIf the taxpayer makes repairs as part of an extensive remodeling or restoration of your property, the whole job is an improvement. Expenses that may be for restoration include expenses for replacing a substantial structural part of your property, repairing damage to your property after you properly adjusted the basis of your property as a result of a casualty loss, or rebuilding your property to a like-new condition. In this case, the painting of the kitchen after installing new cabinets would qualify as an improvement. (Publication 527, pages 5–6)nnAn improvement, in general, adds to the value of property, prolongs its useful life, or adapts it to new uses. Table 1-1 on page 5 of Publication 527 shows examples of many improvements.nnIn this case, Ms. Cross has $3,100 in improvements, which is the sum of $500 for painting, $2,000 for the cabinets, and $600 for the dishwasher. The $400 is currently deductible as repairs for the tub.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(350,12,'Which of the following would be included in gross income on a federal income tax return?','[\"A gift of stock from a parent to a child\",\"Alimony from a divorce decree executed in 2024\",\"Life insurance proceeds received by a child after the death of a parent\",\"A painting received from a client in exchange for legal services\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 67, explains that bartering involves an exchange of property or services, and the fair market value of property or services received in barter is included in income. According to Publication 17, page 76, gifts are not included in income. Publication 17, page 74, specifies that alimony payments received under a divorce or separation agreement executed after 2018 are not reported as income. Life insurance proceeds are not taxable unless they were turned over for a price (Publication 17, page 70).nnThe only correct answer is the painting received from a client in exchange for legal services.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(351,12,'Cyril, who is 68 years of age, received Social Security benefits of $12,000, wages of $5,000, interest and dividends of $4,000, unemployment compensation of $3,000, and municipal bond interest of $1,500. Calculate Cyril\'s adjusted gross income.','[\"$9,600\",\"$17,100\",\"$19,500\",\"$12,000\"]',3,'Interest on a bond used to finance government operations generally is not taxable if the bond is issued by a state, the District of Columbia, a possession of the United States, or any of their political subdivisions. As a result, the municipal bond interest in this problem ($1,500) is excludable (Publication 17, page 60).nnPublication 17, page 73, states that a taxpayer must include in income all unemployment compensation received by the taxpayer. As an aside, the taxpayer should receive a Form 1099-G showing the unemployment compensation paid to him or her.nnPublication 17, pages 62–63, states that some Social Security benefits become taxable if one-half of the benefits plus all other income, including tax-exempt interest, exceed the base amount of $25,000 in the case of a person filing single or head of household ($32,000 if married filing jointly and $0 if married and filing separate).nnIn this case, Cyril has a total income for determining if Social Security benefits are taxable of $19,500, which is the sum of his wages of $5,000, interest and dividends of $4,000, unemployment compensation of $3,000, municipal bond interest of $1,500, and one-half of Social Security benefits of $12,000. Since $19,500 is less than the $25,000 limit, none of Cyril\'s Social Security benefits are included in AGI. (Publication 17, page 63)nnThus, Cyril\'s AGI is $12,000, which is the sum of his wages of $5,000, interest and dividends of $4,000, and unemployment compensation of $3,000. None of Cyril\'s Social Security income or municipal bond interest is included in gross income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(352,12,'John and Mary had a pipe burst in the basement of your rental home. They were unable to reach you on vacation. They had the plumber come out and repair the pipe and damage. They paid the plumber $575. They deducted $575 from their rent of $5,000. How much rent should be considered income that month?','[\"$5,000\",\"$4,425\",\"$5,575\",\"$5,745\"]',0,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in Publication 527, Residential Rental Property (Including Rental of Vacation Homes). In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property.nnIf a tenant pays any of the rental property expenses, the payments are treated as rental income by the property owner and may be deducted as an expense by the property owner if they are deductible rental expenses. (See pages 3–4 of Publication 527.)nnIn this problem, the taxpayer includes the $5,000 ($4,425 actual rent payment and $575 to repair the pipes).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(353,12,'Mr. and Mrs. Able are investors in a mutual fund that is not part of a qualified retirement plan. For 2024, the fund notified them that it had allocated a $9,500 long-term capital gain to their account. Of this total, only $4,500 was distributed in 2024. In addition, the fund paid $500 federal tax on their behalf. What is the correct amount of long-term capital gain that the couple should report on their 2024 tax return?','[\"$10,000\",\"$9,500\",\"$5,000\",\"$4,500\"]',1,'Publication 550, page 30, states that some mutual funds and REITs keep their long-term capital gains and pay tax on them. In this case, the taxpayer still must treat his or her share of these gains as distributions, even though the taxpayer did not actually receive them. This type of dividend is not included on Form 1099-DIV; it is reported on Form 2439, Notice to Shareholder of Undistributed Long-Term Capital Gains.nnMr. and Mrs. Able must report the entire $9,500 as income in year 2024. The undistributed capital gain will increase the couple\'s basis in the mutual fund and they may also take credit for the $500 tax paid on their behalf. The undistributed gain and the tax paid will be reported to the couple on Form 2439.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(354,12,'Dianne deposited $10,000 in a bank to purchase a 6-month money market certificate on October 31, 2023, that matures in 2024. The bank gave her a Form 1099-INT for 2024 showing the $600 interest earned on the certificate. What amount does Dianne report as taxable interest income in 2024?','[\"$200\",\"$300\",\"$400\",\"$600\"]',3,'In general, any interest that a taxpayer receives or that is credited to the taxpayer\'s account and can be withdrawn is taxable income unless stated otherwise (Publication 17, page 53). Examples of interest income include but are not limited to saving accounts, CD interest, and U.S. treasury bills, notes, and bonds (Publication 17, page 55).nnSince Dianne earned the interest in 2024, the interest amount is included in gross income in that year.nnPublication 17, pages 54–55, provides additional information in this area:nnCertificates of deposit and other deferred interest accounts: If a taxpayer opens any of these accounts, interest may be paid at fixed intervals of 1 year or less during the term of the account. In such cases, the taxpayer generally must include this interest in income when the taxpayer actually receives it or is entitled to receive it without paying a substantial penalty. The same is true for accounts that mature in 1 year or less and pay interest in a single payment at maturity.nSee chapter 6 of Publication 17 for detailed information concerning interest income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(355,12,'Rosemary\'s home is used exclusively as her residence all year except for 10 days. During this time, Rosemary rents out her home to alumni for $3,000 while the local college has its homecoming celebration. What amount does Rosemary include on her tax return?','[\"$3,000 as other income on Form 1040\",\"$3,000 as rent income on Schedule C\",\"$3,000 as interest income on Schedule A\",\"None of the rent is included in income.\"]',3,'You generally must include in your gross income all amounts you receive as rent (Publication 527, page 18). However, if you rent property that is also used as your home there is a special 15-day rule (minimal rental use) that applies in calculating your taxable rental income. If you rent the property for less than 15 days during the tax year, the rent received is not included in gross income (Publication 527, page 18).nnGiven that Rosemary rented her home out for only 10 days during the year, the rent received is not included in her income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(356,12,'Jack, a U.S. citizen, was a resident of England for all of 2024. He received $130,000 in wages from an English corporation, and paid taxes to England on this income. What portion of the $130,000 is exempt from U.S. income tax?','[\"$0\",\"$112,000\",\"$126,500\",\"$130,000\"]',2,'In order to lessen the potential for double taxation, United States taxpayers are allowed to take an amount of qualified foreign taxes paid or accrued during the year as a credit or a deduction. Taken as a deduction, foreign income taxes reduce your taxable income. Taken as a credit, foreign income taxes reduce your tax liability. Regardless of which option a taxpayer elects, they must treat all foreign income taxes the same way during that year. (Publication 54, page 24)nnClaiming the credit is done on Schedule 3 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 1, and generally requires a taxpayer to complete and attach Form 1116 to Form 1040. In order to claim the deduction, the taxpayer must itemize their deductions, and therefore take the deduction on Schedule A. (Publication 54, page 24)nnIn addition, United States citizens or resident aliens who work “abroad” are taxed on worldwide income. However, the person may qualify to exclude from gross income up to $126,500 of foreign earned income for 2024 (Publication 54, page 20). However, a taxpayer is not permitted to take the credit or deduction for foreign income taxes paid on earnings that can be excluded from the U.S. tax under any of the following (Publication 54, page 24):nnForeign earned income exclusionnForeign housing exclusionnPossession exclusionnGiven that Jack received $130,000 while he was a resident of England for all of 2024, he may be able to exclude up to $126,500 (not the entire $130,000) from gross income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(357,12,'Where should income be reported when received by an individual from rental (not including self-rentals) of an office building and where no significant services are provided to the tenant?','[\"Other income on Form 1040\",\"Income on Schedule E,\\u00a0Supplemental Income and Loss\",\"Income on Schedule C,\\u00a0Profit or Loss From Business\",\"Income on Schedule D,\\u00a0Capital Gains and Losses\"]',1,'Publication 527, page 12, states that when a taxpayer rents buildings, rooms, or apartments, and provide basic services such as heat and light, trash collection, etc., the taxpayer normally reports the rental income and expenses in Part I of Schedule E (Form 1040).nnIf, on the other hand, the taxpayer provides substantial services that are primarily for the tenant\'s convenience, such as regular cleaning, changing linen, or maid service, the taxpayer reports the rental income and expenses on Schedule C (Form 1040), Profit or Loss From Business, or Schedule C-EZ, Net Profit From Business.nnSubstantial services do not include the furnishing of heat and light, cleaning of public areas, trash collection, etc. For more information on this issue, look at Publication 334, Tax Guide for Small Business (For Individuals Who Use Schedule C or C-EZ).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(358,12,'In 2024, Gene is 85 years of age and single. He received Social Security payments totaling $14,000 (this includes a Medicare premium of $600), dividend and interest income of $21,000, a pension of $30,000, and taxable IRA benefits of $16,000. What is Gene\'s adjusted gross income for 2024?','[\"$80,400\",\"$78,900\",\"$78,390\",\"$67,000\"]',1,'The first issue to be addressed in this problem is whether the taxpayer\'s Social Security benefits are taxable and, if so, to what extent: 50% or 85%. In general, the higher the income amount of the taxpayer, the more likely the benefits will be taxable. Because this taxpayer has income (ignoring Social Security benefits) of $67,000, the 85% rule is the better starting point. In particular, 85% of a person\'s Social Security benefits are taxable if either of the following situations applies (Publication 17, pages 62–64):nnThe total of one-half of the person\'s benefits and all other income is more than $34,000 ($44,000 if the taxpayer is married filing jointly) ornThe taxpayer is married filing separately and lived with his or her spouse at any time during the tax year.nIn this case, the taxpayer satisfies the first situation with a total dollar amount of $74,000 ($67,000 plus one-half of $14,000). Hence, the taxpayer has an AGI amount of $78,900, which is his other income of $67,000 plus 85% of his Social Security benefits of $14,000 ($11,900).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(359,12,'Johnny has various investments. He earns interest and dividends on a certificate of deposit (CD), a savings account, mutual funds, corporate stocks, and corporate bonds. Johnny files his tax returns using the cash method. The interest on the CD is rolled into a new CD with the old principal. He receives the interest from the corporate bonds and savings account on a semi-annual basis. The earnings from the mutual funds are not distributed and are used to purchase additional shares. The dividends from the corporate stocks are reinvested. What income does Johnny have to report currently?','[\"Savings account and CD interest\",\"Corporate stock and mutual fund dividends\",\"Corporate bond and savings account interest\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'In general, any interest that a taxpayer receives or that is credited to the taxpayer\'s account and can be withdrawn is taxable income unless stated otherwise (Publication 17, pages 55–56). Examples of interest income include but are not limited to saving accounts, CD interest, and U.S. treasury bills, notes, and bonds. (Publication 17, pages 55–56)nnOrdinary (taxable) dividends are the most common type of distribution from a corporation. They are paid out of the earnings and profits of a corporation and are ordinary income to the taxpayer. This means they are not capital gains (Publication 550, pages 28–30). A taxpayer can assume that any dividend received on common or preferred stock is an ordinary dividend unless the paying corporation says otherwise.nnSee chapter 6 of Publication 17 and Publication 550 for detailed information concerning interest and dividend income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(360,12,'Mr. Ratchet, a plumber, usually charges $40 per hour for his services. One of his customers gave him a painting in exchange for 4 hours labor plus materials. The painting originally cost the customer $90 and had a current established fair market value of $250. There was no agreed-upon price before the work was done. What is the amount that Mr. Ratchet must include in income and what is his basis in the painting?','[\"Income $250; Basis $250\",\"Income $250; Basis $90\",\"Income $160; Basis $250\",\"Income $160; Basis $90\"]',0,'Publication 551, page 10, states that if a taxpayer receives property for services, the property\'s FMV is taxable. The taxable amount becomes the taxpayer\'s basis. If the services were performed for a price agreed on beforehand, the price will be accepted as the FMV of the property if there is no evidence to the contrary.nnIn this case, Mr. Ratchet would report as income the fair market value of the painting received and the basis of the painting would also be the fair market value.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(361,12,'Jean is a U.S. citizen living and working in France for all of 2024. She received wages of $150,000, dividends of $10,000, and alimony of $20,000 in 2024. She decides to use the foreign earned income exclusion available to her and file Form 2555. What is the amount of Jean\'s foreign earned income before any limitations are applied?','[\"$0\",\"$120,000\",\"$150,000\",\"$170,000\"]',2,'In order to lessen the potential for double taxation, United States taxpayers are allowed to take an amount of qualified foreign taxes paid or accrued during the year as a credit or a deduction. Taken as a deduction, foreign income taxes reduce your taxable income. Taken as a credit, foreign income taxes reduce your tax liability. Regardless of which option a taxpayer elects, they must treat all foreign income taxes the same way during that year (Publication 54, page 24).nnClaiming the credit is done on Schedule 3 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 1, and a taxpayer generally needs to complete and attach Form 1116. In order to claim the deduction, the taxpayer must itemize the deductions and therefore take the deduction on Schedule A (Publication 54, page 25).nnThe foreign earned income exclusion is voluntary. A taxpayer can choose the exclusion by completing the appropriate parts of Form 2555 (Publication 54, page 20). To claim the foreign earned income exclusion, the foreign housing exclusion, or the foreign housing deduction, a taxpayer must have foreign earned income (Publication 54, page 16). Foreign earned income generally is income a taxpayer receives for services performed during a period in which the taxpayer met both of the following requirements:nnthe taxpayer\'s tax home is in a foreign country, andnthe taxpayer meets either the bona fide residence test or the physical presence test.nIn addition, United States taxpayers who work “abroad” are permitted (if they qualify) to exclude from gross income the lesser of foreign earned income or $120,000 for 2024 (Publication 54, page 19). For Jean, the amount of foreign earned income before any limitations that qualifies for the exclusion is $150,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(362,12,'Which of the following items is not considered when determining if a taxpayer\'s Social Security benefits may be taxable?','[\"The exclusion for foreign earned income\",\"Interest that is tax-exempt\",\"Notary fees received\",\"Unemployment benefits\"]',0,'To find out whether any of a taxpayer’s Social Security benefits may be taxable, compare the base amount for their filing status with the total of:nnone-half of their benefits plusnall their other income, including tax-exempt interest.nWhen making this comparison, do not reduce the taxpayer’s other income by any exclusions for:nninterest from qualified U.S. savings bonds,nemployer-provided adoption benefits,nforeign earned income or foreign housing, ornincome earned by bona fide residents of American Samoa or Puerto Rico.nPublication 17, pages 62–64, provides that a taxpayer’s income is not reduced by any exclusions for foreign earned income when determining if a taxpayer’s Social Security benefits may be taxable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(363,12,'Which of the following statements about dividends received from a dividend reinvestment plan is correct?','[\"Reinvested cash dividends are\\u00a0not\\u00a0taxable if not removed from the account.\",\"Reinvested cash dividends are\\u00a0not\\u00a0taxable until the related stock is sold.\",\"Reinvested cash dividends receive capital gains treatment, or if not reinvested, receive ordinary income treatment.\",\"Reinvested cash dividends are taxable as dividend income.\"]',3,'When a taxpayer elects to buy (through an agent) more shares of stock in the corporation instead of receiving the dividends in cash from the corporation, the reinvested dividend amount is reported as dividend income by the taxpayer. Moreover, the reinvested dividends are taxable in the year paid and are added to the basis of the stock or mutual fund.nnIn addition, the taxpayer must report as dividend income any service charge subtracted from the cash dividends before the dividends are used to buy the additional stock. Hence, the full dividend amount is taxable. However, the taxpayer may be able to deduct the service charge.nnPublication 550, page 30, provides additional information on this issue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(364,12,'On June 15, Alfred received .25 bitcoin in payment for services he rendered on March 12. The coins had a value of $31,000 on March 12, $32,000 on June 15, and $29,000 on December 31. What amount is included in Alfred’s gross income?','[\"$29,000 as ordinary income\",\"$31,000 as ordinary income\",\"$32,000 as ordinary income\",\"$32,000 as ordinary income and $1,000 as a capital loss\"]',2,'IRS Notice 2014-21 and IRS News Release 2018-71 provide in Q&A-4 that the basis of virtual currency that a taxpayer receives as payment for goods or services is the fair market value of the virtual currency in U.S. dollars as of the date of receipt.nnFurthermore, Q&A-5 holds that taxpayers will be required to determine the fair market value of virtual currency in U.S. dollars as of the date of payment or receipt. If a virtual currency is listed on an exchange and the exchange rate is established by market supply and demand, the fair market value of the virtual currency is determined by converting the virtual currency into U.S. dollars (or into another real currency, which in turn can be converted into U.S. dollars) at the exchange rate, in a reasonable manner that is consistently applied.nnThus, Alfred would be required to include $32,000 in gross income, which is the FMV of the virtual currency on June 15 (date of receipt).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(365,12,'Minnie\'s tax return for 2024 shows the following income:nn$800 wagesn$6,490 unemployment compensationn$1,000 alimony (received as per divorce agreement prior to January 1, 2019)n$8,000 rental income from apartment buildings she ownsnWhat is Minnie\'s earned income for the purpose of determining how much she can contribute to an IRA?','[\"$800\",\"$7,290\",\"$1,800\",\"$16,290\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 590-A, page 9, a taxpayer can contribute to his or her traditional IRA the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if the taxpayer is 50 or older) or the taxpayer\'s taxable compensation for the year (Publication 590-A, page 6).nnCompensation includes items such as wages, salaries, commissions, self-employment income, alimony and separate maintenance payments, and nontaxable combat pay.nCompensation does not include items such as earnings and profits from property, interest and dividend income, pension or annuity income, deferred compensation, income from certain partnerships, and any amounts the taxpayer excludes from income (other than combat pay). (Publication 590-A, page 6)nIn addition, compensation does not include government-provided unemployment compensation (IRC Section 219(f)(1) and Revenue Procedure 91-18).nnAs a result, Minnie\'s earned income for purposes of determining how much she can contribute to an IRA is $1,800, which is the sum of her wages of $800 and alimony of $1,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(366,12,'What is the maximum contribution that a person can make to an HSA if they have self-only high deductible health plan (HDHP) coverage for 2024?','[\"$2,125\",\"$3,200\",\"$4,150\",\"$7,750\"]',2,'Publication 969, page 3, provides that the minimum annual deductible for HDHP self-only coverage is $1,500 and the maximum out-of-pocket for HDHP self-only coverage is $4,150 for 2024. (Publication 969, page 4)nnIn the case of health savings account (HSA) contributions, the amount an eligible person can contribute to their HSA depends on the type of HDHP coverage the person has, their age, the date they become an eligible individual, and the date the person ceases to be an eligible individual. For 2024, a qualified person that has self-only HDHP coverage can contribute up to $4,150. If the person has family HDHP coverage, they can contribute up to $8,300. (Publication 969, page 5)nnThus, in this case, the correct response is $4,150.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(367,12,'Which of the following taxes is imposed on wagering activities?','[\"Occupational tax only\",\"Wagering tax only\",\"Occupational tax and wagering tax\",\"None of the taxes listed\"]',2,'Federal wagering tax laws apply to both authorized and unauthorized gaming activities conducted by exempt organizations. The facts and circumstances of the types of wagering conducted, as well as the benefits derived therefrom, may have a bearing on whether the wagers are subject to the taxes. Internal Revenue Code Sections 4401 and 4411 impose excise taxes on the gaming industry. Section 4401 figures the tax on the wagers themselves while its companion occupational tax under Section 4411 is figured by two rates of tax. Form 730, Tax on Wagering, and Form 11-C, Special Tax Return and Application for Registry - Wagering, are used for reporting wagering taxes to the Internal Revenue Service. Effective January 1, 1997, Forms 11-C and 730 processing will be centralized at Cincinnati Service Center.nnExcise Tax on Wagering IRC 4401(a)(1) imposes a 0.25 percent tax on the amount of any wager authorized under the law of the state in which accepted. IRC 4401(a)(2) imposes a 2 percent tax on the amount of any wager not described in IRC 4401(a)(2) (i.e., those not authorized by state law).nnIRC 4901 and Reg. 44.4901-1(a) hold that persons who plan to engage in the business of accepting wagers; conducting any wagering pool or lottery; or receive wagers for, or on behalf of, any other person are liable for the tax on wagers. Form 11-C is used by the person who accepts the wagers subject to excise tax to pay the annual occupational tax under IRC 4411. Form 11-C is also used by each individual who accepts wagers for another person to register under IRC 4412 and pay the annual occupational tax. Reg. 44.4412-1 provides that registration is made by filing Form 11-C. After the form is filed and the tax is paid, the Service issues the taxpayer a special tax stamp as evidence of registration and payment. See Reg. 44.4901-1.nnIRC 4411(a) imposes an occupational tax of $500 per year on each person liable for the tax under IRC 4401 on wagers, or upon the person engaged in receiving wagers for or on behalf of any person so liable. IRC 4411(b) reduces the occupational tax to $50 where liability for the tax under IRC 4401 is determined under IRC 4401(a)(1) (i.e., state authorized wagers) and for persons who are engaged in accepting wagers only for or on behalf of persons so liable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(368,12,'Paul owns and operates a gourmet food store as a sole proprietorship out of a building he also owns. Based on the following information regarding 2024, compute his self-employment income (for SE tax purposes) for 2024.nn     Gross receipts                           $125,000n     Cost of goods sold                         63,000n     Utilities                                   7,000n     Real estate taxes                           1,500n     Gain on sale of business truck              2,000n     Depreciation expense                        4,000n     Section 179 deductions                      1,500n     Mortgage interest on building               8,000n     Contributions to Keogh retirement plan      2,000n     Net operating loss from 2020               15,000','[\"$25,000\",\"$27,000\",\"$38,000\",\"$40,000\"]',3,'Publication 334, page 9, provides, in part, that the maximum net self-employment earnings subject to the Social Security part of the self-employment tax is $168,600 for 2024. Thus, the net earnings in excess of $168,600 are not subject to the 12.4% Social Security part of the SE tax. The 2.9% Medicare part of the SE tax, however, is applied to all net earnings.nnFurthermore, Publication 334, page 9, states that a taxpayer must pay self-employment tax and file Schedule SE (Form 1040) if either of the following applies:nnThe taxpayer\'s net earnings from self-employment (excluding church employee income) were $400 or more.nThe taxpayer had church employee income of $108.28 or more.nA taxpayer\'s net earnings are the business gross income minus the allowable business deductions from that business. Although business deductions include contributions to SEP and qualified plans for common-law employees and the deduction for the deductible portion of the taxpayer\'s self-employment tax, these amounts are not included in a taxpayer\'s calculation of net earnings from self-employment or the person\'s self-employment tax. Rather, they are deducted as an adjustment for AGI on lines 14 and 15 of Schedule 1 of Form 1040 (Form 1040 Instructions, page 88).nnIn general, net nonfarm earnings (or net profit) are the amount found on line 31 of Schedule C and included on Schedule 1, line 3 (Schedule C (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) Instructions, pages C-13 and C-14).nnIn Paul\'s case, his self-employment income for the year is $40,000 and it is the gross sales of $125,000 less the total business expenses of $85,000. The business expenses are the sum of the cost of goods sold ($63,000), utilities ($7,000), real estate taxes ($1,500), depreciation expense ($4,000), Section 179 deduction ($1,500), and mortgage interest on building ($8,000).nnNet operating losses from prior years are not included in net earnings from self-employment (Schedule SE (Form 1040) Instructions, page SE-5).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(369,12,'Which of the following earnings are not subject to self-employment tax?','[\"Gains and losses, by a dealer in options or commodities, from dealing or trading in foreign currency contracts and elects to report gains\\/losses on Schedule C\",\"Fees earned by a professional fiduciary who administers a deceased person\'s estate\",\"Fees received for services performed as a notary public\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 334, pages 40 and 41, provides, in part, that taxpayers generally must pay self-employment (SE) tax and file Schedule SE (Form 1040) if their net earnings from self-employment are $400 or more. Schedule SE is used to figure net earnings from self-employment.nnPublication 334, page 41, also provides that fees received by a notary public are reported on Schedule C or C-EZ but are not subject to self-employment tax. The instructions for Schedule SE and Publication 334 list other types of income that are subject to and excluded from self-employment tax (e.g., child employed by parent).nnHence, the correct response is that fees for notary public service are not subject to SE tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(370,12,'Which of the following is not considered earned compensation for IRA contribution purposes?','[\"Deferred compensation\",\"Wages and salaries\",\"Self-employment income\",\"Commissions\"]',0,'Pursuant to Publication 590-A, page 9, the most that a taxpayer can contribute to his or her traditional IRA is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if the taxpayer is 50 or older) or the taxpayer\'s taxable compensation for the year.nnCompensation includes items such as wages, salaries, commissions, self-employment income, and alimony and separate maintenance.nCompensation does not include items such as earnings and profits from property, interest and dividend income, pension or annuity income, deferred compensation, income from certain partnerships, and any amounts the taxpayer excludes from income. (Publication 590-A, pages 6–7)nAs a result, the deferred compensation would not be considered earned compensation for IRA contribution purposes in this problem.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(371,12,'What is the maximum allowable deduction for contributions to a Roth IRA, if neither you nor your spouse was covered for any part of the year by an employer retirement plan in 2024, had a modified AGI of $80,000 from their employers, and both of you are under 50 years of age?','[\"$15,000\",\"$14,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$0\"]',3,'The general rule as given in Publication 590-A, page 39, is that the maximum annual contribution to a person\'s Roth IRA for 2024 is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if you are 50 or older) or the person\'s taxable compensation for the year.nnHowever, the Roth IRA contribution may be reduced or eliminated entirely depending on the taxpayer\'s filing status and modified AGI. If the taxpayer has a filing status of married joint, then the taxpayer is able to make (Publication 590-A, page 42):nna full contribution if the taxpayer has a modified AGI of $230,000 or less,na partial contribution if the taxpayer has a modified AGI of between $230,000 and $240,000, andnno contribution if the taxpayer has a modified AGI of $240,000 or more.nThe maximum contribution amount in this case is $14,000, but it is a nondeductible (not deductible) contribution that is made to a Roth IRA in any year. (Publication 590-A, pages 39 and 42, and Table I-2, page 5)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(372,12,'Which of the following is compensation for the purpose of contributions to individual retirement accounts?','[\"Deferred compensation received\",\"Foreign earned income excluded from income\",\"Pension or annuity income\",\"Taxable alimony and separate maintenance\"]',3,'Compensation, for the purposes of determining the amount of allowable contributions to an individual retirement account, includes wages, salaries, tips, professional fees, bonuses, and other amounts a taxpayer receives for providing personal services. The IRS treats as compensation any amount properly shown in box 1 of Form W-2 Wage and Tax Statement. Compensation also includes commissions, self-employment net income, and taxable alimony and separate maintenance payments.nnRemember, for divorce and separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, you may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse.nnTherefore, only taxable alimony and separate maintenance in the above items is treated as compensation for the purpose of contributions to individual retirement accounts. Note the key word is \"taxable alimony\" in this question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(373,12,'Rena is a 73-year-old single chemical engineer. She works part-time for a pharmaceutical company and earned $57,000 in 2024. Her modified adjusted gross income is $89,000. She participates in her employer\'s pension plan and profit-sharing plan. In 2024, she contributed $7,000 to a traditional IRA. How much of her contribution can Rena deduct in 2024?','[\"$2,750\",\"$6,500\",\"$7,000\",\"$0\"]',3,'Publication 590-A, page 9, states that the maximum annual contribution to a person\'s traditional IRA is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if age 50 or older) or the person\'s taxable compensation for the year.nnIf, however, a taxpayer is covered by an employer retirement plan and the taxpayer did not receive any Social Security benefits, his or her IRA deduction may be reduced or eliminated entirely depending on the taxpayer\'s filing status and modified AGI. That is, a single taxpayer is able to claim:nna full deduction if the taxpayer\'s modified AGI is $77,000 or less,na partial deduction if the taxpayer\'s modified AGI is between $77,000 and $87,000, ornno deduction if the taxpayer\'s modified AGI is $87,000 or more. (Publication 590-A, page 13, Table 1-2)nBecause Rena has a filing status of single, she is covered by a plan, and her modified AGI is $89,000 (over the threshold of $87,000), she cannot make a deductible IRA contribution in 2024. Hence, the correct response is $0.nnNote: This question can appear in a variety of ways and, as such, needs to be read carefully.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(374,12,'Kimberly, age 30, a full-time student with no taxable compensation, married Michael, age 30, during 2024. For the year, Michael had taxable compensation of $40,000. He plans to contribute and deduct $7,000 to his traditional IRA. If he and Kimberly file a joint return, how much may each deduct in 2024 for contributions to their individual traditional IRAs, and what is the compensation Kimberly uses to figure her contribution limit?','[\"IRA Deduction: $7,000; Compensation for Kimberly to Figure IRA Contribution Limit: $33,000\",\"IRA Deduction: $7,000; Compensation for Kimberly to Figure IRA Contribution Limit: $40,000\",\"IRA Deduction: $8,000; Compensation for Kimberly to Figure IRA Contribution Limit: $40,000\",\"IRA Deduction: $8,000; Compensation for Kimberly to Figure IRA Contribution Limit: $33,000\"]',0,'If a taxpayer files a joint return and has taxable compensation that is less than that of the taxpayer\'s spouse, the most that can be contributed for the year to an IRA is the smaller of the following two amounts:nn$7,000 ($8,000 if the taxpayer is 50 or older) ornThe total compensation includible in the gross income of both spouses for the year, reduced by the following two amounts:nThe taxpayer\'s spouse\'s IRA contribution for the year to a traditional IRA andnAny contributions for the year to a Roth IRA on behalf of the taxpayer\'s spouse.nTherefore, the total combined contributions that can be made for the year to both spouses\' IRAs can be as much as $14,000 ($15,000 if only one spouse is 50 or older, or $16,000 if both spouses are 50 or older).nnThus, Kimberly who has no compensation can add Michael\'s compensation, reduced by the amount of his IRA contribution, ($40,000 less $7,000, which is $33,000) to her own compensation ($0) to figure her maximum contribution to a traditional IRA. In her case, $7,000 is her contribution limit, because it is less than $33,000 (her compensation for purposes of figuring her contribution limit).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(375,12,'Alex and Arthur are equal partners in the A & R Partnership. Alex receives a guaranteed payment of $5,000. The partnership had distributive net income (after deducting the guaranteed payment of $5,000) of $80,000. What amounts are subject to self-employment tax?','[\"$37,500 each for Alex and Arthur\",\"$42,500 each for Alex and Arthur\",\"$40,000 each for Alex and Arthur\",\"$45,000 for Alex and $40,000 for Arthur\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 7, provides that guaranteed payments are included in income in the partner\'s tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nnFurthermore, the partner\'s distributive share of ordinary income from a partnership and guaranteed payments are subject to self-employment (SE) tax by including that amount on Schedule SE (Form 1040). (Schedule SE Instructions, page SE-1).nnThe exception to the above rule pertains to limited partners, which is not the case in this problem. Nevertheless, a limited partner generally does not include his or her distributive share of income or loss in computing net earnings from self-employment; however, limited partners do include guaranteed payments. (Schedule SE (Form 1040) Instructions, page SE-4)nnTherefore, Alex would include $45,000 as self-employment income, which is the sum of $5,000 from guaranteed payments and $40,000 from his one-half share of the partnership\'s distributive net income (i.e., $80,000). Arthur, on the other hand, would include only $40,000, which is his one-half share of the partnership\'s distributive net income (i.e., $80,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(376,12,'Anki attended the local university in 2024. She paid $2,500 in tuition and fees, paid $1,000 in room and board, and received a scholarship for $8,000 to cover all the remaining costs. Which of the following statements is correct about the deductibility of these educational expenses?','[\"None of the expenses are deductible in 2024.\",\"Anki can deduct $2,500 as an adjustment to income in 2024.\",\"Anki can deduct $3,500 as an adjustment to income in 2024.\",\"Anki can deduct $4,000 as an adjustment to income in 2024.\"]',0,'The Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Tax Act of 2020 repealed the tuition and fees deduction for tax years beginning after 2020.nnNote: The taxpayer may be entitled to claim the American Opportunity Credit or the Lifetime Learning Credit however those are not an option for this question.nnTherefore, Anki cannot deduct any of the educational expenses in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(377,12,'When figuring compensation for a self-employed individual for purposes of determining the amount of an allowable contribution to a traditional IRA, which of the following statements is not true?','[\"Self-employment income must be reduced by the deduction allowed for one-half of your self-employment taxes.\",\"When you have both self-employment income, and salary and wages, your compensation includes both amounts.\",\"If you have a net loss from self-employment, you must subtract the loss from any salary or wages received when figuring total compensation.\",\"In order to include net earnings from a trade or business as compensation, your personal services must be a material income-producing factor.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 590-A, page 6, compensation in determining the amount of an allowable contribution to a traditional IRA includes wages, salaries, commissions, self-employment income, and alimony and separate maintenance payments.nnIf a taxpayer is self-employed, compensation for this purpose is the net earnings from the trade or business reduced by the total of:nnthe deduction for contributions made on the taxpayer\'s behalf to retirement plans andnthe deduction allowed for the deductible part of a person\'s self-employment taxes.nMoreover, compensation includes earnings from self-employment even if they are not subject to self-employment tax due to religious beliefs.nnAdditionally, if there is a net loss from self-employment, this amount is not subtracted from salaries or wages when calculating total compensation.nnTherefore, all of the responses given are true except a net loss from self-employment is not subtracted from any salary or wages received when figuring total compensation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(378,12,'A self-employed consultant has a business history of net profits and net losses as follows:n   2020     $(400)n   2021       800n   2022       200n   2023      (500)nIn 2024, he would like to pay self-employment tax even though he incurred a loss of $(2,200). Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"He can use either the optional self-employment tax computation or the regular tax method.\",\"He qualifies for the optional self-employment tax computation because he has been in business for 5 years or less.\",\"He does\\u00a0not\\u00a0qualify for the optional self-employment tax computation.\",\"He qualifies for the optional self-employment tax computation because he had positive net earnings in at least 2 of the 3 years.\"]',2,'Publication 334, page 40, provides that a self-employed taxpayer must pay self-employment (SE) tax and file Schedule SE (Form 1040) if the taxpayer\'s net earnings from self-employment were $400 or more.nnIn addition to the regular method for computing a person\'s SE tax, a person may want to use the optional method (see Publication 334, page 42, and Schedule SE (Form 1040) Instructions) when he or she has a loss or a small net profit and the taxpayer:nnwants to receive credit for Social Security benefit coverage,nincurred child or dependent care expenses and could claim a credit,nis entitled to the earned income credit, ornis entitled to the additional child tax credit.nTo qualify for use of the nonfarm optional method as given in Publication 334, page 42, the taxpayer must satisfy all of the following tests:nnThe taxpayer is self-employed on a regular basis. This means that actual net earnings from self-employment were $400 or more in at least 2 of the 3 tax years before the current taxable year for which this method is being elected. The net earnings can be from either farm or nonfarm earnings or both, andnThe taxpayer has used this method less than 5 years. (There is a 5-year lifetime limit.) The years do not have to be one after another, andnThe taxpayer\'s net nonfarm profits were less than $7,103, and less than 72.189% of the taxpayer\'s gross nonfarm income.nThe facts given in this problem do not satisfy the first test of $400 in at least 2 of the 3 years. Therefore, the taxpayer does not qualify for the optional self-employment tax computation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(379,12,'Generally, an IRA contribution is limited to the lesser of $7,000 in 2024 or the taxpayer\'s compensation. However, which of the following items is not treated as compensation for this limitation?','[\"Wages earned by an individual under the age of 18\",\"Taxable alimony\",\"Self-employment loss\",\"Commissions\"]',2,'Unless a taxpayer reaches age 50 before 2025, the most that can be contributed to a traditional IRA for 2024 is the smaller of $7,000 or taxable compensation for the year. (Publication 590-A, page 9)nnIf the taxpayer reaches age 50 before 2025, the most that can be contributed to a traditional IRA for 2024 is the smaller of $8,000 or taxable compensation for the year.nnCompensation for this purpose includes wages (age is not an issue), salaries, commissions, self-employment income, and taxable alimony and separate maintenance payments. Additionally, if there is a net loss from self-employment, this amount is not subtracted from salaries or wages when calculating total compensation. (Publication 590-A, page 6)nnTherefore, all of the listed items are treated as compensation except self-employment loss.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(380,12,'Generally, which of the following rules apply to both traditional IRAs and Roth IRAs in 2024?','[\"Non-rollover contributions are generally limited to $7,000 each year or 100% of compensation, whichever is less.\",\"Contributions are always nondeductible.\",\"RMDs must be taken at age 73.\",\"Contribution phaseout limits are the same for both traditional IRA and Roth IRAs.\"]',0,'Publication 590-A, Table I-2, page 5, provides the contribution limits for both the traditional IRA and a Roth IRA. Unless a wage earner has reached age 50 by the end of 2024, the most that can be contributed to his or her traditional IRA, Roth IRA, or combination of both for 2024 is the smaller of $8,000 if the taxpayer is age 50 or older by the end of 2024 or the person\'s taxable compensation for the year.nnRMDs only apply to traditional IRAs.nnContributions for the traditional IRA may be deductible or nondeductible; contributions to the Roth IRA are always nondeductible. In addition, the phaseout limits for the traditional IRA is lower than those for the Roth IRA.nnThe correct response for this problem is the statement that the non-rollover contribution amount is the same for both IRAs.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(381,12,'Which of the following is not treated as compensation for purposes of figuring an IRA contribution deduction?','[\"Self-employment income\",\"Bonuses\",\"Tips\",\"Pension income\"]',3,'Publication 590-A, page 6, provides that compensation includes wages, salaries, tips, professional fees, bonuses, and self-employment income.nnPublication 590-A, page 7, provides that compensation does not include items such as pensions and annuity income and earnings and profits from property, such as rental income, interest income, and dividend income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(382,12,'In 2024, MaryAnn, a nonworking spouse, files a joint return with Jack, who is not covered by a pension plan at work. Their AGI is $50,000 and Jack, who is 48, plans to contribute $5,500 to a traditional IRA. MaryAnn, who is 51, wishes to contribute to an IRA. What is the maximum amount she can contribute?','[\"$7,500\",\"$7,000\",\"$6,500\",\"$8,000\"]',3,'If a spouse files a joint return and the spouse\'s taxable compensation is less than that of the other spouse, the most that can be contributed for that year to an IRA is the smaller of the following two amounts:nn$7,000 ($8,000 if the taxpayer is 50 or older) ornThe total compensation includible in the gross income of both spouses for the year, reduced by the following amounts:nThe spouse\'s IRA contribution for the year to a traditional IRAnAny contributions for the year to a Roth IRA on behalf of the spousenWhat this means is that even though one spouse is not working, as long as the other spouse has sufficient earnings as described above, they can make combined contributions for the year as much as $14,000 ($15,000 if only one spouse is 50 or older, or $16,000 if both spouses are 50 or older).nnThus, the maximum amount that Mary can contribute to an IRA is $8,000 because she is age 51 and because Jack has enough earnings.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(383,12,'What is your maximum allowable deduction for contributions to a Roth IRA, if neither you nor your spouse was covered for any part of the year by an employer retirement plan, in 2024?','[\"$7,000 if younger than 50\",\"$8,000 if older than 50\",\"Both answer choices are correct.\",\"Neither answer choice is correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 590-A, page 38, a taxpayer, regardless of his or her age, may be able to establish and make nondeductible contributions to a Roth IRA.nnFor the record, if this statement concerned a traditional IRA (not a Roth IRA), then both answer choices would be correct. That is, a taxpayer can contribute $7,000 for each spouse ($8,000 if 50 or older).nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBe careful when reading questions concerning traditional IRAs and Roth IRAs. Traditional IRA contributions can be either deductible or nondeductible, whereas Roth IRA contributions are never deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(384,12,'Edwin and Donna were married. He had established a traditional IRA to which he made contributions and had taken no distributions. The total value of the IRA was $50,000, of which $20,000 was nondeductible contributions. As the spousal beneficiary from inheritance, which of the following applies to Donna?','[\"Edwin\'s $20,000 basis in the IRA may be treated as basis to Donna.\",\"When Donna receives the distribution, she may not roll it over to her own traditional IRA.\",\"Donna must begin receiving periodic distributions by December 31 of the 5th year following Edwin\'s death.\",\"Donna must pay a 10% penalty on the funds in the IRA if she receives an immediate distribution after Edwin\'s death.\"]',0,'Publication 590-B, page 6, provides the general rules for an IRA that is inherited from a spouse. In general, if the surviving spouse inherits a traditional IRA from his or her deceased spouse, the surviving spouse generally can do any of the following:nnTreat it as his or her own IRA by designating himself or herself as the account owner,nTreat it as his or her own IRA by rolling it over into his or her traditional IRA, or to the extent it is taxable, into a qualified employer plan, qualified employee annuity plan (Section 403(a) plan), tax-sheltered annuity plan (Section 403(b) plan), or deferred compensation plan of a state or local government (Section 457 plan), ornTreat himself or herself as the beneficiary rather than treating the IRA as his or her own.nIn addition, if a person inherits a traditional IRA from a person who had a basis in the IRA because of nondeductible contributions, that basis remains with the IRA. (Publication 590-B, page 6)nnFinally, if an IRA owner is under age 59-1/2, the taxpayer must pay a 10% additional tax on the distribution of any assets (money or other property) from his or her traditional IRA. Distributions before you are age 59-1/2 are called early distributions. (Publication 590-B, page 25)nnIn this situation, there are, however, exceptions. In this case, a person may not have to pay the 10% additional tax if the person is in 1 of the 8 situations that are listed in Publication 590-B, page 25. One of the exceptions is the beneficiary of a deceased IRA owner.nnHence, the correct response in this problem is that Edwin\'s $20,000 basis in the IRA will carry over to Donna, his spouse.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(385,12,'The following items are reported on Mr. and Mrs. Spice\'s 2024 joint return:nnNet profit on Mrs. Spice\'s Schedule C of $40,000nMr. Spice paid court-ordered alimony from divorce finalized after December 31, 2018 of $5,000nSelf-employment tax of $8,040 (of which deductible portion is $4,020) on Mrs. Spice\'s Schedule C profitnCompute their adjusted gross income for 2024.','[\"$35,980\",\"$30,980\",\"$26,960\",\"$40,000\"]',0,'There are several pieces of this problem that need to be addressed to determine AGI. First, if a taxpayer is self-employed (a sole proprietor or a partner), a deduction is allowed for the deductible portion of the taxpayer\'s self-employment taxes in 2024. (See Publication 17, Table 11-1, page 100.)nnSecond, for divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, a taxpayer may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse. (See Publication 504, page 17)nnAs a result of the above rules, Mr. and Mrs. Spice have an AGI amount of $35,980, which is the net profit from Mrs. Spice\'s Schedule C (i.e., $40,000) less Mrs. Spice\'s self-employment tax (i.e., $4,020).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(386,12,'Joan received a scholarship for purposes of attending the University of California at Los Angeles. Joan is not a degree candidate. The scholarship consisted of $6,000 for tuition, $1,500 for fees, $500 for books, $800 for required equipment, and $6,000 for room and board. Which of the following amounts should Joan include in her taxable income?','[\"$6,000\",\"$14,800\",\"$0\",\"$6,800\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 77, states, in part, that a candidate for a degree can exclude amounts received as a qualified scholarship or fellowship. A qualified scholarship or fellowship is any amount received by a taxpayer that is for:nntuition and fees to enroll at or attend an educational institution ornfees, books, supplies, and equipment required for courses at the educational institution.nAmounts used for room and board do not qualify for the exclusion.nnSince Joan is not a degree candidate, she would report the entire scholarship amount of $14,800 as taxable income.nnFor additional information on qualified scholarships and fellowship grants, see Publication 970, Tax Benefits for Education.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(387,12,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a health savings account (HSA)?','[\"An eligible individual may make a deductible contribution to an HSA.\",\"An employer on behalf of an eligible individual may contribute what is not included in the individual\'s gross income to an HSA.\",\"A family member may contribute on behalf of an eligible individual to an HSA.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 969, page 3, provides that a health savings account (HSA) may receive contributions from an eligible individual or any other person, including an employer or a family member, on behalf of an eligible individual.nnContributions, other than employer contributions, are deductible on the eligible individual\'s return whether or not the individual itemizes deductions. Employer contributions are not included in income.nnDistributions from an HSA that are used to pay qualified medical expenses are not taxed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(388,12,'When figuring compensation for purposes of determining the amount of an allowable contribution to a traditional IRA, which of the following is an incorrect statement?','[\"Pension or annuity income is not considered as compensation for an IRA plan.\",\"Earnings and profits from property, such as rental income, are considered compensation.\",\"Interest and dividend income are not considered as compensation for an IRA plan.\",\"Generally, any amount you exclude from income is not considered as compensation for an IRA plan.\"]',1,'Compensation, for the purposes of determining the amount of allowable contributions to an individual retirement account, includes wages, salaries, commissions, self-employment income, and alimony and separate maintenance payments.nnCompensation does not include any of the following items:nnEarnings and profits from property, such as rental income, interest income, and dividend incomenPension or annuity incomenDeferred compensation received (compensation payments postponed from a past year)nIncome from a partnership for which you do not provide services that are a material income-producing factornGenerally, any amounts you exclude from income, such as foreign earned income and housing costs (For example, combat pay is nontaxable and thus excluded; however, it is considered compensation for purposes of determining the amount of allowable contributions to an individual retirement account.)nTherefore, earnings and profits from property, such as rental income, are not considered compensation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(389,12,'John is a self-employed carpenter. He reported a profit of $40,000 on his Schedule C. He had other taxable income of $10,000. He paid $4,000 for health insurance. He contributed $5,000 to a Keogh plan. The deductible portion of his self-employment tax was $2,826. He also made a $4,000 contribution to his Roth IRA. What is the amount John can deduct in arriving at AGI?','[\"$19,652\",\"$11,826\",\"$14,652\",\"$15,826\"]',1,'There are several pieces of this problem that need to be addressed to determine the deductible amount in arriving at AGI. First, a self-employed person is able to deduct, as an adjustment to income, up to 100% of the amount paid for medical and qualified long-term care insurance on behalf of the person, person\'s spouse, and dependents. The limitation here is that the insurance plan must be established under the individual\'s trade or business, and the person cannot take this deduction to the extent that the amount of the deduction is more than the taxpayer\'s earned income from that trade or business. (See Form 1040 and 1040-SR Instructions, line 16 on pages 31–32.)nnSecond, if a taxpayer is self-employed (a sole proprietor or a partner), a deduction is allowed up to 50% (not 75%) of the taxpayer\'s self-employment taxes. (See Publication 17, Table 11-1, page 100, and the Form 1040 and 1040-SR Instructions for Schedule 1, line 14 on page 88.)nnThird, qualified plans set up by self-employed individuals are sometimes called Keogh or HR 10 plans. Contributions to Keogh plans are deductible for AGI.nnFinally, contributions to Roth IRAs are not deductible. (Publication 17, page 89)nnAs a result of the above rules, John can deduct $11,826 in arriving at AGI, which is the sum of his health insurance of $4,000, Keogh contribution of $5,000, and the deductible portion of his self-employment taxes ($2,826).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(390,12,'After many years as a bachelor, Buddy, age 50, married Penny, age 63. Penny\'s only income was $10,800 of Social Security. They filed a joint return for tax year 2024 with a modified adjusted gross income of $147,000. Buddy is covered by a retirement plan at work where he receives compensation of $135,000. He wishes to contribute to an IRA for himself and Penny. Which of the following will provide them the greatest allowable tax benefit?','[\"He may contribute $7,000 to each IRA, but only take a deduction for the $7,000 to his IRA.\",\"He may contribute $7,000 to each IRA, but take no deduction for either IRA.\",\"He may contribute $7,000 to each IRA, and take a deduction of $7,000 for each IRA.\",\"He may contribute $7,000 to each IRA, but only take a deduction for the $7,000 to Penny\'s IRA.\"]',3,'Deductible contributions to a traditional IRA are reduced or eliminated depending on the taxpayer\'s filing status, participation in a qualified plan, and modified AGI (MAGI) amounts. Publication 590-A, pages 13 and 14, provides the general rules for taxpayers with a married filing joint status. Traditional IRA deductible contribution limits are as follows for a wage earner that is covered by an employer\'s qualified plan:nnIf MAGI is $123,000 or less, a full deduction is permitted.nIf MAGI is between $123,000 and $143,000, a partial deduction is permitted.nIf MAGI is $143,000 or more, no deduction is permitted.nTraditional IRA deductible contribution limits are as follows for the spouse that is not covered by an employer\'s qualified plan:nnIf MAGI is $230,000 or less, a full deduction is permitted.nIf MAGI is between $230,000 and $240,000, a partial deduction is permitted. nIf MAGI is $240,000 or more, no deduction is permitted.nCoverage under Social Security or railroad retirement is not coverage under an employer retirement plan. In light of the couple\'s MAGI amount and Buddy\'s coverage by an employer-sponsored plan, the best situation is for Buddy to make a $7,000 contribution to both IRAs, but only take a deduction for Penny\'s contribution.nnNote: Of course, since both spouses are 50 or older, they could contribute up to $8,000 each instead of only $7,000 (Publication 590-A, page 8).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(391,12,'Leslie teaches in the local high school and Roger teaches in the local community college. During 2024, Leslie spent $425 on supplies that were used in her classes and Roger spent $150 on supplies that were used in his classes. What are the maximum educator expenses that the couple can claim on their tax return if the couple files jointly in 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$300 for Leslie\",\"$150 for Roger\",\"$450, which is $300 for Leslie and $150 for Roger\"]',1,'Form 1040 Instructions, pages 87 and 88, states, in part, that an eligible educator can deduct up to $300 of qualified expenses paid in the year. If the taxpayer and their spouse are filing jointly and both were eligible educators, the maximum deduction is $600. However, neither spouse can deduct more than $300 of his or her qualified expenses. An eligible educator is a kindergarten through grade 12 teacher, instructor, counselor, principal, or aide who worked in a school for at least 900 hours during a school year.nnIn this case, Leslie is a qualified educator; Roger is not. Thus, the couple would be able to deduct up to $300. That is, Leslie would be able to deduct up to $300 of her $425 expenses and Roger would not be able to deduct any of his expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(392,12,'Consider the following expenditures and determine the total amount that would be deducted as Schedule 1 adjustments in arriving at adjusted gross income (assuming no income limitations) on Form 1040 or 1040-SR, U.S. Individual Income Tax Return:nn$1,000 interest paid on student loann$2,000 paid to a SIMPLE retirement plann$100 jury duty pay given to the employern$500 expenses from the nonbusiness rental of personal property','[\"$3,600\",\"$2,600\",\"$3,100\",\"$1,100\"]',0,'There are a number of adjustments to gross income in determining the AGI amount. This particular problem deals with four such adjustments.nnFirst, there is a special deduction allowed for paying interest on a student loan (also known as an education loan). This deduction can reduce the amount of the taxpayer\'s income subject to tax by up to $2,500 in 2024. To claim this deduction, the allowable amount is entered on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR), line 20. (Publication 970, pages 34 and 35)nnFor more information, see Table 4-2 (Publication 970, page 35), which summarizes the features of the student loan interest deduction.nnSecond, sole proprietors are eligible to deduct contributions to SIMPLE retirement plans for themselves on line 15 of Schedule 1, (Form 1040, U.S. Individual Income Tax Return) (see page 11 of Publication 560).nnThird, a taxpayer reports expenses from nonbusiness rental of personal property on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 8, and enters the amount and “PPR” (personal property rental) on the dotted line next to line 8. (1040 Instructions, lines 8 and 22 on pages 86 and 93)nnFinally, jury duty pay received by a taxpayer must be included in the taxpayer\'s income on line 8 of Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR. If, however, the taxpayer must give the pay to his or her employer because the employee\'s employer continues to pay the person\'s salary while serving on the jury, the taxpayer can deduct the amount turned over to the employer as an adjustment to income. Specifically, the amount repaid to the employer is listed on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 22, and the taxpayer writes “Jury Pay” and the amount on the dotted line next to line 22 (see page 76 of Publication 17 and Form 1040 or 1040-SR Instructions, page 93).nnAs a result, all four items are adjustments to income (also referred to as adjustments for AGI).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(393,12,'Bernie is a self-employed accountant in 2024. He reported net income of $50,000 on his Schedule C for 2024. During the year, Bernie paid the following: $5,200 child support, $5,000 in alimony resulting from a divorce finalized in 2023, $6,000 in medical insurance premiums, deductible portion of self-employment taxes of $3,533, and $2,000 to his IRA plan. What amounts are deductible in arriving at adjusted gross income for 2024?','[\"$25,266\",\"$21,733\",\"$11,533\",\"$16,533\"]',2,'There are several pieces of this problem that need to be addressed to determine the deductible amount in arriving at AGI. First, a self-employed person is able to deduct, as an adjustment to income, up to 100% of the amount paid for medical and qualified long-term care insurance on behalf of the person and the person\'s spouse, dependents, and children who were under age 27 at the end of 2024. The limitation here is that the insurance plan must be established under the individual\'s trade or business, and the person cannot take this deduction to the extent that the amount of the deduction is more than the taxpayer\'s earned income from that trade or business. (See Publication 502, page 21.)nnSecond, if a taxpayer is self-employed (a sole proprietor or a partner), a deduction is allowed for 50% of the taxpayer\'s self-employment taxes in 2024. (See Publication 17, Table 11-1, page 100.)nnThird, because Bernie is self-employed and therefore is not covered under an employer\'s pension plan, he is able to take a deduction for an IRA contribution. (See Table 9-2 in Publication 17, page 81.)nnFinally, for divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, a taxpayer may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse. (Publication 504, page 17)nnAs a result of the above rules, Bernie can deduct $11,533 in arriving at AGI, which is the sum of his medical insurance of $6,000, IRA contribution of $2,000, and the deductible portion of his self-employment taxes of $3,533.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(394,12,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning contributions to a Roth IRA (individual retirement account) in 2024?','[\"Roth IRA contributions are deductible as adjustments to AGI.\",\"The maximum Roth IRA contribution is $7,000 if you are not yet 50.\",\"Roth IRA contributions may be deducted if they fall below certain income limits.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'A taxpayer is not permitted to claim a deduction for any contributions that are made to a Roth IRA. For 2024, the maximum contribution to a Roth IRA for a taxpayer under age 50 (did not celebrate his or her 50th birthday in 2024) is $7,000 or their taxable compensation ($8,000 if 50 or older).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(395,12,'Jim files his tax return as married filing separately. He has not lived with his wife for 2 years. In tax year 2024, by court order, he paid her $500 per month as separate maintenance and $200 per month as child support. What amount can Jim deduct as alimony expense in 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$2,400\",\"$6,000\",\"$8,400\"]',0,'For divorce or separation agreements executed before December 31, 2018, IRC Section 71 permits, alimony and separate maintenance payments are included as income to the recipient, and therefore under IRC Section 215 such payments are deductible by the payer if certain requirements are met. The requirements as given on pages 14–15 of Publication 504 for permitting a deduction for alimony paid are:nnthe payments are required by a divorce or separation instrument,nthe payer and recipient spouse do not file a joint return with each other, npayments are in cash, nsuch payments are not designated as “not alimony,” nspouses are not members of the same household, nno commitment to continue payments after death of the recipient spouse, and npayment is not treated as child support.nBut, for divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, a taxpayer may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse.nnTherefore, given that the court ordered the separate maintenance payments to be made beginning in 2024, he is not entitled to deduct the $6,000 in alimony paid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(396,12,'Scott and Marie (spouses) are equal partners in a law firm. They had gross receipts of $120,000, less expenses of $40,000, resulting in net income of $80,000 for the law firm. Marie received an inheritance of $20,000. In addition, they had municipal bond interest of $3,000 and savings account interest of $2,000. What is their adjusted gross income on a married filing joint return?','[\"$105,000\",\"$142,000\",\"$ 82,000\",\"$102,000\"]',2,'A taxpayer must include for federal income tax purposes all income received from money, property, and services, unless specifically excluded by the code. This question deals with several different taxable and nontaxable items. (Publication 17, page 8)nnTo begin with, a person is self-employed if the person carries on a trade or business as a sole proprietorship, is an independent contractor, is a member of a partnership, or is in business in any other way. In addition, a self-employed person includes in gross income the net profit or loss resulting from the business (line 7 of Schedule C (Form 1040)), which in this case is the partner\'s net income. (Publication 17, page 8)nnConversely, property that is received as a gift, bequest, or inheritance is not included in taxable income (Publication 17, page 76). Finally, all interest received or accrued is fully taxable except interest on bonds used to finance government operations issued by the state or other municipalities (Publication 17, page 60).nnTherefore, Scott and Marie\'s adjusted gross income would be $82,000, computed as follows:nn  Net Income from Partnership          $80,000n  Interest Income on Savings Account     2,000n  Adjusted Gross Income (AGI)          $82,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(397,12,'Celeste, who is single, worked recently for a telephone company in France, and earned $1,500 for which she claimed the foreign earned income exclusion. In addition to that, she earned $1,200 as an employee of an answering service while she was in the U.S. She also received alimony of $400 for the year from her divorce in 2019. What is her maximum amount of allowable contribution to a traditional IRA for tax year 2024?','[\"$1,600\",\"$2,000\",\"$1,200\",\"$1,900\"]',2,'The general rule for 2024 as given in Publication 590-A, page 9, is that the maximum annual contribution to a person\'s traditional IRA is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if you are 50 or older) or the person\'s taxable compensation for the year if neither the taxpayer nor their spouse (if applicable) were covered by an employer retirement plan.nnRemember, for divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, you may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse.nnCompensation does not include items such as earnings and profits from property, such as rental income, interest income, dividend income, pension or annuity income, deferred compensation received (compensation payments postponed from a past year), income from a partnership for which the taxpayer did not provide services that are a material income-producing factor, or any amounts excluded from income (other than combat pay), such as foreign earned income and housing costs. (See Publication 590-A, page 7.)nnThe maximum contribution that Celeste can make into her traditional IRA is $1,200, which is her earned income of $1,200. The $1,500 of foreign income that has been excluded does not count toward compensation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(398,12,'Marco and Leigh Ann Green (spouses) moved from New Jersey to Florida on May 1, 2024, at Marco\'s request. Leigh Ann immediately found a job as a part-time substitute teacher, but only worked 23 weeks during the year. Marco, a self-employed solar heating unit salesman, could not continue in the same line of work after the move. In Florida, he held one full-time job for 10 weeks, then another full-time job for 16 more weeks during 2024. Marco expects that he will start a new full-time job as an employee of a landscaping company in January 2025. Can Marco and Leigh Ann claim a deduction for moving expenses on their 2024 jointly filed return?','[\"They\\u00a0cannot, since Marco did not meet the 39-week test in 2024\",\"They can, since Leigh Ann worked 23 weeks and Marco worked 16 weeks for a total of 39 weeks\",\"They can, since Marco expects to meet the 39-week test in 2025\",\"They\\u00a0cannot, since the deduction is not available in 2024\"]',3,'Publication 3 provides that for tax years beginning after 2017, the deduction for moving expenses is suspended unless the taxpayer is a member of the Armed Forces who moves pursuant to a military order and incident to a permanent change of station.nnThus, Marco and Leigh Ann cannot claim a deduction for moving regardless of their employment status after the move.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(399,12,'During 2024, John (age 52) was self-employed with a net income of $50,000. Which of the following can he deduct as an adjustment to income?','[\"Up to $8,000 contribution to his traditional IRA\",\"Up to 75% of his self-employment taxes\",\"Up to 75% of his self-employed health insurance premiums\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'For 2024, a self-employed taxpayer with a net income of $50,000 can make adjustments to income in the amount of one-half (i.e., 50%) of self-employment tax (Publication 17, page 100, Table 11-1): all (i.e., 100% and not just 75%) of self-employed medical and long-term care insurance (Publication 502, page 21) as long as the taxpayer is not eligible to participate in a health plan subsidized by his or her employer; and $8,000 as an IRA deduction (not covered by a qualified plan and over age 50) (Publication 17, pages 79–80).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(400,12,'Peter and Jill are married and file a joint return. In 2024, Jill was a media relations manager for a large firm and earned $232,500; Peter owns a graphic design business that showed a net profit of $500. In 2024, Jill was covered by an employer\'s plan; Peter was not. Their modified annual gross income was $235,000. What is the maximum deductible amount that Peter can contribute to a traditional IRA?','[\"$0\",\"$500\",\"$3,500\",\"$7,000\"]',2,'The general rule as given in Publication 590-A, page 9, is that the maximum annual contribution to a person\'s traditional IRA is the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if you are 50 or older) or the person\'s taxable compensation for the year.nnIf, however, a taxpayer is not covered by an employer retirement plan, but the taxpayer\'s spouse is, and the taxpayer did not receive any Social Security benefits, his or her IRA deduction may be reduced or eliminated entirely depending on the taxpayer\'s filing status and modified AGI (Publication 590-A, pages 13 through 15). Thus, a taxpayer that has a filing status of married joint is able to claim:nna full deduction if the couple\'s modified AGI is $230,000 or less,na partial deduction if the couple\'s modified AGI is between $230,000 and $240,000, or nno deduction if the couple\'s modified AGI is $240,000 or more. (Publication 590-A, page 13)nBecause Peter and Jill file as married joint, Jill is covered by a qualified plan, and their modified AGI is $235,000 (middle of the partial area), Peter (not covered by a plan) is able to contribute up to one-half of the annual contribution for 2024. That is, he may contribute up to $3,500 (50% of $7,000).nnNote: As an aside, if Peter was 50 or older, he could contribute $4,000 (50% of $8,000). However, since no age is given, you must assume that he is under 50.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(401,12,'Which of the following statements is correct for purposes of figuring and reporting self-employment tax?','[\"If a taxpayer has more than one business, the taxpayer must combine the net profits of all businesses and separately combine the net losses of all the other businesses.\",\"If a taxpayer has more than one business, the taxpayer must combine the net profits and losses of all businesses.\",\"If a taxpayer has more than one business, the taxpayer must treat each business independently.\",\"If a taxpayer has more than one business, the taxpayer must follow state tax law to determine if the net profits and losses are treated separately or combined.\"]',1,'Publication 334, page 44, provides that if a taxpayer has earnings subject to self-employment (SE) tax from more than one trade, business, or profession, the taxpayer must combine the net profit (or loss) from each to determine total earnings subject to SE tax. A loss from one business reduces the taxpayer\'s profit from another business.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(402,12,'Derek is a single, self-employed carpenter and is also an employee of Krispy, Inc. His self-employment net income is $55,000, and he received a W-2 for salaries and wages of $45,000. He is covered by his employer\'s pension plan but they do not offer health insurance to employees. Which of the following statements is correct for 2024\'s Form 1040?','[\"Derek is eligible to take a deduction for his IRA contribution.\",\"Derek is eligible to take a deduction of up to 50% of his self-employment taxes.\",\"Derek is eligible to take a deduction of up to 100% of his health insurance premiums.\",\"Derek is eligible to take a deduction of up to 50% of his self-employment taxes and up to 100% of his health insurance premiums.\"]',3,'First, if a taxpayer is covered by an employer retirement plan, the taxpayer\'s deduction for an individual retirement account (IRA) may be limited or completely phased out, depending on the taxpayer\'s filing status and income. The amount of the deduction begins to phase out when income rises above a certain amount and completely phases out when income reaches a higher amount. These “amounts” are contingent on the filing status of the taxpayer as outlined in Table 9-1 below (Publication 17, page 81).nnIF your filing           AND your modifiednstatus is...                 AGI is...           THEN you can take...nsingle                   $77,000 or less         a full deduction.n                                                                     nor                       more than $77,000       a partial deduction.n                         but less than $87,000n                                                                     nhead of household        $87,000 or more         no deduction.      n                                                                     nmarried filing jointly   $123,000 or less        a full deduction.n                                                                     nor                       more than $123,000      a partial deduction.n                         but less than $143,000                      n                                                                     nqualifying surviving     $143,000 or more        no deduction.n    spouse                                                           nmarried filing           less than $10,000       a partial deduction.nseparately (1)                                                       n                         $10,000 or more         no deduction.n1 If you did not live with your spouse at any time during the year, your filing status is considered \"single\" for this purpose (therefore, your IRA deduction is determined under the \"Single\" column).nnPlease note that even though Derek is covered under his employer\'s plan, he is still eligible to set up a self-employed pension (SEP) based on his self-employed earnings. Making a contribution to a SEP would be deducted as an adjustment to income. However, this is not one of the answer options above.nnSecond, self-employed taxpayers may deduct up to 50% of the taxpayer\'s self-employment taxes (Publication 17, Table 11-1, page 100).nnFinally, self-employed taxpayers may deduct from gross income 100% of amounts paid during the year for health insurance for themselves, spouses, and dependents (Publication 502, pages 21–22) and the taxpayer\'s children who were under age 27 at the end of 2024.nnAs a result, Derek, who is single and covered under his employer\'s pension plan, is unable to take a deduction for an IRA, because his modified AGI is more than $87,000. However, Derek, who is self-employed, is eligible to deduct 50% of his self-employment taxes in 2024, and he is able to deduct 100% of his health insurance premiums in 2024 since he is not covered by an employer plan.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(403,12,'Which of the following is treated as compensation for purposes of determining an allowed IRA contribution?','[\"Income passed through to a limited partner\",\"Foreign earned income that is excluded from income\",\"Pension income\",\"None of the answer choices are treated as compensation for determining an allowed IRA contribution.\"]',3,'Publication 590-A, page 7, provides some situations where income does not count as compensation for IRA contribution purposes. Compensation does not include any of the following:nnEarnings and profits from property, such as rental income, interest income, and dividend incomenPension or annuity incomenDeferred compensation received (compensation payments postponed from a past year)nIncome from a partnership for which the taxpayer does not provide services that are a material income-producing factornAny amounts the taxpayer excludes from income, such as foreign earned income and housing costsnAll of the answer choices are items that would not qualify as compensation for IRA purposes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(404,12,'George, single and age 40, is covered by a pension plan at work. For 2024, George could have contributed and deducted $3,000 to his individual retirement account, but could only afford to contribute $1,000, which he did on April 14, 2024. After April 15, 2024, George contributed $4,000. Since his modified AGI for 2024 was in the reduced IRA contribution range, George computed that his reduced IRA deduction for 2024 was $600. Which of the following is not an option available for George?','[\"He can deduct $2,600 in 2024 since he had a carryover from the immediately preceding tax year.\",\"He can withdraw the nondeductible $3,400 contribution by April 15, 2025.\",\"He can leave the entire contribution in the IRA and elect to treat the entire $4,000 as a nondeductible contribution.\",\"He can leave the entire contribution in the IRA as a $600 deductible contribution and a $3,400 nondeductible contribution.\"]',0,'If contributions to a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA for a year were less than the maximum limit, the taxpayer cannot contribute more after the due date of his or her tax return for that year to make up the difference. Therefore, it is incorrect to state that George can deduct $2,600 in 2024 because of a carryover from the immediately preceding tax year (Publication 590-A, page 9).nnAlthough a taxpayer\'s deduction for IRA contributions may be reduced or eliminated, contributions can be made to the IRA up to the general limit as nondeductible contributions. (Publication 590-A, page 15)nnIn addition, a taxpayer will not have to pay the 6% tax if the taxpayer withdraws the excess contribution amount and any income earned on it by the date the tax return for that year is due, including extensions. (Publication 590-A, page 35)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(405,12,'Maude has a small business that has a profit of $15,000. Her husband, Harold, has a farm that has a loss of $7,000. They are married. Which of the following is correct regarding their self-employment tax computation?','[\"If they file separately, Harold may not elect to use the optional method.\",\"Maude must pay self-employment tax on $15,000.\",\"On a joint return, the self-employment tax may be computed based on $8,000 of income for Maude only.\",\"If they file separately, they may elect to split the net profit for self-employment tax purposes, each paying based on $4,000.\"]',1,'Publication 334, pages 40-41, provides the following information concerning self-employment tax and filing a joint return. If a taxpayer files a joint return, the taxpayer cannot file a joint Schedule SE. This is true whether one spouse or both spouses have earnings subject to SE tax.nnIn addition, a taxpayer\'s spouse is not considered self-employed just because the taxpayer is self-employed. If both of the spouses have earnings subject to SE tax, then each spouse must complete a separate Schedule SE.nnIn this case, Maude must pay self-employment tax on the $15,000 of profit that she made in her business.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(406,12,'Ricky, age 35, and Lucy, age 51, are married and file a joint return. Ricky is covered by an employer plan. In 2024, Ricky had compensation of $100,000 and Lucy had compensation of $12,000. Their modified AGI was $250,000. What is the amount of the deductible contribution that can be made for Lucy to her traditional IRA for 2024?','[\"$7,500\",\"$3,550\",\"$7,000\",\"$0\"]',3,'Deductible contributions to a traditional IRA are reduced, or eliminated, under certain conditions such as the taxpayer\'s filing status, participation in a qualified plan, and modified AGI (MAGI) amounts. In the case of a taxpayer with a married filing joint status (see Publication 590-A, page 13), the deductible contribution limits to a traditional IRA are as follows for a wage earner that is covered by an employer\'s qualified plan:nnIf MAGI is $123,000 or less, a full deduction is permitted.nIf MAGI is between $123,000 and $143,000, a partial deduction is permitted. nIf MAGI is $143,000 or more, no deduction is permitted.nTraditional IRA deductible contribution limits are as follows for the spouse that is not covered by an employer\'s qualified plan: nnIf MAGI is $230,000 or less, a full deduction is permitted.nIf MAGI is between $230,000 and $240,000, a partial deduction is permitted.nIf MAGI is $240,000 or more, no deduction is permitted.nIn light of the couple\'s MAGI amount, no deductible contribution can be made for Lucy or for Ricky to their traditional IRA for 2024. The couple could make a nondeductible contribution since there is no AGI limit on these contributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(407,12,'Dave, single and age 40, is covered by a pension plan at work. For 2023, Dave could have contributed and deducted $4,000, but could only afford to contribute $2,000, which he did on April 14, 2024. After April 15, 2024, Dave contributed $5,000 for tax year 2024. Since his modified AGI for 2024 was over $80,000, Dave computed that his reduced IRA deduction for 2024 was $600. Which of the following is not an option available for Dave?','[\"He can deduct $2,600 in 2024 since he had a carryover from the immediately preceding tax year and elect to treat the $2,000 as a nondeductible contribution.\",\"He can withdraw the nondeductible $4,400 contribution by April 15, 2025.\",\"He can leave the entire contribution in the IRA and elect to treat the entire $5,000 as a nondeductible contribution.\",\"He can leave the entire contribution in the IRA as a $600 deductible contribution and a $4,400 nondeductible contribution.\"]',0,'For 2024, the most that a taxpayer can contribute to his or her traditional IRA is generally the smaller of $7,000 ($8,000 if age 50 or older) or taxable compensation for the year.nnIf contributions to a taxpayer\'s traditional IRA for a year were less than the limit, the taxpayer cannot contribute more after the due date of his or her tax return for that year to make up the difference.nnTherefore, it is incorrect to state that Dave can deduct $2,600 in 2024 because of a carryover from the immediately preceding tax year and elect to treat the $2,000 as a nondeductible contribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(408,12,'Which of the following contributions is the largest possible permitted amount by an eligible unmarried taxpayer, 50 years of age or older, in 2024?','[\"A $8,000 contribution to a traditional IRA and a $8,000 contribution to a Roth IRA\",\"A $7,000 contribution to a traditional IRA and a $7,000 contribution to a Roth IRA\",\"A $4,000 contribution to a traditional IRA and a $4,000 contribution to a Roth IRA\",\"A $3,000 contribution to a traditional IRA and a $3,000 contribution to a Roth IRA\"]',2,'Publication 590-A, pages 5 (IRA) and 42 (Roth IRA), provides, in part, general information concerning contributions and deduction limits to traditional IRAs and Roth IRAs. In general:nnunless a taxpayer reaches age 50 before 2025, the most that can be contributed to the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA or Roth IRA for 2024 is the smaller of $7,000 or the taxpayer\'s taxable compensation for the year, ornif a taxpayer reaches age 50 before 2025, the most that can be contributed to the taxpayer\'s traditional IRA or Roth IRA for 2024 is the smaller of $8,000 or the taxpayer\'s taxable compensation for the year.nA taxpayer can make contributions to both traditional and Roth IRAs for the same year. However, the above limit of $7,000 or $8,000 applies to the aggregate contributions that are made on the taxpayer\'s behalf to the Roth IRA and traditional IRA. (Publication 590-A, pages 5 (Table I-2) and 42 (Table 2-1)nnHence, the taxpayer is able to make a $4,000 contribution to the traditional IRA and a $4,000 contribution to the Roth IRA, which is $8,000 in total.nnNote: This question is tricky because the word “and” appears in each response. Thus, the maximum amount is being split between the IRA and the Roth IRA.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(409,12,'You purchased a heating, ventilating, and air conditioning (HVAC) unit for your rental property on December 15. It was delivered on December 28 and was installed and ready for use on January 2. When should the HVAC unit be considered placed in service?','[\"December 15\\n\",\"December 28\\n\",\"December 31\\n\",\"January 2\\n\"]',3,'A taxpayer begins to depreciate property when it is placed in service in the taxpayer\'s trade or business or for the production of income. Likewise, a taxpayer stops depreciating it either when the taxpayer has fully recovered their cost or other basis, or when the taxpayer retires it from service, whichever happens first.nnProperty is considered placed in service in a rental activity when it is ready and available for a specific use in that activity whether in a business activity, an income-producing activity, a tax-exempt activity, or a personal activity. In this problem, the HVAC is not ready for use until January 2 and as such, that is the date that it is placed in service. See Publication 527, page 6, for a review of the topic.nnnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nOn November 22 of last year, a taxpayer purchased a dishwasher for his rental property. The appliance was delivered on December 7, but was not installed and ready for use until January 3 of this year. Because the dishwasher was not ready for use last year, it is not considered placed in service until this year.nnIf the appliance had been ready for use when it was delivered in December of last year, it would have been considered placed in service in December, even if it was not actually used until this year.nn nBe aware that if the property is placed in service in a personal activity, the taxpayer cannot claim depreciation. However, if the taxpayer changes the property\'s use from personal to business or income-producing, then the taxpayer will be able to claim depreciation deduction. Special rules on the basis of the property do apply.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(410,12,'Bill and Gladys sold securities in 2024. The sale resulted in a capital loss of $7,000. They had no other capital transactions. The taxable income on their joint return was $26,000. What amount of the loss can they carry over to 2025?','[\"$7,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$0\",\"$4,000\"]',3,'Publication 550, pages 100–101, discusses the reporting of gains and losses. In particular, if a taxpayer\'s capital losses are more than the capital gains, the taxpayer can claim a capital loss deduction, which is reported on Form 1040 and enclosed in parentheses.nnThe capital loss deduction, however, has an annual limit that is the lesser of:nn$3,000 ($1,500 if you are married and file a separate return) ornthe taxpayer\'s total net loss as shown on line 16 of Schedule D.nIn this case, Bill and Gladys would have a capital loss carry over of $4,000, which is the difference between the total capital loss of $7,000 and the deductible capital loss of $3,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(411,12,'A taxpayer purchases rental property for $160,000. She uses $25,000 cash and obtains a mortgage for $135,000. She pays closing costs of $10,000, which includes $5,000 in points on the mortgage and $5,000 for bank fees and title costs. Her initial basis in the property is:','[\"$35,000.\",\"$170,000.\",\"$165,000.\",\"$160,000.\"]',2,'The basis of property that is purchased by a taxpayer is usually its cost, which includes the amount paid in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services. In addition, some settlement fees or closing costs can be included in the basis of the property, which includes:nnabstract fees (abstract of title fees),ncharges for installing utility services,nlegal fees (including title search and preparation of the sales contract and deed),nrecording fees,nsurveys,ntransfer taxes,nowner\'s title insurance, andnany amounts the seller owes that the taxpayer agrees to pay, such as back taxes or interest, recording or mortgage fees, charges for improvements or repairs, and sales commissions (see Publication 551, pages 2–3).nPoints are one of the settlement fees and closing costs that a taxpayer cannot include in the basis of property (see Publication 551, page 2–3).nnGiven the information above, the taxpayer in this problem has a basis of $165,000 from the purchase of the property. This basis is the sum of the property cost ($160,000 consisting of $25,000 in cash and $135,000 mortgage) and bank and title costs ($5,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(412,12,'Yasmin purchased 50 shares of Tele Company stock on February 6, 2024, at $20 a share. She sold all 50 shares on February 23, 2024, for $15 a share. Later on the same day, she repurchased 40 shares of Tele Company stock at $16 per share. With only the information provided, what is Yasmin\'s net capital loss that she can deduct on her 2024 return?','[\"$250 net capital loss\",\"$640 net capital loss\",\"$750 net capital loss\",\"$50 net capital loss\"]',3,'Publication 550, pages 84–85, discusses the treatment of property transactions that are known as a wash sale. In general, a taxpayer cannot deduct losses from sales or trades of stock or securities in a wash sale.nnA wash sale occurs when a taxpayer sells or trades stock or securities at a loss and within 30 days before or after the sale whereby the taxpayer or spouse:nnbuys substantially identical stock or securities,nacquires substantially identical stock or securities in a fully taxable tradenacquires a contract or option to buy substantially identical stock or securities, ornacquires substantially identical stock or securities for the taxpayer\'s IRA or Roth IRA.nFurthermore, if a taxpayer sells stock and the taxpayer\'s spouse or a corporation controlled by the taxpayer buys substantially identical stock, the taxpayer has a wash sale.nnIn the case of a wash sale, the disallowed loss is added to the cost of the new stock or securities. The adjustment postpones the loss deduction until the disposition of the new stock or securities. Furthermore, the taxpayer\'s holding period for the new stock or securities includes the holding period of the stock or securities sold.nnPublication 550, pages 84–85, provides, in part, that if the number of shares of substantially identical stock or securities repurchased within the 30 days before or after the sale is either more or less than the number of shares sold by the taxpayer, the taxpayer must determine the particular shares to which the wash sale rules apply. This determination is done by matching the shares bought with an equal number of the shares sold. The shares bought must be matched in the same order that the taxpayer bought them, beginning with the first shares bought. The shares or securities so matched are subject to the wash sale rules.nnExample: A taxpayer bought 100 shares of M stock on September 21, 2023. On February 1, 2024, the taxpayer sold those shares at a $1,000 loss. On each of the 4 days from February 5, 2023, to February 8, 2024, the taxpayer bought 50 shares of substantially identical stock. As a result of the wash sale rules, the taxpayer cannot deduct the $1,000 loss. Rather, the taxpayer must add half the disallowed loss ($500) to the basis of the 50 shares bought on February 5. In addition, the taxpayer would add the other half ($500) to the basis of the shares bought on February 6.nnIn this problem, Yasmin has a wash sale since the stock is sold at a $250 loss on February 23, 2024, and then 40 of the 50 shares are repurchased on the same day. Hence, the loss attributable to the 40 shares cannot be taken by the taxpayer; rather, that portion of the loss amount ($200, which is $250 × (40 shares ÷ 50 shares)) is added to the basis of the 40 shares acquired. As for the 10 shares that are not repurchased, that loss of $50 is deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(413,12,'Bob and Naomi (spouses) sold their boat for $75,000 with a gross profit of $25,000. What is Bob and Naomi\'s gross profit percentage for this sale?','[0.25,\"33-1\\/3%\",0.299999999999999988897769753748434595763683319091796875,0.0299999999999999988897769753748434595763683319091796875]',1,'In this problem, Bob and Naomi sell their boat for $75,000 with a gross profit of $25,000. Hence, the gross profit percentage is 33-1/3%, which is the gross profit of $25,000 divided by the selling price of $75,000 (see Worksheet A on page 3 of Publication 537).g',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(414,12,'Tom gave Fred a rental house. Tom had purchased the property in 2013 for $80,000 and has taken $9,000 in depreciation. Tom\'s adjusted basis was $71,000. The fair market value of the rental house on the day of transfer was $90,000. If Fred sells the house at a gain, his basis in the property will be:','[\"$90,000.\",\"$80,000.\",\"$71,000.\",\"$81,000.\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnPublication 551, page 9, states, in part, that if the FMV of the property received from a donor is equal to or greater than donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis is the donor\'s adjusted basis at the time of the gift.nnIn addition, if the taxpayer holds the gift as business property, the taxpayer\'s basis for figuring any depreciation is the same as the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustments to basis while the taxpayer holds the property.nnSince the gift is business property, the taxpayer\'s basis for figuring any depreciation is the same as the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustments to basis while the taxpayer holds the property. Therefore, Fred uses the adjusted basis of the received property (i.e., $71,000) as his adjusted basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(415,12,'Nature Corporation declared and distributed a stock dividend of 1 share for each 10 shares held by stockholders. Donna had 100 shares ($5.50 per share basis) and received 10 additional shares with a fair market value of $6.00 per share. Which of the following is most applicable to the stock dividend?','[\"100 shares at $5.50 per share basis and 10 shares at zero basis per share\",\"110 shares at $5.00 per share basis and $55 taxable income\",\"110 shares at $5.00 per share\",\"100 shares at $5.00 per share basis and 10 shares at $6.00 per share basis\"]',2,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Generally, stock dividends are not taxable and therefore are not reportable (Publication 550, page 27).nnThe basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital (Publication 551, page 30).nnIn this problem, Donna\'s basis in Nature Corporation stock prior to the stock dividend is $550 (100 shares × $5.50 per share). As a result of the stock dividend, the basis is adjusted to $5.00 per share, which is the original basis of $550 divided by the number of shares after the dividend or 110 shares.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(416,12,'Ron sold property for $10,000. The agreement calls for $1,000 as a down payment and a payment of $1,500 in each of the next 6 years to be made from an irrevocable escrow account. The escrow account contains funds provided by the purchaser for the balance of the purchase price plus interest. How is this transaction handled by Ron for tax purposes?','[\"Ron uses the installment method to report the sale.\",\"Ron uses the installment method to report the sale by electing to pay a special interest charge.\",\"Ron would report the entire gain in the year of sale.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 537, page 7, states that in some cases, the sales agreement or a later agreement may call for the buyer to establish an irrevocable escrow account from which the remaining installment payments (including interest) are to be made. These sales cannot be reported on the installment method. The buyer\'s obligation is paid in full when the balance of the purchase price is deposited into the escrow account. When an escrow account is established, the taxpayer no longer relies on the buyer for the rest of the payments, but on the escrow arrangement.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nA taxpayer sells property for $100,000. The sales agreement calls for a down payment of $10,000 and a payment of $15,000 in each of the next 6 years to be made from an irrevocable escrow account containing the balance of the purchase price plus interest. The taxpayer cannot report the sale on the installment method because the full purchase price is considered received in the year of sale. The taxpayer would report the entire gain in the year of sale.nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(417,12,'You incurred the following expenditures in connection with your rental property. Which of them should be capitalized?','[\"New roof\",\"Install new cabinets\",\"Pave driveway\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Page 5 of Publication 527 states, in part, improvements add to the value of the property, prolong its useful life, or adapt it to new uses. (See also page 5 of Publication 527 for examples of increases to basis.) Improvements include:nnputting a recreation room in an unfinished basement,nadding a bathroom or bedroom,nputting up a new fence,nputting in new plumbing or wiring,nputting on a new roof, andnpaving an unpaved driveway.nIf a taxpayer makes improvements to the property, the cost of the improvement must be capitalized and depreciated as if the improvement were separate property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(418,12,'Emma\'s brother purchased 100 shares of Clockwork, Inc. stock for $10 per share on December 30, 2023. Emma inherited the shares of Clockwork stock from her brother on September 15, 2024, when it had a fair market value of $15 per share. On December 20, 2024, she sold the stock for $20 per share. What is the amount and character of her gain?','[\"The gain of $1,000 is short-term capital gain.\",\"The gain of $1,000 is long-term capital gain.\",\"The gain of $500 is long-term capital gain.\",\"The gain of $500 is short-term capital gain.\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. As provided in Publication 551, pages 9–10, the basis of property that is received from a decedent is generally one of the following:nnThe fair market value (FMV) of the property at the date of the individual\'s death,nThe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation,nThe value under the special-use valuation method for real property used in farming or a closely held business if chosen for estate tax purposes, ornThe decedent\'s adjusted basis in land to the extent of the value excluded from the decedent\'s taxable estate as a qualified conservation easement.nIf a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance or transmission taxes.nnOnce the amount of the gain or loss is determined, the taxpayer must determine whether it is long term or short term. If the investment property is held for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. When investment property is inherited, the capital gain or loss on any later disposition of that property is treated as a long-term capital gain or loss. This is true regardless of how long the taxpayer actually held the property. (Publication 550, page 60)nnIn this problem, the gain on the sale for Emma is long-term capital gains and it equals $500, which is the selling price of $2,000 ($20 × 100 shares) less the adjusted basis of $1,500 ($15 × 100 shares).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(419,12,'Jan owns and operates a store in the downtown shopping mall. She reports her income and expenses as a sole proprietor on a Schedule C. In 2024, one of the financial institutions that she borrowed money from in order to start her business canceled her debt. Jan had a balance due of $5,000 when the debt was canceled. Which of the following statements is true?','[\"Jan does not have to report the forgiveness of the debt as income.\",\"Jan must report the $5,000 debt cancellation as other income on Form 1040.\",\"Jan has to report the $5,000 debt cancellation as income on her Schedule C.\",\"Jan has to report the relief of debt of $5,000 as a long-term gain on Schedule D.\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 68, addresses this issue by stating that, in general, if a debt owed by the taxpayer is canceled or forgiven, other than as a gift or bequest, the taxpayer must include the canceled amount in gross income. If the debt, on the other hand, is intended as a gift, then the taxpayer has no income from the canceled debt. A debt includes any indebtedness for which the taxpayer is liable or which attaches to property held by the taxpayer.nnIf the debt is a nonbusiness debt, the canceled amount is reported on Schedule 1 of (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 8.nnIf it is a business debt, report the amount on Schedule C (Form 1040) (or on Schedule F, Profit or Loss From Farming (Form 1040), if the debt is farm debt and you are a farmer).nnHence, Jan should report the $5,000 as income on Schedule C.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(420,12,'When Chris bought his motorcycle, he paid $500 cash and took over payments when the principal balance was $5,000. He added accessories that cost $1,000. Ten years later, a collector paid Chris $8,000 for the motorcycle. Chris applied the entire $8,000 to the $10,000 purchase price of a new cycle. What are the tax consequences to Chris of these transactions?','[\"$0 taxable gains because the cycle was a personal asset\",\"$2,500 taxable gain\",\"$1,500 taxable gain\",\"$1,500 gain is not taxable; basis in new cycle is reduced to $8,500\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property (see Publication 550, pages 43–44).nnIf the amount realized from a sale or trade is more than the adjusted basis of the property the taxpayer transferred, the difference is a gain, andnIf the adjusted basis of the property that the taxpayer transferred is more than the amount realized, the difference is a loss.nThe adjusted basis of property is the original cost or other original basis properly adjusted (increased or decreased) for certain items. See Publication 550 for more information about determining the adjusted basis of property.nnChris has a taxable gain of $1,500, which is the difference between the selling price of $8,000 and the adjusted basis of $6,500. The adjusted basis is the sum of the cash paid ($500), assumed loan ($5,000), and the added accessories ($1,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(421,12,'Ed purchased a house on an acre of land from Ruth on June 30, 2024. Prior to the purchase, Ed had been renting the house from Ruth for $500 per month. Ed paid the following amounts:n1. $100,000 in loan proceeds to Ruthn2. $2,000 in points to the bankn3. $1,000 in real estate taxes Ruth owed to the townn4. $1,000 in past due rent to Ruthn5. $1,000 in closing costs to the bank for legal, recording, title insurance, and survey feesn6. $1,000 in escrowed real estate taxes to the banknWhat is Ed\'s basis in the house and land purchased from Ruth?','[\"$100,000\",\"$102,000\",\"$104,000\",\"$106,000\"]',1,'Publication 551, pages 2–3, provides that the basis of property that is purchased by a taxpayer is usually its cost, which includes the amount paid in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services. In addition, some settlement fees or closing costs can be included in the basis of the property, which includes:nnabstract fees (abstract of title fees),ncharges for installing utility services,nlegal fees (including title search and preparation of the sales contract and deed),nrecording fees,nsurveys,ntransfer taxes,nowner\'s title insurance, andnany amounts the seller owes that the taxpayer agrees to pay, such as back taxes or interest, recording or mortgage fees, charges for improvements or repairs, and sales commissions.nOther settlement costs that are not included in the basis of property include:nncasualty insurance premiums,nrent for occupancy of the property before closing,ncharges for utilities or other services related to occupancy of the property before closing,ncharges connected with getting a loan such as points, mortgage insurance premiums, loan assumption fees, cost of a credit report, and fees for an appraisal required by a lender, andnfees for refinancing a mortgage.nGiven the information above, Ed has a basis of $102,000 from the purchase of the property. This basis is the sum of the property cost ($100,000), closing costs of $1,000 to the bank for legal, recording, title insurance, and survey fees (these are closing costs, which are not deductible) and $1,000 in real estate taxes Ruth owed to the town.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(422,12,'Sam is a used car dealer and sells his cars to the public. He takes a 20% down payment and receives the remaining amount in equal monthly payments for the 3 years following the sale. How does Sam report these sales?','[\"Sam reports these sales using the installment method.\",\"Sam reports these sales using the installment method by electing to pay a special interest charge.\",\"Sam reports these sales as a regular sale of inventory.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'An installment sale is a sale of property where the taxpayer receives at least one payment after the tax year of the sale. The rules for installment sales do not apply if a taxpayer elects not to use the installment method or the transaction is one for which the installment method may not apply (see Publication 537, pages 2–3).nnThe regular sale of inventory, however, is not an installment sale even if the taxpayer receives a payment after the year of sale. Sales of personal property by a person who regularly sells or otherwise disposes of the same type of personal property on the installment plan are not installment sales. This rule also applies to real property held for sale to customers in the ordinary course of a trade or business. The rule, however, does not apply to an installment sale of property used or produced in farming.nnIn the case of dealers of timeshares and residential lots, the dealer may treat certain sales using the installment method by electing to pay a special interest charge.nnSince Sam regularly sells cars (i.e., his inventory) to the public by means of an installment plan, these transactions would not qualify as an installment sale. Hence, he reports these sales as a regular sale of inventory.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(423,12,'Harry sold 100 acres of land that he had owned for over 30 years. His original cost was $100,000. He sold the property for $500,000 and had settlement costs of $50,000. He received a $150,000 down payment with the balance to be paid over 10 years. What is his gross profit percentage?','[0.8000000000000000444089209850062616169452667236328125,0.6999999999999999555910790149937383830547332763671875,0.5,0.59999999999999997779553950749686919152736663818359375]',1,'In the case of an installment sale, a certain percentage of each payment (after subtracting interest) is reported as installment sale income. This percentage is called the gross profit percentage and is figured by dividing the taxpayer\'s gross profit from the sale by the contract price. The gross profit percentage generally remains the same for each payment you receive. (Publication 537, page 4)nnTo figure the adjusted basis and gross profit percentage for an installment sale, the following worksheet (see Publication 537, page 3) is used:nn1. Enter the selling price for the property.                1._____n2. Enter your adjusted basis for the property.    2._____n3. Enter your selling expenses.                   3._____n4. Enter any depreciation recapture.              4._____n5. Add lines 2, 3, and 4. This is your adjustedn   basis for installment sale purposes.                     5._____n6. Subtract line 5 from line 1. If zero or less,n   enter -0-.                                               6._____n   This is your gross profit.n   If the amount entered on line 6 is zero, Stopn   here. You cannot use the installment method.n7. Enter the contract price for the property.               7._____n8. Divide line 6 by line 7. This is your grossn   profit percentage.                                       8._____nIn this problem, Harry sells his property for $500,000 (item 1), and the property has an adjusted basis for installment sale purposes of $150,000, which is the sum of $100,000 (item 2) and selling expenses of $50,000 (item 3). Hence, the gross profit percentage is 70%, which is the gross profit of $350,000 ($500,000 − $100,000 − $50,000) divided by the selling price of $500,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(424,12,'Sandra joins Sam in forming a partnership. Sandra invests $50,000 in cash. Sam will work for $70,000 a year as a guaranteed payment to partner. Of the $70,000 payment, $50,000 will be retained by the partnership. Assuming that the partnership had zero net income and expenses, what is Sam\'s basis in the partnership and what is his taxable income at the end of the year?','[\"Sam\'s basis in the partnership is $50,000 and taxable income is $20,000.\",\"Sam\'s taxable income is $50,000 and his basis in the partnership is $20,000.\",\"Sam\'s taxable income is $70,000 and his basis is $50,000.\",\"Sam\'s basis in the partnership is $70,000 and taxable income of $70,000.\"]',2,'Guaranteed payments are those made by a partnership to a partner for services or for the use of capital without regard to the partnership income. They are treated as if they were paid to a person who is not a partner and are regarded as ordinary income to the partner (see page 7 of Publication 541).nnA capital interest is an interest that would give the holder a share of the proceeds if the partnership\'s assets were sold at fair market value and the proceeds were distributed in a complete liquidation. This determination generally is made at the time of receipt of the partnership interest. When a capital interest in a partnership is transferred to a partner in exchange for his or her services, the partner must generally recognize as compensation the fair market value of the services (see page 9 of Publication 541).nnGenerally, under IRS Code Section 721, either cash or property need to be transferred for nonrecognition of gain or loss in the formation of a partnership. Under IRS Code Section 721-1(b), the nonrecognition provisions attendant to the formation of a partnership do not apply to the transfer of a partnership interest in connection with the performance of services or in satisfaction of an obligation. The transfer of a partnership interest to a person in connection with the performance of services constitutes a transfer of property to which §83 and its regulations apply.nnHowever, given that the partnership retained the $50,000 of $70,000 paid to Sam for his services, that portion of monies received would be equivalent to a cash contribution that does qualify as an exchange for partnership interest under Section 721. As such, Sam\'s basis in the partnership would be the $50,000. Additionally, Sam would have taxable income of $70,000 received as compensation/guaranteed payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(425,12,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to property received as a gift that has a basis greater than its fair market value?','[\"If it is sold for less than the fair market value, the fair market value at the date of the gift becomes the basis for computing the loss.\",\"If it is sold for less than the adjusted basis but more than the fair market value, the adjusted basis becomes the basis for computing the loss.\",\"If it is sold for more than the fair market value but less than the adjusted basis, the fair market value becomes the basis for computing the gain.\",\"None of the statements are correct.\"]',0,'In order to calculate the basis of property received as a gift, the adjusted basis of the donor just before it was given, the fair market value at the time of the gift, and any gift tax paid must be known.nnIf the gift received has an adjusted basis that is greater than the fair market value at the time of the gift, the basis of the gifted property is contingent on how the asset is sold, at a loss or at a gain. The basis, when there is a gain, is the same as the donor\'s basis plus or minus any required basis adjustments. The basis, when a loss occurs, is the fair market value of the property on the date of gift, plus or minus any required basis adjustments.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(426,12,'Joe exchanged a building for another like-kind building. Joe had a basis of $16,000, plus he had made $10,000 in improvements prior to the exchange. He exchanged it for a building worth $36,000. Joe did not recognize any gain from the exchange on his 2024 individual tax return. What is Joe\'s basis in the new property?','[\"$26,000\",\"$36,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$16,000\"]',0,'Publication 544, page 17, provides a discussion on the basis of property received in a like-kind exchange. If the taxpayer acquires property in a like-kind exchange, the basis of that property is the same as the basis of the property transferred by the taxpayer.nnnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nA taxpayer exchanged real estate held for investment with an adjusted basis of $25,000 for other real estate held for investment. The basis of the taxpayer\'s new property is the same as the basis of the old ($25,000).nn nIf, in addition to giving up like-kind property, the taxpayer pays money in a like-kind exchange, the taxpayer still has no recognized gain or loss. The basis of the property received, on the other hand, is the basis of the property given up, increased by the money paid.nnBe aware that an exchange of personal property for real property does not qualify as a like-kind exchange.nnIn this case, Joe\'s basis in the new building is $26,000, which is the basis of the old building given by Joe ($16,000 basis plus $10,000 in improvements).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(427,12,'How is the sale of Section 1244 (small business) stock treated for federal income tax purposes?','[\"Ordinary loss or ordinary income\",\"Ordinary loss or capital gain\",\"Ordinary income or capital loss\",\"Capital gain or capital loss\"]',1,'A taxpayer can deduct as an ordinary loss, rather than as a capital loss, his or her loss on the sale, trade, or worthlessness of Section 1244 stock. The loss is reported on Form 4797, line 10. Any gain on this stock is capital gain and is reported on Form 8949 if the stock is a capital asset in the taxpayer\'s hands (Publication 550, page 78).nnIn addition, if the basis of the taxpayer\'s Section 1244 stock has increased, through contributions to capital or otherwise, the taxpayer must treat this increase as applying to stock that is not Section 1244 stock when the taxpayer figures the ordinary loss on its sale (Publication 550, page 79).nnAs a result, the sale of Section 1244 stock can be deducted as an ordinary loss and as a capital gain if the stock is being held as a capital asset in the taxpayer\'s hands.nnFor more information on losses on Section 1244 (small business) stock, see chapter 4 of Publication 550.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(428,12,'In 2015, John and Kim Jones (spouses) bought their primary residence for $250,000. In 2024, they sold it for $550,000, taking the maximum allowable exclusion. Which of the following statements best reflects their tax situation?','[\"The couple is\\u00a0not\\u00a0able to exclude any of the gain.\",\"The couple is able to exclude up to $250,000.\",\"The couple is able to exclude up to $300,000 and is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to report the sale on a 2024 tax return.\",\"The couple is able to exclude up to $300,000 but is required to report the sale on a 2024 tax return.\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary residence, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true (see Publication 523, page 3):nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home.nBe aware that there are some exceptions in this area, which are covered more thoroughly in Publication 523, pages 3 through 6.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer satisfies the special rule for excluding up to $250,000 ($500,000 for spouses filing a joint return). Furthermore, the gain from the sale is $300,000, which is the amount received from the sale of $550,000 less the property\'s basis of $250,000. Also, the sale of a taxpayer\'s main home is not reported on the tax return unless the taxpayer has a gain and does not qualify to exclude all of it, or the taxpayer has a gain and chooses not to exclude it (see Publication 523, page 6). Thus, the couple excludes the entire gain and, therefore, they do not report the sale of their main home.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(429,12,'Juan purchased two shares of common stocks in 2024 in a company that markets biotech products. Juan paid $90 for one share and paid $110 for the next share. Later that year, the company declared a 2-for-1 common stock split. Juan\'s new basis in the stock shares is:','[\"average of the four shares at $50 a share.\",\"two shares at $90 a share and two shares at $110 a share.\",\"four shares at $200 a share.\",\"two shares at $45 a share and two shares at $55 a share.\"]',3,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Generally, stock dividends are not taxable and therefore are not reportable. (Publication 550, page 30)nnThe basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital. (Publication 550, pages 60–61)nnIn this problem, Mr. Juan\'s basis in the company\'s stock prior to the stock split is $200 ($90 for one share and $110 for the next share). As a result of the 2-for-1 stock split, Mr. Juan has four shares of stock and the basis in the stock is two shares at $45/share and two shares at $55/share.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(430,12,'In 2022, Mary purchased 10 shares of Acorn Corporation common stock for $100 per share. In 2023, Mary purchased an additional 10 shares of Acorn Corporation common stock for $200 per share. At the end of 2024, Acorn Corporation declared a 2-for-1 common stock split. What is Mary\'s total dollar basis in her Acorn Corporation common stock?','[\"$3,000\",\"$4,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$6,000\"]',0,'The basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital. (Publication 551, page 2)nnIn this problem, the basis in the stock prior to the stock dividend is $3,000 (10 shares × $100 per share and 10 shares × $200 per share). As a result of the stock dividend, the per share basis would be adjusted to 20 shares × $50 per share and 20 shares × $100 per share. However, the total dollar basis for Mary would remain the same as before the stock split, which is $3,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(431,12,'SSB Tax Corporation declared and distributed a stock dividend of 1 share for each 4 shares held by each stockholder. Donn had 100 shares and, as a result of the stock dividend, he received 25 additional shares.','[\"The stock dividend is taxable, since the stockholder received stock in the company in lieu of cash.\",\"The stock dividend is taxable for the fair market value of the shares received on the date of issue.\",\"Donn purchased his 100 shares of stock for $5.00 per share. As a result of the stock dividend, he must adjust the basis of the 125 shares to $4.00 a share.\",\"This is nontaxable because it is a return of capital.\"]',2,'The basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital (Publication 551, page 2).nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nA taxpayer bought 100 shares of XYZ stock for $1,000 or $10 a share. At another time, a taxpayer bought an additional 100 shares of XYZ stock for $1,600 or $16 a share. Now assume that XYZ declares a 2-for-1 stock split. The taxpayer now has 200 shares of XYZ stock with a basis of $1,000 or $5 a share and an additional 200 shares of XYZ stock with a basis of $1,600 or $8 a share.nn n nnThis problem is somewhat tricky, but there is only one possible correct response. The basis in the stock prior to the stock dividend is $500 (100 shares × $5 per share) per the information given in the response. As a result of the stock dividend, the basis is adjusted to $4 per share, which is the original basis of $500 divided by the number of shares after the dividend of 125 shares.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(432,12,'A taxpayer purchased a rental property for $100,000. The taxpayer gave $25,000 as a cash down payment and financed $75,000. Closing costs were $4,000 and points were $4,000. What is his basis in the property?','[\"$33,000\",\"$108,000\",\"$104,000\",\"$100,000\"]',2,'A taxpayer\'s basis is the amount of a taxpayer\'s investment in property for tax purposes. The basis of property that is purchased by a taxpayer is usually its cost, which includes the amount paid in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services (Publication 551, pages 2 and 3). In addition, some settlement fees or closing costs can be included in the basis of the property, which includes the following:nnAbstract fees (abstract of title fees)nCharges for installing utility servicesnLegal fees (including title search and preparation of the sales contract and deed)nRecording feesnSurveysnTransfer taxesnOwner\'s title insurancenAny amounts the seller owes that the taxpayer agrees to pay, such as back taxes or interest, recording or mortgage fees, charges for improvements or repairs, and sales commissionsnNot all settlement fees are added to the basis. A list of these exceptions can be found on page 3 of Publication 551. Points, likewise, are not added to the basis.nnGiven the information above, the taxpayer in this problem has a basis of $104,000, which is the sum of the cost of the property ($100,000) and the closing costs ($4,000). The basis does not include the $4,000 for points that were paid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(433,12,'Jane purchased 300 shares of stock 5 years ago for $20 a share. The directors voted for a 3-for-1 stock split. After the split, Jane had 900 shares. What is Jane\'s basis per share after the split?','[\"$60.00\",\"$20.00\",\"$6.67\",\"$5.00\"]',2,'The basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital (Publication 551, page 2).nnIn this problem, the basis in the stock prior to the stock dividend is $6,000 (300 shares × $20 per share). As a result of the stock dividend, the basis is adjusted to $6.67 per share, which is the original basis of $6,000 divided by the number of shares after the dividend; i.e., 900 shares.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(434,12,'During 2024, Frank sold a piece of land with an adjusted basis of $110,000 to Tony for $200,000. Tony paid $50,000 as a down payment in 2024 and agreed to pay $30,000 per year plus interest for the next 5 years beginning in January 2025. Frank incurred selling expenses of $10,000. What is the amount of gain to be included in Frank\'s gross income for 2024?','[\"$18,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$22,500\",\"$32,000\"]',1,'Publication 537, pages 2 and 3, provides that an installment sale is a sale of property where a taxpayer receives at least one payment after the tax year of the sale. If the taxpayer realizes a gain on an installment sale, the taxpayer may be able to report part of the gain when it is received with each payment. This method of reporting gain is called the installment sale method.nnIf the taxpayer prefers, they can elect out of the installment sale method and choose to report all of their gain in the year of sale. On the other hand, a taxpayer cannot use the installment method to report a loss (although it is unknown why a taxpayer would want to defer the write-off). (Publication 537, pages 4 and 5)nnIn the case of an installment sale, a certain percentage of each payment (after subtracting interest) is reported as installment sale income. This percentage is called the gross profit percentage and is figured by dividing the taxpayer\'s gross profit from the sale by the contract price. The gross profit percentage generally remains the same for each payment the taxpayer receives. (Publication 537, page 4)nnTo figure the adjusted basis and gross profit percentage for an installment sale, the following worksheet (see Worksheet A, Publication 537, page 3) is used:nn1. Enter the selling price for the property.                1._____n2. Enter your adjusted basis for the property.     2._____n3. Enter your selling expenses.                    3._____n4. Enter any depreciation recapture.               4._____n5. Add lines 2, 3, and 4. This is your adjustedn   basis for installment sale purposes.                     5._____n6. Subtract line 5 from line 1. If zero or less,n   enter -0-.                                               6._____n   This is your gross profit.n   If the amount entered on line 6 is zero, Stopn   here. You cannot use the installment method.n7. Enter the contract price for the property.               7._____n8. Divide line 6 by line 7. This is your grossn   profit percentage.                                       8._____nIn this problem, Frank sells his property for $200,000 (item 1) and an adjusted basis for installment sale purposes of $120,000, which is the sum of $110,000 (item 2) and selling expenses of $10,000 (item 3). Hence, the gross profit percentage is 40%, which is the gross profit of $80,000 ($200,000 - $120,000) divided by the selling price of $200,000. Thus, Frank would report a gain of $20,000 in 2024, which is 40% of the $50,000 down payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(435,12,'Shannon and Dan Smith (spouses) purchased Section 1244 (small business) stock in 2024. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"If they incurred a loss on Section 1244 stock, they can deduct the loss as a capital loss rather than as an ordinary loss.\",\"If the stock becomes worthless, they can claim an ordinary loss limited to $50,000 individually or $100,000 together on a joint return, per year.\",\"If the loss is $60,000 and Shannon does not have any other losses, Dan can only deduct $50,000 as ordinary loss on the joint return.\",\"If they incurred a gain on Section 1244 stock, they should treat it as ordinary gain.\"]',1,'A taxpayer can deduct as an ordinary loss, rather than as a capital loss, his or her loss on the sale, trade, or worthlessness of Section 1244 stock (also known as a small business investment company). The loss is reported on Form 4797, line 10. Any gain on this stock is capital gain (not ordinary gain) and is reported on Form 8949 if the stock is a capital asset in the taxpayer\'s hands (page 78 of Publication 550).nnIn addition, if the basis of the taxpayer\'s Section 1244 stock has increased, through contributions to capital or otherwise, the taxpayer must treat this increase as applying to stock that is not Section 1244 stock when the taxpayer figures the ordinary loss on its sale (page 78 of Publication 550).nnFor more information on losses on Section 1244 (small business) stock, see chapter 4 of Publication 550.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(436,12,'Dennis and Martha sell their lake house (which they have owned for 10 years and spend each summer in) for $250,000. Their original cost was $175,000, and they had improvements of $25,000. They have never used the house as a business or rental property. They agreed to take $50,000 down and finance the balance. Monthly payments are to begin next year. How much capital gain must they report in the year of sale?','[\"$10,000\",\"$50,000\",\"$15,000\",\"$0\"]',0,'In the case of an installment sale, a certain percentage of each payment (after subtracting interest) is reported as installment sale income. This percentage is called the gross profit percentage and is figured by dividing the taxpayer\'s gross profit from the sale by the contract price. The gross profit percentage generally remains the same for each payment the taxpayer receives. (Publication 537, page 4)nnTo figure the adjusted basis and gross profit percentage for an installment sale, the following worksheet (see Worksheet A, Publication 537, page 3) is used:nn1. Enter the selling price for the property.                1._____n2. Enter your adjusted basis for the property.    2._____n3. Enter your selling expenses.                   3._____n4. Enter any depreciation recapture.              4._____n5. Add lines 2, 3, and 4. This is your adjustedn   basis for installment sale purposes.                     5._____n6. Subtract line 5 from line 1. If zero or less,n   enter -0-.                                               6._____n   This is your gross profit.n   If the amount entered on line 6 is zero, Stopn   here. You cannot use the installment method.n7. Enter the contract price for the property.               7._____n8. Divide line 6 by line 7. This is your grossn   profit percentage.                                       8._____nIn this problem, Dennis and Martha sell their lake house for $250,000 (item 1) and the house has an adjusted basis for installment sale purposes of $200,000 (item 2), which is the cost of $175,000 plus improvements of $25,000. There are no selling expenses for item 3. The gross profit percentage is 20%, which is the gross profit of $50,000 ($250,000 − $200,000) divided by the selling price of $250,000. Therefore, the capital gain from the $50,000 down payment is $10,000, which is 20% of the $50,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(437,12,'Frances and George sold their principal residence for $1 million in 2024. They purchased the home in 2021 for $250,000. They incurred improvement costs of $100,000, real estate commissions of $60,000, and other settlement costs of $10,000. They lived in this home until the date of sale. Frances and George file a joint return and have not previously excluded a gain on another home. What is their maximum taxable gain?','[\"$750,000\",\"$140,000\",\"$80,000\",\"$150,000\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true.nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 3)nBe aware that there are some exceptions in this area, which are covered more thoroughly in Publication 523, pages 3 through 6.nnIn this problem, the taxpayers satisfy the special rule for excluding $500,000 of gain from the sale of a taxpayer\'s main home. Thus, the gain from the sale is $80,000, which is the amount received of $1 million less the property\'s basis of $350,000 ($250,000 + $100,000), less the real estate commissions of $60,000, less the settlement costs of $10,000, less the exclusion amount of $500,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(438,12,'During the tax year, Dan had these expenses for his rental house:n1. Replaced a screen in the storm doorn2. Replaced the heating systemn3. Sowed grass seed in some bare spots on the lawnn4. Built a detached 2-car garagen5. Installed a new dishwashern6. Bought a welcome mat for the front stoopnWhich of these items must be depreciated rather than deducted as an expense on his Schedule E?','[\"1, 3, 4, and 5\",\"2, 4, 5, and 6\",\"2, 4, and 5\",\"3, 4, and 6\"]',2,'When a taxpayer rents property and incurs expenses, those expenses may either be expensed or capitalized and depreciated over a period of time. In determining which items to expense or depreciate, each expense must be categorized as a repair (expense) or improvement (depreciation). Expenses deemed to be repairs are those expenses that keep up the maintenance on the taxpayer\'s property and do not materially add to the value or useful life of his or her property. Repairs include but are not limited to repainting, fixing gutters or floors, fixing leaks, plastering, and replacing broken windows. (Publication 527, page 5)nnOn the other hand, expenses that add value and prolong the life of the property or adapt it to new uses are categorized as improvements and are treated as capital expense. These expenses must be deducted through depreciation, amortization, or depletion. Examples of improvements or capital expenses include additions, lawn and grounds, heating and air conditioning, plumbing, and interior improvements as given in Table 1-1 on page 5 of Publication 527.nnTherefore, the costs of replacing a screen in the storm door, sowing grass seed in some bare spots on the lawn, and buying a welcome mat for the front stoop are costs that should be expensed as repairs. The costs associated with replacing the heating system, building a detached 2-car garage, and installing a new dishwasher should be treated as capital expenses, and depreciated.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(439,12,'Kiran bought stock in the Big Bang Corporation in 2020 for $2,000. In 2023, Kiran received a return of capital distribution of $100 as a partial return on her investment. In 2024, Kiran sold the stock for $3,000. Her basis in the stock is:','[\"$3,000.\",\"$2,100.\",\"$1,900.\",\"$2,000.\"]',2,'The basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees.nnThe basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital. (Publication 550, page 30)nnIn this problem, Kiran\'s basis in Big Bang Corporation is $1,900, which is the purchase price of $2,000 less the return of capital distribution of $100.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(440,12,'When Fred loaned $2,000 to his brother in 2023, his brother signed a note and made monthly payments until he was injured in an accident in March 2024. Fred is still owed $500 and his brother, who is no longer able to work, has declared bankruptcy. Fred had also guaranteed his brother\'s bank loan as a favor to his brother and was required to pay off the $800 loan balance. Fred, a cash method taxpayer, is also owed $500 rent by a former tenant. How much bad debt deduction can Fred take on his 2024 return?','[\"$1,800\",\"$500\",\"$1,000\",\"$1,300\"]',1,'Publication 550, page 83, provides that if someone owes the taxpayer money that cannot be collected, the taxpayer has a bad debt. In such a case, the taxpayer may be able to deduct the amount owed to him or her when the person figures their tax for the year that the debt becomes worthless.nnBad debts that a person receives and did not arise in the course of operating a trade or business by the taxpayer are nonbusiness bad debts and are deductible as short-term capital losses. To be deductible, nonbusiness bad debts must be totally worthless; a partly worthless nonbusiness debt cannot be deducted.nnA debt must be genuine for the taxpayer to deduct a loss. A debt is genuine if it arises from a debtor-creditor relationship based on a valid and enforceable obligation to repay a fixed or determinable sum of money. In this case, it appears that the debt was an enforceable contract since Fred\'s brother signed a note with monthly payments. Hence the $500 remaining balance is treated as a bad debt.nnTo deduct a bad debt, a taxpayer must have a basis in it; that is, the taxpayer must have included the amount in income or loaned the amount out in cash. A cash basis taxpayer generally cannot take a bad debt deduction for unpaid salaries, wages, rents, fees, interest, dividends, and similar items. Since Fred is a cash basis taxpayer, he has not recognized the rent as income yet; hence, there is no bad debt to be recognized.nnIn this case, Fred is able to claim a nonbusiness bad debt of $500 that resulted from his brother\'s failure to pay the borrowed funds after declaring bankruptcy. The loss attributable to the former tenant is not deductible since the rent was not claimed as income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(441,12,'Sandy bought investment property on March 1, 2023, and sold it on March 1, 2024. What is the character of her gain or loss?','[\"Short term\",\"Neither short term nor long term\",\"Long term\",\"Short term or long term\"]',0,'Pursuant to the information given in Publication 550, pages 83 and 84, the holding period for sold or traded investment property determines whether any capital gain or loss is short-term or long-term. If the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. Likewise, if the taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss.nnTo determine how long the taxpayer held the investment property, begin counting on the date after the day the taxpayer acquired the property (trade date, not settlement date, for securities traded on an established market). The day the taxpayer disposes of the property is part of the holding period.nnNote: Although this is the rule for counting days, but a simple rule is to count either the day of purchase or the date of sale but not both.nnIn this problem, Sandy has a short-term gain or loss from the investment transaction because the property was held for 1 year or less.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(442,12,'Mary, a single woman, bought her home in June 2022 for $350,000. She lived in the house with her mother until she sold it in July 2024 for $900,000. What amount of the gain is Mary able to exclude?','[\"$0\",\"$250,000\",\"$500,000\",\"$550,000\"]',1,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary residence, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 3)nBe aware that there are some exceptions in this area, which are covered more thoroughly in Publication 523, pages 3 through 6.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer satisfies the special rule for excluding up to $250,000. Even though her mother lives in the home, Mary cannot exclude an additional $250,000 on behalf of her mother. The additional exclusion amount is permitted only for spouses. Thus, the gain that Mary must report from the sale (before excluding the $250,000) is $550,000, which is the amount received from the sale of $900,000 less the property\'s basis of $350,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(443,12,'Mr. Rabbitt purchased a home for $200,000. He incurred the following additional expenses:nn$200 fire insurance premiumsn$500 mortgage insurance premiumsn$400 recording feesn$250 owner\'s title insurancenCompute his basis in the property.','[\"$201,350\",\"$200,000\",\"$200,650\",\"$201,150\"]',2,'The basis of property that is purchased by a taxpayer is usually its cost, which includes the amount paid in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services. In addition, some settlement fees or closing costs can be included in the basis of the property, which includes:nnabstract fees (abstract of title fees),ncharges for installing utility services,nlegal fees (including title search and preparation of the sales contract and deed),nrecording fees,nsurveys,ntransfer taxes,nowner\'s title insurance, andnany amounts the seller owes that the taxpayer agrees to pay, such as back taxes or interest, recording or mortgage fees, charges for improvements or repairs, and sales commissions.nOther settlement costs that are not included in the basis of property include:nncasualty insurance premiums,nrent for occupancy of the property before closing,ncharges for utilities or other services related to occupancy of the property before closing,ncharges connected with getting a loan such as points, mortgage insurance premiums, loan assumption fees, cost of a credit report, and fees for an appraisal required by a lender, andnfees for refinancing a mortgage.nPoints are one of the settlement fees and closing costs that a taxpayer cannot include in the basis of property (see Publication 551, pages 2–3).nnGiven the information above, the taxpayer in this problem has a basis of $200,650 from the purchase of the property. This basis is the sum of the property cost ($200,000), recording fees ($400), and owner\'s title insurance ($250).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(444,12,'Charles died and left his daughter Sue a commercial rental property. He purchased the property for $150,000 and had taken $45,000 in depreciation. The fair market value (FMV) on his death was $200,000. Six months after his death, the property was re-titled into Sue\'s name by the estate\'s representative. There was no alternative valuation done on the transfer. The FMV on that day was $210,000. Sue\'s basis in the property is:','[\"$210,000.\",\"$200,000.\",\"$150,000.\",\"$125,000.\"]',1,'As provided in Publication 551, page 10, the basis of property that is received from a decedent is generally:nnthe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death ornthe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation.nIn this problem, the alternate valuation date was not elected; the FMV on the date of death (i.e., $200,000) becomes the rental property\'s basis for Sue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(445,12,'Sharon sold two collections during 2024. These were her only sales. Determine the amount and character of her gains/losses on these sales.nCoin collection she began as a child with a basis of $1,000, sold for $5,000nCollection of original short stories she wrote in 2020, sold for $20,000','[\"$20,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$24,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$4,000 long-term capital gain and $20,000 ordinary income\",\"$24,000 ordinary income\"]',2,'Publication 550, pages 73 and 74, defines what is and is not a capital asset. Almost everything a taxpayer owns and uses for personal purposes or investment is a capital asset. There are a few exceptions, including but not limited to property sold in the normal course of business; copyright; a literary, musical, or artistic composition; a letter; a memorandum; or similar property (such as drafts of speeches, recordings, transcripts, manuscripts, drawings, or photographs), which were created by the taxpayer\'s personal efforts, or prepared or produced for the taxpayer (in the case of a letter, memorandum, or similar property).nnIf the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. nnSharon sold two collections in the year. First, Sharon has a gain of $4,000 ($5,000 less $1,000) for the coin collection, which qualifies as a long-term capital gain transaction. Second, she has ordinary income of $20,000 on the sale of her original short stories because this asset is a literary composition and as such is not a capital asset.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(446,12,'Yang and May Ling (spouses) owned a fashionable handbag store in New York, which they report as a sole proprietorship on their individual return. They had gains for the following transactions during the 2024 year:n1. $600,000 from the sale of a rare coin collection May Ling inherited in February 2023n2. $100,000 received in accounts receivable from sales of 500 bags in November 2024n3. $50,000 from sale of stocks held in their personal account that were purchased in 2022n4. $5,000 for the purchase of supplies such as computer paper, invoices, etc. used in the businessnFrom the information provided, what is the total gross sales  amount and characterization of capital transactions that Yang and May Ling should report for the year 2024?','[\"$650,000 as long-term capital gain\",\"$695,000 as ordinary income\",\"$50,000 as long-term capital gain\",\"$95,000 as short-term capital gain\"]',0,'Once the amount of the gain or loss is determined, the taxpayer must determine whether it is long term or short term. If the investment property is held for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. When investment property is inherited, the capital gain or loss on any later disposition of that property is treated as a long-term capital gain or loss. This is true regardless of how long the taxpayer actually held the property. (Publication 551, pages 9–10)nnPublication 550, page 73, provides a list of items that are considered noncapital assets. Among that list are included:nnaccounts or notes receivable acquired in the ordinary course of a trade or business for services rendered or from the sale of property held mainly for sale to customers (or property that will physically become a part of the merchandise that is for sale to customers) andnsupplies of a type a taxpayer regularly uses or consumes in the ordinary course of his or her trade or business.nIn this problem, there are two capital transactions: sale of a rare coin collection ($600,000) and sale of stocks (50,000). The character of the transactions is presumably long term because the inherited item is long term and the stock was held for more than 1 year.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(447,12,'Which of the following is true regarding a nonbusiness bad debt?','[\"It is deductible as a short-term capital loss.\",\"It is\\u00a0not\\u00a0deductible.\",\"It is deductible only if you itemize.\",\"It is deductible as a long-term capital loss.\"]',0,'When a taxpayer lends money that afterwards cannot be collected, the taxpayer could have a bad debt, which may be deductible in the year the loan becomes uncollectible. For tax purposes there are two categories of bad debt: business and nonbusiness. Business bad debt is derived from the operations of the taxpayer\'s trade or business and is deductible as a business loss. All other bad debts are regarded as nonbusiness and are deductible as short-term capital losses, regardless of how old the debt is.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(448,12,'Reba gave Sari a rental property. Reba had purchased the property in 2013 for $60,000 and took $9,000 in depreciation. Reba\'s adjusted basis was $51,000. The fair market value of the rental house on the day of transfer was $72,000. Assuming that no gift tax was paid, what is Sari\'s basis in the property?','[\"$72,000\",\"$60,000\",\"$51,000\",\"$63,000\"]',2,'In general, a taxpayer that receives property as a gift needs to know the property\'s adjusted basis to the donor just before it was received, its FMV at the time it was received, and any gift tax paid on it in order to determine the property\'s basis. However, if the property is held by the taxpayer as business property (i.e., depreciable property), then the basis for figuring any depreciation, depletion, or amortization deduction is the same as the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustments to basis while the taxpayer is holding the property. See, for example, Publication 551, page 9, for further discussion on this topic.nnIn this problem, Sari received the rental property (depreciable property) from Reba that had an adjusted basis on the date of transfer of $51,000. Sari, as a result, must pick up the $51,000 as the property\'s basis for her calculation of depreciation expense.nnNote: Because the problem states that Reba gave Sari a rental property, one must assume that it is a “gift.” In addition, the problem states that you can assume that no gift tax was paid; hence, the transaction must be a gift.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(449,12,'Sue\'s father purchased 1,000 shares of ABC stock for $10 per share on December 30, 2023. Sue inherited the 1,000 shares of ABC stock from her father on September 15, 2024. The FMV at the time of the inheritance was $20 per share. On December 20, 2024, she sold the stock for $25 per share.','[\"The gain of $15,000 is short-term capital gain.\",\"The gain of $15,000 is long-term capital gain.\",\"The gain of $5,000 is long-term capital gain.\",\"The gain of $5,000 is short-term capital gain.\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. As provided in Publication 551, page 10, the basis of property that is received from a decedent is generally one of the following:nnThe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death ornThe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation.nIf a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance or transmission taxes.nnOnce the amount of the gain or loss is determined, the taxpayer must determine whether it is long term or short term. If the investment property is held for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. When investment property is inherited, the capital gain or loss on any later disposition of that property is treated as a long-term capital gain or loss. This is true regardless of how long the taxpayer actually held the property. (Publication 551, page 10)nnIn this problem, the gain on the sale for Sue is long-term capital gains and it equals $5,000, which is the selling price of $25,000 ($25 × 1,000 shares) less the adjusted basis of $20,000 ($20 × 1,000 shares).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(450,12,'Wanda purchased a manuscript in 1947 for $10. In 2022, the year before her death, Wanda gave the manuscript to her granddaughter Ruth. At the time of the gift, the manuscript had an appraised value of $510. In 2024, Ruth sold the manuscript for $1,010. What is the amount and character of Ruth\'s gain from the sale of this manuscript?','[\"$1,000 long-term capital gain\\n\",\"$1,000 ordinary gain\",\"$500 long-term capital gain\",\"$500 ordinary gain\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnPublication 551, page 9, states, in part, that if the fair market value (FMV) of the property received from a donor is equal to or greater than donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis is the donor\'s adjusted basis at the time of the gift.nnSince the gift had an FMV greater than its adjusted basis, Wanda uses the adjusted basis of the received property (i.e., $10) as her adjusted basis. Hence, the gain from the sale is $1,000, which is the difference between $1,010 and $10.nnFurthermore, if a taxpayer receives a gift of property and the basis is determined by the donor’s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s holding period is considered to have started on the same day the donor\'s holding period started. (Publication 551, page 9)nnIn this case, Ruth has a long-term capital gain of $1,000 because her holding period is considered to have started on the same day as her Grandmother\'s (Wanda, the donor), which means that the asset was held for more than 1 year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(451,12,'The president and CEO of Online, Inc., who had no direct or indirect ownership interest in Online, Inc., personally advanced $50,000 to the corporation as a temporary loan. Online, Inc., declared bankruptcy and was discharged from bankruptcy without repaying the $50,000. Which of the following statements is correct about the treatment of the $50,000 by the president?','[\"This should be treated as a nonbusiness bad debt.\",\"This should be treated as a business bad debt.\",\"This should be treated as a contributed capital.\",\"This should be treated as a stock purchase as soon as Online transfers the stock to the president.\"]',0,'If a taxpayer loans money that cannot be collected, the taxpayer could have a bad debt, which may be deductible in the year the loan becomes uncollectible. For tax purposes there are two categories of bad debt: business and nonbusiness. Business bad debt is derived from the operations of the taxpayer\'s trade or business and is deductible as a business loss. All other bad debts are regarded as nonbusiness and are deductible as short-term capital losses, regardless of how old the debt is.nnGiven that the president and CEO of Online, Inc., personally loaned money to Online, Inc., and had no direct or indirect ownership interest in the company, the $50,000 loaned will be treated as a nonbusiness bad debt for tax purposes in the year it became uncollectible (short-term capital loss).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(452,12,'Your basis in property you inherit from a decedent in 2024 is generally one of the following:','[\"The FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death\",\"The FMV on the alternate valuation date, if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation\",\"The decedent\'s adjusted basis in appreciated property immediately before death that was a gift to the decedent within a year of death.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 551, page 10, states that a taxpayer\'s basis in property inherited from a decedent is generally one of the following:nnThe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death ornThe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation.nIn addition, if a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance or transmission taxes.nnIn the case where appreciated property is inherited from a decedent that the taxpayer or spouse gifted the appreciated property to the deceased during the 1-year period ending on the date of death, the basis is the decedent\'s adjusted basis in the property immediately before death instead of the fair market value. This statement is true if the appreciated property\'s FMV on the day the gift was given to the deceased was more than its adjusted basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(453,12,'In February 2024, Auto Repair, Inc. sold a car with a basis of $12,000 to Mark, its 55% shareholder, for $10,000. In June 2024, Mark sold the car to an unrelated party for $15,000. What is the amount of Mark\'s recognized gain?','[\"$0\",\"$2,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$5,000\"]',2,'Publication 544, pages 21 and 22, states, in part, that when a taxpayer receives property from a related party in a purchase or exchange, a loss is not allowable. Furthermore, if the taxpayer later sells or exchanges the property at a gain, the taxpayer recognizes the gain only to the extent that it is more than the loss previously disallowed to the related party. This rule applies only to the original transferee.nnA loss on the sale or exchange of property between related persons is not deductible. This applies to both direct and indirect transactions, but not to distributions of property from a corporation in a complete liquidation. Publication 544, page 21, provides 13 situations that are classified as related parties. The second illustration states that a related party is one where the individual directly or indirectly owns more than 50% in value of the outstanding stock of the corporation.nnThe question\'s transaction is treated as a related party transaction. As a result, the $2,000 loss (sale price of $10,000 less an adjusted basis of $12,000) from the transfer of the car to Mark by the corporation is disallowed. Mark, as a result, has a basis of $10,000 (his purchase price). If Mark had sold the car for $7,000, he would have only been able to deduct his $3,000 loss. The $2,000 corporate loss would have benefited no taxpayer. Because Mark sold the car for $15,000, he realizes a gain of $5,000. However, he is allowed to reduce his gain by the loss disallowed of $2,000, so his recognized gain is equal to $3,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(454,12,'Heather purchased 500 shares of Investment Growth Mutual Fund on February 15, 2023, for $10 per share. On January 31, 2024, she sold the 500 shares for $1.50 per share. Which of the following is correct?','[\"Heather will have a short-term capital loss of $4,250 on her 2024 tax return and she will be allowed to offset $4,250 of her earnings.\",\"Heather has short-term capital loss of $3,000 on her 2024 tax return.\",\"Heather will have a short-term capital loss of $3,000 on her 2024 tax return and will have to carry forward a short-term loss of $1,250 to her 2025 tax return.\",\"Heather will have a short-term capital loss of $4,250 on her 2024 tax return and will have to carry forward a long-term capital loss of $1,250 to her 2025 tax return.\"]',2,'Pages 97 to 101 of Publication 550 discuss the reporting of gains and losses. In particular, if a taxpayer\'s capital losses are more than the capital gains, the taxpayer can claim a capital loss deduction, which is reported on Form 1040 and enclosed in parentheses.nnThe capital loss deduction, however, has an annual limit that is the lesser of:nn$3,000 ($1,500 if you are married and file a separate return) ornthe taxpayer\'s total net loss as shown on line 16 of Schedule D.nIn this case, the taxpayer can use the total net loss to reduce income dollar for dollar, up to the $3,000 limit. Any amount exceeding the yearly limit on capital loss deductions is carried forward to the next year, and it is treated as if it had occurred in that next year. If part of the loss is still unused, the unused part is carried forward to later years until it is completely used up.nnIn this situation, Heather has a loss of $4,250 ($8.50 per share × 500 shares). Since she can only claim $3,000 in the current year, the excess amount of $1,250 is carried over to the following year. Both are treated as short-term losses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(455,12,'Jeremy owns a duplex. He lives in one half and rents out the other half at fair rental value. He wants to take depreciation on the building, the appliances, and major remodeling in the bathroom on the rental side. What depreciation may be taken?','[\"27.5-year MACRS on both sides of the duplex, 7-year MACRS on the appliances and remodeling\",\"27.5-year MACRS on the rental side, 0 on the personal side, and 7-year MACRS on the appliances and remodeling\",\"27.5-year MACRS on both sides of the duplex, 5-year MACRS on the appliances and remodeling\",\"27.5-year MACRS on the rental and remodeling, 5-year MACRS on the appliances, and no depreciation on the personal side\"]',3,'Depreciation is a means in which costs are recovered by deducting a portion of those costs on your tax return each year. In order to determine the proper amount of depreciation permitted, it is necessary to know the following in regard to the property (Publication 527, page 6):nnBasis in propertynRecovery periodnDepreciation methodnTangible and real property placed in service after 1986 must be depreciated using MACRS. See the following table for recovery periods (Table 2-1, Publication 527, page 9):nn                                           MACRS Recovery Period    n                                        General        Alternativen                                        Depreciation   DepreciationnType of Property                        System         System      n                                                                    nAppliances, such as:n   Stovesn   Refrigerators                        5 years        9 yearsn                                                                     nResidential rental property (buildingsnor structures) and structuralncomponents such as furnaces, waternpipes, venting, etc.                    27.5 years     40 yearsn                                                                     nAdditions and improvements, such as     The recovery period of thena new roof                              property to which then                                        addition or improvement isn                                        made, determined as if the n                                        property were placed inn                                        service at the same time asn                                        the addition or improvement.nAdditionally, if a taxpayer rents a portion of property, the taxpayer must divide the expenses between personal use and rental use. Depreciation is only allowed to be deducted on the part of property that is used for rental purposes as well as furniture and equipment used for rental purposes.nnGiven that Jeremy lives in one half of his duplex and rents the other half out, he may only deduct depreciation on the portion of property used in rental as well as any furniture and equipment used for rental purposes. Therefore, Jeremy may take depreciation on the one-half of the duplex, after backing out the portion allocable to land (the portion that is rented) and the remodeling on the bathroom in that one-half. He may also depreciate the appliances used in the rental. Accordingly, the recovery period for such property (see table above) is 27.5-year MACRS on the rental property and remodeling and 5-year MACRS on the appliances. As stated above, no depreciation is permitted for the personal side.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(456,12,'In 2024, Tran received a vacant parcel of land from her uncle as a gift. Tran\'s uncle purchased the land in 2010 for $15,000, and at the time of the gift to his niece, he paid $500 in gift tax based on the land\'s fair market value of $13,000. Tran did not have any other events that increased or decreased her basis in the gift after she received it. What is her gain if she sold her property for $17,000?','[\"$4,000 gain\",\"$3,500 gain\",\"$2,000 gain\",\"$1,500 gain\"]',2,'In order to calculate the basis of property received as a gift, the adjusted basis of the donor just before it was given, the fair market value at the time of the gift, and any gift tax paid must be known. If the gift received has an adjusted basis that is greater than the fair market value at the time of the gift, the basis of the gifted property is contingent on how the asset is sold, at a loss or at a gain:nnThe basis, when there is a gain, is the same as the donor\'s basis plus or minus any required basis adjustments.nThe basis, when a loss occurs, is the fair market value of the property on the date of gift, plus or minus any required basis adjustments.nIn this case, the FMV of the property was lower than the donor\'s adjusted basis; the gift taxes are not added to the basis for the taxpayer since the asset is being sold for more than the FMV of the property when it was received by Tran. In fact, she is selling the property at a gain. The gain for Tran, therefore, would be $2,000, which is the selling price of $17,000 less the basis of $15,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(457,12,'James sells stock that he purchased in 2018 to his brother John for a $500 loss. He also sells a truck, purchased in 2022, to ABC Corporation (his 100%-owned C corporation) for a profit of $800, including $500 of depreciation recapture. What is the effect of these transactions on James\' 2024 tax return?','[\"A loss of $500 on the stock and no gain on the truck\",\"A disallowed loss on the stock, $500 ordinary gain and $300 long-term capital gain on the truck\",\"A loss of $500 on the stock and $800 ordinary gain on the truck\",\"A disallowed loss on the stock and $800 ordinary gain on the truck\"]',3,'This question deals with transactions between related persons. Generally, when a loss is derived from the sale or exchange of property between related persons, it is disallowed for tax purposes. If the related person that purchased the property at a loss later sells or exchanges that property for a gain, that person recognizes the gain only to the extent it is more than the loss previously disallowed on the initial transaction.nnHowever, gains realized in related party transactions are recognized. Therefore, it is important to understand what the term “related persons” includes. For purposes of this question, any member of a family (i.e., a brother) is deemed to be a related person. Additionally, an individual and a corporation are considered related persons if the individual owns more than 50% of the outstanding stock. (Publication 544, pages 21 and 22)nnAs a result, the loss of $500 realized on the sale of stock to James\' brother will be disallowed. However, the $800 gain realized on the sale of the truck to the corporation will be recognized as ordinary income. Gain on the sale or exchange of property that is depreciable in the hands of the person who receives it is ordinary income if the transaction is either directly or indirectly between a person and the person’s controlled entity or entities.nnFor the rules on depreciation recapture, see Publication 544, pages 27 through 29, and for a list of “related persons,” see Publication 544, pages 21 and 22, and IRC Section 267(b).nnHowever, gains realized in related party transactions are recognized. Therefore, it is important to understand what the term “related persons” includes. For purposes of this question, any member of a family (i.e., a brother) is deemed to be a related person. Additionally, an individual and a corporation are considered related persons if the individual owns more than 50% of the outstanding stock. (Publication 544, pages 21 and 22)nnAs a result, the loss of $500 realized on the sale of stock to James\' brother will be disallowed. However, the $800 gain realized on the sale of the truck to the corporation will be recognized as ordinary income. Gain on the sale or exchange of property that is depreciable in the hands of the person who receives it is ordinary income if the transaction is either directly or indirectly between a person and the person’s controlled entity or entities.nnFor the rules on depreciation recapture, see Publication 544, pages 27 through 29, and for a list of “related persons,” see Publication 544, pages 21 and 22, and IRC Section 267(b).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(458,12,'Thomas loaned friend Susan $10,000 for a down payment on a home. Thomas and Susan signed a note in which Susan agreed to pay $100 a month with an interest rate of 4% until the loan was completely paid. Susan lost both her job and her home in 2023. She filed bankruptcy and went to live with her mother. Thomas sued Susan in court for nonpayment in August 2024, but the court dissolved her debt to Thomas based upon the bankruptcy. When Susan defaulted, the outstanding balance due on the note was $7,000. If Thomas had only wage income reportable during the year, how much would his deductible bad debt be in 2024?','[\"$7,000\",\"$6,900\",\"$3,000\",\"$10,000\"]',2,'If money owed to a taxpayer becomes uncollectible in a given tax year, the taxpayer may have an allowable deduction for bad debt. To be deductible, nonbusiness bad debts must be totally worthless. A person cannot deduct a partly worthless nonbusiness debt.nnThe bad debt must arise from a debtor-creditor relationship based on a valid and enforceable obligation to repay a fixed or determinable sum of money. Those bad debts, incurred outside of operating a business or trade, are categorized as nonbusiness bad debt. Nonbusiness bad debts are deducted as a short-term capital loss on Form 8949, which are then transferred to Schedule D (Form 1040) and are deductible when deemed totally worthless. (Publication 550, page 76)nnPublication 550, page 100, further provides that capital losses are subject to a $3,000 ($1,500 for married filing separate) per year deduction limitation.nnAlthough Thomas has a bad debt of $7,000 that can be deducted as a short-term capital loss, he is limited to $3,000 in 2024 and will carry forward the remaining $4,000 to his 2025 tax return..',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(459,12,'What can be said about the basis of the property received if an individual exchanges property for another property in a like-kind nontaxable exchange and pays an additional amount in cash?','[\"The property received is the basis of the property exchanged, decreased by the cash paid.\",\"The property received is the basis of the property exchanged.\",\"The property received is the basis of the property exchanged, increased by the cash paid.\",\"The property received is the basis of the property received of the original owner.\"]',2,'A nontaxable exchange is an exchange in which a taxpayer is not taxed on any gain and the taxpayer cannot deduct any loss. If a taxpayer receives property in a nontaxable exchange, the basis is usually the same as the basis of the property the taxpayer transferred.nnPublication 551, page 8, states, in part, that if a taxpayer trades property in a like-kind exchange (i.e., a nontaxable exchange) and also pays money, the basis of the property received is the basis of the property given up increased by the money paid.nnBeginning after 2017, nontaxable like-kind exchange treatment under section 1031 applies only to exchanges of real property held for use in a trade or business or for investment, other than real property held primarily for sale. Before 2017, section 1031 also applied to certain exchanges of personal or intangible property.nn In the given case, the basis of the new property received is the basis of the old property plus the cash paid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(460,12,'Fred bought 10 shares of stock on October 1, 2023, for $100. He sold them for $80 on October 1, 2024. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Fred has a long-term capital gain of $20.\",\"Fred has a short-term capital gain of $20.\",\"Fred has a short-term capital loss of $20.\",\"Fred has a long-term capital loss of $20.\"]',2,'The holding period for a capital asset is the length of time the property was owned before it is disposed of by sale or exchange. Holding periods are categorized as “short term” or “long term”. In determining the holding period, the taxpayer begins counting on the day after the property was acquired. Long-term capital assets are those assets held for more than 12 months, leaving short-term capital assets to be those assets that were not held for more than 12 months.nnNote: A shortcut for remembering the holding period is to count all days except either the day of purchase or the day of sale, but do not count both days.nnFred bought the shares of stock on October 1, 2023; his holding period would start on October 2, 2023. Selling the shares on October 1, 2024, causes Fred\'s holding period for the stock to be 12 months (not more than 12 months), therefore generating a short-term loss.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(461,12,'Karen, who is single, paid $150,000 for her residence in January 2019 and lived in it until January 2023. She then moved away and rented her home from February 2023 until she sold it in August 2024 for $240,000. While it was rental property, she deducted $20,000 of depreciation. What amount of gain on the sale of her residence is excludable from income?','[\"$250,000\",\"$90,000\",\"$110,000\",\"$240,000\"]',1,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true.nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., own the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 3)nIn this problem, the taxpayer satisfies the special rule for excluding $250,000. However, if the taxpayer was entitled to take depreciation deductions because the home was used for business purposes or as rental property, the taxpayer cannot exclude the part of the gain equal to any depreciation allowed as a deduction for periods after May 6, 1997. (Publication 523, page 6)nnThus, the gain from the sale is $110,000, which is the amount received of $240,000 less the property\'s basis of $130,000 ($150,000 less $20,000 of depreciation). Of the $110,000, $90,000 is excludable under the special home sale rule, and the $20,000 is recaptured depreciation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(462,12,'Larry purchased 100 shares of ABC stock on May 31, 2023, for $100 per share. On October 28, 2023, he sold the 100 shares for $90 per share. On November 22, 2023, his wife, Vickie, purchased 100 shares of ABC stock for $80 per share. Vickie held the stock until September 30, 2024. On that date, she sold the stock for $110 per share. They filed married filing separately on all returns.','[\"Larry has a short-term loss of $1,000 on his 2023 tax return.\",\"Vickie has short-term gain of $3,000 on her 2024 tax return.\",\"Vickie will have a short-term gain of $3,000 on her 2024 tax return and Larry takes the short-term loss $1,000 on his 2023 tax return.\",\"Vickie will have a long-term gain of $2,000 on her 2024 tax return and Larry will not have any capital loss on his 2023 tax return.\"]',3,'Publication 550 (on pages 84–86) discusses the treatment of property transactions that are known as a wash sale. In general, a taxpayer cannot deduct losses from sales or trades of stock or securities in a wash sale.nnA wash sale occurs when a taxpayer sells or trades stock or securities at a loss and within 30 days before or after the sale whereby the taxpayer or spouse:nnbuys substantially identical stock or securities,nacquires substantially identical stock or securities in a fully taxable trade,nacquires a contract or option to buy substantially identical stock or securities, ornacquires substantially identical stock or securities for the taxpayer\'s IRA or Roth IRA.nFurthermore, if a taxpayer sells stock and the taxpayer\'s spouse or a corporation controlled by the taxpayer buys substantially identical stock, the taxpayer has a wash sale. (See “Wash Sales” in chapter 4 of Publication 550.)nnIn the case of a wash sale, the disallowed loss is added to the cost of the new stock or securities. The adjustment postpones the loss deduction until the disposition of the new stock or securities. Furthermore, the taxpayer\'s holding period for the new stock or securities begins on the same day as the holding period of the stock or securities sold.nnIn this problem, Larry has a wash sale since Vickie, his wife, purchased the same stock within 30 days of Larry\'s sale. The loss of $10 per share is added to Vickie\'s purchase price of $80 per share to yield an adjusted basis of $90 per share. When Vickie sells the stock for $110 per share, she has a long-term capital gain of $2,000 ($20 per share × 100 shares). It is long-term because the holding period began on the date that Larry purchased the stock and ended on the date that Vickie sold it, which is more than 1 year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(463,12,'A taxpayer purchases real estate rental property for $150,000. She pays $25,000 cash and obtains a mortgage for $125,000. She pays closing costs of $8,000, which includes $4,000 in points on the mortgage and $4,000 for bank fees and title costs. The basis in the property is:','[\"$33,000 depreciation, $125,000 amortization.\",\"$158,000, depreciation only.\",\"$154,000 depreciation, $4,000 amortization.\",\"$150,000 depreciation, $8,000 amortization.\"]',2,'A taxpayer\'s basis is the amount of a taxpayer\'s investment in property for tax purposes. In determining the basis for property that is purchased, the settlement fees and closing costs for buying the property are included. Conversely, fees and costs for getting a loan on the property are not part of the basis calculation. A list of settlement costs that are included in basis is given in Publication 551, page 3, and a list of settlement costs that are not included in basis is given on that same page.nnThe amount that a taxpayer pays for points in order to secure a loan is deducted over the term of the loan, i.e., amortized. (For more information on how to deduct points, see pages 2 and 3 of Publication 551 or pages 6 through 8 of Publication 936.)nnTherefore, the basis in the property in the above question is:nn$154,000 depreciation, which is the sum of the purchase price ($150,000) and title costs ($4,000), andn$4,000 amortization (ratably over the life (term) of the mortgage), which is the payment for points.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(464,12,'Alf owns all of the shares of Waxman Corporation, a manufacturer of finished leather products. Alf also owns a 60% partnership interest and his friend Richard owns a 40% partnership interest in York Real Estate Rentals, LLC. York Real Estate Rentals owns and leases warehouse space to numerous businesses. In 2024, York Real Estate Rentals sold a building with an adjusted basis of $100,000 to Waxman Corporation for $80,000. What is the amount of York Real Estate Rentals\' deductible loss in 2024 from this transaction?','[\"$(20,000)\",\"$(12,000)\",\"$(8,000)\",\"$0\"]',3,'Publication 550, page 97, provides that a taxpayer cannot deduct a loss on the sale or trade of property, other than a distribution in complete liquidation of a corporation, if the transaction is directly or indirectly between the taxpayer and the following related parties:nnMembers of the taxpayer\'s family, which include only the taxpayer\'s brothers and sisters, half-brothers and half-sisters, spouse, ancestors (parents, grandparents, etc.), and lineal descendants (children, grandchildren, etc.)nA partnership in which the taxpayer directly or indirectly owns more than 50% of the capital interest or the profits interestnA corporation in which the taxpayer directly or indirectly owns more than 50% in value of the outstanding stocknA tax-exempt charitable or educational organization that is directly or indirectly controlled, in any manner or by any method, by the taxpayer or by a member of the taxpayer\'s family, whether or not this control is legally enforceablenSince Alf owns more than 50% in both the partnership and the corporation that are exchanging the asset, no loss can be deducted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(465,12,'Tom, a single taxpayer, determines that he has both a short-term capital loss of $2,000 and a nondividend distribution of $1,000 from an investment.nnThe following statements are correct, except:','[\"the basis of the investment is reduced by the nondividend distribution.\",\"nondividend distribution is a return of capital.\",\"the short-term capital loss can be used to offset capital gains (if any) for the year.\",\"any unused short-term capital loss may be carried back 3 years.\"]',3,'This question deals with several different issues. First, IRC Section 1(h)(1) and IRC Section 1222 provide specific netting procedures for calculating capital gains and losses. When a taxpayer has a loss from the sale of short-term assets, the loss will first be applied against short-term capital gains, if any, and then, the remaining “net” short-term loss is used to offset any “net” long-term capital gains. Additionally, a taxpayer may carry over net capital losses to future years until the loss is fully utilized (Publication 550, pages 97–101).nnNext, nondividend distributions received by a taxpayer are not treated the same as ordinary dividends or capital gain distributions. Non-dividend distributions consist of return of capital because they are not paid out of earnings and profits. Distributions that are a return of capital are nontaxable distributions that reduce the basis of the investment by the amount of the distribution (Publication 550, page 30).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(466,12,'Rose has the following transactions during the year of 2024:nn  Sale of ACB stock (basis $400)            $800n  Commission paid on sale of ACB stock        50n  Received 200 extra shares of DEF inn    stock split (fair market value)          800n  Decrease in value of GHI mutual fund       600n  JKL stock declared worthless (basisn    $700) (no stock value)                     0nWhat is the net gain or loss Rose will claim on her Schedule D?','[\"$350 loss\",\"$1,000 gain\",\"$300 gain\",\"$650 loss\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnIf the amount realized from a sale or trade is more than the adjusted basis of the property that the taxpayer transfers, the difference is a gain, andnIf the adjusted basis of the property that the taxpayer transfers is more than the amount realized, the difference is a loss. (Publication 550, page 65)nStocks, stock rights, and bonds (other than those held for sale by a securities dealer) that became worthless during the tax year are treated as though they were sold on the last day of the tax year. This affects whether the taxpayer\'s capital loss is long term or short term. (Publication 550, page 54)nnThe basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase such as additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits (Publication 550, pages 62–63). In the case of a stock split, the basis of the stock is reduced by recalculating the adjusted basis before the stock dividend or split by the new number of shares.nnRose has a $350 loss in 2024 from her stock transactions. More specifically, the loss is the sum of the gain from the ACB stock sale of $350 ($800 less $450, which is the stock\'s cost plus commission) and the loss of $700 on the JKL stock that is being declared worthless. There is no gain or loss from the stock dividend or the decrease in value of the mutual fund.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(467,12,'The owner of unimproved land with a basis of $40,000 sold the property for $100,000 in 2022. The seller accepted a note for the entire $100,000 sales price. In 2024, when the buyer still owed $10,000, the note was sold for $9,000 cash. How should the disposition of the note be reported on the seller\'s 2024 return?','[\"$5,000 capital gain\",\"$5,000 ordinary income\",\"$2,000 capital gain\",\"$1,000 capital loss\"]',0,'Publication 537, page 12, provides the general rules for the disposition of an installment obligation. In general, a disposition includes a sale, exchange, cancellation, bequest, distribution, or transmission of an installment obligation. An installment obligation is the buyer\'s note, deed of trust, or other evidence that the buyer will make future payments to the taxpayer.nnIf the taxpayer is using the installment method and he or she disposes of the installment obligation, generally the taxpayer will have a gain or loss to report. If the original installment sale produced ordinary income, the disposition of the obligation results in ordinary income or loss. Likewise, if the original installment sale produced capital income, the disposition of the obligation results in capital gain or loss.nnTwo sets of rules are provided in Publication 537 to compute the gain or loss. The first set is used to figure the gain or loss from the disposition of an installment obligation if the taxpayer sells or exchanges the obligation, or accepts less than face value in satisfaction of the obligation. In this case, the gain or loss is the difference between the taxpayer\'s basis in the obligation and the amount realized.nnThe second set is used to figure the gain or loss from the disposition of the obligation in any other way. That is, the taxpayer\'s gain or loss is the difference between the basis in the obligation and its FMV at the time of the disposition.nnIn this case, the owner uses the first set of rules. The owner has a capital gain of $5,000, which is the amount realized of $9,000 less the basis in the note. In this case, the basis is $4,000 (40% of the $10,000 note). Since the gross profit percentage is 60% (($100,000 - $40,000) ÷ $100,000), then the basis must be 40%, which is 100% − 60%.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(468,12,'A married couple, who are both self-employed and work out of their home, purchased a new home in August 2022 for $420,000. In September 2022, they converted two bedrooms into office space where they meet clients in their home. In April 2024, they sold their home, on which they had taken $40,000 depreciation. Their home sold for $600,000. What amount of the gain is includible in their income on their joint return?','[\"$0\",\"$40,000\",\"$180,000\",\"$220,000\"]',3,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true.nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 3)nIn this problem, the taxpayers do not satisfy the 2-year ownership test for excluding $250,000. Thus, the gain from the sale is $220,000, which is the amount received of $600,000 less the property\'s basis of $380,000 ($420,000 less $40,000 of depreciation).nnBe aware that there are exceptions to the 2-year usage (see Publication 523, pages 3–6). In this case, even if the couple satisfies the 2-year usage, they would need to check out Publication 523 because they used the property partly as a home and partly for business. As a result, the exclusion would need to be adjusted for the home ownership portion (see Publication 523, pages 4–5).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(469,12,'In 2022, Fred purchased 100 shares of Oak Company common stock for $100 per share. In June 2024, Oak Company declared a 2-for-1 common stock split. Fred sells 50% of his Oak Company common stock shares for $200 per share immediately after he receives his stock split shares. He sells his remaining Oak Company shares at the end of 2024 for $100 per share. What is Fred\'s total 2024 gain from the sale of his Oak Company shares?','[\"$15,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$25,000\",\"$30,000\"]',1,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Generally, stock dividends are not taxable and therefore are not reportable. (Publication 550, page 22)nnThe basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital. (Publication 551, page 2)nnIn this problem, the basis in the Oak Company\'s stock after the stock dividend is $50 ($100 ÷ 2). The sale of the first half of his stock produces a gain of $15,000, which is the selling price of $20,000 (100 shares × $200) less the adjusted basis of $5,000 (100 shares × $50). The sale of the second half of his stock produces a gain of $5,000, which is the selling price of $10,000 (100 shares × $100) less the adjusted basis of $5,000 (100 shares × $50). Thus, the total 2024 gain from the sale of Fred\'s Oak Company shares is $20,000.nnThere is a simple way to calculate this problem. The cost for the 100 shares is $10,000 (100 × $100) and the sale price is $30,000 ((100 shares × $200) + (100 shares × $100)). Of course, this trick only applies if the taxpayer sells all the stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(470,12,'When Amelia bought her first home in 2021, she paid $100,000 plus $1,000 closing costs. In 2022, she added a deck that cost $5,000. Then, in July 2024, a real estate dealer accepted her house as a trade-in and allowed her $125,000 (amount received as a trade-in) toward a new house priced at $200,000. How should Amelia report this transaction on her 2024 return?','[\"$19,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$25,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$0 taxable gain and reduce her basis in her new house by $19,000\",\"No reporting required\"]',3,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true (see Publication 523, pages 2 and 3):nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home.nBe aware that there are some exceptions in this area, which are covered more thoroughly in Publication 523, pages 3 through 6.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer satisfies the special rule for excluding $250,000. Thus, the gain from the sale is $19,000, which is the amount received as a trade-in of $125,000 less the property\'s basis of $106,000 ($100,000 + $5,000 + $1,000). However, since the gain of $19,000 is less than the $250,000 exclusion amount, none of it is recognized. Furthermore, the sale of a taxpayer\'s main home is not reported on the tax return unless the taxpayer has a gain and does not qualify to exclude all of it, the taxpayer has a gain and chooses not to exclude it, or the taxpayer received Form 1099-S (see Publication 523, page 15). Thus, Amelia does not report the sale of her main home.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(471,12,'During 2024, Nicholas made the following dispositions of property:nnSold publicly traded stock, which cost $2,000 and had been held for 2 years, for $3,000nSold land, which cost $20,000 and had been held for 9 months, to his brother for $16,000nHow should Nicholas report these dispositions on his 2024 return?','[\"$1,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$3,000 long-term capital loss\",\"$3,000 short-term capital loss\",\"$3,000 ordinary loss\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property (Publication 550, page 58). Once the amount of the gain or loss is determined, the taxpayer must determine whether it is long term or short term. If the investment property is held for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. (Publication 550, page 73)nnWhen investment property is received from a related person in a purchase or exchange and the received property from a related person had a loss, it is not a recognized loss. Rather, the taxpayer that receives the property recognizes the gain only to the extent it is more than the loss previously disallowed to the related person. This rule applies only to the original transferee. (Publication 550, page 72)nnTo illustrate the above point, the following example is given in Publication 550, page 73. Your brother sold stock to you for $7,600. His cost basis was $10,000. His loss of $2,400 was not deductible. You later sell the same stock to an unrelated party for $10,500, realizing a gain of $2,900 ($10,500 − $7,600). Your recognized gain is only $500, the gain that is more than the $2,400 loss not allowed to your brother.nnIn this case, Nicholas has a recognized long-term capital gain of $1,000 from the sale of the publicly traded stock, which is the difference between the selling price of $3,000 and the adjusted basis of $2,000. The sale of the land to his brother, however, results in a loss to a related party and, as such, is not recognized by him.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(472,12,'Kevin bought stock in the Little Dipper Corporation in 2021 for $3,000. In 2023, Kevin received a return of capital distribution of $300 as a partial return on his investment. In 2024, Kevin sold the stock for $5,200. His capital gain from the sale is:','[\"$5,200.\",\"$2,500.\",\"$2,200.\",\"$1,900.\"]',1,'The basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. (Publication 551, page 2)nnThe basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital. (Publication 551, page 2)nnIn this problem, Kevin\'s capital gain in the Little Dipper Corporation is $2,500, which is the selling price of $5,200 less the adjusted basis of $2,700 (purchase price of $3,000 less the return of capital distribution of $300).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(473,12,'Maggie trades stock in ABC Company with an adjusted basis of $7,000 for DEF Company stock with a fair market value of $10,000. She had no other transactions during the year. What is the amount realized and what is her gain or loss on this transaction?','[\"The amount realized is $10,000 and the amount of gain is $3,000.\",\"The amount realized is $10,000 and the amount of loss is $3,000.\",\"The amount realized is $7,000 and the amount of gain is $4,000.\",\"The amount realized is $17,000 and the amount of gain is $3,000.\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnIf the amount realized from a sale or trade is more than the adjusted basis of the property the taxpayer transferred, the difference is a gain, andnIf the adjusted basis of the property you transfer is more than the amount realized, the difference is a loss.nThe adjusted basis of property is the original cost or other original basis properly adjusted (increased or decreased) for certain items.nnMaggie has a gain of $3,000, which is the difference between the amount realized, which is the fair market value of the acquired stock (i.e., $10,000), and the adjusted basis of the traded stock (i.e., $7,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(474,12,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning like-kind exchanges?','[\"The exchange need\\u00a0not\\u00a0be reported on either party\'s tax return since the exchange is nontaxable.\",\"The exchange needs to be reported only on the party\'s tax return that has a recognized gain.\",\"The exchange needs to be reported only on the party\'s tax return that has a recognized gain.\",\"The exchange needs to be reported only on the party\'s tax return that has a recognized gain or loss.\"]',2,'In the case of a like-kind exchange, the taxpayer must report the transaction, even though no gain or loss is recognized, on Form 8824. In addition, if a recognized gain or loss results from the exchange on Form 8824, it is reported on Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) or on Form 4797, Sales of Business Property, whichever form applies.nnFor information on like-kind exchanges, refer to Publication 551, page 8.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(475,12,'To determine net capital gains/losses for the year:','[\"net all capital gains, both long-term and short-term, together.\",\"net short-term gains\\/losses and long-term gains\\/losses separately, then combine.\",\"net short-term gains\\/losses and long-term gains\\/losses and report only any net gains.\",\"net all gain transactions together and all loss transactions together, then combine.\"]',1,'The determination of a taxpayer\'s capital gains or losses in a particular year goes through a process that is better known as the netting rules. That is, a taxpayer figures the total net gain or loss by combining the net short-term capital gain or loss (line 7 of Schedule D, Form 1040) with the net long-term capital gain or loss (line 15 of Schedule D, Form 1040). All short-term items are netted separately, and all long-term items are netted separately before the two are combined.nnFor more information on this issue, you should read Chapter 4 of Publication 550.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(476,12,'Albina purchased 1,000 shares of Global Tech Growth mutual fund on February 15, 2023, for $15 per share. On January 31, 2024, she sold the 1,000 shares of Global Tech Growth mutual fund for $4.50 per share. Albina had no other capital transactions in 2024. Which of the following is correct?','[\"Albina has a short-term capital loss of $10,500 on her 2024 tax return and she will be allowed to offset $10,500 of her earnings.\",\"Albina has a short-term capital loss of $3,000 on her 2024 tax return and no carryover.\",\"Albina has a short-term capital loss of $10,500 in 2024 and will deduct $3,000 on her tax return. She will carry forward a short-term loss of $7,500 to 2025.\",\"Albina has a short-term capital loss of $10,500 in 2024 and will deduct $3,000 on her tax return. She will carry forward a long-term loss of $7,500 to 2025.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 550, pages 83–84, if the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the taxpayer holds the property for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss.nnIn this case, the Global Tech Growth stock transaction is a short-term capital loss of $10,500, which is the difference between the selling price of $4,500 (1,000 shares × $4.50) and adjusted basis of $15,000 (1,000 shares × $15).nnPublication 550, page 100, discusses the reporting of gains and losses. In particular, if a taxpayer\'s capital losses are more than the capital gains, the taxpayer can claim a capital loss deduction, which is reported on Form 1040 or 1040-SR, line 6 and enclosed in parentheses.nnThe capital loss deduction, however, has an annual limit that is the lesser of:nn$3,000 ($1,500 if you are married and file a separate return) ornthe taxpayer\'s total net loss as shown on line 16 of Schedule D (Form 1040 or 1040-SR).nIn this case, Albina would claim the annual limit of $3,000 as a net short-term capital loss and would carry forward the remaining $7,500 short-term capital loss to the following year (or years).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(477,12,'Ted and William agreed to trade apartment buildings with Ted agreeing to pay William $10,000 cash. Ted\'s basis in his apartment building is $40,000. William\'s basis in his apartment building is $50,000. What is Ted\'s basis in his new apartment building?','[\"$50,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$10,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Publication 544, page 16, provides a discussion on the basis of property received in a like-kind exchange. If the taxpayer acquires property in a like-kind exchange, the basis of that property is the same as the basis of the property transferred by the taxpayer.nnnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nA taxpayer exchanged real estate held for investment with an adjusted basis of $25,000 for other real estate held for investment. The basis of the taxpayer\'s new property is the same as the basis of the old ($25,000).nn nIf, in addition to giving up like-kind property, the taxpayer pays money in a like-kind exchange, the taxpayer still has no recognized gain or loss. The basis of the property received, on the other hand, is the basis of the property given up, increased by the money paid.nnIn this case, Ted\'s basis in the new building is $50,000, which is the sum of the basis of the old building given by Ted to William ($40,000) and the cash given by Ted to William ($10,000).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(478,12,'Two years ago, Mark sold real property (basis of $250,000) for $500,000. He received a down payment of $50,000 plus regular monthly payments of principal and interest until 10 months ago. The buyer failed to make further payments resulting in Mark repossessing the real property. What is Mark\'s tax consequence as a result of repossessing the real property?','[\"Mark must recognize the full gain as if he received the full purchase price on the real property.\",\"Mark may have a limited amount of gain.\",\"Mark can claim a loss on the gain previously recognized by him in prior years.\",\"Mark has\\u00a0no\\u00a0further tax consequences as a result of repossessing the real property.\"]',1,'If a taxpayer sells real property under an installment agreement secured by the property, upon repossession of that property the seller will recognize the gain or loss on the repossession and the basis in the repossessed property. (Publication 537, pages 12–13)nnIf the FMV of the repossessed property is more than the total of your basis in the obligation plus any repossession costs, you have a gainnIf the FMV is less, you have a loss. Your gain or loss on the repossession is of the same character (capital or ordinary) as your gain on the original sale.nTo determine the taxable gain or loss on a repossession of personal property reported on the installment method, a taxpayer may use Worksheet C in Publication 537, page 13.nnMark sold real property under an installment agreement of which he had to repossess. By repossessing the real property, Mark may have a limited amount of gain.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(479,12,'The original owner of Felix Plumbing Company stock paid $10,000 for his 100 shares. Stock in Felix Plumbing is qualifying small business stock under Section 1244. The stockholder also made a $2,000 contribution to the capital of Felix Plumbing for a total investment of $12,000. He then sold the 100 shares for $9,000. What is the amount and character of loss that he can deduct on his return for the year of sale?','[\"$3,000 ordinary loss\",\"$3,000 capital loss\",\"$1,000 capital loss\",\"$2,500 ordinary loss and $500 capital loss\"]',3,'A taxpayer can deduct as an ordinary loss, rather than as a capital loss, his or her loss on the sale, trade, or worthlessness of Section 1244 stock (also known as a small business investment company). The loss is reported on Form 4797, Part II, line 10. Any gain on this stock is capital gain and is reported on Form 8949 if the stock is a capital asset in the taxpayer\'s hands (page 79 of Publication 550).nnIn addition, if the basis of the taxpayer\'s Section 1244 stock has increased, through contributions to capital or otherwise, the taxpayer must treat this increase as applying to stock that is not Section 1244 stock when the taxpayer figures the ordinary loss on its sale (“Contributions to capital” on page 79 of Publication 550).nnIn this problem, the owner of Felix Plumbing Company stock has a $3,000 loss ($9,000 less $12,000) from the sale of the Section 1244 stock. However, 1/6th of the basis ($2,000 ÷ $12,000) is attributable to the contribution and as such, the ordinary loss due to the sale of Section 1244 stock is limited to $2,500 ($10,000/$12,000 of $3,000) and the remaining $500 is a capital loss.nnFor more information on losses on Section 1244 (small business) stock, see chapter 4 of Publication 550.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(480,12,'Cost basis of property includes:','[\"certain settlement fees and other costs.\",\"sales taxes charged on the purchase.\",\"real estate taxes paid for seller without reimbursement.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A taxpayer\'s basis is the amount of a taxpayer\'s investment in property for tax purposes. Publication 550, pages 58–60, states, in part, that the cost basis of property purchased by a taxpayer usually is its cost. The cost, however, includes the amount the taxpayer pays in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services. In addition, the cost includes amounts the taxpayer pays for the following items:nnSales taxnFreightnInstallation and testingnExcise taxesnLegal and accounting fees (when they must be capitalized)nRevenue stampsnRecording feesnReal estate taxes (if assumed for the seller)nIn addition, the basis of real estate and business assets may include other items, such as settlement fees and closing costs.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(481,12,'Herb files single and had the following capital gains and losses in 2024:nn$500 loss on the sale of stock he purchased on January 14, 2024, and sold on August 10, 2024n$5,000 loss on the sale of stock purchased October 1, 2023, and sold November 1, 2024n$1,000 gain on the sale of a vacant lot held for 5 yearsnHow should Herb\'s capital gains and losses be initially reported on Schedule D?','[\"$4,500 long-term loss\",\"$4,000 long-term loss and $500 short-term loss\",\"$4,500 long-term loss and $1,000 short-term loss\",\"$5,500 long-term loss and $1,000 short-term gain\\n\"]',1,'Publication 550, pages 73 and 74, defines what is and is not a capital asset. Almost everything a taxpayer owns and uses for personal purposes or investment is a capital asset. There are a few exceptions, including but not limited to property sold in the normal course of business; copyright; a literary, musical, or artistic composition; a letter; a memorandum; or similar property (such as drafts of speeches, recordings, transcripts, manuscripts, drawings, or photographs), which was created by the taxpayer\'s personal efforts, or prepared or produced for the taxpayer (in the case of a letter, memorandum, or similar property).nnIf the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss (Publication 550, page 73).nnHerb would report $5,000 in long-term capital losses from the sale of stock on November 1 and $1,000 in long-term capital gain from the sale of a vacant lot (for a net $4,000 long-term loss). In addition, he would report $500 in short-term capital losses from the sale of stock on August 10.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(482,12,'Harry purchased one share of common stock in a computer company for $90. Shortly after he purchased it, the corporation distributed two new shares of common stock for each share held. What is his basis for each of the three shares of common stock?','[\"$90\",\"$180\",\"$30\",\"$0\"]',2,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Generally, stock dividends are not taxable and therefore are not reportable (Publication 550, page 31).nnThe basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital (Publication 550, pages 30–31).nnIn this problem, the basis in the computer corporation\'s stock prior to the stock dividend is $90. The distribution of the two additional shares results in Harry owning three shares of the stock with a basis of $30 per share ($90 ÷ 3 shares).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(483,12,'In 2019, Ralph received 10 shares of White Corporation stock as a gift from his father. Ralph\'s father had originally paid $10 per share for this stock. The stock was trading for $20 per share at the time of the gift. In 2022, Ralph purchased an additional 20 shares of White Corporation stock for a price of $30 per share. Ralph was charged a $20 transaction fee on this purchase. In October 2024, Ralph sold 20 shares of his White Corporation stock. Ralph cannot adequately identify the shares he disposed of. What is Ralph\'s basis in the White Corporation shares he still owns?','[\"$100\",\"$200\",\"$310\",\"$360\"]',2,'The basis of stocks or bonds is generally the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. If stocks are not acquired through direct purchase, the basis is usually determined by the fair market value (FMV) or the previous owner\'s adjusted basis of the stock. Moreover, adjustments must be made to the basis for certain events that occur after purchase. (Publication 550, page 61)nnIf the fair market value of gifted property at the time of the gift was equal to or more than the donor\'s adjusted basis just before the gift, the basis for gain or loss on the sale of the property is the donor\'s adjusted basis (plus or minus any adjustments to basis during the period the property is held by the donee). Therefore, Ralph\'s basis in the shares gifted from his father is the same as his father\'s basis: $10 per share. (Publication 550, pages 60–61)nnIf you buy and sell securities at various times in varying quantities and you cannot adequately identify the shares you sell, the basis of the securities you sell is the basis of the securities you acquired first (i.e., first-in, first-out) (Publication 550, page 61).nnAs a result, Ralph\'s basis in the White Corporation shares he still owns is $310, calculated as:nn  Basis in 10 shares      $100 ($10 x 10)n  Basis in 20 shares      $620 (($30 x 20) + 20), which is $31/sharen  Sold 20 sharesn    10 shares at $10/sh   (100)n    10 shares at $31/sh   (310)n  Remaining               $310',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(484,12,'Vanessa inherited 100 shares of stock from her grandmother when her grandmother died on December 10, 2023; the fair market value of the stock was $50 per share. Her grandmother paid $40 per share when she purchased the stock on July 1, 2023. If Vanessa sells all 100 shares for $60 per share on June 30, 2024, how should she report the sale on her return for 2024?','[\"$1,000 short-term capital gain\",\"$2,000 short-term capital gain\",\"$1,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$2,000 long-term capital gain\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. As provided in Publication 550, page 60, the basis of property that is received from a decedent is:nnthe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death ornthe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation.nIf a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance taxes.nnOnce the amount of the gain or loss is determined, the taxpayer must determine whether it is long term or short term. If the investment property is held for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the property is held for 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. (Publication 550, page 48) When investment property is inherited, the capital gain or loss on any later disposition of that property is treated as a long-term capital gain or loss. This is true regardless of how long the taxpayer actually held the property. (Publication 550, page 66)nnIn this problem, the gain on the sale for Vanessa is long-term capital gain, and it equals $1,000, which is the selling price of $6,000 ($60 × 100 shares) less the adjusted basis of $5,000 ($50 × 100 shares).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(485,12,'Beth and Donnie purchased a house to use as rental property. They paid the following amounts: $100,000 cash, assumption of an existing $25,000 mortgage, title search $500, recording fees of $100, points for their new loan of $1,000, and the seller\'s part of the property taxes of $1,500. The seller did not reimburse them for the property taxes. What is their cost basis in the house?','[\"$100,000\",\"$125,000\",\"$127,100\",\"$128,100\"]',2,'The basis of property that is purchased by a taxpayer is usually its cost, which includes the amount paid in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services (see Publication 551, pages 2 and 3). In addition, some settlement fees or closing costs can be included in the basis of the property, which includes the following:nnAbstract fees (abstract of title fees)nCharges for installing utility servicesnLegal fees (including title search and preparation of the sales contract and deed)nRecording feesnSurveysnTransfer taxesnOwner\'s title insurancenAny amounts the seller owes that the taxpayer agrees to pay, such as back taxes or interest, recording or mortgage fees, charges for improvements or repairs, and sales commissionsnCasualty insurance premiums, rent for occupancy of the property before closing, charges for utilities or other services related to occupancy of the property before settlement, fees for refinancing a mortgage, and points are a few of the settlement fees and closing costs that a taxpayer cannot include in the basis of property (see Publication 551, page 3).nnGiven the information above, the taxpayer in this problem has a basis of $127,100 from the purchase of the property. This basis is the sum of the property cost ($100,000), assumption of an existing mortgage ($25,000), title search ($500), recording fees ($100), and the seller\'s part of the property taxes ($1,500). The points can be deducted as interest in the current year.nnSee Publication 551, pages 2 and 3, for more information on this calculation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(486,12,'Ethel and George sold an investment property they purchased in 2016 for $300,000. The property was sold for $700,000 with a down payment of $140,000. What is the gross profit percentage?','[\"57.14%\",\"22.86%\",\"28.57%\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'In the case of an installment sale, a certain percentage of each payment (after subtracting interest) is reported as installment sale income. This percentage is called the gross profit percentage and is figured by dividing the taxpayer\'s gross profit from the sale by the contract price. The gross profit percentage generally remains the same for each payment you receive. (Publication 537, page 4)nnTo figure the adjusted basis and gross profit percentage for an installment sale, the following worksheet (see Worksheet A, Publication 537, page 3) is used:nn1. Enter the selling price for the property.                1._____n2. Enter your adjusted basis for the property.    2._____n3. Enter your selling expenses.                   3._____n4. Enter any depreciation recapture.              4._____n5. Add lines 2, 3, and 4. This is your adjustedn   basis for installment sale purposes.                     5._____n6. Subtract line 5 from line 1. If zero or less,n   enter -0-.                                               6._____n   This is your gross profit.n   If the amount entered on line 6 is zero, Stopn   here. You cannot use the installment method.n7. Enter the contract price for the property.               7._____n8. Divide line 6 by line 7. This is your grossn   profit percentage.                                       8._____nIn this problem, Ethel and George sell their property for $700,000 (item 1), and the property has an adjusted basis for installment sale purposes of $300,000 (items 2 and 5). Hence, the gross profit percentage is 57.14%, which is the gross profit of $400,000 ($700,000 − $300,000) divided by the selling price of $700,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(487,12,'Jerry received two acres of land valued at $10,000 as a gift. The donor\'s adjusted basis was $12,000. Jerry subsequently sold the land for $20,000. For purposes of computing his gain, what is Jerry\'s basis in the land?','[\"$12,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$8,000\",\"$2,000\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnPublication 551, page 9, states, in part, that if the FMV of the property received from a donor was less than the donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis for figuring:nngain on its sale or other disposition is the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustment to basis while you held the property, andnloss on its sale or other disposition is the FMV when the taxpayer received the gift plus or minus any required adjustment to basis while he or she held the property.nIn other words, both the loss and gain on sale by the donee are minimized because the loss attributable to the donor at the time of the gift is lost by giving the property away.nnSince the gift had an FMV lower than its adjusted basis, Jerry uses the adjusted basis of the received property (i.e., $12,000) for computing the gain. Hence, the basis is $12,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(488,12,'You may be able to exclude your gain from the sale of a home that you have used for a business if you meet the ownership and use tests. You may be entitled to take depreciation deductions because you used your home for business purposes. What part of your gain may not be excluded?','[\"The part of the gain that is equal to any depreciation allowed as a deduction for periods after May 6, 1997\",\"The part of the gain that is equal to any depreciation allowed as a deduction for periods on or after May 6, 1997\",\"The part of the gain that is equal to any depreciation allowed as a deduction for periods before May 6, 1997\",\"All parts of the gain, including depreciation allowed, are excludable.\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary residence, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true (see Publication 523, page 3):nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home.nHowever, if the taxpayer was entitled to take depreciation deductions because the home was used for business purposes or as rental property, the taxpayer cannot exclude the part of the gain equal to any depreciation allowed as a deduction for periods after May 6, 1997. (Publication 523, page 15)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(489,12,'Charles gave his daughter, Jane, a residential house. He had purchased the house for $250,000 in 2010. The fair market value on the date of the gift was $300,000. Charles added a $25,000 roof the year before he gave it to Jane. Jane converts the house to a residential rental property within 1 year of the gift. Jane\'s basis in the property is:','[\"$300,000.\",\"$250,000.\",\"$225,000.\",\"$275,000.\"]',3,'A taxpayer\'s basis is the amount of a taxpayer\'s investment in property for tax purposes. The basis of property that is received as a gift is the same as the donor\'s adjusted basis at the time of gift if the fair market value of the property is equal to or greater than the donor\'s adjusted basis. Therefore, Jane\'s basis in the property received from Charles is $275,000, which is calculated as the sum of the adjusted basis to Charles on the date of the gift of $250,000 and the additional cost for the roof of $25,000. (Publication 551, page 9)nnPublication 551, page 10 provides that if the property is converted from personal to business, the basis is the lesser of the following two amounts:nnThe FMV of the property on the date of the conversionnThe adjusted basis on the date of the conversionnIn this case, we must assume that the adjusted basis of the gifted property is less than the FMV on the date of conversion since information to the contrary is not provided. Therefore, Jane\'s basis in the property is $275,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(490,12,'Rudy purchased 100 shares of publicly traded stock January 2, 2024, for $1,000. He sold all his shares December 31, 2024, for $1,500. On January 4, 2025, the settlement date, the stocks were actually delivered, and payment received in Rudy\'s account. How and when should Rudy report this sale?','[\"$500 long-term capital gain on 2024 return\",\"$500 short-term capital gain on 2024 return\",\"$500 long-term capital gain on 2025 return\",\"$500 short-term capital gain on 2026 return\"]',1,'In this problem, Rudy recognizes a gain of $500, which is the difference between the cash received of $1,500 and the adjusted basis of $1,000. The next issue is whether the capital gain or loss was a short-term or long-term capital gain or loss. (See Publication 550, page 80.)nnIf the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. (See Publication 550, page 80.)nnWhen stocks and bonds are bought on a securities market, the holding period begins on the day after the trading date that the taxpayer bought the security, and it ends on the trading date that the taxpayer sold the security. The settlement date is the date by which the stock must be delivered, and payment must be made. (See Publication 550, page 80.)nnIn this case, the holding period for Rudy began on January 3 and ended on December 31, which is less than 1 year. Hence, Rudy has a short-term capital gain of $500.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(491,12,'Joe and Jean purchased their primary residence in 2008 for $100,000. While they lived there, they made renovations at a cost of $125,000. They lived there until July 1, 2021. On June 15, 2024, the residence was sold for $800,000. From July 1, 2021, until June 15, 2024, the home was unoccupied. Joe and Jean file a joint return, and they have never excluded a gain from the sale of another home. What is their maximum taxable gain?','[\"$575,000\",\"$0\",\"$75,000\",\"$200,000\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, pages 3–4)nBe aware that there are some exceptions in this area, which are covered more thoroughly in Publication 523, pages 3 through 6.nnIn this problem, the taxpayers satisfy the special rule for excluding $500,000 of gain from the sale of a taxpayer\'s main home. Thus, the gain from the sale is $75,000, which is the amount received of $800,000 less the property\'s basis of $225,000 ($100,000 + $125,000), less the exclusion amount of $500,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(492,12,'Carol provided services in 2019 to Bragg Corporation. Her service contract with Bragg Corporation listed her fee at $50,000 receivable in cash and/or stock. At the time her fee was due Bragg Corporation stock was trading for $1,000 per share. Carol elected to receive $30,000 in cash and 20 shares of Bragg Corporation stock. In 2021, the Bragg Corporation stock split, increasing the number of Carol\'s shares to 40. In 2024, Carol sold 20 shares of her Bragg Corporation stock for $1,500 per share. What is Carol\'s basis in the Bragg Corporation shares she still owns?','[\"$10,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$30,000\",\"$40,000\"]',0,'The basis of stocks or bonds is generally the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. If stocks are not acquired through direct purchase, the basis is usually determined by the fair market value (FMV) or the previous owner\'s adjusted basis of the stock. Moreover, adjustments must be made to the basis for certain events that occur after purchase. Specific to this question, if more stock is received from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, the basis of the original stock is reduced.nnNote: See “Stocks and Bonds” in Chapter 4 of Publication 550 for more information on the basis of stock.nnAs a result, Carol\'s basis in the Bragg Corporation shares she still owns is $10,000, calculated as:nn  Cost of stock             $20,000 (FMV; 20 shares at $1,000)n  Divided byn   number of shares owned   /    40 (20 shares x 2 (for stock split))n  Basis in stock            $   500 per sharenRemaining shares (20) = $10,000 bases (with a unit basis of $500 per share)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(493,12,'Milton spent $70,000 for a building that he used in his business. He made improvements at a cost of $20,000 and deducted depreciation of $10,000. He sold the building for $100,000 cash, and received property having a fair market value of $20,000. The buyer assumed Milton\'s real estate taxes of $3,000 and a mortgage of $17,000 on the building. Selling expenses were $4,000. The gain on the sale is:','[\"$10,000.\",\"$56,000.\",\"$40,000.\",\"$52,000.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 550, pages 65 and 66, the gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnIf the amount realized from a sale or trade is more than the adjusted basis of the property the taxpayer transferred, the difference is a gain, andnIf the adjusted basis of the property transferred is more than the amount realized, the difference is a loss.nThe adjusted basis of property is the original cost or other original basis properly adjusted (increased or decreased) for certain items. See chapter Publication 551, pages 4 through 7, for more information about determining the adjusted basis of property.nnThe amount realized from a sale or trade of property is everything received for the property. This includes the money received plus the fair market value of any property or services received.nnIn this problem, Milton has an adjusted basis of $80,000, which is the cost of $70,000 plus the improvements of $20,000 less the depreciation of $10,000. The amount realized is $136,000, which is the cash of $100,000 plus the property with an FMV of $20,000, plus the taxes paid by the buyer of $3,000, plus the assumed mortgage by the buyer of $17,000, less the selling expenses of $4,000. As a result, the gain on the sale is $56,000 ($136,000 − $80,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(494,12,'John bought his principal residence for $250,000 on May 3, 2023. He sold it on May 3, 2024, for $400,000. What is the amount and character of his gain?','[\"Long-term, ordinary gain of $650,000\",\"Long-term, capital gain of $150,000\",\"Short-term, ordinary gain of $650,000\",\"Short-term, capital gain of $150,000\"]',3,'Pages 15 and 16 of Publication 523 provides that the gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary residence, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 3, page 523)nSince John did not hold the residence for 2 years, these exclusion rules do not apply. Hence, John has a gain to recognize. The question to be answered now is the type of gain: short term or long term.nnIf the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss (Publication 523, pages 15–16).nnTo determine how long the taxpayer held the investment property, begin counting on the date after the day the taxpayer acquired the property (trade date, not settlement date, for securities traded on an established market). The day the taxpayer disposes of the property is part of the holding period.nnNote: Although this is the rule for counting days, a simple rule to count either the day of purchase or the date of sale but not both.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer did not satisfy the special rule for excluding $250,000 and he did not hold the residence for more than 1 year. Thus, the gain from the sale is $150,000, which is the amount received of $400,000 less the property\'s basis of $250,000, and it is short term.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(495,12,'Emily bought 50 shares of stock in 2022 for $500. In 2023, she received a return of capital of $100. She received an additional return of capital of $50 in 2024. What must Emily report as long-term capital gain on her tax return for 2024?','[\"$150\",\"$50\",\"$100\",\"$0\"]',3,'A nondividend distribution is a distribution that is not paid out of the earnings and profits of a corporation. The taxpayer should receive a Form 1099-DIV showing the nondividend distribution (also referred to as a nontaxable distribution).nnA nondividend distribution is treated as a return of capital; it reduces the basis of the taxpayer\'s stock. Hence, it is not taxed at the time received but rather when the stock is sold. Moreover, return of capital distributions continue to be nontaxable until the taxpayer\'s basis in the stock is fully recovered. Once the basis is reduced to zero, any additional return of capital that is received by the taxpayer is treated as a capital gain. The reporting of the capital gain as long-term or short-term capital gain depends on how long the taxpayer held the stock. See Publication 550, pages 30–31, for more discussion of this topic.nnIn this case, the return of capital amounts of $150 ($100 and $50) is less than the adjusted basis ($500) that Emily has in the stock. Hence, Emily has no taxable income and her basis is reduced to $350 after the return of capital.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(496,12,'Mr. Smith and Mr. Jones own competing greenhouses. Mr. Smith has decided to focus exclusively on flower plants and Mr. Jones exclusively on vegetable plants. They agree to swap Mr. Smith\'s inventory of vegetable plants for Mr. Jones\' inventory of flower plants. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"This transaction is a like-kind exchange.\",\"This transaction is a like-kind exchange because the fair market value of the vegetable plants equals the fair market value of the flower plants.\",\"This transaction is\\u00a0not\\u00a0a like-kind exchange because the fair market value of the vegetable plants equals the fair market value of the flower plants.\",\"This transaction is\\u00a0not\\u00a0a like-kind exchange.\"]',3,'Beginning after December 31, 2017, section 1031 like-kind exchange treatment applies only to exchanges of real property held for use in a trade or business or for investment, other than real property held primarily for sale. (Instructions for Form 8824, page 1)nnGenerally, if you exchange business or investment real property solely for business or investment real property of a like kind, section 1031 provides that no gain or loss is recognized. If, as part of the exchange, you also receive other (not like-kind) property or money, gain is recognized to the extent of the other property and money received, but a loss isn\'t recognized.nnIn this case, the investments of flower plants are stock in trade and as such are not real property and do not qualify for like-kind treatment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(497,12,'Which of the following is the depreciable basis in rental property that is placed in service after receiving it as a gift, if the donor\'s basis was less than the fair market value of the property?','[\"The fair market value on the date of the gift plus or minus any required adjustments to basis\",\"The fair market value of the property on the date you converted it to rental property\",\"The donor\'s basis of the property plus or minus any required adjustments to basis\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 551, page 9, provides that if \"the FMV (fair market value) of the property at the time of the gift is less than the donor\'s adjusted basis, your basis depends on whether you have a gain or a loss when you dispose of the property. Your basis for figuring gain is the same as the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustment to basis while you held the property. Your basis for figuring loss is its FMV when you received the gift plus or minus any required adjustment to basis while you held the property. If you use the donor\'s adjusted basis for figuring a gain and get a loss, and then use the FMV for figuring a loss and have a gain, you have neither a gain or loss on the sale or disposition of the property.\"nnIf a gift is converted from personal use to business use; the depreciable basis is the lower of the fair market value or the adjusted basis on the date of conversion.nnTherefore, the depreciable basis in rental property received as a gift in this question would be the donor\'s basis in the property plus or minus any applicable adjustments.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(498,12,'During 2024, Jack sold 500 shares of stock. On December 31, 2024, he received a capital gain distribution of $750 from his mutual fund. He owned his mutual fund shares since June 30, 2023. How should Jack report the capital gain distribution on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$750 short-term capital gain\",\"$750 long-term capital gain\",\"$0\",\"$750 ordinary dividend\"]',1,'Publication 550, pages 30–31, provides, in part, that a capital gain distribution (also called capital gain dividends) is paid to a taxpayer or credited to the taxpayer\'s account by mutual funds or REITs. The gains are shown in box 2a of the Form 1099-DIV that is received by the taxpayer.nnIn addition, these gains are reported as long-term capital gains regardless of how long the taxpayer owned the shares in the mutual fund or REIT.nnSince Jack received a capital gain distribution, the $750 is treated as a long-term capital gain from the transaction. It does not matter how long he owned the investment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(499,12,'Which of the following is not necessary for a taxpayer to claim a nonbusiness bad debt deduction?','[\"To have a basis in the debt\",\"To be totally worthless\",\"To go to court\",\"To be a genuine debt\"]',2,'If money owed to a taxpayer becomes uncollectible in a given tax year, the taxpayer may have an allowable deduction for bad debt. To be deductible, nonbusiness bad debts must be totally worthless. A person cannot deduct a partly worthless nonbusiness debt.nnThe bad debt must arise from a genuine debt, which is one that arises from a debtor-creditor relationship based on a valid and enforceable obligation to repay a fixed or determinable sum of money.nnIn addition, the taxpayer must have a basis in the loan. That is, the taxpayer must have already included the amount in income or loaned-out cash.nnIt is not necessary, however, to go to court to show that a judgment from the court would be uncollectible. The taxpayer must only show that he or she has taken reasonable steps to collect the debt. Bankruptcy of the debtor is generally good evidence of the worthlessness of at least a part of an unsecured and unpreferred debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(500,12,'The cost basis of rental property includes:','[\"fees paid to the settlement attorney.\",\"recording fees and transfer taxes.\",\"real estate taxes paid to the seller without reimbursement.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 551, page 2, states, in part, that the cost basis of property purchased by a taxpayer usually is its cost. The cost, however, includes the amount the taxpayer pays in cash, debt obligations, other property, or services. In addition, the cost includes amounts the taxpayer pays for:nnsales tax,nfreight,ninstallation and testing,nexcise taxes,nlegal and accounting fees (when they must be capitalized),nrevenue stamps,nrecording fees, ornreal estate taxes (if assumed for the seller).nIn addition, the basis of real estate and business assets may include other items such as settlement fees and closing costs.nnIn this situation, all the items listed are included in the cost basis of rental property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(501,12,'In 2024, Billy\'s father deeded him 400 acres of land. The fair market value (FMV) on the date of the transfer was $350,000. His father had paid $40,000 for the land. No gift tax was paid on the transfer. When Billy\'s father died 6 months later, the fair market value of the land was $400,000. What is Billy\'s basis in the 400 acres?','[\"$400,000\",\"$350,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$260,000\"]',2,'In general, a taxpayer that receives property as a gift needs to know the property\'s adjusted basis to the donor just before it was received, its FMV at the time it was received, and any gift tax paid on it in order to determine the property\'s basis.nnAs provided in Publication 551 on page 9, if the FMV of the property is equal to or greater than the donor\'s adjusted basis, the donee\'s basis is the donor\'s adjusted basis at the time the donee received the gift. The basis in the gifted property also is increased by all or part of any gift tax paid, depending on the date of the gift. See Publication 551, page 9, for a discussion on the gift tax adjustment for gifts received before 1977 or after 1976.nnIn this problem, Billy received the land (nondepreciable property) from his father prior to the father\'s death and it had an FMV that exceeded his father\'s adjusted basis. Billy, therefore, would have an adjusted basis in the land of $40,000, which is the same as his father.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(502,12,'Larry purchased stock in 2022 for $100. During 2023, he received a return of capital of $80 on this stock. During 2024, he received another return of capital of $30. Larry had no other stock transactions in 2024. What amount should he report on his 2024 income tax return and what is his basis in the stock at the end of 2024?','[\"$30 capital gain, $100 stock basis\",\"$30 dividend income, $100 stock basis\",\"$10 capital gain, zero stock basis\",\"$10 dividend income, zero stock basis\"]',2,'Publication 550, pages 30–31, states, in part, that a non-dividend distribution (also known as a return of capital distribution) is a distribution that is not paid out of the earnings and profits of a corporation. It is a return of the investor\'s investment in the stock of the company. In such a case, the taxpayer should receive a Form 1099-DIV or other statement from the corporation showing what part of the distribution is a return of capital. On 2024 Form 1099-DIV, a nontaxable return of capital will be shown in box 3.nnA nondividend distribution (i.e., a return of capital reduces the basis of the taxpayer\'s stock. It is not taxed until the basis in the stock is fully recovered. If the taxpayer buys stock in a corporation in different lots at different times, and the taxpayer cannot definitely identify the shares subject to the return of capital, the taxpayer should reduce the basis of the earliest purchases first.nnFurthermore, when the basis of the stock has been reduced to zero, report any additional return of capital that the taxpayer receives as a capital gain. Whether the taxpayer reports it as a long-term or short-term capital gain depends on how long the taxpayer has held the stock.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nYou bought stock in 2021 for $100. In 2023, you received a return of capital of $80. You did not include this amount in your income, but you reduced the basis of your stock to $20. You received a return of capital of $30 in 2024. The first $20 of this amount reduced your basis to zero. You report the other $10 as a long-term capital gain for 2024. You must report as a long-term capital gain any return of capital you receive on this stock in later years.nn n nnIn this case, Larry has a basis of $20 ($100 less $80) after the nontaxable distribution of $80 in 2023. The $30 distribution by the company in 2024 results in a further basis reduction of $20 and a $10 long-term capital gain, which is the excess over basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(503,12,'In 2023, Tony received a gift of 200 shares of mutual funds stock. The stock was worth $20,000 when Tony received it. The donor had originally paid $10,000 for the stock when he bought it in 2019. Tony sold the stock for $15,000 in 2024. What is Tony\'s basis in the stock, disregarding gift tax?','[\"$0\",\"$20,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$15,000\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property.nnPublication 551, page 9, states, in part, that if the fair market value (FMV) of the property received from a donor is equal to or greater than donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis is the donor\'s adjusted basis at the time of the gift. Since the gift had an FMV greater than its adjusted basis, Tony uses the adjusted basis of the received property (i.e., $10,000) as his adjusted basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(504,12,'Jasmine purchased and moved into a home in 2016. She lived in the home until the middle of 2018, when she deployed and was on qualified official extended duty with the Navy. She sold the home in 2024 after returning from active duty and realized a gain of $325,000. What amount may Jasmine exclude?','[\"$0\",\"$83,333\",\"$250,000\",\"$325,000\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary residence, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true (see Publication 523, page 4):nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home.nThere are some exceptions in this area, one of which applies to Jasmine. The 5-year test period for ownership and use can be suspended during any period that a taxpayer or spouse serves on “qualified official extended duty” as a member of the uniformed services or Foreign Service of the United States, as an employee of the intelligence community, or as an employee or volunteer of the Peace Corps. (Publication 523, page 4)nnIn this case, Jasmine would suspend the time that she was on qualified official extended duty, and thus she disregards the time away. Hence, the 5-year period consists of the 5 years before she deployed. Since she is single, however, Jasmine can only exclude $250,000 of the gain.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(505,12,'Mildred and John (spouses) purchased 40 acres of undeveloped land in 1999 for $120,000. They paid personal real estate taxes of $50,000, which they elected to add to the property\'s basis. They sold the property for $600,000, having total settlement costs of $70,000. The settlement costs are allowable as an expense of sale. Mildred and John received a down payment of $100,000 with the balance to be paid over 15 years. What is their gross profit percentage?','[\"60%\",\"72%\",\"68.33%\",\"82%\"]',0,'In the case of an installment sale, a certain percentage of each payment (after subtracting interest) is reported as installment sale income. This percentage is called the gross profit percentage and is figured by dividing the taxpayer\'s gross profit from the sale by the contract price. The gross profit percentage generally remains the same for each payment you receive. (Publication 537, page 4)nnTo figure the adjusted basis and gross profit percentage for an installment sale, the following worksheet (see Publication 537, page 3) is used:nn1. Enter the selling price for the property.                1._____n2. Enter your adjusted basis for the property.    2._____n3. Enter your selling expenses.                   3._____n4. Enter any depreciation recapture.              4._____n5. Add lines 2, 3, and 4. This is your adjustedn   basis for installment sale purposes.                     5._____n6. Subtract line 5 from line 1. If zero or less,n   enter -0-.                                               6._____n   This is your gross profit.n   If the amount entered on line 6 is zero, Stopn   here. You cannot use the installment method.n7. Enter the contract price for the property.               7._____n8. Divide line 6 by line 7. This is your grossn   profit percentage.                                       8._____nIn this problem, Mildred and John sell their property for $600,000 (item 1), and the property has an adjusted basis for installment sale purposes of $240,000, which is the sum of $170,000 (item 2) and selling expenses of $70,000 (item 3). Hence, the gross profit percentage is 60%, which is the gross profit of $360,000 ($600,000 − $170,000 − $70,000) divided by the selling price of $600,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(506,12,'Richard collected baseball cards as a hobby. Richard had shared his interest in this hobby with his niece Susan, who was also an avid card collector. At the time of his death in 2024, Richard\'s collection had a fair market value of $10,000 and an adjusted basis of $2,000, while Susan\'s collection had a fair market value of $5,000 and an adjusted basis of $1,000. Upon his death, Richard\'s entire card collection went to Susan. With the death of her uncle, Susan lost interest in the hobby and sold all of the cards for $20,000. What is Susan\'s gain on the sale of these baseball cards?','[\"$5,000\",\"$9,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$17,000\"]',1,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. As provided in Publication 551, pages 9–10, the basis of property that is received from a decedent is generally one of the following:nnThe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s deathnThe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuationnThe value under the special-use valuation method for real property used in farming or a closely held business if chosen for estate tax purposesnThe decedent\'s adjusted basis in land to the extent of the value excluded from the decedent\'s taxable estate as a qualified conservation easementnIf a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance or transmission taxes.nnIn this problem, the gain on the sale for Susan is $9,000, which is the selling price of $20,000 less the adjusted basis of $11,000 ($10,000 on the inherited cards and $1,000 on Susan\'s cards).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(507,12,'Yousef and Ramina (spouses) purchased 10 shares of stocks in Yam Company on August 31, 2023, for $850. They sold 25 shares of stock in Tray Company for $900 on April 10, 2024. They had purchased the 25 Tray Company shares in 2013 for $100. They also sold 20 shares of stock of Delta Company on December 1, 2024, for $500. They had purchased the 20 Delta Company shares in 2022 for $4,500. Yousef and Ramina\'s taxable income on their joint 2024 return was $33,000 before these stock transactions. Assume that Yousef and Ramina had no other capital transactions in 2024. What is Yousef and Ramina\'s currently deductible capital loss for 2024 and what is their capital loss carryover to the next year?','[\"They can deduct $3,200 in long-term capital loss and carry over a capital loss of $800.\",\"They can deduct $4,000 in long-term capital loss.\",\"They can deduct $3,000 in long-term capital loss and carry over a capital loss of $200.\",\"They can deduct $500 in long-term capital loss.\"]',2,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property (Publication 550, page 65):nnIf the amount realized from a sale or trade is more than the adjusted basis of the property that the taxpayer transfers, the difference is a gain.nIf the adjusted basis of the property that the taxpayer transfers is more than the amount realized, the difference is a loss.nIf a taxpayer\'s capital losses exceed the capital gains, the taxpayer can claim a capital loss deduction (not a basis reduction). However, it should be remembered that the allowable capital loss deduction is the lesser of (1) $3,000 ($1,500 if married and filing a separate return) or (2) the total net loss. See Publication 550, page 100, for more details on this topic.nnYousef and Ramina have a $4,000 ($500 − $4,500) long-term capital loss from the Delta stock sale and an $800 ($900 − $100) long-term capital gain from the Tray stock sale. As a result, the total capital loss for 2024 is $3,200 ($4,000 − $800), which is deductible as $3,000 in long-term capital loss and a capital loss carryover of $200.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(508,12,'Which of the following statements is correct if property is repossessed after making an installment sale?','[\"The taxpayer must recognize any gain resulting from the repossession.\",\"The taxpayer must recognize any loss resulting from the repossession.\",\"The taxpayer must recognize any gain (or loss) resulting from the repossession.\",\"The taxpayer does\\u00a0not\\u00a0recognize any gain (or loss) resulting from the repossession.\"]',2,'When a taxpayer repossesses property after making an installment sale, the taxpayer must figure the following amounts: gain (or loss) on the repossession and basis in the repossessed property. The rules for figuring these amounts depend on the kind of property repossessed. The rules for repossessions of personal property differ from those for real property. (Publication 537, pages 12–15)n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(509,12,'Connor purchased Flora stock in 2018 and sold it in 2024. In 2024, he also traded in a copy machine that he had been using in his business since 2020 for a new model. On December 15, 2024, he inherited 35 shares of Fauna Laboratories stock. What is the holding period for these properties?','[\"All short term\",\"Flora stock long term, copy machine and Fauna stock short term\",\"Flora and Fauna stock long term; copy machine short term\",\"All long term\"]',3,'The holding period for a capital asset is the length of time the property was owned before it is disposed of by sale or exchange. Holding periods are categorized as “short term” or “long term.” In determining the holding period, the taxpayer begins counting on the day after the property was acquired.nnIf a taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If a taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss. (Publication 550, page 80)nnAssets that are inherited are considered to meet the long-term holding period requirements. (Publication 550, page 80)nnGiven that Connor purchased the Flora stock in 2018 and held it until 2024, clearly more than 12 months, the holding period would be characterized as long term. The copy machine that was purchased in 2020 and held until 2024 was also held for more than 12 months; therefore, the holding period would be long term. Since the inherited shares of Fauna Laboratories stock are considered to meet the long-term holding requirements, the stock is regarded as long term, regardless when Connor sells the stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(510,12,'John is a furniture maker and carpenter. He makes half of his income as an employee of Concept Designs, Inc., a fine furniture manufacturing corporation. John makes the other half of his income from a personal business where he purchases, renovates, and then resells houses. In January 2024, John purchased a house that is not his residence for $50,000. He spends $10,000 in materials renovating the house, which he sells in November 2024 for $90,000. What is the amount and character of John\'s gain from this transaction?','[\"$20,000 ordinary gain\",\"$30,000 short-term capital gain\",\"$30,000 ordinary gain\",\"$20,000 short-term capital gain\"]',2,'Publication 550, pages 65 and 66, provides that the gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In this case, John has a gain on the sale of the property of $30,000, which is the difference between the selling price of $90,000 and the adjusted basis of $60,000 ($50,000 purchase price plus $10,000 renovation costs).nnThe next issue is to determine the character of the gain; is it capital or ordinary? Generally, a sale or trade of a capital asset (defined below) results in a capital gain or loss. A sale or trade of a noncapital asset generally results in ordinary gain or loss.nnFor the most part, everything you own and use for personal purposes, pleasure, or investment is a capital asset. A noncapital asset, on the other hand, is property that is not a capital asset.nnThe following kinds of property are not capital assets: property held mainly for sale to customers or property that will physically become part of merchandise for sale to customers. This includes stock in trade, inventory, and other property you hold mainly for sale to customers in your trade or business. (Publication 550, pages 73–13)nAs given above, John sells property that is held mainly for sale to customers in his trade or business, which means the gain of $30,000 is treated as ordinary income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(511,12,'What is an individual\'s basis in inherited property if a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed?','[\"The property\'s alternate valuation date\",\"The property\'s adjusted basis to the decedent at the date of death\",\"The property\'s fair market value at the date of death\",\"The property\'s fair market value at the date of death\"]',2,'Publication 551, pages 9 and 10, states, in part, that a taxpayer\'s basis in property that he or she inherits is usually its fair market value (FMV) at the date of the decedent\'s death. If a federal estate tax return (Form 706) has to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property can be its FMV at the alternate valuation date if the estate qualifies and the personal representative elects to use alternate valuation. Hence, this valuation date can be elected only if an estate tax return is being filed.nnIf a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, then the taxpayer\'s basis in the property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance or transmission taxes.nnThe FMV (not the adjusted basis) at the date of death of the decedent is usually the basis for inherited property. It does not matter if an estate tax return is required to be filed or not. The property\'s alternate valuation date is relevant only if the personal representative makes such an election and, if so, an estate tax return is being filed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(512,12,'Zack had the following capital transactions during 2024:nn2/1/2024—bought 10 shares of ABC stock at $100 per sharen6/1/2024—sold 100 shares of PDQ stock for $50 per share; was purchased 2/1/2023 at $100 per sharen9/9/2024—sold the 10 shares of ABC stock for $150 per sharenHow much can Zack deduct as a capital loss on his return for 2024? (His taxable income is $30,000.)','[\"$4,500 net long-term capital loss; $0 carryover\",\"$3,000 net long-term capital loss; $1,500 long-term capital loss carryover to 2025\",\"$0 net gain or loss; $4,500 long-term capital loss carryover to 2025\",\"$3,000 net short-term capital loss; $1,500 short-term capital loss carryover to 2025\"]',1,'If the taxpayer holds investment property for more than 1 year, any capital gain or loss is a long-term capital gain or loss. If the taxpayer holds the property 1 year or less, any capital gain or loss is a short-term capital gain or loss.nnWhen stocks and bonds are bought on a securities market, the holding period begins on the day after the trading date that the taxpayer bought the security and it ends on the trading date that the taxpayer sold the security (Publication 550, page 80).nnIn this case, the ABC stock transaction is a gain of $500, which is the difference between the selling price of $1,500 (10 shares × $150) and adjusted basis of $1,000 (10 shares × $100). Moreover, the gain is short term because it was held for less than 1 year (bought on February 1 and sold on September 9 of the same year). Secondly, the PDQ stock produces a loss of $5,000, which is the difference between the selling price of $5,000 (100 shares × $50) and adjusted basis of $10,000 (100 shares × $100). Moreover, the loss is long-term because the stock was held for more than 1 year (bought on February 1 of 1 year and sold on June 1 of the following year).nnPages 97 to 101 of Publication 550 discuss the reporting of gains and losses. In particular, if a taxpayer\'s capital losses are more than the capital gains, the taxpayer can claim a capital loss deduction, which is reported on Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR and enclosed in parentheses.nnThe capital loss deduction, however, has an annual limit that is the lesser of:nn$3,000 ($1,500 if you are married and file a separate return) ornthe taxpayer\'s total net loss as shown on line 16 of Schedule D.nIn this case, Zack has a net long-term capital loss of $4,500 ($5,000 − $500) for the year. Zack would claim the annual limit of $3,000 as a net long-term capital loss and would carry forward the remaining $1,500 long-term capital loss to the following year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(513,12,'Anne, who is single, owned and used her house as her main home from January 2019 until January 2023. She then moved away and rented her home from February 2023 until she sold it in August 2024 While it was rented, it accumulated $20,000 in depreciation. Anne paid $12,000 in selling expenses when she sold the house for $240,000. Using a zero basis, compute the amount that is excludable from income.','[\"$208,000\",\"$220,000\",\"$228,000\",\"$240,000\"]',0,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true.nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., own the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 3)nIn this problem, the taxpayer satisfies the special rule for excluding $250,000. However, if the taxpayer was entitled to take depreciation deductions because the home was used for business purposes or as rental property, the taxpayer cannot exclude the part of the gain equal to any depreciation allowed as a deduction for periods after May 6, 1997. (Publication 523, page 15)nnThus, the gain from the sale that is excludable is $208,000, which is the amount realized (amount received of $240,000 less property\'s basis of $0, the depreciation taken of $20,000, and the selling expenses of $12,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(514,12,'Elton declared bankruptcy in the current year. Included in the liabilities discharged in the bankruptcy was a $15,000 personal loan Elton had received from his friend, Edward, 2 years ago. How would Edward treat this for tax purposes?','[\"Ordinary loss on Form 4797\",\"Long-term capital loss on Schedule D\",\"Short-term capital loss on Form 8949\",\"Investment expense subject to 2% miscellaneous itemized deduction limitation\"]',2,'If money owed to a taxpayer becomes uncollectible in a given tax year, the taxpayer may have an allowable deduction for bad debt. The bad debt must arise from a debtor-creditor relationship based on a valid and enforceable obligation to repay a fixed or determinable sum of money.nnThose bad debts incurred outside of operating a business or trade are categorized as nonbusiness bad debt and are deductible when deemed totally worthless (not partially worthless). Nonbusiness bad debts are deducted as a short-term capital loss on Form 8949, which is carried over to Schedule D (Form 1040). (Publication 550, page 54, and Form 8949)nnPublication 550, page 66, further provides that short-term capital losses are subject to a $3,000 ($1,500 for married filing separate) allowable capital loss per year deduction limitation.nnGiven that Elton included in his bankruptcy declaration the $15,000 loan that he received from Edward, a friend, and assuming that this transaction meets the requirements of a genuine debt, Edward may deduct the uncollected monies as a short-term capital loss on Form 8949.nnNote: This is another example of a nonbusiness bad debt where it is unclear whether a genuine debtor-creditor relationship exists. Since there is no correct response if we assume there is no genuine debtor-creditor relationship, we are forced, in this case, to assume that one exists.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(515,12,'In 2018, Joan sold land for $100,000 that had cost $50,000. She received a down payment of $30,000 with the balance to be amortized over 10 years with interest of 8%. In 2024, Joan had to repossess the property due to the failure of the buyer to make payments. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Joan has\\u00a0no\\u00a0tax consequences, as she now owns the land.\",\"Joan has gift tax consequences, as she has forgiven the debt owed to her.\",\"Joan must figure the gain or loss on the repossession and has a basis or $50,000.\",\"Joan must figure the gain or loss as well as the basis as a result of the repossession.\"]',3,'Publication 537, pages 12–13, deals with repossessed property. In particular, the publication states that if a taxpayer repossesses his or her property after making an installment sale, the taxpayer must figure the gain (or loss) on the repossession and the basis in the repossessed property.nnThe rules for figuring these amounts depend on the kind of property that the taxpayer repossesses. That is, the rules for repossessions of personal property differ from those for real property. In addition, the repossession rules apply whether or not title to the property was ever transferred to the buyer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(516,12,'Generally, if you own stock in a small corporation that meets the requirements of Section 1244 (small business) stock and you sell that stock at a loss, the loss is reported as:','[\"short-term loss on Form 8949 limited to $3,000.\",\"ordinary loss on Form 4797 limited to $25,000 for a single individual and limited to $50,000 for those filing a joint return.\",\"long-term loss on Form 8949 limited to $3,000.\",\"ordinary loss on Form 4797 limited to $50,000 for a single individual and limited to $100,000 for those filing a joint return.\"]',3,'If a taxpayer sustains a loss on the sale, exchange, or worthlessness of small corporation stock that meets the requirements of Section 1244, they may take an ordinary loss deduction. The taxpayer would report the loss on Form 4797, line 10. Any loss in excess of the amounts described in the \"Ordinary Loss Limit\" paragraph of Publication 550 (page 52) is reported on Form 8949.nnAs discussed in the \"Ordinary Loss Limit\" paragraph, the maximum deduction permitted for such losses is $50,000 ($100,000 married filing jointly even if only one spouse has this type of loss). The loss is reported on line 10 on Form 4797. In the case where the taxpayer has a loss of $110,000 and the taxpayer\'s spouse has no loss, the taxpayer is able to take a loss of $100,000 on a joint return.nnAny losses in excess of the $50,000 ($100,000 married filing jointly) are reported as capital losses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(517,12,'In 2020, Mr. Chang purchased 50 shares of common stock in Corporation D for $1,000. In 2022, Corporation D declared a stock dividend of 2 shares of its common stock for each 10 shares held. In 2024, D\'s common stock split 2-for-1 at a time when the fair market value was $20 a share. What is Mr. Chang\'s basis in each of his shares of D\'s stock (rounded to the nearest dollar) if both distributions were tax-free and all the stock received was identical to the stock purchased?','[\"$20 for 100 shares and $0 for all additional shares\",\"$8 per share\",\"$17 for 60 shares and $20 for 60 shares\",\"$20 per share\"]',1,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as stock options) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire the corporation\'s stock. Generally, stock dividends and stock rights are not taxable and therefore are not reportable. (Publication 550, page 21)nnThe basis of stocks or bonds generally is the purchase price plus any costs of purchase, such as commissions and recording or transfer fees. The basis of the stock is adjusted for certain events that occur after purchase. For example, if the person receives additional stock from nontaxable stock dividends or stock splits, divide the adjusted basis of the old stock by the number of shares of old and new stock. This rule applies only when the additional stock received is identical to the stock held. Likewise, the basis is reduced when nontaxable distributions are received because they are a return of capital (Publication 550, pages 30–31).nnIn this problem, Mr. Chang\'s basis in Corporation D stock prior to the stock dividend is $1,000 (50 shares × $20 per share). As a result of the first stock dividend of 2 shares for every 10 shares held, Mr. Chang receives 10 additional shares of stock (50 shares ÷ 10 = 5, which is multiplied by 2 for 10 additional shares). The basis of the stock after the stock dividend is reduced to $16.67 per share ($1,000 ÷ 60 shares). In 2019, the stock split doubles the number of shares held to 120 shares (60 × 2) and likewise splits the adjusted basis to $8.33 per share ($16.67 ÷ 2 or $1,000 ÷ 120 shares).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(518,12,'Which of the following statements is incorrect concerning the basis in property inherited from a decedent?','[\"It is generally the fair market value of the property at the alternate valuation date, if elected.\",\"It is generally the fair market value of the property at the date of the decedent\'s death.\",\"It is generally the same basis as the decedent\'s basis at the date of death.\",\"It is the appraisal value at the date of death for state inheritance if a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed.\"]',2,'Publication 551, pages 9 and 10, states that a taxpayer\'s basis in property inherited from a decedent is generally one of the following:nnthe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death,nthe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation,nthe value under the special-use valuation method for real property used in farming or a closely held business if chosen for estate tax purposes, ornthe decedent\'s adjusted basis in land to the extent of the value excluded from the decedent\'s taxable estate as a qualified conservation easement.nIn addition, if a federal estate tax return does not have to be filed, the taxpayer\'s basis in the inherited property is its appraised value at the date of death for state inheritance or transmission taxes.nnTherefore, it is incorrect to say that the basis in the inherited property is the same as the decedent\'s basis at the time of death. It may be, but it need not be the same.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(519,12,'Jim and Jean (spouses) purchased a vacation home in 2018 for $100,000. They sold the property for $500,000 in 2024 and received a down payment of $200,000. They took a mortgage from the purchaser for the remaining $300,000. What is Jim and Jean\'s gross profit percentage on this sale?','[\"40%\",\"60%\",\"80%\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'In the case of an installment sale, a certain percentage of each payment (after subtracting interest) is reported as installment sale income. This percentage is called the gross profit percentage and is figured by dividing the taxpayer\'s gross profit from the sale by the contract price. The gross profit percentage generally remains the same for each payment you receive. (Publication 537, page 4)nnTo figure the adjusted basis and gross profit percentage for an installment sale, the following worksheet (see Publication 537, Worksheet A, page 3) is used:nn1. Enter the selling price for the property.                   1._____n2. Enter your adjusted basis for the property.       2._____n3. Enter your selling expenses.                      3._____n4. Enter any depreciation recapture.                 4._____n5. Add lines 2, 3, and 4. This is your adjustedn   basis for installment sale purposes.                        5._____n6. Subtract line 5 from line 1. If zero or less,n   enter -0-.                                                  6._____n   This is your gross profit.n   If the amount entered on line 6 is zero, Stopn   here. You cannot use the installment method.n7. Enter the contract price for the property.                  7._____n8. Divide line 6 by line 7. This is your grossn   profit percentage.                                          8._____nIn this problem, Jim and Jean sell their vacation house for $500,000 (item 1), and the house has an adjusted basis for installment sale purposes of $100,000 (item 2), which is the cost of the property. The couple did not make any improvements to the property. There are no selling expenses for item 3. The gross profit percentage is 80%, which is the gross profit of $400,000 ($500,000 − $100,000) divided by the selling price of $500,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(520,12,'Mark owned 100% of the stock in Gathers Corporation. In 2024, Gathers Corporation sold a computer with an adjusted basis of $5,000 and a fair market value of $8,000 to Mark\'s Uncle Seth for $4,000. What is the amount of Gathers Corporation\'s deductible loss on the sale of this computer in 2024?','[\"$(4,000)\",\"$(3,000)\",\"$(1,000)\",\"$0\"]',2,'Publication 550, page 71, provides a list of related party transactions that do not result in a recognized loss on the transaction. In particular, a taxpayer cannot deduct a loss on the sale or trade of property, other than a distribution in complete liquidation of a corporation, if the transaction is directly or indirectly between the taxpayer and related parties. With respect to family members, a loss is not recognized if the transaction takes place between the taxpayer (in this case, Mark as sole owner of Gathers Corporation) and members of his family, which include only the taxpayer\'s brothers and sisters, half-brothers and half-sisters, spouse, ancestors (parents, grandparents, etc.), and lineal descendants (children, grandchildren, etc.). Since this sale is between Mark and his uncle, the loss is recognized.nnThe gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. Hence, the loss in this problem is $1,000, which is the difference between $5,000 and $4,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(521,12,'Which of the following statements about stock options is correct?','[\"If a taxpayer satisfies the holding period requirement for an incentive stock option, the gain or loss is capital.\",\"The holding period for stock acquired by exercising an option granted under an employee stock purchase plan begins on the day the option is granted.\",\"If a taxpayer is granted a nonstatutory stock option, the taxpayer does not need to include income from the option even if the fair market value of the option is readily determinable.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Publication 525, pages 11 and 12, a nonstatutory stock option is treated like other property received as compensation by the taxpayer if the option has a readily determinable fair market value at the time it is granted.nnIn the case of an incentive stock option (ISO), if a taxpayer sells stock acquired by exercising an ISO and has satisfied the holding period requirement, the gain or loss from the sale is treated as a capital gain or loss. The sale is reported as explained in the instructions for Schedule D (Form 1040). The basis of the stock is the amount paid by the taxpayer for the stock.nnIf a taxpayer acquires stock by exercising an option granted under an employee stock purchase plan, their holding period for the property acquired begins on the day after the taxpayer exercises the option (not when the option was granted).nnHence, the correct response for this question is if a taxpayer satisfies the holding period requirement for an incentive stock option, the gain or loss is capital.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(522,12,'Ezekiel and Ruth, a married couple filing a joint return, sold their primary residence, which they purchased in 2020 for $250,000. They lived in the home for 4 years before selling it. The home was sold for $675,000. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The couple must report the gain of $175,000 on the sale of their home.\",\"The couple must report the sale because the home was sold for more than $500,000.\",\"The couple does\\u00a0not\\u00a0report the sale because although there is a gain on the sale of the primary residence, they qualify for the exclusion.\",\"The couple must report the sale because the home was sold for more than $500,000 and there was a gain to report.\"]',2,'The gain on the sale of the home is $425,000 ($675,000 − $250,000), which is less than the exclusion amount of $500,000 ($250,000 per spouse) for a primary residence that has been held for more than 2 out of the last 5 years.nnPublication 523, page 3, states that if the taxpayer sold his or her main home, the taxpayer may be able to exclude from income any gain up to a limit of $250,000 ($500,000 on a joint return in most cases). If the taxpayer can exclude all of the gain, the taxpayer does not need to report the sale on his or her tax return (Publication 523, page 15).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(523,12,'You sold a residential lot 2 years ago and reported the $20,000 capital gain on the installment method. In the 3rd year of payments, the buyer defaulted and you had to repossess the lot. In the 1st year you reported $5,000 ($10,000 × 50%) and $3,000 ($6,000 × 50%) in the 2nd year. No payments were received in the 3rd year and you spent $2,500 in legal fees to repossess the property. What is the taxable gain you must report on the repossession?','[\"$0\",\"$9,500\",\"$8,000\",\"$4,000\"]',2,'When a taxpayer repossesses property after making an installment sale, the taxpayer must figure the following amounts: gain (or loss) on the repossession and basis in the repossessed property. The rules for figuring these amounts depend on the kind of property repossessed. The rules for repossessions of personal property differ from those for real property. In addition, special rules may apply if the taxpayer repossesses property that was the taxpayer\'s main home before the sale. (Publication 537, page 12)nnThe rules for the repossession of real property allow the taxpayer to keep essentially the same adjusted basis in the repossessed property the taxpayer had before the original sale. That is, the taxpayer can recover this entire adjusted basis when the property is resold. This, in effect, cancels out the tax treatment that applied to the taxpayer on the original sale and puts the taxpayer in the same tax position as before the sale. (Publication 537, pages 13–14)nnPublication 537, page 14, provides Worksheet D, which is used to calculate the gain or loss resulting from repossession:nn1. Total payments received before repossession      $16,000n2. Total gain already reported as income              8,000n3. Difference between items 1 and 2                   8,000n4. Gross profit on the original sale                 20,000n5. Cost of repossession                               2,500n6. Sum of items 2 and 5                              10,500n7. Difference between items 6 and 4                   9,500n8. Lesser of items 3 and 7 is the taxable gain        8,000nAs a result of the repossession, the taxpayer in this problem would report an $8,000 gain on the repossession.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(524,12,'Ray, who is the principal owner of an engineering firm, several years ago loaned $2,000 to a friend to be repaid on demand with interest at 6%. No payments of interest or principal had been made when the friend declared bankruptcy and this loan was discharged. The accrued interest to date is $360. Ray files his tax returns on a cash basis. What amount can Ray write off as a nonbusiness bad debt?','[\"$0\",\"$360\",\"$2,000\",\"$2,360\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer may deduct the amount arising as a nonbusiness bad debt if it is totally worthless and is deducted on the tax return for the year the debt becomes worthless.nnThe debt, however, must be genuine for the taxpayer, which means it arises from a debtor-creditor relationship based on a valid and enforceable obligation to repay a fixed or determinable sum of money. (See Publication 550, page 83.)nnIn the case where a taxpayer lends money to a relative or friend with the understanding that it may or may not be repaid, it is considered a gift and not a loan, and as such, it cannot be taken as a bad debt deduction. See Publication 550, page 83, for more information on this topic.nnNote: What makes this problem difficult to respond to is determining whether a true debtor-creditor relationship exists. Since no mention of a signed document is given in the facts, one is left to assume that such a document does not exist.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(525,12,'Clyde, a single person, sold his principal residence for $700,000. He purchased his home in 2015 for $150,000 and lived there until he sold it in 2024. He paid for capital improvements of $75,000, paid real estate commissions of $36,000, and other settlement costs of $4,000. How much taxable gain must Clyde report?','[\"None\",\"$185,000\",\"$435,000\",\"$225,000\"]',1,'The gain or loss on a sale or trade of property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. In the case of a personal residence that is the primary one, a special rule applies whereby the taxpayer can exclude up to $250,000 per spouse of the gain on the sale of the main home if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer meets the ownership test (i.e., owned the home for at least 2 of the last 5 years)nThe taxpayer meets the use test (i.e., lived in the main home for at least 2 of the last 5 years).nDuring the 2-year period ending on the date of the sale, the taxpayer did not exclude gain from the sale of another home. (Publication 523, page 3)nIn this problem, the taxpayer presumably satisfies the special rule for excluding $250,000. Thus, the gain from the sale to Clyde is $185,000, which is the sale price of $700,000 less the property\'s basis of $150,000, less the capital improvements of $75,000, less the real estate commissions of $36,000, less other settlement costs of $4,000, and less the exclusion amount of $250,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(526,12,'Darryl received several acres of land from his father as a gift. At the time of the gift, the land had a fair market value of $85,000. The father\'s adjusted basis in the land was $105,000. Two years later, Darryl sold the land for $90,000. No events occurred that increased or decreased Darryl\'s basis in the land. What was Darryl\'s gain or (loss) on the sale of the land?','[\"$(15,000)\",\"$5,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$0\"]',3,'The basis of property received as a gift requires the recipient to know the property\'s adjusted basis to the donor, fair market value (FMV), and any gift tax paid by the donor. Once this information is known, the gain or loss on a sale or trade of the gifted property is found by comparing the amount realized with the adjusted basis of the property. If the FMV is less than the donor\'s adjusted basis, the basis depends on whether you have a gain or loss when you dispose of the property.nnPublication 551, page 9, states, in part, that if the FMV of the property received from a donor was less than the donor\'s adjusted basis, the taxpayer\'s basis for figuring:nngain on its sale or other disposition is the donor\'s adjusted basis plus or minus any required adjustment to basis while the taxpayer held the property, andnloss on its sale or other disposition is the FMV when the taxpayer received the gift plus or minus any required adjustment to basis while he or she held the property.nIn other words, both the loss and gain on sale by the donee are minimized because the loss attributable to the donor at the time of the gift is lost by giving the property away.nnSince the gift had an FMV lower than its basis, Darryl uses the adjusted basis of the received property (i.e., $105,000) for computing the gain, which is higher than the sale price of $90,000. On the other hand, he uses the FMV of the donor (i.e., $85,000) for computing the loss, which is lower than the sale price of $90,000. Because the sale price of the property is between the FMV and the adjusted basis, Darryl does not recognize any gains or losses from the sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(527,12,'Upon the death of her mother, Janice inherited a home. At the time of her mother\'s death, the fair market value of the home was $100,000. Her mother had purchased the home as a primary residence in 2006 at a cost of $35,000. What is the basis in the inherited property by Janice?','[\"$35,000\",\"$65,000\",\"$100,000\",\"Some other number\"]',2,'Publication 551, pages 9 and 10, states that a taxpayer\'s basis in property inherited from a decedent is generally one of the following:nnthe FMV of the property at the date of the individual\'s death,nthe FMV on the alternate valuation date if the personal representative for the estate chooses to use alternate valuation,nthe value under the special-use valuation method for real property used in farming or a closely held business if chosen for estate tax purposes, ornthe decedent\'s adjusted basis in land to the extent of the value excluded from the decedent\'s taxable estate as a qualified conservation easement.nAs a result, Janice\'s basis in the inherited property from her mother is $100,000, which is the FMV of the home at the time of her mother\'s death.nnThis question is somewhat tricky; it assumes that an estate tax return was not or did not need to be filed because no information is given to that effect. If an estate tax return was necessary, then Janice (or the personal representative) would have the option to elect the FMV on the alternate valuation date.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(528,3,'Which of the following conditions would not prevent an individual from qualifying for the earned income credit for the year 2024?n','[\"Married filing separately filing status\",\"Being a qualified child of another person\",\"Being age 27\",\"Investment income of $11,950\"]',2,'Table 1, which appears on page 2 of Publication 596, provides a capsule presentation on the qualification rules for the earned income credit.nnFrom the information given in Table 1, the only condition that would not prevent an individual from qualifying for the EIC is being age 25, which is the age requirement for a person without a qualifying child (see Rule 11). This appears in Chapter 3 of Table 1 (“Rules If You Do Not Have a Qualifying Child”).nnChapter 1 of Table 1 (“Rules for Everyone”) states that the filing status cannot be married filing separately (Rule 3). Chapter 1 (Rule 6) also states that your “investment income must be $11,000 or less.” Chapter 3 (Rule 13) of Table 1 (“Rules If You Do Not Have a Qualifying Child”) says that you “cannot be a qualifying child of another person.”',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(529,3,'Mr. and Mrs. Ramirez have adjusted gross income of $49,000 in 2024 and nontaxable combat pay of $8,500. The couple also has one qualifying child. What is the income amount used by the couple to qualify for the earned income tax credit?','[\"$8,500\",\"$49,000\",\"$37,500\",\"The couple does not qualify for the EIC.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 596, page 2, the earned income credit (EIC) is a tax credit for those taxpayers who work and have earned income below a threshold amount as provided in Table 1 (Publication 596, page 2). Earned income includes wages, salaries, tips, and other taxable employee pay. Nontaxable employee pay, such as certain dependent care benefits and adoption benefits, is not earned income.nnPursuant to Publication 596, page 18, a taxpayer may elect to include nontaxable combat pay in earned income when calculating the earned income credit in 2024.nnIn the Ramirez\'s case, they would not qualify for the EIC if they included the $8,500 of nontaxable combat pay. The threshold amount for a couple filing married with one qualifying child is $56,004 for 2024 and they would have an AGI of $57,500 ($49,000 + $8,500). (Publication 596, Table 1, page 2)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(530,3,'If you have a dependent that you cannot claim for the child tax credit, the dependent may still qualify you for which $500 credit?','[\"The Alternative Minimum Tax Credit\",\"That State and Local Income Tax Credit\",\"The Credit for Other Dependents\",\"The Credit for Foreign Dependents\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 111 provides, in part, that the other dependent credit (ODC) is a nonrefundable credit of up to $500 for each eligible dependent who can’t be claimed for the child tax credit.nnLike the child tax credit, the ODC has a threshold AGI amount of $400,000 in the case of a joint return and $200,000 in the case of all other taxpayers.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(531,3,'Thomas claimed the earned income credit (EIC) on his 2022 tax return, which was filed in March 2024. The IRS determined that he was not entitled to the EIC and that his error was due to reckless or intentional disregard of the EIC rules. In September 2024, he received a statutory notice of deficiency telling him an adjustment would be made and tax assessed unless he filed a petition with the Tax Court within 90 days. Thomas did not act on this notice within 90 days. Therefore, his EIC was denied in December 2024. Which of the following applies to Thomas?','[\"He can claim the EIC on his 2024 tax return if he attaches Form 8862.\",\"He cannot claim the EIC until he files his 2025 tax return, and only then if he attaches Form 8862.\",\"He cannot claim the EIC until he files his 2026 tax return, and only then if he attaches Form 8862.\",\"He cannot claim the EIC until he files his 2027 tax return, and only then if he attaches Form 8862.\"]',2,'If the IRS determined that a taxpayer was not entitled to the EIC and that the error was due to reckless or intentional disregard of the EIC rules, then they are unable to claim the credit for 2 years. The problem that can arise is the timing on the notification.nnIn this case, the taxpayer is not able to claim the EIC on his 2024 tax return because he received the notice of denial in December 2024, which is before he filed his 2024 tax return. Hence, he cannot claim the EIC for tax year 2024 or 2025. The taxpayer can, however, claim the EIC on his 2026 tax return, but only if he attaches Form 8862 to that return.nnThus, the penalty that the taxpayer has suffered is the loss of the tax credit for 2 years. In this case, Thomas cannot claim the EIC until he files his 2026 tax return, and only then if he attaches Form 8862.nnPublication 596 provides several timing examples on page 21.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(532,3,'Ginger is a United States citizen who paid the following 2024 foreign income taxes:nn$10,000 tax paid to England on consulting fee incomen$5,000 tax paid to Spain on earned income for which she claimed the foreign earned income exclusionn$1,000 tax paid to France which she deducted as an itemized deductionnThese were Ginger\'s only sources of income during 2024. Her U.S. tax liability was $23,000. What amount of foreign tax credit can she claim on her 2024 return?','[\"$16,000\",\"$0\",\"$10,000\",\"$7,000\"]',1,'Publication 54, page 23, provides, in part, that a taxpayer can take either a credit or a deduction for income taxes paid to a foreign country or a U.S. possession. Taken as a deduction, foreign income taxes reduce a taxpayer\'s taxable income. Taken as a credit, foreign income taxes reduce a taxpayer\'s tax liability.nnBe aware, however, that a taxpayer must treat all foreign income taxes the same way. A taxpayer generally cannot deduct some foreign income taxes and take credit for others.nnIn this case, Ginger has elected to deduct the taxes paid in France, and as a result, she is unable to claim the foreign tax credit on the taxes paid to England.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(533,3,'Each of the following can be qualifying persons for purposes of claiming the child and dependent care credit, except:','[\"a spouse who was physically or mentally unable to care for himself or herself.\",\"a dependent, age 14 who is claimed as a dependent.\",\"a dependent who was physically unable to care for himself or herself for whom the dependency exemption would have been claimed if the dependent had earned less than $5,050 in gross income.\",\"a 10-year-old child who is your dependent and for whom you can claim a dependency exemption.\"]',1,'In order for a qualifying person to claim the dependent care credit in 2024, the dependent child must be under age 13 (not age 14) when the care is provided. (Publication 503, page 3)nnPublication 503, pages 3, states, in part, that a taxpayer\'s child and dependent care expenses must be for the care of one or more qualifying persons. A qualifying person is:nnthe taxpayer\'s dependent who was under age 13 when the care was provided and for whom the taxpayer can claim an exemption,nthe taxpayer\'s spouse who was physically or mentally not able to care for himself or herself and lived with the taxpayer for more than half the year, ornthe taxpayer\'s dependent who was physically or mentally not able to care for himself or herself and for whom the taxpayer can claim an exemption (or could claim an exemption except the person had $5,050 or more of gross income or filed a joint return, or the taxpayer or spouse, if filing jointly, could be claimed as a dependent on someone else\'s return).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(534,3,'Which of the following households would not satisfy the eligibility rules for the earned income tax credit?','[\"A single-parent household\",\"A married-parent household\",\"A head of household\",\"All of the households listed would qualify for the EIC.\"]',3,'Table 1, which appears on page 2 of Publication 596, provides a capsule presentation on the qualification rules for the earned income credit (EIC).nnFrom the information given for the EIC in Publication 596, all households qualify except if a taxpayer has a filing status of married filing separately.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(535,3,'For purposes of claiming the child tax credit, which of the following is not a requirement for a qualifying child?','[\"The child must be under age 18 at the end of the year.\",\"The child must be a citizen or resident of the United States.\",\"The child must be claimed as your dependent.\",\"The child must satisfy a relationship such as an eligible foster child.\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 110, provides that a taxpayer is eligible for the child tax credit of $2,000 for each qualifying child. A qualifying child is defined as a child that is under age 17 at the end of 2024, is a citizen or resident of the United States, did not provide over half of his or her own support, lived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), and satisfies the relationship test (taxpayer\'s son, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild); brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., niece or nephew) if the taxpayer cares for the individual as their own child; or eligible foster child).nnUnder age 17 (not 18) at the end of the tax year,nA U.S. citizen, U.S. national, or resident of the United States,nDid not provide over half of his or her own support for 2024,nLived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), andnMust be the taxpayer\'s:nSon, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, foster child, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild), ornBrother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild, niece, or nephew).nAdditionally, the credit is further reduced by modified adjusted gross income starting at the following amounts:nnMarried filing jointly: $400,000nAll other tax filers: $200,000nUnder certain circumstances, a taxpayer may qualify for the additional child tax credit of up to $1,600 per qualifying dependent, which may give them a refund even if they do not owe any tax (i.e., all or part of the child tax credit may be refundable). (See Publication 17, page 110)nnIn this case, the age requirement for a qualifying child is under age 17 (not 18).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(536,3,'Which of the following households do not satisfy the eligibility rules for the earned income tax credit (EIC)?','[\"Timothy maintains a single-parent household and has a filing status of single.\",\"Lisa maintains a single-parent household and has a filing status of married filing separately.\",\"Georgia maintains a single-parent household after her spouse died in the prior year and has a filing status of qualifying surviving spouse.\",\"All of the households qualify for the EIC.\"]',1,'Table 1, which appears on page 2 of Publication 596, provides a capsule presentation on the qualification rules for the earned income credit (EIC).nnFrom the information given in Rule 3 appearing on page 5 of Publication 596, Lisa does not qualify since she has a filing status of married filing separate.nnNote: As an aside, if Lisa did not live with her spouse in their home at any time during the last 6 months of the year, she may be able to file as head of household, instead of married filing separately. In this case, she may qualify for the EIC.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(537,3,'Which of the following is considered a math or clerical error for a taxpayer claiming the earned income tax credit?','[\"A taxpayer that is required but fails to attach Form 8862 to the tax return\",\"A taxpayer that forgets to include a Social Security number on the tax form\",\"A taxpayer that makes an arithmetic error on the EIC form\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'A taxpayer may have their EIC denied or reduced as a result of a math or clerical error.nnWhat constitutes a math error is a situation where the taxpayer makes an arithmetic error on the tax form. In such a case, the Service can correct such errors and still process the claim. Also, a taxpayer that doesn\'t provide a correct a Social Security number on the tax form has a clerical error. In this case, however, the claim for the EIC will be denied but it is still treated as a math error.nnAnother example of a math or clerical error is when a taxpayer is required and fails to attach Form 8862 to the tax return.nnAs a result, all of the responses in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(538,3,'Which of the following amounts that are paid to a person who both cares for a qualifying child and provides household services while the parents work are not included in the computation of the childcare credit?','[\"Cleaning\",\"Cooking\",\"Gardening\",\"Cleaning and cooking\"]',2,'Expenses associated with the childcare tax credit include the cost of household services that meet the work-related expense test. To satisfy this test, the costs must be partly for the well-being and protection of a qualifying person. Otherwise, the costs are not treated as childcare expense. (Publication 503, page 7)nnHousehold services are ordinary and usual services done in and around the taxpayer\'s home that are necessary to run the home. They include the services of a housekeeper, maid, or cook. However, they do not include the services of a chauffeur, bartender, or gardener. See “Household Services” in Publication 503, page 8, for more information.nnAs a result of the above discussion, it is reasonable to say that all amounts paid to a person who both cares for a qualifying child and provides household services such as cleaning or cooking while the parents work are included as childcare expenses. Gardening, on the other hand, is not an expense that provides well-being or protection to the qualifying child.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(539,3,'George and Jean, an unmarried couple living together, have no income other than their wages. George earned $27,000 and Jean earned $13,000. Both individuals claim a tax filing status of single. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to the earned income credit?','[\"Both George and Jean qualify for the credit.\",\"Only George qualifies for the credit.\",\"Only Jean qualifies for the credit.\",\"Neither George nor Jean qualifies for the credit.\"]',2,'In order to qualify for the earned income credit, a taxpayer without any children must have earned less than $18,591. Given that George earned more than the limit, he does not qualify for the credit. Jean, on the other hand, earned only $13,000 and, therefore, she does qualify for the credit. See Rule 1 on page 4 of Publication 596 for rules governing earned income and not married filing jointly.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(540,3,'The taxpayer has a child under the age of 24 who is a full-time student in their second year of college. The student will be claimed as a dependent on the taxpayer\'s return. The student\'s educational expenses included $8,000 for tuition and $4,000 for room and board. The student received a $5,000 scholarship for tuition use only, as well as an additional $2,500 scholarship to pay any of the student\'s college expenses. The taxpayer paid the remaining $4,500.nnWhich of the following statements is correct, based on the information above?','[\"The student can claim the American Opportunity credit on the student\'s return for tuition expenses of $3,000 when the student reports the additional $2,500 scholarship as income.\\n\",\"The taxpayer can claim the American Opportunity credit on the taxpayer\'s return for tuition expenses of $3,000 when the student reports the additional $2,500 scholarship as income.\",\"The taxpayer can claim the American Opportunity credit on the taxpayer\'s return for tuition expenses of $3,000, and neither the taxpayer nor the student should report any of the additional $2,500 scholarship as income.\",\"The taxpayer can claim the American Opportunity credit on the taxpayer\'s return for tuition expenses of $3,000 when the taxpayer reports the additional $2,500 scholarship as income.\"]',1,'Publication 970, page 16, states that scholarships and fellowship grants included in the student\'s income do not reduce the student’s qualified education expenses available for calculating the American Opportunity Credit. If the student reports the $2,500 scholarship as income on their return, the taxpayer claiming the student as a dependent can use the remaining tuition expenses of $3,000 to claim the American Opportunity Credit.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(541,3,'Franz and Hilda are married and file a joint return. They have one qualifying child. Franz worked as a gardener and earned $11,000 in 2024. Hilda is a noncitizen and cannot get a Social Security number (SSN). Which of the following statements is correct concerning the earned income credit (EIC)?','[\"The couple can claim the EIC.\",\"The couple\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0claim the EIC because their earned income exceeds the maximum qualifying amount.\",\"The couple\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0claim the EIC because Hilda is not able to get an SSN.\",\"The couple\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0claim the EIC because Hilda is not able to get an SSN, but Franz could claim the EIC if he files as married separate.\"]',2,'Publication 596, page 5, states, in part, that under Rule 2 for claiming the EIC, the taxpayer (and the taxpayer\'s spouse if filing a joint return) must have a valid SSN issued by the Social Security Administration (SSA). Also, Rule 3 states that a taxpayer\'s filing status cannot be married filing separately.nnSince Franz and Hilda file a joint return and Hilda cannot obtain a valid SSN, the couple is not eligible to claim the earned income credit for their qualifying child.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(542,3,'Virginia\'s earned income for 2024 was $14,000. She paid $3,000 to a qualifying childcare center for the care of her 2-year-old son while she worked. She received $2,000 from Social Services to assist with her childcare expenses. How would Virginia\'s childcare credit for 2024 be computed?','[\"35% of $1,000\",\"50% of $1,000\",\"50% of $3,000\",\"31% of $1,000\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer may be able to claim the dependent care credit if the taxpayer pays someone to care for his or her dependent that is under age 13 or for the taxpayer\'s spouse or dependent that is not able to care for him or herself. For tax year 2024, the credit can be up to 35% of the taxpayer\'s expenses. To qualify for the credit, the taxpayer must pay these expenses so that they can work or look for work. (Publication 503, page 2)nnIf a taxpayer receives dependent care benefits, the dollar limit for purposes of the credit may be reduced (Publication 503, page 13). Dependent care benefits include:nnamounts the taxpayer\'s employer pays directly to either the taxpayer or the taxpayer\'s care provider for the care of his or her qualifying person while at work,nthe fair market value of care in a day-care facility provided or sponsored by the taxpayer\'s employer, andnpre-tax contributions the taxpayer made under a dependent care flexible spending arrangement.nIn this case, Virginia\'s adjusted gross income is $14,000, which corresponds to a credit rate of 35%, and her dependent care expenses are $1,000, which corresponds to the difference between the total cost of $3,000 and the assistance she received of $2,000. Thus, Virginia is able to claim a dependent care credit of $350, which is 35% of $1,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(543,3,'Which of the following is earned income for earned income tax credit purposes?','[\"Unemployment compensation\",\"Alimony\",\"The wages of a minister who has an exemption from self-employment tax\",\"The wages of an inmate working in the prison laundry\"]',2,'Low-income individuals who have earned income and meet certain requirements may be eligible for the refundable earned income tax credit. Publication 596, page 7, explicitly identifies under Rule 7 those amounts that fall under earned income and items that are not included in earned income.nnEarned income includes:nnwages, salaries, tips, and other taxable employee pay,nnet earnings from self-employment, andngross income received as a statutory employee.nNontaxable employee pay, such as certain dependent care benefits and adoption benefits, is not earned income. However, there is an exception for nontaxable combat pay. A taxpayer can elect to include his or her nontaxable combat pay in earned income for the earned income credit calculation.nnPublication 596, page 8, states that earned income does not include interest and dividends, pensions and annuities, Social Security and railroad retirement benefits (including disability benefits), alimony and child support, welfare benefits, workers\' compensation benefits, unemployment compensation (insurance), nontaxable foster care payments, and veterans\' benefits, including VA rehabilitation payments. Additionally, earnings while an inmate are not includible in earned income when determining the earned income credit.nnIn addition, whether or not a person has an approved Form 4361 (Application for Exemption From Self-Employment Tax for Use by Ministers, Members of Religious Orders and Christian Science Practitioners), amounts received for performing ministerial duties as an employee count as earned income. nnTherefore, in determining the earned income for earned income tax credit purposes in the above question, wages of a minister who has an exemption from self-employment tax are the only monies that would be deemed earned income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(544,3,'John and Joan Smith both work full time. Their dependent children, ages 4 and 6, attend day care where the expense for 2024 was $5,200. Box 10 of John\'s W-2 shows his dependent care benefit received was $5,000. Which of the following statements is correct concerning Form 2441, Child and Dependent Care Expenses?','[\"Form 2441 is required because their day care expenses exceeded the dependent care benefits received.\",\"The couple is\\u00a0not\\u00a0eligible for the credit because they receive benefits from their employer.\",\"Form 2441 is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required because their day care expenses exceeded the dependent care benefits dollar amount.\",\"Form 2441 is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required because their day care expenses exceeded the dependent care benefits received.\"]',0,'Publication 503, page 3, states that a qualifying taxpayer is able to claim the child and dependent care credit by filing Form 1040, Form 1040-SR, or Form 1040NR, not Form 1040NR-EZ and meet all the tests.nnIf the taxpayer received any dependent care benefits from his or her employer during the year, the taxpayer may be able to exclude from income all or part of them. To do so, the taxpayer must complete Part III of Form 2441 before figuring the amount of the credit. (Publication 503, page 10)nnThe amount of the dollar limit (see Publication 503, page 13) remains the same no matter how long, during the year, a taxpayer has a qualifying person in his or her household. The dollar limit is $3,000 in the case of one qualifying person and $6,000 in the case of more than one qualifying person.nnFurthermore, if a taxpayer receives dependent care benefits that are excluded or deducted from his or her income, the taxpayer must subtract that amount from the dollar limit that applies. This is better known as the reduced dollar limit. The reduced dollar limit is figured on Part III of Form 2441.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nGeorge is a widower with one child and earns $24,000 a year. He pays work-related expenses of $2,900 for the care of his 4-year-old child and qualifies to claim the credit for child and dependent care expenses.nnHis employer pays an additional $1,000 under a dependent care benefit plan. This $1,000 is excluded from George\'s income. Although the dollar limit for his work-related expenses is $3,000 (one qualifying person), George figures his credit on only $2,000 of the $2,900 work-related expenses he paid. This is because his dollar limit is reduced.nn n nnIn John and Joan Smith\'s situation, the couple are able to claim the dependent care credit on the excess dependent care costs (i.e., $200, which is $5,200 less $5,000) against the remaining dependent care limit of $1,000 (the $6,000 limit for two qualifying children, which is reduced by the $5,000 benefits received).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(545,3,'Which of the following is correct about claiming the child tax credit?','[\"It can be claimed on Form 1040.\",\"It can be claimed on Form 1041.\",\"It can be claimed on Form 1040-SR.\",\"It can be claimed on Form 1040 or 1040-SR.\"]',3,'The child tax credit and the other dependent credit are claimed on Form 1040, Form 1040-SR, or Form 1040-NR. In addition, the taxpayer must provide the name and identification number (usually a Social Security number) on the taxpayer\'s tax return for each qualifying child.nnTo figure the credit, first review the Child Tax Credit Worksheet in the Form 1040, Form 1040-SR, or 1040-NR Instructions. nnIt also should be known that this credit, like the adoption credit and child and dependent care credit, is a nonrefundable credit, which means the taxpayer must have a tax liability to offset these credits. However, if the taxpayer has no tax liability, he or she may qualify for the additional child tax credit. (See “Limits on the Credit” appearing in Publication 17, page 110–111, for more information.)nnAlthough there are technically three correct responses in this question, the best one (i.e., the correct one) is it can be claimed on Form 1040 or 1040-SR.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(546,3,'Mr. and Mrs. Pine both work full-time. They have three children ages 18, 6, and 3. For purposes of claiming the childcare credit, which of the following expenses qualify?','[\"Payments to the taxpayer\'s 18-year-old daughter to care for her 3-year-old sister\",\"Payments to the taxpayer\'s 20-year-old niece, who lives with them and can be claimed as their dependent\",\"Payments to the taxpayer\'s mother, who lives with them but does not qualify as their dependent\",\"Payments to a private school for their 6-year-old to attend first grade\"]',2,'The child and dependent care credit can be claimed by a taxpayer only if the taxpayer files Form 1040 or 1040-SR or Form 1040-NR and meets all the following tests as provided in Publication 503, page 3:nnThe care must be for one or more qualifying persons who are identified on the form used by the taxpayer to claim the credit.nThe taxpayer (and spouse if married) must have earned income during the year.nThe taxpayer must pay child and dependent care expenses so the taxpayer (and spouse if married) can work or look for work. Be aware that a person is not considered working if the taxpayer is doing unpaid volunteer work or volunteer work for a nominal salary. (Publication 503, page 2)nThe taxpayer must make payments for child and dependent care to someone the taxpayer (or spouse) cannot claim as a dependent. If the taxpayer makes payments to the taxpayer\'s child, he or she cannot be the taxpayer\'s dependent and must be age 19 or older by the end of the year. The taxpayer cannot make payments to his or her spouse or the parent of the qualifying person if the qualifying person is the taxpayer\'s child and under age 13.nThe taxpayer\'s filing status must be single, head of household, qualifying widow(er), or married filing jointly. The taxpayer must file a joint return if married, unless an exception applies to the taxpayer.nThe taxpayer must identify the care provider on the taxpayer\'s tax return.nIf the taxpayer excludes or deducts dependent care benefits provided by a dependent care benefits plan, the total amount excluded or deducted by the taxpayer must be less than the dollar limit for qualifying expenses (generally, $3,000 if one qualifying person was cared for or $6,000 if two or more qualifying persons were cared for). (If two or more qualifying persons were cared for, the amount the taxpayer excludes or deducts will always be less than the dollar limit, since the amount the taxpayer can exclude or deduct is limited to $5,000.)nFor a good presentation on these tests, see Figure A on page 5 of Publication 503.nnIn this problem, payments to the taxpayer\'s daughter and niece do not qualify since the caregivers can be claimed as dependents by the taxpayer, and the private school does not qualify because the expenses are for first grade. Expenses for kindergarten or a higher grade are not qualified expenses. Therefore, the only qualifying expense is the payment to the taxpayer\'s mother, who cannot be claimed as a dependent by the taxpayers.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(547,3,'George and Jean, a married couple living together, have no income other than their wages. George earned $12,000 and Jean earned $9,000. They have two minor children and have decided to file married filing separate tax returns, each claiming one child as a dependent. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to the earned income credit?','[\"Both George and Jean qualify for the credit.\",\"Only George qualifies for the credit because he has the higher earned income amount.\",\"Only Jean qualifies for the credit because she has the lower earned income amount.\",\"Neither George nor Jean qualifies for the credit.\"]',3,'In order to qualify for the earned income credit, married taxpayers who live together must file a joint tax return. Given that George and Jean decided to file married filing separate tax returns, each claiming one child as a dependent, both are disqualified from receiving the earned income credit. See Rule 3, appearing on page 5 of Publication 596, which states that a taxpayer’s filing status cannot be “married filing separately.\"n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(548,3,'What is the maximum retirement savings contributions credit (saver\'s credit) a married couple can claim if they satisfy all of the qualifications?','[\"$500\",\"$1,000\",\"$2,000\",\"$4,000\"]',2,'Publication 590-A, page 45, states that the amount of the credit a taxpayer can get is based on the contributions the taxpayer makes and their credit rate. The taxpayer’s credit rate can be as low as 10% or as high as 50% and it depends on the taxpayer’s income and filing status. See Form 8880, Credit for Qualified Retirement Savings Contributions, to determine the credit rate.nnThe maximum contribution taken into account is $2,000 per person. On a joint return, up to $4,000 is taken into account. Thus, in this case, the maximum credit amount the couple may be eligible for is $2,000, which is equal to a contribution of $4,000 times 50%.nnThe credit is figured on Form 8880. The credit is reported on Schedule 3 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 4, and Form 8880 is attached to the return.nnBe aware, the modified AGI limits for this credit increased in 2024 to $76,500 for those filing married jointly, $54,375 for those filing head of household, and $38,250 for all other tax filers (Publication 590-A, page 46).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(549,3,'Carol, an individual taxpayer, received a Form 1099-DIV from her global mutual fund that showed dividend income of $500 and foreign taxes withheld of $67. This is the only foreign source income she received for the year. Her income tax before any credits is $4,320. On which of the following forms may Carol elect to claim a credit for the foreign tax paid?','[\"Form 1040, \\\"Tax and Credits\\\" Foreign Tax Credit\",\"Schedule 3 (Form 1040), Line 1, \\\"Foreign Tax Credit\\\"\",\"Form 1040, Schedule A,\\u00a0Itemized Deductions, line 6, \\\"Other Taxes\\\"\",\"Form 1040, Schedule B, by electing to reduce the dividend income by $134 ($67 \\u00d7 2)\"]',1,'According to IRC Section 27, a taxpayer is allowed to apply taxes paid or accrued on foreign income as a credit against any U.S. income tax. Generally, a taxpayer may need to file Form 1116 (Publication 54, page 25) with Form 1040 or 1040-SR to claim the foreign tax credit. The foreign tax credit is limited to the part of the taxpayer\'s total U.S. tax that is in proportion to the taxpayer\'s taxable income from sources outside the United States compared to the taxpayer\'s total taxable income. A taxpayer will not be subject to the limit and may still qualify and elect not to file Form 1116 if all of the following requirements are met:nn The only foreign source income for the tax year is passive income (dividends, interest, royalties, etc.) that is reported to the taxpayer on a payee statement; andnThe qualified foreign taxes for the tax year are not more than $300 ($600 if filing a joint return); and nThe election is made for the tax year.nTaxpayers meeting these requirements may claim the credit directly on Form 1040. The amount of foreign income tax not allowed as a credit because of the limit can be carried back 1 year and carried forward 10 years. (Publication 54, page 25)nnGiven that Carol is an individual taxpayer, only has passive foreign income, and her foreign taxes paid for the year are $67 (less than $300), she may elect to claim the credit on Line 1 of Schedule 3 (Form 1040). The total of Line 8 of Schedule 3 will transfer to Form 1040, Tax and Credits Section.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(550,3,'Which of the following are due diligence requirements for a tax preparer when claiming the earned income credit (EIC) for a taxpayer on a 2024 tax return?','[\"The checklist is based on information reasonably obtained by the preparer.\",\"The preparer has complied with the knowledge requirements.\",\"The preparer keeps the checklist for his or her files.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Form 8867 is a paid preparer\'s (not a taxpayer\'s) due diligence checklist that should be completed by a tax preparer. It is required to be filed with tax returns for any taxpayer claiming the EIC, child tax credit (CTC), additional child tax credit, and American opportunity tax credit (AOTC). In addition, beginning with 2018 tax returns, this form must be filed for any taxpayer claiming Head of Household.nnIn addition, Part 1 of the checklist contains eight questions on the due diligence requirements for the tax preparer:nnThe first question asks whether the tax preparer completed Form 8867 based on information provided by the taxpayer or reasonably obtained by the tax preparer.nThe second question asks whether the tax preparer completed the appropriate worksheets for the four tax credits or the tax preparer’s own worksheet.nThe third question applies to satisfying the knowledge requirement.nThe fourth question applies to whether the information provided by the taxpayer appears to be incorrect.nThe fifth question asks whether the tax preparer satisfied the record retention requirement.nThe sixth question asks whether the taxpayer could provide documentation to substantiate eligibility for the credit amount being claimed.nThe seventh question asks if the tax preparer asked if any of the credits were disallowed or reduced in a previous year.nThe eighth question pertains to taxpayers with self-employment income and filing a Schedule C.nAs a result, all of the responses given for this question are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(551,3,'Laurie is a sophomore in the University of Nebraska\'s degree program in dentistry. In 2024, Laurie paid $3,000 in tuition, $500 for books, and $250 for rented dental equipment. Laurie purchased her books online instead of at the university. Laurie also paid room and board of $3,500. What is the total qualifying educational expense under the American Opportunity Credit for Laurie in 2024?','[\"$3,500\",\"$3,750\",\"$7,250\",\"$3,000\"]',1,'Publication 970, pages 12–13, provides that qualified education expenses are amounts paid in 2024 for tuition and fees required for enrollment or attendance at an eligible educational institution. It does not matter if the expenses were paid in cash, by check, by credit or debit card, or with borrowed funds.nnOnly certain expenses for course-related books, supplies, and equipment qualify.nnIn the case of the American Opportunity Tax Credit (AOTC), qualified education expenses include amounts spent on books, supplies, and equipment needed for a course of study, whether or not the materials are purchased from the educational institution as a condition of enrollment or attendance.nnPublication 970, page 23 states, in the case of the Lifetime Learning Credit, qualified education expenses include only amounts spent on books, supplies, and equipment only if required to be paid to the educational institution as a condition of enrollment or attendance.nnPublication 970, pages 28 and 29 states qualified education expenses do not include amounts paid for insurance, medical expenses (including student health fees), room and board, transportation, or similar personal, living, or family expenses.nnIn this case, Laurie has qualifying educational expenses of $3,750 under the AOTC, which is the sum of her tuition ($3,000), books ($500), and rented dental equipment ($250).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(552,3,'Which of the following is not a requirement for a qualifying child for purposes of the child tax credit?','[\"The child is claimed as your dependent.\",\"The child was under age 18 at the end of 2024 or under age 24 at the end of 2024 and was a student.\",\"The child is your son, daughter, adopted child, grandchild, stepchild, or foster child.\",\"The child is a citizen or resident of the United States.\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 109, provides that a taxpayer is eligible for the child tax credit of $2,000 for each qualifying child. A qualifying child is defined as a child that is under age 17 at the end of 2024, is a citizen or resident of the United States, did not provide over half of his or her own support, lived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), and satisfies the relationship test (taxpayer\'s son, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild); brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., niece or nephew) if the taxpayer cares for the individual as their own child; or eligible foster child).nnThe child tax credit is further reduced below $2,000 if the taxpayer\'s modified adjusted gross income (AGI) is above $400,000 and the taxpayer is married filing jointly; $200,000 for all other tax filers. (Publication 17, page 111)nnAs a result, a requirement for qualifying a child for purposes of the child tax credit does not include whether the child was under age 18 at the end of 2024 or under age 24 at the end of 2024 and was a student.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(553,3,'Scott and Kathy (spouses) have a son who turned 18 years of age on December 30, 2024. Scott and Kathy have a modified adjusted gross income of $105,000 and claimed their son as a dependent on their return for 2024. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the child tax credit?','[\"The couple qualifies for the full credit on their son.\",\"The couple qualifies for part of but\\u00a0not\\u00a0the full credit on their son.\",\"The couple does\\u00a0not\\u00a0qualify for any of the credit on their son.\",\"There is not enough information to respond to this question.\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 110, provides that a taxpayer is eligible for the child tax credit of $2,000 for each qualifying child. A qualifying child is defined as a child that is under age 17 at the end of 2024, is a citizen or resident of the United States, did not provide over half of his or her own support, lived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), and satisfies the relationship test (taxpayer\'s son, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild); brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., niece or nephew) if the taxpayer cares for the individual as their own child; or eligible foster child).nnUnder age 17 at the end of the tax year,nA U.S. citizen, U.S. national, or resident of the United States,nDid not provide over half of his or her own support,nLived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), andnMust be the taxpayer\'s:nSon, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, foster child, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild), ornBrother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., niece or nephew).nAdditionally, the credit is further reduced below $2,000 by modified adjusted gross income starting at the following amounts:nnMarried filing jointly: $400,000nAll other tax filers: $200,000nUnder certain circumstances, all or part of the child tax credit may be refundable.nnIn this case, the age requirement for a qualifying child is violated since the child is age 17 by year-end (not under age 17). Hence, the couple does not qualify.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(554,3,'Which of the following statements is correct about filing Form 8867 with a 2024 tax return concerning the paid preparer\'s earned income credit (EIC)?','[\"It contains a due diligence requirements section.\",\"It contains a checklist section for documents provided to the tax preparer.\",\"It is a tax preparer\'s checklist that is filed with the taxpayer\'s tax return.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Form 8867 is a paid preparer\'s (not a taxpayer\'s) due diligence checklist that should be completed by a tax preparer. It is required to be filed with tax returns for any taxpayer claiming the EIC, child tax credit (CTC), additional child tax credit, and American opportunity tax credit (AOTC). In addition, beginning with 2018 tax returns, this form must be filed for any taxpayer claiming Head of Household.nnThe checklist currently has six parts:nnThe first part (Due Diligence Requirements) is applicable to all taxpayers claiming any of the four tax credits to determine whether the taxpayer satisfies the basic requirements for claiming the credit.nThe second part pertains to Due Diligence Questions pertaining to Returns Claiming EIC.nThe third part pertains to Due Diligence Questions pertaining to Returns Claiming CTC/ACTC/ODC.nThe fourth part pertains to Due Diligence Questions pertaining to Returns Claiming the AOTC.nThe fifth part pertains to Head of Household.nThe sixth part certifies the credit eligibility by the tax preparer.nAs a result, all three responses are correct. The form must be filed with the tax return and it is a tax preparer\'s due diligence checklist.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(555,3,'Hollie filed as head of household and would like to take the child tax credit for Amanda in 2024. Which of the following statements is incorrect regarding the child tax credit?','[\"Amanda must be under age 18 at the end of the tax year.\",\"Hollie must claim Amanda as a dependent.\",\"A portion of the child tax credit may be refundable.\",\"If Hollie\'s adjusted gross income is above $200,000, her credit will be reduced or eliminated.\"]',0,'Publication 17, pages 109–110, provides that a taxpayer is eligible for the child tax credit of $2,000 for each qualifying child. A qualifying child is defined as a child that is under age 17 at the end of 2024, is a citizen or resident of the United States, did not provide over half of his or her own support, lived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), and satisfies the relationship test (taxpayer\'s son, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild); brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., niece or nephew) if the taxpayer cares for the individual as their own child; or eligible foster child).nnA qualifying child for purposes of the child tax credit must be all of the following:nnUnder age 17 (not 18) at the end of the tax year,nA U.S. citizen, U.S. national, or resident of the United States,nDid not provide over half of his or her own support for 2024,nLived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024 (with limited exceptions), andnMust be the taxpayer\'s:nSon, daughter, adopted child, stepchild, foster child, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., grandchild), ornBrother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendent of any of them (e.g., niece or nephew).nAdditionally, the credit is reduced by modified adjusted gross income starting at the following amounts:nnMarried filing jointly: $400,000nAll other tax filings: $200,000 (Publication 17, page 106)nBeginning in 2018, a taxpayer may be able to claim the other dependent credit (ODC) for a dependent. The ODC is a nonrefundable credit of up to $500 for each eligible dependent who cannot be claimed for the child tax credit.nnUnder certain circumstances, a taxpayer may be able to take an additional child tax credit (of up to $1,600 per qualifying child) if they are not able to claim the full amount of the child tax credit. This is sometimes referred to as a refundable part of the credit. See Publication 17, page 105, for additional information on the additional tax credit.nnTherefore, Amanda must be under age 17, not under age 18, at the end of the tax year in order to be deemed a qualifying child.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(556,3,'Joe is eligible for employer health coverage for 2024. His household income for 2024 was $33,000 and his share of premiums for self-only coverage cost $3,400. Joe decides to enroll in employer coverage. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the premium tax credit (PTC)?','[\"Joe is eligible to claim the PTC.\",\"Joe is not eligible to claim the PTC.\",\"Joe is eligible to claim the PTC, but only on the amount exceeding the 9.12% of household income.\",\"Joe is eligible to claim the PTC, but only on the amount up to the 9.12% of household income.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 974, page 11, employer health coverage is generally considered affordable for the taxpayer and a family member if the taxpayer’s share of the annual costs for self-only coverage, which is sometimes referred to as the employee required contributions, is not more than 9.12% of the taxpayer’s tax family’s household income for 2024.nnHowever, employer-sponsored coverage is not considered affordable if, when the taxpayer or a family member enrolled in a qualified health plan, the taxpayer gave accurate information about the availability of employer coverage to the Marketplace, and the Marketplace determined that the taxpayer was eligible for APTC (advance payments for the premium tax credit) for the individual’s coverage in the qualified health plan.nnPursuant to Publication 974, page 11, employer health coverage is not considered affordable if, when the taxpayer enrolls in a qualified health plan, the Marketplace determines that the taxpayer’s share of the premiums cost for employer coverage will be more than 9.12% of what the Marketplace estimates will be the taxpayer’s household income.nnPursuant to Publication 974, page 10, even if a taxpayer and other members of their tax family had the opportunity to enroll in coverage offered by the taxpayer’s employer that qualifies as minimum essential coverage (MEC), the taxpayer is considered eligible for an employer-sponsored plan (and cannot get the PTC for their coverage in a qualified health plan) only if the employer-sponsored coverage is affordable to the employee and the coverage provides minimum value. The taxpayer’s family members also may be unable to get the PTC for coverage in a qualified health plan for months they were eligible to enroll in employer-sponsored coverage, but only if it was affordable and provided minimum value for the employee.nnIf a taxpayer or the taxpayer’s family member(s) enrolls in the employer coverage, the individual enrolled cannot get the PTC for coverage in a qualified health plan, even if the employer coverage is not affordable or does not provide minimum value.nnAs a result, Joe is not eligible for PTC in a qualified health plan because he enrolled in the employer coverage.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(557,3,'Which of the following is not a requirement for the earned income credit?','[\"The taxpayer must be 25 or older.\",\"The taxpayer must have a dependent child.\",\"The taxpayer must live in the United States for more than half of the year.\",\"The taxpayer may not be a qualifying child of another person.\"]',1,'Taxpayers without dependent children may still qualify for the earned income credit (see Table 1 (Chapter 1 and Chapter 3) on page 2 of Publication 596) if they meet certain criteria. A partial list of the criteria includes the following:nnBe at least 25 years of age and under 65 years oldnMay not be a taxpayer for whom a dependency exemption is allowed by another taxpayer nMay not be a qualifying child of another person nMust have lived in the United States for more than half of the year nMust have earned income nMust have investment income no greater than $11,600',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(558,3,'Which of the following statements is correct about filing Form 8867 with a 2024 tax return concerning the paid preparer\'s earned income credit (EIC)?','[\"It is a taxpayer\'s checklist that is filed with their tax return.\",\"It contains a due diligence requirements section for tax returns claiming the EIC.\",\"It is set up for taxpayers with one or two children only.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',1,'Form 8867 is a paid preparer\'s (not a taxpayer\'s) due diligence checklist that should be completed by a tax preparer. It is required to be filed with tax returns for any taxpayer claiming the EIC, child tax credit (CTC), additional child tax credit, and American opportunity tax credit (AOTC). In addition, beginning with 2018 tax returns, this form must be filed for any taxpayer claiming Head of Household.nnThe checklist currently has six parts:nnThe first part (Due Diligence Requirements) is applicable to all taxpayers claiming any of the four tax credits to determine whether the taxpayer satisfies the basic requirements for claiming the credit.nThe second part pertains to Due Diligence Questions pertaining to Returns Claiming EIC.nThe third part pertains to Due Diligence Questions pertaining to Returns Claiming CTC/ACTC/ODC.nThe fourth part pertains to Due Diligence Questions pertaining to Returns Claiming the AOTC.nThe fifth part pertains to claiming Head of Household.nThe sixth part certifies the credit eligibility by the tax preparer.nAs a result, the only correct response for this question is that the checklist contains a due diligence requirements section for tax returns claiming the EIC.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(559,3,'Trudy, age 46, is single. Her 2024 wages were $19,100. Her permanently disabled child, Brandy, age 26, and her 10-year-old son, Juniper, lived with her the entire year. Use the following excerpt of the earned income credit table to compute Trudy\'s earned income credit for 2024.nn2024 Earned Income Credit Table (excerpt, not full table) from Publication 596, page 27:nn Income:    But Less    For Single,  Head of Household, orn At least     Than       Qualifying Widower, and you have----  n                           No        1         2          3n                        Children   Child    Children   Childrenn $19,000    $19,050       $0      $4,213     $6,960     $7,830n  19,050     19,100        0       4,213      6,960      7,830n  19,100     19,150        0       4,213      6,960      7,830n  19,150     19,200        0       4,213      6,960      7,830n  19,200     19,250        0       4,213      6,960      7,830','[\"$0\",\"$4,213\",\"$6,960\",\"$7,830\"]',2,'To qualify for the earned income credit, a taxpayer must work and have earned income or in the case of a married couple, at least one spouse works and has earned income. If the taxpayer is an employee, earned income includes all the taxable income received from his or her employer. (Publication 596, page 7)nnIn this case, Trudy has earned income of $19,100 and has two children. Although Brandy is age 26, she is permanently disabled and, as such, she is always a child according to the age test criteria (Publication 596, page 17). Hence, Trudy is able to claim an earned income credit of $6,960.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(560,3,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the foreign earned income exclusion?','[\"A taxpayer can take a credit (but\\u00a0not\\u00a0a deduction) for foreign income taxes paid on income that the taxpayer excludes from U.S. tax.\",\"A taxpayer can take a deduction (but\\u00a0not\\u00a0a credit) for foreign income taxes paid on income that the taxpayer excludes from U.S. tax.\",\"A taxpayer can take a credit (or a deduction) for foreign income taxes paid on income that the taxpayer excludes from U.S. tax.\",\"A taxpayer\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0take a credit (or a deduction) for foreign income taxes paid on income that the taxpayer excludes from U.S. tax.\"]',3,'Publication 54, page 23, provides, in part, that a taxpayer can take either a credit or a deduction for income taxes paid to a foreign country or a U.S. possession. Taken as a deduction, foreign income taxes reduce a taxpayer\'s taxable income. Taken as a credit, foreign income taxes reduce a taxpayer\'s tax liability.nnBe aware, however, that a taxpayer must treat all foreign income taxes the same way. A taxpayer generally cannot deduct some foreign income taxes and take credit for others.nnAs provided on page 19 of Publication 54, once a taxpayer chooses to exclude foreign earned income, that choice remains in effect for that year and all later years unless the taxpayer revokes it.nnOnce a taxpayer chooses to exclude foreign earned income, the taxpayer cannot take a foreign tax credit or deduction for taxes on income that is excluded. If, however, a taxpayer does take a credit or deduction for any of those taxes in a subsequent year, their election for the foreign earned income exclusion will be revoked beginning with that year.nnIf a taxpayer claims the foreign earned income exclusion, he or she will not qualify for the earned income credit for the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(561,3,'Which of the following is true regarding the premium tax credit (PTC)?','[\"Married individuals are always required to file a joint return to qualify for the credit.\",\"The PTC can only be claimed if the individual was enrolled in a qualified health plan for at least six months.\",\"Form 1095-A,\\u00a0Health Insurance Marketplace Statement, is not needed to complete Form 8962,\\u00a0Premium Tax Credit (PTC).\",\"No PTC is allowed for an individual\\u2019s coverage for any period that an individual is not lawfully present in the United States\"]',3,'Individuals who are not lawfully present in the U.S. are not eligible for coverage through the Marketplace and, therefore, are not eligible for the premium tax credit (PTC). According to Publication 974, page 4, the PTC can be claimed if, for at least one month of the year, all of the following are true:nnan individual in your tax family was enrolled in a qualified health plan offered through the Marketplace on the first day of the month,nthe individual was not eligible for any other coverage, andnenrollment premiums were paid.nIt further notes that the taxpayer cannot be claimed as a dependent and must meet the household income requirement of 100% of the poverty level. The PTC is claimed on Form 8962.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(562,3,'Which of the following is not a test to determine if a child is a qualifying child for the earned income tax credit (EITC)?','[\"Relationship\",\"Age\",\"Residency\",\"Support\"]',3,'Publication 596, page 9, states in Rule 8, in part, that a taxpayer\'s child is a qualifying child for the earned income credit if the child meets four tests: Relationship, Age, Residency, and Joint Return. As a result, there is no support test requirement for this tax credit. (See Figure A, page 10 of Publication 596, for a complete set of rules for claiming the EIC.)n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(563,3,'Zach and Myra have four children ranging in age from 2 to 10. Zach has wages of $80,000 and Myra $25,000. Two of the children went to Child Nursery School, Inc. at a total cost of $8,000. The two older children attended a qualified after-school program that costs $2,500. What amount of childcare expenses can be used to determine the credit on their 2024 return?','[\"$10,500\",\"$2,500\",\"$4,800\",\"$6,000\"]',3,'A taxpayer may be able to claim the child and dependent care credit if the taxpayer pays someone to care for his or her dependent that is under age 13 or for the taxpayer\'s spouse or dependent who is not able to care for him or herself. The credit can be up to 35% of the taxpayer\'s expenses. (Publication 503, page 13)nnThere is a dollar limit on the amount of work-related expenses that apply in computing the credit. Specifically, the amount is the lesser of the total dependent care expenses or $3,000 if one dependent ($6,000 if more than one dependent), so that the taxpayer and spouse, if any, can work or look for work. (Publication 503, pages 12–13)nnAs a result, the amount of child care expenses that can be used to determine the credit for Zach and Myra for year 2024 is $6,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(564,3,'Jerry has two dependent children, Greg and Mandy, who are attending an accredited college in 2024. Greg is a senior who spent $7,000 for tuition and fees. Mandy, a freshman with no prior postsecondary education, had tuition expenses of $4,000. Jerry meets all the income and filing status requirements for the education credits. There is no tax-free assistance to pay these expenses. Jerry\'s tax liability before credits equals $14,000. What is the maximum credit that Jerry may claim on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$1,400 Lifetime Learning Credit\",\"$5,000 American Opportunity Tax Credit\",\"$2,500 American Opportunity Tax Credit and $2,800 Lifetime Learning Credit\",\"$1,800 Hope Credit and $1,400 Lifetime Learning Credit\"]',1,'In general, taxpayers are able to claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit (AOTC) if they can satisfy all three of the following requirements (Publication 970, page 11):nnthe taxpayer pays qualified education expenses of higher education,nthe taxpayer pays the tuition and related expenses for an eligible student, andnthe eligible student is the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s spouse, or a dependent for which the taxpayer claims on their tax return.nThe student must be enrolled at least half-time for at least one academic period that began during 2024 (or the first 3 months of 2025 if qualified expenses were paid in 2024).nnThe AOTC is an education tax credit that is available for 2024.nnIn this case, a person is able to claim a maximum credit per student of $2,500 (100% of the first $2,000 and 25% of the next $2,000 of qualified education expenses). The credit is available for the first 4 years of postsecondary education, and 40% of the credit is refundable for most taxpayers. (Publication 970, page 20)nnIf the taxpayer is married and filing a joint return, the amount of AOTC and Lifetime Learning Credit for 2024 is gradually reduced (phased out) if their modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) is between $160,000 and $180,000. For all other taxpayers, the phaseout range is between $80,000 and $90,000 (Publication 970, page 22).nnThe amount of the Lifetime Learning Credit is 20% of the first $10,000 of qualified education expenses the taxpayer paid for all eligible students. The maximum amount of Lifetime Learning Credit the taxpayer can claim for 2024 is $2,000 (0.20 × $10,000) (Publication 970, page 23). The Lifetime Learning credit phaseout threshold was increased beginning in 2022 and the deduction for tuition and fees is no longer available. nnJerry is eligible to claim an $800 ($4,000 × 0.20) Lifetime Learning Credit for Mandy, who is a freshman and had tuition expenses of $4,000. In addition, Jerry is able to claim a $1,400 ($7,000 × 0.20) Lifetime Learning Credit for Greg, who is a senior and had tuition expenses of $7,000. On the other hand, Jerry can take a $5,000 AOTC. Since only one of the two credits can be taken for a child and since the AOTC is largest, it is best for Jerry to claim the $5,000 AOTC.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(565,3,'Jennifer and Rob married on December 10. During the same year, Rob enrolled in an accredited college to further his career; he received a Form 1098-T, Tuition Statement, from the college. Jennifer was employed with an income of $45,000 and paid for Rob’s education expenses. Based on their circumstances, what is the correct method to report the education credit?','[\"The couple must file a joint return to claim an education credit.\",\"Based on Jennifer\\u2019s AGI, the couple cannot claim an education credit.\",\"Rob is ineligible to claim an education credit because Jennifer paid his education expenses.\",\"Jennifer should report nonqualified education expenses on Form 8863,\\u00a0Education Credits\\u00a0(American opportunity and lifetime learning credits).\"]',0,'Publication 970, pages 11 and 12, provides that a taxpayer can claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit (AOTC) if all three of the following requirements are met:nnThe taxpayer pays qualified education expenses of higher education.nThe taxpayer pays the education expenses for an eligible student.nThe eligible student is either the taxpayer, the taxpayer’s spouse, or a dependent for whom the taxpayer claims an exemption on his or her tax return.nIn addition, a taxpayer cannot claim the American opportunity credit if the couple’s filing status is married filing separately.nnTo be eligible to claim the American Opportunity Tax Credit or Lifetime Learning Credit, the law requires a taxpayer (or a dependent) to have received a Form 1098-T from an eligible educational institution to claim the tuition and fees deduction, American opportunity credit, or the lifetime learning credit. (Form 8863 Instructions, page 1)nnHowever, a taxpayer may still claim the credit even when the student does not receive a 1098-T provided that certain conditions are met (as per Form 8863). If a student’s educational institution is not required to provide a Form 1098-T to the student, a taxpayer may claim one of these education benefits without a Form 1098-T if the taxpayer otherwise qualifies, can demonstrate that the taxpayer (or a dependent) was enrolled at an eligible educational institution, and can substantiate the payment of qualified tuition and related expenses. (Form 8863 Instructions, page 1)nnAs a result, the only correct response is the couple must file a joint tax return in order to claim the AOTC credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(566,3,'Which of the following statements about the earned income credit in 2024 is correct?','[\"Nontaxable combat pay can be included in earned income when calculating the earned income credit.\",\"Nontaxable military pay can be included in earned income when calculating the earned income credit.\",\"Nontaxable combat pay\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0be included in earned income when calculating the earned income credit.\",\"Nontaxable combat pay and nontaxable military pay can be included in earned income when calculating the earned income credit.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Publication 596, page 2, the earned income credit (EIC) is a tax credit for those taxpayers who work and have earned income below a threshold amount as provided in Table 1 (Publication 596, page 2). Earned income includes wages, salaries, tips, and other taxable employee pay. Nontaxable employee pay, such as certain dependent care benefits and adoption benefits, is not earned income. (Publication 596, page 7)nnHowever, there is an exception for nontaxable combat pay. Specifically, a taxpayer may include nontaxable combat pay in earned income when calculating the earned income credit. Note the key word here is “may.” Thus, a taxpayer is not required to include nontaxable combat pay. Examples of nontaxable military pay are combat pay, the Basic Allowance for Housing, and the Basic Allowance for Subsistence. (Publication 596, page 19)nnA taxpayer, however, should compute the credit with and without the nontaxable combat pay to determine whether to include or exclude it when making the election.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(567,3,'Which of the following taxpayers is likely to be assessed a penalty when filing a claim for the earned income tax credit?','[\"A taxpayer who failed to provide a correct Social Security number\",\"A taxpayer who calculated the EIC incorrectly\",\"A taxpayer who disregards the rules for claiming the EIC\",\"All of the taxpayers listed would be assessed a penalty.\"]',2,'A taxpayer may have their EIC denied or reduced as a result of a math or clerical error.nnWhat constitutes a math error is a situation where the taxpayer makes an arithmetic error on the tax form. In such a case, the Service can correct such errors and still process the claim. Also, a taxpayer that forgets to include a Social Security number on the tax form has a clerical error. In this case, however, the claim for the EIC will be denied. These types of errors are not likely to result in an assessed penalty. (Publication 596, pages 20–21)nnA taxpayer that shows negligence or disregard of the rules and regulations, however, is likely to be assessed an accuracy-related penalty. (Publication 17, page 20)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(568,3,'Which of the following forms is generally filed by a taxpayer that is repaying the first-time homebuyer credit?','[\"Form 1040-NR\",\"Form 1040A\",\"Form 1040\",\"Form 1040-ES\"]',2,'The repayment requirement has expired for homes purchased after 2008. The repayment requirement continues to apply to homes purchased in 2008.nnThe Form 5405 Instructions, page 1, provide that a taxpayer must file Form 5405 (Repayment of the First-Time Homebuyer Credit) with their 2024 tax return if they purchased the home in 2008 and they either:nndisposed of it in 2024 ornceased using it as their main home in 2024.nIn these cases, the taxpayer needs to repay the balance of the unpaid credit with their 2023 tax return.nnSince 2024 is the last year for the credit, Form 5405 is not required. Taxpayers will just need to report the final payment on Schedule 2 (Form 1040), line 10.nnForm 1040-NR is an income tax return filed by a U.S. nonresident alien. In addition, Form 1040-A and 1040-EZ are no longer available for tax years 2018 and later.nnIn general, the taxpayer will need to only file Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR to repay the credit amount from the claimed first-time homebuyer credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(569,3,'Which of the following taxpayers may claim the earned income credit for 2024?','[\"Ginger, 50 years of age, who has a qualifying child for whom she provides sole support. She received $15,000 in Social Security benefits and $500 in interest income in 2024.\",\"Cinnamon, 42 years old, who was divorced the entire year. She had investment income of $3,000 and W-2 wages of $10,000.\",\"Woody, age 51, who is single and lived in a homeless shelter during 2024 and received retirement benefits of $7,000.\",\"Cherrie, age 35, who is single and has one qualifying child. She had $50,000 in wages and her adjusted gross income is $50,000.\"]',1,'Table 1, which appears on page 2 of Publication 596, provides a capsule presentation on the qualification\'s rules for the earned income credit. As provided by Table 1, the rules applicable for tax year 2024 to everyone are as follows:nnYour adjusted gross income (AGI) must be less than:n$59,899 ($66,819 for married filing jointly) if you have three or more qualifying children,n$55,578 ($62,688 for married filing jointly) if you have two qualifying children,n$49,084 ($56,004 for married filing jointly) if you have one qualifying child, orn$18,591 ($25,511 for married filing jointly) if you do not have a qualifying child.nYou must have a valid Social Security number (SSN).nYour filing status cannot be “married filing separately.”nYou must be a U.S. citizen or resident alien all year.nYou cannot file Form 2555 (relating to foreign earned income).nYour investment income must be $11,600 or less.nYou must have earned income.nIn this case, Ginger and Woody do not qualify since neither has any earned income; and Cherrie does not qualify since she has too much income. Cinnamon qualifies because her investment income and her W-2 wages are both below the respective threshold amounts.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(570,3,'Which of the following is a disqualification for the child and dependent care credit?','[\"Head of household filing status\",\"Making childcare payments to relatives\",\"Paying for care for your spouse who is not physically or mentally able to care for himself or herself while you work\",\"Childcare only while you perform unpaid volunteer work\"]',3,'The child and dependent care credit can be claimed by a taxpayer only if the taxpayer files Form 1040, 1040-SR, 1040-NR, not 1040-NR-EZ and meets all the following tests:nnThe care must be for one or more qualifying persons who are identified on the form used by the taxpayer to claim the credit.nThe taxpayer (and spouse if married) must have earned income during the year.nThe taxpayer must pay child and dependent care expenses so the taxpayer (and spouse if married) can work or look for work. Be aware that a person is not considered working if the taxpayer is doing unpaid volunteer work or volunteer work for a nominal salary. (Publication 503, page 7)nThe taxpayer must make payments for child and dependent care to someone the taxpayer (or spouse) cannot claim as a dependent. If the taxpayer makes payments to the taxpayer\'s child, he or she cannot be the taxpayer\'s dependent and must be age 19 or older by the end of the year. Likewise, payments cannot be made to the taxpayer\'s spouse or parent of the taxpayer\'s qualifying person if the person is the taxpayer\'s child and under age 13.nThe taxpayer\'s filing status must be single, head of household, qualifying widow(er), or married filing jointly. The taxpayer must file a joint return if married, unless an exception applies to the taxpayer.nThe taxpayer must identify the care provider on the taxpayer\'s tax return.nIf the taxpayer excludes or deducts dependent care benefits provided by a dependent care benefits plan, the total amount excluded or deducted by the taxpayer must be less than the dollar limit for qualifying expenses (generally, $3,000 if one qualifying person was cared for or $6,000 if two or more qualifying persons were cared for). (If two or more qualifying persons were cared for, the amount the taxpayer excludes or deducts will always be less than the dollar limit, since the amount the taxpayer can exclude or deduct is limited to $5,000.)nFor a good presentation on these tests, see Publication 503.nnIn this problem, a taxpayer would be disqualified from the tax credit while the taxpayer was performing volunteer work as given in item 3 above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(571,3,'Which of the following taxpayers cannot claim the earned income credit for tax year 2024?','[\"Jeannie has interest income of $8,600.\",\"Bart has tax-exempt income of $7,750.\",\"Louisa has dividends of $2,900 and interest income of $9,000.\",\"Tomas has capital gain income of $9,000.\"]',2,'Taxpayers whose investment income is in excess of $11,600 in 2024 may not claim the earned income credit. Generally, investment income is composed of the following items: taxable interest, tax-exempt interest, dividend income, and capital gain income. See the Rule 6 discussion appearing on page 6 of Publication 596.nnIn this problem, Louisa has investment income of $11,900 (dividends of $2,900 and interest income of $9,000), which exceeds the $11,600 limit. All the other taxpayers have investment income below the threshold amount.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(572,3,'Jim\'s W-2 comprises his entire adjusted gross income of $16,000. Which of the following situations qualifies for the earned income credit (EIC) if all other EIC rules are met in 2024?','[\"Jim is eligible to claim the EIC if he files single and has no qualifying child.\",\"Jim is\\u00a0not\\u00a0eligible to claim the EIC if he files single and has no qualifying child.\",\"Jim is eligible to claim the EIC if he files single, is 18 years of age, and has no qualifying child.\",\"Jim is eligible to claim the EIC if he returned to the United States in October 2024 after 3 years of living abroad.\"]',0,'Taxpayers without dependent children may still qualify for the earned income credit (see Chapter 3 of Table 1 on page 2 of Publication 596) if they meet the following criteria:nnBe at least 25 years of age and under 65 years old nMay not be a taxpayer for whom a dependency exemption is allowed by another taxpayer nMay not be a qualifying child of another person nMust have lived in the United States for more than half of the yearnIn addition, a taxpayer\'s adjusted gross income must be less than $18,591 ($25,511 for married filing jointly) if the taxpayer does not have a qualifying child (see Chapter 1 of Table 1). In Jim\'s case, he has an AGI figure of $16,000, which is less than $18,591, and as such, he qualifies for the earned income tax credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(573,3,'Which of the following individuals qualifies to claim the saver\'s credit in 2024, assuming that they satisfy all other qualifications for the credit?','[\"Sara, who graduated in June of the current year\",\"Amy, who was born in 2007\",\"Jessica, who is single and has adjusted gross income of $30,000\",\"All of the taxpayers listed here qualify.\"]',2,'Publication 590-A, page 45, provides the eligibility criteria for a taxpayer to claim the saver\'s credit on their 2024 income tax return. If a taxpayer makes an eligible contribution to a qualified retirement plan, an eligible deferred compensation plan, or an IRA, they can claim the credit if all of the following apply:nnThe taxpayer was born before January 2, 2007 (i.e., age 17).nThe taxpayer is not a full-time student (explained below).nNo one else, such as the taxpayer\'s parent(s), claims an exemption for the taxpayer on their tax return.nThe taxpayer\'s adjusted gross income is not more than:n$76,500 if filing status is married filing jointly,n$54,375 if filing status is head of household, orn$38,250 if filing status is single, married filing separately, or qualifying surviving spouse.nIn addition, a taxpayer is a full-time student if, during some part of each of 5 calendar months (not necessarily consecutive) during the calendar year, they are either:nna full-time student at a school that has a regular teaching staff, course of study, and regularly enrolled body of students in attendance, orna student taking a full-time, on-farm training course given by either a school that has a regular teaching staff, course of study, and regularly enrolled body of students in attendance, or a state, county, or local government.nThus, in this problem, Jessica is the only person qualified to claim the saver’s credit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(574,3,'Cindy and James have an AGI amount in 2024 of $150,000. They adopt a U.S. child with special needs by year-end. What is the maximum adoption credit that the couple can claim in 2024 considering the following expenses that they paid in adopting the child?nn   Attorney fees                           $2,500n   Adoption fees                            2,200n   Court costs                                500n   Travel expense                             750n   Meals and lodging during their travels     150','[\"$2,200\",\"$5,950\",\"$6,100\",\"$16,810\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 17, pages 2 and 3, a taxpayer may be able to take a tax credit of up to $16,810 for qualified expenses paid to adopt an eligible child in 2024. The credit may be allowed for the adoption of a child with special needs even if the taxpayer does not have any qualified expenses.nnFirst, a taxpayer\'s credit is reduced if modified AGI is greater than $252,150 and less than $292,150 and is zero if the modified AGI is or is greater than $292,150.nnSecond, adoption expenses must be reasonable and necessary expenses directly related to, and whose principal purpose is for, the legal adoption for an eligible child. Examples of qualifying expenses include adoption fees, court costs, attorney fees, travel expenses (including amounts spent for meals and lodging while away from home), and re-adoption expense to adopt a foreign child. Examples of nonqualifying expenses include those that violate state or federal law, are for carrying out any surrogate parenting arrangement, are for adopting a taxpayer\'s spouse\'s child, or are paid or reimbursed by the taxpayer\'s employer or any other person or organization.nnThird, if a taxpayer adopts a U.S. child with special needs, they may be able to exclude up to $16,810 and claim a credit for additional expenses up to $16,810 (minus any qualified adoption expenses claimed for the same child in a prior year). The exclusion may be available even if the taxpayer or their employer did not pay any qualified adoption expenses, provided the employer has a written qualified adoption assistance program. (See Form 8839 Instructions, page 3.)nnAs a result, the couple can claim the entire $16,810 credit in 2024 because the adoption is of a special-needs child. If the couple had adopted a child without special needs, they could claim a credit of $6,100, which is the sum of the expenses ($2,500, $2,200, $500, $750, and $150).nnIn addition, if the eligible child is a foreign child, the taxpayer cannot take the adoption credit or exclusion unless the adoption becomes final. A child is a foreign child if he or she was not a citizen or resident of the United States (including U.S. possessions) at the time the adoption effort began. The taxpayer should take the credit or exclusion as shown in the \"Foreign Adoption\" table appearing on page 3 of the Form 8839 Instructions.nnBecause the adoption credit is not refundable after 2011, a taxpayer may be able to carry forward any unused credit amounts to future tax years. The 2024 Form 8839 and its instructions will have information on the credit carryforward. (See Form 8839 Instructions, page 8.)n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(575,3,'A couple filed their 2008 return as married filing jointly and claimed $7,500 for the first-time homebuyer credit. The couple used this home as a primary residence. In 2024 they converted the home into rental property. What, if any, is the tax obligation of the taxpayers regarding the first-time homebuyer credit?','[\"They must pay the unpaid balance of the credit.\",\"Since they used this home as a primary residence for 5 years, there is no requirement to repay.\",\"They must prorate the credit received over 15 years and repay 50% of the original credit.\",\"They must reduce their depreciable basis in the property by 50% of the unpaid balance of the credit.\"]',0,'The Form 5405 Instructions, page 1, provide that a taxpayer must file Form 5405 (Repayment of the First-Time Homebuyer Credit) with their 2024 tax return if they purchased the home in 2008 and:nnThey disposed of it in 2024; or:nThey ceased using it as their main home in 2024.nIn the case of a 2008 purchase where the taxpayer disposes of the home or where it ceases to be the main home, the taxpayer must repay the balance of the unpaid credit with their 2024 tax return.nnThe exception to the repayment is if the taxpayer’s home was destroyed or condemned, or they disposed of the home under threat of condemnation, and they didn\'t acquire a new main home within 2 years of the event. None of the repayment exceptions apply to this question. 2024 is the final year for credit repayment.nnHence, the correct response is the taxpayer must pay the unpaid balance of the credit since they are no longer using it as their main home.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(576,3,'Which of the following cannot claim the premium tax credit?','[\"An individual whose spouse is enrolled in a qualified health plan\",\"An individual who inherited a $1.5 million non-income-producing vacation home\",\"An individual whose household income increases to 390% of the federal poverty line\",\"An individual who becomes eligible as a dependent on their parent\\u2019s joint tax return\"]',3,'Publication 974, page 4, addresses the issue of who can take the premium tax credit (PTC). A person can take the PTC for 2024 if they meet the conditions under (1) and (2):nnFor at least one month of the year, all of the following were true:nAn individual in the person’s tax family was enrolled in a qualified health plan offered through the Health Insurance Marketplace on the first day of the month.nThat individual was not eligible for minimum essential coverage for the month, other than coverage in the individual market. An individual is generally considered eligible for minimum essential coverage for the month only if he or she was eligible for every day of the month. (See “Minimum Essential Coverage” on page 8 of Publication 974.)nThe portion of the enrollment premiums for the month for which the individual is responsible was paid by the due date of their tax return (not including extensions). However, if the individual became eligible for the advanced premium tax credit (APTC) because of a successful eligibility appeal, see “Enrollment premiums” on page 6 of Publication 974 for the date by which the individual’s portion of the enrollment premiums must be paid.nThe individual is an applicable taxpayer for 2024, which means they must meet all of the following requirements:nThe individual’s household income for 2024 is at least 100% but no more than 400% of the federal poverty line for their family size (see “Line 4” in the Form 8962 Instructions). However, having household income below 100% of the federal poverty line will not disqualify the individual from taking the PTC if they meet certain requirements described under “Household income below 100% of the federal poverty line” under “Line 6” in the Form 8962 Instructions, page 8.nNo one can claim the individual as a dependent on a tax return for 2024.nIf the individual was married at the end of 2024, generally they must file a joint return. However, filing a separate return from the individual’s spouse will not disqualify the individual from being an applicable taxpayer if they meet certain requirements described under “Married taxpayers,” which is covered in Publication 974, page 7.nAn individual is not entitled to the PTC for health coverage for an individual for any period during which the individual is not lawfully present in the United States.nnOf the four possible situations, an individual who becomes eligible as a dependent on their parent’s joint tax return is not eligible to claim the PTC.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(577,3,'Which of the following taxpayers would be said to have made a math or clerical error when claiming the earned income tax credit?','[\"Taxpayer A, who failed to provide a correct Social Security number\",\"Taxpayer B, who calculated the EIC incorrectly\",\"Both Taxpayers A and B made a math or clerical error.\",\"Neither Taxpayer A nor Taxpayer B made a math or clerical error.\"]',2,'A taxpayer may have their EIC denied or reduced as a result of a math or clerical error. In such cases, the taxpayer is not required to attach Form 8862 to their next tax return.nnWhat constitutes a math error is a situation where the taxpayer makes an arithmetic error on the tax form. In such a case, the Service can correct such errors and still process the claim. Also, a taxpayer that forgets to include a Social Security number on the tax form has a clerical error. In this case, however, the claim for the earned income credit (EIC) will be denied.nnAs a result, both Taxpayers A and B in this problem are seen to have made a math or clerical error in claiming the EIC.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(578,3,'Lenard (age 32) is eligible to enroll in his employer’s health plan that is both affordable and provides minimum value during the open enrollment period. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the premium tax credit (PTC)?','[\"Lenard is eligible to claim the PTC if he elects not to enroll in the employer\\u2019s plan.\",\"Lenard is eligible to claim the PTC for the entire year if he elects to enroll in the employer\\u2019s plan for only part of the year.\",\"Lenard is eligible to claim the PTC if his father is enrolled in his company\\u2019s plan and Lenard lives at his father\\u2019s home.\",\"Lenard is not eligible to claim the PTC if he elects not to enroll in the company\\u2019s plan.\"]',3,'If the taxpayer can enroll in employer coverage that is affordable and provides minimum value during an enrollment period and they elect not to enroll, they cannot claim the PTC for their coverage in a qualified health plan for the period they could have been enrolled in the employer coverage.nnPursuant to Publication 974, page 11, a taxpayer is not treated as eligible for employer coverage for those months that the taxpayer cannot receive benefits under the employer plan; for example, the taxpayer is in a waiting period before they are eligible to participate in the employer plan.nnAn individual who is not a member of the taxpayer’s tax family (for example, an adult nondependent child under age 26) but who can enroll in a taxpayer’s employer coverage is deemed to be eligible for the employer coverage only for the months the individual is enrolled. Lenard would not be eligible to enroll in his father’s plan since he is over age 26. (Publication 974, page 11)nnPursuant to Publication 974, page 12, employer health coverage is not considered affordable if, when the taxpayer enrolls in a qualified health plan, the Marketplace determines that the taxpayer’s share of the premiums cost for employer coverage will be more than 9.12% of what the Marketplace estimates will be the taxpayer’s household income.nnAs a result, Lenard is not eligible to claim the PTC in a qualified health plan because he is eligible to enroll (and elected not to enroll) in the employer coverage, which is both affordable and provides minimum coverage.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(579,3,'Martha and Max have two children. Martha and Max each have earned income of $10,000. They decided to file separate returns, with each one of them claiming one child as a dependent. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to claiming the earned income credit (EIC)?','[\"Either Martha or Max can claim the EIC, but not both spouses.\",\"Neither Martha nor Max can claim the EIC.\",\"Only Martha can claim the EIC.\",\"Only Max can claim the EIC.\"]',1,'As found in Rule 3 on page 5 of Publication 596, a taxpayer that is married is required to file a joint return in order to claim the EIC.nnThere is an exception to this rule as given in the explanation for Rule 3: the taxpayer cannot file as married filing separately unless the taxpayer\'s spouse did not live in the taxpayer\'s home at any time during the last 6 months of the year. In this case, the taxpayer may be able to file as head of household, instead of married filing separately, and as such may be able to claim the EIC.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(580,3,'Two taxpayers married on November 30. That same year, the husband enrolled in an accredited college to further his career and subsequently received a Form 1098-T, Tuition Statement. The wife was employed with an income of $45,000 and paid for the husband\'s education expenses. The taxpayers did not receive any other income for the year. Based on their circumstances, what is the correct method to report the education credit?','[\"Taxpayers must file a joint return to claim an education credit\",\"Based on the wife\'s AGI, they do not qualify to claim an education credit\",\"Husband is ineligible to claim an education credit because the wife paid his education expenses\",\"Wife should report nonqualified education expenses on Form 8663,\\u00a0Education Credits (American Opportunity and Lifetime Learning Credits)\"]',0,'According to Publication 970, eligible students for education credits include the taxpayer, their spouse, or a dependent listed on their tax return, as detailed on page 11. Furthermore, page 12 specifies that those who are married but file separately are not eligible to claim education credits. Therefore, since the couple is married and the taxpayer has covered the spouse’s educational expenses at an accredited institution, they must file a joint tax return to claim the credit. The income limits for claiming the American Opportunity and Lifetime Learning Credits range from $160,000 to $180,000 for those filing jointly, which means their income of $45,000 is well below this threshold. For reporting qualified education expenses, Form 8863 is the appropriate form, and it should not include nonqualified expenses.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(581,3,'Which of the following organizations qualify for deductible contributions (not dues)?','[\"A public library in your city\",\"The Salvation Army\",\"Churches\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'In order to deduct charitable contributions, those contributions must be made to a qualified organization. To become a qualified organization, most organizations, other than churches and governments, must apply to the IRS for such status. (Publication 526, page 2)nnThe money or property you give to the following organizations would be deductible as charitable contributions (Table 1, Publication 526, page 3):nnChurches, synagogues, temples, mosques, and other religious organizationsnFederal, state, and local governments, if your contribution is solely for public purposes (for example, a gift to reduce the public debt)nNonprofit schools and hospitalsnPublic parks and recreation facilitiesnThe Salvation Army, American Red Cross, CARE, Goodwill Industries, United Way, Boy Scouts of America, Girl Scouts of America, Boys and Girls Clubs of America, etc.nWar veterans\' groups',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(582,3,'Jack had the following income in 2024:nn$59,800 in wagesn$200 in interestn$10,000 in gambling winningsn$5,000 in short-term capital gainsnJack filed a Schedule A, Itemized Deductions, for 2024. While preparing that schedule, Jack listed the following deduction items he had incurred during the year:nn$2,500 in medical expensesn$8,000 of mortgage interest paidn$2,000 in real estate taxesn$1,600 in state taxesn$12,000 in gambling lossesn$3,400 in employee business expensesnWhat is the total amount of Schedule A itemized deductions that Jack can report in 2024?','[\"$26,000\",\"$23,500\",\"$21,600\",\"$21,000\"]',2,'There are a number of rules associated with calculating the amount of itemized deductions. To begin with, deductible real estate taxes are any state, local, or foreign taxes on real property levied for the general public welfare. A taxpayer can deduct these taxes only if they are assessed uniformly against all property under the jurisdiction of the taxing authority. The proceeds must be for general community or governmental purposes and not be a payment for a special privilege granted or service rendered to the taxpayer. Similarly, state and local income taxes are deductible. In this case, Jack is limited to $3,600 ($2,000 + $1,600). (Publication 17, pages 97–100, and Table 11-1 on page 100). Also be aware that the deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if married filing separately) beginning in 2018.nnPublication 502, page 3, provides that a taxpayer can deduct on Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) only the amount of the taxpayer\'s medical and dental expenses that is more than 7.5% of the taxpayer\'s adjusted gross income. In this case, Jack cannot deduct any medical expenses because his medical expenses of $2,500 are less than the limit amount of $5,625 ($75,000 × 0.075). (The 7.5% floor was extended for all taxpayers by the Further Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2020.)nnPublication 936, page 2 and the Instructions to Schedule A, Form 1040, page A-8, state, in general, that home mortgage interest is an itemized deduction and includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home), not to exceed the cost of the home. The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home or a second mortgage. Jack\'s mortgage amount is $8,000.nnPublication 17, page 76, provides that a taxpayer must report the full amount of his or her gambling winnings for the year on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) line 8. In addition, the taxpayer is able to deduct any gambling losses for the year on line 16, Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), as a miscellaneous deduction that is not subject to the 2% limitation. A taxpayer cannot deduct gambling losses that are more than the winnings. If the taxpayer cannot or does not itemize, then the taxpayer must still claim the gambling winning but cannot deduct losses. Thus, Jack can claim $10,000 as his gambling losses for the year.nnFinally, a taxpayer may no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses unless they fall into one of the following categories of employment or have certain qualified educator expenses (Publication 17, page 102). The eligible categories are:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnTherefore, unless a taxpayer falls into one of the qualified categories of employment, miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation can no longer be claimed. Jack cannot claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions. (Publication 17, page 102)nnThe total itemized deductions that Jack can take on his 2024 tax return is $21,600, which is the sum of $1,600, $2,000, $8,000, and $10,000 of the $12,000 gambling losses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(583,3,'A single taxpayer in 2024 may enjoy the benefit of IRC Section 199A without limitation if she does not have taxable income in excess of what amount?','[\"$191,950\",\"$182,100\",\"$241,950\",\"$483,901\"]',0,'The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 (TCJA) created IRC Section 199A, which allows owners of pass-through entities to deduct 20% of their qualified business income, with certain limitations being phased in for taxpayers with taxable income exceeding $383,900 (joint filers) or $191,950 (other filers) in 2024.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(584,3,'Jeremy decided to itemize on his 2024 return. He has the following receipts. Compute the amount of deduction for taxes he can take on his Schedule A, Itemized Deductions.nnState income tax: $3,000nFederal income tax: $12,000nCounty real estate tax: $2,000nFee for his car inspection that he uses only personally: $50nHomeowners\' association fees on his personal home: $500nSelf-employment tax of $1,000','[\"$18,550\",\"$6,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$5,500\"]',2,'Table 11-1, which appears on page 100 of Publication 17, contains a listing of the taxes that are generally deductible by a taxpayer as an itemized deduction. The list contains items such as state and local taxes, foreign income taxes, real estate taxes, and property taxes.nnThe following list of items generally is not deductible as real estate taxes: taxes for local benefits, itemized charges for services (such as trash and garbage pickup fees), transfer taxes (or stamp taxes), rent increases due to higher real estate taxes, and homeowners\' association charges. (Publication 17, page 100)nnPersonal property tax is deductible if it is a state or local tax that is charged on personal property, based only on the value of the personal property, and charged on a yearly basis, even if it is collected more or less than once a year. (Publication 17, page 100)nnFinally, self-employment taxes are deductible as an adjustment for AGI and not as an itemized deduction. (Publication 17, page 100)nnNote: The deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if married filing separately).nnHence, Jeremy would have $5,000 in itemized taxes for the year ($3,000 in state income taxes and $2,000 in county real estate taxes).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(585,3,'Generally, a taxpayer may deduct the cost of medical expenses on Schedule A for which of the following?','[\"Doctor-prescribed birth control pills\",\"Controlled substances like marijuana that are in violation of federal law\",\"Trips for general health improvement\",\"Maternity clothes\"]',0,'Medical expenses include amounts paid for the diagnosis, cure, mitigation, treatment, or prevention of disease, and the costs for treatments affecting any part or function of the body. The primary purpose of the medical care expenses must be primarily to alleviate or prevent a physical or mental defect or illness. Dental expenses that are incurred are also deemed to be medical expenses. If the expenses incurred are merely beneficial to general health, such as vitamins or a vacation, they are not deductible. Additionally, medical expenses include the premiums paid for medical insurance, amounts paid for qualified long-term care services, and limited amounts paid for qualified long-term care insurance contracts. (Publication 502, page 5)nnAccording to Revenue Ruling 73-200, birth control pills are considered deductible medical expenses. However, Publication 502, page 16 indicates that maternity clothes are not deductible, and Regulation Section 1.213-1(e)(1)(iv) denies the deductibility of trips made for general health improvement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(586,3,'Thomas files a Form 1040-NR in 2024. Which of the following items cannot be deducted as an itemized deduction on his 2024 return?','[\"State and local income taxes withheld from the taxpayer\'s salary during 2024 on income connected with a U.S. trade or business\",\"Losses related to exempt income connected with a non-U.S. business in 2024\",\"Deductions apportioned to income connected with a U.S. business in 2024\",\"Contributions given to U.S. organizations that are religious, charitable, educational, or scientific in purpose\"]',1,'The Form 1040-NR Instructions, page 38, provide that a person filing Form 1040NR includes only those deductions and losses properly allocated and apportioned to income effectively connected with a U.S. trade or business. A person, however, does not include deductions and/or losses that relate to exempt income or to income that is not effectively connected with a U.S. trade or business.nnState and local income taxes withheld from the taxpayer\'s salary during 2024 on income connected with a U.S. trade or business are deductible. Likewise, contributions given to U.S. organizations that are religious, charitable, educational, scientific, or literary in purpose are deductible.nnAs a result, Thomas cannot include as an itemized deduction loss related to exempt income connected with a non-U.S. business in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(587,3,'George had the following income and expenses:nnInterest and ordinary dividend income of $8,000nGross wages of $100,000nMargin interest of $10,000nMortgage interest of $6,000nInterest of $3,000 on a mobile home used as a second homenCredit card interest of $2,000nHow much interest can George deduct on Schedule A for 2024?','[\"$21,000\",\"$18,000\",\"$17,000\",\"$19,000\"]',2,'The Instructions to Schedule A, Form 1040, page 8, indicate a taxpayer cannot deduct personal interest. Examples of personal interest include car loans, credit card interest, etc. The instructions also indicate the taxpayer is entitled to deduct qualified home mortgage interest and interest on student loans (on Schedule 1).nnPublication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan (provided that the equity loan is used to buy, build, or improve the residence). Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnIn the case where a taxpayer borrows money to buy property that is held for investment, the interest that the taxpayer pays is investment interest and it can be deducted up to the amount of investment income. However, a person cannot deduct interest incurred to produce tax-exempt income. Investment income generally includes items such as interest, ordinary dividends, annuities, and royalties (Publication 550, pages 45–46).nnGeorge is able to deduct $17,000 of interest expenses, which is the sum of his mortgage interest of $6,000, interest on his second home (i.e., mobile home) loan of $3,000, and interest on his margin account of $8,000, which equals his investment income for the year (interest and dividend income of $8,000). The remaining margin interest of $2,000 ($10,000 − $8,000) cannot be deducted; however, George can carry over this amount to the next tax year. The interest carried over is treated as investment interest paid or accrued in that next year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(588,3,'A taxpayer is a cash basis taxpayer. During the year, he paid the following medical expenses for himself and his daughter, Johanna, whom he claims as a dependent on his tax return:nn$310 for glasses for Johanna and $290 for himselfn$650 for a dental root canal procedure for himn$900 for hospital emergency services; of which $700 was paid by insurance in the same yearn$1,250 for Johanna\'s braces, which he charged to his credit card in December and paid in January of the next yearn$500 for prescriptions for allergiesn$2,200 cosmetic plastic surgerynThe taxpayer\'s medical expense deduction before limitations is:','[\"$6,100.\",\"$4,150.\",\"$3,200.\",\"$5,400.\"]',2,'The list of items that are and are not treated as deductible medical and dental expenses are provided on pages 15–17 of Publication 502. The following items are deductible medical and dental expenses:nnHospital services fees (lab work, therapy, nursing services, surgery, etc.)nMedical services fees (from doctors, dentists, surgeons, specialists, and other medical practitioners)nPrescription medicines (prescribed by a doctor) and insulinnSpecial items (artificial limbs, false teeth, eyeglasses, contact lenses, hearing aids, crutches, wheelchair, etc.)nAccording to page 15 of Publication 502, expenses incurred for surgery that is purely cosmetic are not deductible.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer is able claim medical expenses of $3,200, which is the sum of glasses for Johanna and the taxpayer of $600, dental cost of $650, hospital ER services of $900, Johanna\'s braces of $1,250, and prescriptions of $500, less the insurance company\'s reimbursement amount of $700. Cosmetic plastic surgery costs are not deductible medical expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(589,3,'During the year 2024, Ted is self-employed and drives his car 5,000 miles to visit clients, 10,000 miles to get to his office, and 500 miles to attend business-related seminars. He also spent $300 for airfare to another business seminar and $200 for parking at his office. Using 67 cents per mile, what is his deductible transportation expense?','[\"$500\",\"$3,985\",\"$4,185\",\"$10,385\"]',1,'Publication 463, pages 13 through 17, states that there are some expenses a taxpayer can deduct for business transportation when not traveling away from home. These expenses include the cost of transportation by air, rail, bus, taxi, etc., and the cost of driving and maintaining the taxpayer\'s car.nnTransportation expenses include the ordinary and necessary costs of all of the following.nnnGetting from one workplace to another in the course of your business or profession when you are traveling within the area of your tax home (Tax home is defined under the heading of “Travel Expenses” in chapter 1 of Publication 463.)nVisiting clients or customersnGoing to a business meeting away from your regular workplacenGetting from your home to a temporary workplace when you have one or more regular places of work (These temporary workplaces can be either within the area of the taxpayer\'s tax home or outside that area.)nTed would be able to deduct $3,685 in transportation expense for the year. This amount is equal to the sum of mileage expense for his car of $3,685 (5,500 miles × 0.67 per mile) and airfare to a business seminar of $300. The mileage to the office and his parking expense at the office are not deductible.nnnNote: For 2024, the standard mileage rate for the cost of operating your car for business use is 67 cents (0.67) per mile. (Publication 463, page 14) If the taxpayer was an employee with unreimbursed business expenses, he or she cannot deduct the expenses because TJCA suspended the 2% miscellaneous deductions for 2018 through 2026.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(590,3,'Of the following medical expenses paid by Bill during 2024, how much can he deduct (before limitations)?nn$1,000 for his wife Mary\'s hospitalization in 2023; they were married in 2024 when Bill paid for the services.n$1,000 for Mary\'s daughter\'s braces; she is Bill and Mary\'s dependent in 2024 (assume expenses were paid in 2024).n$2,000 for Bill\'s son\'s 2023 medical treatment; he was Bill\'s dependent in 2023 but does not qualify for 2024.','[\"$4,000\",\"$2,000\",\"$1,000\",\"$0\"]',0,'According to Publication 502, page 3, a taxpayer can include expenses paid for themselves, as well as those paid for someone who was their spouse or their dependent either when the services were provided or when you paid for them. Spouse\'s medical expenses can be deducted if either the couple was married at the time of the receipt of medical services or at the time the medical expenses were paid. Therefore, Bill can deduct his wife Mary\'s hospitalization of $1,000 even if they were incurred prior to their marriage as long as he paid for the expenses while married.nnBill can also deduct his stepdaughter\'s braces expenses as she is his dependent. Similar to the above, the requirement to be able to deduct medical expenses for a dependent if the person was a dependent either at the time the medical services were provided or at the time you paid the expense. The same applies to Bill\'s son. As such, Bill can deduct all $4,000 medical expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(591,3,'Tim and Tina teach in the local high school. During 2024, Tina spent $425 on supplies that were used in her classes and Tim spent $150 on supplies that were used in his classes. What are the maximum educator expenses that the couple can claim on their tax return if the couple files jointly in 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$450, which is $300 for Tina and $150 for Tim\",\"$400, which is $250 for Tina and $150 for Tim\",\"$575, which is $425 for Tina and $150 for Tim\"]',1,'Form 1040 Instructions, page 87, states, in part, that an eligible educator can deduct up to $300 of qualified expenses paid in the year as an adjustment to gross income on Form 1040 or 1040-SR, line 11. In the case where both spouses are eligible educators and are filing a joint return, the maximum deduction is $600. However, neither spouse can deduct more than $300 of his or her qualified expenses.nnAn eligible educator is a kindergarten through grade 12 teacher, instructor, counselor, principal, or aide who worked in a school for at least 900 hours during a school year.nnIn this case, the couple would be able to deduct up to $450. That is, Tina would be able to deduct up to $300 of her $425 expenses and Tim would be able to deduct up to $150 of his expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(592,3,'Which of the following statements is correct regarding Form 8995, Qualified Business Income (QBI) Deduction Simplified Computation?','[\"Corporations should complete the Form 8995 to claim the QBI Deduction on their corporate returns\",\"Taxpayers will receive the Form 8995 from the IRS, if they are determined to be eligible for the QBI Deduction\",\"A single individual with QBI, whose taxable income doesn\'t exceed the threshold amount, should use the Form 8995 to claim the QBI Deduction\",\"A partnership is required to attach Form 8995 to their partnership tax return to claim the QBI Deduction\"]',2,'Only individuals, eligible trusts, and estates can use Form 8995 to calculate the QBI deduction. The QBI deduction is 20% of the qualified business income from pass-through entities, as well as qualified real estate investment trust (REIT) dividends and qualified publicly traded partnership (PTP) income. The QBI deduction is not available to C corporations.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(593,3,'Which of the following may not be deducted as medical expenses? (Disregard any limitations that may apply.)','[\"$1,000 long-term care insurance\",\"$300 for maternity clothes\",\"$600 for eyeglasses\",\"$3,000 to a family physician for medical care\"]',1,'The lists for items that are and are not treated as deductible medical and dental expenses are provided on pages 15 through 17 of Publication 502. The following items are deductible medical and dental expenses:nnHospital services fees (lab work, therapy, nursing services, surgery, etc.)nMedical services fees (from doctors, dentists, surgeons, specialists, and other medical practitioners)nPrescription medicines (prescribed by a doctor) and insulinnSpecial items (artificial limbs, false teeth, eyeglasses, contact lenses, hearing aids, crutches, wheelchair, etc.)nPage 16 of the same Publication indicates maternity clothes are not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(594,3,'How is QBI defined?','[\"The net amount of income, gain, deductions, and loss from the operation of a business, including investment income\",\"The net amount of income and gain from the operations of a business, excluding investment income\",\"The net amount of income and gains from the operations of a business, including investment income\",\"The net amount of income, gain, deductions, and loss from the operation of a business, excluding investment income\"]',3,'Between 2018 and 2025, individuals will get a deduction of 20% of qualified business income (QBI) from pass-through entities, such as partnerships, limited liability companies, S corporations, and sole proprietorships (including a sole-member limited liability company). QBI is the net amount of income, gain, deduction, and loss from the operation of a business, not including investment income.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(595,3,'As a result of an accident, Thomas is required by his doctor to use a wheelchair. He arranges to have a ramp built at his front door and widens all the doorways to accommodate his wheelchair. The value of his house has not increased. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The costs of the ramp and its installation are deductible as a medical expense.\",\"The costs of the widening of the doorways are deductible as a medical expense.\",\"The total cost of these improvements is deductible as a medical expense.\",\"The total cost of these improvements is\\u00a0not\\u00a0deductible as a medical expense.\"]',2,'Publication 502, page 6, states that a taxpayer can include in medical expenses amounts that are paid for special equipment installed in a home, or for improvements, if their main purpose is medical care for the taxpayer, taxpayer\'s spouse, or dependent. The cost of permanent improvements that increase the value of property may be partly included as a medical expense. The cost of the improvement is reduced by the increase in the value of the taxpayer\'s property. The difference is a medical expense. If the value of the property is not increased by the improvement, the entire cost is included as a medical expense.nnCertain improvements made to accommodate a home to a taxpayer\'s disabled condition, or that of the taxpayer\'s spouse or dependents that live with the taxpayer, do not usually increase the value of the home and the cost can be included in full as medical expenses. These improvements include, but are not limited to:nnconstructing entrance or exit ramps for the person\'s home,nwidening doorways at entrances or exits to the person\'s home, andnmoving or modifying electrical outlets and fixtures.nFor a more detailed discussion of this topic, including additional examples of qualified improvement, see Publication 502.nnSince the improvements did not increase the value of Thomas\'s home, the total cost of these improvements is deductible as a medical expense.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(596,3,'Which of the following types of taxes can be deducted on Schedule A?','[\"Transfer taxes on the sale of a residence\",\"A tax on a motor vehicle based on engine horsepower\",\"A tax on a motor vehicle based on vehicle weight\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Table 11-1, which appears on page 100 of Publication 17, contains a listing of the taxes that are generally deductible by a taxpayer as an itemized deduction. The list contains items such as state and local taxes, foreign income taxes, real estate taxes, and personal property taxes.nnTransfer taxes (or stamp taxes) and similar taxes and charges on the sale of a personal home are not deductible. If they are paid by the buyer, they are included in the cost basis of the property. (Publication 17, page 101)nnPersonal property tax is deductible if it is a state or local tax that is charged on personal property, based only on the value of the personal property, and charged on a yearly basis, even if it is collected more or less than once a year. (Publication 17, page 101)nnAs a result, none of the taxes listed above are deductible on Schedule A.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(597,3,'Alberta and Archie (wife and husband) had water damage in their home during 2024 that ruined the furniture in their basement. The following items were completely destroyed and were not salvageable:nn                         Fair Marketn                       Value Just Prior      Originaln  Damaged Items           to Damage         Item Cost n Antique bed frame          $5,000            $ 4,000n Pool table                  8,000             10,000n Large-screen TV               700              2,500nTheir homeowner\'s insurance policy had a $10,000 deductible for the personal property, which was deducted from their insurance reimbursement of $12,700. Their adjusted gross income for 2024 was $30,000. What is the amount of casualty loss that Alberta and Archie can claim on their joint return for 2024?','[\"$10,000\",\"$6,500\",\"$6,900\",\"$0\"]',3,'The deduction for casualty and theft losses of personal-use property is limited. For tax years beginning after 2017 and before 2026, personal casualty and theft losses of an individual are deductible only to the extent they’re attributable to a federally declared disaster. The loss deduction is subject to the $100 limit per casualty and 10% of your adjusted gross income (AGI) limitation. (Publication 547, page 3)nnSince Alberta and Archie have a sustained a loss from a personal casualty and not a federal declared disaster, they are not able to claim a casualty loss.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(598,3,'Ernest, a self-employed watchmaker, traveled to Germany in September 2024. During his 5-day stay in Germany, he attended a 2-hour watchmaking seminar in the city of Berlin on a Monday and took a 4-hour tour of a watch manufacturing facility in Dresden on a Wednesday. The rest of the time Ernest spent hiking and touring the countryside. Ernest incurred the following costs for this trip:nnRound-trip airfare of $500nLodging of $1,000nMeals of $300nSeminar and tour registration fees of $200nIn 2024, what is the amount that Ernest can deduct for travel, meals, and entertainment for this trip to Germany?','[\"$2,000\",\"$800\",\"$200\",\"$0\"]',2,'Publication 463, page 7, provides that if a taxpayer travels outside the United States primarily for vacation or for investment purposes, the entire cost of the trip is a nondeductible personal expense. If, however, the taxpayer spends some time attending brief professional seminars or a continuing education program during his or her travels, the taxpayer can deduct registration fees and other expenses the taxpayer incurs that are directly related to his or her business.nnIn this case, Ernest spent little time on business and as such, he is unable to claim any of his costs as business expenses, except for the seminar and tour registration fees of $200.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(599,3,'During the year, Ron paid $85 to have his tax return prepared. He also paid a lawyer $215 to prepare his will. At work, he paid union dues of $650, bought safety boots for $200, and contributed $75 to collections for sick co-workers. What is Ron\'s miscellaneous deduction on his Schedule A, before the 2% limitation?','[\"$935\",\"$0\",\"$1,010\",\"$1,150\"]',1,'Beginning in 2018, certain miscellaneous deductions have been suspended. Two categories of miscellaneous expenses that have been suspended are: miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% AGI floor and those expenses that are traditionally nondeductible under the Internal Revenue Code.nnSuspended miscellaneous itemized deductions include:nnUnreimbursed employee expenses (exceptions apply, see below), which included union dues, uniforms, certain education expenses.nAppraisal FeesnInvestment Fees and Expenses (includes safe deposit box fees)nCasualty and theft lossesnDepreciation on home computernFees to collect interest and dividendsnHobby expensesnIndirect Deductions of Pass-through EntitiesnLegal expenses.nUnless Ron is in one of the four categories of excepted professionals who continue to be allowed to deduct unreimbursed employee business expenses, he cannot deduct them on his Schedule A.nnBeginning in 2018, certain miscellaneous deductions have been suspended. Two categories of miscellaneous expenses that have been suspended are: miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% AGI floor and those expenses that are traditionally nondeductible under the Internal Revenue Code.nnArmed Forces reservists.nQualified performing artists.nFee-basis state or local government officials.nEmployees with impairment-related work expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(600,3,'Keith and Margaret had an adjusted gross income of $100,000. They had real estate taxes of $4,000, mortgage interest of $12,000, home equity loan interest of $6,000 (used to substantially improve the home), automobile loan interest of $3,000, second home mortgage interest of $4,000 (proceeds used to purchase a new car), and credit card interest of $2,000. What is the total allowable interest deduction?','[\"$26,000\",\"$18,000\",\"$22,000\",\"$12,000\"]',1,'The instructions to Schedule A (Form 1040), page 8, indicate a taxpayer cannot deduct personal interest. Examples of personal interest include car loans, credit card interest, etc. The instructions also indicate the taxpayer is entitled to deduct qualified home mortgage interest and interest on student loans (on Schedule 1).nnPublication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan (provided that the equity loan is used to improve the residence). Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnFor Keith and Margaret, they are able to deduct $18,000 of interest expenses, which is the sum of the couple\'s mortgage of $12,000 and interest on the home equity loan of $6,000. Automobile loan interest and credit card interest are not deductible interest for tax purposes. Real estate taxes of $4,000 are deductible as taxes (not interest).nnNote: Regarding the second home mortgage interest of $4,000, Publication 936, page 1 states, \"No matter when the indebtedness was incurred, you can no longer deduct the interest from a loan secured by your home to the extent the loan proceeds weren\'t used to buy, build, or substantially improve your home.\" Since the interest was used to purchase a new car and was not related to the home, the second home mortgage interest of $4,000 would not be deductible on Schedule A.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(601,3,'In 2024, John donated $100 to the United Way, $200 to Veterans of Foreign Wars, and $300 to his neighbor whose home was destroyed by a tornado. How much is John\'s deduction for charitable contributions for 2024?','[\"$300\",\"$400\",\"$500\",\"$600\"]',0,'Publication 526, page 21, provides, in part, that a charitable contribution is a donation or gift to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. It is voluntary and is made without getting, or expecting to get, anything of equal value.nnIn this problem, one must assume that the United Way and the Veterans of Foreign Wars are both qualified organizations and as such, John\'s contributions of $300 ($100 and $200, respectively) qualify as deductions (see Table 1 in Publication 526, page 3). It is also assumed John meets the substantiation for his charitable contributions (copy of check, receipts, etc.) John\'s contribution to his neighbor, however, would not qualify since the contribution is to a person and not to a qualified charity.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(602,3,'Ms. Hazelnut works in sales. None of her expenditures are reimbursed by her employer. Her adjusted gross income is $100,000. She has the following expenditures during 2024:nnCost of computer class needed for her job: $500nBusiness liability insurance: $250nDues to chamber of commerce where she obtains leads for her business: $250nAirfare to visit her mother: $1,000nCost of two new business suits: $500nCompute Ms. Hazelnut\'s miscellaneous itemized deductions after limitations.','[\"$0\",\"$250\",\"$1,000\",\"$2,500\"]',0,'Beginning in 2018, a taxpayer can no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses unless they fall into one of the following categories of employment or have certain qualified educator expenses (Publication 17, page 101). The eligible categories are:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnTherefore, unless a taxpayer falls into one of the qualified categories of employment, miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation can no longer be claimed. Ms. Hazelnut cannot claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions. (Publication 17, page 100)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(603,3,'Contribution deductions may be limited to 20%, 30%, or 50% of your adjusted gross income. Organizations that qualify for the 50% limit include:','[\"churches and conventions or associations of churches.\",\"educational organizations with regular faculty and curriculum and regularly enrolled students.\",\"hospitals and certain medical research organizations associated with these hospitals.\",\"All of the organizations listed\"]',3,'Publication 526, page 15, discusses organizations that fall into the 50% limit organizations for deductible charitable contributions. A partial list of the types of organizations that are 50% limit organizations includes the following:nnChurches and conventions or associations of churchesnEducational organizations with a regular faculty and curriculum that normally have a regularly enrolled student body attending classes on sitenHospitals and certain medical research organizations associated with these hospitalsnPublicly supported charitiesnAs a result of TCJA of 2017, the amount a taxpayer can deduct for charitable cash contributions generally is limited to no more than 60% of their adjusted gross income. Their deduction, however, may be further limited to 50% (non-cash 50% charitable contributions), 30%, or 20% of their AGI depending on the type of property given and the type of organization the property is given to. A higher limit applies to certain qualified conservation contributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(604,3,'For medical expenses to be deductible as an itemized deduction in the current year, the expense must exceed what percentage of adjusted gross income?','[\"2.00%\",\"7.50%\",0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625,\"Medical expenses are no longer deductible\"]',1,'Publication 502, page 3, states that only the amount of medical expenses that exceeds 7.5% of adjusted gross income (AGI) can be deducted.nnFor example: If a client has an AGI of $100,000 and medical expenses of $5,000, since $7,500 is 7.5% of their AGI, the client is unable to deduct any medical expenses. However, if the client’s medical expenses were $8,000, they would be able to deduct $500 in medical expenses ($8,000 - $7,500).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(605,3,'Jean and Robert have total wages of $95,000 plus interest income of $3,000 and dividends of $2,000 (assume these are nonqualified dividends). They paid mortgage interest of $7,000 (assume indebtedness does not exceed $750,000), car loan interest of $2,000, mobile home interest of $4,000, personal loan interest of $1,000, and margin interest of $6,000. How much interest can Jean and Robert deduct on Schedule A?','[\"$16,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$12,000\",\"$13,000\"]',0,'Publication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest is an itemized deduction and includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan. Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnIn addition, Publication 550, page 45, states, in general, investment interest expense is limited to the amount of a taxpayer\'s net investment income, which is the difference between investment income and investment expense. Note that Form 4952 is used to compute the allowable investment interest expense for the year. Any investment interest not deductible in the current year can be carried over to the next tax year.nnFor Jean and Robert, they are able to deduct $16,000 of interest expenses, which is the sum of the couple\'s mortgage of $7,000, mobile home interest (second home) of $4,000, and interest on their margin account of $5,000, which equals the investment income of the couple (interest income of $3,000 and dividend income of $2,000). Automobile loan interest and personal loan interest are not deductible interest for tax purposes. The remaining $1,000 of interest on the margin account is not deductible since it exceeds the investment income for the year; however, Jean and Robert can carry over this amount to the next tax year. The interest carried over is treated as investment interest paid or accrued in that next year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(606,3,'Which of the following mandatory employee contributions are deductible as a state income tax on Schedule A of Form 1040 in 2024?nn1. Alaska Unemployment Compensation Fund.n2. New York Nonoccupational Disability Benefit Fundn3. Rhode Island Temporary Disability Benefit Fundn4. Washington State Supplemental Workmen\'s Compensation Fund','[\"1 and 2 only\",\"1, 2, and 3 only\",\"All of the contributions listed are deductible.\",\"None of the contributions listed are deductible.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 17, pages 97 and 98, mandatory contributions made to state benefit funds withheld from a taxpayer\'s wages and that provide protection against loss of wages are deductible as state income taxes on Schedule A.nnIncluded in this category are payments such as the:nnUnemployment Compensation Fund of Alaska, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania;nNonoccupational Disability Benefit Fund of California, New Jersey, and New York;nRhode Island Temporary Disability Benefit Fund; andnWashington State Supplemental Workmen\'s Compensation Fund.nEmployee contributions to private or voluntary disability plans are not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(607,3,'Samuel, a civil engineer, drives his own vehicle to various locations to inspect bridges for safety standard requirements. His employer reimburses Samuel $400 each month for various business expenses and does not expect Samuel to provide proof of his expenses. His employer included this $4,800 reimbursement in Samuel\'s 2024 W-2 as part of his wages. In 2024, Samuel incurred $3,000 in transportation expense, $1,000 in parking and tolls expense, $1,800 in car repairs expense, and $600 for expenses while attending a professional association convention. Assume that Samuel uses the vehicle for business purposes only and that he maintains adequate documentation to support all of his above expenditures.nnWhat amount is Samuel entitled to deduct on his Schedule A for itemized deductions?','[\"$6,400 of expenses subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation\",\"$1,600, the difference between his expenditures and what he was reimbursed\",\"$0 since he cannot deduct expenses subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation\",\"$4,800 since his employer follows a nonaccountable plan\"]',2,'The treatment of reimbursements depends on the type of plan maintained by the employer; there are two basic types of reimbursement arrangements: accountable plans and nonaccountable plans. (Publication 463, page 29)nnIf the plan is an accountable plan, the employer should not include any reimbursements in the employee\'s W-2 as part of his or her wages. If the employer did include the reimbursement amounts, then the employee should ask for a corrected Form W-2. If the plan is a nonaccountable plan, employees generally must complete Form 2106 to deduct travel, transportation, and entertainment expenses incurred. (Publication 463, page 29)nnUnder prior TCJA law, since Samuel uses his vehicle for business purposes only, he would be able to deduct all the expenses associated with the vehicle\'s use. Thus, he can deduct $6,400, which is the sum of $3,000, $1,000, $1,800, and $600 as a 2% miscellaneous deduction.nnHowever, TCJA has suspended the 2% miscellaneous deductions for 2018 through 2026, except for Armed Forces reservists, fee-based state or local government officials, qualified performing artists, or disabled employees with impairment-related work expenses. Therefore, Samuel cannot claim any deduction. (Publication 17, page 102)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(608,3,'A taxpayer is a cash basis taxpayer. In 2024, he incurred the following medical expenses for himself and his daughter, Terry, whom he claims as a dependent on his tax return.nn$250 for glasses for Terry and $200 for glasses for himselfn$800 for dental work for himselfn$900 for hospital emergency services, of which $700 was paid by insurancen$1,250 for Terry\'s braces, which he charged to his credit card in December 2024 and paid in Januaryn$300 for prescriptions for allergiesn$1,500 medical insurancenWhat is the taxpayer\'s medical expense deduction before limitations?','[\"$5,200\",\"$4,500\",\"$4,200\",\"$3,950\"]',1,'The lists for items that are and are not treated as deductible medical and dental expenses are provided in Publication 502, pages 5 through 17.nnThe following is a partial list of medical and dental expenses that are deductible:nnBirth control pill prescribed by your doctornEye surgery to promote the correct function of the eyenGuide dogs or other animals aiding the blind, deaf, and disablednPrescription medicines (prescribed by a doctor) and insulinnSpecial items (artificial limbs, false teeth, eyeglasses, contact lenses, hearing aids, crutches, wheelchair, etc.)nHospital services fess (lab work, therapy, nursing services, surgery, etc.)nMedical and hospital insurance premiumsnMedical services fees (from doctors, dentists, surgeons, specialists, and other medical practitioners)nIn this problem, the taxpayer is able to claim medical expenses of $4,500, which is the sum of glasses for Terry and the taxpayer of $450, dental cost of $800, hospital ER services of $900, Terry\'s braces of $1,250, prescriptions of $300, and medical insurance of $1,500, less the insurance company\'s reimbursement amount of $700.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(609,3,'Sonja is a calendar-year taxpayer. A flood damaged her home in June 2024. The flood damaged or destroyed a considerable amount of property in her town. The president declared the area that includes Sonja\'s town a federal disaster area under section 401 of the Stafford Act as a result of the flood. In which year can Sonja choose to deduct the flood loss on her home?','[\"Only in 2023\",\"Only in 2024\",\"In either 2023 or 2024\",\"In either 2024 or 2025\"]',2,'Publication 547, page 3 states, in part, that there are three types of casualty losses:nnA federal casualty loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a federally declared disaster.nA disaster loss is a loss that is attributable to a federally declared disaster and that occurs in an area eligible for assistance pursuant to the Presidential declaration.nA qualified disaster loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a major disaster declared by the President under section 401 of the Stafford Act in 2016, as well as other specified events. If you suffered a qualified disaster loss, you are eligible to claim a casualty loss deduction, to elect to claim the loss in the preceding tax year, and to deduct the loss without itemizing other deductions on Schedule A (Form 1040).nGiven that in 2024, Sonja experienced a loss due to flooding in a qualified federally declared disaster area, she can elect to claim the loss in 2024 (the year the disaster occurred) or 2023 (the year that preceded the year the disaster occurred).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(610,3,'Joe made the following charitable contributions in 2024. How much can he deduct on Schedule A, Itemized Deductions?nn$300 check to local church but no written acknowledgmentn$600 by payroll deduction of $50 per month to United Wayn$100 fair market value of clothing donated that is in fair condition on September 1, 2024n$200 cash contribution to a local qualified charity','[\"$1,200\",\"$900\",\"$800\",\"$600\"]',3,'Publication 526, page 2, provides that a taxpayer can deduct contributions of money or property that are made to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. A contribution is “for the use of” a qualified organization when it is held in a legally enforceable trust for the qualified organization or in a similar legal arrangement.nnWith respect to contributed property to a qualified organization, a taxpayer generally can deduct the fair market value of the property at the time of the contribution. In the case of clothing and household items, a person cannot take a deduction for these items unless the item is in good used condition or better. An exception to this rule is if the taxpayer deducts more than $500 for an item and a qualified appraisal of the item is included in the return, a deduction for an item that is not in good used condition or better is deductible. (Publication 526, page 8)nnAnother restriction on the deductibility of charitable contributions pertains to the amount contributed. In particular, a taxpayer can claim a deduction for a contribution of $250 or more only if the taxpayer has a contemporaneously written acknowledgment of the contribution from the qualified organization or if the taxpayer has certain payroll deduction records (Publication 526, page 20). In figuring whether a taxpayer\'s contribution is $250 or more, the taxpayer does not combine multiple contributions. For example, if a person gave $25 per week, the weekly contributions do not need to be combined. Each payment is a separate contribution.nnA taxpayer cannot deduct a cash contribution, regardless of the amount, unless the taxpayer keeps records to prove the amount of the contribution made during the year. The kind of record required includes a bank record (e.g., a canceled check, a bank or credit union statement, or a credit card statement), a receipt, or a payroll deduction record. (Publication 526, page 20)nnGiven the above restrictions, Joe\'s charitable contributions for the year are limited to $600, which is the sum of his payroll deduction plan. The $200 cash contribution is not deductible since he has no documentation; the $300 contribution to his church is not permitted because he lacks an acknowledgment; and the clothes donation is not in good condition.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(611,3,'If the taxpayer makes a contribution by cash, check, credit card, or payroll deduction to a qualified organization, what record of the contribution is the taxpayer required to obtain from the organization?','[\"If the amount is for some item or service, like a charity dinner, and over $100, the taxpayer must have a separate acknowledgment for each contribution.\",\"For annual payroll deductions over $250, the taxpayer must have a separate acknowledgment for each contribution.\",\"Weekly contributions of $50 to the taxpayer\'s church must have a separate acknowledgment for each contribution.\",\"For contributions under $250, the taxpayer must keep an account, statement, receipt, or other reliable written record.\"]',3,'Publication 526, page 2, provides that a taxpayer can deduct contributions of money or property that are made to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. A contribution is “for the use of” a qualified organization when it is held in a legally enforceable trust for the qualified organization or in a similar legal arrangement.nnWith respect to contributed property to a qualified organization, a taxpayer generally can deduct the fair market value of the property at the time of the contribution.nnAnother restriction on the deductibility of charitable contributions pertains to the need to have an acknowledgment from the qualified organization (see Publication 526, page 20). In particular, a taxpayer can claim a deduction for a contribution of $250 or more only if the taxpayer has contemporaneous written acknowledgment of the contribution from the qualified organization or if the taxpayer has certain payroll deduction records.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nIf the taxpayer made more than one contribution of $250 or more, the taxpayer must have either a separate acknowledgment for each contribution or one acknowledgment that shows his or her total contributions.nn n nnA taxpayer cannot deduct a cash contribution, regardless of the amount, unless the taxpayer keeps as a record of the contribution a bank record (such as a canceled check, a bank copy of a canceled check, or a bank statement containing the name of the charity, the date, and the amount) or a written communication from the charity.nnGiven the above restrictions, the taxpayer needs to keep an account, statement, receipt or other reliable written record for contributions under $250 to satisfy the charitable contribution qualifications.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(612,3,'The rules of a university state that an individual can become a faculty member only if he or she achieves an advanced or graduate degree. University rules also state that an individual, hired as a temporary instructor without an advanced or graduate degree, can keep his or her instructing job only as long as he or she shows satisfactory progress toward achievement of this advanced or graduate degree. Mike has a bachelor\'s degree and was previously hired as a temporary instructor at this university. Mike is taking graduate courses toward his advanced degree, but has not met the minimum educational requirements to qualify as a faculty member. Which of the following statements is correct concerning Mike\'s graduate courses?','[\"The courses are considered to be qualifying work-related education.\",\"The courses are considered to be qualifying work-related education only if his employer signs a statement that his job requires the advanced degree.\",\"The courses are considered to be qualifying work-related education retroactively after he completes the advanced degree.\",\"The courses are\\u00a0not\\u00a0considered to be qualifying work-related education.\"]',3,'Prior to 2018, once a taxpayer meets the minimum educational requirements for his or her job, the taxpayer\'s employer or the law may require additional education. This additional education is qualifying work-related education and was deductible as a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% of AGI limitation if all three of the following requirements are met:nnIt is required for you to keep your present salary, status, or job,nThe requirement serves a bona fide business purpose of your employer, andnThe education is not part of a program that will qualify you for a new trade or business.nPrior to 2018, these education expenses would be included and reported under unreimbursed employee expenses. Beginning in 2018, a taxpayer can no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses unless they fall into one of the following categories of employment or have certain qualified educator expenses (Publication 17, page 98). The eligible categories are:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnTherefore, unless a taxpayer falls into one of the qualified categories of employment, miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation can no longer be claimed. Mike, therefore, cannot claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions. (Publication 17, page 102)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(613,3,'Which of the following miscellaneous itemized deductions is not subject to the 2% adjusted gross income limitation in 2024?','[\"Federal estate tax on income in respect of a decedent\",\"Gambling losses up to the amount of gambling winnings\",\"Casualty and theft losses from income-producing property\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 105, further provides a list of items that are deductible as miscellaneous itemized deductions that are not subject to the 2% limit. These items are reported on Schedule A (Form 1040 and Form 1040-SR), line 16 or Schedule A (Form 1040NR), line 7. The list of items includes but is not limited to:nnamortizable premium on taxable bonds,ncasualty and theft losses from income-producing property,nfederal estate tax on income in respect of a decedent,ngambling losses up to the amount of gambling winnings, nimpairment-related work expenses of persons with disabilities, nlosses from Ponzi-type investment schemes, nrepayments of more than $3,000 under a claim of right, nunlawful discrimination claims, and nunrecovered investment in an annuity.nAs a result of the above list, all the listed items are deductible as miscellaneous deductions that are not subject to the 2% limitation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(614,3,'Which of the following entertainment activities are deductible as a business expense?','[\"A meeting or discussion at a nightclub, theater, or sporting event\",\"A meeting or discussion during what is essentially a social gathering, such as a cocktail party\",\"A meeting with a group that includes persons who are not business associates at places such as cocktail lounges, country clubs, golf clubs, athletic clubs, or vacation resorts\",\"None of the listed entertainment activities are deductible entertainment expenses.\"]',3,'Publication 463, page 10, states, in part, for tax years 2018 through 2025 entertainment expenses are no longer deductible. The cost of business meals generally remains deductible, subject to the 50% limitation. See Section 274 for additional information on the changes.nnEntertainment includes any activity generally considered to provide entertainment, amusement, or recreation. Generally, entertainment expenses are nondeductible for expenses paid after December 2017. Facilities used in connection with entertainment and related membership dues (such as country club dues) are also non-deductible. Meal expenses are limited to 50% unless an exception applies.nnAs a result of the new law, the taxpayer is not able to deduct any of the entertainment expenses given in this problem.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(615,3,'Jack\'s antique car caught fire and was totally destroyed. The car was appraised for $22,500. Jack only had it insured for $15,000 since this was more than enough to cover his adjusted basis of $9,000. He decided not to replace the car. What should Jack report on his 2024 tax return?','[\"Deduct a loss of $7,500\",\"Deduct a loss of $6,000\",\"Report income of $6,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 547, page 3, provides, in part, that a casualty is the damage, destruction, or loss of property resulting from an identifiable event that is sudden, unexpected, or unusual.nnFor tax years 2018 through 2025, if you are an individual, casualty losses of personal-use property are deductible only if the loss is attributable to a federally declared disaster (federal casualty loss).nnOn the other hand, if a taxpayer receives an insurance or other reimbursement that is more than their adjusted basis in the destroyed or stolen property, they have a gain from the casualty or theft. In this case, they must include this gain in their income in the year the reimbursement is received, unless the taxpayer chooses to postpone reporting the gain as explained in Publication 547, page 13.nnIn this case, Jack has an adjusted basis of $9,000 and a decrease in the FMV of $22,500 ($22,500 − $0). Since the smaller of the two calculations is $9,000, this amount is compared to the insurance coverage, which is $15,000. The result is that Jack has income (not a loss) of $6,000 from the casualty, which he must claim on his tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(616,3,'Raul and Monika (spouses) are both lawyers and they contribute money to various organizations each year. They file a joint return and their adjusted gross income for 2024 is $100,000. They contributed to the following organizations in 2024:nn$5,000 to Alta Sierra country clubn$10,000 to prevent cruelty to animalsn$2,000 to State Bar association (This state bar association is not a political subdivision of the state, serves both public and private purposes, and the funds\' uses are unrestricted and can be for private purposes.)n$12,000 to a cancer research foundationnDonated clothing to the Salvation Army (Raul purchased the items for $1,000, but the fair market value of the same items at a thrift store is equal to $50.) The clothing is in good used condition.nHow much can Raul and Monika deduct as charitable contributions for the year 2024?','[\"$29,050\",\"$25,000\",\"$22,050\",\"$24,000\"]',2,'IncorrectnIn order to deduct charitable contributions, those contributions must be made to a qualified organization. To become a qualified organization, most organizations, other than churches and governments, must apply to the IRS for such status. (Publication 526, page 2)nnThe money or property you give to the following organizations would be deductible as charitable contributions as provided in Table 1 (Publication 526, page 3):nnChurches, a convention or association of churches, synagogues, temples, mosques, and other religious organizationsnFederal, state, and local governments, if your contribution is solely for public purposes (for example, a gift to reduce the public debt)nNonprofit hospitals and medical research organizationsnMost nonprofit charitable organizations such as United Way, including the Salvation Army, American Red Cross, CARE, and Goodwill IndustriesnMost nonprofit educational organizations, including Boy Scouts of America, Girl Scouts of America, Boys and Girls Clubs of America, colleges, and museumsnWar veterans\' groupsnExpenses paid for a student living with the taxpayer, sponsored by a qualified organizationnOut-of-pocket expenses when the taxpayer serves a qualified organization as a volunteernWith respect to contributed property to a qualified organization, a taxpayer generally can deduct the fair market value of the property at the time of the contribution (Publication 526, page 8). In the case of clothing and household items, a person cannot take a deduction for these items unless the item is in good used condition or better. An exception to this rule is if the taxpayer deducts more than $500 for an item and a qualified appraisal of the item is included in the return, a deduction for an item that is not in good used condition or better is deductible. (Publication 526, page 8)nnIn this case, the couple can deduct $22,050, which is the sum of $10,000 for cruelty prevention, $12,000 for cancer research, and $50 for fair market value (FMV) of the clothing donation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(617,3,'Mr. Hardwood has an adjusted gross income of $50,000. In 2024, he donated capital gain property valued at $25,000 to his church and did not choose to reduce the fair market value of the property by the amount that would have been long-term capital gain if he had sold it. His basis in the property was $20,000. In addition, he made the following contributions:nn$500 to upgrade the city public parkn$1,000 to the Hill City Chamber of Commercen$5,000 to a charitable organization in GermanynCompute Mr. Hardwood\'s deduction for charitable contributions in the current year (without regard to any carryover or carryback amounts).','[\"$25,000\",\"$31,500\",\"$16,500\",\"$15,500\"]',3,'Publication 526, page 2, provides, in part, that a taxpayer can deduct contributions of money or property that are made by the taxpayer to, or “for the use of,” a qualified organization. In general, a charitable contribution is a donation or gift to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. It is voluntary and is made without getting, or expecting to get, anything of equal value.nnIn the case of donated property, Publication 526, page 8, provides, in part, that if you contribute property to a qualified organization, you generally can deduct the fair market value of the property at the time of the contribution. Publication 526, pages 15–16, further provides that a special 30% limit applies to gifts of capital gain property to 50% limit organizations. However, the special 30% limit does not apply when you choose to reduce the fair market value of the property by the amount that would have been long-term capital gain if you had sold the property. Instead, only the 50% limit applies.nnThis special 30% limit for capital gain property is separate from the other 30% limit. Therefore, the deduction of a contribution subject to one 30% limit does not reduce the amount you can deduct for contributions subject to the other 30% limit. However, the total you deduct cannot be more than 50% of your adjusted gross income.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nYour adjusted gross income is $50,000. During the year, you gave capital gain property with a fair market value of $15,000 to a 50% limit organization. You do not choose to reduce the property\'s fair market value by its appreciation in value. You also gave $10,000 cash to a qualified organization that is not a 50% limit organization. The $15,000 gift of property is subject to one 30% limit and the $10,000 cash contribution is subject to the other 30% limit. The $10,000 cash contribution is fully deductible because the contribution is not more than the smaller of (i) 30% of your AGI ($15,000) and (ii) 50% of your AGI minus all contributions to a 50% organization ($25,000 – $15,000 = $10,000). The $15,000 is also fully deductible because the contribution is no more than 30% of your AGI minus all contributions to a 50% organization subject to the 60% or 50% limit ($25,000 – $10,000 = $15,000). Neither amount is reduced by the other, so the total deductible contribution is $25,000 (which is also not more than $50,000 of your AGI). (Publication 526, page 15)nn n nnA list of nonqualified organizations is provided in Table 1, page 3 of Publication 526. Contributions to nonqualified organizations include but not limited to contributions to chambers of commerce and foreign organizations. As such, they are not deductible as charitable contributions.nnIn this case, Mr. Hardwood has a charitable deduction of $15,500, which is the sum of capital gain property donation (limited to 30% of $50,000 or $15,000) and the city public park contribution ($500).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(618,3,'Which of the following costs are deductible on Form 1040, Schedule A, as taxes in 2024?nn1. Personal property tax on an airplanen2. Garbage pickup itemized on the real estate billn3. Real estate tax on property owned in Canadan4. Taxes for local benefits','[1,\"2 and 4\",\"1 and 3\",\"None of the costs are deductible.\"]',0,'If a taxpayer pays taxes that are not directly connected to a trade or business or with income-producing property, those taxes may be deductible as an itemized deduction on Schedule A. The following (as given in Publication 17, page 100, in Table 11-1 and discussed on page 100) illustrates which taxes may and may not be deducted.nn                       You Can Deduct           You Cannot Deduct      nReal Estate Taxes    State and local real    Taxes for local benefitsn                       estate taxes            (with exceptions)n n                                              Trash and garbage pickupn                                               fees (with exceptions)nn                                              Foreign real estate taxesn n                     Tenant\'s share of       Rent increase due to n                       real estate taxes       higher real estaten                       paid by cooperative     taxesn                       housing corporationn                                             Homeowners associationn                                               charges                 nPersonal Property    State and local         Custom duties that are notn  Taxes                personal property     expenses of your trade orn                       taxes                 business                  nOther Taxes          Taxes that are          State and local sales andn                       expenses of your        use taxes (see noten                       trade or business       below)n                       or of producing       n                       income                Federal excise taxes, suchn                                              as telephone taxesnn                     One-half of self-n                     employment tax paidnAdditionally, the following two tests must be met for any tax to be deducted (Publication 17, page 97):nnThe tax must be imposed on you, andnThe tax must be paid during your tax year.nAccordingly, the personal property tax on an airplane is the only taxes in the above question that may be deducted.nnTaxes for local benefits cannot be deducted, as indicated on page 101 of Publication 17. Foreign real estate taxes are no longer deductible as per TCJA of 2017.nnNote: The deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if married filing separately) beginning in 2018.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(619,3,'Johnny has been divorced for 4 years. He failed to make his alimony and support payments. The court ordered him to pay $1,500 as interest on the back alimony and support payments. He paid interest of $1,000 on a car loan, $2,500 on his outstanding credit card balance, $6,000 on a home equity loan not used to substantially improve home, and $10,000 on his mortgage. Other interest payments amounted to $2,500 on various appliance loan payments. How much is Johnny\'s deductible interest?','[\"$16,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$23,500\",\"$17,500\"]',1,'Instructions to Schedule A, Form 1040, page 8 indicate a taxpayer cannot deduct personal interest. Examples of personal interest include car loans, credit card interest, etc. The instructions also indicate the taxpayer is entitled to deduct qualified home mortgage interest and interest on student loans (on Schedule 1).nnPublication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan (provided that the equity loan is used to buy, build or improve the residence). Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnNo matter when the indebtedness was incurred, a taxpayer can no longer deduct the interest from a loan secured by their home (e.g., an equity loan) to the extent the loan proceeds weren\'t used to buy, build, or substantially improve their home.nnFor Johnny, he is only able to deduct $10,000 of interest expenses for his mortgage. The interest on the home equity loan of $6,000 is no longer deductible. Personal interest is not deductible for federal income tax purposes. As a result, interest on back alimony payments, automobile loan interest, credit card interest, and other various interest payments are not deductible interest for tax purposes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(620,3,'Cecilia, employed as a nurse, incurred the following expenses during 2024:n1. $2,000 in attorney fees related to the collection of alimony paymentsn2. $8,000 in gambling lossesn3. $1,000 in uniform purchase costsn4. $900 in union duesnCecilia also had stereo equipment valued at $3,000 stolen from her home in 2024. Cecilia\'s adjusted gross income (AGI) for 2024 was $90,000, included in which were gambling winnings of $2,000. For 2024, what is the amount of miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% of AGI limitation?n','[\"$3,900\",\"$2,100\",\"$100\",\"$0\"]',3,'Uniform dues and uniform purchase costs are examples of unreimbursed employee business expenses.nnBeginning in 2018, a taxpayer can no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses unless they fall into one of the following categories of employment or have certain qualified educator expenses (Publication 17, page 102). The eligible categories are:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnOther miscellaneous deductions subject to the 2% floor that have been suspended beginning 2018 include investment fees and expenses, hobby expenses, safe deposit box rent, tax preparation fees to name a few. See Publication 17, page 102 for a complete list.nnPublication 17, page 76, provides that a taxpayer must report the full amount of his or her gambling winnings for the year on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 8. In addition, the taxpayer is able to deduct any gambling losses for the year on line 16, Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), as a miscellaneous deduction that is not subject to the 2% limitation. A taxpayer cannot deduct gambling losses that are more than the winnings. If the taxpayer cannot or does not itemize, then the taxpayer must still claim the gambling winnings but cannot deduct losses. Thus, Cecilia can claim $2,000 as her gambling losses for the year as a miscellaneous deduction but are not subject to the 2% adjustment.nnHence, Cecilia cannot deduct any miscellaneous itemized deductions, which are subject to the 2% limitation.nnNote: Gambling losses are deductible, but not as 2% expenses. The questions asks for the total expenses that can be deducted as miscellaneous costs subject to the 2% floor limitation. Based on the above, the correct answer is $0.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(621,3,'In 2024, the U.S. President declared a federal disaster due to the flooding in one of the U.S. states. Lisa lives in that area and lost her home in the flood. What choice does she have regarding when she can claim the loss on her tax return?','[\"It must be claimed in 2023 if the return has not been filed by the date of the loss.\",\"It must be claimed in 2024 if the loss is greater than the modified adjusted gross income.\",\"It may be claimed in 2025 if an election is filed with the 2024 return.\",\"It may be claimed in 2023 or 2024.\"]',3,'Publication 547, page 3 states, in part, that there are three types of casualty losses:nnA federal casualty loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a federally declared disaster.nA disaster loss is a loss that is attributable to a federally declared disaster and that occurs in an area eligible for assistance pursuant to the Presidential declaration.nA qualified disaster loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a major disaster declared by the President under section 401 of the Stafford Act in 2016, as well as other specified events. If you suffered a qualified disaster loss, you are eligible to claim a casualty loss deduction, to elect to claim the loss in the preceding tax year, and to deduct the loss without itemizing other deductions on Schedule A (Form 1040).nIf a taxpayer suffered a qualified disaster loss, they are eligible to claim the loss on the current tax year or amended return for the preceding tax year. (Publication 547, page 16)nnGiven that, Lisa experienced a loss due to flooding in a qualified federally declared disaster area in 2024, she can elect to claim the loss in 2024, the year the disaster occurred, or 2023, the year that preceded the year the disaster occurred.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(622,3,'Martha quit her biology research job in August 2023 to become a full-time biology graduate student. She completed the graduate program in August 2024 and immediately took a job with a different employer as a biology researcher. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to deducting the cost of her education?','[\"It is\\u00a0not\\u00a0deductible as qualifying work-related education since it is a miscellaneous itemized deduction.\",\"It is deductible as qualifying work-related education only if Martha returned to her former employer.\",\"It is deductible as qualifying work-related education only if Martha does not return to her former employer.\",\"It is deductible as qualifying work-related education whether Martha returns to her former employer or takes a job with a new employer.\"]',0,'Prior to 2018, certain expenses including qualifying educational costs would be deductible on Schedule A as an unreimbursed employee expense. Beginning in 2018, a taxpayer can no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses unless they fall into one of the following categories of employment or have certain qualified educator expenses (Publication 17, page 102). The eligible categories are:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnTherefore, unless a taxpayer falls into one of the qualified categories of employment, miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation such as business deductions for work-related education can no longer be claimed. Martha cannot claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions. (Publication 17, page 102)nnPublication 970, pages 61 and 62, provides that a person that takes a temporary absence for a year or less in order to get education to maintain or improve skills needed in their present work and returns to the same general type of work is able to claim the education cost as qualifying work-related education. Hence, the employee does not need to return to the employer that he or she took the leave from, but the employee must return to the same general type of work.nnIf the absence is for more than a year, it is considered an indefinite absence and the cost would not be considered qualifying work-related education cost. Education during an indefinite absence, even if it maintains or improves skills needed in a person\'s present work, is considered to qualify the person for a new trade or business. In this case, it would not qualify as work-related education.nnSince Martha is not self-employed and is not in one of the qualified categories, she is unable to claim the education as a miscellaneous deduction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(623,3,'Paula won $5,000 in the lottery in 2024. She also won $200 playing bingo at her lodge hall. She is not a professional gambler. She kept meticulous records of the $6,550 she spent on gambling expenses. How much may she deduct on her Schedule A, as a miscellaneous deduction not subject to the 2% limitation?','[\"$0\",\"$200\",\"$5,200\",\"$6,550\"]',2,'Publication 17 (page 76) provides that a taxpayer must report the full amount of a person\'s gambling winnings for the year on Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR), line 8. In addition, the taxpayer is able to deduct any gambling losses for the year on Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), line 16 as a miscellaneous deduction that is not subject to the 2% limitation (Publication 17, page 105). A taxpayer cannot deduct gambling losses that are more than the winnings. If the taxpayer cannot or does not itemize, then the taxpayer must still claim the gambling winning but cannot deduct losses.nnA taxpayer must keep an accurate diary or similar record of his or her losses and winnings if they wish to deduct any of the gambling expenses.nnPaula is able to deduct up to $5,200 of her gambling losses ($5,000 + $200), which is the amount of her gambling winnings for the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(624,3,'Mr. Green must use a wheelchair. Upon advice from his doctor, in 2024 he installed an elevator and widened the front entrance of his house, incurring $10,000 and $3,000 in respective costs. Mr. Green had purchased his house for $146,000. An appraisal showed the fair market value of Mr. Green\'s house immediately after these modifications at $154,000. Also, in 2024, Mr. Green decided to join a health club primarily to improve business contacts and for recreational purposes. He paid a $1,250 annual membership fee to make use of this facility.nnCompute Mr. Green\'s currently deductible medical expense.','[\"$14,250\",\"$5,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$6,250\"]',1,'Publication 502, page 6, states that a taxpayer can include in medical expenses amounts that are paid for special equipment installed in a home, or for improvements, if their main purpose is medical care for the taxpayer, taxpayer\'s spouse, or dependent. The cost of permanent improvements that increase the value of property may be partly included as a medical expense. The cost of the improvement is reduced by the increase in the value of the taxpayer\'s property. The difference is a medical expense. If the value of the property is not increased by the improvement, the entire cost is included as a medical expense.nnCertain improvements made to accommodate a home to a taxpayer\'s disabled condition, or that of the taxpayer\'s spouse or dependents that live with the taxpayer, do not usually increase the value of the home and the cost can be included in full as medical expenses. These improvements include but are not limited to:nnconstructing entrance or exit ramps for the person\'s home andnwidening doorways at entrances or exits to the person\'s home.nFor a more detailed discussion of this topic as well as a list of additional qualified improvements, see Publication 502, page 6.nnPublication 502, page 16, also states that a taxpayer cannot include in medical expenses health club dues, or amounts paid to improve one\'s general health or to relieve physical or mental discomfort not related to a particular medical condition. That is, a taxpayer cannot include in medical expenses the cost of membership in any club organized for business, pleasure, recreation, or other social purpose.nnMr. Green, therefore, can only deduct the excess cost of the improvements (i.e., $5,000), which is the difference between the cost of $13,000 and the increased appraisal of $8,000 ($154,000 less $146,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(625,3,'IRC Section 199A provides a deduction that can be claimed by certain business owners for qualified business income. What is the amount of this deduction?','[0.200000000000000011102230246251565404236316680908203125,0.299999999999999988897769753748434595763683319091796875,0.25,0.1499999999999999944488848768742172978818416595458984375]',0,'IRC Section 199A was created under the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 (TCJA). The amount of the deduction is 20% of qualified business income (QBI) and is available to noncorporate taxpayers. The deduction is subject to multiple limitations based on the type of trade or business, the taxpayer’s taxable income, the amount of W-2 wages paid with respect to the qualified trade or business, and the unadjusted basis of qualified property held by the trade or business.nnNotwithstanding these limitations, taxpayers with qualified business income (which does not include income from performing services as an employee) and with taxable income under $191,950 (or $383,900 for joint returns) in 2024 will generally be eligible for the deduction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(626,3,'James, who is an employee, does not receive any reimbursement for his meals and entertainment expenses of clients. In May, he had the following expenses:nn$500 for use of a yacht for a day\'s fishing with two clientsn$50 lunch with a client with whom he discusses a new product linen$200 for dues to the country club where he plays golf with a client who provides James with 40% of his projectsn$50 for a cheese package given to one of his clients on the client\'s birthdaynBefore the consideration of any limitations, what is the total of his deductible expenses for May?','[\"$0\",\"$100\",\"$800\",\"$600\"]',0,'Publication 17, pages 102 and 103, provides, in part, that a taxpayer can no longer claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation, including unreimbursed employee expenses. However, a taxpayer may be able to deduct certain unreimbursed employee business expenses if they fall into one of the following categories of employment:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnGiven the facts above, James does not fall under one of the exception categories. Hence, he would not be able to deduct any of his meals and entertainment expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(627,3,'Which of the following would disqualify points from being fully deductible in the year paid?','[\"The points were computed as a percentage of the amount of the mortgage.\",\"The loan proceeds were used to purchase a second home.\",\"The payment of points is common in your area.\",\"The points are clearly stated on the settlement statement.\"]',1,'Publication 936, pages 5–7, discusses the rules associated with the deductibility of points paid in the purchase of a home. In general, a person cannot deduct the full amount of points in the year paid because they are prepaid interest and as such they must be deducted ratably over the life (term) of the mortgage.nnAs you might expect, there is an exception to the general rule. A person can fully deduct points in the year paid if the person meets all the following tests. (For a quick guide to the exception, see Figure B, which appears on page 7 of Publication 936.)nnThe loan is secured by the taxpayer\'s main home, which is the one that the person ordinarily lives in most of the time.nPaying points is an established business practice in the area where the loan was made.nThe points paid were not more than the points generally charged in that area.nThe person uses the cash method of accounting. This means the taxpayer reports income in the year the taxpayer receives it and deducts expenses in the year the taxpayer pays them. Most individuals use this method.nThe points were not paid in place of amounts that ordinarily are stated separately on the settlement statement, such as appraisal fees, inspection fees, title fees, attorney fees, and property taxes.nThe funds that the taxpayer provided at or before closing, plus any points the seller paid, were as least as much as the points charged. The funds provided by the taxpayer do not have to have been applied to the points. They can include a down payment, an escrow deposit, earnest money, and other funds paid at or before closing for any purpose. The taxpayer cannot have borrowed these funds from the lender or mortgage broker. nThe taxpayer used the loan to buy or build the taxpayer\'s main home. nThe points were computed as a percentage of the principal amount of the mortgage.nThe amount is clearly shown on the settlement statement (such as the Settlement Statement, Form HUD-1) as points charged for the mortgage. The points may be shown as paid from either the taxpayer\'s funds or the seller\'s funds.nIn this case, the loan proceeds used to purchase a second home can be deducted over the life (term) or the mortgage, but they would not qualify for deductibility in a single year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(628,3,'Which of the following statements is not true regarding documentation requirements for charitable contributions?','[\"If the total deduction for all noncash contributions for the year is more than $500, Section A of Form 8283,\\u00a0Noncash Charitable Contributions,\\u00a0must be completed.\",\"A noncash contribution of less than $250 must be supported by a receipt or other written acknowledgment from the charitable organization.\",\"A deduction of more than $1,000 for one property item generally requires that a written appraisal be obtained and attached to the return.\",\"A contribution charged to a credit card is a cash contribution for purposes of documentation requirements.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 526, page 20, cash contributions include those paid by cash, check, electronic funds transfer, debit card, credit card, or payroll deduction. They also include out-of-pocket expenses when services are donated.nnFor a contribution made in cash, the records that a taxpayer must keep depend upon whether the contribution is less than $250 or if the contribution is greater than or equal to $250.nnFor each cash contribution, regardless of the amount, a taxpayer cannot deduct the contribution unless the taxpayer has one of the following:nnA bank record that shows the name of the qualified organization, the date of the contribution, and the amount of the contribution. Bank records may include a canceled check or may include a legible and readable account statement that shows:na canceled check,na bank or credit union statement, orna credit card statement.nA receipt from the charitable organization showing the name of the organization, date of the contribution, and amount of the contributionnThe payroll deduction recordsnIn the case of a noncash contribution of less than $250, the taxpayer must get and keep a receipt (letter or other written communications) from the charitable organization showing (1) the name of the charitable organization, (2) the date and address of the charitable contribution, and (3) a reasonably detailed description of the property. (Publication 526, page 21)nnPublication 526, page 21, provides that in the case of a noncash contribution of over $5,000 (not $1,000 as given in the above problem) for one property item or a group of similar property items, the taxpayer must satisfy a number of issues described under “Deductions Over $500 But Not Over $5,000” and must also obtain a qualified written appraisal of the donated property from a qualified appraiser.nnPublication 526, page 21, provides, in part, that if a taxpayer\'s total deduction for all noncash contributions for the year is over $500, the taxpayer must complete Form 8283, and attach it to his or her Form 1040.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(629,3,'Alice paid her mother\'s hospital bill. Her mother is not her dependent. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Alice can deduct her mother\'s hospital bill as a medical expense on her return.\",\"Alice can deduct part but not all of her mother\'s hospital bill as a medical expense on her return.\",\"Alice can deduct her mother\'s hospital bill as a medical expense on her return only if her mother agrees.\",\"Alice\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0deduct any of her mother\'s hospital bill as a medical expense on her return.\"]',3,'In general, a taxpayer can include medical expenses that are paid for the taxpayer, spouse, and/or dependent in the year the services were provided or when paid by the taxpayer (Publication 502, page 3). There are different rules for decedents and for individuals that are subject to multiple support agreements.nnSince Alice\'s mother is not her dependent, she is not eligible to deduct the hospital bill as a medical expense.nnFor more discussion on medical expenses, you need to see Publication 502, pages 3 through 5.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(630,3,'During 2024, Ms. Gonzales paid $800 for real estate taxes on her primary residence and $600 on her mountain cabin. Her filing status is single, and she celebrated her 65th birthday on January 1, 2025. What standard deduction amount can Ms. Gonzales claim on her tax return for 2024?','[\"$14,600\",\"$16,550\",\"$17,550\",\"$21,900\"]',1,'Table 10-2 on page 96 of Publication 17 provides the standard deduction amounts for taxpayers born before January 2, 1960 (i.e., age 65 or older), or who are blind. Ms. Gonzales is able to claim $16,550 as her standard deduction, which is the amount listed for a single taxpayer claiming either age 65 or blind.nnFor those interested, $16,550 is the sum of $14,600 for a filing status of single and $1,950 for being age 65 as of January 1, 2025. Please note the special rule that a person is treated as being age 65 in 2024 even though their birthday is celebrated on January 1, 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(631,3,'Rosa purchased a home in Quogue, New York, in 2010 but she lives in Brooklyn with her sister. She lets her son Bob and his wife Samantha live in the Quogue house. Astoria Bank holds the mortgage with only Rosa\'s name on the property, as she did not add her son\'s name to the property deed. Since Bob lives in the Quogue house, he makes the monthly mortgage payments to Astoria Bank. Who can deduct the mortgage interest expense for the year 2024?','[\"Bob, since he makes the payments\",\"Rosa, since she owns the property and is liable for the payments\",\"Both, since they are related\",\"Neither, since Rosa is not paying her liability and Bob is paying for what he is not liable\"]',1,'Instructions to Schedule A, Form 1040, page A-8 indicate a taxpayer cannot deduct personal interest. Examples of personal interest include car loans, credit card interest, etc. The instructions also indicate the taxpayer is entitled to deduct qualified home mortgage interest and interest on student loans (on Schedule 1).nnPublication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan (provided that the equity loan is used to buy, build or improve the residence). Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnA taxpayer can deduct home mortgage interest only if the taxpayer meets all the following conditions:nnThe taxpayer must file Form 1040 or 1040-SR and itemize deductions on Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR).nBoth the taxpayer and the lender must intend that the loan be repaid.nThe mortgage is a secured debt on a qualified home in which the taxpayer has an ownership interest.nAs a result, since Rosa owns the property and only Rosa is liable for the mortgage payments, Rosa is the taxpayer that can claim the interest expense deduction.nnPublication 936nPage 2',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(632,3,'Which of the following statements is correct about a taxpayer that lives in more than one state with a sales tax law?','[\"The taxpayer must use the amount listed for the state in which the taxpayer claims residency.\",\"The taxpayer must prorate the amount by the number of days that the taxpayer lives in each state.\",\"The taxpayer must prorate the amount by the number of months that the taxpayer lives in each state.\",\"The use of the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables amount is not available in 2024.\"]',1,'A taxpayer that lives in more than one state must prorate the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables amount by the number of days (not months) that the taxpayer lives in each state (Schedule A (Form 1040) Instructions, page A-4).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(633,3,'Cindy is a salesperson employed by a window manufacturing company and she travels to various locations to sell her products. She drives 12,000 miles a year. She adequately accounts to her employer for her business expenses. Her employer reimburses her $3,600 for the mileage driven at 30 cents a mile. Based on the standard mileage rate, her expense was $6,720. Cindy is entitled to deduct on Schedule A, Itemized Deductions, transportation expenses of:','[\"$0 since Cindy cannot file Form 2106\",\"$3,120 as excess expense over the reimbursed expense\",\"$3,600 since she was reimbursed for that amount\",\"$6,720 since she can claim the standard mileage rate\"]',0,'Publication 463, page 13, states that there are some expenses a taxpayer can deduct for business transportation when not traveling away from home. These expenses include the cost of transportation by air, rail, bus, taxi, etc., and the cost of driving and maintaining the taxpayer\'s car.nnTransportation expenses include the ordinary and necessary costs of all of the following:nnGetting from one workplace to another in the course of your business or profession when you are traveling within the area of your tax home (Tax home is defined under the heading of “Travel Expenses” in chapter 20 of Publication 17.)nVisiting clients or customersnGoing to a business meeting away from your regular workplacenGetting from your home to a temporary workplace when you have one or more regular places of work (These temporary workplaces can be either within the area of the taxpayer\'s tax home or outside that area.)nUnder prior TCJA law, Cindy would be able to deduct $3,120 in transportation expense for the year, which is the difference between the amount of $6,720 that is based on the standard mileage as given in this problem and the $3,600 that Cindy is reimbursed by her employer. It should be noted that when an employee uses his or her car in the performance of the taxpayer\'s job as an employee, the excess expense is deductible on Form 2106 or Form 2106-EZ.nnSince Cindy is an employee with unreimbursed business expenses, she cannot deduct the expenses because TCJA suspended the 2% miscellaneous deductions for 2018 through 2026. (Publication 17, page 102)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(634,3,'David is an interstate truck driver subject to Department of Transportation hours of service but is not an employee. In 2024, what percent of his meals can he deduct while working as an interstate truck driver?','[0.5,0.75,0.8000000000000000444089209850062616169452667236328125,0.90000000000000002220446049250313080847263336181640625]',2,'A taxpayer can deduct 50% of the expenses incurred for business-related meals.nnThe business meal expenses are required to be incurred for food and beverages provided by a restaurant. However, a taxpayer can deduct a higher percentage of their meal expenses while traveling away from their tax home if the meals take place during or incident to any period subject to the Department of Transportation\'s “hours of service” limits. The percentage, in this situation, is 80%.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(635,3,'All of the following capital improvements may be itemized and deducted as medical expenses, except:','[\"the cost of constructing wheelchair accessible ramps for your home.\",\"the cost of modifying a car with special hand controls.\",\"lowering or modifying kitchen cabinets and equipment.\",\"an elevator costing $8,000 that adds $8,000 to the appraised value of your home.\"]',3,'Publication 502, page 6, states that a taxpayer can include in medical expenses amounts that are paid for special equipment installed in a home, or for improvements, if their main purpose is medical care for the taxpayer, taxpayer\'s spouse, or dependent. The cost of permanent improvements that increase the value of your property may be partly included as a medical expense. The cost of the improvement is reduced by the increase in the value of the taxpayer\'s property. The difference is a medical expense. If the value of the property is not increased by the improvement, the entire cost is included as a medical expense.nnCertain improvements made to accommodate a home to a taxpayer\'s disabled condition, or spouse or dependents that live with the taxpayer do not usually increase the value of the home and the cost can be included in full as medical expenses. These improvements include, but are not limited to, the following items:nnconstructing entrance or exit ramps for the taxpayer\'s home,nwidening doorways at entrances or exits to the taxpayer\'s home, andninstalling porch lifts and other forms of lifts (but elevators generally add value to the house).nFor a more detailed discussion of this topic and a list of other qualified medical improvements, see Publication 502.nnThis question is tricky because it indicates the elevator did not add value to the house; hence, it is the correct response to this question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(636,3,'During 2024, Ms. Gonzales paid $2,000 for real estate taxes on property she rents to others and $3,425 real estate taxes on her residence. In addition, she paid Social Security taxes of $650 for household help, $1,250 for state income taxes to New Jersey and $1,400 in New Jersey sales tax. What amount can Ms. Gonzales deduct as an itemized deduction on her tax return for 2024?','[\"$4,675\",\"$4,825\",\"$5,525\",\"$6,875\"]',1,'The instructions for line 5 of Schedule A (Form 1040), page A-3, state the deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if married filing separately). In addition, line 5a states that a taxpayer can deduct as an itemized deduction on Schedule A (Form 1040) either state and local income taxes or state and local sales tax. The taxpayer cannot deduct both in the same year.nnPublication 17, page 97, also provides that the taxpayer cannot deduct state and local income taxes paid on income that is exempt from federal income tax, unless the exempt income is interest income.nnDeductible real estate taxes, on the other hand, are any state, local, or foreign taxes on real property levied for the general public welfare. A taxpayer can deduct these taxes only if they are based on the assessed value of the real property and charged uniformly against all property under the jurisdiction of the taxing authority. (See Publication 17, page 100.) Real estate tax, however, paid on rental property is a rental deduction, and as such, the amount appears on Schedule E. (See Publication 17, page 101)nnPublication 17, page 101, goes on to stipulate that Social Security and other employment taxes for household workers that a taxpayer pays cannot be deducted. However, the taxpayer may be able to include them in medical or childcare expenses.nnMs. Gonzales\' itemized deductions for 2024 are $4,825, which is the sum of $3,425 (real estate tax on her residence) and $1,400 (New Jersey state sales tax).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(637,3,'Which of the following expenses are not deductible as medical expenses?','[\"Insulin used for diabetes\",\"A wig purchased upon the advice of a physician for the mental health of a patient who has lost all of his\\/her hair from disease\",\"Swimming lessons recommended by a doctor for improvement of general health\\n\",\"Acupuncture used for migraines\"]',2,'Publication 502, pages 5 through 17, provides a detailed list and discussion of items that are and are not treated as deductible medical and dental expenses. The following is a partial list of medical and dental expenses that are deductible according to Publication 502:nnAcupuncturenPrescription medicines (prescribed by a doctor) and insulin (except for insulin, a taxpayer cannot include in medical expenses amounts paid for a drug that is not prescribed)nThe cost of a wig purchased upon the advice of a physician for the mental health of a patient who has lost all of his or her hair from diseasenPublication 502, pages 15 through 17, also provides a list of items that are not deductible. In particular, the costs of dancing lessons, swimming lessons, etc. are not deductible even if they are recommended by a doctor, if they are only for the improvement of general health.nnAs a result, the only item listed in this question that is not deductible as a medical expense is swimming lessons recommended by a doctor for improvement of general health.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(638,3,'James and his two brothers each provided 1/3rd of their mother\'s total support. Under a multiple support agreement, James is allowed to claim his mother as a dependent in 2024. Medical expenses paid by James for his mother amounted to $6,000 and his brothers reimbursed him 2/3rds of these expenses. What is the amount James can consider as part of medical expenses in the preparation of his individual tax return in 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$1,850\",\"$2,000\",\"$6,000\"]',2,'The medical deduction for James is limited to the amount he paid less reimbursements. In this case, James can claim only $2,000, which is the difference between $6,000 (total cost) less $4,000 (2/3rds reimbursed). Interestingly, if the brothers had structured their payments differently, James could have had a larger deduction. For example, if they had agreed James would pay all the medical expenses and the other brothers paid other types of expenses, James could have deducted all the medical expenses.nnPublication 502, page 4, provides the following example: You and your three brothers each provide 1/4th of your mother\'s total support. Under a multiple support agreement, you treat your mother as your dependent. You paid all of her medical expenses. Your brothers repaid you for 3/4ths of these expenses. In figuring your medical expense deduction, you can include only 1/4th of your mother\'s medical expenses. Your brothers cannot include any part of the expenses. However, if you and your brothers share the nonmedical support items and you separately pay all of your mother\'s medical expenses, you can include the amount you paid for her medical expenses in your medical expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(639,3,'Julie made cash contributions to her local chapter of the Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (SPCA) to care for stray dogs and cats. She donated several times a year but she paid less than $250 for the entire year. These are the only charitable contributions Julie makes during the year. What documentation must Julie keep and provide to the Internal Revenue Service upon request in order to substantiate her tax return charitable contribution deduction?','[\"No documentation is necessary since the contribution is less than $250.\",\"A receipt for each donation that shows the amount, date, and to whom paid\",\"An acknowledgment from the SPCA that she made contributions during the year\",\"A self-prepared statement or letter would be sufficient for contributions less than $250.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 526, page 20, cash contributions include those paid by cash, check, electronic funds transfer, debit card, credit card, or payroll deduction. They also include out-of-pocket expenses when services are donated. For a contribution made in cash, the records that a taxpayer must keep depend upon whether the contribution is less than $250 or if the contribution is greater than or equal to $250.nnA taxpayer can\'t deduct a cash contribution, regardless of the amount, unless a taxpayer keeps one of the following:nnA bank record that shows the name of the qualified organization, the date of the contribution, and the amount of the contribution. Bank records may include a canceled check or may include a legible and readable account statement that shows:na canceled check,na bank or credit union statement, orna credit card statement.nA receipt from the charitable organization showing the name of the organization, date of the contribution, and the amount of the contributionnThe payroll deduction recordsnIn the case of a noncash contribution of less than $250, the taxpayer must get and keep a receipt (letter or other written communications) from the charitable organization showing (1) the name of the charitable organization, (2) the date and location of the charitable contribution, and (3) a reasonably detailed description of the property. (Publication 526, page 21)nnGiven the above restrictions, the taxpayer needs to keep a receipt for each donation that shows the amount, date, and to whom paid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(640,3,'Max loaned his 16-year-old son $2,000 to buy a car. At age 22, the son declared bankruptcy and he was discharged from all debt, including the $2,000 and accrued $250 in interest. What amount would be deductible by Max as a nonbusiness bad debt?','[\"$0\",\"$250\",\"$2,000\",\"$2,250\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer may be able to deduct the amount arising as a nonbusiness bad debt if it is totally worthless and is deducted on the tax return for the year the debt becomes worthless. A taxpayer can\'t deduct a partly worthless nonbusiness bad debt. (Publication 550, page 76)nnThe debt, however, must be genuine for the taxpayer, which means it arises from a debtor-creditor relationship based on a valid and enforceable obligation to repay a fixed or determinable sum of money. When minor children borrow from their parents to pay for their basic needs, there is no genuine debt and as such, the bad debt cannot be deducted for such a loan. See Publication 550, page 76, for more information on this topic.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(641,3,'Chester and Mary, a married couple, have interest and ordinary dividends (investment income) of $14,000. They have margin interest of $16,000, home mortgage interest of $12,000, equity loan interest of $3,000 on a $50,000 loan, credit card interest of $4,500, and automobile loan interest of $2,000. The home equity loan was not used to buy, build, or substantially improve their home. They have no tax-exempt investments. What amount can they take as interest deductions after limitations?','[\"$26,000\",\"$29,000\",\"$31,000\",\"$37,500\"]',0,'Instructions to Schedule A, Form 1040, page A-8 indicate a taxpayer cannot deduct personal interest. Examples of personal interest include car loans, credit card interest, etc. The instructions also indicate the taxpayer is entitled to deduct qualified home mortgage interest and interest on student loans (on Schedule 1).nnPublication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan (provided that the equity loan is used to buy, build or improve the residence). Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnIn the case where a taxpayer borrows money to buy property that is held for investment, the interest that the taxpayer pays is investment interest and it can be deducted up to the amount of investment income. However, a person cannot deduct interest incurred to produce tax-exempt income. Investment income generally includes items such as interest, ordinary dividends, annuities, and royalties (Publication 550, page 32).nnChester and Mary are able to deduct $26,000 of interest expenses, which is the sum of their mortgage interest of $12,000 and interest on their margin account of $14,000, which equals their investment income for the year (interest and dividend income of $14,000). Since no information is given about the use of the equity line of credit, we must assume that the funds were not used to buy, build or substantially improve the taxpayer’s home. Thus, the interest on the equity line of debt is not deductible. The remaining margin interest of $2,000 ($16,000 − $14,000) cannot be deducted; however, Chester and Mary can carry over this amount to the next tax year. The interest carried over is treated as investment interest paid or accrued in that next year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(642,3,'Which of the following are deductible as entertainment facilities expenses?','[\"Cost of yacht and hunting lodge\",\"Cost of bowling alley and tennis courts\",\"Cost of hotel suite and home in a vacation resort\",\"None of the answer choices are deductible costs.\"]',3,'For tax years 2018 through 2025, the treatment of certain meals and entertainment expenses changed. In general, entertainment, amusement, or recreation expenses are no longer deductible. The cost of business meals generally remains deductible, subject to the 50% limitation. nnGenerally, a taxpayer cannot deduct any expense for the use of an entertainment facility. This includes expenses for depreciation and operating costs such as rent, utilities, maintenance, and protection.nnAn entertainment facility is any property that the taxpayer owns, rents, or uses for entertainment. Examples include a yacht, hunting lodge, fishing camp, swimming pool, tennis court, bowling alley, car, airplane, apartment, hotel suite, or home in a vacation resort.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17');
INSERT INTO `tbl_unit_questions` VALUES (643,3,'To qualify for a medical expense deduction as your dependent, a person must be your dependent either at the time the medical services were provided or at the time you paid the expenses. A person generally qualifies as your dependent for purposes of the medical expense deduction if:','[\"the person would qualify as a dependent except for the amount of gross income.\",\"the person was a foreign student staying briefly at your home.\",\"the person is your sibling\'s unmarried adult child.\",\"the person is the unrelated caregiver for your elderly parents.\"]',0,'A taxpayer is generally allowed to deduct medical expenses that are paid for themselves as well as those paid for their spouse or dependent, either when the services were provided or when they were paid for. (Publication 502, page 3)nnA person generally qualifies as the taxpayer\'s dependent for purposes of the medical expense deduction if the person was a qualifying child or a qualifying relative, and the person was a U.S. citizen or national, or a resident of the United States, Canada, or Mexico. In the case where a qualifying child was adopted, and the taxpayer is a U.S. citizen or U.S. national and the adopted child lived with the taxpayer as a member of the household for 2024, that child does not have to be a U.S. citizen or national or a resident of the United States, Canada, or Mexico.nnA qualifying child is a child who:nnis the taxpayer\'s son, daughter, stepchild, foster child, brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister, or a descendant of any of them (for example, the taxpayer\'s grandchild, niece, or nephew),nat the end of 2024 was:nunder age 19,nunder age 24 and a full-time student, ornany age if permanently and totally disabled,nlived with the taxpayer for more than half of 2024,ndid not provide over half of his or her own support for 2024, andndid not file a joint return, or, if he or she did, it was only to claim a refund because there was no tax liability.nA qualifying relative is a person:nnwho is the taxpayer\'s:nson, daughter, stepchild, foster child, or a descendant of any of them (for example, grandchild),nbrother, sister, or a son or daughter of either of them,nfather, mother, or an ancestor or sibling of either of them (for example, grandmother, grandfather, aunt, or uncle),nstepbrother, stepsister, stepfather, stepmother, son-in-law, daughter-in-law, father-in-law, mother-in-law, brother-in-law, or sister-in-law, ornany other person (other than the taxpayer\'s spouse) who lived with the taxpayer all year as a member of the household if the relationship does not violate local law;nwho was not a qualifying child of any other person for 2024; andnfor whom the taxpayer provided over half of the support in 2024.nYou can include the medical expenses of any person who would have been your dependent except that they received gross income of $5,050 or more in 2024, they filed a joint return in 2024, or they or their spouse, if filing jointly, could be claimed as a dependent on someone else\'s 2024 return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(644,3,'Some contributions may be limited to 50% of the taxpayer\'s adjusted gross income. Deductions to the following organizations are subject to the 50% limitation on deductible contributions:','[\"Churches and conventions or associations of churches, and educational organizations with regular faculty and curriculum and regularly enrolled students\",\"Hospitals and certain medical research organizations associated with these hospitals\",\"Kiwanis, Rotary, and Lions Club who raise money for public causes\",\"Both churches and conventions or associations of churches, and educational organizations with regular faculty and curriculum and regularly enrolled students;\\u00a0AND\\u00a0hospitals and certain medical research organizations associated with these hospitals\"]',3,'The amount of deduction permitted for charitable contributions for any tax year is limited. The amount you can deduct for cash charitable contributions generally is limited to no more than 60% of your adjusted gross income (AGI). A taxpayer’s deduction may be further limited to 50% (for non-cash 50% charitable contributions), 30%, or 20% of your AGI, depending on the type of property the taxpayer gives and the type of organization they give it to. A higher limit applies to certain qualified conservation contributions. Generally, contributions to the following organizations qualify for the 50% limit:nnChurches and conventions or associations of churchesnEducational organizations with a regular faculty and curriculum that normally have a regularly enrolled student body attending classes on sitenHospitals and certain medical research organizations associated with these hospitalsnPublicly supported charitiesnPrivate non-operating foundations that make qualifying distributions of 100% of contributions within 2-1/2 months following the year they receive the contributionsnCertain private foundations whose contributions are pooled in a common fund, the income and principal of which are paid to public charitiesnA 30% limit applies to the following contributions:nnContributions to all qualified organizations other than 50% limit organizations (This includes gifts to veterans\' organizations, fraternal societies, nonprofit cemeteries, and certain private non-operating foundations.)nContributions for the use of any organizationnTherefore, contributions to churches and conventions or associations of churches, educational organizations with regular faculty and curriculum and regularly enrolled students, and hospitals and certain medical research organizations associated with these hospitals would be subject to the 50% limitation.nnAs a result of TCJA of 2017, the amount a taxpayer can deduct for charitable contributions generally is limited to no more than 60% of their adjusted gross income. Their deduction, however, may be further limited to 50%, 30%, or 20% of their AGI depending on the type of property given and the type of organization the property is given to. A higher limit applies to certain qualified conservation contributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(645,3,'Which of the following items are work clothes or uniforms that are deductible as miscellaneous itemized deductions?','[\"Fire-retardant clothing worn by firefighters\",\"White bib overalls worn by a professional painter\",\"Blue work clothes worn by a welder\",\"None of the answer choices are deductible costs.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 102, provides, in part, that a taxpayer can no longer claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation, including unreimbursed employee expenses. However, a taxpayer may be able to deduct certain unreimbursed employee business expenses if they fall into one of the following categories of employment:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnAs a result of the elimination of the miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% floor by the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, none of the above items are deductible as miscellaneous itemized deductions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(646,3,'Which of the following will qualify for an educational deduction on Schedule A in 2024?','[\"The employer reimburses the taxpayer\'s expenses under a tuition reimbursement (nontaxable) program.\",\"The education maintains or improves skills needed in the taxpayer\'s present work.\",\"The education is required by the taxpayer\'s employer or the law to keep the taxpayer\'s present salary, status, or job. The required education must serve a bona fide business purpose of the taxpayer\'s employer.\",\"None of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Prior to 2018, a taxpayer was permitted to take a deduction for the costs of qualifying work-related education as a business expense. The expenses must have been for education that meets at least one of the following tests:nnThe education was required by your employer or the law to keep your then salary, status, or job. (The required education must have served a bona fide business purpose of your employer.)nThe education maintained or improved skills needed in your then work.nIn prior years, an individual could deduct the costs of qualifying work-related education as a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% floor.nnBeginning in 2018, an individual can no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses that are subject to the 2% of AGI limitation. Publication 17, page 102 indicates there are four categories of taxpayers that can still claim miscellaneous deductions that are subject to the 2% floor:nnArmed Forces reservists;nQualified performing artists;nFee-basis state or local government officials;nEmployees with impairment-related work expenses.nIn this situation, an employee\'s educational expenses are not deductible on Schedule A. (Publication 970, page 65)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(647,3,'nMatt paid interest in 2024 as follows:nn$100 on his personal credit cardn$200 on funds borrowed in order to purchase $6,000 in tax-exempt securitiesn$500 interest on his personal car loan (He does not use his car for business.)n$10,000 on his home mortgagenWhat is the amount of Matt\'s deductible interest in 2024?','[\"$17,400\",\"$10,600\",\"$10,000\",\"$10,800\"]',2,'Instructions to Schedule A, Form 1040, page A-8 indicate a taxpayer cannot deduct personal interest. Examples of personal interest include car loans, credit card interest, etc. The instructions also indicate the taxpayer is entitled to deduct qualified home mortgage interest and interest on student loans (on Schedule 1).nnPublication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan (provided that the equity loan is used to buy, build or improve the residence). Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2).nnIn the case where a taxpayer borrows money to buy property that is held for investment, the interest that the taxpayer pays is investment interest and it can be deducted up to the amount of investment income. However, a person cannot deduct interest incurred to produce tax-exempt income. Investment income generally includes items such as interest, ordinary dividends, annuities, and royalties (Publication 550, pages 45–46).nnMatt is able to deduct $10,000 of mortgage interest expense for the year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(648,3,'Which of the following statements is correct for the deductibility of state and local taxes by using the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables amount in 2024 if a taxpayer pays sales tax on the purchase of a new car?nn1. A taxpayer may use only the amount given in the table for deduction on a taxpayer\'s return.n2. A taxpayer may add to the table any sales taxes paid on a purchased car for deduction on a taxpayer\'s return.n3. A taxpayer may claim the actual sales taxes paid as a deduction on a taxpayer\'s return.','[\"The taxpayer can only elect method 1.\",\"The taxpayer can elect either method 2 or method 3.\",\"The taxpayer can only elect method 2.\",\"The taxpayer can only elect method 3.\"]',1,'The instructions for line 5 of Schedule A (Form 1040), pages A-3 and A-4, state that the deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if married filing separately). In addition, line 5a states that a taxpayer can deduct from adjusted gross income either state and local income taxes or state and local sales tax. The taxpayer cannot deduct both in the same year.nnIn addition, a taxpayer can deduct either his or her actual expenses (which would include the sales tax paid on specific items such as a motor vehicle, boat, etc.) or an amount figured using the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables in the instructions for Schedule A, Form 1040.nnIf the taxpayer uses the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables, they may be able to add to the table any state and local general sales tax paid on motor vehicles, motorcycles, motor homes, RVs, SUVs, trucks, vans, and off-road vehicles. (For more information, see the instructions for line 7 of the State and Local General Sales Tax Deduction Worksheet on page A-7 of the Schedule A (Form 1040) Instructions.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(649,3,'In order to deduct a personal casualty and theft loss, the loss must be:','[\"related to a federally declared disaster area.\",\"reduced by the amount of your standard deduction.\",\"less than 10% of your adjusted gross income.\",\"deducted over a three-year consecutive period.\"]',0,'Personal casualty and theft losses of an individual sustained in tax years beginning after 2017 are deductible only to the extent they are attributable to a federally declared disaster.nnAn exception to the rule above, limiting the personal casualty and theft loss deduction to losses attributable to a federally declared disaster, applies if you have personal casualty gains for the tax year. In this case, you can reduce your personal casualty gains by any casualty losses not attributable to a federally declared disaster. Any excess gain is used to reduce losses from a federally declared disaster. Personal casualty and theft losses not attributable to a federally declared disaster are subject to the $100 per casualty and 10% of your adjusted gross income (AGI) limitations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(650,3,'Jill divorced her husband, James, in 2023. Their son, Harry, lived with Jill for all of 2024 and qualified as her dependent. However, the divorce decree indicates James can take the exemption. Jill paid $1,200 in medical expenses for Harry and James paid $2,000. Jill entered into a multiple support agreement with her three brothers to assist with their mother\'s care. Jill provided 1/4th of her mother\'s support and paid $1,500 in medical expenses, which was her quarter share. Without regard to adjusted gross income limitations, compute Jill\'s medical expense deduction for 2024.','[\"$1,200\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,700\",\"$0\"]',0,'Publication 502, page 4, provides, in part, that in the case where a taxpayer is considered to have provided more than half of a person\'s support under a multiple support agreement, the taxpayer can include the medical expenses paid by the taxpayer for that person, even if the taxpayer cannot claim an exemption for that person. However, any medical expense paid by the other members of the multiple support agreement cannot be claimed by the taxpayer and they cannot claim any of the medical expenses. (See the example on page 4 of Publication 502.)nnIn the case of a child of divorced or separated parents, the child can be treated as a dependent of both parents. Hence, each parent can include the medical expenses that he or she pays for the child, even if the other parent claims the child\'s dependency, if certain criteria are satisfied. (Publication 502, page 4)nnIn this case, Jill is unable to claim any of the medical expenses for her mother since a multiple support agreement is filed and she provided only 25% of her mother\'s medical expenses. On the other hand, she is able to claim the $1,200 for her son because he qualifies as her dependent even though her former husband can claim him as his dependent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(651,3,'Thomas is sole proprietor of a small company. He recently negotiated a substantial sale. Following the signing of the contract, Thomas took the clients to dinner at a cost of $150. What is Thomas\'s deductible meal expense on his Schedule C for 2024?','[\"$112.50\",\"$0\",\"$75\",\"$150\"]',2,'Publication 463, page 10, states, in part, a taxpayer may deduct 50% of the cost of business meals if the taxpayer (or an employee) is present and the food or beverages are not considered lavish or extravagant. The meals may be provided to a current or potential business customer, client, consultant, or similar business contact. The business meal expenses are required to be incurred for food and beverages provided by a restaurant.nnWith respect to activities generally considered entertainment, amusement, or recreation, these expenses are no longer deductible. However, food and beverages that are provided during entertainment events are not considered entertainment if purchased separately from the entertainment, or if the cost of the food and beverages is stated separately from the cost of the entertainment on one or more bills, invoices, or receipts. However, the entertainment disallowance rule may not be circumvented through inflating the amount charged for food and beverages.nnThomas\'s deductible expense for meals is limited to $75, which is 50% of the total cost of the meal ($150).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(652,3,'In 2024, Janice volunteered at her local art museum where she conducted art education seminars. She was required to wear a blazer that the museum provided, but she paid the dry-cleaning costs of $200 for the year. The blazer was not suitable for everyday use. Her travel to and from the museum was 1,000 miles for the year. She estimates the value of the time she contributed during the year at $2,000 ($20 per hour × 100 hours). Her Schedule A deduction for charitable contributions is which of the following?','[\"$2,340\",\"$2,140\",\"$140\",\"$340\"]',3,'Publication 526, page 2, provides, in part, that a charitable contribution is a donation or gift to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. It is voluntary and is made without getting, or expecting to get, anything of equal value.nnIn the case of volunteer work, a person is not able to deduct the value of his or her time but can deduct any out-of-pocket costs. For example, a volunteer can deduct the cost and upkeep of uniforms that are not suitable for everyday use and that the taxpayer must wear while performing donated services for a charitable organization. A volunteer also can deduct 14 cents per mile for travel to and from the charitable activity (see material and Table 2 on page 5 in Publication 526).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(653,3,'Lisa travels to various locations during her work week. Using the following data, determine the number of miles she may claim as transportation expenses for this period:nnMonday—40 miles, round trip, from home to her full-time jobnTuesday—20 miles from home to her full-time job, then 10 miles from her full-time job to her part-time job, then 30 miles to her homenWednesday—60 miles, round trip, from her home to her part-time job; she did not work at her full-time job','[\"70 miles\",\"20 miles\",\"10 miles\",\"0 miles\"]',3,'Publication 463, pages 13–14, provides that there are some expenses that a taxpayer can deduct for business transportation when not traveling away from home. These expenses include the cost of transportation by air, rail, bus, taxi, etc., and the cost of driving and maintaining the taxpayer\'s car. Transportation expenses include the ordinary and necessary costs of all of the following:nnGetting from one workplace to another in the course of your business or profession when you are traveling within the area of your tax homenVisiting clients or customersnGoing to a business meeting away from your regular workplacenGetting from your home to a temporary workplace when you have one or more regular places of work (These temporary workplaces can be either within the area of the taxpayer\'s tax home or outside that area.)nA set of examples of deductible transportation expenses is given on pages 14 and 15 of Publication 463 that addresses when a taxpayer can deduct transportation expenses based on the location of the taxpayer\'s work and home. Transportation expenses the taxpayer has going between home and a part-time job on a day off from the taxpayer\'s main job are commuting expenses. In addition, Example 3 (on page 14 under the caption “Examples of deductible transportation”) states transportation expenses between the taxpayer\'s home and a person\'s first contact are nondeductible commuting expenses. Transportation expenses between the last business contact and home are also nondeductible commuting expenses. Although the taxpayer cannot deduct the costs of the first and last trips, the taxpayer can deduct the costs of going from one client or customer to another.nnUnder prior law, an employee could deduct transportation expenses to a second job as a 2% miscellaneous deduction. However, TCJA has suspended the 2% miscellaneous deductions for 2018 through 2026, except for Armed Forces reservists, fee-based state or local government officials, qualified performing artists, or disabled employees with impairment-related work expenses. nnTherefore, Lisa cannot deduct any miles associated with her commute from her full-time job to her part-time job.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(654,3,'Matt has a certified statement from his optometrist on December 1, 2024, that confirms he can see no better than 20/250. For tax year 2024, which of the following is correct?','[\"Matt is\\u00a0not\\u00a0eligible for the higher standard deduction for blindness as he is only partially blind.\",\"Matt is eligible for the higher standard deduction for blindness in 2024.\",\"Matt is eligible for the higher standard deduction for blindness in 2025, the first full year of his blindness.\",\"Matt is\\u00a0not\\u00a0eligible for the higher standard deduction for blindness as he can see better than 20\\/300.\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 94, provides that if a taxpayer is blind on the last day of the year and the taxpayer does not itemize deductions, the taxpayer is entitled to a higher standard deduction. Be aware that a taxpayer can qualify for this benefit if he or she is totally or partly blind.nnIf a taxpayer is partly blind, the taxpayer must get a certified statement from an eye doctor or registered optometrist that:nnthe taxpayer cannot see better than 20/200 in the better eye with glasses or contact lenses, ornthe taxpayer\'s field of vision is not more than 20 degrees (see Publication 17, page 90).nIf the taxpayer\'s eye condition will never improve beyond these limits, the statement should include this fact. The taxpayer must keep the statement in his or her records.nnIf, on the other hand, the taxpayer\'s vision can be corrected beyond these limits only by contact lenses that the taxpayer can wear only briefly because of pain, infection, or ulcers, the taxpayer is still eligible to take the higher standard deduction for blindness if he or she otherwise qualifies.nnSince Matt\'s vision is 20/250, which is worse than 20/200, he is eligible for the higher standard deduction for blindness in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(655,3,'Bethany and Michael (wife and husband) are itemizing their Schedule A expenses on their tax year 2024 return. Michael traveled to Japan for his employer, but was not reimbursed. His meal expenses totaled $500. How much can Michael deduct for meals?','[\"$250\",\"$500\",\"$150\",\"$0\"]',3,'Beginning in 2018, a taxpayer can no longer claim a deduction for unreimbursed employee expenses unless they fall into one of the following categories of employment or have certain qualified educator expenses (Publication 17, page 102). The eligible categories are:nnArmed Forces reservistsnQualified performing artistsnFee-basis state or local government officialsnEmployees with impairment-related work expensesnTherefore, unless a taxpayer falls into one of the qualified categories of employment, miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation can no longer be claimed.nnIn this case, Michael cannot claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions. (Publication 17, page 102)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(656,3,'Carla borrowed $100,000 to buy land for investment. Her income sources for the year include $3,000 interest, $1,000 dividends (assume nonqualified), and $4,000 royalties. How much of the $5,000 interest expense paid on the land loan can she deduct this year?','[\"$8,000\",\"$4,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$3,000\"]',2,'Publication 550, pages 45–46, provides that in the case where a taxpayer borrows money to buy property that is held for investment, the interest that the taxpayer pays is investment interest expense and it can be deducted up to the amount of investment income. However, a person cannot deduct interest incurred to produce tax-exempt income.nnInvestment income generally includes gross income from property held for investment such as interest, dividends, annuities, and royalties not derived in the ordinary course of a trade or business. It also includes property that produces gain or loss (not derived in the ordinary course of a trade or business) from the sale or trade of property producing these types of income or held for investment (other than an interest in a passive activity).nnForm 4952, Investment Interest Expense Deduction, is used to figure a taxpayer’s deduction for investment interest unless one of the exceptions apply (see Publication 550, pages 46–47).nnFor Carla, she is able to deduct the entire $5,000 of interest expenses because it is less than her total investment income of $8,000, which is the sum of her interest of $3,000, dividends of $1,000, and royalties of $4,000.nnNote: This is a tricky question in that royalties are not always investment income; they can be business income appearing on a Schedule C. In general, you should assume that royalties are investment income unless told otherwise or it is obvious from the facts given in the question. Further please note, that Instructions to Form 4952 indicate that only ordinary dividends represent income that can offset investment interest expense. Qualified dividends are subtracted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(657,3,'Which of the following expenses are deductible on Form 1040, Schedule A, Itemized Deductions?','[\"Investment fees and expenses\",\"Hobby expenses\",\"Amortizable premium on taxable bonds\",\"Trustee\'s administrative fees for IRAs\"]',2,'Beginning in 2018, certain miscellaneous deductions have been suspended. Two categories of miscellaneous expenses that have been suspended are: miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% AGI floor and those expenses that are traditionally nondeductible under the Internal Revenue Code.nnSuspended miscellaneous itemized deductions include:nnUnreimbursed employee expenses (exceptions apply)nAppraisal feesnInvestment fees and expensesnCasualty and theft lossesnDepreciation on home computernFees to collect interest and dividendsnHobby expensesnIndirect Deductions of Pass-through EntitiesnLegal expenses.nItems that are not subject to the 2% of AGI limit are still deductible as miscellaneous itemized deductions. These items are reported on Schedule A (Form 1040 and 1040-SR) and include items such as:nnAmortizable premium on taxable bondsnFederal estate tax on income in respect of a decedentnUnlawful discrimination claimsnGambling losses up to the amount of gambling winningsnHence, the correct response is the amortizable premium on a taxable bond, which is an itemized deduction that appears on line 16 of Schedule A. Publication 529, pages 9 through 11, provides a list of other items that are deductible as a miscellaneous deduction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(658,3,'Robin, an employee, had the following unreimbursed employee expenses in 2024:nn$100 professional license renewaln$75 subscription to professional journaln$500 business liability insurancenHer adjusted gross income was $40,000. What net amount can Robin deduct?','[\"$675\",\"$0\",\"$575\",\"$175\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 102, provides, in part, that a taxpayer can no longer claim any miscellaneous itemized deductions that are subject to the 2% of adjusted gross income limitation, including unreimbursed employee expenses. However, a taxpayer may be able to deduct certain unreimbursed employee business expenses if they fall into one of the following categories of employment:nnArmed Forces reservists;nQualified performing artists;nFee-basis state or local government officials; ornEmployees with impairment-related work expenses.nAs a result of the elimination of the miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% floor by the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, none of the above items are deductible as miscellaneous itemized deductions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(659,3,'nMr. and Mrs. Mead, both full-time teachers, wanted to volunteer their services to work for the victims of a major disaster. Their services consisted of going to various neighborhoods in the community to raise funds for the cause. While volunteering, the Meads kept records of the costs involved. These costs included time spent, out-of-pocket expenses for travel, and car expenses:nnThe Meads valued their volunteer time at $500 total for the year.nOut-of-pocket expenses that were directly related to their services rendered at $25 for parking fees and $350 for gas and oilnCar expenses for new tires at $200 and registration fees at $90nIf the Meads elect to take the actual expenses, in 2024 how much can they deduct?','[\"$375\",\"$665\",\"$875\",\"$1,165\"]',0,'Publication 526, page 5, provides that a taxpayer may be able to deduct some amounts the taxpayer pays in giving services to a qualified organization. The amounts must be:nnunreimbursed,ndirectly connected with the services,nexpenses the taxpayer had only because of the services he or she gave, andnnot personal, living, or family expenses.nTable 2 on page 5 contains questions and answers that apply to some individuals who volunteer their services.nnIn addition, a taxpayer cannot deduct the value of his or her time or services (see Publication 526, page 7), including but not limited to:nnvalue of blood given to a blood bank andndues, fees, or bills paid to country clubs, lodges, fraternal orders, or similar groups.nAs a result, the Meads can deduct $375 as charitable contributions for the year, which is the sum of their out-of-pocket expenses ($25 for parking fees and $350 for gas and oil). None of the other expenses are deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(660,3,'In September 2024, 2 months after Jim and Betty finished constructing a barn, it was completely destroyed by a hurricane. Their adjusted basis in the barn was its cost, $40,000. It was not covered by insurance. The entire community has been declared a federal disaster area. Jim and Betty may elect to do which of the following?','[\"Deduct $40,000 in either 2024 or 2025\",\"Deduct $40,000 in either 2023 or 2024\",\"Deduct $40,000 in 2023, or 2024, or 2025\",\"No deduction in any year because the loss is personal\"]',1,'For tax years 2018 through 2025, if you are an individual, casualty losses of personal-use property are deductible only if the loss is attributable to a federally declared disaster (federal casualty loss). If the event causing you to suffer a personal casualty loss occurred before January 1, 2018, but the casualty loss wasn’t sustained until January 1, 2018, or later, the casualty loss isn’t deductible.nnA qualified disaster loss is an individual’s casualty or theft loss of personal-use property that is attributable to a major disaster declared by the President under the Robert T. Stafford Disaster Relief and Emergency Assistance Act. (Publication 547, page 3)nnIn such situations, the taxpayer is able to deduct the loss on the taxpayer\'s return or amended return for the tax year immediately preceding the tax year in which the disaster happened. If the person files an amended return, the loss is treated as having occurred in the preceding year. (Publication 547, page 16)nnIn this case, Jim and Betty can deduct the entire loss of $40,000 in the current year or in the prior year by filing an amended tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(661,3,'Tax preparation fees for individuals are deductible for the current year as:','[\"they are not deductible.\",\"a tax credit on Schedule 1.\",\"an investment expense on Schedule A.\",\"a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% limit.\"]',0,'Before 2018, tax preparation fees were deductible as a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% limit. However, due to the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, effective from 2018 to 2025, tax preparation fees are no longer deductible.nnThe correct answer is that they are not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(662,3,'During 2024, Ms. Gonzales paid $2,000 for real estate taxes on property she rents to others and $3,425 real estate taxes on her residence. In addition, she paid Social Security taxes of $650 for household help and $1,250 for state income taxes to New Jersey. What amount can Ms. Gonzales deduct as an itemized deduction on her tax return for 2024?','[\"$4,675\",\"$5,325\",\"$6,675\",\"$7,325\"]',0,'Publication 17, page 98, states that a taxpayer can deduct state and local income taxes. However, the taxpayer cannot deduct state and local income taxes paid on income that is exempt from federal income tax, unless the exempt income is interest income.nnBeginning in 2005, a taxpayer can elect to deduct state and local general sales taxes instead of state and local income taxes as an itemized deduction on Schedule A of Form 1040 (Publication 17, page 98).nnDeductible real estate taxes, on the other hand, are any state or local taxes on real property levied for the general public welfare. A taxpayer can deduct these taxes only if they are based on the assessed value of the real property and charged uniformly against all property under the jurisdiction of the taxing authority. (See Publication 17, page 98.) Real estate taxes, however, paid on property that produces rent or royalty income are deductible on Schedule E (Publication 17, page 100).nnPublication 17, page 102, goes on to stipulate that Social Security and other employment taxes for household workers that a taxpayer pays cannot be deducted. However, the taxpayer may be able to include them in medical expenses that are deductible or child care expenses that allow the taxpayer to claim the child and dependent care credit.nnFor tax years 2018 through 2026, the deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if filing married separately). State and local taxes are the taxes that you include on Schedule A (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), lines 5a, 5b, and 5c.nnMs. Gonzales\' itemized deductions for 2024 are $4,675, which is the sum of $3,425 (real estate tax on her residence) and $1,250 (New Jersey state income taxes). Of course, Ms. Gonzales would be wiser to claim the standard deduction of $14,600, which is greater than the itemized amount of $4,675 unless her total itemized deductions exceed $14,600.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(663,3,'Mr. Cedar broke his hip and must now use a wheelchair. He modified his home to accommodate the wheelchair. He had his home appraised for refinancing just before the improvements to his home. The value of his home was $200,000. After he made the modifications and improvements listed below, the value was $202,000. Mr. Cedar incurred the following expenses during the year. Without consideration of adjusted gross income limitations, compute the amount Mr. Cedar may claim on his 2024 tax return as a medical expense:nn$3,000 to construct a ramp in the entrance of his home to accommodate his wheelchairn$4,000 for installation of a lift to transport the wheelchair from the first to the second floor of his housen$1,000 for adding handrails around his tubn$200 to repair his chimney','[\"$8,200\",\"$6,200\",\"$6,000\",\"$8,000\"]',2,'Publication 502, page 6, states that a taxpayer can include in medical expenses amounts that are paid for special equipment installed in a home, or for improvements, if their main purpose is medical care for the taxpayer, taxpayer\'s spouse, or dependent. The cost of permanent improvements that increase the value of property may be partly included as a medical expense. The cost of the improvement is reduced by the increase in the value of the taxpayer\'s property. The difference is a medical expense. If the value of the property is not increased by the improvement, the entire cost is included as a medical expense.nnCertain improvements made to accommodate a home to a taxpayer\'s disabled condition, or spouse or dependents that live with the taxpayer, do not usually increase the value of the home, and the cost can be included in full as medical expenses. These improvements include, but are not limited to, constructing entrance or exit ramps for the person\'s home; widening doorways at entrances or exits to the person\'s home; and installing railings, support bars, or other modifications to bathrooms. (See Publication 502, page 6, for a complete list of expenses.)nnIn this case, Mr. Cedar may claim $6,000 in medical expenses, which is the total cost for medical improvements ($8,000) less the increase in property value ($2,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(664,3,'If an involuntary conversion occurs when your property is destroyed, stolen, condemned, or disposed of under the threat of condemnation and you receive other property or money in payment, such as insurance or a condemnation award, which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Gain or loss from an involuntary conversion of your property is usually recognized for tax purposes unless the property is your main home.\",\"You may not have to report a gain on an involuntary conversion if you receive property that is similar or related in service or use to the converted property.\",\"If you receive money or property that is not similar or related in service or use to the involuntarily converted property and you buy qualifying replacement property within a certain period of time, you can choose to postpone reporting the gain.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 544, pages 6 and 7, provides that an involuntary conversion occurs when a person\'s property is destroyed, stolen, condemned, or disposed of under the threat of condemnation and the person receives other property or money in payment, such as insurance or a condemnation award. Involuntary conversions are also called involuntary exchanges.nnIn addition, a gain or loss from an involuntary conversion on a taxpayer\'s property is usually recognized for tax purposes unless the property is the taxpayer\'s main home. The gain or loss is reported on the taxpayer\'s tax return for the year that it is realized.nnA taxpayer cannot deduct a loss from an involuntary conversion of property that was held for personal use unless the loss resulted from a casualty or theft. However, depending on the type of property received by the taxpayer, a gain may not need to be reported on an involuntary conversion. That is, the gain is not reported if the taxpayer received property that is similar or related in service or use to the converted property. The basis for the new property is the same basis for the converted property. This means that the gain is deferred until a taxable sale or exchange occurs.nnIf the taxpayer receives money or property that is not similar or related in service or use to the involuntarily converted property and the taxpayer buys qualifying replacement property within a certain period of time, the taxpayer can choose to postpone reporting the gain.nnAs a result, all of the statements given in this question are correct responses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(665,3,'Which of the following is a medical deduction?','[\"Health club dues advised by your doctor\",\"Maternity clothing\",\"Legal abortion\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 502, pages 5 through 17 list all of the deductible medical expenses. Per page 5, costs associated with legal abortion are deductible. However, per page 16 maternity clothes and health club dues, even if following doctor\'s advice, cannot be included as deductible medical and dental expenses.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(666,3,'Sam owns a plumbing supply business that he reports as a sole proprietorship. Sam spends a great deal of time and money entertaining clients. A lot of Sam\'s business is conducted in restaurants and on the golf course. In 2024, Sam incurred the following expenses:nn$2,000 in meal expenditures for client business dinners in restaurantsn$300 in babysitting fees during client business dinnersn$1,000 in golf club membership duesn$200 in golf equipmentnIn 2024, what is the amount that Sam can deduct for business expenses?','[\"$3,000\",\"$1,000\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,000\"]',1,'In order to answer this question, one must understand what is meant by “entertainment expenses.” Entertainment expenses include any activity that is considered to provide entertainment, amusement, or recreation. Entertainment expenses include but are not limited to entertaining guests at nightclubs; at social, athletic, and sporting clubs; at theaters; at sporting events; or on hunting, fishing, vacation, or similar trips.nnA taxpayer can no longer take a deduction for any expenses related to activities generally considered entertainment, amusement, or recreation. A taxpayer can continue to deduct 50% of the cost of business meals if the taxpayer (or their employee) is present and the food or beverages are not considered lavish or extravagant. For more information, see Chapter 2 of Publication 463. (Publication 463 pages 10–11)nnnPublication 463, page 10, explicitly states that dues paid to country clubs and golf clubs are not deductible.nnGiven the facts above, Sam is only able to deduct the meal expenditure of $1,000 as a business expense.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(667,3,'Vera and Jack (wife and husband) contributed $18,000 in cash to their synagogue during 2024. They also donated $3,000 to a private foundation that is a nonprofit cemetery organization. They knew a 30% limit applies to contributions to such foundations. Their adjusted gross income for the year 2024 was $30,000. Vera and Jack\'s deductible contribution for the year 2024 and any carryover to next year is:','[\"$18,000 with $0 carryover to next year.\",\"$15,000 with $2,100 carryover to next year.\",\"$15,000 with $6,000 carryover to next year.\",\"$18,000 with $3,000 carryover to next year.\"]',3,'As a result of TCJA of 2017, if a taxpayer makes cash contributions during the year to a 50% organization, their deduction for the cash contributions is limited to 60% of their AGI. (Publication 526, page 14)nnPublication 526, pages 15 and 16, provides the general rules when a taxpayer\'s contributions are subject to more than one of the contribution limits (i.e., 50%, 30%, and 20%). In general, the rules state that a taxpayer can deduct charitable contributions as follows:nnCash contributions subject to the limit based on 60% of adjusted gross income (AGI). Deduct the contributions that don\'t exceed 60% of your adjusted gross income.nNoncash contributions (other than qualified conservation contributions) subject on the limit based on 50% of AGI. Deduct the contributions that don\'t exceed 50% of your AGI minus your cash contributions falling under the 60% limit to a 50% organization.nCash and noncash contributions (other than capital gain property) subject to the limit based on 30% of AGI. Deduct the contributions that don\'t exceed the smaller of:n30% of adjusted gross income orn50% of adjusted gross income (minus the taxpayer\'s contributions to 50% limit organizations), including contributions of capital gain property subject to the special 30% limitnIn addition, a taxpayer can carry over any contribution amounts that he or she is unable to deduct in the current year because the contribution amount exceeds his or her AGI (adjusted gross income) limits. The taxpayer, in such cases, can deduct the excess in each of the next 5 years until it is used up, but not beyond that time per Publication 526, page 19.nnIn this case, Vera and Jack would be able to deduct up to $18,000 in 2024, which is the maximum amount under the 60% cash limit (60% of $30,000) and the remaining $3,000 is carried over to 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(668,3,'During 2024, Ms. Tina paid $2,000 for state income taxes to Ohio, $1,400 in general sales tax, and $1,200 in sales tax on the purchase of a motorcycle. What amount can Ms. Tina deduct as an itemized deduction on her tax return for 2024?','[\"$1,400\",\"$2,000\",\"$2,600\",\"$3,200\"]',2,'The instructions for line 5 of Schedule A (Form 1040), pages A-3 and A-4, state that the deduction for state and local taxes is limited to $10,000 ($5,000 if married filing separately). In addition, line 5a states that a taxpayer can deduct from adjusted gross income either state and local income taxes or state and local sales tax. The taxpayer cannot deduct both in the same year.nnIn addition, a taxpayer can deduct either his or her actual expenses (which would include the sales tax paid on specific items such as a motor vehicle, boat, etc.) or an amount figured using the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables in the instructions for Schedule A, Form 1040.nnIf the taxpayer uses the Optional State and Certain Local Sales Tax Tables, he or she may be able to add to the table any state and local general sales tax paid on motor vehicles, motorcycles, motor homes, RVs, SUVs, trucks, vans, and off-road vehicles. (For more information, see the instructions for line 7 of the State and Local General Sales Tax Deduction Worksheet on page A-7 of the Schedule A (Form 1040) Instructions.)nnMs. Tina\'s itemized deductions for 2024 are $2,600, which is the sum of $1,400 (general sales tax) and $1,200 (state sales tax on motorcycle purchase).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(669,3,'Tax preparation fees are generally deductible as:','[\"They are not deductible.\",\"a miscellaneous itemized deduction subject to the 2% limit.\",\"an investment expense on Schedule A.\",\"a tax credit on Schedule 1.\"]',0,'Beginning 2018, miscellaneous expenses are subject to the 2% AGI floor are suspended.nnItems that are no longer deductible include investment fees and expenses, hobby expenses, safe deposit box rent, tax preparation fees to name a few. See Publication 17, pages 102–105 for a more complete list.nnAs a result of the elimination of the miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% floor by the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, tax preparation fees are not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(670,3,'What is the latest date for treating medical expenses as paid at the time the medical services were provided for a decedent that are paid from his or her estate?','[\"Within 1 week after the date of death\",\"Within 9 months after the date of death\",\"Within 1 year after the date of death\",\"Within 2 years after the date of death\"]',2,'The time limit for payment is only 1 year following the death of the decedent. This privilege is an election that is made by the surviving spouse or personal representative by attaching a statement to the Form 1040 on which the expenses are claimed stating that the expenses have not and will not be claimed on the estate tax return.nnPublication 502, page 5, states that the survivor or personal representative of a decedent can choose to treat certain expenses paid by the decedent\'s estate for the decedent\'s medical care as paid by the decedent at the time the medical services were provided. The expenses must be paid within the 1-year period beginning with the day after the date of death.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(671,3,'You can include medical expenses that you paid for a child before adoption, if the child qualified as your dependent:','[\"when the medical services were provided and when the expenses were paid.\",\"within 6 months of when the medical services were provided and when the expenses were paid.\",\"when the medical services were provided or when the expenses were paid.\",\"within 6 months of when the medical services were provided or when the expenses were paid.\"]',2,'Publication 502, page 3, states that a taxpayer can include medical expenses that the taxpayer paid for a child before adoption, if the child qualified as the taxpayer\'s dependent when the medical services were provided or when the expenses were paid.nnFurthermore, if the taxpayer paid back an adoption agency or other persons for medical expenses they paid under an agreement with the taxpayer, the taxpayer is treated as having paid those expenses provided the taxpayer clearly substantiated that the payment is directly attributable to the medical care of the child. Be aware that if the taxpayer paid the agency or other person for medical care that was provided and paid for before adoption negotiations began, the taxpayer cannot include them as medical expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(672,3,'Mary and George are both employed by H.T. Forest & Co. Her salary was $35,000 and his was $30,000. During the year they made the following interest payments: mortgage $8,000, car loan $2,000, home equity loan (proceeds used for personal debt consolidation) $3,000, and interest on margin account $4,000. In addition to their salaries, they had interest income of $1,500 and ordinary dividend income of $1,000. What is the amount that Mary and George will be able to deduct on Schedule A?','[\"$8,000\",\"$10,500\",\"$13,500\",\"$15,000\"]',1,'Publication 936, page 2, states, in general, that home mortgage interest is an itemized deduction and includes any interest that is paid on a loan secured by the taxpayer\'s home (main home or a second home). The loan may be a mortgage to buy the taxpayer\'s home, a second mortgage, a line of credit, or a home equity loan. Deductibility of interest associated with a mortgage loan is limited to $750,000 for loans originating after December 15, 2017 (Publication 936, page 2). Further, Publication 936, page 1, states that interest on home equity loans and lines of credit is deductible only if the borrowed funds are used to buy, build, or substantially improve the taxpayer’s home that secures the loan. The loan must be secured by the taxpayer’s main home or second home (qualified residence).nnIn addition, Publication 550, pages 35 and 46, states, in general, investment interest expense is limited to the amount of a taxpayer\'s net investment income, which is the difference between investment income and investment expense. Note that Form 4952 is used to compute the allowable investment interest expense for the year. Any investment interest not deductible in the current year can be carried over to the next tax year.nnFor Mary and George, they are able to deduct $10,500 of interest expenses, which is the sum of the couple\'s mortgage of $8,000 and interest on their margin account of $2,500, which equals the investment income of the couple (interest income of $1,500 and dividend income of $1,000). The remaining $1,500 of interest on the margin account is not deductible since it exceeds the investment income for the year; however, Mary and George can carry over this amount to the next tax year. The interest carried over is treated as investment interest paid or accrued in that next year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(673,3,'Joe has the following records of charitable contributions he made in 2024. How much can he deduct on Schedule A, Itemized Deductions?nn$300 check to local church but no written acknowledgmentn$600 by payroll deduction of $50 per month to the United Wayn$400 fair market value of furniture to a qualifying shelter with receipt and acknowledgment from the shelter dated February 1, 2025','[\"$1,300\",\"$900\",\"$600\",\"$1,000\"]',2,'Publication 526, page 3, provides that a taxpayer can deduct contributions of money or property that are made to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. A gift or contribution is “for the use of” a qualified organization when it is held in a legally enforceable trust for the qualified organization or in a similar legal arrangement.nnWith respect to contributed property to a qualified organization, a taxpayer generally can deduct the fair market value of the property at the time of the contribution (Publication 526, page 3). Be aware, a taxpayer cannot take a deduction for clothing or household items donated, unless the clothing or household items are in good used condition or better. (Publication 526, page 8)nnCash contributions include those paid by cash, checks, electronic funds transfer, debit card, credit card, or payroll deduction. A taxpayer cannot deduct a cash contribution, regardless of the amount, unless the taxpayer keeps as a record of the contribution a bank record (such as a canceled check, a bank copy of a canceled check, or a bank statement containing the name of the charity, the date, and the amount) or a written communication from the charity. (Publication 526, page 20)nnAnother restriction on the deductibility of charitable contributions pertains to the amount contributed. In particular, a taxpayer can claim a deduction for a contribution of $250 or more only if the taxpayer has a contemporaneous written acknowledgment of the contribution from the qualified organization or if the taxpayer has certain payroll deduction records (Publication 526, page 20). In figuring whether a taxpayer\'s contribution is $250 or more, the taxpayer does not combine multiple contributions. For example, if a person gave $25 per week, the weekly contributions do not need to be combined. Each payment is a separate contribution.nnGiven the above restrictions, Joe\'s charitable contributions for the year are limited to $600, which was made through his payroll deduction plan. The $300 contribution to his church is not permitted because it is over $250, and he lacks a written acknowledgment, and the $400 of furniture is deductible in the year it was donated (i.e., the following year).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(674,3,'Upon reviewing a new client\'s prior-year tax return, the preparer sees taxes paid for the first-time homebuyer credit. The preparer should ask the taxpayer all of the following except:','[\"Are the taxpayers still using the home that generated the credit as their main home?\",\"Was the entire credit used toward the purchase of their main home?\",\"How much of the original credit was repaid on prior years\\u2019 returns?\",\"What was the total amount of the original credit received?\"]',1,'The Form 5405 Instructions, page 1, provide that a taxpayer must file Form 5405 (Repayment of the First-Time Homebuyer Credit) with their 2024 tax return if they purchased the home in 2008 and they either:nndisposed of it in 2024 ornceased using it as their main home in 2024.nIn these cases, the taxpayer needs to repay the balance of the unpaid credit with their 2024 tax return.nnSince 2024 is the last year for the credit, Form 5405 is not required. Taxpayers will just need to report the final payment on Schedule 2 (Form 1040), line 10.nnNote: The repayment requirement has expired for homes purchased after 2008. However, the repayment requirement continues to apply to homes purchased in 2008.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(675,3,'A taxpayer may deduct the cost of medical expenses for the following items, except:','[\"doctor-prescribed drugs, including birth control pills.\",\"controlled substances in violation of federal law.\",\"laser eye surgery, contacts, eyeglasses, and hearing aids.\",\"guide dogs for the visually impaired and the cost of the dogs\' care.\"]',1,'The lists for items that are and are not treated as deductible medical and dental expenses are provided in Publication 502, pages 5 through 17.nnThe following is a partial list of medical and dental expenses that are deductible:nnBirth control pills prescribed by your doctornEye surgery—to promote the correct function of the eyenGuide dogs or other animals aiding the blind, deaf, and disablednPrescription medicines (prescribed by a doctor) and insulinnSpecial items (artificial limbs, false teeth, eyeglasses, contact lenses, hearing aids, crutches, wheelchair, etc.)nAll of the items in this problem are listed above as deductible medical expenses except for controlled substances in violation of federal law.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(676,3,'Alona is a student, and her personal car was destroyed by a tornado in May 2024. It was found several days later severely damaged. The decrease in fair market value (less than her adjusted basis) was $3,500. In addition, a personal laptop computer in the car at the time was never recovered (fair market value $500, also less than her adjusted basis). The area was declared a federal disaster area. What is the amount and treatment of the casualty loss after considering the $100 minimum floor, but before the AGI limitation?','[\"Schedule A loss of $3,000 for the car and computer\",\"Schedule D loss of $3,400 for the car and a Schedule A loss of $400 for the computer\",\"Schedule A loss of $3,900 for the car and the computer\",\"Schedule D loss of $4,000 for the car and the computer\"]',2,'The deduction for casualty and theft losses of personal-use property is limited. For tax years beginning after 2017 and before 2026, personal casualty and theft losses of an individual are deductible only to the extent they are attributable to a federally declared disaster. The loss deduction is subject to the $100 and 10% rules as discussed on page 10 of Publication 547.nnIn the case of nonbusiness casualty and theft losses, a taxpayer is able to deduct the loss as an itemized deduction. The amount of the loss as provided on page 6 of Publication 547 is as follows:nnDetermine the adjusted basis in the property before the casualty or theft, nDetermine the decrease in fair market value of the property as a result of the casualty or theft, andnFrom the smaller of the amounts determined in the two prior calculations, subtract any insurance or other reimbursement received or expected to receive.nIn Alona\'s case, the decrease in the FMV for her recovered stolen car is $3,500 and for her unrecovered laptop computer is $500. The result is that Alona has a Schedule A loss of $3,900 for the car and computer, which is the sum of the two losses ($3,500 and $500) less the $100 deduction per incident (Publication 547, pages 10–11).  Since the computer was inside the car when it was stolen, the two losses are treated as a single event.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(677,13,'How are premiums for health insurance paid by a partnership on behalf of a partner for services treated?','[\"As guaranteed payments\",\"As distributive income\",\"As fringe benefits\",\"As a deductible business expense\"]',0,'Guaranteed payments are those made by a partnership to a partner that are determined without regard to the partnership\'s income.nnPremiums for health insurance paid by a partnership on behalf of a partner for services as a partner are treated as guaranteed payments. The partnership can deduct the payments as a business expense and the partner must include them in gross income. However, if the partnership accounts for insurance paid for a partner as a reduction in distributions to the partner, the partnership cannot deduct the premiums.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(678,13,'For property contributed after June 8, 1997, a partner generally must recognize gain on the distribution of property (other than money) if the partner contributed appreciated property to the partnership during:','[\"the 3-year period before the distribution.\",\"the 5-year period before the distribution.\",\"the 7-year period before the distribution.\",\"the 10-year period before the distribution.\"]',2,'A partner generally must recognize gain on the distribution of property (other than money) if the partner contributed appreciated property to the partnership during the 7-year period before the distribution.nnBe aware that a 5-year period applied to property contributed before June 9, 1997, or under a written binding contract (1) that was in effect on June 8, 1997, and at all times thereafter before the contribution and (2) that provides for the contribution of a fixed amount of property. (This rule has been taken out of the current Publication 541 but is noted here to give an historical perspective of why the date June 8, 1997, was given in the question above and how rules can change over time.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(679,13,'Michael has a partnership interest with a zero basis. The partnership has inventory valued at $250,000. Michael\'s share of the ordinary income to be received from the sale of the inventory would be $10,000. In 2024, Michael sells his partnership interest for $30,000. Michael will report the following gain in 2024:','[\"$30,000 capital gain\",\"$20,000 ordinary gain and $10,000 capital gain\",\"$10,000 ordinary gain and $20,000 capital gain\",\"No gain or loss\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nnThe income or loss realized by a partner upon the sale or exchange of its interest in unrealized receivables and inventory items is the amount that would have been allocated to the partner if the partnership had sold all of its property for cash at fair market value, in a fully taxable transaction, immediately prior to the partner\'s transfer of interest in the partnership. (Publication 541, page 12)nnIn this case, Michael has a gain of $30,000 ($30,000 − $0) from the sale of his interest in the partnership. The treatment of the gain, however, is $10,000 ordinary income, which is attributable to the inventory, and $20,000 capital gain, which is attributable to the capital investment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(680,13,'Sandy and Buffy formed the S & B Partnership in November 2024. They began business operations in December 2024. During 2024, they incurred the following costs:n1. $2,500 to their attorney for negotiating and preparing the partnership agreementn2. $250 for filing fees for the partnership agreementn3. $1,000 to their CPA for services incident to the organization of the partnershipn4. $500 in costs associated with transferring assets to the partnershipnWhat is the maximum dollar amount that S & B Partnership can elect to deduct as organizational costs in 2024?','[\"$3,750\",\"$4,250\",\"$4,000\",\"$1,750\"]',0,'Publication 583, pages 9 and 10, provides that a taxpayer can elect to amortize certain costs for setting up and organizing a business. The amortization period starts with the month the taxpayer\'s active trade or business begins. For costs paid or incurred after September 8, 2008, a taxpayer can elect to deduct a limited amount of start-up and organization costs in the year that the active trade or business begins. The costs that are not deducted currently can be amortized ratably over a 180-month period.nnA taxpayer can elect to deduct up to $5,000 of business start-up costs and $5,000 of organizational costs as a current business expense for 2024. The $5,000 deduction is reduced by the amount the taxpayer\'s total costs exceed $50,000. Any remaining costs must be amortized ratably over a 180-month period. (Publication 583, pages 9–10)nnThe costs of organizing a partnership are the direct costs of creating the partnership. Organizational costs include the following fees (Publication 583, pages 9–10):nnLegal fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, such as negotiation and preparation of the partnership agreementnAccounting fees for services incident to the organization of the partnershipnFiling feesnAn example of a cost that cannot be amortized is the cost of acquiring assets for the partnership or transferring assets to the partnership.nnTaxpayers are no longer required to attach a statement to their tax return to elect to amortize start-up or organizational costs paid or incurred after September 8, 2008.nnIn this case, the partnership can deduct $3,750, which is the sum of the attorney costs ($2,500), filing fees ($250), and CPA costs ($1,000). The $500 for transferring assets to the partnership is not a qualified organizational expense.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(681,13,'On November 15, 2024, Partnership Z paid $10,000 in accounting and legal fees to prepare and file the partnership agreement. The partnership began business on December 1, 2024. Which of the following is a permissible election for treatment of the $10,000 payment?','[\"Deduct $10,000\",\"Deduct $5,000 and amortize the remaining $5,000 over a 5-year period\",\"Deduct $5,000 and amortize the remaining $5,000 over 180 months\",\"Amortize $10,000 over a 5-year period\"]',2,'Publication 583, page 29 and 30, provides that a taxpayer can elect to amortize certain costs for setting up and organizing his or her business. The amortization period starts with the month the taxpayer\'s active trade or business begins. For costs paid or incurred after September 8, 2008, a taxpayer can elect to deduct a limited amount of start-up and organization costs. The costs that are not deducted currently can be amortized ratably over a 180-month period.nnA taxpayer can elect to deduct up to $5,000 of business start-up costs and $5,000 of organizational costs as a current business expense for 2024. (Publication 583, page 27)nnThe $5,000 deduction is reduced by the amount the total start-up or organizational costs exceed $50,000. Any remaining costs must be amortized ratably over a 180-month period. (IRC Section 195)nnThe cost must qualify as a business start-up cost, an organizational cost for a corporation, or an organizational cost for a partnership. In the case of a partnership, organizational costs include legal fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, such as negotiation and preparation of the partnership agreement, accounting fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, and filing fees. (Publication 583, page 29)nnPartnership Z, therefore, can deduct $5,000 and amortize the remaining $5,000 over 180 months beginning with December 2024 (i.e., the month that the business begins operations).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(682,13,'A partner is considered not at risk for which of the following amounts?','[\"The money and adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed to the activity\",\"The partner\'s share of net income retained by the partnership\",\"An allocation of a loss, deduction, or expense attributable to a partnership\'s nonrecourse liability\",\"Certain amounts borrowed by the partnership for use in the activity if the partner is personally liable for repayment\"]',2,'A taxpayer is not considered at risk for amounts protected against loss through nonrecourse financing, guarantees, stop loss agreements, or other similar arrangements. On the other hand, a taxpayer is considered at risk for qualified nonrecourse financing secured by real property used in an activity of holding real property.nnThus, a partner is not at risk for a partnership\'s nonrecourse liability. (Publication 925, page 14)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(683,13,'When payments are made to a retiring partner, or successor in interest of a deceased partner, for an interest in the partnership property, which of the following is correct?','[\"Payments that are based on partnership income are not taxable as a distributive share of partnership income but for the interest in the partnership.\",\"A retiring partner is treated as a partner until his\\/her interest in the partnership has been completely liquidated.\",\"Payments made for a retiring partner\'s share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables are treated as made in exchange for partnership property if capital is not a material income-producing factor and the retiring partner was a general partner.\",\"If the amount of the payment is based on partnership income, the payment is treated as a guaranteed payment.\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 12, states, in part, that payments made by the partnership to a retiring partner or successor in interest of a deceased partner in return for the partner\'s entire interest in the partnership may have to be allocated between payments in liquidation of the partner\'s interest in partnership property and other payments. The partnership\'s payments include an assumption of the partner\'s share of partnership liabilities treated as a distribution of money.nnFor income tax purposes, a retiring partner or successor in interest of a deceased partner is treated as a partner until his or her interest in the partnership has been completely liquidated, which is the correct response to this problem.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(684,13,'Payments made by a partnership to a partner that are determined without regard to the partnership income are called:','[\"guaranteed payments.\",\"minimum payments.\",\"ordinary income.\",\"capital gains.\"]',0,'Publication 541, pages 7 and 8, addresses the issue of guaranteed payments. First (and relevant for this question), guaranteed payments are those made by a partnership to a partner that is determined without regard to the partnership\'s income. Second, premiums for health insurance paid by a partnership on behalf of a partner for services as a partner are treated as guaranteed payments. Third, guaranteed payments are included in income in the partner\'s tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nnFinally, if guaranteed payments to a partner result in a partnership loss in which the partner shares, the partner must report the full amount of the guaranteed payments as ordinary income. The partner also separately takes into account his or her distributive share of the partnership loss, to the extent of the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(685,13,'Mark, a 50% partner in the X & Y Partnership, uses the percentage method to compute his depletion allowance for the gas and oil property owned by the partnership. His allocable share of the property is $100,000. Additionally, the fair market value of the property is $100,000. Sixty-five percent (65%) of his taxable income for 2024 equals $65,000. The percentage depletion rate is 15% for natural gas and oil sold. X & Y is a small producer, and the average daily production does not exceed the depletable oil and gas quantity. Mark\'s share of the gross sale of oil and gas deposits was $30,000. What is Mark\'s depletion deduction for 2024?','[\"$4,500\",\"$9,750\",\"$9,000\",\"$5,250\"]',0,'Publication 544, pages 36 and 37, states, in part, if a taxpayer has an economic interest in mineral property or standing timber, the taxpayer can take a deduction for depletion. In general, depletion is the using up of natural resources by mining, quarrying stone, drilling, or cutting timber. The depletion deduction allows an owner or operator to account for the reduction of a product\'s reserves.nnA taxpayer has an economic interest if both of the following apply:nnA taxpayer has acquired by investment any interest in mineral deposits or standing timber.nA taxpayer has a legal right to income from the extraction of the mineral or cutting of the timber to which a taxpayer must look for a return of his or her capital investment.nThere are two ways of figuring depletion: cost depletion and percentage depletion. Generally, a taxpayer must use the method that gives the larger deduction. However, unless the taxpayer is an independent producer or royalty owner, a taxpayer cannot use percentage depletion for oil and gas wells.nnIn the case of percentage depletion, the taxpayer simply multiplies a certain percentage, specified for each mineral, by the taxpayer\'s gross income from the property during the tax year. (Publication 544, page 37)nnIn Mark\'s case, he is able to claim a percentage depletion of $4,500, which is the result of the depletion rate of 15% times the gross income from the oil and gas deposits of $30,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(686,13,'Greg and Elaine formed Spring Lawn, Ltd., a calendar year partnership, in 2024 to provide yard maintenance to residential customers. Before they began operations in May 2024, they incurred legal fees of $2,000 and consulting expenses of $1,000 to draft the partnership agreement and file the required forms. They also paid a commission of $600 to a broker to market partnership interests. If duly elected, how much of these expenses may be deducted as organization costs on Spring Lawn\'s partnership tax return for 2024?','[\"$400\",\"$0\",\"$3,000\",\"$150\"]',2,'Publication 583, pages 9–10, presents the organization expenses that can be amortized by a partnership, which include:nnlegal fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, such as negotiation and preparation of a partnership agreement,naccounting fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, andnfiling fees.nSome expenses cannot be amortized (regardless of how the partnership characterizes them), including expenses connected with the following actions:nnAcquiring assets for the partnership or transferring assets to the partnershipnAdmitting or removing partners other than at the time the partnership is first organizednMaking a contract relating to the operation of the partnership trade or business (even if the contract is between the partnership and one of its members)nSyndicating the partnershipnAfter September 8, 2008, a taxpayer can elect to deduct a limited amount of start-up and organization costs. The costs that are not deducted currently can be amortized ratably over a 180-month period. (Publication 583, page 10)nnA taxpayer can elect to deduct up to $5,000 of business start-up costs and $5,000 of organizational costs as a current business expense for 2024. The $5,000 deduction is reduced by the amount the taxpayer\'s total costs exceed $50,000. Any remaining costs must be amortized ratably over a 180-month period. (Publication 583, page 10)nnThe amortization period starts with the month that the taxpayer\'s active trade or business begins.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nTaxpayers can elect to amortize start-up or organizational costs by completing and attaching Form 4562 to their tax return.nn n nnThe total organization costs for Spring Lawn, Ltd., are $3,000, which is the lesser of the maximum $5,000 deduction and the total organization costs of $3,000.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBe advised that this type of question appears often on the exam in one form or another.nPublication 583, pages 9–10, presents the organization expenses that can be amortized by a partnership, which include:nnlegal fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, such as negotiation and preparation of a partnership agreement,naccounting fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, andnfiling fees.nSome expenses cannot be amortized (regardless of how the partnership characterizes them), including expenses connected with the following actions:nnAcquiring assets for the partnership or transferring assets to the partnershipnAdmitting or removing partners other than at the time the partnership is first organizednMaking a contract relating to the operation of the partnership trade or business (even if the contract is between the partnership and one of its members)nSyndicating the partnershipnAfter September 8, 2008, a taxpayer can elect to deduct a limited amount of start-up and organization costs. The costs that are not deducted currently can be amortized ratably over a 180-month period. (Publication 583, page 10)nnA taxpayer can elect to deduct up to $5,000 of business start-up costs and $5,000 of organizational costs as a current business expense for 2024. The $5,000 deduction is reduced by the amount the taxpayer\'s total costs exceed $50,000. Any remaining costs must be amortized ratably over a 180-month period. (Publication 583, page 10)nnThe amortization period starts with the month that the taxpayer\'s active trade or business begins.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nTaxpayers can elect to amortize start-up or organizational costs by completing and attaching Form 4562 to their tax return.nn n nnThe total organization costs for Spring Lawn, Ltd., are $3,000, which is the lesser of the maximum $5,000 deduction and the total organization costs of $3,000.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBe advised that this type of question appears often on the exam in one form or another.  n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(687,13,'Lori\'s outside basis in the Briar Patch Partnership at January 1, 2024, was $11,000. She is a 50% partner and shares profits and losses in the same ratio. For 2024, the partnership\'s ordinary business income was $40,000 and tax-exempt interest income was $200. Lori received a cash distribution from the partnership of $700 in 2024. If the partnership were to liquidate on December 31, 2024, what would be Lori\'s basis for determining gain or loss?','[\"$24,900\",\"$30,750\",\"$30,400\",\"$30,300\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 10, provides that a partner\'s interest is increased and decreased by certain transactions. For example, the basis is increased by items such as:nnthe partner\'s additional contribution to the partnership andnthe partner\'s distributive share of taxable and nontaxable partnership income.nSimilarly, a partner\'s basis is decreased by events such as:nnthe partner\'s distributive share of the partnership\'s losses,nthe partner\'s distributive share of nondeductible partnership expenses that are not capital expenditures, andnmoney or adjusted basis of property distributed to a partner.nLori\'s basis in the partnership for determining gain and loss on the termination would be $30,400, which is the sum of $11,000 (her beginning of the year basis), $20,000 (50% share of partnership income), and $100 (50% share of tax-exempt interest), less the $700 cash distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(688,13,'A contribution of money or other property to the partnership followed by a distribution of different property from the partnership to the partner is treated as a sale of property if:n1. Rule 1: the partner\'s right to the distribution does not depend on the success of partnership\'s operations.n2. Rule 2: the distribution would not have been made but for the contribution.','[\"Satisfaction of Rule 1 alone\",\"Satisfaction of Rule 2 alone\",\"Satisfaction of both Rule 1 and Rule 2\",\"The transaction is always treated as a sale because it is a disguised sale.\"]',2,'A disguised sale is one where a contribution of money or other property to the partnership is followed by a distribution of different property from the partnership to the partner. In this case, the transaction is treated not as a contribution and distribution, but as a sale of property, if both of the following tests are met:nnthe distribution would not have been made but for the contribution, andnthe partner\'s right to the distribution does not depend on the success of partnership operations. (Treasury Regulation 1.707-3(b)(1) and Publication 541, page 8)nAll facts and circumstances are considered in determining if the contribution and distribution are more properly characterized as a sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(689,13,'Jane gave each of her two children, Jake and Jeff, a 30% interest in her clothing store. Capital is a material income-producing factor. Jeff is 21, has worked in the store since he was 15, has developed significant sales skills, and helps his mom with the management duties. Jake is 25, married, has a job in another state, and does not participate in any of the store\'s management decisions. Who are recognized as partners?','[\"Jane\",\"Jane and Jake\",\"Jane, Jake, and Jeff\",\"Jane and Jeff\"]',2,'Publication 541, pages 2 and 3, states that members of a family can be partners. However, family members (or any other person) will be recognized as partners only if one of the following requirements is met:nnif capital is a material income-producing factor, they acquired their capital interest in a bona fide transaction (even if by gift or purchase from another family member), actually own the partnership interest, and actually control the interest, ornif capital is not a material income-producing factor, they joined together in good faith to conduct a business. They agreed that contributions of each entitle them to a share in the profits, and some capital or service has been (or is) provided by each partner.nIn this problem, Jane gave each of her two children a 30% interest in the partnership where capital is a material income-producing factor. Therefore, Jane and both children are recognized as partners. Participation in the business is not a relevant factor for this issue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(690,13,'All of the following are correct when a partnership is notified of an exchange of partnership interests involving unrealized receivables or inventory items, except:','[\"Form 8308 is filed with Form 1065 for the tax year that includes the last day of the calendar year in which the exchange took place.\",\"The partnership must file Form 8308,\\u00a0Report of a Sale or Exchange of Certain Partnership Interests,\\u00a0only if the notification occurs after the Form 1065 for the year of the exchange has been filed.\",\"Form 8308 is filed separately within 30 days of the notification, if notified of an exchange after filing Form 1065.\",\"Form 8308 states the date of the exchange.\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 12, states that a partnership must file Form 8308, Report of a Sale or Exchange of Certain Partnership Interests, when it is notified of an exchange of partnership interests involving unrealized receivables or inventory items. More specifically:nnForm 8308 is filed with Form 1065 for the tax year that includes the last day of the calendar year in which the exchange took place, ornForm 8308 is filed separately within 30 days of the notification, if the partnership is notified of an exchange after filing Form 1065.nForm 8308 provides the telephone number of the partnership, states the date of the exchange, and states the names, addresses, and taxpayer identification numbers of the partnership filing the return and the transferee and transferor in the exchange.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(691,13,'An election to amortize may be made for qualifying costs of organization for a partnership. Which of the following is not considered a qualifying cost?','[\"A cost incurred in the creation of the partnership and\\u00a0not\\u00a0for starting or operating the partnership trade or business\",\"Accounting fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership\",\"Legal fees for preparation of the partnership agreement\",\"The costs of acquiring assets for the partnership\"]',3,'Publication 583, pages 9 and 10, states a partnership can amortize an organizational cost only if it satisfies all of these five tests:nnIt is for the creation of the partnership and not for starting or operating the partnership.nIt is chargeable to a capital account.nIt could be amortized over the life of the partnership if the partnership had a fixed life.nIt is incurred by the due date of the partnership return (excluding extensions) for the first tax year.nIt is for a type of item normally expected to benefit the partnership throughout its entire life.nIf the five tests are satisfied, then the organization expenses that can be amortized by a partnership include the following:nnLegal fees for services incident to the organization of the partnership, such as negotiation and preparation of a partnership agreementnAccounting fees for services incident to the organization of the partnershipnFiling feesnSome expenses cannot be amortized (regardless of how the partnership characterizes them), including expenses connected with the following actions:nnacquiring assets for the partnership or transferring assets to the partnership,nadmitting or removing partners other than at the time the partnership is first organized,nmaking a contract relating to the operation of the partnership trade or business (even if the contract is between the partnership and one of its members), andnsyndicating the partnership.nIn this problem, the one item that is listed that cannot be amortized as an organization cost is the costs of acquiring assets for the partnership.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(692,13,'If the partner\'s distributive share of a partnership item cannot be determined under the partnership agreement, it is determined by his or her interest in the partnership. The partnership interest is determined by taking into account all of the following items, except:','[\"the partner\'s relative contributions to the partnership.\",\"the interests of the partners in economic profits and losses (if different from interests in taxable income or loss) and in cash flow and other nonliquidating distributions.\",\"the amount of the partnership\'s nonrecourse liabilities.\",\"the right of the partners to distributions of capital upon liquidation.\"]',2,'The instructions for Form 1065 (page 31) provide that if the partnership agreement does not provide for the partner\'s share of income, gain, loss, deduction, or credit, or if the allocation does not have substantial economic effect, the partner\'s distributive share of the partnership items is generally determined by the partner\'s interest in the partnership. (See Regulation Section 1.704-1.)nnPursuant to Regulation Section 1.704-1, the partner\'s interest is determined by taking into account all of the following items:nnthe partners\' relative contributions to the partnership,nthe interests of the partners in economic profits and losses (if different from interests in taxable income or loss) and in cash flow and other nonliquidating distributions, andnthe rights of the partners to distributions of capital upon liquidation.nThe partner\'s interest does not include the amount of the partnership\'s nonrecourse liabilities. These liabilities do not have any economic effect because the partner does not bear the economic burden corresponding to that allocation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(693,13,'Patti and Kae formed a partnership in which they share income and losses equally. Kae contributes land on which there is a recourse mortgage of $18,000. The land has an adjusted basis to Kae of $15,000 and a fair market value of $20,000 at the time of the contribution. Patti contributes $2,000 to the partnership in cash. What amount of gain should Kae recognize as a result of the contribution of property?','[\"$0\",\"$9,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$2,000\"]',0,'Publication 541, page 9, states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. Any increase in a partner\'s individual liabilities because of an assumption of partnership liabilities is considered a contribution of money to the partnership by the partner.nnFurthermore, neither the partner nor the partnership usually recognizes a gain or loss when property is contributed to the partnership in exchange for a partnership interest. This applies whether a partnership is being formed or is already operating. The partnership\'s holding period for the property includes the partner\'s holding period. (Publication 541, page 8)nnIn this problem, Kae\'s contribution of property with an FMV of $20,000 and an adjusted basis of $15,000 does not result in a gain from the transfer to the partnership. Since Kae and Patti are equal partners, Kae\'s basis would decrease by the mortgage assumed by the partnership and increase by the share of recourse liabilities assumed by Kae. As such, Kae\'s basis is: $15,000 (adjusted basis of asset) less $18,000 (mortgage assumed by partnership) + $9,000 (recourse liability) equals $6,000. Since Kae\'s basis is positive, no gain or loss would be recognized for this contribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(694,13,'Losses will not be allowed from a sale or exchange of property (other than an interest in the partnership) directly or indirectly between a partnership and:','[\"a person whose direct interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.\",\"a person whose indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.\",\"a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.\",\"a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 75%.\"]',2,'If the sale or exchange is between two partnerships in which the same persons directly or indirectly own more than 50% of the capital or profits interests in each partnership, no deduction of a loss is allowed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(695,13,'The Marmalade Partnership has two partners who share partnership income and loss equally. The partnership has a fiscal tax year ending on June 30. In 2024, the partnership changes to a required tax year because there is no majority interest and files its tax return on the calendar tax year basis. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The partnership is required to file an application for a change in tax year and obtain IRS approval.\",\"The partnership is able to get automatic approval by filing an application for a change in tax year by the due date for filing the tax return for the short period required to effect such a change.\",\"The partnership is able to get automatic approval by filing an application for a change in tax year by the due date for filing the tax return for the current tax year.\",\"The partnership is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file an application for a change in tax year because it is a required tax year change.\"]',1,'Publication 538, page 5, addresses the issues associated with partnerships and required tax year elections. Specifically, if a partnership changes to a required tax year because of one of the following three rules, the partnership can get automatic approval by filing Form 1128 and following Revenue Procedure 2006-46. The short period return must indicate at the top of page 1 \"Filed under section 1.706-1\".nnThat is, the partnership does not need to obtain the IRS\'s approval for the change, but it must file the application for a change in tax year.nnIf one or more partners having the same tax year own a majority interest (more than 50%) in partnership profits and capital, the partnership must use the tax year of those partners; ornIf there is no majority interest tax year, the partnership must use the tax year of all its principal partners (i.e., one who has a 5% or more interest); ornIf there is no majority interest tax year and the principal partners do not have the same tax year, the partnership generally must use a tax year that results in the least aggregate deferral of income to the partners.nMoreover, if a partnership changes to a required tax year because of one of the above rules, the partnership is able to get automatic approval by filing Form 1128. An application for a change in tax year by the due date (including extensions) for filing the tax return for the short period is required to effect such a change (Form 1128 Instructions, pages 5 and 6).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(696,13,'In which of the following ownership combinations would Fred be treated as owning more than 50% of the partnership?','[\"Fred 20%, Fred\'s Son 20%, Fred\'s Uncle 60%\",\"Fred 25%, Fred\'s Wife 10%, Fred\'s Aunt 65%\",\"Fred 40%, Fred\'s Nephew 20%, Fred\'s Son 40%\",\"Fred 45%, Fred\'s Cousin 55%\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 8, provides a rule to determine if a partner has more than 50% ownership, which is as follows:nnan interest directly or indirectly owned by or for a corporation, partnership, estate, or trust is considered to be owned proportionately by or for its shareholders, partners, or beneficiaries,nan individual is considered to own the interest directly or indirectly owned by or for the individual\'s family. For this rule, “family” includes only brothers, sisters, half-brothers, half-sisters, spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants, ornif a person is considered to own an interest using rule (1), that person (the “constructive owner”) is treated as if actually owning that interest when rules (1) and (2) are applied. However, if a person is considered to own an interest using rule (2), that person is not treated as actually owning that interest in reapplying rule (2) to make another person the constructive owner.nIn this problem, Fred is treated as owning more than 50% in the case where he owns 40% and his son owns 40%, which is 80% ownership. The other 20% ownership by Fred\'s nephew does not constructively count for Fred.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:17'),(697,13,'Archie sells his 50% interest in XYZ Partnership to Hal for $5,000 cash. His outside basis in the partnership is $3,500. The partnership has inventory and a capital asset with respect to basis of $6,000 and $2,000. The respective fair market values of the inventory and capital asset are $8,000 and $1,000. Archie should properly recognize:','[\"ordinary income of $2,000 and a capital loss of $500.\",\"capital gain of $1,500 on the sale of his partnership interest.\",\"ordinary income of $1,500, the amount of cash he received.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner also must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nnThe income or loss realized by a partner upon the sale or exchange of its interest in unrealized receivables and inventory items is the amount that would have been allocated to the partner if the partnership had sold all of its property for cash at fair market value, in a fully taxable transaction, immediately prior to the partner\'s transfer of interest in the partnership. (Publication 541, page 12)nnIn this case, Archie has a gain of $1,500 ($5,000 − $3,500) from the sale of his 50% interest in the partnership. The treatment of the gain, however, is $1,000 ordinary income (($8,000 − $6,000) × 0.50), which is attributable to the inventory, and therefore a $500 capital gain ($1,500 less $1,000), which is attributable to the capital investment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(698,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the income of a partner and its taxation as self-employment income?','[\"The partnership\'s income or loss through the partnership year is included if the partner dies during the partnership tax year.\",\"Limited partners include only guaranteed payments for services actually rendered to or on behalf of the partnership.\",\"The partnership\'s income or loss is included on the joint self-employment tax form in the case where a husband and wife are both partners.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'The instructions for Schedule SE (Form 1040), page SE-4, provide information concerning self-employment income in the case of partnership income and loss. If a taxpayer is a general or limited partner in the partnership, the amount of net earnings from self-employment from Schedule K-1 is included as self-employment income. General partners should reduce this amount by certain expenses and limited partners include only guaranteed payments for services actually rendered to or on behalf of the partnership.nnIf a partner dies and the partnership continued, include in self-employment income the deceased\'s distributive share of the partnership\'s ordinary income or loss through the end of the month (not the end of the partnership\'s tax year) in which he or she died (see IRC Section 1402(f)).nnIf a married couple is both partners in a partnership, each spouse must report his or her net earnings from self-employment from the partnership. That is, each spouse files a separate Schedule SE (there is no joint Schedule SE).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(699,13,'Under a partnership agreement, June is to receive 40% of the partnership income but not less than $12,000 a year. The partnership has net income of $20,000. What is the guaranteed payment that the partnership can deduct in figuring its ordinary income on page 1 of Form 1065?','[\"$0\",\"$3,200\",\"$4,000\",\"$8,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 7, discusses the treatment of minimum payments. If a partner is to receive a minimum payment from the partnership, the guaranteed payment is the amount by which the minimum payment is more than the partner\'s distributive share of the partnership income before taking into account the guaranteed payment.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nUnder a partnership agreement, Divya is to receive 30% of the partnership income, but not less than $8,000. The partnership has net income of $20,000. Divya\'s share, without regard to the minimum guarantee, is $6,000 (30% × $20,000). The guaranteed payment that can be deducted by the partnership is $2,000 ($8,000 − $6,000). Divya\'s income from the partnership is $8,000, and the remaining $12,000 of partnership income will be reported by the other partners in proportion to their shares under the partnership agreement.nn n nnThe partnership is able to deduct $4,000 of the $12,000 as a guaranteed payment to June. The $4,000 is the difference between June\'s minimum payment of $12,000 and her distributive share of the partnership income of $8,000 (40% of $20,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(700,13,'Sharon\'s basis in S & P partnership is $185,000. In a complete liquidation of Sharon\'s interest in S & P, Sharon received the following:n              S and P\'s Basis      Fair Market ValuenCash              $ 5,000              $  5,000nBuilding           50,000               100,000nLand               40,000                50,000nWhat is Sharon\'s basis in the building?','[\"$50,000\",\"$100,000\",\"$116,667\",\"$120,000\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 6, states that the basis of property received in complete liquidation of a partner\'s interest is the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership reduced by any money distributed to the partner in the same transaction.nnIf the basis of property received is the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership (reduced by money received in the same transaction), it must be divided among the properties distributed to the partner. For property distributed after August 5, 1997, allocate the basis using the following rules:nnAllocate the basis first to unrealized receivables and inventory items included in the distribution by assigning a basis to each item equal to the partnership\'s adjusted basis in the item immediately before the distribution. If the total of these assigned bases exceeds the allocable basis, decrease the assigned bases by the amount of the excess.nAllocate any remaining basis to properties other than unrealized receivables and inventory items by assigning a basis to each property equal to the partnership\'s adjusted basis in the property immediately before the distribution. If the allocable basis exceeds the total of these assigned bases, increase the assigned bases by the amount of the excess. If the total of these assigned bases exceeds the allocable basis, decrease the assigned bases by the amount of the excess.nAllocate any basis increase required as a result of the above rule (2) first to properties with unrealized appreciation to the extent of the unrealized appreciation. (If the basis increase is less than the total unrealized appreciation, allocate it among those properties in proportion to their respective amounts of unrealized appreciation.) Allocate any remaining basis increase among all of the properties in proportion to their respective fair market values.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nEun\'s basis in her partnership interest is $55,000. In a distribution in liquidation of her entire interest, she receives properties A and B, neither of which is inventory or unrealized receivables. Property A has an adjusted basis to the partnership of $5,000 and an FMV of $40,000. Property B has an adjusted basis to the partnership of $10,000 and an FMV of $10,000.nnTo figure her basis in each property, Eun first assigns bases of $5,000 to property A and $10,000 to property B (their adjusted bases to the partnership). This leaves a $40,000 basis increase (the $55,000 allocable basis minus the $15,000 total of the assigned bases). She first allocates $35,000 to property A (its unrealized appreciation). The remaining $5,000 is allocated between the properties based on their FMV. $4,000 ($40,000 ÷ $50,000) is allocated to property A, and $1,000 ($10,000 ÷ $50,000) is allocated to property B. Eun\'s basis in property A is $44,000 ($5,000 + $35,000 + $4,000), and her basis in property B is $11,000 ($10,000 + $1,000).nn n nnSharon\'s basis in the building would be $120,000.nnFirst, Sharon reduces her adjusted basis of $185,000 by the cash amount distributed of $5,000, which leaves her with $180,000 to assign the remaining distributed properties.nSecond, Sharon assigns bases of $50,000 to the building and $40,000 to the land (partnership\'s adjusted basis, which leaves an excess amount of $90,000 ($185,000 − $5,000 (cash) − $90,000 (building and land\'s bases))).nThird, Sharon raises the building and land\'s bases for unrealized appreciation, which is $100,000 to the building and $50,000 to the land, which equals $150,000. After accounting for the unrealized appreciation, an excess of $30,000 ($185,000 − $5,000 − $150,000) still remains.nFourth, Sharon assigns the $30,000 to the building and land proportionally; building receives $20,000 (($100,000 ÷ $150,000) × $30,000) and land receives $10,000 (($50,000 ÷ $150,000) × $30,000).nAs a result, the building\'s basis is $120,000 ($100,000 + $20,000) and the land\'s basis is $60,000 ($50,000 + $10,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(701,13,'Abercrombie Partnership sold a capital asset to Freeman Partnership at a loss of $50,000. Abercrombie had held the property for 5 months. Abercrombie is owned 30% by Doug, 30% by Fred, and 40% by Dale, Doug\'s brother. Freeman Partnership is owned 80% by ABC Corporation. Doug owns 25% of the stock of ABC Corporation and Dale\'s daughter, Deb, owns 60% of the stock of ABC Corporation. How much of the loss should Abercrombie allow for tax purposes on their tax return for the year of the sale?','[\"$50,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$0\",\"$35,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 8, addresses the special rules applying to a sale or exchange of property between a partnership and certain persons. In the case of a loss, the losses will not be allowed from a sale or exchange of property (other than some interest in the partnership) directly or indirectly between a partnership and a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.nnIf the sale or exchange is between two partnerships in which the same persons directly or indirectly own more than 50% of the capital or profits interests in each partnership, no deduction of a loss is allowed. The basis of each partner\'s interest, however, in the partnership is decreased (but not below zero) by the partner\'s share of the disallowed loss.nnIf the purchaser later sells the property, only the gain realized that is greater than the loss not allowed will be taxable. If any gain from the sale of the property is not recognized because of this rule, the basis of each partner\'s interest in the partnership is increased by the partner\'s share of that gain.nnPublication 541, page 8, further provides the rule to determine if a partner has more than 50% ownership. More specifically:nnAn interest directly or indirectly owned by or for a corporation, partnership, estate, or trust is considered to be owned proportionately by or for its shareholders, partners, or beneficiaries.nAn individual is considered to own the interest directly or indirectly owned by or for the individual\'s family. For this rule, “family” includes only brothers, sisters, half-brothers, half-sisters, spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants.nIf a person is considered to own an interest using rule (1), that person (the “constructive owner”) is treated as if actually owning that interest when rules (1) and (2) are applied. However, if a person is considered to own an interest using rule (2), that person is not treated as actually owning that interest in reapplying rule (2) to make another person the constructive owner.nDale owns 70% of the Abercrombie partnership (40% Dale and 30% Doug, Dale\'s brother) and 68% of the Freeman partnership (80% of (25% Doug and 60% of Deb, Dale\'s daughter)). Hence, the transfer of the property from Abercrombie to Freeman at a $50,000 loss cannot be taken by Abercrombie or, in other words, recognized.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(702,13,'Which of the following statements is generally correct?','[\"A limited partner does not have an economic risk of loss in partnership recourse liabilities.\",\"A limited partner does not have an obligation to contribute additional capital to the partnership.\",\"A guarantee by a limited partner of a partnership\'s liability results in the limited partner having an economic risk of loss in partnership recourse liabilities.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A limited partner generally has no obligation to contribute additional capital to the partnership and therefore does not have economic risk of loss in partnership recourse liabilities. Thus, absent some other factor, such as the guarantee of a partnership liability by the limited partner or the limited partner making the loan to the partnership, a limited partner generally does not have a share of partnership recourse liabilities.nnThus, absent some other factor such as the guarantee of a partnership liability by the limited partner or the limited partner making the loan to the partnership, a limited partner generally does not have a share of partnership recourse liabilities (i.e., debt).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(703,13,'Jean and Mary each have a 50% interest in JM Partnership. The partnership and the partners all file calendar year tax returns. For the 2023 tax year return, JM Partnership had a $22,000 loss. Jean\'s adjusted basis in her partnership interest on January 1, 2023, was $5,000. JM Partnership reported a $25,000 gain on its 2024 tax year return. There are no other adjustments to Jean\'s basis in the partnership for 2023 or 2024. There were no distributions to the partners in either year. What is the amount of partnership income or (loss) that Jean will show on her 2024 individual Form 1040?','[\"$0\",\"$1,500\",\"$6,500\",\"$12,500\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 5, provides that a partnership distribution is not taken into account in determining the partner\'s distributive share of partnership income or loss. If any gain or loss from the distribution is recognized by the partner, it must be reported on his or her return for the tax year in which the distribution is received.nnWith respect to the partner\'s adjusted basis in his or her partnership, the partnership interest is decreased (but not below zero) by the money and adjusted basis of property distributed to the partner. Furthermore, a partner recognizes a loss on a partnership distribution only to the extent of the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. There are exceptions to this general rule, such as the liquidation at a partner\'s retirement or death, that are not relevant here.nnHowever, any loss not allowed for this reason will be allowed as a deduction (up to the partner\'s basis) at the end of any succeeding year in which the partner increases his or her basis to more than zero (IRC Section 704(d)).nnAs a result of the above rules, Jean\'s share of the partnership loss for 2023 is $11,000, but she is only able to claim $5,000, which is her adjusted basis in the partnership. As a result of claiming the $5,000 loss in 2023, Jean\'s basis at the end of 2023 is zero. The remaining loss of $6,000 ($11,000 –$5,000) is carried over and suspended until Jean\'s basis would increase as a result of capital contributions and/or income allocation.nnIn 2024, the partnership has a $25,000 gain, of which Jean\'s share is 50%, or $12,500. But since Jean had a loss carryover of $6,000 ($11,000 loss in 2023 less $5,000 basis), she has partnership income in 2024 of $6,500 ($12,500 income less the $6,000 loss carryover). Jean\'s adjusted basis in the partnership for 2024 is $6,500.nnPlease note individuals who invest in partnerships are limited in their ability to deduct losses by the three sets of limitations: basis (section 704(d)), at-risk (section 465), and passive activity loss limitations (section 469).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(704,13,'Bill and Jimmy formed a new partnership. Bill contributes property that has an adjusted basis of $1,400 and a fair market value of $2,000 to the partnership. Jimmy contributes $2,000 in cash to the partnership. Each partner\'s capital account as reflected on the partnership\'s books is $2,000. What is the adjusted basis of each partner\'s interest?','[\"Bill\'s at $1,400 and Jimmy\'s at $1,400\",\"Bill\'s at $1,400 and Jimmy\'s at $2,000\",\"Bill\'s at $1,700 and Jimmy\'s at $1,700\",\"Bill\'s at $2,000 and Jimmy\'s at $2,000\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 9, states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. Any increase in a partner\'s individual liabilities because of an assumption of partnership liabilities is considered a contribution of money to the partnership by the partner.nnIn this problem, Bill contributed property that has an adjusted basis of $1,400 (his basis) and Jimmy contributes $2,000 in cash (his basis).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(705,13,'Shizaam Bakery operates as a calendar-year partnership. Shizaam\'s two partners, Kalla and Henry, share profits and losses 60% and 40%, respectively. For tax year ended December 31, 2024, Shizaam had the following income and expense:nn   Gross sales                   $270,000n   Cost of goods sold              80,000n   Interest income from bank        2,500n   Wages expense                   50,000n   Short-term capital loss          5,000nCompute the partnership\'s ordinary income and flow through amounts to partners.','[\"Kalla\\u2014ordinary income $85,500 and short-term capital loss $3,000; Henry\\u2014ordinary income $57,000 and short-term capital loss $2,000\",\"Kalla\\u2014ordinary income $82,500; Henry \\u2013 ordinary income $55,000\",\"Kalla\\u2014ordinary income $81,000, interest income $1,500, and short-term capital loss $3,000; Henry\\u2014ordinary income $54,000, interest income $1,000, and short-term capital loss $2,000\",\"Kalla\\u2014ordinary income $84,000, interest income $1,500, and short-term capital loss $3,000; Henry\\u2014ordinary income $56,000, interest income $1,000, and short-term capital loss $2,000\"]',3,'A partnership computes its income and files its return in the same manner as an individual. The ordinary business income for a partnership as given on Form 1065 is computed as:nngross receipts or sales less cost of goods sold plus other partnership income, lessnsalaries and wages,nguaranteed payments to partners,nrepairs and maintenance,nbad debts,nrent,ntaxes and licenses,ninterest,ndepreciation,nretirement plans,nemployee benefit programs, andnother deductions.nIn addition, certain other items are separately stated on the partnership return and included as separate items on each partner\'s return (Schedule K-1, Part III (Form 1065)). They include but are not limited to the following:nnOrdinary income or loss from trade or business activitiesnNet income or loss from rental real estate activitiesnNet income or loss from other rental activitiesnGuaranteed payments to partnersnInterest incomenGains and losses from sales or exchanges of capital assetsnGains and losses from sales or exchanges of property described in Section 1231 of the IRCnCharitable contributionsnOrdinary and qualified dividendsnDividends (passed through to corporate partners) that are eligible for the dividends-received deduction (IRC Section 243 generally) by the attachment of a statement per page 8 of the Schedule K-1 (Form 1065) InstructionsnTaxes paid or accrued to foreign countries and U.S. possessionsnOther items of income, gain, loss, deduction, or credit, as provided by regulationsnIn this problem, Kalla has ordinary income $84,000 (60% of ($270,000 - $80,000 - $50,000)), interest income of $1,500 (60% of $2,500), and short-term capital loss of $3,000 (60% of $5,000).nnHenry, on the other hand, has ordinary income $56,000 (40% of ($270,000 - $80,000 - $50,000)), interest income of $1,000 (40% of $2,500), and short-term capital loss of $2,000 (40% of $5,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(706,13,'Larkspur, a calendar year partnership, is owned equally by Nathan, Jerry, Jon, and Marty. The partnership agreement states that Nathan will receive 25% of the profit (loss) of the partnership with a minimum of $15,000 for his services to the partnership. The other partners are each to receive 25% of the profit (loss). The net income of the partnership without regard to the $15,000 minimum is $40,000 for 2024. The partnership should deduct a guaranteed payment of:','[\"$15,000.\",\"$10,000.\",\"$0.\",\"$5,000.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 7, discusses the treatment of minimum payments. If a partner is to receive a minimum payment from the partnership, the guaranteed payment is the amount by which the minimum payment is more than the partner\'s distributive share of the partnership income before taking into account the guaranteed payment.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nUnder a partnership agreement, Divya is to receive 30% of the partnership income, but not less than $8,000. The partnership has net income of $20,000. Divya\'s share, without regard to the minimum guarantee, is $6,000 (30% × $20,000). The guaranteed payment that can be deducted by the partnership is $2,000 ($8,000 − $6,000). Divya\'s income from the partnership is $8,000, and the remaining $12,000 of partnership income will be reported by the other partners in proportion to their shares under the partnership agreement.nn n nnThe partnership is able to deduct $5,000 of the $15,000 as a guaranteed payment to Nathan. The $5,000 is the difference between Nathan\'s minimum payment of $15,000 and his distributive share of the partnership income of $10,000 (25% of $40,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(707,13,'Mike invested $10,000 cash for a 25% interest in Matthew and Lewis partnership. Mike materially participates in the partnership business. Matthew and Lewis Partnership had an $80,000 loss in 2024. The partnership agreement states that Mike is additionally liable for all of the partnership liabilities of $5,000. What is the amount of Mike\'s deductible loss for Matthew and Lewis Partnership?','[\"$10,000\",\"$11,250\",\"$15,000\",\"$20,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 5, provides that a partner does not recognize loss on a partnership distribution unless all of the following requirements are met. First, the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership exceeds the distribution. Second, the partner\'s entire interest in the partnership is liquidated. Third, the distribution is in money, unrealized receivables, or inventory items. To simplify, a partner\'s distributive share of partnership loss is allowed only to the extent of the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. The adjusted basis is figured at the end of the partnership\'s tax year in which the loss occurred, before taking the loss into account. If the loss is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis, the excess amount is not deductible for that year.nnPublication 541, page 9, further states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. Any increase in a partner\'s individual liabilities because of an assumption of partnership liabilities is considered a contribution of money to the partnership by the partner.nnAs a result of the above rulings, Mike\'s adjusted basis in the partnership is $15,000, which is the invested $10,000 and assumed liabilities of $5,000. Since his portion of the partnership loss is $20,000 (25% of $80,000), he is limited to the lesser of the loss ($20,000) or adjusted basis ($15,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(708,13,'Jason owns a 55% capital interest in ABC Partnership. His brother owns 60% interest in XYZ Partnership. ABC sold a piece of property with an adjusted basis of $50,000 and a fair market value of $55,000 to XYZ for $45,000. What is ABC\'s recognized loss?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$5,500\",\"$10,000\"]',0,'Publication 541, page 8, addresses the special rules applying to a sale or exchange of property between a partnership and certain persons. In the case of a loss, the losses will not be allowed from a sale or exchange of property (other than some interest in the partnership) directly or indirectly between a partnership and a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.nnIf the sale or exchange is between two partnerships in which the same persons directly or indirectly own more than 50% of the capital or profits interests in each partnership, no deduction of a loss is allowed. The basis of each partner\'s interest, however, in the partnership is decreased (but not below zero) by the partner\'s share of the disallowed loss.nnIf the purchaser later sells the property, only the gain realized that is greater than the loss not allowed will be taxable. If any gain from the sale of the property is not recognized because of this rule, the basis of each partner\'s interest in the partnership is increased by the partner\'s share of that gain.nnPublication 541, page 8, further provides the rule to determine if a partner has more than 50% ownership. More specifically:nnan interest directly or indirectly owned by or for a corporation, partnership, estate, or trust is considered to be owned proportionately by or for its shareholders, partners, or beneficiaries.nan individual is considered to own the interest directly or indirectly owned by or for the individual\'s family. For this rule, “family” includes only brothers, sisters, half-brothers, half-sisters, spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants.nif a person is considered to own an interest using rule (1), that person (the “constructive owner”) is treated as if actually owning that interest when rules (1) and (2) are applied. However, if a person is considered to own an interest using rule (2), that person is not treated as actually owning that interest in reapplying rule (2) to make another person the constructive owner.nJason owns more than 50% in both the ABC partnership (55% directly) and the XYZ partnership (60% indirectly). Hence, the transfer of the property (adjusted basis of $50,000) from ABC to XYZ for $45,000 produces a $5,000 loss that ABC is not able to take or, in other words, recognize on the sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(709,13,'Jack and Ted formed an equal partnership. Jack contributed $10,000 cash and Ted contributed depreciable equipment that he has owned for 6 months with a fair market value of $10,000 and an adjusted basis of $2,000. Ted had taken $3,000 in depreciation on the equipment before he transferred it to the partnership. What amount should Ted report as a gain as a result of this transaction?','[\"$0\",\"$3,000\",\"$4,000\",\"$8,000\"]',0,'Publication 541, page 9, states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. If the partner must recognize gain as a result of the contribution, this gain is included in the basis of his or her interest. Any increase in a partner\'s individual liabilities because of an assumption of partnership liabilities is considered a contribution of money to the partnership by the partner.nnHowever, neither the partner nor the partnership usually recognizes a gain or loss when property is contributed to the partnership in exchange for a partnership interest. This applies whether a partnership is being formed or is already operating. The partnership\'s holding period for the property includes the partner\'s holding period. (Publication 541, page 8)nnTed\'s contribution of property with an FMV of $10,000 and an adjusted basis of $2,000 does not result in a gain from the transfer to the partnership. Assume the basis of $2,000 already included depreciation of $3,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(710,13,'Peter is a partner in the Waltz, Foxtrot, and Tango Partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the tax year was $30,000, which includes his $12,000 share of partnership liabilities. Peter sold his interest in the partnership for $20,000, and was relieved of his share of partnership liabilities. What is the gain or (loss) Peter must recognize?','[\"$0\",\"$32,000\",\"$(10,000)\",\"$2,000\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nnnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nKumar became a limited partner in ABC Partnership by contributing $10,000 in cash on the formation of the partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the current year is $20,000, which includes his $15,000 share of partnership liabilities. The partnership has no unrealized receivables or inventory items. Kumar sells his interest in the partnership for $10,000 in cash. He had been paid his share of the partnership income for the tax year.nnKumar realizes $25,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($10,000 cash payment + $15,000 liability relief). He reports $5,000 ($25,000 realized - $20,000 basis) as a capital gain.nn nIn this problem, Peter would recognize a gain of $2,000 from selling his partnership interest to the partnership. The gain is the difference between the selling price of $20,000 and his adjusted basis of $18,000, which is the difference between his original adjusted basis of $30,000 and the release of his portion of the partnership\'s liabilities of $12,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(711,13,'Partner A received inventory items with a basis of $20,000 in complete dissolution of a partnership. Within 5 years, Partner A sells the entire inventory for $30,000. What amount and type of gain should Partner A report?','[\"$0\",\"$10,000 short-term capital gain\",\"$10,000 long-term capital gain\",\"$10,000 ordinary gain\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 12, addresses the treatment of a partner\'s disposition of distributed unrealized receivables or inventory items. In general, any gain or loss on a sale or exchange of unrealized receivables or inventory items a partner received in a distribution is an ordinary gain or loss. For this purpose, inventory items do not include real or depreciable business property, even if they are not held more than 1 year.nn nn 	Example 1	 n 	 	 n 	nOscar, a distributee partner, received his share of accounts receivable when his law firm dissolved. The partnership used the cash method of accounting, so the receivables had a basis of zero. If Oscar later collects the receivables or sells them, the amount he receives will be ordinary income.nn n nnIf a distributee partner sells inventory items held for more than 5 years after the distribution, the type of gain or loss depends on how they are being used on the date sold. The gain or loss is capital gain or loss if the property is a capital asset in the partner\'s hands at the time sold.nn nn 	Example 2	 n 	 	 n 	nMarucia receives, through dissolution of her partnership, inventory that has a basis of $19,000. Within 5 years, she sells the inventory for $24,000. The $5,000 gain is taxed as ordinary income. If she had held the inventory for more than 5 years, her gain would have been capital gain, provided the inventory was a capital asset in her hands at the time of sale.nn n nnPartner A has a gain on the sale of the inventory of $10,000, which is the difference between the selling price of $30,000 and the basis of $20,000 for the inventory. Further, since Partner A sold the inventory items within 5 years, the $10,000 gain on the sale is treated as ordinary income (not a capital gain).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(712,13,'Bryan had a 50% interest in a partnership and he materially participates in the partnership business. Bryan\'s adjusted basis in the partnership was $40,000 at the beginning of 2024. There were no distributions to Bryan during the year. During 2024, the partnership borrowed $180,000 from a local bank for the following reasons:nn  Purchased business equipment               $120,000n  Paid off existing liabilities in full        60,000nAll of the partners are personally liable for all of the partnership debts. The partnership incurred a $300,000 loss in 2024. What amount of the loss can Bryan claim on his 2024 individual tax return?','[\"$150,000\",\"$100,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$0\"]',1,'Publication 541, pages 4 and 5, provides that a partner\'s distributive share of partnership loss is allowed only to the extent of the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. The adjusted basis is figured at the end of the partnership\'s tax year in which the loss occurred, before taking the loss into account. If the loss is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis, the excess amount is not deductible for that year.nnPublication 541, pages 9 and 10, further states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. Any increase in a partner\'s individual liabilities because of an assumption of partnership liabilities is considered a contribution of money to the partnership by the partner. Likewise, the decrease in the partnership\'s liabilities is a decrease in the partner\'s basis.nnAs a result of the above rules, Bryan\'s adjusted basis in the partnership before accounting for the partnership\'s loss is $100,000, which is his adjusted basis of $40,000 and assumed liabilities of $60,000 (50% of $180,000 − 50% of $60,000). Since his portion of the partnership loss is $150,000 (50% of $300,000), he is limited to the lesser of the loss ($150,000) or adjusted basis ($100,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(713,13,'Carol owns 50% of the capital interest in ABC Partnership and 50% of the profits interest in XYZ Partnership. In 2022 for $100,000, ABC Partnership sells land to XYZ Partnership, which XYZ Partnership will use in its trade or business. The ABC Partnership\'s adjusted basis in the land at the time of the sale was $120,000. In 2024, the XYZ Partnership sells the land to an unrelated third party for $160,000. How much gain will the XYZ Partnership recognize in 2024?','[\"$30,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$60,000\",\"$20,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 8, addresses the special rules applying to a sale or exchange of property between a partnership and certain persons. In the case of a loss, the losses will not be allowed from a sale or exchange of property (other than some interest in the partnership) directly or indirectly between a partnership and a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.nnIf the sale or exchange is between two partnerships in which the same persons directly or indirectly own more than 50% of the capital or profits interests in each partnership, no deduction of a loss is allowed. The basis of each partner\'s interest, however, in the partnership is decreased (but not below zero) by the partner\'s share of the disallowed loss.nnIf the purchaser later sells the property, only the gain realized that is greater than the loss not allowed will be taxable. If any gain from the sale of the property is not recognized because of this rule, the basis of each partner\'s interest in the partnership is increased by the partner\'s share of that gain.nnCarol owns 50% (not more than 50%) in both the ABC partnership and the XYZ partnership. Hence, the transfer of the property (adjusted basis of $120,000) from ABC to XYZ for $100,000 produces a $20,000 loss that ABC is able to take and recognize. Hence, the subsequent sale of the land by XYZ to an unrelated third party produces a $60,000 recognized gain, which is the difference between the sale price of $160,000 and the adjusted basis of $100,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(714,13,'A partnership, in which Jane is a 50% owner, had a profit of $80,000 before deducting any compensation to the partners as a guaranteed payment. The partnership agreement provides for a 50-50 sharing of income. Capital is a material income-producing factor. During the year, Jane performed services worth $20,000. What is the total income Jane should report from the partnership?','[\"$20,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$50,000\",\"$80,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 7, provides that for certain transactions between a partner and his or her partnership, the partner is treated as not being a member of the partnership. One such transaction is the performing of services for, or transferring property to, a partnership if (1) there is a related allocation and distribution to a partner and (2) the entire transaction, when viewed together, is properly characterized as occurring between the partnership and a partner not acting in the capacity of a partner.nnPublication 541, page 7, also notes that guaranteed payments are those made by a partnership to a partner that are determined without regard to the partnership\'s income. A partnership treats guaranteed payments for services, or for the use of capital, as if they were made to a person who is not a partner. This treatment is for purposes of determining gross income and deductible business expenses only.nnGuaranteed payments are included in income in the partner\'s tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nUnder the terms of a partnership agreement, Erica is entitled to a fixed annual payment of $10,000 without regard to the income of the partnership. Her distributive share of the partnership income is 10%. The partnership has $50,000 of ordinary income after deducting the guaranteed payment. She must include ordinary income of $15,000 ($10,000 guaranteed payment + $5,000 ($50,000 × 10%) distributive share) on her individual tax return for her tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nn n nnIn this problem, Jane is a 50% owner in the partnership where capital is a material income-producing factor. Jane, therefore, would claim income for the year of $50,000, which is the sum of $20,000 for performed services and $30,000 for her 50% share of the partnership\'s profits after the guaranteed payment ($80,000 − $20,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(715,13,'Upon the receipt of a distribution, a retiring partner or successor in interest of a deceased partner will recognize:','[\"gain only to the extent that any money distributed is less than the partner\'s adjusted basis in the partnership.\\n\",\"gain only to the extent that any money distributed is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis in the partnership.\",\"gain only to the extent that any money and property distributed is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis in the partnership.\",\"gain only to the extent that any money and inventory distributed is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis in the partnership.\"]',1,'The rules on a gain or loss on a distribution to a retiring partner are found on page 13 of Publication 541. Upon the receipt of the distribution, the retiring partner or successor in interest of a deceased partner will recognize gain only to the extent that any money (and marketable securities treated as money) distributed is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis in the partnership. The partner will recognize a loss only if the distribution is in money, unrealized receivables, and inventory items. No loss is recognized if any other property is received.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(716,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a husband and wife that jointly own and operate an unincorporated business that has shares in the profits and losses, are not under the community property laws of a state, and where only one spouse materially participates?','[\"The couple must file as a partnership.\",\"Each spouse must file a separate Schedule C or C-EZ.\",\"The couple has the option to file as either a partnership or sole proprietorship.\",\"The couple must file a single Schedule C for the business.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Publication 334, page 3, if a husband and wife jointly own and operate an unincorporated business and share in the profits and losses, the spouses are treated as partners in a partnership. This is true whether or not the couple has a formal partnership agreement. Hence, they cannot file a Schedule C for the business.nnThere are two exceptions to the above rule. First, in the case of a business owned and operated in a community property state, the couple has the option to treat the business as either a sole proprietorship or a partnership. The only states with community property laws are Arizona, California, Idaho, Louisiana, Nevada, New Mexico, Texas, Washington, and Wisconsin.nnSecond, if both spouses materially participate as the only members of a jointly owned and operated business, and they file a joint return for the tax year, they can make a joint election to be taxed as a qualified joint venture instead of a partnership. In this case, each spouse files a separate Schedule C and a separate Schedule SE.nnSince the business is not in a community property state nor are both spouses materially participating, neither exception to the partnership rule applies.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(717,13,'Jeff and his brother each own a 40% interest in J&K Partnership. Jeff also owns a 70% interest in Mega Partnership. In 2022, J&K sold a building to Mega Partnership for $100,000. J&K\'s adjusted basis of the building at the time of the sale was $110,000. In 2024, Mega sold the building for $115,000. How much gain or (loss) will Mega recognize in 2024?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$15,000\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 8, addresses the special rules applying to a sale or exchange of property between a partnership and certain persons. In the case of a loss, the losses will not be allowed from a sale or exchange of property (other than some interest in the partnership) directly or indirectly between a partnership and a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.nnIf the sale or exchange is between two partnerships in which the same persons directly or indirectly own more than 50% of the capital or profits interests in each partnership, no deduction of a loss is allowed. The basis of each partner\'s interest, however, in the partnership is decreased (but not below zero) by the partner\'s share of the disallowed loss.nnIf the purchaser later sells the property, only the gain realized that is greater than the loss not allowed will be taxable. If any gain from the sale of the property is not recognized because of this rule, the basis of each partner\'s interest in the partnership is increased by the partner\'s share of that gain.nnJeff owns more than 50% in both the J&K partnership and the Mega partnership. Hence, the transfer of the building (adjusted basis of $110,000) to Mega for $100,000 produces a $10,000 loss that Jeff is not able to take or, in other words, recognize. When Mega sells the building in a later year for $115,000, Mega recognizes a gain of $5,000, which is the difference between the selling price and the adjusted basis of the building when acquired by Mega ($110,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(718,13,'On January 1, 2024, Ben and Jerry each own 50% of the B&J Fudge partnership. B&J Fudge employs the cash method of accounting and receives $1,000 in interest income each month from an unrelated party loan receivable. On July 1, 2024, Jerry purchased 50% of Ben\'s partnership interest. There were no other changes in partnership interest for the remainder of the 2024 year. How much does Ben report as his ratable share of the interest income for 2024?','[\"$7,500\",\"$6,000\",\"$4,500\",\"$3,000\"]',2,'If a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. Unrealized receivables include any rights to payment not already included in income. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset. Hence, it does not result in a capital gain or loss.nnIn this case, Ben would report $4,500 as ordinary income, which is the sum of his pro rata share of the interest ($3,000, which is 50% of $6,000) from the first 6 months of the year and his pro rata share of the interest ($1,500, which is 25% of $6,000) from the final 6 months of the year.nnLikewise, Jerry would report $7,500 as ordinary income, which is the sum of his pro rata share of the interest ($3,000, which is 50% of $6,000) from the first 6 months of the year and his pro rata share of the interest ($4,500, which is 75% of $6,000) from the final 6 months of the year.nnNote: There are two tricks in this question. The first trick is that Jerry purchases 50% of Ben\'s 50% ownership, which results in Ben owning 25% and Jerry owning 75% for the second half of the year. The second trick is the question pertains to Ben and not Jerry.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(719,13,'The Logo Partnership sells computers and maintains its accounting system on the accrual basis. Logo sold and delivered a computer on December 27, 2024, and billed the customer $3,250 on January 7, 2025. Logo received the $3,250 payment on February 15, 2025. The check cleared on February 22, 2025. On which date will Logo recognize this income?','[\"December 27, 2024\",\"January 7, 2025\",\"February 15, 2025\",\"February 22, 2025\"]',0,'Publication 538, page 10, states that a taxpayer generally reports income in the year earned and deducts or capitalizes expenses in the year incurred under an accrual method of accounting. The purpose of an accrual method of accounting is to match income and expenses in the correct year.nnMore specifically, a taxpayer generally includes an amount as gross income for the tax year in which all events that fix the taxpayer\'s rights to receive the income have occurred and the taxpayer can determine the amount with reasonable accuracy. Under this rule, the taxpayer reports an amount in the taxpayer\'s gross income on the earliest of the following dates:nnWhen a taxpayer receives paymentnWhen the income amount is due to a taxpayernWhen a taxpayer earns the incomenWhen title has passednAs a result, Logo would recognize income from this problem\'s sale on December 27, 2024, which is the date the item was sold and delivered.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(720,13,'Joan\'s adjusted basis in the So-Lo Partnership is $15,000. She received a non-liquidating cash distribution of $2,500 and a piece of land with an adjusted basis of $7,500 and a fair market value of $5,000. What is the gain or loss to be recognized at the time of the distribution?','[\"$5,000 loss\",\"$2,500 loss\",\"$0\",\"$5,000 gain\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 5, provides, in part, that a partner generally recognizes gain on a partnership distribution only to the extent any money (and marketable securities treated as money) included in the distribution exceeds the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership.nnAny gain recognized is generally treated as capital gain from the sale of the partnership interest on the date of the distribution. If partnership property (other than marketable securities treated as money) is distributed to a partner, he or she generally does not recognize any gain/loss until the sale or other disposition of the property.nnAs a result, Joan would not recognize any gain from the receipt of the $2,500 in cash and the piece of land with an FMV of $5,000 (adjusted basis of $7,500) because the cash does not exceed her adjusted basis of $15,000 in the partnership and she has not sold the land yet.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(721,13,'Members of a family who must meet special requirements to be recognized as partners for determining a partner\'s distributive share include all of the following, except:','[\"spouses.\",\"ancestors.\",\"lineal descendants.\",\"brothers and sisters.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 3, states, in part, that for purposes of determining a partner\'s distributive share, an interest purchased by one family member from another family member is considered a gift from the seller. The fair market value of the purchased interest is considered donated capital.nnFor this purpose, members of a family include only spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants (or a trust for the primary benefit of those persons).nnIn this problem, the only group that does not meet the classification of being members of the family is the brothers and sisters.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(722,13,'All of the following are true statements describing guaranteed payments, except:','[\"payments made to a partner without regard to the partnership\'s income.\\n\",\"guaranteed payments are included in income in the partner\'s tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.\",\"premiums for health insurance paid by a partnership on behalf of a partner for services as a partner are treated as guaranteed payments.\",\"guaranteed payments to a partner cannot create a loss on the partnership return (Form 1065).\"]',3,'Pages 7 and 8 of Publication 541 address the issue of guaranteed payments. First, guaranteed payments are those made by a partnership to a partner that is determined without regard to the partnership\'s income. Second, the partnership generally deducts guaranteed payments on line 10 of Form 1065 as a business expense. Third, premiums for health insurance paid by a partnership on behalf of a partner for services as a partner are treated as guaranteed payments. Fourth, guaranteed payments are included in income in the partner\'s tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nnFinally, if guaranteed payments to a partner result in a partnership loss in which the partner shares, the partner must report the full amount of the guaranteed payments as ordinary income. Therefore, the partner separately takes into account his or her distributive share of the partnership loss, to the extent of the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. Hence, the statement that guaranteed payments to a partner cannot create a loss on the partnership return is not correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(723,13,'Jacob contributes property with a fair market value of $7,000, adjusted basis of $4,000, and a mortgage of $1,000, which the partnership assumes, to a partnership for a 40% interest in the partnership. What is Jacob\'s basis in his partnership interest?','[\"$4,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$6,000\",\"$3,400\"]',3,'Publication 541, pages 9 and 10, states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. If contributed property is subject to a debt or if a partner\'s liabilities are assumed by the partnership the basis of that partner\'s interest is reduced (but not below zero) by the liability assumed by the other partners. This partner must reduce his or her basis because the assumption of the liability is treated as a distribution of money to that partner. The other partners\' assumption of the liability is treated as a contribution by them of money to the partnership.nnExample: Ivan acquired a 20% interest in a partnership by contributing property that had an adjusted basis to him of $8,000 and a $4,000 mortgage. The partnership assumed payment of the mortgage. The basis of Ivan\'s interest is as follows:nn    Adjusted basis of contributed property   $8,000n    Minus: Part of mortgage assumed byn      other partners                          3,200 (.80 × $4,000)n    Basis of Ivan\'s partnership interest     $4,800nFurthermore, neither the partner nor the partnership usually recognizes a gain or loss when property is contributed to the partnership in exchange for a partnership interest. This applies whether a partnership is being formed or is already operating. The partnership\'s holding period for the property includes the partner\'s holding period.nnIn this problem, Jacob\'s contribution of property with an FMV of $7,000, an adjusted basis of $4,000, and a mortgage of $1,000 that is assumed by the partnership results in a basis for Jacob of $3,400. Jacob\'s basis is the adjusted basis of the transferred property ($4,000) less $600, which is his share of the transferred mortgage assumed by the partnership (60% of $1,000).nnNote: Another way to look at this calculation is the sum of Jacob\'s basis in the property ($4,000) less the transferred mortgage ($1,000) plus Jacob\'s share of the transferred mortgage ($400, which is 40% of $1,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(724,13,'Zeke is a partner in Butter and Egg Partnership. Zeke is to receive 40% of the partnership\'s income, but not less than $20,000. The partnership has a net income of $10,000 after deducting the $20,000 on the current-year return. How much can the partnership deduct for Zeke\'s guaranteed payment on Form 1065, U.S. Return of Partnership Income?','[\"$0\",\"$8,000\",\"$12,000\",\"$20,000\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 7, discusses the treatment of minimum payments. If a partner is to receive a minimum payment from the partnership, the guaranteed payment is the amount by which the minimum payment is more than the partner\'s distributive share of the partnership income before taking into account the guaranteed payment.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nUnder a partnership agreement, Divya is to receive 30% of the partnership income, but not less than $8,000. The partnership has net income of $20,000. Divya\'s share, without regard to the minimum guarantee, is $6,000 (30% of $20,000). The guaranteed payment that can be deducted by the partnership is $2,000 ($8,000 − $6,000). Divya\'s income from the partnership is $8,000, and the remaining $12,000 of partnership income will be reported by the other partners in proportion to their shares under the partnership agreement.nn n nnThe partnership is able to deduct $8,000 of the $20,000 as a guaranteed payment to Zeke. The $8,000 is difference between Zeke\'s minimum payment of $20,000 and his distributive share of the partnership income of $12,000 (40% of $30,000). The trick to this question is the wording of the problem; that is, the partnership’s income is $10,000 after the $20,000 minimum payment. Therefore, the partnership had $30,000 of income before the guaranteed payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(725,13,'Members of a family can be made members of a partnership by gift (or any other person) without restrictions if:','[\"the partnership agreement states that they have a right to share in earnings and profits of the partnership.\",\"capital is not a material income-producing factor.\",\"capital is a material income-producing factor.\",\"the partnership agreement designates who the partners are, what degree of service they will perform for the partnership, and the extent to which they share in the profits, losses, and other attributes of the partnership.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 541, page 3, if a family member (or any other person) receives a gift of a capital interest in a partnership in which capital is a material income-producing factor, the donee’s distributive share of partnership income is subject to both of the following restrictions:nnIt must be figured by reducing the partnership income by reasonable compensation for services the donor renders to the partnership, ornThe donee’s distributive share of partnership income attributable to donated capital must not be proportionately greater than the donor’s distributive share attributable to the donor’s capital.nFor the purpose of determining a partner’s distributive share, an interest purchased by one family member from another family member is considered a gift from the seller. The fair market value of the purchased interest is considered donated capital. For this purpose, members of a family include only spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants (or a trust for the primary benefit of those persons).nnIn this case, the second requirement is given as a response because if capital is not a material income-producing factor, these restrictions do not apply.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(726,13,'Don and Warren formed an equal partnership to build drag racing vehicles. Don contributed $5,000 in cash and Warren contributed a truck with a fair market value of $5,000 and an adjusted tax basis of $4,500. They plan to use the truck for hauling parts and cars. When Warren purchased the truck 1 year earlier, he elected to use the straight-line method to depreciate the truck using the mid-year convention over its 5-year recovery period. The partnership should:','[\"record the truck on the books at $5,000 and depreciate it using the allowable method and convention over a 5-year recovery period.\",\"record the truck on the books at $5,000 and depreciate it over its remaining recovery period using the straight-line method and mid-year convention.\",\"record the truck on the books at $4,500 and depreciate it over its remaining recovery period using the straight-line method and mid-year convention.\",\"record the truck on the books at $4,500 and depreciate it using the allowable method and convention over a 5-year recovery period.\"]',2,'Publication 946, page 11, provides that a contribution of property to a partnership in exchange for a partnership interest is a nontaxable transfer. In such cases, the partnership must continue to use the same depreciation method as the transferor and figure depreciation as if the transfer had not occurred.nnAs a result, the partnership would record the truck on the books at $4,500 and depreciate in the same manner as it was being depreciated by Warren before it was contributed to the partnership.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(727,13,'Henry is a partner in XYZ Partnership. Henry\'s adjusted basis of his partnership interest is $20,000, which includes his $5,000 share of partnership liabilities. Henry sells his interest in the partnership for $15,000. What is Henry\'s gain or (loss) on the sale?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$(5,000)\",\"$10,000\"]',0,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nKumar became a limited partner in ABC Partnership by contributing $10,000 in cash on the formation of the partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the current year is $20,000, which includes his $15,000 share of partnership liabilities. The partnership has no unrealized receivables or inventory items. Kumar sells his interest in the partnership for $10,000 in cash. He had been paid his share of the partnership income for the tax year.nnKumar realizes $25,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($10,000 cash payment + $15,000 liability relief). He reports $5,000 ($25,000 realized - $20,000 basis) as a capital gain.nn n nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nnIn this problem, Henry realizes $20,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($15,000 cash payment + $5,000 liability relief). Henry has no gain or loss since his adjusted basis of $20,000 equals the amount realized from the sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(728,13,'On January 1, 2023, Brian contributed $20,000 cash to Lock and Key Partnership for a 25% interest. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of 2024 was $35,000, which included his $16,000 share of partnership liabilities and the contributed cash. The partnership had no other liabilities and no unrealized receivables or substantially appreciated inventory items. On December 31, 2024, Brian sold his entire interest in Lock and Key Partnership for $19,000 cash. Brian did not take any distributions in 2024. What is the amount of Brian\'s capital gain or (loss)?','[\"$0\",\"$(1,000)\",\"$16,000\",\"$19,000\"]',0,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nn nnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nKumar became a limited partner in ABC Partnership by contributing $10,000 in cash on the formation of the partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the current year is $20,000, which includes his $15,000 share of partnership liabilities. The partnership has no unrealized receivables or inventory items. Kumar sells his interest in the partnership for $10,000 in cash. He had been paid his share of the partnership income for the tax year.nnKumar realizes $25,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($10,000 cash payment + $15,000 liability relief). He reports $5,000 ($25,000 realized − $20,000 basis) as a capital gain.nn n nnIn this problem, Brian realizes $35,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($19,000 cash payment + $16,000 liability relief). Brian has no gain or loss since his adjusted basis of $35,000 equals the amount realized from the sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(729,13,'Which of the following situations terminates a partnership?','[\"At least 25% of the total interest in the partnership capital and profits is sold or exchanged within a 12-month period, excluding a sale or exchange to another partner.\",\"Less than 50% of the total interest in the partnership capital and profits is sold or exchanged within a 12-month period, including a sale or exchange to another partner.\",\"At least 50% of the total interest in the partnership capital and profits is sold or exchanged within a 12-month period, including a sale or exchange to another partner.\",\"At least 25% of the total interest in the partnership capital and profits is sold or exchanged within a 12-month period, including a sale or exchange to another partner.\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 4, and the instructions for Form 1065, page 4, provide, as well as point out to see Section 1.708-1 of the regulations, that a partnership terminates when one of the following events takes place:nnall its operations are discontinued and no part of any business, financial operation, or venture is continued by any of its partners in a partnership, ornat least 50% of the total interest in partnership capital and profits is sold or exchanged within a 12-month period, including a sale or exchange to another partner.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(730,13,'The adjusted basis in Carol\'s partnership interest is $50,000. She receives a distribution of $10,000 cash and land that has an adjusted basis of $30,000 and an FMV of $50,000. What is Carol\'s adjusted basis in the land?','[\"$20,000\",\"$30,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$50,000\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 6, states that unless there is a complete liquidation of a partner\'s interest, the basis of property (other than money) distributed to the partner by a partnership is its adjusted basis to the partnership immediately before the distribution. However, the basis of the property to the partner cannot be more than the adjusted basis of his or her interest in the partnership reduced by any money received in the same transaction.nn nn 	Example 1	 n 	 	 n 	nThe adjusted basis of Emily\'s partnership interest is $30,000. She receives a distribution of property that has an adjusted basis of $20,000 to the partnership and $4,000 in cash. Her basis for the property is $20,000.nn n nn nn 	Example 2	 n 	 	 n 	nThe adjusted basis of Steve\'s partnership interest is $10,000. He receives a distribution of $4,000 cash and property that has an adjusted basis to the partnership of $8,000. His basis for the distributed property is limited to $6,000 ($10,000 − $4,000, the cash he receives).nn n nnCarol\'s basis in the land would be $30,000, which is the partnership\'s adjusted basis in the property. This is not a complete liquidation, and Carol\'s partnership interest after reducing it for the cash distribution is $40,000 ($50,000 − $10,000), which is greater than the adjusted basis of the land.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(731,13,'If a partner receives money or property inventory in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his/her share of the partnership\'s inventory items results in:','[\"capital gain or loss.\",\"ordinary income or loss.\",\"ordinary income or capital loss.\",\"capital gain or ordinary loss.\"]',1,'If a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset. Hence, it does not result in a capital gain or loss.nnThis treatment applies to the unrealized receivables part of a payment to a retiring partner or successor in interest of a deceased partner only if that part is not treated as paid in exchange for partnership property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(732,13,'Ed and Bob form a partnership with contributions of $30,000 each. Bob is not a general partner. Under the partnership agreement, Ed and Bob share all partnership profits and losses equally. The partnership borrows $70,000 to purchase depreciable equipment to be used in the partnership\'s business. Ed was required under the partnership agreement to pay the creditor if the partnership defaulted. Based upon these facts, what are Ed and Bob\'s basis in the partnership?','[\"Ed, $30,000; Bob, $30,000\",\"Ed, $65,000; Bob, $65,000\",\"Ed, $100,000; Bob, $30,000\",\"Ed, $100,000; Bob, $100,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, pages 9 and 10, states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. In addition, a partner’s interest increases by any additional contributions to the partnership, including an increased share of, or assumption of, partnership liabilities; the partner’s distributive share of taxable and nontaxable partnership income; and the partner’s distributive share of the excess of the deductions for depletion over the basis of the depletable property.nnA partnership liability is a recourse liability to the extent that any partner or a related person has an economic risk of loss for that liability. Conversely, a partnership liability is a nonrecourse liability if no partner or related person has an economic risk for that liability.nnIn addition, a partner\'s share of nonrecourse liabilities is generally proportionate to his or her share of partnership profits. However, this rule may not apply if the partnership has taken deductions attributable to nonrecourse liabilities or the partnership holds property that was contributed by a partner.nnAs a result of the above information, Ed\'s adjusted basis in the partnership is $100,000, which is his investment of $30,000 and assumed liabilities of $70,000, and Bob\'s adjusted basis in the partnership is $30,000, which is his investment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(733,13,'Simon and Maggie Partnership, a calendar-year partnership, with two partners, filed its 2023 Form 1065 tax return on December 31, 2024. An extension of time to file was not filed. What is the amount of their penalty for failing to file?','[\"$0\",\"$5,600\",\"$4,400\",\"$4,700\"]',3,'The instructions for Form 1065 (pages 5 and 6) provide, in part, that a penalty is assessed against any partnership that must file a partnership return and fails to file on time, including extensions, or fails to file a return with all the information required.nnIn 2024, the penalty is $235 for each month (or part of a month) the return is late or incomplete, up to 12 months times the total number of partners in the partnership during any part of the tax year.nnThe penalty will not be imposed if the partnership can show reasonable cause for its failure to file a complete or timely return. Do not attach an explanation when filing the return. Rather, wait until the partnership receives a notice about a penalty after it files the return. The partnership may send the IRS an explanation and the Service will determine if the explanation meets reasonable-cause criteria.nnIn this case, Simon and Maggie are subject to the fine for failing to timely file their partnership return. The penalty is $4,700, which is $235 × 2 (number of partners) × 10 (number of months late, up to a maximum of 12 months).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(734,13,'John is a partner in the Milo partnership. During the tax year, John personally assumed $10,000 of the partnership\'s liabilities. How is the assumption of partnership debt by John treated?','[\"As a distribution of money to John by the partnership and a decrease in John\'s basis in the partnership\",\"As a distribution of money to John by the partnership and an increase in John\'s basis in the partnership\",\"As a decrease in John\'s basis in the partnership\",\"As an increase in John\'s basis in the partnership\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 9, states, in part, a partner\'s basis is increased by the partner\'s additional contributions to the partnership, including an increased share of, or assumption of, partnership liabilities.nnTherefore, the correct response in this problem is that John\'s partnership basis will increase by his assumption of partnership debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(735,13,'In a sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership, which of the following partnership assets is treated as unrealized receivables?','[\"Franchises\",\"Trademarks\",\"Mining property for which exploration expenses were deducted\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 12, states, in part, that if a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, unrealized receivables include potential gain that would be ordinary income if the following partnership property were sold at its fair market value on the date of the payment:nnmining property for which exploration expenses were deducted,nstock in a Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC),ncertain farmland for which expenses for soil and water conservation or land clearing were deducted,nfranchises, trademarks, or trade names,noil, gas, or geothermal property, for which tangible drilling and development costs were deducted,nstock of certain controlled foreign corporations,nmarket discount bonds and short-term obligations, andnproperty subject to recapture of depreciation under IRC Sections 1245 and 1250.nAs highlighted above, all three items are listed in this problem and as such are treated as unrealized receivables. (For a complete list of the items falling under this category, see page 12 of Publication 541.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(736,13,'A loss incurred from the abandonment of a partnership interest is an ordinary loss when:','[\"the partner receives a de minimis or deemed distribution.\",\"the partner\'s capital account reflects a positive balance.\",\"the partner transfers the entire interest to a non-related party.\",\"the transaction is not a sale or exchange and the partner has not received an actual or deemed distribution from the partnership.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that a loss incurred from the abandonment or worthlessness of a partnership interest is an ordinary loss only if both of the following tests are met:nnthe transaction is not a sale or exchange, andnthe partner has not received an actual or deemed distribution from the partnership.nIf, however, the partner receives even a de minimis actual or deemed distribution, the entire loss generally is a capital loss. Information for reporting an abandonment loss can be found in the instructions for Form 4797.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(737,13,'Jasmine, a calendar year taxpayer, is a partner in Jasmine and Prince Partnership that has a fiscal year ending March 31. Starting April 1, 2024, Jasmine receives a fixed monthly guaranteed payment of $1,000 a month without regard to the income of the partnership. How much of the guaranteed payment will Jasmine report on her 2024 tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$8,000\",\"$9,000\",\"$12,000\"]',0,'Publication 541, pages 7 and 8, provides that guaranteed payments are included in income in the partner\'s tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nn nn 	Example 1	 n 	 	 n 	nUnder the terms of a partnership agreement, Erica is entitled to a fixed annual payment of $10,000 without regard to the income of the partnership. Her distributive share of the partnership income is 10%. The partnership has $50,000 of ordinary income after deducting the guaranteed payment. She must include ordinary income of $15,000 ($10,000 guaranteed payment + $5,000 (10% of $50,000) distributive share) on her individual income tax return for her tax year in which the partnership\'s tax year ends.nn n nn nn 	Example 2	 n 	 	 n 	nLamont is a calendar year taxpayer who is a partner in a partnership. The partnership uses a fiscal year that ended January 31, 2024. Lamont received guaranteed payments from the partnership from February 1, 2023, until December 31, 2023. He must include these guaranteed payments in income for 2024 and report them on his 2024 income tax return.nn n nnIn this case, Jasmine must report $0 of guaranteed payments on her 2024 tax return because the partnership\'s tax year ends in 2025, which is equal to the $1,000 per month payment times 12 months (April 2024 to March 2025).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(738,13,'Mary and Jonah formed the Quaking Aspen Partnership. Mary contributed $25,000 in cash and Jonah contributed property with an adjusted basis of $40,000 and with a fair market value of $25,000. Quaking Aspen sells the contributed property to an unrelated party more than 2 years after start-up for $27,000. How much gain (or loss) should the partnership recognize on this sale of the contributed property?','[\"$0\",\"$2,000 gain\",\"$15,000 loss\",\"$13,000 loss\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 8, provides that usually neither the partner nor the partnership recognizes a gain or loss when property is contributed to the partnership in exchange for a partnership interest. This applies whether a partnership is being formed or is already operating. The partnership\'s holding period for the property includes the partner\'s holding period.nnIn this case, the contribution and sale appear to be more than 2 years apart and, as such, there is no disguised sale with Jonah\'s initial contribution and an actual sale has occurred that results in a loss of $13,000 (sale price of $27,000 less adjusted basis of $40,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(739,13,'Paul is a partner in the Cortney, Delta, and Gamma Partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the year 2024 was $42,000, which includes his $15,000 share of partnership liabilities. Paul sold his interest in the partnership for $30,000 and was relieved of his share of partnership liabilities. What is the gain or (loss) Paul must recognize?','[\"$0\",\"$45,000\",\"$(12,000)\",\"$3,000\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nn nnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nKumar became a limited partner in ABC Partnership by contributing $10,000 in cash on the formation of the partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the current year is $20,000, which includes his $15,000 share of partnership liabilities. The partnership has no unrealized receivables or inventory items. Kumar sells his interest in the partnership for $10,000 in cash. He had been paid his share of the partnership income for the tax year.nnKumar realizes $25,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($10,000 cash payment + $15,000 liability relief). He reports $5,000 ($25,000 realized − $20,000 basis) as a capital gain.nn n nnIn this problem, Paul would recognize a gain of $3,000 from selling his partnership interest to the partnership. The amount received would be the sum of cash received and the amount of liability of which he was relieved: $30,000 + $15,000, for a total of $45,000. His realized gain would be $3,000, which is the difference between amount received, $45,000, and his adjusted basis of $42,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(740,13,'Generally, no gain or loss is recognized by the partnership or a partner when the partner contributes property to the partnership, unless:','[\"the partnership is being formed.\",\"a gain is realized on the transfer of property to a partnership that would be treated as an investment company if the partnership were incorporated.\",\"the partnership is already operating.\",\"unencumbered depreciable property is contributed.\"]',1,'Usually, neither the partner nor the partnership recognizes a gain or loss when property is contributed to the partnership in exchange for a partnership interest. This applies whether a partnership is being formed or is already operating. The partnership\'s holding period for the property includes the partner\'s holding period.nnThere are exceptions to the general rule. Specifically, gain is recognized when property is contributed (in exchange for an interest in the partnership) to a partnership that would be treated as an investment company if it were incorporated. Another exception, which is not relevant to this problem, would be a disguised sale.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(741,13,'Alberta Partnership sold a capital asset to Firsts Partnership at a loss of $70,000. Alberta had held the property for 5 months. Alberta is owned 30% by Dorothy, 30% by Fred, and 40% by Dale, Dorothy\'s brother. Firsts Partnership is owned 80% by ABC Corporation. Dorothy owns 25% of the stock of ABC Corporation and Dale\'s daughter, Deb, owns 60% of the stock of ABC Corporation. How much of the loss should Alberta allow for tax purposes on their tax return for the year of the sale?','[\"$70,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$0\",\"$35,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 8, addresses the special rules applying to a sale or exchange of property between a partnership and certain persons. In the case of a loss, the losses will not be allowed from a sale or exchange of property (other than some interest in the partnership) directly or indirectly between a partnership and a person whose direct or indirect interest in the capital or profits of the partnership is more than 50%.nnIf the sale or exchange is between two partnerships in which the same persons directly or indirectly own more than 50% of the capital or profits interests in each partnership, no deduction of a loss is allowed. The basis of each partner\'s interest, however, in the partnership is decreased (but not below zero) by the partner\'s share of the disallowed loss.nnIf the purchaser later sells the property, only the gain realized that is greater than the loss not allowed will be taxable. If any gain from the sale of the property is not recognized because of this rule, the basis of each partner\'s interest in the partnership is increased by the partner\'s share of that gain.nnPublication 541, page 8, further provides the rule to determine if a partner has more than 50% ownership. More specifically:nnAn interest directly or indirectly owned by or for a corporation, partnership, estate, or trust is considered to be owned proportionately by or for its shareholders, partners, or beneficiaries.nAn individual is considered to own the interest directly or indirectly owned by or for the individual\'s family. For this rule, “family” includes only brothers, sisters, half-brothers, half-sisters, spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants.nIf a person is considered to own an interest using rule (1), that person (the “constructive owner”) is treated as if actually owning that interest when rules (1) and (2) are applied. However, if a person is considered to own an interest using rule (2), that person is not treated as actually owning that interest in reapplying rule (2) to make another person the constructive owner.nDale is the focus because he is the owner with the greatest percentage of ownership of the Alberta Partnership at 40% before attribution is considered. Thus, when Alberta does their sale with Firsts Partnership, it is Dale that should be first analyzed because once the over 50% attribution is established, the question is answered and the loss disallowed. That is, Dale owns 70% of Alberta Partnership (40% Dale and 30% Dorothy, Dale’s sister). Dale owns by attribution 68% (which is 85% of 80%) of Firsts Partnership (ABC Corporation owns 80% of Firsts Partnership, therefore Dale owns 85% of ABC Corporation (25% Dorothy, Dale’s sister and 60% of Deb, Dale\'s daughter)).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(742,13,'In 2024, Linda sold her partnership interest for $25,000. Her adjusted basis at the time of the sale is $22,500, which includes her $12,500 share of partnership liabilities. When she initially invested in the partnership, she contributed $10,000 worth of equipment. There was no profit or loss at the partnership level at the time she sold her interest. The partnership had no unrealized receivables or substantially appreciated inventory items. What is the amount and nature of her gain or loss from the sale of her partnership interest in 2024?','[\"$7,500 ordinary loss\",\"$10,000 capital gain\",\"$12,500 ordinary gain\",\"$15,000 capital gain\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner also must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nnThe income or loss realized by a partner upon the sale or exchange of its interest in unrealized receivables and inventory items is the amount that would have been allocated to the partner if the partnership had sold all of its property for cash at fair market value, in a fully taxable transaction, immediately prior to the partner\'s transfer of interest in the partnership. (Publication 541, page 12)nnIn this case, Linda receives $37,500 from the sale; she receives cash of $25,000 and liability forgiveness of $12,500. Therefore, she has a gain of $15,000 ($37,500 − $22,500) from the sale of her interest in the partnership. The treatment of the gain is capital because the partnership had no receivables or inventory, which would be ordinary.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(743,13,'The due date, without regard to extensions, of a domestic partnership filing a Form 1065, U.S. Return of Partnership Income, is the 15th day of which month following the end of the tax year?','[\"3rd\",\"4th\",\"6th\",\"9th\"]',0,'The instructions for Form 1065, page 6, provide that a domestic partnership must file Form 1065 by the 15th day of the 3rd month following the date its tax year ended as shown at the top of Form 1065, which is generally March 15 following the close of the partnership\'s tax year if its accounting period is the calendar year.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nIf the due date for filing a return falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, then the taxpayer must file by the next day that is not a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday.nn n nnBe advised that certain partnerships with more than 100 partners are required to file Form 1065, Schedules K-1, and related forms and schedules electronically (Form 1065 Instructions, page 5).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(744,13,'Clyde is a limited partner in Marathon Marchers Partnership. He contributed $40,000 in cash on the formation of the partnership. His current adjusted basis in the partnership is $50,000, which includes his share of partnership liabilities of $10,000. Clyde\'s share of unrealized receivables in the partnership is $12,000. Clyde sold his partnership interest for $85,000 cash. What is the amount and character of Clyde\'s gain?','[\"Capital gain $0; Ordinary gain $35,900\",\"Capital gain $45,000; Ordinary gain $0\",\"Capital gain $33,000; Ordinary gain $12,000\",\"Capital gain $23,000; Ordinary gain $12,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nKumar became a limited partner in ABC Partnership by contributing $10,000 in cash on the formation of the partnership. The adjusted basis of his partnership interest at the end of the current year is $20,000, which includes his $15,000 share of partnership liabilities. The partnership has no unrealized receivables or inventory items. Kumar sells his interest in the partnership for $10,000 in cash. He had been paid his share of the partnership income for the tax year.nnKumar realizes $25,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($10,000 cash payment + $15,000 liability relief). He reports $5,000 ($25,000 realized − $20,000 basis) as a capital gain.nn n nnIn this problem, Clyde realizes $95,000 from the sale of his partnership interest ($85,000 cash payment + $10,000 liability relief). Thus, Clyde has a gain from the sale of $45,000 ($95,000 − $50,000). Clyde therefore reports $12,000 as ordinary income (his share of unrealized receivables) and $33,000 ($95,000 − $12,000 − $50,000 (adjusted basis)) as capital gains.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(745,13,'Jane and Bill are equal partners in J & B Partnership. The partnership incurred a $10,000 loss last year. Jane and Bill\'s adjusted basis in the partnership at the beginning of last year was $2,000 each. Under the partnership agreement, Jane and Bill share all partnership profits and losses equally. The partnership borrowed $20,000 last year to purchase depreciable equipment to be used in the partnership\'s business. Jane was required under the partnership agreement to pay the creditor if the partnership defaulted. Based upon these facts, what are Jane and Bill\'s allowable losses on last year\'s tax return?','[\"Jane $2,000; Bill $2,000\",\"Jane $5,000; Bill $2,000\",\"Jane $5,000; Bill $5,000\",\"Jane $10,000; Bill $0\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 5, provides that a partner does not recognize loss on a partnership distribution unless all of the following requirements are met. First, the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership exceeds the distribution. Second, the partner\'s entire interest in the partnership is liquidated. Third, the distribution is in money, unrealized receivables, or inventory items.nnTo simplify, a partner\'s distributive share of partnership loss is allowed only to the extent of the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. The adjusted basis is figured at the end of the partnership\'s tax year in which the loss occurred, before taking the loss into account. If the loss is more than the partner\'s adjusted basis, the excess amount is not deductible for that year; the excess loss is suspended until the partner\'s basis becomes positive again and able to absorb the suspended loss.nnPublication 541, page 9, further states, in part, that the basis of a partnership interest is the money plus the adjusted basis of any property the partner contributed. Any increase in a partner\'s individual liabilities because of an assumption of partnership liabilities is considered a contribution of money to the partnership by the partner.nnAs a result of the above, Jane has an allowable loss for the year of $5,000, which is the lesser of her portion of the partnership\'s loss for the year of $5,000 or her adjusted basis of $22,000 ($2,000 beginning basis plus $20,000 assumed liabilities). Bill, on the other hand, has an allowable loss for the year of $2,000, which is the lesser of his portion of the loss of $5,000 or his adjusted basis of $2,000 ($2,000 beginning basis).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(746,13,'Under terms of the partnership agreement, Joyce is entitled to a fixed annual payment of $20,000 and her partner $30,000 without regard to the income of the partnership. Joyce\'s distributive share of the partnership income is 10%. The partnership income is $60,000 of ordinary income after deducting the guaranteed payments. How much ordinary income from the partnership will be included on Joyce\'s individual income tax return?','[\"$6,000\",\"$24,000\",\"$26,000\",\"$29,000\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 7, states that guaranteed payments are treated as a partner\'s distributive share of ordinary income. The individual partner reports guaranteed payments on Schedule E (page 2) (Form 1040) as ordinary income, along with his or her distributive share of the partnership\'s other ordinary income.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nUnder the terms of a partnership agreement, Erica is entitled to a fixed annual payment of $10,000 without regard to the income of the partnership. Her distributive share of the partnership income is 10%. The partnership has $50,000 of ordinary income after deducting the guaranteed payment. She must include ordinary income of $15,000 ($10,000 guaranteed payment + $5,000 ($50,000 × 10%) distributive share) on her individual income tax return for her tax year in which the partnership’s tax year ends.nn n nnJoyce in this problem would report $26,000 on her income tax return, which is the sum of $20,000 as a fixed annual payment (i.e., a guaranteed payment) and $6,000 as her 10% share of the profits from the partnership ($60,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(747,13,'Abraham becomes an equal partner in the Kit, Kat, and Kidd Partnership in 2024. In 2023, he filed his personal tax return on the calendar tax year basis. The partnership reports income and expenses on the fiscal tax year basis. How should Abraham report partnership income or loss distributed to him?','[\"Abraham may choose a fiscal year to report income and expenses.\",\"Abraham must report income and expenses on the calendar year basis.\",\"Abraham may choose either a calendar tax year or fiscal tax year to report income and expenses.\",\"Abraham may choose a fiscal tax year and later obtain IRS approval if he wishes to change to a calendar tax year for reporting income and expenses.\"]',1,'Publication 538, page 4, states that generally individuals must adopt the calendar year. An individual can adopt a fiscal year provided that the individual maintains his or her books and records on the basis of the adopted fiscal year.nnIf a taxpayer files his or her first tax return using the calendar tax year and later begins business as a sole proprietor, becomes a partner in a partnership, or becomes a shareholder in an S corporation, the taxpayer must continue to use the calendar year unless the taxpayer obtains approval from the IRS to change it or is otherwise allowed to change it without IRS approval (Publication 538, pages 2 and 3).nnAs a result, Abraham must report income and expenses on the calendar year basis for the current tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(748,13,'The L&J Auto Parts Store operated as an accrual-based partnership and filed a Form 1065 for 2024. In addition to receipts from parts sales of $250,000, they had the following other items of income and expenses for 2024:nn  Salaries                           $(50,000)n  Insurance                            (5,000)n  Charitable Contributions             (5,000)n  Licenses                             (5,000)n  Rental Income                        25,000n  Guaranteed Payments to Partners     (75,000)nWhat is the correct ordinary income or loss that L&J should report on line 22 of their 2024 Form 1065?','[\"$85,000\",\"$115,000\",\"$100,000\",\"$150,000\"]',1,'A partnership computes its income and files its return in the same manner as an individual. The ordinary business income for a partnership as given on Form 1065 is computed as:nngross receipts or sales less cost of goods sold plus other partnership income, lessnsalaries and wages,nguaranteed payments to partners,nrepairs and maintenance,nbad debts,nrent,ntaxes and licenses,ninterest,ndepreciation,nretirement plans,nemployee benefit programs, andnother deductions.nIn addition, certain other items are separately stated on the partnership return and included as separate items on each partner\'s return (Schedule K-1, Part III (Form 1065)). They include but are not limited to the following:nnOrdinary income or loss from trade or business activitiesnNet income or loss from rental real estate activitiesnNet income or loss from other rental activitiesnGuaranteed payments to partnersnInterest incomenGains and losses from sales or exchanges of capital assetsnGains and losses from sales or exchanges of property described in Section 1231 of the IRCnCharitable contributionsnOrdinary and qualified dividendsnDividends passed through to corporate partners that are eligible for the dividends-received deduction (IRC Section 243 generally) by the attachment of a statement per page 8 of the Schedule K-1 (Form 1065) InstructionsnTaxes paid or accrued to foreign countries and U.S. possessionsnOther items of income, gain, loss, deduction, or credit, as provided by regulationsnIn this problem, the L&J income for the year is $115,000, which is the difference between the sales of $250,000 and the expenses of $135,000. The partnership expenses are the sum of the salaries ($50,000), insurance ($5,000), licenses ($5,000), and guaranteed payments to the partners ($75,000). The charitable contributions and rental income would be separately reported to the partner.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(749,13,'Jane received a gift from her mother of a capital interest in a family partnership in which capital is a material income-producing factor. Which of the following statements is correct about the donee\'s distributive share of partnership income?nn1. It must be figured by reducing the partnership income by reasonable compensation for services the donor renders to the partnership.n2. The donee\'s distributive share of partnership income attributable to donated capital must not be proportionately greater than the donor\'s distributive share attributable to the donor\'s capital.','[\"Item 1 alone is correct.\",\"Item 2 alone is correct.\",\"Items 1 and 2 together are correct.\",\"There are\\u00a0no\\u00a0limits on the amount that can be allocated to Jane as a distributive share of income from the partnership.\"]',2,'If a family member (or any other person) receives a gift of a capital interest in a partnership in which capital is a material income-producing factor, the donee\'s distributive share of partnership income is subject to both of the following restrictions:nnit must be figured by reducing the partnership income by reasonable compensation for services the donor renders to the partnership, andnthe donee\'s distributive share of partnership income attributable to donated capital must not be proportionately greater than the donor\'s distributive share attributable to the donor\'s capital.nHence, both statements taken together are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(750,13,'An individual is considered as owning the partnership interest that is directly or indirectly owned by, or for, his or her family. Which of the following is considered to be family?','[\"Brothers and sisters\",\"Half-brothers and half-sisters\",\"Ancestors and lineal descendants\",\"All of the answer choices are considered family.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 8, states, in part, that the following rules apply to determine if there is more than 50% ownership in partnership capital or profits:nnAn interest directly or indirectly owned by, or for, a corporation, partnership, estate, or trust is considered to be owned proportionately by, or for, its shareholders, partners, or beneficiaries.nAn individual is considered to own the interest directly or indirectly owned by, or for, the individual\'s family. For this rule, “family” includes only brothers, sisters, half-brothers, half-sisters, spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants.nThus, all of the answer choices are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(751,13,'Michael has a partnership interest with a zero basis. The partnership has inventory valued at $350,000. Michael\'s share of the ordinary income to be received from the sale of the inventory would be $40,000. In 2024, Michael sells his partnership interest for $55,000. Michael will report the following gain in 2024:','[\"$55,000 capital gain\",\"$40,000 ordinary gain and $15,000 capital gain\",\"$15,000 ordinary gain and $40,000 capital gain\",\"No gain or loss\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset.nnThe income or loss realized by a partner upon the sale or exchange of its interest in unrealized receivables and inventory items is the amount that would have been allocated to the partner if the partnership had sold all of its property for cash at fair market value, in a fully taxable transaction, immediately prior to the partner\'s transfer of interest in the partnership. (Publication 541, page 12)nnIn this case, Michael has a gain of $55,000 ($55,000 − $0) from the sale of his interest in the partnership. The treatment of the gain, however, is $40,000 ordinary income, which is attributable to the inventory, and $15,000 capital gain, which is attributable to the capital investment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(752,13,'Under a partnership agreement, Fred is to receive 30% of the partnership income, but not less than $8,000. The partnership has net income of $20,000 for the current tax year. What is the amount of guaranteed payment that can be deducted by the partnership for the current tax year?','[\"$8,000\",\"$6,000\",\"$2,000\",\"$0\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 7, discusses the treatment of minimum payments. If a partner is to receive a minimum payment from the partnership, the guaranteed payment is the amount by which the minimum payment is more than the partner\'s distributive share of the partnership income before taking into account the guaranteed payment.nnUnder the partnership agreement, Fred is to receive 30% of the partnership income, but not less than $8,000. The partnership has net income of $20,000. Fred\'s share, without regard to the minimum payment, is $6,000 (0.30 × $20,000). The guaranteed payment that can be deducted by the partnership is $2,000 ($8,000 − $6,000). Fred\'s income from the partnership is $8,000, and the remaining $12,000 of partnership income will be reported by the other partners in proportion to their shares under the partnership agreement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(753,13,'A partner\'s basis in a partnership is decreased by all of the following, except:','[\"assumption of partnership liabilities.\",\"partner\'s distributive share of the partnership\'s losses.\",\"partner\'s distributive share of nondeductible partnership expenses that are not capital expenditures.\",\"property distributed to a partner.\"]',0,'Publication 541, pages 9 and 10, states, in part, a partner\'s basis is increased by the partner\'s additional contributions to the partnership, including an increased share of, or assumption of, partnership liabilities.nnSimilarly, a partner\'s basis is decreased (but never below zero) by events such as:nnpartner\'s distributive share of the partnership\'s losses,npartner\'s distributive share of nondeductible partnership expenses that are not capital expenditures,nmoney and adjusted basis of property distributed to a partner by the partnership, andnthe partner\'s deduction for depletion for any partnership oil and gas wells, up to the proportionate share of the adjusted basis of the wells allocated to the partner.nIn this problem, the assumption of partnership liabilities increases (not decreases) a partner\'s basis in the partnership.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(754,13,'The excess of the fair market value of a franchise over its cost at the date of the sale or exchange of a partnership asset is considered to be:','[\"an unrealized receivable.\",\"a guaranteed payment.\",\"an installment payment.\",\"an exchange.\"]',0,'Unrealized receivables include potential gain that would be ordinary income if the partnership property were sold at its fair market value on the date of the payment. A list of items that are considered unrealized receivables is provided on page 12 of Publication 541. One group of items listed in this section includes franchises, trademarks, or trade names.nnThe income or loss realized by a partner upon the sale or exchange of its interest in unrealized receivables (e.g., franchise) and inventory items is the amount that would have been allocated to the partner if the partnership had sold all of its property for cash at fair market value, in a fully taxable transaction, immediately prior to the partner\'s transfer of interest in the partnership.nnFinally, any gain or loss recognized that is attributable to the unrealized receivables and inventory items will be ordinary gain or loss.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(755,13,'Comfy Chairs Manufacturing, Ltd., operates as a partnership and files Form 1065. Comfy manufactures inflatable lounge chairs. During tax year ended December 31, 2024, Comfy generated income and expenses as stated below. What is the correct amount of ordinary income (loss) from trade or business activities Comfy should report on Form 1065 (Schedule K) for 2024?nn   Employee wages                     $15,000n   Income from rental real estate      20,000n   Charitable contributions               500n   Cost of goods sold                  10,000n   Income from chair sales             75,000','[\"$65,000\",\"$69,500\",\"$50,000\",\"$30,000\"]',2,'A partnership computes its income, files its return in the same manner as an individual, and reports only trade or business activity deductions. The ordinary business income for a partnership as given on Form 1065 (see Form 1065, page 1) is computed as:nngross receipts or sales less cost of goods sold plus other partnership income, lessnsalaries and wages,nrepairs and maintenance,nbad debts,nrent,ntaxes and licenses,ninterest,ndepreciation,nretirement plans,nemployee benefit programs, andnother deductions.nCertain deductions, however, are not allowed to the partnership. Items that are separately stated on the partnership return and included as separate items on the partners\' returns (Schedule K-1, Part III (Form 1065)) are:nnordinary income or loss from trade or business activities,nnet income or loss from rental real estate activities,nnet income or loss from other rental activities,nguaranteed payments to partners,ninterest income, dividends, and royalties,ngains and losses from sales or exchanges of property described in Section 1231 of the IRC,ndividends (passed through to corporate partners) that are eligible for the dividends-received deduction by the attachment of a statement per page 8 of the Schedule K-1 (Form 1065) Instructionsntaxes paid or accrued to foreign countries and U.S. possessions, andnother items of income, gain, loss, deduction (e.g., Section 179, charitable contributions), or credit, as provided by regulations. Examples include nonbusiness expenses, intangible drilling and development costs, and soil and water conservation expenses.nIn this problem, the ordinary income from the trade or business that should be reported on Schedule K (Form 1065) is $50,000, which is the difference between the income from chair sales ($75,000) and cost of goods sold ($10,000), and wages ($15,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(756,13,'Greg, a partner in Masters Partnership, receives $1,000 cash and property worth $2,000 in which Masters has a basis of $1,500. Greg\'s outside basis at the time of the distribution is $20,000. The Partnership has assets of $40,000 and no outstanding liabilities. This distribution is at the end of the year after partnership income (loss) has been recorded. How much gain should Greg recognize on the distribution and what is his basis in the property received?','[\"Greg recognizes a gain of $500 on the property received and his basis in the property is $2,000.\",\"Greg recognizes gain of $1,500 on the property and cash received. His basis in the property received is $3,500.\",\"Greg recognizes no gain on the property received. His basis in the property received is $1,500.\",\"Greg recognizes a gain of $1,000. His basis in the property received is $1,500.\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 6, states that unless there is a complete liquidation of a partner\'s interest, the basis of property (other than money) distributed to the partner by a partnership is its adjusted basis to the partnership immediately before the distribution. However, the basis of the property to the partner cannot be more than the adjusted basis of his or her interest in the partnership reduced by any money received in the same transaction.nn nn 	Example 1	 n 	 	 n 	nThe adjusted basis of Emily\'s partnership interest is $30,000. She receives a distribution of property that has an adjusted basis of $20,000 to the partnership and $4,000 in cash. Her basis for the property is $20,000.nn n nn nn 	Example 2	 n 	 	 n 	nThe adjusted basis of Steve\'s partnership interest is $10,000. He receives a distribution of $4,000 cash and property that has an adjusted basis to the partnership of $8,000. His basis for the distributed property is limited to $6,000 ($10,000 - $4,000, the cash he receives).nn n nnGreg\'s basis in the partnership is significantly greater than the value of the distributed property. Hence, Greg would not recognize a gain from the property received from the partnership and his basis in the property received is $1,500, which is the basis of the property in the partnership prior to the distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(757,13,'Abby sells her 50% interest in the ABC partnership to Marty for $1,000 cash. Her outside basis at that time is $775. The partnership has inventory and a capital asset with respective bases of $1,200 and $300 and respective fair market values of $1,500 and $450. Abby should properly recognize:','[\"ordinary income of $300 and a capital loss of $75.\",\"capital gain of $225 on the sale of her partnership interest.\",\"an ordinary gain of $225 since she received cash of at least that amount.\",\"ordinary income of $150 and a capital gain of $75.\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 11, provides that the sale or exchange of a partner\'s interest in a partnership usually results in capital gain or loss. In addition, gain or loss is the difference between the amount realized and the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership. If the selling partner is relieved of any partnership liabilities, that partner must include the liability relief as part of the amount realized for his or her interest.nnIf, however, a partner receives money or property in exchange for any part of a partnership interest, the amount due to his or her share of the partnership\'s unrealized receivables or inventory items results in ordinary income or loss. This amount is treated as if it were received for the sale or exchange of property that is not a capital asset. This treatment applies to the unrealized receivables part of the payments to a retiring partner or a successor in interest of a deceased partner only if that part is not treated as paid in exchange for partnership property.nnnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nYou are a partner in ABC Partnership. The adjusted basis of your partnership interest at the end of the current year is zero. Your share of potential ordinary income from partnership depreciable property is $5,000. The partnership has no other unrealized receivables or inventory items. You sell your interest in the partnership for $10,000 in cash and you report the entire amount as a gain, since your adjusted basis in the partnership is zero. You report as ordinary income your $5,000 share of potential ordinary income from the partnership\'s depreciable property. The remaining $5,000 is capital gain.nn nIn this problem, Abby realizes $1,000 from the sale of her partnership interest (cash received). Her gain is determined as the difference between the amount realized and her outside basis or $1,000 less $775 equals $225. Once the amount of the gain has been determined, the character of the gain has to be calculated. Abby reports $150 as ordinary income (her share of unrealized receivables: 50% of ($1,500 – $1,200)) and $75 as capital gains (her share of capital assets (50% of ($450 – $300))).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(758,13,'Payments made by a partnership in liquidation of the interest of a retiring partner in exchange for his/her interest in the partnership property are treated as:','[\"a guaranteed payment if made over a 5-year period.\",\"a guaranteed payment regardless of the period paid.\",\"a distribution.\",\"a distributive share.\"]',2,'Payments made in liquidation of the interest of a retiring partner in exchange for his/her interest in the partnership property are considered a distribution, not a distributive share or guaranteed payment that could give rise to a deduction (or its equivalent) for the partnership.nnOther payments made by the partnership to a retiring partner or successor in interest of a deceased partner that are not made in exchange for an interest in partnership property are treated as distributive shares of partnership income or guaranteed payments.nnFurthermore, this rule applies regardless of the time over which the payments are to be made (not 5 years, as listed as one of the incorrect choices for this question). It applies to payments made for the partner\'s share of unrealized receivables and goodwill not treated as a distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(759,13,'Which of the following would not total more than 50% ownership in T, F, and J Partnership for Ted?','[\"Ted 40%, Ted\'s Wife 5%, Ted\'s Son 10%, Ted\'s Brother 45%\",\"Ted 40%, Ted\'s Wife 20%, Ted\'s Dad\'s estate 10%, Ted\'s Brother 30%\",\"Ted 40%, Ted\'s Wife 5%, Ted\'s Cousin 55%\",\"Ted 40%, Ted\'s Wife 5%, Ted\'s Son\'s Corporation 55%\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 8, provides a rule to determine if a partner has more than 50% ownership, which is as follows:nnan interest directly or indirectly owned by or for a corporation, partnership, estate, or trust is considered to be owned proportionately by or for its shareholders, partners, or beneficiaries,nan individual is considered to own the interest directly or indirectly owned by or for the individual\'s family. For this rule, “family” includes only brothers, sisters, half-brothers, half-sisters, spouses, ancestors, and lineal descendants, ornif a person is considered to own an interest using rule (1), that person (the “constructive owner”) is treated as if actually owning that interest when rules (1) and (2) are applied. However, if a person is considered to own an interest using rule (2), that person is not treated as actually owning that interest in reapplying rule (2) to make another person the constructive owner.nIn this problem, Ted does not have more than 50% ownership in the case where he owns 40% and his wife owns 5%, which is 45% ownership. The other 55% ownership by Ted\'s cousin does not constructively count for Ted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(760,13,'A partner\'s basis in a partnership interest includes the partner\'s share of a partnership liability in all of the following, except:','[\"a liability that creates or increases the partnership\'s basis in any of its assets.\",\"a partner\'s share of accrued but unpaid expenses of a cash basis partnership.\",\"a liability that is a nondeductible, noncapital expense of the partnership.\",\"a liability that gives rise to a current deduction to the partnership.\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 10, provides that a partner\'s basis in a partnership interest includes the partner\'s share of a partnership liability only if, and to the extent that, the liability:nncreates or increases the partnership\'s basis in any of its assets, ngives rise to a current deduction to the partnership, ornis a nondeductible, noncapital expense of the partnership.nA partner\'s share of accrued but unpaid expenses or accounts payable of a cash basis partnership are not included in the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(761,13,'Melissa contributed property with an adjusted basis of $100,000 and a fair market value of $134,000 to the partnership. As a result of the contribution, Melissa recognized a gain of $12,000. What is the partnership\'s basis for determining depreciation and gain or loss on the disposition of the property?','[\"$100,000\",\"$112,000\",\"$134,000\",\"$146,000\"]',1,'As provided on page 9 of Publication 541, if a partner contributes property to a partnership, the partnership\'s basis for determining depreciation, depletion, and gain or loss for the property is the same as the partner\'s adjusted basis for the property when it was contributed, increased by any gain recognized by the partner at the time of contribution.nnIn this case, the partnership would have a basis in the property of $112,000, which is the sum of $100,000 (adjusted basis) and $12,000 (recognized gain by Melissa).nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nIf there was no gain for Melissa to recognize, her basis would have been the adjusted basis of the property contributed (i.e., $100,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(762,13,'The adjusted basis of Rebecca\'s partnership interest is $17,500. She received a distribution of $9,000 cash and a piece of land with an adjusted basis of $2,500 and a fair market value of $4,000. What is the gain to be recognized at the time of these distributions?','[\"$1,500\",\"$0\",\"$4,500\",\"$6,000\"]',1,'Publication 541, page 5, provides, in part, that a partner generally recognizes a gain on a partnership distribution only to the extent any money (and marketable securities treated as money) included in the distribution exceeds the adjusted basis of the partner\'s interest in the partnership.nnAny gain recognized is generally treated as capital gain from the sale of the partnership interest on the date of the distribution. If partnership property (other than marketable securities treated as money) is distributed to a partner, he or she generally does not recognize any gain/loss until the sale or other disposition of the property.nnAs a result, Rebecca would not recognize any gain from the receipt of the $9,000 in cash and the piece of land with an FMV of $4,000 (adjusted basis of $2,500) because the cash does not exceed her adjusted basis of $17,500 in the partnership, and she has not sold the land yet.nnWith respect to the basis of the property received by Rebecca, Publication 541, page 6, states that unless there is a complete liquidation of a partner\'s interest, the basis of property (other than money) distributed to the partner by a partnership is its adjusted basis to the partnership immediately before the distribution. However, the basis of the property to the partner cannot be more than the adjusted basis of his or her interest in the partnership reduced by any money received in the same transaction.nnExample: The adjusted basis of Steve\'s partnership interest is $10,000. He receives a distribution of $4,000 cash and property that has an adjusted basis to the partnership of $8,000. His basis for the distributed property is limited to $6,000 ($10,000 − $4,000, the cash he receives).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(763,13,'All of the following items are treated as unrealized receivables in a sale of a partnership interest, except:','[\"certain farmland for which expenses for soil and water conservation or land clearing were deducted.\",\"property subject to recapture of depreciation under IRC Sections 1245 and 1250.\",\"property distributed that has a fair market value in excess of the partner\'s basis.\",\"franchises, trademarks, or trade names.\"]',2,'Publication 541, page 12, defines unrealized receivables. That is, unrealized receivables include any rights to payment not already included in income for the following items:nngoods delivered or to be delivered to the extent the payment would be treated as received for property other than a capital asset, andnservices rendered or to be rendered.nIn addition, unrealized receivables include potential gain that would be ordinary income if the following partnership property were sold at its fair market value on the date of the payment:nnmining property for which exploration expenses were deducted,nstock in a Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC),ncertain farmland for which expenses for soil and water conservation or land clearing were deducted,nfranchises, trademarks, or trade names,noil, gas, or geothermal property, for which intangible drilling and development costs were deducted,nstock of certain controlled foreign corporations,nmarket discount bonds and short-term obligations, andnproperty subject to depreciation recapture under IRC Sections 1245 and 1250.nIn light of the items listed above, the only item in this problem that is not listed as an unrealized receivable is property distributed that has a fair market value in excess of the partner\'s basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(764,13,'Which of the following statements is correct about nonrecourse liabilities?','[\"A partnership liability is a nonrecourse liability if no partner or related person has an economic risk of loss for that liability.\",\"A partnership\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0legally have nonrecourse liabilities.\",\"A partnership\'s liability is a nonrecourse liability if a person related to one of the partners has an economic risk of loss for that liability.\",\"A partner\'s share of nonrecourse liabilities is generally split equally among the partners.\"]',0,'A partnership liability is a recourse liability to the extent that any partner or a related person has an economic risk of loss for that liability. Conversely, a partnership liability is a nonrecourse liability if no partner or related person has an economic risk of loss for that liability.nnIn addition, a partner\'s share of nonrecourse liabilities is generally proportionate to his or her share of partnership profits. However, this rule may not apply if the partnership has taken deductions attributable to nonrecourse liabilities or the partnership holds property that was contributed by a partner.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(765,13,'Which shareholders must consent to have a corporation\'s S election revoked?','[\"Any shareholder regardless of percentage ownership\",\"Any two shareholders holding at least 10% each\",\"All shareholders regardless of percentage ownership\",\"Any shareholder or group of shareholders owning more than 50%\"]',3,'An S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made. The revocation can specify an effective revocation date that is on or after the day the revocation is filed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(766,13,'Wanda owns 100% of S corporation, Milk Enterprises. At the beginning of 2024, she had a zero basis and an unused ordinary loss carryover from Milk Enterprises in the amount of $5,000. During the year, Wanda secured a bank loan of $10,000 on her personal residence and made a shareholder loan of that amount to Milk Enterprises. At the end of 2024, Milk Enterprises reported on its Schedule K a $1,000 ordinary loss and a $3,000 cash distribution made to Wanda. Wanda has $10,000 in flow-through reportable income from other S corporations. How much of Milk Enterprises\' ordinary loss can Wanda deduct on her personal return?','[\"$6,000 in loss\",\"$5,000 in loss\",\"$3,000 in loss\",\"$0 in loss\"]',0,'The basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnAdditionally, a shareholder\'s distributive share of loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year. In addition, the adjusted basis of a shareholder in an S corporation is increased by any loans made by the shareholder to the corporation.nnAccordingly, the amount of Milk Enterprises\' ordinary loss (before passive and at-risk limitations) that Wanda can deduct on her personal return is $6,000, computed as follows:nn  Beginning Basis             $     0n    Plus: Shareholder Loan     10,000n    Less: Distributions         3,000n  Ending Basis                $ 7,000n n  Unused Carryover Losses       5,000n  Current-Year Losses           1,000n  Allowable Loss              $ 6,000nWanda\'s new basis in Milk Enterprises is $1,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(767,13,'Mary is the sole shareholder of A Company, Inc. (an S corporation), as well as a 50% shareholder in B Company, Inc., also an S corporation. During the 2024 tax year, both companies acquired qualified assets in order to take the IRC Section 179 election for the full allowable amount.nCalculate the maximum amount of Section 179 deduction Mary will be able to recognize on her personal income tax return for the 2024 tax year.','[\"$1,160,000\",\"$3,050,000\",\"$1,220,000\",\"None; depreciation is not a pass-through item.\"]',2,'Pursuant to page 30 of the instructions for Form 1120-S, the amount of depreciation claimed under IRC Section 179 by an S corporation is not deductible by the corporation. Rather, the amount of Section 179 depreciation is passed through to the shareholder.nnFor 2024, the maximum Section 179 expense is $1,220,000. In addition, this limit for an individual taxpayer is reduced by the amount by which the cost of Section 179 property placed in service during the year is more than $3,050,000 (Instructions for Form 4562, pages 3–5).nnTherefore, the maximum amount of Section 179 deductions which Mary will be able to recognize on her personal income tax return is $1,220,000.nn                  A Company, Inc.   B Company, Inc.n  Max Deduction    $1,220,000          $1,220,000n  Shareholder %          1.00                0.50n                   $1,220,000          $  610,000nnTotal: $1,830,000 ($1,220,000 + $610,000)nAlthough the maximum amount of Section 179 deduction that can be passed through to Mary is $1,830,000 for A Company and B Company, only $1,220,000 may be recognized in any single year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(768,13,'An S corporation generally must file its Form 1120-S by the 15th day of the ________ month after the end of its tax year.','[\"3rd\",\"4th\",\"5th\",\"6th\"]',0,'The instructions for Form 1120-S, page 3, provide that an S corporation must file its Form 1120-S by the 15th day of the 3rd month after the end of its tax year. For a calendar-year corporation, the due date is March 15. This is true for most S corporations.nnHence, the correct response for an S corporation is it must file its Form 1120-S by the 15th day of the 3rd month after the end of its tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(769,13,'All of the following situations would require the ABC Corporation to be subject to the excess net passive income tax for the year ending December 31, 2024, if its passive investment income is in excess of 25% of the gross receipts, except:','[\"it has always been an S corporation.\",\"it was previously a C corporation.\",\"it engaged in a tax-free reorganization with a C corporation.\",\"None of the answer choices are exceptions.\"]',0,'In the instructions for filing a Form 1120-S, the information for line 22a (page 19) provides the general statement for excess net passive income tax for an S corporation. In general, if the corporation has always been an S corporation, the excess net passive income tax does not apply and, likewise, if it has not always been an S corporation, it would be subject to the tax.nnSince ABC Corporation has always been an S corporation, it is not subject to the excess net passive income tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(770,13,'Which of the following is correct regarding a corporation electing S corporation status?','[\"A corporation can have no more than 75 shareholders\",\"Voting and non-voting stock in a corporation will prevent S corporation election\",\"A non-resident alien shareholder will prevent S corporation election\",\"Spouses are treated as two separate shareholders when considering the maximum number of shareholders to qualify for S corporation election\"]',2,'To elect S corporation status, an entity must meet the following criteria:nnIt is a domestic corporation or eligible domestic entity that files Form 2553 on time.nIt has no more than 100 shareholders, counting families and spouses as one shareholder.nShareholders are individuals, estates, exempt organizations (section 401(a) or 501(c)(3)), or certain trusts.nIt has no nonresident alien shareholders.nIt has only one class of stock.nIt is not an ineligible corporation (e.g., certain banks, insurance companies, or DISCs).nIt uses a permitted tax year (e.g., calendar year, natural business year).nAll shareholders consent to the S corporation election.nThe correct answer is that a non-resident alien shareholder will prevent S corporation election.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(771,13,'Mark owns 50% of an S corporation, Wick, Inc., and has a basis in that corporation of $3,000 at the beginning of 2024. At the end of 2024, Wick, Inc., reports ordinary income of $2,000 and makes a distribution to Mark of a truck with an adjusted basis of $5,000 and a fair market value of $7,000. How much income must Mark report on his personal 2024 return from this distribution?','[\"$0\",\"$1,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$5,000\"]',2,'Generally, a corporate distribution to an S corporation shareholder is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnThe basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnWhen appreciated property is distributed, gain is recognized in the same manner as if the S corporation had sold the property to the shareholders at its FMV (Section 311(b)). As such, the gain passes through to the shareholders (increasing the shareholder’s basis in S corporation stock) and increases their basis in the property received. However, losses are not recognized, unless the property is distributed in a liquidation of a corporation.nnThe type of gain is unknown in this problem and, as such, the problem asks only for the income amount.nnTherefore, Mark will have to report income of $3,000, determined as follows:nn   FMV of Property Received                $7,000n   Less Basis (lesser of FMV and ending     n    (basis; see calculation below)          5,000  Return of Capitaln   Remaining                               $2,000  Capital Gainn   Plus Gain on Truck                       1,000  (Capital or Ordinary)n   Total Income Reported                   $3,000nnBasis Calculation:n   Beginning Basis                         $3,000n   Plus Ordinary Income (50% of $2,000)     1,000n   Plus Gain on Truck (50% of $2,000)       1,000n   Ending Basis before truck dist.         $5,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(772,13,'What is the tax treatment in the case where an S corporation has no earnings and profits and distributes cash or property to a shareholder whose basis in their stock has been reduced to zero?','[\"Such distributions generally are treated as ordinary income to the shareholder.\",\"Such distributions generally are treated as a return of capital to the shareholder.\",\"Such distributions generally are treated as capital gains income to the shareholder.\",\"Such distributions generally are treated as miscellaneous income to the shareholder.\"]',2,'Earnings & Profit (E&P) is an economic concept specifically related to C corporations. An S corporation can possess accumulated E&P only if it was previously a C corporation or it acquired the assets of a C corporation in a Section 381 transaction. Absent these two conditions, an S corporation cannot posses E&P. If the S corporation does have E&P, a distribution will be taxed as a dividend if the distribution is deemed to have been made out of the E&P (see below for more details).nnRegulation Section 1.1368-1(c) provides that a distribution by an S corporation that has no accumulated E&P is taxed under a two-tier approach:nnfirst, the distribution is a tax-free reduction of the shareholder’s basis in the corporation stock; thennany distribution in excess of the shareholder’s stock basis is treated as a gain from the sale or exchange of the underlying stock.nFor an S corporation that has accumulated E&P, the taxability and nature of the gain to the receiving shareholder is a function of the S corporation’s Accumulated Adjustments Account (AAA) balance, E&P balance and shareholder’s stock basis. To the extent AAA account is zero or negative, any distribution deemed to have been made out of the E&P balance will be considered a dividend.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(773,13,'All of the following statements are correct concerning an S corporation except which of the following?','[\"It is a \\u201cpass through\\u201d entity for tax purposes.\",\"It files an informational return.\",\"It is not subject to any taxes at the corporate level.\",\"Form 2553 is used to elect S corporation status.\"]',2,'Even though an S corporation is a “pass through” entity for tax purpose and an “informational return” is filed, S corporations may still owe tax (see lines 22a, 22b, and 22c of Form 1120-S Instructions, pages 20 through 21). An S corporation may owe income tax in the following instances:nnIf, at the end of any tax year, the corporation had accumulated earnings and profits, and its passive investment income under IRC Section 1362(d)(3) is more than 25% of its gross receipts, the corporation may owe tax on its excess net passive income.nA corporation with net recognized built-in gain (as defined in IRC Section 1374(d)(2)) may owe tax on its built-in gains.nA corporation that claimed investment credit before its first year as an S corporation will be liable for any investment credit recapture tax.nA corporation that used the LIFO inventory method for the year immediately preceding its first year as an S corporation may owe an additional tax due to LIFO recapture. The tax is paid in four equal installments, the first of which must be paid by the due date (not including extensions) of the corporation\'s income tax return for its last tax year as a C corporation.nForm 2553 is used to elect S corporation status.nnFor more details on these taxes, see the instructions for lines 22a, 22b, and 22c of Form 1120-S.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(774,13,'On January 1, 2024, Acme, Inc., a calendar year S corporation, was owned by four individuals as follows: John: 50%, Bob: 25%, Dave: 20%, and Tom: 5%. On March 31, 2024, John sold his shares to Bob. On the same day, Dave sold his shares to Tom. For the tax year ending December 31, 2024, the company realized an operating loss of $100,000. Assuming that all four had sufficient basis in their stock, calculate each shareholder\'s recognizable loss for the 2024 tax year. To assist in the calculation, assume a 360-day calendar year, with 30 days in each month.','[\"John: $50,000, Bob: $25,000, Dave: $20,000, and Tom: $5,000\",\"John: $0, Bob: $75,000, Dave: $0, and Tom: $25,000\",\"John: $12,500, Bob: $62,500, Dave: $5,000, and Tom: $20,000\",\"John: $12,500, Bob: $56,200, Dave: $5,000, and Tom: $18,750\"]',2,'Items of income, gain, loss, deduction, or credit are allocated to a shareholder on a daily basis, according to the number of shares or stock held by the shareholder on each day of the corporation\'s tax year. Shareholders who dispose of stock are treated as shareholders for the day of their disposition. Shareholders who die are treated as shareholders for the day of their death.nnIf a shareholder terminates his or her interest in a corporation during the tax year, the corporation may make an irrevocable election to allocate income and expenses, etc. as if the corporation\'s tax year consisted of 2 years, the first of which ends on the close of the day the qualifying disposition occurs. A qualifying disposition can occur when a disposition by a shareholder of the corporation of at least 20% of the corporation\'s outstanding stock in one or more transactions in any 30-day period during the year.nnSince no qualifying election was made, the net operating loss will be allocated based on the time of ownership by each partner. Therefore, each shareholder, John, Bob, Dave, and Tom will receive their proportionate share of the operating loss, determined as follows:nn              1/1/24 - 3/31/24             4/01/24 - 12/31/24     n       %   $25,000((100,000/12)×3) +  %  75,000((100,000/12)×9) =  Total n John .50  $12,500 ($25,000 × .50) +  0           0             = $12,500n Bob  .25  $ 6,250 ($25,000 × .25) + .75 $56,250($75,000 × .75) = $62,500n Dave .20  $ 5,000 ($25,000 × .20) +  0           0             = $ 5,000n Tom  .05  $ 1,250 ($25,000 × .05) + .25 $18,750($75,000 × .25) = $20,000nPlease refer to computational example in Item G, page 26 of the 1120 S Instructions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(775,13,'Which of the following will disqualify a corporation from electing S corporation status?','[\"A non-resident alien stockholder\",\"Voting and non-voting stock\",\"An employee stock option plan shareholder\",\"75 shareholders\"]',0,'A corporation or other entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all the following tests.nnIt is (a) a domestic corporation, or (b) a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all the other tests listed below.nIt has no more than 100 shareholders. The taxpayer can treat an individual and his or her spouse (and their estates) as one shareholder for this test. The taxpayer can also treat all members of a family (as defined in section 1361(c)(1)(B)) and their estates as one shareholder for this test. For additional situations in which certain entities will be treated as members of a family, see Regulations section 1.1361-1(e)(3)(ii). All others are treated as separate shareholders. For details, see section 1361(c)(1).nIts only shareholders are individuals, estates, except organizations described in section 401(a) or 501(c)(3), or certain trusts described in section 1361(c)(2)(A)nIt has no nonresident alien shareholdersnIt has only one class of stock (disregarding differences in voting rights). Generally, a corporation is treated as having only one class of stock if all outstanding shares of the corporation\'s stock confer identical rights to distribution and liquidation proceeds.nIt isn’t one of the ineligible corporations.nIt has or will adopt or change to a calendar tax year, natural business year, ownership tax year, tax year elected under section 444, a 52-53-week tax year, or any other tax year (including a 52-53-week tax year) for which the corporation establishes a business purpose, andnEach shareholder consents as explained in the instructions for column K.nTherefore, the correct response is a non-resident alien stockholder.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(776,13,'If an S corporation has no accumulated earnings and profits from prior operations as a C corporation, any amount distributed to a shareholder:','[\"must be returned to the S corporation.\",\"increases the shareholder\'s basis in the stock.\",\"decreases the shareholder\'s basis in the stock.\",\"has no effect on the shareholder\'s basis in the stock.\"]',2,'Earnings & Profit (E&P) is an economic concept specifically related to C corporations. An S corporation can possess accumulated E&P only if it was previously a C corporation or it acquired the assets of a C corporation in a Section 381 transaction. Absent these two conditions, an S corporation cannot possess E&P. If the S corporation does have an E&P, a distribution will be taxed as a dividend if the distribution is deemed to have been made out of the E&P (see below for more details).nnRegulation Section 1.1368-1(c) provides that a distribution by an S corporation that has no accumulated E&P is taxed under a two-tier approach:nnfirst, the distribution is a tax-free reduction of the shareholder’s basis in the corporation stock; thennany distribution in excess of the shareholder’s stock basis is treated as a gain from the sale or exchange of the underlying stock.nFor an S corporation that has accumulated E&P, the taxability and nature of the gain to the receiving shareholder is a function of the S corporation’s Accumulated Adjustments Account (AAA) balance, E&P balance and shareholder’s stock basis. To the extent AAA account is zero or negative, any distribution deemed to have been made out of the E&P balance will be considered a dividend.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(777,13,'At the beginning of 2024, Tim had a $2,000 stock basis in the S corporation, World, Inc. Tim owns 25% of the outstanding World, Inc., stock. At the end of 2024, World, Inc., reported on its Schedule K a $16,000 ordinary loss, $4,000 of tax-exempt interest income, and $2,000 in nondeductible expense. Tim has $10,000 in flow-through reportable income from other S corporations. How much of the 2024 World, Inc., ordinary loss can Tim deduct on his personal return?','[\"$0 in loss\",\"$2,500 in loss\",\"$3,000 in loss\",\"$4,000 in loss\"]',1,'The basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnAdditionally, a shareholder\'s distributive share of loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year.nnAccordingly, the maximum amount of ordinary loss (before passive and at-risk limitations) Tim can deduct on his 2024 tax return is $2,500, computed as follows:nn  Beginning Basis                 $2,000n  Plus:n    Tax-Exempt Interest (25%)      1,000n  Less:n    Nondeductible Expenses (25%)     500n  Ending Basis                    $2,500nn  Allowable Loss                  $2,500, which is limitedn                                          to the basis',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(778,13,'Which of the following statements regarding the built-in gains tax of an S corporation is true in 2024?','[\"The built-in gains tax is treated as a loss sustained by the corporation during the same tax year.\",\"S corporation built-in gains tax is recognized in the 7th year beginning with the year the S election is made.\",\"S corporation built-in gains tax is passed through and paid at the shareholder level.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Even though an S corporation is a “pass through” entity for tax purposes and an “informational return” is filed, S corporations may still owe tax. An S corporation may owe income tax in the following instances:nnIf, at the end of any tax year, the corporation had accumulated earnings and profits, and its passive investment income under IRC Section 1362(d)(3) is more than 25% of its gross receipts, the corporation may owe tax on its excess net passive income.nA corporation with net recognized built-in gain (as defined in IRC Section 1374(d)(2)) may owe tax on its built-in gains.nA corporation that claimed investment credit before its first year as an S corporation will be liable for any investment credit recapture tax.nA corporation that used the LIFO inventory method for the year immediately preceding its first year as an S corporation may owe an additional tax due to LIFO recapture. The tax is paid in four equal installments, the first of which must be paid by the due date (not including extensions) of the corporation\'s income tax return for its last tax year as a C corporation (see IRC Section 1374).nAdditionally, and more specific to this question, the S corporation net recognized built-in gains tax can be recognized only in the 5-year period beginning with the 1st day of the 1st taxable year for which the corporation was an S corporation, per IRC Section 1374(d)(7)(A).nnHence, none of the answer choices are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(779,13,'Which of the following items are required to be separately stated to an S corporation\'s shareholders?','[\"Net short-term capital gain or loss\",\"Charitable contributions\",\"Foreign taxes paid to the government of a foreign country\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'All items of income, gain, deduction, loss, credit, etc. recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders. Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, deduction, or credit that is separately stated by the S corporation, regardless of whether or not a distribution was made to the shareholder.nnThe shareholders\' pro rata share items include items such as the following:nnOrdinary business income (loss)nNet rental real estate incomenInterest incomenDividendsnRoyaltiesnCharitable contributionsnSection 179 deductionnNet short-term capital gain or lossnForeign taxes paid to the government of a foreign countrynThese items as well as other deductible items, credits, and foreign transactions are listed separately on Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S.nnTherefore, all of the above items are required to be separately stated to an S corporation\'s shareholders.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(780,13,'The shareholders of Hope, Inc., an S corporation, wish to revoke its S election effective December 31, 2024. The total number of shares issued and outstanding at the time of the election is 100,000 shares. Which of the following shareholders are required to consent to have the S corporation election revoked?n1. Bob owns 20,000 sharesn2. Dana owns 50,000 sharesn3. Sally owns 30,000 shares','[\"Dana\",\"Bob and Sally\",\"Dana and one other shareholder\",\"Dana, Bob, and Sally\"]',2,'An S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made. The revocation can specify an effective revocation date that is on or after the day the revocation is filed.nnTherefore, in order to have the S corporation election revoked, Dana who owns 50% needs at least one other shareholder to consent to the revocation to achieve more than the 50% requirement as follows:nn                  Shares     Percentage          n  Bob             20,000     20% (20,000/100,000)n  Dana            50,000     50% (50,000/100,000)  Need MORE THAN 50%n  Sally           30,000     30% (30,000/100,000)n  Total Shares   100,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(781,13,'Which of the following statements regarding distributions from an S corporation is correct?','[\"Property distributions are applied in a different manner than cash distributions.\",\"Absent an election, distributions are considered to come first from accumulated earnings and profits, if the corporation has accumulated earnings and profits from when it was a C corporation.\",\"A shareholder\'s right to nontaxable distributions from previously taxed income may be transferred to another person.\",\"A distribution from the previously taxed income account is tax-free to the extent of a shareholder\'s basis in his\\/her stock in the corporation.\"]',3,'Unless the corporation makes an election, property distributions (including cash) are applied in the following order:nnAccumulated Adjustments Account (AAA)nPreviously Taxed Income (PTI), also called Previously Taxed Earnings and Profits (PTEP)nAccumulated Earnings and Profits (AE & P)nOther Adjustments Account (OAA)nAny remaining Shareholder\'s Equity AccountsnEach shareholder\'s right to nontaxable distributions from previously taxed income is personal and cannot be transferred to another person. Additionally, any distributions that are made from previously taxed income, also called previously taxed earnings and profits, are tax-free to the extent of a shareholder\'s basis in his/her stock in the corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(782,13,'Which of the following is correct about an S corporation election?','[\"When a new shareholder is added to an existing S corporation, the new shareholder must sign and submit a revised Form 2553.\",\"If an individual and his or her spouse have a community interest, only one of the spouses must sign Form 2553.\",\"If a new shareholder is added after the election is made but before the effective date, Form 2553 must be refiled with all of the shareholders\' signatures.\",\"If a shareholder withdraws before the election is made but after the proposed effective date, Form 2553 must be signed by all of the shareholders, including the withdrawn shareholder.\"]',3,'The following rules apply for shareholders\' consent as provided by the instructions for Form 2553, pages 4 and 5:nnFor an election filed before the effective date entered, only shareholders who own stock on the day the election is made need to consent to the election.nFor an election filed on or after the effective date entered, shareholders and former shareholders who owned stock at any time during the period beginning on the effective date and ending on the day the election is made need to consent to the election.nIf the corporation timely filed an election, but one or more shareholders did not timely file a consent, see Regulation Section 1.1362-6(b)(3)(iii).nThere are a few other stipulations for the correct signers of Form 2553:nnIf an individual and his or her spouse have a community interest, both must consent.nIf a new shareholder is added after the election is made but before the effective date, Form 2553 does not need to be refiled with all of the shareholders\' signatures. This stipulation is no longer listed in the instructions for Form 2553, but it is still valid per Regulation Section 1.1362-6(a)(2)(i), where it states that once a valid election is made, new shareholders need not consent to that election.nA minor\'s consent is made by the minor, legal representative of the minor, or a natural or adoptive parent of the minor if no legal representative has been appointed.nAs a result of the above rules, it is apparent that when a new shareholder enters into an existing S corporation, the new shareholder is not required to consent to the election.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(783,13,'Which of the following is considered a separately stated item for Form 1120-S shareholders?','[\"Charitable contributions\",\"Low-income housing credit\",\"Section 179 expense deduction\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'In most cases, an S corporation does not pay tax on its income. Instead, income, gain, deduction, loss, credit, etc. recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders. Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, deduction, or credit that is separately stated by the S corporation, regardless of whether or not a distribution was made to the shareholder. (Publication 525, page 18)nnThe shareholders\' pro rata share items include charitable contributions, the Section 179 expense deduction, and the low-income housing credit. These items as well as other separately listed items are reported separately on Schedule K and Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S.nnTherefore, all of the above items are required to be separately stated for Form 1120-S shareholders.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(784,13,'All of the following situations would require the Richards Corporation to be subject to the excess net passive income tax for the year ending December 31, 2024, if its passive investment income is in excess of 25% of the gross receipts, except:','[\"it has always been an S corporation.\",\"it was previously a C corporation.\",\"it engaged in a tax-free reorganization with a C corporation.\",\"None of the answer choices are exceptions.\"]',0,'In the instructions for filing a Form 1120-S, the information for line 22a (page 19) provides the general statement that the excess net passive income and LIFO recapture tax applies if the corporation was previously a C corporation or if the corporation engaged in a tax-free reorganization with a C corporation. Therefore, if the corporation has always been an S corporation, the excess net passive income tax does not apply.nnSince Richards Corporation has always been an S corporation, it is not subject to the excess net passive income tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(785,13,'What is the maximum number of shareholders a corporation may have to be eligible to elect to be treated as an S corporation?','[25,50,100,200]',2,'A corporation or other entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all the following tests.nnIt is (a) a domestic corporation, or (b) a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all the other tests listed below.nIt has no more than 100 shareholders. The taxpayer can treat an individual and his or her spouse (and their estates) as one shareholder for this test. The taxpayer can also treat all members of a family (as defined in section 1361(c)(1)(B)) and their estates as one shareholder for this test. For additional situations in which certain entities will be treated as members of a family, see Regulations section 1.1361-1(e)(3)(ii). All others are treated as separate shareholders. For details, see section 1361(c)(1).nIts only shareholders are individuals, estates, except organizations described in section 401(a) or 501(c)(3), or certain trusts described in section 1361(c)(2)(A)nIt has no nonresident alien shareholdersnIt has only one class of stock (disregarding differences in voting rights). Generally, a corporation is treated as having only one class of stock if all outstanding shares of the corporation\'s stock confer identical rights to distribution and liquidation proceeds.nIt isn’t one of the ineligible corporations.nIt has or will adopt or change to a calendar tax year, natural business year, ownership tax year, tax year elected under section 444, a 52-53-week tax year, or any other tax year (including a 52-53-week tax year) for which the corporation establishes a business purpose, andnEach shareholder consents as explained in the instructions for column K.nTherefore, the correct response is 100 shareholders.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(786,13,'Which of the following is true regarding distributions from an S corporation?','[\"Distributions do not include cash, only property\",\"Distributions of appreciated property are valued at the fair market value on original date of purchase\",\"Dividends paid to shareholders from accumulated earnings and profits are reported on Schedule K-1\",\"Property distributions (except for cash) require a statement attached to the Form 1120S reporting the date the property was acquired, the distribution date, the property\'s fair market value on the distribution date, and the basis in the property distributed\"]',3,'According to the IRS instructions for Form 1120-S, page 39, property distributions (except for cash) from an S corporation must include specific reporting requirements. When an S corporation distributes property, it needs to attach a statement to Form 1120-S. This statement must detail:nnThe date the property was acquired by the corporation.nThe distribution date of the property to the shareholders.nThe fair market value (FMV) of the property on the distribution date.nThe basis of the property distributed. Dividends paid to shareholders from accumulated earnings and profits are reported on 1099-DIV.nTherefore, the correct answer is that property distributions require a statement attached to Form 1120-S with the detailed information above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(787,13,'An S corporation can be subject to which of the following taxes?','[\"Built-in gains tax\",\"Excess net passive income tax\",\"Built-in gains tax and excess net passive income tax\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Even though an S corporation is a “pass through” entity for tax purposes and an “informational return” is filed, S corporations may still owe tax. An S corporation may owe income tax if the corporation previously was a C corporation or if the corporation engaged in a tax-free reorganization with a C corporation. For example:nnIf, at the end of any tax year, the corporation had accumulated earnings and profits, and its passive investment income under IRC Section 1362(d)(3) is more than 25% of its gross receipts, the corporation may owe tax on its excess net passive income.nA corporation with net recognized built-in gain (as defined in IRC Section 1374(d)(2)) may owe tax on its built-in gains.nA corporation that claimed investment credit before its first year as an S corporation will be liable for any investment credit recapture tax.nA corporation that used the LIFO inventory method for the year immediately preceding its first year as an S corporation may owe an additional tax due to LIFO recapture. The tax is paid in four equal installments, the first of which must be paid by the due date (not including extensions) of the corporation\'s income tax return for its last tax year as a C corporation.nFor more details on these taxes, see the instructions for Form 1120-S, pages 19 through 21.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(788,13,'ABC Corporation commenced business on July 20, 2024. What is the final date at which ABC could file an election for S corporation status and be recognized as valid for the 2024 tax year?','[\"September 15, 2024\",\"October 15, 2024\",\"December 31, 2024\",\"October 5, 2024\"]',3,'The election for S corporation status must be filed:nnat any time before the 16th day of the 3rd month of the tax year, if filed during the tax year the election is to take effect, ornat any time during the preceding tax year. An election made no later than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of a tax year that is less than 2-1/2 months long is treated as timely made for that tax year.nAn election made after the 15th day of the 3rd month but before the end of the tax year is effective for the next year.nnNow, one must be careful in implementing this provision. The proper calculation for this period is best illustrated in the examples that are given in the Form 2553 Instructions. For example, a calendar-year small business corporation begins its first tax year on January 7. The 2-month period ends March 6 and 15 days after that is March 21. To be an S corporation beginning with its first tax year, the corporation must file Form 2553 during the period that begins January 7 and ends March 21. Because the corporation had no prior tax year, an election made before January 7 will not be valid.nnTherefore, since ABC Corporation commenced business on July 20, 2024, the final date to file an election for S corporation status to be recognized as valid for the 2024 tax year would be no later than 2 months and 15 days after July 20, 2024 (i.e., October 5, 2024).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(789,13,'An S corporation\'s stockholders’ basis is generally increased by:','[\"distributions.\",\" nontaxable discharge of indebtedness.\",\"separately stated loss items.\",\"taxable income.\"]',3,'Generally, a corporate distribution to an S corporation shareholder is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnThe basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nThus, the basis is generally increased by all income, which would include taxable income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(790,13,'Bob\'s share of an S corporation loss is $50,000 for 2024 and his basis in his stock on December 31, 2023, is $25,000. He loaned the S corporation $10,000 during 2024, which has not been repaid. What maximum amount of loss (before passive activity and at-risk limitations) can Bob deduct on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$35,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$50,000\",\"$25,000\"]',0,'A shareholder\'s distributive share of loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year but can be carried forward indefinitely and deducted in a later year, subject to the basis limit for that year. In addition, the adjusted basis of a shareholder in an S corporation is increased by any loans made by the shareholder to the corporation.nnAccordingly, the maximum amount of loss (before passive activity and at-risk limitations) Bob can deduct on his 2024 tax return is $35,000, which is his basis and is computed as follows:nn  Beginning Basis       $25,000n  Shareholder Loan       10,000n  Adjusted Basis        $35,000nn  Allowable Loss        $35,000*n* Loss limited to basis',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(791,13,'Which of the following would not reduce a shareholder\'s basis in S corporation stock?','[\"A shareholder\'s pro-rata share of an expense not deductible in computing the corporation\'s taxable income\",\"A shareholder\'s share of all loss and deduction items of the S corporation that are separately stated and passed through to the shareholder\",\"A shareholder\'s pro-rata share of any non-separately stated loss of the S corporation\",\"The excess of the corporation\'s deductions for depletion over the basis of the property subject to depletion\"]',3,'The basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnTherefore, in the above question, the excess of the corporation\'s deductions for depletion over the basis of the property subject to depletion would increase (not reduce) a shareholder\'s basis in S corporation stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(792,13,'Nevertoolate Corporation was established on January 1, 2024. 100% of the shareholders elected to adopt S status for the company and properly completed IRS Form 2553. However, the company\'s tax accountant did not file the form. On July 1, 2024, the new accountant discovered the filing omission. Select the best available remedy for the corporation to elect S status from the following:','[\"File the Form 2553, as originally prepared, on or before the end of the first tax year of the corporation.\",\"Prepare a new Form 2553 and adopt a \\u201cshort year\\u201d period for S status.\",\"File the original Form 2553 and explain the reasonable cause on Form 2553.\",\"The company may file the prepared Form 2553; however, consent for S status will not be effective earlier than January 1, 2025.\"]',2,'Generally, the election for S corporation status must be filed:nnat any time before the 16th day of the 3rd month of the tax year, if filed during the tax year the election is to take effect, ornat any time during the preceding tax year it is to take effect.nAn election made no later than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of a tax year that is less than 2-1/2 months long is treated as timely made for that tax year.nnHowever, an election made after the due date will be accepted as timely filed if the corporation can show that the failure to file on time was due to reasonable cause.nnTo request relief for a late election, a corporation that meets certain requirements can explain the reasonable cause in the designated space on page 1 of Form 2553 or on an attached statement. The reasonable cause requirements include the following:nnThe corporation intended to be classified as an S corporation as of the date entered on line E of Form 2553.nThe corporation fails to qualify to elect to be an S corporation solely because of the failure to timely file Form 2553.nThe corporation has reasonable cause for its failure to timely file Form 2553.nForm 2553 will be filed within 3 years and 75 days of the date entered online E of Form 2553.nThe corporation files Form 2553 with the current Form 1120-S if all earlier Forms 1120-S have been filed. The election can be attached to the first Form 1120-S for the year including the effective date if filed simultaneously with any other delinquent Form 1120-S. Form 2553 can also be filed separately.nThe corporation must provide statements from all shareholders stating that they have reported their income on all affected returns consistent with the S corporation election on any affected return for the tax year beginning on the date entered online E of Form 2553.nTo request relief for a late election when the above requirements are not met, the corporation generally must request a private letter ruling and pay a user fee in accordance with Revenue Procedure 2017-1, 2017-1 IRB 1 (or its successor).nnFor this reason, Nevertoolate Corporation should file the original Form 2553 and explain the reasonable cause within 3 years and 75 days of the date entered online E of Form 2553.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(793,13,'At the end of 2015, Green, Inc., was a C corporation with $50,000 in earnings and profits. Green, Inc., elected to be treated as an S corporation beginning with the 2016 year. At the end of 2024, Green has a balance of $10,000 in its Other Adjustments Account, a balance of $20,000 in its Accumulated Adjustment Account, and a balance of $50,000 in earnings and profits. Green made cash distributions of $25,000 to each of its 50% shareholders. Green makes no elections relating to the source of distributions. What is the remaining Green, Inc., earnings and profits balance after the shareholder distributions?','[\"$50,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$30,000\",\"$20,000\"]',3,'Unless the corporation makes an election as to the source of its distribution, property distributions (including cash) are applied in the following order:nnreduce the Accumulated Adjustment Account (AAA) determined without regard to any net negative adjustment for the tax year (but not below zero). If distributions during the tax year exceed the AAA at the close of the tax year determined without regard to any net negative adjustment for the tax year, the AAA is allocated pro rata to each distribution made during the tax year,nreduce shareholders\' previously taxed income (PTI) account, also called previously taxed earnings and profits (PTEP), for any IRC Section 1375(d) (as in effect before 1983) distributions,nreduce accumulated E&P,nreduce the other adjustments account (OAA), thennreduce any remaining shareholders\' equity accounts.nTherefore, Green, Inc.\'s, remaining earnings and profits balance after the shareholder distributions is $20,000, computed as follows:nn  Amount of Distribution:  $50,000 ($25,000 × 2)nn  1st out of AAA           $20,000n  2nd out of E and P        30,000n                           $50,000nn  Beginning E and P        $50,000n  Deducted                  30,000n  Remaining                $20,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(794,13,'An S corporation will be subject to excess net passive income tax:','[\"even if it has always been an S corporation.\",\"if it has passive investment income for the year that is at least 20% of gross receipts.\",\"even if it has always been an S corporation and it has passive investment income for the year that is at least 20% of gross receipts.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The excess net passive income and LIFO recapture tax applies if an S corporation was previously a C corporation or if the corporation engaged in a tax-free reorganization with a C corporation. If either of these two situations occurred, then if the corporation has accumulated earnings and profits (AE&P) at the close of its tax year, has passive investment income for the tax year that is in excess of 25% of gross receipts, and has taxable income at year-end, the corporation must pay a tax on the excess net passive income.nnHowever, if the corporation has always been an S corporation, the excess net passive income tax does not apply.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(795,13,'ACME, Inc., a widget manufacturer, is an S corporation, which converted from C corporation status in 2018. During its years as a C corporation, it realized substantial earnings and profits and invested in real estate, equity markets, and term certificates of deposit. For the tax year ending December 31, 2024, the company realized the following income:n1. $40,000 gross receipts from the production of widgetsn2. $20,000 net income from real estate rentalsn3. $5,000 net interest incomenAssuming that the corporate tax rate is 21%, calculate the amount of tax, if any, that the S corporation will have to pay with their annual return.','[\"$2,100\",\"$3,150\",\"$11,550\",\"$0\"]',1,'Even though an S corporation is a “pass through” entity for tax purpose and an “informational return” is filed, S corporations may still owe tax. An S corporation may owe income tax in the following instances:nnIf, at the end of any tax year, the corporation had accumulated earnings and profits, and its passive investment income under IRC Section 1362(d)(3) is more than 25% of its gross receipts, the corporation may owe tax on its excess net passive income.nA corporation with net recognized built-in gain (as defined in IRC Section 1374(d)(2)) may owe tax on its built-in gains.nA corporation that claimed investment credit before its first year as an S corporation will be liable for any investment credit recapture tax.nA corporation that used the LIFO inventory method for the year immediately preceding its first year as an S corporation may owe an additional tax due to LIFO recapture. The tax is paid in four equal installments, the first of which must be paid by the due date (not including extensions) of the corporation\'s income tax return for its last tax year as a C corporation.nFor more details on these taxes, see pages 20–21 of the instructions for Form 1120-S.nnGiven that ACME, Inc., has accumulated earnings and profits and its passive income of $25,000 ($20,000 + $5,000) is more than 25% of its gross receipts ($40,000 × 0.25 = $10,000) the corporation is required to pay tax on the excess net passive income in the amount of $3,150, computed as follows:nn  Excess Passive Income ($25,000 − $10,000)   $15,000n  Tax Rate                                       0.21n  Amount of Tax:                              $ 3,150',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(796,13,'All of the following are correct statements about S corporations, except:','[\"All items of income, gain, and deduction recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders.\",\"Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, and deduction that is separately stated by the S corporation up to the amount distributed.\",\"S corporation deductions that are clearly and directly allocable to portfolio income are items separately stated to the shareholders.\",\"Items are listed separately on Schedule K and Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S.\"]',1,'All items of income, gain, deduction, loss, credit, etc. recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders. Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, deduction, or credit that is separately stated by the S corporation, regardless if a distribution was or was not made (Publication 525, page 17).nnThe shareholders\' pro rata share items include charitable contributions, the IRC Section 179 expense deduction, and the low-income housing credit. These items are listed separately on Schedule K and Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S.nnTherefore, items that are clearly and directly allocable to portfolio income are items separately stated to the shareholders.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(797,13,'John is a shareholder in an S corporation, which sent him a Form K-1 for the tax year ending 2024. The K-1 reflected ordinary income of $10,000 to John. However, there was no actual distribution of cash to any shareholder. How should John handle the income reported on the K-1?','[\"John may elect to treat the income for the year as a return of his original capital contribution.\",\"John recognizes income up to the amount actually received during the tax year.\",\"John recognizes the $10,000 as income even though he did not actually receive any of it.\",\"John should request a corrected Form K-1 be issued.\"]',2,'All items of income, gain, deduction, loss, credit, etc. recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders. Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, deduction, or credit that is separately stated by the S corporation, regardless of whether or not a distribution was made to the shareholder.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(798,13,'All of the following statements are correct concerning an S corporation, except:','[\"once an S corporation election is made, it stays in effect until it is terminated.\",\"an election to terminate requires the consent of all shareholders.\",\"the revocation may specify a revocation date that is on or after the date the revocation is filed.\",\"an election automatically terminates under special situations.\"]',1,'A corporation can revoke its S corporation status by specifying an effective revocation date that is on or after the day the revocation is filed. If no date is specified, the revocation is effective at the start of the tax year if the revocation is made on or before the 15th day of the 3rd month of that tax year. If no date is specified and the revocation is made after the 15th day of the 3rd month of the tax year, the revocation is effective at the start of next year. (Form 1120S Instructions, page 2)nnAn election terminates automatically in certain situations as spelled out on page 2 of the instructions for Form 1120-S.nnAn S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% (not the consent of all shareholders) of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(799,13,'On January 1, 2024, Bob purchased 50% of the stock of Lebeck Industries, an S corporation, for $100,000, and Bob also loaned the corporation $20,000. At the end of the 2024, Lebeck Industries incurred an ordinary loss of $180,000. How much of the loss can Bob deduct on his personal income tax return for 2024?','[\"$ 90,000\",\"$180,000\",\"$ 0\",\"$120,000\"]',0,'A shareholder\'s distributive share of a loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year. In addition, the adjusted basis of a shareholder in an S corporation is increased by any loans made by the shareholder to the corporation.nnAccordingly, the maximum amount of loss Bob can deduct on his 2024 tax return is $90,000, computed as follows:nn  Beginning Basis    $100,000n  Shareholder Loan     20,000n  Adjusted Basis     $120,000nn  Allowable Loss     $ 90,000  ($180,000 × 50%), which is less thann                                 shareholder\'s basis',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(800,13,'On January 1, 2024, Tom, Dick, and Harry were sole and equal shareholders of ABC, Inc., a calendar-year C corporation. On February 1, 2024, Tom sold all of his interest in the corporation to Dick. On March 1, 2024, Dick decides to convert the corporation to an S corporation, effective January 1, 2024. Regarding the desired conversion, which of the following statements is true?','[\"Since Dick now owns over 51% of the corporation, he can unilaterally prepare and submit the proper election application, IRS Form 2553.\",\"Since the S corporation election requires consent by 100% of the shareholders, both Dick and Harry must sign the application to elect to be treated as an S corporation.\",\"Since Tom, Dick, and Harry were all shareholders as of January 1, 2024, all three must consent to elect to treat the corporation as an S corporation.\",\"Since there was a change in stock ownership after the beginning of the corporation\'s tax year, any election to treat the corporation as an S corporation will not be effective earlier than January 1, 2025.\"]',2,'A corporation or other entity that is eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation must use Form 2553 to make an S corporation election and it must satisfy all eight tests given on page 1 of the instructions for Form 2553. One of the tests is that each shareholder consents to the election.nnFor an election filed before the effective date, only shareholders who own stock on the day the election is made need to consent to the election.nnFor an election filed on or after the effective date (no more than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of the tax year the election is to take effect), all shareholders or former shareholders who own stock at any time during the period beginning on the effective date and ending on the day the election is made must consent to the election. (Form 2553 Instructions, page 4)nnGiven that Tom, Dick, and Harry were all shareholders as of January 1, 2024 (the intended effective date), all three must consent to elect to treat the corporation as an S corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(801,13,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"An S corporation may own shares of a C corporation.\",\"A C corporation may own shares of an S corporation.\",\"An S corporation may\\u00a0not\\u00a0own shares of an S corporation.\",\"A partnership may own shares of an S corporation.\"]',0,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation that timely files Form 2553 and meets all the other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts (partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders).nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock.nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year as required by IRC Section 1378 or makes an IRC Section 444 election to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.nAn S corporation can have a C corporation or an S corporation subsidiary. An S corporation can elect to treat one or more of its wholly owned eligible subsidiaries as a qualified subchapter S subsidiary (QSub) that is not an ineligible corporation. (IRC Section 1361)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(802,13,'Which of the following statements regarding the termination of an S corporation election is true?','[\"The election may be revoked with the consent of shareholders who, at the time the revocation is made, hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares.\",\"The election may be revoked by the board of directors of the corporation only if they are not shareholders.\",\"The election terminates automatically if the corporation derives more than 25% of its gross receipts from passive investment income during the year.\",\"The election may be revoked by the Internal Revenue Service if there is a history of 10 years of operating losses.\"]',0,'An S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made. Likewise, it is terminated if the corporation derives more than 25% of its gross receipts from passive investment income during each of 3 (not 1) consecutive tax years.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(803,13,'The Acme Corporation wishes to be treated as an S corporation for the year ending December 31, 2024. The corporation must file Form 2553, Election by a Small Business Corporation, before what date?','[\"December 31, 2024\",\"March 15, 2024\",\"March 15, 2025\",\"February 15, 2025\"]',1,'The election for S corporation status must be filed:nnno more than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of the tax year the election is to take effect ornat any time during the preceding tax year it is to take effect.nFor this purpose, the 2-month period begins on the day of the month the tax year begins, and ends with the close of the day before the numerically corresponding day of the 2nd calendar month following that month. If there is no corresponding day, use the close of the last day of the calendar month.nnAccordingly, the Acme Corporation must file Form 2553, Election by a Small Business Corporation, before March 15, 2024, if they wish to be treated as an S corporation for the year ending December 31, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(804,13,'An S corporation without prior C corporation earnings and profits must maintain the Accumulated Adjustments Account in order to:','[\"determine the tax effect of any cash distributions.\",\"determine the tax effect of possible future post-merger distributions.\",\"determine the tax effect of distributions of property.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'The accumulated adjustments account (AAA) is an account of the S corporation that generally reflects the accumulated undistributed net income of the corporation for the corporation\'s post-1982 years. S corporations with accumulated E&P must maintain the AAA to determine the tax effect of distributions during S years and the post-termination transition period. An S corporation without accumulated E&P does not need to maintain the AAA in order to determine the tax effect of distributions. Nevertheless, if an S corporation without accumulated E&P engages in certain transactions to which IRC Section 381(a) applies, such as a merger into an S corporation with accumulated E&P, the S corporation must be able to calculate its AAA at the time of the merger for purposes of determining the tax effect of post-merger distributions.nnTherefore, an S corporation without prior C corporation earnings and profits must maintain the Accumulated Adjustments Account in order to determine the tax effect of possible future post-merger distributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(805,13,'Regarding a corporation\'s election for S status, which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Generally, a properly completed and timely filed election for S corporation status must be made by the 15th day of the 4th month of the start of business or beginning of the entity\'s tax year.\",\"A filed election for S status will be deemed made timely, if it is included with the corporation\'s initial filing of its annual report of income on Form 1120-S.\",\"A corporation cannot file for S status unless it has a tax year ending on December 31.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The election for S corporation status must be filed:nnat any time before the 16th day of the 3rd month of the tax year, if filed during the tax year the election is to take effect, ornat any time during the preceding tax year. An election made no later than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of a tax year that is less than 2-1/2 months long is treated as timely made for that tax year.nAdditionally, the corporation must have a permitted tax year as required by IRC Section 1378 or makes a Section 444 election per the Internal Revenue Code to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year. Section 1378 defines a permitted tax year as a tax year ending December 31, or any other tax year for which the corporation establishes a business purpose to the satisfaction of the IRS.nnAccordingly, in the above question all statements regarding a corporation\'s election for S status are incorrect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(806,13,'We Converted, Inc., elected S corporation status in 2020, after 10 years as a C corporation. At the date of conversion, the company had a $50,000 net operating loss (NOL) carryover, which it incurred in 2019, and a $25,000 capital loss carryover. In 2024, the company sold a vacant piece of property it owned since 2010. The sales price of the property was $100,000 and an original cost of $25,000.nnGiven the circumstances, as stated above, which of the following statements is correct?','[\"No amount of gain is taxable to the S corporation, because the total of the NOL and capital loss carryover ($75,000) can be used to offset the capital gain on the sale of the property.\",\"Only $50,000 of the $75,000 capital gain is subject to S corporation tax.\",\"$75,000 of the capital gain is taxable, since the S corporation cannot succeed to the beneficial tax attributes of a former C corporation.\",\"No amount of gain is taxable to the S corporation because all income items are separately stated to the shareholders.\"]',0,'Generally, when an S corporation is converted from a C corporation, the corporation is not permitted to carry forward items from a C corporation year. However, there is an exception to this rule when the S corporation must recognize built-in gain. Accordingly, an S corporation can utilize net operating loss (NOL) carryforwards and capital loss carryforwards from its “C” years to offset the amount on which the built-in gains tax is computed.nnIn addition, any excess NOL or capital loss after the offset may be carried forward to offset future income subject to the built-in gains tax.nnGiven the circumstances, as stated above, no amount of gain is taxable to the S corporation, because the total of the NOL and capital loss carryover ($75,000) can be used to offset the capital gain on the sale of the property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(807,13,'All of the following are true regarding cancellation of debt income for S corporations EXCEPT:','[\"the canceled amount is considered gross income on Form 1120-S.\",\"the amount of canceled debt excluded from income will increase the basis of the shareholders\\u2019 stock.\",\"the pro rata share of the canceled debt income will pass through to the shareholders.\",\"canceled debt income may be excluded to the amount of insolvency of the S corporation.\"]',1,'Generally, when a taxpayer has their debt discharged or cancelled, that becomes gross income per IRC Section 61(a)(11). However, the taxpayer may be able to exclude that cancellation of debt (COD) income based on the reason for the discharge per IRC Section 108(a).nnFor S corporations, the rules for excluding income from debt cancellation because of bankruptcy or insolvency apply at the corporate level; thus, not at the shareholder level (Publication 908, page 29). If the S corporation had a debt discharged resulting from a Title 11 bankruptcy proceeding or while insolvent, Shareholders are directed to see Form 982, Reduction of Tax Attributes Due to Discharge of Indebtedness, and Publication 908, Bankruptcy Tax Guide, per Form 1120-S Instructions, page 14. The Schedule K-1 (Form 1120-S) Instructions, page 3, states that the shareholder’s stock basis is not increased by the excluded discharge of indebtedness income of the S corporation per IRC Section 108(a) and 108(d)(7)(A). Hence, a shareholder with this exclusion needs to consider the preparation of Form 982.nnIn addition, for purposes of Form 982 preparation, the excluded discharge of indebtedness will be listed as a net operation loss (NOL). For S corporations, a loss or deduction that is disallowed for the tax year of the debt cancellation because it exceeds the shareholders basis in the corporation’s stock and debt, is treated as an NOL for that tax year in making the required reduction of tax attributes for the amount of the cancelled debt (Publication 908, page 29). The Form 982 Instructions do not make this point. But it is stated in Regulation Section 1.108-7(d) generally, that if an S corporation excludes COD income from gross income under section 108(a), the amount excluded shall be applied to reduce the S corporation\'s tax attributes as the NOL attribute (deemed NOL) of the S corporation for the taxable year of the discharge.nnHence the one answer that is not true for the question is that the amount of canceled debt excluded from income will increase the basis of the shareholders’ stock. On the contrary, as discussed above, the amount of canceled debt excluded from income does not increase the basis of the shareholders’ stock',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(808,13,'All of the following events would cause an S corporation to cease qualifying as an S corporation, except:','[\"having more than 100 shareholders.\",\"the transfer of its stock to a corporation\",\"the transfer of its stock to a nonresident alien.\",\"failure of the passive income test for 2 consecutive years.\"]',3,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts (partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders).nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock.nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year or makes a Section 444 election per the Internal Revenue Code to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.nThere are several conditions that cause the S corporation\'s status to terminate automatically. These cases are described on page 2 of the 1120-S Instructions.nnIf an S corporation, for 3 consecutive years, has accumulated earnings and profits as well as passive investment income that exceeds 25% of its gross receipts, its election is ended beginning with the following tax year. (Form 1120-S Instructions, page 2)nnTherefore, all of the above items, except for failing the passive income test for 2 consecutive years, would cause an S corporation to cease qualifying as an S corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(809,13,'Pine Street Corporation is an S corporation. The Form 1120-S for 2024 reflects a $3,500 ordinary loss. Mr. Jones, the sole shareholder of Pine Street Corporation, has a basis in the corporation on January 1, 2024, of $1,500. Which of following statements is correct?','[\"Mr. Jones may deduct a $3,500 loss on his 2024 return.\",\"Mr. Jones may deduct a $1,500 loss on his 2024 return and carry back a $2,000 loss to 2021.\",\"Mr. Jones may deduct a $1,500 loss on his 2024 return and carry forward a $2,000 loss indefinitely.\",\"Mr. Jones may deduct a $1,500 loss on his 2024 return and loses the remaining $2,000 loss.\"]',2,'A shareholder\'s distributive share of loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year and may be carried forward indefinitely. In addition, the adjusted basis of a shareholder in an S corporation is increased by any loans made by the shareholder to the corporation.nnAccordingly, the maximum amount of loss (before passive and at-risk limitations) Mr. Jones can deduct on his 2024 tax return is $1,500, computed as follows:nn  Beginning Basis     $1,500n  Shareholder Loan         0n  Adjusted Basis      $1,500nn  Allowable Loss      $1,500*n* Loss limited to basis',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(810,13,'On December 1, 2024, Bob elected to terminate his corporation\'s S status, effective January 1, 2025. Bob owns 55% of the corporation\'s stock. If Bob changes his mind, what is the earliest date that Bob could have his S corporation status reinstated without IRS consent?','[\"January 1, 2027\",\"December 1, 2028\",\"January 1, 2030\",\"Since election to terminate S corporation status requires 100% of the outstanding shareholders\' consent, the revocation is not valid and the S corporation qualifies until properly terminated.\"]',2,'An S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made. The revocation may specify an effective revocation date that is on or after the day the revocation is filed. If no date is specified, the revocation is effective at the start of a tax year, if the revocation is made on or before the 15th day of the 3rd month of that tax year.nnAfter an S election has been terminated, the corporation (or a successor corporation) can make another election on Form 2553 only with IRS consent for any tax year before the 5th tax year after the 1st tax year in which the termination took effect.nnTherefore, the earliest date at which Bob could re-elect S status for his corporation without IRS consent is January 1, 2030.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(811,13,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation if it meets the following test(s):','[\"It is a domestic corporation.\",\"It has no more than 100 shareholders. A husband and wife (and their estates) are treated as 1 shareholder for this requirement. All other persons are treated as separate shareholders.\",\"It has only one class of stock.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts (partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders).nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock.nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year or makes a Section 444 election per the Internal Revenue Code to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.nIn this problem, all the responses are tests for a corporation wanting to elect S corporation status.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(812,13,'Which of the following items is not a separately stated item of a qualifying S corporation?','[\"Interest income\",\"Charitable contributions\",\"Interest income on business receivable balances\",\"Net long-term capital gain\"]',2,'All items of income, gain, deduction, loss, credit, etc. recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders. Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, deduction, or credit that is separately stated by the S corporation, regardless of whether or not a distribution was made to the shareholder.nnThe shareholders\' pro rata share items include interest income, charitable contributions, and net long-term capital gain. These items are listed separately on Schedule K and Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S.nnInterest income derived in the ordinary course of the corporation\'s trade or business (such as interest charged on receivables balances) is included on line 5 of Form 1120S (Form 1120-S Instructions, page 14).nnTherefore, all of the above items are required to be separately stated for Form 1120S shareholders, except interest income on business receivable balances.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(813,13,'Which of the following will not affect a shareholder\'s basis in his/her S corporation stock?','[\"Any Section 179 depreciation deduction, which is separately stated to the shareholder.\",\"Any tax-exempt income earned by the corporation which is separately stated to the shareholder.\",\"Any Section 1245 capital loss which is recognized by the corporation and separately stated to the shareholder.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'In general, an S corporation does not pay tax on its income. Instead, the income, losses, deductions, and credits of the corporation are separately stated on each shareholder\'s K-1 and passed through to the shareholder based on their pro rata share. These items are reported on the shareholder\'s tax return. Therefore, the items passed through to the shareholder will increase or decrease the basis of their S corporation stock as appropriate.nnThus, all of the items listed in the above question are separately stated items that would pass through to the shareholder and either increase or decrease their S corporation stock basis.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(814,13,'Which of the following statements is correct in the case where a shareholder in an S corporation makes a loan to the corporation?','[\"The shareholder\'s adjusted basis in the corporate stock is increased by the amount of the loan.\",\"The shareholder\'s adjusted basis in the S corporation is effectively increased by the amount of the loan.\",\"The shareholder\'s adjusted basis in the S corporation is effectively increased by their proportionate share of the loan.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Pursuant to page 2 of the instructions for Schedule K-1 (Form 1120-S), the basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnGenerally, the deduction for the taxpayer\'s share of aggregate losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1 is limited to the basis of the taxpayer\'s stock and loans from the S corporation shareholder.nnTherefore, by an S corporation shareholder making a loan to the corporation, the shareholder\'s adjusted basis in the S corporation is effectively increased by the amount of the loan.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(815,13,'The Richards Corporation has a tax year ending June 30. The corporation wishes to elect S corporation status. In order to have the S election effective for the 2025 tax year beginning July 1, 2024, before which of the following dates must Form 2553 be filed with the proper IRS Service Center?','[\"June 15, 2024\",\"January 1, 2025\",\"September 16, 2024\",\"December 31, 2024\"]',2,'The election for S corporation status must be filed:nnat any time before the 16th day of the 3rd month of the tax year, if filed during the tax year the election is to take effect, ornat any time during the preceding tax year. An election made no later than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of a tax year that is less than 2-1/2 months long is treated as timely made for that tax year.nAccordingly, the Richards Corporation must file Form 2553, Election by a Small Business Corporation, before September 16, 2024, if they wish to have the S election effective for the 2025 tax year beginning July 1, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(816,13,'As of December 31, 2024, John is a 50% shareholder of XYZ, Inc., an S corporation, as well as a 75% shareholder of ABC, Inc., also an S corporation. Both companies are calendar-year taxpayers. Because of profitable years, each company elected to use the maximum depreciation deduction allowable under IRC Section 179 for the year. Assuming that each election was valid, what is the maximum amount of Section 179 deductions that can be recognized by John?','[\"$3,050,000\",\"$1,220,000\",\"$1,160,000\",\"None; depreciation is not a pass-through item.\"]',1,'Pursuant to page 26 of the Instructions for Form 1120-S, the amount of depreciation claimed under IRC Section 179 by an S corporation is not deductible by the corporation. Rather, the amount of Section 179 depreciation is passed through to the shareholder.nnFor 2024, the maximum Section 179 expense is $1,220,000. In addition, this limit is reduced by the amount by which the cost of Section 179 property placed in service during the year is more than $3,050,000 (Instructions for Form 4562, pages 3 to 5).nnTherefore, the maximum amount of Section 179 deductions, which can be passed through to John is $1,220,000, computed as follows:nn                     XYZ, Inc.      ABC, Inc.n  Max. Deduction    $1,220,000     $1,220,000n  Shareholder %           0.50           0.75n                    $  610,000     $  915,000nn  Total:            $1,525,000  ($610,000 + $915,000)nAlthough the maximum amount of Section 179 deduction that can be passed through to John is $1,525,000, only $1,220,000 may be recognized in any single year. John\'s basis in each S corporation will be reduced by the full depreciation ($610,000 for XYZ and $915,000 for ABC) regardless of the limitation applied to John on his personal return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(817,13,'Bob and Sally, unmarried taxpayers, were equal sole shareholders of Lostalot, Inc., an S corporation. The corporation realized a $50,000 operating loss for the tax year ending December 31, 2024. As of December 31, 2023, Bob\'s basis in his stock was $15,000 and Sally\'s was $5,000. During the 2024 tax year, Sally mortgaged her home for $25,000 and lent the money to the corporation. Although not personally liable, Bob told her not to worry and that if anything happened, he would help pay the mortgage debt. Calculate the amount of allowable loss deduction each shareholder would be able to recognize on his or her individual 2024 tax return.','[\"Bob $25,000 and Sally $25,000\",\"Bob $15,000 and Sally $5,000\",\"Bob $15,000 and Sally $30,000\",\"Bob $15,000 and Sally $25,000\"]',3,'A shareholder\'s distributive share of loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year but can be carried forward indefinitely and deducted in a later year, subject to the basis limit for that year. In addition, the adjusted basis of a shareholder in an S corporation is increased by any loans made by the shareholder to the corporation.nnAccordingly, the amount of allowable loss deduction for each shareholder is as follows:nn                           Bob            Sally n  Beginning Basis        $15,000         $ 5,000n  Shareholder Loan             0          25,000n  Adjusted Basis         $15,000         $30,000nn  Allowable Loss         $15,000*        $25,000n* Loss of $25,000, which is $50,000 × 50%, is limited to basis of $15,000.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nWatch out for this type of problem. You may be so busy calculating the basis that you forget to calculate how much loss is attributable to each shareholder. Also, Sally is still liable for the contributed debt amount even though Bob says he will help (not enforceable onto Bob).nn n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(818,13,'Which of the following corporations has not made a valid S corporation election for the current year if 100% of the stockholders of the corporation elect, in writing, to adopt subchapter S status for their corporation?','[\"S corporation status is requested on September 3, 2024, for a tax year beginning on July 1, 2024.\",\"S corporation status is requested on October 16, 2024, for a tax year beginning on July 1, 2024.\",\"S corporation status is requested on April 16, 2024, for a tax year beginning on July 1, 2024.\",\"All of the answer choices are valid S corporation elections.\"]',1,'The election for S corporation status must be filed:nnat any time before the 16th day of the 3rd month of the tax year, if filed during the tax year the election is to take effect, ornat any time during the preceding tax year. An election made no later than 2 months and 15 days after the beginning of a tax year that is less than 2-1/2 months long is treated as timely made for that tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(819,13,'Kevin, the 100% owner of an S corporation, has an adjusted basis in stock before losses and deductions at the end of 2024 in the amount of $12,000. The 2024 corporate return shows a $20,000 ordinary loss and a $5,000 charitable contribution expense. What are the allowable losses and deductions Kevin may claim on his 2024 tax return?','[\"$12,000 ordinary loss and $0 contribution expense\",\"$9,600 ordinary loss and $2,400 contribution expense\",\"$7,000 ordinary loss and $5,000 contribution expense\",\"$12,000 ordinary loss and $5,000 contribution expense\"]',1,'As provided in the instructions for Schedule K-1 (Form 1120-S), the basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnPer Regulation Section 1.1366-2(a)(5), if the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the aggregate amount of losses and deductions is greater than the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock in the corporation, then the limitation on losses and deductions must be allocated among the shareholder\'s pro rata share of each loss or deduction. The disallowed losses and deductions are carried forward from prior years.nnAs such, Kevin may claim $9,600 ordinary loss and $2,400 contribution expense, calculated as follows:nn  Beginning Basis              $12,000n  Less: Contribution Expense     2,400 ($5,000 x 12,000, divided by then                                        sum of $5,000 and $20,000)n  Subtotal                     $ 9,600nn  Allowable Loss               $ 9,600 (loss of $20,000 limite',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(820,13,'Jamison Corporation made various payments and transfers to and for its shareholders, Robert and James, during the year. Which of the following is not a reportable distribution? (Assume sufficient earnings and profits.)','[\"Monthly cash payments of $500 to Robert\",\"Transfer of stocks held for investment to both Robert and James\",\"Use of a company vehicle by James\' daughter at college\",\"Reasonable salary to both Robert and James\"]',3,'If a corporation pays an employee who is also a shareholder a salary that is unreasonably high considering the services actually performed by the shareholder-employee, the excessive part of the salary may be treated as a distribution to the shareholder-employee.nnThus, Jamison Corporation\'s payment of a reasonable salary to both Robert and James (shareholders) would not be a reportable distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(821,13,'Which of the following conditions will prevent a corporation from qualifying as an S corporation?','[\"The corporation has both common and preferred stock.\",\"The corporation has 70 shareholders.\",\"One shareholder is an estate.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation that timely files Form 2553 and meets all the other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts (partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders).nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock (IRC Section 1361(b)(1)(D)).nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year as required by IRC Section 1378 or makes an IRC Section 444 election to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.nAs such, the only condition in the above question that will prevent a corporation from qualifying as an S corporation is if the corporation has both common and preferred stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(822,13,'On January 1, 2024, Allen purchased 50% of the outstanding shares of an S corporation, Ball Enterprises, for $1,000. At year-end Ball Enterprises had $5,000 in ordinary income, $1,000 in net income from rental real estate, and had made $2,000 in charitable contributions. Ball Enterprises had also paid $700 to Allen\'s golf instructor and $300 for a titanium driver Allen uses as a member at his country club. What is Allen\'s basis in Ball Enterprises at the end of 2024?','[\"$2,000\",\"$2,500\",\"$3,500\",\"$5,000\"]',0,'The basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnTherefore, Allen\'s basis in Ball Enterprises at the end of 2024 is $2,000 and is computed as follows:nn  Basis                                   $1,000n  Plus: Ordinary income (50%)              2,500n  Plus: Rental real estate income (50%)      500n  Less: Property distributions             1,000 (700 + 300)n  Less: Charitable contributions (50%)     1,000n     Ending Basis                         $2,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(823,13,'An S corporation election is permitted if a corporation passes the following tests, except:','[\"it is a domestic corporation.\",\"it owns a qualified subchapter S subsidiary.\",\"it has 200 shareholders.\",\"it has one class of stock.\"]',2,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all the other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts (partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders).nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock.nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year or makes a Section 444 election per the Internal Revenue Code to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.nAn S corporation is permitted to own a qualified subchapter S subsidiary (QSSS or QSub). This includes any domestic corporation that qualifies as an S corporation and is 100% owned by an S corporation parent which elects to treat it as a QSSS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(824,13,'Cancellation of debt (COD) income for a subchapter S corporation:','[\"flows to shareholder if income is excluded by the S corporation.\",\"is recognized as income to an S corporation regardless of the extent of corporate insolvency.\",\"is not excluded from gross income to the S corporation when granted in Chapter 11 reorganizations.\",\"gives rise to income which flows to shareholders if income is not excluded by the S corporation.\"]',3,'Generally, when a taxpayer has their debt discharged or cancelled, that becomes gross income per IRC Section 61(a)(11). However, the taxpayer may be able to exclude that cancellation of debt (COD) income based on the reason for the discharge per IRC Section 108(a).nnFor S corporations, the rules for excluding income from debt cancellation because of bankruptcy or insolvency apply at the corporate level; thus, not at the shareholder level (Publication 908, page 19). If the S corporation had a debt discharged resulting from a Title 11 bankruptcy proceeding or while insolvent, shareholders are directed to see Form 982, Reduction of Tax Attributes Due to Discharge of Indebtedness, and Publication 908, Bankruptcy Tax Guide, per the Instructions for Form 1120-S, page 14. The Schedule K-1 (Form 1120-S) Instructions, page 3, state that the shareholder’s stock basis is not increased by the excluded discharge of indebtedness income of the S corporation per IRC Section 108(a) and 108(d)(7)(A). Hence, a shareholder with this exclusion needs to consider the preparation of Form 982.nnIn addition, for purposes of Form 982 preparation, the excluded discharge of indebtedness will be listed as a net operation loss (NOL). For S corporations, a loss or deduction that is disallowed for the tax year of the debt cancellation because it exceeds the shareholders basis in the corporation\'s stock and debt, is treated as an NOL for that tax year in making the required reduction of tax attributes for the amount of the cancelled debt (Publication 908, page 19). The Form 982 Instructions do not make this point. But it is stated in Regulation Section 1.108-7(d) generally, that if an S corporation excludes COD income from gross income under section 108(a), the amount excluded shall be applied to reduce the S corporation\'s tax attributes as the NOL attribute (deemed NOL) of the S corporation for the taxable year of the discharge.nnHence the best answer to this question, as discussed above, is that COD income for an S corporation gives rise to income which flows to shareholders if income is not excluded by the S corporation.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(825,13,'If an S corporation, which has accumulated earnings and profits (AE&P), is allowed to treat shareholder distributions as being made from the AE&P account, how will those distributions be taxed, if at all?','[\"They will be taxed as dividend income.\",\"They will be taxed as ordinary earned income.\",\"They will be taxed as capital gain income.\",\"They will\\u00a0not\\u00a0be taxed, as it would be deemed a return of shareholder capital.\"]',0,'Earnings & Profit (E&P) is an economic concept specifically related to C corporations. An S corporation can possess accumulated E&P only if it was previously a C corporation or it acquired the assets of a C corporation in a Section 381 transaction. Absent these two conditions, an S corporation cannot possess E&P. If the S corporation does have an E&P, a distribution will be taxed as a dividend if the distribution is deemed to have been made out of the E&P (see below for more details).nnRegulation Section 1.1368-1(c) provides that a distribution by an S corporation that has no accumulated E&P is taxed under a two-tier approach:nnfirst, the distribution is a tax-free reduction of the shareholder’s basis in the corporation stock; thennany distribution in excess of the shareholder’s stock basis is treated as a gain from the sale or exchange of the underlying stock.nFor an S corporation that has accumulated E&P, the taxability and nature of the gain to the receiving shareholder is a function of the S corporation’s Accumulated Adjustments Account (AAA) balance, E&P balance and shareholder’s stock basis. To the extent AAA account is zero or negative, any distribution deemed to have been made out of the E&P balance will be considered a dividend.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(826,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning an S corporation?','[\"A corporation that has elected S status and has filed Form 1120-S for several years may terminate its S election by simply filing a Form 1120 in a subsequent year.\",\"An S election may be revoked only with the consent of all shareholders who hold issued and outstanding shares of stock at the time revocation is made.\",\"Once an S corporation has been terminated, the corporation cannot make another S corporation election for any tax year before the 5th tax year after the 1st tax year in which the termination took effect.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'To revoke the election, the corporation must file a statement with the appropriate service center listed under “Where to File” in the instructions for Form 2553. In the statement, the corporation must notify the IRS that it is revoking its election to be an S corporation. An S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made.nnIt should be noted that after an S election has been terminated, the corporation (or a successor corporation) can make another election on Form 2553 only with IRS consent for any tax year before the 5th tax year after the 1st tax year in which the termination took effect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(827,13,'On January 1, 2024, Harbor, Inc., a calendar-year S corporation, had three shareholders (Bob, Dave, and John). Bob owned 50% of the stock, while Dave and John each owned 25%. On July 1, 2024, Bob sold his stock equally to Dave and John. Which of the following statements is correct if at the end of the tax year the corporation has a net operating loss, a qualifying disposition election is made, and Dave and John\'s basis in their stock is sufficient?','[\"50% of the net operating loss will flow through to Dave\",\"50% of the net operating loss will flow through to John\",\"50% of the net operating loss will flow through to Bob\",\"The corporation must treat the tax year as 2 years.\"]',2,'If a shareholder terminates his or her interest in a corporation during the tax year, the corporation with the consent of all affected shareholders (including those whose interest is terminated) may make an election to allocate income and expenses, etc. as if the corporation\'s tax year consisted of 2 years, the first of which ends on the close of the day that the qualifying disposition occurs. A qualifying disposition can occur when a disposition by a shareholder of the corporation of at least 20% of the corporation\'s outstanding stock in one or more transactions in any 30-day period during the year.nnGiven that Bob disposed of 50% of the outstanding stock, the net operating loss will be allocated as though Harbor, Inc., had 2 tax years; therefore, each shareholder, Bob, John, and David will receive their proportionate share of all required separately stated items.nnNote: If a qualifying election were not made, the Instructions to Form 1120-S, page 24, prescribe the computation for each shareholder’s percentage. As such, each shareholder’s percentage of ownership is weighted for the number of days in the tax year that stock was owned. In this case, Bob would be deemed to have owned 25% of the stock, whereas Dave and John would have 37.5% each.nnNote: The corporation may (not must) treat the tax year as 2 years. This is a real “gotcha” question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(828,13,'Previous years cash distributions to a shareholder have reduced his/her stock basis to zero in an S corporation. How will any further cash distributions be treated for tax purposes if the company continues to have losses?','[\"It will be treated as a deemed sale of the shareholder\'s stock.\",\"It will be treated as a capital contribution to the corporation.\",\"It will receive passive activity loss treatment, subject to any limitations.\",\"It will be carried over indefinitely to be offset with future earnings.\"]',0,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s).nnIf the corporation does not have adequate earnings and profits, the excess amount distributed is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock. To the extent that the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder realizes a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(829,13,'Which of the following conditions must be satisfied for a corporation to qualify as an S corporation?','[\"The corporation cannot have an estate as a shareholder.\",\"The corporation must have less than 100 shareholders.\",\"The corporation cannot issue more than one class of stock.\",\"At least 80% of the shareholders must agree to the S corporation election.\"]',2,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than (not less than) 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts. (Partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders.)nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock.nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year or makes a Section 444 election to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(830,13,'Which of the following statements is correct about an S corporation election?','[\"It is made for periods of 5 years, which may be renewed.\",\"It stays in effect until it is terminated.\",\"It may be terminated after 10 years, but not sooner.\",\"It cannot be terminated after 10 years.\"]',1,'The instructions for Form 1120-S, page 2, state that once a corporation makes an S corporation election, the election stays in effect until it is terminated. IRS consent generally is required for another election by the corporation on Form 2553 for any tax year before the 5th tax year after the 1st tax year in which the termination took effect. See Regulation Section 1.1362-5 for more details.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(831,13,'Which of the following is not eligible to be a shareholder of an S corporation?','[\"A domestic partnership\",\"Individuals who are not nonresident aliens\",\"Estates\",\"An exempt organization as described in IRC Section 401(a) or 501(c)(3).\"]',0,'A corporation may elect to be an S corporation only if it meets all of the following tests:nnThe entity must be a domestic corporation, or a domestic entity eligible to elect to be treated as a corporation, that timely files Form 2553 and meets all other tests listed below.nThe corporation may not have more than 100 shareholders.nThe corporation\'s shareholders are limited to individuals, estates, certain exempt organizations, or certain trusts (partnerships and corporations are not permitted shareholders).nThe corporation has no nonresident alien shareholders.nThere is only one class of stock.nThe entity is not one of the following ineligible corporations:nA bank or thrift institution that uses the reserve method of accounting for bad debts under IRC Section 585nAn insurance company subject to tax under the rules of Subchapter L of the Internal Revenue CodenA corporation that has elected to be treated as a possessions corporation under IRC Section 936nA Domestic International Sales Corporation (DISC) or former DISCnThe corporation has a permitted tax year or makes a Section 444 election per the Internal Revenue Code to have a tax year other than a permitted tax year.nEach shareholder consents to the election.nGiven the above, a domestic partnership is not eligible to be a shareholder of an S corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(832,13,'Robert owns 50% of an S corporation, Blue Sky, Inc., and has a basis in that corporation of $5,000 at the beginning of 2024. At the end of 2024, Blue Sky reports ordinary income of $10,000 and makes a distribution to Robert of a manuscript originally purchased for $1,000 but now valued at $8,000. How much income must Robert report on his personal 2024 return from this distribution?','[\"$0\",\"$1,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$8,000\"]',0,'Generally, a corporate distribution to an S corporation shareholder is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnThe basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnAn S corporation can distribute property to its shareholders. If property is distributed, the amount of the distribution is considered to be the property’s fair market value (IRC Section 301(b)). When appreciated property is distributed, gain is recognized in the same manner as if the S corporation had sold the property to the shareholders at its FMV (Section 311(b)). The gain passes through to the shareholders and increases their basis in such property. However, losses are not recognized, unless the property is distributed in a liquidation of a corporation.nnAs such, Robert is not required to report any income, determined as follows:nn  FMV of Property Received              $ 8,000n  Less Basis (lesser of FMV and endingn   basis; see calculation below)          8,000  Return of Capitaln  Remaining                             $     0nn Basis Calculation:n  Beginning Basis                        $ 5,000n  Plus Ordinary income (50% of $10,000)    5,000n  Ending Basis before property dist.     $10,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(833,13,'Sam\'s basis in S corporation stock was $100,000 before adjusting for current-year activity. After consideration of each of the items below, what is Sam\'s basis in his S corporation stock?nn$10,000 tax-exempt incomen$20,000 non-separately stated incomen$15,000 excess of depletion deduction over the basis of the property being depleted','[\"$110,000\",\"$145,000\",\"$105,000\",\"$125,000\"]',1,'The basis of an S corporation shareholder\'s stock (generally, its cost) is adjusted as follows and, except as noted, in the order listed. In addition, basis may be adjusted under other provisions of the Internal Revenue Code:nnBasis is increased by (a) all income (including tax-exempt income) reported on Schedule K-1 and (b) the excess of the deduction for depletion (other than oil and gas depletion) over the basis of the property subject to depletion.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) property distributions (including cash) made by the corporation reported on Schedule K-1, box 16, code D, minus (b) the amount of such distributions in excess of the basis of the shareholder\'s stock.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by (a) nondeductible expenses and (b) the depletion deduction for any oil and gas property held by the corporation, but only to the extent the shareholder\'s pro rata share of the property\'s adjusted basis exceeds that deduction.nBasis is decreased (but not below zero) by all deductible losses and deductions reported on Schedule K-1.nNote that the taxpayer can make an election to deduct items in (4) in the list above before nondeductible items in (3).nnTherefore, Sam\'s basis in his S corporation is $145,000 and is computed as follows:nn  Beginning Basis:                  $100,000n  Plus:n    Tax-Exempt Interest               10,000n    Non-Separately Stated Income      20,000n    Excess Depletion                  15,000n  Ending Basis:                     $145,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(834,13,'Mary is the president of Should-A-Thought, Inc., a C corporation. She owns 48% of the corporate stock. From inception in 2022, the company has lost money. She feels that the company will continue to be unprofitable for the next 3–5 years. She wants to convert to an S corporation to take advantage of the prior losses. Which of the following statements is correct if Should-A-Thought, Inc., timely files the proper form to elect to be an S corporation for the current year?','[\"Prior losses of the company will flow through to Mary\'s personal income tax return.\",\"Prior losses of the company can be used to offset any built-in gains tax to the S corporation.\",\"Prior losses of the company will flow through to Mary as an increase in her basis.\",\"Prior losses of the company will flow through to the S corporation.\"]',1,'Generally, when an S corporation is converted from a C corporation, the corporation is not permitted to carry forward items from a C corporation year. However, there is an exception to this rule when the S corporation must recognize built-in gain. Accordingly, an S corporation can utilize net operating loss (NOL) carryforwards and capital loss carryforwards from its “C” years to offset the amount on which the built-in gains tax is computed.nnTo better appreciate the built-in gain issue, see the discussion of item 8 appearing on pages 21 and 22 of the instructions for Form 1120-S.nnGiven the circumstances, as stated above, no built-in gain amounts exist; therefore, no amounts carry over to the S corporation and the prior losses of the company will not flow through to Mary\'s personal tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(835,13,'XYZ Corporation is a qualified S corporation. In 2024, its books and records reflected the following transactions:nn  Business Income                                $ 500,000n  Real Estate Rental Loss                          (20,000)n  Interest Income                                    5,000n  Salaries and Wages                               (50,000)n  Depreciation (without Section 179 Expense)       (40,000)n  Section 179 Expense                              (10,000)n  Other Business Deductions                       (300,000)nWhat is XYZ\'s ordinary income (loss) to be reported on its 2024 Form 1120-S?','[\"$85,000\",\"$110,000\",\"$115,000\",\"$105,000\"]',1,'All items of income, gain, deduction, loss, credit, etc. recognized at the corporate level are passed through to the shareholders. Each shareholder includes in his taxable income his pro rata share of each item of income, loss, deduction, or credit that is separately stated by the S corporation, regardless of whether or not a distribution was made to the shareholder. (IRC Section 1366(a))nnThe shareholders\' pro rata share of deductible items reported separately on Schedule K-1 includes (but is not limited to) the following items:nnExpenses incurred for the production of income instead of in a trade or businessnOrdinary business income (loss)nNet rental real estate incomenInterest incomenDividendsnRoyaltiesnCharitable contributionsnSection 179 deductionnNet short-term capital gain or lossnForeign taxes paid to the government of a foreign countrynThese items as well as other deductible items, credits, and foreign transactions are listed separately on Schedule K and Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S.nnSpecific to this question, the shareholders\' pro rata share items include interest income, the Section 179 expense deduction, and real estate losses. These items are listed separately on Schedule K and Schedule K-1 of Form 1120-S; that is, they are not part of the ordinary income calculation on line 1 in Part III of the Schedule K-1.nnAccordingly, XYZ Corporation\'s ordinary income for 2024 is $110,000, calculated as follows:nn  Business Income              $500,000n  Salaries and Wages            (50,000)n  Depreciation                  (40,000)n  Other Business Deductions    (300,000)n  Ordinary Income              $110,000nNote: All other items are separately stated on the shareholder\'s Schedule K-1.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(836,13,'Mary is a 50% shareholder in an S corporation, which suffered a $100,000 loss for the tax year ending December 31, 2024. Mary\'s basis in her stock as of December 31, 2024, was $25,000 before recording the loss. What can Mary do with the disallowed loss of $25,000?','[\"Carry back the loss 3 years to offset any personal taxes paid.\",\"Carry forward the loss indefinitely for use if her basis in her stock is sufficiently restored.\",\"Nothing. There is no provision for using disallowed losses from an S corporation, in any other tax year but that in which the loss occurred.\",\"Mary does not have a disallowed loss and can use the full $50,000 loss in the 2024 tax year.\"]',1,'A shareholder\'s distributive share of loss from an S corporation is limited to the shareholder\'s stock basis in that corporation. Therefore, losses that exceed a shareholder\'s basis are disallowed for that year. Disallowed losses are carried forward indefinitely for use subject to the basis limit for that year.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(837,13,'On December 1, 2023, Raoul, a 55% shareholder in R & B, Inc., an S corporation, elected to terminate R & B\'s status as an S corporation, effective on January 1, 2024. It continued to operate as a C corporation. What would be the earliest date that it could again elect S status without IRS consent?','[\"January 1, 2025\",\"December 1, 2028\",\"January 1, 2029\",\"Since election to terminate S status requires 100% of the outstanding shareholders\' consent, Raoul cannot make the election by himself.\"]',2,'An S election may be revoked only with the consent of shareholders who hold more than 50% of the number of issued and outstanding shares of stock (including nonvoting stock) at the time revocation is made. The revocation may specify an effective revocation date that is on or after the day the revocation is filed:nnIf no date is specified, the revocation is effective at the start of a tax year, if the revocation is made on or before the 15th day of the 3rd month of that tax year.nIf no date is specified, the revocation is effective at the start of the next tax year, if the revocation is made after the 15th day of the 3rd month of the tax year.nAfter an S election has been terminated, the corporation (or a successor corporation) can make another election on Form 2553 only with IRS consent for any tax year before the 5th tax year after the 1st tax year in which the termination took effect.nnTherefore, the S election revocation is effective on January 1, 2024, and the earliest date at which R & B could re-elect S status without IRS consent is January 1, 2029.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(838,13,'An S corporation stockholder\'s basis is generally increased by:','[\"distributions.\",\"taxable income.\",\"separately stated loss items.\",\"nontaxable discharge of indebtedness.\"]',1,'Shareholder basis starts with the initial capital contribution to the S corporation, or the initial cost of stock purchased from the S corporation. That amount is increased by ordinary income, separately stated income items, tax-exempt income, and excess depletion. Shareholder basis is decreased by ordinary losses, separately stated loss items, nondeductible expenses, non-dividend distributions, and depletion for oil and gas.nnThe correct answer is taxable income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(839,13,'Generally, all of the following entities may use the cash method of accounting, except:','[\"a farming corporation with gross receipts of $30 million (indexed for inflation) or less.\",\"an entity with no inventories and average annual gross receipts of $30 million (indexed for inflation) or less.\",\"a qualified personal service corporation.\",\"a corporation that has a significant purpose to avoid federal income taxes.\"]',3,'Page 8 of Publication 538 indicates that most individuals and many small businesses use the cash method of accounting. If, however, a taxpayer produces, purchases, or sells merchandise, the taxpayer must keep an inventory and use an accrual method for sales and purchases of merchandise.nnIn addition, some entities are prohibited (or excluded) from using the cash method (Publication 538, page 9), including any combination of methods that includes the cash method. More specifically:nna corporation (other than an S corporation) with average annual gross receipts exceeding $30 million in 2024 (indexed for inflation) unless it meets the gross receipts test,na partnership with a corporation (other than an S corporation) as a partner, and with the partnership having average annual gross receipts exceeding $30 million in 2024 (indexed for inflation) unless it meets the gross receipts test, orna tax shelter as defined in Section 448(d)(3).nA corporation or partnership (not a tax shelter) meets the gross receipts test if its average annual gross receipts for the 3 preceding tax years were $30 million or less for 2024 (indexed for inflation) for each prior tax year. An entity\'s average annual gross receipts for a prior tax year are determined by adding the gross receipts for that tax year and the 2 preceding tax years and then dividing by 3.nnThere are special exceptions to the exclusion rules. A qualified personal service corporation is not prohibited from using the cash method of accounting. (Publication 538, pages 9 and 10)nnIn addition, a taxpayer engaged in the trade or business of farming is allowed to use the cash method for its farming business. However, certain corporations (other than S corporations) and partnerships that have a partner that is a corporation must use an accrual method for their farming business, unless they meet the gross receipts test. (Publication 538, page 9)nnAs given in Publication 225, page 6, the following businesses, if engaged in farming, must use an accrual method of accounting:nnA corporation that has gross receipts of more than $30 million (adjusted for inflation in Publication 225)nA partnership with a corporation as a partner, if that corporation meets the requirements of (1) abovenA tax shelter.nAs a result, a corporation that has a significant purpose to avoid federal income tax is a tax shelter; as such, it is not permitted to use the cash method.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(840,13,'Which of the following entities must file a Form 8832, Entity Classification Election, in order to be taxed as a corporation for federal tax purposes?','[\"An insurance company\",\"A limited liability company\",\"A business wholly owned by a state or local government\",\"Certain foreign businesses\"]',1,'The rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation. The following businesses formed after 1996 are taxed as corporations:nnA business formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as incorporated as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnA business formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state or local governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Internal Revenue Code (for example, certain publicly traded partnerships)nCertain foreign businessesnAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporation (e.g., a limited liability company) by filing Form 8832nFor more information, see the instructions in Form 8832.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(841,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a business that is not operated for the purpose of making a profit?','[\"Any expenses resulting to the business cannot be used to offset any income from the business.\",\"Any loss resulting to the business cannot be used to offset income from salaries and wages in the current year.\",\"Any loss resulting to the business can be carried forward for 5 years.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 525, page 32, provides, in part, that if a taxpayer does not carry on a business or investment activity to make a profit, there is a limit on the deductions that he or she can take. That is, a taxpayer cannot use a loss from the activity to offset other income. Activities done as a hobby, or mainly for sport or recreation, are often not entered into for profit. Other income would include wages and salaries that the taxpayer receives.nnThe limit on not-for-profit losses applies to individuals, partnerships, estates, trusts, and S corporations. It does not apply to corporations other than S corporations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(842,13,'The Pine Tree Partnership produces and sells toys. It had gross receipts of $30,000,000 in 2024. It had gross receipts of $17,500,000 in 2021, $30,000,000 in 2022, and $42,500,000 in 2023. Which of the following statements is correct for Pine Tree?','[\"The taxpayer may use the cash method of accounting for 2024.\",\"The taxpayer is not a qualifying small business for 2024.\",\"The taxpayer is not required to account for their inventory.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Publication 538, page 13, provides, in part, that an inventory is necessary to clearly show income when the production, purchase, or sale of merchandise is an income-producing factor. In such cases, the taxpayer must account for an inventory in their business by use of the accrual method for purchases and sales.nnSome taxpayers, however, can use the cash method of accounting if they are a small business taxpayer but they must still use a method of accounting for inventory that clearly reflects income. These taxpayers are a qualifying small business taxpayer if:nnaverage annual gross receipts of $30 million or less (indexed for inflation) for the three prior tax years, andnthe taxpayer\'s business is not a tax shelter as defined under IRC Section 448(d)(3).nIn this case, Pine Tree is required to account for their inventory because their production and sale of toys, as their merchandise, is an income-producing factor. However, they would be able (not required) to use the cash basis of accounting for 2024 under the tests for a qualifying small business taxpayer since its average annual gross receipts for the prior three tax years (2021, 2022, and 2023) are $30 million or less (($17,500,000 + $30,000,000 + $42,500,000) ÷ 3).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(843,13,'Which of the following rules is not correct for establishing a partnership\'s tax year if one or more partners in a partnership have different tax years?','[\"If there is no partner or partners with a majority interest tax year, the partnership must use the tax year of all its principal partners.\",\"If there is no majority interest tax year and the principal partners do not have the same tax year, the partnership generally must use a tax year that results in the most aggregate deferral of income to the partners.\",\"If one or more partners having the same tax year own an interest in partnership profits and capital of more than 50%, the partnership must use the tax year of those partners.\",\"If a partnership\'s majority interest tax year changes, it will not be required to change to another tax year for 2 years following the year of change.\"]',1,'A partnership generally must conform its tax year to its partners\' tax years. The rules for determining the required tax year are as follows:nnMajority tax year. If one or more partners having the same tax year own an interest in partnership profits and capital of more than 50% (a majority interest), the partnership must use the tax year of those partners.nTesting day. The partnership determines that there is a majority tax year on the testing day, which is usually the 1st day of the partnership\'s current tax year or the days during such representative period as the Secretary of the Treasury may prescribe.nChange in tax year. If a partnership\'s majority tax year changes, it will not be required to change to another tax year for 2 years following the year of change. (See IRC Section 706(b)(4) for the definition of majority interest taxable year.)nIf there is no majority tax year, the partnership must use the tax year common to all of its principal partners. A principal partner is one who has a 5% or more interest in the profits or capital of the partnership.nIf there is no majority tax year and the principal partners do not have a tax year common to all principal partners, the partnership generally must use a tax year that results in the least (not most) aggregate deferral of income to the partners.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(844,13,'Which of the following situations does not require an employer to have an employer identification number (EIN)?','[\"A taxpayer that files a pension tax return\",\"A taxpayer that pays wages to one or more employees\",\"A taxpayer that files an excise tax return\",\"All of the answer choices require an EIN.\"]',3,'Publication 334, page 6, states that a taxpayer must also have an employer identification number (EIN) to use as a taxpayer identification number if the taxpayer either pays wages to one or more employees or files pension or excise tax returns.nnThe taxpayer who must have an EIN, must include it along with their SSN on Schedule C as instructed.nnAs a result, all of the taxpayers in this problem require an EIN.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(845,13,'Which of the following is not an acceptable inventory practice?','[\"You claim a casualty or theft loss of inventory through the increase in the cost of goods sold by properly reporting your opening and closing inventories.\",\"To properly value inventory at cost, reduce the invoice price of inventory by a trade discount.\",\"Under the lower of cost or market method, compare the market value of each item on hand on the inventory date with its cost and use the lower of the two as its inventory value.\",\"To properly value inventory at cost, include only the direct costs associated with each item.\"]',3,'To properly value inventory under the cost method, a taxpayer must include all direct and indirect costs associated with it:nnFor merchandise on hand at the beginning of the tax year, cost means the ending inventory price of the goods.nFor merchandise purchased during the year, cost means the invoice price minus appropriate discounts plus transportation or other charges incurred in acquiring the goods. It can also include other costs that have to be capitalized under the uniform capitalization rules.nFor merchandise produced during the year, cost means all direct and indirect costs that have to be capitalized under the uniform capitalization rules.nYou can claim a casualty or theft loss of inventory through the increase in the cost of goods sold by properly reporting the opening and closing inventories. The loss cannot be claimed again as a casualty or theft loss. Alternatively, you can choose to claim the loss separately as a casualty or theft loss. In this case, you must adjust opening inventory or purchases to eliminate the loss items and avoid counting the loss twice (Publication 538, page 16).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(846,13,'What is the classification for federal income tax purposes of a domestic LLC with at least two members that does not file Form 8832?','[\"C corporation\",\"Partnership\",\"S corporation\",\"LLC\"]',1,'Publication 541, pages 2 and 3, state that a limited liability company (LLC) is an entity formed under state law and, unlike a partnership, none of the members of an LLC are personally liable for its debts. An LLC may be classified for federal income tax purposes as a partnership, a corporation, or an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner. See Form 8832 and Treasury Regulation Section 301.7701-3 for more details.nnA domestic LLC with at least two members that does not file Form 8832 is classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(847,13,'When must a taxpayer adopt his or her first tax year?','[\"By the due date including extensions for filing a return\",\"By filing his or her first income tax return by the due date (including extensions) for filing a return for that year\",\"By December 31\",\"By the due date excluding extensions for filing a return\"]',1,'A taxpayer adopts a tax year by filing his or her first income tax return by the due date (including extensions) for filing a return for that year. Some taxpayers have a required tax year that is required under the IRC or the regulations. A taxpayer cannot adopt a tax year by merely filing an application for an extension, filing for an employer identification number (EIN), or by paying estimated taxes.nnA tax year is an annual accounting period for keeping records and reporting income and expenses. It may be a calendar year or a fiscal year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(848,13,'All of the following statements are correct, except:','[\"you adopt a tax year when you file your first tax return, and you must adopt your first tax year by the due date (including extensions) for filing a return.\",\"a tax year is an annual accounting period for keeping records and reporting income and expenses.\",\"a taxpayer can elect a 52-53\\u2013week tax year.\",\"a taxpayer can elect a calendar tax year.\"]',0,'It is not correct to say that a taxpayer must adopt their first tax year by the due date including extensions for filing a return. Rather, unless a taxpayer has a required tax year, the taxpayer adopts a tax year by filing their first income tax return using that tax year.nnA tax year is an annual accounting period for keeping records and reporting income and expenses. The tax years that a taxpayer can use are:nna fiscal year (including a 52-53–week tax year) orna calendar tax year.nA taxpayer cannot adopt a tax year by merely:nnfiling an application for an extension of time to file an income tax return,nfiling an application for an employer identification number (EIN), ornpaying estimated taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(849,13,'Which of the following dates would not be considered the end of a tax year?','[\"The last Friday in June\",\"September 30, 2024\",\"April 15, 2024\",\"December 31, 2024\"]',2,'Pages 2 and 3 of Publication 538 discuss the various tax periods. A calendar year is 12 consecutive months beginning January 1 and ending December 31. A fiscal year is 12 consecutive months ending on the last day of any month except December. A 52-53–week tax year is a fiscal year that varies from 52 to 53 weeks but may not end on the last day of a month. Under this election, the 52-53–week tax year must always end on the same day of the week. That is, the 52-53–week tax year must always end on:nnwhatever date this same day of the week last occurs in a calendar month ornwhatever date this same day of the week falls that is nearest to the last day of the calendar month.nGiven the above information, April 15 would not be considered the end of a tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(850,13,'What is the tax rate that applies to capital gain income for a condominium management homeowners association that files its tax return on Form 1120-H?','[0.1499999999999999944488848768742172978818416595458984375,0.299999999999999988897769753748434595763683319091796875,0.320000000000000006661338147750939242541790008544921875,0.34999999999999997779553950749686919152736663818359375]',1,'Pages 1 and 2 of the instructions for Form 1120-H provides that the taxable income of a homeowners association that files its tax return on Form 1120-H is taxed at a flat rate of:nn30% for condominium management associations and residential real estate associations andn32% for timeshare associations.nThese rates apply to both ordinary and capital gains income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(851,13,'The Rising Moon Partnership with a fiscal year ending March 31 terminated the partnership on January 31, 2024. If no extension is filed by Rising Moon, by what date must they file their final Form 1065, U.S. Return of Partnership Income?','[\"February 15, 2024\",\"March 15, 2024\",\"April 15, 2024\",\"May 15, 2024\"]',2,'If a partnership is terminated before the end of the tax year, Form 1065 must be filed for the short period, which is the period from the beginning of the tax year through the date of termination. The return is due on the 15th day of the 3rd month following the date of termination.nnIn this case, the partnership is terminated on January 31 and thus it must file a short form by April 15 of the same year, which is the 15th day of the 3rd month following January 31.nnConsequently, the correct response in this particular case is April 15, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(852,13,'A partnership, S corporation, or personal service corporation (PSC) can elect to use a tax year other than its required tax year if it:','[\"elects a year that meets the deferral period requirement.\",\"is not a member of a tiered structure as defined by the regulations.\",\"has not previously had an election in effect to use a tax year other than its required tax year.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 538, page 6, provides that a partnership, S corporation, electing S corporation, or personal service corporation (PSC) can elect under IRC Section 444 to use a tax year other than its required tax year if it satisfies certain restrictions.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nA partnership or S corporation that makes a Section 444 election must make certain required payments and a PSC must make certain distributions. The Section 444 election does not apply to any partnership, S corporation, or PSC that establishes a business purpose for a different period.nn n nnA partnership, S corporation, or PSC can make a Section 444 election if it meets all of the following requirements:nnIt is not a member of a tiered structure (defined in Regulation Section 1.444-2T).nIt has not previously had a Section 444 election in effect.nIt elects a year that meets the deferral period requirement.nIn this problem, all of the answer choices are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(853,13,'Certain partnerships that do not actively conduct a business can elect to be completely or partially excluded from being treated as a partnership for federal tax purposes. Which of the following conditions qualifies for such treatment?','[\"If at least 75% of the partners agree to the election\",\"If at least 80% of the partners agree to the election\",\"If at least 95% of the partners agree to the election\",\"If 100% of the partners agree to the election\"]',3,'Publication 541, page 4, provides, in part, that partnerships that do not actively conduct a business can choose to be completely or partially excluded from being treated as partnerships for federal income tax purposes. To qualify for such treatment, all of the partners (not a percentage of the partners) must agree to make the choice, and the partners must be able to compute their own taxable income without computing the partnership\'s income.nnOne should realize, however, that the partners are not exempt from the rule that limits a partner\'s distributive share of partnership loss to the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. Nor are they exempt from the requirement of a business purpose for adopting a tax year for the partnership that differs from its required tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(854,13,'Which of the following types of domestic business entities, formed after 1996, generally is taxed as a partnership unless it files Form 8832?','[\"A two-member limited liability company (LLC)\",\"A business formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock association\",\"A business formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as a corporation, body corporate, or body politic\",\"A business wholly owned by a state or local government\"]',0,'Publication 541, pages 2 and 3, states that a limited liability company (LLC) is an entity formed under state law and, unlike a partnership, none of the members of an LLC are personally liable for its debts. An LLC may be classified for federal income tax purposes as a partnership, a corporation, or an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner.nnA two-member limited liability company will be classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes unless it elects to be classified as a corporation or was formed before 1997 and was taxed as a corporation.nnThe rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation. The following businesses, for example, formed after 1996 are taxed as corporations:nnAn organization formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as incorporated as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnAn organization formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state, local, or foreign governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Internal Revenue Code (for example, certain publicly traded partnerships)nCertain foreign organizations identified in Regulation Section 301.7701-2(b)(8)nA tax-exempt organizationnA real estate investment trustnAn organization classified as a trust under Regulation Section 301.7701-4 or otherwise subject to special treatment under the Internal Revenue CodenAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832nFor more information, see the instructions in Form 8832 on pages 4 and 5.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(855,13,'Which of the following types of domestic business entities, formed after 1996, need not be taxed as a corporation?','[\"A business formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock association\",\"Any business that elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832\",\"A business entity that has publicly traded shares or ownership interests\",\"A business wholly owned by a state or local government\"]',2,'The rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation. The following businesses formed after 1996 are taxed as corporations:nnAn organization formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as incorporated as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnAn organization formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state or local governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Internal Revenue Code (e.g., certain publicly traded partnerships)nCertain foreign businessesnAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832 (e.g., a limited liability company (LLC))nThe only answer choice that is not specifically required to be taxed as a corporation is a business entity that has publicly traded shares or ownership interests.nnFor more information, see the instructions in Form 8832.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(856,13,'What is the filing date for Form 1120-H by an association?','[\"Apr-15\",\"15th day of the 4th month after the end of the association\'s tax year.\",\"15th day of the 5th month after the end of the association\'s tax year.\",\"15th day of the 6th month after the end of the association\'s tax year.\"]',1,'The instructions for Form 1120-H, pages 2 through 4, provide that an association must file Form 1120-H by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of the association\'s tax year. However, an association with a fiscal year ending June 30 must file by the 15th day of 3rd month after the end of its tax year. Also, the liability cannot be included with the tax return. Rather, it must be deposited using EFTPS (Electronic Federal Tax Payment System) or by its tax professional, financial institution, payroll service, or other trusted third party to make deposits on its behalf.nnAn association can file Form 7004, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns, to request a 6-month extension of time to file or a 7-month extension of time with a fiscal year ending June 30.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(857,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a qualifying small business taxpayer in 2024?','[\"The taxpayer can use the cash method of accounting even if he or she produces, purchases, or sells merchandise.\",\"The taxpayer\'s business is a tax shelter.\",\"The taxpayer must meet the gross receipts test of $5 million or less for each of the 3 prior tax years.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Publication 334, page 15, provides, in part, that if a taxpayer produces, purchases, or sells merchandise in his or her business, the taxpayer must keep an inventory and use the accrual method for purchases and sales of merchandise.nnSome taxpayers, however, can use the cash method of accounting even if they produce, purchase, or sell merchandise by accounting for inventoriable items as materials and supplies that are not incidental. These taxpayers are a qualifying small business taxpayer if:nnaverage annual gross receipts of $30 million or less for the three prior tax years; andnthe taxpayer\'s business is not a tax shelter as defined under IRC Section 448(d)(3).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(858,13,'New ABC Partnership is organized in 2024 with three general partners. The partners include a corporation with a tax year ending on March 31 and a 60% interest in partnership capital and profits, and two individuals, each having a calendar tax year and a 20% interest in partnership capital and profits. The partnership\'s required tax year ends on:','[\"March 31.\",\"September 30.\",\"October 31.\",\"December 31.\"]',0,'A partnership generally must conform its tax year to its partners\' tax years. The rules for determining the required tax year are as follows:nnMajority interest tax year is adopted if one or more partners having the same tax year own an interest in partnership profits and capital of more than 50% (a majority interest).nPrincipal partner tax year is adopted if there is no majority interest tax year; a principal partner is one who has a 5% or more interest in the profits or capital of the partnership.nLeast aggregate deferral of income is adopted if there is no majority interest tax year and the principal partners do not have the same tax year; the partnership generally must use a tax year that results in the least aggregate deferral of income to the partners.nSince the corporation has the majority interest in the partnership, its tax year of March 31 is adopted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(859,13,'Given the fact patterns below, which of the following entities may not use the cash method of accounting?','[\"The Acme Partnership had gross receipts of $18.5 million in 2023. Its gross receipts for 2022 were $41 million and its gross receipts for 2021 were $10.5 million.\",\"John Jones manufactures and sells fans. His average annual gross receipts from 2021 to 2023 are $28,000,000.\",\"Dallas Partnership has two partners since 2021\\u2014Joe Dallas, an individual, and Deer, Inc., a corporation. Dallas Partnership averaged annual gross receipts from 2021 to 2023 of $36 million.\",\"John Gibb files his 2024 Form 1040 with an attached Schedule C reflecting $31 million in gross receipts from selling real estate.\"]',2,'Most individuals and many small businesses use the cash method of accounting. Generally, however, if a taxpayer produces, purchases, or sells merchandise, the taxpayer must keep an inventory and use an accrual method for sales and purchases of merchandise (Publication 538, page 8).nnThe following entities cannot use the cash method; including any combination of methods that include the cash method (see Publication 538, page 9):nnA corporation (other than an S corporation) with average annual gross receipts for the three preceding tax years exceeding $30 million for 2024 (indexed for inflation).nA partnership with a corporation (other than an S corporation) as a partner and with the partnership having average annual gross receipts for the three preceding tax years exceeding $30 million (indexed for inflation). This is the situation for Dallas Partnership.nA tax shelter, as defined in Section 448(d)(3).nAn entity\'s average annual gross receipts are determined by adding the gross receipts for the 3 preceding tax years, and dividing the total by 3.nnIn the case where a taxpayer must account for inventories (e.g., production, purchase, or sale of merchandise is an income-producing factor), the accrual method is required unless the taxpayer satisfies the qualifying small business taxpayer exceptions (see Publication 538, pages 13 and 14).nnA qualifying small business taxpayer satisfies the gross receipts test with average annual gross receipts of $30 million or less for 2024 (indexed for inflation) for the 3 prior tax years (e.g., John Jones).nnA qualifying small business taxpayer satisfies the gross receipts test with average annual gross receipts of $30 million or less for 2024 (indexed for inflation) (e.g., Acme).nnFinally, John Gibb qualifies to use the cash method because real estate held for sale by a real estate dealer in the ordinary course of business is not included as inventory (see Publication 538, page 14).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(860,13,'Which of the following statements is not correct?','[\"Under an accrual method of accounting, you generally report income in the year earned and deduct or capitalize expenses in the year incurred.\",\"Under an accrual method of accounting, you generally report receipt of an advance payment for services to be performed in a later tax year as income in the year you receive the payment.\",\"Under an accrual method of accounting, business expenses and interest owed to a related person who uses the cash method of accounting are deductible when the \\u201call-events test\\u201d has been met.\",\"Under an accrual method of accounting, you can generally take a current deduction for taxes when economic performance occurs.\"]',2,'Pages 10 through 13 of Publication 538 provide responses to a number of the issues pertaining to the accrual method of accounting. First, a taxpayer generally reports income in the year earned and deducts or capitalizes expenses in the year incurred under an accrual method of accounting. The purpose of an accrual method of accounting is to match income and expenses in the correct year (Publication 538, page 10).nnSecond, and the response for this question, business expenses and interest owed to a related person who uses the cash method of accounting are not deductible when the all-events test is satisfied, but rather when the payment is made and the corresponding amount is includible in the related person\'s gross income (Publication 538, page 13).nnThird, a taxpayer generally includes an advance payment for services to be performed in a later tax year as income in the year in which it is received (Publication 538, page 10).nnFinally, a taxpayer can generally deduct or capitalize a business expense when the all-events test has been met, which is that all events have occurred that fix the fact of liability and the liability can be determined with reasonable accuracy, and when economic performance has occurred. In this case, a taxpayer can deduct taxes when economic performance has occurred, which generally occurs as estimated income tax, property taxes, employment taxes, etc. are paid (Publication 538, pages 12–13).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(861,13,'Which of the following types of domestic business entities, formed after 1996, must be taxed as a corporation?n1. An associationn2. An insurance companyn3. Any business formed under state law that refers to itself as a corporationn4. A single-member limited liability company','[\"1, 2, and 3 only\",\"3 only\",\"2 and 3 only\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'The rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation. The following businesses formed after 1996 are taxed as corporations:nnAn organization formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as incorporated as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnAn organization formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state or local governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Internal Revenue Code (for example, certain publicly traded partnerships)nCertain foreign businessesnAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832nFor more information, see the instructions in Form 8832.nnAdditionally, a two-member limited liability company may be classified for federal income tax purposes as either a partnership or a corporation.nnA business entity with a single member such as a single-member limited liability company can choose to be classified as either an association taxable as a corporation or disregarded as an entity separate from its owner.nnAs a result, the following types of domestic business entities, formed after 1996, must be taxed as a corporation in the above question: an association, an insurance company, and any business formed under state law that refers to itself as a corporation.nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(862,13,'Which of the following business entities generally would be taxed as a corporation today?','[\"A business entity formed before 1997 that was taxed as a corporation\",\"A business entity formed under federal or state law that refers to it as a corporation\",\"An insurance company\",\"All of the answer choices generally would be taxed as a corporation.\"]',3,'The rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation.nnThe following businesses formed after 1996 would be taxed as corporations:nnA business entity formed under federal or state law that refers to it as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnA business entity formed under state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state or local governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Code (e.g., certain publicly traded partnerships)nCertain foreign businessesnAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporationnFor more information, see Publication 542, pages 2 and 3, and the instructions on page 4 of Form 8832.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(863,13,'In determining whether you are carrying on an activity for profit, several factors are taken into account. All of the following are factors to consider, except:','[\"you are carrying on two different business activities. When you combine the income and expenses together, you have a net profit.\",\"your losses are due to circumstances beyond your control.\",\"you can expect to make a future profit from the appreciation of the assets used in the activity.\",\"you were successful in making a profit in similar activities in the past.\"]',0,'Publication 525, page 32, provides, in part, that if a taxpayer does not carry on a business or investment activity to make a profit, there is a limit on the deductions that he or she can take. That is, a taxpayer cannot use a loss from the activity to offset other income.nnIn determining whether a taxpayer is carrying on an activity for profit, several factors are considered. No one factor alone is decisive. Among the factors to consider are whether:nnthe taxpayer carries on the activity in a businesslike manner,nthe time and effort put into the activity indicate the taxpayer\'s intent to make it profitable,nthe taxpayer depends on income from the activity for his or her livelihood,nthe taxpayer\'s losses are due to circumstances beyond his or her control (or are normal in the start-up phase of this type of business),nthe taxpayer changes the methods of operation in an attempt to improve profitability,nthe taxpayer, or advisors, have the knowledge needed to carry on the activity as a successful business,nthe taxpayer was successful in making a profit in similar activities in the past,nthe activity makes a profit in some years, andnthe taxpayer can expect to make a future profit from the appreciation of the assets used in the activity.nThe only item in this problem that is not listed above as a factor to consider is when a taxpayer is carrying on two different business activities.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(864,13,'Which of the following is classified as exempt function income included in assessments for association property?','[\"Payments from nonmembers\",\"Interest on amounts in a sinking fund\",\"Maintenance costs of association property\",\"Members\' payments for transportation\"]',2,'Exempt function income consists of membership dues, fees, or assessments from owners of condominium housing units; owners of real property in the case of a residential real estate management association; or owners of timeshare rights to use, or timeshare ownership interests in, real property in the case of a timeshare association. The instructions for Form 1120-H, page 2, provides that the exempt function income includes assessments made to:nnpay principal, interest, and real estate taxes on association property,nmaintain association property, andnclear snow from public areas and remove trash.nIncome that is not exempt function income includes:nnamounts that are not includible in the organization\'s gross income other than under Section 528 (e.g., tax-exempt interest),npayments from nonmembers,npayment from members for special use of the organization\'s facilities, apart from the use generally available to all members,ninterest on amounts in a sinking fund,npayments for work done on nonassociation property, andnmembers\' payments for transportation.nFor more information on this topic, see Regulation Section 1.528-9.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(865,13,'A domestic limited liability company with at least two members that does not file Form 8832, Entity Classification Election, is classified as:','[\"an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner by applying the rules in Regulation Section 301.7701-3.\",\"a partnership.\",\"a corporation.\",\"a non-entity that requires members to report the income and related expenses on Form 1040.\"]',1,'A limited liability company (LLC) is an entity formed under state law by filing articles of organization as an LLC. Unlike a partnership, none of the members of an LLC are personally liable for its debts.nnThe instructions for Form 1065, page 3, state that a domestic LLC with at least two members that does not file Form 8832 is classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(866,13,'Which of the following types of domestic business entities, formed after 1996, generally is taxed as a partnership unless it elects to be classified as a corporation?','[\"A two-member limited liability company (LLC)\",\"A business formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock association\",\"An insurance company\",\"A business wholly owned by a state or local government\"]',0,'Publication 541, pages 2 and 3, states that a limited liability company (LLC) is an entity formed under state law and, unlike a partnership, none of the members of an LLC are personally liable for its debts. An LLC may be classified for federal income tax purposes as a partnership, a corporation, or an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner.nnA two-member limited liability company will be classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes unless it elects to be classified as a corporation (Form 8832) or was formed before 1997 and was taxed as a corporation. (Publication 541, pages 2 and 3)nnFor more information, see the instructions in Form 8832 on pages 4 and 5.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(867,13,'Partnership XYZ was formed on September 15, 2024, and elected to use a fiscal year ending November 30. Partnership XYZ was required to file its return by which of the following dates?','[\"December 31, 2024\",\"January 15, 2025\",\"February 15, 2025\",\"April 15, 2025\"]',2,'The instructions for Form 1065 provide that the due date for filing Form 1065 is generally March 15 following the close of the partnership\'s tax year if its accounting period is the calendar year. A fiscal-year partnership generally must file its return by the 15th day of the 3rd month following the close of its fiscal year.nnSince the partnership in this problem has elected November 30 as its fiscal year-end, their return is due by February 15, 2025, which is the 15th day of the 3rd month following November 30, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(868,13,'Eric, a cash basis taxpayer, owned 25% of Watson, Inc., stock. Watson files a calendar-year Form 1120, U.S. Corporation Income Tax Return, employing the accrual method of accounting. Eric loaned Watson $100,000 at the beginning of 2023. The accrued interest on this loan was $5,000 as of December 31, 2023. Watson paid Eric the $5,000 in January 2024. How should Eric report the interest income and Watson, Inc., report the interest expense from this transaction?','[\"Watson, Inc., reports the expense in 2023 and Eric reports the income in 2023.\",\"Watson, Inc., reports the expense in 2023 and Eric reports the income in 2024.\",\"Watson, Inc., reports the expense in 2024 and Eric reports the income in 2024.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 538 (page 13) stipulates that business expenses and interest owed to a related person who uses the cash method of accounting are not deductible until the taxpayer makes the payment and the corresponding amount is includible in the related person\'s gross income. Determine the relationship for this rule as of the end of the tax year for which the expense or interest would otherwise be deductible.nnIf a deduction is denied, the rule will continue to apply even if the relationship with the person ends before the expense or interest is includible in the gross income of that person. These rules also deny the deduction of losses on the sale of exchange of property between related persons. (Publication 542, page 9)nnFor purposes of this rule, a list is provided on pages 9 and 10 of Publication 542 that details which persons are related. The second item on the list includes an individual and a corporation when the individual owns, directly or indirectly, more than 50% of the value of the outstanding stock of the corporation.nnSince Eric owns less than 50% of Watson, a related party transaction does not exist and therefore the interest would be reported as follows: Watson, Inc., reports the expense in 2023 and Eric reports the income in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(869,13,'The following methods of accounting for inventory are considered acceptable, except:','[\"cost.\",\"first-in, first-out.\",\"last-in, first-out.\",\"trade discount method.\"]',3,'Publication 538, pages 13 through 16, discusses the acceptable methods for valuing inventories. Among the acceptable methods, the taxpayer may select the FIFO (first in, first out), LIFO (last in, first out), cost, LCM (lower of cost or market), or retail method, to name a few.nnA trade discount, on the other hand, would not be an acceptable inventory method because it is a discount allowed against the purchase price regardless of when the payment is made. Generally, it is for volume or quantity purchases. When a taxpayer receives a trade discount, the taxpayer must reduce the cost of inventory by a trade (or quantity) discount. Hence, it is not an inventory valuation method.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(870,13,'Auto Body Express, LLC, a limited liability company, filed Form 1065 for calendar year 2024 on March 15, 2025. The general partner was not available to sign the return, so the in-house tax manager signed the return. The tax manager prepared the return, but is not a limited liability company member. All of the following statements are correct, except:','[\"the partnership has timely filed its tax return.\",\"since the tax manager is not a member of the LLC, the return has not been signed.\",\"since the tax manager is not a member of the LLC, the return has not been signed.\",\"Form 1065 may be signed by a general partner.\"]',0,'Note that this question is asking for the incorrect statement, so \"the partnership has timely filed its tax return\" is the correct (false) answer.nnIn general, every partnership that engages in a trade or business or has gross income must file an information return on Form 1065 showing its income, deductions, and other required information. The partnership return must show the names and addresses of each partner and each partner\'s distributive share of taxable income. (Publication 541, page 4)nnForm 1065 is not considered to be a return unless it is signed. The return must be signed by either a partner or LLC member (Form 1065 Instructions, page 5). When a return is made for a partnership by a receiver, trustee, or assignee, the fiduciary must sign the return, instead of the partner or LLC member, and it must be accompanied by a copy of the order or instructions of the court authorizing signing of the return or form.nnWhen filing an AAR (administrative adjustment request), Form 1065 must be signed by the partnership representative (or the designated individual if the partnership representative is an entity) for the reviewed year.nnSince the tax manager is not a member of the LLC, the return has not been signed; therefore, it is not timely filed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(871,13,'Which of the following situations does not require an employer to have an employer identification number (EIN)?','[\"Any taxpayer that starts a new business\",\"A taxpayer that pays wages to one or more employees\",\"A taxpayer that files pension or excise tax returns\",\"All of the answer choices require an EIN.\"]',0,'Publication 334, page 5, states that a taxpayer must have an employer identification number (EIN) to use as a taxpayer identification number if the taxpayer either pays wages to one or more employees or files pension or excise tax returns.nnThe taxpayer who must have an EIN must include it along with their SSN on Schedule C as instructed.nnTherefore, an EIN is not needed by all new businesses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(872,13,'Which of the following statements is incorrect concerning the conversion from a partnership to an LLC (limited liability company)?','[\"It is not considered a sale, exchange, or liquidation of any partnership interest.\",\"The partnership\'s tax year does not close.\",\"The LLC cannot continue to use the partnership\'s taxpayer identification number.\",\"The conversion may change some of the partners\\u2019 bases in their partnership interests if the partnership has recourse liabilities that become nonrecourse liabilities.\"]',2,'The conversion of a partnership into an LLC classified as a partnership for federal tax purposes does not terminate the partnership. The conversion is not a sale, exchange, or liquidation of any partnership interest; the partnership\'s tax year does not close; and the LLC can continue to use the partnership\'s taxpayer identification number.nnThe conversion, however, may change some of the partners\' bases in their partnership interests if the partnership has recourse liabilities that become nonrecourse liabilities.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(873,13,'Which of the following types of domestic business entities, formed after 1996 cannot be taxed as a corporation?nn1. An insurance companyn2. An associationn3. A limited liability company with two or more active membersn4. An entity that elects to be treated as a real estate mortgage investment conduit','[\"4 only\",\"1, 2, and 4 only\",\"3 only\",\"2 only\"]',0,'The rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation. The following businesses formed after 1996 are taxed as corporations:nnAn organization formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as incorporated as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnAn organization formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state or local governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Internal Revenue Code (for example, certain publicly traded partnerships)nCertain foreign businessesnAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832nFor more information, see the instructions in Form 8832.nnA two-member limited liability company may be classified for federal income tax purposes as either a partnership or a corporation.nnAs a result, the only type of domestic business entity, formed after 1996, that cannot be taxed as a corporation in the above question is an entity that elects to be treated as a real estate mortgage investment conduit (REMIC). (See IRC Section 860A.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(874,13,'Bob Moon forms Moon Enterprises LLC (Limited Liability Company) during the year. What form must Moon Enterprises LLC file in order to elect to be taxed as a C corporation?','[\"Form 1065,\\u00a0U.S. Partnership Tax Return\",\"Form 8832,\\u00a0Entity Classification Election\",\"Form 1120,\\u00a0U.S. Corporation Income Tax Return\",\"Form 7004,\\u00a0Application for Extension of Time to File for Corporations\"]',1,'Publication 541, pages 2 and 3, states that a limited liability company (LLC) is an entity formed under state law and, unlike a partnership, none of the members of an LLC are personally liable for its debts. An LLC may be classified for federal income tax purposes as a partnership, a corporation, or an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner.nnPublication 541, page 3, states, in part, that a domestic LLC with at least two members that does not file Form 8832 is classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes.nnGenerally, an eligible entity that does not file Form 8832 will be classified under the default rules, which holds that a domestic eligible entity is:nna partnership if it has two or more members orndisregarded as an entity separate from its owner if it has a single owner. (Form 8832, page 4)nIn the case of an LLC with one member that is not treated as a corporation, the taxpayer is treated as a sole proprietorship. Hence, Bob Moon would need to file Form 8832 in order to be treated as a corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(875,13,'What percentage of partners needs to agree to an election to be completely or partially excluded from being treated as a partnership for federal tax purposes if the partnership does not actively conduct a business?','[\"100% of the partners must agree to the election.\",\"At least 95% of the partners must agree to the election.\",\"At least 80% of the partners must agree to the election.\",\"At least 75% of the partners must agree to the election.\"]',0,'Publication 541, page 4, provides, in part, that partnerships that do not actively conduct a business can choose to be completely or partially excluded from being treated as partnerships for federal income tax purposes. To qualify for such treatment, all of the partners must agree (i.e., 100%) to make the choice, and the partners must be able to compute their own taxable income without computing the partnership\'s income.nnHowever, one should realize that the partners are not exempt from the rule that limits a partner\'s distributive share of partnership loss to the adjusted basis of the partner\'s partnership interest. Nor are they exempt from the requirement of a business purpose for adopting a tax year for the partnership that differs from its required tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(876,13,'Which of the following tax rates apply to a timeshare association\'s income that files its tax return on Form 1120-H?','[\"15% for capital gain income and 30% for ordinary income\",\"30% for capital gain income and 30% for ordinary income\",\"30% for capital gain income and 32% for ordinary income\",\"32% for capital gain income and 32% for ordinary income\"]',3,'The instructions for Form 1120-H, pages 1 and 2, provide that the taxable income of a homeowners association that files its tax return on Form 1120-H is taxed at a flat rate of:nn30% for condominium management associations and residential real estate associations andn32% for timeshare associations.nThese rates apply to both ordinary and capital gains income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(877,13,'What is the filing date for a tax-exempt organization filing Form 990?','[\"Apr-15\",\"15th day of the 3rd month after the end of the organization\'s tax year\",\"15th day of the 5th month after the end of the organization\'s tax year\",\"15th day of the 6th month after the end of the organization\'s tax year\"]',2,'The instructions for Form 990, page 6, and the instructions for Form 990-EZ, page 5, provide that an exempt organization must file Form 990 or Form 990-EZ by the 15th day of the 5th month after the end of the organization\'s tax year. In the case of a calendar-year organization, the filing date would be May 15. If the regular due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, it should be filed on the next business day.nnIf the organization is liquidated, dissolved, or terminated, it should be filed by the 15th day of the 5th month after liquidation, dissolution, or termination.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(878,13,'A newly formed single-member domestic limited liability company (LLC) is eligible to file an election to be taxed as a:','[\"disregarded entity or a partnership.\",\"partnership or a corporation.\",\"corporation or a disregarded entity.\",\"trust or partnership.\"]',2,'The instructions for Form 1065, page 3, provides a general discussion of a limited liability company (LLC). An LLC is an entity formed under state law by filing articles of organization as an LLC. Unlike a partnership, none of the members of an LLC are personally liable for its debts. An LLC may be classified for federal income tax purposes as a partnership, a corporation, or an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner by applying the rules in Regulation Section 301.7701-3. See Form 8832 and Regulation Section 301.7701-3 for more details.nnA domestic LLC with at least two members that does not file Form 8832 (i.e., election to be taxed as a corporation or a disregarded entity) is classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes. Per the instructions on page 4 of Form 8832, a single-owner LLC is by default an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner unless an election to be taxed as a corporation is made. Hence, the correct response for this question is an LLC is eligible to file an election to be taxed as a corporation or a disregarded entity.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(879,13,'Which of the following business entities would not be taxed as a corporation today for federal income tax purposes unless specifically elected otherwise using Form 8832?','[\"A single-member limited liability company\",\"An insurance company\",\"Certain banks\",\"A business entity formed under federal or state law that refers to it as a corporation\"]',0,'For federal income tax purposes, a limited liability company (LLC) may be classified either as a partnership, a corporation, or an entity disregarded as an entity separate from its owner by applying the rules in Regulation Section 301.7701-3. A two-member LLC will be classified as a partnership for federal income tax purposes unless it elects to be classified as a corporation or was formed before 1997 and was taxed as a corporation. (Publication 541, pages 2 and 3)nnPursuant to Publication 334, page 3, a single-member LLC is generally disregarded as an entity separate from its owner and reports its income and deductions on its owner\'s federal income tax return (i.e., Schedule C) unless an election is made to treat the LLC as a corporation.nnExcept for a business entity automatically classified as a corporation, a business entity with at least two members can choose to be classified as either a corporation or a partnership. (Instructions for Form 1065, page 10)nnThe following businesses, for example, as noted on page 2 of Publication 541, formed after 1996 would be taxed as corporations:nnA business entity formed under federal or state law that refers to it as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnA business entity formed under federal or state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state, local, or foreign government',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(880,13,'','[\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"]',0,'',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(881,13,'James Williams is the sole shareholder of Crystal Ball Enterprises, Inc. He received $100 dividend distribution from his corporation for the current tax year. Current earnings of Crystal Ball were $1,000. What reporting requirements apply to this distribution?','[\"No reporting requirements apply because the distribution is less than $600.\",\"No reporting requirements apply because the distribution is not taxable.\",\"Form 1099-DIV should be filed because the distribution is a dividend and is at least $10.\",\"Form 1099-MISC should be filed to report miscellaneous income.\"]',2,'A corporation is required to issue Form 1099-DIV to each person:nnto whom they have paid dividends (including capital gains dividends and exempt-interest dividends) and other distributions on stock of $10 or more,nfor whom they have withheld and paid any foreign tax on dividends and other distributors on stock,nfor whom they have withheld any federal income tax on dividends under the backup withholding rules, ornto whom they have paid $600 or more as part of a liquidation.nThus, Crystal Ball Enterprises, Inc., is required to issue Form 1099-DIV as a result of the first item on the list above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(882,13,'Weal, Inc., had taxable income in 2024 of $10,000. Due to a downturn in its core business operations, Weal isn\'t sure if they are expected to make estimated tax payments for the 2025 tax year. Which of the following statements is correct concerning Weal making estimated tax payments for the 2025 tax year?','[\"Weal must make installment payments of estimated tax because the company had taxable income in the prior year.\",\"Weal must make installment payments of estimated tax if the company expects income to be $500 or more for 2025.\",\"Weal must make installment payments of estimated tax if the company expects estimated tax to be $500 or more for 2025.\",\"Weal must make installment payments of estimated tax if the company expects income or taxable income to be $500 or more for 2025.\"]',2,'Generally, a corporation is required to make installment payments if the estimated tax (not estimated income) is $500 or more. If the corporation does not pay the installments when they are due, it could be subject to an underpayment penalty.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(883,13,'Charles Watson owns 100% of the outstanding shares of Watson Corporation. Charles acquired these shares in 2018 for $5,000. Watson Corporation had total earnings and profits at the end of 2024 of $10,000. On December 31, 2024, Watson Corporation distributed $8,000 in cash and property with a fair market value of $7,000 to Charles. In 2024, how much in capital gain must Charles Watson report from this distribution?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$15,000\"]',0,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). Any part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnTherefore, Charles Watson is not required to report any capital gain from this distribution, computed as follows:nn  Cash and Property Received         $15,000n  Less:n  Accumulated Earnings and Profits    10,000 (treated as Dividend)n  Basis (Acquired Stock in 2018n    for $5,000)                        5,000n  Remaining:                         $     0',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(884,13,'Carol Corporation and Brown Corporation are domestic corporations. The Carol Corporation owns 25% of the Brown Corporation. Carol Corporation\'s income from business for tax year 2024 is $500,000, and business expenses are $750,000. In addition to the income from business, Carol Corporation also received dividends from Brown Corporation in the amount of $100,000. Carol Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is:','[\"$50,000.\",\"$65,000.\",\"$100,000.\",\"$25,000.\"]',1,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the Carol Corporation owns 25% (20% or more) of Brown Corporation, the Carol Corporation may take a 65% deduction on the dividends received in 2024 from Brown Corporation.nnTherefore, Carol Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is $65,000 (65% of $100,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(885,13,'Generally, if a new corporation is filing a short-period return with a tax year ending on July 31, it must file its income tax return by:','[\"October 15.\",\"November 15.\",\"December 15.\",\"January 31 of the following year.\"]',1,'Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. A new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends. The IRS will grant a corporation an extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes Form 7004 (Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns) properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(886,13,'Sarah owns all 100 outstanding shares of York Corporation stock. Sarah\'s basis for her stock is $10,000. York Corporation has earnings and profits of $500,000. York Corporation redeems 25 of Sarah\'s shares for $85,000. How does Sarah treat the stock redemption?','[\"Sarah must report an $85,000 long-term capital gain on her individual return.\",\"Sarah must report an $85,000 dividend distribution on her individual return.\",\"Sarah must report an $85,000 short-term capital gain on her individual return.\",\"Sarah does\\u00a0not\\u00a0report the $85,000 gain on her individual return.\"]',1,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either a sale or exchange or a dividend treatment for a shareholder. Accordingly:nnif a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock will be treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder andnif the corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is not comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., disproportionate among shareholders), the redemption will be characterized as a sale or exchange.nBy redeeming the 25 shares of outstanding stock from Sarah, 100% shareholder, York Corporation acted in a manner that was equivalent to a dividend distribution. For that reason, the redemption will be classified as dividend income to the shareholders.nnTherefore, Sarah will report dividend income of $85,000, not a capital gain, on her individual return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(887,13,'Under which of the following situations is a corporation required to make estimated tax payments?','[\"Estimated income is $500 or more.\",\"Estimated income is $1,000 or more.\",\"Estimated tax is $500 or more.\",\"Estimated tax is $1,000 or more.\"]',2,'Generally, a corporation is required to make installment payments if the estimated tax is $500 or more.nnInstallment payments are due by the 15th day of the 4th, 6th, 9th, and 12th months of the corporation\'s tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(888,13,'Wargo Corporation has two equal shareholders, Karen and Bob. Each shareholder owns 10 shares of Wargo stock and has owned the stock for several years. Each share has a $100 basis and a $150 FMV. Wargo, which has sufficient E&P, redeems 5 shares from each shareholder at the $150 FMV. What income, if any, do Karen and Bob each recognize as a result of the redemption of Wargo Corporation stock?','[\"$750 Dividend income\",\"$1,500 Capital gain\",\"$0\",\"$1,000 Dividend income\"]',0,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either sale or exchange or dividend treatment for a shareholder:nnIf a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock will be treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder.nIf the corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is not comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., disproportionate among shareholders), the redemption will be characterized as a sale or exchange.nBy redeeming the 5 shares of stock per shareholder, Wargo Corporation acted in a manner that was equivalent to a dividend distribution. For that reason, the redemption will be classified as dividend income to the shareholders. Therefore, Karen and Bob both will receive $750 in dividend income ($150 × 5 = $750).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(889,13,'Colin Corporation acquired 100% of the Lebeck Corporation stock several years ago for $100,000. In 2024 (the current year), Lebeck Corporation was liquidated, and assets having a $130,000 FMV and $50,000 tax basis were transferred to Colin Corporation. Immediately following the liquidation, Colin Corporation sells the assets for $130,000. What is total gain or loss if any will Colin Corporation realize from the sales of the assets?','[\"$30,000 gain\",\"$80,000 gain\",\"$(50,000) loss\",\"$0 none\"]',1,'IRC Section 332 states, in part, that a corporate shareholder that owns at least 80% of the stock per IRC Section 1504(a)(2) of a subsidiary recognizes neither gain nor loss when it completely liquidates the subsidiary. By not recognizing gain or loss on the receipt of the subsidiary\'s property in complete liquidation, the parent must assume the subsidiary\'s basis in the distributed property.nnTherefore, Colin Corporation will realize a gain of $80,000, which is part Section 1245 recapture and part capital gains. Colin Corporation\'s gain is a result of the subsequent asset sale and not as a result of the merger/liquidation of the acquired Lebeck Corporation. The realized amount is computed as follows:nn Sale Price of Property                 $130,000n Less:n   Lebeck\'s Basis in the Property        (50,000)n Colin Corporation\'s Recognized Gain    $ 80,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(890,13,'If a corporation\'s tax year ends December 31, it generally must file its income tax return by:','[\"June 15 of the following year.\",\"March 15 of the following year.\",\"April 15 of following year.\",\"October 15 of the following year.\"]',2,'Generally, for the tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. A new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends. The IRS will grant a corporation an extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes the form properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnIf the due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the due date for filing is extended to the next business day.nnAccordingly, if a corporation\'s tax year ends December 31, it generally must file its income tax return by April 15 of the following year.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nFor an individual, the filing date is the 15th day of the 4th month.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(891,13,'James Corporation made various payments and transfers to and for its shareholders, Rob and Jim, during the year. Which of the following is not a reportable distribution? (Assume sufficient earnings and profits.)','[\"Monthly cash payments of $500 to Rob\",\"Transfer of stocks held for investment to both Rob and Jim\",\"Use of a company vehicle by Jim\'s daughter at college\",\"Reasonable salary to both Rob and Jim\"]',3,'If a corporation pays an employee who is also a shareholder a salary that is unreasonably high considering the services actually performed by the shareholder-employee, the excessive part of the salary may be treated as a distribution to the shareholder-employee. (For more information on reasonableness, see Publication 542, page 17.)nnThus, James Corporation\'s payment of a reasonable salary to both Rob and Jim (shareholders) would not be a reportable distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(892,13,'The board of directors of Walden Corporation authorized a year-end distribution to its three shareholders. Each distribution would be equal in value, but the shareholder could choose to receive the distribution in cash or corporation stock. If a shareholder chose to receive corporate stock, the distribution should be treated as:','[\"a tax-free distribution of stock.\",\"a distribution of property.\",\"a like-kind exchange.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock dividends and stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders. However, if any shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights, the stock and stock rights are treated as property distributions and the shareholder will recognize taxable income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(893,13,'Which one of the following statements is incorrect with regard to property distributions?','[\"All stock distributions are treated as property distributions.\",\"Property distributions to shareholders are measured by their FMV on the distribution date adjusted for liabilities.\",\"The distributing corporation treats the property distributed as though sold to the shareholder at FMV or the amount of liabilities the shareholder assumes, whichever is greater.\",\"The shareholder\'s basis in the property distributed is usually the FMV on the date of distribution.\"]',0,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as \"stock options\") are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders.nnDistributions of stock and stock rights, however, are treated as property and therefore taxable distributions if any of the following apply:nnAny shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights.nThe distribution gives cash or other property to some shareholders and an increase in the percentage interest in the corporation\'s assets or earnings and profits to other shareholders.nThe distribution is in convertible preferred stock and has the same result as in item (2).nThe distribution gives preferred stock to some common stock shareholders and gives common stock to other common stock shareholders.nThe distribution is on preferred stock.nIn addition, the amount of a distribution is generally the amount of any money paid to the shareholder plus the fair market value (FMV) of any property transferred to the shareholder. However, this amount is reduced (but not below zero) by:nnany liability of the corporation the shareholder assumes in connection with the distribution andnany liability to which the property is subject immediately before, and immediately after, the distribution.nThe FMV of any property distributed to a shareholder becomes the shareholder\'s basis in that property.nnFinally, a corporation will recognize a gain on the distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. This is generally the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of the actual FMV or the amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nnConsequently, in the above question, all statements are correct in regard to property distributions except that all stock distributions/stock rights are treated as property distributions. In general, they are nontaxable and therefore they are not treated as property distributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(894,13,'How do you report a payment if you make a payment that may be a dividend but you are unable to determine whether any part of the payment is a dividend by the time you must file Form 1099-DIV?','[\"The entire payment must be reported as interest.\",\"The entire payment must be reported as miscellaneous income.\",\"The entire payment must be reported as a dividend.\",\"The entire payment is\\u00a0not\\u00a0reported.\"]',2,'Form 1099-DIV must be issued to each person to whom have been paid dividends and other distributions on stock of $10 or more. Moreover, if a payment is made that may be a dividend but, at the time Form 1099-DIV is required to be filed, it is undeterminable whether any part is a dividend, the entire payment must be reported as a dividend.nnNote: Pursuant to IRC Section 316, the term \"dividend\" means any distribution of property made by a corporation to its shareholders out of its earnings and profits accumulated after February 28, 1913, or out of its earnings and profits of the taxable year (computed as of the close of the taxable year without diminution by reason of any distributions made during the taxable year), without regard to the amount of the earnings and profits at the time the distribution was made.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(895,13,'Which of the following statements regarding the corporate dividends-received deduction is not true?','[\"Generally, a corporation can deduct 50% of the dividends received from a corporation of which it owns less than 20%.\",\"Generally, a corporation can deduct 65% of the dividends received from a corporation of which it owns 20% or more.\",\"The dividends-received deduction is unlimited (assume no dividends from controlled foreign corporations).\",\"No deduction is allowed for dividends from tax-exempt corporations.\"]',2,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnAdditionally, the total deduction for dividends received or accrued is generally limited (in the following order) to:nn65% of the difference between taxable income and the 100% deduction allowed for dividends received from affiliated corporations, or by a small business investment company, for dividends received or accrued from 20%-owned corporations, thenn80% of the difference between taxable income and the 100% deduction allowed for dividends received from affiliated corporations, or by a small business investment company, for dividends received or accrued from less-than-20%-owned corporations (reducing taxable income by the total dividends received from 20%-owned corporations).nCorporations cannot take a deduction for dividends received from a corporation exempt from tax under IRC Section 501 or 521 either for the tax year of the distribution or the preceding tax year.nnTherefore, the only statement in the above question that is not true regarding the corporate dividends-received deduction is that the dividends-received deduction is unlimited.nnNote: With the passing of TCJA, a new type of tax was introduced for U.S. taxpayers, including corporations that control foreign corporations established abroad (CFCs). As a result, the U.S. entity recognizes and is taxed on its pro-rata share of the CFCs deemed earnings for the year. In return, when the CFC actually distributes the previously taxed earnings to its U.S. shareholder, the U.S. corporation is entitled to a 100% dividend received deduction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(896,13,'During 2024, Chris Corporation, a domestic corporation, had the following income, expenses, and deductions:n   Gross receipts                                 $95,000n   Net capital gains                               10,000n   Expenses, not including cash contributions      65,000n   Contributions to qualified charities            20,000n   Net operating loss carryover from 2023          30,000nWhat is the amount of Chris Corporation\'s allowable charitable contribution deduction for tax year 2024?','[\"$1,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$4,000\",\"$3,000\"]',0,'A corporation can claim a limited deduction for charitable contributions made in cash or other property. The contribution is deductible if made to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. For more information on qualified organizations, see Publication 526, Charitable Contributions.nnA corporation cannot deduct charitable contributions that exceed 10% of its taxable income for the tax year. Accordingly, taxable income for this purpose is calculated without:nnthe deduction for charitable contributions,nthe deduction for dividends received,nany net operating loss carryback to the tax year, andnany capital loss carryback to the tax year.nTherefore, Chris Corporation\'s current-year charitable contribution deduction for 2024 is $1,000, which is 10% of taxable income ($10,000). The taxable income amount for computing the charitable contribution limitation is $10,000, which is Gross Receipts ($95,000) plus Net Capital Gains ($10,000), less Expenses, not including Charitable Contributions ($65,000), less Net Operating Loss Carryover from 2023 ($30,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(897,13,'When must Form 1099-DIV be furnished to recipients of a liquidating distribution?','[\"Only if property is distributed as part of the liquidation\",\"Only if cash is distributed as part of the liquidation\",\"If cash or property is distributed as part of the liquidation and the distribution is $10 or more\",\"If cash or property is distributed as part of the liquidation and the distribution is $600 or more\"]',3,'A corporation is required to issue Form 1099-DIV to each person:nnto whom they have paid dividends (including capital gains dividends) and other distributions on stock of $10 or more,nfor whom they have withheld and paid any foreign tax on dividends and other distributors on stock,nfor whom they have withheld any federal income tax on dividends under the backup withholding rules, ornto whom they have paid $600 or more as part of a liquidation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(898,13,'During the tax year, Bass Corporation, a domestic corporation, received $200,000 in dividends from Trout Corporation, also a domestic corporation, in which it has a 22% interest. Bass\'s taxable income is $360,000 before the dividends-received deduction. What is the amount of Bass Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction?','[\"$0\",\"$130,000\",\"$160,000\",\"$200,000\"]',1,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the Bass Corporation owns 22% (20% or more) of Trout Corporation, the Bass Corporation may take a 65% deduction on the dividends received from Trout Corporation. Therefore, Bass Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is $130,000, computed as follows:nn  Dividends Received                $200,000n  65% Deduction                     ×   0.65n  Dividends-Received Deduction      $130,00',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(899,13,'If a corporation allows earnings to accumulate beyond the reasonable needs of the business, it may be subject to an accumulated earnings tax of:','[\"10%.\",\"15%.\",\"20%.\",\"25%.\"]',2,'A corporation can accumulate its earnings for a possible expansion or other bona fide business reasons. However, if a corporation allows earnings to accumulate beyond the reasonable needs of the business, it may be subject to an accumulated earnings tax of 20%. If the accumulated earnings tax applies, interest applies to the tax from the date the corporate return was originally due, without extensions.nnThe absence of a bona fide business reason for a corporation’s accumulated earnings may be indicated by many different circumstances, such as a lack of regular distributions to its shareholders or withdrawals by the shareholders classified as personal loans. However, actual moves to expand the business generally qualify as a bona fide use of the accumulations.nnThe fact that a corporation has an unreasonable accumulation of earnings is sufficient to establish liability for the accumulated earnings tax unless the corporation can show the earnings were not accumulated to allow its individual shareholders to avoid income tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(900,13,'During the 2024 calendar year, the Lance Corporation made a $40,000 cash distribution to its sole shareholder. Lance Corporation\'s current-year earnings and profits (as of the close of the year and without reduction for distributions during the year) is $25,000. Accumulated earnings and profits is $10,000. What amount of dividend should be reported on Form 1099-DIV issued to the shareholder for the year 2024?','[\"$40,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$0\",\"$35,000\"]',3,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). Any part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnTherefore, Lance Corporation should issue a 1099-DIV with a $35,000 dividend amount to the shareholder, computed as follows:nn  Current Earnings and Profits       $25,000n  Accumulated Earnings and Profits    10,000n  Dividend                           $35,000n nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nLance also would reduce his basis in the stock of Lance Corporation by $5,000 ($40,000 less $35,000).nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(901,13,'Walnut, Inc., is a C corporation that was started in 2013. At the beginning of the current year, Walnut, Inc., has accumulated earnings and profits of $100,000. During the current year, Walnut makes a $5,000 distribution to its 100% shareholder in the 1st month of each quarter. At the end of the current year, Walnut had $150,000 in gross income and $140,000 in allowable expenses from ordinary business operations. Walnut also received $5,000 in fully tax-exempt interest from state bonds. What part of the 2nd-quarter distribution is treated as a distribution of accumulated earnings and profits?','[\"$1,250\",\"$2,500\",\"$3,750\",\"$5,000\"]',0,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions are first made from current earnings, then from accumulated earnings and profits and are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). Any part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnTherefore, $1,250 of the 2nd-quarter distribution is treated as a distribution of accumulated earnings, computed as follows:nn  Current Earnings and Profits       $  3,750 (See calculation below)n  Accumulated Earnings and Profits      1,250n     Dividend                        $  5,000nn  Quarterly Earnings and Profits:n  Gross Income:                      $150,000n  Plus: Tax-Exempt Income               5,000n  Less: Allowable Expenses            140,000n  Earnings                           $ 15,000nn  Per Quarter ($15,000/4)            $  3,750',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(902,13,'When are estimated tax payments due for a corporation?','[\"By the 15th day of the 4th, 6th, 9th, and 12th months of a corporation\'s tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 3rd, 6th, 9th, and 12th months of a corporation\'s tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 4th, 6th, and 9th months of the calendar year and the 1st month of the following year\",\"By the 15th day of the 4th, 6th, 9th, and 12th months of a calendar year\"]',0,'Generally, a corporation is required to make installment payments if the estimated tax is $500 or more. Installment payments are due by the 15th day of the 4th, 6th, 9th, and 12th months of the corporation\'s tax year.nnIf any due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the installment is due on the next regular business day.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(903,13,'Under what condition is a corporation required to report a distribution of property given to a shareholder as part of a liquidation on Form 1099-DIV?','[\"The fair market value of the property is $10 or more.\",\"The fair market value of the property is $400 or more.\",\"The fair market value of the property is $500 or more.\",\"The fair market value of the property is $600 or more.\"]',3,'A corporation is required to issue Form 1099-DIV to each person to whom they have:nnpaid dividends (including capital gains dividends and exempt-interest dividends) and other distributions on stock of $10 or more,nwithheld and paid any foreign tax on dividends and other distributions on stock,nwithheld any federal income tax on dividends under the backup withholding rules, ornpaid $600 or more as part of a liquidation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(904,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the distribution of stock rights (also known as “stock options”) to shareholders?','[\"They are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock.\",\"They are generally tax-free to shareholders.\",\"Both of the answer choices are correct.\",\"Neither of the answer choices is correct.\"]',2,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders.nnHowever, there are situations whereby the stock dividends and stock rights become taxable. For example, if any shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights, the stock and stock rights are treated as property and are governed by different rules. For other taxable situations, see Publication 542, page 18.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(905,13,'Olympic Corporation distributed real estate with an FMV of $500,000 to its sole shareholder, Joshua. Olympic\'s basis in the real estate is $400,000. What is the tax effect of the distribution to Olympic and what is Joshua\'s basis in the real estate?','[\"$0 gain\\/loss to Olympic; $400,000 basis to Joshua\",\"$100,000 gain to Olympic; $400,000 basis to Joshua\",\"$0 gain\\/loss to Olympic; $500,000 basis to Joshua\",\"$100,000 gain to Olympic; $500,000 basis to Joshua\"]',3,'A corporation will recognize a gain on distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nAdditionally, the fair market value becomes the shareholder\'s basis in the property.nnAs a result of the distribution, the Olympic Corporation will recognize a gain of $100,000, and Joshua will have a basis of $500,000, determined as follows:nnRecognized Gain: nn FMV               $500,000 Basis to Joshuan Less:n    Basis          (400,000)n Recognized Gain   $100,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(906,13,'The Richards Corporation distributed an airplane to its only shareholder, Bob. The airplane had an FMV of $75,000 and an adjusted basis to the Richards Corporation of $50,000. The airplane was subject to a secured loan of $90,000, which Bob assumed. What is the Richards Corporation\'s gain or loss on the distribution?','[\"$0\",\"$40,000\",\"$(15,000)\",\"$25,000\"]',1,'A corporation will recognize a gain on distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nAs a result of the distribution, the Richards Corporation will recognize a gain of $40,000, determined as follows:nn Liabilities (greater than FMV)   $90,000n Less:n   Basis                          (50,000)n Recognized Gain                  $40,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(907,13,'Rachel purchased 100 shares of Comet Corporation stock for $500 in 2021. In 2024, Rachel received $5,000 in a distribution from the partial liquidation of Comet Corporation. On her personal 2024 income tax return, Rachel must report income from this transaction as:','[\"dividends.\",\"capital gains.\",\"other.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Liquidating distributions (also called liquidating dividends) are distributions a taxpayer receives during a partial or complete liquidation of a corporation. These distributions are, at least in part, one form of a return of capital. They may be paid in one or more installments. Furthermore, the taxpayer will receive Form 1099-DIV from the corporation showing the amount of the liquidating distribution.nnA liquidating distribution is not taxable to a shareholder until the shareholder has recovered the entire basis in the stock. Once the entire basis is received, the remaining distribution is treated as a capital gain. Whether the capital gain is long-term or short-term depends on the taxpayer\'s holding period of the stock.nnTherefore, Rachel must report $4,500 ($5,000 − $500) from this transaction as capital gains.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(908,13,'ABC Corporation\'s tax year ends on October 31, 2024. When is ABC Corporation\'s income tax return required to be filed?','[\"January 31, 2025\",\"January 15, 2025\",\"February 15, 2025\",\"February 28, 2025\"]',2,'Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. Therefore, ABC Corporation\'s income tax return is due by February 15, 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(909,13,'The Charlie Corporation, a calendar-year, accrual-basis taxpayer, distributed shares of the David Corporation stock to Charlie\'s employees in lieu of salaries. The salary expense would have been deductible as compensation if paid in cash. On the date of the payment, Charlie\'s adjusted basis in David Corporation\'s stock was $20,000 and the stock\'s fair market value was $100,000. What is the tax effect to Charlie Corporation?','[\"$100,000 deduction\",\"$20,000 deduction\",\"$20,000 deduction and $80,000 recognized gain\",\"$100,000 deduction and $80,000 recognized gain\"]',3,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock dividends and stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders. However, if any shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights, the stock and stock rights are treated as property and are governed by different rules.nnWith a distribution of property to a shareholder, a corporation will recognize a gain if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold.nnAs a result of the distribution, the Charlie Corporation will have $100,000 deduction in salary expense and recognize a gain of $80,000, determined as follows:nn FMV               $100,000 (Salary expense)n Less:n    Basis           (20,000)n Recognized Gain   $ 80,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(910,13,'Lantern Corporation is in the process of dissolving and has filed a request with the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) for a prompt assessment. Assuming that all other requirements are met, if the request is granted, the period within which the IRS may assess a tax liability is shortened to how many months?','[\"24 months\",\"18 months\",\"36 months\",\"12 months\"]',1,'Pursuant to IRC Section 6501(a), the Service generally has 3 years after an income tax return is filed to assess additional tax or to begin court action to collect the tax. However, the fiduciary representing a dissolving corporation or a decedent\'s estate may request a prompt assessment of tax under the IRC Section 6501(d). This will limit the time to 18 months from the date the fiduciary files the request but not beyond 3 years from the date the return is filed.nnAccordingly, the period within which the IRS may assess a tax liability on the Lantern Corporation is shortened to 18 months.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(911,13,'The Johnson Corporation owns 15% of the White Corporation. In 2024, Johnson Corporation received dividends on the White Corporation stock. Which of the following actions is available to Johnson Corporation?','[\"It may take a dividends-received deduction of 100% of those dividends.\",\"It may take a dividends-received deduction of 65% of those dividends.\",\"It may take a dividends-received deduction of 50% of those dividends.\",\"It may\\u00a0not\\u00a0take a dividends-received deduction since it owns less than 20% of the company.\"]',2,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the Johnson Corporation owns 15% (less than 20%) of the White Corporation, the Johnson Corporation may take a 50% deduction on the dividends received in 2024 from the White Corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(912,13,'Rose Corporation is a calendar-year filing corporation that had accumulated earnings and profits at the end of 2023 of $5,000. At the end of 2024, Rose Corporation had current-year earnings and profits of $1,000. On December 31, 2024, Rose Corporation distributed to sole shareholder Paul Rose an automobile purchased for $10,000 with a fair market value of $8,000. Paul Rose assumed a liability on the automobile of $1,000. What amount of dividend paid to Paul Rose must Rose Corporation report as an ordinary dividend on Form 1099-DIV?','[\"$6,000\",\"$7,000\",\"$8,000\",\"$10,000\"]',0,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). Any part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnTherefore, Rose Corporation should issue a Form 1099-DIV showing a dividend of $6,000 to the shareholder, computed as follows:nn  Current Earnings and Profits:      $1,000n  Accumulated Earnings and Profits    5,000n  Dividend                           $6,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(913,13,'Edward owns 5 of the 1,000 outstanding shares of Wasco, Inc., stock. Edward purchased his 5 shares in 2019 for $500 per share. During 2024, Wasco, Inc., stock trades at a high of $2,000 per share. At the end of 2023, Wasco has earnings and profits of $1 million. Wasco redeems all of Edward\'s 5 shares at the end of 2024 for $1,500 per share. What amount of capital gain in 2024 must Edward report from the redemption of his Wasco, Inc., stock?','[\"$2,500\",\"$0\",\"$7,500\",\"$5,000\"]',3,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either sale or exchange or dividend treatment for the shareholder. Accordingly, if a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is “equivalent” to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock will be treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder. On the other hand, if the corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is not equivalent to a dividend distribution (i.e., disproportionate among shareholders), the redemption will be characterized as a sale or exchange.nnBy Wasco Corporation only redeeming Edward\'s stock shares, they acted in a manner that was not comparable to a dividend distribution. For that reason, the redemption will be classified as a sale. As a result, Edward will recognize $5,000 in income, calculated as follows:nn  Received in Redemption:  $7,500  ($1,500 x 5 shares)n     Less Basis in Stock    2,500  ($500 x 5 shares)n  Income                   $5,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(914,13,'What is the tax consequence when a corporation cancels a shareholder\'s debt without repayment by the shareholder?','[\"The amount canceled is treated as a stock dividend to the shareholder.\",\"The amount canceled is treated as a nontaxable distribution to the shareholder.\",\"The amount canceled is treated as a distribution to the shareholder.\",\"The amount canceled is treated as a contributed capital by the shareholder.\"]',2,'The amount canceled is treated as a contributed capital by the shareholder.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(915,13,'Abbot Corporation\'s tax year ends on June 30, 2024. If Abbot Corporation (a domestic corporation) timely files a Form 7004, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns, what is the extended due date of Abbot Corporation\'s income tax return for tax year ended June 30, 2024?','[\"March 15, 2025\",\"March 30, 2025\",\"April 15, 2025\",\"May 15, 2025\"]',2,'Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. A new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends. The IRS will grant a corporation a 6-month extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes the form properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnHowever, a corporation with a fiscal tax year ending June 30 must file by the 15th day of the 3rd month after the end of its tax year. In the case of any return for a taxable year of a C corporation which ends on June 30 and begins before January 1, 2026, the first sentence of IRC Section 6081(b) shall be applied by substituting \"7 months\" for \"6 months.\"nnAccordingly, if a corporation files Form 7004, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns, but does not pay any tax due by the due date of the original return for which the extension applies, the IRS will not grant the extension.nnAs such, Abbot Corporation\'s new due date is April 15, 2025, which is 7 months after the due date of September 15, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(916,13,'Wargo Corporation has two equal shareholders, Karen and Bob. Each shareholder owns 10 shares of Wargo stock and has owned the stock for several years. Each share has a $100 basis and a $150 FMV. Wargo, which has sufficient earnings and profits, redeems 5 shares from Bob at the $150 FMV. What income, if any, does Bob recognize as a result of the redemption?','[\"$750\",\"$250\",\"$500\",\"$1,000\"]',1,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either sale or exchange or dividend treatment for a shareholder. Accordingly, if a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is “equivalent” to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock will be treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder. On the other hand, if the corporation redeems its stock in manner that is not equivalent to a dividend distribution (i.e., disproportionate among shareholders), the redemption will be characterized as a sale or exchange.nnBy Wargo Corporation only redeeming Bob\'s stock shares, they acted in a manner that was not comparable to a dividend distribution. For that reason, the redemption will be classified as a sale. As a result, Bob will recognize $250 in income, calculated as follows:nn FMV of Stock      $ 750  (5 x $150)n Less:n  Basis in Stock    (500) (5 x $100)n Income            $ 250',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(917,13,'Which of the following statements is correct about charitable contributions?','[\"Contributions made from a self-employed business account are deductible in full on Schedule C in the year of contribution.\",\"Contributions made from an S corporation account are deductible in full on Schedule C in the year of contribution.\",\"Contributions made from a corporation account (including S corporations) are deductible in full on Schedule C in the year of contribution.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Cash payments to an organization, charitable or otherwise, may be deductible as business expenses if the payments are not charitable contributions or gifts and are directly related to the taxpayer’s business. If the payments are charitable contributions or gifts, you cannot deduct them as business expenses. See exception below for C corporations.nnFor example, a taxpayer paid $15 to a local church for a half-page ad in a program for a concert it is sponsoring. The purpose of the ad was to encourage readers to buy the taxpayer\'s product. The payment is not a charitable contribution. However, it can be deducted as an advertising expense.nnCorporations (other than S corporations), on the other hand, can deduct charitable contributions on their income tax returns. However, these deductions are subject to limitations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(918,13,'In 2024 Green, Inc., had gross receipts from sales of $500,000, dividends of $100,000 from a domestic corporation in which Green, Inc., owned 50% of the stock, and operating expenses of $800,000. What is the 2024 net operating loss for Green, Inc.?','[\"$200,000\",\"$265,000\",\"$300,000\",\"$330,000\"]',1,'A corporation figures a net operating loss (NOL) in the same way it calculates taxable income. It starts with its gross income and subtracts its deductions. If its deductions are more than its gross income, the corporation has an NOL (Publication 542, page 14).nnFurthermore, a corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnIf a corporation has an NOL for a tax year, the dividends-received deduction limit of 65% (or 50%) of taxable income does not apply. To determine whether a corporation has an NOL, figure the dividends-received deduction without the 65% (or 50%) of taxable income limit. (Publication 542, page 11)nnGiven the above, Green, Inc., owns 50% (more than 20%) of a domestic corporation; therefore, Green may take a 65% deduction on the dividends received in 2024 from the domestic corporation.nnTherefore, Green, Inc.\'s, net operating loss for 2024 is $(265,000), determined as follows:nn   Income from business                                        $ 500,000n   Dividends received                                            100,000n   Gross income                                                $ 600,000n   Deductions (expenses)                                        (800,000)n   Taxable income before special deductions                    $(200,000)n   Minus: Deduction for dividends received, 65% of $100,000      (65,000)n   Net operating loss                                          $(265,000)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(919,13,'Which of the following requirements must be met for a corporation to request a 6-month extension for filing its tax return?','[\"The corporation must complete and file Form 7004,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns.\",\"The corporation must complete and file Form 7004,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns,\\u00a0and pay any balance due by the due date of the return for which the extension applies.\",\"The corporation must complete and file Form 7004,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns,\\u00a0and pay any balance due by the original due date of the return.\",\"The corporation must complete and file Form 7004,\\u00a0Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns,\\u00a0and pay any balance due within 45 days of the original due date of the return.\"]',2,'Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. A new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends. A corporation that has dissolved must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the date it dissolved.nnHowever, a corporation with a fiscal tax year ending June 30 must file by the 15th day of the 3rd month after the end of its tax year.nnThe IRS will grant a calendar-year corporation a 6-month extension of time (and a June 30 fiscal-year corporation a 7-month extension of time) to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes Form 7004 properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnAccordingly, if a corporation files Form 7004, Application for Automatic Extension of Time to File Certain Business Income Tax, Information, and Other Returns, but does not pay any balance due by the due date of the return for which the extension applies, the IRS will not grant the extension. For more information, see the instructions in Form 7004.nnBe aware, Form 7004 does not extend the time for paying the tax due on the return. Interest, and possibly penalties, will be charged on any part of the final tax due not shown as a balance due on Form 7004. Moreover, the interest is figured from the original due date of the return to the date of payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(920,13,'Which of the following statements is correct if a corporate distribution to a shareholder exceeds earnings and profits (both current and accumulated) and exceeds the shareholder\'s basis in the corporate stock?','[\"The shareholder has a gain from the sale or exchange of property.\",\"The shareholder has a loss from the sale or exchange of property.\",\"The shareholder has\\u00a0no\\u00a0gain or loss from the sale or exchange of property.\",\"The shareholder has dividend income from the sale or exchange of property.\"]',0,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s).nnIf the corporation does not have adequate earnings and profits, the excess amount distributed is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock. To the extent that the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder realizes a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(921,13,'Arnold acquired 10 shares of Klesco, Inc., stock in 2020 for $50 per share. Klesco decided in 2024 to reacquire all of its outstanding stock, which it did for $200 per share. What amount of capital gain in 2024 must Arnold report on the redemption of his Klesco stock?','[\"$0\",\"$500\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,000\"]',2,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either a sale or exchange or a dividend treatment for a shareholder. Accordingly, if a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock is treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder. However, if a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is comparable to the sale or exchange of stock (i.e., complete redemption of all the stock owned by the shareholder or a redemption that is substantially disproportionate), the redemption of stock is treated as a sale or exchange to the shareholder.nnThe redemption of Arnold’s 10 shares is in complete redemption of all the stock he owns and, as such, the transaction will be considered a sale or exchange.nnTherefore, Arnold will recognize $1,500 in capital gain, calculated as follows:nn Amount Distributed   $2,000  ($200 × 10 shares)n Less:n  Basis in Stock        (500) ($50 × 10 shares)n Gain                 $1,500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(922,13,'Hinges, Inc., has a fiscal year-end of June 30, 2024. What is the last date on which Hinges, Inc., can request an extension of time to file its tax return for the year ended June 30, 2024?','[\"September 15, 2024\",\"October 15, 2024\",\"March 15, 2025\",\"April 15, 2025\"]',0,'Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. A new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends. The IRS will grant a corporation an extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the corporation completes the form properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnHowever, a corporation with a fiscal tax year ending June 30 must file by the 15th day of the 3rd month after the end of its tax year. Accordingly, the last date that Hinges, Inc., can request an extension of time to file its tax return for the year ended June 30, 2024, is September 15, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(923,13,'Able, a calendar-year, domestic for-profit corporation, is in a Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceeding and has no income for 2024. When must the bankruptcy trustee of Able Corporation file a Form 1120 for tax year 2024?','[\"No later than March 15, 2025, or request an extension\",\"No later than March 15, 2025; an extension is\\u00a0not\\u00a0permissible\",\"No later than April 15, 2025, or request an extension\",\"No later than April 15, 2025; an extension is\\u00a0not\\u00a0permissible\"]',2,'Unless exempt under IRC Section 501, all domestic corporations in existence for any part of a taxable year (including corporations in bankruptcy) must file an income tax return whether or not they have taxable income.nnGenerally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year.nnA new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends.nnA corporation that has dissolved must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the date it dissolved.nnThe IRS will grant a corporation a 6-month extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes the form properly (Form 7004), files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnAccordingly, Able Corporation must file Form 1120 for the current year no later than April 15, 2025, or request an extension.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(924,13,'Hughes Corporation paid a $400 dividend to a shareholder in 2024. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"No\\u00a0Form 1099-DIV was required because the payment was not $600 or more.\",\"No\\u00a0Form 1099-DIV was required because the payment was not $500 or more.\",\"Form 1099-DIV was required because the payment was $400 or more.\",\"Form 1099-DIV was required because the payment was $10 or more.\"]',3,'A corporation is required to issue Form 1099-DIV to each person:nnto whom they have paid dividends (including capital gains dividends and exempt-interest dividends) and other distributions on stock of $10 or more,nfor whom they have withheld and paid any foreign tax on dividends and other distributors on stock,nfor whom they have withheld any federal income tax on dividends under the backup withholding rules, ornto whom they have paid $600 or more as part of a liquidation.nThus, the Hughes Corporation is required to issue Form 1099-DIV.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(925,13,'Common kinds of distributions by a corporation to shareholders are:','[\"ordinary dividends.\",\"capital gain distributions.\",\"nontaxable distributions.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Distributions such as dividends, capital gain distributions, or nontaxable distributions (also known as nondividend distributions) are common kinds of distributions made by a corporation to its shareholders. Details of these different forms are given in Publication 550.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(926,13,'A corporate payer of an individual shareholder dividend does not have the taxpayer identification number for that shareholder. What backup withholding percentage rate must the corporate payer use for this shareholder\'s dividend payments?','[0.1499999999999999944488848768742172978818416595458984375,0.2399999999999999911182158029987476766109466552734375,0.2800000000000000266453525910037569701671600341796875,0.36999999999999999555910790149937383830547332763671875]',1,'If a recipient does not furnish its TIN (taxpayer identification number) to the taxpayer in the manner required, the taxpayer must backup withhold at a 24% rate on certain dividend payments reported on Form 1099-DIV. Hence, if a corporate payer of an individual shareholder dividend does not have the taxpayer identification number for that shareholder, the corporate payer is required to withhold 24% in backup withholdings.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(927,13,'Robert owns 100 shares of Oswald, Inc., stock he purchased in 2018 for $10 per share. The 100 shares that Robert owns represent all of the outstanding Oswald stock. In 2024, Oswald redeems 25 of Robert\'s shares for $50 per share. Oswald had earnings and profits in 2024 of $100,000. Robert must report what amount of capital gain from this 2024 redemption of his Oswald, Inc., stock?','[\"$0\",\"$1,000\",\"$4,000\",\"$5,000\"]',0,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either a sale or exchange or a dividend treatment for a shareholder. Accordingly, if a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock is treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder leading to an ordinary income transaction.nnOn the other hand, if the corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is not comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., disproportionate among shareholders), the redemption will be characterized as a sale or exchange leading to a capital transaction.nnBy redeeming the 25 shares of outstanding stock from Robert, 100% shareholder, Oswald, Inc., acted in a manner that was equivalent to a dividend distribution. That is because Robert\'s proportional ownership of Oswald has not changed. For that reason, the redemption will be classified as dividend income to the shareholder.nnTherefore, Robert will report dividend income, not a capital gain, on his individual return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(928,13,'In 2020, Mark purchased 100 shares of Roman, Inc., for $10 per share. In 2024, Roman, Inc., completely liquidated and distributed $8,000 to Mark. Mark must report income from this distribution as:','[\"ordinary other income.\",\"dividends.\",\"capital gains.\",\"return of capital.\"]',2,'Publication 550, page 21, provides that liquidating distributions, sometimes called liquidating dividends, are distributions the taxpayer receives during a partial or complete liquidation of a corporation. These distributions are, at least in part, one form of a return of capital. They may be paid in one or more installments. The taxpayer will receive Form 1099-DIV from the corporation showing the taxpayer the amount of the liquidating distribution in box 8 or 9.nnAny liquidating distribution the taxpayer receives is not taxable to the taxpayer until he or she has recovered the basis of his or her stock. After the basis of the taxpayer\'s stock has been reduced to zero, the taxpayer must report the liquidating distribution as a capital gain. Whether the taxpayer reports the gain as a long-term or short-term capital gain depends on how long the taxpayer has held the stock.nnTherefore, Mark must report income from this transaction as capital gains.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(929,13,'When Paul formed his corporation 5 years ago, he invested $5,000 in corporate stock. In 2024, when his basis in the stock was $10,000, he liquidated his corporation, receiving $15,000 cash. How should Paul report this disposal on his 2024 return?','[\"No reporting required for liquidating distributions\",\"Report $10,000 long-term capital gain\",\"Report $5,000 long-term capital gain\",\"Report $5,000 ordinary income\"]',2,'When a corporation distributes property as part of a complete liquidation, the distribution is treated as full payment in exchange for the stock. The shareholder\'s gain or loss from a distribution is determined by subtracting the basis of the stock from the amount distributed. The difference is a capital loss or gain.nnTherefore, Paul will have a $5,000 long-term capital gain, calculated as follows:nn Amount Distributed    $15,000n Less:n    Basis in Stock     (10,000)n Gain                  $ 5,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(930,13,'Brady Corporation of Cleveland, Ohio, is a multinational conglomerate. In 2003, Brady Corporation established and owned 100% of the stock of Toms, Inc., of Dayton, Ohio. Toms, Inc., was established for the purpose of manufacturing rubber gaskets, which Brady Corporation uses in many of its international operations. By the beginning of 2024, Brady Corporation had sold 30% of the outstanding Toms stock. In July 2024, Toms declares a dividend and pays $100,000 to Brady Corporation. In 2024, Brady Corporation, subject to certain limits, takes what amount as a dividends-received deduction?','[\"$0\",\"$50,000\",\"$65,000\",\"$100,000\"]',2,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the Brady Corporation of Cleveland owns 70% (100% − 30%), which is more than 20% of Toms, Inc., of Dayton, the Brady Corporation may take a 65% deduction on the dividends received in 2024 from Toms, Inc. Therefore, Brady Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is $65,000, computed as follows:nn   Dividends Received                $100,000n   65% Deduction                     ×   0.65n   Dividends-Received Deduction      $ 65,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(931,13,'Athena Corporation, a calendar year, accrual basis corporation, made cash charitable contributions totaling $40,000 during 2024. Prior to determining its charitable contribution deduction, Athena had taxable income of $300,000 after taking the dividends-received deduction of $42,000. What is the amount of Athena Corporation\'s current-year charitable contribution deduction for 2024?','[\"$40,000\",\"$34,200\",\"$30,000\",\"$32,400\"]',1,'A corporation can claim a limited deduction for charitable contributions made in cash or other property. The contribution is deductible if made to, or for the use of, a qualified organization. For more information on qualified organizations, see Publication 526, Charitable Contributions.nnA corporation cannot deduct charitable contributions that exceed 10% of its taxable income for the tax year. Accordingly, taxable income for this purpose is calculated without:nnthe deduction for charitable contributions,nthe deduction allowed under IRC Section 249 for bond premium,nthe deduction for dividends received,nthe domestic production activities deduction,nany net operating loss carryback to the tax year, andnany capital loss carryback to the tax year.nTherefore, Athena Corporation\'s current-year charitable contribution deduction for 2024 is $34,200, computed as follows:nn  Taxable Income (includesn   dividends-received deduction)      $300,000n  Plus:n    Dividends-Received Deduction        42,000n  Taxable Income                      $342,000n  Limit (10% of taxable income)       x   0.10n  Charitable Contribution Deduction   $ 34,200',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(932,13,'ABC, an eligible entity, made an election by filing Form 8832, Entity Classification Election, on December 15, 2023, to be taxed as a partnership effective for January 1, 2024. Under the general rule, what is the earliest date ABC can elect to be taxed as a corporation by filing another Form 8832?','[\"January 1, 2027\",\"January 1, 2029\",\"December 15, 2027\",\"December 15, 2029\"]',1,'Once an eligible entity makes an election to change its classification, the entity generally cannot change its classification by election again during the 60 months after the effective date of the election. Therefore, the earliest date that ABC can elect to be treated as a corporation is January 1, 2029.nnThe IRS, however, may (by private letter ruling) permit the entity to change its classification by election within the 60-month period if more than 50% of the ownership interests in the entity, as of the effective date of the election, are owned by persons that did not own any interests in the entity on the effective date or the filing date of the entity\'s prior election (see description of lines 2a and 2b on page 6 of Form 8832).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(933,13,'All of the following statements are correct, except:','[\"any domestic entity after January 1, 1997, that is formed to conduct business and is designated as a corporation under state law may elect out of corporate tax treatment.\",\"a business formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as a body politic is taxed as a corporation.\",\"a business that wants to be a corporation elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832.\",\"a business wholly owned by a state or local government is taxed as a corporation.\"]',0,'The rules used to determine whether a business is taxed as a corporation changed for businesses formed after 1996. A business formed before 1997 and taxed as a corporation under the old rules will generally continue to be taxed as a corporation. The following businesses formed after 1996 are taxed as corporations:nnA business formed under a federal or state law that refers to it as incorporated as a corporation, body corporate, or body politicnA business formed under a state law that refers to it as a joint-stock company or joint-stock associationnAn insurance companynCertain banksnA business wholly owned by a state or local governmentnA business specifically required to be taxed as a corporation by the Internal Revenue CodenCertain foreign businessesnAny other business that elects to be taxed as a corporation by filing Form 8832nNot all corporations are eligible to elect out of corporate taxation just by virtue of filing Form 8832. For more information, see the instructions in Form 8832.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(934,13,'John and Jim each own 5% of J & J Partnership, which was founded in 2003. J & J is a calendar-year taxpayer. On March 20, 2024, they elected to be treated as a corporation for federal tax purposes by filing a Form 8832. What is the earliest date that J & J can be treated as a corporation?','[\"January 1, 2024\",\"March 20, 2024\",\"January 5, 2024\",\"January 1, 2025\"]',2,'Generally, the election to be treated as a corporation will take effect on the date entered on line 8 of Form 8832 or on the date filed if no date is entered on line 8. However, an election specifying an entity\'s classification for federal tax purposes can take effect no more than 75 days prior to the date the election is filed, nor can it take effect later than 12 months after the date on which the election is filed.nnAccordingly, the earliest date that J & J can be treated as a corporation would be January 5, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(935,13,'The Jonas Corporation forgot to request an extension and filed its Form 1120 late for calendar year 2024. It paid the $600 balance due when it filed the return on July 22, 2025. The delinquency penalty for late filing will be:','[\"$100.00.\",\"$650.00.\",\"$0.\",\"$510.00.\"]',3,'If a corporation does not file its tax return by the required due date, including extensions, it may be penalized 5% of the unpaid tax for each month or part of a month the return is late, up to a maximum of 25% of the unpaid tax. In addition, a corporation that does not pay the tax when due may be penalized half of 1% of the unpaid tax for each month or part of a month the tax is not paid, up to a maximum of 25% of the unpaid tax.nnHowever, if the corporation is charged a penalty for late payment of tax for the same period of time, the penalty for late filing is reduced by the amount of the penalty for late payment per IRC Section 6651(c)(1). The minimum penalty for a return that is over 60 days late is the smaller of the tax due or $510. The penalty will not be imposed if the corporation can show the failure to file on time was due to a reasonable cause.nnTherefore, the Jonas Corporation is beyond 60 days and as such it will have a delinquency penalty of $510, calculated as follows:nn  Tax Due                     $ 600.00n  Penalty % (4 months x .05)      0.20n  Calculated Penalty          $ 120.00nn  Minimum Penalty Due         $ 510.00 for a return over 60 days laten                                       (lesser of $510 or the',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(936,13,'During 2024, the NOGO Corporation had the following items of income and expenses:nn   Income from operations                     $50,000n   Dividend income from Cooper Corporationn       (a 10% owned corporation)               90,000n   Expenses of operations                      40,000nWhat is the NOGO Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction, if any?','[\"$58,500\",\"$45,000\",\"$63,000\",\"$90,000\"]',1,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the NOGO Corporation owns 10% (less than 20%) of Cooper Corporation, the NOGO Corporation may take a 50% deduction on the dividends received in 2024 from Cooper Corporation. Therefore, NOGO Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is $45,000, computed as follows:nn   Dividends Received                $90,000n   50% Deduction                     ×  0.50n   Dividends-Received Deduction      $45,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(937,13,'Hughes Corporation transferred shares of stock to Joe Brown in full satisfaction of a debt that Hughes Corporation owed to Joe Brown. Which of the following statements is correct concerning this transaction?','[\"Because this is a qualifying nontaxable exchange, no income or expense will be recognized by either party.\",\"Because this is a qualifying nontaxable exchange, both parties must attach a complete statement of all relevant facts to their tax returns about the exchange.\",\"Because this is\\u00a0not\\u00a0a tax-free exchange, income or expense may be recognized.\",\"Because this is a qualifying nontaxable exchange, both parties must attach a complete statement of all relevant facts to their tax returns about the exchange and no income or expense will be recognized by either party.\"]',2,'When property (or money and property) is exchanged to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the taxpayer or groups of taxpayers are in control of the corporation (at least 80%), the exchange is usually not taxable.nnThe tax-free exchange of property for stock, however, does not apply when:nnthe corporation is an investment company,nthe shareholder transfers the property in a bankruptcy or similar proceeding in exchange for stock used to pay creditors, ornstock is received in exchange for the corporation\'s debt or for interest on the corporation\'s debt that accrued while the shareholder had held the debt.nAs a result, this is not a tax-free exchange and income or expense may be recognized.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(938,13,'Annual statement Form 1099-DIV must be furnished to recipients of which of the following?','[\"Liquidating distributions\",\"Patronage dividends\",\"Both of the answer choices are correct.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Taxpayers are required to issue Form 1099-DIV to each person:nnto whom they have paid dividends and other distributions on stock of $10 or more,nfor whom they have withheld and paid any foreign tax on dividends and other distributions of stock,nfor whom they have withheld any federal income tax under the backup withholding rules, ornto whom they have paid $600 or more as part of a liquidation.nTaxpayers are required to issue Form 1099-PATR (not a Form 1099-DIV) for each person to whom the cooperative has paid at least $10 in patronage dividends and other distributions described in IRC Section 6044(b) or from whom the taxpayer withheld any federal income tax under the backup withholding rules regardless of the amount of the payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(939,13,'Which of the following is correct regarding the accumulated earnings on a corporation?','[\"If the tax applies, interest is calculated from the date the return was filed.\",\"The tax rate is 25%.\",\"Interest is calculated on the tax from the date the return was originally due, without extensions.\",\"Treat an accumulation of $250,000 or less as within the reasonable needs of a business whose principal function is performing services.\"]',2,'According to Publication 542, pages 15–16, a corporation can accumulate earnings for a possible expansion or bona fide business reason that is reasonable for the needs of the business. If it accumulates beyond those needs, it may be subjected to an accumulated earnings tax of 20%. $250,000 is within reasonable needs of most businesses but personal services businesses have a lower threshold of $150,000. If the tax is assessed, interest applies from the due date of the return, excluding extensions.nnThe correct answer is that interest is calculated on the tax from the date the return was originally due, without extensions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(940,13,'What is the tax treatment in the case where a distribution gives cash or other property to some shareholders and gives stock shares that increase the percentage of interest in the corporation\'s assets or earnings and profits to other shareholders?','[\"The distribution of the stock is treated as if it were a nontaxable stock distribution to all shareholders.\",\"The distribution of the stock is treated as if it were a distribution of property to those shareholders only receiving stock shares.\",\"The distribution of the stock is treated as if it were a distribution of property to those shareholders only receiving cash or other property.\",\"The distribution of the stock is treated as if it were a taxable distribution of property to all shareholders.\"]',3,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock dividends and stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders.nnHowever, distributions of stock and stock rights are treated as property (i.e., taxable transactions) if any of the following apply:nnAny shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights.nThe distribution gives cash or other property to some shareholders and an increase in the percentage interest in the corporation\'s assets or earnings and profits to other shareholders.nThe distribution is in convertible preferred stock and has the same result as in item (2).nThe distribution gives preferred stock to some common stock shareholders and gives common stock to other common stock shareholders.nThe distribution is on preferred stock.nAs a result of item 2 above, the distribution of stock in this case is treated as if it were a taxable distribution of property to all shareholders.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(941,13,'Waco, Inc., reported net capital gains as follows:nnTax year 2020 at $6,000nTax year 2022 at $8,000nTax year 2023 at $1,000nIn tax year 2024, Waco, Inc., had $40,000 in long-term capital losses and $25,000 in short-term capital gains. How much net capital loss will be available for Waco to carry into tax year 2025?','[\"$0\",\"$6,000\",\"$14,000\",\"$15,000\"]',1,'A corporation can deduct capital losses only up to the amount of its capital gains. In other words, if a corporation has an excess capital loss, it cannot deduct the loss in the current tax year. Instead, it carries the loss to other tax years and deducts it from any net capital gains that occur in those years.nnA capital loss is carried to other years in the following order:nn3 years prior to the loss year,n2 years prior to the loss year,n1 year prior to the loss year, and thennany loss remaining is carried forward for 5 years.nTherefore, Waco, Inc., will have $6,000 of net capital loss available to carry forward to tax year 2025, calculated as follows:nn2024:nnShort-Term Capital Gain          $25,000nLong-Term Capital Loss            40,000nNet Capital Loss                 $15,000nnCarrybacks:n  2020 (4 years)                       0n  2022 (2 years)                  (8,000)n  2023 (1 year)                   (1,000)nNet Capital Loss Carryforward    $ 6,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(942,13,'Corporations cannot take a deduction for dividends received from the following entities, except:','[\"a regulated investment company.\",\"a real estate investment trust.\",\"a corporation whose stock has been held less than 46 days during the 91-day period beginning 45 days before the stock becomes ex-dividend with respect to the dividend.\",\"any corporation under an obligation (pursuant to a short sale or otherwise) to make related payments for positions in substantially similar or related property.\"]',0,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividends owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividends. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnAdditionally, no deduction is allowed for certain dividends. Accordingly, corporations cannot take a deduction for dividends received from the following entities:nnA real estate investment trust (REIT)nCorporations exempt from tax under IRC Section 501 or 521 either for the tax year of the distribution or the preceding tax yearnA corporation whose stock was held less than 46 days during the 91-day period beginning 45 days before the stock became ex-dividend with respect to the dividend. Ex-dividend means the holder has no rights to the dividendnA corporation whose preferred stock was held less than 91 days during the 181-day period beginning 90 days before the stock became ex-dividend with respect to the dividend if the dividends received are for a period or periods totaling more than 366 daysnAny corporation that is under an obligation (pursuant to a short sale or otherwise) to make related payments with respect to positions in substantially similar or related propertynTherefore, corporations cannot take a deduction for dividends received from all of the above highlighted entities except a regulated investment company, which is not included in the list.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(943,13,'All of the following statements are correct, except:','[\"corporate liquidations of property generally are treated as a sale or exchange.\",\"gain generally is recognized by the corporation on a liquidating distribution of assets to the distributee at fair market value.\",\"loss generally is not recognized by the corporation on a liquidating distribution of assets to the distributee at fair market value.\",\"Form 1099-DIV records the fair market value of all noncash liquidation distributions.\"]',2,'Corporate liquidations of property generally are treated as a sale or exchange. Gain or loss generally is recognized by the corporation on a liquidating sale of its assets. Gain or loss generally is recognized also on a liquidating distribution of assets as if the corporation sold the assets to the distributee at fair market value.nnIn addition, box 10 on Form 1099-DIV records the fair market value of all noncash liquidation distributions (see page 4 of the instructions for Form 1099-DIV).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(944,13,'Corporations generally must make estimated tax payments if they expect their estimated tax (income tax less credits) to be equal to or more than:','[\"$1.\",\"$500.\",\"$600.\",\"$1,000.\"]',1,'Generally, a corporation is required to make installment payments if the estimated tax is $500 or more. Installment payments are due by the 15th day of the 4th, 6th, 9th, and 12th months of the corporation\'s tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(945,13,'Copper Corporation had the following income and expenses during its calendar year of 2024:nn$250,000 in income from operationsn$175,000 in expenses from operationsn$15,000 in qualifying dividends from domestic corporations (10% ownership)nWhat is Copper Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction for 2024?','[\"$15,000\",\"$7,500\",\"$10,500\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the Copper Corporation owns 10% (less than 20%) in domestic corporations in which they received dividends from, the Copper Corporation may take a 50% deduction on the dividends received in 2024. Therefore, Copper Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is $7,500, computed as follows:nn  Dividends Received                 $15,000n  50% Deduction                      ×  0.50n  Dividends-Received Deduction       $ 7,500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(946,13,'The Green Corporation owns 25% of the stock of the Cande Corporation. In 2024, the Green Corporation received $10,000 dividends from the Cande Corporation stock. Assuming that no other limitations apply, the Green Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is:','[\"$5,000.\",\"$6,500.\",\"$2,500.\",\"$0.\"]',1,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividend owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividend. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that the Green Corporation owns 25% (20% or more) of the Cande Corporation, the Green Corporation may take a 65% deduction on the dividends received in 2024 from the Cande Corporation. Therefore, the Green Corporation\'s dividends-received deduction is $6,500, which is the 65% deduction of the dividends received (65% of $10,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(947,13,'Arena, Inc., decided to distribute shares of its own stock to its employees at year-end as a reward for a profitable year. Each employee was to receive 10 shares with a fair market value of $100 per share. Employees were offered a choice of cash or the stock dividend. What is the tax effect to the employees of this distribution?','[\"$0; distributions of stock dividends and stock rights are tax-free to shareholders\",\"$1,000 taxable income to the employees who chose to receive cash and no effect on the employees who received stock\",\"$1,000 taxable income to each employee\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock dividends and stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders. However, if any shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights, the shareholder will recognize taxable income.nnAs a result of the distribution, the employees will have $1,000 of taxable income each, determined as follows:nn FMV of shares distributed       $  100n Number of shares distributed    x   10n Taxable income per employee     $1,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(948,13,'Gus Corporation, a C corporation, is owned equally by Al, Bill, and Charlie. Their stock basis on December 31 is as follows: Al, $20,000; Bill, $40,000; and Charlie, $40,000. Gus Corporation has earnings and profits of $90,000 at the end of the calendar year and will continue as a viable entity. Al wants to exit the corporation and pursue other interests. He surrenders all his shares and receives $15,000. What are the tax consequences to Al of this complete redemption?','[\"$5,000 capital loss\",\"$5,000 capital gain\",\"$15,000 ordinary dividend\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'A distribution by a corporation in redemption of its stock can result in either sale or exchange or dividend treatment for a shareholder:nnIf a corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., pro rata to all shareholders), the redemption of stock will be treated as a taxable dividend to the shareholder.nIf the corporation redeems its stock in a manner that is not comparable to a dividend distribution (i.e., disproportionate among shareholders), the redemption will be characterized as a sale or exchange.nBy Gus Corporation only redeeming Al\'s stock shares, they acted in a manner that was not comparable to a dividend distribution. For that reason, the redemption will be classified as a sale.nnTherefore, Al will have a $5,000 capital loss, calculated as follows:nn Amount Distributed:   $ 15,000n Less:n    Basis in Stock      (20,000)n Loss                  $ (5,000)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(949,13,'Gold Corporation distributes land with a fair market value of $25,000 to its sole shareholder, Donna Gold, who assumes the mortgage on the land of $35,000. This land had an adjusted basis to Gold Corporation of $20,000. Gold Corporation must recognize how much of a gain on this distribution?','[\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$15,000\",\"$25,000\"]',2,'A corporation will recognize a gain on distribution of property to a shareholder if the fair market value (FMV) of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nAdditionally, the fair market value becomes the shareholder\'s basis in the property.nnAs a result of the distribution, Gold Corporation will recognize a gain of $15,000, determined as follows:nn Amount of Liabilities Assumed   $35,000n Less:n    Basis                        (20,000)n Recognized Gain                 $15,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(950,13,'Which of the following is correct for purposes of determining whether a distribution from a corporation is taxable to a shareholder as a dividend?','[\"Taxable income may be substituted for current earnings and profits when reporting dividends.\",\"Only current earnings and profits are reported as dividend.\",\"Only accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividend.\",\"Current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividend.\"]',3,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from either current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s).nnAny part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(951,13,'In 2018, Adam purchased 100 shares of Call Corporation stock for $50 per share. During 2024, Call Corporation completely liquidated. After paying its liabilities, Call Corporation distributed to its shareholders $10,000 in cash and appreciated property sold for $90,000. Adam\'s portion received a liquidating distribution from Call Corporation of $10,000. Adam must report what amount of capital gains income from this distribution?','[\"$4,500\",\"$5,000\",\"$22,500\",\"$25,000\"]',1,'When a corporation distributes property as part of a complete liquidation, the distribution is treated as full payment in exchange for the stock. The shareholder\'s gain or loss from a distribution is determined by subtracting the basis of the stock from the amount distributed. The difference is a capital loss or gain.nnTherefore, Adam will recognize $5,000 in capital gain, calculated as follows:nn  Amount Distributed   $10,000n  Less:n    Basis in Stock      (5,000) ($50 x 100 shares)n  Capital Gain         $ 5,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(952,13,'Sky Corporation is a C corporation. Jake owns 80% of all of the outstanding shares of Sky Corporation stock. In 2015, Jake advanced funds to Sky Corporation as a loan. The loan instrument executed between Jake and Sky Corporation is a demand note. The principal balance due on the loan from Sky Corporation is $300,000. After Jake demanded repayment of the outstanding loan on March 20, 2024, Sky Corporation transferred to Jake preferred stock with a fair market value of $325,000 in settlement of the debt. Jake has the right to require Sky Corporation to redeem the preferred stock. Which of the following is true?','[\"The transfer of stock to Jake qualifies as a Section 351 transfer.\",\"The transfer of stock is a nontaxable transaction because Jake is in control of the corporation.\",\"The transfer of stock to Jake is a Section 1244 Qualified Small Business Stock transaction.\",\"Jake must recognize income on the transaction.\"]',3,'If in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, money, or property other than stock is received, a gain may have to be recognized by the shareholder. If a gain must be recognized, the gain is only up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received.nnMore specific to this question, nonqualified preferred stock is treated as property other than stock. Generally, it is preferred stock with any of the following features:nnthe holder has the right to require the issuer or a related person to redeem or buy the stock,nthe issuer or a related person is required to redeem or buy the stock,nthe issuer or a related person has the right to redeem or buy the stock and, on the issue date, it is more likely than not that the right will be exercised, ornthe dividend rate on the stock varies with reference to interest rates, commodity prices, or similar indices.nFor a detailed definition of nonqualified preferred stock, see IRC Section 351(g)(2).nnAs a result, Jake must recognize income on the transaction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(953,13,'During the calendar year, the Baker Corporation distributed a dividend in the form of a building to its sole shareholder. The building has a fair market value of $60,000 and an adjusted basis of $20,000. The corporation has sufficient earnings and profits. Not considering any potential tax effect of any taxes on the distribution, the net effect of the transaction on earnings and profits is:','[\"an increase of $40,000.\",\"an increase of $20,000.\",\"a decrease of $40,000.\",\"a decrease of $20,000.\"]',3,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). Any part of a distribution that is not from earnings and profits is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the stock in the hands of the shareholder. To the extent the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock, the shareholder has a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnnn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThe general rule on the distribution of property (including cash) by a corporation is that the earnings and profits are reduced by the amount of cash distributed and the adjusted basis of any other property distributed. (IRC Section 312)nn nTherefore, the distribution of property will decrease Baker Corporation\'s earnings and profits by the adjusted basis of the building, $20,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(954,13,'ABC Company, a corporate taxpayer, has a fiscal year ending September 30. The due date, excluding extension, for filing their return is:','[\"January 15.\",\"November 15.\",\"December 1.\",\"December 15.\"]',0,'Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. A new corporation filing a short-period return must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the short period ends. Finally, a corporation that has dissolved must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the date it dissolved.nnThe IRS will grant a corporation an extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes Form 7004 properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnAccordingly, the due date, excluding extension, for ABC Company to file their tax return is January 15.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(955,13,'In 2024, Omega, Inc., partially compensates employee Tom Jones with 100 shares of stock. Omega stock is selling for $200 per share at the time Tom receives his shares. On December 31, 2024, Tom sells his 100 shares of Omega stock for $300 each. How much of an employee compensation expense can Omega deduct in 2024 for Tom\'s 100 shares?','[\"$0\",\"$10,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$30,000\"]',2,'If you transfer property (including your company\'s stock) to an employee as payment for services, you can generally deduct it as wages. The amount you can deduct is the property\'s fair market value on the date of the transfer less any amount the employee paid for the property.nnYou can claim the deduction only for the tax year in which your employee includes the property\'s value in income. Your employee is deemed to have included the value in income if you report it on Form W-2 in a timely manner. These rules also apply to property transferred to an independent contractor for services.nnA corporation recognizes no gain or loss when it pays for services with its own stock. If a gain or loss is recognized, it is the difference between the FMV (fair market value) of the property and its adjusted basis on the date of transfer.nnAs a result of the distribution, Omega, Inc., will have $20,000 deduction in salary expense ($200 × 100 shares of stock).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(956,13,'Heron, Inc., made a distribution of real estate with an FMV of $100,000 to its only shareholder, Jennifer, on December 31, 2024. Heron\'s basis in the property was $60,000. Current-year earnings and profits of Heron (before the distribution) are $10,000 and it has accumulated $20,000 earnings and profits from prior years. Jennifer\'s basis in her Heron stock is $5,000. What will be the tax effect to Jennifer?','[\"$100,000 dividend and $5,000 return of capital\",\"$70,000 dividend, $5,000 return of capital, and $25,000 capital gain\",\"$30,000 dividend, $5,000 return of capital, $25,000 capital gain\",\"$30,000 dividend, $5,000 return of capital, and $60,000 capital gain\"]',1,'Generally, for a C corporation, a distribution to shareholder is considered to be made out of current Earnings and Profits (E&P) and Accumulated E&P. Per Publication 542, page 17, distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). If the corporation does not have adequate earnings and profits, the excess amount distributed is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock. To the extent that the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder realizes a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnThe order that the items are addressed is first E&P/Acc. E&P, then stock basis. Any remaining amount is a gain.nnThe corporation itself does record a gain at the corporate level because it is distributing appreciated property: FMV = $100,000 vs. basis of $60,000. Property distributions from C corporations are described in Section 312.nnTherefore, Jennifer will have dividend income of $70,000, which is the sum of current-year and accumulated E&P, and a capital gain of $25,000, determined as follows:nn  FMV of Property Received                 $100,000n  Less:n    Current-Year E&P            50,000n    Accumulated E&P             20,000n                               $70,000     $ 30,000 Remaining Amountn  Less:n    Basis                                     5,000 Return of Capitaln  Remaining                                $ 25,000 Capital GainnCurrent-year E&P is derived from $10,000 as given in the problem plus $40,000 of gain the corporation must recognize upon distribution of appreciated property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(957,13,'Which of the following charitable contributions is deductible for tax year 2024 for a calendar-year corporation that uses the accrual method of accounting?','[\"A charitable contribution paid on April 10, 2025, for tax year 2024\",\"A charitable contribution paid on June 10, 2025, for tax year 2024\",\"Both answer choices are correct.\",\"Neither answer choice is correct.\"]',0,'A corporation using an accrual method of accounting can choose to deduct unpaid contributions for the tax year the board of directors authorizes them if it pays them by the due date for filing the corporation’s tax return (not including extensions). A declaration stating that the board of directors adopted the resolution during the tax year must accompany the return. The declaration must include the date the resolution was adopted.nnNote: Generally, for tax years beginning after December 31, 2015, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. Also, a corporation with a fiscal tax year ending June 30 must file by the 15th day of the 3rd month after the end of its tax year. But according to the law, C corporations with a June 30 filing also can make a charitable contribution by the 15th day of the 4th month even though they must file by the 15th day of the 3rd month, which would make the IRS publication incorrect for these corporations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(958,13,'Croaker, Inc., is a taxable domestic corporation. Dana Corporation, a large manufacturing corporation, owns 15% of Croaker\'s outstanding stock. In 2024, Dana Corporation received $100,000 in dividends from Croaker. Dana Corporation received no other dividends in 2024. Dana Corporation may deduct, within certain limits, what percentage of the dividends received?','[0.1499999999999999944488848768742172978818416595458984375,0.5,0.65000000000000002220446049250313080847263336181640625,1]',1,'A corporation is permitted to deduct a percentage of certain dividends received during its tax year. A corporation can deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received if the corporation receiving the dividends owns less than 20% of the corporation distributing the dividends. If the corporation owns 20% or more of the distributing corporation\'s stock, it can, subject to certain limits, deduct 65% of the dividends received.nnGiven that Dana Corporation owns 15% (less than 20%) of Croaker, Inc., Dana Corporation may deduct, within certain limits, 50% of the dividends received.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(959,13,'ABC Corporation is dissolved on July 9, 2024. What is the due date, without extensions, for the filing of the final corporate income tax return?','[\"November 15, 2024\",\"December 31, 2024\",\"April 15, 2025\",\"November 9, 2024\"]',0,'Generally, a corporation must file its income tax return by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. In the case of a corporation that has dissolved, it must generally file by the 15th day of the 4th month after the date it dissolved.nnThe IRS will grant a corporation a 6-month extension of time to file a corporation income tax return if the company completes the form properly, files it, and pays any tax due by the original due date for the return.nnGiven that ABC Corporation was dissolved on July 9, 2024, the filing of the final corporate income tax return would be due November 15, 2024 (the 15th day of the 4th month following the dissolution date).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(960,13,'In 2024, pursuant to a complete liquidation, Richards Corporation distributes the following to a shareholder: Inventory, basis $10,000, FMV $20,000; and land held as an investment, basis $5,000, FMV $40,000. The land is subject to a $30,000 liability. What are the amounts and character of income to be recognized by Richards Corporation?','[\"$10,000 ordinary income; $35,000 capital gain\",\"$10,000 ordinary income; $65,000 capital gain\",\"$0 ordinary income; $0 capital gain\",\"$10,000 ordinary income; $5,000 capital gain\"]',0,'Corporate liquidations of property generally are treated as a sale or exchange. Gain or loss generally is recognized by the corporation on a liquidating sale of its assets. Gain or loss generally is recognized by the corporation on a liquidating distribution of assets to the distributee at fair market value.nnIn certain cases in which the distributee is a corporation in control of the distributing corporation, the distribution may not be taxable. For more information, see IRC Section 332 and related regulations.nnAdditionally, the sale of a business usually is not a sale of one asset but rather all assets. When sold, the sale of capital assets results in capital gain or loss, whereas the sale of real property or depreciable property used in the business and held longer than 1 year are Section 1231 gains or losses. Moreover, the sale of inventory results in an ordinary gain or loss (Publication 544, pages 22 and 23).nnTherefore, the Richards Corporation will have $10,000 in ordinary income and a $35,000 capital gain, determined as follows:nn            Inventory          Investment Landn FMV         $20,000               $40,000n Less:n   Basis     (10,000)               (5,000)n             $10,000 (ordinary)    $35,000 (capital gain)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(961,13,'Acme Corporation made payments during the year that are required to be reported on Form 1099-DIV to the IRS and the recipients. What are the due dates to file Form 1099-DIV if they file the forms electronically with the IRS and in paper format with the recipients?','[\"Filing date to IRS: February 28; Filing date to recipients: January 31\",\"Filing date to IRS: March 31; Filing date to recipients: January 31\",\"Filing date to IRS: March 15; Filing date to recipients: March 15\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'The general instructions for Form 1099, page 6, provide a guide to information return filing. Form 1099-DIV has a due date to the IRS of February 28 if on paper or March 31 if it is filed electronically (Form 1099 Instructions, page 6) and to the recipient of January 31 (Form 1099 Instructions, page 15) or March 15 if reporting by trustees and middlemen of WHFITs (widely held fixed investment trusts) (Form 1099 Instructions, page 16).nnIf the regular due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the form may be filed by the next business day.nnTherefore, Acme Corporation must file with the IRS by March 31 and to their recipients by January 31.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(962,13,'The following statements regarding qualified personal service corporations are true, except:nn1. a qualified personal service corporation is taxed at a flat rate of 21%.n2. a qualified personal service corporation must meet two tests:none of performance of certain personal services andnownership directly or indirectly of at least 95% of the corporation\'s stock.n3. the passive activity rules may apply to a personal service corporation if the corporation is not an S corporation and the employee-owners own 10% of the fair market value of the personal service corporation\'s outstanding stock on the last day of the current tax year.n4. personal services are those performed in the fields of accounting, actuarial science, architecture, consulting, engineering, health (including veterinary services), law, and the performing arts.','[\"2 and 3\",\"3 only\",\"1 and 3\",\"4 only\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 542, page 16, for tax years beginning after 2017, a corporation, including a qualified personal service corporation is taxed at a flat rate of 21% on taxable income. Additionally, as provided with further detail in IRC Section 448(d)(2) and Publication 542, page 3:nnSubstantially all of the activities of which involve the performance of services in the fields of health, law, engineering, architecture, accounting, actuarial science, performing arts, or consulting, andnSubstantially, all of the stock of which (by value) is held directly (or indirectly through 1 or more partnerships, S corporations, or qualified personal service corporations) by:nEmployees performing services for such corporation in connection with the activities involving a field referred to in subparagraph 1,nRetired employees who had performed such services for such corporation,nThe estate of any individual described in the first two categories,nAny other person who acquired such stock by reason of the death of an individual described in the first two bullet points.nPublication 542, page 3 further stipulates that a personal service corporation is required to meet the following requirements:nnIts principal activity during the “testing period” is performing personal services. The testing period for any tax year is the prior tax year. If the corporation has just been formed, the testing period begins on the 1st day of its tax year and ends on the earlier of:nthe last day of its tax year ornthe last day of the calendar year in which its tax year begins.nIts employee-owners substantially perform the services in item (1). This requirement is met if more than 20% of the corporation\'s compensation cost for its activities of performing personal services during the testing period is for personal services performed by employee-owners.nIts employee-owners own more than 10% of the fair market value of its outstanding stock on the last day of the testing period.nThe IRS limits the deductions a personal service corporation (PSC) can take for passive activity losses. If the personal service corporation has a loss from a passive activity, that loss can only be used to offset passive activity income. The PSC is required to file Form 8810 to compute the amount of passive activity losses allowed for the filing period. Page 1 of Form 8810 Instructions defines a PSC as a corporation whose principal activity for the testing period for the tax year is the performance of personal services. The services must be substantially performed by employee-owners. Employee-owners must own more than 10% of the fair market value of the corporation’s outstanding stock on the last day of the testing period. Principal activities, types of personal services, and definition of substantial performance by employee-owners are the same as described above, in paragraphs 1, 2, and 3.nnTherefore, all of the above statements regarding qualified personal services corporations are true except the passive activity rules may apply to a personal service corporation if the corporation is not an S corporation and the employee-owners own 10% of the fair market value of the personal service corporation\'s outstanding stock on the last day of the current tax year. Here the statement indicates the employee-owners own 10% and the correct rule is more than 10%.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(963,13,'What is the corporation\'s basis in property received in a taxable exchange when a gain is recognized by the transferor?','[\"FMV of the property received, which may generally be measured by the adjusted basis of the property in the hands of the transferor, plus any gain recognized by the transferor\",\"FMV of the property received, which may generally be measured by the adjusted basis of the property in the hands of the transferor, less any gain recognized by the transferor\",\"FMV of the property received, which may generally be measured by the adjusted basis of the property in the hands of the transferor\",\"FMV of the property received\"]',0,'A corporation that receives property from a shareholder in exchange for its stock generally has the same basis the shareholder had in the property, increased by any gain the shareholder had to recognize on the exchange.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(964,13,'The West Corporation distributes property with a basis of $1,000 and a fair market value of $4,000 subject to a liability of $6,000 to Jeff, a shareholder. What is the gain or loss, if any, the West Corporation must recognize as a result of the distribution?','[\"$3,000 gain\",\"$1,000 loss\",\"$5,000 gain\",\"$0\"]',2,'A corporation will recognize a gain on distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nAs a result of the distribution, the West Corporation will recognize a gain of $5,000, determined as follows:nn Liabilities (greater than FMV)   $6,000n Less:n    Basis                         (1,000)n Recognized Gain                  $5,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(965,13,'Robert transferred an office building that has an adjusted basis of $60,000 and a fair market value of $105,000 to the Wargo Corporation in exchange for 100% of Wargo Corporation stock and $10,000 cash. The building was subject to a mortgage of $25,000, which Wargo Corporation assumed. The fair market value of the stock was $75,000. Which is the amount of Robert\'s realized gain and recognized gain?','[\"Realized: $55,000; Recognized: $30,000\",\"Realized: $50,000; Recognized: $30,000\",\"Realized: $50,000; Recognized: $10,000\",\"Realized: $35,000; Recognized: $10,000\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. If, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. Additionally, if the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received by the shareholder.nnThus, Robert\'s realized gain is $50,000 and his recognized gain is $10,000, determined as follows:nnn FMV of stock received      $ 75,000n Cash received                10,000n Assumed liability            25,000n Total received             $110,000n Less:n   Adjusted basis             60,000n Realized gain              $ 50,000nDue to the fact that the recognized gain is limited to the amount of cash received, Robert\'s recognized gain in the transaction would be $10,000 (the amount of cash he received).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(966,13,'Which of the following statements is correct if ABC Corporation gives equity stock received in exchange for personal services of JT?','[\"JT has income for the fair market value of the equity stock.\",\"Neither party has income from the transactions because it is a qualifying nontaxable exchange.\",\"ABC has income for the fair market value of the equity stock.\",\"JT has no income from the transaction.\"]',0,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. However, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation.nnTherefore, the value of stock received for services is ordinary income to the recipient.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(967,13,'Alpha Corporation owns 75% of the voting stock of Sky Net, Inc. Alpha Corporation\'s stock ownership in Sky Net also represents 75% of the total value of the stock. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Sky Net is a member of a controlled group with Alpha Corporation as the common parent.\",\"Alpha is a member of a controlled group with Sky Net Corporation as the common parent.\",\"Sky Net and Alpha are members of a controlled group with no common parent.\",\"Sky Net is\\u00a0not\\u00a0a member of a controlled group with Alpha Corporation as the common parent.\"]',3,'A controlled group of corporations is a group that is related through common ownership. There are two types of controlled groups: parent-subsidiary and brother-sister. This question deals with the parent-subsidiary type of relationship. A parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected through ownership with a common parent if:nnat least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of each of the corporations, except the common parent corporation, is directly or indirectly owned by one or more of the other corporations; andnthe common parent corporation directly or indirectly owns stock possessing at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of at least one of the other corporations, excluding, in computing such voting power or value, stock owned directly by such other corporations (Schedule O (Form 1120) Instructions, pages 1 and 2).nGiven that Alpha Corporation owns 75% of Sky Net, Inc., the 80% rules have not been met and therefore Sky Net is not a member of a controlled group with Alpha Corporation as the common parent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(968,13,'Jonah Corporation is owned by Alfred, Scott (Alfred\'s son), and Christina (Alfred\'s niece). Alfred owns 50 shares in Jonah Corporation, Scott owns 25 shares, and Christina owns 25 shares. How many shares does Alfred constructively own?','[25,50,75,100]',2,'There is a set of rules for determining whether an individual directly or indirectly owns any of the outstanding stock of a corporation (see Publication 542, pages 9 and 10). For this question, the following rule applies: \"An individual is treated as owning the stock owned, directly or indirectly, by or for the individual\'s family. Family includes only brothers and sisters (including half-brothers and half-sisters), a spouse, ancestors, and lineal descendants.\"nnTherefore, Alfred is treated as owning 75% of the stock in Jonah Corporation, determined as follows:nn Alfred                    50%n Plus:n   Scott (Alfred\'s Son)    25%n Total Shares              75%nNote: The stock owned by Alfred’s niece is not attributed to him.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(969,13,'John, Mark, Steve, and Tom organize the J M S & T Corporation by transferring the following:nn                         Transferor\'s    Fairn                           Adjusted     Market       ConsiderationnTransferor     Asset        Basis        Value          Received     n   John      Land         $50,000       $70,000    37 shares of stockn   Mark      Equipment    $35,000       $40,000    22 shares of stockn   Steve     Tools        $45,000       $35,000    19 shares of stockn   Tom       Cash         $40,000       $40,000    22 shares of stockn                                                   100 shares TotalnThe land contributed by John is subject to a mortgage in the amount of $30,000. J M S & T Corporation assumes John\'s mortgage on the land. The 100 shares represent all of the outstanding stock of J M S & T Corporation. Which of the following is correct?','[\"The exchange qualifies for IRC Section 351 nontaxable treatment.\",\"The exchange does not qualify for IRC Section 351 nontaxable treatment.\",\"The exchange qualifies for IRC Section 351 nontaxable treatment, but John must recognize $30,000 of capital gain.\",\"The exchange qualifies for IRC Section 351 nontaxable treatment, but John must recognize $20,000 of capital gain.\"]',0,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. To be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnIf, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. If the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received. However, an exception to this rule occurs when the liabilities the corporation assumed are more than the adjusted basis in the property transferred. Under these circumstances, a gain is recognized up to the difference. Since John\'s basis is $50,000, which is greater than the transferred liability of $30,000, no gain is recognized.nnGiven the above information, the exchange qualifies for IRC Section 351 nontaxable treatment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(970,13,'How is the value of PT corporation stock that is given to Tom in exchange for services treated for federal income tax purposes?','[\"It is a qualifying nontaxable exchange and, as such, it is not taxable to either party.\",\"It is treated as a capital transaction only to Tom.\",\"It is treated as a capital transaction only to the PT corporation.\",\"It is treated as ordinary income to Tom.\"]',3,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. However, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation.nnTherefore, the value of stock received for services is ordinary income to the recipient and ordinary deduction to the corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(971,13,'Jose has formed Salsa Corporation with only one class of voting stock and all stock has voting rights. In order to apply Internal Revenue Code Section 351 treatment of nonrecognition of any gain, Jose has to have what percentage of control of ownership of Salsa Corporation immediately after he transfers his assets to the corporation for stock?','[\"At least 75% of the total voting stock\",\"At least 50% of the total voting stock\",\"At least 80% of the total voting stock\",\"At least 20% of the total voting stock\"]',2,'To be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnAs a result, Jose must have at least 80% of the total voting stock of Salsa Corporation in order to apply the Internal Revenue Code Section 351 treatment of nonrecognition of any gain.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(972,13,'Fran transfers real property and a mortgage to a corporation in exchange for stock. Fran is in control of the corporation immediately after the transfer. The real property has a fair market value of $500,000 and the mortgage transferred to the corporation is $350,000. Fran has an adjusted basis in the real property of $300,000. What is the amount of income required to be recognized by Fran, if any?','[\"$350,000\",\"$550,000\",\"$50,000\",\"$0\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable.nnIf, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. Additionally, if the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received. There are two exceptions to this treatment.nnFirst, if the liabilities the corporation assumes are more than the shareholder’s adjusted basis in the property transferred (which is the case here), gain is recognized up to the difference.nnSecond, if there is no good business reason for the corporation to assume the shareholder’s liabilities, or if the shareholder\'s main purpose in the exchange is to avoid federal income tax, the assumption is treated as if the shareholder received money in the amount of the liabilities.nnLikewise, Treasury Regulation Section 1.357-2(a) provides, in part, that if an individual transfers, under IRC Section 351, properties having a total basis in his hands of $20,000, one of which has a basis of $10,000 but is subject to a mortgage of $30,000, to a corporation controlled by him, such individual will be subject to tax with respect to $10,000, the excess of the amount of the liability over the total adjusted basis of all the properties in his hands.nnThus, Fran is required to recognize $50,000 of income as a result of the excess mortgage amount ($350,000) over the adjusted basis in the transferred real property ($300,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(973,13,'Which of the following statements about a controlled group of corporations is true?','[\"Members of a controlled group are entitled to only one accumulated earnings tax credit.\",\"A parent corporation and its 80% owned subsidiary make up a controlled group.\",\"No subsidiary of a consolidated group should file a Schedule O on its own behalf.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'In line with the instructions for Part II (“Apportionments”) of Form 1120, Schedule O, members of a controlled group are entitled to allocate the $250,000 accumulated earnings credit unequally if they adopt an apportionment plan or have an apportionment plan in effect. Hence, the group is entitled to only one accumulated earnings tax credit (Schedule O (Form 1120) Instructions, page 6).nnAdditionally, a parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected through ownership with a common parent if:nnat least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of each of the corporations, except the common parent corporation, is directly or indirectly owned by one or more of the other corporations; andnthe common parent corporation directly or indirectly owns stock possessing at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of at least one of the other corporations, excluding, in computing such voting power or value, stock owned directly by such other corporations (Schedule O (Form 1120) Instructions, pages 1–2).nIf one or more of the component members of a controlled group are also members of a consolidated group, then the common parent of that consolidated group must file one Schedule O on behalf of the members of that consolidated group. No subsidiary of a consolidated group should file a Schedule O on its own behalf.nnConsequently, all of the answer choices are correct in regard to a controlled group of corporations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(974,13,'Joyce and Edward combine their sole proprietorships by forming the Lair Corporation. Joyce transfers land and a building having a combined $50,000 adjusted basis and a $100,000 FMV to the corporation in exchange for 40% of the Lair Corporation stock. Edward transfers equipment with a $60,000 adjusted basis and a $150,000 FMV to the corporation in exchange for 60% of the Lair stock with a par value of $10. Joyce and Edward received no other property than the Lair stock. What is Edward\'s recognized gain on this transaction?','[\"$60,000\",\"$90,000\",\"$-0-\",\"$150,000\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnEdward made a transfer of qualified property to Lair Corporation. Edward, in conjunction with Joyce, was in control immediately after the transfer (40% + 60%). Edward only received stock in exchange for his transfer of property. Therefore, Edward\'s exchange of property for stock in the Lair Corporation is a tax-free exchange, and Edward\'s recognized gain is zero.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(975,13,'In the current tax year, Yasmine transferred land with an adjusted basis to her of $40,000 and a fair market value of $95,000 to Nadir Corporation in exchange for 100% of Nadir Corporation\'s only class of stock. The land was subject to a liability of $45,000, which Nadir Corporation assumed. The fair market value of Nadir Corporation\'s stock at the time of the transfer was $50,000. What amount of gain must Yasmine recognize and what is her basis in the Nadir Corporation stock?','[\"$0 recognized gain, $40,000 basis\",\"$55,000 recognized gain, $95,000 basis\",\"$5,000 recognized gain, $0 basis\",\"$5,000 recognized gain, $45,000 basis\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. To be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnIf, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. If the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received by the shareholder. However, an exception to this rule occurs when the liabilities the corporation assumed are more than the adjusted basis in the property transferred. Under these circumstances, a gain is recognized up to the difference.nnIn addition, the basis of the stock a shareholder receives is the adjusted basis of the property that was transferred. This is increased by any amount treated as a dividend, plus any gain recognized on the exchange. Moreover, the basis is decreased by any cash received, the fair market value of any other property received, and any loss recognized on the exchange. The basis is also decreased by the amount of any liability the corporation or another party to the exchange assumes.nnThus, Yasmine\'s taxable gain is $5,000 and her basis in the stock received is $0, computed as follows:nnTaxable Gain:                        Basis:nnLiabilities Assumed      $45,000     Adjusted Basis           $40,000nLess:                                Less:n  Adjusted Basis          40,000       Liability Assumed       45,000nTaxable Gain             $ 5,000     Basis in New Stock       $     0nNote: The basis cannot be negative.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(976,13,'The Dana Corporation has two subsidiary corporations. In order to determine that the subsidiary corporations are in a controlled corporate group, which of the following must be true?','[\"Ten or fewer persons (individuals, estates, or trusts) own at least 80% of the voting stock or value of shares of each of two or more corporations.\",\"Ten or fewer persons own more than 50% of the voting power or value of shares of each corporation, considering a particular person\'s stock only to the extent that it is owned identically with regard to each corporation.\",\"A persons\' stock ownership is not taken into account for purposes of the 80% requirement unless that shareholder owns stock in all of the corporations considered to be in the group.\",\"The subsidiaries must be located in the same state.\"]',2,'A controlled group of corporations is a group that is related through common ownership. There are two types of controlled groups: parent-subsidiary and brother-sister. This question deals with the parent-subsidiary type of relationship. A parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected through ownership with a common parent, if at least 80% of stock is owned by one or more of the corporations (other than the common parent) and the common parent owns at least 80% of at least one of the other corporations.nnTherefore, the person\'s stock ownership is not taken into account for purposes of the 80% requirement unless that shareholder owns stock in all of the corporations considered to be in the group in order to determine if the two subsidiary corporations of the Dana Corporation are to be deemed a controlled group.nnIn the case of a brother-sister group, it generally is two or more corporations where the same 5 (not 10) or fewer persons directly or indirectly own the stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(977,13,'Which of the following statements about a controlled group corporation is false?','[\"John Corporation owns 80% of the voting power and value of James Corporation stock. John Corporation and James Corporation are members of a controlled group.\",\"Allen Corporation owns 80% of the voting power and value of Brown Corporation stock. Brown Corporation owns 80% of the voting power and value of Cole Corporation. Allen Corporation, Brown Corporation, and Cole Corporation are members of a controlled group.\",\"Members of a controlled group must use graduated taxable income bracket amounts.\",\"Members of a controlled group may be either members of a combined group, parent-subsidiary corporations, or brother-sister corporations.\"]',2,'A controlled group of corporations is a group that is related through common ownership. There are two types of controlled groups: parent-subsidiary and brother-sister.nnA parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected though ownership with a common parent if at least 80% of stock is owned by one or more of the corporations (other than the common parent) and the common parent owns at least 80% of at least one of the other corporations.nnA brother-sister controlled group exists if the following are true:nnfive or fewer persons (individuals, estates, or trusts) own at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of voting stock, or at least 80% of the total value of all classes of stock, of each corporation in a group of two or more corporations. A person\'s stock ownership is considered only if that person owns stock in each of these corporations, andnthese five or fewer persons (individuals, estates, or trusts) own more than 50% of the total combined voting power of all classes of voting stock, or more than 50% of the total values of all classes of stock, of each corporation in a group of two or more corporations. A person\'s stock ownership is considered only to the extent it is identical with respect to each of these corporations.nIRC Section 11(b) states, in part, that the amount of the tax imposed for each taxable year on the taxable income of every corporation shall be 21% of taxable income. There are currently no different rules for members of a controlled.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(978,13,'Bob and Charles, as a group, transfer a building with a basis of $100,000 to the ABC Corporation in exchange for 66.67% of each class of stock with a fair market value of $300,000. The other 33.33% of the stock was already issued to Alice. What is the gain, if any, that Bob, Charles, or the ABC Corporation must recognize?','[\"Bob and Charles, $0; ABC Corporation, $0\",\"Bob and Charles, $0; ABC Corporation, $300,000\",\"Bob and Charles, $200,000; ABC Corporation, $0\",\"Bob and Charles, $0; ABC Corporation, $200,000\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnDue to the fact that Bob and Charles transferred property with a basis of $100,000 to ABC Corporation in exchange for only 66.67% of each class of stock (FMV of $300,000), they are not in control immediately after the transfer. Accordingly, Bob and Charles will recognize a taxable gain of $200,000 on the transaction, calculated as follows:nn  FMV of stock received             $300,000n  Less:n    Basis of property transferred    100,000n  Recognized gain                   $200,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(979,13,'The Cole Corporation distributes $75,000 in cash along with land having a $50,000 adjusted basis and a $60,000 FMV to its shareholder. What gain, if any, must Cole Corporation recognize?','[\"$10,000\",\"$75,000\",\"$25,000\",\"$0\"]',0,'Most distributions from a corporation are in the form of money, but they may also be in stock or other property. Distributions of cash do not generate recognized gains for the corporation. However, a corporation will recognize a gain on the distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. This is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. For this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nThus, the Cole Corporation will have a recognized gain of $10,000, computed as follows:nn FMV of the Land                  $60,000n Less:n    Adjusted Basis of the Land    (50,000)n Recognized Gain                  $10,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(980,13,'Which of the following statements is correct if you transfer property (or money and property) to a corporation solely in exchange for stock in that corporation (other than nonqualified preferred stock) and immediately thereafter you are in control of the corporation?','[\"The exchange is usually\\u00a0not\\u00a0taxable.\",\"The exchange is usually taxable partly as capital gains income and partly as ordinary income.\",\"The exchange is usually taxable as capital gains income.\",\"The exchange is usually taxable as ordinary income.\"]',0,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This tax-free exchange applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation that is being formed or is already in existence.nnThe above rule applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating. There are some exceptions to the rule. For example:nnthe corporation is an investment company;nthe transfer of the property is done in a bankruptcy or similar proceeding in exchange for stock used to pay creditors; ornthe stock is received in exchange for the corporation\'s debt (other than a security) or for interest on the corporation\'s debt (including a security) that accrued while the stockholder held the debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(981,13,'Mary owns a farm with an adjusted basis of $500,000 and a mortgage of $200,000. She exchanged the farm for stock in a transfer under IRC Section 351. What is her basis in the new stock?','[\"$300,000\",\"$200,000\",\"$500,000\",\"$700,000\"]',0,'Generally, the basis of the stock a shareholder receives is the adjusted basis of the property that was transferred. This is increased by any amount treated as a dividend, plus any gain recognized on the exchange. Additionally, the basis is decreased by any cash received, the fair market value of any other property received, and any loss recognized on the exchange. The basis is also decreased by the amount of any liability the corporation or another party to the exchange assumes.nnThus, Mary\'s basis in the new stock is $300,000, computed as follows:nn  Adjusted Basis          $500,000n  Less:n    Liability Assumed      200,000n  Basis in New Stock      $300,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(982,13,'When Susan formed a corporation in 2024, she transferred property with a basis of $100,000 to the corporation in exchange for 75% of the stock. The fair market value of the stock she received was $200,000. How should Susan report this transaction on her 2024 tax return?','[\"Report $100,000 taxable gain\",\"No reporting required because the exchange is nontaxable\",\"Attach a statement reporting the nontaxable exchange\",\"Report $166,667 taxable gain\"]',0,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnDue to the fact that Susan transferred property with a basis of $100,000 in exchange for only 75% of the stock (FMV of $200,000), she was not in control immediately after the transfer. Accordingly, Susan will recognize a taxable gain of $100,000 on the transaction, calculated as follows:nn FMV of Stock Received             $200,000n Less:n   Basis of Property Transferred    100,000n Recognized Gain                   $100,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(983,13,'Sally transferred a building with an FMV of $200,000 to Alta, Inc., in exchange for 100% of the stock, which had an FMV of $150,000. Her basis in the building was $100,000. Alta, Inc., also assumed Sally\'s $10,000 mortgage on the building. Which of the following choices correctly reflects Sally\'s taxable gain and her basis in the stock received?','[\"Recognized gain of $60,000 and a basis in the stock of $100,000\",\"Recognized gain of $0 and a basis in the stock of $90,000\",\"Recognized gain of $50,000 and a basis in the stock of $100,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. To be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnIf, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. If the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received by the shareholder.nnIn addition, the basis of the stock a shareholder receives is the adjusted basis of the property that was transferred. This is increased by any amount treated as a dividend, plus any gain recognized on the exchange. Moreover, the basis in decreased by any cash received, the fair market value of any other property you received, and any loss recognized on the exchange. The basis is also decreased by the amount of any liability the corporation or another party to the exchange assumes.nnThus, Sally\'s taxable gain is $0 and her basis in the stock received is $90,000, computed as follows:nn Adjusted Basis           $100,000n Less:n   Liability Assumed        10,000n Basis in New Stock       $ 90,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(984,13,'Karen transferred property with an adjusted basis of $45,000 and fair market value of $50,000 to Holiday Corporation in exchange for 65% of Holiday Corporation\'s only class of stock. At the time of the transfer, the stock Karen received has a fair market value of $55,000. What is Holiday Corporation\'s basis in the property after the exchange?','[\"$-0-\",\"$45,000\",\"$55,000\",\"$60,000\"]',2,'A corporation that receives property from a shareholder in exchange for its stock generally has the same basis the shareholder had in the property, increased by any gain the shareholder had to recognize on the exchange (Publication 542, page 5).nnA shareholder must recognize gain on a transfer of money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, if immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) is not in control the corporation.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnDue to the fact that Karen transferred property with a basis of $45,000 to Holiday Corporation in exchange for only 65% of stock (FMV of $55,000), she is not in control immediately after the transfer. Therefore, she has a recognized gain of $10,000, which is the FMV of stock received ($55,000) less the basis of the property transferred ($45,000).nnAccordingly, Holiday Corporation\'s basis in the property after the exchange is $55,000, which is the adjusted basis of $45,000 plus the recognized gain of $10,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(985,13,'Bob and John make the following transfers to Builders Corporation in return for 100% of the stock in the corporation:nn          Asset and Value      Asset and Valuen          Transferred to       Transferred to      Percentage ofn              Builders           Shareholder       Stock Receivedn Bob     $100,000 cash          $10,000 land             80%n John    $ 30,000 property      $ 5,000 cash             20%n         (Basis of $10,000)nWhat is the amount of gain Bob and John must recognize on the transfers?','[\"Bob must recognize $10,000 gain and John must recognize $25,000 gain.\",\"Bob recognizes $10,000 gain and John recognizes $5,000 gain.\",\"Bob recognizes no gain and John recognizes $5,000 gain.\",\"Bob recognizes $10,000 gain and John recognizes $20,000 gain.\"]',2,'Publication 542, page 3, provides, in part, that if a taxpayer transfers property (or money and property) to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation (other than nonqualified preferred stock) and immediately afterward the taxpayer is in control of the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the taxpayer or group of transferors must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nYou and Bill Jones buy property for $100,000. You both organize a corporation when the property has a fair market value of $300,000. You transfer the property to the corporation for all its authorized capital stock, which has a par value of $300,000. No gain is recognized by you, Bill, or the corporation.nn n nnIf, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the taxpayer also receives money or property other than stock, the taxpayer may have to recognize gain. That is, the taxpayer must recognize gain only up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property the taxpayer receives. Per Publication 542, page 4, the rules for figuring the recognized gain in this situation generally follow those for a partially nontaxable exchange discussed in Publication 544 under the subject of like-kind exchanges. Publication 544, page 16, notes that if a gain is realized it must be recognized, but only to the extent of the money and the fair market value of the unlike property received.nnIn this problem, therefore, Bob does not recognize any gain due to there being no realized gain ($90,000 fair market value of stock received plus $10,000 value of land received less $100,000 cash transferred to the corporation). John recognizes $5,000 gain despite realizing a $20,000 gain ($25,000 fair market value of stock received plus $5,000 cash received less $10,000 basis of property transferred to the corporation) due to the recognition being limited up to the amount of money he received.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(986,13,'Bob and Frank buy an apartment building for $100,000. Both Bob and Frank organize the Acme Property Corporation when the apartment building has a fair market value of $500,000. They transfer the building to the corporation for all of its authorized capital stock, which has a par value of $500,000. What is the gain, if any, that Bob, Frank, or the Acme Property Corporation must recognize?','[\"Bob $250,000, Frank $250,000, Acme Property Corporation $500,000\",\"Bob none, Frank none, Acme Property Corporation none\",\"Bob none, Frank none, Acme Property Corporation $500,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation.nnThe above rule applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating. There are some exceptions to the rule. For example:nnthe corporation is an investment company;nthe transfer of the property is done in a bankruptcy or similar proceeding in exchange for stock used to pay creditors; ornthe stock is received in exchange for the corporation\'s debt (other than a security) or for interest on the corporation\'s debt (including a security) that accrued while the stockholder held the debt.nTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnBob and Frank made a transfer of qualified property to Acme Property Corporation. Both were in control immediately after the transfer. Bob and Frank only received stock in exchange for the transfer of property. Therefore, the recognized gain for Bob, Frank, and the Acme Property Corporation is zero.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(987,13,'Mario and Jim are considering incorporating their pizza shop. If Mario and Jim incorporate, they would transfer the following assets to the corporation in exchange for 100% of the stock.nn                                 Basis                     FMVn                           Mario        Jim         Mario        JimnCash                      $ 5,000     $ 4,000     $  5,000     $ 4,000nEquipment                  10,000      31,000       30,000      30,000nFurniture and fixtures      1,000         -0-       12,000       1,000nBuilding                   40,000         -0-      100,000         -0-nTotals                    $56,000     $35,000     $147,000     $35,000nIf they went forward with the incorporation, how much gain/loss would Mario have to report on his individual tax return for the year of transfer?','[\"$91,000\",\"$0\",\"$91,000 loss\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnMario and Jim made a transfer of qualified property to the corporation. Both were in control immediately after the transfer. Mario and Jim received stock in exchange for the transfer of property. Therefore, Mario would not have any recognized gain to report on his individual tax return for the year of the transfer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(988,13,'Hank transfers land with an adjusted basis of $500,000 to Handy Hank\'s, Inc. In exchange, he receives shares of stock with a fair market value of $300,000 and cash in the amount of $175,000. Hank owns 51% of all of the outstanding stock of Handy Hank\'s, Inc., immediately after the transfer. What is Hank\'s deductible loss on the transaction, if any?','[\"$0\",\"$25,000 loss\",\"$200,000 loss\",\"$325,000 loss\"]',0,'If a shareholder has a loss from an exchange of property for stock and owns, directly or indirectly, more than 50% of the corporation\'s stock, the loss is nondeductible (Publication 542, page 4). Therefore, there is no deductible loss on the transaction.nnNote: See “Nondeductible Loss” under “Sales and Exchanges Between Related Persons” on page 21 of Publication 544 for more information on this issue.nnGiven that Hank transferred property with a basis of $500,000 in exchange for $175,000 in cash and 51% (more than 50%) of the stock (FMV of $300,000); he has a nondeductible loss of $25,000, determined as follows:nn  FMV of Stock Received                $300,000n  Cash Received                         175,000n  Total Received                       $475,000n  Less Basis of Property Transferred    500,000n  Nondeductible Loss                   $ 25,000n                                       ========nNote: If this question were to say that Hank owned 50% of the corporation\'s stock after the transaction, then he would have a recognized loss because he does not own more than 50%.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(989,13,'Which of the following requirements must be met for a group of corporations to be considered a brother-sister controlled group?','[\"Five or fewer persons (individuals, estates, or trusts) own at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of voting stock, or at least 80% of the total value of all classes of stock, of each corporation in a group of two or more corporations. A person\'s stock ownership is considered only if that person owns stock in each of these corporations.\",\"Five or fewer persons (individuals, estates, or trusts) own more than 50% of the total combined voting power of all classes of voting stock, or more than 50% of the total values of all classes of stock, of each corporation in a group of two or more corporations. A person\'s stock ownership is considered only to the extent it is identical with respect to each of these corporations.\",\"Both of the answer choices are correct.\",\"Neither answer choice is correct.\"]',2,'A controlled group of corporations is a group that is related through common ownership. There are two types of controlled groups: parent-subsidiary and brother-sister. (See IRC Section 1563.)nnThis question deals with the brother-sister type of relationship. A brother-sister controlled group is two or more corporations if the same five or fewer persons who are individuals, estates, or trusts directly or indirectly own stock possessing:nnat least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of voting stock, or at least 80% of the total value of all classes of stock, of each corporation in a group of two or more corporations (a person\'s stock ownership is considered only if that person owns stock in each of these corporations) (known as the 80% test) andnmore than 50% of the total combined voting power of all classes of voting stock, or more than 50% of the total value of all classes of stock, of each corporation in a group of two or more corporations (a person\'s stock ownership is considered only to the extent it is identical with respect to each of these corporations) (known as the 50% test).nThus, both situations must be met for a group of corporations to be considered a brother-sister controlled group.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(990,13,'Philly Corp. distributed an office building to its 60% shareholder. The fair market value of the building on the date of the distribution was $300,000. Philly\'s basis in the building was $200,000. The shareholder assumed the mortgage on the building that had a principal balance of $100,000 on the date of distribution. Current-year earnings and profits of Philly Corp. were $400,000. No other distributions were made during the year.nnWhat should the shareholder report on his tax return for the year of the distribution?','[\"$0; distributions to shareholders result in no gain or loss to the shareholder\",\"$300,000 dividend\",\"$200,000 dividend\",\"$100,000 dividend\"]',2,'Generally, a corporate distribution to a shareholder is treated as a distribution of earnings and profits. Distributions made from current or accumulated earnings and profits are reported as dividends to the shareholder(s). If the corporation does not have adequate earnings and profits, the excess amount distributed is applied against and reduces the adjusted basis of the shareholder\'s stock. To the extent that the balance is more than the adjusted basis of the stock, the shareholder realizes a gain (usually a capital gain) from the sale or exchange of property.nnAdditionally, the amount of a distribution is generally the amount of any money paid to the shareholder plus the fair market value (FMV) of any property transferred to the shareholder. However, this amount is reduced (but not below zero) by any liability of the corporation the shareholder assumes in connection with the distribution or any liability to which the property is subject immediately before, and immediately after, the distribution.nnThe FMV of any property distributed to a shareholder becomes the shareholder’s basis in that property.nnTherefore, the shareholder will have dividend income of $200,000, determined as follows:nn FMV of Property Received   $300,000n Less:n    Liability Assumed       (100,000)n Amount Received            $200,000, which are dividends (theren                                      are adequate earnings andn                                      profits)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(991,13,'The Star Corporation bought real estate on December 4, 2023. On June 3, 2024, the corporation traded it for another parcel of real estate in a nontaxable exchange. When does the holding period to determine whether the capital gain was long-term or short-term begin for Star Corporation if it sells the land that it acquired in the nontaxable exchange?','[\"December 4, 2023\",\"December 5, 2023\",\"June 3, 2024\",\"June 4, 2024\"]',1,'The holding period for a capital asset is the length of time the property was owned before it is disposed of by sale or exchange. Holding periods are categorized as “short term” or “long term.” In determining the holding period, the taxpayer begins counting on the day after the property was acquired. Long-term capital assets are those assets held for more than 12 months, leaving short-term capital assets to be those assets that were not held for more than 12 months.nnNote: A simple counting rule for determining the holding period is to count either the day acquired or the day sold, but not both. However, when looking for the starting period, you need to begin with the day after acquisition.nnIn addition, IRS Publication 544, page 35, provides details on holding periods in relation to different types of acquisitions. More specific to this question, the holding period for nontaxable exchanges begins on the same day as the taxpayer\'s holding period for the old property.nnTherefore, Star Corporation\'s holding period starts on December 5, 2023, the day after the old property was acquired.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(992,13,'Essex Corporation is a domestic corporation founded in 2016. Essex was originally authorized 100,000 shares with a per share value of $10. In 2016, Essex issued 50,000 shares and retained 50,000 shares. In 2024, the fair market value of an Essex share of stock equaled $100. During 2024, Essex hired a consulting firm to improve its data processing systems at a contracted cost of $20,000. The consulting work was completed in 2024 and the consulting firm agreed to accept 200 shares of Essex stock as payment of the contract. In 2024, Essex Corporation is required to report this transaction as:','[\"$20,000 in ordinary other income.\",\"$2,000 in capital loss.\",\"$0 nontaxable exchange.\",\"$18,000 in capital gain.\"]',2,'If you transfer property (including your company\'s stock) to an employee as payment for services, you can generally deduct it as wages. The amount you can deduct is the property\'s fair market value on the date of the transfer less any amount the employee paid for the property.nnYou can claim the deduction only for the tax year in which your employee includes the property\'s value in income. Your employee is deemed to have included the value in income if you report it on Form W-2 in a timely manner. These rules also apply to property transferred to an independent contractor for services.nnA corporation recognizes no gain or loss when it pays for services with its own stock. If a gain or loss is recognized, it is the difference between the FMV (fair market value) of the property and its adjusted basis on the date of transfer.nnIn this case, the company has transferred its own stock for services and, therefore, it is treated as a $0 nontaxable exchange.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(993,13,'Which of the following is an example of nonqualified preferred stock in a Section 351 transaction?','[\"The holder of the stock has the right to require the issuer or a related person to redeem or buy the stock.\",\"The issuer of the stock is required to redeem or buy the stock.\",\"The dividend rate on the stock varies with reference to interest rates, commodity process, or similar indices.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Nonqualified preferred stock is treated as property other than stock. Generally, it is preferred stock with any of the following features:nnthe holder has the right to require the issuer or a related person to redeem or buy the stock,nthe issuer or a related person is required to redeem or buy the stock,nthe issuer or a related person has the right to redeem or buy the stock and, on the issue date, it is more likely than not that the right will be exercised, ornthe dividend rate on the stock varies with reference to interest rates, commodity prices, or similar indices.nFor a detailed definition of nonqualified preferred stock, see IRC Section 351(g)(2).nnTherefore, all of the answer choices listed are examples of nonqualified preferred stock in a Section 351 transaction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(994,13,'Betsy contributes $60,000 in cash to a corporation. In return, Betsy receives from the corporation 100 shares of common stock and an antique artwork with a fair market value of $5,000. Which of the following statements is correct concerning this transaction?','[\"Betsy is required to recognize gain upon receipt of the corporate stock and artwork.\",\"Betsy is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to recognize any gain upon receipt of the artwork.\",\"Betsy\\u00a0may\\u00a0be required to recognize gain upon receipt of the artwork.\",\"Betsy is required to recognize gain upon receipt of the corporate stock.\"]',2,'If, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. If the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(995,13,'Which of the following statements is correct if a shareholder transfers a liability to a corporation along with the property, and the transferred liability exceeds the adjusted basis in the property transferred to the corporation?','[\"No gain is recognized.\",\"Gain is recognized up to the amount of the difference between the adjusted basis of the properties and the FMV of the property on the date of transfer.\",\"Gain is recognized up to the amount of the difference between the FMV of the properties and the FMV of the liabilities assumed.\",\"Gain is recognized up to the amount of the difference between the adjusted basis of the properties and the FMV of the liabilities assumed.\"]',3,'If a shareholder transfers a liability to a corporation along with the property, the exchange generally is not treated as if the shareholder received money or other property. However, there are two exceptions to this treatment:nnIf the liabilities the corporation assumes are more than the adjusted basis in the property transferred, gain is recognized up to the difference.nIf there is no good business reason for the corporation to assume the shareholder\'s liabilities, or if the shareholder\'s main purpose in the exchange is to avoid federal income tax, the assumption is treated as if the shareholder received money in the amount of the liabilities.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(996,13,'John was one of five incorporators of Builders, Inc. Each received stock valued at $100,000. The other four shareholders each contributed $100,000 for their stock. John contributed $50,000 and his services to build the corporate headquarters. He valued his services at $50,000. How much income must John recognize on this transaction?','[\"$100,000 of ordinary income\",\"$50,000 of ordinary income and $50,000 of capital gain income\",\"No income recognition\",\"$50,000 of ordinary income\"]',3,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. However, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Therefore, the value of stock received for services is income to the recipient.nnThe $50,000 of cash contributed in exchange for $50,000 in stock falls under the tax-free exchange rules. However, the $50,000 of services performed in exchange for $50,000 of stock does not and, therefore, John will recognize $50,000 of ordinary income on this part of the transaction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(997,13,'Which of the following statements are true?nn1. Members of a controlled group no longer need to use a graduated corporate tax structure.n2. When a controlled group adopts or changes an apportionment plan, each member must attach to its tax return a copy of its consent to this plan.n3. The filing of a Schedule O by a component member provides the required information as to the status of the group\'s apportionment plan.n4. If no apportionment plan is adopted, members of a controlled group must divide the amount of any tax-benefit item equally among themselves.','[\"1, 2, and 3\",\"2, 3, and 4\",\"1, 3, and 4\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'The instructions for Form 1120, Schedule O, page 1, provide, in part, that the graduated corporate tax structure has been replaced with a flat 21% corporate tax rate.nnIf no apportionment plan is adopted, members of a controlled group must divide the amount of any tax-benefit item equally amongst themselves (without regard to whether any members also are members of a consolidated group).nnA corporation must file Schedule O with its income tax return, amended return, or claim for refund for each tax year that the corporation is a component member of a controlled group, even if no apportionment plan is currently filed or the amounts apportioned have not changed from the previous tax year.nnThe filing of a Schedule O, however, by a component member provides the required information as to the status of the group\'s apportionment plan. Such information must indicate, when applicable, whether all the component members of the controlled group are adopting, amending, or terminating an apportionment plan. In addition, the agreement must be signed by a person authorized to sign on behalf of each component member of the controlled group. NO member should attach this agreement (or a copy of it) to their income tax return. Each component member must keep, as part of its records, either the original or a copy of the signed agreement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(998,13,'If a corporation transfers its stock to an employee as payment for services, the amount the corporation can deduct would be:','[\"the corporation\'s basis in the stock transferred.\",\"the fair market value of the stock on the date of the transfer.\",\"the fair market value of the stock when the corporation issues the W-2.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'When a corporation transfers stock to an employee for services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation, the value of stock received for services is income to the recipient. As a result, the fair market value of the stock on the date of the transfer is a deduction for the corporation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(999,13,'Bob and Sam transfer a building with a basis of $100,000 to the Redwood Corporation in exchange for 75% of each class of stock with a fair market value of $300,000. The other 25% of the stock was already issued to Betty. What is the gain, if any, that Bob, Sam, or the Redwood Corporation must recognize?','[\"Bob and Sam, none; Redwood Corporation none\",\"Bob and Sam, none; Redwood Corporation $300,000\",\"Bob and Sam, $200,000; Redwood Corporation none\",\"Bob and Sam, none; Redwood Corporation $200,000\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation.nnThe above rule applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating. There are some exceptions to the rule, but they are not applicable for this question.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnDue to the fact that Bob and Sam transferred property with a basis of $100,000 to Redwood Corporation in exchange for only 75% of each class of stock (FMV of $300,000), they are not in control immediately after the transfer. Accordingly, Bob and Sam will recognize a taxable gain of $200,000 on the transaction, calculated as follows:nnn FMV of stock received             $300,000n Less:n   Basis of property transferred    100,000n Recognized gain                   $200,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1000,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a distribution of amortized property from a corporation to a shareholder?','[\"The corporation recognizes a gain if the fair market value of the property is less than its adjusted basis.\",\"The corporation does\\u00a0not\\u00a0recognize a gain if the fair market value of the property is more than its adjusted basis.\",\"The corporation recognizes a gain if the fair market value of the property is more than its adjusted basis.\",\"The corporation recognizes a gain if the fair market value of the property is more than its adjusted basis and the depreciation recapture rules do not apply.\"]',2,'A corporation will recognize a gain on the distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. This is generally the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold.nnIf the property was depreciable or amortizable, the corporation may have to treat all or part of the gain as ordinary income resulting from the depreciation recapture provision.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1001,13,'Richard Crepe, MD, owns 100% of the outstanding stock of Crepe Corporation. All of Crepe Corporation\'s income and expenditures are derived from the medical services provided by Dr. Crepe. At the end of 2024, Crepe Corporation had $10,000 in reportable taxable income. How much federal income tax was Crepe Corporation required to pay for the 2024 year?','[\"$3,500\",\"$2,500\",\"$3,400\",\"$2,100\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 542, page 16, for tax years beginning after 2017, a corporation, including qualified personal service corporation, is taxed at a flat rate of 21% on taxable income. For a full description of a personal service corporation, please refer to IRC Section 448(d)(2).nnAs such, Richard Crepe, MD, is required to pay $2,100 ($10,000 × 21%) in federal income taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1002,13,'J. Hancock, a furniture retailer, incorporates his sole proprietorship by transferring cash, accounts receivable, inventory, fixtures, transportation equipment, and a building for 100% of the B shares (nonvoting) stock in the new corporation. At the same time, his new co-owner, T. Jefferson received 100% of the A shares (voting) stock in the corporation for his transfer of $100,000. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Neither will have to report a taxable transaction.\",\"Only J. Hancock will have to report a taxable transaction.\",\"Only T. Jefferson will have to report a taxable transaction.\",\"Each will have to report a taxable transaction.\"]',0,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnJ. Hancock and T. Jefferson made a transfer of qualified property to the corporation. Both were in control immediately after the transfer. J. Hancock and T. Jefferson only received stock in exchange for the transfer of property. Therefore, neither J. Hancock nor T. Jefferson has a taxable transaction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1003,13,'What is the applicable tax rate for a qualified personal service corporation?','[\"Flat 35% tax rate\",\"The same rates as applicable to an individual taxpayer\",\"The same rates as applicable to a corporation\",\"Flat 28% tax rate\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 542, page 15, for tax years beginning after 2017, a corporation, including a qualified personal service corporation is taxed at a flat rate of 21% on taxable income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1004,13,'Allen contributes machinery and real property to Jack Corporation that has been in existence for several years as follows:nn                   Adjusted     Fair Marketn     Asset           Basis         Value   n Machinery         $100,000      $150,000n Real Property     $500,000      $550,000nJack Corporation has two classes of stock—one with voting rights and one without voting rights. In exchange for the machinery and real property, Allen receives stock with a fair market value of $700,000. Immediately after the transfer, Allen owns 75% of the outstanding shares of corporate stock with voting power and 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock of the corporation. Which of the following statements is true?','[\"$100,000 gain is recognized by Allen.\",\"No gain is recognized by Allen.\",\"$100,000 loss is recognized by the corporation.\",\"$100,000 gain is recognized by Allen and the corporation will recognize a loss in the amount of $100,000.\"]',0,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This tax-free exchange applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation that is being formed or is already in existence.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnSince Allen transferred property with a basis of $600,000 to Jack Corporation in exchange for only 75% of the outstanding shares of the corporate stock with voting power and 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock, he is not in control immediately after the transfer. Accordingly, Allen will recognize a taxable gain of $100,000 on the transaction, calculated as follows:nn  FMV of Stock Received                  $700,000n  Less: Basis of Property Transferred     600,000n  Recognized Gain                        $100,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1005,13,'Which of the following is correct in the case where a group of transferors exchanges property for controlling stock in a corporation?','[\"If a proportionate transfer occurs, it will always be treated as a nontaxable exchange.\",\"If a disproportionate transfer occurs, it will be treated for tax purposes in accordance with its nature.\",\"Both of the answer choices are correct.\",\"Neither answer choice is correct.\"]',1,'If you transfer property (or money and property) to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation (other than nonqualified preferred stock), and immediately afterward you are in control of the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable.nnIf a group of transferors exchanges property for corporate stock, each transferor does not have to receive stock in proportion to his or her interest in the property transferred. However, if a disproportionate transfer does occur it will be treated for tax purposes in accordance with its nature. It may be treated as if the stock was first received in proportion and then some of it was used to make gifts, pay compensation for services, or satisfy the obligations of the transferor.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThis is a tricky question in that the one response says, “If a proportionate transfer occurs, it will always be treated as a nontaxable exchange.” Yet, the fact is that it usually is treated as nontaxable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1006,13,'Which of the following situations generally will qualify as a nontaxable exchange for a corporation?','[\"The transfer is property for stock and the transferors are in control of the transferee corporation immediately after the transfer.\",\"The corporation is an investment company.\",\"The transfer is property for stock in a bankruptcy proceeding to pay creditors.\",\"All of the situations will qualify.\"]',0,'nIf one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This tax-free exchange applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation that is being formed or is already in existence.nnA nontaxable exchange does not apply in the following situations:nnThe corporation is an investment company.nThe transfer is property for stock in a bankruptcy proceeding to pay creditors.nThe stock is received in exchange for the corporation\'s debt (other than a security) or for interest on the corporation\'s debt (including a security) that accrued while the taxpayer held the debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1007,13,'Bob transfers property worth $50,000 to the Acme Corporation and provides personal services worth $5,000 in exchange for stock valued at $55,000. Immediately after the exchange Bob owns 90.9% of Acme\'s outstanding stock. What is Bob\'s gain, if any?','[\"No capital gain, no ordinary income\",\"No capital gain, $5,000 ordinary income\",\"No capital gain, $50,000 ordinary income\",\"$5,000 capital gain, no ordinary income\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. To be in control of a corporation, the shareholder or group of shareholders must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnNote: In this situation, Bob owns 90.9% of the outstanding stock (50,000 ÷ 55,000), which is greater than the 80% required.nnIn addition, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Therefore, the value of stock received for services is ordinary income to the recipient.nnThe transfer of property worth $50,000 in exchange for stock falls under the tax-free exchange rules. However, the $5,000 of services performed in exchange for stock does not, and therefore Bob will recognize $5,000 of ordinary income, calculated as follows:nn  Stock received         $55,000n  Property (tax-free)    (50,000)n  Remaining              $ 5,000  Services performed (not propertyn                                  under the tax-free rule',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1008,13,'A distribution of taxable stock rights or dividends generally is treated the same as:','[\"any other property distribution and the holding period begins on the distribution date.\",\" the distribution of an obligation of the distributing corporation.\",\"a cash distribution.\",\"any other property distribution, but the holding period begins on the day after the issue of the underlying stock.\"]',0,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock rights and stock dividends are generally tax-free to shareholders.nnHowever, stock and stock rights are treated as property and are governed under money and property distribution rules (i.e., taxable) if certain conditions exist. For example, these rules would apply if any shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights. A list of other conditions is presented on page 32 of Publication 550.nnIf a taxpayer receives taxable stock dividends or stock rights, the fair market value at the time of the distribution is included in income. (Publication 550, page 31)nnIn determining how long an asset was held, the taxpayer generally begins counting on the date of distribution that the taxable stock dividend property was acquired (Publication 550, pages 80 and 81). If, on the other hand, the taxpayer receives nontaxable stock rights, the holding period begins on the same day as the holding period of the underlying stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1009,13,'Mrs. O\'Dell transferred property that had an adjusted basis to her of $20,000 and an FMV of $50,000, to Sinex Corporation in exchange for 100% of Sinex Corporation\'s only class of stock, $5,000 cash, and office furniture worth $5,000. At the time of the transfer, the stock had an FMV of $40,000. What amount of gain must Mrs. O\'Dell recognize?','[\"$-0-\",\"$10,000\",\"$50,000\",\"$30,000\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. To be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnIf, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. If the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received by the shareholder.nnAccordingly, Mrs. O\'Dell must recognize a gain of $10,000 ($5,000 cash plus office furniture worth $5,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1010,13,'Rand Corporation distributes land to a shareholder. The fair market value of the land exceeds its basis to the corporation. Which of the following statements is true with regard to this transaction?','[\"Rand Corporation must recognize gain on this distribution.\",\"Rand Corporation realizes but does\\u00a0not\\u00a0recognize gain on this distribution.\",\"Rand Corporation has\\u00a0neither\\u00a0a realized nor a recognized gain on this distribution.\",\"The stockholder has a recognized loss on this distribution.\"]',0,'A corporation will recognize a gain on distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nIf the property was depreciable or amortizable, the corporation may have to treat all or part of the gain as ordinary income resulting from the depreciation recapture provision.nnGiven that Rand Corporation\'s fair market value of the land exceeds its basis to the corporation, Rand Corporation must recognize gain on this distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1011,13,'During the tax year, Bill Jones, an attorney, provided all of the legal services for the incorporation of MindTech, a newly formed corporation. In exchange for these services, Bill received a check for $3,000 and stock of MindTech valued at $10,000. What will attorney Bill Jones have to report with respect to the above transaction?','[\"Ordinary income of $3,000\",\"Ordinary income of $13,000\",\"Ordinary income of $3,000 and capital gain income of $10,000\",\"Bill Jones does\\u00a0not\\u00a0report any income.\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. However, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Therefore, the exchange of property for services would not qualify. (Publication 542, pages 3 and 4)nnAs a result, the exchange of property or services results in income at the time received. In this case, the fair market value of stock received for services is income to the recipient. (Publication 17, page 67)nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nA taxpayer is a self-employed attorney who performs legal services for a client, a small corporation. The corporation gives the attorney shares of its stock as payment for his or her services. The attorney must include the fair market value of the shares in his or her income on Schedule C (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) in the year the stock is received.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1012,13,'Ned accepted stock in his employer\'s company valued at $1,000 instead of his $1,000 salary payment. Which tax consequence of this transaction is correct?','[\"No income to Ned because stock distributions are not taxable.\",\"No salary expense for his employer because no payment of salary was made.\",\"Ned must recognize $1,000 income because the stock is payment for services.\",\"This is a nontaxable exchange of property for stock.\"]',2,'Distributions by a corporation of its own stock are commonly known as stock dividends. Stock rights (also known as “stock options”) are distributions by a corporation of rights to acquire its stock. Distributions of stock dividends and stock rights are generally tax-free to shareholders.nnHowever, if any shareholder has the choice to receive cash or other property instead of stock or stock rights, the stock and stock rights are treated as property and are governed by different rules, and the shareholder must recognize income. (See IRS Publication 542, pages 17 to 18, for more details on property distributions.)nnThe term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Thus, the value of stock received for services is income to the recipient (Publication 542, page 4).nnTherefore, the tax consequence is that Ned must recognize $1,000 income because the stock is payment for services.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1013,13,'Healey, Inc., owned a parcel of undeveloped land with an adjusted basis of $10,000, an attached liability of $4,000, and a fair market value of $15,000. In 2024, this land was distributed by Healey to its sole shareholder, who also assumed the liability. Healey will recognize how much of a gain on this distribution?','[\"$0\",\"$1,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\"]',2,'A corporation will recognize a gain on distribution of property to a shareholder if the FMV of the property is more than its adjusted basis. Generally, this is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold. However, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of:nnthe actual FMV ornthe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the property.nAs such, Healy, Inc., will recognize gain of $5,000 on this distribution, computed as follows:nn  FMV                $15,000n  Less:n    Basis            (10,000)n  Recognized Gain    $ 5,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1014,13,'Tech Corporation was formed by three shareholders: Able, Baker, and Charlie. Charlie agreed to provide all of the legal work of organization and incorporation for $5,000 cash and $5,000 worth of stock in Tech Corporation. Which of the following statements regarding the exchange is true?','[\"Charlie will recognize $5,000 in ordinary income.\",\"Charlie will recognize $10,000 in ordinary income.\",\"Charlie will recognize $5,000 ordinary income and $5,000 capital gain.\",\"Charlie will not have to recognize any income because the transfer is nontaxable.\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable.nnThe term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Therefore, the value of stock received for services is income to the recipient.nnGiven that the $10,000 of services performed in exchange for cash and stock does not fall under the tax-free exchange rules, Charlie will recognize $10,000 of ordinary income. Stock received in exchange for services rendered must be included in Charlie\'s income as ordinary income (Publication 17, page 67).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1015,13,'Pietro transfers property worth $50,000 to Vino, Inc., and also provides personal services worth $5,000 in exchange for stock valued at $55,000. Immediately after the exchange, Pietro owns 90% of Vino\'s outstanding stock. What is Pietro\'s income recognition, if any?','[\"$55,000 Capital Gain, $-0- Ordinary Income\",\"$-0- Capital Gain, $5,000 Ordinary Income\",\"$-0- Capital Gain, $50,000 Ordinary Income\",\"$5,000 Capital Gain, $-0- Ordinary Income\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. However, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Therefore, the value of stock received for services is income to the recipient.nnThe transfer of property worth $50,000 in exchange for stock falls under the tax-free exchange rules. However, the $5,000 of services performed in exchange for stock does not and therefore Pietro will recognize $5,000 of ordinary income, which is the difference between the stock received of $55,000 and the property (tax-free) of 50,000. The remaining amount of $5,000 is for services performed (not property under the tax-free rule).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1016,13,'Bugs Corporation owns 100% of the stock of Grasshopper Corporation and 30% of the stock of Gnat Corporation. Grasshopper also owns 50% of Gnat stock. Each corporation has only one class of stock outstanding. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The Bugs, Grasshopper, and Gnat corporations are members of the same controlled group.\",\"The Grasshopper and Gnat corporations are members of the same controlled group.\",\"The Bugs and Gnat corporations are members of the same controlled group.\",\"The Bugs, Grasshopper, and Gnat corporations are\\u00a0not\\u00a0members of the same controlled group.\"]',0,'A controlled group of corporations is a group that is related through common ownership. There are two types of controlled groups: parent-subsidiary and brother-sister. This question deals with the parent-subsidiary type of relationship. A parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected through ownership with a common parent if:nnat least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of each of the corporations, except the common parent corporation, is directly or indirectly owned by one or more of the other corporations; andnthe common parent corporation directly or indirectly owns stock possessing at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of at least one of the other corporations, excluding, in computing such voting power or value, stock owned directly by such other corporations (Schedule O (Form 1120) Instructions, pages 1–2).nGiven that Bugs Corporation owns 30% of Gnat Corporation and 100% of Grasshopper (which owns 50% of Gnat Corporation), the 80% rules have been met. The Bugs, Grasshopper, and Gnat corporations are therefore members of the same controlled group.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1017,13,'The Smart Corporation distributes an office building to Collin, a shareholder of the corporation. The fair market value of the building exceeds its basis to the corporation. Which of the following statements is true with regard to this transaction?','[\"Smart Corporation realizes but does not recognize gain on this distribution.\",\"Smart Corporation elects not to report the gain on this distribution.\",\"Smart Corporation must recognize gain on this distribution.\",\"Collin must recognize the losses on this distribution on his return as a shareholder.\"]',2,'Most distributions from a corporation are in the form of money, but they may also be in stock or other property. Distributions of cash do not generate recognized gains for the corporation. However, a corporation will recognize a gain on the distribution of property to a shareholder if the fair market value (FMV) of the property is more than its adjusted basis. This is the same treatment the corporation would receive if the property were sold.nnHowever, for this purpose, the FMV of the property is the greater of the following amounts:nnThe actual FMVnThe amount of any liabilities the shareholder assumed in connection with the distribution of the propertynTherefore, Smart Corporation must recognize gain on this distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1018,13,'Donna exchanges property having an $18,000 adjusted basis and a $35,000 fair market value for 70 out of the 100 shares of the newly created Table Corporation stock. Evelyn exchanges legal services worth $15,000 for the remaining 30 out of the 100 shares of Table Corporation stock. Which of the following is correct?','[\"Evelyn recognizes no income, and the exchange is nontaxable.\",\"Evelyn must recognize $15,000 of income, but Donna\'s transfer of property qualifies under IRC Section 351 as nontaxable.\",\"Evelyn must recognize $15,000 of income, and Donna must recognize $17,000 gain on the exchange.\",\"The exchange qualifies as a nontaxable exchange under IRC Section 351.\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. However, the term “property” does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing corporation. Therefore, the value of stock received for services is ordinary income to the recipient.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnThe term \"property\" does not include services rendered or to be rendered to the issuing company. Hence, Evelyn\'s exchange of $15,000 of legal services for stock does not fall under the tax-free rules, and she will recognize $15,000 of ordinary income.nnWhen a corporation receives property for its stock in a taxable exchange to the transferor, the corporation\'s basis for the property is the fair market value of the stock on the date of the exchange. If the corporation\'s stock has no established market value at the time of the exchange, it may be considered to be the equivalent of the fair market value of the property received.nnIf a corporation acquires property from a shareholder as paid-in surplus or as a contribution to capital, the basis of the property to the corporation is the same as it was to the transferor, increased by the amount of gain recognized by the transferor on the transfer (IRC Section 362).nnA corporation that receives property from the transferor in exchange for its stock generally has the same basis that the transferor had in the property, increased by any gain the transferor recognized in the exchange.nnDue to the fact that Donna transferred property with a basis of $18,000 and an FMV of $35,000 to Table Corporation in exchange for only 70% of stock, she is not in control immediately after the transfer. Accordingly, Donna will recognize a taxable gain of $17,000 on the transaction, calculated as follows:nn  FMV of Property Transferred       $35,000n  Less:n    Basis of Property Transferred   (18,000)n  Recognized Gain                   $17,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1019,13,'Mr. Smith and Mr. Jones each transfer property with a basis of $10,000 to a corporation in exchange for stock with a fair market value of $30,000. The total stock received by them represents 75% of each class of stock of the corporation. The other 25% of each class of stock was issued earlier to Mr. Brown, an unrelated person. The taxable consequences are:','[\"none because it is transfer of property for stock.\",\"Mr. Smith and Mr. Jones each recognize a gain of $20,000.\",\"Mr. Smith and Mr. Jones each recognize a gain of $30,000.\",\"80% of the transaction is recognized as a taxable gain.\"]',1,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This rule applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation. It also applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating.nnTo be in control of a corporation, the shareholder(s) must own, immediately after the exchange, at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote and at least 80% of the outstanding shares of each class of nonvoting stock.nnSince Mr. Smith and Mr. Jones transferred property with a basis of $10,000 to a corporation in exchange for only 75% of each class of stock, they are not in control immediately after the transfer. Accordingly, Mr. Smith and Mr. Jones will recognize a taxable gain of $20,000 on the transaction, calculated as follows:nn  FMV of Stock Received              $30,000n  Less:n    Basis of Property Transferred     10,000n  Recognized Gain                    $20,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1020,13,'Which of the following statements is correct when assets owned by an individual are free of debt and are properly contributed to a new corporation in exchange for stock in that company and immediately thereafter that individual is in control of the corporation?','[\"Will result in a taxable event to both the individual and the corporation\",\"Will result in a taxable event to the individual only\",\"Will result in a taxable event to the corporation only\",\"Will\\u00a0not\\u00a0result in a taxable event to either the individual or the corporation\"]',3,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. This tax-free exchange applies both to individuals and to groups who transfer property to a corporation.nnThe above rule applies whether the corporation is being formed or is already operating. There are some exceptions to the rule. For example:nnthe corporation is an investment company;nthe transfer of the property is done in a bankruptcy or similar proceeding in exchange for stock used to pay creditors; ornthe stock is received in exchange for the corporation\'s debt (other than a security) or for interest on the corporation\'s debt (including a security) that accrued while the stockholder held the debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1021,13,'The basis of property you buy is usually its cost. In determining the acquisition basis in C corporation stock, a shareholder must know:','[\"the amount paid in cash or property.\",\"the amount paid in cash and debt obligations.\",\"the value of provided services and debt obligations assumed.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The basis of property that you buy is usually the cost. The cost is the amount a taxpayer pays in cash, debt obligations, and other property or services. Additionally, if the shareholder receives investment property for services, the shareholder must know the value of the provided services. If the services were performed for a price that was agreed to beforehand, this price will be accepted as the fair market value of the property if there is no evidence to the contrary.nnTherefore, all of the items listed must be known in order to determine the acquisition basis in C corporation stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1022,13,'York, Inc., directly owns stock of Ajax Corporation. To determine if Ajax Corporation is a member of a controlled group with York, Inc., as the common parent, York must own at least what percentage of the voting and total value of the Ajax Corporation stock?','[0.5100000000000000088817841970012523233890533447265625,0.75,0.8000000000000000444089209850062616169452667236328125,1]',2,'A controlled group of corporations is a group that is related through common ownership. There are two types of controlled groups: parent-subsidiary and brother-sister. This question deals with the parent-subsidiary type of relationship.nnA parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected through ownership with a common parent if:nnat least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of each of the corporations, except the common parent corporation, is directly or indirectly owned by one or more of the other corporations; andnthe common parent corporation directly or indirectly owns stock possessing at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of at least one of the other corporations, excluding, in computing such voting power or value, stock owned directly by such other corporations (Schedule O (Form 1120) Instructions, pages 1 and 2).nIn this case, Ajax Corporation is a member of a controlled group with York, Inc., as the common parent if York owns at least 80% of the voting and total value of Ajax Corporation stock.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1023,13,'Jenny transferred a factory building with an adjusted basis of $70,000 and a fair market value of $110,000 to the Crystal Corporation in exchange for 100% of Crystal Corporation stock and $20,000 cash. The building was subject to a mortgage of $25,000, which Crystal Corporation assumed. The fair market value of the stock was $75,000. Which is the amount of Jenny\'s realized gain and recognized gain?','[\"Realized: $25,000; Recognized: $25,000\",\"Realized: $50,000; Recognized: $40,000\",\"Realized: $50,000; Recognized: $20,000\",\"Realized: $35,000; Recognized: $20,000\"]',2,'If one or more shareholders transfer money or property to a corporation in exchange for stock in that corporation, and immediately afterwards the shareholder(s) control the corporation, the exchange is usually not taxable. If, in an otherwise nontaxable exchange of property for corporate stock, the shareholder also receives money or property other than stock, a gain may be recognized. The shareholder will only recognize gain up to the amount of money plus the fair market value of the other property received. Additionally, if the corporation assumes any liabilities, the exchange generally is not treated as if money or other property was received by the shareholder.nnThus, Jenny\'s realized gain is $50,000 and her recognized gain is $20,000, determined as follows:nn FMV of stock received     $ 75,000n Cash received               20,000n Assumed liability           25,000n Total received            $120,000n Less:n   Adjusted basis            70,000n Realized gain             $ 50,000nDue to the fact that the recognized gain is limited to the amount of cash received, Jenny\'s recognized gain in the transaction would be $20,000 (the amount of cash she received).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1024,13,'Westover Health Services, Inc., a personal service corporation, has two shareholders. Westover was incorporated in 2005 and has made irregular and infrequent distributions to its shareholders. The balance sheet of Westover Health Services, Inc., reflects unappropriated retained earnings in the amount of $800,000 and no marketable securities. Westover has no specific, definite, and feasible plans for use of the earnings accumulation in its business. It has been determined that the amount needed to redeem a deceased shareholder\'s stock is $500,000. What is the amount of accumulated earnings tax that Westover Health Services could be subject to for tax year ended December 31, 2024?','[\"$10,000\",\"$19,300\",\"$30,000\",\"$0\"]',2,'A corporation can accumulate its earnings for a possible expansion or other bona fide business reasons. However, if a corporation allows earnings to accumulate beyond the reasonable needs of the business, it may be subject to an accumulated earnings tax of 20%.nnTo determine if the corporation is subject to this tax, first treat an accumulation of $250,000 or less generally as within the reasonable needs of most businesses. Treat an accumulation of $150,000 or less as within the reasonable needs of a business whose principal function is performing services in the fields of accounting, actuarial science, architecture, consulting, engineering, health (including veterinary services), law, and the performing arts.nnIn determining if the corporation has accumulated earnings and profits beyond its reasonable needs, value the listed and readily marketable securities owned by the corporation and purchased with its earnings and profits at net liquidation value, not at cost.nnReasonable needs of the business include the following:nnSpecific, definite, and feasible plans for use of the earnings accumulation in the businessnThe amount necessary to redeem the corporation\'s stock included in a deceased shareholder\'s gross estate, if the amount does not exceed the reasonably anticipated total estate and inheritance taxes and funeral and administration expenses incurred by the shareholder\'s estatenThe absence of a bona fide business reason for a corporation\'s accumulated earnings may be indicated by many different circumstances, such as a lack of regular distributions to its shareholders or withdrawals by the shareholders classified as personal loans. However, actual moves to expand the business generally qualify as a bona fide use of the accumulations. The fact that a corporation has an unreasonable accumulation of earnings is sufficient to establish liability for the accumulated earnings tax unless the corporation can show the earnings were not accumulated to allow its individual shareholders to avoid income tax.nnAs such, the amount of accumulated earnings tax that Westover Health Services, Inc., could be subject to for tax year ended December 31, 2024, is $30,000, computed as follows:nn  Unappropriated retained earnings:     $800,000n  - Allowable retained earnings          150,000n  - Deceased shareholder redemption      500,000n  Amount that may be subject to tax     $150,000n  Tax rate                                  0.20n  Accumulated earnings tax              $ 30,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1025,13,'Which of the following statements about a controlled group of corporations is true?','[\"The amount of the tax imposed for each taxable year on the taxable income of every corporation shall be 21% of taxable income.\",\"A parent corporation and its 80% owned subsidiary make up a controlled group.\",\"All members of a controlled group need not use the parent corporation\'s tax year.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'IRC Section 11(b) states, in part, that the amount of the tax imposed for each taxable year on the taxable income of every corporation shall be 21% of taxable income.nnAdditionally, a parent-subsidiary control group exists when a group of one or more chains of corporations are connected through ownership with a common parent if:nnat least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of each of the corporations, except the common parent corporation, is directly or indirectly owned by one or more of the other corporations; andnthe common parent corporation directly or indirectly owns stock possessing at least 80% of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock entitled to vote or at least 80% of the total value of shares of all classes of stock of at least one of the other corporations, excluding, in computing such voting power or value, stock owned directly by such other corporations (Schedule O (Form 1120) Instructions, pages 1–2).nFinally, a corporation is a component member of a controlled group of corporations on December 31 of any year unless it is excluded. For example, a member of such a group is excluded if it is a member for less than half the number of days in such taxable year that proceeds such December 31. As a result, it is not required that all members of a “controlled group” elect the parent corporation\'s tax year.nnConsequently, all of the listed statements are correct in regard to a controlled group of corporations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1026,13,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a car dealership?','[\"If a car dealership receives a trade discount, a reduction in the cost of cars purchased for resale, the dealership must reduce its cost basis in the cars by the amount of the discount.\",\"If the dealership receives a cash discount, a reduction in the invoice price for paying within a prescribed time, the dealership may allocate the discount to a special discount income account and report the discounts as income for the taxable period.\",\"If the dealership receives a cash discount, a reduction in the invoice price for paying within a prescribed time, the dealership may reduce its cost basis in the cars.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 334, page 28, addresses the issue of trade and cash discounts. In particular, a merchant must use the cost of all merchandise that is bought for sale. If the merchant is a manufacturer or producer, this includes the cost of all raw materials or parts purchased for manufacture into a finished product.nnA trade discount is the difference between the stated prices of articles and the actual prices paid for them. In this case, the taxpayer must use the prices paid (not the stated prices) in figuring the cost of purchases. An automobile dealer, for example, must record the cost of a car in inventory reduced by a manufacturer\'s rebate that represents a trade discount.nnCash discounts are amounts deducted from the purchase invoice price by the supplier for prompt payments. There are two methods of accounting for cash discounts. The taxpayer may either credit them to a separate discount account or deduct them from total purchases for the year. Whichever method is used by the taxpayer, he or she must continue to utilize it for consistency. To change the method of figuring inventory cost, the taxpayer must file Form 3115, Application for Change in Accounting Method.nnTherefore, all of the answer choices in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1027,13,'When Jill formed a corporation in 2024, she transferred property with a basis of $100,000 to the corporation in exchange for 75% of the stock. The fair market value of the stock she received was $50,000. How should Jill report this transaction on her 2024 tax return?','[\"No reporting is required because the exchange is nontaxable.\",\"Report a $50,000 capital loss.\",\"Jill has a nondeductible $50,000 loss.\",\"Report a $50,000 ordinary loss.\"]',2,'If a shareholder has a loss from an exchange of property for stock and owns, directly or indirectly, more than 50% of the corporation\'s stock, the loss is nondeductible.nnGiven that Jill transferred property with a basis of $100,000 in exchange for 75% (more than 50%) of the stock (FMV of $50,000); she has a nondeductible loss of $50,000, determined as follows:nn FMV of Stock Received              $ 50,000n Less:n   Basis of Property Transferred     100,000n Nondeductible Loss                 $ 50,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1028,13,'Which of the following is a correct statement about a Section 351 property exchange for stock in a corporation?','[\"A statement of all facts relevant to the exchange must be attached to the individual\'s tax return only.\",\"A statement of all facts relevant to the exchange must be attached to the corporation\'s tax return only.\",\"A statement of all facts relevant to the exchange must be attached to the individual\'s (or individuals\') tax return(s) as well as to the corporate tax return in the year of the exchange.\",\"A statement of all facts relevant to the exchange must be attached to either the individual\'s (or individuals\') tax return(s) or the corporate tax return in the year of the exchange, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0both.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 542, page 3, both the corporation and any person involved in a nontaxable exchange of property for stock must attach to their income tax returns a complete statement of all facts pertinent to the exchange. For more information, one needs to consult with Treasury Regulation 1.351-3.nnAccording to Treasury Regulation 1.351-3, every shareholder that makes a Section 351 property exchange for stock in a corporation shall file, with his or her income tax return for the taxable year in which the exchange occurs, a complete statement of all facts relevant to the exchange.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1029,4,'The executor of the Smith estate made a distribution of 100% of the estate\'s assets prior to paying the estate\'s income tax liability. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the payment of that tax liability?','[\"The beneficiary can be liable for any taxes due.\",\"The executor (or executrix) can be liable for any taxes due.\",\"The beneficiary and executor (or executrix) are equally liable for any taxes due.\",\"No one is liable for any taxes due.\"]',0,'An estate is a taxable entity separate from the decedent and comes into being with the death of the individual. It exists until the final distribution of its assets to the heirs and other beneficiaries. The income earned by the assets during this period must be reported by the estate.nnAs such, the income tax liability of an estate attaches to the assets of the estate. If the income is distributed or must be distributed during the current tax year, the income is reportable by each beneficiary on his or her individual income tax return. If the income does not have to be distributed and is not distributed but is retained by the estate, the income tax on the income is payable by the estate. If the income is distributed later without the payment of the taxes due, the beneficiary can be liable for tax due and unpaid to the extent of the value of the estate assets received.nnIncome of the estate is taxed to either the estate or the beneficiary, but not to both.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1030,4,'Which of the following simple trusts must file a tax return?','[\"A trust with no taxable income\",\"A trust with gross income of $500\",\"A trust with a beneficiary who is a nonresident alien\",\"None of the trusts listed are required to file a tax return.\"]',2,'A trust must file a tax return (Form 1041) if it has any of the following items: any taxable income for the tax year, gross income of $600 or more (regardless of taxable income),  a beneficiary who is a nonresident alien, or if the trust held a qualified opportunity fund at any time during the year.nnAccordingly, a trust could have zero taxable income or have gross income of less than $600 and still be required to file a tax return; however, it is not always required. The trust with a beneficiary who is a nonresident alien is always required to file a tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1031,4,'XYZ Trust is a complex trust. What is the trust\'s distribution deduction based on the following information (capital gains are allocated to income, there is no interest income, and there is no charitable contribution)?nn  Adjusted total income                                $10,000n  Capital gain (included in adjusted total income)       2,000n  Income required to be distributed currently            5,000','[\"$10,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$0\",\"$8,000\"]',1,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries.nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trust is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). (See Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnTherefore, XYZ Trust will be able to deduct $5,000 as an income distribution deduction, determined as follows:nnDNI                          $10,000 (Line 7, Schedule B, Form 1041)nAmount distributed           $ 5,000 (Line 11, Schedule B, Form 1041)nIncome distributionn  deduction (limited to DNI) $ 5,000 (Line 15, Schedule B, Form 1041)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1032,4,'Which of the following is correct if you are the beneficiary of a trust that must distribute all its income currently?','[\"The beneficiary must report its share of the DNI if the beneficiary did not actually receive it or the beneficiary\'s proportionate share of the DNI if the distributed amount exceeds the DNI.\",\"The beneficiary must report the amount the beneficiary actually received, not the beneficiary\'s share of the DNI.\",\"The beneficiary must report the amount that exceeds the DNI amount only.\",\"The trust must pay the tax on the beneficiary\'s distributive share of income.\"]',0,'Pursuant to the Instructions for Form 1041, pages 18 and 19, a trust may qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently;nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes; andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nA complex trust is any trust that does not qualify as a simple trust as explained above.nnThe beneficiary of a simple trust must include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI. (Form 1041 Instructions, page 41)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1033,4,'After Mary died on June 30, 2024, her executor identified the following items belonging to her estate:nn1. Personal residence with a fair market value of $400,000 and an existing     mortgage of $100,000n2. Certificate of deposit in the amount of $150,000, of which $10,000 was accrued interest payable at maturity on August 1, 2024n3. Stock portfolio with a value at date of death of $1 million and a basis of $500,000n4. Life insurance policy, with her daughter named as an irrevocable beneficiary, in the amount of $150,000nAssuming that no alternate valuation date is elected, what is the gross value of Mary\'s estate?','[\"$1,700,000\",\"$1,090,000\",\"$1,550,000\",\"$1,450,000\"]',2,'The gross estate is valued at the date of death, unless the alternate valuation method is elected. The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes (as given on pages 1 and 2 of the Instructions for Form 706):nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nThe proceeds of all insurance must be included in the estate on the life of the decedent not receivable by, or for the benefit of, the decedent\'s estate if the decedent possessed at death any of the following incidents of ownership, exercisable either alone or in conjunction with any person or entity (Form 706 Instructions, page 27):nnThe right of the insured or estate to its economic benefitsnThe power to change the beneficiarynThe power to surrender or cancel the policynThe power to assign the policy or to revoke an assignmentnThe power to pledge the policy for a loannThe power to obtain from the insurer a loan against the surrender value of the policynA reversionary interest if the value of the reversionary interest was more than 5% of the value of the policy immediately before the decedent diednAccordingly, the life insurance policy with her daughter named as an irrevocable beneficiary does not have the incidents of ownership and is not included, so the gross value of Mary\'s estate is $1,550,000, determined as follows:nn  Personal Residence        $  400,000n  Certificate of Deposit       150,000n  Stocks                     1,000,000n  Gross Estate              $1,550,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1034,4,'The trust instrument for RJC Trust is silent as to the allocation of capital gains. In 2024, RJC Trust, a simple trust, had taxable interest income of $4,000, capital gains of $3,000, paid a fiduciary fee of $625, and had tax-exempt interest of $1,000. If the general rule to determine the allocation of the capital transaction is applied, what amount of taxable income is distributed to the beneficiaries in 2024?','[\"$6,500\",\"$6,375\",\"$3,500\",\"$3,375\"]',2,'Beneficiaries of trusts are required to include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI. Additionally, deductions that are applicable to an item of income that is not included in the computation of DNI or attributable to corpus, such as fiduciary fees for tax-exempt interest, are not allowed to offset taxable income. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 41)nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the RJC Trust will pass $3,500 in taxable income to the beneficiaries, which is the taxable interest income of $4,000 less the fiduciary fee of $500. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 41)nn  Taxable Interest      $4,000n  Less: Fiduciary Fee      500  (625 x ($4,000/$5,000))n  Taxable Income        $3,500nNote: Regulation Section 1.212-1(i) provides in part that expenses are only deductible to the extent that they are applicable to taxable income. Accordingly, the $625 cannot be deducted in full but must be expensed based on the taxable versus nontaxable income, i.e., only $500 is allocable to taxable income. Likewise, we could have deducted $547 (($7,000 ÷ $8,000) × $625) to reflect total taxable income or a resulting taxable income of $3,453, which is not one of the responses given. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 31)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1035,4,'All of the following returns would include income in respect of a decedent except:','[\"the final Form 1040 for the decedent\",\"the decedent\'s estate, Form 1041, if the decedent\\u2019s estate receives right to the income.\",\"the Form 1040 of any person to whom the decedent\\u2019s estate properly distributes the income.\",\"the beneficiary\\u2019s Form 1040, if the right to income arising out of the decedent\\u2019s death is passed directly to the beneficiary and is never acquired by the decedent\\u2019s estate.\"]',0,'The decedents income includible on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return. (Publication 559, page 5)nnAll income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that wasn\'t properly includible on the final return is income in respect of a decedent. (Publication 559, page 10)nnHence, the final Form 1040 would not include income in respect of a decedent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1036,4,'Trust B has distributable net income of $60,000, which includes $5,000 of tax-exempt income. The trustee distributed $75,000 to the trust\'s sole beneficiary. What amount will be shown as the distribution deduction on the trust\'s Form 1041?','[\"$55,000\",\"$60,000\",\"$70,000\",\"$75,000\"]',0,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries (Form 1041 Instructions, page 4).nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts for amounts paid, credited, or required to be distributed to beneficiaries is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). (See Form 1041 Instructions, page 4, and Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnTherefore, Trust B will be able to deduct $55,000 as an income distribution deduction, determined as follows:nnDNI                            $60,000   Line 7, Schedule B, Form 1041nLess:n  Tax-exempt interest           (5,000)  Line 2, Schedule B, Form 1041nTentative income distribution  $55,000   Line 14, Schedule B, Form 1041n  deductionn  nAmount distributed             $75,000   Line 11, Schedule B, Form 1041nLess:n  Tax-exempt income             (5,000)  Line 12, Schedule B, Form 1041nTentative income distribution  $70,000   Line 13, Schedule B, Form 1041n  deductionnIncome distribution deductionn  (lesser of line 13 or 14, n   and limited to DNI)         $55,000   Line 15, Schedule B, Form 1041n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1037,4,'What is the tax consequence of a taxpayer receiving the wages that were due to a decedent at the time of their death?','[\"There is no tax consequence. Inheritances are not taxable.\",\"The income is considered a long-term capital gain because it was inherited.\",\"The income is considered ordinary income just as it would have been considered for the decedent.\",\"The income is considered a short-term capital gain if it is paid out within one year of the decedent\'s death.\"]',2,'Publication 559, page 14, provides that the character of income received in respect of a decedent remains the same as it would have been to the decedent if the decedent were alive. Wages are not reduced by any amounts withheld by the employer and should be issued on Form 1099-MISC if the income is $600 or more. Wages paid as income in respect of a decedent are not subject to federal income tax withholding but are subject to Social Security and Medicare taxes if paid during the calendar year of death. These taxes are included on the decedent\'s Form W-2 with taxes withheld prior to death. Wages are not included in box 1 of Form W-2. Wages paid as IRD after the year of death generally are not subject to withholding of any federal taxes.nnThe correct answer is that income is considered ordinary income just as it would have been considered for the decedent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1038,4,'The Alan Trust must distribute all of its income annually. Shown below are the trust\'s income and expenses for the year ($100 of the fiduciary fee is allocable to the nontaxable interest). Based on this information, how much taxable income will be passed through to the trust\'s beneficiaries?nn  Taxable interest        $3,000n  Tax-exempt interest      1,000n  Fiduciary fee              400','[\"$2,600\",\"$2,700\",\"$3,000\",\"$3,600\"]',1,'Beneficiaries of a simple trust are required to include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI. (Form 1041 Instructions, page 41)nnGenerally, items of deduction that enter into the computation of DNI are allocated among the items of income to the extent such allocation is not inconsistent with the rules set out in IRC Section 469 and its regulations, relating to passive activity loss limitations, in the following order.nnFirst, all deductions directly attributable to a specific class of income are deducted from that income. For example, rental expenses, to the extent allowable, are deducted from rental income.nnSecond, deductions that are not directly attributable to a specific class of income generally may be allocated to any class of income, as long as a reasonable portion is allocated to any tax-exempt income. Deductions considered not directly attributable to a specific class of income under this rule include fiduciary fees, safe deposit box rental charges, and state income and personal property taxes. The charitable deduction, however, must be ratably apportioned among each class of income included in DNI. (See the instructions for Form 1041, page 41, and Form 1041.)nnIRC Section 212 expenses that are directly allocable to tax-exempt interest are allocated only to tax-exempt interest. A reasonable proportion of IRC Section 212 expenses that are indirectly allocable to both tax-exempt interest and other income must be allocated to each class of income. (Form 1041 Instructions, page 30)nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the Alan Trust will pass $2,700 in taxable income to the beneficiaries, which is the interest income of $3,000 less the applicable fiduciary fee of $300 ($400 − $100), where the $100 is equal to $400 × ($1,000 ÷ $4,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1039,4,'Which of the following includes income in respect of a decedent?','[\"The final Form 1040 for the decedent\",\"The decedent\'s estate, Form 706, if the decedent\'s estate receives the right to the income\",\"The Form 1040 of any person to whom the decedent\'s estate properly distributes the income\",\"The beneficiary\'s Form 709, as a gift to the beneficiary\"]',2,'Income in respect of a decedent (IRD) is all income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that was NOT properly includible on the final return, therefore it is not reported on the final Form 1040 of the decedent.nnIRD must be included in the income of one of the following: :nnThe estate (Form 1041)nThe beneficiary (Form 1040)nAny person whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it (Form 1040)nPublication 559, page 37, provides that Form 706 is filed when the gross estate of the decedent plus any adjusted taxable gifts and gift tax exemption is valued at more than $13,610,000 for 2024. This number is adjusted annually for inflation. Page 38 indicates that form 709 is used for gift tax returns.nnThe correct answer is the Form 1040 of any person to whom the decedent’s estate properly distributes the income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1040,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning an estate of a domestic decedent or a domestic trust that had no tax liability for the full 12-month 2024 tax year?','[\"It is required to make estimated tax payments in 2025 because the 1-year exception rule does not apply.\",\"It is required to make estimated tax payments in 2025 because it had no tax liability for the full 12-month 2024 tax year.\",\"It is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to make estimated tax payments in 2025 because the 2024 tax return had no tax liability.\",\"It is required to make estimated tax payments in 2025 because there are no exceptions.\"]',2,'Estates with tax years ending 2 or more years after the date of the decedent\'s death must pay estimated tax in the same manner as individuals. That means that during the first 2 years following the death of the taxpayer, no estimated payments are necessary.nnGenerally, estimated tax must be paid if the estate is expected to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least $1,000 in tax for 2025. The taxpayer will not, however, have to pay estimated tax if the taxpayer expects the withholding and credits to be at least:nn90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 return orn100% of the tax shown on the 2024 return and 110% if the estate\'s 2024 adjusted gross income (AGI) was more than $150,000.nThe general rule is that the first estimated tax payment must be made by April 15. The taxpayer can either pay all of his or her estimated tax at that time or pay it in four equal amounts as follows: April 15, 2025; June 15, 2025; September 15, 2025; and January 15, 2026.nnNo estimated payments are required because the 2024 tax return had no tax liability in the prior tax year, so the estate will meet the 100% of prior-year tax test.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1041,4,'The Ray Irrevocable Trust incurred a net operating loss (NOL) from normal business operations in 2024, which is during its 4th, non-final year of existence. Ray\'s children are the income beneficiaries of the trust. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the NOL?','[\"The NOL is passed through to the beneficiaries and claimed on their returns.\",\"The NOL is carried back or, if elected, carried forward under the same rules for individuals.\",\"The NOL is carried forward only and can only be passed through in the final year of a trust.\",\"The NOL can only be claimed in the final year of the trust.\"]',2,'Under the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (TCJA), an NOL for a tax year, could only be carried forward to subsequent years and cannot be carried back. An exception for farming losses allowed a 2-year carryback provision (Instructions for Form 1041, page 28).nnOn the termination of the estate or trust, any unused NOL carryover that would be allowable to the estate or trust in a later tax year, but for the termination, is allowed to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate or trust. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 28)nnIf the estate or trust has for its final year deductions (excluding the charitable deductions and exemptions) in excess of its gross income, the excess is allowed as an itemized deduction to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate or trust. In addition, an unused NOL carryover that is allowed to beneficiaries cannot also be treated as an excess deduction. However, if the final year of the estate or trust is also the last year of the NOL carryover period, the NOL carryover not absorbed in that tax year by the estate or trust is included as an excess deduction. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 28)nnGiven that Ray Irrevocable Trust incurred the net operating loss during a “non-final” year, the NOL can only be carried forward under the same rules for individuals beginning in 2018 as a result of TCJA.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1042,4,'Snickers Trust did not file an estate tax return Form 1041 for the 2024 year. At the beginning of 2025, Snickers Trust expects withholding and credits to be less than 90% of the tax reportable at year-end. Snickers Trust must pay estimated income tax for 2025 if it expects to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least what amount?','[\"$100\",\"$600\",\"$1,000\",\"$2,500\"]',2,'Generally, estimated tax must be paid if the estate is expected to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least $1,000 in tax for 2025. You will not, however, have to pay estimated tax if you expect the withholding and credits to be at least:nn90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 return orn100% of the tax shown on the 2024 return. (The percentage is 110% if the estate\'s 2024 adjusted gross income (AGI) was more than $150,000.)nHowever, if a return was not filed for 2024 or that return did not cover a full 12 months, the 100% of the tax shown on the 2023 return exception does not apply.nnTherefore, Snickers Trust must pay estimated tax for 2025 if it expects to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least $1,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1043,4,'The Emerson estate has distributable net income (DNI) of $20,000 on its 2024 return. The only distribution the executor made during the year was $10,000, paid to the decedent\'s son, Sam. The distribution was made to fulfill a bequest stated in the decedent\'s will, which required that one payment of $10,000 be paid to Sam within 6 months of Mr. Emerson\'s death and the remainder at the settlement of the estate. Which of the following statements is true regarding who will pay tax on the estate\'s income?','[\"Sam must pay tax on $10,000.\",\"Sam must pay tax on $20,000.\",\"Sam is not required to pay tax on the distribution.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'A bequest is the act of giving or leaving property to another through the last will and testament. Generally, any distribution of income (or property in kind) to a beneficiary is an allowable deduction to the estate and is includible in the beneficiary\'s gross income to the extent of the estate\'s distributable net income. However, a distribution will not be an allowable deduction to the estate and will not be includible in the beneficiary\'s gross income if the distribution meets the following requirements:nnit is required by the terms of the will,nit is a gift or bequest of a specific sum of money or property, andnit is paid out in three or fewer installments under the terms of the will.nTherefore, since the distribution to Sam meets the above requirements, Sam is not required to pay tax on the distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1044,4,'Trust Y has taxable interest and dividends of $9,000 and tax-exempt interest of $1,000. The only expense the trust incurred was a trustee fee of $500. Based on this information, what amount of adjusted tax-exempt interest is included in the trust\'s distributable net income?','[\"$8,550\",\"$500\",\"$950\",\"$1,000\"]',2,'A trust will arrive at distributable net income (DNI) by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. (See Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the amount of adjusted tax-exempt interest that should be included in the trust\'s DNI, any expenses that are directly allocable to tax-exempt interest are deducted (Form 1041 Instructions, page 30).nnTherefore, $950 of adjusted tax-exempt interest is included in the trust\'s distributable net income, calculated as follows:nnn Tax-Exempt Interest           $1,000n Less:n    Trustee Fee (Prorated)        (50), 10% ($1,000 / $10,000) of $500n Adjusted Tax-Exempt Interest  $  950',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1045,4,'Which of the following will not shorten the period for assessing the tax when a fiduciary representing a dissolving corporation requests a prompt assessment of tax under Internal Revenue Code Section 6501(d) by filing a Form 4810?','[\"Where the taxpayer did not report substantial amounts of gross income\",\"Where the taxpayer was filing a final return\",\"Where the taxpayer filed a false return\",\"Where the taxpayer did not report substantial amounts of gross income or where the taxpayer filed a false return\"]',3,'The Internal Revenue Service ordinarily has 3 years from the date an income tax return is filed, or its due date, whichever is later, to charge any additional tax due. However, a personal representative may request a prompt assessment of tax after the return has been filed. This reduces the time from making the assessment to 18 months from the date the written request for prompt assessment was received. This request can be made for any tax return (except the estate tax return) of the decedent or the decedent’s estate. This may permit a quicker settlement of the tax liability of the estate and an earlier final distribution of the assets to the beneficiaries.nnForm 4810 can be used for making this request. However, it must be filed separately from any other document.nnIf taxpayer or the decedent failed to report substantial amounts of gross income (more than 25% of the gross income reported on the return) or filed a false or fraudulent return, the taxpayer\'s request for prompt assessment will not shorten the period during which the IRS may assess the additional tax. However, such a request may relieve the taxpayer of personal liability for the tax if the taxpayer did not have knowledge of the unpaid tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1046,4,'A fiduciary representing a dissolving corporation may file a request for prompt assessment of tax. Generally, this request reduces the time allowed for assessment to:','[\"12 months.\",\"18 months.\",\"24 months.\",\"30 months.\"]',1,'Normally, the Internal Revenue Service has 3 years after an income tax return is filed to assess additional tax or to begin court action to collect the tax. However, a personal representative may request a prompt assessment of tax after the return has been filed. This reduces the time for making the assessment to 18 months from the date the written request for prompt assessment was received.nnThe fiduciary representing a dissolving corporation, or an administrator of a decedent\'s estate, may request a prompt assessment of tax under Internal Revenue Code (IRC) Section 6501(d). This will limit the time to 18 months from the date the fiduciary files the request, but not beyond 3 years from the date the return is filed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1047,4,'From the information below, determine the taxable income on Form 1041 for Hal\'s estate for the 2024 calendar year.nn  Income                                Expenses                  n  Taxable interest          $ 2,000     Attorney\'s fees     $5,000n  Dividends                   3,000     Property taxes       1,500n  401(k) distributions       50,000 nThe property taxes had accrued prior to Hal\'s death. They were deducted on the estate\'s Form 706. The estate distributed $10,000 of taxable income to beneficiaries.','[\"$38,500\",\"$39,400\",\"$40,000\",\"$48,500\"]',1,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. The income distribution deduction determines the amount of any distributions taxed to the beneficiaries (Instructions for Form 1041, page 3).nnAdditionally, a decedent\'s estate is allowed a $600 exemption (Instructions for Form 1041, page 27, line 21).nnSince the property taxes were accrued prior to Hal’s death, they were deducted on Form 706 and are therefore not deductible on the estate’s Form 1041.nnAs a result, the taxable income for Hal\'s estate after allowing the estate exemption amount is $39,400, calculated as follows:nn  401(k) Distribution          $50,000n  Taxable Interest               2,000n  Dividends                      3,000 n  Total Income                 $55,000n  Less:n    Distribution Deduction     (10,000)n    Attorney                    (5,000)n    Estate Exemption              (600)n  Taxable Income               $39,400',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1048,4,'The trustee of a grantor type trust must never:','[\"give all payers of income the name and TIN of the grantor and the address of the trust.\",\"file a trust return, completing only the entity information, and attach a statement identifying the grantor to whom the income is taxable.\",\"file Forms 1099 with the IRS showing the trust income as paid to the grantor.\",\"file a trust return, figuring the tax on all income and deductions of the trust.\"]',3,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor. This also applies to any portion of a trust that is treated as a grantor trust.nnIf the entire trust is a grantor trust, the trustee fills in only the entity portion of Form 1041. Therefore, the trustee does not file a trust return, figuring the tax on all income and deductions of the trust.nnIf only part of the trust is a grantor type trust, the portion of the income, deductions, etc., that is allocable to the non-grantor part of the trust is reported on Form 1041, under normal reporting rules. The amounts that are allocable directly to the grantor are shown only on an attachment to the form. Schedule K-1 (Form 1041) is not used as attachment. However, Schedule K-1 is used to reflect any income distributed from the portion of the trust that isn\'t taxable directly to the grantor or owner.nnThe fiduciary must give the grantor (owner) of the trust a copy of the attachment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1049,4,'John, a self-employed carpenter, died on January 8, 2024. Which of the following, if allowable, could be deducted on John\'s final Form 1040?','[\"Unused net operating loss carryover from 2023\",\"The full amount of his standard deduction (without pro-ration)\",\"Medical expenses paid by the estate within 1 year of death\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Generally, the rules for deductions allowed to an individual also apply to the decedent\'s final income tax return, such as the standard deduction (if itemized deductions are not claimed) and unused net operating loss carryovers from prior years. Additionally, if the decedent\'s medical expenses are paid out of the estate during the 1-year period beginning with the day after death, an election can be made to treat all, or part, of the expenses as paid by the decedent at the time they were incurred.nnThus, in preparing John\'s final Form 1040, all the above items, if allowable, may be deducted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1050,4,'How is the income that is taxable to the grantor of a grantor-type trust reported?','[\"Gains and losses on stock sold during the year by the trust are reported on Form 1041.\",\"Gains and losses on stock sold during the year by the trust are netted together and reported on a separate schedule attached to Form 1041.\",\"Gains and losses on stock sold during the year by the trust are reported separately on a separate schedule attached to Form 1041.\",\"Gains and losses on stock sold during the year by the trust are reported to the grantor by issuing a Schedule K-1 (Form 1041).\"]',2,'In the case of a grantor trust, if only part of the trust is a grantor-type trust, the portion of the income, deductions, etc. that is allocable to the non-grantor part of the trust is reported on Form 1041, under normal reporting rules. Amounts, on the other hand, that are allocable directly to the grantor are shown only on an attachment to the form. Also, the amounts are not shown on Schedule K-1 (Form 1041) but rather on the attachment to Form 1041. Schedule K-1, however, is used to reflect any income distributed from the portion of the trust that is not taxable directly to the grantor or owner.nnThe fiduciary must give the grantor (owner) of the trust a copy of the attachment.nnn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nThe John Doe Trust is a grantor-type trust. During the year, the trust sold 100 shares of ABC stock for $1,010 in which it had a basis of $10 and 200 shares of XYZ stock for $10 in which it had a $1,020 basis.nnThe trust does not report these transactions on Form 1041. Instead, a schedule is attached to the Form 1041 showing each stock transaction separately and in the same detail as John Doe (grantor and owner) will need to report these transactions on his Form 8949, Sales and Other Dispositions of Capital Assets, and Schedule D (Form 1040). The trust does not net the capital gains and losses, nor does it issue John Doe a Schedule K-1 (Form 1041) showing a $10 long-term capital loss. (Instructions for Form 1041, pages 13–14)nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1051,4,'In general, which of the following statements is false?','[\"An estate or trust may use the net operating loss not able to be used by the decedent in his final Form 1040 filing.\",\"An estate or trust cannot carry its net operating loss back 5 years.\",\"If a farming loss, the estate or trust may carry the loss back 2 years.\",\"An estate or trust may elect to carry its net operating loss forward.\"]',0,'nGenerally, an NOL (net operating loss) can only be carried forward to subsequent years and cannot be carried back. The 2-year carryback period only applies to the portion of an NOL attributable to a farming loss.nnAny NOLs the deceased individual had at the time of death cannot be transferred or carryforward to the estate. To the extent the deceased individual continued to have a reportable NOL on his final 1040 filing, that NOL would not be transferrable to the estate and thus would be lost. (Revenue Ruling 74-175)nnTherefore, given the above, the only false statement is that an estate or trust may use the net operating loss not able to be used by a decedent in his final Form 1040 filing.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1052,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning payments received on an inherited installment obligation?','[\"It is taxable only to the estate.\",\"It is taxable to the beneficiary in total upon receipt of the inherited obligation.\",\"It is taxable to the beneficiary at the same gross profit percentage used by the decedent.\",\"It is taxable to the beneficiary in total upon receipt of the last installment payment.\"]',2,'When an installment obligation is inherited, the same gross profit percentage used by the decedent to calculate the profit portion of each payment is used to determine the amount of income that is taxable to the beneficiary. That is, the beneficiary would include in their income the same profit the decedent would have included had death not occurred.nnLikewise, if the taxpayer disposes of an installment obligation acquired from a decedent (other than by transfer to the obligor), the rules for figuring the gain or loss on the disposition apply to the taxpayer.nnFor more information, see Publication 537, Installment Sales.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1053,4,'Allecia, a cash-basis taxpayer, died on July 15, 2024. Which of the following items of income is includible on her final return?','[\"Dividends of $20 that were declared on July 10 but not received in the mail until July 25\",\"Interest of $500 earned on and credited to Allecia\'s savings account on July 15\",\"Consulting income of $300. Allecia completed the job on July 2. The client mailed the payment on July 14 and the check arrived at Allecia\'s home on July 22.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'The decedent\'s income includible on his or her final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return.nnAccordingly, if the decedent accounted for income under the cash method, only those items actually or constructively received before death are included in the final return.nnIncome is constructively received when an amount is credited to a person\'s account or made available to them without restriction. In this case, Allecia had constructive receipt of the interest on her savings account.nnMore specifically, a dividend was constructively received if it was available for use by the decedent without restriction. If the corporation customarily mailed its dividend checks, the dividend was includible when received. If the individual died between the time the dividend was declared and the time it was received in the mail, the decedent did not constructively receive it before death.nnAs for the consulting income, Allecia did not constructively receive the payment prior to death. Hence, it would not be included in her final return.nnTherefore, the only item of income includible on Allecia\'s final return is the interest on her savings account.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1054,4,'Which of the following statements is correct?nn1. A trustee for an individual’s bankruptcy estate must file a return if the bankruptcy estate has gross income of $14,600 in 2024.n2. The IRS may file an estimated Request for Administrative Expenses if a trustee fails to file a tax return for an individual’s bankruptcy.','[\"Item 1 only\",\"Item 2 only\",\"Both items 1 and 2\",\"Neither item 1 nor 2\"]',2,'A bankruptcy estate is created when an individual debtor files a petition under either Chapter 7 or 11 of Title 11 of the U.S. Code and it is treated as a separate taxable entity. The bankruptcy estate is administered by a trustee or a debtor-in-possession.nnEvery trustee (or debtor-in-possession) for an individual\'s bankruptcy estate under Chapter 7 or 11 of Title 11 of the U.S. Code must file a return if the bankruptcy estate has gross income of $14,600 or more for tax years beginning in 2024. Moreover, failure to file the tax return may result in an estimated Request for Administrative Expenses being filed by the IRS in the bankruptcy proceeding or a motion to compel filing of the return.nnThe filing of a tax return for the bankruptcy estate does not relieve the individual debtor(s) of his, her, or their individual tax obligations.nnTherefore, both statements given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1055,4,'The grantor of Trust A retained the right to the income of the trust and to determine the timing and amount of distributions. Who pays the tax on the income if the grantor distributes the income to his daughter?','[\"The daughter\",\"The grantor\",\"The trust\",\"Either the grantor or the daughter\"]',1,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. This also can apply to only a portion of a trust. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor. This also applies to any portion of a trust that is treated as a grantor trust.nnAs a result, if the grantor of a trust retains the right to the income of the trust and to determine the timing and amount of any distributions, the trust is classified as a grantor trust. As a grantor trust, all income and deductions are taxed to the grantor.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1056,4,'Which of the following requirements must be satisfied for a trust to qualify as a simple trust?','[\"The trust requires that all income must be distributed currently.\",\"The trust does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes.\",\"The trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.\",\"All of the answer choices are required.\"]',3,'A trust will qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently,nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nTherefore, all of the responses are necessary requirements to be satisfied if the trust is to qualify as a simple trust.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1057,4,'As a general rule, a trust may qualify as a simple trust if:','[\"the trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently.\",\"the trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.\",\"the trust has no provisions for charitable contributions.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A trust will qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently,nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1058,4,'John died on January 1, 2024. A calendar year was elected for his estate. No distributions were made by the estate. Based on the following, what is the taxable income (Form 1041) of the estate for the December 31, 2024, year-end? Allow for the estate\'s exemption amount.nn  Taxable interest       $2,000n  Tax-exempt interest     1,000n  Capital gain            3,000n  Executor\'s fees           300','[\"$6,300\",\"$4,200\",\"$4,800\",\"$4,900\"]',1,'When completing Form 1041, any items that are income in respect of a decedent must be accounted for. (See the Instructions for Form 1041, page 4, for a detailed list of items regarded as income in respect of a decedent.) Generally, income in respect of a decedent is income that a decedent was entitled to receive but that was not properly includible in the decedent\'s final income tax return under the decedent\'s method of accounting.nnAdditionally, a decedent\'s estate is allowed a $600 exemption (Instructions for Form 1041, page 27, line 21).nnGenerally, no deduction that would otherwise be allowable is allowed for any expense (whether for business or to produce income) that is allocable to tax-exempt income. There are some exceptions of tax-exempt income, as noted on page 22 of the Instructions for Form 1041:nnCertain death benefitsnInterest on state or local bondsnCompensation for injuries or sicknessnIncome from discharge of indebtedness in a Title 11 casenIn addition, state income taxes and business expenses that are allocable to tax-exempt income are an exception. However, expenses that are directly allocable to tax-exempt income are allocated only to tax-exempt income. A reasonable proportion of expenses indirectly allocable to both tax-exempt income and other income must be allocated to each class of income. (Form 1041 Instructions, page 22)nnTherefore, the amount of taxable income that must be reported on the 2024 U.S. Income Tax Return for Estates and Trusts (Form 1041) is $4,200, determined as follows:nn  Taxable Interest        $2,000n  Plus Capital Gain        3,000n  Less Executor\'s Fees       200 (300 x ($2,000/$3,000))n  Less Exemption Amount      600n     Taxable Income       $4,200nNote: The default rule under section 643 (a) (3) is that capital gains are considered trust principal, not Income in the fiduciary accounting sense, unless the capital gains are (1) paid, credited, or required to be distributed to any beneficiary during the taxable year, or (2) paid, permanently set aside, or to be used for charitable purposes. Therefore, capital gains were not used in the total income for the tax exempt calculation. Alternatively, we could have deducted $250 (($5,000 ÷ $6,000) × $300) resulting in a taxable income of $4,150 which is not one of the responses given.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1059,4,'Given the following information, what is the distributable net income (DNI) for the simple trust established by Mr. Bill?nn1. $20,000 in dividend incomen2. $25,000 in taxable interest incomen3. $10,000 in tax-exempt interest incomen4. $20,000 in long-term capital gains (capital gains are allocable to corpus)','[\"$70,000\",\"$60,000\",\"$55,000\",\"$45,000\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction (IDD) for distributions to beneficiaries. The income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI) (Form 1041 Instructions, page 4).nnThe trust arrives at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income, which is the amount appearing on line 17 on page 1 of Form 1041.nnA simple trust is one that (Instructions for Form 1041, page 18):nnrequires all income be distributed currently,ndoes not provide any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andndoes not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nHence, when calculating the DNI for a simple trust, any amounts allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount.nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the distribution net income is $55,000, as calculated on Form 1041:nnForm 1041:                                              nLine 1   Interest income                        $25,000nLine 2   Ordinary dividends                      20,000nLine 9   Total income (combine lines 1 and 2)   $45,000n nForm 1041, Schedule B:                                  nLine 1   Adj. total income                      $45,000*nLine 2   Adj. tax-exempt interest                10,000nLine 7   DNI (combine lines 1 and 2)            $55,000nLine 12  Tax-exempt income                      (10,000)nLine 15  Income distribution deductions         $45,000n* This figure comes from line 9 above.nnThe best way to appreciate this issue is to look at Form 1041 and/or its instructions. The calculation of DNI (line 7 of Schedule B) includes tax-exempt interest (line 2 of Schedule B) that is not associated with a charitable contribution. However, the income distribution deduction (IDD) (line 15 of Schedule B) deducts the tax-exempt interest appearing in DNI (line 7 of Schedule B). So, the income distribution deduction cannot be greater than DNI, but it can be less than DNI. In this problem, DNI is $55,000, but IDD is $45,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1060,4,'Bill Johnson\'s will provides that $10,000 a year would be paid to his widow and $5,000 a year to his son out of the estate\'s income. There were no charitable contributions made. If the estate\'s distributable net income for the year was $12,000, how much of the distribution to Bill\'s son is taxable to him?','[\"$4,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$8,000\",\"$10,000\"]',0,'Beneficiaries must include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (figured without taking into account the charitable deduction), his or her proportionate share of the DNI (distributable net income).nnGiven that the estate had $12,000 of distributable net income to distribute, Bill\'s son should report taxable income of $4,000, computed as follows:nn  DNI                  $12,000n  33.3% Beneficiary      0.333 ($5,000 / $15,000)n  To Bill\'s Son        $ 4,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1061,4,'Under the terms of Robert\'s will, annual payments are to be made from the estate\'s income as follows:nn   Spouse       $10,000n   Daughter       5,000n   Son            5,000nThere are no charitable contributions for the year, and the distributable net income is $10,000. How much should each beneficiary include in his or her respective gross income?','[\"Spouse $10,000, Daughter $0, Son $0\",\"Spouse $10,000, Daughter $5,000, Son $5,000\",\"Spouse $5,000, Daughter $2,500, Son $2,500\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Beneficiaries of a simple trust must include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI. The determination of whether trust income is required to be distributed currently depends on the terms of the trust instrument and applicable local law.nnGiven that the estate had $10,000 of distributable net income to distribute, the spouse should report taxable income of $5,000 and both the daughter and son $2,500 computed as follows:nn  DNI                        $10,000n  50% Beneficiary               0.50  ($10,000/$20,000)n  To the spouse              $ 5,000nn  DNI                        $10,000n  25% Beneficiary               0.25  ($5,000/$20,000)n  To the daughter and son    $ 2,500 each',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1062,4,'The trustee of a simple trust has prepared Form 1041 for the tax year ending December 31, 2024. After determining the proportionate share of distributable net income for each beneficiary, the trustee must provide the beneficiary a copy of which federal form for inclusion on the beneficiary\'s Form 1040 for the year 2024?','[\"Form 1099-MISC\",\"Schedule K-1 (Form 1041)\",\"Form 1099-T\",\"No form, since a simple trust does not distribute income\"]',1,'A Schedule K-1 (Form 1041) is used to report the beneficiary\'s share of income, deductions, and credits from a trust or a decedent\'s estate.nnThe fiduciary (or one of the joint fiduciaries) must file Schedule K-1. A copy of each beneficiary\'s Schedule K-1 is attached to the Form 1041 filed with the IRS, and each beneficiary is given a copy of his or her respective Schedule K-1. In addition, a copy of each Schedule K-1 must be retained for the fiduciary\'s records.nnNote: Grantor type trusts do not use Schedule K-1 (Form 1041) to report the income, deductions, or credits of the grantor (or another person treated as owner). Rather, the entity information of Form 1041 is completed, and the dollar amounts are shown only on an attachment to the form (Grantor letter, not Schedule K-1).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1063,4,'Which of the following statements regarding grantor trusts is true?','[\"A grantor of a grantor trust does not report income from the trust unless distributions are made from the trust.\",\"A grantor trust is a good way to shelter income.\",\"Income from a grantor trust is taxed to the grantor in the same manner as if no trust existed.\",\"All of the statements are true.\"]',2,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor, regardless of distributions.nnTherefore, the correct response here is income from a grantor trust is taxed to the grantor in the same manner as if no trust existed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1064,4,'Frank owned and operated a machine shop. He used the cash method of accounting. At the time of his death in 2024, Frank was owed $5,000 for work his shop had performed. This $5,000 amount was paid prior to Frank\'s estate being settled. The sole beneficiary of the estate is Frank\'s son Jim, but the $5,000 was not distributed to Jim before the settlement of Frank\'s estate. The $5,000 must be included in the income of:','[\"Frank\'s final income tax return.\",\"Frank\'s estate\'s income tax return.\",\"the income tax return of beneficiary Jim.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'The decedent\'s includible income on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return.nnAccordingly, if the decedent accounted for income under the cash method, only those items actually or constructively received before death are included in the final return (Publication 559, page 6).nnIncome in respect of a decedent must be included in the income of one of the following:nnThe decedent\'s estate, if the estate receives it,nThe beneficiary, if the right to income passes directly to the beneficiary and the beneficiary receives it, ornAny person to whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it. (Publication 559, page 13)nSee Publication 559, pages 13 through 15, for a detailed list of items regarded as income in respect of a decedent.nnTherefore, since the $5,000 was received after Frank’s death and not distributed to Jim, the amount is included in Frank\'s estate’s income tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1065,4,'Which of the following is true regarding income in respect of a decedent (IRD)?','[\"The character of the IRD changes once the decedent passes away.\",\"IRD is income the decedent would have received had death not occurred and was properly included in the decedent\'s final return.\",\"If an individual receives IRD and includes it on their return, they are not allowed a deduction for the estate tax attributable to the item of IRD as reported on Form 706.\",\"IRD must be included as income by either the decedent\'s estate, if the estate receives it, or the beneficiary, if the right to income is passed directly to the beneficiary and the beneficiary receives it, or any person to whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it.\"]',3,'IRD is all income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that was NOT properly includible on the final return. IRD must be included in one of the following:nnThe estatenThe beneficiary ornAny person whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive itnPublication 559, page 14, provides that the character of income received in respect of a decedent remains the same as it would have been to the decedent if the decedent were alive.nnThe correct answer is that the IRD must be included as income by either the decedent’s estate, if the estate receives it, or the beneficiary, if the right to income is passed directly to the beneficiary and the beneficiary receives it, or any person to who the estate properly distributes the right to receive it.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1066,4,'Harry, a single person, died in 2024. The executor does not elect the alternate valuation date. Given the following information, determine the value of Harry\'s gross estate.nn                                                         FMV at Daten                                                          of Death  nCertificates of deposit                                  $  100,000nMortgage receivable on sale of property                   2,000,000nPainting and collectibles                                   500,000nIncome tax refunds due from 2023 individual tax return       30,000nHousehold goods and personal effects                         20,000','[\"$2,600,000\",\"$2,650,000\",\"$2,620,000\",\"$2,120,000\"]',1,'The gross estate is valued at the date of death, unless the alternate valuation method is elected. The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nAccordingly, all of the above amounts are includible in Harry\'s gross estate.nnTherefore, the value of Harry\'s gross estate is $2,650,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1067,4,'Estimated tax payments are not required from a decedent\'s estate, except:','[\"for any tax year ending before the date that is 3 years after the decedent\'s death.\",\"when the estate is expected to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, less than $1,000 in tax for 2025.\",\"when the estate expects the withholding and credits to be at least 90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 return.\",\"when the estate expects the withholding and credits to be at least 100% of the tax shown on the 2024 return.\"]',0,'In general, estimated tax must be paid if the estate or trust is expected to owe, after subtracting any withholding and credits, at least $1,000 in tax. You will not, however, have to pay estimated tax if you expect the withholding and credits to be at least:nn90% of the tax to be shown on the 2025 return orn100% of the tax shown on the 2024 return. (The percentage is 110% if the estate\'s 2024 adjusted gross income (AGI) was more than $150,000.)nEstimated tax payments are not required under certain situations: first, an estate of a domestic decedent or a domestic trust that had no tax liability for the full 12-month 2024 tax year; second, a decedent’s estates for any tax year ending before the date that is 2 years after the decedent\'s death.nnTherefore, estates with tax years ending 2 or more years after the date of the decedent\'s death must pay estimated tax in the same manner as individuals.nnThe general rule is that you must make your first estimated tax payment by April 15.nnYou can either pay all of your estimated tax at that time or pay it in four equal amounts.nnAs stated above, there are exceptions to the above rules. In this problem, an estate that ends before the date that is 2 (not 3) years after the decedent\'s death is not required to pay estimated taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1068,4,'Which of the following is correct if you are the beneficiary of an estate that must distribute all its income currently?','[\"You must report your share of the distributable net income (DNI) if you did not actually receive it or your proportionate share of the DNI if the distributed amount exceeds the DNI.\",\"You must report the amount you actually receive, not your share of the distributable net income (DNI).\",\"You must report the amount that exceeds the DNI amount only.\",\"Beneficiaries are\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to report any of the DNI amount.\"]',0,'Beneficiaries of an estate that must distribute all its income currently must include in their gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 41)nnTherefore, the correct response for this question is that you must report your share of the distributable net income (DNI) if you did not actually receive it or your proportionate share of the DNI if the distributed amount exceeds the DNI.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1069,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a grantor type trust?','[\"It is a legal entity under federal law.\",\"Since the grantor has relinquished complete control over the trust, it is recognized as a separate taxable entity for income tax purposes.\",\"All of the income and deductions are treated as belonging directly to the grantor of a grantor trust (not the trust).\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'A grantor type trust is a legal trust under applicable state law (not federal law) that is not recognized as a separate taxable entity for income tax purposes if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits.nnIn addition, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor, because the grantor has not relinquished complete control over the trust.nnNote: This is a common question that has historically appeared in the exam; however, it does not mean that you will see the question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1070,4,'A fiduciary representing a dissolving corporation may request a prompt assessment of tax under Internal Revenue Code Section 6501(d). This will limit the time the Internal Revenue Service has to assess additional tax or to begin court action to collect the tax from the date the fiduciary files the request to:','[\"6 months.\",\"12 months.\",\"18 months.\",\"24 months.\"]',2,'Normally, the Internal Revenue Service has 3 years after an income tax return is filed to assess additional tax or to begin court action to collect the tax. The fiduciary representing a dissolving corporation, or an administrator of a decedent\'s estate, may request a prompt assessment of tax under Internal Revenue Code (IRC) Section 6501(d). This will limit the time to 18 months from the date the fiduciary files the request, but not beyond 3 years from the date the return is filed.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1071,4,'The John Q estate fiscal tax year runs from April 1, 2023, to March 31, 2024. The estate made distributions to beneficiaries on December 12, 2023, and March 15, 2024. Assuming that the estate has taxable income, in what year will its beneficiaries be required to report taxable distributions?','[2023,2024,\"Both 2023 and 2024\",\"Neither 2023 nor 2024\"]',1,'Generally, taxable distributions from an estate should be included on a beneficiary\'s tax return in the year it was received. However, if the beneficiary\'s tax year is different from the estate\'s tax year, the taxable distribution must be reported on the beneficiary\'s return for the tax year in which the last day of the estate\'s tax year falls.nn nn 	Example	 n 	 	 n 	nFor example, if the tax year of the estate is a fiscal year ending on June 30, 2024, and the beneficiary\'s tax year is the calendar year, the beneficiary will include in gross income for the tax year ending December 31, 2024, his or her share of the estate\'s distributable net income distributed or required to be distributed during the fiscal year ending the previous June 30. (Publication 559, page 23)nn n nnAs a result, the beneficiaries of John Q estate must report the distributions received in 2024, the tax year in which the last day of the estate\'s tax year falls, March 31, 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1072,4,'The computation of distributable net income of a trust considers which of the following items?','[\"Income distribution deduction\",\"Exemption\",\"Tax-exempt interest\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'A trust will arrive at distributable net income by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. In calculating its distributable net income (DNI), a trust will include adjusted total income, adjusted tax-exempt interest, total net gain from Schedule D (Form 1041), and charitable deductions, to name a few. (See Form 1041, Schedule B, page 2.)nnTo figure the adjusted tax-exempt interest, expenses that are directly allocable to tax-exempt income are allocated only to tax-exempt income. A reasonable proportion of expenses indirectly allocable to both tax-exempt income and other income must be allocated to each class of income. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 24)nnMore specifically, a person must first add tax-exempt interest income and any expenses allowable under IRC Section 212 allocable to tax-exempt interest, and any interest expense allocable to tax-exempt interest. Next, the person subtracts the amount of tax-exempt interest (including exempt-interest dividends) received.nnIRC Section 212 expenses (any expenses that are directly allocable to tax-exempt interest) are deducted. A reasonable proportion of IRC Section 212 expenses that are indirectly allocable to both tax-exempt interest and other income must be allocated to each class of income. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 31)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1073,4,'The JLB Trust is a simple trust. Alan is the sole beneficiary of the trust. Capital gains are allocable to corpus. Based on the following information, what is the trust\'s distribution deduction?nn   Interest           $1,700n   Dividends             300n   Capital gains       2,000n   Fiduciary fee       1,000','[\"$1,000\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,000\",\"$3,000\"]',0,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries.nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income as figured on Schedule B. (See the instructions for Form 1041, pages 3 and 4; and Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the DNI for a simple trust, any amounts allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount.nnThe distributable net income is $1,000, which is the interest income of $1,700 plus the ordinary dividends of $300 less the fiduciary fees of $1,000. Thus, the JLB Trust\'s distribution deduction is limited to the DNI or $1,000 in this case.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1074,4,'An irrevocable trust was established for the medical care of Joan\'s mother. During the tax year, the trust received interest and dividend income in the amount of $20,000. Per the trust provisions, the trustee paid $10,000 of medical expenses directly to the care provider. It also paid $1,000 of investment interest expense. Assuming that this is a complex trust, determine the trust\'s distributable net income for the year.','[\"$20,000\",\"$19,000\",\"$9,000\",\"$10,000\"]',1,'A trust or a decedent\'s estate is a separate legal entity for federal tax purposes. A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. (Form 1041 Instructions, page 4)nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts for amounts paid, credited, or required to be distributed to the beneficiaries is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). (This amount is figured on Schedule B, line 7, on Form 1041.) (Form 1041 Instructions, page 4)nnA trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. (See Schedule B on Form 1041, page 2.)nnTherefore, the trust\'s distributable net income for the year is $19,000, determined as follows:nn  Interest and Dividends          $20,000n  Less:n    Investment Interest Expense    (1,000)n  Adjusted Total Income           $19,000n  Plus:n    Schedule B Adjustments              0n  Distributable Net Income        $19,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1075,4,'What is the minimum amount of gross income for the year that a simple trust must file if a tax return is to be filed?','[\"$500\",\"$600\",\"$750\",\"$1,000\"]',1,'In the case of a trust, the fiduciary (or one of the joint fiduciaries) must file a tax return (Form 1041) for a domestic trust taxable under IRC Section 641 if it has any of the following items:nnany taxable income for the tax year,ngross income of $600 or more (regardless of taxable income), orna beneficiary who is a nonresident alien.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1076,4,'All of the following are true regarding income in respect of a decedent (IRD) EXCEPT:','[\"IRD is income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that wasn\\u2019t properly included in the decedent\\u2019s final return.\",\"the character of the IRD remains the same as it would have been to the decedent had they not passed.\",\"if an individual receives IRD and includes it on their return, they are not allowed a deduction for the estate tax attributable to the item of IRD as reported on Form 706.\",\"IRD must be included as income on either the decedent\'s estate return, if the estate receives it, or the beneficiary, if the right to income is passed directly to the beneficiary and the beneficiary receives it, or any person to whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it.\"]',2,'The decedents income includible on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return. (Publication 559, page 5)nnPursuant to Publication 559, page 10, income in respect of a decedent must be included in the income of one of the following.nnThe decedent\'s estate, if the estate receives it.nThe beneficiary, if the right to income is passed directly to the beneficiary and the beneficiary receives it.nAny person to whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it.nFinally, if a person is required to include income in respect of a decedent in their gross income and an estate tax return (Form 706) was filed for the decedent, you may be able to claim a deduction for the estate tax paid on that income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1077,4,'The Wilder Trust is a complex trust with a controlling instrument that specifically allocates capital transactions to the corpus of the trust. The instrument goes on to state that $2,000 will be set aside out of gross income for charitable purposes and that $10,000 in income is required to be distributed each year. At the end of 2024, the Wilder Trust had $20,000 in gross income, which included $5,000 in capital gains. If there was no other information to consider, what would the Wilder Trust\'s income distribution deduction be for 2024?','[\"$18,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$5,000\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. (Form 1041 Instructions, page 3)nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income as figured on Schedule B. (See Schedule B on Form 1041 and the instructions for Form 1041, page 4.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the DNI for a complex trust, any amounts allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount.nnThus, given that DNI (see calculation below) is more than the amount required to be distributed, the income distribution deduction for 2024 is $10,000, which is the lesser of amount distributed ($10,000) or DNI ($13,000).nn  Gross income                 $20,000n  Less:n     Charitable contribution    (2,000)n  Adjusted total income        $18,000n  Less:n     Capital gains              (5,000)n  Distributable net income     $13,000*n* This is what the income distribution deduction is limited to. However, no limitation is placed on the deduction because the amount required to be distributed is less than the DNI. See page 4 of the instructions for Form 1041 for more details on this rule.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1078,4,'The decedent was a cash basis taxpayer who had chosen not to report the interest each year from his series EE savings bonds that he purchased during his lifetime. Which of the following two options is available to the executor of the decedent\'s estate?nn1. The person (executor, administrator, etc.) who must file the final income tax return of the decedent can elect to include in it all of the interest earned on the bonds before the decedent\'s death and, if elected, the decedent\'s estate or beneficiary includes in its return only the interest earned after the date of death.n2. The person (executor, administrator, etc.) who must file the final income tax return of the decedent can elect to include in it none of the interest earned on the bonds before the decedent\'s death and, if elected, all of the interest earned before and after the decedent\'s death is income to the estate or beneficiary.','[\"Item 1 only\",\"Item 2 only\",\"Both items 1 and 2\",\"Neither item 1 nor 2\"]',2,'If bonds owned by a cash method taxpayer who chose not to report the interest each year are transferred due to death, the interest earned before death must be reported in one of the following ways:nn1. The person (executor, administrator, etc.) who must file the final income tax return of the decedent can elect to include in it all of the interest earned on the bonds before the decedent\'s death. The transferee (decedent\'s estate or beneficiary) then includes in its return only the interest earned after the date of death, orn2. If the election in (1) above was not made, the interest earned to the date of death is income in respect of the decedent and is not included in the decedent\'s final return. In this case, all of the interest earned before and after the decedent\'s death is income to the transferee (estate or beneficiary).nNote: If the cash method taxpayer had chosen to report the interest each year, the increase in value of the bonds (interest earned) in the year of death up to the date of death must be reported on the decedent\'s final return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1079,4,'If a trust has adjusted total income of $10,000, distributable net income of $11,000, and it is required to currently distribute $12,000, what is its income distribution deduction?','[\"$11,000\",\"$12,000\",\"$2,000\",\"$10,000\"]',0,'A trust or a decedent\'s estate is a separate legal entity for federal tax purposes. A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries (Instructions for Form 1041, page 4).nnThe beneficiary of a decedent\'s estate or complex trust must include in his or her gross income the sum of:nnthe amount of the income required to be distributed currently, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the DNI (figured without taking into account the charitable deduction), his or her proportionate share of the DNI (as so figured), andnall other amounts properly paid, credited, or required to be distributed, or if the sum of the income required to be distributed currently and other amounts properly paid, credited, or required to be distributed to all beneficiaries exceeds the DNI, his or her proportionate share of the excess of DNI over the income required to be distributed currently. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 41–42)nThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. (See the instructions for Form 1041, page 4.)nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the income distribution deduction is $11,000 because it is limited to the DNI.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1080,4,'Which of the following types of trusts are not considered a separate legal entity for federal tax purposes?','[\"Simple trusts\",\"Tax-exempt trusts\",\"Grantor trusts\",\"Complex trusts\"]',2,'A trust or a decedent\'s estate is a separate legal entity for federal tax purposes. A decedent\'s estate comes into existence at the time of death of an individual. A trust may be created during an individual\'s life (inter vivos) or at the time of his or her death under a will (testamentary). If a trust instrument contains certain provisions, then the person creating the trust (the grantor) is treated as the owner of the trust’s assets and is called a grantor trust. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 4)nnA trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for income tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 14)nnA grantor type trust is a legal trust under applicable state law that is not recognized as a separate taxable entity for income tax purposes because the grantor or other substantial owners have not relinquished complete dominion and control over the trust. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 19)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1081,4,'Generally, in determining the taxable income for most taxpayers, Internal Revenue Code (IRC) Section 469 limits the deduction of losses from passive activities to the amount of income derived from all passive activities. Which of the following statements is correct for an estate or trust that has a loss from a passive activity owned by the estate or trust?','[\"It can be used to offset portfolio income (interest, dividends, royalties, annuities, etc.) of the estate or trust in determining taxable income.\",\"It can offset passive activity losses only against passive activity income in the current year.\",\"It can offset passive activity losses only against passive activity income and any passive activity losses or credits that are not allowed in the current year can be carried forward to the next year.\",\"It can be used to offset portfolio income of the estate or trust in determining taxable income and any passive activity losses or credits that are not allowed in the current year can be carried forward to the next year.\"]',2,'A passive activity is any trade or business activity in which the taxpayer does not materially participate. Rental activities are passive activities regardless of the taxpayer\'s participation, unless the taxpayer meets certain eligibility requirements.nnIndividuals, estates, and trusts can offset passive activity losses only against passive activity income. Passive activity losses or credits that are not allowed in one tax year can be carried forward to the next year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1082,4,'Which of the following would be a characteristic of an abusive trust?','[\"Promises tax benefits with no meaningful change in the taxpayer\'s control over the taxpayer\'s income\",\"Promises benefits of deductions for personal expenses paid by the trust\",\"Promises tax benefits with no meaningful change in the taxpayer\'s benefit from the taxpayer\'s assets\",\"All of the answer choices are characteristics of an abusive trust.\"]',3,'Certain trust arrangements purport to reduce or eliminate federal taxes in ways that are not permitted under the law. Abusive trust arrangements typically are promoted by the promise of tax benefits with no meaningful change in the taxpayer\'s control over or benefit from the taxpayer\'s income or assets. The promised benefits may include:nnreduction or elimination of income subject to tax,ndeductions for personal expenses paid by the trust,ndepreciation of deductions of an owner\'s personal residence and furnishings,na stepped-up basis for property transferred to the trust,nthe reduction or elimination of self-employment taxes, andnthe reduction or elimination of gift and estate taxes.nAs a result, all of the responses in this problem exhibit characteristics of being an abusive trust.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1083,4,'The income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts for amounts paid, credited, or required to be distributed to beneficiaries is limited to:','[\"adjusted total income.\",\"distributable net income.\",\"the lesser of adjusted total income or distributable net income.\",\"the greater of adjusted total income or distributable net income.\"]',1,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. (See the instructions for Form 1041, page 4.)nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. (See the instructions for Form 1041, page 4 and Form 1041, page 2.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1084,4,'John Smith died on March 30, 2024. From January 1, 2024, to March 30, 2024, $2,000 in medical bills had been paid by John. The following additional medical bills were received and paid by the executor out of John\'s estate:nnFrom March 31, 2024, to December 31, 2024, in the amount of $5,000nFrom January 1, 2025, to March 30, 2025, in the amount of $5,000nFrom March 31, 2025, to April 6, 2025, in the amount of $3,000nThe executor of John\'s estate may elect to deduct what amount of the medical expenses (subject to percentage limitations) on John\'s final income tax return, Form 1040, if deductions are itemized?','[\"$2,000\",\"$7,000\",\"$12,000\",\"$15,000\"]',2,'The decedent\'s includible income on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return.nnAccordingly, if the decedent accounted for income under the cash method, only those items actually or constructively received before death are included in the final return (Publication 559, page 6).nnIn addition, the rules for deductions allowed to an individual also apply to the decedent\'s final income tax return, such as the standard deduction and unused net operating loss carryovers from prior years. Additionally, if the decedent\'s medical expenses are paid out of the estate during the 1-year period beginning with the day after death, an election can be made to treat all, or part, of the expenses as paid by the decedent at the time they were incurred.nnThus, in preparing John\'s final Form 1040, the executor of John\'s estate may elect to deduct $12,000 ($5,000 + $5,000 + $2,000) of medical expenses. The $3,000 paid after March 30, 2025, is beyond the 1-year period and, as such, it is not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1085,4,'In 2024, Exeter Trust had taxable interest of $2,000, capital gains of $6,000, and a fiduciary fee of $1,000. The trust instrument allocates capital gains to income. At the end of 2024, the fiduciary retains $3,000 and distributes $4,000. What is the distributable net income (DNI) of Exeter Trust for 2024?','[\"$4,000\",\"$4,375\",\"$7,000\",\"$7,375\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 3)nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income as figured on Schedule B. (See Schedule B on Form 1041 and the Instructions for Form 1041, page 4.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the DNI for a simple trust, any amounts allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount. However, the capital gains are allocated to income.nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the distributable net income is $7,000, calculated as follows:nn  Interest Income                      $2,000n  Capital Gains (allocate to income)    6,000n  Less:n     Fiduciary Fee                     (1,000)n  Distributable Net Income             $7,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1086,4,'Anissa is the sole beneficiary of her father\'s estate. The estate was closed 10 months after her father\'s death, and the executor is filing one (first and final) Form 1041. After all expenses of the estate were paid, the following amounts were paid out to Anissa.nn   Cash                           $ 12,000n   IRA (decedent had no basis)     300,000n   Wages paid after death            6,000n   Stock                            75,000n   Life insurance                  150,000nHow much, if any, of the payment will be reported on Anissa\'s Form 1040 federal income tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$6,000\",\"$306,000\",\"$543,000\"]',2,'How income from an estate is reported on a beneficiary\'s tax return depends on the character of the income in the hands of the estate. Each item of income keeps the same character in the beneficiary\'s hands as it had in the hands of the estate.nnIf the items of income distributed or considered to be distributed to the beneficiaries include dividends, tax-exempt interest, or capital gains, they will keep the same character in the beneficiaries\' hands for purposes of the tax treatment given those items (Publication 559, page 22).nnMore specific to this question, if an individual receives life insurance proceeds because of the death of the insured (or because the insured is a member of the U.S. uniformed services who is missing in action) those proceeds are not taxable unless the policy was turned over to the recipient for a price (Publication 559, page 13).nnTherefore, Anissa will have to report $306,000 of the payment on her Form 1040 federal income tax return, computed as follows:nn  IRA (decedent had no basis)    $300,000n  Wages paid after death            6,000n  Taxable                        $306,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1087,4,'The Marker Estate did not make any distributions to beneficiaries in 2024. From the information below, determine the estate\'s taxable income after allowing the estate exemption amount.nn  Taxable interest               $ 1,000n  Gain on sale of stock            5,000n  IRA distribution ($0 basis)     50,000n  Executor\'s fees                  5,000','[\"$400\",\"$11,600\",\"$50,400\",\"$55,600\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. The income distribution deduction determines the amount of any distributions taxed to the beneficiaries (Form 1041 Instructions, page 3).nnAdditionally, a decedent\'s estate is allowed a $600 exemption (instructions for Form 1041, page 27, line 21).nnAs a result, the Marker Estate\'s taxable income after allowing the estate exemption amount is $50,400, calculated as follows:nn  IRA Distribution       $50,000n  Taxable Interest         1,000n  Gain on Stock Sale       5,000n  Total Income           $56,000n  Executor\'s Fees         (5,000)n  Estate Exemption          (600)n  Taxable Income         $50,400',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1088,4,'Trust A is a simple trust with two equal beneficiaries, Jim and Randy. In 2024, the trust had $30,000 of distributable net income, all from taxable interest. During the year, the trust distributed $5,000 to Jim and $10,000 to Randy. Based on this information, the trustee should issue K-1\'s as follows:','[\"Jim $5,000; Randy $10,000\",\"Jim $15,000; Randy $15,000\",\"Jim $10,000; Randy $20,000\",\"Jim $30,000; Randy $30,000\"]',1,'The beneficiary of a simple trust must include in his or her gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI (Instructions for Form 1041, page 41).nnGiven that Trust A had $30,000 of distributable net income to distribute, the K-1\'s should be issued for $15,000 to both Jim and Randy (equal beneficiaries), computed as follows:nn  DNI                          $30,000n  50% Beneficiary                 0.50n  To each equal beneficiary    $15,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1089,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the personal exemption amount of the decedent on the final income tax return in 2024?','[\"It is equal to zero for the year of death.\",\"It is prorated for the portion of the year in days before the date of death.\",\"It is prorated for the portion of the year in whole months before the date of death.\",\"It is equal to the full amount for the year of death.\"]',0,'Prior to 2018, the full amount of the decedent\'s personal exemption may be claimed on the final income tax return. If the decedent was another person\'s dependent (for example, a parent\'s), the personal exemption cannot be claimed on the decedent\'s final return.nnAs a result of TCJA, a taxpayer can claim a personal exemption deduction for yourself, spouse or dependent (IRC Section 151). However, the deduction for personal exemptions and dependents are set to zero for tax years 2018 through 2025. Thus, the correct response is zero for the year of death.nnBe careful: The option \"it is equal to the full amount for the year of death\" is technically correct since it is equal to the full amount, which is zero for 2024. The better choice is the first response, which states it is equal to zero.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1090,4,'Christopher wants to create a revocable grantor trust that will own all of his stocks and rental properties. Which statement regarding income of the trust is true?','[\"Christopher will be taxed only on income that is distributed to him.\",\"Christopher will be taxed on all income of the trust, regardless of distributions.\",\"State law will determine how much of the trust income is taxable to Christopher.\",\"If the rental income is passive, it will not be taxable to him.\"]',1,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. This also can apply to only a portion of a trust. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor.nnIn addition, the grantor is treated as an owner of any portion of a trust in which he or she has a reversionary interest in either the income or corpus therefrom, if, as of the inception of that portion of the trust, the value of the reversionary interest is more than 5% of the value of that portion. This rule also applies in the case of the owner\'s spouse.nnNote: The grantor is treated as holding any power or interest that was held by either the grantor\'s spouse at the time that the power or interest was created or who became the grantor\'s spouse after the creation of that power or interest.nnAs a result, all of the income from Christopher\'s revocable grantor trust will be taxed to him, regardless of distributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1091,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the executor of an estate and the filing of a Form 1041, U.S. Income Tax Return for Estates and Trusts?','[\"Calendar year and fiscal year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 and Schedules K-1 on or before April 15.\",\"Calendar year and fiscal year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 and Schedules K-1 by the 15th day of the 4th month following the close of the tax year.\",\"Calendar year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 and Schedules K-1 on or before April 15. Fiscal year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 by the 15th day of the 4th month following the close of the tax year.\",\"Calendar year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 and Schedules K-1 by the 15th day of the 4th month following the close of the tax year. Fiscal year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 on or before April 15.\"]',2,'Calendar year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 and Schedules K-1 on or before April 15, 2025. nnFiscal year estates and trusts must file Form 1041 by the 15th day of the 4th month following the close of the tax year. If the due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the form is filed on the next business day.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nAn estate that has a tax year that ends on June 30, 2024, must file Form 1041 by October 15, 2024, which is the 15th day of the 4th month following June.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1092,4,'Which of the following statements is correct about spouses that elect to split gifts?','[\"The election applies to all gifts made in the current tax year.\",\"The election applies to all gifts made in future tax years until the election is revoked.\",\"The election applies to all gifts made in the current tax year even if the couple is granted a divorce.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'While a married couple may not file a joint gift tax return, the IRS permits spouses to split gifts under certain conditions. If both spouses agree, all gifts during the calendar year will be considered as made one-half by each spouse if:nnboth spouses were married to one another at the time of the gift,ndivorced or widowed after the gift, the spouse did not remarry during the rest of the calendar year,nneither of the spouses was a nonresident alien at the time of the gift, andna spouse was not given a general power of appointment over the property interest transferred.nNote: If spouses agree to split their gifts, they should file both of their individual gift tax returns in the same envelope to help the IRS process the returns and to avoid correspondence from the IRS; but do not attach the gift tax returns to the Form 1040.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1093,4,'Given the following information, determine the value of Sara\'s gross estate in 2024:nn                                                     FMV at Daten                                                      of Death  nBeneficiary for life of a QTIP trustn   (Qualified terminal interest property)           $10,000,000nIrrevocable trust (Sara was the grantor,n   but retained no interest in the trust)             1,000,000nRevocable grantor type trust (Sara was the grantor)     500,000','[\"$10,500,000\",\"$11,500,000\",\"$11,000,000\",\"$500,000\"]',0,'The gross estate is valued at the date of death, unless the alternate valuation method is elected. The gross estate includes all property in which the decedent had an interest (including real property outside the United States). It also includes:nncertain transfers made during the decedent\'s life without an adequate and full consideration in money or money\'s worth;nannuities;nthe includible portion of joint estates with right of survivorship;nthe includible portion of tenancies by the entirety;ncertain life insurance proceeds (even though payable to beneficiaries other than the estate);nproperty over which the decedent possessed a general power of appointment;ndower or curtesy (or statutory estate) of the surviving spouse; andncommunity property to the extent of the decedent\'s interest as defined by applicable law.nAccordingly, the value of Sara\'s gross estate in 2024 is $10.5 million, determined as follows:nn  QTIP Trust                $10,000,000n  Revocable Grantor Trust       500,000n  Gross Estate              $10,500,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1094,4,'The Large Trust is a simple trust. Bert Little is the sole beneficiary of the trust. Capital gains are allocable to corpus. Based on the following information, what is the trust\'s distribution deduction?nn  Interest            $1,700n  Dividend               300n  Capital gains        2,000n  Fiduciary fee        1,000','[\"$1,000\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,000\",\"$3,000\"]',0,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries.nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. (See Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the DNI for a simple trust, any amounts allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount.nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the Large Trust\'s distribution deduction is $1,000, calculated as follows:nn  Interest Income              $1,700n  Ordinary Dividends              300n  Less:n    Fiduciary Fee              (1,000)n  Distributable Net Income     $1,000nn  Distribution Deduction       $1,000, which is limited to DNI',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1095,4,'Which of the following statements concerning the character of the income that you receive in respect of a decedent is correct?','[\"It is not the same as it would be to the decedent if he or she were alive.\",\"If it would have been ordinary or capital to the decedent, it is capital to you.\",\"If it would have been ordinary or capital to the decedent, it is ordinary to you.\",\"If it would have been capital to the decedent, it is capital to you.\"]',3,'According to Publication 559, page 14, the character of the income the beneficiary receives in respect of a decedent is the same as it would be to the decedent if he or she were alive. For example, if the income would have been capital gain to the decedent, it is capital gain to the beneficiary.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1096,4,'In 2021, Thomas Hatch established the TWH Trust. TWH is a revocable trust. Thomas contributed cash, a significant stock portfolio, and tax-exempt bonds to this trust when he established it. In 2024, the TWH Trust had income consisting of $5,000 in taxable interest, $3,000 in ordinary dividends, and $2,000 in tax-exempt interest. Thomas has never relinquished dominion and control of the TWH Trust. What amount of the TWH Trust\'s income is taxable to Thomas Hatch in 2024?','[\"$10,000\",\"$8,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$0\"]',1,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor.nnAs a result, all of the income from Thomas\'s revocable trust will be taxed to him, regardless of distributions. Thus, Thomas includes $8,000 in income, which is the sum of the taxable interest ($5,000) and ordinary dividends ($3,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1097,4,'A trust that promises tax benefits with no meaningful change in the taxpayer\'s control over or benefit from the taxpayer\'s income or assets generally is seen as:','[\"a simple trust.\",\"a grantor trust.\",\"an abusive trust.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Certain trust arrangements purport to reduce or eliminate federal taxes in ways that are not permitted under the law. Abusive trust arrangements typically are promoted by the promise of tax benefits with no meaningful change in the taxpayer\'s control over or benefit from the taxpayer\'s income or assets. The promised benefits may include:nnreduction or elimination of income subject to tax,ndeductions for personal expenses paid by the trust,ndepreciation of deductions of an owner\'s personal residence and furnishings,na stepped-up basis for property transferred to the trust,nthe reduction or elimination of self-employment taxes, andnthe reduction or elimination of gift and estate taxes.nIn general, abusive trust arrangements often use trusts to hide the true ownership of assets or to disguise the substance of transactions. These arrangements frequently involve more than one trust, each holding different assets of the taxpayer.nnTherefore, a trust that promises tax benefits with no meaningful change in the taxpayer\'s control over or benefit from the taxpayer\'s income or assets generally is seen as an abusive trust.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1098,4,'Where is the income of a grantor trust reported?','[\"Grantor\'s return regardless of whether a distribution is or is not made from the trust to the grantor\",\"Grantor\'s return only if distributions from the trust are made to the grantor\",\"Grantor\'s return only if no distributions from the trust are made to the grantor\",\"The income is\\u00a0not\\u00a0reported.\"]',0,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor, regardless of distributions. Hence, it is the grantor\'s return that reports the income from the grantor\'s trust. (Instructions for Form 1041, pages 13–14)nnIf the entire trust is a grantor trust, fill in only the entity information of Form 1041. Don\'t show any dollar amounts on the form itself; show dollar amounts only on an attachment to the form. Don\'t use Schedule K-1 (Form 1041) as the attachment.nnIn addition, a grantor trust is a legal trust under applicable state law that is not recognized as a separate taxable entity for income tax purposes because the grantor or other substantial owners have not relinquished complete dominion and control over the trust. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 19)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1099,4,'Which of the following is not an example of income in respect of a decedent?','[\"Wages earned before death, but unpaid at the time of death\",\"A dividend check that was received by the decedent, but cashed after death\",\"The taxable portion of an inherited IRA\",\"The taxable portion of payments received on an inherited installment obligation\"]',1,'The decedent\'s income includible on his or her final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return.nnAccordingly, if the decedent accounted for income under the cash method, only those items actually or constructively received before death are included in the final return (Publication 559, page 5).nnAll income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that was not properly includible on the final return is income in respect of a decedent (Publication 559, page 24).nnSpecific types of income in respect of a decedent include:nnthe entire amount of wages or other employee compensation earned by the decedent but unpaid at the time of death,nthe taxable portion of an inherited IRA, andnthe taxable portion of payments received on an inherited installment obligation.nTherefore, a dividend check received by the decedent but cashed after death was received and available to the decedent for use without restriction, and thus would appear on the decedent\'s final tax return and would not be deemed to be an example of income in respect of a decedent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1100,4,'A net operating loss (NOL) was created in the course of conducting the decedent\'s business, which is held by the estate. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the use of the NOL that remains in the final year of the estate?','[\"It would be allowed to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate if the carryover would have been allowed to the estate in a later tax year if the estate had not been terminated.\",\"It would be allowed to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate only if the unused NOL is a capital loss carryover.\",\"It would be allowed to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate regardless whether the carryover would have been allowed to the estate in a later tax year if the estate had not been terminated.\",\"It is never passed through to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate.\"]',0,'The termination of an estate generally is marked by the end of the period of administration and by the distribution of the assets to the beneficiaries under the terms of the will or under the laws of succession of the state if there is no will. These beneficiaries may or may not be the same persons as the beneficiaries of the estate\'s income.nnIf the estate has unused loss carryover or excess deductions for its last tax year, they are allowed to those beneficiaries who succeed to the estate’s property.nnAny unused net operating loss carryover or capital loss carryover existing upon the termination of an estate is allowed to the beneficiaries succeeding to the property of the estate. That is, these deductions will be claimed on the beneficiary\'s tax return. This treatment is allowable only if the carryover would have been allowed to the estate in a later tax year if the estate had not been terminated.nnBoth types of carryovers generally keep their same character for the beneficiary as they had for the estate. However, if the beneficiary of a capital loss carryover is a corporation, the corporation will treat the carryover as a short-term capital loss regardless of its status in the estate. The net operating loss carryover and the capital loss carryover are used in figuring the beneficiary\'s adjusted gross income and taxable income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1101,4,'The Morrison Trust requires that all trust income be distributed at least annually. There are no provisions for charitable contributions. To be treated as a simple trust, what must also be true?','[\"Trust income can consist of interest and dividends only.\",\"There were no other distributions of corpus in the current year.\",\"All beneficiaries must be U.S. citizens or resident aliens.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'A trust will qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently,nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nGiven that the Morrison Trust requires all trust income to be distributed currently, and there are no provisions for charitable contributions, the only other requirement for the trust to be deemed a simple trust is that it does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1102,4,'Simon transfers $100,000 of marketable common stock to his mother on April 8. Simon\'s basis in the stock is $80,000. On August 5 of the same year, Simon\'s mother unexpectantly dies; the stock has a fair market value on this date of $105,000. The executor notifies Simon that the gift has been refused and is being returned to Simon on December 8 when the stock has a market value of $115,000. What is Simon\'s basis in the returned stock?','[\"$80,000\",\"$100,000\",\"$105,000\",\"$115,000\"]',0,'The instructions for Form 709, page 3, state, in part, that a donee\'s refusal to accept a gift is called a disclaimer. Moreover, if a person makes a qualified disclaimer with respect to any interest in property, the property will be treated as if it had never been transferred to that person.nnTo be a qualified disclaimer, a refusal to accept an interest in property must meet the following conditions:nnThe refusal must be in writing.nThe refusal must be received by the donor, the legal representative of the donor, the holder of the legal title to the property to which the interest relates, or the person in possession of the property within 9 months after the later of:nthe day on which the transfer creating the interest is made ornthe day on which the disclaimant reaches age 21.nThe disclaimant must not have accepted the interest or any of its benefits.nAs a result of the refusal, the interest must pass without any direction from the disclaimant to either:nthe spouse of the decedent orna person other than the disclaimant.nThe refusal must be irrevocable and unqualified.nFinally, the 9-month period for making the disclaimer generally is determined separately for each taxable transfer.nnAs a result, Simon would keep the original basis of $80,000 for the stock and no gift tax return is necessary since the act is a qualified disclaimer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1103,4,'Which of the following statements is correct about a beneficiary of a simple trust?','[\"The beneficiary must include in his or her gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed.\",\"The trust instrument is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to distribute currently all income.\",\"The trust instrument may provide to set aside amounts permanently for charitable purposes.\",\"The trust may distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.\"]',0,'A trust will qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently,nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nAdditionally, the beneficiary of a simple trust must include in his or her gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI.nnA complex trust is any trust that doesn\'t qualify as a simple trust as explained above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1104,4,'The MLN Trust had the following income and deductions.nn  Taxable interest     $4,000n  Capital gain          1,000n  Fiduciary fee           500nAssuming that capital gains are allocable to corpus, determine the trust\'s distributable net income.','[\"$3,500\",\"$4,000\",\"$4,500\",\"$5,000\"]',0,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 3)nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income as figured on Schedule B. (See the instructions for Form 1041, page 4.)nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the MLN Trust\'s distributable net income is $3,500, which is the AGI of $4,500 (interest income of $4,000 plus capital gains of $1,000 less the fiduciary fee of $500) less the capital gain of $1,000 (allocable to corpus).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1105,4,'After Mary\'s death on August 1, 2024, her estate received the following:nn1. $50,000 life insurance proceedsn2. $1,000 interest income from a certificate of deposit that matured on August 5, 2024n3. $2,000 annual royalty on a patentnWhat amount of taxable income must be reported on the 2024 U.S. Income Tax Return for Estates and Trusts (Form 1041)?','[\"$53,000\",\"$52,400\",\"$3,000\",\"$2,400\"]',3,'When completing Form 1041, any items that are income in respect of a decedent (IRD) must be accounted for. (See the instructions for Form 1041, page 4, for a detailed list of items regarded as income in respect of a decedent.) Generally, income in respect of a decedent is income that a decedent was entitled to receive but that was not properly includible in the decedent\'s final income tax return under the decedent\'s method of accounting.nnAdditionally, a decedent\'s estate is allowed a $600 exemption (Form 1041 Instructions, page 27, line 21).nnTherefore, the amount of taxable income that must be reported on the 2024 U.S. Income Tax Return for Estates and Trusts (Form 1041) is $2,400, determined as follows:nn  Interest Income    $1,000n  Patent Royalty      2,000n  Less:n    Exemption          (600)n  Taxable Income     $2,400nNote: Be careful when reading these questions. Specifically, some questions ask for taxable income and others ask for gross income. In this question, you are asked for taxable income. Hence, the exemption amount is deducted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1106,4,'John Smith died on June 30, 2024. His personal representative enlisted the aid of John\'s nephew, an Enrolled Agent, to prepare a fiduciary income tax return (Form 1041) for the calendar year 2024. John\'s nephew did not charge a fee for the preparation of the return. Who must sign the return prior to filing?','[\"Only John\'s personal representative\",\"Only John\'s nephew\",\"Both the personal representative and the preparer\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'The fiduciary, or an authorized representative, must sign Form 1041. If there are joint fiduciaries, only one is required to sign the return. In addition, if someone prepares the return and does not charge for their services, that person should not sign the return.nnIf someone is paid to prepare a tax return, they must sign the return as a paid preparer and fill in the other blanks in the \"Paid Preparer Use Only\" area of the return. Information in this area includes a person’s preparer tax identification number (PTIN), firm name, address, EIN, and phone number.nnThus, only John\'s personal representative must sign the return prior to filing.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1107,4,'The decedent died on June 30, 2024. The decedent used the cash method of accounting, and a calendar year-end. What total amount of the following is includible in the decedent\'s final return (Form 1040)?nn   Taxable interest (earned equally all year)   $2,000n   Dividends (declared on June 15, 2024, andn      received on July 10, 2024)                   500n   Final wages (received July 10, 2024)          2,500n         Total                                  $5,000','[\"$1,000\",\"$2,500\",\"$4,000\",\"$3,500\"]',0,'The decedent\'s includible income on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return.nnAccordingly, if the decedent accounted for income under the cash method, only those items actually or constructively received before death are included in the final return.nnA dividend is considered constructively received if it was available for use by the decedent without restrictions, which is not the case for this decedent.nnTherefore, the total amount of income that is includible in the decedent\'s final return is $1,000, which is one-half of the taxable interest earned equally all year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1108,4,'Stanley, a decedent, had a $2,000 net operating loss carryforward to his final year. The maximum allowable amount of net operating loss carryforward deducted on his final income tax return was $500. What amount of the unused operating loss is carried forward to the Stanley\'s estate income tax return? (The decedent\'s final 1040 did not generate any additional net operating loss.)','[\"$0\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Generally, an NOL (net operating loss) can be carried forward to subsequent years and cannot be carried back. The 2-year carryback period only applies to the portion of an NOL attributable to a farming loss.nnAny NOLs the deceased individual had at the time of death cannot be transferred or carryforward to the estate. To the extent the deceased individual continued to have a reportable NOL on his final 1040 filing, that NOL would not be transferrable to the estate and thus would be lost. (Revenue Ruling 74-175)nnGiven the above, none of the unused operating loss is carried forward to Stanley\'s estate income tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1109,4,'The LMH Trust is a simple trust. Given the following information, determine the trust\'s distribution deduction.nn   Adjusted total income                $15,000n   Adjusted tax-exempt interestn     (not included in total income)       2,000n   Capital gain allocable to corpus       3,000','[\"$10,000\",\"$12,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$15,000\"]',1,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries.nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income as figured on Schedule B. (See the instructions for Form 1041, pages 3 and 4; and Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the DNI for a simple trust, any amounts allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount.nnThe distributable net income is $12,000, which is the AGI amount of $15,000 less the capital gains of $3,000. Thus, the LMH Trust\'s distribution deduction is limited to the DNI or $12,000 in this case (the capital gain is subtracted because it is applicable to the corpus, which is a special rule for simple trusts).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1110,4,'The MRY Trust has adjusted total income of $10,000. This amount includes a $1,000 capital loss. The trust had no tax-exempt interest income for the year. Determine the trust\'s distributable net income.','[\"$9,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$11,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction (IDD) for distributions to beneficiaries. The income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI) (Instructions for Form 1041, pages 3 and 4; and Form 1041, Schedule B).nnThe trust arrives at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income, which is the amount appearing on line 17 on page 1 of Form 1041.nnForm 1041, Schedule B:nnLine 1: Adj. total income             $10,000nLine 6: Net loss from pg. 1, line 4     1,000*nLine 7: DNI                           $11,000n* Losses are positive numbers here and gains are negative numbers.nnTherefore, Trust B has a DNI of $11,000 and as such will be able to deduct up to $11,000 as an income distribution deduction.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1111,4,'Based on the following information, what is the total allowable deduction against the decedent\'s estate?nn   Mortgages and notes (receivable)     $10,000n   Income in respect of a decedent        5,000n   Funeral expenses                      12,000n   Attorney fees                         20,000','[\"$47,000\",\"$32,000\",\"$42,000\",\"$10,000\"]',1,'An estate will arrive at the tentative taxable estate (Form 706, Part 2, line 3a) by subtracting allowable deductions against its gross estate. A recapitulation of the gross estate and deductions appear as Schedules listed on Form 706, Part 5. The deductions appear on lines 14 through 22 of Form 706, Part 5, and as applicable to this question, the following expenses are permitted as deductions on line 2 of the Tax Computation (Part 2):nnFuneral expenses and administrative expenses, which include attorney\'s fees (Schedule J, Form 706, lines A and B2)nDebts of the decedent (Schedule K, Form 706)nMortgages and liens (Schedule K, Form 706)nSince the mortgages and notes are receivable, they are income items and as such are not deductible items against the decedent’s estate on Schedule K. Therefore, the total allowable deductions against the decedent\'s estate are $32,000, which are the funeral expenses and attorney fees. (Form 706 Instructions, pages 33–34)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1112,4,'Which of the following conditions requires Form 1041, U.S. Income Tax Return for Estates and Trusts, to be filed for a decedent\'s estate?','[\"If the gross income for the tax year is $500 or more, and any beneficiary of the estate is a nonresident alien\",\"If the gross income for the tax year is $600 or more, and any beneficiary of the estate is a nonresident alien\",\"If the gross income for the tax year is $600 or more, or any beneficiary of the estate is a nonresident alien\",\"If the gross income for the tax year is $500 or more, or any beneficiary of the estate is a nonresident alien\"]',2,'The fiduciary (or one of the joint fiduciaries) must file Form 1041 for a domestic estate that has:nngross income for the tax year of $600 or more, orna beneficiary who is a nonresident alien.nif the deceased held a qualified investment in a qualified opportunity fund (QOF) at any time during the year, they must file their return with Form 8997 attached.nAn estate is a domestic estate if it is not a foreign estate. That is, a foreign estate is one the income of which is from sources outside the United States that is not effectively connected with the conduct of a U.S. trade or business and is not includible in gross income.nnIn the case of a foreign estate, Form 1040NR, U.S. Nonresident Alien Income Tax Return is filed instead of Form 1041.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1113,4,'The Tom Trust requires that all trust income be distributed at least annually. There are no provisions for charitable contributions. To be treated as a simple trust, what must also be true?','[\"Trust income can consist of interest and dividends only.\",\"There were no distributions of corpus in the current year.\",\"All beneficiaries must be U.S. citizens or resident aliens.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'A trust will qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently,nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nGiven that the Tom Trust requires all trust income to be distributed annually, and there are no provisions for charitable contributions, the only other requirement for the trust to be deemed a simple trust is that it does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1114,4,'A paycheck issued after the date of death to a taxpayer for work performed prior to death is considered:','[\"non-taxable income.\",\"income in respect of a decedent.\",\"excess compensation.\",\"deferred income.\"]',1,'The entire amount of wages or other employee compensation earned by the decedent but unpaid at the time of death is income in respect of a decedent. The income isn\'t reduced by any amounts withheld by the employer. If the income is $600 or more, the employer should report it in box 3 of Form 1099-NEC.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1115,4,'ABC Trust had the following income and deductions:nn   Taxable interest     $5,000n   Capital gain          1,000n   Fiduciary fee           700nThe trust had no tax-exempt income for the year. Per the trust instrument, capital gains are not allocated to corpus. What is the distributable net income (DNI)?','[\"$6,700\",\"$6,300\",\"$5,300\",\"$4,700\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries.nnThe income distribution deduction allowable to estates and trusts is limited to its distributable net income (DNI). A trust will arrive at DNI by adding and subtracting applicable amounts against its adjusted total income. (See Schedule B on Form 1041.)nnMore specific to the issue in this question, when calculating the DNI, any amounts that are allocable to the corpus are disregarded in determining the adjusted total income amount, but the information given says that the capital gains are NOT allocated to corpus.nnThus, based on the information provided in the above question, the distribution net income is $5,300, calculated as follows:nn   Taxable interest           $5,000n   Plus: Capital gain          1,000n   Less: Fiduciary fee          (700)n   Distributable net income   $5,300',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1116,4,'Ms. Smith, a cash method taxpayer, died on September 30, 2024. Subsequent to her death, but prior to December 31, 2024, her beneficiary received:nn$1,500 in rental income,n$20,000 in proceeds from a life insurance policy, andn$6,000 in dividend declared on September 27, 2024.nWhat amount is considered income in respect of a decedent?','[\"$1,500\",\"$7,500\",\"$3,000\",\"$27,500\"]',1,'The decedent\'s income includible on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return.nnAdditionally, if the decedent accounted for income under the cash method, only those items actually or constructively received before death are included in the final return.nnGenerally, if the decedent receives accelerated death benefits either on his or her life or on the life of another person, those benefits are not included in the decedent\'s income.nnTherefore, the amount of income in respect of a decedent is $7,500, computed as follows:nn                                  Receivedn                                 After Deathn  Rental Income                    $1,500n  Dividend                          6,000n  Income in Respect of Decedent    $7,500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1117,4,'The Bordman Trust, an ongoing trust, was created in 2011. It has net operating loss (NOL) in 2024. Which of the following statements is true regarding the trustee\'s choices for claiming the loss?','[\"Carry the NOL back to 2011.\",\"Carry the NOL forward.\",\"Waive the 2-year carryback period and pass the NOL through to beneficiaries.\",\"Waive the 2-year carryback period and carry the NOL forward.\"]',1,'Generally, an NOL can only be carried forward to subsequent years and cannot be carried back. The 2-year carryback period only applies to the portion of an NOL attributable to a farming loss.nnThus, the trustee of the Bordman Trust can only carry the NOL forward to subsequent years.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1118,4,'Gary died on March 18, 2024. The estate tax year ends on December 31, 2024. The estate had the following items of income during the year:nn Interest                                              $   250n Dividends                                                 150n Stock sale-stock proceeds net of broker\'s commission   10,000n Basis of the stock                                      9,900nThe estate made no distributions during 2024. Which of the following statements regarding the requirement to file a Form 1041 tax return is true?','[\"The estate is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file a tax return.\",\"The estate is required to file a tax return.\",\"If the estate has expenses that reduce its income below $600, no estate tax return is required.\",\"The estate is required to file a tax return\\u00a0and\\u00a0if the estate has expenses that reduce its income below $600, no estate tax return is required.\"]',0,'The fiduciary (or one of the joint fiduciaries) must file Form 1041 for a domestic estate that has:nngross income for the tax year of $600 or more orna beneficiary who is a nonresident alien, ornif the deceased held a qualified investment in a qualified opportunity fund (QOF) at any time during the year, they must file their return with Form 8997 attached.nGiven that the estate had less than $600 in gross income ($250 in interest plus $150 in dividends plus $100 gain on sale ($10,000 less $9,900)), the estate is not required to file a tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1119,4,'The ABC Trust has only nondisabled beneficiaries. The trust is not required to distribute its net income to its beneficiaries, but it does make discretionary distributions. From the information below, determine the amount of taxable income that will be taxed to the trust on its 2024 return (deduct the exemption amount before selecting the answer).nn  Adjusted total income      $70,000n  Distribution deduction      40,000n  Exemption                      ?','[\"$29,400\",\"$29,700\",\"$29,900\",\"$30,000\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. The income distribution deduction determines the amount of any distributions taxed to the beneficiaries. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 3)nnAdditionally, trusts are allowed an exemption amount depending on the type of trust. A trust whose governing instrument requires that all income be distributed currently is allowed a $300 exemption, even if it distributed amounts other than income during the tax year. A qualified disability trust is allowed a $5,050 exemption for 2024. This amount is not subject to phaseout. All other trusts are allowed a $100 exemption. (Instructions for Form 1041, page 27)nnAs a result, the ABC Trust\'s taxable income after allowing the $100 exemption amount (other trust) is $29,900, calculated as follows:nn  Adjusted total income       $70,000n  Less:n    Distribution deduction     40,000 n  Total taxable income        $30,000n  Exemption                      (100)n  Taxable income              $29,900',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1120,4,'John, a retired insurance salesman, died in 2024. Using the information below, determine the amount of income in respect of a decedent that must be reported on the estate\'s Form 1041 income tax return.nn                                 Received Before    Received Aftern                                      Death              Death    n  Wages                              $10,000           $  3,000n  Renewal commissions                 20,000              7,000n  Life insurance (on John\'s life)                       100,000','[\"$3,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$110,000\",\"$170,000\"]',1,'The decedent\'s income includible on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return (Publication 559, page 5).nnAdditionally, all income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that was not properly includible on the final return is income in respect of a decedent (Publication 559, page 6).nnGenerally, if the decedent receives accelerated death benefits either on his or her own life or on the life of another person, those benefits are not included in the decedent\'s income (Publication 559, page 8).nnThe amount of income in respect of a decedent that must be reported on the estate\'s Form 1041 income tax return is $10,000, computed as follows:nn                                  Received n                                 After Deathn  Wages                            $ 3,000n  Renewal Commissions                7,000n  Income in Respect of Decedent    $10,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1121,4,'A trust was required to distribute $10,000 a year to its sole beneficiary out of the trust\'s income for the year. In 2024, the distributable net income of the trust was $8,000 and the actual amount distributed was $7,000. How much income must the beneficiary report for 2024?','[\"$10,000\",\"$8,000\",\"$0\",\"$7,000\"]',1,'A trust will qualify as a simple trust if:nnthe trust instrument requires that all income must be distributed currently,nthe trust instrument does not provide that any amounts are to be paid, permanently set aside, or used for charitable purposes, andnthe trust does not distribute amounts allocated to the corpus of the trust.nAdditionally, the beneficiary of a simple trust must include in his or her gross income the amount of the income required to be distributed currently, whether or not distributed, or if the income required to be distributed currently to all beneficiaries exceeds the distributable net income (DNI), his or her proportionate share of the DNI.nnGiven that the trust had $8,000 of distributable net income to distribute, the beneficiary should report income of $8,000, computed as follows:nn  DNI                    $8,000n  100% Beneficiary       x  1.0n  To the beneficiary     $8,000',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1122,4,'From the information below, determine the taxable income on Form 1041 for the estate of Janice.nn  Income                               Expenses                    n  Taxable interest          $4,000     Attorney\'s fees      $1,500n  Tax-exempt interest        2,000     Funeral expenses      5,000n  Dividends                  3,000          n  Gain on sale of stock      1,000','[\"$8,000\",\"$5,900\",\"$6,200\",\"$2,000\"]',2,'A trust or decedent\'s estate figures its gross income in much the same manner as an individual. Most deductions and credits allowed to individuals are also allowed to estates and trusts. However, one major distinction is that a trust or decedent\'s estate is allowed an income distribution deduction for distributions to beneficiaries. To figure this deduction, the fiduciary must complete Schedule B of Form 1041. The income distribution deduction determines the amount of any distributions taxed to the beneficiaries (Form 1041 Instructions, page 3).nnAdditionally, a decedent\'s estate is allowed a $600 exemption. Trusts, on the other hand, are allowed an exemption amount depending on the type of trust. A trust whose governing instrument requires that all income be distributed currently is allowed a $300 exemption, even if it distributed amounts other than income during the tax year. A qualified disability trust is allowed a $5,050 exemption for 2024. This amount is not subject to phaseout.nnAll other trusts are allowed a $100 exemption (Form 1041 Instructions, page 27).nnWith respect to the attorney fees, a reasonable amount must be allocated to the tax-exempt interest. Hence, a reasonable amount to deduct is $1,200 (($8,000 ÷ $10,000) × $1,500).nnCaution: It is common to see the reasonable amount being calculated based on the interest-only amounts. In that case, the deductible amount would have been $1,000 (($4,000 ÷ $6,000) × $1,500) and the correct response would have been $6,400, which is not given.nnAs a result, the taxable income attributable to the estate of Janice is $6,200, calculated as follows:nn  Taxable Interest     $4,000n  Dividends             3,000n  Gain                  1,000n  Total Income         $8,000n  Less:n    Attorney           (1,200)n    Exemption            (600)n  Taxable Income       $6,200nFuneral expenses are deductible on Form 706.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1123,4,'Income in respect of a decedent must not be included in the income of which of the following?','[\"The decedent\'s final 1040 filing\",\"The decedent\'s estate (if received by the estate)\",\"The beneficiary\'s filing (if the right to income is passed directly to and received by the beneficiary)\",\"Any person to whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it\"]',0,'The decedent\'s income includible on the final return is generally determined as if the person were still alive except that the taxable period is usually shorter because it ends on the date of death. The method of accounting regularly used by the decedent before death also determines the income includible on the final return (Publication 559, page 6).nnAdditionally, all income the decedent would have received had death not occurred that was not properly includible on the final return is income in respect of a decedent.nnPublication 559, page 13, states that income in respect of a decedent must be included in the income of one of the following:nnthe decedent\'s estate, if the estate receives it;nthe beneficiary, if the right to income is passed directly to the beneficiary and the beneficiary receives it; ornany person to whom the estate properly distributes the right to receive it.nTherefore, income in respect of a decedent must not be included in the income of the decedent’s final Form 1040 filing',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1124,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a grantor type trust?','[\"It is a legal entity under applicable state law.\",\"Since the grantor has not relinquished complete control over the trust, it is not recognized as a separate taxable entity for income tax purposes.\",\"All of the income and deductions are treated as belonging directly to the grantor of a grantor trust (not the trust).\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A trust is a grantor trust if the grantor retains certain powers or ownership benefits. In general, a grantor trust is ignored for tax purposes and all of the income, deductions, etc. are treated as belonging directly to the grantor (not the trust). This also applies to any portion of a trust that is treated as a grantor trust (Instructions for Form 1041, pages 13–14).nnIn addition, a grantor type trust is a legal trust under applicable state law that is not recognized as a separate taxable entity for income tax purposes because the grantor has not relinquished complete dominion and control over the trust (Instructions for Form 1041, pages 18–19).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1125,4,'John Jacobsen is a cash basis cattle rancher. In 2024, John sold 12 head of cattle for $9,600. The cattle were born on his ranch in 2021. During the 3 years that John used these cattle in his breeding operation, he spent $10,000 for feed and other expenses related to the cattle. How much is John\'s gain or loss for 2024, and where should he report the amount on his federal income tax return?','[\"John should report a net gain of $9,600 on Form 4797.\",\"John should report a net loss of $400 on Form 4797.\",\"John should report $9,600 from the sale of the cattle on Schedule F.\",\"John should report a net loss of $400 on Schedule F.\"]',0,'Publication 225, page 10, provides the general rules for income reporting for farmers. To begin, income from farming reported on Schedule F (Form 1040) includes amounts received by the taxpayer from cultivating, operating, or managing a farm for gain or profit, either as owner or tenant. This includes income from operating a stock, dairy, poultry, fish, fruit, or truck farm and income from operating a plantation, ranch, range, or orchard. It also includes income from the sale of crop shares if the farmer materially participates in producing the crop.nnAssuming that John uses the cash method (and not the accrual method) of accounting, he is able to deduct breeding fees as a farm business expense. If he was required to use the accrual method, he would be required to capitalize the costs. (Publication 225, page 22)nnNote: IRC Section 447(a) provides the general rule that the accrual method of accounting shall be used in computing taxable income from farming of a corporation engaged in the trade or business of farming, or a partnership engaged in the trade or business of farming, if a corporation is a partner in such partnership.nnPublication 225, page 11, provides that income reported on Schedule F does not include gains or losses from sales or other dispositions of the following farm assets: land, depreciable farm equipment, buildings and structures, and livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes. Rather, the sales of livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes may result in ordinary or capital gains or losses, depending on the circumstances. In either case, the taxpayer should always report these sales on Form 4797.nnIn this problem, the farmer sold 12 head of cattle for $9,600, which is the gain on the sale. The selling price is the gain in this example because the cows had no adjusted basis, since they were “born” to the farmer rather than purchased. This gain on the sale of livestock held for breeding is reported on Form 4797. In addition, the $10,000 cost of feed and other expenses related to the cattle is expensed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1126,4,'Farmer John, a cash basis farmer, operates a cow-calf breeding operation. The breeder cows are not primarily held for sale. In addition to the calves raised on his farm, John also purchases calves for resale. During 2024, John had the following acquisitions and dispositions of cattle:nn  Purchase of 30 calves for resale             $ 3,420n  Sale of 30 calves purchased for resale         6,100n  Sale of 45 calves raised by John              10,400n  Sale of 10 breeder cows                        6,750n  Original cost of breeder cows                  5,500n  Accumulated depreciation on breeder cows       2,860nWhat amount should John include in gross income on his Schedule F for 2024?','[\"$13,080\",\"$15,720\",\"$16,500\",\"$18,580\"]',0,'Publication 225, page 9, provides that when a farmer sells livestock, produce, grains, or other products raised on the taxpayer\'s farm for sale or bought for resale, the entire amount received is reported on Schedule F (Form 1040). This includes money and the fair market value of any property or services received.nnMore specifically, when a farmer sells farm products bought for resale, the profit or loss is the difference between the selling price (money plus the fair market value of any property) and the basis in the item (usually the item\'s cost).nnIn addition, sales of livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes may result in ordinary or capital gains or losses, depending on the circumstances. In either case, these transactions are reported on Form 4797 instead of Schedule F and therefore are not part of gross income from farming.nnFarmer John would report $13,080 in gross income, which is the sum of $10,400 from the sale of the 45 calves and the profit of $2,680 ($6,100 − $3,420) from the sale of the 30 calves. The sale of the breeder cows would not be shown in gross income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1127,4,'Farmer Judy is a calendar year taxpayer who uses the cash method of accounting. She normally sells 200 head of sheep a year. Because of a drought, she sold 250 head of sheep in 2024. Farmer Judy realized $50,000 from the sale. The affected area was declared a disaster area eligible for federal assistance on March 12, 2024. How much, if any, income can Farmer Judy postpone to 2025?','[\"$10,000\",\"$50,000\",\"$12,500\",\"$0, since only sales because of flooding qualify for postponement\"]',0,'Publication 225, page 11, provides a special provision for farmers that sell or exchange more livestock, including poultry, than the farmer normally would in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition. That is, the farmer may be able to postpone reporting the gain from the additional animals until the next year. The farmer/taxpayer must meet all the following conditions to qualify:nnThe taxpayer\'s principal trade or business is farming.nThe taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting.nThe taxpayer can show that, under his or her usual business practices, he or she would not have sold or exchanged the additional animals this year except for the weather-related condition.nThe weather-related condition caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.nOne should realize that sales or exchanges made before an area became eligible for federal assistance qualify if the weather-related condition that caused the sale or exchange also caused the area to be designated as eligible for federal assistance. The designation can be made by the president, the Department of Agriculture (or any of its agencies), or by other federal departments or agencies.nnFarmer Judy appears to qualify for postponing the proceeds received from the sale of the additional head of sheep in 2024 until 2025. Thus, she can postpone $10,000, which is the amount attributable to the added sales ((50 head of sheep ÷ 250 head of sheep) × $50,000).nnFarmer Judy determines this amount by dividing the total income realized from the sale of all livestock in the class during the tax year ($50,000) by the total number of such livestock sold during the same tax year (250 head of sheep). She does not include any postponed gain in this part of the formula. Then, Judy multiplies the quotient she just determined by the excess number of such livestock sold solely because of weather-related conditions (50 head of sheep).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1128,4,'Leonard Brown operated a cattle and grain farm in 2024. Leonard sold $42,000 of grain and $23,000 of cattle held for breeding purposes. Leonard also received patronage dividends from the local feed store of $432, feed assistance payments of $1,200, and $1,500 for haying a neighbor\'s meadow. Leonard should report the following on Schedule F of his federal income tax return for 2024:','[\"$45,132.\",\"$67,700.\",\"$44,700.\",\"$66,932.\"]',0,'Publication 225, page 10, provides the general rules for income reporting for farmers. To begin, income from farming reported on Schedule F (Form 1040) includes amounts received by the taxpayer from cultivating, operating, or managing a farm for gain or profit, either as owner or tenant. This includes income from operating a stock, dairy, poultry, fish, fruit, or truck farm and income from operating a plantation, ranch, range, orchard, or grove. It also includes income from the sale of crop shares if the farmer materially participates in producing the crop.nnIncome received from operating a nursery, which specializes in growing ornamental plants, is considered to be income from farming.nnIn addition, when a farmer sells livestock, produce, grains, or other products raised on a farm for sale or bought for resale, the entire amount received is reported on Schedule F. This includes money and the fair market value of any property or services received.nnIncome reported on Schedule F does not include gains or losses from sales or other dispositions of the following farm assets: land, depreciable farm equipment, buildings and structures, and livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes. Rather, it is reported on Form 4797.nnPublication 225, page 13, presents the information concerning feed assistance and repayment. More specifically, the Disaster Assistance Act of 1988 authorizes programs to provide feed assistance, reimbursement payments, and other benefits to qualifying livestock producers if the Secretary of Agriculture determines that, because of a natural disaster, a livestock emergency exists. In such cases, a taxpayer includes in income the market value of donated feed, the difference between the market value and the price paid for feed purchased at below market prices, and any cost reimbursement received. The taxpayer must include these benefits in income in the year received, and the taxpayer cannot postpone reporting them under the rules for weather-related sales of livestock or crop insurance proceeds.nnIf a farmer pastures someone else\'s livestock and takes care of them for a fee, the income is from the farming business and is reported as other income on Schedule F. (Publication 225, page 10)nnPublication 225, page 15, provides that a taxpayer generally reports patronage dividends as income on Schedule F, lines 3a and 3b, for the tax year they are received. Patronage dividends include money paid as a patronage dividend, the stated dollar value of qualified written notices of allocation, and the fair market value of other property.nnLeonard Brown would report $45,132 on his Schedule F. This amount is the sum of the grain ($42,000), patronage dividends ($432), feed assistance ($1,200), and the haying income ($1,500).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1129,4,'What tax reporting options are available to a farmer who sells more livestock, including poultry, than he or she normally would in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition?','[\"May be able to carry back the gain from selling the additional animals to the prior year\",\"May be able to postpone reporting one-half of the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year\",\"May be able to postpone reporting the entire gain from selling the additional animals until the next year\",\"May be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until 2 years from the current year\"]',2,'(Note: This question generally appears on the exam in one form or another in most years.)nnPublication 225, page 10, provides a special rule for farmers where sales are caused by weather-related conditions. In particular, if a farmer sells more livestock, including poultry, than normally would occur in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition, the farmer may be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year.nnTo take advantage of this special provision, the farmer must meet all the following conditions:nnYour principal trade or business is farming.nYou use the cash method of accounting.nYou can show that, under your usual business practices, you would not have sold the additional animals this year except for the weather-related condition.nThe weather-related condition caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1130,4,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the use of farm income averaging?','[\"It may create alternative minimum tax.\",\"A farmer can use income averaging and may reduce total tax even if the farmer owes AMT.\",\"Income averaging cannot be used, changed, or canceled on an amended return.\",\"Income averaging is elected by filing Schedule F.\"]',1,'Publication 225, pages 19–20, provides that a farmer is able to choose income averaging in computing his or her regular tax liability. However, income averaging is not used to determine regular tax or tentative minimum tax when figuring AMT. Therefore, a farmer can use income averaging and may reduce his or her total tax even if the farmer owes AMT.nnIn addition, income averaging is elected by filing Schedule J of Form 1040 (not Schedule F) and it can be used on a late return or used, changed, or canceled on an amended return if the time for filing a claim for refund has not expired for that election year.nnNote: Publication 225, pages 19–20 provides that farmers electing farm income averaging may want to include taxable income from the fair market value (trade value) of traded farm assets as electable farm income. Under the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, personal property, such as tractors and equipment, no longer qualifies for a like-kind exchange and is now subject to depreciation recapture on the FMV of the trade as if cash was exchanged.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1131,4,'For tax year 2024, farm income averaging may be elected as a tax computation method:','[\"only before March 1 of the year following the end of the tax year.\",\"any time before the statute expires for the tax year of the election.\",\"after the due date of the return, but only when other changes are made to the return, such as an IRS audit adjustment.\",\"only if you were engaged as a corporation in farming in the election year and all of the base years.\"]',1,'Publication 225, pages 19–20, provides that, in general, a taxpayer can use income averaging to figure his or her tax for any year in which the taxpayer was engaged in a farming business as an individual, a partner in a partnership, or a shareholder in an S corporation. Corporations, partnerships, S corporations, estates, and trusts cannot use income averaging.nnA taxpayer can use income averaging by filing Schedule J (Form 1040) with the taxpayer\'s timely filed (including extensions) return for the year. A taxpayer can also use income averaging on a late return, or use, change, or cancel it on an amended return, if the time for filing a claim for refund has not expired for that election year. In general, a taxpayer must file the claim for refund within 3 years from the date of filing the original return or 2 years from the date the taxpayer paid the tax, whichever is later. (Publication 225, pages 19–20)nnGiven the above rules, the correct response to this question is any time before the statute expires for the tax year of the election.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1132,4,'A farmer has the following sources of income:nn  Milk sales                          $100,000n  Sales of old dairy cows               12,000n  Agricultural Program Payments         30,000n  Sales of calves raised for sale        2,000n  Corn sales                            24,000n  Tractor sold                           7,000nThe income to be reported on Schedule F, Profit or Loss from Farming, is:','[\"$175,000.\",\"$156,000.\",\"$168,000.\",\"$163,000.\"]',1,'Publication 225, page 9, states that farm income is reported on Schedule F (Form 1040).nnIncome from farming includes amounts received from cultivating, operating, or managing a farm for gain or profit, either as owner or tenant. This includes income from operating a stock, dairy, poultry, fish, fruit, or truck farm and income from operating a plantation, ranch, range, or orchard. It also includes income from the sale of crop shares if the taxpayer materially participates in producing the crop. Income received from operating a nursery, which specializes in growing ornamental plants, is considered to be income from farming.nnPublication 225, page 9, provides that the farmer must include in income most government payments, such as those for approved conservation practices, livestock indemnity payments, or livestock forage disaster payments whether received in cash, materials, services, or commodity certificates. However, the farmer can exclude from income some payments received under certain cost-sharing conservation programs. The agricultural program payment is reported on the appropriate line of Schedule F, Part 1.nnFarming income, however, does not include gains or losses from sales or other dispositions of the following farm assets: land, depreciable farm equipment, buildings and structures, and livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes (Publication 225, page 10).nnAs a result, the farmer in this problem has farming income of $156,000, which is the sum of $100,000 for milk sales, $30,000 for Agricultural Program Payments, $24,000 for corn sales, and $2,000 for sales of calves raised for sale ($100,000 + $30,000 + $24,000 + $2,000). The sale of the tractor (depreciable farm equipment) and the sale of old dairy cows (livestock held for dairy purposes) are not included in farming income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1133,4,'In November 2023, Farmer Smith, a cash basis taxpayer, sells 100 additional beef feeder cattle (raised for resale) due to severe lack of water in his area. Normally, these feeders would not have been sold until February 2024. The transaction is correctly reported:','[\"in 2023 as a capital gain or loss.\",\"in 2024 as a capital gain or loss.\",\"upon election, as ordinary farm income in either 2023 or 2024.\",\"as not taxable due to drought conditions.\"]',2,'Publication 225, page 10, provides a special rule for farmers where sales are caused by weather-related conditions. In particular, if a farmer sells more livestock, including poultry, than he or she normally would in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition, the farmer may be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year.nnTo take advantage of this special provision, the farmer must meet all the following conditions:nnThe taxpayer\'s principal trade or business is farming.nThe taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting.nThe taxpayer can show that, under his or her usual business practices, the taxpayer would not have sold or exchanged the additional animals this year except for the weather-related condition.nThe weather-related condition caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.nIn addition, when a farmer sells livestock, produce, grains, or other products that the farmer raised on his or her farm for sale or bought for resale, the entire amount that the farmer receives is reported as ordinary farm income on Schedule F (Form 1040). (Publication 225, page 10)nnThus, Farmer Smith can, upon election, claim as ordinary farm income the amount he receives from the sale of his beef feeder cattle in either 2023 or 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1134,4,'Sandy had the following total gross income for 2024:nn   Taxable interest                   $45,000n   Dividends                            1,000n   Rental income (Schedule E)           1,500n   Farm income (Schedule F)            75,000n   Gain from sale of farm animals       5,000nHow much of Sandy\'s gross income qualifies as gross income from farming?','[\"$75,000\",\"$80,000\",\"$81,500\",\"$127,500\"]',1,'Publication 225, page 10, provides the general rules for sales of business property for farmers. To begin with, income from farming reported on Schedule F (Form 1040) includes amounts received by the taxpayer from cultivating, operating, or managing a farm for gain or profit, either as owner or tenant. This includes income from operating a stock, dairy, poultry, fish, fruit, or truck farm and income from operating a plantation, ranch, range, or orchard. It also includes income from the sale of crop shares if the farmer materially participates in producing the crop.nnIncome reported on Schedule F does not include gains or losses from sales or other dispositions of the following farm assets: land, depreciable farm equipment, buildings and structures, and livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes. Since the problem does not state that the farm animals were livestock held for draft, breeding, sport or dairy, we must assume that they were raised on the farm for sale or bought for resale.nnIn addition, when a farmer sells livestock, produce, grains, or other products that the farmer raised on his or her farm for sale or bought for resale, the entire amount that the farmer receives is reported on Schedule F. This includes money and the fair market value of any property or services the farmer receives.nnAssuming that the farm animals were raised on the farm for sale or bought for resale, Sandy would report $80,000 as gross income from farming. The $80,000 is the sum of $75,000 from farm income and $5,000 from sale of farm animals.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1135,4,'Bobby Rice is an unincorporated grain farmer in Louisiana with a calendar year-end. He does not live or farm in a disaster area. Bobby computed an estimated tax liability of $25,000 for 2024. To avoid the failure to pay estimated tax penalty, he should:','[\"make his first 2024 estimated tax payment by March 1, 2025.\",\"pay all his 2024 estimated taxes by February 15, 2025, and file his tax return by April 15, 2025.\",\"include any alternative minimum tax he expects to owe in his calculation of 2024 estimated taxes.\",\"pay all of his 2024 estimated taxes by the due date of his return.\"]',2,'Publication 505, pages 22–23, provides that if at least 2/3rds of a taxpayer\'s gross income for 2023 or 2024 is from farming, the taxpayer\'s required annual payment is the smaller of:nn66-2/3% (0.6667) of the total tax for 2024 orn100% of the total tax shown on the 2023 return (2023 return must cover all 12 months)nPage 26 of Publication 505 further provides: if at least two thirds (2/3) of the taxpayers gross income for 2023 or 2024 is from farming or fishing, they will have only one payment due date for the 2024 estimated tax, January 15, 2025. Further, if the taxpayer files their 2024 Form 1040 or 1040-SR by March 1, 2025, they do not need to make an estimated tax payment.nnForm 2210 Instructions, page 2, provides that if the taxpayer\'s gross income from farming or fishing is at least two-thirds of their annual gross income from all sources for 2023 and 2024, and the taxpayer filed Form 1040, 1040-SR, or 1041 and paid the entire tax due by March 1, 2024, the taxpayer will not owe a penalty for underpayment of estimated tax. If the taxpayer meets the first test (gross income test), but not the second (payment is not made by March 1), the taxpayer must use Form 2210-F to see if they owe a penalty. If total tax owed for 2024 is less than $1,000, no penalty should be assessed (Form 2210-F, page 2).nnIn addition, estimated taxes are used to pay not only income tax, but self-employment tax and alternative minimum tax as well (Publication 505, page 1).nnFor this problem, Bobby Rice can avoid any filing or estimated tax penalty by including any AMT (alternative minimum tax) that he expects to owe in his calculation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1136,4,'Which of the following statements is correct about crop insurance and disaster payments?','[\"The insurance proceeds can be deferred only if the farmer can show that the income from the crops would normally be reported in a tax year following the year of damage.\",\"An accrual basis taxpayer can elect to include crop insurance proceeds in income for the tax year following the tax year in which the crops were damaged.\",\"Insurance proceeds received in the tax year following the tax year in which the crops were destroyed can be deferred until the tax year following receipt of the proceeds.\",\"A separate election to defer the inclusion of crop disaster payments must be made for each damaged crop of the trade or business.\"]',0,'Publication 225, pages 12–13, provides, in part, that a taxpayer farmer must include in income any crop insurance proceeds received as the result of crop damage, or reduction of crop revenue, or both in the year received.nnHowever, Publication 225, pages 12–13, provides a special rule for choosing to postpone reporting until the following year. A taxpayer can postpone reporting crop insurance proceeds as income until the year following the year the damage occurred if the taxpayer meets all of the following conditions:nnthe taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting,nthe taxpayer receives the crop insurance proceeds in the same tax year the crops are damaged, andnthe taxpayer can show that under his or her normal business practice the taxpayer would have included income from the damaged crops in any tax year following the year the damage occurred.nDeferral isn\'t permitted for proceeds received from revenue insurance policies.nnTo postpone reporting crop insurance proceeds received in 2024, report the amount received on line 6a of Schedule F (Form 1040), but do not include it as a taxable amount on line 6b. Check the box on line 6c and attach a statement to the tax return. The statement must include the taxpayer\'s name and address and other information that can be found on pages 12–13 of Publication 225.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1137,4,'Dan, a calendar year taxpayer, has the following amounts of gross income for 2024:nn   Wages           $ 10,000n   Interest           2,000n   Farm income      200,000nDan has tax, including self-employment tax, of $20,000, and withholding of $1,000. To avoid any filing or estimated tax penalties, Dan must:','[\"file an estimated tax payment by January 15, 2025, and pay 60% of the tax due.\",\"file his tax return and pay all tax due by March 1, 2025.\",\"file an estimated tax payment by March 1, 2025, and pay 66.67% of the tax due.\",\"file his tax return and pay all tax due by April 15, 2025.\"]',1,'Publication 225 (pages 88–89) provides the rules for the due dates for qualified farmers. If at least 2/3rds of the farmer\'s gross income for 2023 or 2024 was from farming, the farmer is a qualified farmer and can choose either of the following options for his or her 2024 tax and not be penalized for failure to pay estimated tax:nnMake his or her required annual payment by January 15, 2025, and file his or her Form 1040 by April 15, 2025, ornFile his or her Form 1040 by March 1, 2025, and pay all of the tax due.nThe required annual payment mentioned in the first option above is the smaller of the following amounts:nn66.67% (.6667) of his or her total tax for 2024, orn100% of the total tax shown on his or her 2023 return (The return must cover all 12 months).nThus, Dan can avoid any filing or estimated tax penalty by filing his tax return and pay all tax due by March 1, 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1138,4,'If you sell more livestock than you normally would in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition, you may be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year. You must meet all of the following conditions to make the election, except:','[\"you can show that, under your usual business practices, you would not have sold the animals this year except for the weather-related conditions.\",\"the weather-related conditions caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.\",\"you use the accrual method of accounting.\",\"your principal trade or business is farming.\"]',2,'Publication 225, page 10, provides that if a farmer sells more livestock, including poultry, than he or she normally would in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition, the taxpayer may be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year. To do so, the taxpayer must meet all the following conditions:nnThe taxpayer\'s principal trade or business is farming.nThe taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting.nThe taxpayer can show that, under his or her usual business practices, the taxpayer would not have sold the additional animals this year except for the weather-related condition.nThe weather-related condition caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.nThe use of the accrual method of accounting is not one of the conditions. Rather, the cash method is a condition.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1139,4,'The Post and Rail Partnership traded a piece of farmland with an adjusted basis of $4,000 for a farm tractor that has a fair market value of $9,000 and an adjusted basis of $8,000. What is the recognized gain or loss?','[\"$5,000\",\"$4,000\",\"$1,000\",\"None, it is a like-kind exchange.\"]',0,'Publication 544, page 3, provides the general rule that a gain or loss is usually realized when property is sold or exchanged. A gain is the amount the taxpayer realizes from a sale or exchange of property that is more than its adjusted basis. A loss is the adjusted basis of the property that is more than the amount the taxpayer realizes.nnFor exchanges completed after December 31, 2017, the nonrecognition rules for like-kind exchanges apply only to exchanges of real property not held primarily for sale. The nonrecognition rules no longer apply to personal property.nnIn this case, the taxpayer receives a farm tractor that has an FMV of $9,000 and gives up farm property that has an adjusted basis of $4,000. Since this exchange is not like-kind property, the taxpayer has a gain of $5,000, which is the difference between the $9,000 and $4,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1140,4,'Under which of the following conditions may a farmer who sells more livestock than he normally would in a year because of a drought, elect to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals to the following year?','[\"The taxpayer\'s principal business is farming.\",\"The taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting.\",\"The taxpayer can show that he would not have sold the additional animals if not for the weather conditions.\",\"All of the answer choices are necessary conditions.\"]',3,'Publication 225, page 10, provides a special rule for farmers where sales are caused by weather-related conditions. In particular, if a farmer sells more livestock, including poultry, than normally would occur in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition, the farmer may be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year.nnTo take advantage of this special provision, the farmer must meet all the following conditions:nnThe taxpayer\'s principal trade or business is farming.nThe taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting.nThe taxpayer can show that, under his or her usual business practices, the taxpayer would not have sold the additional animals this year except for the weather-related condition.nThe weather-related condition caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.nThe IRS annually issues a notice in late September that list severe drought areas for livestock sold on account of drought. Notice 2024-70 was issued for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1141,4,'If at least 2/3rds of your gross income for 2023 or 2024 was from farming, only one estimated tax payment is due. The required annual payment is the:','[\"larger of 2\\/3rds of your total tax for 2024 or 100% of the total tax shown on your full-year 2023 return.\",\"smaller of 2\\/3rds of your total tax for 2023 or 100% of the total tax shown on your full-year 2024 return.\",\"larger of 2\\/3rds of your total tax for 2023 or 100% of the total tax shown on your full-year 2024 return.\",\"smaller of 2\\/3rds of your total tax for 2024 or 100% of the total tax shown on your full-year 2023 return.\"]',3,'Publication 225, pages 88–89, provides the rules for the due dates for qualified farmers. If at least 2/3rds of the farmer\'s gross income for 2023 or 2024 was from farming, the taxpayer is a qualified farmer and can choose either of the following options for his 20243 tax and not be penalized for failure to pay estimated tax:nnMake the required annual payment by January 15, 2025, and file the Form 1040 by April 15, 2025, ornFile the Form 1040 by March 1, 2025, and pay all of the tax due.nThe required annual payment is the smaller of:nn66.67% (.6667) of their total tax for 2024 orn100% of the total tax shown on their 2023 return (the return must cover all 12 months).nFor this problem, the required annual payment is the smaller of 2/3rds of the taxpayer\'s total tax for 2024 or 100% of the total tax shown on their full-year 2023 return. See Figure 15-1 on page 89 of Publication 225.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1142,4,'Which of the following statements is correct in regard to postponing gains from sales caused by drought conditions?','[\"Livestock not raised or sold in a drought area will qualify if the sale occurred solely because of drought conditions.\",\"Livestock sold before the area became eligible for federal assistance qualify so long as the drought that caused the sale also caused the area to be designated as eligible for federal assistance.\",\"Poultry qualifies if the sale was due to drought conditions.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 225, page 10, provides a special rule for farmers where sales are caused by weather-related conditions. In particular, if a farmer sells more livestock, including poultry, than normally would occur in a year because of a drought, flood, or other weather-related condition, the farmer may be able to postpone reporting the gain from selling the additional animals until the next year.nnTo take advantage of this special provision, the farmer must meet all the following conditions:nnThe taxpayer\'s principal trade or business is farming.nThe taxpayer uses the cash method of accounting.nThe taxpayer can show that, under his or her usual business practices, the taxpayer would not have sold the additional animals this year except for the weather-related condition.nThe weather-related condition caused an area to be designated as eligible for assistance by the federal government.nSales or exchanges made before an area became eligible for federal assistance qualify if the weather-related condition that caused the sale or exchange also caused the area to be designated as eligible for federal assistance.nnThe livestock does not have to be raised or sold in an area affected by a weather-related condition for the postponement to apply. However, the sale must occur solely because of a weather-related condition that affected the water, grazing, or other requirements of the livestock. This requirement generally will not be met if the costs of food, water, or other requirements of the livestock affected by the weather-related condition are not substantial in relation to the total costs of holding the livestock.nnIn light of the above rules, all of the items listed in this problem are correct statements.nnIn addition, the IRS annually issues a notice in late September that lists severe drought areas for livestock sold on account of drought. Notice 2024-70 was issued for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1143,4,'A farmer sold a 3-year-old raised dairy cow for $600. It cost him $75 for shipping and commissions to sell the cow. He reports this sale as follows on his tax return:','[\"A loss of $75 on his Schedule F\",\"A Section 1245 gain of $525 reported on Form 4797\",\"A gain of $525 reported on Schedule F as ordinary farm income\",\"A Section 1231 gain of $525 reported on Form 4797\"]',3,'Publication 225, page 10, provides the general rules for sales of business property for farmers. To begin, income from farming reported on Schedule F (Form 1040), which includes amounts received by the taxpayer from cultivating, operating, or managing a farm for gain or profit, either as owner or tenant. This includes income from operating a stock, dairy, poultry, fish, fruit, or truck farm and income from operating a plantation, ranch, range, or orchard. It also includes income from the sale of crop shares if the farmer materially participates in producing the crop.nnIncome received from operating a nursery, which specializes in growing ornamental plants, is considered to be income from farming.nnAmounts received from the sale of products raised on the farm for sale (or bought for resale), such as livestock, produce, or grains, are reported on Schedule F.nnHowever, as provided on page 9 of Publication 225 (under Form 4797 header), sales of livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes may result in ordinary or capital gains or losses, depending on the circumstances. In either case, a taxpayer should always report these sales on Form 4797 (under Section 1231 gains) instead of Schedule F.nnIn this problem, the farmer sold a 3-year-old raised dairy cow, which would fall under the category of income that is not reported on Schedule F but rather on Form 4797. The amount to be reported is $525, which is the difference between the selling price of $600 and the cost of shipping the cow of $75. Apparently, the cow had no adjusted basis to account for. If it did, the adjusted basis would be subtracted from the selling price for purposes of determining profit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1144,4,'Farm income averaging is computed on Schedule J, which may be filed:','[\"for the current year when a taxpayer files Schedule F showing a farm loss.\",\"for the current year when a taxpayer files Schedule F showing net income from farming.\",\"only by the IRS after the taxpayer\'s return is completed and reviewed.\",\"on a family farming corporation with less than $30 million in gross receipts.\"]',1,'Publication 225, page 9, provides that farmers report farm income on Schedule F (Form 1040) to figure net profit or loss from regular farming operations.nnPublication 225, page 19, provides that if a taxpayer is engaged in a farming business, he or she may be able to average all or some of the farm income by allocating it to the 3 prior years. This may result in a lower tax liability if the taxpayer\'s current-year income is higher and the taxpayer\'s taxable income which includes income from farming from 1 or more of the 3 prior years was low. The key factor here is that the current year’s income is higher; hence, it is not a loss.nnNow, if a farmer elects to use farm income averaging, he or she does so by filing Schedule J (Form 1040) with his or her timely filed (including extensions) return for the year. Hence, Schedule J may be filed with Schedule F showing net income from farming.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1145,4,'How must a corporate horse breeder account for breeding fees under Section 447?','[\"Use the accrual method of accounting for tax purposes and capitalize the breeding fees and allocate them to the cost basis of offspring.\",\"Use the accrual method of accounting for tax purposes and amortize the breeding fees over a 5-year period.\",\"Use the accrual method of accounting for tax purposes and depreciate the breeding fees as 3-year property under MACRS.\",\"Use the cash method of accounting for tax purposes and expense the breeding fees in the year purchased.\"]',0,'Under an accrual method of accounting, you generally report income in the year earned and deduct or capitalize expenses in the year incurred. The purpose of an accrual method of accounting is to correctly match income and expenses. Certain businesses engaged in farming must use an accrual method of accounting for their farm business and for sales and purchases of inventory items. (Publication 225, page 7)nnIRC Section 447(a) provides the general rule that the accrual method of accounting shall be used in computing taxable income from farming of a corporation engaged in the trade or business of farming, or a partnership engaged in the trade or business of farming, if a corporation is a partner in such partnership. Publication 225, page 7, gives other limitations to the kinds of corporations or other organizations that are required to use accrual accounting. In general, the following businesses are required to use an accrual method of accounting:nnA corporation that has gross receipts of more than $30 million.nA partnership with a corporation as a partner, if that corporation meets the $30 million requirement, ornA tax shelter.nWith respect to breeding fees, Publication 225, page 22, provides that a taxpayer can deduct breeding fees as a farm business expense. If, however, the taxpayer uses the accrual method of accounting (as a corporation does), the taxpayer must capitalize breeding fees and allocate them to the cost basis of the calf, foal, etc.nnNote: Breeding fees are not discussed in IRC Section 447.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1146,4,'Which of the following is correct for a taxpayer electing farm income averaging?nn1. TP A files Schedule J (Form 1040) with his or her timely filed tax return for the year.n2. TP B can use farm income averaging on an amended return that is filed within 3 years from the date the original return is filed or within 3 years from the date the tax is paid, whichever is earlier.n3. TP C files Schedule J (Form 1040) with his or her filed tax return during the extension period for the year.','[\"TP A and TP B\",\"TP A and TP C\",\"TP B and TP C\",\"TP A, TP B, and TP C\"]',1,'Publication 225, page 19, states, in part, that a taxpayer can use farm income averaging by filing Schedule J (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) with his or her timely filed (including extensions) return for the year. In addition, the taxpayer can use farm income averaging on a late return, or use, change, or cancel it on an amended return, if the time for filing a claim for refund has not expired for that election year.nnThe taxpayer generally must file the claim for refund within 3 years from the date the original return is filed or 2 years (not 3 years as given in the TP B situation) from the date the tax is paid, whichever is later.nnTherefore, TP A and TP C are able to use farm income averaging, but TP B cannot.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1147,4,'Farmer Bob sold a breeding cow on March 8, 2024, for $2,500. Expenses related to the sale were $250. Farmer Bob deducted $1,000 in costs of raising the cow during the years the cow was raised. What is Farmer Bob\'s gain (or loss) on the sale of the breeding cow, without regard to the uniform capitalization rules?','[\"$(350)\",\"$1,150\",\"$2,250\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 225, pages 10–11, provides the general rules for sales of business property for farmers. To begin with, income from farming reported on Schedule F (Form 1040) includes amounts received by the taxpayer from cultivating, operating, or managing a farm for gain or profit, either as owner or tenant. This includes income from operating a stock, dairy, poultry, fish, fruit, or truck farm and income from operating a plantation, ranch, range, or orchard. It also includes income from the sale of crop shares if the farmer materially participates in producing the crop.nnNote: Income received from operating a nursery, which specializes in growing ornamental plants, is considered to be income from farming.nnIncome reported on Schedule F does not include gains or losses from sales or other dispositions of the following farm assets: land, depreciable farm equipment, buildings and structures, and livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes.nnSales of livestock held for draft, breeding, sport, or dairy purposes may result in ordinary or capital gains or losses, depending on the circumstances. In either case, a taxpayer should always report these sales on Form 4797 instead of Schedule F.nnIn this problem, the farmer sold a breeding cow, which would fall under the category of income that is not reported on Schedule F but rather on Form 4797. The amount to be reported is $2,250, which is the difference between the selling price of $2,500 and the expenses related to the sale of $250. Apparently, the cow had no adjusted basis to account for. If there had been an adjusted basis, it would have been subtracted from the selling price.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1148,4,'Qualified farmers have which of the following choices to file their tax return without incurring any penalties?','[\"File and pay 100% of the tax due by March 1 each year.\",\"File one estimated payment for 2\\/3rds of the tax by January 15 and file and pay the balance by April 15.\",\"File and pay the tax due by April 15 each year.\",\"File and pay 100% of the tax due by March 1 each year\\u00a0or\\u00a0file one estimated payment for 2\\/3rds of the tax by January 15 and file and pay the balance by April 15.\"]',3,'Publication 225, page 89, provides the rules for the due dates for qualified farmers. First, if at least 2/3rds of the farmer\'s gross income for 2023 or 2024 was from farming, the farmer is a qualified farmer for 2024.nnSecond, special rules for qualified farmers provide that they can choose either of the following options for their 2024 tax and not be penalized for failure to pay estimated tax if they:nnfile 2024 tax return and pay all of the tax due by March 1, 2025,nhad 2024 income tax withholding (including any amount applied to their 2024 estimated tax from their 2024 return) of at least 66-2/3% of the total tax shown on their 2023 tax return or 100% of the total tax shown on their 2024 return, or nmake only one estimated tax (their required annual payment) by January 15, 2025, using special rules to figure the amount of the payment.nThe required annual payment mentioned in the last option is the smaller of the following amounts:nn66.67% (.6667) of their total tax for 2024, orn100% of the total tax shown on their 2023 return (the return must cover all 12 months).nThus, there are two correct responses in this problem as shown in Figure 15-1 of Publication 225 (page 89): file and pay 100% of the tax due by March 1 each year; or file one estimated payment for 2/3rds of the tax by January 15, and file and pay the balance by April 15.nnThus, the best response is the one containing two correct responses and not the single correct responses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1149,4,'The receipt of agricultural program payments by a farmer for refraining from growing crops should be reported as:','[\"miscellaneous income on Form 1040.\",\"farm income, not subject to self-employment tax.\",\"rental income, not subject to self-employment tax.\",\"farm income, subject to self-employment tax.\"]',3,'Publication 225, page 13, provides that a farmer must include in income most government payments, such as those for approved conservation practices, livestock indemnity payments, or livestock forage disaster payments whether received in cash, materials, services, or commodity certificates. However, the farmer can exclude from income some payments received under certain cost-sharing conservation programs.nnAgricultural program payments, for example, are included in farming income on Schedule F, Part I (Form 1040), which is carried forward to the self-employment tax calculation.nnHence, the correct response to this question is the receipt of agricultural program payments by a farmer for refraining from growing crops should be reported as farm income that is subject to self-employment tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1150,4,'When is Form 990 for a tax-exempt organization that is a calendar year taxpayer required to be filed?','[\"By March 15 following the end of its tax year\",\"By April 15 following the end of its tax year\",\"By May 15 following the end of its tax year\",\"By October 15 following the end of its tax year\"]',2,'The due date for Form 990, 990-EZ, or 990-PF is the 15th day of the 5th month after the end of the organization\'s accounting period. For example, for a calendar year taxpayer, Form 990, 990-EZ, or 990-PF is due May 15 of the following year, as given in Publication 557, page 12. If any date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the return will be due the next business day.nnThus, the form must be filed by May 15 following the end of its tax year. Also, an organization can apply for an automatic 6-month extension by filing Form 8868 (prior to 2017, it was an automatic 3-month extension).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1151,4,'An organization may qualify as an organization described under Section 501(c)(3) if it is organized and operated exclusively for which of the following purposes?','[\"Charitable\",\"Business\",\"Political action\",\"Personal\"]',0,'Section 501 (c)3 describes organizations set up and operated exclusively for religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary or educational purposes, or to foster national or international amateur sports competition, or for the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnThe correct answer is charitable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1152,4,'Form 990-EZ is a shortened version of Form 990. It is designed for use by small exempt organizations and nonexempt charitable trusts. Which of the following requirements must an organization meet so that it may file Form 990-EZ instead of Form 990?','[\"Its gross receipts during the year were less than $200,000 and its total assets at the end of the year were less than $500,000.\",\"Its gross receipts during the year were less than $100,000 and its total assets at the end of the year were less than $250,000.\",\"Its gross receipts during the year were less than $100,000 and its total assets at the end of the year were less than $500,000.\",\"Its gross receipts during the year were less than $200,000 and its total assets at the end of the year were less than $250,000.\"]',0,'Form 990-EZ is a shortened version of Form 990. It is designed for use by small exempt organizations and nonexempt charitable trusts.nnAn organization may file Form 990-EZ, instead of Form 990, if it meets both of the following requirements:nnIts gross receipts during the year are less than $200,000nIts total assets at the end of the year are less than $500,000nIf an organization does not satisfy both conditions, it cannot file Form 990-EZ. Instead, the organization must file Form 990.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1153,4,'Of the organizations listed below, which could not receive approval for tax-exempt status under Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(3)?','[\"A local chapter of the Red Cross\",\"A partnership for scientific research\",\"A college alumni association\",\"A local boys\' or girls\' club\"]',1,'Publication 557, page 22, provides, in part, that an organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more of the following purposes: religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary, educational, fostering national or international amateur sports competition (but only if none of its activities involve providing athletic facilities or equipment), and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnTo qualify, the organization must be a corporation (including a limited liability company), unincorporated association, or trust. A trust is a fund or foundation and will qualify. However, an individual or a partnership will not qualify.nnExamples of qualifying organizations include nonprofit old-age homes, parent-teacher associations, charitable hospitals or other charitable organizations, alumni associations, schools, chapters of the Red Cross, Boys\' or Girls\' Clubs, and churches. (Publication 557, page 22)nnHence, a partnership for scientific research would not qualify under IRC Section 501(c)(3).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1154,4,'Which of the following organizations may request exempt status under the Internal Revenue Code as charitable organizations?','[\"A religious organization\",\"A school\",\"An animal welfare organization\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 557, page 22, provides that an organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more of the following purposes: religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary, educational, fostering national or international amateur sports competition (but only if none of its activities involve providing athletic facilities or equipment), and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnHence, all the organizations that are listed in this problem qualify for exempt status.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1155,4,'Which of the following types of organizations will not be recognized as exempt from federal income tax?','[\"Civic associations\",\"Volunteer fire companies\",\"Social and recreation clubs\",\"All of the organizations listed would qualify.\"]',3,'nPublication 557, pages 48–49, states that if a taxpayer\'s organization is not organized for profit and will be operated primarily to promote social welfare to benefit the community, it may qualify for exemption under section 501(c)(4). Under this section, the taxpayer must use Form 8976 (Notice of Intent to Operate Under Section 501(c)(4)) to provide notice to the IRS within 60 days of its establishment.nnIn addition, the taxpayer may apply for recognition of exemption from federal income tax under Section 501(c)(4) by filing Form 1024-A (Application for Recognition of Exemption Under Section 501(c)(4)). Types of organizations that are considered to be social welfare organizations are civic associations and volunteer fire companies.nnTo qualify for exemption under Section 501(c)(4), no part of the organization\'s net earnings can inure to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual. If the organization provides an excess benefit to certain persons, an excise tax may be imposed.nnA local association of employees (501(c)(4)) whose membership is limited to employees of a designated person or persons in a particular municipality, and whose income will be devoted exclusively to charitable, educational, or recreational purposes. (Publication 557, page 52)nnHence, all the organizations listed may apply for exempt status.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1156,4,'Which return might a tax-exempt organization be required to file?','[\"Employment tax returns\",\"Annual information return, Form 990\",\"Report of cash received\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Most exempt organizations (including private foundations) must file various returns and reports at some time during (or following the close of) their accounting period (Publication 557, page 10).nnEvery employer, including an organization exempt from federal income tax, who pays wages to employees is responsible for withholding, depositing, paying, and reporting federal income tax, Social Security and Medicare (FICA) taxes, and federal unemployment tax (FUTA), unless that employer is specifically excepted by law from those requirements or if the taxes clearly do not apply (Publication 557, page 13).nnIn addition, every organization exempt from federal income tax under Section 501(a) must file an annual exempt organization return, with a few exceptions. (See Publication 557, page 11, for a list of these exceptions.) Similarly, exempt organizations, other than private foundations, must file their annual information returns on Form 990 or Form 990-EZ unless excepted from filing or allowed to submit Form 990-N (Publication 557, page 11).nnFinally, an exempt organization that receives, in the course of its activities, more than $10,000 cash in one transaction (or two or more related transactions) that is not a charitable contribution, must report the transaction to the IRS on Form 8300, Report of Cash Payments Over $10,000 Received in a Trade or Business. (Publication 557, page 18)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1157,4,'An organization may not qualify for exemption from federal income tax under Internal Revenue Code Section 501 if it is organized and operated exclusively as a:','[\"parent-teacher association.\",\"alumni association.\",\"political action committee.\",\"chapter of the Red Cross.\"]',2,'Publication 557, page 22, provides that an organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more of the following purposes: religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary, educational, fostering national or international amateur sports competition (but only if none of its activities involve providing athletic facilities or equipment), and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnExamples of qualifying organizations listed in Publication 557 (page 22) include churches, parent-teacher associations, charitable hospitals or other charitable organizations, alumni associations, chapters of the Red Cross, nonprofit old age homes, Boys\' and Girls\' Clubs, and schools.nnHence, a political action committee is not one of the purposes covered for exemption from federal income tax.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1158,4,'An exempt organization that is required to report unrelated business income must make installment payments of estimated tax if its estimated tax (tax minus allowable credits) is expected to be:','[\"$500 or more.\",\"$1,000 or more.\",\"$1,500 or more.\",\"$2,500 or more.\"]',0,'Pursuant to page 15 of the instructions for Form 990, Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax, and page 3 of the instructions for Form 990-T, Exempt Organization Business Income Tax Return, all tax-exempt organizations must make installment payments of estimated tax if its estimated tax (tax minus allowable credits) is expected to be $500 or more.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1159,4,'Which form is filed to apply for exemption status under IRC Section 501(c)(3)?','[\"Form 1023\",\"Form 1024\",\"Form 8718\",\"A letter to the IRS, no specific form\"]',0,'Most organizations seeking recognition of exemption from federal income tax must use a specific application form prescribed by the IRS in Rev. Proc. 2019-5. For example, Publication 557, pages, 3–4 provides:nnForm 1023 should be filed to apply for recognition of exemption from federal income tax under IRC Section 501(c)(3).nIf an organization is applying for recognition of exemption under IRC Section 501(a), Form 1024 should be filed.nAlso, new Form 1024-A is filed to apply for recognition of exemption from federal income tax under IRC Section 501(c)(4).nForm 8718 is the user fee for exempt organization determination letter request; it is not a determination letter application.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1160,4,'When is a tax-exempt organization required to file Form 990?','[\"By the 15th day of the 3rd month following the end of its tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 4th month following the end of its tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 5th month following the end of its tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 6th month following the end of its tax year\"]',2,'The due date for Form 990, 990-EZ, or 990-PF is the 15th day of the 5th month after the end of the organization\'s accounting period. For example, for a calendar year taxpayer, Form 990, 990-EZ, or 990-PF is due May 15 of the following year as given in Publication 557, page 12.nnThus, the form must be filed by the 15th day of the 5th month following the end of its tax year.nnNote: Beginning in 2017, an automatic 6-month extension of time to file these forms is available by filing Form 8868. No signature or explanation is needed for the automatic 6-month extension (see the instructions for Form 8868).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1161,4,'An organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more qualified purposes. Which of the following purposes is qualified?','[\"Testing for public safety\",\"Religious\",\"Fostering national or international amateur sports competition\",\"All of the responses are qualified purposes.\"]',3,'Publication 557, page 22, provides that an organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more of the following purposes: religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary, educational, fostering national or international amateur sports competition (but only if none of its activities involve providing athletic facilities or equipment), and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnHence, all of the purposes listed would qualify an organization.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1162,4,'An organization may not qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for which of the following purposes?','[\"Charitable, religious, educational, scientific, or literary\",\"Testing for public safety\",\"Amateur sports competition, providing athletic equipment\",\"All of the listed purposes qualify.\"]',2,'Publication 557, page 22, provides that an organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more of the following purposes: religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary, educational, fostering national or international amateur sports competition (but only if none of its activities involve providing athletic facilities or equipment), and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnHence, the amateur sports competition qualifies, except if it is providing athletic facilities or equipment.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1163,4,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"If an exempt organization\\u2019s gross receipts are normally $50,000 or less, it must file Form 990-N.\",\"Political organizations are not required to file Form 990-N.\",\"Form 990 is filed by the 15th day of the 5th month after the organization\\u2019s accounting period ends.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'If an exempt organization’s gross receipts are normally $50,000 or less, it must submit Form 990-N, Electronic Notice (e-Postcard) for Tax-Exempt Organizations Not Required to File Form 990 or 990-EZ, unless the organization chooses not to file Form 990 or 990-EZ. (Instructions for Form 990, page 3)nnA tax-exempt political organization must file Form 990 or 990-EZ if it had $25,000 or more in gross receipts during its tax year, even if its gross receipts are normally $50,000 or less, unless it meets one of the exceptions. (Instructions for Form 990, page 3)nnA qualified state or local political organization must file Form 990 or 990-EZ only if it has gross receipts of $100,000 or more. (Instructions for Form 990, page 3)nnAs stated above, political organizations are required to file Form 990 or 990-EZ if it had $25,000 or more in gross receipts during its tax year, unless it meets one of the exceptions for certain political organizations under Section B; they are not required to submit Form 990-N.nnForm 990 is required to be filed by the 15th day of the 5th month after the organization’s accounting period ends. This is true for all Form 990s. (Instructions for Form 990, page 6)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1164,4,'When must an exempt organization (other than an employee trust) that is required to report unrelated business income file Form 990-T?','[\"By the 15th day of the 3rd month after the close of the organization\'s tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 4th month after the close of the organization\'s tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 5th month after the close of the organization\'s tax year\",\"By the 15th day of the 6th month after the close of the organization\'s tax year\"]',2,'Pursuant to page 3 of the instructions for Form 990-T, an employees\' trust defined in IRC Section 401(a), an IRA (including SEPs and SIMPLEs), a Roth IRA, a Coverdell ESA, or an Archer MSA must file Form 990-T by the 15th day of the 4th month after the end of its tax year. All other organizations must file Form 990-T by the 15th day of the 5th month after the end of their tax year.nnIn the case where the regular due date falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, the organization may file the form on the next business day. If the return is filed late, interest and penalties may apply.nnCorporations may request an automatic 6-month extension of time to file Form 990-T by using Form 8868, Application for Extension of Time to File an Exempt Organization Return.nnTrusts may request an automatic 6-month extension of time to file by using Form 8868.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1165,4,'An organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more qualified purposes. Which of the following purposes is qualified?','[\"Charitable\",\"Religious\",\"Educational\",\"All of the responses are qualified purposes.\"]',3,'Publication 557, page 22, provides that an organization may qualify for exemption from federal income tax if it is organized and operated exclusively for one or more of the following purposes: religious, charitable, scientific, testing for public safety, literary, educational, fostering national or international amateur sports competition (but only if none of its activities involve providing athletic facilities or equipment), and the prevention of cruelty to children or animals.nnTo qualify, the organization must be a corporation (including a limited liability company), unincorporated association, or trust. Sole proprietorships, partnerships, individuals, or loosely associated groups of individuals will not qualify. Examples of qualifying organizations include nonprofit old-age homes, parent-teacher associations, charitable hospitals or other charitable organizations, alumni associations, schools, chapters of the Red Cross, Boys’ or Girls’ Clubs, and churches.nnHence, all of the purposes listed would qualify an organization.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1166,4,'Which of the following statements concerning contributions by business entities to their employees\' retirement accounts is correct?','[\"Sole proprietors deduct them on Schedule C.\",\"Partnerships deduct them on Form 1065.\",\"Corporations deduct them on Form 1120 or Form 1120-S.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 560, page 16, addresses the issue of where to deduct contributions. In general, a taxpayer deducts the contributions made by the taxpayer for common-law employees on the taxpayer\'s tax return. That is to say:nnsole proprietors deduct them on Schedule C (Form 1040 or 1040-SR), or Schedule F (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) in the case of farming,npartnerships deduct them on Form 1065, andncorporations deduct them on Form 1120 or Form 1120-S.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1167,4,'What tax credit rate may an employer with less than 50 employees claim on the ordinary and necessary costs of starting a SEP, SIMPLE, or qualified pension plan?','[\"50% of the first $5,000 of costs\",\"25% of the first $1,000 of costs\",\"100% of costs up to $5,000\",\"50% of the first $1,000 of costs\"]',2,'Eligible employers may be able to claim a tax credit of up to $5,000, for three years, for the ordinary and necessary costs of starting a SEP, SIMPLE IRA, or qualified plan. A tax credit reduces the amount of taxes on a dollar-for-dollar basis.nnEligible employers must meet the following requirements:nnless than 100 or fewer employees who received at least $5,000 in compensation from you for the preceding yearnat least one plan participant who was a non-highly compensated employee, andnin the three years before the first year you\'re eligible for the credit, the employees were not substantially the same employees who received contributions or accrued benefits in another plan sponsored by you, a member of a controlled group that includes you, or a predecessor of either.nFor 2024, the credit is 100% of qualified startup costs paid or incurred during the tax year for up to 50 employees. The credit is 50% for employers with more than 50 employees. This question specifically mentions less than 50 employees.nnA taxpayer can choose to start claiming the credit in the tax year before the tax year in which the plan becomes effective if they qualify.nnTo claim the credit, Form 8881 must be filed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1168,4,'In December 2023, Gail worked for ABC Co. and participated in their retirement plan. On February 1, 2024, Gail was employed by XYZ Corp., which has a qualified retirement plan. On March 1, 2024, the ABC Co. plan administrator distributed to Gail her vested share of the plan. Gail was 42 years old at the time of distribution. What must Gail do in order to avoid paying taxes and penalties on her withdrawal?','[\"Deposit the plan funds in a personal savings account at a local bank\",\"Contribute the distribution to the XYZ Corp. plan within 60 days\",\"Give the plan funds to Gail\'s sister who is unemployed\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Distributions from a qualified plan minus a prorated part of any cost basis are subject to income tax in the year they are distributed. Since most recipients have no cost basis, a distribution is generally fully taxable. An exception is a distribution that is properly rolled over.nnIn general, and as discussed in Publication 560, page 29, a recipient of an eligible rollover distribution from a qualified plan can defer the tax on it by rolling it over into a traditional IRA or another eligible retirement plan. However, it may be subject to withholding.nnThus, Gail can avoid paying taxes and penalties if she contributes the distribution to the XYZ Corporation\'s plan within the 60-day rollover period. Of course, this assumes that the XYZ Corporation’s plan permits rollover contributions.nnGail will not avoid the early distribution penalty if she deposits the plan funds in a personal savings account at a local bank or gives the plan funds to her sister who is unemployed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1169,4,'Marie (age 24) is a sole proprietor. She has no employees but has established a 401(k) SIMPLE plan. Net profit on her Schedule C is $21,000. What is the maximum amount that Marie can make in 2024 as an elective deferral to her 401(k) SIMPLE?','[\"$15,500\",\"$16,000\",\"$18,000\",\"$19,500\"]',1,'Publication 560, page 10, addresses the salary reduction contributions limits. Salary reduction contributions (employee-chosen contributions or elective deferrals) that a taxpayer\'s employer can make on behalf of the employee under a SIMPLE plan are limited to $16,000 for 2024.nnAdditional elective deferrals can be contributed to a taxpayer\'s SIMPLE if the taxpayer reached age 50 by the end of 2024, and no other elective deferrals can be made for the taxpayer to the plan for the year because of limits or restrictions, such as the regular annual limit. The most that can be contributed in additional elective deferral to the SIMPLE is the lesser of $3,500 for 2024 or the taxpayer\'s compensation for the year reduced by other elective deferrals for the year.nnHence, Marie is under age 50 and therefore can make a deductible contribution of only $16,000 to her SIMPLE in year 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1170,4,'All of the following statements are correct, except:','[\"a qualified plan does not include a 401(k) plan.\",\"a defined contribution plan can be either a profit-sharing plan or a money purchase pension plan.\",\"a defined contribution plan provides an individual account for each participant in the plan.\",\"a defined contribution plan provides benefits to a participant largely based on the amount contributed to that participant\'s account.\"]',0,'Publication 560, page 18, states, in part, that a defined contribution plan provides an individual account for each participant in the plan. It provides benefits to a participant largely based on the amount contributed to that participant\'s account.nnA defined contribution plan can be either a profit-sharing plan OR a money purchase pension plan.nnAn employer\'s qualified plan (see Publication 560, page 24) can include a cash or deferred arrangement under which participants can choose to have the employer contribute part of their before-tax compensation to the plan rather than receive the compensation in cash. A plan with this type of arrangement is popularly known as a “401(k) plan.”',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1171,4,'The 2024 basic limit on elective deferrals in 401(k) plans (excluding SIMPLE plans) for participants under age 50 is:','[\"$30,000.\",\"$23,000.\",\"$22,500.\",\"$30,500.\"]',1,'nThere is a limit on the amount an employee can defer each year under 401(k) plans. The basic limit on elective deferrals is $23,000 for 2024. If, in conjunction with other plans, the deferral limit is exceeded, the difference is included in the employee\'s gross income.nnAdditionally, a 401(k) plan can permit participants who are age 50 or over at the end of the calendar year to also make catch-up contributions. The catch-up contribution limit for 2024 is $7,500, which would permit a participant that was 50 or older in 2024 the opportunity to contribute up to $30,500.nnTherefore, the basic limit on elective deferral in a 401(k) plan for participants under age 50 for 2024 is $23,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1172,4,'Amy, a self-employed consultant, contributes more to her profit-sharing plan than she can deduct for the year. Amy can carry over and deduct the excess in later years combined with her normal contributions. Her contribution in later years is limited to which of the following?','[\"15% of the participating employee compensation\",\"25% of the participating employee compensation\",\"100% of the participating employee compensation\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'For tax year 2024, a participant in a defined contribution plan, which includes a profit-sharing plan, is able to contribute the smaller of $69,000 for 2024 or 100% of the participant\'s compensation. A table providing the limits for most qualified plans is found on page 4 of Publication 560.nnIn Amy\'s case, she can contribute up to 100% of her compensation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1173,4,'For 2024, what is the maximum amount that can be contributed on your behalf, assuming that other requirements are met, to a SIMPLE plan if you are over 50 years old?','[\"$16,000\",\"$18,500\",\"$19,000\",\"$19,500\"]',3,'Publication 560, page 15, provides the limits for an employee\'s contribution to an employer\'s SIMPLE plan. The amount the employee chooses to have contributed to a SIMPLE IRA on his or her behalf cannot be more than $16,000 for 2024.nnA SIMPLE IRA plan can permit participants who are age 50 or over at the end of the calendar year to also make catch-up contributions. The catch-up contribution limit for $3,500 for 2024. Salary reduction contributions are not treated as catch-up contributions for 2024 until they exceed $16,000. However, the catch-up contribution a participant can make for a year cannot exceed the lesser of:nnthe catch-up contribution limit ornthe excess of the participant\'s compensation over the salary reduction contributions that are not catch-up contributions.nAs a result, the maximum amount that can be contributed on your behalf, assuming that other requirements are met, to a SIMPLE plan if you are over 50 years old is $19,500 for 2024, which is $16,000 for the basic contribution and $3,500 for the catch-up contribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1174,4,'Ira, your only employee, earned $280,000 in 2024. What is the maximum contribution that you can make to his SEP-IRA for the year?','[\"$70,000\",\"$23,000\",\"$69,000\",\"$66,000\"]',2,'Contributions a taxpayer makes for 2024 to a common-law employee\'s SEP-IRA cannot exceed the lesser of 25% of the employee\'s compensation ($70,000, which is 25% of $280,000) or $69,000. Compensation generally does not include the employee\'s contributions to the SEP (Publication 560, page 4).nnAs a result, the maximum contribution that can be made to Ira\'s SEP-IRA for 2024 is $69,000.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1175,4,'Which of the following correctly states the maximum allowable catch-up contribution for a participant age 50 or over for the year 2024?','[\"$7,500 for a 401(k) plan\",\"$3,000 for a SIMPLE plan\",\"$2,500 for a traditional IRA\",\"$4,500 for a Roth IRA\"]',0,'A 401(k) plan can permit participants who are age 50 or over at the end of the calendar year to also make catch-up contributions. The catch-up contribution limit is $7,500 for 2024.nnElective deferrals are not treated as catch-up contributions for 2024 until they exceed the $23,000 contribution limit for 2024. However, the catch-up contribution a participant can make for a year cannot exceed the lesser of:nnthe catch-up contribution limit ornthe excess of the participant\'s compensation over the elective deferrals that are not catch-up contributions.nFor 2024, the catch-up amount is $3,500 in the case of a SIMPLE 401(k) plan and a SIMPLE IRA plan (Publication 560, page 10) and $1,000 is added to the $7,000 limit for a total of $8,000 if a taxpayer is age 50 or older for either the traditional or Roth IRA (Publication 590-A, pages 9 and 39).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1176,4,'Jeff, age 30, began participating in a SIMPLE retirement account on January 1, 2022. He took an early distribution from the account on December 1, 2023. Which of the following penalty rates is he subject to on the early distribution?','[0,0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625,0.25,0.5]',2,'Publication 560, page 16, provides the basic rules that apply to an early distribution from a SIMPLE plan. In general, the additional tax on early distributions applies to SIMPLE IRAs as in the case of an IRA.nnIf a distribution, however, is an early distribution and occurs during the 2-year period following the date on which the taxpayer first participated in the employer\'s SIMPLE plan, the additional tax on early distributions is increased from 10% to 25%.nnIn Jeff\'s case, his distribution is within 2 years of first participating. Thus, he is subject to the 25% penalty.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1177,4,'On May 20, 2025, Michael prepared his 2024 calendar year tax return late and failed to file an extension. He reported $70,000 net profit from his first year in business (amount carried from Schedule C to line 12 of Form 1040). He wants to establish a money purchase qualified plan and contribute the maximum amount. He has no employees. The most Michael can contribute to his qualified plan for 2024 is:','[\"$0.\",\"$14,000.\",\"$66,000.\",\"$70,000.\"]',0,'There are two basic steps in setting up a qualified plan. First, an employer adopts a written plan. Then the employer invests the plan assets.nnThe employer is responsible for setting up and maintaining the plan. In general, there is a set-up deadline for qualified plans. To take a deduction for contributions for a tax year, a taxpayer\'s plan must be set up by the return due date, including extensions, of the year for which contributions will apply.nnIn this case, Michael has decided to set up his money purchase plan after the due date of the return and didn\'t file an extension. He is too late for a 2024 contribution. The correct response therefore is $0 for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1178,4,'Your qualified 401(k) plan can include what type of contribution arrangement?','[\"Cash\",\"Elective deferral\",\"Both of the answer choices are correct.\",\"Neither of the answer choices is correct.\"]',2,'Publication 560, page 24, states, in part, that a qualified 401(k) plan can include a cash or deferred arrangement under which participants can choose to have the employer contribute part of their before-tax compensation to the plan rather than receive the compensation in cash. A plan with this type of arrangement is popularly known as a “401(k) plan.”nnThus, in this problem, a qualified 401(k) plan can include contribution arrangements of cash or elective deferral.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1179,4,'Deb (age 35) is self-employed and has no other employees. Her net earnings are $12,500, after the deduction for one-half of self-employment tax, but before deducting any contributions she makes to her own SIMPLE. What is the most that can be contributed to Deb\'s SIMPLE for 2024 (employer and employee contributions)?','[\"$12,875\",\"$14,000\",\"$13,000\",\"$16,000\"]',2,'The general information about contributions to a SIMPLE plan can be found in Publication 560, page 13. To begin with, an employer is generally required to match each employee\'s salary reduction contributions on a dollar-for-dollar basis up to 4% of the employee\'s compensation. This requirement does not apply if the employer made nonelective contributions.nnNext, the amount that the employee chooses to have the employer contribute to a SIMPLE IRA on his or her behalf cannot be more than $16,000 for 2024. These contributions must be expressed as a percentage of the employee\'s compensation unless the employer permits the employee to express them as a specific dollar amount.nnFinally, a SIMPLE IRA plan can permit participants who are age 50 or over at the end of the calendar year to also make catch-up contributions. The catch-up contribution limit is $3,500 for 2024. Deb does not qualify to make a catch-up contribution since she is only 35 years of age.nnDeb, therefore, can contribute to her SIMPLE plan up to $13,000, which is $12,500 on her behalf as an employee and $500 (4% of $12,500) on her behalf as the employer.nnNote: Beginning in 2024, the elective deferral limit is increased to 110% of the applicable deferral limit for employers with no more than 25 employees with a minimum compensation of $5,000. Employers with more than 25 employees can elect the higher limit. This would increase the 3% election to 4%. These increased limits don’t apply if the employer had another qualified plan within the three years preceding the first year of the SIMPLE plan.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1180,4,'Which of the following is more than the allowable contribution amount to a self-employed retirement plan in 2024?','[\"Contribution of $15,000 to a self-employed individual\'s own defined contribution Keogh plan. The individual\'s net earnings from self-employment (on Schedule C) are $40,000.\",\"$18,000 to the SEP-IRA of an employee who earned $100,000 in 2024\",\"$17,000 contribution into a SIMPLE IRA by an employee who earns $30,000\",\"A contribution of $16,000 to an employee\'s account in a defined contribution plan. The employee earned $40,000.\"]',2,'Profit sharing plans are one type of Keogh plan that allows a business to contribute up to the lesser of 100% of the compensation or $69,000 for 2024. In this case, $15,000 would be required to be less than $40,000.nnFor 2024, a defined contribution plan\'s annual contributions and other additions (excluding earnings) to the account of a participant cannot exceed the lesser of 100% of the participant\'s compensation (i.e., $40,000 of net earnings) or $69,000 for 2024. In this case, $16,000 is less than $40,000. nnContributions a taxpayer makes for 2024 to a common-law employee\'s SEP-IRA cannot exceed the lesser of 25% of the employee\'s compensation (i.e., $25,000, which is 25% of $100,000) or $69,000. Compensation generally does not include the taxpayer\'s contributions to the SEP. In this case, $18,000 is less than $25,000.nnPublication 560, page 15, provides the limits for an employee\'s contribution to an employer\'s SIMPLE plan. The amount the employee chooses to have contributed to a SIMPLE IRA on his or her behalf cannot be more than $16,000 for 2024.nnAs a result, the $17,000 contribution to the SIMPLE plan by an employee who earns $30,000 is more than the allowable contribution amount of $16,000 for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1181,4,'Charles, a sole proprietor, contributes to his self-employed pension plan. Where will he take his deduction on his income tax return?','[\"Form 1040, Schedule C\",\"Form 1040, Schedule 1\",\"Form 1040, Schedule A\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 560, page 23, provides the general information on where to deduct contributions made to a qualified plan:nnIn the case of common-law employees, the contributions are deducted on the employer\'s tax return.nIn the case of sole proprietors, the contributions are deducted on Schedule C (Form 1040 or 1040-SR) or Schedule F (for farming).nIn the case of partnerships, the contributions are deducted on Form 1065 for employees but on Schedule 1 (Form 1040) for partners.nIn the case of a corporation, the contributions are deducted on Form 1120 or Form 1120-S.nSole proprietors and partners, however, deduct the contributions for themselves on line 15 of Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR).nnThus, Charles, a sole proprietor, would deduct his contributions to his self-employed plan on line 15 of Schedule 1.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1182,4,'In which of the following plans can a self-employed individual participate?','[\"Simplified employee pension (SEP) plan\",\"Savings incentive match plan for employees (SIMPLE plan)\",\"Both of the listed plans\",\"Neither of the listed plans\"]',2,'A self-employed individual can establish for oneself or one\'s employees any of the following plans: simplified employee pension (SEP), savings incentive match plan for employees (SIMPLE plan), or a qualified plan (including a Keogh or HR 10 plan).nnSEP, SIMPLE, and qualified plans offer a small business and their employees a tax favored way to save for retirement. The owner can deduct contributions made to the plan for his or her employees on line 19 of Schedule C. If the owner is a sole proprietor, he or she can deduct contributions made to the plan for him- or herself on line 15 of Schedule 1 (Form 1040 or 1040-SR). In addition, the owner can deduct trustees\' fees if contributions to the plan do not cover them.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1183,4,'Generally, the deadline to file Form 5500, Annual Return/Report of Employee Benefit Plan is the:','[\"fifteenth day of the fourth month after the end of the plan year.\",\"fifteenth day of the fifth month after the end of the plan year.\",\"fifteenth day of the seventh month after the end of the plan year.\",\"last day of the seventh month after the end of the plan year.\"]',3,'Form 5500 Instructions, page 2 provides that all pension benefit plans covered by ERISA must file an annual return/report except as provided in this section. The return/ report must be filed whether or not the plan is “tax-qualified,” benefits no longer accrue, contributions were not made this plan year, or contributions are no longer made. Pension benefit plans required to file include both defined benefit plans and defined contribution plans.nnAll required forms, schedules, statements, and attachments must be filed by the last day of the 7th calendar month after the end of the plan year (not to exceed 12 months in length) that began in 2024. If the plan year differs from the 2024 calendar year, fill in the fiscal year beginning and ending dates in the space provided. (Form 5500 Instructions, page 4)nnNote: Form 5500 and its instructions are found on the DOL website: https://www.dol.gov/agencies/ebsa/employers-and-advisers/plan-administration-and-compliance/reporting-and-filing/form-5500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1184,4,'Which of the following situations is ineligible for filing Form 5500-EZ by a taxpayer?','[\"Zachary owns a small business (not a partnership) for which he has established a Keogh plan for himself and one employee, who is unrelated to Zachary.\",\"Trevor owns a small business (not a partnership) for which he has established a Keogh plan for himself and his spouse.\",\"A business partnership establishes a plan that covers the three partners.\",\"Tiper is a sole proprietor with no employees; she has established a Keogh plan for herself.\"]',0,'As provided in Publication 560, page 32, a taxpayer may file Form 5500-EZ if the plan is a one-participant plan and had total assets of more than $250,000 at year-end. A one-participant plan is defined as one where:nnthe plan only covers the taxpayer (or the taxpayer and the taxpayer\'s spouse) and the taxpayer (or the taxpayer and the taxpayer\'s spouse) owns the entire business (the business may be incorporated or unincorporated), ornthe plan only covers one or more partners (or partner(s) and spouse(s)) in a business partnership.nA one-participant plan may not file an annual return on Form 5500. Every one-participant plan required to file an annual return must file either Form 5500-EZ or Form 5500-SF.nnSince Zachary\'s Keogh plan covers both an employee and himself, he cannot file Form 5500-EZ.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1185,4,'Which of the following statements is correct if you receive a distribution from your employer\'s qualified plan of any part of the balance of your nondeductible employee contributions and the earnings from them?','[\"You may roll over any part of the distribution.\",\"You may roll over only the contribution portion of the distribution.\",\"You may roll over only the earnings portion of the distribution.\",\"You must roll over the entire distribution or none of the distribution.\"]',0,'A distribution of the employee\'s nondeductible contributions (i.e., nontaxable amounts) may qualify as a rollover distribution to another qualified retirement plan or an IRC Section 403(b) plan, or to a traditional IRA. The transfer must be made either (1) through a direct (trustee-to-trustee) rollover to a defined contribution plan that separately accounts for the taxable and nontaxable parts of the rollover, or (2) through a rollover to a traditional IRA.nnHence, the correct response is that the taxpayer may roll over any part of the distribution.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1186,4,'Which of the following is a false statement?','[\"A plan participant must pay withholding tax on all amounts being directly rolled over to an eligible plan.\",\"A plan participant may choose to have an eligible rollover distribution transferred directly to a traditional IRA.\",\"A plan participant may choose to have any part or all of an eligible rollover distribution paid directly to another eligible retirement plan.\",\"If an eligible rollover distribution is paid to the plan participant, generally there will be tax withheld.\"]',0,'Publication 560, page 29, states that the recipient of an eligible rollover distribution from a qualified plan can defer the tax on it by rolling it over into a traditional IRA or another eligible retirement plan.nnHowever, it may be subject to withholdings. That is, if, during a year, a qualified plan pays to a participant one or more eligible rollover distributions that are reasonably expected to total $200 or more, the payor must withhold 20% of the taxable portion of each distribution for federal income tax.nnThe general exception to the above rule is if, instead of having the distribution paid to him or her, the participant chooses to have the plan pay it directly to an IRA or another eligible retirement plan (a direct rollover), no withholding is required.nnThe false statement in this problem is that to have a direct rollover, you must pay withholding tax on the amount being rolled over.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1187,4,'Carmine is a self-employed consultant with one employee, Devin, who earned $48,000 in 2024. Devin contributed the maximum amount to his SIMPLE 401(k) plan under which an employee can choose to make salary contributions of up to 15% of pay. Carmine made a 4% matching contribution. Which of the following correctly represents the amount that Carmine will deduct for compensation and benefits paid to Devin in 2024?','[\"$48,000 wages and $6,000 retirement plan contribution\",\"$48,000 wages\",\"$48,000 wages and $1,920 retirement plan contribution\",\"$48,000 wages and $1,440 retirement plan contribution\"]',2,'Compensation for employees is the total wages, tips, and other compensation from the employer subject to federal income tax withholding and the amounts paid for domestic service in a private home, local college club, or local chapter of a college fraternity or sorority. Compensation also includes the salary reduction contributions made under this plan, compensation deferred under an IRC Section 457 plan, and the employees\' elective deferrals under an IRC Section 401(k) plan, a SARSEP, or an IRC Section 403(b) annuity contract. See, for example, Publication 560, pages 8 and 9.nnAlthough the employee can choose to make contributions in an amount expressed as a percentage of the employee\'s compensation, the amount cannot exceed $16,000 for 2024. (Publication 560, page 15)nnAs a result, Carmine would deduct $48,000 wages and $1,920 (4% of $48,000) retirement plan contribution as compensation and benefits paid to Devin in 2024.nnNote: Beginning in 2024, the elective deferral limit is increased to 110% of the applicable deferral limit for employers with no more than 25 employees with a minimum compensation of $5,000. Employers with more than 25 employees can elect the higher limit. This would increase the 3% election to 4%. These increased limits don’t apply if the employer had another qualified plan within the three years preceding the first year of the SIMPLE plan.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1188,4,'Joe (single, age 51) wants to defer the maximum amount possible to his 401(k) plan. What is the amount of basic and catch-up contributions he may make for tax year 2024?','[\"$22,500\",\"$7,500\",\"$23,000\",\"$30,500\"]',3,'A 401(k) plan can permit participants who are age 50 or over at the end of the calendar year to also make catch-up contributions. The catch-up contribution limit for 2024 is $7,500.nnElective deferrals are not treated as catch-up contributions for 2024 until they exceed the $23,000 limit in 2024. The amount for age 50 or over for 2024 is $30,500. However, the catch-up contribution a participant can make for a year cannot exceed the lesser of:nnthe catch-up contribution limit ornthe excess of the participant\'s compensation over the elective deferrals that are not catch-up contributions.nTherefore, Joe\'s basic and catch-up contributions for 2024 are $23,000 and $7,500, for a total of $30,500.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1189,4,'Joaquin is a small business owner who maintains a SIMPLE plan for his employees:nnJan is a 42-year-old part-timer who has worked for Joaquin in this business since 2018. She works 15 hours per week. She earned $13,500 in 2024.nMalik is a 72-year-old seasonal worker who works from September through December. He has worked for Joaquin in this business since 2019 and earned $6,000 in 2024.nMonica is 21 years old and works 10 hours per week, all year. She has worked for Joaquin since June 2023 and earned $4,800 in 2024.nJoaquin\'s business had net taxable income in 2024 of $62,300. All employees and Joaquin are U.S. citizens and none of them are union members. Which of the individuals listed below can be excluded from coverage under the SIMPLE plan in 2024?','[\"Jan\",\"Malik\",\"Monica\",\"Joaquin\"]',2,'An employee must be allowed to participate in an employer\'s SIMPLE plan if the employee:nnreceived at least $5,000 in compensation from his or her employer during any 2 years prior to the current year, andnis reasonably expected to receive at least $5,000 in compensation during the calendar year for which contributions are made.nIn addition, the term “employee” includes a self-employed individual who received earned income.nnIn this problem, Monica has worked only 1 year and has compensation of $4,800, which is less than the threshold amount of $5,000. Hence, Joaquin can exclude Monica from participating in the SIMPLE plan.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1190,4,'Which of the following retirement plans does not have a salary reduction (elective deferral) component to it?','[\"Simplified employee pension plan (SEP)\",\"SIMPLE IRA plan\",\"SIMPLE 401(k) plan\",\"Qualified 401(k) plan\"]',0,'Publication 560 provides the general rules associated with retirement plans. On page 8, SEPs are discussed as a simplified method for a taxpayer to make contributions toward their own retirement and their employees\' retirement. Under a SEP, the taxpayer makes contributions directly to a traditional individual retirement account (called a SEP-IRA) set up for each eligible employee. There is no provision here for an employee to make salary reduction contributions.nnA SIMPLE plan can be set up by an employer who had 100 or fewer employees who received at least $5,000 in compensation from the employer for the preceding calendar year and who meets certain other requirements. Under a SIMPLE plan, employees can choose to make salary reduction contributions rather than receiving these amounts as part of their regular pay. In addition, the taxpayer will contribute matching or nonelective contributions. There are two types of SIMPLE plans: SIMPLE IRA and SIMPLE 401(k). (Publication 560, pages 13 through 15)nnFinally, page 24 discusses the basic provisions of a 401(k) plan where a taxpayer establishes a qualified plan that can include a cash or deferred arrangement under which participants can choose to have the employer contribute part of their before-tax compensation to the plan rather than receive the compensation in cash. A plan of this type of arrangement is popularly known as a \"401(k) plan.\" This contribution is called an “elective deferral” because participants choose (elect) to set aside the money, and they defer the tax on the money until it is distributed to them.nnHence, the SEP is the only retirement plan listed above that does not have a salary reduction (elective deferral) component to it.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1191,4,'The SIMPLE 401(k) plan is a qualified retirement plan. The SIMPLE is not subject to nondiscrimination and top-heavy rules if the plan meets all of the conditions, except:','[\"Under the plan, the employee may choose salary reduction contributions to a trust up to $16,000 for 2024.\",\"Participants age 50 and over can make a catch-up contribution up to $3,500 for 2024.\",\"Employers must make matching contributions of up to 4% of compensation for the year or nonelective contributions of 2% of compensation on behalf of each eligible employee who has at least $5,000 of compensation from his employer for the year.\",\"The employee\'s rights to any contributions are forfeitable.\"]',3,'A SIMPLE 401(k) plan is not subject to the nondiscrimination and top-heavy rules if the plan meets the conditions listed below:nnUnder the plan, an employee can choose to have his or her employer make salary reduction contributions for the year to a trust in an amount expressed as a percentage of the employee\'s compensation, but not more than $16,000 for 2024. If permitted under the plan, an employee who is age 50 or over can also make a catch-up contribution of up to $3,500 for 2024.nThe employer must make either matching contributions up to 4% of compensation for the year, or nonelective contributions of 2% of compensation on behalf of each eligible employee who has at least $5,000 of compensation for the year.nNo other contributions can be made to the trust.nNo contributions are made, and no benefits accrue, for services during the year under any other qualified retirement plan of the employer on behalf of any employee eligible to participate in the SIMPLE 401(k) plan.nThe employee\'s rights to any contributions are nonforfeitable (not forfeitable as given in this problem).nAdditionally, no more than $345,000 in 2024 of the employee\'s compensation can be considered in figuring salary reduction contributions, matching contributions, and nonelective contributions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1192,4,'All of the following are reporting requirements of a qualified retirement plan subject to ERISA except:','[\"submit Form 5500,\\u00a0Annual Return\\/Report of Employee Benefit Plan.\",\"information on certain contributions, conversions, and distributions to retirement plans reported on Form 8606.\",\"distributions from the plan are reported on Form 1099-R.\",\"participants must receive period statements of their retirement benefits.\"]',1,'Form 5500 Instructions, page 2, provides that all pension benefit plans covered by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) must file an annual return/report except as provided in this section. The return/report must be filed whether or not the plan is “tax-qualified,” benefits no longer accrue, contributions were not made this plan year, or contributions are no longer made. Pension benefit plans required to file include both defined benefit plans and defined contribution plans.nnForm 1099-R is filed for each person to whom a company made a designated distribution or are treated as having made a distribution of $10 or more from profit-sharing or retirement plans, any individual retirement arrangements (IRAs), annuities, pensions, insurance contracts, survivor income benefit plans, permanent and total disability payments under life insurance contracts, charitable gift annuities, etc. (Form 1099-R Instructions, page 1)nnThe DOL report and disclosure guide for employee benefit plans provide on page 2 that a summary annual report is required to participants and pension plan beneficiaries receiving benefits within 9 months after end of plan year or 2 months after due date for filing Form 5500.nnNote: Form 5500 and its instructions are found on the DOL website: https://www.dol.gov/agencies/ebsa/employers-and-advisers/plan-administration-and-compliance/reporting-and-filing/form-5500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1193,4,'Which of the following is not a disqualified person for purposes of determining whether a prohibited transaction has been entered into under the qualified retirement plan rules?','[\"A plan fiduciary who deposits contributions into his or her own account and uses the funds to pay personal business expenses\",\"A 70-year-old individual who receives a distribution of the full value of his retirement account from a plan established by a business that he owns\",\"A fiduciary that invests the plan\'s assets in FGH partnership. FGH deposits 10% of the plan\'s assets into the fiduciary\'s own account.\",\"An employee who provides services to the plan\"]',1,'Prohibited transactions are transactions between the plan and a disqualified person that are prohibited by law. If a taxpayer is a disqualified person who takes part in a prohibited transaction, the taxpayer must pay a tax. Prohibited transactions generally include the following transactions (Publication 560, page 31):nnA transfer of plan income or assets to, or use of them by or for the benefit of, a disqualified personnAny act of a fiduciary by which he or she deals with plan income or assets in his or her own interestnThe receipt of consideration by a fiduciary for his or her own account from any party dealing with the plan in a transaction that involves plan income or assetsnAny of the following acts between the plan and a disqualified person: selling, exchanging, or leasing property; lending money or extending credit; or furnishing goods, services, or facilitiesnA list of disqualified persons for determining prohibited transactions is found on page 31 of Publication 560. A partial listing of disqualified persons includes:nna fiduciary of the plan,na person providing services to the plan,nan employer, any of whose employees are covered by the plan, andnan employee organization, any of whose members are covered by the plan.nA prohibited transaction does not take place if the taxpayer is a disqualified person and receives any benefit to which the taxpayer is entitled as a plan participant or beneficiary. However, the benefit must be figured and paid under the same terms as for all other participants and beneficiaries.nnIn this case, the 70-year-old owner and plan participant would not be a disqualified person for determining whether a prohibited transaction has been entered into, because the owner is receiving the benefits that he or she is entitled to as the plan participant.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1194,4,'Lenore, who is 43 years old, opened a SIMPLE IRA on January 19, 2023. On September 22, 2024, she withdrew the entire $10,000 value of the account. The distribution does not meet any early withdrawal exceptions to the additional tax on early distributions. How much additional tax (penalty) is this distribution subject to?','[\"$600\",\"$1,000\",\"$1,500\",\"$2,500\"]',3,'Publication 560, page 16, states, in part, that distributions from a SIMPLE IRA are subject to IRA rules and generally are includible in income for the year received. Tax-free rollovers can be made from one SIMPLE IRA into another SIMPLE IRA.nnA rollover, however, from a SIMPLE IRA to a non-SIMPLE IRA can be made tax-free only after a 2-year participation in the SIMPLE IRA plan. Early withdrawals generally are subject to a 10% additional tax. However, the additional tax is increased to 25% if funds are withdrawn within 2 years of beginning participation.nnLenore has made an early withdrawal from the SIMPLE plan, and the withdrawal is made within the first 2 years. Hence, she incurs a 25% penalty on the taxable amount. The additional tax on the early distribution is $2,500 (25% of $10,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1195,4,'Mike is self-employed. He is a calendar year taxpayer. If he wants to set up a SIMPLE plan for his business for the year 2024, he must do so by (including extensions):','[\"December 31, 2023.\",\"January 31, 2024.\",\"April 15, 2024.\",\"October 1, 2024.\"]',3,'Publication 560, page 9, provides that a person can set up a SIMPLE IRA plan effective on any date from January 1 through October 1 of a year, provided the taxpayer did not previously maintain a SIMPLE IRA plan.nnThis requirement does not apply if the taxpayer is a new employer whose business comes into existence after October 1 of the year the SIMPLE IRA plan is set up and the taxpayer set up a SIMPLE IRA plan as soon as administratively feasible after the taxpayer\'s business came into existence.nnIf the taxpayer previously maintained a SIMPLE IRA plan, the taxpayer can set up a SIMPLE IRA plan effective only on January 1 of a year.nnA SIMPLE IRA plan cannot have an effective date that is before the date the plan is actually adopted.nnHence, Mike has until October 1, 2024, to set up the SIMPLE plan for his business.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1196,4,'John, a self-employed taxpayer, has a SEP plan for his business. He has three eligible employees, Sara (age 35), Joseph (age 37), and Jean (age 45), who have worked for him for the past 10 years. For the year 2024, Sara earned $21,000, Joseph earned $25,000, and Jean earned $30,000. John wants to elect the 25% contribution rate so he can put as much as possible in for himself. If he elects 25%, how much must he contribute to the plan for his employees?','[\"$0\",\"$18,000\",\"$19,000\",\"$38,000\"]',2,'Publication 560, page 8, provides that in the case of a SEP:nnthe maximum contribution that an employer can make is the smaller of $69,000 or 25% of the participant\'s compensation in 2024 andnthe maximum deduction that an employer can take is 25% of all participants\' compensation.nHence, if John elects the 25% contribution rate, he would contribute $19,000 to the plan for his employees. The $19,000 is 25% of $76,000, which is the employee\'s total compensation ($21,000 + $25,000 + $30,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1197,4,'Dr. Jay purchased an apartment building as an investment and the property is available to rent. The apartments are fully furnished. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"He can depreciate the purchase price of the apartment building.\",\"He can elect to deduct, as a Section 179 deduction, up to $500,000 of the portion of the cost allocable to the furnishings and depreciate the remaining amount.\",\"He can elect to deduct, as a Section 179 deduction, the purchase price of the apartment building.\",\"He must capitalize the purchase price of the apartment building.\"]',0,'As stated on page 6 of Publication 527, a taxpayer recovers the cost of income-producing property through yearly tax deductions, which is known as depreciating the property. The three basic factors that are needed to determine the depreciation amount are basis of property, recovery period for the property, and depreciation method selected.nnThe IRC Section 179 deduction is a means of recovering part or all of the cost of certain qualifying property in the year it is placed in service (Publication 527, page 6). Residential rental property is defined in Publication 527, page 9, as real property that is a rental building or structure (including a mobile home), if 80% or more of its annual gross rental income for the year is from dwelling units. Per Publication 946, page 16, residential rental property is not eligible property for purposes of Section 179 depreciation.nnNote: Residential rental property does not include a unit in a hotel, motel, inn, or other establishment where more than half of the units are used on a transient basis.nnThe capitalization response is incorrect because it assumes that the taxpayer capitalizes the cost of the property without claiming annual depreciation expense on the property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1198,4,'If an individual taxpayer’s passive losses in rental real estate cannot be used in the current year, then:','[\"the loss can be carried back 2 years but not carried forward.\",\"the loss can be carried forward 20 years.\",\"the loss can be carried forward indefinitely.\",\"the loss must be added back to the property\\u2019s basis.\"]',2,'Unless proven otherwise, rental real estate activities are defined as passive activities. In general, passive activity losses can only be used to offset passive activity gains. If the losses cannot be used by passive activity gains, these losses can be carried forward indefinitely or until the property is disposed of in a taxable transaction.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1199,4,'Barkley owns a vacation cabin that was rented to unrelated parties for 10 days during the year for $2,500. The cabin was used personally by Barkley for three months and left vacant for the rest of the year. Expenses for the cabin were as follows:nn   Real estate taxes             $1,000n   Maintenance and utilities      2,000nHow much rental income (loss) is included in Barkley\'s adjusted gross income?','[\"$0\",\"$500\",\"$(500)\",\"$(1,500)\"]',0,'When a personal residence is rented out for under 15 days during a taxable year, none of the rental income is included in income, nor are any rental deductions allowed for the rental use of the residence. Real estate taxes and home mortgage interest, if any, could still be used as itemized deductions if the taxpayer can benefit from itemizing.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1200,4,'Cory owns an apartment building. In addition to providing the utilities for his tenants, he also cleans the halls and utility room and picks up the trash. On what tax form must Cory report the rentals if he is not a real estate professional?','[\"Form 1040 as other income\",\"Schedule C,\\u00a0Profit or Loss From Business\",\"Schedule E,\\u00a0Supplemental Income and Loss\",\"None of the rent payments are taxable.\"]',2,'If a taxpayer rents a building, room, or an apartment and provides limited additional services, such as heat, light, and trash collection, etc., the rental income and expenses of renting such property would be reported on Schedule E.nnOn the other hand, if a taxpayer provides significant services that are predominantly for the convenience of the tenant, such as regular cleaning, changing of linen, and maid service, the rental income and expenses would be reported on Schedule C.nnGiven that Cory, who rents his apartment building out, also provides limited services such as the utilities, cleaning of the halls and utility room, and picking up trash, he may report the rental income and expenses on a Schedule E. Cory is not required to file Schedule C, Profit or Loss From Business, because he does not provide significant services that are primarily for the convenience of the tenants.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1201,4,'John and Mary had a pipe burst in the basement of your rental home. They were unable to reach you on vacation. They had the plumber come out and repair the pipe and damage. They paid the plumber $575. They deducted $575 from their rent of $5,000. How much rent should be considered income that month?','[\"$5,000\",\"$4,425\",\"$5,575\",\"$5,745\"]',0,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in Publication 527, Residential Rental Property (Including Rental of Vacation Homes). In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property.nnIf a tenant pays any of the rental property expenses, the payments are treated as rental income by the property owner and may be deducted as an expense by the property owner if they are deductible rental expenses. (See pages 3–4 of Publication 527.)nnIn this problem, the taxpayer includes the $5,000 ($4,425 actual rent payment and $575 to repair the pipes).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1202,4,'Smith (single filing status) has an adjusted gross income (AGI) of $120,000 without taking into consideration $40,000 of losses from rental real estate activities. Smith actively participates in the rental real estate activities. What amount of the rental losses may Smith deduct in determining taxable income?','[\"$0\",\"$15,000\",\"$20,000\",\"$40,000\"]',1,'Individuals (and married taxpayers filing jointly) may offset up to $25,000 of ordinary income with losses from rental real estate activities. This exemption is reduced (but not below zero) by 50% of the amount by which the adjusted gross income (AGI) of the taxpayer for the year exceeds $100,000. (Note that married taxpayers filing separately may each offset $12,500, reduced (but not below zero) by 50% of the amount by which the AGI of each taxpayer exceeds $50,000.)nnTherefore, $25,000 − (($120,000 − $100,000) × 0.50) = $15,000 deduction allowed.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1203,4,'Mary From, single, owned rental real estate which generated a tax loss of $60,000. Mary materially participated in the rental activity. Mary\'s adjusted gross income before considering the $60,000 loss was $130,000. What amount of the loss can offset income from nonpassive sources?','[\"$15,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$0\",\"$60,000\"]',1,'Rental activities are considered passive activities even if the taxpayer materially participates. However, for rental real estate activities, a loss up to $25,000 may be deducted. However, the $25,000 loss must be reduced by half of the adjusted gross income (before the loss) in excess of $100,000. Thus, the deduction is $10,000 ($25,000 − (0.50 × $30,000)).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1204,4,'Which of the following is not rental income in the year received?','[\"Security deposit, equal to 1 month\'s rent, to be refunded at the end of the lease if the building passes inspection\",\"Payment to cancel the remaining lease\",\"Repairs paid by the tenant in lieu of rent\",\"January 2024 rent received December 2023\"]',0,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in general on pages 2 and 3 of Publication 527. In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts that are received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. Similarly, any amounts received from a tenant to cancel a lease are treated as rent and therefore are included in income.nnIn addition to amounts received as normal rent payments, there are other amounts that may be rental income and as such are included in rental income. Advance rent, for example, is any amount received before the period that it covers. These payments are included in rental income in the year received regardless of the period covered or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using.nnIf a tenant pays any of the taxpayer\'s expenses, the payments are rental income and therefore are included in income.nnSecurity deposits, on the other hand, are not included in rental income when it is received if the amount is to be returned to the tenant at the end of the lease. If the taxpayer keeps part or all of the security deposit during any year because the tenant does not live up to the terms of the lease, the amount retained becomes income for that year.nnIf an amount called a security deposit is to be used as a final payment of rent, it is advance rent, and as such, it is included as rental income in the year that it is received.nnIn this problem, all the items listed are included as rental income with one exception. That is, the taxpayer does not include the security deposit because it is to be refunded at the end of the lease if the property passes final inspection, and therefore, it is not an advanced rent payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1205,4,'Tom Lewis, a single taxpayer, received $8,400 in gross receipts from his rental property. The expenses for the residential rental property were:nn   Bank mortgage interest      $1,200n   Real estate taxes              700n   Insurance                      500n   MACRS depreciation           3,500nTom\'s total income on his individual tax return will be increased by what amount as a result of the rental activities?','[\"$8,400\",\"$7,200\",\"$6,500\",\"$2,500\"]',3,'Rental income is included in gross income by individuals and the expenses used to generate the rental income are deductible by the individual as rental expenses. For this question, all the expense items shown are deductible rental expenses. Tom\'s net rental income is calculated as follows:nn    Gross Receipts           $8,400n    less:n      mortgage interest      (1,200)n      real estate taxes        (700)n      insurance                (500)n      depreciation           (3,500)n   Net Rental Income         $2,500',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1206,4,'Taxpayers who actively participate in the rental of residential real estate may deduct losses to arrive at AGI up to an annual limit of:','[\"$10,000.\",\"$15,000.\",\"$25,000.\",\"$50,000.\"]',2,'Rental losses of up to $25,000 annually may be deducted to arrive at AGI of the individuals who own at least 10% of the property.nnThe deductions for losses begin to phase out at modified AGI of $100,000 for single or married, filling jointly taxpayers, and are completely phased out when modified AGI is $150,000. The phaseout begins at $50,000 for taxpayers filing separate returns and is completely phased out once modified AGI reaches $75,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1207,4,'How are repainting and fixing leaks in a rental property treated if they are part of an extensive remodeling of the property?','[\"The costs of repainting and fixing leaks are\\u00a0not\\u00a0currently deductible as repairs.\",\"The cost of repainting, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0the cost of fixing leaks, is currently deductible as repairs.\",\"The cost of fixing leaks, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0the cost of repainting, is currently deductible as repairs.\",\"The costs of repainting and fixing leaks are currently deductible as repairs.\"]',0,'In 2013, the IRS issued TD 9636 (Tangible Property Final Regulations), applicable to tax year beginning on or after January 1, 2014 which finalized the guidance on Sections 162(a) and 263(a).nnThe “plan of rehabilitation” doctrine provided that a taxpayer must capitalize otherwise deductible repair or maintenance costs if they were incurred as part of a general rehabilitation, modernization and improvement to property (Moss v. Commissioner, United States v. Wehrli). The 2011 temporary regulations provided that a taxpayer must capitalize both the direct costs of an improvement as well as the indirect costs that directly benefit or are incurred by reason of improvement. The exception to this provision allowed a taxpayer to capitalize repair and maintenance costs incurred with connection with a personal residence if the costs were incurred at the time of a substantial residential remodel. The final regulations retain the rules from the 2011 temporary regulations and continue to provide that indirect costs, such as repair and maintenance costs, that do not directly benefit and that are not incurred by reason of an improvement are not required to be capitalized under section 263(a), regardless of whether they are incurred at the same time as an improvement.nnSince these expenses are direct costs intended to restore the property (i.e., repainting and fixing existing leaks), the expenses cannot be treated as repairs but rather as capital improvements, per the above.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1208,4,'The term “active participation” for a passive activity loss is relevant in relation to:','[\"rental real estate activities.\",\"working interests in oil and gas properties.\",\"passive activities in which the taxpayer materially participates.\",\"passive activities in which the taxpayer does not materially participate.\"]',0,'In general, passive activity losses in excess of passive activity income are not allowed. There is an exception to the rule for rental real estate activities; if an individual actively participated in a rental real estate activity, they may be able to deduct up to $25,000 of passive activity loss from nonpassive income. Participation in management decisions such as new tenant approval, rental terms, repairs, and capital expenditures is sufficient to meet the “active participation” definition.nnThe passive activity rules apply to individuals, estates, trusts, personal service corporations, and closely held C corporations. The passive activity loss rules do not apply to partnerships, widely held C corporations, or S corporations.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1209,4,'During a major sports event, a taxpayer rented his primary residence to spectators for 10 days. The taxpayer\'s rental income and expenses were as follows:nn   Rental income                  $10,000n   Prorated mortgage and taxes      1,000n   Advertising                        500n   Commissions                      1,000nHow much net rental income must the taxpayer report on the tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$7,500\",\"$8,500\",\"$1,000\"]',0,'Generally, rental income must be reported as rental income by the taxpayer. However, when a personal residence is rented out for less than 15 days, no rental income is recognized and expenses are also not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1210,4,'Adams owns a second residence that is used for both personal and rental purposes. During Year 1, Adams used the second residence for 50 days and rented the residence for 200 days. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Depreciation may not be deducted on the property under any circumstances.\",\"A rental loss may be deducted if rental-related expenses exceed rental income.\",\"Utilities and maintenance on the property must be divided between personal and rental use.\",\"All mortgage interest and taxes on the property will be deducted to determine the property\\u2019s net income or loss.\"]',2,'Since Adams made rental use of the property more than 14 days or 10% of the total rented days, he must allocate the total expenses between the rental use and personal use based on the number of days used for each purpose.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1211,4,'Adrienne purchased a beach house in the current year. She plans to spend a great deal of time there over the summer but has agreed to rent it out to some co-workers for a month. Should Adrienne include the income on her tax return and, if so, how much?','[\"Yes, all of it\",\"No, none of it is taxable\",\"All of the income less a prorated share of any mortgage interest and real estate taxes\",\"Only 1\\/12 of the income should be reported.\"]',2,'When a personal residence is rented out for more than 14 days, the income should be included as taxable but can be netted with the prorated share of mortgage interest, real estate taxes, and any other related expenses compared to the rental time period.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1212,4,'Ms. Cross owns a house that she rents to non-related parties. She incurred the following costs during the tax year:nn1. $400 to resurface a tub in the master bathroomn2. $500 to paint the kitchen after installing new cabinetsn3. $2,000 to replace cabinets in the kitchenn4. $600 to replace the built-in dishwashernHow should these costs be characterized and in what amounts?','[\"$3,100 as improvements to be capitalized and $400 as repairs\",\"$400 as improvements to be capitalized and $3,100 as repair\",\"$3,500 as improvements to be capitalized\",\"$2,000 as improvements to be capitalized and $1,500 as repairs\"]',0,'Publication 527, page 5, provides that a taxpayer can deduct the cost of repairs to the taxpayer\'s rental property. The taxpayer cannot deduct the cost of improvements; rather, the taxpayer recovers the cost of improvements by taking depreciation.nnA repair keeps the property in good operating condition. It does not materially add to the value of the property or substantially prolong its life. In general, an expense for repairing or maintaining rental property may be deducted if the expense is not required to be capitalized. Repainting the property inside or out, fixing gutters or floors, fixing leaks, plastering, and replacing broken windows are examples of repairs. (Publication 527, page 5)nnIf the taxpayer makes repairs as part of an extensive remodeling or restoration of your property, the whole job is an improvement. Expenses that may be for restoration include expenses for replacing a substantial structural part of your property, repairing damage to your property after you properly adjusted the basis of your property as a result of a casualty loss, or rebuilding your property to a like-new condition. In this case, the painting of the kitchen after installing new cabinets would qualify as an improvement. (Publication 527, pages 5–6)nnAn improvement, in general, adds to the value of property, prolongs its useful life, or adapts it to new uses. Table 1-1 on page 5 of Publication 527 shows examples of many improvements.nnIn this case, Ms. Cross has $3,100 in improvements, which is the sum of $500 for painting, $2,000 for the cabinets, and $600 for the dishwasher. The $400 is currently deductible as repairs for the tub.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1213,4,'Peter owned a cottage on the lake that he bought in 2023. In 2024, he rented the cottage for 10 days to a stranger and used the cottage for 20 days for his own personal use. The cottage was not used the rest of the year. Peter had rental income of $1,000 and he paid $600 for repairs. How should Peter report these activities on his 2024 return?','[\"$1,000 income, $600 expense\",\"$333 income, $200 expense\",\"$0 income, $0 expense\",\"$667 income, $400 expense\"]',2,'In general, a person must include in gross income all amounts received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. (Publication 527, pages 2–3)nnIf the taxpayer has any personal use of the dwelling unit (including vacation home) that is rented, the taxpayer must divide the total expenses between rental use and personal use. Also, the rental expense deductions may be limited. (Publication 527, pages 3–5)nnAre you ready for some good news? There is an exception for minimal rental use by the taxpayer. Specifically, if the taxpayer uses the dwelling unit as a home and it rented for fewer than 15 days during the year, none of the rent is included in income and none of the rental expenses are deductible. See page 19 in Publication 527 for more information on rental income and expense.nnPeter in this problem would include $0 in income and would have $0 in expenses since it was rented for less than 15 days.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1214,4,'You own a vacation home on Amelia Island, Florida, which you rented for 10 days in the calendar year. The rental expenses were $2,000 and rental income was $5,000. How much of the rental income should be reported on the tax return?','[\"$5,000\",\"$3,000\",\"$0\",\"$7,000\"]',2,'Generally, a person must include in gross income all amounts received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. If the taxpayer has any personal use of the dwelling unit (including vacation home) that is rented, the taxpayer must divide the total expenses between rental use and personal use.nnThere is an exception for minimal rental use by the taxpayer. Specifically, if the taxpayer uses the dwelling unit as a home and it is rented for fewer than 15 days during the year, none of the rent is included in income and none of the rental expenses are deductible. See page 19 in Publication 527 for more information on rental income and expense.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1215,4,'When reporting rental income, an individual taxpayer must use which accounting method?','[\"Cash basis\",\"Cash basis or accrual basis\",\"Accrual basis\",\"Hybrid\"]',1,'A taxpayer has the choice of accounting methods when reporting rental income. A cash-basis taxpayer can select accrual basis for their rental activities.nnThe one exception to this rule is prepaid rent. Regardless of which methodology chosen, prepaid rent must be recognized when received.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1216,4,'Owners of at least 10% of a residential rental unit who actively participate in the rental can deduct losses up to $25,000 a year. However, a phaseout of the deduction begins at $100,000 of adjusted gross income. The deduction of the rental loss is completely phased out at what level?','[\"$125,000\",\"$150,000\",\"$175,000\",\"$200,000\"]',1,'For every $2 of adjusted gross income (AGI) over the $100,000 level, one dollar of that real estate loss is phased out, so that at $150,000 in AGI, the full deduction is phased out.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1217,4,'Passive activity losses of an individual taxpayer can generally be used to offset:','[\"income from the rental of a residence.\",\"a guaranteed payment received from a partnership.\",\"dividends income from a foreign corporation.\",\"interest income on U.S. Treasury notes.\"]',0,'Generally, losses from passive activities may only be used to offset income from passive activities. Passive activities include the following:nnTrade or business in which the taxpayer does not materially participatenRental activitiesnLimited partnership activitynAccordingly, passive activity losses can generally be used to offset rental of a residence.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1218,4,'Ms. Winter owns an apartment complex. She received $5,000 in December 2024 to cover the January rents for tenants who will be on vacation January 15, 2025, when the rent is due. Although she is a cash basis taxpayer for purposes of filing her return, she uses the accrual method of accounting to maintain her books on the rental property. What amount should Ms. Winter report if she uses the accrual method of accounting?','[\"$0 in 2024 and $0 in 2025\",\"$0 in 2024 and $5,000 in 2025\",\"$5,000 in 2024 and $0 in 2025\",\"$5,000 in 2024 and $5,000 in 2025\"]',2,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in general in Publication 527. In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts that are received as rent. Rental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property.nnIn addition to amounts received as normal rent payments, there are other amounts that may be rental income and as such are included in rental income. Advance rent, for example, is any amount received before the period that it covers. These payments are included in rental income in the year received regardless of the period covered or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer includes the $5,000 of advance rent as rental income in the year received (i.e., 2024). It does not matter what period the payment is for or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using. (See Publication 527, pages 3–4.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1219,4,'Bearing is an individual taxpayer who uses the filing status of single. A review of Bearing\'s Year 2 records disclosed the following tax information:nn   Wages                                       $ 18,000n   Taxable interest and qualifying dividends      4,000n   Schedule C trucking business net income       32,000n   Rental (loss) from residential property      (35,000)n   Limited partnership (loss)                    (5,000)nBearing actively participated in the rental property and was a limited partner in the partnership. Bearing had sufficient amounts at risk for the rental property and the partnership. What is Bearing\'s Year 2 adjusted gross income?','[\"$14,000\",\"$19,000\",\"$29,000\",\"$54,000\"]',2,'Items included in AGI: Wages ($18,000) + Taxable interest and qualified dividends ($4,000) + Schedule C income from business ($32,000) − Maximum allowed deduction for residential rental property ($25,000) = $29,000 AGI.nnThe limited partnership loss is not deductible as it is a passive activity. The rental loss may be deducted up to a maximum of $25,000 for a single taxpayer. All other income items are taxable.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1220,4,'Which of the following costs incurred on rental property should be classified as a capital improvement?','[\"Replacing a 20-year-old roof\",\"Repainting all of the interior walls\",\"Refinishing the existing wood floors\",\"Replacing a broken windowpane\"]',0,'Publication 527, pages 3–4, states, in part, a taxpayer can deduct the cost of repairs to rental property if the taxpayer is not required to capitalize the expense. A taxpayer must capitalize any expense they pay to improve their rental property. An expense is for an improvement if it results in a betterment to the taxpayer\'s property, restores the property, or adapts the property to a new or different use.nnA repair keeps the taxpayer\'s property in good operating condition. It does not materially add to the value of the taxpayer\'s property or substantially prolong its life (Publication 550, page 58).nnImprovements, on the other hand, have a useful life of more than 1 year, add to the value of the property, prolong its useful life, or adapt it to new uses. (See page 58 of Publication 550 for examples of increases to basis.) Improvements include:nnputting a recreation room in an unfinished basement,nadding a bathroom or bedroom,nputting up a new fence,nputting in new plumbing or wiring,nputting on a new roof, andnpaving an unpaved driveway.nFurthermore, if a taxpayer makes an improvement to the property, the cost of the improvement must be capitalized and depreciated as if the improvement were separate property.nnIn this case, replacing a 20-year-old roof would be classified as a capital improvement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1221,4,'Michelle lives in a great neighborhood in New York City. As an experiment, she decides to rent out her apartment for 10 days while she is on vacation. She receives $2,000 in rental income for those 10 days. How much is taxable on her current-year return?','[\"$2,000\",\"$0\",\"$1,000\",\"$4,000\"]',1,'When a personal residence is rented out for a period of less than 15 days, no rental income is taxable and no expenses are deductible.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1222,4,'Dr. O’Day has adjusted gross income of $200,000 comprised of dividend income of $5,000, interest income of $10,000, and $185,000 of Schedule C net income. She also has incurred a rental real estate loss of $10,000. How much of the loss can she take on her current tax return?','[\"$0\",\"$10,000\",\"$5,000\",\"$2,000\"]',0,'Rental real estate activities are considered passive activities, so any losses incurred from these activities can only be used to offset gains from other passive activities. It is important to note that if you earn over $100,000 annually, the special allowance for rental deductions will begin to phase out. For single taxpayers and married couples filing jointly, this allowance will be completely zeroed out once their income reaches $150,000. For those married but filing separately, the allowance will be half that amount.nnDr. O\' Day\'s income exceeds $150,000, so she must carry forward the loss to future years until she has the opportunity to offset it or dispose of the rental property.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1223,4,'Where should income be reported when received by an individual from rental (not including self-rentals) of an office building and where no significant services are provided to the tenant?','[\"Other income on Form 1040\",\"Income on Schedule E,\\u00a0Supplemental Income and Loss\",\"Income on Schedule C,\\u00a0Profit or Loss From Business\",\"Income on Schedule D,\\u00a0Capital Gains and Losses\"]',1,'Publication 527, page 12, states that when a taxpayer rents buildings, rooms, or apartments, and provide basic services such as heat and light, trash collection, etc., the taxpayer normally reports the rental income and expenses in Part I of Schedule E (Form 1040).nnIf, on the other hand, the taxpayer provides substantial services that are primarily for the tenant\'s convenience, such as regular cleaning, changing linen, or maid service, the taxpayer reports the rental income and expenses on Schedule C (Form 1040), Profit or Loss From Business, or Schedule C-EZ, Net Profit From Business.nnSubstantial services do not include the furnishing of heat and light, cleaning of public areas, trash collection, etc. For more information on this issue, look at Publication 334, Tax Guide for Small Business (For Individuals Who Use Schedule C or C-EZ).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1224,4,'Paul owns a second home at the lake. During the tax year, he spent 3 weeks (21 days) at the lake home, rented it to his daughter for three 3-day weekends for a total of $220, and rented it to friends for 10 weeks (70 days) at fair rental value of $300 per week. His expenses for the year include the following:nn  Depreciation          $2,000n  Insurance                100n  Mortgage interest      1,000n  Real estate taxes      2,000n  Utilities              1,000nWhat amount may he deduct for expenses on his Schedule E, Supplemental Income and Loss?','[\"$2,100\",\"$3,000\",\"$3,220\",\"$1,000\"]',2,'If a taxpayer uses a dwelling unit for both rental and personal purposes, the expenses for such must be divided between the rental use and the personal use based on the number of days used for each purpose.nnThe following rules (as given on page 17 of Publication 527) should be regarded when dividing expenses:nnAny day that the unit is rented at a fair rental price is a day of rental use even if the unit was used for personal purposes that day, andnAny day that the unit is available for rent but not actually rented is not a day of rental use.nAdditionally, rental deductions are limited if a taxpayer rents property for 15 or more days during the tax year and uses it for the greater of (a) more than 14 days or (b) more than 10% of the number of days during the year for which the home is rented. Under this limitation the amount of rental activity deductions may not exceed the amount by which the gross income derived from such activity exceeds the deductions otherwise allowable for the property such as interest and taxes (similar to hobby loss rules). (See Publication 527, pages 17 and 18.)nnGiven that Paul\'s rental income was $3,220, his applicable deductions are limited to that extent. The rental property was used 100 days, which is the sum of 70 days (rental), 21 days (personal use), and 9 days (daughter\'s use). All expenses are based on 70% (70 days rented ÷ 100 days used) and the deductible expense would be calculated as follows:nn  Interest                 $ 700 of the $1,000n  Taxes                    1,400 of the $2,000n  Insurance                   70 of the $100n  Utilities, etc.            700 of the $1,000n  Depreciation             1,400 of the $2,000n  Maximum deductible      $4,270 which exceeds the rental incomen                                 amount of $3,220nSee Worksheet 9-1 for figuring the limit on rental deductions (Publication 527, pages 20 and 21).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1225,4,'John frequently pays for repairs in his apartment and gives the receipts to his landlord in lieu of part of his rental payment. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The landlord does\\u00a0not\\u00a0deduct the repair expenses and does not report the repair expense amounts as rental income.\",\"The landlord is entitled to deduct the repair expenses (noncapital improvements) on his tax return.\",\"The landlord must report the repair expense amounts as rental income.\",\"The landlord is entitled to deduct the repair expenses (noncapital improvements) on his tax return but must also report these amounts as rental income.\"]',3,'Publication 527, page 3, states in part that expenses paid by a tenant are considered rental income by the landlord or owner of the rent property. That means the taxpayer must include the amount spent by the tenant in gross income.nnIn addition, the taxpayer (i.e., property owner) can deduct the expenses paid by the tenant if they are deductible rental expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1226,4,'In December of Year 4, John (a cash-basis taxpayer) received a $2,000 payment from Tom who signed a year\'s lease to rent John\'s house. The $2,000 payment consisted of the following:nn   1st Month\'s Rent (for the month of December, Year 4)      $800n   Last Month\'s Rent (for the month of December, Year 5)      800n   Security Deposit (to be returned at end of lease)          400nHow much should John include as rental income on his Year 4 tax return as a result of the $2,000 payment?','[\"$800\",\"$1,200\",\"$1,600\",\"$2,000\"]',2,'Security deposits by a lessee for performance of the terms of a lease are not income to the lessor if the deposits are returnable to the lessee. In this case, the $400 security deposit is not included in John\'s income for the current year.nnSince the last month\'s rent is received in the current year, it is included in income for the current year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1227,4,'A married couple reported the following items for the current year:nn   Salaries                            $95,000n   Dividends                             1,000n   Interest income on savings account      500n   Loss from rental real estate         (2,000)nBoth spouses actively participate in the rental real estate activities. What is the taxpayers\' adjusted gross income on a joint return for the year?','[\"$94,500\",\"$95,000\",\"$96,500\",\"$98,500\"]',0,'Certain taxpayers may deduct real estate rental losses from active and portfolio income, provided that the taxpayers materially participate in the real property trade or business. Generally, up to $25,000 of losses from such activities may be deducted against active income and portfolio income, but the $25,000 deduction is reduced by 50% of the taxpayer’s adjusted gross income (AGI) in excess of $100,000.nnFor this question, AGI is $94,500 ($95,000 + $1,000 + $500 – $2,000).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1228,4,'Rosemary\'s home is used exclusively as her residence all year except for 10 days. During this time, Rosemary rents out her home to alumni for $3,000 while the local college has its homecoming celebration. What amount does Rosemary include on her tax return?','[\"$3,000 as other income on Form 1040\",\"$3,000 as rent income on Schedule C\",\"$3,000 as interest income on Schedule A\",\"None of the rent is included in income.\"]',3,'You generally must include in your gross income all amounts you receive as rent (Publication 527, page 19). However, if you rent property that is also used as your home there is a special 15-day rule (minimal rental use) that applies in calculating your taxable rental income. If you rent the property less than 15 days during the tax year, the rent received is not included in gross income (Publication 527, page 19).nnGiven that Rosemary rented her home out for only 10 days during the year, the rent received is not included in her income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1229,4,'Nare, an accrual-basis taxpayer, owns a building which was rented to Mott under a 10-year lease expiring August 31, Year 7. On January 2, Year 5, Mott paid $30,000 as consideration for canceling the lease. On November 1, Year 5, Nare leased the building to Pine under a 5-year lease. Pine paid Nare $10,000 rent for the two months of November and December and an additional $5,000 for the last month\'s rent. What amount of rental income should Nare report in its Year 5 income tax return?','[\"$10,000\",\"$15,000\",\"$40,000\",\"$45,000\"]',3,'01/02/Yr. 5 payment from Mott for lease cancellation         $30,000n   11/01/Yr. 5 November and December rent payment from Pine      10,000n   11/01/Yr. 5 additional payment from Pine                       5,000n   Total rental income for Year 5                               $45,000n                                                                =======nAny amount received as rent must be included in income in the year of receipt whether the taxpayer is accrual or cash basis. In general, any payment to or made on the behalf of a landlord of any kind is additional rent income.nnAny amounts received by a landlord in consideration for cancellation of a lease are additional rent revenue (and not capitalized).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1230,4,'Kathy rented out her summer home for 80 days and used it personally for 20 days. She paid $1,000 for utilities and $2,000 for repairs. Rental income was $8,000. What was Kathy\'s net rental income?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$5,600\",\"$8,000\"]',2,'If a taxpayer uses a dwelling unit (including a vacation home) for both rental and personal purposes, the expenses for such must be divided between the rental use and the personal use based on the number of days used for each purpose. (Publication 527, pages 17–19)nnThe following rules should be regarded when dividing expenses (Publication 527, page 17):nnAny day that the unit is rented at a fair rental price is a day of rental use even if the unit was used for personal purposes that day.nAny day that the unit is available for rent but not actually rented is not a day of rental use.nAdditionally, rental deductions are limited if a taxpayer rents property for 15 or more days during the tax year and uses it for the greater of (a) more than 14 days or (b) more than 10% of the number of days during the year for which the home is rented. Under this limitation, the amount of rental activity deductions may not exceed the amount by which the gross income derived from such activity exceeds the deductions otherwise allowable for the property, such as interest and taxes (similar to hobby loss rules). (Publication 527, page 18)nnGiven that Kathy\'s rental income was $8,000, her applicable deductions are limited to that extent. The rental property was used 100 days, which is the sum of 80 days (rental) and 20 days (personal use). All expenses are based on 80% (80 days rented ÷ 100 days used) and the deductible expense would be calculated as follows:nn  Utilities, etc.          $ 800 of the $1,000n  Repairs                  1,600 of the $2,000n  Maximum deductible      $2,400 which does not exceed the rentaln                                 income amount of $8,000nSee Worksheet 5-1 of Publication 527 (pages 20–21) for figuring the limit on rental deductions.nnAs a result, Kathy\'s net rental income is $5,600, which is the rental income of $8,000 less the maximum deductible rental expenses of $2,400.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1231,4,'John and Mary moved into your rental property and paid a $10,000 security deposit. You agreed to use this security deposit as their last month\'s rent. Additionally, they paid a painting contractor $2,500 to paint the interior. How much of these payments should be reported as rental income for this year?','[\"$0\",\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\",\"$12,500\"]',3,'Rental income and expenses are discussed in Publication 527, Residential Rental Income (Including Rental of Vacation Homes). In general, a taxpayer must include in gross income all amounts received as rent.nnRental income is any payment received for the use or occupation of property. In addition to amounts received as normal rent payments, there are other amounts that may be rental income and as such are included in rental income. Advance rent, for example, is any amount received before the period that it covers. These payments are included in rental income in the year received regardless of the period covered or the method of accounting that the taxpayer is using. (See page 3 of Publication 527.)nnSecurity deposits, on the other hand, are not included in rental income when it is received if the amount is to be returned to the tenant at the end of the lease. If the taxpayer keeps part or all of the security deposit during any year because the tenant does not live up to the terms of the lease, the amount retained becomes income for that year.nnIf an amount called a security deposit is to be used as a final payment of rent, it is advance rent and as such, it is included as rental income in the year that it is received.nnIf a tenant pays any of the rental property expenses, the payments are treated as rental income by the property owner and may be deducted as an expense by the property owner if they are deductible rental expenses.nnIn this problem, the taxpayer includes the entire $12,500 ($10,000 as advanced rent and $2,500 as tenant-paid expenses on the property) as rental income.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:18'),(1232,9,'John Bright recently passed the Special Enrollment Examination and is advertising for his business. Which of the following presentations will violate the Circular 230 rules for advertising?','[\"John Bright, enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"John Bright, Certified Enrolled Agent\",\"John Bright, enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"John Bright, admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.30(a)(1), presents the general rules on advertising and solicitation restrictions. In particular, a practitioner may not, with respect to any IRS matter, in any way use or participate in the use of any form of public communication or private solicitation containing a false, fraudulent, or coercive statement or claim; or a misleading or deceptive statement or claim.nnEnrolled agents, in describing their professional designation, may not utilize the term of “certified” or imply an employer/employee relationship with the IRS.nnExamples of acceptable descriptions are “enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service,” “enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service,” and “admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.”',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1233,9,'In order to satisfy Circular 230 that a person will not be sanctioned for failing to exercise due diligence, an enrolled agent:nn1. must complete all tasks involved with the representation of a taxpayer herself.n2. may rely on the work product of another person if the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.','[\"Item 1 is correct.\",\"Item 2 is correct.\",\"Items 1 and 2 are correct.\",\"Neither item is correct.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides that a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to IRS matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the IRS.nFurthermore, a practitioner will be presumed to have exercised due diligence for purposes of this section if the practitioner relies on the work product of another person and the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.nnHence, Circular 230 provides that an enrolled agent can rely on another as long as certain measures are taken by the enrolled agent to ensure due diligence.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1234,9,'Which of the following procedures is expected for ensuring best practices by the tax advisor with the responsibility for overseeing a firm\'s practice of preparing or assisting in the preparation of tax returns to the IRS?','[\"The advisor is responsible for reviewing most if not all employees\' work before it is submitted to the IRS.\",\"The advisor should take reasonable steps to ensure that the firm\'s procedures for all members, associates, and employees are consistent with best practices.\",\"The advisor must be an attorney or CPA.\",\"The advisor is responsible for reviewing most if not all employees\' work before it is submitted to the IRS\\u00a0and\\u00a0must be an attorney or CPA.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.36(a), provides that any individual (such as a tax advisor) who has or shares principal authority and responsibility for overseeing a firm\'s practice governed by Circular 230, including the provision of providing advice concerning federal tax matters and preparation of tax returns, claims for refund, or other documents for submission to the IRS, must take reasonable steps to ensure that the firm has adequate procedures in effect for all members, associates, and employees for purposes of complying with subparts A, B, and C of Circular 230.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1235,9,'Donald, an enrolled agent, has knowledge that a client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States. What is Donald\'s response?','[\"Donald must advise the client of such noncompliance.\",\"Donald should but is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to advise the client of such noncompliance.\",\"Donald is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to advise the client of such noncompliance.\",\"Donald must withdraw from the engagement.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.21, addresses the issue of knowledge of client\'s omission by a person practicing before the IRS. In particular, a practitioner who, having been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the IRS, knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper, which the client is required by the revenue laws of the United States to execute, shall advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnHence, the correct response for this problem is that Donald must advise the client of their noncompliance.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1236,9,'A notice of disbarment or suspension of a certified public accountant from practice before the Internal Revenue Service is issued to which of the following?','[\"IRS employees\",\"Interested departments and agencies of the federal government\",\"State authorities\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'On the issuance of a final order censuring, suspending, or disbarring a practitioner or a final order disqualifying an appraiser, notification of the censure, suspension, disbarment, or disqualification will be given to appropriate officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service and interested departments and agencies of the federal government.nnThe Internal Revenue Service may determine the manner of giving notice to the proper authorities of the state by which the censured, suspended, or disbarred person was licensed to practice.nnHence, all of the items listed in this problem are correct responses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1237,9,'Except as provided in other sections of Circular 230, which of the following presumes that a practitioner exercised due diligence?nn1. If the practitioner relies on the work product of another personn2. If the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person','[\"Only item 1 is necessary.\",\"Only item 2 is necessary.\",\"Either item 1 or 2 is necessary.\",\"Both items 1 and 2 are necessary.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides that a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to IRS matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, ANDnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the IRS.nFurthermore, a practitioner will be presumed to have exercised due diligence for purposes of this section if the practitioner relies on the work product of another person and the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1238,9,'An Enrolled Agent (EA) is in the process of representing Taxpayer A before the Internal Revenue Service for a tax matter. Taxpayer A\'s ex-husband also asked the EA to represent him for the same matter. Which of the following is NOT required for the EA to represent both?','[\"The EA must notify the Office of Professional Responsibility that the EA will be representing both taxpayers.\",\"Both taxpayers must waive the conflict of interest and give informed consent in writing to the EA.\",\"The EA must reasonably believe that the EA will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to both taxpayers.\",\"The representation is not prohibited by law.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.29(b), provides that notwithstanding the existence of a conflict of interest under paragraph (a) of this section, the practitioner may represent a client if:nnthe practitioner reasonably believes that the practitioner will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to each affected client,nthe representation is not prohibited by law, andneach affected client gives informed consent, confirmed in writing, within a reasonable time after the informed consent, but in no event later than 30 days.nIn addition, copies of the written consents must be retained by the practitioner for at least 36 months from the date of the conclusion of the representation of the affected clients and the written consents must be provided to any officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service on request. (Circular 230, Section 10.29(c))nnAn EA is NOT required to notify the Office of Professional Responsibility that they will be representing both taxpayers.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1239,9,'What position is held in Circular 230 with respect to representing conflicting interests before the IRS?','[\"An enrolled agent is prohibited from representing conflicting interest.\",\"Written consent by the conflicting parties must be maintained for 35 months.\",\"It is permissible if the affected clients give informed consent.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.29, addresses the issue of conflicting interests. In particular, no attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary shall represent conflicting interests in his or her practice before the Internal Revenue Service, except if:nnthe practitioner reasonably believes that the practitioner will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to each affected client,nthe representation is not prohibited by law, andneach affected client waives the conflict of interest and gives informed consent, confirmed in writing by each affected client, at the time the existence of the conflict of interest is known by the practitioner. The confirmation may be made within a reasonable period after the informed consent, but in no event later than 30 days.nFurthermore, an enrolled agent must retain copies of the written consent for at least 36 months from the date of conclusion of the representation of the affected clients, and the written consents must be provided to any officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service on request.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBe careful of this potentially tricky question; the list given in Circular 230, Section 10.29, and shown above is written with the word “and,” not “or,” after the second bullet item. Therefore, all three conditions in the list must be present, as opposed to any one of them.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1240,9,'Kopel was engaged to prepare Raff\'s 2024 federal income tax return. During the tax preparation interview, Raff told Kopel that he paid $3,000 in property taxes in 2024. Actually, Raff\'s property taxes amounted to only $600. Based on Raff\'s word, Kopel deducted the $3,000 on Raff\'s tax return. Kopel had no reason to believe that the information was incorrect. Kopel did not request underlying documentation and was reasonably satisfied by Raff\'s representation that Raff had adequate records to support the deduction. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"To avoid the preparer penalty for willful understatement of tax liability, Kopel was obligated to examine the underlying documentation for the deduction.\",\"To avoid the preparer penalty for willful understatement of tax liability, Kopel would be required to obtain Raff\'s representation in writing.\",\"Kopel is\\u00a0not\\u00a0subject to the preparer penalty for willful understatement of tax liability because the deduction that was claimed was more than 25% of the actual amount that should have been deducted.\",\"Kopel is\\u00a0not\\u00a0subject to the preparer penalty for willful understatement of tax liability because Kopel was justified in relying on Raff\'s representation.\"]',3,'In tax practice, the tax return preparer is justified in relying in good faith upon the client\'s representations. The tax return preparer who acts in good faith is not required to obtain verification of representations made by the client. Section 10.31, paragraph (d) states: \"A practitioner advising a client to take a position on a tax return, document, affidavit or other paper submitted to the Internal Revenue Service, or preparing or signing a tax return as a preparer, generally may rely in good faith without verification upon information furnished by the client.” The practitioner is still required to make reasonable inquiries if the information appears to be incorrect, inconsistent, or incomplete.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1241,9,'A practitioner may represent conflicting interests provided that each affected client waives the conflict by:','[\"oral consent.\",\"written, notarized consent.\",\"informed consent.\",\"informed, written consent.\"]',3,'Generally, a practitioner cannot represent conflicting interests in practice before the IRS. However, if each of the affected clients waives the conflict of interest by informed, written consent, the practitioner may represent the conflicting interests. Section 10.29 of Circular 230 explains that \"a conflict of interest exists if (1) The representation of one client will be directly adverse to [the interests of] another client,\" or there is significant risk that representing one client will be “materially limited by the practitioner’s responsibilities to another client, a former client or a third person, or by a personal interest of the practitioner.”nnThe practitioner must retain copies of the written consent for 36 months from the conclusion of the matter for which the consent was given.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1242,9,'Stuart Light, an enrolled agent, received a complaint from the Internal Revenue Service for disreputable conduct. Which one of the following items was not required to be listed in the complaint?','[\"A demand for an answer to the charges\",\"The unit and employee of the Internal Revenue Service that recommended the action against Stuart\",\"The specific sanctions that are recommended against Stuart\",\"The charges against Stuart\"]',1,'A proceeding is instituted by the filing of a complaint. Circular 230, Section 10.62, provides the necessary contents in a complaint for disreputable conduct. In general, there are three items to be included: charges, specifications of sanctions, and demand for answers.nnCharges: A complaint must name the respondent, provide a clear and concise description of the facts and law that constitute the basis for the proceeding, and be signed by an authorized representative of the Internal Revenue Service under Section 10.69(a)(1) of Circular 230. A complaint is sufficient if it fairly informs the respondent of the charges brought so that he or she is able to prepare a defense.nSpecification of sanction: The complaint must specify the sanction sought against the practitioner or appraiser. If the sanction sought is a suspension, the duration of the suspension sought must be specified.nDemand for answer: The respondent must be notified in the complaint or in a separate paper attached to the complaint of the time for answering the complaint, which may not be less than 30 days from the date of service of the complaint, the name and address of the Administrative Law Judge with whom the answer must be filed, the name and address of the person representing the Internal Revenue Service to whom a copy of the answer must be served, and that a decision by default may be rendered against the respondent in the event an answer is not filed as required.nHence, the unit and employee of the Internal Revenue Service that recommended the action against Stuart are not required to be listed in the complaint.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1243,9,'A conflict of interest exists if:nn1. the representation of one client will be directly adverse to another client.n2. there is a significant risk that the representation of one or more clients will be materially limited by the practitioner\'s responsibilities to another client.','[\"1 only\",\"2 only\",\"1 or 2\",\"Neither 1 nor 2\"]',2,'According to Circular 230, Section 10.29(a), a conflict of interest exists if:nnthe representation of one client will be directly adverse to another client ORnthere is a significant risk that the representation of one or more clients will be materially limited by the practitioner\'s responsibilities to another client, a former client or a third person, or by a personal interest of the practitioner.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1244,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning Charlie, an enrolled agent, and the submission of records or information upon the lawful request by an IRS representative?','[\"He is required to submit such documents in all circumstances.\",\"He is required to submit such documents unless he believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the records are privileged.\",\"He is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to submit such documents unless ordered by the courts.\",\"He is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to submit such documents unless he believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the records are not harmful to his client.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.20, provides the basic rules for when information is to be furnished to the IRS.nnIn general, a practitioner must, on a proper and lawful request by a duly authorized officer or employee of the IRS, promptly submit records or information in any matter before the IRS, unless the practitioner believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the records or information are privileged.nnAs the above basic rule provides, the taxpayer\'s representative is not required in all circumstances to submit records or information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1245,9,'How is a proceeding for a violation of the regulations in Circular 230 instituted against an attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary?','[\"An aggrieved taxpayer files a petition with the U.S. Tax Court stating a claim against the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary.\",\"The Commissioner of the IRS files a complaint against the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary with the U.S. Tax Court.\",\"The authorized representative of the Internal Revenue Service signs a complaint naming the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary and fairly informs them of the charges brought so that the respondent is able to prepare a defense.\",\"The Secretary of the Treasury files a complaint against the attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.60, provides that whenever it is determined that a practitioner (or employer, firm, or other entity, if applicable) violated any provision of the laws governing practice before the IRS or the regulations in this part, the practitioner may be reprimanded or, in accordance with Section 10.62, subject to a proceeding for sanctions as described in Section 10.50, which are censure, suspension, or disbarment of the practitioner.nnA proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner is instituted by the filing of a complaint (as noted in Section 10.60 (\"Institution of proceeding\")). The necessary contents of the filing as given in Section 10.62 require the person to name the respondent and provide a clear and concise description of the facts and law that constitute the basis for the proceeding, and the filing must be signed by an authorized representative of the IRS under Section 10.69(a)(1).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1246,9,'What level of authority is needed for a tax return preparer to avoid an unreasonable position penalty on a tax return if the position was not disclosed and is not a tax shelter or reportable transaction?','[\"There is or was substantial authority for the position.\",\"There is reasonable basis for the position.\",\"The position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.\",\"There is a 1-in-3, or greater, likelihood of being sustained on its merits.\"]',0,'A tax return preparer is liable for a penalty under Section 6694(a) (i.e., penalty for understatement due to unreasonable position) unless they satisfy an exception provided for the defined three categories: general, disclosed position, and tax shelter or reportable transaction.nnThe general category exception, which pertains when the position is not disclosed, is satisfied if there is or was substantial authority for the position.nThe disclosed position category exception is satisfied when the position is disclosed, item 3 below (on the tax shelter or reportable transaction category exception) does not apply, and there is reasonable basis for the position.nThe tax shelter or reportable transaction category exception is satisfied unless it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.nIn addition, no penalty shall be imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.nnThus, in this situation, substantial authority for the position must apply to avoid an unreasonable position since the tax return preparer did not disclose the position.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1247,9,'Where is the hearing held for suspension or disbarment of a person authorized to practice before the IRS?','[\"Before the U.S. Tax Court\",\"Before the District Court\",\"Before the Administrative Law Judge\",\"Before the Secretary of the Treasury\"]',2,'Proceedings on complaints for sanction (as described in Circular 230, Section 10.50—i.e., censure, suspension, or disbarment) of a practitioner, employer, firm, or appraiser will be conducted by an Administrative Law Judge appointed as provided by 5 USC 3105. It is not held before the Tax Court, District Court, or Secretary of the Treasury.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1248,9,'While reviewing a new client\'s prior-year tax returns, a tax return preparer became aware that the client did not properly file all required federal income tax returns. Under Treasury Circular 230, what should the tax return preparer do in this situation?','[\"Notify the Tax Court of the situation and request a ruling of continuance\",\"Notify the Internal Revenue Service of the client\'s noncompliance\",\"Resign from the engagement\",\"Advise the client of the consequences of the noncompliance\"]',3,'Practice before the IRS is defined in Circular 230 as involving all matters connected with a presentation to the IRS, or any of its officers or employees, relating to a taxpayer’s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the IRS. Circular 230 states that a practitioner who knows that a client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper has a duty to advise the client promptly of such noncompliance, error, or omission.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1249,9,'What action can be taken against an enrolled agent for a materially false or misleading statement that the client decides to make on a document submitted to the IRS?','[\"No action can be taken against the agent as long as the client is the one that makes the final decision to submit the document containing the false or misleading statement.\",\"The agent can be censured or suspended but\\u00a0not\\u00a0disbarred by the IRS as long as the client is the one that makes the final decision to submit the document containing the false or misleading statement.\",\"The agent can be censured but\\u00a0not\\u00a0suspended by the IRS even if the client makes the final decision to submit the document containing the false or misleading statement.\",\"The agent can be censured, suspended, or disbarred by the IRS even if it is the client that makes the final decision to submit the document containing the false or misleading statement.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.50, provides the general rules for sanctions of a tax practitioner. In particular, the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate, after notice and an opportunity for a proceeding, may censure, suspend, or disbar any practitioner from practice before the Internal Revenue Service if the practitioner is shown to be incompetent or disreputable (within the meaning of Circular 230, Section 10.51), fails to comply with any regulation in this part, or with intent to defraud, willfully and knowingly misleads or threatens a client or prospective client. Censure is a public reprimand.nnCircular 230, Section 10.51, provides that incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be sanctioned under Section 10.50 (i.e., censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service) includes, but is not limited to:nnconviction of any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United States;nconviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust;nconviction of any felony under federal or state law for which the conduct involved renders the practitioner unfit to practice before the Internal Revenue Service;ngiving false or misleading information, or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information, to the Department of the Treasury or any officer or employee thereof, or to any tribunal authorized to pass upon federal tax matters, in connection with any matter pending or likely to be pending before them, knowing such information to be false or misleading.nIn this problem, the enrolled agent may be sanctioned because he or she has participated in the act.nnNote: The above areas of conduct are but four of the 18 areas listed in Section 10.51.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1250,9,'The Internal Revenue Service notified Sally in February 2024 that she passed the Special Enrollment Examination. She submitted her application for enrollment and received the initial enrollment on June 15, 2024. Her continuing professional education requirements until the first full renewal cycle are that:','[\"she does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to complete any continuing professional education requirements until the first full renewal cycle.\",\"she must complete 2 hours of credit for each full month and each part of a month left in the current renewal cycle.\",\"she must complete a minimum of 72 hours of continuing professional education unless she is within less than a year before the end of the current cycle.\",\"she must complete 2 hours of credit for only each full month left in the current renewal cycle.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.6(e)(2) states, in part, that an individual who receives initial enrollment during an enrollment cycle must complete 2 hours of qualifying continuing education credit for each month enrolled during the enrollment cycle. More importantly, enrollment for any part of a month is considered enrollment for the entire month. In addition, a minimum of 16 hours of continuing education credit, including two hours of ethics or professional conduct, must be completed during each enrollment year of an enrollment cycle.nnThus, Sally received the initial enrollment on June 15, 2024 in year 3 of an enrollment cycle. As a result, she is required to complete 14 hours of credit before December 31st of the current year, which is 2 hours of credit for each full month (July through December or 6 months) and each part of a month (meaning June or 1 month) left in the current renewal cycle.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1251,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the renewal of enrollment by an enrolled agent?','[\"An enrolled agent whose Social Security number ends with the number 0, 1, 2, or 3 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2024, and January 31, 2025.\",\"The renewal of enrollment is effective on March 1 for an individual who properly completes the renewal process.\",\"Failure to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will justify an individual\'s failure to satisfy this requirement.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(d), provides the rules associated with renewal of enrollment as an enrolled agent or enrolled retirement plan agent. In particular:nnan enrolled agent whose Social Security number ends with the number 0, 1, 2, or 3 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2024, and January 31, 2025, and thereafter every 3 years; nan enrolled agent whose Social Security number ends with the number 4, 5, or 6 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2025, and January 31, 2026, and thereafter every 3 years; andnan enrolled agent whose Social Security number ends with the number 7, 8, or 9 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2026 and January 31, 2027, and thereafter every 3 years.nIn addition, the renewal of enrollment is effective on April 1 of the renewal year (i.e., 2025 in this response) (not March 1) for an individual who properly completes the renewal process. And finally, failure to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will not justify an individual\'s failure to satisfy this requirement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1252,9,'Sara Birch became an enrolled agent on March 12, 2024. Sara is ordering business cards and advertising for her accounting and tax practice. Of the following presentations listed below, which one will violate the Circular 230 rules for advertising?','[\"Sara Birch, Enrolled Agent, certified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Sara Birch, Enrolled Agent, representing taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Sara Birch, enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Sara Birch, EA, admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.30(a)(1), presents the general rules on solicitation, advertising, and solicitation restrictions. In particular, “A practitioner may not, with respect to any Internal Revenue Service matter, in any way use or participate in the use of any form of public communication or private solicitation containing a false, fraudulent, or coercive statement or claim; or a misleading or deceptive statement or claim.”nnEnrolled agents, in describing their professional designation, may not utilize the term “certified” or imply an employer/employee relationship with the IRS. Examples of acceptable descriptions are “enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service,” “enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service,” and “admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.”nnSara is able to inform people of her status of being an enrolled agent by indicating that she is permitted to practice before the IRS, she is enrolled to represent taxpayers before the IRS, or she is admitted to practice before the IRS. Sara is not authorized by Circular 230 to say that she is certified by the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1253,9,'Under Treasury Circular 230, when may a practitioner interfere with the prompt and lawful request for documents from the IRS?','[\"Only if the practitioner acts in good conscience\",\"Only if the practitioner has reasonable grounds\",\"Only if the practitioner believes the documents are privileged\",\"Only if the practitioner believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the information is privileged\"]',3,'A practitioner may not interfere, or attempt to interfere, with any proper and lawful effort by the Internal Revenue Service, its officers or employees, to obtain any record or information unless the practitioner believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the record or information is privileged.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1254,9,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Any individual for compensation may prepare a tax return.\",\"Any individual may appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS.\",\"Any individual may furnish information at the request of the IRS or any of its officers or employees.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Section 10.8(a) of Circular 230, any individual who for compensation prepares or assists with the preparation of all or substantially all of a tax return or claim for refund must have a preparer tax identification number.nnPursuant to Section 10.8(b) of Circular 230, any individual may for compensation prepare or assist with the preparation of a tax return or claim for refund (provided the individual prepares less than all or substantially all of a tax return or claim for refund), appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS, or furnish information at the request of the IRS or any of its officers or employees. Hence, all of the responses are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1255,9,'Under Treasury Circular 230, a practitioner may be sanctioned for which of the following?','[\"Gross incompetence\",\"Willful violation of the regulations\",\"Prohibited solicitation of employment\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A practitioner may be sanctioned for a variety of items, including violating any of the regulations willfully, recklessly, or through gross incompetence (Treasury Circular 230, Section 10.52). The practitioner may also be sanctioned for “solicitation of employment as prohibited under §10.30, the use of false or misleading representations with intent to deceive a client or prospective client in order to procure employment or intimating that the practitioner is able improperly to obtain special consideration or action from the Internal Revenue Service or any officer or employee thereof.” (Section 10.51(a)(5))n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1256,9,'In preparing Watt’s individual income tax return, Stark, EA, took a deduction contrary to a Tax Court decision that had disallowed a similar deduction. Stark’s position was adopted in good faith and with a reasonable belief that the Tax Court decision failed to conform to the Internal Revenue Code. Under the circumstances, Stark will:','[\"not be liable for a preparer penalty unless the understatement of taxes is at least 25% of Watt\\u2019s tax liability.\",\"not be liable for a preparer penalty if Stark exercised due diligence.\",\"be liable for the preparer\\u2019s negligence penalty.\",\"be liable for the preparer\\u2019s penalty because of Stark\\u2019s intentional disregard of the Tax Court decision.\"]',1,'IRC Section 6501 contains a penalty for the omission of at least 25% of gross income, not tax liability.nnUnder IRC Section 6694(a)(3), no penalty will be imposed if there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the preparer acted in good faith. The penalty under this section applies if there is an intentional disregard of rules or regulations—not court cases. IRC Section 6662(c) defines negligence as the failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with tax law. A position taken in good faith would not be negligent.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1257,9,'Margaret Smith is a CPA who is representing John and Mary Jones before the Wage and Investment Division of the Internal Revenue Service. The Service is questioning John and Mary on contributions that were listed on Schedule A of their 2021 Form 1040. While reviewing the documentation provided by John and Mary, Margaret discovers contributions that were made to a nonqualified organization. What is the appropriate action for Margaret to take?','[\"Margaret must advise John and Mary on how to keep the omission from being discovered by the IRS.\",\"Margaret must notify the Internal Revenue Service that she is no longer representing John and Mary by withdrawing her Form 2848.\",\"Margaret must advise John and Mary promptly of the omission and the consequences provided by the Internal Revenue Code and regulations for such omission.\",\"Margaret must immediately advise the Internal Revenue Service examiner of the nonqualified contributions.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.21, provides that a practitioner who, having been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service, knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper which the client submitted or executed under the revenue laws of the United States, must advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission. The practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnIn this case, Margaret must advise John and Mary promptly of the omission and the consequences provided by the Internal Revenue Code and regulations for such omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1258,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the issuance of an enrollment card to an individual applying for enrollment to practice before the IRS?','[\"An enrolled agent can only practice before the IRS if his or her enrollment card is valid.\",\"An enrolled agent\'s enrollment card is issued by the Director of the Office of Professional Responsibility.\",\"Each enrollment card for an enrolled agent is valid for 1 year.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(b), states that the Internal Revenue Service will issue an enrollment or registration card or certificate to each individual whose application for enrollment to practice before the IRS is approved. Each card or certificate is valid for the period stated on the card or certificate, which is generally 3 years (not 1 year) for an enrolled agent. Finally, an individual is not eligible to practice before the IRS if the card or certificate is not valid.nnAs a result, the only correct statement is that an enrolled agent can only practice before the IRS if his or her enrollment card is valid.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1259,9,'Michael Smith is an enrolled agent with an office that employs four other enrolled agents. Kimberly Wilson is a CPA who was suspended from practice for 1 year by the Internal Revenue Service. Kimberly knows Michael and asks him for employment for the 1-year period of suspension. Michael employs Kimberly for the sole purpose of corresponding and communicating with the Internal Revenue Service on issues arising for Michael\'s clients. Which of the following statements is correct about the hiring under Circular 230?','[\"It is allowed because Kimberly\'s suspension is for less than 2 years.\",\"It is allowed because Kimberly is limited to corresponding and communicating with the IRS.\",\"It is allowed because the clients are really Michael\'s, not Kimberly\'s.\",\"None of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.24, provides information pertaining to assistance from disbarred or suspended persons and former IRS employees. In particular, a practitioner may not, knowingly and directly or indirectly:nnaccept assistance from or assist any person who is under disbarment or suspension from practice before the Internal Revenue Service if the assistance relates to a matter or matters constituting practice before the Internal Revenue Service ornaccept assistance from any former government employee where the provisions of Section 10.25 (\"Practice by former government employees, their partners and their associates\") or any federal law would be violated.nTherefore, none of the responses are correct. Michael cannot accept assistance from a person who has been suspended pursuant to Circular 230. Kimberly\'s correspondence with the IRS is considered practice before the Internal Revenue Service.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1260,9,'Sam, an enrolled agent, is representing Fred before the Examination Division of the Internal Revenue Service. The Internal Revenue Service is questioning Fred on his Schedule C gross income that is listed on the 2022 tax return. While reviewing the documentation Fred provided, Sam discovers income that was omitted from the tax return. What is the appropriate action for Sam to take?','[\"Sam must immediately advise the Internal Revenue Service examiner of the omitted income.\",\"Sam must notify the Internal Revenue Service that he is no longer representing Fred by withdrawing his Form 2848.\",\"Sam must advise Fred promptly of the omission and the consequences provided by the Internal Revenue Code and regulations for such omission.\",\"Sam must advise Fred on how to keep the omission from being discovered by the Internal Revenue Service.\"]',2,'Upon learning of the omitted income, Sam is obligated as an enrolled agent to notify Fred of the error and its tax consequence.nnCircular 230, Section 10.21, provides that a practitioner who, having been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the IRS, knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper which the client submitted or executed under the revenue laws of the United States, must advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnThe practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1261,9,'Circular 230, Section 10.34, discusses standards for advising clients with respect to tax return positions and for preparing or signing returns. Which of the statements below is true?','[\"A practitioner may not advise a client to submit a document to the Internal Revenue Service if the purpose is to delay or impede the administration of the federal tax laws or if it is frivolous.\",\"A practitioner advising a client to take a position on a tax return, or preparing or signing a tax return as a preparer, must inform the client of the penalties reasonably likely to apply to the client with respect to the position advised, prepared, or reported.\",\"A practitioner advising a client to take a position on a tax return, or preparing or signing a tax return as a preparer, generally may rely in good faith without verification upon information furnished by the client. The practitioner may not, however, ignore the implications of information furnished to, or actually known by, the practitioner, and must make reasonable inquiries if the information as furnished appears to be incorrect, inconsistent with an important fact or another factual assumption, or incomplete.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'When preparing to sign a tax return by a tax preparer, Circular 230, Section 10.34(d), provides guidance on relying on information furnished by clients. Specifically, a practitioner advising a client to take a position on a tax return or preparing, or signing a tax return as a preparer, generally may rely in good faith without verification upon information furnished by the client. The practitioner may not, however, ignore the implications of information furnished to, or actually known by, the practitioner, and must make reasonable inquiries if the information as furnished appears to be incorrect, inconsistent with an important fact or another factual assumption, or incomplete.nnCircular 230, Section 10.34(c), provides that a practitioner must inform a client of any penalties that are reasonably likely to apply to the client with respect to a position taken on a tax return if the practitioner advised the client with respect to the position; or the practitioner prepared or signed the tax return; and any document, affidavit, or other paper submitted to the Internal Revenue Service.nnCircular 230, Section 10.34(b), provides that a practitioner may not advise a client to take a position on a document, affidavit, or other paper submitted to the Internal Revenue Service unless the position is not frivolous. In addition, a practitioner may not advise a client to submit a document, affidavit, or other paper to the Internal Revenue Service if the purpose of which is to delay or impede the administration of the federal tax laws; that is frivolous; or that contains or omits information in a manner that demonstrates an intentional disregard of a rule or regulation unless the practitioner also advises the client to submit a document that evidences a good faith challenge to the rule or regulation.nnHence, all of the above statements are true.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1262,9,'To maintain active enrollment to practice before the Internal Revenue Service, each individual enrolled is required to have his or her enrollment renewed. The Internal Revenue Service will notify the individual of his or her renewal of enrollment and will issue the individual a card to evidence enrollment. Which of the following statements about renewal of enrollment is correct?','[\"A reasonable refundable fee may be charged for each application for renewal of enrollment filed with the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"Failure by an individual to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will be justification for the failure to timely renew enrollment.\",\"Forms required for renewal may only be obtained from the National Association of Enrolled Agents.\",\"The enrollment cycle is a 3-year period and all enrolled agents must renew as prescribed by the last digit of their Social Security number.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.6, provides the general rules for enrollment of enrolled agents, enrolled retirement plan agents, and registered tax return preparers before the Internal Revenue Service. Paragraph (d) provides the rules for renewal of enrollment. Specifically, enrolled agents and enrolled retirement plan agents must renew their status with the IRS to maintain eligibility to practice before the Internal Revenue Service. Failure by an individual to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will not be justification for the failure to satisfy this requirement.nnThe enrollment cycle is a 3-year period and all enrolled agents must renew as prescribed by the last digit of their Social Security number.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1263,9,'Ms. Smith hired Tom, an enrolled agent, to prepare her federal income tax return for 2024. While gathering information to prepare the return, Tom discovered that Ms. Smith failed to file required tax returns for the previous two tax years. What does Circular 230 require Tom to do?','[\"Advise Ms. Smith that she did not comply with the Internal Revenue laws by failing to file her federal income tax returns for both prior tax years.\",\"Inform the Internal Revenue Service that Ms. Smith did not comply with the Internal Revenue laws by failing to file her federal income tax returns for both prior tax years.\",\"Withdraw from the engagement.\",\"Circular 230 is silent on this point.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.21, provides that a practitioner who, having been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the IRS, knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper which the client submitted or executed under the revenue laws of the United States, must advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnSimply stated, the practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1264,9,'Enrolled agents generally must complete continuing education credits for renewed enrollment. Which of the following describes the credit requirements for an agent on May 1, 2025?','[\"A minimum of 72 hours must be completed in\\u00a0each year\\u00a0of an enrollment cycle.\",\"A minimum of 24 hours must be completed in\\u00a0each year\\u00a0of an enrollment cycle, including 2 hours of ethics or professional conduct.\",\"A minimum of 80 hours must be completed during each 3-year enrollment cycle.\",\"A minimum of 16 hours must be completed in\\u00a0each year\\u00a0of the enrollment cycle, including 2 hours of ethics or professional conduct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(d), provides that an enrolled agent is required to have his or her enrollment renewed based on the last digit of their Social Security number or tax identification number. For example, an agent with a number ending in 0, 1, 2, or 3 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2024, and January 31, 2025, and thereafter every 3 years (i.e., November 1, 2024; November 1, 2027; and so forth). Likewise, a number ending in 4, 5, or 6 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2025, and January 31, 2026, and a number ending in 7, 8, or 9 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2026, and January 31, 2027.nnCircular 230, Section 10.6(e), further provides that an enrolled agent applying for renewal of enrollment must certify, in the manner prescribed by the Internal Revenue Service, that he or she has satisfied the requisite number of continuing education hours:nnFor renewed enrollment, a person must satisfy a minimum of 72 hours of continuing education credit, including 6 hours of ethics or professional conduct, during each 3-year period, which is known as an enrollment cycle. In addition, a person must satisfy a minimum of 16 hours of continuing education credit, including 2 hours of ethics or professional conduct, in each year of the enrollment cycle.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1265,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the issuance of an enrollment card to an individual applying for enrollment to practice before the IRS?','[\"An enrolled agent can only practice before the IRS if his or her enrollment card is valid.\",\"An enrolled agent is required to obtain a preparer tax identification number.\",\"Each enrollment card is valid for the period stated on the card.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(b), states the Internal Revenue Service will issue an enrollment card to each individual whose application to practice before the IRS is approved. Each card or certificate is valid for the period stated on the card or certificate. A registered tax return preparer is not eligible to practice before the IRS if his or her enrollment card is not valid.nnThe card or certificate is in addition to any notification that may be provided to each individual who obtains a preparer tax identification number (PTIN).nnAs a result, all of the statements given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1266,9,'How long must each practitioner maintain records of his or her completed continuing education (CE) credits?','[\"CE credit information does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to be retained by the enrolled agent since the qualifying organization provides the Internal Revenue Service a list of each participant that completed CE credits.\",\"CE credit information must be maintained for a period of 4 years from the date they are completed.\",\"CE credit information must be retained for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment.\",\"CE credit information must be retained for a period of 1 year following the year they are completed.\"]',2,'The recordkeeping requirements for qualifying continuing professional education by an enrolled agent are found in Circular 230, Section 10.6(h). The specifics are that each individual applying for renewal must retain for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment the information required with regard to qualifying continuing professional education credit hours. This same rule applies to instructors, discussion leaders, and speakers.nnHence, the correct response for this problem is an enrolled agent must retain the verification of CE taken for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1267,9,'Select the statement below that is correct with respect to the contents of an answer that is filed in rebuttal to a complaint filed by the Internal Revenue Service.','[\"The answer must be written and general denials are permitted.\",\"The respondent does not have to admit or deny all of the allegations set forth in the complaint and can state they are without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation.\",\"The respondent may not deny a material allegation in the complaint that he or she knows to be true, or state that he or she is without sufficient information to form a belief, when the respondent possesses the required information.\",\"The respondent does not have to state affirmatively any special matters of defense on which he or she relies.\"]',2,'According to Circular 230, Section 10.64(b), the answer by a respondent must be written and contain a statement of facts that constitute the respondent\'s grounds of defense. General denials are not permitted. The respondent must specifically admit or deny each allegation set forth in the complaint, except that the respondent may state that the respondent is without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation. The respondent, nevertheless, may not deny a material allegation in the complaint that he or she knows to be true, or state that he or she is without sufficient information to form a belief, when the respondent possesses the required information. The respondent also must state affirmatively any special matters of defense on which he or she relies.nnTherefore, the only correct statement is the respondent may not deny a material allegation in the complaint that he or she knows to be true, or state that he or she is without sufficient information to form a belief, when the respondent possesses the required information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1268,9,'Identify the appropriate action that a practitioner should take when he or she becomes aware of an error or omission on a client\'s return.','[\"Amend the return and provide it to the client.\",\"Inform the IRS of the noncompliance, error, or omission.\",\"Do nothing.\",\"Promptly advise the client of such noncompliance, error, or omission.\"]',3,'If a practitioner has been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service and knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper which the client submitted or executed under the revenue laws of the United States, the practitioner must advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnIn addition, the practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1269,9,'Which of the following acts constitute(s) grounds for a tax preparer penalty?nnI. Without the taxpayer\'s consent, the tax preparer disclosed taxpayer income tax return information under an order from a state court.   nII. At the taxpayer\'s suggestion, the tax preparer deducted the expenses of the taxpayer\'s personal domestic help as a business expense on the taxpayer\'s individual tax return.','[\"I only\",\"II only\",\"Both I and II\",\"Neither I nor II\"]',1,'Taxpayer return information may be disclosed without penalty if the information is (1) to a tax processor to file electronically, (2) for peer review of the preparer, (3) for administrative order by a state agency or state court order. Preparers are subject to a penalty of $5,000 or 75 percent of the income derived (or to be derived) by the tax return preparer with respect to the return or claim for a willful attempt to understate tax liability. The rules and regulations clearly do not permit a deduction for a taxpayer\'s personal domestic help as a business expense.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1270,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the issuance of an enrollment card to an individual applying for enrollment to practice before the IRS?','[\"An enrolled agent can only practice before the IRS if his or her enrollment card is valid.\",\"An enrollment card is issued by the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"Each enrollment card is valid for the period stated on the card.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(b), states that the Internal Revenue Service will issue an enrollment or registration card or certificate to each individual whose application for enrollment to practice before the IRS is approved. Each card or certificate is valid for the period stated on the card or certificate. Finally, an individual is not eligible to practice before the IRS if the card or certificate is not valid.nnAs a result, all of the statements given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1271,9,'Harold, an enrolled agent, must exercise due diligence when preparing any document involving IRS matters:','[\"in preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters.\",\"in determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury.\",\"in determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"in all of the responses given.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides the general rule for a practitioner and due diligence as to accuracy. That is, a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to Internal Revenue Service matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service.nHence, the practitioner needs to exercise due diligence in all of the answer choices given in this question.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1272,9,'Sam is an enrolled agent and a partner in the firm of Taxes-R-Us, LLP. One of Sam\'s former partners is under investigation by the Internal Revenue Service for disreputable conduct. Sam has been asked by the IRS to provide information regarding his former partner. Sam must provide all the information requested unless:','[\"he has credible evidence that the former partner is not guilty of the disreputable conduct.\",\"he believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the information requested is privileged or that the request is of doubtful legality.\",\"the partnership agreement prohibits him from providing the information.\",\"the conduct in question relates to one of Sam\'s clients.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.20, a practitioner must, on a proper and lawful request by a duly authorized officer or employee of the IRS, promptly submit records or information in any matter before the IRS unless the practitioner believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the records or information are privileged.nnHence, Sam must provide all information requested unless he believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the records or information are privileged.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1273,9,'An EA prepares income tax returns for a client. After the client signs and mails the returns, the EA discovers an error. According to Treasury Circular 230, the EA must:','[\"document the error in workpapers.\",\"prepare an amended return within 30 days of the discovery of the error.\",\"promptly advise the client of the error.\",\"promptly resign from the engagement and cooperate with the successor accountant.\"]',2,'When an error is found in a return that has previously been filed with the IRS, the EA must promptly notify the client of the error. After notification, the EA should be available to file an amended return to correct the error, if agreed to by the client.nnIn addition, the practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1274,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the renewal of enrollment by an enrolled agent?','[\"An enrolled agent whose Social Security number ends with the number 4 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2024, and January 31, 2025.\",\"The renewal of enrollment is effective on April 1 for an individual who properly completes the renewal process.\",\"Failure to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will justify an individual\'s failure to satisfy this requirement.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(d), provides the rules associated with renewal of enrollment as an enrolled agent or enrolled retirement plan agent. In particular, an enrolled agent whose Social Security number ends with the number 0, 1, 2, or 3 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2024, and January 31, 2025, and thereafter every 3 years. Those with a Social Security number that ends with the number 4, 5, or 6 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2025, and January 31, 2026, and those with a number that ends with the number 7, 8, or 9 must apply for renewal between November 1, 2026, and January 31, 2027.nnIn addition, the renewal of enrollment is effective on April 1 of the renewal year (i.e., 2025 for those with a Social Security number that ends with the number 0, 1, 2, or 3) for an individual who properly completes the renewal process. Finally, failure to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will not justify an individual\'s failure to satisfy this requirement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1275,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning an enrolled agent?','[\"An agent is permitted to charge any amount of fee to represent a client before the IRS.\",\"The Service provides a fee structure for agents to charge when representing a client before the IRS.\",\"An agent is expected to provide free service to represent a client before the IRS if the agent prepared the return.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'“A practitioner may not charge an unconscionable fee for representing a client in a matter before the Internal Revenue Service” (Circular 230, Section 10.27(a)). In addition, a practitioner cannot charge a contingent fee for service rendered in connection with any matter before the IRS with certain exceptions as covered under Circular 230, Section 10.27(b) and provided below.nnA practitioner may charge a contingent fee for services rendered in connection with the Service’s examination of, or challenge to:nnan original tax return ornan amended return or claim for refund or credit where the amended return or claim for refund or credit was filed within 120 days of the taxpayer receiving a written notice of the examination of, or a written challenge to the original tax return.nIn addition, a practitioner may charge a contingent fee for services rendered in connection with a claim for credit or refund filed solely in connection with the determination of statutory interest or penalties assessed by the Internal Revenue Service.nnFinally, a practitioner may charge a contingent fee for services rendered in connection with any judicial proceeding arising under the Internal Revenue Code (IRC).nnLikewise, the Service does not provide a fee structure for agents to charge when representing a client before the IRS, and an agent is not expected to provide free service to represent a client before the IRS if the agent prepared the return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1276,9,'While preparing a client\'s individual federal tax return, the EA noticed that there was an error in the previous year\'s tax return that was prepared by another tax return preparer. The EA has which of the following responsibilities to this client?','[\"Inform the client and recommend corrective action\",\"Inform the client and the previous tax return preparer in writing and leave it to their discretion whether a correction should be made.\",\"Discuss the matter verbally with the former tax return preparer and suggest that corrective action be taken for the client.\",\"Notify the IRS if the error could be considered fraudulent or could involve other taxpayers.\"]',0,'Under the confidentiality rules, the tax practitioner is prohibited from discussing tax return information with anyone without the prior consent of the client. Treasury Circular 230, Section 10.21 requires tax practitioners to promptly inform a taxpayer of any error or omission or other noncompliance that the tax practitioner becomes aware of. The practitioner must also inform that taxpayer of the consequences of such error or omission or other noncompliance.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1277,9,'Who presides over a hearing on a complaint for disbarment based on a violation of the laws or regulations governing practice before the IRS?','[\"The Commissioner of IRS\",\"An Administrative Law Judge\",\"A U.S. Tax Court Judge\",\"The Secretary of the Treasury\"]',1,'In accordance with Circular 230, Section 10.72, an Administrative Law Judge will preside at the hearing on a complaint filed under Section 10.60 for the censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner, employer, firm, or other entity or disqualification of an appraiser.nnHearings will be stenographically recorded and transcribed and the testimony of witnesses will be taken under oath or affirmation. Hearings will be conducted pursuant to 5 USC 556.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1278,9,'Which of the following statements is correct regarding a tax return preparer\'s penalty for aiding and abetting the understatement of a tax liability?','[\"The penalty applies to a person who provides only clerical assistance.\",\"The penalty does not apply if another penalty is assessed with respect to the same action.\",\"The taxpayer must have knowledge of the action causing the penalty for the penalty to apply.\",\"The penalty applies to a return preparer who knows about and does not prevent the actions of a subordinate who understates the tax liability.\\n\"]',3,'A practitioner may be sanctioned for giving false or misleading information or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information to the Department of the Treasury, or any officer or employee thereof, or to any tribunal authorized to pass upon federal tax matters, in connection with any matter pending or likely to be pending before them, knowing the information to be false or misleading. Facts or other matters contained in testimony, federal tax returns, financial statements, applications for enrollment, affidavits, declarations, and any other document or statement, written or oral, are included in the term “information.”nnA subordinate would be considered to be under the control of practitioner and thus the practitioner would be participating in understating the tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1279,9,'After a decision has been made on a complaint filed against a practitioner, the practitioner or the IRS may appeal the decision. Which statement is correct with respect to filing an appeal of the decision?','[\"Within 30 days from the date of the District Court Judge\'s decision, either party may appeal to the Secretary of the Treasury, or his or her delegate deciding appeals.\",\"Within 30 days from the date of the District Court Judge\'s decision, either party may appeal to the Supreme Court.\",\"Within 30 days from the date of the Administrative Law Judge\'s decision, either party may appeal to the Secretary of the Treasury, or his or her delegate deciding appeals.\",\"Within 45 days from the date of the Administrative Law Judge\'s decision, either party may appeal to the Secretary of the Treasury, or his or her delegate deciding appeals.\"]',2,'According to Circular 230, Section 10.77, either party may appeal to the Secretary of the Treasury or his or her delegate deciding appeals.nnThe notice of appeal and brief must be filed, in duplicate, with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals, at an address for appeals that is identified to the parties with the decision of the Administrative Law Judge. The notice of appeal and brief must be filed within 30 days of the date that the decision of the Administrative Law Judge is served on the parties. The appealing party must serve a copy of the notice of appeal and the brief to any non-appealing party or, if the party is represented, the non-appealing party\'s representative.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1280,9,'Frank Maple, a certified public accountant, represents his brother, Joe Maple, and Joe\'s business partner, Bill Smith. Joe Maple and Bill Smith are equal shareholders in the Joe & Bill Corporation. The Internal Revenue Service examined the corporation and determined that one of the shareholders committed fraud, but could not determine which shareholder it was. Frank has made an appointment with the Internal Revenue Service to determine which partner was guilty. Which of the following statements reflects what Frank should do in accordance with Circular 230?','[\"Meet with the Internal Revenue Service and try to convince the examiner that each shareholder is equally guilty.\",\"Advise Joe and Bill that they should dissolve the corporation, thereby making it difficult for the Internal Revenue Service to pursue the issue.\",\"Advise Joe and Bill that he cannot represent them because there is a conflict of interest.\",\"Advise Joe and Bill on creating documents that will convince the Internal Revenue Service that neither shareholder is guilty of fraud.\"]',2,'According to Circular 230, a conflict of interest exists if:nnthe representation of one client will be directly adverse to another client ornthere is a significant risk that the representation of one or more clients will be materially limited by the practitioner\'s responsibilities to another client, a former client or a third person, or by a personal interest of the practitioner.nIn this case, Frank would need to advise Joe and Bill that he cannot represent them because there is a conflict of interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1281,9,'Ray was suspended from practice for 4 months by the Internal Revenue Service. Which of the following is Ray permitted to do during the period of suspension?','[\"Appear as a witness for the taxpayer\",\"Sign closing agreements regarding tax liabilities\",\"Represent taxpayers before the IRS with respect to returns Ray did\\u00a0not\\u00a0prepare\",\"Sign a consent to extend the statute of limitations for the assessment and collection of tax\"]',0,'The effect of a suspension is covered by Circular 230, Section 10.79(b). In particular, when the final decision in a case is against the respondent (or the respondent has offered his or her consent and such consent has been accepted by the Internal Revenue Service) and such decision is for suspension, the respondent will not be permitted to practice before the IRS during the period of suspension.nnPractice before the IRS covers all matters as provided in Circular 230 relating to any of the following per Publication 947, page 3:nnCommunicating with the IRS for a taxpayer regarding the taxpayer’s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws and regulations administered by the IRSnRepresenting a taxpayer at conferences, hearings, or meetings with the IRSnPreparing and filing documents, including tax returns, with the IRS for a taxpayernProviding a client with written tax advice on one or more Federal tax mattersnFurnishing information at the request of the IRS or appearing as a witness for the taxpayer is not practice before the IRS.nnAs a result, Ray would not be able to sign closing agreements regarding tax liabilities, represent taxpayers before the IRS with respect to tax returns, he did not prepare, or sign a consent to extend the statute of limitations for the assessment and collection of tax. In fact, the only thing that Ray is permitted to do is to appear as a witness for the taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1282,9,'A tax preparer has advised a company to take a position on its tax return. The tax preparer believes that there is a 75% probability the position will be sustained if audited by the IRS. If the position is not sustained, an accuracy-related penalty and a late-payment penalty would apply. What is the tax preparer\'s responsibility regarding disclosure of the penalty to the company?','[\"The tax preparer is responsible for disclosing the risk of both penalties to the company.\",\"The tax preparer is responsible for disclosing only the accuracy-related penalty to the company.\",\"The tax preparer is responsible for disclosing only the late-payment penalty to the company.\",\"The tax preparer has no responsibility for disclosing any potential penalties to the company, because the position will probably be sustained on audit.\"]',0,'A practitioner must inform a client of any and all penalties that might to apply to the client with respect to a position taken on a tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1283,9,'Sandy is an enrolled agent. She is preparing a brochure to hand to prospective clients and would like to explain the designation “enrolled agent.” Which of the following statements is Sandy not permitted to use?','[\"\\u201cI am enrolled to practice before the IRS.\\u201d\",\"\\u201cI am enrolled to represent taxpayers before the IRS.\\u201d\",\"\\u201cI am certified by the IRS.\\u201d\",\"\\u201cI am admitted to practice before the IRS.\\u201d\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.30, presents the general rules on solicitation, advertising, and solicitation restrictions. In particular, “A practitioner may not, with respect to any Internal Revenue Service matter, in any way use or participate in the use of any form of public communication or private solicitation containing a false, fraudulent, or coercive statement or claim; or a misleading or deceptive statement or claim.”nnEnrolled agents, in describing their professional designation, may not utilize the term “certified” or imply an employer/employee relationship with the IRS. Examples of acceptable descriptions are “enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service,” “enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service,” and “admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.”nnTherefore, Sandy is able to inform people of her status of being an enrolled agent by indicating that she is enrolled to practice before the IRS, she is enrolled to represent taxpayers before the IRS, or she is admitted to practice before the IRS. Circular 230 goes on to say that an enrolled agent may not utilize the term of “certified” or imply an employer/employee relationship with the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1284,9,'What is the exception for an unreasonable position on a tax return if the position was disclosed and is not a tax shelter or reportable transaction?','[\"There is or was substantial authority for the position.\",\"There is reasonable basis for the position.\",\"The position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.\",\"There is a 1-in-3, or greater, likelihood of being sustained on its merits.\"]',1,'A tax return preparer is liable for a penalty under IRC Section 6694(a) (i.e., penalty for understatement due to unreasonable position) unless they satisfy an exception provided for the defined three categories: general, disclosed position, and tax shelter or reportable transaction.nnThe general category exception is satisfied if there is or was substantial authority for the position.nThe disclosed position category exception, which pertains to this question, is satisfied if item 3 (below) does not apply and there is reasonable basis for the position.nThe tax shelter or reportable transaction category exception is satisfied unless it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.nIn addition, no penalty shall be imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1285,9,'An appeal from the initial decision ordering disbarment is made to which of the following?','[\"The Secretary of the Treasury\",\"The Administrative Law Judge\",\"The U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia\",\"The U.S. Tax Court\"]',0,'Within 180 days after the conclusion of a hearing and the receipt of any proposed findings and conclusions timely submitted by the parties, the Administrative Law Judge should enter a decision in the case. (Circular 230, Section 10.76)nnCircular 230, Section 10.77(a), further provides that any party to the proceeding under Subpart D of Circular 230 (i.e., \"Rules Applicable to Disciplinary Proceedings\") may appeal the decision of the Administrative Law Judge by filing a notice of appeal with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals. The notice of appeal must include a brief that states exceptions to the decision of Administrative Law Judge and supporting reasons for such exceptions.nnThe notice of appeal and brief must be filed, in duplicate, with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals, at an address for appeals that is identified to the parties with the decision of the Administrative Law Judge. The notice of appeal and brief must be filed within 30 days of the date that the decision of the Administrative Law Judge is served on the parties. The appealing party must serve a copy of the notice of appeal and the brief to any non-appealing party or, if the party is represented, the non-appealing party\'s representative.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1286,9,'Tax return preparers can be subject to penalties under the Internal Revenue Code for failure to do any of the following, except:','[\"sign a tax return as a preparer.\",\"disclose a conflict of interest.\",\"provide a client with a copy of the tax return.\",\"keep a record of returns prepared.\"]',1,'The tax preparer must sign the tax return and include the preparer\'s address and IRS identification number. A copy of the return must be provided to the taxpayer when the return is signed. The tax preparer must maintain a file of returns and log of all returns for three years after the close of the return period. These are all addressed in the Internal Revenue Code; conflict of interest is not.nnThe rule regarding conflicts of interest is contained in Treasury Circular 230.nnThe tax preparer is not allowed to represent conflicting interests before the IRS. However, each affected client can give consent and waive the conflict of interest. No penalty is designated for a conflict of interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1287,9,'Under Treasury Circular 230, which of the following actions of an EA tax advisor is characteristic of a best practice in rendering tax advice?','[\"Requesting written evidence from a client that the fee proposal for tax advice has been approved by the board of directors\",\"Recommending to the client that the advisor\'s tax advice be made orally instead of in a written memorandum\",\"Establishing relevant facts, evaluating the reasonableness of assumptions and representations, and arriving at a conclusion supported by the law and facts in a tax memorandum\",\"Requiring the client to supply a written representation, signed under penalties of perjury, concerning the facts and statements provided to the EA for preparing a tax memorandum\"]',2,'According to Circular 230, Section 10.33 “best practices”, tax advisors should provide clients with the highest quality representation concerning Federal tax issues by adhering to best practices in providing advice and in preparing or assisting in the preparation of a submission to the Internal Revenue Service. Best practices include:nncommunicating clearly with the client regarding the terms of the engagement.nestablishing the facts, determining which facts are relevant, evaluating the reasonableness of any assumptions or representations, relating the applicable law to the relevant facts, and arriving at a conclusion supported by the law and the facts.nadvising the client regarding the import of the conclusions reached.nacting fairly and with integrity in practice before the Internal Revenue Service.nAdditionally, an EA can rely on information furnished by a client in the preparation of a tax memorandum. If the information seems to be incorrect, inconsistent, or incomplete, the EA must make reasonable inquiries. When the facts are established, then relevant tax law must be applied accurately to the known facts.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1288,9,'The disclosure of a tax return position will reduce or eliminate an accuracy-related penalty on the taxpayer in which of the following circumstances?','[\"The position is frivolous.\",\"The position is\\u00a0not\\u00a0properly substantiated.\",\"The position concerns a tax shelter with substantial authority.\",\"The position does\\u00a0not\\u00a0concern a tax shelter and has a reasonable basis.\"]',3,'A penalty can be imposed on a taxpayer who fails to pay a sufficient amount of estimated income taxes where an underpayment is due to the IRS defeating the taxpayer’s position on the tax return. Provided the taxpayer disclosed the tax return position and can show a reasonable basis for the position, and the position is not related to a tax shelter, any accuracy-related penalty may be reduced or eliminated.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1289,9,'Ms. Dent hired Lacy, an enrolled agent, to prepare her federal income tax return for 2024. While gathering information to prepare the return, Lacy discovered that Ms. Dent failed to file federal income tax returns for the 2022 and 2023 tax years. Circular 230 requires that Lacy do the following:','[\"Promptly advise Ms. Dent that she did not comply with the Internal Revenue laws by failing to file federal income tax returns for the 2022 and 2023 tax years.\",\"Refuse to prepare Ms. Dent\'s 2024 federal income tax return unless she files her 2022 and 2023 federal income tax returns.\",\"Inform the IRS that Ms. Dent did not file federal income tax returns for the 2022 and 2023 tax years.\",\"Both refuse to prepare Ms. Dent\'s 2024 federal income tax return unless she files her 2022 and 2023 federal income tax returns and inform the IRS that Ms. Dent did not file federal income tax returns for the 2022 and 2023 tax years.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.21, addresses the issue of knowledge of client\'s omission by a person practicing before the IRS. In particular, each attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary who, having been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the IRS, knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper, which the client is required by the revenue laws of the United States to execute, shall advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission. Also, the practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnIn this problem, Lacy must advise Ms. Dent of her noncompliance in filing the earlier year tax returns.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1290,9,'Mike is an enrolled agent. Widget, Inc., is an accrual basis taxpayer. In 2025, while preparing Widget\'s 2024 return, Mike discovered that Widget failed to include income on its 2023 return that Widget received in 2024, but that should have been included in income in 2023 under the accrual method of accounting. What must Mike do?','[\"Advise Widget of the error and the consequences of the error.\",\"Include the income on the 2024 return.\",\"Refuse to prepare Widget\'s 2024 return until Widget agrees to amend its 2023 return to include the amount in income.\",\"Change Widget to the cash method of accounting.\"]',0,'Upon learning of the company\'s failure to record income in the proper year, Mike is obligated to notify the company of the error and its tax consequence as an enrolled agent.nnCircular 230, Section 10.21, provides that a practitioner who, having been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the IRS, knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper which the client submitted or executed under the revenue laws of the United States, must advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnThe practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1291,9,'The IRS requested client records from a tax return preparer who does not have possession or control of the records. According to Treasury Circular 230, the tax return preparer must:','[\"notify the IRS of the identity of any person the tax return preparer believes could have the records.\",\"require the client to submit the records to the IRS or withdraw from the engagement.\",\"obtain the records from the client and submit them to the IRS.\",\"contact all third parties associated with the records, such as banks and employers, to obtain the requested records for submission to the IRS.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Treasury Circular 230, Section 10.20(a), “A practitioner must, on a proper and lawful request by a duly authorized officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service, promptly submit records or information in any matter before the Internal Revenue Service unless the practitioner believes in good faith and on reasonable grounds that the records or information are privileged.”nnIn addition, “Where the requested records or information are not in the possession of, or subject to the control of, the practitioner or the practitioner’s client, the practitioner must promptly notify the requesting Internal Revenue Service officer or employee and the practitioner must provide any information that the practitioner has regarding the identity of any person who the practitioner believes may have possession or control of the requested records or information.”nnHence, the tax return preparer must notify the IRS of the identity of any person who, according to the tax return preparer’s belief, could have the records.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1292,9,'In preparing a client\'s current-year individual income tax return, a tax practitioner discovers an error in the prior year\'s return. Under the rules of practice prescribed in Treasury Circular 230, the tax practitioner:','[\"is barred from preparing the current year\'s return until the prior-year error is rectified.\",\"must advise the client of the error.\",\"is required to notify the IRS of the error.\",\"must file an amended return to correct the error.\"]',1,'Treasury Circular 230 requires tax practitioners to promptly inform a taxpayer of any error or omission or other noncompliance that the tax practitioner becomes aware of. The practitioner must also inform that taxpayer of the consequences of such error or omission or other noncompliance.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1293,9,'Which of the following statements is correct for Edward, an enrolled agent?','[\"He may knowingly employ a person who has been suspended but\\u00a0not\\u00a0someone disbarred by the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"He may knowingly accept employment from a person who has been suspended by the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"He may knowingly accept employment from a person who has been disbarred by the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"He may\\u00a0not\\u00a0knowingly employ a person who has been suspended or disbarred by the Internal Revenue Service.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.24, provides information pertaining to assistance from disbarred or suspended persons and former IRS employees. In particular, no attorney, certified public accountant, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary shall, in practice before the IRS, knowingly and directly or indirectly:nnemploy or accept assistance from any person who is under disbarment or suspension from practice before the Internal Revenue Service, if the assistance relates to matters constituting practice before the IRS, ornaccept assistance from any former government employee where the provisions of Section 10.25 (\"Practice by former government employees, their partners and their associates\") or any federal law would be violated.nTherefore, Edward cannot employ a person or accept employment from a person who has been suspended or disbarred.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1294,9,'If a practitioner is disbarred from practice before the IRS, when may a practitioner petition for reinstatement?','[\"After 1 year\",\"After 3 years\",\"After 5 years\",\"After 10 years\"]',2,'A practitioner disbarred or suspended may petition for reinstatement before the Internal Revenue Service after 5 years. Reinstatement is not granted unless the IRS is assured that the petitioner is not likely to repeat the actions that led to the disbarment, and that granting such reinstatement would not be contrary to the public interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1295,9,'In August 2023, Jake, an attorney, is charged by the Internal Revenue Service with acts of misconduct, and a complaint is served upon him. What is the least number of days that the Internal Revenue Service can give Jake?','[\"No less than 10 days from the date of service to file an answer\",\"No less than 15 days from the date of service to file an answer\",\"No less than 30 days from the date of service to file an answer\",\"No less than 45 days from the date of service to file an answer\"]',2,'Under Section 10.62(c) of Circular 230, the Internal Revenue Service must, in the complaint or in a separate paper attached to the complaint, notify the respondent of:nnthe time for answering the complaint, which may not be less than 30 days from the date the complaint is served,nthe name and address of the Administrative Law Judge with whom the answer must be filed,nthe name and address of the person representing the Internal Revenue Service to whom a copy of the answer must be served, andnthat a decision by default may be rendered against the respondent in the event an answer is not filed as required.nJake, therefore, must be given at least 30 days to respond to the complaint.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1296,9,'Sandra, an enrolled agent, prepares Linda\'s income tax return for the current tax year. Linda sold some stock in a corporation and believes the proceeds of the stock are all a return of capital and, therefore, not included in her gross income. After research, Sandra determines that the transaction is not a tax shelter or reportable transaction and there is reasonable basis for Linda\'s position. Under what circumstances can Sandra sign Linda\'s return if the proceeds are not included in income reported on the return and do not violate the unreasonable position standard under IRC Section 6694?','[\"If the position is disclosed on the tax return\",\"If Sandra documents her disagreement with Linda\'s position and keeps it in her file\",\"If Linda agrees in writing not to dispute any IRS challenge to the position\",\"Under no circumstances\"]',0,'A tax return preparer is liable for a penalty under IRC Section 6694(a) (i.e., penalty for understatement due to unreasonable position) unless they satisfy an exception provided for the defined three categories: general, disclosed positions, and tax shelter or reportable transactions.nnThe general category exception is satisfied if there is or was substantial authority for the position.nThe disclosed position category exception, which pertains to this question, is satisfied if item 3 (below) does not apply and there is reasonable basis for the position.nThe tax shelter or reportable transaction category exception is satisfied unless it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.nIn addition, no penalty shall be imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.nnThus, Sandra can sign Linda\'s return if the position is disclosed, has reasonable basis, and is adequately disclosed on the return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1297,9,'Josephine Jones, an enrolled agent, received a complaint from the Internal Revenue Service. Select the statement below that is correct with respect to the contents of the answer that Josephine will file in rebuttal to the complaint.','[\"Josephine may only state a general denial of the allegations.\",\"Josephine must specifically admit or deny each allegation set forth in the complaint and may not state that she is without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation.\",\"Josephine may deny a material allegation in the complaint even though she knows it to be true.\",\"Josephine must specifically admit or deny each allegation set forth in the complaint, except that she may state that she is without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation.\"]',3,'According to Circular 230, Section 10.64, the answers by a respondent must be written and contain a statement of facts that constitute the respondent\'s grounds of defense. General denials are not permitted. The respondent must specifically admit or deny each allegation set forth in the complaint, except that the respondent may state that he or she is without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation. The respondent, nevertheless, may not deny a material allegation in the complaint that he or she knows to be true, or state that he or she is without sufficient information to form a belief, when the respondent possesses the required information. The respondent also must state affirmatively any special matters of defense on which he or she relies.nnTherefore, the only correct statement is the respondent must specifically admit or deny each allegation set forth in the complaint, except that she may state that she is without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1298,9,'Enrolled agents generally must complete continuing education credits for renewed enrollment. Which of the following describes the credit requirements?','[\"A minimum of 72 hours must be completed during each 3-year enrollment cycle.\",\"A minimum of 24 hours must be completed during each 3-year enrollment cycle.\",\"A minimum of 80 hours must be completed, overall, for the entire enrollment cycle.\",\"A minimum of 24 hours must be completed in each year of the enrollment cycle.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(e), provides tin order to qualify for renewal as an enrolled agent, an individual must certify, in the manner prescribed by the Internal Revenue Service, that the individual has satisfied the requisite number of hours for continuing education hours.nnA person must satisfy a minimum of 72 hours of continuing education credit (including 6 hours of ethics or professional conduct) during each 3-year period, which is known as an enrollment cycle. In addition, a person must satisfy a minimum of 16 hours of continuing education credit, including 2 hours of ethics or professional conduct, during each calendar year in the enrollment term.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1299,9,'A practitioner who is disbarred may seek reinstatement after:','[\"1 year.\",\"2 years.\",\"4 years.\",\"5 years.\"]',3,'The petition for reinstatement is addressed in Circular 230, Section 10.81(a). In general:nn\"A practitioner disbarred or suspended under Section 10.60, or suspended under Section 10.82, or a disqualified appraiser may petition for reinstatement before the Internal Revenue Service after the expiration of 5 years following such disbarment, suspension, or disqualification....Reinstatement will not be granted unless the Internal Revenue Service is satisfied that the petitioner is not likely to engage thereafter in conduct contrary to the regulations in this part, and that granting such reinstatement would not be contrary to the public interest.\"',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1300,9,'Generally, each individual who applies for renewal to practice before the Internal Revenue Service must retain the information required with regard to qualifying continuing professional education hours. How long must verification of CE taken be retained?','[\"For a period of 5 years following the date of renewal of enrollment\",\"For a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment\",\"For a period of 1 year following the date of renewal of enrollment\",\"For a period of 3 years if it is an initial enrollment\"]',1,'The recordkeeping requirements for qualifying continuing professional education by an enrolled agent are found in Circular 230, Section 10.6(h). Each individual applying for renewal must retain for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment the information required with regard to qualifying continuing professional education credit hours.nnSuch information includes:nnthe name of the sponsoring organization,nthe location of the program,nthe title of the program and description of its content,nwritten outlines, course syllabi, textbook, and/or electronic materials provided or required for the course,nthe dates attended,nthe credit hours claimed,nthe name(s) of the instructor(s), discussion leader(s), or speaker(s), if appropriate, andnthe certificate of completion and/or signed statement of the hours of attendance obtained from the continuing education provider.nHence, the correct response for this problem is an enrolled agent must retain for verification of CE taken for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1301,9,'To maintain active enrollment to practice before the Internal Revenue Service, each individual enrolled is required to have his or her enrollment renewed. The Internal Revenue Service will notify the individual of his or her renewal of enrollment and will issue the individual a card to evidence enrollment. Which of the following statements about renewal of enrollment is correct?','[\"A reasonable refundable fee may be charged for each application for renewal of enrollment filed with the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"Failure by an individual to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will not be justification for the failure to timely renew enrollment.\",\"Forms required for renewal may only be obtained from the National Association of Enrolled Agents.\",\"The enrollment cycle is a 3-year period and all enrolled agents must renew at the same time, no matter when they first became enrolled agents.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.6, provides the general rules for enrollment of enrolled agents, enrolled retirement plan agents, and registered tax return preparers before the Internal Revenue Service. Paragraph (d) provides the rules for renewal of enrollment. Specifically, enrolled agents and enrolled retirement plan agents must renew their status with the IRS to maintain eligibility to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.nnFailure by an individual to receive notification from the Internal Revenue Service of the renewal requirement will not be justification for the failure to satisfy this requirement. (Circular 230, Section 10.6(d)(1))',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1302,9,'What must an enrolled agent have in order to prepare, sign, and submit a client\'s tax return?','[\"Registration card\",\"Preparer tax identification number\",\"Either a registration card or a preparer tax identification number is necessary.\",\"Both a registration card and a preparer tax identification number are necessary.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.6(b), the IRS will issue an enrollment or registration card or certificate to each individual whose application to practice before the IRS is approved. Each card or certificate will be valid for the period stated on the card or certificate. An enrolled agent, enrolled retirement plan agent, or registered tax return preparer may not practice before the IRS if the card or certificate is not current or otherwise valid. The card or certificate is in addition to any notification that may be provided to each individual who obtains a preparer tax identification number (PTIN).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1303,9,'When must a practitioner exercise due diligence?','[\"In determining the correctness of oral or written representations in any matter administered by the IRS\",\"In preparing, approving, and filing returns\",\"In determining the correctness of oral or written representations by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'A practitioner must exercise due diligence in:nndetermining the correctness of oral or written representations in any matter administered by the IRS,npreparing, approving, and filing returns, andndetermining the correctness of oral or written representations by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1304,9,'In the process of preparing Purple Corporation\'s 2023 return, John, an enrolled agent, provided to Purple Corporation calculations he had prepared computing basis of property, which was sold and reported on the Form 4797 filed with Form 1120. Later, when Purple Corporation\'s 2023 return was examined by the Internal Revenue Service, Purple Corporation refused to provide the Internal Revenue Service with the calculations, claiming that this was a privileged communication between Purple and its federally authorized practitioner. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Purple Corporation does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because it is privileged under the Federal Tax Practitioner privilege rules.\",\"Purple Corporation must provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because privilege does not apply to a determination with respect to an item that will be presented to the government on an original return.\",\"Purple Corporation must provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because the Federal Tax Practitioner privilege does not apply to documents written by John, as he is not a CPA.\",\"Purple Corporation does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service if they believe this transaction might be construed as a tax shelter.\"]',1,'Generally, the same confidentiality protection that you have with an attorney also applies to certain communications that you have with federally authorized practitioners. \"Federal authorized tax practitioners\" means any individuals who are authorized under federal law to practice before the IRS, including attorneys, certified public accountants, enrolled agents, enrolled actuaries, and certain other individuals allowed to practice before the IRS.nnConfidential communications are those that:nnadvise you on tax matters within the scope of the practitioner\'s authority to practice before the IRS,nwould be confidential between an attorney and you, andnrelate to noncriminal tax matters before the IRS ornrelate to noncriminal tax proceedings brought in federal court by or against the United States.nAs such, Purple Corporation must provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because privilege does not apply to a determination with respect to an item that will be presented to the government on an original return. (See also IRC Section 7525(a).)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1305,9,'The IRS began an examination of Mr. Jones\' 2023 income tax return. Mr. Jones hired Tyler, an enrolled agent and former IRS employee, to represent him before the IRS. Tyler wrote a memorandum to Mr. Jones outlining the issues that might be raised by the IRS and how to address these issues. Tyler correctly marked this memorandum as confidential and privileged under Section 7525 of the Internal Revenue Code. During the examination, the Revenue Officer assigned to the case asked Tyler for a copy of the memorandum. Mr. Jones, invoking the Section 7525 privilege, told Tyler not to disclose it to the Revenue Officer. Tyler is not required to provide the Revenue Officer with a copy of the memorandum because:','[\"the Revenue Officer did not issue a summons requesting it.\",\"Section 7525 extends the attorney client privilege to federally authorized tax practitioners.\",\"Circular 230 does not authorize officers or employees of the IRS to request any documents other than a tax return.\",\"the IRS cannot request documents during an examination.\"]',1,'IRC Section 7525(a)(1) provides the general rule for confidentiality privileges relating to taxpayer communications. In particular, and with respect to tax advice, the same common-law protections of confidentiality which apply to a communication between a taxpayer and an attorney shall also apply to a communication between a taxpayer and any federally authorized tax practitioner to the extent the communication would be considered a privileged communication if it were between a taxpayer and an attorney.nnHence, Tyler is not required to provide the Revenue Officer with a copy of the memorandum.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1306,9,'Frank, an enrolled agent, has the right to make solicitations of employment involving IRS matters:','[\"unless it violates federal or state law.\",\"as long as it clearly identifies the solicitation and the source for choosing the recipient.\",\"unless it violates a practitioner\'s professional code of conduct rules.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.30, provides the general rules for solicitation of new business. In particular, a practitioner may not make, directly or indirectly, an uninvited written or oral solicitation of employment in matters related to the Internal Revenue Service if the solicitation violates federal or state law or other applicable rules, e.g., attorneys are precluded from making a solicitation that is prohibited by conduct rules applicable to all attorneys in their state(s) of licensure. Any lawful solicitation made by or on behalf of a practitioner eligible to practice before the Internal Revenue Service must, nevertheless, clearly identify the solicitation as such and, if applicable, identify the source of the information used in choosing the recipient.nnThus, all of the responses are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1307,9,'Annie Holt, an enrolled agent, was issued findings of fact, conclusions of law, and a decision ruling that she committed acts of misconduct, which were violations under Circular 230, and therefore a decision was entered ruling that she should be disbarred. Which of the following statements is correct about Annie Holt?','[\"Annie has a right to appeal within 15 days from the date of the Administrative Law Judge\'s decision.\",\"Annie has a right to appeal within 30 days from the date of the Administrative Law Judge\'s decision.\",\"Annie has a right to appeal within 45 days from the date of the Administrative Law Judge\'s decision.\",\"The Administrative Law Judge\'s decision is final and thus Annie is not able to appeal the decision.\"]',1,'The decision of the Administrative Law Judge may be appealed in accordance with Circular 230, Section 10.77. That is, either party may appeal the decision of the Administrative Law Judge by filing a notice of appeal with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals. The notice of appeal must include a brief that states exceptions to the decision of the Administrative Law Judge and supporting reasons for such exceptions.nnThe notice of appeal and brief must be filed, in duplicate, with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals, at an address for appeals that is identified to the parties with the decision of the Administrative Law Judge. The notice of appeal and brief must be filed within 30 days of the date that the decision of the Administrative Law Judge is served on the parties. The appealing party must serve a copy of the notice of appeal and the brief to any non-appealing party or, if the party is represented, the non-appealing party\'s representative.nnWithin 30 days of receiving the copy of the appellant\'s brief, the other party may file a response brief with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals, using the address identified for appeals. A copy of the response brief must be served at the same time on the opposing party or, if the party is represented, the opposing party\'s representative.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1308,9,'Pursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.22, a practitioner must exercise due diligence:','[\"in preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to IRS matters.\",\"in determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury.\",\"in determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the IRS.\\n\",\"in all of the responses given.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides that a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to IRS matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the IRS.nFurthermore, a practitioner will be presumed to have exercised due diligence for purposes of this section if the practitioner relies on the work product of another person and the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1309,9,'While preparing a tax return for a new client and reviewing the client\'s prior-year return, a tax return preparer noticed an error made by the client\'s former tax preparer. According to Treasury Department Circular 230, which of the following is the tax return preparer specifically required to do in this case?','[\"Contact the tax return preparer who made the error and suggest that an amended return be prepared for the client.\",\"Inform the client of the error and insist that the return be amended.\",\"Inform the client of the error and advise of the consequences.\",\"Advise the client to contact the tax return preparer of the prior-year return.\"]',2,'Treasury Department Circular 230 requires a practitioner who knows that a client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper, to advise the client promptly of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnContacting the tax preparer who made the error and suggesting that an amended return be prepared for the client, informing the client of the error and insisting that the return be amended, or advising the client to contact the tax preparer of the prior-year return are not options provided for in this circumstance.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1310,9,'Failure to file an answer to a complaint instituting a proceeding for disbarment by the original or extended deadline constitutes:','[\"an admission of the allegations in the complaint and a waiver of a hearing.\",\"an error that can be corrected by filing the answer with the Administrative Law Judge within 1 year of the original (or extended) deadline.\",\"grounds for criminal sanctions.\",\"equitable estoppel against the practitioner.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.64, a respondent is expected to file an answer to a complaint instituting a proceeding for disbarment with the Administrative Law Judge, and served on the Internal Revenue Service, within the time specified in the complaint unless, on request or application of the respondent, the time is extended by the Administrative Law Judge.nnThe answers must be written and contain a statement of facts that constitute the respondent\'s grounds of defense. General denials are not permitted. The respondent must specifically admit or deny each allegation set forth in the complaint, except that the respondent may state that the respondent is without sufficient information to admit or deny a specific allegation. The respondent, nevertheless, may not deny a material allegation in the complaint that the respondent knows to be true, or state that the respondent is without sufficient information to form a belief, when the respondent possesses the required information. The respondent also must state affirmatively any special matters of defense on which he or she relies.nnEvery allegation in the complaint that is not denied in the answer is deemed admitted and will be considered proved; no further evidence in respect of such allegation need be adduced at a hearing.nnFurthermore, failure to file an answer within the time prescribed (or within the time for answer as extended by the Administrative Law Judge), constitutes an admission of the allegations of the complaint and a waiver of hearing, and the Administrative Law Judge may make the decision by default without a hearing or further procedure. A decision by default constitutes a decision under Section 10.76.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1311,9,'When advertising their services, an enrolled agent may use which one of the following phrases to describe their professional designation?','[\"Certified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Enrolled as a representative of the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Licensed to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\"]',1,'Enrolled agents, enrolled retirement plan agents, or registered tax return preparers, in describing their professional designation, may not utilize the term \"certified\" or imply an employer/employee relationship with the Internal Revenue Service. Examples of acceptable descriptions for enrolled agents are \"enrolled to represent taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service,\" \"enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service,\" and \"admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.\"nnnThe correct answer is admitted to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1312,9,'How much time does a person have to timely appeal an initial decision ordering disbarment?','[\"15 days from the date of the decision\",\"30 days from the date of the decision\",\"45 days from the date of the decision\",\"There is no appeal from this decision.\"]',1,'Proceedings on complaints for the censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner or the disqualification of an appraiser will be conducted by an Administrative Law Judge appointed as provided by 5 USC 3105. (Circular 230, Section 10.70)nnCircular 230, Section 10.77, provides that the notice of appeal and brief must be filed, in duplicate, with the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate deciding appeals, at an address for appeals that is identified to the parties with the decision of the Administrative Law Judge. The notice of appeal and brief must be filed within 30 days of the date that the decision of the Administrative Law Judge is served on the parties. The appealing party must serve a copy of the notice of appeal and the brief to any non-appealing party or, if the party is represented, the non-appealing party\'s representative.nnHence, the respondent has 30 days from the date of the decision to appeal an initial decision ordering disbarment.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1313,9,'What does Circular 230 permit for an individual that is charged with violating the regulations under Circular 230?','[\"To appear in person\",\"To be represented by counsel\",\"To be represented by another practitioner\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.69(a)(2), provides that a respondent to disciplinary hearings may appear in person, be represented by a practitioner, or be represented by an attorney who has not filed a declaration with the IRS pursuant to Section 10.3 (\"Who may practice\"). A practitioner or an attorney representing a respondent or proposed respondent may sign the answer or any document required to be filed in the proceeding on behalf of the respondent. Therefore, all the answer choices are correct. An individual charged with violating the regulations under Circular 230 may appear in person or be represented by counsel or another practitioner.nnIn addition, the Internal Revenue Service may be represented in the proceedings under this part by an attorney or other employee of the Internal Revenue Service.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1314,9,'According to the standards of the profession, which of the following statements is correct regarding the action to be taken by an EA who discovers an error in a client\'s previously filed tax return?nnI. Advise the client of the error and recommend the measures to be taken.nII. Withdraw from the professional relationship regardless of whether or not the client corrects the error.','[\"I only\",\"II only\",\"Both I and II\",\"Neither I nor II\"]',0,'When an EA discovers an error in a client\'s previously filed tax return, the EA should advise the client of the error and recommend the measures to be taken. If the client refuses to correct the error, the EA may consider withdrawing from the professional relationship; withdrawal is not required or expected if the client corrects the error.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1315,9,'Joseph Smith, an enrolled agent, has represented Stephen Francis before the Internal Revenue Service and also prepared returns for Stephen in each of the last 3 years. Stephen was divorced last year, and his ex-wife, Lindsay, stops by Joseph\'s office and asks Joseph to represent her before the Internal Revenue Service with respect to the examination of her return that she filed separately from her husband in a year in which they were separated but not yet divorced. Which of the following actions may Joseph undertake?','[\"Because the representation involves a tax return for which Lindsay filed separately, and Lindsay was separated at the time, Joseph may undertake the representation of Lindsay without considering whether a conflict of interest exists between Lindsay and her former spouse.\",\"Since Lindsay filed separately, Joseph is free to undertake the representation of Lindsay.\",\"Since Lindsay is divorced from Stephen, Joseph is free to undertake the representation of Lindsay.\",\"Even though the representation involves a tax return for which Lindsay filed separately, and Lindsay was separated at the time, Joseph may\\u00a0not\\u00a0undertake the representation of Lindsay without considering whether a conflict of interest exists between Lindsay and her former spouse.\"]',3,'According to Circular 230, section 10.29(a), a conflict of interest exists if:nnthe representation of one client will be directly adverse to another client, ORnthere is a significant risk that the representation of one or more clients will be materially limited by the practitioner\'s responsibilities to another client, a former client or a third person, or by a personal interest of the practitioner.nIn this case, the representation of Stephen\'s ex-wife by Joseph before the IRS on a tax return when the couple was not yet divorced could be directly adverse to Joseph, his current client. Hence, a conflict of interest is likely to exist between Lindsay and her former spouse.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1316,9,'Which of the following fee arrangements generally would not be permitted under the ethical standards published in the Treasury Department Circular 230?','[\"A referral fee paid by a CPA to obtain a client\",\"A commission for compiling a client\'s internal-use financial statements\",\"A contingent fee for preparing a client\'s income tax return\",\"A contingent fee for representing a client in tax court\"]',2,'Treasury Circular 230, section 10.27(c) defines a contingent fee as a fee that is based, in whole, or in part, on whether a position taken on a tax return or other filings avoids challenge by the Internal Revenue Service or is sustained either by the Internal Revenue Service or in litigation. For example, it would be prohibited for a tax return preparer\'s fee to increase if the tax refund increases. A contingent fee for preparing a client’s income tax return is not listed in Circular 230 as a permissible type of contingent fee, as defined in paragraphs (2), (3), and (4) of Section 10.27.nnCharging a contingent fee is permitted for representing a client in a tax examination or in tax court. Referral fees to obtain clients and commissions for compiling internal-use financial statements are permitted.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1317,9,'A tax preparer prepares a client\'s tax return containing business travel expenses, including the costs of operating an automobile used for business, without inquiring about the existence of documentation for any of the expenses. Which statement best describes the consequence of the tax preparer\'s lack of inquiry in the event of an IRS audit disallowing certain expenses?','[\"The tax preparer may be assessed a tax return preparer penalty.\",\"The tax preparer may be charged with preparing a fraudulent return.\",\"The client will not owe an understatement penalty if the return is audited and the expenses disallowed.\",\"The client will not be subject to a fraud penalty.\"]',0,'A tax preparer may in good faith rely on information provided by the client. The preparer should make reasonable inquiries if the information appears to be incorrect, incomplete, or inconsistent on the basis of known facts. Since documentation is required to deduct automobile expenses, the tax preparer may receive a tax return preparer penalty.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1318,9,'Identify the individual below who is not eligible to practice before the IRS. None of the individuals are under suspension or disbarment.','[\"Enrolled actuary, with respect to specified statutory issues\",\"Attorney\",\"Certified public accountant\",\"Certified financial planner\"]',3,'As provided in Circular 230, Section 10.3, any of the following individuals can practice before the IRS:nnAttorneysnCertified public accountants (CPAs)nEnrolled agentsnEnrolled actuaries, limited to certain issuesnEnrolled retirement plan agents, limited to certain issuesnRegistered tax return preparers, limited representation, and only for the 2014 tax filing seasonnAccordingly, a certified financial planner would not be eligible to practice before the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1319,9,'Under Treasury Circular 230, in which of the following situations is an EA prohibited from giving written advice concerning one or more federal tax issues?','[\"The EA takes into account the possibility that a tax return will not be audited.\",\"The EA reasonably relies upon representations of the client.\",\"The EA considers all relevant facts that are known.\",\"The EA takes into consideration assumptions about future events related to the relevant facts.\"]',0,'The EA should not recommend a tax return position that exploits the audit selection process of a taxing authority. The EA should not recommend extreme or doubtful positions simply because the chance of an audit is very low.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1320,9,'Able was requested by his client to represent him in connection with an IRS audit. What can be said about Able?','[\"Able must be either an attorney or a certified public accountant.\",\"Able is practicing before the IRS.\",\"Able cannot represent the client.\",\"Able must be an attorney, certified public accountant, or enrolled agent.\"]',1,'Throughout an examination, a taxpayer can act on their own behalf or have someone represent them or accompany them. If the taxpayer filed a joint tax return, the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s spouse, or both, can meet with the IRS. Furthermore, the taxpayer can have someone represent or accompany them. (Publication 556, page 3)nnThis person can be any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled agent (a person enrolled to practice before the IRS), an enrolled actuary, or the person who prepared the return and signed it as the preparer. Given the limited information, one must assume that Able prepared the client\'s tax return.nnPublication 947, page 3, states that practice before the IRS covers all matters relating to any of the following:nnCommunicating with the IRS for a taxpayer regarding the taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws and regulations administered by the IRSnRepresenting a taxpayer at conferences, hearings, or meetings with the IRSnPreparing, filing, or submitting documents, or advising on the preparation, filing, or submission of documents, including tax returns, with the IRS on behalf of a taxpayernProviding a client with written advice on one or more Federal tax mattersnFurnishing information at the request of the IRS or appearing as a witness for the taxpayer is not practice before the IRS.nnAs a result, one would say that Able is practicing before the IRS by representing his client in connection with an IRS audit.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1321,9,'What can be said about Paul, who is a barber and prepares federal tax returns for $25 apiece during the tax filing season?','[\"Paul is considered a tax return preparer.\",\"Paul is\\u00a0not\\u00a0considered a tax return preparer because his fee per return is below the threshold amount.\",\"Paul is\\u00a0not\\u00a0considered a tax return preparer because he does not employ anyone.\",\"Paul is\\u00a0not\\u00a0considered a tax return preparer.\"]',0,'IRC Section 7701(a)(36)(A) provides that the term “tax return preparer” means any person who prepares for compensation, or who employs one or more persons to prepare for compensation, any return of tax imposed by this title (Title 26, IRC) or any claim for refund of tax imposed by this title (Title 26, IRC). For purposes of the preceding sentence, the preparation of a substantial portion of a return or claim for refund shall be treated as if it were the preparation of such return or claim for refund.nnSince Paul is paid to prepare federal income tax returns, he is a tax return preparer. The amount of the compensation is irrelevant.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1322,9,'Treasury Circular 230 contains:','[\"rules of conduct applicable to enrolled agents, enrolled actuaries, attorneys, and certified public accountants.\",\"rules regarding disciplinary actions for violating the regulations.\",\"the rules regarding eligibility to become an enrolled agent and renewal of enrollment.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The rules regarding eligibility for enrollment as an enrolled agent and registered tax return preparers as well as the rules for renewal of enrollment are found in Circular 230, Sections 10.4 and 10.6(d), respectively.nnOne should be aware that the category of registered tax return preparers does not exist at this moment given the Loving decision in 2014 (Revenue Procedure 2014-42).nnCircular 230, Section 10.0 states, in part, that rules governing the recognition of attorneys, certified public accountants, enrolled agents, enrolled retirement plan agents, and other persons representing taxpayers before the IRS are provided in Circular 230. Moreover, Subpart C of Circular 230 prescribes the sanctions for violating the regulations, Subpart D contains the rules applicable to disciplinary proceedings, and Subpart E contains general provisions relating to the availability of official records.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1323,9,'Nancy had e-mail correspondence in 2022 with her longtime tax return preparer, an enrolled agent. The correspondence related to tax advice on the depreciation of rental property Nancy had acquired in 2022. Nancy never filed the 2022 or subsequent returns. Nancy was notified by the Internal Revenue Service that she is the subject of a criminal investigation for the failure to file her returns. The Internal Revenue Service has issued a subpoena to obtain the e-mails as part of its investigation. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the e-mails with her preparer?','[\"The e-mails are confidential communications between Nancy and her federally authorized practitioner.\",\"The e-mails are protected under Internal Revenue Code Section 7525.\",\"The e-mails are\\u00a0not\\u00a0confidential communications because this is a criminal investigation.\",\"The e-mails are seen to be privileged communications.\"]',2,'IRC Section 7525(a)(1) provides the general rule for confidentiality privileges relating to taxpayer communications. With respect to tax advice, the same common-law protections of confidentiality which apply to a communication between a taxpayer and an attorney shall also apply to a communication between a taxpayer and any federally authorized tax practitioner to the extent the communication would be considered a privileged communication if it were between a taxpayer and an attorney.nnIn addition, the above paragraph may only be asserted in any noncriminal tax matter before the IRS and any noncriminal tax proceeding in federal court brought by or against the United States. Confidentiality privileges will not apply to communication between a federally authorized tax practitioner and any person in connection with the promotion of the direct or indirect participation of the person in any tax shelter, under IRC Section 7525(b)(1).nnPublication 556, pages 3 and 4, states confidential communications are those that:nnadvise you on tax matters within the scope of the practitioner\'s authority to practice before the IRS,nwould be confidential between an attorney and you, andnrelate to noncriminal tax matters before the IRS, ornrelate to noncriminal tax proceedings brought in federal court by or against the United States.nSince this is a criminal investigation, Nancy\'s e-mails with her preparer are not confidential communications under Internal Revenue Code Section 7525.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1324,9,'Practice before the Internal Revenue Service comprehends all matters connected with a presentation to the Internal Revenue Service or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the Internal Revenue Service. Which of the following is not considered a practice before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"Preparing and filing documents\",\"Furnishing information at the request of the IRS\",\"Representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings\",\"Communicating with the IRS\"]',1,'Practice before the IRS comprehends all matters connected with a presentation to the IRS or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the IRS. Such presentations include, but are not limited to, preparing documents; filing documents; corresponding and communicating with the IRS; rendering written advice with respect to any entity, transaction, plan, or arrangement, or other plan or arrangement having a potential for tax avoidance or evasion; and representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings. (Circular 230, Section 10.2)nnAdditionally, any individual may for compensation prepare or assist with the preparation of a tax return or claim for refund (provided the individual prepares less than substantially all of the tax return or claim for refund), appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS, or furnish information at the request of the IRS or any of its officers or employees. (Circular 230, Section 10.8)nnFurthermore, just preparing a tax return, furnishing information at the request of the IRS, or appearing as a witness for the taxpayer is not practice before the IRS. These acts can be performed by anyone.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19');
INSERT INTO `tbl_unit_questions` VALUES (1325,9,'Which of the following is considered practice before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"Preparing a tax return for an individual\",\"Furnishing information at the request of the IRS\",\"Appearing as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS\",\"None of the answer choices are considered practice before the IRS.\"]',3,'Practice before the IRS comprehends all matters connected with a presentation to the IRS or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws and regulations administered by the IRS.nnSuch presentations include, but are not limited to:nnpreparing documents, filing documents, corresponding and communicating with the IRS;nrendering written advice with respect to any entity, transaction, plan or arrangement, or other plan or arrangement having a potential for tax avoidance or evasion; andnrepresenting a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings.nAdditionally, any individual may for compensation prepare or assist with the preparation of a tax return or claim for refund (provided the individual prepares less than substantially all of the tax return or claim for refund), appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the Internal Revenue Service, or furnish information at the request of the Internal Revenue Service or any of its officers or employees. In such cases, the individual would not be seen as practicing before the IRS.nnTherefore, none of the items listed in the question qualify as practice before the IRS; rather, only the above items given in the explanation are considered practice before the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1326,9,'Which of the following items are criteria for a person to enroll as an enrolled agent?nn1. The applicant demonstrates special competence in tax matters by written IRS (or its agent) examination.n2. The applicant refrains from engaging in any conduct that would justify suspension or disbarment.n3. The applicant possesses a current or otherwise valid preparer tax identification number or other prescribed identifying number.','[\"Item 1 only\",\"Items 1 and 2 only\",\"Items 1 and 3 only\",\"Items 1, 2, and 3\"]',3,'To practice before the IRS as an enrolled agent, a person must apply as required by forms or procedures established and published by the Internal Revenue Service, including proper execution of required forms under oath or affirmation (Circular 230, Section 10.5(a)).nnPursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.4(a), the Commissioner of the IRS, or delegate, will grant enrollment as an enrolled agent to an applicant 18 years of age or older \"who demonstrates special competence in tax matters by written examination administered by, or administered under the oversight of, the Internal Revenue Service, who possesses a current or otherwise valid preparer tax identification number or other prescribed identifying number, and who has not engaged in any conduct that would justify the suspension or disbarment of any practitioner under the provisions of this part.\"',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1327,9,'Jane is a certified public accountant who specializes in preparing federal tax returns. Which of the following returns would qualify Jane as a tax return preparer?','[\" Estate or gift tax returns\",\"Excise tax returns\",\"Withholding tax returns\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Regulation Section 301.7701-15(a), a tax return preparer is any person who prepares for compensation, or who employs one or more persons to prepare for compensation, all or a substantial portion of any return of tax or any claim for refund of tax under the Internal Revenue Code.nnAs a result, Jane\'s areas of expertise would qualify her as a tax return preparer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1328,9,'The following is authorized to represent a taxpayer before the IRS:','[\"An individual representing a member of his\\/her immediate family\",\"A regular full-time employee of an individual employer representing the employer\",\"An officer or full-time employee of a corporation representing the corporation\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Due to a special relationship with a taxpayer, the following unenrolled individuals can represent the specified taxpayers before the IRS, provided they present satisfactory identification and, except in the case of an individual described in item 1 below, proof of authority to represent the taxpayer:nnAn individual can represent himself or herself before the IRS and does not have to file a written declaration of qualification and authority.nAn individual can represent members of his or her immediate family. Immediate family means a spouse, child, parent, brother, or sister of the individual.nA bona fide officer of a corporation (including a parent, subsidiary, or other affiliated corporation), association, or organized group can represent the corporation, association, or organized group. An officer of a governmental unit, agency, or authority, in the course of his or her official duties, can represent the organization before the IRS.nA general partner can represent the partnership before the IRS. For partnerships, under the new Centralized Audit regime, the partnership is represented by the partnership representative who may be a current partner or an outside third party.nA regular full-time employee can represent his or her employer. An employer can be, but is not limited to, an individual, partnership, corporation (including a parent, subsidiary, or other affiliated corporation), association, trust, receivership, guardianship, estate, organized group, governmental unit, agency, or authority.nA fiduciary (trustee, executor, administrator, receiver, or guardian) stands in the position of a taxpayer and acts as the taxpayer, not as a representative.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1329,9,'Which of the following individuals qualifies as a practitioner under Circular 230?','[\"Certified public accountant\",\"Enrolled actuary\",\"Attorney\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.2(a)(5), defines a practitioner to mean any individual described in paragraphs (a), (b), (c), (d), (e), or (f) of Section 10.3, which includes an attorney, CPA, enrolled agent, enrolled actuary, enrolled retirement plan agent, or registered tax return preparer.nnOne should be aware that the category of registered tax return preparers does not exist at this moment given the Loving decision in 2014 (Revenue Procedure 2014-42). Registered tax return preparers that do not have any of the credentials mentioned above, have either limited representation rights, if they are enrolled in the Annual Filing Season Program (for returns filed after December 31, 2015), or tax return preparation rights only, if they are PTIN holders for returns filed after January 1, 2016.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1330,9,'Which of the following tasks can be performed by any Enrolled Agent (EA) on behalf of their client?','[\"Prepare and file a suit for refund in United States District Court\",\"Prepare and sign a protest to challenge the examination results in the IRS Appeals Office\",\"Prepare and sign a United States Tax Court petition to contest a notice of deficiency\",\"Prepare and file a bankruptcy petition in United States Bankruptcy Court due to unpaid tax balances\"]',1,'Pursuant to Form 12203, Request for Appeals Review, when a taxpayer doesn’t agree with the IRS proposed adjustments or changes and the taxpayer has submitted all supporting information, explanations, or documents, the taxpayer may:nndiscuss the IRS findings with the person identified (or their supervisor) in the heading on the IRS letter that provided the taxpayer the information; and if the taxpayer can\'t reach agreement;nappeal the case by requesting an Appeals Review.nIf the taxpayer requests an appeal review, they can represent themselves in the in Appeals. Alternatively, they can be represented by another person as long as the person is an attorney, a certified public accountant, or an enrolled agent authorized to practice before the IRS.nnAlso, if the taxpayer plans to have their representative talk without the taxpayer being present, then a signed copy of a completed power of attorney (Form 2848, Power of Attorney and Declaration of Representative) must be filed.nnFinally, if a taxpayer\'s representative prepares and signs the protest, he or she must stipulate that:nnThey submitted the protest and accompanying documents, andnWhether they know personally that the facts stated in the protest and accompanying document are true and correct.nUnder Publication 947, page 7, \"Acts performed\", attorneys, certified public accountants, and enrolled agents may perform the following acts:nnrepresent you before any office or employee of the IRS.nsign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refund.nsign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of tax.nsign a closing agreement.nAll of the above are acts authorized before the Internal Revenue Service, not extended to the U.S. Courts.nnTherefore, an EA may prepare and sign a protest to challenge the examination results in the IRS Appeals Office.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1331,9,'Identify the individual below who is generally not eligible to practice before the IRS. None of the individuals are under suspension or disbarment.','[\"Enrolled agent\",\"Attorney\",\"Certified public accountant\",\"State employee\"]',3,'As provided in Circular 230, Section 10.3, any of the following individuals can practice before the IRS:nnAttorneysnCertified public accountants (CPAs)nEnrolled agentsnEnrolled actuaries, limited to certain issuesnEnrolled retirement plan agents, limited to certain issuesnIn addition, no officer or employee of any state, or subdivision of any state, whose duties require him or her to pass upon, investigate, or deal with tax matters for such state or subdivision, may practice before the IRS, if such employment may disclose facts or information applicable to federal tax matters. Hence, a state employee generally is not eligible to practice before the IRS.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nCircular 230, Section 10.3(f)(3), provides that a registered tax return preparer (RTRP) may represent taxpayers before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the IRS (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination if the RTRP signed the tax return or claim for refund for the taxable year or period under examination. For returns filed after December 31, 2015, only Annual Filing Season Program participants have these limited rights.nnOne should be aware that the category of registered tax return preparers does not exist at this moment given the Loving decision in 2014 (Revenue Procedure 2014-42). However, it is still listed in the updated version of Circular 230 and is applicable to tax returns filed during the 2014 tax season only.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1332,9,'An Enrolled Agent’s communications with a client may be privileged if they concern:','[\"encouraging the client to participate in a tax shelter.\",\"preparing the client\\u2019s tax return.\",\"representing the client in an IRS examination.\",\"a criminal tax investigation.\"]',2,'IRC Section 7525(a)(1) provides the general rule for confidentiality privileges relating to taxpayer communications. With respect to tax advice, the same common-law protections of confidentiality which apply to a communication between a taxpayer and an attorney shall also apply to a communication between a taxpayer and any federally authorized tax practitioner to the extent the communication would be considered a privileged communication if it were between a taxpayer and an attorney.nnIRC Section 7525(b)(2) specifically excludes communication between a federally authorized tax practitioner and their client concerning the promotion of tax shelters from the confidentiality privileges stipulated in IRC Section 7525(a)(1).nnIn addition, the above paragraph may only be asserted in any noncriminal tax matter before the IRS and any noncriminal tax proceeding in federal court brought by or against the United States.nnPublication 556, pages 3 and 4, states confidential communications are those that:nnadvise you on tax matters within the scope of the practitioner\'s authority to practice before the IRS,nwould be confidential between an attorney and you, andnrelate to noncriminal tax matters before the IRS, ornrelate to noncriminal tax proceedings brought in federal court by or against the United States.nAn Enrolled Agent’s communications with a client may be privileged if they are representing a client in an IRS examination.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1333,9,'With respect to unenrolled return preparers, which of the following statements is correct?','[\"An unenrolled return preparer is an individual other than an attorney, CPA, enrolled agent, or enrolled actuary who prepares and signs a taxpayer\'s return as the preparer, or who prepares a return but is not required (by the instructions to the return or regulations) to sign the return.\",\"An unenrolled return preparer is only permitted to appear as a taxpayer\'s representative before a customer service representative of the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"An unenrolled preparer may receive refund checks on behalf of the taxpayer if Form 8821 has been executed.\",\"An unenrolled preparer is permitted to represent a taxpayer over the telephone with the Automated Collection System unit.\"]',0,'Publication 947, page 3, states that an unenrolled return preparer is an individual other than an attorney, CPA, enrolled agent, enrolled retirement plan agent, or enrolled actuary who prepares and signs a taxpayer\'s return as the paid preparer, or who prepares a return but is not required (by the instructions to the return or regulations) to sign the return.nnUnenrolled return preparers may represent taxpayers only before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) and only during an examination of the tax returns they prepared and signed prior to December 31, 2015. Unenrolled return preparers may not represent taxpayers before appeals officers, revenue officers, counsel, or similar officers or employees of the Internal Revenue Service or the Department of Treasury. Unenrolled return preparers may not execute closing agreements, extend the statutory period for tax assessments or collection of tax, execute waivers, or sign any document on behalf of a taxpayer. (Publication 947, page 4)nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBeginning January 1, 2016, only unenrolled return preparers with a valid PTIN and who hold a record of completion for BOTH the tax return year (2015 or thereafter) under examination and the year the examination is conducted may represent under certain conditions as specified on page 4 of Publication 947.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1334,9,'Matt, an enrolled agent, provided tax advice to XYZ Corporation on a federal tax matter. The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) is reviewing a required filing of the XYZ Corporation and asks to see a copy of Matt\'s tax advice. The tax advice is not protected by the federally authorized tax practitioner privilege under IRC Section 7525 from disclosure to the SEC because:','[\"Matt is not a lawyer.\",\"Matt is not a CPA.\",\"the federally authorized tax practitioner privilege protects advice only against disclosure to the IRS, not other government agencies.\",\"the federally authorized tax practitioner privilege protects only advice to individuals.\"]',2,'Matt cannot seek protection under IRC Section 7525 from disclosure to the SEC because the federally authorized tax practitioner privilege protects advice only against disclosure to the IRS, not other government agencies.nnThe general rule under IRC Section 7525(a)(1) provides that the same common-law protections of confidentiality which apply to a communication between a taxpayer and an attorney shall also apply to a communication between a taxpayer and any federally authorized tax practitioner to the extent the communication would be considered a privileged communication if it were between a taxpayer and an attorney with respect to tax advice.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1335,9,'An enrolled agent (EA) may represent a taxpayer:','[\"at conferences or meetings with the IRS Examination Division.\",\"only if the EA prepared the return under examination.\",\"at all tax related federal court proceedings.\",\"before the Taxpayer Advocate Service and the Tax Court.\"]',0,'An enrolled agent does not need to have prepared a return to represent a taxpayer regarding it. Enrolled agents are not authorized to represent taxpayers in federal courts, including the U.S. Tax Court. However, they can represent taxpayers before the Taxpayer Advocate Service. Enrolled agents cannot represent taxpayers in the Tax Court unless they are specially admitted to practice before it. The correct answer is that an enrolled agent has the authority to represent taxpayers during IRS examinations and meetings with the IRS Examination Division.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1336,9,'How many future years will the IRS record to the Centralized Authorization File (CAF) at the taxpayer’s request based on receipt of a valid Form 2848 authorizing representation for tax years or periods?','[\"December 31 of year of receipt + 1 year\",\"December 31 of year of receipt + 2 years\",\"December 31 of year of receipt + 3 years\",\"December 31 of year of receipt + 4 years\"]',2,'The IRS will record to the CAF at the taxpayer’s request based on the receipt of a valid Form 2848 authorizing representation for December 31 of the year of the receipt plus 3 years.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1337,9,'Louis, the volunteer treasurer of a nonprofit organization and a member of its board of directors, compiles the data and fills out its annual Form 990, Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax. Under the Internal Revenue Code, Louis is not considered a tax return preparer because:','[\"he is a member of the board of directors.\",\"the return does not contain a claim for a tax refund.\",\"he is not compensated.\",\"returns for nonprofit organizations are exempt from the preparer rules.\"]',2,'Compensated tax return preparers can be liable for such things as tax evasion, perjury on a tax return, or bribery of an IRS employee. Since Louis is not a paid tax return preparer, he is not considered a tax return preparer and therefore cannot sign the tax return.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1338,9,'Authorized Internal Revenue Service e-file Providers are not considered to be tax preparers as long as their services are limited to “typing, reproduction, or other mechanical assistance in the preparation of a return.” Hence, they are subject to assessment of any and all return preparer penalties by the Internal Revenue Service if:','[\"they alter the return for a transposition error.\",\"they alter the return for an arithmetic correction.\",\"they alter the deduction amount on an item in the return.\",\"All of the answer choices are nonsubstantive changes.\"]',2,'Publication 1345, pages 40 and 41, provides that preparer penalties may be asserted against an individual or firm meeting the definition of a tax preparer under IRC Section 7701(a)(36) and Regulation Section 301.7701-15. Preparer penalties that may be asserted under appropriate circumstances include, but are not limited to, those set forth in IRC Sections 6694, 6695, 6701, and 6713.nnUnder Regulation Section 301.7701-15(c), Authorized IRS e-file Providers are not tax return preparers for the purpose of assessing most preparer penalties as long as their services are limited to “typing, reproduction, or other mechanical assistance in the preparation of a return or claim for refund.”nnIf an ERO, Intermediate Service Provider, Transmitter, or the product of a Software Developer alters the return information in a non-substantive way, this alteration is considered to come under the “mechanical assistance” exception described in Regulation Section 301.7701-15(c). A nonsubstantive change is a correction or change limited to a transposition error, misplaced entry, spelling error, or arithmetic correction.nnIf an ERO, Intermediate Service Provider, Transmitter, or the product of a Software Developer alters the return in a way that does not come under the “mechanical assistance” exception, the IRS may hold the Provider liable for income tax return preparer penalties.nn(See Regulation Section 301.7701-15(c); Revenue Ruling 85-189, 1985-2 CB 341, which describes a situation where the Software Developer was determined to be a tax return preparer and subject to certain preparer penalties.)nnThus, the statement made in this problem that an ERO is still subject to assessment of any and all return preparer penalties by the Internal Revenue Service is correct if the ERO alters the deduction amount on an item in the return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1339,9,'Identify the item below that is not considered practice before the IRS:','[\"corresponding with the Internal Revenue Service on behalf of a client.\",\"preparing a tax return for an individual.\",\"representing a client at an audit.\",\"calling the IRS to discuss a letter received by a client.\"]',1,'Practice before the IRS comprehends all matters connected with a presentation to the IRS or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the IRS. Such presentations include, but are not limited to, preparing documents; filing documents; corresponding and communicating with the IRS; rendering written advice with respect to any entity, transaction, plan, or arrangement, or other plan or arrangement having a potential for tax avoidance or evasion; and representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings (Circular 230, Section 10.2, Paragraph (4)).nnAdditionally, any individual may for compensation prepare or assist with the preparation of a tax return or claim for refund (provided the individual prepares less than substantially all of the tax return or claim for refund), appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS, or furnish information at the request of the IRS or any of its officers or employees (Circular 230, Section 10.8(b)). In such cases, the individual would not be seen as practicing before the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1340,9,'Practice before the Internal Revenue Service comprehends all matters connected with a presentation to the Internal Revenue Service or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the Internal Revenue Service. Which of the following is not considered practice before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"Representing a client at conferences\",\"Communicating with the IRS\",\"Appearing as a witness for the taxpayer\",\"Preparing and filing documents\"]',2,'Practice before the IRS comprehends all matters connected with a presentation to the IRS or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the IRS. Such presentations include, but are not limited to, preparing documents; filing documents; corresponding and communicating with the IRS; rendering written advice with respect to any entity, transaction, plan, or arrangement, or other plan or arrangement having a potential for tax avoidance or evasion; and representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings. (Circular 230, Section 10.2)nnAdditionally, any individual may for compensation prepare or assist with the preparation of a tax return or claim for refund (provided the individual prepares less than substantially all of the tax return or claim for refund), appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS, or furnish information at the request of the IRS or any of its officers or employees. (Circular 230, Section 10.8)nnFurthermore, just preparing a tax return, furnishing information at the request of the IRS, or appearing as a witness for the taxpayer is not practice before the IRS. These acts can be performed by anyone.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1341,9,'What action can an applicant take if an application for enrollment is denied?','[\"The applicant can reapply in 3 months.\",\"The applicant can appeal the decision by filing a written protest within 30 days of receipt of the notice.\",\"The applicant can appeal the decision by filing a written protest within 45 days of receipt of the notice.\",\"The applicant can appeal the decision by filing a written protest within 60 days of receipt of the notice.\"]',1,'An applicant will be informed in writing as to the reason(s) for any denial of an application. The applicant may, within 30 days after receipt of the notice of denial of enrollment, file a written protest of the denial as prescribed by the IRS in forms, guidance, or other appropriate guidance.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1342,9,'To meet due diligence requirements, which of the following is true regarding the Earned Income Credit Worksheet and Form 8867?','[\"A record must be kept of how, when, and from whom the information used to prepare the Form 8867 and the Worksheets was obtained\",\"Form 8867 does not need to be filed with the return if all information used to complete the form was provided by the taxpayer in writing.\",\"A record of any questions the taxpayer may have asked the tax preparer about their eligibility for the credits should be retained\",\"Copies of documents provided by the taxpayer that the return preparer relied on to determine the eligibility for the credits do not need to be retained by the preparer.\"]',0,'To meet due diligence requirements, tax professionals should do the following:nnInterview the taxpayer, ask adequate questions, document the questions and responses, and review sufficient information to determine eligibility for the credit(s) and/or HOH filing status, and to calculate the amount(s) of the credit(s) claimed.nComplete Form 8867 truthfully and accurately, and perform the actions described on Form 8867 for any claimed credit(s) and HOH filing status.nSubmit Form 8867 as required.nRetain the following records for 3 years from the specified dates: nA copy of Form 8867.nThe applicable Worksheet(s) or your own worksheet(s) for any credits claimed.nCopies of documents provided by the taxpayer used to determine eligibility and calculate the credit(s).nA record of how, when, and from whom the information used to prepare Form 8867 and the Worksheet(s) was obtained.nA record of any additional information relied upon, including questions asked and the taxpayer’s responses, to determine eligibility and calculate the credit(s).nThe IRS mandates that tax preparers maintain detailed records of how, when, and from whom they obtained the information used to complete Form 8867 and associated worksheets. This requirement helps ensure that preparers exercise due diligence and can substantiate the information used to claim the credits.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1343,9,'A taxpayer filed an appeal of an IRS examination and then signed IRS Form 8821, Tax Information Authorization, on behalf of an unenrolled tax preparer. Which of the following is correct?','[\"The unenrolled return preparer may represent the client before IRS Appeals based on the Form 8821.\",\"The unenrolled return preparer may represent the client before IRS Appeals with the oral consent of the client.\",\"The unenrolled return preparer may represent the client before IRS Appeals with a note attached by the client.\",\"The unenrolled return preparer may not represent the client before IRS Appeals.\"]',3,'Pursuant to the Instructions for Form 2848, page 2, an unenrolled return preparer is an individual other than an attorney, CPA, enrolled agent, enrolled retirement plan agent, or enrolled actuary who prepares and signs a taxpayer\'s return as the paid preparer, or who prepares a return but is not required (by the instructions to the return or regulations) to sign the return.nnUnenrolled return preparers may represent taxpayers only before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination of the tax returns they prepared and signed (or prepared if there is no signature space on the form).nnUnenrolled return preparers cannot represent taxpayers, regardless of the circumstances requiring representation, before appeals officers, revenue officers, counsel, or similar officers or employees of the Internal Revenue Service or the Department of Treasury. Unenrolled return preparers cannot execute closing agreements, extend the statutory period for tax assessments or collection of tax, execute waivers, or sign any document on behalf of a taxpayer.nnNote: Beginning January 1, 2016, only unenrolled return preparers with a valid PTIN and who hold a record of completion for BOTH the tax return year (2015 or thereafter) under examination and the year the examination is conducted may represent under certain conditions as specified on page 2 of Form 2848 Instructions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1344,9,'Of the following statements, which one is not considered practice before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"Communicating with the Internal Revenue Service for a taxpayer regarding the taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws and regulations administered by the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Representing a taxpayer at conferences, hearings, or meetings with the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Preparing a tax return or furnishing information at the request of the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Preparing and filing necessary documents at the request of the Internal Revenue Service for a taxpayer and discussing issues\"]',2,'Practice before the Internal Revenue Service is defined in Circular 230, Section 10.2(a)(4), to comprehend all matters connected with a presentation to the Internal Revenue Service or any of its officers or employees relating to a taxpayer\'s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the Internal Revenue Service. Such presentations include, but are not limited to, preparing and filing documents; corresponding and communicating with the Internal Revenue Service; rendering written advice with respect to any entity, transaction, plan, or arrangement, or other plan or arrangement having a potential for tax avoidance or evasion; and representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings.nnHence, preparing a tax return or furnishing information at the request of the Internal Revenue Service does not fall within the definition of practice before the Internal Revenue Service.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1345,9,'Which of the following statements is correct for enrolled actuaries?','[\"They are authorized to practice before the IRS the same as an enrolled agent.\",\"They are authorized to practice before the IRS for those issues concerning the governing of employee retirement plans.\",\"They are authorized to act as a representative only before a customer representative or a revenue agent.\",\"They are\\u00a0not\\u00a0authorized to practice before the IRS.\"]',1,'Any individual who is enrolled as an actuary by the Joint Board for the Enrollment of Actuaries, and who is not currently under suspension or disbarment from practice before the IRS, may practice before the IRS. However, they first must file with the IRS a written declaration stating that they are currently qualified as an enrolled actuary and they are authorized to represent the party or parties on whose behalf they are acting.nnThe practice of enrolled actuaries is limited to certain Internal Revenue Code sections that relate to their area of expertise, principally those sections governing employee retirement plans.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1346,9,'Which of the following is not an example of practicing before the IRS as defined in Circular 230?','[\"Preparing and filing documents\",\"Corresponding and communicating with the IRS\",\"Rendering written advice on recent IRS decisions\",\"Representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings\"]',2,'Practice before the IRS is defined in Treasury Circular 230 as involving all matters connected with a presentation to the IRS, or any of its officers or employees, relating to a taxpayer’s rights, privileges, or liabilities under laws or regulations administered by the IRS. This includes preparing and filing documents; corresponding and communicating with the IRS; rendering written advice with respect to any entity, transaction, plan, or arrangement; and representing a client at conferences, hearings, and meetings.nnRendering written advice on recent IRS decisions is not an example of practicing before the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1347,9,'Which of the following individuals will not be treated as a tax return preparer under the Internal Revenue Code?','[\"An individual who prepares income tax returns for compensation\",\"An enrolled agent\",\"A lawyer\",\"All of the individuals listed are tax return preparers.\"]',3,'All of the individuals listed are treated as tax return preparers: a lawyer, an enrolled agent, and an individual who prepares tax returns for compensation.nnAn individual who prepares and signs a tax return for compensation is treated as a tax preparer by the IRS. There are limitations on this person\'s role in representing clients unless they fall into one of the following categories:nnEnrolled agentsnEnrolled actuariesnCPAsnLawyersnAnnual filing season program participantsnPublication 556, page 3, provides, in part, that throughout the examination of a taxpayer\'s tax return, they can act on their own behalf or have someone represent them or accompany them. If the taxpayer filed a joint return, either the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s spouse, or both can meet with the IRS.nnFurthermore, the taxpayer can have someone represent or accompany the taxpayer. This person can be any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled agent (a person enrolled to practice before the IRS), an enrolled actuary, or the person who prepared the return and signed it as the preparer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1348,9,'Which of the below statements is correct regarding complaints for the sanctioning of a practitioner, employer, firm, appraiser, or other entity for violations of the regulations governing practice before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"A United States Tax Court judge oversees proceedings regarding the complaint.\",\"In general, discovery may be permitted at the discretion of an Administrative Law Judge.\",\"Within 30 days of receipt of the answer, the presiding judge will notify the parties of the right to request discovery and the timeframe for filing a request.\",\"The complaint can only be served on the respondent in person by a designated employee of the Internal Revenue Service.\"]',1,'Circular 230 Section 10.71(a) states that “In general. Discovery may be permitted, at the discretion of the Administrative Law Judge, only upon written motion demonstrating the relevance, materiality and reasonableness of the requested discovery and subject to the requirements of §10.72(d)(2) and (3). Within 10 days of receipt of the answer, the Administrative Law Judge will notify the parties of the right to request discovery and the timeframe for filing a request. A request for discovery, and objections, must be filed in accordance with §10.68. In response to a request for discovery, the Administrative Law Judge may order:nnDepositions upon oral examination; ornAnswers to requests for admission.nA United States Tax Court judge does not oversee the proceedings. A copy of the complaint does not have to be served in person.nnThe correct answer is that in general, discovery may be permitted at the discretion of an Administrative Law Judge.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1349,9,'A practitioner can be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service for incompetence and/or disreputable conduct. Which one of the following is considered disreputable conduct?','[\"Conviction of any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United States\",\"Conviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust\",\"Giving false or misleading information or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information to the Department of the Treasury or any officer or employee thereof\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service includes a number of items that are listed in Circular 230, Section 10.51. The following is a sample of items included in this section:nnConviction of any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United StatesnConviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trustnConviction of any felony under federal or state law for which the conduct involved renders the practitioner unfit to practice before the Internal Revenue ServicenGiving false or misleading information, or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information, to the Department of the Treasury or any officer or employee thereof, or to any tribunal authorized to pass upon federal tax matters, in connection with any matter pending or likely to be pending before them, knowing such information to be false or misleadingnAs a result, all of the responses given are reasons for censure, suspension, or disbarment. The key word in these responses is \"conviction.\"',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1350,9,'An enrolled agent can be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service for incompetence and/or disreputable conduct. Which one of the following is considered disreputable conduct?','[\"Being indicted for any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United States\",\"Having your motor vehicle license suspended as a result of numerous traffic violations\",\"Being indicted of any felony under federal or state law for which the conduct involved renders the practitioner unfit to practice before the Internal Revenue Service\",\"Giving false or misleading information, or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information, to the Department of the Treasury or any officer or employee thereof\"]',3,'Incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be sanctioned under Section 10.50 (i.e., censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service) includes, but is not limited to:nnconviction (note that Section 10.51 states “conviction” of a felony, not indictment) of any felony under federal or state law for which the conduct involved renders the practitioner unfit to practice before the Internal Revenue Service or of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust;nmisappropriation of, or failure properly and promptly to remit funds received from a client for the purpose of payment of taxes or other obligations due the United States; orndisbarment or suspension from practice as an attorney, certified public accountant, public accountant, or actuary by any duly constituted authority of any state, territory, possession of the United States, including a commonwealth, or the District of Columbia, any federal court of record or any federal agency, body, or board.nMore specific to this question, disreputable conduct is giving false or misleading information, or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information, to the Department of the Treasury or any officer or employee thereof, or to any tribunal authorized to pass upon federal tax matters, in connection with any matter pending or likely to be pending before them, knowing such information to be false or misleading. Facts or other matters contained in testimony, federal tax returns, financial statements, applications for enrollment, affidavits, declarations, or any other document or statement, written or oral, are included in the term information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1351,9,'Harold, an enrolled agent, advises prospective clients that he is able to obtain approval of qualified retirement plans with unique vesting provisions because of his close relationship with the IRS territory manager of the Tax Exempt and Government Entities operating unit in his locality. What does this type of employment solicitation constitute?','[\"Disreputable conduct subjecting Harold to potential suspension (but\\u00a0not\\u00a0disbarment) from IRS practice\",\"Disreputable conduct subjecting Harold to potential disbarment or suspension from IRS practice\",\"Disreputable conduct subjecting Harold to potential expulsion from IRS practice\",\"Disreputable conduct subjecting Harold to potential fines from IRS practice\"]',1,'Pursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.51(a), incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice (under Section 10.50) before the Internal Revenue Service includes, but is not limited to, solicitation of employment as prohibited under Section 10.30, the use of false or misleading representations with intent to deceive a client or prospective client in order to procure employment, or intimating that the practitioner is able to improperly obtain special consideration or action from the Internal Revenue Service or officer or employee thereof.nnNote: See Circular 230, Section 10.51, for a list of 18 specific items that fall under this category.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1352,9,'A practitioner can be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service for incompetence and/or disreputable conduct. Which one of the following is considered disreputable conduct?','[\"Willfully failing to file on electronic media a tax return prepared by the practitioner that is required by federal law to be filed unless due to reasonable cause\",\"Willfully preparing all or substantially all of, or signing, a tax return or claim for refund when the practitioner does not possess a current or otherwise valid preparer tax identification number\",\"Willfully representing a taxpayer before an officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service unless the practitioner is authorized to do so\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be sanctioned under Section 10.51 (i.e., censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service) includes, but is not limited to, the following:nnWillfully failing to file on magnetic or other electronic media a tax return prepared by the practitioner when the practitioner is required to do so by the federal tax laws, unless the failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglectnWillfully preparing all or substantially all of, or signing, a tax return or claim for refund when the practitioner does not possess a current or otherwise valid preparer tax identification number (PTIN) or other prescribed identifying numbernWillfully representing a taxpayer before an officer or employee of the IRS unless the practitioner is authorized to do sonGiven the above list, disreputable conduct includes all of the answer choices given in this problem. But be aware that there are 18 reasons listed in this Section 10.51 and only 3 are given in this problem. Hence, you may want to review this section to become familiar with the other reasons.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1353,9,'An enrolled agent may be disbarred or suspended from IRS practice for which of the following conducts?','[\"Criminal conviction of an offense under the Internal Revenue Code\",\"Misappropriation of funds received from a client for the purpose of tax payments\",\"Disbarment or suspension from the practice as an attorney, CPA, accountant or actuary\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.50, states that the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate, after notice and an opportunity for a proceeding, may censure, suspend, or disbar any practitioner from practice before the Internal Revenue Service if the practitioner is shown to be incompetent or disreputable (within the meaning of Section 10.51).nnPursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.51 provides, in part, that incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service includes, but is not limited to:nnconviction of any felony under federal or state law for which the conduct involved renders the practitioner unfit to practice before the Internal Revenue Service,nmisappropriation of, or failure to properly and promptly remit funds received from a client for the purpose of payment of taxes or other obligations due the United States, orndisbarment or suspension from practice as an attorney, certified public accountant, public accountant, or actuary by any duly constituted authority of any state, territory, possession of the United States, including a commonwealth, or the District of Columbia, any federal court of record or any federal agency, body, or board.nNote: See Circular 230, Section 10.51, for a list of 18 specific items that fall under this category.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1354,9,'Mary Pecan, a CPA, prepared a tax return for a client. The return contained a frivolous position that could not be defended under any circumstances. The examiner who conducted the examination made a referral within the Internal Revenue Service. Which of the following actions is incorrect?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service will make a final, binding decision as to the appropriate sanction for Mary.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service may reprimand the practitioner.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service may institute a proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of the practitioner.\",\"An Administrative Law Judge will preside at the hearing on a complaint filed for the censure, suspension, or disbarment of the practitioner.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.60(a), provides, in part, that whenever it is determined that a practitioner (or employer, firm, or other entity, if applicable) violated any provision of the laws governing practice before the IRS or regulations in this part, the practitioner may be reprimanded or, in accordance with Section 10.62, subject to a proceeding for sanction described in Section 10.50 (e.g., censure, suspension, or disbarment of the practitioner). A proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner is instituted by the filing of a complaint.nnIn general, Section 10.72 of Circular 230 provides that an Administrative Law Judge will preside at the hearing on a complaint filed under Section 10.60 for the censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner or disqualification of an appraiser.nnHence, the Internal Revenue Service will not make a final, binding decision as to the appropriate sanction for Mary.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1355,9,'A new client visits an Enrolled Agent (EA). The taxpayer believes that the U S tax system is purely voluntary and filed a return showing no income tax, requesting all withholding be refunded. The IRS assessed a $5,000 frivolous return penalty.nnThe taxpayer has received a Notice of Intent to Levy and Right to Collection Due Process (CDP) Hearing concerning the $5,000 penalty. The taxpayer wants the EA to present the previous arguments about the tax system.nnWhich of the following is a correct statement regarding the CDP hearing request raising arguments previously deemed frivolous?','[\"The taxpayer will be given 30 days to withdraw or amend the CDP request in order to avoid a frivolous submission penalty.\",\"The EA would not be subject to a frivolous submission penalty by submitting the CDP hearing request.\",\"The EA would be subject to a frivolous submission penalty of $7,500 by submitting the CDP hearing request.\",\"In all circumstances, filing the CDP request will suspend any levies while Appeals considers the request.\"]',0,'Frivolous tax submission is defined in Publication 17, page 21 as a filing that does not include enough information to figure the correct tax or that contains information clearly showing that the tax your reported is substantially incorrect. Notice 2010-33, 2010-17, I.R.B. 609 contains a list of positions that are identified as frivolous. According to the same Publication, a penalty of $5,000 may be imposed for filing a frivolous tax return or any other type of frivolous submission.nnIf the Secretary of Treasury provides a person with notice that a submission is a specified frivolous submission and the taxpayer elects to withdraw such submission within 30 days after such notice, the penalty of $5,000 (not $7,500) imposed under this section shall not apply with respect to such submission. IRC Section 6702(b)(3)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1356,9,'Which of the following from Circular 230 is correct regarding sanctions against an enrolled agent (EA)?','[\"There cannot be both monetary and nonmonetary sanctions imposed.\",\"An EA can face imprisonment up to 3 years.\",\"An EA can be censured.\",\"A monetary penalty can exceed the gross income derived from the conduct giving rise to the penalty.\"]',2,'Circular 230 allows for both monetary and nonmonetary sanctions to be imposed simultaneously on an enrolled agent. Sanctions can include disbarment, suspension, censure, and monetary penalties. Imprisonment is a criminal penalty and not covered under Circular 230 administrative sanctions. Circular 230 specifies that a monetary penalty imposed on an enrolled agent cannot exceed the gross income derived from the conduct giving rise to the penalty.nnAccording to Circular 230, Section 10.50, an enrolled agent can be censured as a form of nonmonetary sanction. Censure is a public reprimand.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1357,9,'A frivolous income tax return is one that does not include enough information to figure the correct tax or that contains certain information clearly showing that the tax that was reported is substantially incorrect. If a taxpayer files a frivolous return, which penalty applies specifically to the taxpayer for the frivolous return?','[\"$50 for failure to supply the taxpayer\'s Social Security number\",\"20% of the underpayment, reduced for those items for which there was adequate disclosure made\",\"$5,000 frivolous return penalty, applied in addition to any other applicable penalty or penalties\",\"$100 for the failure to furnish the tax shelter registration number\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 21, provides that a taxpayer may have to pay a penalty of $5,000 if the taxpayer files a frivolous tax return or other frivolous submissions. A frivolous tax return is one that does not include enough information to figure the correct tax or that contains information clearly showing that the tax reported is substantially incorrect.nnFor more information on frivolous returns, frivolous submissions, and a list of positions that are identified as frivolous, see IRS Notice 2010-33 (2010-17 IRB 609), available at www.irs.gov.nnA taxpayer will have to pay the penalty if he or she filed this kind of return or submission based on a frivolous position on the taxpayer\'s part or a desire to delay or interfere with the administration of federal income tax laws. This includes altering or striking out the preprinted language above the space provided for the taxpayer\'s signature.nnThis penalty is added to any other penalty provided by law.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1358,9,'An Enrolled Agent (EA) can be sanctioned under Circular 230 in each of the following ways EXCEPT:','[\"monetary penalty.\",\"imprisonment.\",\"censure.\",\"disbarment.\"]',1,'Circular 230, Section 10.50, states that the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate, after notice and an opportunity for a proceeding, may censure, suspend, or disbar any practitioner from practice before the Internal Revenue Service if the practitioner is shown to be incompetent or disreputable (within the meaning of Section 10.51).nnIn addition, Circular 230, Section 10.50(c) provides, in part, that the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate, after notice and an opportunity for a proceeding, may impose a monetary penalty on any practitioner who engages in conduct subject to sanction under this section.nnTherefore, the only recourse that is not available as a sanctionable act is imprisonment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1359,9,'Whenever it is determined that a practitioner violated any provision of the laws or regulations in Circular 230, the Internal Revenue Service may reprimand the practitioner or institute a proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of the practitioner. Which of the following statements is correct concerning this issue?nn1. A proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner is instituted by the filing of a complaint.n2. A proceeding will be instituted regardless of whether the proposed respondent previously has been advised in writing of the law, facts, and conduct warranting such action and has been accorded an opportunity to dispute facts, assert additional facts, and make arguments.','[\"Only statement 1 is correct.\",\"Only statement 2 is correct.\",\"Both statements 1 and 2 are correct.\",\"Both statements 1 and 2 are\\u00a0incorrect.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.60, provides that whenever it is determined that a practitioner (or employer, firm, or other entity, if applicable) violated any provision of the laws governing practice before the IRS or the regulations in this part, the practitioner may be reprimanded or, in accordance with Section 10.62, subject to a proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of the practitioner.nnA proceeding for censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner is instituted by the filing of a complaint as described in Section 10.62. The complaint must name the respondent, provide a clear and concise description of the facts and law that constitute the basis for the proceeding, and be signed by an authorized representative of the IRS under Section 10.69(a)(1). A complaint is sufficient if it fairly informs the respondent of the charges brought so that the respondent is able to prepare a defense.nnExcept in unusual circumstances as provided in Section 10.82, a proceeding will not be instituted unless the proposed respondent previously has been advised in writing of the law, facts, and conduct warranting such action and has been accorded an opportunity to dispute facts, assert additional facts, and make arguments. (Circular 230, Section 10.60(c))',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1360,9,'According to Treasury Circular 230, can a monetary penalty be imposed on a practitioner in addition to censure, sanction, or disbarment?','[\"No, monetary penalties are not allowed.\",\"Yes, the amount of the monetary penalty is determined by the Secretary of the Treasury.\",\"Yes, monetary penalties are allowed up to $10,000.\",\"Yes, monetary penalties are allowed, but the amount shall not exceed the gross income derived (or to be derived) from the conduct giving rise to the penalty.\"]',3,'Treasury Circular 230, Section 10.50(c), states the following: “The Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate, after notice and an opportunity for a proceeding, may impose a monetary penalty on any practitioner who engages in conduct subject to sanction under paragraph (a) of this section [10.50]....The amount of the penalty shall not exceed the gross income derived (or to be derived) from the conduct giving rise to the penalty.”n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1361,9,'Under Treasury Department Circular No. 230, all of the following are considered to be incompetence and disreputable conduct EXCEPT:','[\"conviction of any criminal offense under the Federal tax laws.\",\"conviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust.\",\"willfully disclosing tax return information with the consent of the taxpayer.\",\"willfully failing to sign a tax return prepared by the tax practitioner as required by Federal tax laws, unless the failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.50, states that the Secretary of the Treasury, or delegate, after notice and an opportunity for a proceeding, may censure, suspend, or disbar any practitioner from practice before the Internal Revenue Service if the practitioner is shown to be incompetent or disreputable (within the meaning of Section 10.51).nnPursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.51 provides, in part, that incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the Internal Revenue Service includes, but is not limited to:nnconviction of any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United States;nconviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust;nwillfully failing to sign a tax return prepared by the practitioner when the practitioner’s signature is required by Federal tax laws unless the failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect.nwillfully disclosing or otherwise using a tax return or tax return information in a manner not authorized by the Internal Revenue Code, contrary to the order of a court of competent jurisdiction, or contrary to the order of an administrative law judge in a proceeding instituted under §10.60., ornwillfully preparing all or substantially all of, or signing, a tax return or claim for refund when the practitioner does not possess a current or otherwise valid preparer tax identification number or other prescribed identifying number.nNote: See Circular 230, Section 10.51, for a list of 18 specific items that fall under this category.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1362,9,'Under Treasury Circular 230, a practitioner may be:','[\"censured.\",\"suspended.\",\"disbarred.\",\"censured, suspended, or disbarred.\"]',3,'If a practitioner is shown to be incompetent, refuses to comply with the rules of Circular 230, or acts with the intent to defraud or willingly and knowingly mislead or threaten a client, then the Secretary of the Treasury can censure, suspend, or even disbar the practitioner.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1363,9,'Which of the following acts are seen under Circular 230 as incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the IRS?','[\"Conviction of any criminal offense under the revenue laws of the United States\",\"Criminal conviction under state law for embezzlement\",\"Conviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust\",\"All of the answer choices are acts of incompetence and disreputable conduct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.51, provides a list of actions that fall under the heading of incompetence and disreputable conduct. In general, incompetence and disreputable conduct for which a practitioner may be censured, suspended, or disbarred from practice before the IRS includes but is not limited to acts such as:nnconviction of any criminal offense under the federal tax laws,nconviction of any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust,nconviction of any felony under federal or state law for which the conduct involved renders the practitioner unfit to practice before the Internal Revenue Service, orngiving false or misleading information or participating in any way in the giving of false or misleading information, to the Department of Treasury or any officer or employee thereof.nSince embezzlement is an offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust, it would be considered disreputable conduct under item 2 above.nnSee Circular 230, Section 10.51, for a complete list of all 18 actions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1364,9,'John Jones prepared a return for a client that contained a frivolous position that could not be defended under any circumstances. The examiner who conducted the examination referred Mr. Jones to the Internal Revenue Service. After all procedural requirements had been met; the Internal Revenue Service filed a complaint against John Jones. Which statement below is correct with respect to the hearing that will take place for the complaint filed against Mr. Jones?','[\"An Administrative Law Judge will preside at the hearing on a complaint filed for the censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner or disqualification of an appraiser.\",\"A request by a practitioner or appraiser that a hearing in a disciplinary proceeding concerning him or her be public, and that the record of such disciplinary proceeding be made available for inspection by interested persons may be granted by a U.S. District Court judge.\",\"The U.S. District Court judge assigned to the case will determine the location of the hearing.\",\"If either party to the proceeding fails to appear at the hearing, after notice of the proceeding has been sent to him or her, the party will be deemed to have waived the right to a hearing and the U.S. District Court judge may make his or her decision against the absent party by default.\"]',0,'According to Circular 230, Section 10.72(a), an Administrative Law Judge will preside at the hearing on a complaint filed under Section 10.60 for the censure, suspension, or disbarment of a practitioner or disqualification of an appraiser.nnAs provided in Circular 230, Section 10.72(d)(2), the Administrative Law Judge may grant a request by a practitioner or appraiser that all the pleadings and evidence of the disciplinary proceeding be made available for inspection where the parties stipulate in advance to adopt the protective measures in Section 10.72(d)(4), which state, in part: \"The Administrative Law Judge will issue a protective order to ensure that the identifying information is available to the parties and the Administrative Law Judge for purposes of the proceeding, but is not disclosed to, or open to inspection by, the public.\"nnThe location of a hearing will be determined by the agreement of the parties with the approval of the Administrative Law Judge. But in the absence of such agreement and approval, the hearing will be held in Washington, D.C. (Circular 230, Section 10.72(e)).nnIf either party fails to appear at the hearing, after notice of the proceeding has been sent to him or her, the party will be deemed to have waived the right to a hearing and the Administrative Law Judge (not the U.S. District Court judge) may make his or her decision against the absent party by default (Circular 230, Section 10.72(f)).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1365,9,'What is the penalty for a taxpayer who fails to timely file a tax return (including extensions)?','[\"A penalty of 1% a month (up to a maximum of 5%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\",\"A penalty of 2.5% a month (up to a maximum of 10.0%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\",\"A penalty of 5% a month (up to a maximum of 25%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\",\"A penalty of 7.5% a month (up to a maximum of 20%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\"]',2,'A penalty of 5% per month (up to a maximum of 25%) is imposed on the amount of tax shown as being due on the return if a taxpayer fails to file a tax return by the due date, including any extension. The minimum penalty amount is the smaller of $510 or 100% of the unpaid tax.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1366,9,'What is the penalty if fraud is the reason for failure to timely file?','[\"A penalty of 10% per month (with a maximum of 50%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\",\"A penalty of 15% per month (with a maximum of 75%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\",\"A penalty of 20% per month (with a maximum of 50%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\",\"A penalty of 25% per month (with a maximum of 75%) of the deficiency on the tax return (when filed)\"]',1,'A penalty of 5% per month (up to a maximum of 25%) is imposed on the amount of tax shown as being due on the return if a taxpayer fails to file a tax return by the due date, including any extension. The minimum penalty amount is the smaller of $510 or 100% of the unpaid tax. If fraud is the reason for failure to file on a timely basis, then the penalty is 15% per month (with a maximum of 75%).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1367,9,'If a person is paid to prepare, assist in preparing, or review a tax return, then he or she must:','[\"sign the tax return and decide whether or not to provide the other information in the paid preparer\'s area of the tax return.\",\"sign the tax return and provide the other information in the paid preparer\'s area of the tax return.\",\"decide whether or not to sign the tax return but must provide the other information in the paid preparer\'s area of the tax return.\",\"decide whether or not to sign the tax return and decide whether or not to provide the other information in the paid preparer\'s area of the tax return.\"]',1,'IRC Section 6695(c) states that any person who is a tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund and who fails to comply with IRC Section 6109(a)(4) with respect to such return or claim shall pay a penalty of $60 for each failure, with a maximum penalty of $30,000 imposed with respect to each calendar year, unless it is shown that the failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect.nnIRC Section 6695(a) provides that any person who is an income tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund who fails to furnish a copy of the tax return to the taxpayer (i.e., comply with IRC Section 6107(a)) shall pay a penalty of $60 for such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect. The maximum penalty imposed under this subsection on any person with respect to documents filed during any calendar year shall not exceed $30,000 for 2024.nnHence, a tax preparer must sign the tax return and provide the other information in the paid preparer\'s area of the tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1368,9,'What is the penalty if you understate your income tax because you show negligence (i.e., failure to keep adequate books and records) or disregard of the rules or regulations?','[\"20% of the underpayment\",\"$500\",\"$60\",\"25% of the underpayment\"]',0,'IRC Section 6662 discusses the accuracy-related penalty. In general, a taxpayer can incur an accuracy-related penalty of 20% for underpayments of tax due to negligence or disregard of rules or regulations, or substantial understatement of tax or a failure to disclose a foreign financial asset. A penalty of 40% can be imposed for tax benefits claimed for a transaction that lacks economic substance or fails to disclose a foreign financial asset.nnOther penalties that a taxpayer may incur include but are not limited to $5,000 if a taxpayer files a frivolous return or other frivolous submissions. A frivolous tax return is one that does not include enough information to figure the correct tax or that contains information clearly showing that the tax the taxpayer reported is substantially incorrect (Publication 17, page 21).nnIn addition, a $60 penalty is assessed for each occurrence whereby the taxpayer fails to supply a Social Security number for the taxpayer, or any other person listed on the return (Publication 17, page 21).nnPublication 17, page 21, states, in part, that a penalty of 5% per month or part of a month, but not more than 25%, is assessed in the case where a taxpayer fails to file his or her tax return by the due date (including extensions).nnIn this case, the taxpayer would incur an accuracy-related penalty of 20% of the underpayment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1369,9,'If a taxpayer files a claim for a refund that is greater than the amount actually allowable, what is the percentage of the penalty of the improperly claimed amount?','[0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625,0.1499999999999999944488848768742172978818416595458984375,0.200000000000000011102230246251565404236316680908203125,0.25]',2,'A penalty equal to 20% of the improperly claimed amount applies if a taxpayer files a claim for a refund that is greater than the allowable amount. The penalty does not apply if the taxpayer can show a reasonable basis for the excessive refund claim.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1370,9,'What is the maximum fine (criminal penalty) for an individual taxpayer for willful attempt to evade or defeat tax?','[\"$50,000\",\"$100,000\",\"$250,000\",\"$500,000\"]',1,'The maximum penalty for willfully attempting to evade or defeat tax is a $100,000 fine and/or five years in prison for an individual taxpayer. For a corporation, there is no imprisonment, but the maximum fine is $500,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1371,9,'What penalty is provided by IRC Section 6694 to tax return preparers that prepare a return that understates a taxpayer\'s liability due to an unreasonable position and the preparer reasonably should have known of the position?','[\"The greater of $5,000 or 100% of the income derived by the preparer with respect to the return\",\"The greater of $5,000 or 50% of the income derived by the preparer with respect to the return\",\"The greater of $1,000 or 50% of the income derived by the preparer with respect to the return\",\"The greater of $1,000 or 100% of the income derived by the preparer with respect to the return\"]',2,'IRC Section 6694(a)(1) provides, in part, that if a tax return preparer prepares any return or claim of refund with respect to which any part of an understatement of liability is due to an unreasonable position and knew (or reasonably should have known) of the position, such tax return preparer shall pay a penalty with respect to each such return or claim in an amount equal to the greater of:nn$1,000 orn50% of the income derived (or to be derived) by the tax return preparer with respect to the return or claim.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1372,9,'What is the penalty for failure to provide the taxpayer with a copy of her return?','[\"$120 for each failure, but no more than $5,000 in a return period\",\"$240 for each failure, but no more than $10,000 in a return period\",\"$60 for each failure, but no more than $28,000 in a return period\",\"$60 for each failure, but no more than $30,000 in a return period\"]',3,'Compensated tax return preparers must furnish the taxpayer with a copy of the prepared return no later than the time the original return is presented for signing. Under IRC 6695(a), in calendar year 2024 the penalty is $60 for each failure, but no more than a total of $30,000 in a return period for this and other \"assessable penalties.\"n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1373,9,'Barbara is an enrolled agent who only prepares tax returns. One of her clients was audited by the IRS and a substantial income tax deficiency resulted. Barbara was determined by the IRS to be a tax return preparer and a preparer penalty was assessed. Which of the following actions is available to Barbara?','[\"Barbara can contest the validity of the penalty in Tax Court without making any payment of the penalty.\",\"Barbara can contest the validity of the penalty in Tax Court by paying at least 15% of the assessed penalty.\",\"Barbara can contest the validity of the penalty in District Court by paying at least 15% of the assessed penalty.\",\"Barbara can contest the validity of the penalty in District Court without making any payment of the penalty.\"]',2,'Pursuant to IRC Section 6694(c), a preparer can contest the validity of a preparer penalty if they pay at least 15% of the assessed preparer penalty and fines within 30 days after the day on which notice, and demand of any penalty is made against the tax return preparer. Moreover, the preparer must file his or her claim for refund of the amount paid in the appropriate U.S. District Court.nnTherefore, Barbara can contest the validity of the penalty by filing a claim for refund in the U.S. District Court and by paying at least 15% of the assessed penalty.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1374,9,'If you are employed as a tax preparer employee by a company, which of the following penalties may be assessed to you as a tax preparer?','[\"$60 per return for failure to furnish a copy of the return to the taxpayer\",\"$60 per return for failure to furnish preparer\'s identifying number to the taxpayer\",\"$60 per return for failure to maintain copies of returns prepared or maintain a listing of clients\",\"None of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'A tax preparer is subject to penalties by the IRS if the preparer fails to furnish a copy of the tax return to the taxpayer pursuant to IRC Section 6695(a), fails to retain a copy of the return or a list of the return (including the name and taxpayer identification number of the taxpayer for whom the return or claim was prepared) pursuant to IRC Section 6695(d), or fails to furnish his or her identification number to the taxpayer pursuant to IRC Section 6695(c).nnHowever, IRC Section 7701(a)(36)(B)(ii) provides that a person shall not be a “tax return preparer” merely because such person prepares a return or claim for refund of the employer (or of an officer or employee of the employer) by whom he or she is regularly and continuously employed.nnSince this person is not a tax preparer pursuant to the IRC, none of the penalty items that are listed in this problem apply to this person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1375,9,'What is the civil penalty if a taxpayer claims withholding allowances that are based on false information?','[\"$100\",\"$250\",\"$500\",\"$1,000\"]',2,'A civil penalty of $500 applies if a taxpayer claims withholding allowances that are based on false information. Note that a criminal penalty can also apply to a willful failure to supply information or for willfully supplying false or fraudulent information regarding withholding, which is an additional fine of up to $1,000 and/or up to one year in prison.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1376,9,'What is the first-tier penalty for which a compensated preparer may be liable for each tax return or claim for refund that understates the taxpayer’s liability due to an unreasonable position?','[\"The sum of $1,000\",\"Fifty percent (50%) of income derived by the taxpayer\",\"The sum of $10,000\",\"The greater of $1,000 or 50% of income derived by the tax return preparer with respect to the return or claim\"]',3,'The first-tier penalty is the greater of $1,000 or 50% of income derived by the tax preparer. (Note that there is also a second-tier penalty of $5,000 or 75% penalty of income derived if the preparer willfully or recklessly understated the liability.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1377,9,'Isaac\'s income tax return for 2023 was examined. This resulted in an income tax deficiency in the amount of $50,000 from two $25,000 adjustments. The Revenue Agent determined that Isaac was negligent involving the first adjustment and proposed an accuracy-related penalty. The second adjustment was discovered by the Revenue Agent based upon a disclosure statement in the tax return and did not relate to a tax shelter. What is the amount of penalty that the Revenue Agent can propose?','[\"$2,500\",\"$5,000\",\"$10,000\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'With respect to this question, IRC Section 6662(a) discusses the accuracy-related penalty. In general, an accuracy-related penalty of 20% can be charged for underpayments of tax due to negligence or disregard of rules or regulations or substantial understatement of tax.nnIRC Section 6662(c) defines the term “negligence” to include any failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the provisions of this title, and the term “disregard” includes any careless, reckless, or intentional disregard.nnPublication 17, pages 20 and 21, further provides information on accuracy related penalties. That is, the penalty is 40% of any portion of the underpayment that is attributable to an undisclosed noneconomic substance transaction or an undisclosed foreign financial asset transaction. Furthermore, the taxpayer can avoid the penalty for disregard of rules or regulations if he or she adequately discloses on the return a position that has at least a reasonable basis. This exception, however, will not apply to an item that is attributable to a tax shelter.nnIn this case, the Revenue Agent can propose a penalty of $5,000, which is 20% of the first adjustment amount of $25,000. No penalty would apply to the second adjustment since it was disclosed. Be aware that this statement is often overlooked by a person taking the exam.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1378,9,'Which of the following is required of an income tax preparer?nn1. She must maintain her records for 3 years.n2. She is required to retain a copy of the return.n3. She is required to retain a list of the names, identification numbers, and tax years for which returns were prepared.','[\"1, 2, and 3 are required.\",\"1 is required as well as 2 or 3.\",\"1, 2, or 3 is required.\",\"1 or 2 is required as well as 3.\"]',1,'The tax return preparer must keep for 3 years (following the close of the return period) a copy of the return (either a paper copy or in digital form) or a list of the names, identification numbers, and tax years for whom returns were prepared (IRC Section 6107(b)). In addition, the tax return preparer must make such copy or list available for inspection upon request by the Secretary of the Treasury.nnIRC Section 6695(d) addresses the issue of failing to retain a copy or list. Specifically, any person who is a tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund who fails to comply with Section 6107(b) with respect to such return or claim shall pay a penalty of $60 for each such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect. The maximum penalty imposed under this subsection on any person with respect to any return period shall not exceed $30,000 for 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1379,9,'Which of the following is correct if you work for a firm as a tax return preparer and fail to furnish a copy of the tax return to the taxpayer?','[\"You may be assessed a penalty of $60 per return.\",\"You may be assessed a penalty of $160 per return.\",\"You may be assessed a penalty of $60 per return for failure to furnish a copy of the tax return to the taxpayer, unless such failure is due to reasonable cause and not to willful neglect.\",\"You would\\u00a0not\\u00a0be assessed a penalty because you are not an income tax preparer.\"]',2,'IRC Section 6695(a) states that any person who is a tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund and who fails to furnish a copy of the tax return to the taxpayer (IRC Section 6107) shall pay a penalty of $60 for such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect. The maximum penalty imposed on any person with respect to documents filed during any calendar year shall not exceed $30,000 for year 2024.nnNote: IRC Section 6695 covers a number of penalties associated with the preparation of tax returns.nnIRC Section 7701(a)(36) provides that a person who prepares for compensation, or who employs one or more persons to prepare for compensation, any return of tax is deemed a tax return preparer. However, a person shall not be a “tax return preparer” merely because such person:nnfurnishes typing, reproducing, or other mechanical assistance,nprepares a return or claim for refund of the employer (or of an officer or employee of the employer) by whom he is regularly and continuously employed,nprepares as a fiduciary a return or claim for refund for any person, ornprepares a claim for refund for a taxpayer in response to any notice of deficiency issued to such taxpayer or in response to any waiver of restriction after the commencement of an audit of such taxpayer or another taxpayer if a determination in such audit of such other taxpayer directly or indirectly affects the tax liability of such taxpayer.nAs a result, the person in this problem is a tax preparer and therefore should be assessed a penalty for failure to furnish a copy of the return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1380,9,'In preparing an Earned Income Credit Worksheet and Form 8867, to meet the due diligence requirements, a return preparer must retain for a certain period all of the following EXCEPT:','[\"a record of from whom the information used to prepare the Form 8867 and the worksheets was obtained.\",\"a copy of the Form 8867.\",\"a record of any questions the taxpayer may have asked the tax preparer about their eligibility for the credits.\",\"Copies of documents provided by the taxpayer that the return preparer relied on to determine the eligibility for the credits\"]',2,'As provided on page 5 of the Instructions for Form 8867, a tax preparer is required to maintain the following records to meet the due diligence requirements:nnA copy of Form 8867;nThe applicable worksheet(s) or the tax preparer’s own worksheet(s) for any credit claimed by the taxpayer;nCopies of any documents provided by the taxpayer on which the tax preparer relied to determine the taxpayer’s eligibility for, and the amount of the credit(s);nA record of how, when, and from whom the information used to prepare Form 8867 and the worksheet(s) was obtained, andnA record of any additional questions the tax preparer may have asked to determine eligibility for, and the amount of, the credit(s), and the taxpayer’s answers.nThe due diligence penalty applies to each of the four tax credits independently beginning in 2016. Starting in 2018, head of household is included on the due diligence checklist, which makes five items on the checklist. The penalty is annually adjusted for inflation.nnTherefore, a record of any additional questions the tax preparer (not the taxpayer) may have asked to determine eligibility for, and the amount of, the credit(s), and the taxpayer\'s answers is required to be retained.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1381,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a penalty assessed on a preparer under IRC Section 6694 for a return prepared in October 2024?','[\"The penalty must be abated up to the amount already paid if in the final judicial decision there is no understatement of liability.\",\"The penalty must be abated and any amount paid refunded if in the final judicial decision there is no understatement of liability.\",\"A penalty of not less than $1,500 is assessed against a tax preparer if the understatement of liability is due to a willful attempt to understate the liability.\",\"A penalty of not less than $500 is assessed against a tax preparer if the understatement of liability is due to an unrealistic position of being sustained on its merits.\"]',1,'IRC Section 6694(d) provides the rules concerning the abatement of penalty where taxpayer liability is not understated. More specifically, if at any time there is a final administrative determination or a final judicial decision that there was no understatement of liability in the case of any return, such assessment shall be abated; and if any portion of such penalty has been paid, the amount so paid shall be refunded to the person who made such payment as an overpayment of tax without regard to any period of limitations which, but for this subsection, would apply to the making of such refund.nnIn the case of an understatement of a taxpayer’s liability by a tax return preparer due to willful or reckless conduct, the penalty shall equal the greater of $5,000 (not $1,500) or 75% of the income derived by the tax return preparer with respect to the return or claim for refund. (IRC Section 6694(b))nnLikewise, a penalty is assessed against the tax return preparer that is the greater of $1,000 (not $500) or 50% of the income derived by the tax return preparer for the returns prepared, if the understatement of liability is due to an unreasonable position and the preparer knew (or reasonably should have known) of the position. (IRC Section 6694 (a))',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1382,9,'A tax preparer filed a return for a taxpayer and used the taxpayer\'s detailed check register containing both business and personal expenses. If the tax preparer knowingly included personal expenses as deductible business expenses on the taxpayer\'s business, then the:','[\"tax preparer will be liable only for penalties for taking an unreasonable position that led to an understatement.\",\"taxpayer will be liable for penalties for taking an unreasonable position that led to an understatement.\",\"\\n\\ntax preparer will be liable for penalties arising from an understatement due to willful or reckless conduct.\",\"taxpayer will be liable for penalties attributable to transactions lacking economic substance.\"]',2,'A compensated tax return preparer can be liable for civil and criminal penalties for negligently or intentionally understating a taxpayer’s liability. A compensated preparer can be liable for the greater of $1,000 or a 50% penalty of income derived (first-tier penalty) for each tax return or claim for refund that understates the taxpayer\'s liability due to unreasonable positions. There is a second-tier penalty of $5,000 or 75% penalty of income derived if the preparer willfully or recklessly understated the liability.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1383,9,'Donna is a secretary who prepares income tax returns during the tax filing season. Donna does not keep a copy of the returns she prepares but she does keep a record of her clients\' names, identification numbers, tax year, and type of return prepared. What penalties is Donna subject to?','[\"$60 for each copy of a tax return she does not retain up to a maximum of $30,000 for each year\",\"$60 for each copy of a tax return she does not retain and no annual limit\",\"$60 for each copy of a tax return she does not retain for each of the 3 years required to be retained\",\"No penalty is imposed.\"]',3,'IRC Section 6695(d) requires that a tax preparer must retain a copy OR list of tax returns prepared by the person (as prescribed in IRC Section 6107(b)). Failure to comply with the above rules shall result in a penalty of $60 for each such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect. The maximum penalty imposed under this subsection on any person with respect to any return period shall not exceed $30,000 in 2024.nnThe tax return preparer must keep for 3 years (following the close of the return period) a copy of the return (either a paper copy or in digital form) OR a list of the names, identification numbers, and tax years for whom returns were prepared (IRC Section 6107).nnSince Donna has maintained a list that includes all of the required information, she would not be subject to the penalty. The implication here, although not stated, is she maintains her records for at least 3 years.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1384,9,'Under which of the following conditions is a tax return preparer not subject to a penalty associated with the understatement of a taxpayer\'s liability due to an unreasonable position in the case of a reportable transaction?','[\"There is a 1-in-3, or greater, likelihood of being sustained on its merits.\",\"There is reasonable basis for the position.\",\"The position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.\",\"There is or was substantial authority for the position.\"]',2,'A tax return preparer is liable for a penalty under IRC Section 6694(a)(2) (i.e., penalty for understatement due to unreasonable position) unless they satisfy an exception provided for the defined three categories: general, disclosed position, and tax shelter or reportable transaction.nnThe general category exception is satisfied if there is or was substantial authority for the position.nThe disclosed position category exception is satisfied if item 3 (below) does not apply and there is reasonable basis for the position.nThe tax shelter or reportable transaction category exception is satisfied unless it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.nIn addition, no penalty shall be imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.nnIn this case, the question is tricky because it states the case as a reportable transaction; as such, the exception is satisfied only if it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1385,9,'To avoid imposition of the accuracy-related penalty for a substantial understatement of income tax, which of the following is a type of authority that may be relied upon by the taxpayer to try to show substantial authority for the tax treatment of an item?','[\"www.irs.gov\",\"Revenue rulings\",\"IRS Forms\",\"IRS Publications\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 20, provides that an accuracy-related penalty can be imposed for underpayments of tax due to:nnnegligence or disregard of rules or regulations,nsubstantial understatement of tax,nclaiming a tax benefit for a transaction that lacks economic substance, ornfailure to disclose a foreign financial asset.nA taxpayer understates their tax if the tax shown on their return is less than the correct tax. The understatement is substantial if it is more than the larger of 10% of the correct tax or $5,000. However, the amount of the understatement may be reduced to the extent the understatement is due to:nnsubstantial authority, ornadequate disclosure and a reasonable basis.nWhether there is or was substantial authority for the tax treatment of an item depends on the facts and circumstances. Some of the items that may be considered are court opinions, Treasury regulations, revenue rulings, revenue procedures, and notices and announcements issued by the IRS and published in the Internal Revenue Bulletin that involve the same or similar circumstances as the taxpayer.nnAuthority does not include items such as www.irs.gov, IRS Publications, or IRS Forms or their Instructions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1386,9,'Which of the following is correct about an income tax return preparer that is required to sign a tax return?','[\"Failure to sign the return is subject to a $60 penalty.\",\"Failure to sign the return is subject to a $120 penalty.\",\"Failure to sign the return is subject to a penalty in each of the tax return\'s open years.\",\"Failure to sign the return is subject to a warning but no penalty.\"]',0,'IRC Section 6695(b) provides that any person who is a tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund, who is required by regulations prescribed by the Treasury Secretary to sign such return or claim, and who fails to comply with such regulations with respect to such return or claim shall pay a penalty of $60 for such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect. The maximum penalty imposed under this subsection on any person with respect to documents filed during any calendar year shall not exceed $30,000 in 2024.nnAs a result of the above Code section, failure to sign the return is subject to a $60 penalty.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1387,9,'One of the accuracy-related penalties for taxpayers is for negligence or disregard of rules and regulations. The penalty is a percentage of the underpayment. What is that percentage?','[0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625,0.1499999999999999944488848768742172978818416595458984375,0.200000000000000011102230246251565404236316680908203125,0.25]',2,'The accuracy-related penalty combines several related penalties so that multiple penalties will not apply to a single understatement of tax.nnEach of the accuracy-related penalties is 20% of the portion of the tax underpayment attributable to (1) negligence or disregard of rules and regulations, (2) substantial understatement of tax liability, (3) substantial valuation overstatement, or (4) substantial valuation understatement. The penalty will not apply if the taxpayer can show a reasonable basis for the position that was taken on the return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1388,9,'What is the second-tier penalty if a tax preparer willfully or recklessly understated a taxpayer’s liability?','[\"The greater of $2,000 or 60% of the liability\",\"The greater of $3,000 or 60% of the liability\",\"The greater of $5,000 or 65% of the liability\",\"The greater of $5,000 or 75% of the liability\"]',3,'The penalty is the greater of $5,000 or 75% of the liability. (Note that there is also a first-tier penalty of the greater of $1,000 or 50% of income derived by the tax preparer for each tax return or claim for refund that understates the taxpayer’s liability due to unreasonable positions.)nnIRC Section 6694(b)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1389,9,'What is the maximum prison sentence for willful attempt to evade or defeat tax?','[\"3 years\",\"4 years\",\"5 years\",\"10 years\"]',2,'The maximum penalty for a willful attempt by an individual to evade or defeat tax is a $100,000 fine and/or five years in prison. For a corporation, there is no imprisonment, but the maximum fine is $500,000.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1390,9,'Which of the following statements is incorrect with respect to signing a taxpayer\'s income tax return?','[\"Both spouses must sign the return when filing a joint tax return.\",\"A child (or parent or guardian) must sign the return when a child is required to file a tax return.\",\"Taxpayers can use an electronic signature to sign their tax return when e-filing a return.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct. (There are no incorrect statements.)\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 17, page 23, in the case of a joint return, both spouses must sign the return, even if only one of the spouses had income. Likewise, if a child has to file a tax return but cannot sign the return, the child\'s parent, guardian, or another legally responsible person must sign the child\'s name, followed by the words “By (person\'s signature), parent for minor child”.nnPublication 17, pages 22 and 23, also provides, in part, that both spouses may be held responsible, jointly and individually, for the tax and any interest or penalty due on your joint return. This means that if one spouse doesn\'t pay the tax due, the other may have to. Or, if one spouse doesn\'t report the correct tax, both spouses may be responsible for any additional taxes assessed by the IRS. One spouse may be held responsible for all the tax due even if all the income was earned by the other spouse.nnIn addition, both spouses may be held jointly and individually responsible for any tax, interest, and penalties due on a joint return filed before the couple’s divorce. This responsibility may apply even if the divorce decree states that the former spouse will be responsible for any amounts due on previously filed joint returns.nnFinally, Publication 17, page 14, provides that if a taxpayer e-files their return, the taxpayer can use an electronic signature to sign the tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1391,9,'Which of the following statements is correct about filing Form 8867 with a 2024 tax return concerning the paid preparer\'s child tax credit?','[\"It does not apply to the child tax credit.\",\"It contains a due diligence requirements section.\",\"It does not apply to head of household filing status.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',1,'Form 8867 is a paid preparer\'s (not a taxpayer\'s) due diligence checklist that should be completed by a tax preparer. Beginning with the filing of 2016 tax returns, Form 8867 is required to be filed with the tax returns claiming the earned income credit, child tax credit/additional child tax credit, and/or American opportunity tax credit. In addition, Form 8867 was expanded to include tax returns claiming head of household filing status. nnIn addition, the checklist has six parts:nnDue Diligence RequirementsnDue Diligence Questions for Returns Claiming EICnDue Diligence Questions for Returns Claiming CTC/ACTC/ODCnDue Diligence Questions for Returns Claiming AOTCnDue Diligence Questions for Returns Claiming Head of HouseholdnEligibility CertificationnAs a result, the only correct response for this question is that the checklist contains a due diligence requirements section.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1392,9,'Which, if any, of the following could result in penalties imposed on an income tax return preparer?nnI. Knowing or reckless disclosure or use of tax information obtained in preparing a returnnII. A willful attempt to understate any client’s tax liability on a return or claim for refund','[\"Neither I nor II\",\"I only\",\"II only\",\"Both I and II\"]',3,'Two sections of the Internal Revenue Code (IRC Sections 6713(a) and 7216(a)) impose penalties for the disclosure of information obtained to prepare a tax return.nnIRC Section 6694(b) imposes a penalty for an understatement due to willful or reckless conduct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1393,9,'Willie is the owner of an accounting firm. One of Willie\'s employees prepares an income tax return for a client and opines that a deduction can be claimed for a bad debt. If the return is examined and the deduction is disallowed, Willie will not be subject to a preparer penalty under which of the following circumstances?','[\"The position was disclosed on the return and it had a reasonable basis.\",\"There is reasonable cause for the understatement and the preparer acted in good faith.\",\"There is substantial authority to sustain the position taken on the return.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'A tax return preparer is liable for a penalty under IRC Section 6694(a) (i.e., penalty for understatement due to unreasonable position) unless they satisfy an exception provided for the defined three categories: general, disclosed position, and tax shelter or reportable transaction.nnThe general category exception is satisfied if there is or was substantial authority for the position.nThe disclosed position category exception is satisfied if item 3 (below) does not apply and there is reasonable basis for the position.nThe tax shelter or reportable transaction category exception is satisfied unless it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.nIn addition, no penalty shall be imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1394,9,'What is the penalty if a taxpayer fails to pay the tax as shown due on the tax return?','[\"A penalty of 0.5% per month (up to a maximum of 25%)\",\"A penalty of 1% per month (up to a maximum of 5%)\",\"A penalty of 2% per month (up to a maximum of 10%)\",\"A penalty of 3.5% per month (up to a maximum of 14%)\"]',0,'If a taxpayer fails to pay the tax shown as due on the return, a penalty of 0.5% per month (up to a maximum of 25%) is imposed on the tax due. The penalty amount is doubled if the taxpayer fails to pay the tax once a deficiency assessment has been made.nnThis penalty does not apply during the automatic 6-month extension of time to file period if at least 90% of the actual tax liability was paid in on or before the due date of the return and the balance paid when the return was filed.nnIf a notice of intent to levy is issued, the rate will increase to 1% at the start of the first month beginning at least 10 days after the day that the notice is issued.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1395,9,'Janet is not an enrolled agent, CPA, attorney, or enrolled actuary. In 2024, the president of Widgets-R-Us engaged Janet to prepare the company\'s 2023 Form 1120-S. She prepared the 2023 income tax return for Widgets-R-Us and signed it as the preparer. This is the only return Janet prepared for Widgets-R-Us. In December 2023, the IRS began an examination of Widgets-R-Us\' 2022 and 2023 federal income tax returns. Janet has a power of attorney to represent Widgets-R-Us for 2022 and 2023. Under Circular 230, Janet is permitted to represent Widgets-R-Us during the examination with regard to its:','[\"2022 Form 1120-S only.\",\"2023 Form 1120-S only.\",\"2022 and 2023 Forms 1120-S.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Pursuant to Publication 947, pages 3 and 4, the following list of individuals qualifies to sign and therefore act as a representative of the taxpayer. The qualifying individuals include an attorney, certified public accountant, and enrolled agent, as well as the following:nnOfficer—a bona fide officer of the taxpayer\'s organizationnFull-Time Employee—a full-time employee of the taxpayernFamily Member—a member of the taxpayer\'s immediate family (i.e., spouse, parent, child, brother, or sister)nUnenrolled Return Preparer—the authority to practice before the Internal Revenue Service is limited. The unenrolled return preparer must have prepared the return in question and the return must be under examination by the IRS.nnSince Janet is an unenrolled return preparer, she can represent Widgets-R-Us during the examination of the 2023 Form 1120-S only, which is the return that she prepared.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1396,9,'What penalty may be assessed an income tax return preparer that fails to be diligent in determining eligibility for a taxpayer claiming the earned income credit for 2024 (return filed in 2025)?','[\"$560 per return\",\"$635 per return\",\"$600 per return\",\"$1,200 per return\"]',1,'IRC Section 6695(g) states that any person who is an income tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund and who fails to comply with due diligence requirements as imposed by the Treasury Secretary by regulations with respect to determining eligibility for, or the amount of, the earned income credit shall pay a penalty of $635 in 2024 for returns filed in 2025 (adjusted annually for COLA) for each such failure. There is no maximum penalty limit for this violation (Rev. Proc. 2019-44).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1397,9,'The Internal Revenue Code and the regulations do not impose penalties on tax return preparers for which of the following?','[\"Failure to sign a prepared tax return as a tax preparer\",\"Failure to provide a copy of a prepared tax return to the taxpayer\",\"Failure to notify a taxpayer about an inadvertent error on a tax return filed 10 years ago\",\"Failure to retain copies of prepared tax returns or a list of taxpayers for whom such returns were prepared for the last 3 years\"]',2,'Failure to notify a taxpayer about an inadvertent error on a tax return filed 10 years ago will not result in a penalty on tax return preparers.nnFailure to sign a prepared tax return as a tax preparer, provide a copy of the return to the taxpayer, or retain copies of prepared tax returns will result in a penalty of $60 per failure. These are “other assessable penalties” with a total of all such penalties not to exceed $30,000 in a given return period in 2024.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1398,9,'Which of the following statements is correct about any person who employs a tax return preparer to prepare tax returns?','[\"The person must file an information return with the IRS that contains the name, taxpayer identification number, and place of employment of each preparer employed during any return period.\",\"The person must maintain a record of the name, taxpayer identification number, and place of employment of each preparer employed during any return period.\",\"The person must file an information return with the Department of Labor that contains the name, taxpayer identification number, and place of employment of each preparer employed during any return period.\",\"The person is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file an information return or maintain a record of information on his or her preparers.\"]',1,'Pursuant to IRC Section 6060, any person who employs a tax return preparer to prepare any return or claim for refund other than for such person at any time during a return period shall make a return setting forth the name, taxpayer identification number, and place of work of each tax return preparer employed by him or her at any time during such period. The return required by this section shall be filed, in such manner as the Secretary may by regulations prescribe, on or before the first July 31 following the end of such return period.nnHowever, the IRS does not currently require any such information form to be filed. Rather, a person shall satisfy the requirements of IRC Section 6060 (as given above) by retaining a record of such information. (Regulation Section 1.6060-1)nnFor purposes of this section, any individual who in acting as a tax return preparer is not the employee of another tax return preparer shall be treated as his or her own employer.nnFor purposes of this section, the term \"return period\" means the 12-month period beginning on July 1 of each year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1399,9,'What penalty may be asserted by the IRS if an income tax return preparer knows or reasonably should have known that the tax on a return he or she prepared is understated due to a position for which there was not a realistic possibility of being sustained on its merits?','[\"A penalty of $250\",\"A penalty of $1,000\",\"A penalty of $1,500\",\"A penalty of $5,000\"]',1,'IRC Section 6694(a) provides that a penalty is assessed against the tax return preparer if the understatement of liability is due to an unreasonable position and the tax preparer knew (or reasonably should have known) of the position. The penalty is the greater of:nn$1,000 orn50% of the income derived by the tax return preparer with respect to the return or claim for refund.nPursuant to IRC Section 6694, an unreasonable position is one that in general is a position where there is or was no substantial authority for the position. In addition:nnif the position was disclosed as provided in IRC Section 6662(d)(2)(B)(ii)(I) and it is not a tax shelter or reportable transaction, the position is unreasonable unless there is a reasonable basis for the position; ornif the position is with respect to a tax shelter or a reportable transaction to which IRC Section 6662A applies, the position is unreasonable unless it is reasonable to believe that the position would more likely than not be sustained on its merits.nNo penalty shall be imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1400,9,'Which of the following statements defines the term “negligence”?','[\"It includes a failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the tax law in preparing a return.\",\"It includes a failure to make a reasonable attempt to exercise ordinary and reasonable care in preparing a return.\",\"It includes a failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the tax law (Internal Revenue Code).\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'As defined in IRC Section 6662, an underpayment of tax may incur an accuracy-related penalty of 20% on that portion of the underpayment in the case of:nnnegligence or disregard of rules or regulations,nany substantial understatement of income tax,nany substantial valuation misstatement under Chapter 1 of the Internal Revenue Code (i.e., normal taxes and surtaxes),nany substantial overstatement of pension liabilities,nany substantial estate or gift tax valuation understatement,nany disallowance of claimed tax benefits by reason of a transaction lacking economic substance,nany undisclosed foreign financial asset understatement, ornan inconsistent estate basis.nIRC Section 6662(c) defines negligence for the imposition of accuracy-related penalty to include any failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the provisions of this title (i.e., IRC), and the term “disregard” includes any careless, reckless, or intentional disregard.nnPublication 17 defines negligence as \"failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the tax law or to exercise ordinary and reasonable care in preparing a return. Negligence also includes failures to keep adequate books and records.\" Finally, a negligence penalty can be avoided if the taxpayer has a reasonable basis for the position taken.nnTherefore, all of the answer choices provided are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1401,9,'What is the maximum accuracy-related penalty for the underpayment of tax that the Internal Revenue Service can assert if you understate your income tax because of negligent acts or a disregard of the rules or regulations?','[\"$500\",\"20% of the underpayment\",\"25% of the underpayment\",\"40% of the underpayment\"]',1,'Publication 17, page 21, provides that an accuracy-related penalty can be imposed for underpayments of tax due to:nnnegligence or disregard of rules or regulations,nsubstantial understatement of tax,nclaiming a tax benefit for a transaction that lacks economic substance, ornfailure to disclose a foreign financial asset.nNegligence includes any failure to make a reasonable attempt to comply with the provisions of the Internal Revenue Code. It also includes any failure to keep adequate books and records. A return position that has a reasonable basis is not negligence.nnDisregard includes any careless, reckless, or intentional disregard of rules or regulations.nnThe penalty is 20% for negligence or disregard of the rules or regulations, or substantial understatement of tax, and 40% of any portion of the underpayment that is attributable to an undisclosed noneconomic substance transaction (lacks economic substance) or an undisclosed foreign financial asset transaction (fail to disclose a foreign financial asset).nnThe penalty for disregard of rules and regulations can be avoided through adequate disclosure if all of the following are true:nnThe taxpayer keeps adequate books and records.nThe taxpayer has a reasonable basis for his or her position on the tax issue.nThe taxpayer makes an adequate disclosure of his or her position.nIn addition, penalties may be imposed for late filing (5% per month or part of a month, but not more than 25%) and for filing a fraudulent return (15% per month or part of a month, but not more than 75% of the underpayment due to fraud).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1402,9,'What is the maximum penalty for failing to file Form 8867, Paid Preparer’s Due Diligence Checklist, if the taxpayer claimed both the earned income tax credit and claimed head of household filing status on their 2024 tax return?','[\"$635\",\"$600\",\"$1,200\",\"$1,270\"]',3,'Regulation Sections 1.6695-2 and 1.6695-2T provide guidance on satisfying the due diligence requirement for a paid tax return preparer claiming the earned income tax credit, the child tax credit/additional child tax credit, and/or the American opportunity tax credit for a client. Failure to comply with the due diligence regulations results in a $635 penalty for each failure on a 2024 tax return.nnThe due diligence penalty applies to each of the four tax credits independently. Therefore, the maximum penalty for failing to comply where a taxpayer who claims the earned income tax credit and files as head of household on their 2024 tax return (filed in 2025) is $1,270 (2 infractions × $635). The penalty is $635 for 2024 per error (Rev. Proc. 2019-44).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1403,9,'George is a truck driver who is also a licensed return preparer and specializes in preparing income tax returns claiming the American opportunity tax credit (AOTC). George will not be subject to a preparer penalty for an erroneously claimed AOTC if he complies with which one of the following?','[\"Completion of Form 8867,\\u00a0Paid Preparer\\u2019s Due Diligence Checklist,\\u00a0based upon information provided by the client and filed with the tax return or claim for refund\",\"Completion of the computation worksheet for the AOTC based upon information provided by the client\",\"Knowledge or reason to know that the information used to determine eligibility for an amount of the AOTC is correct\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Regulation Sections 1.6695-2 and 1.6695-2T provide guidance on satisfying the due diligence requirement for a tax return preparer claiming the earned income tax credit, the child tax credit/additional child tax credit, and/or the American opportunity tax credit, and head of household filing status for a client and thereby avoiding the penalty for each failure. In general, the regulation provides, in part, that a preparer must satisfy the following due diligence requirements:nnCompletion and submission of Form 8867, Paid Preparer’s Due Diligence Checklist, or such other form as may be prescribed by the IRS and filed with the tax return or claim for refundnComputation of credit: The tax return preparer must either complete the applicable worksheet in the Form 1040 Instructions (if any) or such other form and such other information as may be prescribed by the IRS; or otherwise record in one or more documents in the tax return preparer’s papers or electronic files the AOTC computations, including the method and information used to make the computation.nKnowledge: The preparer must not know, or have reason to know, that any information used by the preparer in determining the taxpayer\'s eligibility for, or the amount of, the AOTC is incorrect. The preparer may not ignore the implications of information furnished to, or known by, the preparer, and must make reasonable inquiries if the information furnished to, or known by, the preparer appears to be incorrect, inconsistent, or incomplete.nRetention of records: The preparer must retain a copy of Form 8867 (or successor form), any applicable worksheet (or other record of the AOTC computation), and a record of how and when the information used to complete the Form 8867 (or successor form) and the applicable worksheet (or other record of the AOTC computation) was obtained by the preparer, including the identity of any person furnishing the information.nGeorge will not be subject to a preparer penalty if he complies with all four of the requirements given in this problem.nnThe due diligence penalty applies to each of the four tax credits and the head of household filing status independently. The penalty is annually adjusted for inflation.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1404,9,'A paid preparer must:nn1. give the taxpayer a copy of his or her tax return.n2. give the taxpayer a copy of his or her tax return that has a claim for refund.n3. sign the tax return after the taxpayer signs the tax return.','[\"1 and 3\",\"2 and 3\",\"1 and 2\",\"1, 2, and 3\"]',2,'IRC Section 6695(a) provides that any person who is a tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund who fails to furnish a copy of the tax return to the taxpayer (i.e., comply with IRC Section 6107(a)) shall pay a penalty of $60 for such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect. The maximum penalty imposed under this subsection on any person with respect to documents filed during any calendar year shall not exceed $30,000 (as of 2024). Hence, items 1 and 2 are correct.nnRegulation Section 1.6695-1(b) provides that a tax return preparer shall sign the return or claim for refund after it is completed and before it is presented to the taxpayer for signature. Hence, item 3 is incorrect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1405,9,'Morgan, a sole practitioner EA, prepares individual and corporate income tax returns. What documentation is Morgan required to retain concerning each return prepared?','[\"An unrelated party compliance statement\",\"Taxpayer\'s name and identification number or a copy of the tax return\",\"Workpapers associated with the preparation of each tax return\",\"A power of attorney\"]',1,'One requirement the IRS imposes on tax return preparers is that records be maintained for at least three years for each return. The records that the IRS requires to be maintained include the taxpayer\'s name and identification number or a copy of the tax return. A penalty of $60 per incident (up to $30,000 in calendar year 2024) can apply to preparers who fail to maintain the required records. (IRC Section 6695(d))nnIn addition to the requirements of the IRS, each state may impose record keeping requirements which may include retention of the tax return and workpapers and/or longer holding periods.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1406,9,'Frankie is a truck driver who is also a licensed return preparer and specializes in preparing income tax returns claiming the earned income credit (EIC). Frankie will not be subject to a preparer penalty for an erroneously claimed EIC if he complies with which one of the following?','[\"Completion of Form 8867,\\u00a0Paid Preparer\\u2019s Due Diligence Checklist,\\u00a0based upon information provided by the client and filed with the tax return or claim for refund\",\"Completion of the computation worksheet for the EIC based upon information provided by the client\",\"Knowledge or reason to know that the information used to determine eligibility for an amount of the EIC is correct\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Regulation Sections 1.6695-2 and 1.6695-2T provide guidance on satisfying the due diligence requirement for a tax return preparer claiming the earned income tax credit, child tax credit/additional child tax credit, and/or American opportunity tax credit for a client and also the head of household filing status. Failing to comply with the due diligence requirement results in a penalty for each failure. In general, the regulation provides, in part, that a preparer must satisfy the following due diligence requirements:nnCompletion and submission of Form 8867, Paid Preparer’s Due Diligence Checklist, or such other form as may be prescribed by the IRS and filed with the tax return or claim for refundnComputation of Credit: The tax return preparer must either complete the EIC Worksheet in the Instructions for Form 1040 or such other form and such other information as may be prescribed by the IRS; or otherwise record in one or more documents in the tax return preparer’s papers or electronic files the EIC computations, including the method and information used to make the computation.nKnowledge: The preparer must not know, or have reason to know, that any information used by the preparer in determining the taxpayer\'s eligibility for, or the amount of, the EIC is incorrect. The preparer may not ignore the implications of information furnished to, or known by, the preparer, and must make reasonable inquiries if the information furnished to, or known by, the preparer appears to be incorrect, inconsistent, or incomplete.nRetention of Records: The preparer must retain a copy of Form 8867 (or successor form), the EIC Worksheet (or other record of the EIC computation), and a record of how and when the information used to complete the Form 8867 (or successor form) and the EIC Worksheet (or other record of the EIC computation) was obtained by the preparer, including the identity of any person furnishing the information.nFrankie will not be subject to a preparer penalty if he complies with all four of the requirements given in this problem.nnThe due diligence penalty applies to each of the four tax credits and the head of household filing status independently. The penalty is annually adjusted for inflation. As such, the penalty is $635 for 2024 returns filed in 2025 (adjusted annually for COLA). Failure to comply with two of the credits results in a penalty of $1,270 for returns filed in 2025, and failing to comply with all four items results in a penalty of $2,540 for returns filed in 2025.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1407,9,'What can be said about a preparer who is paid to review a tax return?','[\"He does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to sign or fill in the other blanks in the paid preparer\'s area of the return.\",\"He does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to sign as long as he fills in the other blanks in the paid preparer\'s area of the return.\",\"He must sign and fill in the other blanks in the paid preparer\'s area of the return.\",\"He must sign but is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to fill in the other blanks in the paid preparer\'s area of the return.\"]',2,'Regulation Section 301.7701-15(a) provides that a tax return preparer is any person who prepares for compensation, or who employs one or more persons to prepare for compensation, all or a substantial portion of any return of tax or any claim for refund of tax under the Internal Revenue Code. In addition, a signing tax return preparer is the individual tax return preparer who has the primary responsibility for the overall substantive accuracy of the preparation of such return or claim for refund.nnIRC Section 6695(b) states that any person who is a tax return preparer with respect to any return or claim for refund, who is required by regulations prescribed by the Secretary to sign such return or claim, and who fails to comply with such regulations with respect to such return or claim shall pay a penalty of $60 for such failure, unless it is shown that such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect.nnIf the signing tax return preparer is unavailable for signature, another tax return preparer shall review the entire preparation of the return or claim for refund, and then shall sign the return or claim for refund. The tax return preparer shall sign the return in the manner prescribed by the Commissioner of the IRS in forms, instructions, or other appropriate guidance. (Regulation Section 1.6695-1(b))nnIn this case, a person who reviews the tax return for compensation (i.e., is paid) is a tax preparer and therefore is required to sign the tax return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1408,9,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a penalty for a tax return preparer who understates a taxpayer\'s liability?','[\"No penalty is imposed if the understatement of tax liability is related to a tax shelter and was properly disclosed, and if there was substantial authority for the position.\",\"If there is a final judicial decision that there was\\u00a0no\\u00a0understatement of liability, the related tax preparer penalty paid earlier is\\u00a0not\\u00a0refundable.\",\"In general, the penalty does\\u00a0not\\u00a0apply\\u00a0unless\\u00a0the understatement of the tax liability is at least $10,000.\",\"No penalty is imposed if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and the tax return preparer acted in good faith.\"]',3,'Per Publication 17, page 20 an understatement of tax liability occurs when the tax shown on the tax return is less than the correct tax. However, the understatement becomes substantial when it exceeds the greater of 10% of the correct tax or $5,000. The Publication further provides that the amount of the understatement may be reduced to the extent the understatement is due to:nnsubstantial authority, ornadequate disclosure and a reasonable basis.nIf an item on the return is attributable to a tax shelter, there is no reduction for an adequate disclosure. There is a reduction for a position with substantial authority, but only if supported by tax treatment that was more likely than not the proper treatment.nnTwo Code sections impose penalties on compensated tax return preparers. IRC Section 6694 imposes penalties on paid preparers who take unreasonable positions on tax returns or refund claims that result in an understatement of a taxpayer\'s liability. IRC Section 6694 provides specific details regarding who has responsibility for a position on a return, what is considered an unreasonable position, information verification requirements, and the basis for penalty assessment. The maximum penalties under IRC Section 6694 are percentages of any fee the preparer charged to prepare the return.nnGenerally, the penalty can be waived if it is shown that there is reasonable cause for the understatement and that the tax return preparer acted in good faith. There is no specific penalty relief related to tax shelters; in fact, this is an area where additional penalties can be assessed.nnIRC Section 6695 provides for further assessable penalties when a preparer fails to complete specific administrative responsibilities such as failing to retain a copy of the return, sign the return, or furnish a copy to the taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1409,9,'What is the penalty for failure to provide the taxpayer with a copy of her return?','[\"$120 for each failure, but no more than $5,000 in a return period\",\"$240 for each failure, but no more than $24,000 in a return period\",\"$55 for each failure, but no more than $28,000 in a return period\",\"$60 for each failure, but no more than $30,000 in a return period\"]',3,'Compensated tax return preparers must furnish the taxpayer with a copy of the prepared return no later than the time the original return is presented for signing. Under IRC 6695(a), in calendar year 2024 the penalty is $60 for each failure, but no more than a total of $30,000 in a return period for this and other \"assessable penalties.\"n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1410,9,'If there is an underpayment of tax on your return due to fraud, how much is the maximum penalty that can be added to your tax?','[\"20% of the underpayment due to fraud\",\"20% of the underpayment, reduced for those items for which there was adequate disclosure\",\"$500 added to any other penalty provided by law\",\"75% of the underpayment due to fraud\"]',3,'If there is an underpayment of tax on a taxpayer\'s return due to fraud, a penalty of 75% of the underpayment due to fraud will be added to the taxpayer\'s tax. (Publication 17, page 21)nnOn the other hand, if the taxpayer’s failure to file is due to fraud, the penalty is 15% for each month or part of a month that the taxpayer\'s return is late, up to a maximum of 75%. (Publication 17, page 21)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1411,9,'Lawson, an EA, discovers material noncompliance with a specific Internal Revenue Code (IRC) requirement in the prior-year return of a new client. Which of the following actions should Lawson take?','[\"Wait for the statute of limitations to expire\",\"Discuss the requirement of the IRC with the client and recommend that the client amend the return\",\"Contact the IRS and discuss courses of action\",\"Contact the prior tax return preparer and discuss the client\'s exposure\"]',1,'If a practitioner has been retained by a client with respect to a matter administered by the Internal Revenue Service and knows that the client has not complied with the revenue laws of the United States or has made an error in or omission from any return, document, affidavit, or other paper which the client submitted or executed under the revenue laws of the United States, the practitioner must advise the client promptly of the fact of such noncompliance, error, or omission.nnIn addition, the practitioner must advise the client of the consequences as provided under the Code and regulations of such noncompliance, error, or omission.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1412,9,'Each individual applying for renewal as an enrolled agent must complete CE credits during each year of enrollment. How long must each practitioner maintain records of their completed CE credits?','[\"CE credits do\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to be retained by the enrolled agent since the qualifying organization provides the Internal Revenue Service a list of each participant that completed CE credits.\",\"The enrolled agent does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to retain any proof of CE credits because they must be submitted to the Internal Revenue Service as they are completed.\",\"The enrolled agent must retain, for a period of 1 year from the date she completed the CE credit, information required (as listed in Circular 230) that documents successful completion of qualified CE credits.\",\"The enrolled agent applying for renewal must retain the information required (as listed in Circular 230) which documents successful completion of qualified CE credits, for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment.\"]',3,'The recordkeeping requirements for qualifying continuing professional education by an enrolled agent, instructor, discussion leader, or speaker are found in Circular 230, Section 10.6(h). The specifics are that each individual applying for renewal must retain for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment the information required with regard to qualifying continuing professional education credit hours.nnHence, the correct response for this problem is an enrolled agent must retain the verification of CE taken for a period of 4 years following the date of renewal of enrollment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1413,9,'An individual who received initial enrollment during an enrollment cycle must complete 2 hours of qualifying continuing education credit for each month enrolled during the enrollment cycle. Which of the following statements concerning enrollment for part of a month is correct?','[\"Two (2) credit hours are required for the partial month.\",\"One (1) credit hour is required for the partial month.\",\"One (1) credit hour is required if enrolled in the second half of the month and 2 credit hours are required if enrolled in the first half of the month.\",\"Zero (0) credit hours are required for the partial month.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.6(e)(2)(iii), provides that an enrolled agent applying for renewal of enrollment must certify, on the application for renewal form prescribed by the Internal Revenue Service, that he or she has satisfied the continuing education (CE) requirements:nnFor renewed enrollment, a person must satisfy a minimum of 2 hours of qualifying continuing education credit for each month enrolled during the enrollment cycle, which is 72 hours of continuing education credit during each 3-year period, which is known as an enrollment cycle. Enrollment for any part of a month is considered enrollment for the entire month.nIn addition, a person must satisfy a minimum of 16 hours of continuing education credit (including 2 hours of ethics or professional conduct) during each calendar year in the enrollment term.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1414,8,'To avoid tax return preparer penalties for a return\'s understated tax liability due to an intentional disregard of the regulations, which of the following actions must a tax preparer take?','[\"Audit the taxpayer\'s corresponding business operations.\",\"Review the accuracy of the taxpayer\'s books and records.\",\"Make reasonable inquiries to determine if the taxpayer\'s information is incomplete.\",\"Examine the taxpayer\'s supporting documents.\"]',2,'Tax return preparer penalties are covered in both Circular 230 and 26 CFR 1.6694-1(e). An audit or review is not required and examination of the taxpayer\'s supporting documents is only sometimes required. Reasonable inquiries, however, are generally required.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1415,8,'Rich, an enrolled agent, is currently representing Dana before the Internal Revenue Service. Mike, Dana\'s former business partner, asks Rich to represent him before the Internal Revenue Service. Notwithstanding the existence of a conflict of interest between Dana and Mike, Rich may still represent Mike before the Internal Revenue Service if certain requirements are met. Which of the following is not a requirement that Rich has to satisfy before he can represent Mike?','[\"Dana and Mike must each give informed consent, confirmed in writing, to Rich.\",\"Rich must reasonably believe that he will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to both Dana and Mike.\",\"Rich must immediately notify the Internal Revenue Service in writing that he is representing both Dana and Mike.\",\"The representation is not prohibited by law.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.29(b), provides that notwithstanding the existence of a conflict of interest under paragraph (a) of this section, the practitioner may represent a client if:nnthe practitioner reasonably believes that the practitioner will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to each affected client,nthe representation is not prohibited by law, andneach affected client gives informed consent, confirmed in writing, within a reasonable time after the informed consent, but in no event later than 30 days.nIn addition, copies of the written consents must be retained by the practitioner for at least 36 months from the date of the conclusion of the representation of the affected clients and the written consents must be provided to any officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service on request.nnRich does not need to immediately notify the Internal Revenue Service in writing that he is representing both Dana and Mike.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1416,8,'Paul, an enrolled agent, is currently representing Rosa before the Internal Revenue Service. Mike, Rosa\'s former business partner, asks Paul to represent him before the Internal Revenue Service. Notwithstanding the existence of a conflict of interest between Rosa and Mike, Paul may still represent Mike before the Internal Revenue Service if certain requirements are met. Which of the following is not a requirement that Paul has to satisfy before he can represent Mike?','[\"Paul must retain copies of the written consent for at least 48 months from the date of the conclusion of the representation of the affected clients.\",\"Paul must reasonably believe that he will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to both Rosa and Mike.\",\"Rosa and Mike must each give informed consent, confirmed in writing, to Paul.\",\"The representation is not prohibited by law.\"]',0,'Circular 230, Section 10.29(b), provides that notwithstanding the existence of a conflict of interest under paragraph (a) of this section, the practitioner may represent a client if:nnthe practitioner reasonably believes that the practitioner will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to each affected client,nthe representation is not prohibited by law, andneach affected client gives informed consent, confirmed in writing, within a reasonable time after the informed consent, but in no event later than 30 days.nIn addition, copies of the written consents must be retained by the practitioner for at least 36 (not 48) months from the date of the conclusion of the representation of the affected clients and the written consents must be provided to any officer or employee of the Internal Revenue Service on request. (Circular 230, Section 10.29(c))nnPaul does not need to retain copies of the written consent for at least 48 months from the date of the conclusion of the representation of the affected clients.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1417,8,'Which form does a taxpayer file with the IRS in 2025 if he or she needs a copy of a lost or destroyed 2023 tax return, including all attachments and Form W-2?','[\"Form 4506\",\"Form 4506T-EZ\",\"Form 4506-T\",\"The Service can only provide forms for the prior tax year (i.e., 2024).\"]',0,'A taxpayer files Form 4506 if the taxpayer needs a copy of Form 1040, 1120, 941, etc. and all attachments as originally submitted to the IRS, including Form(s) W-2, schedules, or amended returns. Copies of Forms 1040, 1040-A, and 1040-EZ are generally available for 7 years from filing before they are destroyed by law. There is a fee for each return requested (Form 4506, line 6).nnLikewise, a taxpayer files Form 4506-T-EZ if the taxpayer needs to order a 1040 series tax return transcript, which includes most lines of the original tax return. This service is free of charge.nnFinally, a taxpayer files Form 4506-T if the taxpayer only needs information from his or her return. In this case, the taxpayer requests a return transcript, which includes most of the line items of a tax return as filed with the IRS. Return transcripts are available for the current year and returns processed during the prior 3 processing years.nnSince the taxpayer is requesting a copy of his or her tax return, the taxpayer must file Form 4506.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1418,8,'A taxpayer files Form 4506-T, Request for Transcript of Tax Return, for which of the following taxpayer situations?','[\"To request an account transcript\",\"To request a transcript of a Form W-2\",\"To request a Form 1065 transcript\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to the instructions for Form 4506-T, a taxpayer files Form 4506-T to request tax return information or to designate a third party (see item 5 on Form 4506-T) to receive the information.nnIn particular, a taxpayer may request:nna return transcript, which includes most of the line items of a tax return as filed with the IRS,nan account transcript, which contains information on the financial status of the account, such as payments made on the account, penalty assessments, and adjustments made by the taxpayer or the IRS after the return was filed,na record of account, which is a combination of line item information and later adjustments to the account for the current year and 3 prior tax years,na verification of nonfiling, which is proof from the IRS that a taxpayer did not file a return for the year, orna Form W-2, Form 1099 series, Form 1098 series, or Form 5498 series transcript.nIn addition, the taxpayer must specify the year or period requested. Hence all the responses are correct (Form 4506-T, line 6).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1419,8,'Arnie is an enrolled agent who prepares income tax returns for his clients. Which of the following statements is not correct with respect to Arnie\'s responsibilities on completing a client\'s tax return?','[\"Arnie must make reasonable inquiries if the information as furnished appears to be incorrect or incomplete.\",\"Arnie is required to audit, examine, or review books and records, business operations, or other evidence to verify independently information provided by the taxpayer.\",\"Arnie may rely in good faith without verification upon a tax return that has been previously prepared by another tax return preparer and filed with the IRS.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',1,'For purposes of IRC Sections 6694(a) and (b), the tax return preparer generally may rely in good faith without verification upon information furnished by the taxpayer. Also, a tax return preparer may rely in good faith and without verification upon information and advice furnished by another advisor, another tax return preparer, or other party (including another advisor or tax return preparer at the tax return preparer\'s firm).nnThe tax return preparer is not required to audit, examine, or review books and records, business operations, documents, or other evidence to verify independently information provided by the taxpayer, advisor, other tax return preparer, or other party.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1420,8,'Jennifer is an enrolled agent who prepares income tax returns for her clients. Which of the following statements is correct with respect to Jennifer\'s responsibilities on completing a client\'s tax return?','[\"She must make reasonable inquiries if the information as furnished appears to be incorrect or incomplete.\",\"She may not ignore the implications of information furnished to her or actually known by her.\",\"She need not verify the positions on the original return when preparing an amended return (including a claim for refund).\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'For purposes of tax return preparer penalties under IRC Sections 6694(a) and (b), the tax return preparer generally may rely in good faith without verification upon information furnished by the taxpayer. Also, a tax return preparer may rely in good faith and without verification upon information and advice furnished by another advisor, another tax return preparer, or other party (including another advisor or tax return preparer at the tax return preparer\'s firm). The tax return preparer is not required to audit, examine, or review books and records, business operations, documents, or other evidence to verify independently information provided by the taxpayer, advisor, other tax return preparer, or other party.nnIn addition, a tax return preparer may rely in good faith without verification upon a tax return that has been previously prepared by a taxpayer or another tax return preparer and filed with the IRS. For example, a tax return preparer who prepares an amended return (including a claim for refund) need not verify the positions on the original return. The tax return preparer, however, may not ignore the implications of information furnished to the tax return preparer or actually known by the tax return preparer. The tax return preparer must make reasonable inquiries if the information as furnished appears to be incorrect or incomplete. The tax return preparer must confirm that the position being relied upon has not been adjusted by examination or otherwise.nnHence, all of the responses are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1421,8,'Nancy received a Notice of Tax Due and Demand for Payment in the amount of $25,000 as a result of an examination of her 2022 Form 1040, U.S. Individual Income Tax Return. She is not able to pay the entire amount at this time and would like to set up an Installment Agreement. Which of the following statements is true regarding setting up an Installment Agreement?','[\"Installment Agreements generally require equal monthly payments.\",\"Nancy must file all tax returns that are required to be filed.\",\"Nancy will be charged a user fee to set up an Installment Agreement.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 594, page 3, provides an overview for filing a tax return, billing, and collection. When a tax return is filed, the IRS checks the accuracy of the math and if the taxpayer has paid the correct amount. If the correct amount has not been paid, a bill called a Notice of Tax Due and Demand for Payment will be sent. The bill includes the taxes plus interest and penalties.nnPublication 594, page 3, provides, in part, if a taxpayer is unable to pay all of the taxes at that time, the taxpayer should pay as much as he or she can and thereby reduce the amount of interest and penalty. At this point, the taxpayer needs to contact the nearest IRS office to explain the situation. The taxpayer should have their financial information available, including their monthly income and expenses. Based on the taxpayer’s ability to pay, the IRS may provide alternate payment options.nnIf a taxpayer is unable to pay in full now, they can apply for an Installment Agreement, which is a smaller periodic payment over time. To be eligible for an Installment Agreement, the taxpayer must file all required tax returns and the IRS may ask the taxpayer to fill out a Collection Information Statement (Form 433-F, 433-A, and/or 433-B) and provide proof of their financial status.nnThe instructions for Form 9465, Installment Agreement Request, page 1, provide that a taxpayer is usually notified within 30 days whether the request is approved or denied. However, if this request is for tax due on a return filed by the taxpayer after March 31, it may take the IRS longer than 30 days to reply. If the request is approved, a notice is issued to the taxpayer detailing the terms of the agreement and requesting a user fee. The amount of the user fee can vary depending on whether the taxpayer sets up an Installment Agreement online or agrees to pay by direct debit. The user fees are:nn$22, if the taxpayer sets up an online payment agreement and makes the payments by direct debit;n$107, if the taxpayer does not set up an online payment agreement but makes the payments by direct debit;n$69, if the taxpayer sets up an online payment agreement but does not make the payments by direct debit; orn$178, if the taxpayer does not set up an online payment agreement and does not make the payments by direct debit.nNote: See the “About Form 9465, Installment Agreement Request” page at www.irs.gov for up-to-date information on this issue.nnTherefore, all of the answer choices are true regarding an installment agreement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1422,8,'In the process of examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability, the Internal Revenue Service may contact third parties. Which of the following statements is incorrect?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service must give the taxpayer reasonable notice before making any inquiries of third parties.\",\"The Service is not required to give notice to a taxpayer of third-party contacts if they are pending criminal investigation.\",\"The Service must give a taxpayer a record of persons contacted on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request.\",\"The Service must give the taxpayer a record of persons to be contacted before contacting any third party.\"]',3,'Page 3 of Publication 556 provides, in part, that the IRS must give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons. In examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability, the IRS may contact third parties such as the taxpayer\'s neighbors, banks, employers, or employees.nnThe IRS must also give a taxpayer notice of specific contacts by providing the taxpayer with a record of persons contacted on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request.nnAs one might suspect, there are exceptions to the above policy. The provision does not apply:nnto any pending criminal investigation,nwhen providing notice would jeopardize collection of any tax liability,nwhere providing notice may result in reprisal against any person, ornwhen the taxpayer authorized the contact.nThus, the IRS must notify the taxpayer of specific contacts by providing the taxpayer with a record of persons contacted (not those to be contacted) on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1423,8,'The IRS is permitted to grant a guaranteed installment agreement as long as the taxpayer has not failed to file any income tax returns or pay any tax shown on such returns during any of the preceding:','[\"3 taxable years.\",\"5 taxable years.\",\"7 taxable years.\",\"10 taxable years.\"]',1,'Pursuant to IRC § 6159(c), the Secretary of Treasury is required to enter into an agreement to accept the full payment of such tax in installments if, as of the date the individual offers to enter into the agreement—nnthe aggregate amount of such liability (determined without regard to interest, penalties, additions to the tax, and additional amounts) does not exceed $10,000;nthe taxpayer (and, if such liability relates to a joint return, the taxpayer\'s spouse) has not, during any of the preceding 5 taxable years;nfailed to file any return of tax imposed by subtitle A;nfailed to pay any tax required to be shown on any such return; ornentered into an installment agreement under this section for payment of any tax imposed by subtitle A,nthe Secretary determines that the taxpayer is financially unable to pay such liability in full when due (and the taxpayer submits such information as the Secretary may require to make such determination);nthe agreement requires full payment of such liability within 3 years; andnthe taxpayer agrees to comply with the provisions of this title for the period such agreement is in effect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1424,8,'Which form is filed for collecting information concerning a business that is not a sole proprietorship?','[\"Form 433-A\",\"Form 433-B\",\"Form 433-D\",\"Form 433-F\"]',1,'Publication 594, page 2, provides, in part, if a taxpayer is unable to pay the full amount due, all of the taxes at that time, the taxpayer should pay as much as he or she can and thereby reduce the amount of interest and penalty. At this point, the taxpayer needs to contact the IRS to explain the situation. The taxpayer should have their financial information available, including their monthly income and expenses. Based on the taxpayer’s ability to pay, the IRS may provide alternate payment options such as setting up an installment agreement online.nnIf a taxpayer is unable to pay in full, they can apply for an Installment Agreement, which is a smaller periodic payment over time, or an Offer in Compromise.nnTo be eligible for an Installment Agreement, the taxpayer must file all required tax returns and the IRS may ask the taxpayer to fill out a Collection Information Statement (Form 433-F, 433-A, and/or 433-B) and provide proof of their financial status. (Publication 594, page 3)nnForm 433-A is the Collection Information Statement for Wage Earners and Self-Employed Individuals and provides detailed information about the taxpayer\'s income, assets, liabilities, and equity positions.nForm 433-B is the Collection Information Statement for Businesses such as partnerships, corporations, and LLC members.nForm 433-D is the Installment Agreement form.nForm 433-F is the Collection Information Statement that provides detailed information similar to Form 433-A but is required when the tax amount is more than $50,000.nIf a taxpayer owes $50,000 or less, they may be eligible to use the IRS\'s Online Payment Agreement web application.nnDepending on the taxpayer\'s situation, they may be required to file both Forms 433-A and 433-B.nnSince this is a business that is not a sole proprietorship, they would be required to file Form 433-B. If, on the other hand, this was a sole proprietorship, they would be required to file Form 433-A.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1425,8,'The IRS may accept an Offer in Compromise filed by the taxpayer or their representative under which of the conditions below?','[\"The taxpayer\'s tax debt might not be accurate.\",\"All the taxpayer\'s liabilities have been referred to the Department of Justice for prosecution or defense.\",\"The taxpayer has filed Chapter 13 bankruptcy.\",\"The taxpayer failed to file all legally required tax returns before the offer is submitted.\"]',0,'An Offer in Compromise may be accepted by the IRS if:nnThe tax debt may not be accuratenThere is insufficient assets and income to pay the amount duenPaying the amount would cause an economic hardship or be unjust',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1426,8,'An Enrolled Agent (EA) prepared an individual income tax return for a taxpayer with a balance due of $25,597. The taxpayer is not able to pay the entire amount upon filing and would like to set up an installment agreement. Which of the following statements are correct with regard to this agreement?','[\"The taxpayer must be in filing compliance.\",\"Since the taxpayer owed more than $25,000 the taxpayer may not apply online.\",\"The taxpayer will not be charged a user fee to set up this installment agreement.\",\"The taxpayer will not be charged interest and penalties while making installment payments.\"]',0,'Publication 594, page 3, provides options if a taxpayer can’t pay in full at the present. One option is to apply for an Installment Agreement Payment Plan, which means the IRS will allow the taxpayer to make smaller periodic payments over time.nnA setup fee applies to all agreements over 120 days.nnThe taxpayer may apply online for a reduced setup fee if the total combined balance of individual income tax, penalty and interest is $50,000 or less.nnBut to be eligible for an Installment Agreement, the taxpayer must file ALL required tax returns. Hence, the correct response for this question is “The taxpayer must be in filing compliance”.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1427,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning bankruptcy proceedings?','[\"They will always permanently stop the Internal Revenue Service from enforcement action.\",\"They will always eliminate the taxpayer\'s tax liability.\",\"They will eliminate all property liens placed by the Internal Revenue Service on the taxpayer\'s assets.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 594, page 2, states, in part, that if a taxpayer is involved in bankruptcy proceedings, the taxpayer should contact his or her local IRS office. While the proceeding may not eliminate the taxpayer\'s tax debt, it may temporarily stop IRS enforcement action from collecting a debt related to the bankruptcy.nnPublication 908, page 17, provides that not all debts are dischargeable. Many tax debts are excepted from the bankruptcy discharge. The scope of the bankruptcy discharge depends on the chapter under which the case was filed and the nature of the debt.nnHence, the statements that bankruptcy proceedings will always permanently stop the IRS from enforcement action, eliminate the taxpayer\'s tax liability, and eliminate all property liens placed by the IRS on the taxpayer\'s assets are incorrect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1428,8,'Madonna received a Notice of Tax Due and Demand for Payment in the amount of $30,000 as a result of an examination of her 2023 Form 1040. She is not able to pay the entire amount at this time and would like to set up an Installment Agreement. Which of the following statements is not true regarding setting up an Installment Agreement?','[\"Madonna must wait for a Notice of Federal Tax Lien to be filed before she can request an Installment Agreement.\",\"Madonna may have to fill out a Collection Information Statement.\",\"Madonna will be charged a user fee to set up an Installment Agreement.\",\"Madonna must file all of her returns that are due to be eligible for an Installment Agreement.\"]',0,'Publication 594, pages 2 and 3, provides an overview for filing a tax return, billing, and collection. When a tax return is filed, and a final decision is made establishing the taxpayer’s correct tax, the IRS records the amount in their records. If the correct amount has not been paid, a bill will be sent. The bill includes the taxes, plus interest and penalties.nnPublication 594, page 3, provides, in part, if a taxpayer is unable to pay the full amount due, all of the taxes at that time, the taxpayer should pay as much as he or she can and thereby reduce the amount of interest and penalty. At this point, the taxpayer needs to contact the IRS. The taxpayer should have their financial information available, including their monthly income and expenses. Based on the taxpayer’s ability to pay, the IRS may provide alternate payment options.nnIf a taxpayer is unable to pay in full now, they can apply for an Installment Agreement, which is a smaller periodic payment over time, or an Offer in Compromise. To be eligible for an Installment Agreement, the taxpayer must file all required tax returns and the IRS may ask the taxpayer to fill out a Collection Information Statement (Form 433-F, 433-A, and/or 433-B) and provide proof of their financial status. If the amount owed is less than $50,000, a taxpayer can apply online for a payment plan instead of filing Form 9465 and benefit from lower user fees.nnThe instructions for Form 9465, Installment Agreement Request, page 1, provide that a taxpayer is usually notified within 30 days whether the request is approved or denied. However, if this request is for tax due on a return filed by the taxpayer after March 31, it may take the IRS longer than 30 days to reply. If the request is approved, a notice is issued to the taxpayer detailing the terms of the agreement and requesting a user fee. The amount of the user fee can vary depending on whether the taxpayer sets up an Installment Agreement online or agrees to pay by direct debit. The fees are:nn$22, if the taxpayer sets up an online payment agreement and makes the payments by direct debit;n$107, if the taxpayer does not set up an online payment agreement but makes the payments by direct debit;n$69, if the taxpayer sets up an online payment agreement but does not make the payments by direct debit; orn$178, if the taxpayer does not set up an online payment agreement and does not make the payments by direct debit. This includes payroll deduction agreements on Form 2159.nTaxpayers with income at or below established levels may qualify for a reduced user fee of $43 (if the taxpayer\'s AGI is at or below 250% of the federal poverty level) for establishing the Installment Agreement. If a taxpayer does not make their payments on time or does not pay any balance due on a return that is filed later, the taxpayer will be in default on the agreement. As a result, the IRS may take enforcement actions, such as the filing of a Notice of Federal Tax Lien or an IRS levy action, to collect the entire amount owed. (Instructions for Form 9465, pages 1–2)nnNote: See the “About Form 9465, Installment Agreement Request” page at www.irs.gov for up-to-date information on this issue.nnTherefore, all of the statements are true, except the response stating that Madonna must wait for a Notice of Federal Tax Lien to be filed before she can request an Installment Agreement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1429,8,'Which of the following statements is not correct about bankruptcy proceedings?','[\"The bankruptcy court does not have authority to determine the tax amount owed prior to bankruptcy.\",\"They will always result in the discharge of all federal tax liabilities.\",\"The filing of a bankruptcy petition automatically results in a stay of any Tax Court proceeding on determining a tax liability.\",\"Property with an IRS lien for taxes owed that would be discharged by the bankruptcy proceedings may still be collectable by the IRS.\"]',1,'Publication 908, page 17, states, in part, that the bankruptcy court may enter an order discharging the debtor from personal liability for certain debts, including taxes. The order for discharge is a permanent order of the court prohibiting the creditors from acting against the debtor personally to collect the debt. However, secured creditors with valid pre-bankruptcy liens may enforce them to recover property secured by the lien.nnNot all debts are dischargeable. Many tax debts are excepted from the bankruptcy discharge. As a general rule, the following tax debts, including interest that is applicable to an individual that files under chapter 7, are not subject to discharge: taxes entitled to eighth priority, taxes for which no return was filed, taxes for which a return was filed late after 2 years before the bankruptcy petition was filed, taxes for which a fraudulent return was filed, and taxes that the taxpayer willfully attempted to evade or defeat. As a result, bankruptcy proceedings do not always result in the discharge of federal tax liabilities.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1430,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning which tax debts are not subject to discharge for an individual taxpayer in most bankruptcies, such as cases under Chapter 7, Chapter 11, Chapter 12, and Chapter 13?','[\"Taxes for which no return was filed\",\"Taxes for which a fraudulent return was filed\",\"Taxes that the debtor willfully attempted to evade or defeat\",\"All of the answer choices are not subject to discharge for an individual taxpayer in most bankruptcies.\"]',3,'As stated in Publication 908, page 17, a bankruptcy court may enter an order discharging the debtor from personal liability for certain debts, including taxes. Not all debts are dischargeable, however. Many tax debts are excepted from the bankruptcy discharge. For the bankruptcy cases under Chapter 7, Chapter 11, Chapter 12, and Chapter 13, the following taxes are not subject to discharge for all of these bankruptcies for individuals (see unsecured tax claims section, item 3):nnTaxes for which no return was filednTaxes for which a return was filed late after 2 years before the bankruptcy petition was filednTaxes for which a fraudulent return was filednTaxes that the debtor willfully attempted to evade or defeatnAs a result, all of the answer choices in this question are correct; they are not subject to discharge for an individual taxpayer in most bankruptcies.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1431,8,'Which of the following is a written determination issued to a taxpayer by an Associate Office in response to a taxpayer\'s written inquiry prior to the filing of the tax return?','[\"An information letter\",\"A letter ruling\",\"A determination letter\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Revenue Procedure 2020-1, Section 2.01, provides, in part, that a letter ruling is a written determination issued to a taxpayer by an Associate Office in response to a taxpayer\'s written inquiry, filed prior to the filing of returns or reports that are required by the tax laws, about its status for tax purposes or the tax effects of its acts or transactions. A letter ruling interprets the tax laws and applies them to the taxpayer’s specific set of facts. Once issued, a letter ruling may be revoked or modified for a number of reasons.nnA determination letter is a written determination issued by a Director that applies the principles and precedents previously announced by the Service to a specific set of facts. It is issued only when a determination can be made based on clearly established rules in a statute, a tax treaty, the regulations, a conclusion in a revenue ruling, or an opinion or court decision that represents the position of the Service (Revenue Procedure 2019-1, Section 2.03).nnAn information letter is a statement issued by an Associate Office or Director that calls attention to a well-established interpretation or principle of tax law (including a tax treaty) without applying it to a specific set of facts (Revenue Procedure 2019-1, Section 2.04).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1432,8,'Which of the following courts hears only tax cases and its rulings can be cited as precedent?','[\"District Court\",\"U.S. Court of Federal Claims\",\"Tax Court\",\"Small Case Division\"]',2,'The District Court hears federal cases pertaining to both tax and nontax issues. Unlike the Tax Court, a taxpayer may request a jury trial in the district court. District Court decisions can be cited as precedent by both the taxpayer and the IRS. The District Court follows the precedents set by the Supreme Court and the Circuit Court of Appeals for the circuit in which the taxpayer is a resident.nnThe U.S. Court of Federal Claims is located in Washington, D.C., and is made up of 16 judges who hear money claims founded upon the Constitution, federal statutes, executive regulations, or contracts (express or implied) with the United States. Hence, this court hears both tax and nontax cases. Decisions by this court can be cited as precedent by both the taxpayer and the IRS. The Court of Federal Claims follows the precedents set by the Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. (For more information, see, for example, the “About Federal Courts” page of www.uscourts.gov.)nnThe Tax Court rules on disputes between taxpayers and the IRS involving underpayment of federal income, gift taxes, and estate taxes. Like the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, the Tax Court is located in Washington, D.C. However, these judges hear only tax cases. Like interpretations that are issued by the Treasury, judicial decisions can be cited as precedent by both the taxpayer and the IRS.nnIf the amount in the case is $50,000 or less for any 1 tax year or period, the small tax case procedure is available upon request if the Tax Court approves. There is no appeal to the decision rendered by this court for either the taxpayer or the IRS. Moreover, since the opinion is not published, it cannot be cited as precedent (IRC Section 7463).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1433,8,'Which of the following are not published in the Internal Revenue Bulletins?','[\"Private letter rulings\",\"Revenue rulings\",\"Treasury decisions\",\"Announcements\"]',0,'As shown on pages i through iii of IRB 2020-53, an Internal Revenue Bulletin (IRB) contains actions on decisions, announcements, some court decisions, notices, proposed regulations, Treasury decisions, revenue rulings, and revenue procedures. Private letter rulings, however, are not published in the IRBs. They are available from some publishing companies and also in the IRS \"Electronic Reading Room\" webpage at www.irs.gov.nnA cumulative list of all revenue rulings, revenue procedures, Treasury decisions, etc. is published in Internal Revenue Bulletins. IRB 2020-53 offers a full reference table for all announcements, notices, proposed regulations, revenue procedures and rulings, and treasury decisions on pages ii and iii. IRBs are available online from the IRS at www.irs.gov/irb. (Internal Revenue Bulletin 2020-53, pages ii–iii (Rev. 12/28/2020))',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1434,8,'Which of the following has the highest legal authority and may be used as a precedent by the Service?','[\"Revenue ruling\",\"Revenue procedure\",\"Treasury decision\",\"Letter ruling\"]',2,'The Secretary of the Treasury is specifically charged by Congress with the responsibility to administer and enforce the Internal Revenue Code. Specifically, IRC Section 7805(a) states in part that the Secretary shall prescribe all needful rules and regulations for the enforcement of the Internal Revenue Code.nnThe mission statement at the beginning of any Internal Revenue Bulletin (a list of IRBs starting from 1995 to present can be found at https://apps.irs.gov/app/picklist/list/internalRevenueBulletins.html) further provides that rulings and procedures reported in the IRB do not have the force and effect of Treasury Department Regulations (also known as Treasury decisions), but they may be used as precedents. Unpublished rulings will not be relied on, used, or cited as precedents by Service personnel in the disposition of other cases.nnA “letter ruling” is a written determination issued to a taxpayer by an Associate Office in response to the taxpayer\'s written inquiry, filed prior to the filing of returns or reports that are required by the tax laws, about its status for tax purposes or the tax effects of its acts or transactions. A letter ruling interprets the tax laws and applies them to the taxpayer\'s specific set of facts. As such, a private letter ruling has legal authority, but only for that person; hence, it cannot be cited as precedent by anyone. nnTherefore, the highest authority from the Treasury is a Treasury decision (also known as a final regulation) (IRB 2020-53, IRS Mission).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1435,8,'Which of the following may contain a position of the IRS involving substantive guidance of the Internal Revenue Code or other provisions of tax law and is published in Internal Revenue Bulletins (IRBs)?','[\"Notices and Announcements\",\"Notices only\",\"IRS news release\",\"Announcements only\"]',0,'Notices and Announcements are used generally when expeditious guidance is needed that may contain substantive guidance regarding a position of the IRS involving the tax laws or contain guidance to taxpayers of a procedural nature. They are published in the Internal Revenue Bulletins (IRBs). The Internal Revenue Manual, Part 32, Chapter 2, Section 2 “Summary of the Published Guidance Process” defines a notice as a public pronouncement by the Service that may contain guidance that involves substantive interpretations of the Internal Revenue Code or other provisions of the law. Notices may be used in circumstances in which a revenue ruling or revenue procedure would not be appropriate. Notices may be used to solicit public comments on issues under consideration, in connection with non-regulatory guidance, such as a revenue procedure.nnAn announcement is a public pronouncement that has only immediate or short-term value. For example, an announcement can be used to summarize the law or regulations without making any substantive interpretation or to notify taxpayers of existence of an election or an approaching deadline for making an election.nnSince Notices and Announcements that contain substantive or procedural guidance are intended to be relied on by taxpayers, they are equivalent of revenue rulings and revenue procedures.nnThe IRS\'s Media Relations Office also puts out IRS news releases to provide relevant information to the general public about the tax treatment of items that are deducted, expensed, or included in gross income. News releases are generally sent to the news media and are not published in the IRBs.nnAn Action on Decision (AOD) is a document issued by the Internal Revenue Service regarding whether the Service will follow an adverse tax decision. The response may be issued with respect to case decisions that were given by the Tax Court, District Court, Court of Federal Claims, or Circuit Courts of Appeals. AODs are published in the Internal Revenue Bulletins. (For an example, see IRB 2016-40, \"Actions Relating to Decisions of the Tax Court,\" with decisions concerning Giant Eagle, Inc. v. Commissioner.)n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1436,8,'Which of the following have public hearings before becoming effective?','[\"Revenue rulings\",\"Revenue procedures\",\"Treasury decisions\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Reg 601.601 provides that, unlike Treasury decisions, no public hearings are held on revenue rulings or revenue procedures. As a result, revenue rulings do not have the force of (i.e., they have less authority than) a regulation that is issued by the Treasury. Revenue rulings and procedures are issued only by the IRS National Office and are published in the Internal Revenue Bulletins (IRBs).n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1437,8,'Of the items listed below, which records are not considered basic records?','[\"Sales slips, invoices, receipts, and cancelled checks or other proof of payment\",\"Brokerage statements, mutual fund statements, Form(s) 1099, and Form(s) 2439\",\"W-2 forms, Form 1099-DIV, and Form 1099-INT\",\"All of the items listed are considered basic records.\"]',3,'Publication 17, page 17, states that basic records are documents that everybody should keep. These are the records that prove a taxpayer\'s income and expenses. If a taxpayer, for example, owns a home or investments, the taxpayer\'s basic records should contain documents related to those items.nnFor income, a taxpayer’s basic records prove the amounts a taxpayer reports as income, such as wages (Form W-2), dividends and interest (Form(s) 1099), and partnership or S corporation distributions (Schedule K-1).nnFor expenses, a taxpayer’s basic records prove the expenses for which the taxpayer can claim a deduction (or credit) on their tax return such as alimony, charitable contributions, mortgage interest, and real estate taxes. In addition, a taxpayer may have childcare expenses for which they can claim a credit (supporting documentation in this area is critically important).nnNote: For divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, alimony is no longer deductible.nnA taxpayer’s basic records should enable them to determine the basis or adjusted basis of the taxpayer’s home.nnIn the case of investments, the basic records should enable the taxpayer to determine their basis in an investment so that they can determine the gain or loss on the sale of said investment. A taxpayer’s records (brokerage statements, mutual fund statements, etc.) should show the purchase price, sales price, and commissions as well as any reinvested dividends, stock splits, and original issue discounts.nnAs a result, the correct response for this problem is that all of the responses are basic records that a taxpayer should maintain.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1438,8,'Which of the following items is acceptable as adequate recordkeeping for deducting unreimbursed travel expenses by an employee in 2024?','[\"Personal statement\",\"An account book or log\",\"Trip sheet\",\"Unreimbursed travel expenses are not deductible\"]',3,'Pursuant to the Instructions for Form 2106, page 2, an employee cannot deduct expenses for travel (including meals unless the employee used the standard meal allowance), entertainment, gifts, or use of a car or other listed property unless the employee kept records to prove the time, place, business purpose, business relationship (for gifts), and amounts of these expenses. Generally, an employee must also have receipts for all lodging expenses (regardless of the amount) and any other expense of $75 or more.nnMoreover, due to the suspension of miscellaneous itemized deductions subject to the 2% floor under IRC section 67(a), employees who do not fit into one of the listed categories may not use Form 2106. Qualified individuals include members of the Armed Forces reserves, a qualified performing artist, a fee-basis state or local government official, or a disabled employee with impairment-related work expenses. Therefore, the correct response is travel expenses are not deductible for an employee with travel expenses. (Instructions for Form 2106, page 4)nnA taxpayer is required to provide adequate records to support travel expenses. Items that qualify as adequate records include but are not limited to an account book, diary, log, statement of expense, trip sheets, or similar records. nnSince this question pertains to unreimbursed employee expenses, the correct response is that these expenses are not deductible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1439,8,'A taxpayer is provided a $300 per month mileage allowance for business travel from their employer. Which of the following must be true for this to be a non-taxable item?','[\"The taxpayer must return any excess reimbursement within 180 days after the expense was paid or incurred.\",\"The taxpayer must adequately account for the expenses within 60 days after they were paid or incurred.\",\"The taxpayer must receive the advance within 60 days of the time the taxpayer has the expense.\",\"The taxpayer must adequately account for the expenses within 120 days after they were paid or incurred.\"]',1,'Publication 463 provides that the tax treatment for reimbursements of employee business expenses. Reimbursements treated as paid under an accountable plan are not reported as pay. Reimbursements treated as paid under nonaccountable plan, are reported as pay (see Publication 15 for more information). As such, if the three rules of an accountable plan described below are met, the employer should not include any reimbursements in wages reported in Box 1 of Form W-2.nnPursuant to Publication 463, page 29, an accountable plan for an employer\'s reimbursement or allowance arrangement must include all of the following rules: nnThe expense must have a business connection, that is, the employee must have paid or incurred deductible expenses while performing services as an employee of their employer.nThe employee must adequately account to the employer for the expenses within a reasonable period (within the tax year is not reasonable).nThe employee must return (not keep) any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period.nOne of the rules for an accountable plan is that the employee must adequately account for their expenses to their employer. Adequate accounting includes a statement of expense, an account book, a diary, or a similar record in which each expense is entered at or near the time incurred, along with documentary evidence of travel, mileage, and other employee business expenses. A per diem or car allowance satisfies the adequate accounting requirement under certain conditions:nnthe employer reasonably limits payment of employee expenses to those that are ordinary and necessary in the conduct of the trade or businessnthe allowance is similar in form to and not more than the federal ratenthe employee proves the time (dates) place, and business purpose of expenses to employer within a reasonable period of timenthe employee is not related to the employer.nThe regular federal per diem rate is the highest amount that the federal government will pay its employees for lodging and meals and incidental expenses while they are traveling away from home in a particular area. The rates are different for different locations. Per diem rates are published at gsa.gov/per diem.nnIn conclusion, to be non-taxable, the allowance has to be made under an accountable plan and the allowance must be within federal statutory limits for per diem allowances.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1440,8,'Under Treasury Circular 230, a practitioner must exercise due diligence in:','[\"the preparation of tax returns.\",\"determining\\u00a0 the correctness of oral statements made by the practitioner before the IRS.\",\"determining the correctness of oral or written representations made to clients.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides that a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to IRS matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the IRS.nFurthermore, a practitioner will be presumed to have exercised due diligence for purposes of this section if the practitioner relies on the work product of another person and the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1441,8,'What is included in the definition of “tax return” for purposes of Circular 230 (regulations governing practice)?','[\"An amended return and additional tax liability\",\"An amended return and a claim for refund\",\"An estate and tax return\",\"An individual or corporate tax return\"]',1,'Section 10.2(a)(6) of Circular 230 defines a tax return to include an amended tax return and a claim for refund. In this question, the key word is \"included\" in the definition.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1442,8,'Which of the following documents should a taxpayer who pays alimony keep a copy of?','[\"Divorce decree\",\"Support decree\",\"Former spouse\'s Social Security number\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 504, pages 12 and 13, provides the general provision that alimony is a payment to or for a spouse or former spouse under a divorce or separation instrument. It does not include voluntary payments that are not made under a divorce or separation instrument.nnHowever, for divorce or separation agreements executed after December 31, 2018, spouses may no longer deduct an amount equal to the alimony or separate maintenance payments paid during the tax year, nor will the alimony or separate maintenance payments be included in the gross income of the recipient spouse.nnFor divorces prior to January 1, 2019, a taxpayer paying alimony should keep a copy of the written separation agreement or the divorce, separate maintenance, or support decree as well as the former spouse\'s Social Security number. The former spouse’s Social Security number or individual taxpayer identification number must be entered on the taxpayer’s Schedule 1 of Form 1040, line 2a. Failure to provide the Social Security number may result in a $50 penalty. Per Publication 504, only cash payments, including checks and money orders qualify as alimony. Similar to claiming any other type of deduction the taxpayer should retain copies of canceled checks to substantiate the payment made to the former spouse in order to substantiate the deduction. nnA taxpayer receiving alimony should likewise keep a copy of the written separation agreement or the divorce, separate maintenance, or support decree.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1443,8,'Which of the following are basic records that a taxpayer should keep demonstrating the taxpayer has determined the correct tax liability?','[\"Brokerage statements\",\"Bank statements\",\"Insurance records\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 17, page 17, “basic records” are documents that everybody should keep. These are the records that prove a taxpayer\'s income and expenses. If a taxpayer owns a home or investments, the basic records should contain documents related to those items. For example:nnfor items of income, a taxpayer would keep Forms W-2, Forms 1099, bank statements, brokerage statements, and Forms K-1;nfor items of expenses, a taxpayer would keep alimony payments, bank statements for mortgage interest, real estate tax payments, sales receipts, invoices, receipts, canceled checks, and written documentation from charities;nfor items of the home, a taxpayer would keep closing statements, purchase and sales invoices, proof of payment, insurance records, and receipts for improvement costs; andnfor items of investments, a taxpayer would keep brokerage statements, mutual fund statements, and Forms 1099 and 2439.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1444,8,'Joe, a contractor, paid an individual $600 total for subcontractor services in tax year 2024, and withheld $150 in backup withholding. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Joe is required to file a Form 1099-NEC.\",\"Joe is required to file a W-2 form.\",\"Joe is required to file both a Form 1099-NEC and a W-2 form.\",\"Joe is\\u00a0not\\u00a0required to file any forms on the subcontractor.\"]',0,'Publication 15, page 6, provides that a taxpayer may be required to file information returns to report certain types of payments made during the year. A taxpayer, for example, must file Form 1099-MISC, Miscellaneous Income, to report payments of $600 or more to persons not treated as employees (e.g., independent contractors), for services performed for the taxpayer\'s trade or business.nnBeginning with tax year 2020, Form 1099-NEC is used for reporting nonemployee compensation. A taxpayer files Form 1099-NEC for each person in the course of business to whom the taxpayer paid the following during the year:nnAt least $600 in:nServices performed by someone who is not your employee (including parts and materials)nCash payments for fish (or other aquatic life) you purchase from anyone engaged in the trade or business of catching fish; ornPayments to an attorney.nThe form must also be filed for each person from whom the taxpayer withheld any federal income tax (box 4) under the backup withholding rules regardless of the amount of the payment.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1445,8,'Which of the following rules must be satisfied for an employer\'s reimbursement plan to be considered an accountable plan?','[\"The expenses must have a business purpose.\",\"The reimbursement must be adequately accounted for within the tax year.\",\"The taxpayer should but is not required to return any excess reimbursement.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'Pursuant to Publication 463, page 29, an accountable plan for an employer\'s reimbursement or allowance arrangement must include all of the following rules:nnThe expense must have a business connection, that is, the employee must have paid or incurred deductible expenses while performing services as an employee of their employernThe employee must adequately account to the employer for the expenses within a reasonable period (within the tax year is not necessarily reasonable).nThe employee must return (not keep) any excess reimbursement or allowance within a reasonable period.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1446,8,'Arnie is an enrolled agent who prepares income tax returns for his clients. One of his clients submitted a list of expenses to be claimed on Schedule C of the tax return. Arnie qualifies as a return preparer and, as such, is required to comply with which one of the following conditions?','[\"Arnie is required to independently verify the client\'s information.\",\"Arnie can ignore implications of information known by him.\",\"Inquiry is not required if the information appears to be incorrect or incomplete.\",\"Appropriate inquiries are required to determine whether the client has substantiation for travel and entertainment expenses.\"]',3,'When preparing to sign a tax return by a tax preparer, Circular 230, Section 10.34(d), provides guidance on relying on information furnished by clients. Specifically, a practitioner advising a client to take a position on a tax return, document, affidavit, or other paper submitted to the IRS, or preparing or signing a tax return as a preparer, generally may rely in good faith without verification of information furnished by the client. The practitioner may not, however, ignore the implications of information furnished to, or actually known by, the practitioner, and must make reasonable inquiries if the information as furnished appears to be incorrect, inconsistent with an important fact or another factual assumption, or incomplete.nnArnie, in this case, would be required to make appropriate inquiries to determine whether the client has substantiation for travel and entertainment expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1447,8,'Mike is an enrolled agent. For the past 5 years, the information that Anne provided Mike to prepare her return included a Schedule K-1 from a partnership showing significant income. However, Mike did not see a Schedule K-1 from the partnership among the information Anne provided to him this year. What does due diligence require Mike to do?','[\"Without talking to Anne, Mike should estimate the amount that would be reported as income on the Schedule K-1 based on last year\'s Schedule K-1 and include that amount on Anne\'s return.\",\"Call Anne\'s financial advisor and ask him about Anne\'s investments.\",\"Nothing, because Mike is required to rely only on the information provided by his client, even if he has a reason to know the information is not accurate.\",\"Ask Anne about the fact that she did not provide him with a Schedule K-1.\"]',3,'Being an enrolled agent, Mike should be asking why Anne is not providing him with a copy of the Schedule K-1. Otherwise, he is not satisfying the diligence as to accuracy provision in Circular 230.nnTo be more specific, Circular 230, Section 10.22, provides that a practitioner must exercise due diligence:nnin preparing or assisting in the preparation of, approving, and filing tax returns, documents, affidavits, and other papers relating to IRS matters,nin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to the Department of the Treasury, andnin determining the correctness of oral or written representations made by the practitioner to clients with reference to any matter administered by the IRS.nFurthermore, a practitioner will be presumed to have exercised due diligence for purposes of this section if the practitioner relies on the work product of another person and the practitioner used reasonable care in engaging, supervising, training, and evaluating the person, taking proper account of the nature of the relationship between the practitioner and the person.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1448,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning documentation for a taxpayer?','[\"A checkbook can be used to keep records of both income and expenses.\",\"A checkbook can be used to keep records of income but not expenses.\",\"A checkbook can be used to keep records of expenses but not income.\",\"A checkbook cannot be used to keep records of income or expenses.\"]',0,'As stated in Publication 583, page 12, the law does not require any specific kind of records, except in a few cases. Thus, a taxpayer can choose any recordkeeping system suited to his or her business that clearly shows their income and expenses.nnA taxpayer should set up their recordkeeping system using an accounting method that clearly shows their income for their tax year. If a taxpayer is in more than one business, they should keep a complete and separate set of records for each business.nnA taxpayer’s recordkeeping system should include a summary of their business transactions. As such, the books must show the taxpayer’s gross income, as well as their deductions and credits. For most small businesses, the business checkbook is the main source for entries in the business books.nnMore importantly, a taxpayer must keep supporting documents of all business transactions. Purchases, sales, payroll, and other transactions a taxpayer has in their business generate supporting documents. Supporting documents include sales slips, paid bills, invoices, receipts, deposit slips, and canceled checks, to name a few. Thus, it is critical to keep these supporting documents to help prove a deduction.nnIn this case, the correct response is a checkbook can be used to keep records of both income and expenses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1449,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning adequate proof for establishing an expense of a business purpose for income tax purposes?','[\"A canceled check of a hotel is adequate proof.\",\"An itinerary of a business meeting is adequate proof.\",\"Both a canceled check of a hotel and an itinerary of a business meeting are necessary.\",\"Either a canceled check of a hotel or an itinerary of a business meeting is adequate.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 463, pages 24 and 25, states that a taxpayer should keep adequate records or prove their expenses or have enough evidence that will support their own statement. Adequate records include an account book, diary, log, statement of expense, trip sheets, or similar record. Moreover, they should also keep documentary evidence that, together with their record, will support each element of an expense. Adequate evidence is considered adequate if it shows the amount, date, place, and essential character of the expense.nnA canceled check, together with a bill from the payee, ordinarily establishes the cost. However, a canceled check by itself does not prove a business expense without other evidence to show that it was for a business purpose. Hence, a taxpayer would need both the canceled check and the itinerary of the business meeting to provide adequate support of the expense and business purpose.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1450,8,'Sam timely filed his U.S. individual income tax return for calendar year 2015 without any extensions. The return showed a balance of income taxes due in the amount of $75,000. Sam has not paid his IRS liability, nor has he entered into any Installment Agreement extending the statute of limitations or submitted any Offer in Compromise. The statute of limitations for collection of Sam\'s tax liability expires on which of the following dates?','[\"April 17, 2019\",\"April 17, 2025\",\"December 31, 2025\",\"April 17, 2026\"]',3,'By law, the IRS has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for 10 years from the date of assessment. In this case, Sam timely filed his return for 2015, which means that the clock for his return starts on April 17, 2016, and would continue to run for 10 years or until April 17, 2026.nnNote: Be careful; this is a tricky question. It pertains to the time for collecting taxes, which is 10 years, and not the time for assessing additional taxes, which is generally 3 years. Also, the question says the tax return for 2015 was timely filed, which means a 2015 tax return is due by April 17, 2016, which is when the 10-year clock starts. The April 15 due date may vary by a few days in subsequent years due to weekends and holidays. The date is the same for consistency.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1451,8,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA)?','[\"The IRS is required to release all documents that are subject to FOIA requests.\",\"The FOIA sets standards for determining which records must be made available for public inspection.\",\"The FOIA applies to records created but not obtained by an agency and under control at the time of the request.\",\"The FOIA requires the IRS to collect information it does not have that is requested.\"]',1,'Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Guidelines, Section A, that are provided on the IRS website, all IRS records are subject to FOIA requests. However, FOIA does not require the IRS to release all documents that are subject to FOIA requests. The IRS may withhold information pursuant to nine exemptions and three exclusions contained in the FOIA statute.nnThe FOIA applies to records either created or obtained by an agency and under agency control at the time of the FOIA request. Agencies within the executive branch of the federal government, including the Executive Office of the President and independent regulatory agencies, are subject to the FOIA. State governments, municipal corporations, the courts, Congress, and private citizens are not subject to the FOIA.nnIn addition, the FOIA sets standards for determining which records must be made available for public inspection and which records (or portions of records) should or may be withheld from disclosure. The law also provides administrative and judicial remedies for those denied access to records. Above all, the statute requires federal agencies to provide the fullest possible disclosure of information to the public.nnThe FOIA only applies to existing records. FOIA does not require the IRS to collect information it does not have, or to research or analyze data for a requester. The IRS is only required to look for an existing record or document in response to a FOIA request. The IRS is not obliged to create a new record to comply with a FOIA request. However, when records are maintained in a computer, the IRS may be required to retrieve information in response to a FOIA request. The process of retrieving the information may result in the creation of a new document when the data is printed out on paper or written on computer tape or disk.nnHence the only correct response for this question is that the FOIA sets standards for determining which records must be made available for public inspection.nnNote: A copy of the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Guidelines is available from the IRS website (www.irs.gov). A copy is also available from the main screen of this review through the \"IRS Publications\" link (under “Internal Revenue Bulletins, Etc.”). See https://www.irs.gov/privacy-disclosure/freedom-of-information-act-foia-guidelines.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1452,8,'What action can a taxpayer take if the IRS disallows or rejects his timely filed claim for a refund or does not act on his claim within 6 months after he files it?','[\"The taxpayer has no recourse in this situation.\",\"The taxpayer can only take his claim to the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.\",\"The taxpayer can only take his claim to the U.S. District Court.\",\"The taxpayer can take his claim to the U.S. District Court or to the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.\"]',3,'Generally, the U.S. District Court and U.S. Court of Federal Claims hear tax cases only after a taxpayer pays the tax and files a claim for a credit or refund.nnPursuant to Publication 556, page 13, if a taxpayer\'s claim is totally or partially disallowed by the IRS, the taxpayer should receive a notice of claim disallowance. If the IRS does not act upon the claim within 6 months from the date the taxpayer filed it, the taxpayer can file suit for a refund in the taxpayer\'s U.S. District Court or in the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.nnA taxpayer generally must file suit for a credit or refund no later than 2 years after the IRS informs the taxpayer that the claim has been rejected.nnIn addition, Publication 556, pages 15 and 16, provides the general rules for claims filed. In general, claims are usually processed shortly after they are filed. A taxpayer\'s claim may be denied, accepted as filed, or it may be examined.nnIf a claim is examined, the procedures are almost the same as in the examination of a tax return.nIf, however, a taxpayer is filing a claim for credit or refund based only on contested income tax or on estate tax or gift tax issues considered in previously examined returns and the taxpayer does not want to appeal within the IRS, the taxpayer should request in writing that the claim be immediately rejected. A notice of claim disallowance will then be promptly sent to the taxpayer.nIn this case, the taxpayer has 2 years from the date of mailing of the notice of disallowance to file a refund suit in the U.S. District Court or in the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1453,8,'An enrolled agent (EA) is in the process of representing a taxpayer before the Internal Revenue Service for a tax matter involving a tax return the taxpayer filed claiming married filing jointly with her former husband. The taxpayer\'s former husband also asked the EA to represent him for the same matter. Which of the following is true regarding the EA representing them both?','[\"The EA must notify the Office of Professional Responsibility that the EA will be representing both taxpayers.\",\"Each taxpayer only needs to provide consent verbally, if the EA documents the day consent was given.\",\"The EA must reasonably believe that the EA will be able to provide competent and diligent representation to both taxpayers.\",\"Confirmation of a conflict of interest must be made within 60 days from the time of consent by both taxpayers.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.29 requires that an EA must reasonably believe they can provide competent and diligent representation to each affected client despite the conflict of interest. Furthermore, the EA must obtain written consent from both clients after fully disclosing the conflict of interest. This ensures that both clients are aware of the potential conflict and agree to the representation under those circumstances.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1454,8,'During the course of examining Ollie\'s income tax return, the Revenue Agent required information from third-party sources. Which of the following provisions does not apply to the Revenue Agent giving Ollie reasonable notice before contacting third parties?','[\"Pending criminal investigation\",\"Providing notice might result in reprisal against the contact\",\"Ollie authorizes the contact\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 556 (page 3) provides, in part, that the IRS must give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons about a taxpayer\'s tax matters. In examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability, the IRS may contact third parties such as the taxpayer\'s neighbors, banks, employers, or employees.nnThe IRS must also give a taxpayer notice of specific contacts by providing the taxpayer with a record of persons contacted on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request.nnAs one might suspect, there are exceptions to the above policy. The provision does not apply:nnto any pending criminal investigation,nwhen providing notice would jeopardize collection of any tax liability,nwhere providing notice may result in reprisal against any person, ornwhen the taxpayer authorized the contact.nThus, all the statements that are given in this problem are exceptions for the Revenue Agent giving Ollie reasonable notice before contacting third parties.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1455,8,'Due to the COVID extended deadline, Wesley timely filed his tax year 2020 Form 1040 tax return on May 17, 2021, and paid the $2,000 tax as shown on the return at the time of filing. The return was subsequently examined, and Wesley signed an agreement form for the proposed changes on October 31, 2022. He paid the additional tax due of $10,000 on December 31, 2022. In 2024, Wesley located missing records, which he believes would make $5,000 of the additional assessment erroneous. Which of the following statements accurately states the date by which Wesley must file a claim for refund?','[\"October 31, 2024, 2 years from signing the agreement form\",\"May 17, 2024, 3 years from the due date of the original return\",\"December 31, 2024, 2 years from when the additional tax was paid\",\"No claim for refund can be filed since an examination agreement form was signed.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 13, states that, in general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the taxpayer filed the original return or 2 years from the date the tax was paid, whichever is later. If the taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnIn this case, Wesley must file a claim for refund no later than December 31, 2024, which is the later of the two dates (2 years from when the additional tax was paid).nnNote: Due to COVID, the 2019 tax year deadline was extended to July 15, 2020, moving the statute of limitations to three years later in July (not April) for that tax year. For the 2020 tax year, the deadline was moved to May 17, 2021, shifting the 3-year statute of limitations to May (not April) for that tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1456,8,'Karl had his 2021 income tax return examined resulting in adjustments. Karl has administratively appealed the adjustments. Some of them were sustained, resulting in an income tax deficiency in the amount of $45,000. He now wants to appeal his case to the U.S. Tax Court. He will handle the case himself since he cannot afford a lawyer. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"The IRS is entitled to invoke the Small Tax Case procedure\",\"If the Small Tax Case procedure is accepted by the Tax Court, Karl will be required to seek the services of an attorney.\",\"Karl is entitled to invoke the Small Tax Case procedure.\",\"Karl is entitled to invoke the Small Tax Case procedure, but if elected, he will be required to seek the services of an attorney.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 12, provides the criteria associated with qualifying as a small tax case. If the amount in the taxpayer\'s case is $50,000 or less for any 1 tax year or period, the Tax Court has a simple alternative to solve the case. At the taxpayer\'s request and if the Tax Court approves, the taxpayer\'s case can be handled under the small tax case procedure.nnIn the small tax case procedures, the taxpayer can present the taxpayer\'s case to the Tax Court for a decision that is final, and that the taxpayer cannot appeal.nnSince Karl\'s tax deficiency after administrative appeals is less than $50,000, he can petition for the small tax case procedures.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1457,8,'Which of the following statements about the Taxpayer Advocate Service (TAS) is correct?','[\"The taxpayer pays a nominal charge for using this service.\",\"Members of the TAS are not part of the IRS.\",\"The TAS is available for both businesses and individuals.\",\"None of the responses are correct.\"]',2,'As provided on page 1 of Publication 1546, the Taxpayer Advocate Service (TAS) is an independent organization within the IRS that helps taxpayers and protects taxpayer rights. TAS can help resolve problems that the taxpayer cannot resolve with the IRS, and their service is free.nnThe law requires each TAS office to secure and maintain means of communication independent of other IRS offices. Each local office has a separate phone, fax, and mailing address. TAS has the discretion to not disclose a taxpayer’s information to the IRS. In general, however, to provide the taxpayer with assistance or relief, TAS will likely have to disclose the information to an IRS employee or employees. (Publication 1546, page 6)nnA taxpayer should try to resolve their problem with the IRS, but if they cannot resolve it, then they should seek TAS assistance. TAS can help if (Publication 1546, page 4):nnthe taxpayer’s problem with the IRS is causing financial difficulties for the taxpayer, the taxpayer’s family, or the taxpayer’s business.nthe taxpayer faces (or the taxpayer’s business is facing) an immediate threat of adverse action.nthe taxpayer has tried repeatedly to contact the IRS, but no one has responded, or the IRS has not responded by the date promised.nprocesses, systems, or procedures within the IRS are not operating efficiently and causing delays in the IRS response to the issues.nA taxpayer may contact the Taxpayer Advocate Service by:nncalling the phone number listed in the TAS brochure for the TAS office nearest the taxpayer,ncalling their toll-free line at 1-877-777-4778,nfiling Form 911, Request for Taxpayer Advocate Service Assistance (and Application for Taxpayer Assistance Order), with the TAS, ornasking an IRS employee to complete Form 911 on the taxpayer\'s behalf.nTo get a copy of Form 911 or learn more about the TAS, go to the Taxpayer Advocate Service page at www.irs.gov/advocate.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1458,8,'In the process of preparing Orlo Corporation\'s 2021 return, Dave, an enrolled agent, provided to Orlo Corporation calculations he had prepared computing basis of property that was sold and reported on the Form 4797 filed with Form 1120. Later, when Orlo Corporation\'s 2021 return was examined by the Internal Revenue Service, Orlo Corporation refuses to provide the Internal Revenue Service with the calculations, claiming that this was a privileged communication between Orlo Corporation and its federally authorized practitioner. Which of the following statements is true?','[\"Orlo Corporation does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because they are privileged under the Federal Tax Practitioner privilege rules.\",\"Orlo Corporation must provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because privilege does not apply to a determination with respect to an item that will be presented to the government on an original return.\",\"Orlo Corporation must provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because the Federal Tax Practitioner privilege does not apply to documents written by Dave because he is not a CPA.\",\"Orlo Corporation does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have to provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service if they believe this transaction might be construed as a tax shelter.\"]',1,'Publication 947, page 6, provides some general rules for communications that are confidential. In particular, confidentiality generally applies only to tax advice between a federally authorized tax practitioner and a taxpayer. Federally authorized tax practitioners include attorneys, certified public accountants, enrolled agents, enrolled actuaries, and certain other individuals allowed to practice before the IRS.nnTax advice is advice in regard to a matter that is within the scope of the practitioner\'s authority to practice.nnThe confidentiality protection applies to communications that would be considered privileged if they were between the taxpayer and an attorney and that relate to:nnnoncriminal tax matters before the IRS ornnoncriminal tax proceedings brought in federal court by or against the United States.nThis protection of tax advice communications does not apply to any written communications between a federally authorized tax practitioner and any person, including a director, shareholder, officer, employee, agent, or representative of a corporation, if the communication involves the promotion of the direct or indirect participation of the corporation in any tax shelter.nnIn this case, Orlo Corporation must provide the calculations to the Internal Revenue Service because privilege does not apply to a determination with respect to an item that will be presented to the government on an original return. It applies to advice. (See also IRC Section 7525(a) and Publication 556, pages 3–4.)',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1459,8,'What action must a taxpayer take if they make a mistake on a submitted tax return?','[\"Call the local IRS Service Center and report the error.\",\"Correct the mistake on next year\'s tax return.\",\"File Form 1040-X correcting the errors.\",\"Wait and see if the Service catches the error.\"]',2,'Pursuant to Publication 17, pages 18–19, errors may delay a taxpayer\'s refund or result in notices being sent to them. If a taxpayer discovers an error, the taxpayer can file an amended return or claim for refund.nnForm 1040-X, Amended U.S. Individual Income Tax Return, is filed to correct a return that the taxpayer has already filed. Starting with tax year 2019, individual amended tax returns can be filed electronically.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1460,8,'You must keep your records as long as they may be needed for the administration of any provision of the Internal Revenue Code. Generally, this means you must keep records that support items shown on your return until the period of limitations for that return runs out. The period of limitations is the period of time in which you can amend your return to claim a credit or refund, or the Internal Revenue Service can assess additional tax. Which statement listed below is incorrect?','[\"If no other provisions apply, the statute of limitations is 3 years after the return was filed.\",\"If more than 25% of gross income has been omitted from the tax return, the statute of limitations is 6 years after the return was filed, unless the omitted amount was disclosed in the return or in a statement attached to the return, in a manner adequate to apprise the Internal Revenue Service of the nature and amount of the omission.\",\"If a fraudulent return is filed, the statute of limitations is 7 years.\",\"If a tax return is not filed at all, there is no statute of limitations.\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 18, provides the following period of limitations. (Returns filed before the due date are treated as being filed on the due date.)nnA fraudulent return has no statute of limitations (not a 7-year statute of limitations).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1461,8,'In the process of examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability, the Internal Revenue Service may contact third parties. Which of the following statements is incorrect about the responsibility of the Internal Revenue Service to the taxpayer?','[\"Reasonable notice must be given by the IRS before making any inquiries of third parties.\",\"Notification must include the specific names of those the IRS intends to contact.\",\"Reasonable notice is\\u00a0not\\u00a0necessary where it may result in reprisal against any person.\",\"Reasonable notice is\\u00a0not\\u00a0necessary when it would jeopardize collection of any tax liability.\"]',1,'Publication 556 (page 3) provides, in part, that the IRS must give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons: “You must be given reasonable notice in advance that, in examining or collecting your tax liability, the IRS may contact third parties such as your neighbors, banks, employers, or employees.”nnThe IRS must also give a taxpayer notice of specific contacts by providing the taxpayer with a record of persons contacted on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request. The IRS is not required to give the specific names of those it intends to contact as part of its notification to contact third parties.nnAs one might suspect, there are exceptions to the above policy. The provision does not apply to any pending criminal investigation, when providing notice would jeopardize collection of any tax liability, where providing notice may result in reprisal against any person, or when you authorized the contact.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1462,8,'Which of the following transactions would be considered tax evasion?','[\"Tony writes a $200 check to his favorite charity on December 30, 2024, mails it on January 15, 2025, and deducts it on his 2024 tax return.\",\"Wendy pays her January 15, 2025, state estimated income taxes on December 15, 2024, and deducts them on her 2024 tax return.\",\"Lisa sells her taxable bond fund and uses the proceeds to purchase a tax-exempt municipal bond fund.\",\"Hai contributes $5,000 to his traditional IRA and thereby reduces his tax liability by $1,250.\"]',0,'In general, a taxpayer reduces his or her tax liability by taking advantage of tax-deductible transactions such as retirement investments, home interest expense, tax-exempt investments, and so forth. These types of deductions are referred to as tax avoidance transactions because they are legal transactions recognized in the Internal Revenue Code. Tax evasion, on the other hand, is the illegal nonpayment of taxes in a period. In the middle of these two extreme points is a category referred to as abusive tax avoidance transactions, which would include abusive tax shelters. The Treasury Department and IRS are halting these types of transactions. IRS Notice 2009-59 contains a list of 34 transactions that have been identified as \"listed transactions\" that are a type of abusive tax avoidance transaction.nnAlthough Tony\'s transaction is not a \"listed transaction\" as described in IRS Notice 2009-59, he is claiming a contribution deduction in a period where he has not made such a contribution. As such, this would be seen as a tax evasion transaction. He is avoiding taxes in 1 year by delaying them to the following year. A check mailed to a charity is considered delivered on the date the check is mailed, not written as in Tony’s case. Alternatively, if Tony had used his credit card on December 30 to make the contribution, it would be deductible in the year the charge is made (i.e., 2024) even though he will not pay the credit card charge until 2025. (Publication 526, page 14)nnIn the other three taxpayers\' situations, the taxpayers are employing tax planning strategies, which are in accordance with the Code and as such would be viewed as tax avoidance transactions. These transactions are legal.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1463,8,'Barry\'s individual income tax return for 2022 was examined by the IRS, which resulted in a tax assessment in the amount of $10,000. Thereafter, Barry discovered papers that he believed would show that the IRS determination was erroneous. Barry can claim a refund of income taxes as follows:','[\"Take a credit for the amount on his 2022 return\",\"File Form 1045,\\u00a0Application for Tentative Refund\",\"File an amended return within 3 years from the date he filed his original return for 2022, or 2 years from the date he paid the tax, whichever is later\",\"Immediately sue for a refund in court\"]',2,'In general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the original return is filed or 2 years from the date the taxpayer paid the tax, whichever is later. If a taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnThere is an exception to the above rule. Specifically, if the due date to file a return or a claim for a credit or refund is a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, it is filed on time if it is filed on the next business day. Returns you filed before the due date are considered filed on the due date. This is true even when the due date is a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday.nnHence, Barry is able to file an amended return within 3 years from the date he filed his original return for 2022, or 2 years from the date that he paid the tax, whichever is later.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1464,8,'Harry claimed gambling losses on his income tax return. The return was examined by the IRS and the losses were disallowed. Harry pursued an appeal before the IRS Appeals Office, which sustained the Revenue Agent\'s adjustment. Harry now wants to take his case to a judge. In which of the following courts can Harry file a tax action?','[\"U.S. Court of Federal Claims\",\"U.S. District Court\",\"U.S. Tax Court\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'If a taxpayer and the IRS disagree after the Appeals conference, the taxpayer can take his or her case to the U.S. Tax Court, the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, or the U.S. District Court. These courts are independent of the IRS.nnGenerally, the Tax Court hears cases before any tax has been assessed and paid; however, a taxpayer can pay the tax after the notice of deficiency has been issued and still petition the Tax Court for review.nnGenerally, a taxpayer can file suit for a credit or refund in his or her U.S. District Court or in the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1465,8,'Dominic timely filed his tax year 2019 Form 1040 tax return on July 15, 2020 and paid the $2,000 tax as shown on the return at the time of filing. The return was subsequently examined, and Dominic signed an agreement form for the proposed changes on October 31, 2021. He paid the additional tax due of $10,000 on December 31, 2021. In 2024, Dominic located missing records, which he believes would make $5,000 of the additional assessment erroneous. Which of the following statements accurately states Dominic\'s options for filing a refund claim?','[\"He can file by October 31, 2023, 2 years from signing the agreement form\",\"He can file by July 15, 2023, 3 years from the due date of the original return\",\"He can file by December 31, 2023, 2 years from when the additional tax was paid\",\"No claim for refund can be filed since the statute of limitations has passed.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 13, states that, in general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the taxpayer filed the original return or 2 years from the date the tax was paid, whichever is later. If the taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnIn this case, Dominic had to file a claim for refund by December 31, 2023, which is the later of the two dates (2 years from when the additional tax was paid, i.e., December 31, 2023; or 3 years from the date the taxpayer filed the original return, i.e., July 15, 2023). Since he did not discover the supporting documents until 2024, the statute of limitations has expired, and he is unable to file for refund.nnNote: Due to COVID, the 2019 tax year deadline was extended to July 15, 2020, moving the statute of limitations to three years later in July (not April) for that tax year. For the 2020 tax year, the deadline was moved to May 17, 2021, shifting the 3-year statute of limitations to May (not April) for that tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1466,8,'Generally, the statute of limitations for the collection of outstanding income tax liabilities is:','[\"3 years after the due date of the return.\",\"3 years after the tax is assessed.\",\"10 years after the tax is assessed.\",\"10 years from the last day of the tax period (calendar or fiscal) for which the return is filed.\"]',2,'By law, the IRS has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for 10 years from the date the taxpayer\'s tax was assessed.nnThe 10-year collection period is suspended:nnwhile the IRS and the Office of Appeals consider a request for an Installment Agreement or an Offer in Compromise,nfrom the date the taxpayer requests a Collection Due Process (CDP) hearing until Appeals issues a CDP Notice of Determination or, if the taxpayer seeks review in the Tax Court, until the Tax Court\'s decision becomes final,nfrom the date the taxpayer requests innocent spouse relief until a final Notice of Determination is issued,nfor tax periods included in a bankruptcy while the automatic stay is in effect, plus an additional 6 months, ornwhile the taxpayer is residing outside the United States, if the taxpayer is absent for a continuous period of at least 6 months.nThe amount of time the suspension is in effect will be added to the time remaining in the 10-year period. For example, if the 10-year period is suspended for 6 months, the time left in the period the IRS has to collect will increase by 6 months.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nBe aware that this question may be asked as follows: “Generally, the statute of limitations for the collection of income tax is:”',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1467,8,'The IRS does not need to give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons except:','[\"when providing notice would jeopardize collection of any tax liability.\",\"where providing notice may result in reprisal against any person.\",\"when examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability.\",\"when the taxpayer authorized the contact.\"]',2,'Publication 556 (page 3) provides, in part, that the IRS must give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons when examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability. The IRS may contact third parties such as your neighbors, banks, employers, or employees during this investigation.nnThe IRS also must give a taxpayer notice of specific contacts by providing the taxpayer with a record of persons contacted on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request.nnAs one might suspect, there are exceptions to the above policy. The provision does not apply to any pending criminal investigation, when providing notice would jeopardize collection of any tax liability, where providing notice may result in reprisal against any person, or when the taxpayer authorized the contact.nnThus, the IRS does need to give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons when they are examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1468,8,'Which of the following conditions must be present for a taxpayer to be eligible for assistance from the Taxpayer Advocate Service in resolving a tax problem with the IRS?','[\"The problem with the IRS is causing financial difficulties for the taxpayer, their family, or their business.\",\"The taxpayer faces (or their business is facing) an immediate threat of adverse action.\",\"The taxpayer has tried repeatedly to contact the IRS, but no one has responded, or the IRS has not responded by the date promised.\",\"At least one of the conditions listed must be present.\"]',3,'In order for a taxpayer to be eligible for assistance from the Taxpayer Advocate Service in resolving a tax problem with the IRS, at least one of the following conditions must be present (under the caption of “When to Come to Us”):nnThe problem with the IRS is causing financial difficulties for the taxpayer, their family, or their business.nThe taxpayer faces (or their business is facing) an immediate threat of adverse action.nThe taxpayer has tried repeatedly to contact the IRS, but no one has responded, or the IRS has not responded by the date promised.n nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThe Taxpayer Advocate Service is an independent organization within the IRS whose employees assist taxpayers who are experiencing economic harm, who are seeking help in resolving tax problems that have not been resolved through normal channels, or who believe that an IRS system or procedure is not working as it should.nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1469,8,'Bethany timely filed her 2020 Form 1040 tax return and paid the $2,000 tax as shown on the return at the time of filing. The return was subsequently examined, and Bethany signed an agreement form for the proposed changes on August 20, 2022. She paid the additional tax due of $5,000 on September 30, 2022. In 2024, Tiffany located missing records that she believes would make $3,000 of the additional assessment erroneous. Which of the following statements accurately states the date by which Bethany must file a claim for refund to get the $3,000 back?','[\"August 20, 2024, 2 years from signing the agreement form\",\"May 17, 2024, 3 years from the due date of the original return (due to COVID extension)\",\"September 30, 2024, 2 years from when the additional tax was paid\",\"No claim for refund can be filed since an examination agreement form was signed.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 13, states that, in general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the taxpayer filed the original return or 2 years from the date the tax was paid, whichever is later. If the taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnIn this case, Bethany must file a claim for refund by September 30, 2024, which is the later of the two dates (2 years from when the additional tax was paid).nnNote: Due to COVID, the 2019 tax year deadline was extended to July 15, 2020, moving the statute of limitations to three years later in July (not April) for that tax year. For the 2020 tax year, the deadline was moved to May 17, 2021, shifting the three-year statute of limitations to May (not April) for that tax year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1470,8,'Disputes involving what areas of taxation may be resolved in the U.S. Tax Court?','[\"Income tax\",\"Gift tax\",\"Estate tax\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'As provided on page 2 of Publication 5, the taxpayer can go to the U.S. Tax Court if a disagreement with the IRS is over whether a taxpayer owes additional income tax, estate tax, gift tax, employment tax involving IRS employment status determinations, or certain excise taxes.nnTax controversies such as those involving some employment tax issues or manufacturers\' excise taxes are heard by the District Court or the Court of Federal Claims; they cannot be heard by the Tax Court.nnTherefore, a dispute involving income, gift, or estate taxes may be resolved in the U.S. Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1471,8,'How long does a taxpayer have from the date of the Statutory Notice of Deficiency to file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court if he or she resides outside the United States?','[\"30 days\",\"90 days\",\"150 days\",\"180 days\"]',2,'The Statutory Notice of Deficiency is referred to as the Notice of Deficiency, and it is also known as the 90-day letter because this is the time that the taxpayer has to file a petition with the Tax Court.nnPublication 556, page 5, provides that a taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the 30-day letter to tell the IRS whether he or she will accept or appeal the proposed changes.nnIf the taxpayer does not respond to the 30-day letter, or if the taxpayer later does not reach an agreement with an Appeals Officer, the IRS will send a 90-day letter, which also is known as a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer will have 90 days (150 days if the taxpayer\'s address is outside the United States) from the date of this notice to file a petition with the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1472,8,'Joe, a calendar year taxpayer, filed his federal income tax return, with a refund due, for tax year 2024 on April 1, 2025. The last day to timely file a claim for refund with respect to that return is:','[\"April 1, 2027.\",\"April 15, 2027.\",\"April 1, 2028.\",\"April 15, 2028.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 13, states that, in general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the taxpayer filed the original return or 2 years from the date the tax was paid, whichever is later. If the taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnAlso, if the due date to file a return or a claim for a credit or refund is a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, it is filed on the next business day. Returns that are filed before the due date are considered filed on the due date.nnThus, Joe must file a claim for a refund by April 15, 2028, for his tax return that was filed on April 1, 2025, but was not due until April 15, 2025. nnNote: April 15 due date may vary by a few days in subsequent years due to weekends and holidays. The date is the same for consistency.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1473,8,'Generally, how long does the IRS have to collect outstanding federal taxes?','[\"10 years from the due date of the return\",\"10 years from the date the return is filed\",\"10 years from the date of the notice of deficiency\",\"10 years from the date of assessment\"]',3,'By law, the IRS has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for 10 years from the date of assessment. The 10-year collection period may be suspended under certain circumstances that are discussed in Publication 594 on pages 3 and 4.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1474,8,'The IRS has begun an examination of Mark\'s income tax return. The IRS would like to ask Mark\'s neighbors questions with respect to that examination. There is no pending criminal investigation into the matter and there is no evidence that such contact will result in reprisals against the neighbors or jeopardize collection of the tax liability. Before the IRS contacts the neighbors, the IRS must:','[\"provide Mark with reasonable notice of the contact.\",\"make an assessment of Mark\'s tax liability.\",\"ask the court for a third-party record keeper subpoena.\",\"mail Mark a statutory notice of deficiency.\"]',0,'Publication 556 (page 3) provides, in part, that the IRS must give a taxpayer reasonable notice before contacting other persons when examining or collecting a taxpayer\'s tax liability. The IRS may contact third parties such as the taxpayer\'s neighbors, banks, employers, or employees as part of this examination or collection process.nnThe IRS also must give a taxpayer notice of specific contacts by providing the taxpayer with a record of persons contacted on both a periodic basis and upon the taxpayer\'s request.nnAs one might suspect, there are exceptions to the above policy. The provision does not apply to any pending criminal investigation, when providing notice would jeopardize collection of any tax liability, where providing notice may result in reprisal against any person, or when the taxpayer authorized the contact.nnThus, the IRS must provide Mark with reasonable notice before contacting his neighbors.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1475,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a small tax case?','[\"A small tax case is one that is $100,000 or less for any tax year or period.\",\"A small tax case can be presented by the taxpayer to the Tax Court for a decision that is final and that cannot be appealed.\",\"A small tax case decision can be appealed to the Tax Court.\",\"A small tax case is one that is requested by the IRS and the taxpayer agrees to it.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 12, provides information on the small tax case procedure. If the amount in a taxpayer\'s case is $50,000 or less for any 1 tax year or period, the Tax Court has a simpler alternative to solve the taxpayer\'s case. At the taxpayer\'s request and if the Tax Court approves, the taxpayer\'s case can be handled under the small tax case procedure. In this procedure, the taxpayer can present his or her case to the Tax Court for a decision that is final and that cannot be appealed.nnAs a result of the above information, the only correct statement is the one that states a small tax case can be presented by the taxpayer to the Tax Court for a decision that is final and that cannot be appealed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1476,8,'A disagreement with the Internal Revenue Service can be taken to the U.S. Tax Court if:','[\"it pertains to income tax.\",\"a statutory notice of deficiency has been issued.\",\"a petition is filed within 90 days from the date a statutory notice of deficiency is mailed (150 days if it is addressed to the taxpayer outside the United States).\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'If a disagreement with the IRS is over whether a taxpayer owes additional income tax, estate tax, gift tax, certain excise taxes, or penalties related to these proposed liabilities, the taxpayer can go to the U.S. Tax Court. A taxpayer starts this process after the IRS issues a formal letter stating the amounts that the IRS believes the taxpayer owes. This letter is called a notice of deficiency. The taxpayer has 90 days from the date the notice of deficiency is mailed to file a petition with the Tax Court (or 150 days if the notice is addressed outside the United States).nnTherefore, all of the above items would allow the disagreement with the Internal Revenue Service to be taken to the U.S. Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1477,8,'Disputes involving which areas of taxation may not be resolved in a deficiency determination proceeding in U.S. Tax Court?','[\"Income tax\",\"Gift tax\",\"Employment tax not involving IRS employment status determination\",\"Estate tax\"]',2,'If a disagreement with the IRS is over whether a taxpayer owes additional income tax, estate tax, gift tax, employment tax involving IRS employment status determinations, or certain excise taxes, the taxpayer can go to the U.S. Tax Court.nnTax controversies such as those involving some employment tax issues or manufacturers\' excise taxes are heard by the District Court or the Court of Federal Claims; they cannot be heard by the Tax Court.nnTherefore, all of the above items would allow the disagreement with the Internal Revenue Service to be taken the U.S. Tax Court except for employment taxes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1478,8,'For how long a period does the Internal Revenue Service generally have the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes?','[\"For not more than 3 years from the date of assessment\",\"For not more than 7 years from the date of assessment\",\"For not more than 10 years from the date of assessment\",\"There is no time limit placed on the IRS.\"]',2,'By law, the IRS has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for 10 years from the date of assessment. The 10-year collection period is suspended:nnwhile the IRS and the Office of Appeals consider a request for an Installment Agreement or an Offer in Compromise,nfrom the date the taxpayer requests a Collection Due Process (CDP) hearing until Appeals issues a CDP Notice of Determination, or the taxpayer seeks review in the Tax Court until the Tax Court\'s decision becomes final,nfrom the date the taxpayer requests innocent spouse relief until a final Notice of Determination is issued,nfor tax periods included in a bankruptcy while the automatic stay is in effect, plus an additional 6 months, ornwhile the taxpayer is residing outside the United States, or the taxpayer is absent for a continuous period of at least 6 months.nThe amount of time the suspension is in effect will be added to the 10-year period. Thus, a 6-month suspension increases the time to collect to 10 years and 6 months.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1479,8,'Charlie had income tax withheld from his wages during 2020 in the amount of $5,000. Charlie filed an automatic extension of time to file his tax return for that year to October 15, 2021, together with making an additional payment in the amount of $2,000 with the extension. Charlie filed his tax return on December 15, 2021, and paid the balance shown to be due on the return of $1,000 on that date. Charlie discovered an error in his return on December 1, 2024. On that same date, he filed a claim for refund in the amount of $6,000. Assuming that the grounds set forth in the claim are proper, what refund can Charlie recover for 2020?','[\"$6,000\",\"$2,000\",\"$1,000\",\"$0\"]',2,'In general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the original return is filed or 2 years from the date the taxpayer paid the tax, whichever is later. If a taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnIn addition, if a taxpayer files his or her claim within 3 years after filing his or her tax return, the credit or refund cannot be more than the part of the tax paid within the 3 years before filing the claim. Several examples of this rule are provided in Publication 556, page 15.nnSince Charlie is filing for a refund on December 1, 2024, he can only seek a refund for any taxes paid since December 1, 2021, which is within the 3-year period of filing his return. In this case, Charlie is limited to seeking a refund of only $1,000, which was paid on December 15, 2021.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1480,8,'Nancy, a calendar year taxpayer, filed her federal income tax return for tax year 2022, which was due on April 15, 2023, on May 1, 2023. Nancy did not request, and therefore did not receive, an extension of time to file her 2022 federal income tax return. Nancy paid the amount due as shown on the 2022 return on June 30, 2023. Based on these facts, the last day for the IRS to assess additional tax with respect to Nancy\'s 2022 return is:','[\"June 20, 2025.\",\"April 15, 2026.\",\"May 1, 2026.\",\"June 20, 2026.\"]',2,'Publication 17, page 18, provides the period in which a taxpayer can amend their tax return to claim a credit or refund or the IRS can assess additional tax. Specifically, Table 1-7 shows the following period of limitations:nnnnBecause of the provided limitations, the last day for the IRS to assess additional tax with respect to Nancy\'s 2022 return is May 1, 2026, which is 3 years from the date of filing (which is May 1, 2023).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1481,8,'The “Small Tax Case” procedures in the Tax Court allow resolution of cases under a set of rules that are simpler than the normal Tax Court procedures. A case may be designated a “Small Tax Case” in the Tax Court if the amount of tax at issue for each tax year or period is not more than:','[\"$50,000.\",\"$100,000.\",\"$125,000.\",\"$150,000.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 12, states that at the taxpayer\'s request and with the Tax Court\'s agreement, small tax case procedures are available to simplify the case resolution process when the amount at issue is $50,000 or less for any 1 tax year or period. However, decisions given in this court are final and not appealable by either party.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1482,8,'After assessment, as a general rule, the Internal Revenue Service has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for:','[\"3 years.\",\"5 years.\",\"10 years.\",\"20 years.\"]',2,'By law, the IRS has the authority to collect outstanding federal taxes for 10 years from the date of assessment, assuming no suspension to the collection time was granted. The 10-year collection period is suspended:nnwhile the IRS and the Office of Appeals consider a request for an Installment Agreement or an Offer in Compromise,nfrom the date the taxpayer requests a Collection Due Process (CDP) hearing until Appeals issues a CDP Notice of Determination, or the taxpayer seeks review in the Tax Court,nfrom the date the taxpayer requests innocent spouse relief until a final Notice of Determination is issued,nfor tax periods included in a bankruptcy while the automatic stay is in effect, plus an additional 6 months, ornwhile the taxpayer is residing outside the United States, or the taxpayer is absent for a continuous period of at least 6 months.nThe amount of time the suspension is in effect will be added to the 10-year period. Thus, a 6-month suspension increases the time to collect to 10 years and 6 months.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1483,8,'Which of the following tasks may be performed by an enrolled agent on behalf of his or her client?','[\"Prepare and file a suit for refund in United States District Court.\",\"Prepare and sign a United States Tax Court petition to contest a notice of deficiency.\",\"Prepare and sign a protest to challenge examination results in the IRS Independent Office of Appeals.\",\"Prepare and file a bankruptcy petition in United States Bankruptcy Court due to unpaid tax balances.\"]',2,'Circular 230, Section 10.32, outlines the tasks that can be performed by individuals practicing before the IRS, including enrolled agents (EAs). Enrolled agents are authorized to represent taxpayers before the IRS, but their authority is limited in certain legal proceedings.nnEnrolled agents are not licensed to practice law and cannot represent clients in federal courts therefore they cannot file a suit for refund in U.S. District Court. While enrolled agents can represent clients in front of the IRS, they are not authorized to prepare and sign petitions for the United States Tax Court. Only attorneys, CPAs, and those specially admitted to practice before the Tax Court can sign and file such petitions. Preparing and filing a bankruptcy petition involves practicing law, which is outside the scope of what an enrolled agent can do. Only licensed attorneys can represent clients in bankruptcy proceedings.nnTo prepare and sign a protest to challenge examination results in the IRS Independent Office of Appeals is within the scope of what an enrolled agent is authorized to do.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1484,8,'A claim for refund must be filed:','[\"no later than 3 years after you filed your original return.\",\"no later than 2 years from the date you paid the tax.\",\"no later than 3 years after you filed your original return or no later than 2 years from the date you paid the tax, whichever is later.\",\"4 years after making estimated payments.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 13, addresses the timing issue for filing a claim for refund. It states that, in general, a taxpayer must file a claim for a credit or refund within 3 years from the date the taxpayer filed the original return or 2 years from the date the tax was paid, whichever is later. If the taxpayer does not file a claim within this period, the taxpayer may no longer be entitled to a credit or a refund.nnIf the due date to file a return or a claim for a credit or refund is a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday, it is filed on time if it is filed on the next business day. Returns filed by a taxpayer before the due date are considered filed on the due date. This is true even when the due date is a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1485,8,'In which of the following courts can a taxpayer seek relief if the taxpayer disagrees with the IRS after the Appeals conference?','[\"The taxpayer can take the case\\u00a0only\\u00a0to the U.S. Tax Court.\",\"The taxpayer can take the case\\u00a0only\\u00a0to the U.S. District Court or the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.\",\"The taxpayer can take the case\\u00a0only\\u00a0to the U.S. Tax Court or the U.S. District Court.\",\"The taxpayer can take the case to the U.S. Tax Court, the U.S. District Court, or the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 9, provides that if a taxpayer and the IRS still disagree after the Appeals conference, the taxpayer can take the case to the U.S. Tax Court (taxes owed), the U.S. Court of Federal Claims (refund claimed), or the U.S. District Court (refund claimed). All of these courts are independent of the IRS.nnIf a taxpayer elects to bypass the IRS\'s Appeals system, the taxpayer may be able to take the case to one of the courts listed above. But a case petitioned to the Tax Court will normally be considered for settlement by an Appeals Office before the Tax Court hears the case.nnnn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nIf a taxpayer unreasonably fails to pursue the IRS\'s Appeals system, or if the case is intended primarily to cause a delay or the taxpayer\'s position is frivolous or groundless, the Tax Court may impose a penalty of up to $25,000.nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1486,8,'A power of attorney may not be used to:','[\"authorize a recognized representative to receive the original of notices sent to the taxpayer by the IRS.\",\"sign a closing agreement.\",\"represent the taxpayer before any office of the IRS.\",\"endorse or cash a refund check drawn on the U.S. Treasury.\"]',3,'Publication 947, page 6, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating or endorsing a check by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. It is most often used when a taxpayer wants another individual to represent him or her at a conference with the IRS or to prepare and file a written response to the IRS.nnAs provided in Circular 230, Section 10.31, a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability. Thus, a tax representative is not authorized to endorse or cash a client\'s check.nnMoreover, a practitioner who negotiates a taxpayer’s check is assessed a penalty pursuant to IRC § 6695(f).nnThe power of attorney does not include endorsing or cashing a check by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1487,8,'Which of the following publications provides the statement of procedural rules for conference and practice requirements?','[\"IRS Publication 947\",\"IRS Publication 216\",\"Circular 230\",\"There is no publication on this topic.\"]',1,'IRS Publication 216, Conference and Practice Requirements, provides the statement of procedural rules for conference and practice requirements. More specifically, Regulation Section 601.501 as reproduced in the publication provides the rules concerning, among other things, the representation of taxpayers before the IRS under the authority of a power of attorney. These rules apply to all offices of the IRS in all matters under the jurisdiction of the IRS and apply to practice before the IRS (as defined in 31 CFR 10.2(a) and 10.7(a)(7)).nnThese rules detail the means by which a recognized representative is authorized to act on behalf of a taxpayer. Such authority must be evidenced by a power of attorney and declaration of representative filed with the appropriate office of the Internal Revenue Service.nnIRS Publication 947 discusses who can represent a taxpayer before the IRS and what forms or documents are used to authorize a person to represent a taxpayer.nnCircular 230 contains rules governing the recognition of attorneys, certified public accountants, enrolled agents, enrolled retirement plan agents, registered tax return preparers, and other persons representing taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1488,8,'What must a taxpayer do to appoint a representative to act on a taxpayer\'s behalf before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"A certified letter is filed\\u00a0only\\u00a0if the taxpayer wants to name a person(s) to represent them and that person is recognized to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"Form 2848 is filed\\u00a0only\\u00a0if the taxpayer wants to name a person(s) to represent them and that person is recognized to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"Form 2848 is filed\\u00a0only\\u00a0if the taxpayer wants to name a person(s) to represent them and that person is\\u00a0not\\u00a0recognized to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"A certified letter is filed\\u00a0only\\u00a0if the taxpayer wants to name a person(s) to represent them and that person is\\u00a0not\\u00a0recognized to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.\"]',1,'Publication 947, pages 7 and 8, states a taxpayer must submit a power of attorney when the taxpayer wants to authorize an individual to receive confidential tax information and represent the taxpayer before the IRS. A power of attorney is most often required when a taxpayer wants to authorize another individual to perform at least one of the following acts on behalf of the taxpayer:nnRepresent the taxpayer at a meeting with the IRS.nPrepare and file a written response to the IRS.nForm 2848 is used to appoint a representative to act on behalf of the taxpayer before the IRS. The taxpayer can file this form only if the taxpayer wants to name a person(s) to represent the taxpayer and that person is recognized to practice before the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1489,8,'Which of the following may a taxpayer authorize under very limited circumstances, as described in the instructions to Form 2848, to receive and endorse a refund check on behalf of the taxpayer?','[\"An attorney, CPA, or enrolled agent\",\"An attorney or CPA\",\"An attorney\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 947, pages 7 and 8, provides general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnAn authorized representative can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.nnTherefore, the answer choices in this problem are incorrect because a representative of the taxpayer cannot endorse or cash a taxpayer\'s check.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1490,8,'A Centralized Authorization File (CAF) is an automated file containing information regarding the authority of an individual appointed under a power of attorney or person designated under a tax information authorization. Which of the following powers of attorney will be recorded on the CAF?','[\"If it relates to a specific tax period\",\"If it pertains to a corporate dissolution\",\"If it is a request to change accounting methods or periods\",\"If it is a request for a private letter ruling or technical advice\"]',0,'As provided in the instructions for line 4 of Form 2848, the IRS records powers of attorney on the CAF system. The CAF system is a computer file system containing information regarding the authority of individuals appointed under powers of attorney. The system gives IRS personnel quicker access to authorization information without requesting the original documents from the taxpayer or representative.nnA specific-use power of attorney is a one-time or specific-issue grant of authority to a representative or is a power of attorney that does not relate to a specific tax period that the IRS does not record on the CAF. Hence, a power of attorney will be recorded on the CAF if it relates to a specific tax period (except for civil penalties) or if it is for a specific issue. Examples of specific uses not recorded on the CAF include but are not limited to:nnrequests for a private letter ruling or technical advice,napplications for an EIN (Employer Identification Number),nclaims filed on Form 843, Claim for Refund and Request for Abatement,ncorporate dissolutions,nCircular 230 disciplinary investigations and proceedings, andnrequests to change accounting methods or periods.nIn addition, a specific-use power of attorney will not revoke any prior powers of attorney.nnIn this case, a power of attorney will not be recorded on the CAF if it does not relate to a specific tax period.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1491,8,'Which of the following is correct of a newly filed power of attorney concerning the same matter as the previous power of attorney?','[\"If a new representative is included on the newly filed power of attorney, then the new representative is automatically added to the list of authorized representatives.\",\"The new power of attorney automatically revokes the prior power of attorney.\",\"The new power of attorney automatically revokes any Forms 8821 that are in effect.\",\"The new power of attorney automatically revokes the prior power of attorney and any Forms 8821 that are in effect.\"]',1,'Instructions for Form 2848, page 7, provide if a power of attorney is filed on the CAF system, it generally will revoke any earlier power of attorney previously recorded on the system for the same matter.nnIf this power of attorney is for a specific use or is not filed on the CAF, this power of attorney only will revoke an earlier power of attorney that is on file with the same office and for the same matter.nnPublication 947, page 10, states a newly filed power of attorney concerning the same matter will revoke a previously filed power of attorney.nnThe new power of attorney, however, will not revoke the prior power of attorney if it specifically states it does not revoke such prior power of attorney and either of the following is attached to the new power of attorney:nnA copy of the unrevoked prior power of attorney, ornA statement signed by the taxpayer listing the name and address of each representative authorized under the prior unrevoked power of attorney.nFurthermore, the filing of Form 2848 will not revoke any Form 8821 that is in effect.nnTherefore, the correct statement in this problem is the new power of attorney automatically revokes the prior power of attorney.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1492,8,'What is the purpose of the Centralized Authorization File (CAF) number?','[\"Before the PTIN, this was the number a preparer would use to sign an electronically filed return.\",\"The CAF number is another means of tracking enrolled agents.\",\"Use of the CAF number allows the IRS to verify an individual\'s authority to represent the taxpayer before the IRS.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 9, addresses the issues associated with the processing of a non-IRS power of attorney. In general, the IRS has a centralized computer database system called the Centralized Authorization File (CAF) system. This system contains information on the authority of taxpayer representatives.nnWhen a taxpayer submits a power of attorney document to the IRS, it is processed for inclusion on the CAF system. Entry of the taxpayer\'s power of attorney on the CAF system enables IRS personnel, who do not have a copy of the power of attorney, to verify the authority of the taxpayer\'s representative by accessing the centralized authorization file.nnFinally, it also enables the IRS to automatically send copies of notices and other IRS communications to the taxpayer\'s representative.nnThus, the purpose of the CAF number is to allow the IRS to verify an individual\'s authority to represent the taxpayer before the Service.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1493,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a tax preparer who is not an enrolled agent, CPA, or attorney?','[\"He may represent any taxpayer before appeals officers of the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"He may sign a closing agreement.\",\"He may sign a consent form to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a tax.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to the limited representation rights provided in the Instructions for Form 2848 (page 2), unenrolled return preparers may only represent taxpayers before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination of the taxable period covered by the tax return they prepared and signed.nnUnenrolled return preparers cannot represent taxpayers, regardless of the circumstances requiring representation, before appeals officers, revenue officers, attorneys from the Office of Chief Counsel, or similar officers or employees of the Internal Revenue Service or the Department of Treasury. Unenrolled return preparers cannot execute closing agreements, extend the statutory period for tax assessments or collection of tax, execute waivers, execute claims for refund, or sign any document on behalf of a taxpayer.nnAs provided on page 7 of Publication 947, attorneys, CPAs, and enrolled agents (not unenrolled preparers) may perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnTherefore, none of the responses in this question are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1494,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning an enrolled agent?','[\"He may represent any taxpayer before a Revenue Officer of the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"He may sign a closing agreement.\",\"He may sign a consent form to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a tax.\",\"All of the three answer choices given are correct.\"]',3,'Attorneys, CPAs, and enrolled agents (NOT unenrolled preparers) may perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners must not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability.nnTherefore, all three of the answer choices given in this question are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1495,8,'Which of the following is correct concerning Leonore, an enrolled agent who prepares an income tax return for Jamison?','[\"She can receive and endorse an IRS refund check payable to Jamison.\",\"She\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0receive but she can endorse an IRS refund check payable to Jamison.\",\"She\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0endorse but she can deposit an IRS refund check payable to Jamison in her business account.\",\"She is not authorized to endorse or otherwise negotiate an IRS refund check payable to Jamison.\"]',3,'Practitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.nnThus, a representative of the taxpayer must not endorse or cash a taxpayer\'s check. Be careful in this question to appreciate the subtlety of the response; the enrolled agent cannot receive the refund in his or her account.nnPursuant to IRC § 6695(f), a practitioner who negotiates a taxpayer’s check is assessed a penalty.nn',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1496,8,'Which of the following items does entry onto the Centralized Authorization File (CAF) system enable Internal Revenue Service employees who do not have access to the actual power of attorney or tax information authorization to do?nn1.Determine whether a recognized representative or appointee is authorized to discuss specific confidential tax informationn2. Determine the extent to which a recognized representative or appointee has been authorized to represent a taxpayern3. Send copies of notices and other Internal Revenue Service communications to the person (individual or other entity) designated on the form','[\"Items 1 and 2 are accessible.\",\"Items 1 and 3 are accessible.\",\"Items 2 and 3 are accessible.\",\"Items 1, 2, and 3 are accessible.\"]',3,'Publication 947, pages 8 and 9, provides the issues associated with the processing of a non-IRS power of attorney. In general, the IRS will accept a non-IRS power of attorney, but a completed Form 2848 must be attached in order for the power of attorney to be entered on the centralized authorization file system (CAF system). This system contains information on the authority of taxpayer representatives.nnWhen a taxpayer submits a power of attorney document to the IRS, it is processed for inclusion on the CAF system. Entry of the taxpayer\'s power of attorney on the CAF system enables IRS personnel, who do not have a copy of the power of attorney, to verify the authority of the taxpayer\'s representative by accessing the centralized authorization file. It also enables the IRS to automatically send copies of notices and other IRS communications to the taxpayer\'s representative.nnA taxpayer can have his or her non-IRS power of attorney entered on the CAF system by attaching it to a completed transmittal Form 2848 and submitting it to the IRS. The taxpayer\'s signature is not required; however, the taxpayer\'s attorney-in-fact must sign the declaration of representative.nnThus, the purpose of the CAF number is to allow the IRS to verify an individual\'s authority to represent the taxpayer before the Service. Therefore, all three items are accessible.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1497,8,'A power of attorney is required when you want to authorize any individual to do the following:','[\"To represent you at a conference with the IRS\",\"To prepare and file a written response to the IRS\",\"To sign the offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of tax deficiency\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 947, page 7, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check. It is most often used when a taxpayer wants another individual to represent him or her at a conference with the IRS or to prepare and file a written response to the IRS. However, the authority granted to an unenrolled preparer is limited.nnAn authorized representative (except for an unenrolled return preparer, whose authority and powers are limited) can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnAll three items that are listed in this problem require a power of attorney. Hence, all are correct responses.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1498,8,'John Bitter wants his associate, Bill Sweet, to be informed about his business tax account. John wants to disclose only this information and grant no other authority. Which form should be filed to give Bill this authorization?','[\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0should\\u00a0not\\u00a0be used in this situation.\",\"Form 2848,\\u00a0Power of Attorney,\\u00a0should be used in this situation.\",\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0should be used in this situation.\",\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0or Form 2848,\\u00a0Power of Attorney,\\u00a0should be used in this situation.\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 11, provides the general rules for when a power of attorney is not required. A taxpayer does not have to file a power of attorney to authorize the disclosure of tax return information. This is done using Form 8821, Tax Information Authorization.nnForm 8821 authorizes any individual, corporation, firm, organization, or partnership the taxpayer designates to inspect and/or receive confidential information verbally or in writing for the type of tax and the year or periods listed on Form 8821. Section 6103(c) limits disclosure and use of return information received pursuant to the taxpayer’s consent and holds the recipient subject to penalties for any unauthorized access, other use, or redisclosure without the taxpayer’s express permission or request.nnIn contrast, Form 2848 authorizes a third-party to represent the taxpayer before the IRS. With the exception of unenrolled preparers whose rights representation rights are limited, federally authorized third-parties are granted authority under Form 2848 to inspect and/or receive confidential information and perform all acts (sign agreements, consents, waivers, etc.) that the taxpayer himself/herself would be able to perform with respect to the matters described on Form 2848.nnHence, Form 8821 should be used to limit the associate\'s authorization to only access information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1499,8,'Which of the following representatives can be authorized by a taxpayer by inserting a provision on Form 2848, Power of Attorney and Declaration of Representative, to receive and endorse a refund check on behalf of the taxpayer?','[\"An attorney\",\"A CPA\",\"An enrolled agent\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 947, page 6, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnAny representative, other than an unenrolled preparer, can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnMoreover, if a practitioner endorses or otherwise negotiates any check issued by the federal government, they can be assessed a penalty per IRC § 6695(f).nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1500,8,'Under which of the following situations can a representative be given any notice or other written communication required or permitted to be given to a taxpayer in any matter before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"Any federally authorized practitioner acting on behalf of a taxpayer can be given any notice or other written communication if the taxpayer is not present\\u00a0only\\u00a0if the taxpayer has filed a power of attorney.\",\"Any federally authorized practitioner acting on behalf of a taxpayer can be given any notice or other written communication if the taxpayer is not present.\",\"A federally authorized practitioner acting on behalf of a taxpayer can be given any notice or other written communication\\u00a0only\\u00a0in the presence of the taxpayer.\",\"There is\\u00a0no\\u00a0circumstance that permits a federally authorized practitioner acting on behalf of a taxpayer to be given any notice or other written communication about the taxpayer.\"]',0,'As given in Publication 556, pages 8 and 9, a taxpayer can represent himself or herself at an Appeals conference, or the taxpayer can be represented by any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled actuary, or an enrolled agent, but not an unenrolled return preparer.nnBut if the taxpayer\'s representative attends a conference without the taxpayer, he or she can receive or inspect confidential information only if the taxpayer has filed a power of attorney or a tax information authorization. That is, the taxpayer can use a Form 2848 or any other properly written power of attorney or authorization.nnAs given in Publication 947, page 4, unenrolled return preparers may only represent taxpayers before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination of the taxable period covered by the tax return they prepared and signed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1501,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the filing of a new power of attorney (Form 2848)?','[\"It revokes all prior powers of attorney regardless of the matter to which it pertains.\",\"It revokes any Form 8821 that is in effect.\",\"It will\\u00a0not\\u00a0revoke the prior power of attorney if certain procedures are followed.\",\"None of the responses are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 10, states a newly filed power of attorney concerning the same matter will revoke a previously filed power of attorney. The new power of attorney, however, will not revoke the prior power of attorney if it specifically states it does not revoke such prior power of attorney and either of the following is attached to the new power of attorney:nnA copy of the unrevoked prior power of attorney, ornA statement signed by the taxpayer listing the name and address of each representative authorized under the prior unrevoked power of attorney.nFurthermore, the filing of Form 2848 will not revoke any Form 8821 that is in effect and, similarly, the filing of Form 8821 will not revoke any Form 2848 that is in effect.nnTherefore, the correct response states that it will not revoke the prior power of attorney if certain procedures (as listed above) are followed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1502,8,'Which of the following is correct concerning a power of attorney?','[\"It must be mailed to the IRS.\",\"It must be hand-delivered to the IRS.\",\"It must be sent by fax (facsimile transmission) to the IRS.\",\"It should be mailed, faxed, or submitted online to the IRS.\"]',3,'The Instructions for Form 2848, page 2, provides that a power of attorney form (i.e., Form 2848) should be mailed to the office handling the specific matter. Otherwise, it should be mailed, faxed, or submitted online directly to the IRS address according to the \"Where to File Chart.\"nnIn addition, the taxpayer\'s representative is able to file Form 2848 electronically via the IRS website (see page 10 of Publication 947). The taxpayer and the tax professional must sign Form 2848. The signatures on the form can be handwritten or electronic. For the electronic signature option for a new client, the tax professional must authenticate the client\'s identity. The tax professional may also use the \"submit Form 2848 and 8821 online\" to withdraw previous authorizations.nnSignatures on mailed or faxed forms must be handwritten. Electronic signatures are not allowed.nnThus, the best response to this question is a power of attorney form should be sent by mail or fax to the IRS',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1503,8,'The following statements are given to you as an enrolled agent:nn1. The filing of Form 8821 will revoke any Form 2848 that is in effect.n2. The filing of Form 2848 will revoke any Form 8821 that is in effect.','[\"Item 1 is correct.\",\"Item 2 is correct.\",\"Both items 1 and 2 are correct.\",\"Both items 1 and 2 are\\u00a0incorrect.\"]',3,'Publication 947, page 10, states that a newly filed power of attorney (Form 2848) concerning the same matter will revoke a previously filed power of attorney.nnThe new power of attorney, however, will not revoke the prior power of attorney if it specifically states it does not revoke such prior power of attorney and either of the following is attached to the new power of attorney:nna copy of the unrevoked prior power of attorney, orna statement signed by the taxpayer listing the name and address of each representative authorized under the prior unrevoked power of attorney.nFurthermore, the filing of Form 2848 will not revoke any Form 8821 that is in effect.nnThe instructions for Form 8821, page 1, provide that Form 8821 authorizes any individual, corporation, firm, organization, or partnership the taxpayer designates to inspect and/or receive the taxpayer\'s confidential information verbally or in writing for the type of tax and the years or periods the taxpayer lists on Form 8821. Form 8821 (not Form 2848) is also used to delete or revoke prior tax information authorizations. Likewise, Form 2848 (not Form 8821) is filed to authorize an individual to represent the taxpayer before the IRS. The appointee may not substitute another party as the taxpayer\'s authorized designee. Therefore, both items are incorrect.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1504,8,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to the power of attorney authorization?','[\"A power of attorney is an oral authorization for any individual to act on behalf of a taxpayer with respect to tax matters.\",\"A power of attorney allows the named representative to sign a taxpayer\'s personal income tax return.\",\"A power of attorney can authorize a taxpayer\'s representative to receive and endorse a refund check of the taxpayer.\",\"A power of attorney may limit the named representative with respect to the acts that he or she may be allowed to do.\"]',3,'Publication 947, pages 7 and 8, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check. As a result, power of attorney may limit the named representative as to what acts they may or may not perform on behalf of the taxpayer.nnIn general, a representative can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnGenerally, the representative named on the Form 2848, Power of Attorney cannot sign an income tax return unless:nnthe signature is permitted under the Internal Revenue Code and other regulations (Reg. Sec. 1.6012-1(a)(5)).nthe taxpayers specifically authorize this in its Power of Attorney.nThe regulation permits the authorized representative to sign a taxpayer\'s return if the taxpayer is unable to sign the return due to disease or injury, continuous absence from the United States for a period of at least 60 days before the date required by law for filing the return, or other good cause if specific permission is requested and granted by the IRS. Absent these special circumstances, the representative cannot sign a return on behalf of a taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1505,8,'Under what condition does Circular 230 permit an enrolled agent to cash a taxpayer\'s refund check?','[\"The amount of the check is less than the amount of the total fee outstanding on the date the check is cashed.\",\"The amount of the check is less than $100.\",\"The check is endorsed by the taxpayer.\",\"Circular 230 prohibits an enrolled agent from cashing a taxpayer\'s refund check.\"]',3,'Publication 947, page 6, provides general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnCircular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1506,8,'A properly executed power of attorney must contain all of the following except:','[\"the identification number of the taxpayer (i.e., Social Security number or employer identification number).\",\"the specific year(s) and period(s) involved.\",\"the name of the preparer of the return for the year(s) and period(s) involved.\",\"the signature of the appointed representative.\"]',2,'A properly executed power of attorney must contain specific items, as given on lines 1 through 7 of Form 2848 and discussed on pages 11 and 12 of Publication 947, including but not limited to:nn(line 1) taxpayer information (i.e., name, street address, and Social Security number or employer identification number),n(line 2) the representative (the name and current address of the taxpayer\'s chosen representative),n(line 3) tax matters (i.e., acts authorized by taxpayer such as description of tax matters, tax forms, and specific year(s) and period(s) involved; as well as authority to sign any agreements, consents, or similar documents),n(line 5a) additional acts authorized,n(line 6) retention/revocation of prior power(s) of attorney, andn(line 7) the signature of the taxpayer or appointed representative.nPublication 947, pages 11 and 12, provides general information and an example that illustrates how to complete Form 2848. Also see the IRS instructions for Form 2848 for more information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1507,8,'An unenrolled preparer can represent the taxpayer before the IRS to:','[\"represent the taxpayer before any office of the IRS.\",\"sign a consent form to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a tax.\",\"sign a closing agreement\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 9, provides that a taxpayer can represent himself or herself at an Appeals conference. Similarly, the taxpayer can be represented by any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled actuary, or an enrolled agent.nnPursuant to the instructions for Form 2848, page 2, unenrolled return preparers may only represent taxpayers before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination of the taxable period covered by the tax return they prepared and signed.nnUnenrolled return preparers cannot represent taxpayers, regardless of the circumstances requiring representation, before appeals officers, revenue officers, counsel, or similar officers or employees of the Internal Revenue Service or the Department of Treasury. Unenrolled return preparers cannot execute closing agreements, extend the statutory period for tax assessments or collection of tax, execute waivers, execute claims for refund, or sign any document on behalf of a taxpayer.nnMore specifically, Publication 947, pages 7 and 8, provides, in part, that any representative, other than an unenrolled preparer, can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnThus, none of the responses are applicable to an unenrolled preparer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1508,8,'Which of the following may an enrolled agent not be authorized to do by a client under a properly executed power of attorney?','[\"Represent the taxpayer before any office of the IRS\",\"Sign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency\",\"Endorse or cash a refund check drawn on the U.S. Treasury\",\"Sign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a tax\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 7, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnAn enrolled agent can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnIndividuals subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnPursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.31 provides a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability. Thus, a tax representative is not authorized to endorse or cash a client\'s check.nnA practitioner who negotiates a taxpayer’s check is assessed a penalty pursuant to IRC § 6695(f).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1509,8,'Which of the following statements is correct with respect to the limited practice of an unenrolled return preparer?','[\"An unenrolled return preparer may represent the taxpayer, before certain types of Internal Revenue Service personnel, with respect to an examination regarding the return that he or she prepared.\",\"An unenrolled return preparer is permitted to appear as a taxpayer\'s representative before any function of the Internal Revenue Service as long as he or she prepared the return.\",\"If authorized by the taxpayer, an unenrolled return preparer can sign consents to extend the statutory period for assessment or collection of tax.\",\"An unenrolled preparer may receive a refund check on behalf of the taxpayer if permission has been granted to the unenrolled preparer with a Form 8821.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 9, provides that a taxpayer can represent himself or herself at an Appeals conference. Similarly, the taxpayer can be represented by any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled actuary, or an enrolled agent.nnIf, however, the taxpayer\'s representative attends a conference without the taxpayer, he or she can receive or inspect confidential information only if the taxpayer has filed a power of attorney or a tax information authorization, which is done using a Form 2848 or any other properly written power of attorney or authorization.nnPursuant to the instructions for Form 2848 (page 2), unenrolled return preparers may only represent taxpayers before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination of the taxable period covered by the tax return they prepared and signed.nnUnenrolled return preparers cannot represent taxpayers, regardless of the circumstances requiring representation, before appeals officers, revenue officers, counsel, or similar officers or employees of the Internal Revenue Service or the Department of Treasury. Unenrolled return preparers cannot execute closing agreements, extend the statutory period for tax assessments or collection of tax, execute waivers, execute claims for refund, or sign any document on behalf of a taxpayer.nnThus, the correct statement in this problem is that an unenrolled return preparer may represent the taxpayer, before certain types of Internal Revenue Service personnel, with respect to an examination regarding the return that he or she prepared.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1510,8,'Which of the following tax return preparers may receive and endorse a taxpayer\'s refund check and invest the proceeds in a mutual fund if the representative has the taxpayer\'s approval?','[\"Attorney or certified public accountant\",\"Enrolled agent or enrolled actuary\",\"Registered tax return preparer, attorney, certified public accountant, or enrolled agent\",\"None of the listed tax return preparers are permitted to endorse and invest the taxpayer\'s tax refund check.\"]',3,'Practitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.nnPursuant to the instructions for Form 2848 (page 2), unenrolled return preparers may only represent taxpayers before revenue agents, customer service representatives, or similar officers and employees of the Internal Revenue Service (including the Taxpayer Advocate Service) during an examination of the taxable period covered by the tax return they prepared and signed.nnUnenrolled return preparers cannot represent taxpayers, regardless of the circumstances requiring representation, before appeals officers, revenue officers, attorneys from the Office of Chief Counsel, or similar officers or employees of the Internal Revenue Service or the Department of Treasury. Unenrolled return preparers cannot execute closing agreements, extend the statutory period for tax assessments or collection of tax, execute waivers, execute claims for refund, or sign any document on behalf of a taxpayer.nnHence, a representative of the taxpayer must not endorse, or cash, a taxpayer\'s check.nnA practitioner who negotiates a taxpayer’s check is assessed a penalty pursuant to IRC § 6695(f).',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1511,8,'A taxpayer filed an appeal of an IRS examination and then signed Form 8821, Tax Information Authorization, authorizing an enrolled agent (EA) to receive the taxpayer’s confidential tax information related to the matter before the Independent Office of Appeals. Which of the following is correct regarding the EA’s ability to represent the taxpayer regarding the appeal?','[\"The EA may represent the client based on the Form 8821.\",\"The EA may represent the client with the oral consent of the client.\",\"The EA may represent the client with a note attached to Form 8821.\",\"The EA may not represent the client based on the Form 8821.\"]',3,'Form 8821 does not authorize an EA to speak on a client’s behalf, to execute a request to allow disclosure of a return or return information to another third party, or to advocate a position regarding federal tax laws, execute waivers, consents, closing agreements, or represent a taxpayer in any other manner before the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1512,8,'Which of the following may use Form 2848, Power of Attorney and Declaration of Representative, and thereby act as a representative of the taxpayer?nn1. An attorney, certified public accountant, or enrolled agentn2. A bona fide officer of the taxpayer\'s organizationn3. A member of the taxpayer\'s immediate family (i.e., spouse, parent, child, brother, or sister)n4. A full-time employee of the taxpayer','[\"Only group 1\",\"Only groups 1 and 2\",\"Only groups 1, 2, and 3\",\"Groups 1, 2, 3, and 4\"]',3,'Pursuant to Form 2848 and its instructions (Part II, pages 7–8), the following list of individuals qualifies to sign and therefore act as a representative of the taxpayer. The qualifying individuals include an attorney, certified public accountant, and enrolled agent, as well as the following:nnOfficer—a bona fide officer of the taxpayer\'s organizationnFull-Time Employee—a full-time employee of the taxpayernFamily Member—a member of the taxpayer\'s immediate family (i.e., spouse, parent, child, brother, or sister)nEnrolled ActuarynUnenrolled Return Preparer—the authority to practice before the IRS is limited (see page 2 of the Instructions for Form 2848). The unenrolled return preparer must have prepared the return in question and the return must be under examination by the IRS.nStudent Attorney, Student CPA, and Enrolled Retirement AgentnHence, the individuals listed in all four groups are eligible representatives.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1513,8,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a CAF number?','[\"It is a unique 9-digit number assigned to all representatives of a single taxpayer.\",\"It indicates that a person is authorized to practice before the IRS.\",\"It is the 9-digit Social Security number assigned to each representative of a single taxpayer.\",\"It does\\u00a0not\\u00a0indicate that a person is authorized to practice before the IRS.\"]',3,'As provided in the instructions for Form 2848, line 2, the CAF (Centralized Authorization File) number is a unique 9-digit identification number (not the SSN, EIN, PTIN, or enrollment card number) that the IRS assigns to representatives (not of a single taxpayer). When completing this form, the 9-digit number for each representative (not all of the representatives) is needed. Moreover, the CAF number is not an indication of authority to practice and the representative should use the assigned CAF number on all future powers of attorney.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1514,8,'A practitioner who prepares tax returns may endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect to a tax liability in which of the following circumstances?','[\"With the permission of the client\",\"Only if the money goes into a trust account for the benefit of the client\",\"Never\",\"With the written consent of the client\"]',2,'A practitioner may never endorse or negotiate any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, into an account owned or controlled by the practitioner) issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1515,8,'Who is authorized to practice before the IRS if they hold power of attorney?','[\"Any person considered an enrolled agent under Circular 230, who is not currently under suspension or disbarment from practice before the IRS who files a written declaration that he or she is currently qualified as an enrolled agent and is authorized to represent the particular party on whose behalf he or she acts.\",\"Any attorney who is not currently under suspension or disbarment from practice before the IRS who files a written declaration that he or she is currently qualified as an attorney and is authorized to represent the particular party on whose behalf he or she acts.\",\"Both statements are correct.\",\"Neither statement is correct.\"]',2,'Publication 947 (pages 3 and 4) provides that any individual who is recognized to practice (a recognized representative) can practice before the IRS. A recognized representative includes an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled agent (a person enrolled to practice before the IRS), an enrolled actuary, or the unenrolled return preparer who prepared the return and signed it as the preparer.nnHowever, the recognized representative must be designated as the taxpayer\'s power of attorney and file a written declaration with the IRS stating that he or she is authorized and qualified to represent a particular taxpayer. Form 2848 can be used for this purpose.nnPursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.3, an attorney, CPA, or enrolled agent is a recognized representative if he or she is not currently under suspension or disbarment from practice before the IRS. He or she may practice before the IRS by filing with the IRS a written declaration that he or she is currently qualified as an attorney, CPA, or an enrolled agent and is authorized to represent the party or parties on whose behalf he or she acts.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1516,8,'How many years in the future can an authorization on a Form 2848 be recorded to the Centralized Authentication File (CAF)?','[\"Current year +1\",\"Current year +2\",\"Current year +3\",\"Current year +4\"]',2,'Pursuant to the Instructions for Form 2848, page 3, a taxpayer may list the current year/period and any tax years or periods that have already ended as of the date they sign the power of attorney. The taxpayer may also list future tax years or periods. However, the IRS will not record on the CAF system future tax years or periods listed that exceed 3 years from December 31 of the year that the IRS receives the power of attorney.nnThe taxpayer must enter the description of the matter, the tax form number, and the future year(s) or period(s). If the matter relates to estate tax, enter the date of the decedent\'s death instead of the year or period. If the matter relates to an employee plan, include the plan number in the description of the matter.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1517,8,'Which of the following acts is not permitted for an enrolled agent who is authorized to act on behalf of the taxpayer that has properly filed a power of attorney?','[\"Represent the taxpayer before any office of the IRS\",\"Sign a consent form to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a tax\",\"Receive and endorse, or cash, a refund check drawn on the U.S. Treasury\",\"Sign a closing agreement\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 7, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnAn enrolled agent can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.nnThus, a representative of the taxpayer is not authorized to endorse or cash a taxpayer\'s check.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1518,8,'A taxpayer must use a power of attorney to do which of the following?','[\"Authorize an individual to prepare the taxpayer\'s return\",\"Authorize an individual to represent a taxpayer at a conference with the IRS\",\"Authorize the IRS to disclose tax information to an individual\",\"Authorize an individual to provide information to the IRS\"]',1,'Publication 947, page 7, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney (Form 2848) is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. The individual, however, must be a person eligible to practice before the IRS (Instructions for Form 2848). If the authorization is not limited (unenrolled tax preparers have limited authorization), the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnA power of attorney is not required in some situations when dealing with the IRS. The following situations are examples of not needing a power of attorney (Publication 947, page 11):nnProviding information to the IRSnAuthorizing the disclosure of tax return information through Form 8821nAllowing the IRS to discuss return information with a third-party designee via the checkbox provided on a tax return or other documentnAllowing a partnership representative (PR) to perform acts for the partnership under the centralized partnership audit regime for tax years beginning after December 31, 2017 (However, see \"caution\" below for early election.)nAllowing a tax matters partner or person (TMP) to perform acts for the partnershipnAllowing the IRS to discuss return information with a fiduciarynCaution: For partnership tax years beginning after December 31, 2017, the Bipartisan Budget Act of 2015, which repealed the TEFRA partnership audit and litigation procedures and the rules applicable to electing large partnerships and replaced them with a new centralized partnership audit regime, has eliminated the role of “tax matters partner” and replaced it with “partnership representative.” Pursuant to Treasury Regulation 301.9100-22, certain partnerships can elect to have the new regime apply to partnership returns for tax years beginning after November 2, 2015, and before January 1, 2018.nnPursuant to Circular 230, Section 10.8(b), any individual may prepare a tax return, appear as a witness for the taxpayer before the IRS, or furnish information at the request of the IRS or any of its officers or employees.nnAs a result, a taxpayer must use a power of attorney to authorize an individual to represent them at an IRS conference.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1519,8,'Phil, an enrolled agent, prepares William\'s income tax return. William gives Phil power of attorney. The IRS sends William\'s $100 refund check to Phil\'s office. William is very slow in paying his bills and owes Phil $500 for tax services. Phil should:','[\"use William\'s check as collateral for a $100 loan to tide him over until William pays him.\",\"refuse to give William the check until William pays him the $500.\",\"get William\'s written authorization to endorse the check, cash the check, and reduce the amount William owes him to $400.\",\"turn the check directly over to William.\"]',3,'Publication 947, page 6, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on behalf of the taxpayer in tax matters. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating or endorsing a check.nnAttorneys, certified public accountants, and enrolled agents may perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners (individuals subject to Circular 230) may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability.nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.nnPhil, as an enrolled agent, should simply turn the check directly over to William.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1520,8,'John prepares tax returns. John is not an enrolled agent, CPA, or attorney. In 2023, new clients, Mr. and Mrs. Black, engage John to prepare their 2022 joint income tax return. John prepares the Black\'s 2022 joint income tax return and signs it as the preparer. This is the only return John has prepared for the Blacks. In March 2024, Mr. and Mrs. Black receive a notice from the IRS with regard to their 2021 and 2022 joint income tax returns. Mr. and Mrs. Black ask John to contact the IRS to resolve the matter with regard to both of their joint income tax returns, but do not provide John with a power of attorney. Which of the following is correct?','[\"John is\\u00a0not\\u00a0permitted to represent or advocate a position before the IRS on behalf of Mr. and Mrs. Black concerning their 2021 return.\",\"John is\\u00a0not\\u00a0permitted to represent or advocate a position before the IRS on behalf of Mr. and Mrs. Black concerning their 2022 return.\",\"John is\\u00a0not\\u00a0permitted to represent or advocate a position before the IRS on behalf of Mr. and Mrs. Black concerning their 2021 or 2022 return.\",\"John is permitted to represent or advocate a position before the IRS on behalf of Mr. and Mrs. Black concerning their 2021 or 2022 return.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 3, provides a taxpayer with some basic information when the person\'s tax return is being examined. In general, and throughout the examination, the taxpayer is able to act on his or her own behalf or have someone represent them or accompany them.nnnIf the taxpayer filed a joint tax return, the taxpayer, the taxpayer\'s spouse, or both, can meet with the IRS. The taxpayer can have someone represent or accompany them. This person can be any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled agent (a person enrolled to practice before the IRS), an enrolled actuary, or the person who prepared the return and signed it as the preparer. In addition, a taxpayer can represent himself or herself at an Appeals conference, or the taxpayer can be represented by any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled actuary, or an enrolled agent (Publication 556, page 9). If the taxpayer\'s representative attends the conference without the taxpayer, then the representative can receive or inspect confidential information only if a power of attorney (Form 2848) or a tax information authorization has been filed.nnThe critical difference between the two statements is that a person who prepares the return and signs it as the preparer may represent the taxpayer only for the return that they prepared, which is the case in this problem. John prepared the 2022 return (not the 2021 return); he as an unenrolled agent and without power of attorney cannot handle the 2021 return, but he could handle the 2022 return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1521,8,'Judith wants to revoke a power of attorney that she previously executed and does not want to name a new representative. In order to do this, what is Judith\'s most appropriate action?','[\"Judith must call the Internal Revenue Service toll-free number, verify that she is Judith, and inform them she wants to revoke the current power of attorney that is on file.\",\"Judith must send a letter to her nearest Internal Revenue Service Center informing them that she wants to revoke the current power of attorney that is on file.\",\"Judith must send a copy of the previously executed power of attorney to the Internal Revenue Service with the word \\\"REVOKE\\\" written across the top of the power of attorney with the original current signature and date under the annotation.\",\"Judith must send a new power of attorney to the Internal Revenue Service office(s) where the prior power was originally filed and name herself as the representative.\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 10, provides the general rules for revoking an existing power of attorney. If a taxpayer wants to revoke a previously executed power of attorney and does not want to name a new representative, or if a representative wants to withdraw from representation, send a copy of the previously executed power of attorney to the IRS and follow the procedures below.nnThe copy of the power of attorney must have a current signature of the taxpayer if the taxpayer is revoking or a current signature of the representative if the representative is withdrawing. If the taxpayer is revoking the power of attorney, write “REVOKE” across the top of the first page with the taxpayer\'s current signature and date below this annotation on Form 2848. If the representative is withdrawing the power of attorney, write “WITHDRAW” across the top of the first page with the representative\'s current signature and date below this annotation on Form 2848.nnIf a taxpayer or a representative does not have a copy of the power of attorney he or she wants to revoke or withdraw, send a statement to the IRS. The statement of revocation or withdrawal must indicate that the authority of the power of attorney is revoked or withdrawn, must list the tax matters and periods, and must be signed and dated by the taxpayer or representative as applicable. If the taxpayer is revoking, list the name and address of each recognized representative whose authority is revoked. If the representative is withdrawing, list the name, TIN (taxpayer identification number), and address (if known) of the taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1522,8,'Clark, a professional tax return preparer, prepared and signed a client\'s 2024 federal income tax return that resulted in a $600 refund. Which of the following statements is correct with regard to an Internal Revenue Code penalty Clark may be subject to for endorsing and cashing the client\'s refund check?','[\"Clark will be subject to the penalty if Clark endorses and cashes the check.\",\"Clark may endorse and cash the check, without penalty, if Clark is enrolled to practice before the Internal Revenue Service.\",\"Clark may\\u00a0not\\u00a0endorse and cash the check, without penalty, because the check is for more than $500.\",\"Clark may endorse and cash the check, without penalty, if the amount does\\u00a0not\\u00a0exceed Clark\'s fee for preparation of the return.\"]',0,'Clark is not permitted to endorse and cash (i.e., convert) a client\'s federal income tax refund check regardless of the check\'s amount, Clark\'s status as an enrolled agent, or the preparation fee owed to Clark. IRC Section 6695(f) imposes a penalty for a tax return preparer who endorses or negotiates any check made in respect of taxes imposed by Title 26 which is issued to a taxpayer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1523,8,'Which of the following is a practitioner who holds a power of attorney not allowed to do?','[\"Represent a taxpayer before any office of the IRS\",\"Sign a closing agreement\",\"Cash a taxpayer\'s federal income tax refund check\",\"Sign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of tax\"]',2,'Publication 947, page 6, provides general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnCircular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.nnThus, a representative of the taxpayer cannot cash a taxpayer\'s federal income tax refund check.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1524,8,'Which of the following would not allow the Internal Revenue Service to disclose the results of an examination of your 2023 Form 1040 to the return preparer of the 2024 return?','[\"You submit a power of attorney, Form 2848, with the Internal Revenue Service authorizing representation by your return preparer for income tax matters for tax years 2021, 2022, and 2023.\",\"You submit a tax information authorization, Form 8821, with the Internal Revenue Service for your return preparer for income tax matters for the tax year 2023.\",\"You checked the \\u201cYes\\u201d box in the third-party designee area of the 2023 tax return and entered \\u201cPreparer\\u201d after the return preparer\'s name in the designee space.\",\"Your return preparer is also your legal guardian and submits a Form 56,\\u00a0Notice Concerning Fiduciary Relationship.\"]',2,'If you checked the box in the signature area of your income tax return (Form 1040 or Form 1040-SR) to allow the IRS to discuss your return with another person (a third-party designee), this authorization does not replace Form 2848. The box you checked on your return only authorizes the other person to receive information about the processing of your return and the status of your refund during the period your return is being processed.nnAs a result, checking the “Yes” box in the third-party designee area of the 2023 tax return and entering “Preparer” after the return preparer\'s name in the designee space would not allow the Internal Revenue Service to disclose the results of an examination of your 2023 Form 1040 to the return preparer of the 2024 return.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1525,8,'A power of attorney is required when a taxpayer:','[\"wants to represent himself or herself at a conference with the IRS.\",\"wants another to represent himself or herself at a conference with the IRS.\",\"wants to submit a written response on behalf of himself or herself to the IRS.\",\"wants to authorize another person to represent himself or herself at a conference with the IRS, or prepare and file a written response to the IRS.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 9, provides that a taxpayer can represent himself or herself at an Appeals conference. Similarly, the taxpayer can be represented by any federally authorized practitioner, including an attorney, a certified public accountant, an enrolled actuary, or an enrolled agent.nnIf, however, the taxpayer\'s representative attends a conference without the taxpayer, he or she can receive or inspect confidential information only if the taxpayer has filed a power of attorney or a tax information authorization, which is done using Form 2848, or any other properly written power of attorney or authorization.nnPublication 947, pages 7 and 8, provides the general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney (Form 2848) is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on behalf of the taxpayer in tax matters. The individual, however, must be a person eligible to practice before the IRS (Instructions for Form 2848), which means the representative is subject to Circular 230. The authority granted to an unenrolled preparer is limited.nnThus, the best response is that a power of attorney is required when a taxpayer wants to authorize another person to represent himself or herself at a conference with the IRS or prepare and file a written response to the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1526,8,'Which of the following is correct regarding a refund check?','[\"Form 2848,\\u00a0Power of Attorney and Declaration of Representative,\\u00a0may be used to authorize cashing of a refund check.\",\"Form 2848,\\u00a0Power of Attorney and Declaration of Representative,\\u00a0may not be used to negotiate a refund check.\",\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0must be signed before a refund check may be applied to a fee for electronic filing.\",\"Both Form 2848 and Form 8821 must be used to authorize cashing a refund check.\"]',1,'Publication 947, page 7, provides general information about the power of attorney. In particular, a power of attorney is a taxpayer\'s written authorization for an individual to receive a taxpayer’s confidential tax information from the IRS and to perform certain actions on their behalf. If the authorization is not limited, the individual can generally perform all acts that the taxpayer can perform, except negotiating a check.nnAn authorized representative of the taxpayer can usually perform the following acts under a power of attorney:nnRepresent the taxpayer before any office of the IRSnSign an offer or a waiver of restriction on assessment or collection of a tax deficiency, or a waiver of notice of disallowance of claim for credit or refundnSign a consent to extend the statutory time period for assessment or collection of a taxnSign a closing agreementnPractitioners subject to Circular 230 may not endorse or otherwise negotiate (cash) any check (including directing or accepting payment by any means, electronic or otherwise, in an account owned or controlled by the practitioner or any firm or other entity with whom the practitioner is associated) issued to the taxpayer by the government in respect of a Federal tax liability. (Publication 947, page 6)nnLikewise, Circular 230, Section 10.31, provides that a practitioner who prepares tax returns may not endorse or otherwise negotiate any check issued to a client by the government in respect of a federal tax liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1527,8,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0is used to allow a taxpayer\'s appointee to advocate their position.\",\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0is used to allow the inspection and\\/or receipt of confidential information to third parties.\",\"Form 8821,\\u00a0Tax Information Authorization,\\u00a0is used to authorize individuals to execute waivers, consents, or closing agreements.\",\"Form 2848,\\u00a0Power of Attorney,\\u00a0is used to allow limited disclosure of tax return information to an unenrolled return preparer.\"]',1,'As provided in the Instructions for Form 8821, Tax Information Authorization (Form 8821) authorizes any individual, corporation, firm, organization, or partnership designated by the taxpayer to inspect and/or receive his or her confidential information, verbally or in writing, in any office of the IRS for the type of tax and the years or periods listed on the form.nnForm 8821 is strictly a disclosure authorization form and cannot be used to designate an individual to represent (or advocate on behalf of) the taxpayer. If the taxpayer wants to name a representative, the taxpayer should use Form 2848.nnForm 2848 authorizes a third-party to represent the taxpayer before the IRS. With the exception of unenrolled preparers whose representation rights are limited, federally authorized third-parties are granted authority under Form 2848 to inspect and/or receive confidential information and perform all acts (sign agreements, consents, waivers, etc.) that the taxpayer himself/herself would be able to perform with nnThus, Form 8821, Tax Information Authorization, is used to allow limited disclosure of tax return information to a third party.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1528,8,'Which of the following procedures must be followed to add a representative to an existing power of attorney?nn1. Submit an updated Form 2848 to the IRS office(s) where the related return or the original power of attorney was filed.n2. Telephone the IRS Service Center where the related return or the original power of attorney was filed.','[\"Only item 1 is satisfactory.\",\"Only item 2 is satisfactory.\",\"Item 1 or 2 is satisfactory.\",\"Neither item 1 nor item 2 is satisfactory.\"]',0,'Publication 947, page 10, provides the general rules for updating a power of attorney. A taxpayer must submit any update or modification to an existing power of attorney in writing. The taxpayer\'s signature (or the signature of the individual(s) authorized to sign on the taxpayer\'s behalf) is required.nnThe updating is done by sending the updated Form 2848 or non-IRS power of attorney to the IRS office(s) where the taxpayer previously sent the original(s), including the center where the related return was or will be filed. Any recognized representative may substitute or delegate authority if the substitution or delegation is specifically authorized in the original power of attorney. To make a substitution or delegation, the representative must file the following items with the IRS office(s) where the power of attorney was filed:nnA written notice of substitution or delegation signed by the recognized representative,nA written declaration of representative made by the new representative, andnA copy of the power of attorney that specifically authorizes the substitution or delegationnA telephone call will not satisfy the above rules for updating a power of attorney.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1529,11,'The Notice of Deficiency is also known as:','[\"a 30-day letter because the taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the letter to file a petition with the Tax Court.\\n\",\"a 90-day letter because the taxpayer generally has 90 days from the date of the letter to file a petition with the Tax Court.\\n\",\"an Information Document Request (IDR) because the taxpayer is asked for information to support his or her position regarding his or her liability for tax.\",\"a notice and demand because the taxpayer is put on notice that the tax liability is due and owing.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 5, provides that a taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the 30-day letter to tell the IRS whether he or she will accept or appeal the proposed changes.nnIf the taxpayer does not respond to the 30-day letter, or if the taxpayer later does not reach an agreement with an Appeals Officer, the IRS will send a 90-day letter, which is also known as a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer will have 90 days (150 days if it is addressed to a person outside the United States) from the date of this notice to file a petition with the Tax Court.nnnn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThe Statutory Notice of Deficiency is also referred to as the Notice of Deficiency and as the 90-day letter because this is the time that the taxpayer has to file a petition with the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1530,11,'Which of the following conditions is the best response to when the Internal Revenue Service may abate (reduce) the amount of interest you owe?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have the authority to abate the interest owed by a taxpayer.\",\"The interest is due to an unreasonable error by an Internal Revenue Service officer in performing a ministerial or managerial act.\",\"The interest is due to an unreasonable delay by an Internal Revenue Service employee in performing a ministerial or managerial act.\",\"The interest is due to an unreasonable error or delay by an Internal Revenue Service officer or employee in performing a ministerial or managerial act.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 7, provides that the IRS may abate (reduce) the amount of interest owed by the taxpayer if the interest is due to an unreasonable error or delay by an IRS officer or employee in performing a ministerial or managerial act. Only the amount of interest on income, estate, gift, generation-skipping, and certain excise taxes can be reduced.nnA ministerial act is a procedure or mechanical act, not involving the exercise of judgment or discretion, during the processing of a case after all prerequisites have taken place. A decision concerning the proper application of federal tax law (or other federal or state law) is not a ministerial act.nA managerial act is an administrative act during the processing of a case that involves the loss of records or the exercise of judgment or discretion concerning the management of personnel. A decision concerning the proper application of federal tax law (or other federal or state law) is not a managerial act.nThe amount of interest will not be reduced if the taxpayer or anyone related to the taxpayer contributed significantly to the error or delay. Also, the interest will be reduced only if the error or delay happened after the IRS contacted the taxpayer in writing about the deficiency or payment on which the interest is based. An audit notification letter is such a contact.nnThe IRS cannot reduce the amount of interest due to a general administrative decision, such as a decision on how to organize the processing of tax returns.nnHence, the IRS may abate the amount of interest a taxpayer owes when the interest is due to an unreasonable error or delay by either an IRS officer or employee in performing a ministerial or managerial act.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1531,11,'Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"A warrant is a legal claim against a taxpayer\'s property used as a security for the tax debt.\",\"A lien is a legal seizure of a taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt.\",\"A lien is a legal claim against a taxpayer\'s property used as a security for the tax debt.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'A lien is a legal claim to a taxpayer\'s current and future property, such as a house or car, and rights to property, such as wages and bank accounts. The lien comes into existence if a taxpayer fails to pay the tax amount due after receiving the first bill.nnA legal seizure of a taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt is a levy. Levies are different from liens; a lien is a claim used as security for the tax debt, while a levy takes the property to satisfy the tax debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1532,11,'What does a Notice of Federal Tax Lien mean to a taxpayer\'s creditors?','[\"The IRS has a claim against all of the taxpayer\'s currently owned property.\",\"The IRS has a claim against all of the taxpayer\'s owned property, including property acquired by the taxpayer after the lien was filed.\",\"The IRS is in the process of seizing all of the taxpayer\'s currently owned property.\",\"The IRS is in the process of seizing all of the taxpayer\'s currently owned property and will seize any property acquired by the taxpayer until the tax liability is paid in full.\"]',1,'Publication 594, page 5, provides that the IRS files a Notice of Federal Tax Lien in the public records to establish the priority of their claim versus the claims of other creditors. The Notice of Federal Tax Lien is filed with local or state authorities, such as county recorder of deeds of the Secretary of State offices.nnIf a Notice of Federal Tax Lien is filed against the taxpayer, it may be reported by consumer credit reporting agencies. This can have a negative effect on the taxpayer’s credit rating and make it difficult for them to receive credit (such as a loan or credit card). Employers, landlords, and others may also use this information and not favorably view the fact that a Notice of Federal Tax Lien has been filed against the taxpayer.nnThe lien attaches to all of the taxpayer\'s current and future property (such as a house or car) and to all of the taxpayer\'s rights to property (such as the accounts receivable of the taxpayer\'s business). The lien automatically comes into existence if the taxpayer does not pay their amount due after receiving their first bill.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1533,11,'Julie, who lives in Washington, D.C., operated a business without books and records. Her business income and expenses were reported on Schedule C. Julie\'s tax return for 2021 was examined and substantial adjustments were proposed. Julie disagreed with the adjustments and wants to take her case directly to Tax Court. A Statutory Notice of Deficiency was issued to Julie by the IRS Area Director. Julie can file a petition for a small tax case before the U.S. Tax Court during which of the following periods beginning from the date of the issuance of the notice?','[\"30 days\",\"90 days\",\"150 days\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'The Statutory Notice of Deficiency is referred to as the Notice of Deficiency, and it is also known as the 90-day letter because this is the time that the taxpayer has to file a petition with the Tax Court.nnPublication 556, page 5, provides that a taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the 30-day letter to tell the IRS whether he or she will accept or appeal the proposed changes.nnIf the taxpayer does not respond to the 30-day letter, or if the taxpayer later does not reach an agreement with an Appeals Officer, the IRS will send a 90-day letter, which is also known as a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer will have 90 days (150 days if it is addressed to a person outside the United States) from the date of this notice to file a petition with the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1534,11,'What action may a taxpayer take when the taxpayer and the IRS do not reach agreement on proposed audit changes?','[\"The taxpayer may request the case be handled under the small tax case procedures if the tax liability is less than $100,000.\",\"The taxpayer may take the case directly to the Tax Court.\",\"The taxpayer must seek settlement by an Appeals Office before going to the Tax Court.\",\"The IRS decision is final and\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0be appealed.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 8, states, in part, that if a taxpayer does not agree with any or all of the IRS findings, the taxpayer may request a meeting or a telephone conference with the supervisor of the person who issued the findings. If the taxpayer still disagrees, the taxpayer may (must not) appeal the case to the Appeals Office of the IRS.nnIf the taxpayer decides to do nothing and the case involves an examination of the taxpayer\'s income, estate, gift, and certain excise taxes or penalties, the taxpayer will receive a formal Notice of Deficiency. The Notice of Deficiency allows the taxpayer to go to the Tax Court and tells the taxpayer the procedure to follow.nnIf the taxpayer does not go to the Tax Court, the IRS will send the taxpayer a bill for the amount due.nnIf the taxpayer and Appeals do not agree on some or all of the issues after the Appeals conference, or if the taxpayer skipped the Appeals system, the taxpayer may take the case to the U.S. Tax Court (money owed), the U.S. Court of Federal Claims (sue for a refund), or the taxpayer\'s U.S. District Court (sue for refund) after satisfying certain procedural and jurisdictional requirements (Publication 556, page 12).nnIn addition, if the amount in a taxpayer\'s case is $50,000 or less for any 1 tax year or period, the Tax Court has a simple alternative to solve the taxpayer\'s case (Publication 556, page 12). At the taxpayer\'s request and if the Tax Court approves, the taxpayer\'s case can be handled under the small tax case procedure. In this procedure, the taxpayer can present his or her case to the Tax Court for a decision that is final and that cannot be appealed by either party.nnSince the taxpayer is not required but is strongly encouraged, the correct response here is the taxpayer may take the case directly to the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1535,11,'If your tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to your tax liaility:','[\"you may ignore the examination notice.\",\"you should call the Taxpayer Advocate Office and file a complaint.\",\"you should call the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.\",\"you should write a letter to the Service Center and complain that the Revenue Agents are harassing you.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight to the issue of repeat examinations. If a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer should contact the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1536,11,'Kevin Blue had his 2021 tax return examined by the Internal Revenue Service. He did not agree with the results and was informed by the examiner that he could appeal the findings to the Appeals Office. Kevin decided he would rather have his case heard in Tax Court and bypass the Appeals Office. Which of the following is correct?','[\"Kevin must go to the Appeals Office of the IRS before he can file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court.\",\"Kevin must file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court immediately after he advises the examiner that he wants to go to Tax Court and before he receives the Statutory Notice of Deficiency (90-day) letter.\",\"Kevin should wait to receive the Statutory Notice of Deficiency (90-day) letter before he petitions the U.S. Tax Court.\",\"Kevin must pay the tax before he can file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 9, discusses the issue presented in this problem. Specifically, if the taxpayer and Appeals do not agree on some or all of the issues after the taxpayer\'s Appeals conference, or if the taxpayer skipped the IRS\'s Appeals system, the taxpayer may take his or her case to the U.S. Tax Court, the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, or the taxpayer\'s U.S. District Court, after satisfying certain procedural and jurisdictional requirements. These courts are independent judicial bodies and have no connection with the IRS.nnIf a taxpayer\'s disagreement with the IRS is over whether he or she owes additional income tax, estate tax, gift tax, certain excise taxes, or penalties related to these proposed liabilities, the taxpayer can go to the U.S. Tax Court. (Other types of tax controversies, such as those involving some employment tax issues or manufacturers\' excise taxes, cannot be heard by the Tax Court.)nnThe taxpayer can do this after the IRS issues a formal letter stating the amounts that the IRS believes the taxpayer owes. This letter is called a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer has 90 days from the date this notice is mailed to the taxpayer to file a petition with the Tax Court (or 150 days if the notice is addressed to the taxpayer outside the United States). The last date to file the petition will be entered on the Notice of Deficiency issued to the taxpayer by the IRS.nnGiven the above information, Kevin should wait to receive the Statutory Notice of Deficiency (90-day) letter before he petitions the U.S. Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1537,11,'Which of the following would be a reason for the IRS to grant a taxpayer\'s request to transfer an examination to an area other than the area in which the taxpayer lives?','[\"The examination can occur more quickly and conveniently in another district.\",\"The taxpayer feels that another district would be more favorable to his situation.\",\"There are\\u00a0no\\u00a0reasons that permit the transferring of a case to another district.\",\"The Tax Court orders the IRS to transfer the case to another district.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 4, provides a reason for transferring a case to another district. Generally, a taxpayer\'s return is examined in the IRS district where the taxpayer lives. But if his or her return can be examined more quickly and conveniently in another district, such as where the taxpayer\'s books and records are located, then the taxpayer can ask to have the case transferred to that district.nnHence, the best response in this question is that the examination can occur more quickly and conveniently in another district.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1538,11,'The Installment Agreement is one of the acceptable methods of paying off a tax debt to the U.S. Treasury. Financial information on a “Collection Information Statement” may be required as a condition of the Installment Agreement. Generally, an Installment Agreement cannot be turned down without this statement if the dollar amount is:','[\"$20,000 or less if it is a joint return.\",\"$25,000 or more.\",\"at least $15,000 for the current year, but less than $20,000 for all years.\",\"$10,000 or less.\"]',3,'Publication 594, page 3, provides that if a taxpayer cannot pay all the taxes owed at the current time, the taxpayer can contact the IRS to explain their situation and request more time to pay their debt. Prior to approving a taxpayer’s request to delay collection until they are able to pay, the IRS may request the taxpayer to fill out Collection Information Statements (Form 433-F, Form 433-A, and Form 433-B) to help them compare the taxpayer\'s monthly income with expenses to determine the amount that a taxpayer can pay.nnAnother method of paying off a tax debt to the U.S. Treasury is the Installment Agreement (Publication 594, page 2). Form 9465 is used to request a monthly installment plan if you are an individual who owes income tax. However, the instructions for Form 9465 provide that the request for an Installment Agreement cannot be turned down if the amount owed is not more than $10,000 in tax and the following criteria are satisfied:nnThe taxpayer, and spouse, if applicable, have timely filed all income tax returns and paid any income tax due during the past 5 tax years and have not entered into an Installment Agreement for payment of income taxes.nThe taxpayer agrees to pay the full amount owed within 3 years and to comply with the tax laws while the agreement is in effect.nThe IRS determines that the taxpayer is financially unable to pay the liability owed in full when it is due.nIn this case and if the taxpayer meets the other criteria as given above, the IRS cannot turn down the installment plan request if the amount owed is $10,000 or less.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1539,11,'Which fee arrangement described below is permissible for an Electronic Return Originator (ERO)?','[\"Fees based on AGI from the tax return\",\"Fees based on percentage of refund\",\"Fees based on taxable income from the tax return\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Circular 230, Section 10.27, provides that a practitioner (which would include an Authorized IRS e-file Provider) may not base their fees on a percentage of the refund amount or compute their fees using any figure from tax returns. In addition, separate fees may not be charged for direct deposits.nnTherefore, none of the responses are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1540,11,'Which of the following can a representative that is qualified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service do on behalf of a client?','[\"Prepare a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference\",\"Sign a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference\",\"Prepare and sign a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference\",\"Review the client\'s prepared written protest to request an Appeals conference\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 8, provides that when a taxpayer requests an Appeals conference, the taxpayer may also need to file a formal written protest or a small case request with the office named in the Service\'s letter to the taxpayer.nnWhen a protest is required, it must be sent within the time limit specified in the letter and it must include the items required in the protest. One of the required items is the taxpayer must sign the written protest, stating that it is true, under the penalties of perjury. Likewise, if the taxpayer\'s representative prepares and signs the protest for the taxpayer, he or she must substitute a declaration stating:nnthat he or she submitted the protest and accompanying documents andnwhether he or she knows personally that the facts stated in the protest and accompanying documents are true and correct.nFinally, the taxpayer\'s representative must be qualified to practice before the IRS.nnTherefore, a representative qualified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service can prepare or sign a formal written protest on behalf of a client to request an Appeals conference.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1541,11,'For court proceedings resulting from examinations started after July 1998:','[\"the IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue.\",\"taxpayers are no longer required to maintain records to substantiate items claimed on tax returns.\",\"the IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue if the taxpayer has introduced credible evidence relating to the issue.\",\"the taxpayer has the burden of proof for any factual issue.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 9, provides information on burden of proof. For court proceedings resulting from examinations started after July 22, 1998, the IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue if the taxpayer has introduced credible evidence relating to the issue. The taxpayer, however, also must have:nncomplied with all substantiation requirements of the Internal Revenue Code,nmaintained all records required by the Internal Revenue Code,ncooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the taxpayer\'s tax return, andnhad a net worth of $7 million or less and not more than 500 employees at the time the taxpayer\'s tax liability is contested in any court proceeding if the taxpayer\'s tax return is for a corporation, partnership, or trust.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1542,11,'Lorie owed the IRS $150,000. Lorie owned a money market account with a major stock brokerage firm that had a value of $200,000. Which of the following statements is correct concerning the IRS?','[\"The IRS can force the brokerage firm to pay $150,000 from the account by levying the account.\",\"The IRS can force the brokerage firm to pay $150,000 from the account by serving a notice of lien on it.\",\"The maximum amount that the IRS can levy is one-half of Lorie\'s money market account.\",\"The IRS\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0take any action against Lorie\'s assets.\"]',0,'Publication 594, pages 5 and 6, states a levy (not a lien) is a legal seizure of the taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt. Moreover, the IRS is able to levy the total tax liability from a person\'s assets; it is not limited to one-half. Hence, the IRS can force the brokerage firm to pay $150,000 from the account by levying the account.nnIn addition, you should realize that liens are different from levies. A lien is a claim used as security for the tax debt, while a levy actually takes the property to satisfy the tax debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1543,11,'The Tax Court has generally held that taxpayers who rely on software to justify errors on self-prepared returns are:','[\"not liable for the IRC Section 6662 accuracy-related penalty.\",\"liable for the IRC Section 6662 accuracy-related penalty.\",\"liable for 20% of the IRC Section 6662 accuracy-related penalty.\",\"liable for 40% of the IRC Section 6662 accuracy-related penalty.\"]',1,'Reg. 1.6664-4 provides that no penalty may be imposed under section 6662 with respect to any portion of an underpayment upon a showing by the taxpayer that there was reasonable cause for, and the taxpayer acted in good faith with respect to, such portion.nnCircumstances that may indicate reasonable cause and good faith include an honest misunderstanding of fact or law that is reasonable in light of all the facts and circumstances, including the experience, knowledge and education of the taxpayer. An isolated computational or transcriptional error generally is not inconsistent with reasonable cause and good faith.nnHowever, reliance on an information return or on the advice of a professional tax advisor or an appraiser does not necessarily demonstrate reasonable cause and good faith. Similarly, reasonable cause and good faith is not necessarily indicated by reliance on facts that, unknown to the taxpayer, are incorrect.nnReliance on an information return, professional advice or other facts, however, constitutes reasonable cause and good faith if, under all the circumstances, such reliance was reasonable, and the taxpayer acted in good faith.nnThis is a tricky question in that it relies on the ruling in TC Memo 2011-69 (03/24/2011), which held that the misuse of tax preparation software, even if unintentional or accidental, is no defense to penalties under section 6662. Thus, the real issue is whether the software made the error, or the taxpayer entered incorrect information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1544,11,'Which of the following is correct concerning a taxpayer\'s request to have the tax return examination moved to another IRS area?','[\"A taxpayer\'s return is examined only in the IRS district where the taxpayer lives.\",\"A taxpayer\'s return may be moved if the taxpayer\'s books and records are located in the other area.\",\"A taxpayer\'s return may be moved if the taxpayer does not want anyone to know that he is being examined.\",\"A taxpayer\'s return may be moved by simply filing Form TRAN within 10 days of the notice.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 4, provides a reason for transferring a case to another district. Generally, a taxpayer\'s return is examined in the IRS district where the taxpayer lives. But if his or her return can be examined more quickly and conveniently in another district, such as where the taxpayer\'s books and records are located, then the taxpayer can ask to have the case transferred to that area.nnHence, the taxpayer\'s return may be moved if the taxpayer\'s books and records are located in the other area.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1545,11,'Which of the following best describes a levy when it relates to a tax debt?','[\"A levy is\\u00a0not\\u00a0a legal seizure of property.\",\"A levy on salary or wages will not be applied if the period for collection has ended.\",\"A levy can only be released by the filing of a lien.\",\"A levy can be applied to wearing apparel and schoolbooks.\"]',1,'Publication 594, page 5, states a lien is a legal claim to all of a taxpayer\'s current and future property as security for the tax debt.nnAs an aside, a levy is different from a lien. A levy is a legal seizure of the taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt. nnPublication 594, page 6, provides general information concerning the levying of a taxpayer\'s wages, salary, commissions, or other payments for personal services; federal payments, such as federal retirement or federal vendor payments; or a taxpayer\'s bank account. In general, if the IRS serves a levy on the above-mentioned items, the IRS must release a levy with respect to salary or wages if:nnthe taxpayer pays his or her tax debt in full,nother arrangements are made, ornthe collection period ends.nIn this case, the best description of a levy is one on salary or wages, and it ends when the time expires for legally collecting the tax.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThere are other situations where the IRS must release a levy that are discussed on pages 6 and 7 of Publication 594.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1546,11,'Which of the following may the Internal Revenue Service settle by accepting an Offer in Compromise for less than the full amount of the balance due?','[\"A tax deficiency, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0penalties and accrued interest\",\"A tax deficiency plus penalties, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0accrued interest\",\"A tax deficiency plus accrued interest, but\\u00a0not\\u00a0penalties\",\"A tax deficiency plus penalties and accrued interest\"]',3,'According to Publication 594, the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) may accept an Offer in Compromise (OIC) to settle unpaid tax accounts for less than the full amount of the balance due. IRC Section 601.2013(a)(2) provides: “An offer in compromise of taxes, interest, delinquency penalties, or specific penalties may be based on either inability to pay or doubt as to liability. Offers in compromise arise usually when payments of assessed liabilities are demanded, penalties for delinquency in filing returns are asserted, or specific civil or criminal penalties are incurred by taxpayers. Based on this, we infer that the offer in compromise applies to all taxes, including any interest, penalties, or additional amounts arising under the Internal Revenue laws.”nnThe IRS may accept an Offer in Compromise if:nnThey agree that the taxpayer\'s tax debt may not be accurate,nThe taxpayer has insufficient assets and income to pay the amount due, ornBecause of the taxpayer\'s exceptional circumstances, paying the amount due would cause an economic hardship or would be unjust.nThe OIC program is an option for those taxpayers who are unable to pay their tax account in a lump sum or through an Installment Agreement and have exhausted their search for other payment arrangements. The IRS may legally compromise a tax liability for one of three reasons that are given on page 3 of Publication 594 and as provided in the Form 656-B Booklet.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1547,11,'Caroline received an audit notification letter scheduling an appointment for July 1, 2023, for the examination of her tax year 2021 Form 1040 return. The week before the scheduled appointment, she received a telephone call from the Internal Revenue Service office canceling the appointment. She was told that she would be contacted at a later date to reschedule the appointment. She was not contacted until July 1, 2024, when she was advised of a new appointment date. Errors identified in the examination resulted in her owing additional tax of $4,000 plus accrued interest of $600. Caroline does not believe that she should have to pay interest for the period that she was waiting for her appointment to be rescheduled. How should she proceed?','[\"Pay the tax and interest and deduct the interest on her 2024 return, the year paid.\",\"Immediately request an Appeals conference to contest the interest.\",\"Request an abatement of the interest by filing a Form 843 with the Internal Revenue Service Center where she filed her 2021 return.\",\"Immediately petition the Tax Court to contest the interest.\"]',2,'The IRS may abate (reduce) the amount of interest the taxpayer owes if the interest is due to an unreasonable error or delay by an IRS officer or employee in performing a ministerial or managerial act. Only the interest on income, estate, gift, generation-skipping, and certain excise taxes can be reduced.nnA ministerial act is a procedure or mechanical act, not involving the exercise of judgment or discretion, during the processing of a case after all prerequisites have taken place. A decision concerning the proper application of federal tax law (or other federal or state law) is not a ministerial act.nA managerial act is an administrative act during the processing of a case that involves the loss of records or the exercise of judgment or discretion concerning the management of personnel. A decision concerning the proper application of federal tax law (or other federal or state law) is not a managerial act.nA taxpayer makes a request for abatement (reduction) of interest on Form 843. The taxpayer generally files the form with the IRS Service Center that initially received the tax return with the error or delay.nnIf the taxpayer paid the interest, he or she must file Form 843 within 3 years from the date that he or she filed the original return or 2 years from the date that he or she paid the interest. If the interest has not been paid, the time limitations for filing Form 843 do not apply.nnIf the taxpayer\'s request for abatement of interest is denied, the taxpayer can appeal the decision to the IRS Appeals Office.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1548,11,'What action can a taxpayer take who has been audited for the same items in either of 2 preceding years, had no change proposed on his or her tax liability, and receives notice that his or her return has been selected for examination?','[\"He can disregard the notice under the repeat examination rule.\",\"He must submit to the examination.\",\"He may contact the Internal Revenue Service and request that the examination be discontinued under the repeat examination rule.\",\"He must submit to the examination because the repeat examination rule pertains to the 3 preceding years.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight into the issue of repeat examinations. In particular, the IRS tries to avoid repeat examinations of the same items, but sometimes this happens. If a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer should contact the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1549,11,'The Internal Revenue Service may accept an Offer in Compromise to settle unpaid tax accounts for less than the full amount due. A Collection Information Statement (financial statement) is not required with the offer when the reason for the offer is:','[\"doubt as to liability.\",\"doubt as to collectability.\",\"to promote effective tax administration.\",\"economic hardship.\"]',0,'Form 656-B (Booklet), Offer in Compromise, page 1, provides the general rules for making an Offer in Compromise (OIC). An Offer in Compromise (offer) is an agreement between the taxpayer and the IRS that settles a tax debt for less than the full amount owed. The offer program provides eligible taxpayers with a path toward paying off their tax debt and getting a \"fresh start.\" The ultimate goal is a compromise that suits the best interest of both the taxpayer and the IRS. To be considered, generally the taxpayer must make an appropriate offer based on what the IRS considers the taxpayer\'s true ability to pay.nnSubmitting an application does not ensure that the IRS will accept the taxpayer\'s offer. It begins a process of evaluation and verification by the IRS, taking into consideration any special circumstances that might affect the taxpayer\'s ability to pay.nnThe IRS may legally compromise a tax liability for one of the following reasons: doubt as to liability, doubt as to collectability, or to promote effective tax administration (Tax Topic 204).nnA taxpayer may submit an Offer in Compromise by completing Form 656, which is included in the Form 656 Booklet (Form 656-B). If, however, the taxpayer is basing his or her offer on doubt as to collectability or promotion of effective tax administration, the taxpayer must also submit Form 433-A, Collection Information Statement for Wage Earners and Self-Employed Individuals. The reason for filing Form 656 is given in Section 3 of the form as a checkbox for either doubt as to collectability or effective tax administration.nnPublication 594, page 3, refers to these three reasons as:nn\"We agree that your tax debt may not be accurate\",n\"You have insufficient assets and income to pay the amount due\", orn\"Because of your exceptional circumstances, paying the amount due would cause an economic hardship or would be unjust.\"nIf a taxpayer has a legitimate doubt that they owe part or all of the tax debt, they will need to complete a Form 656-L, Offer in Compromise (Doubt as to Liability). If the taxpayer does not dispute the amount of the tax debt, they should not file a Form 656-L.nnThe Form 656-B Booklet, page 3, explains there are two types of OIC payment terms that the IRS and the taxpayer may agree to:nnLump-sum cash requires 20% of the total offer amount to be paid with the offer and the remaining balance paid within five or fewer installments within 5 or fewer months from the date of notice of acceptance.nPeriodic payment requires the first payment with the offer and the remaining balance paid within 6 to 24 months, in accordance with the taxpayer\'s proposed offer terms.nIn this case, the Collection Information Statement is not necessary if the taxpayer is filing an offer on the grounds there is a doubt as to the liability.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1550,11,'In some cases, a spouse will be relieved of the tax, interest, and penalties on a joint return. Which of the following types of relief is not relief from a joint tax return?','[\"Innocent spouse relief\",\"Separation of liability relief\",\"Equitable relief\",\"Injured spouse relief\"]',3,'Publication 971, pages 1 and 2, states, in part, that many married taxpayers choose to file a joint tax return because of certain benefits this filing status allows. Both taxpayers are jointly and individually responsible for the tax and any interest or penalty due on the joint return even if they later divorce. This is true even if a divorce decree states that a former spouse will be responsible for any amounts due on previously filed joint returns.nnOne spouse may be held responsible for all the tax due even if all the income was earned by the other spouse. In some cases, a spouse (or former spouse) will be relieved of the tax, interest, and penalties on a joint tax return. Three types of relief are available: innocent spouse relief, relief by separation of liability, and equitable relief.nnA taxpayer may also seek relief under the injured spouse rules if the taxpayer\'s share of the overpayment shown on the taxpayer\'s joint return was, or is expected to be, applied against the taxpayer\'s spouse\'s past-due federal debts, state taxes, state unemployment compensation debts, child or spousal support payments, or a federal nontax debt, such as a student loan. If the taxpayer is an injured spouse, they may be entitled to receive a refund of their share of the overpayment.nnIn this problem, injured spouse relief is not a type of relief from a joint tax return, because it deals with an overpayment, not relief from taxes owed, penalty, and interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1551,11,'Which of the following conditions is the best response to when the Internal Revenue Service may provide relief from the amount of penalty a taxpayer may owe?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have the authority to provide relief from the penalty owed by a taxpayer.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service does have the authority to provide relief from the penalty owed by a taxpayer, even when the law does not allow it.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have the authority to provide relief from the penalty owed by a taxpayer when allowed by law if the taxpayer can show that they acted reasonably and in good faith.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service does have the authority to provide relief from the penalty owed by a taxpayer when allowed by law if the taxpayer relied on the incorrect advice of an IRS employee.\"]',3,'IRC Section 6404(f) provides that the Internal Revenue Service may grant relief from certain penalties resulting from erroneous advice furnished to the taxpayer in writing by an officer or employee of the IRS, acting in such officer’s or employee’s official capacity.nnHence, the best answer for this question is that the Internal Revenue Service does have the authority to provide relief from certain penalties owed by a taxpayer when allowed by law if the taxpayer relied on the incorrect advice of an IRS employee. The key issue here is the advice needs to be in written form for IRC Section 6404(f) to be applicable.nnThe taxpayer can also request penalty abatement provided the taxpayer can show reasonable cause and that they acted in good faith.nnThe IRS may provide administrative relief from a penalty that would otherwise be applicable under its First Time Penalty Abatement policy.nnYou may qualify for administrative relief from penalties for failing to file a tax return, pay on time, and/or to deposit taxes when due under the Service\'s First Time Penalty Abatement policy if the following are true:nnYou didn’t previously have to file a return or you have no penalties for the 3 tax years prior to the tax year in which you received a penalty.nYou filed all currently required returns or filed an extension of time to file.nYou have paid, or arranged to pay, any tax due.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1552,11,'What remedies does a taxpayer have if the IRS prematurely seizes property?','[\"They may file a claim with the IRS to recover economic damages.\",\"They may sue for damages against the federal government.\",\"They may sue for damages against the IRS employees.\",\"They have no recourse.\"]',0,'If the IRS intentionally or negligently does not follow Internal Revenue law while collecting a taxpayer’s taxes, or the IRS wrongfully seized the property of the wrong taxpayer, a taxpayer may be entitled to recover economic damages. Some limitations may apply.nnThe taxpayer must file an administrative claim with the Advisory Group Manager for the taxpayer’s area. The taxpayer must mail their written claim to the attention of the Advisory Group Manager at the address listed in Publication 4235, Collection Advisory Group Numbers and Addresses.nnIf the claim is denied, the taxpayer may sue the federal government, but not IRS employees, for economic damages.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1553,11,'How long does a taxpayer have from the date of the Statutory Notice of Deficiency to file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court if he or she resides outside the United States?','[\"30 days\",\"90 days\",\"150 days\",\"180 days\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 5, provides that a taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the 30-day letter to tell the IRS whether he or she will accept or appeal the proposed changes.nnIf the taxpayer does not respond to the 30-day letter, or if the taxpayer later does not reach an agreement with an Appeals Officer, the IRS will send a 90-day letter, which also is known as a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer will have 90 days (150 days if the taxpayer\'s address is outside the United States) from the date of this notice to file a petition with the Tax Court.nnThe Statutory Notice of Deficiency is referred to as the Notice of Deficiency, and it is also known as the 90-day letter because this is the time that the taxpayer has to file a petition with the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1554,11,'For the IRS to grant a guaranteed installment agreement, a taxpayer must have not failed to file any income tax returns or pay any tax shown on such returns during any of the preceding:','[\"3 taxable years.\",\"5 taxable years.\",\"6 taxable years.\",\"10 taxable years.\"]',1,'The IRS must agree to an installment payment plan for an individual’s tax debt under the following conditions:nnThe tax debt, excluding interest and penalties, is $10,000 or less.nOver the past 5 years, the taxpayer (and spouse, if it\'s a joint return):nFiled all required tax returns.nPaid all taxes due.nDid not have an installment agreement.nThe IRS confirms that the taxpayer cannot pay the debt in full immediately and requires the taxpayer to provide necessary financial information.nThe plan must ensure the tax debt is fully paid within 3 years.nThe taxpayer must agree to follow all tax laws while the installment plan is active.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1555,11,'Richard\'s 2020 and 2022 returns were examined for charitable contributions and employee business expenses. Both examinations resulted in no change to the return as filed. Richard has been notified that his 2023 return has been selected for examination for claimed business bad debts. Which of the following actions is likely to occur?','[\"Since Richard has two prior no change audits, upon notifying the Internal Revenue Service, the examination should be discontinued.\",\"Since Richard\'s employee business expenses were a no change audit, upon notifying the Internal Revenue Service, the examination should be discontinued.\",\"Since Richard\'s prior reviews were on different items, the current examination should continue.\",\"Richard can disregard the notice.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight to the issue of repeat examinations. In particular, the IRS tries to avoid repeat examinations of the same items, but sometimes this happens. If a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer should contact the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.nnIn this case, the examination cannot be discontinued by notifying the IRS of a repeat audit because Richard\'s 2023 return has been selected for examination due to business bad debts claimed (not charitable contributions or employee business expenses), which is a new item.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1556,11,'Which of the following is incorrect with respect to filing a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference?','[\"A qualified representative can prepare or sign the protest.\",\"A qualified representative can prepare and sign the protest if a substitute declaration statement is attached.\",\"A taxpayer is the only one permitted to sign the protest.\",\"An unenrolled agent is not allowed to sign the protest.\"]',2,'Publication 556, pages 8 and 9, provides that when a taxpayer requests an Appeals conference, the taxpayer may also need to file a formal written protest or a small case request with the office named in the Service\'s letter to the taxpayer.nnWhen a protest is required, the taxpayer must sign the written protest, stating that it is true, under the penalties of perjury. Likewise, if the taxpayer\'s representative prepares and signs the protest for the taxpayer, he or she must substitute a declaration stating:nnthat he or she submitted the protest and accompanying documents andnwhether he or she knows personally that the facts stated in the protest and accompanying documents are true and correct.nFinally, the taxpayer\'s representative must be qualified to practice before the IRS.nnTherefore, a representative qualified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service can prepare and/or sign a formal written protest on behalf of a client to request an Appeals conference.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1557,11,'Which of the following permits the Internal Revenue Service to legally seize your property to satisfy a tax debt?','[\"A levy\",\"A lien\",\"A federal lien\",\"The IRS is prohibited from legally seizing a person\'s property.\"]',0,'Publication 594 (pages 5 and 6) states a levy is a legal seizure of the taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt.nnIt also should be noted that liens are different from levies. A lien is a claim used as security for the tax debt, while a levy takes the property to satisfy the tax debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1558,11,'Joseph received a bill from the Internal Revenue Service for additional tax due of $1,000 plus accrued interest of $150. What happens if Joseph pays the $1,000 tax in full?','[\"Any additional interest will stop accruing.\",\"The accrued interest of $150 will be abated.\",\"Interest will continue to accrue.\",\"The $1,000 payment will be returned to the taxpayer and interest and penalties will continue.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 2, provides that a taxpayer\'s return may be examined for a variety of reasons, and the examination may take place in any one of several ways. After the examination, if any changes to a taxpayer\'s tax are proposed, either the taxpayer can agree with those changes and pay any additional tax owed, or the taxpayer can disagree with the changes and appeal the decision.nnPublication 556, page 4, states, in part, that if a taxpayer agrees with the proposed changes after the examination, the taxpayer can sign an agreement form and pay any additional tax owed. A taxpayer must pay interest on any additional tax.nnIf the taxpayer pays when he or she signs the agreement, the interest is generally figured from the due date of the return to the date of the payment.nIf the taxpayer does not pay the additional tax when he or she signs the agreement, the taxpayer will receive a bill that includes interest.nIf the taxpayer pays the amount due within 10 business days of the billing date, the taxpayer will not have to pay more interest or penalties. This period is extended to 21 calendar days if the amount due is less than $100,000.nTo stop the accrual of interest on both tax and interest, a taxpayer must make a deposit or payment for both the tax and interest that has accrued as of the date of deposit or payment.nnGiven the information above, Joseph will incur additional interest if he only pays the $1,000 taxes and not the accrued interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1559,11,'Which of the following statements is correct if a taxpayer agrees to changes made during an examination and he signs an agreement, but does not pay the taxes due?','[\"If the taxpayer pays when he or she signs the agreement, the interest is generally waived from the due date of the return to the date of the payment.\",\"If the taxpayer does\\u00a0not\\u00a0pay the additional tax when he or she signs the agreement, the taxpayer will receive a bill that includes interest and an additional penalty.\",\"If the taxpayer pays the amount due within 21 calendar days of the billing date and the amount is less than $100,000, the taxpayer will not have to pay more interest or penalties.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 2, provides that a taxpayer\'s return may be examined for a variety of reasons, and the examination may take place in any one of several ways. After the examination, if any changes to a taxpayer\'s tax are proposed, either the taxpayer can agree with those changes and pay any additional tax owed, or the taxpayer can disagree with the changes and appeal the decision.nnPublication 556, page 4, provides the general provision if the taxpayer agrees with the proposed changes. Specifically:nnIf a taxpayer agrees with the proposed changes after the examination, the taxpayer can sign an agreement form and pay any additional tax he or she may owe. A taxpayer must pay interest on any additional tax and the interest is generally figured (not waived) from the due date of the return to the date of the payment.nIf the taxpayer does not pay the additional tax when he or she signs the agreement, the taxpayer will receive a bill that includes interest (not an additional penalty).nIf the taxpayer pays the amount due within 10 business days of the billing date, the taxpayer will not have to pay more interest or penalties. This period is extended to 21 calendar days if the amount due is less than $100,000.nIf the taxpayer is due a refund, the taxpayer will receive it sooner if they sign the agreement form. Moreover, the taxpayer will be paid interest on the refund amount.nGiven the information above, if the taxpayer pays the amount due within 21 calendar days of the billing date and the amount is less than $100,000, the taxpayer will not have to pay more interest or penalties.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1560,11,'Which of the following statements is not correct if you lived in a location declared by the President of the United States to be a disaster area after 1996?','[\"The IRS may abate interest on income tax owed by the taxpayer on certain taxes.\",\"The IRS may retroactively abate interest on income tax owed during the declared disaster period if a taxpayer was granted an extension.\",\"The IRS may abate interest on income tax for the length of any extension period granted for filing income tax returns.\",\"The IRS may abate but may\\u00a0not\\u00a0retroactively abate interest on income tax for the length of any extension period granted for filing income tax returns.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 8, states that if a taxpayer is (or was) affected by a presidentially declared disaster occurring after 1996 or a taxpayer has been affected by a terrorist or military action occurring after September 10, 2001, the IRS may abate (reduce) the amount of interest the taxpayer owes on certain taxes. The IRS may abate interest for the period of any additional time to file or pay that the IRS provides on account of the disaster or the terrorist or military action. The IRS will issue a notice or news release indicating who are affected taxpayers and stating the period of relief.nnSimilarly, if a taxpayer is eligible for relief from interest, but was charged interest on the period of relief, the IRS may retroactively abate the taxpayer\'s interest.nnTo the extent possible, the IRS can take the following actions: make appropriate adjustments to the taxpayer\'s account, notify the taxpayer when the adjustments are made, or refund any interest paid by the taxpayer where appropriate.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1561,11,'Sam is the sole shareholder in an S corporation. The S corporation was examined, and the IRS proposed a $20,000 deficiency. What must Sam do to request an Appeals conference?','[\"File a formal written protest\",\"Pay the deficiency\",\"Hire a federally authorized tax practitioner to represent the S corporation\",\"Nothing, because he is eligible for the small case procedure\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 8, provides that when a person requests an Appeals conference, the person may also need to file either a formal written protest or a small case request with the office named in the letter the taxpayer received.nnThe following cases require a person to file a written protest:nnIn all employee plan and exempt organization cases without regard to the dollar amount at issuenIn all partnership and S corporation cases without regard to the dollar amount at issuenIn all other cases, unless the taxpayer qualifies for the small case request procedure, or other special appeal procedures, such as requesting Appeals consideration of liens, levies, seizures, or Installment AgreementsnThe instructions for submitting a written protest are found in Publication 556.nnIf Sam decides that he wants to request an Appeals conference regarding the IRS proposed $20,000 deficiency, he will need to file a formal written protest because this is an S corporation issue.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1562,11,'Which of the following gives the Internal Revenue Service a legal claim to your property as security for payment of your tax debt?','[\"A warrant\",\"A levy\",\"A federal lien\",\"The IRS is prohibited from placing a legal claim on a taxpayer\'s property.\"]',2,'Publication 594, pages 5 and 6, states a lien (also known as a federal lien) is a claim used as security for the tax debt.nnAs an aside, a levy is different from a lien. A levy is a legal seizure of the taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1563,11,'Jose received a bill from the Internal Revenue Service for additional tax due of $2,000 plus accrued interest of $300. What happens if Jose pays the $2,000 tax in full?','[\"Any additional interest will stop accruing.\",\"Interest will continue to accrue.\",\"The accrued interest of $300 will be abated.\",\"The $2,000 payment will be returned to the taxpayer and interest and penalties will continue.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 2, provides that a taxpayer\'s return may be examined for a variety of reasons, and the examination may take place in any one of several ways. After the examination, if any changes to a taxpayer\'s tax are proposed, either the taxpayer can agree with those changes and pay any additional tax owed, or the taxpayer can disagree with the changes and appeal the decision.nnIn addition, Publication 556, page 4, states, in part, that if a taxpayer agrees with the proposed changes after the examination, the taxpayer can sign an agreement form and pay any additional tax owed. A taxpayer must pay interest on any additional tax.nnIf the taxpayer pays when he or she signs the agreement, the interest is generally figured from the due date of the return to the date of the payment.nIf the taxpayer does not pay the additional tax when he or she signs the agreement, the taxpayer will receive a bill that includes interest.nIf the taxpayer pays the amount due within 10 business days of the billing date, the taxpayer will not have to pay more interest or penalties. This period is extended to 21 calendar days if the amount due is less than $100,000.nTo stop the accrual of interest on both tax and interest, a taxpayer must make a deposit or payment for both the tax and interest that has accrued as of the date of deposit or payment.nnIt also should be noted that if the taxpayer is due a refund, the taxpayer will receive it sooner if the taxpayer signs the agreement form. Moreover, the taxpayer will be paid interest on the refund.nnGiven the information above, Jose will incur additional interest if he only pays the $2,000 taxes and does not pay the accrued interest.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1564,11,'If a taxpayer and the IRS fail to settle a non-docketed examination controversy in the IRS Independent Office of Appeals, the next event to occur is:','[\"issues of a notice of deficiency.\",\"issuance of notice and demand for payment.\",\"referral of the case to the Taxpayer Advocate Service.\",\"return of the case to the assigned Revenue Agent for further review.\"]',0,'According to IRS Publication 556, pages 5–7, if a taxpayer and the IRS cannot reach a settlement on a non-docketed examination controversy in the IRS Independent Office of Appeals, the next step is the issuance of a notice of deficiency. This notice, often referred to as a \"90-day letter,\" formally states the IRS\'s determination that additional tax is owed and gives the taxpayer 90 days to either pay the amount due or file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court to contest the deficiency.nnThe issuance of notice and demand for payment occurs after the deficiency has been assessed and if no petition is filed. The referral to the Taxpayer Advocate Service is not a typical procedural step in this context. The return of the case to the assigned Revenue Agent for further review does not happen after the appeals process if an agreement is not reached.nnTherefore, the correct answer is the issuance of a notice of deficiency.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1565,11,'Which of the following gives the IRS legal claim to an individual\'s property?','[\"A warrant\",\"A lien\",\"A levy\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 594, page 5, states a levy is a legal seizure of a taxpayer\'s property to satisfy a tax debt. Levies are different from liens. A tax lien is a legal claim against all the taxpayer\'s current and future property, such as a house or car, and rights to property, such as wages and bank accounts. The lien automatically comes into existence if the taxpayer does not pay the tax amount due after receiving the first bill.nnThus, a lien is a claim used as security for the tax debt, while a levy takes a person\'s property to satisfy the tax debt.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1566,11,'If you do not agree with the Internal Revenue Service examination conclusion, you may take your case to which of the following?','[\"U.S. Tax Court\",\"U.S. Court of Federal Claims\",\"U.S. District Court\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Publication 556, page 12, discusses the issue presented in this problem. Specifically, if the taxpayer and Appeals do not agree on some or all of the issues after the taxpayer\'s Appeals conference, or if the taxpayer skipped the IRS\'s Appeals system, the taxpayer may take his or her case to the U.S. Tax Court, the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, or the taxpayer\'s U.S. District Court, after satisfying certain procedural and jurisdictional requirements. These courts are independent judicial bodies and have no connection with the IRS.nnIf a taxpayer\'s disagreement with the IRS is over whether he or she owes additional income tax, estate tax, gift tax, certain excise taxes, or penalties related to these proposed liabilities, the taxpayer can go to the U.S. Tax Court. (Other types of tax controversies, such as those involving some employment tax issues or manufacturers\' excise taxes, cannot be heard by the Tax Court.)nnThus, a taxpayer can take his or her case to any of the three courts listed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1567,11,'If the IRS selects a return for audit and the taxpayer responds that they have been audited:','[\"within the prior 5 years, the IRS will discontinue the examination.\",\"within the prior 2 years, the IRS will discontinue the examination.\",\"within the prior 2 years, the IRS may discontinue the examination.\",\"within the prior 5 years, the IRS may discontinue the examination.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight into the issue of repeat examinations. In particular, if a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer can contact the IRS to see if the examination can be discontinued.nnThe best statement in this problem is the examination has taken place in the last 2 years and the IRS is contacted to see if the examination may be (not will be) discontinued.nn nn 	Note	 n 	 	 n 	nThe response to this question is correct, but this question is a bit tricky in that the return was selected for audit, but it does not indicate whether the audit is for the same issue. As you can see from the response, the criteria for requesting discontinuation of the audit is contingent on both the 2-year window and the repeat issue.nn n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1568,11,'Which of the following is true with respect to an Offer in Compromise?','[\"The taxpayer may be allowed to pay less than the full amount owed.\",\"Collection actions, such as levy, may be delayed.\",\"A rejected offer may be appealed.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) may accept an Offer in Compromise (OIC) to settle unpaid tax accounts for less than the full amount of the balance due. The IRS may accept an OIC if:nnthe IRS agrees that the taxpayer’s tax debt may not be accurate,nthe taxpayer has insufficient assets and income to pay the amount due, ornbecause of the taxpayer’s exceptional circumstances, paying the amount due would cause an economic hardship or would be unjust.nThe OIC program is an option for those taxpayers who are unable to pay their tax account in a lump sum or through an Installment Agreement and have exhausted their search for other payment arrangements.nnAs provided on page 3 of the Form 656-B Booklet, there is a $205 application fee for submitting Form 656. However, there is an exception to the application fee. If the taxpayer is an individual or a sole proprietor, or a disregarded single-member LLC taxed as a sole proprietor AND the taxpayer’s household gross income meets the Low-Income Certification guidelines, the taxpayer will not be required to send the application fee. See page 2 of Form 656 to see the qualifications for satisfying the Low-Income Certification.nnMoreover, a taxpayer may be eligible to receive a refund of the application fee if the IRS:nnaccepts the offer to promote effective tax administration, ornaccepts the offer based on doubts as to collectability and determines that collecting an amount greater than the amount offered would create an economic hardship.nTo be considered for an Offer in Compromise, all returns that are due must be filed and, if applicable, be current with all Federal Tax Deposits. Collection actions, such as a levy, may be delayed.nnAdditionally, Publication 594, page 3, provides that if an Offer in Compromise is rejected, it may be appealed (see Publication 1660).nnThus, all the responses given in this problem are correct with respect to an Offer in Compromise.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1569,11,'An accuracy-related penalty applies to the portion of tax underpayment attributable to:nnI. negligence or a disregard of the tax rules or regulations.nII. any substantial understatement of income tax.','[\"I only\",\"II only\",\"Both I and II\",\"Neither I nor II\"]',2,'An accuracy-related penalty applies to the portion of tax underpayment attributable to either negligence or a disregard of the tax rules or regulations and any substantial understatement of income tax.nnNote: A 20% “accuracy-related” civil penalty applies to the portion of an understatement of tax on a tax return that is due (absent reasonable cause) to:nnnegligence or a disregard of rules or regulations,nsubstantial understatement of income tax,nsubstantial valuation misstatement,nsubstantial overstatements of pension liabilities, ornsubstantial estate or gift tax valuation understatement.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1570,11,'During February 2024, Arnold\'s tax return for 2023 was selected for an IRS examination in Los Angeles, California. This is where Arnold lived, maintained his business in 2023, and had his accountant prepare his tax return. Late in 2024, Arnold moved to Biloxi, Mississippi, and took his books and records with him. Which of the following options is available to Arnold?','[\"Arnold can request to have his case transferred to Biloxi, Mississippi.\",\"Arnold must return to Los Angeles, California, for the IRS examination.\",\"Arnold can request to have his case transferred to El Paso, Texas, which is the midpoint between his former and current homes.\",\"Arnold can request the examination be waived since he has relocated to another state.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 4, provides that a taxpayer\'s return is examined in the IRS district where the taxpayer lives. But if his or her return can be examined more quickly and conveniently in another district, such as where the taxpayer\'s books and records are located, then the taxpayer can ask to have the case transferred to that district.nnSince Arnold\'s books and records are now located in Biloxi, Mississippi, he can request to have his case transferred from Los Angeles to Biloxi. Thus, he can request the transfer.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1571,11,'A taxpayer received a notice from the IRS saying a prior year’s tax return had been examined, creating a tax assessment of $2,560. The taxpayer disagrees with the amount of tax assessed. In which of the following situations can a taxpayer not request an audit reconsideration?','[\"The taxpayer moved and never received the examination notice.\",\"The taxpayer neither appeared for the examination nor sent information to the IRS.\",\"There is new documentation for the examination.\",\"The taxpayer already paid the full amount owed.\"]',3,'Publication 3598, page 2 provides the following reasons that a taxpayer may request audit reconsideration. The four reasons are:nnDid not appear for the taxpayer’s auditnMoved and did not receive correspondence from the IRSnHave additional information to present that the taxpayer did not provide during their original auditnDisagree with the assessment from the auditnA taxpayer cannot request an audit reconsideration if they already paid the full amount owed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1572,11,'What does a Notice of Federal Tax Lien mean to a taxpayer\'s creditors?','[\"The IRS has a claim against all of the taxpayer\'s currently owned property.\",\"The IRS has a claim against all of the taxpayer\'s owned property, including property acquired by the taxpayer after the lien was filed.\",\"The IRS is in the process of seizing all of the taxpayer\'s currently owned property.\",\"The IRS is in the process of seizing all of the taxpayer\'s currently owned property and will seize any property acquired by the taxpayer until the tax liability is paid in full.\"]',1,'Publication 594, page 5, provides that a lien gives the IRS a legal claim to a taxpayer\'s property as security for payment of his or her debt. The federal tax lien arises when the taxpayer does not pay the amount due after receiving their first bill. It applies to property (such as the taxpayer\'s home and car) and to any current and future rights the taxpayer has to property.nnIn addition, the IRS files a Notice of Federal Tax Lien in the public records to establish the priority of their claim versus the claims of other creditors. The Notice of Federal Tax Lien is filed with local or state authorities, such as county recorder of deeds or the Secretary of State offices.nnIf a Notice of Federal Tax Lien is filed against the taxpayer, it may be reported by consumer credit reporting agencies. This can have a negative effect on the taxpayer\'s credit rating and make it difficult for them to receive credit (such as a loan or credit card). Employers, landlords, and others may also use this information and not favorably view the fact that a Notice of Federal Tax Lien has been filed against the taxpayer.n',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1573,11,'An enrolled agent\'s written communications with a client may be privileged if they concern:','[\"a criminal tax investigation.\",\"preparing the client\'s tax return.\",\"representing the client in an IRS examination.\",\"encouraging the client to participate in a tax shelter.\"]',2,'Under Internal Revenue Code Section 7525, the confidentiality privilege between a taxpayer and a federally authorized tax practitioner, such as an enrolled agent, applies to written communications concerning tax advice. This privilege is similar to the attorney-client privilege and applies to communications made in the context of noncriminal tax matters before the IRS, such as during an examination. However, it does not apply to communications regarding criminal tax investigations, the preparation of tax returns, or advice related to tax shelters. Therefore, written communications between an enrolled agent and a client may be privileged if they pertain to representing the client in an IRS examination.nnThe correct answer is representing the client in an IRS examination.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1574,11,'Dave operates a retail business as a sole proprietorship with stores in several locations in the Toledo, Ohio, area. The books and records for all of the stores are maintained at the main store near his residence. Dave\'s tax returns have always been prepared by his longtime accountant in Toledo. Dave has been notified that his 2022 Form 1040 has been selected for an examination. Dave\'s brother-in-law in Detroit, Michigan, a district away, has just passed the enrolled agent\'s examination and Dave\'s wife would like him to handle the examination. Which of the following statements is most likely correct?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service will likely approve a transfer to the Detroit office.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will likely approve a transfer to the Detroit office if the taxpayer transfers his books up to Detroit.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will likely require the examination to take place in Toledo.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will likely approve a transfer to the Detroit office, provided a properly executed Form 2848 is submitted with the request.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 4, provides a reason for transferring a case to another district. Generally, a taxpayer\'s return is examined in the IRS district where the taxpayer lives. But if his or her return can be examined more quickly and conveniently in another district, such as where the taxpayer\'s books and records are located, then the taxpayer can ask to have the case transferred to that district.nnForm 2848 is a power of attorney for another person to represent the taxpayer. If properly executed, it will allow Dave\'s brother-in-law to represent him. (Publication 556, page 9)nnSome examinations are handled entirely by mail. Examinations not handled by mail can take place in the taxpayer\'s home, the taxpayer\'s place of business, an Internal Revenue office, or the office of the taxpayer\'s authorized representative. If the time, place, or method is not convenient for the taxpayer, the examiner will try to work out something more suitable. However, the IRS makes the final determination of when, where, and how the examination will take place. (Publication 556, page 3)nnIn this case, there is no reason for transferring the examination to another district. Hence, the Internal Revenue Service will likely require the examination to take place in Toledo, where Dave operates his business.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1575,11,'How long does a taxpayer have from the date of the Notice of Deficiency to file a petition with the U.S. Tax Court if he resides within the United States?','[\"30 days\",\"90 days\",\"150 days\",\"180 days\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 5, provides that a taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the 30-day letter to tell the IRS whether he or she will accept or appeal the proposed changes.nnIf the taxpayer does not respond to the 30-day letter, or if the taxpayer later does not reach an agreement with an Appeals Officer, the IRS will send a 90-day letter, which also is known as a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer will have 90 days (150 days if the taxpayer\'s address is outside the United States) from the date of this notice to file a petition with the Tax Court.nnAs an aside, the Statutory Notice of Deficiency is referred to as the Notice of Deficiency, and it is also known as the 90-day letter because this is the time that the taxpayer has to file a petition with the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1576,11,'An Enrolled Agent\'s (EA\'s) client is an individual taxpayer who is requesting assistance with a proposed penalty. All of the following are methods of addressing the penalty, EXCEPT:','[\"prior to a penalty being assessed in an examination, it may be appealed via deficiency procedures.\",\"prior to assessment, the EA can request binding arbitration to reconsider the penalty.\",\"after the penalty has been assessed, a written request for abatement can be submitted.\",\"after the penalty has been assessed and paid, the EA can prepare a claim for refund.\"]',1,'Section 20.1.1.4 of the Internal Revenue Manual (11-21-2017) provides that various administrative and legislative remedies are provided for taxpayers who disagree with the IRS’s determination that they are liable for a particular penalty. Generally, when a taxpayer disagrees with our determination regarding a penalty, he or she has the right to an administrative appeal.nnTaxpayers have the right to challenge the assertion or assessment of a penalty, and generally may do so at any stage in the penalty process. Taxpayers may request the following:nnA review of the penalty prior to assessment (e.g., deficiency procedures),nA penalty abatement after it is assessed, and either before or after it is paid (post-assessment review), ornAn abatement and refund after payment (claim for refund).nTaxpayers may indicate their disagreement with the IRS either verbally or in writing, or if the penalty has already been paid, by filing a claim for refund or credit.nnIf agreement cannot be reached at the area field office or the campus, the taxpayer may request a conference with the employee’s immediate manager, or (in most cases) the taxpayer may request that the case be forwarded to Appeals. Taxpayers should provide a written request for consideration by Appeals.nnGiven the information above, the EA can appeal via the deficiency procedures (but not request binding arbitration) to reconsider the penalty before the assessment,',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1577,11,'The examination of Greta\'s tax return for 2023 resulted in adjustments creating a tax liability in the amount of $30,000. Greta does not believe she owes anything. A Notice of Proposed Income Tax Deficiency is issued to Greta, who wants to appeal the Revenue Agent\'s adjustments to the IRS Office of Appeals. Greta must file a written protest letter no later than which of the following periods?','[\"10 days\",\"30 days\",\"90 days\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Publication 556, pages 4 and 5, addresses the issues associated with the IRS examination. If the taxpayer does not agree with the proposed changes, the examiner will explain the appeal rights. If the examination takes place in an IRS office, the taxpayer can request an immediate meeting with the examiner\'s supervisor to explain his or her position. If an agreement is reached, the case will be closed.nnIf the taxpayer cannot reach an agreement with the supervisor at this meeting, or if the examination took place outside of an IRS office, the examiner will write up the case explaining the taxpayer\'s position and the IRS\'s position. The examiner will forward the case for processing.nnMost cases that are not docketed in any court qualify for fast track mediation. Mediation can take place as early as a conference that the taxpayer requests with the examiner\'s supervisor. The process involves an Appeals Officer who has been trained in mediation.nnWithin a few weeks after the closing conference with the examiner and/or supervisor, the taxpayer will receive a package that contains a letter (known as a 30-day letter) notifying the taxpayer of his or her right to appeal the proposed changes within 30 days.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1578,11,'How many days after a Collection Due Process hearing with the Office of Appeals to discuss an Internal Revenue Service levy or lien does a taxpayer have to seek review of the determination?','[\"The taxpayer does\\u00a0not\\u00a0have the right to bring suit after this hearing.\",\"The taxpayer has 30 days from the date of the determination.\",\"The taxpayer has 90 days from the date of the determination.\",\"The taxpayer has 180 days from the date of the determination.\"]',1,'According to Publication 594, page 5, at the conclusion of a taxpayer\'s Collection Due Process hearing (also referred to as a CDP hearing), the IRS Office of Appeals will issue a determination. That determination either will support the continued existence of the filed federal tax lien or will determine the lien should be released, or withdrawn. If the taxpayer disagrees with the determination, the taxpayer will have 30 days after the date of the determination to seek review of the determination in the U.S. Tax Court or appeal under the Collection Appeals Program.nnSee Publication 1660, Collection Appeal Rights, for more information.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1579,11,'What remedies does a taxpayer have if the IRS denies the taxpayer\'s claim for economic damages as a result of the IRS knowingly failing to release a Notice of Federal Tax Lien on the taxpayer?','[\"They may appeal the decision to the Taxpayer Advocate Office.\",\"They may sue for damages against the federal government.\",\"They may sue for damages against the IRS employees.\",\"There is no appeal to the IRS\'s decision.\"]',1,'If the IRS intentionally or negligently did not follow Internal Revenue law while collecting a taxpayer\'s taxes, or the IRS wrongfully seized the property of the wrong taxpayer, that taxpayer may be entitled to recover economic damages. Some limitations may apply.nnThe taxpayer must file an administrative claim with the Advisory Group Manager for the taxpayer’s area. The taxpayer must mail their written claim to the attention of the Advisory Group Manager at the address listed in Publication 4235, Collection Advisory Group Numbers and Addresses.nnIf the claim is denied, the taxpayer may sue the federal government, but not IRS employees, for economic damages.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1580,11,'When dealing with IRS employees, you have certain rights. Which of the following most accurately reflects those rights?','[\"A right of appeal is available for most collection actions.\",\"A right of representation is only available in audit matters; it is not available for collection matters.\",\"A case may not be transferred to a different IRS office, even if your authorized representative is located in an area different from your residence.\",\"If you disagree with the IRS employee who handles your case, you must first have the employee\'s permission before requesting a meeting with the manager.\"]',0,'Publication 594, page 4, highlights how to appeal an IRS decision. A taxpayer has the right to appeal most collection actions to the IRS Office of Appeals (Appeals). Appeals is separate from and independent of the IRS Collection office that initiates collections actions. Appeals ensures and protects its independence by adhering to a strict policy prohibiting certain communications with the IRS Collection office or other IRS offices, such as discussions regarding the strength or weakness of your case. When an IRS office is to be engaged in discussions, the taxpayer will be invited to participate in the conference, or provided any written document to give the taxpayer an opportunity to comment.nnThe main options for appeals are either Collection Due Process or the Collection Appeals Program. The purpose of a Collection Due Process hearing is to have Appeals review collection actions that were taken or have been proposed. After Appeals has made their determination and the taxpayer does not agree, the taxpayer can go to court to appeal the determination.nnUnder the Collection Appeals Program (CAP), if a taxpayer disagrees with an IRS employee’s decision regarding any levy, seizure, or Notice of Federal Tax Lien filing and wants to appeal it, the taxpayer can ask the IRS employee\'s manager to review their case. If the taxpayer disagrees with the manager’s decision, the taxpayer may continue with the Collection Appeals Program as outlined in Publication 1660. Instances in which a taxpayer can pursue the Collection Appeals Program include, but are not limited to, the following:nnBefore or after the IRS files a Notice of Federal Tax LiennBefore or after the IRS seizes (\"levies\") the taxpayer\'s propertynAfter the IRS rejects, terminates, or proposes to terminate a taxpayer’s Installment Agreement (A conference with the manager is recommended, but not required.)nIn this problem, the most accurate statement that reflects a person\'s rights when dealing with an IRS employee is the right to appeal most IRS collection actions.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1581,11,'If you do not agree with the Internal Revenue Service examination conclusion, you may take your case to the U.S. Tax Court for the following:','[\"State income tax examination\",\"Federal income tax examination\",\"Federal estate tax examination\",\"Both federal income tax examination and federal estate tax examination\"]',3,'As provided on page 12 of Publication 556, the taxpayer can go to the U.S. Tax Court if a disagreement with the IRS is over whether a taxpayer owes additional income tax, estate tax, gift tax, certain excise taxes, or penalties related to these proposed liabilities.nnTax controversies such as those involving some employment tax issues or manufacturers\' excise taxes cannot be heard by the Tax Court. Rather, these disputes are heard by the U.S. District Court.nnTherefore, a dispute involving the state may not be resolved in the U.S. Tax Court; the taxpayer must seek relief from the state\'s court system.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1582,11,'Ned\'s individual income tax return was under IRS examination. Five (5) months before the expiration of the statute of limitations, the Revenue Agent wanted Ned to agree to extend the statute of limitations. Which of the following statements is not correct?','[\"The extension can be a fixed-date consent.\",\"The agreement may include a time extension or be limited to specific tax issues; but it cannot contain both.\",\"The extension can be an open-ended consent.\",\"The agreement may include both a time extension and be limited to specific tax issues.\"]',1,'Publication 1035, page 1, provides the basic rules for extending the tax assessment period. Congress, recognizing that additional time may sometimes be needed to fairly resolve a tax examination, has provided for extending the statutory period by written agreement between the taxpayer and the Service. These agreements are called “consents” and generally apply to all taxes except estate tax. To provide consistency, the Service has developed forms for the written consents. The signed consent form is considered binding to both the Service and the taxpayer.nnThere are two basic kinds of consents: the fixed-date consent and the open-ended consent. The fixed-date consent sets a specific expiration date for the extension of the statute, while the open-ended consent extends the statute for an indefinite length of time. In the open-ended consent, the extension period generally remains open until 90 days after either the taxpayer or the Service sends the prescribed notice ending the agreement.nnIn addition to extending the length of the assessment statutory period, consent agreements may also limit further examination or appeal activities to specific tax issues. These agreements are called “restricted consents” and have either a fixed or open-ended date of expiration. It is the Service\'s position that the taxpayer has a right to request a restricted consent; however, as a general rule, the Service will not enter into restricted consents unless certain conditions exist, which are given on page 2 of Publication 1035.nnNed, therefore, can request that the extension of the statute of limitation be restricted to particular issues on the tax return, and there also can be a time extension.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1583,11,'Jim and Tammy, husband and wife, were both employed and filed a joint return, which showed they were entitled to a refund of $1,000. Rather than receiving the refund of $1,000, they received a notice advising them that the entire refund was applied to an amount due that Jim owed from a prior year, which was before they were married. What is the likely outcome if Tammy files Form 8857, Request for Innocent Spouse Relief?','[\"Tammy will receive a refund of $500 and Jim will still owe $500 in back taxes.\",\"Tammy will receive a refund of $1,000 and Jim will still owe $1,000 in back taxes.\",\"Tammy is\\u00a0not\\u00a0an innocent spouse, but she may seek remedy under the injured spouse provisions.\",\"Tammy is an innocent spouse, but she will\\u00a0not\\u00a0qualify for any refund.\"]',2,'Publication 971, page 5, provides that a taxpayer requests innocent spouse relief by filing Form 8857, Request for Innocent Spouse Relief, which relieves the taxpayer of paying tax, interest, and penalties if the taxpayer\'s spouse (or former spouse) improperly reported items or omitted items on the taxpayer\'s tax return. Generally, the tax, interest, and penalties that qualify for relief can only be collected from a taxpayer\'s spouse (or former spouse). However, a taxpayer is jointly and individually responsible for any tax, interest, and penalties that do not qualify for relief.nnA taxpayer must meet all of the following conditions to qualify for innocent spouse relief:nnThe taxpayer must have filed a joint return, which has an understatement of tax due to erroneous items of the taxpayer\'s spouse (or former spouse).nThe taxpayer must establish that, at the time the taxpayer signed the joint return, the taxpayer did not know, and had no reason to know, that there was an understatement of tax.nTaking into account all the facts and circumstances, it would be unfair to hold the spouse liable for the understatement of tax.nPursuant to Publication 971, page 2, a taxpayer can be an injured spouse if the taxpayer\'s share of the overpayment was, or is expected to be, applied (offset) against the other taxpayer\'s past-due federal tax, child or spousal support, federal nontax debt (such as a student loan), or state income tax. In this case, the taxpayer completes Form 8379, Injured Spouse Allocation, if the taxpayer wants his or her share of the overpayment shown on the joint return refunded to the taxpayer.nnPublication 971, page 17, provides that if the taxpayer\'s residence is in a community property state, the taxpayer may file Form 8379 if only he or she satisfies one of the following injured spouse conditions:nnis not legally obligated to pay the past-due amount andnsatisfies any one of the following conditions:nMade and reported tax paymentsnHad earned income such as wages, salaries, or self-employment income and claimed the earned income credit or the additional child tax creditnClaimed a refundable tax credit, such as the health coverage tax credit or the refundable credit for prior-year minimum taxnGiven the above rules, Tammy does not meet the requirements for innocent spouse and therefore cannot file Form 8857. On the other hand, she may qualify for relief due as an injured spouse and, as such, she can file Form 8379 to obtain her portion of the refund.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1584,11,'After the issuance of a Statutory Notice of Deficiency, failure to timely file a petition with the Tax Court will result in which of the following?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service will issue a 30-day letter.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will assess the tax it says the taxpayer owes.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will issue a 90-day letter.\",\"You will be required to post a deposit before being allowed to request an extension for time to file a petition.\"]',1,'In the situation where a taxpayer disagrees with the IRS over its assessment of additional taxes owed, the Service urges taxpayers to appeal the IRS\'s decision with the Appeals Office. The Office of Appeals can settle most differences without expensive and time-consuming court trials.nnIf the taxpayer and the Appeals Office do not agree on some or all of the issues after the taxpayer\'s Appeals conference, or if the taxpayer skipped the Appeals system, the taxpayer may take his or her case to the U.S. Tax Court, the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, or the taxpayer\'s U.S. District Court, after satisfying certain procedural and jurisdictional requirements.nnA taxpayer starts this process after the IRS issues a formal letter (known as a Notice of Deficiency) stating the amounts that the IRS believes the taxpayer owes. The taxpayer has 90 days from the mailing date of the notice of deficiency to file a petition with the Tax Court (or 150 days if the notice is addressed outside the United States). Failure to file timely results in the IRS assessing the tax that it says the taxpayer owes. Publication 5, page 1 indicates: \"If you do not go to the Tax Court, we will send you a bill for the amount due.\"',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1585,11,'An enrolled agent\'s (EA\'s) client is an individual taxpayer who is requesting assistance with a penalty. Which of the following is a method of waiving the penalty?','[\"Prior to a penalty\\u2019s assessment and before any request for relief has been denied, or a 30-day letter has been issued, the EA can request a conference with the IRS Independent Office of Appeals.\",\"Prior to a penalty\\u2019s assessment, the EA can request binding arbitration to reconsider the penalty.\",\"Before the penalty has been assessed, the EA can submit a written request for penalty abatement.\",\"After the penalty has been assessed and paid, the EA can file a claim for refund with the IRS.\"]',3,'After the penalty has been assessed and paid, the EA can file a claim for refund with the IRS. Penalty abatement requests are generally made after the penalty has been assessed, and if the taxpayer has paid the penalty, they can then file a claim for a refund. A conference with the IRS Independent Office of Appeals typically occurs after the penalty has been assessed. Binding arbitration is not available for reconsidering penalties. A penalty abatement cannot be abated before the penalty has been assessed. Thus, the appropriate method for contesting a penalty after it has been assessed is filing a claim for refund with the IRS.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1586,11,'What action may a taxpayer take if he does not agree with the proposed changes from an examination?','[\"The taxpayer must go directly to Appeals within 15 days.\",\"The taxpayer can request an immediate meeting with the examiner\'s supervisor to explain the taxpayer\'s position.\",\"The taxpayer must go directly to Tax Court within 90 days.\",\"The taxpayer has no appeals after an examination.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 4, states in part that if a taxpayer does not agree with the proposed changes during an examination, the examiner will explain the appeal rights to the taxpayer. If the examination takes place in an IRS office, the taxpayer can request an immediate meeting with the examiner\'s supervisor to explain the taxpayer\'s position. If an agreement is reached, the case will be closed.nnIf an agreement cannot be reached with the supervisor or if the examination takes place outside the IRS office, the examiner will write up the taxpayer\'s case, explaining the taxpayer\'s position and the IRS\'s position. The examiner will forward the write-up for processing.nnAs a result, the taxpayer does not need to go directly to an appeal if they do not agree. The taxpayer can request an immediate meeting with the examiner\'s supervisor to explain the taxpayer\'s position.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1587,11,'Which of the following is correct with respect to a representative qualified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service?','[\"He can prepare but\\u00a0not\\u00a0sign a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference.\",\"He can sign but\\u00a0not\\u00a0prepare a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference.\",\"He can prepare and sign a formal written protest to request an Appeals conference.\",\"He\\u00a0cannot\\u00a0prepare and sign the client\'s prepared written protest to request an Appeals conference.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 8, provides that when a taxpayer requests an Appeals conference, the taxpayer may also need to file a formal written protest or a small case request with the office named in the Service\'s letter to the taxpayer.nnWhen a protest is required, the taxpayer must sign the written protest, stating that it is true, under the penalties of perjury. Likewise, if the taxpayer\'s representative prepares and signs the protest for the taxpayer, he or she must substitute a declaration stating:nnthat he or she submitted the protest and accompanying documents andnwhether he or she knows personally that the facts stated in the protest and accompanying documents are true and correct.nFinally, the taxpayer\'s representative must be qualified to practice before the IRS.nnTherefore, a representative qualified to practice before the Internal Revenue Service can prepare and/or sign a formal written protest on behalf of a client to request an Appeals conference.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1588,11,'A lien is a legal claim to property as security or payment for a tax debt. Select the best answer regarding the filing of a Notice of Federal Tax Lien:','[\"It may be filed simultaneously with the first bill for taxes due.\",\"It may be filed when a tax deficiency resulting from an audit is agreed to.\",\"It may\\u00a0not\\u00a0be filed when an Installment Agreement is in effect and payments are being made.\",\"It may be filed after the taxpayer does not pay their first bill for taxes due.\"]',3,'Publication 594, page 5, provides that the IRS may file a Notice of Federal Tax Lien in the public records, which means that a taxpayer\'s creditors are publicly notified that the Service has a claim against all of the taxpayer\'s property, including property acquired by the taxpayer after the lien was filed.nnIn general, liens give the IRS a legal claim to a taxpayer\'s property as security for payment of an existing tax debt. The federal tax lien automatically comes into existence when the taxpayer does not pay the amount due after receiving their first bill.nnIn this problem, the best answer regarding the filing of a Notice of Federal Tax Lien is that it may be filed after the taxpayer does not pay their first bill for taxes due.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1589,11,'What options does a taxpayer have after the Notice of Deficiency has been issued and the tax assessed is paid?','[\"The taxpayer has no legal action because the taxpayer paid the tax.\",\"The taxpayer can petition the Tax Court for review even though the tax has been paid.\",\"The taxpayer cannot petition the Tax Court for review because the taxpayer paid the tax.\",\"None of the answer choices are correct.\"]',1,'Generally, the Tax Court hears cases before any tax has been assessed and paid; however, a taxpayer can pay the tax after the Notice of Deficiency has been issued and still petition the Tax Court for review. The purpose for paying the tax in this case is to stop the accrual of any additional interest and penalties.nnIf the taxpayer does not file the petition on time, the proposed tax will be assessed, a bill will be sent, and the taxpayer will not be able to take the case to the Tax Court. Under the law, the taxpayer must pay the tax within 21 days (10 business days if the amount is $100,000 or more).nnRefer to Publication 594 for further details on the IRS collection procedures.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1590,11,'Which of the following may the Internal Revenue Service settle by accepting an Offer in Compromise for less than the full amount of the balance due?','[\"Doubt as to whether or not the assessed tax is correct\",\"Doubt as to the collectability\",\"Doubt as to whether or not the assessed tax is correct and doubt as to the collectability\",\"A tax deficiency plus accrued interest, but not penalties\"]',2,'Publication 594, page 3, provides the general rules for making an Offer in Compromise (OIC). In general, the IRS may accept an Offer in Compromise to settle unpaid tax accounts for less than the full amount of the balance due. This applies to all taxes, including any interest, penalties, or additional amounts arising under the laws and regulations administered by the IRS for one of the following reasons:nnThe IRS agrees that the taxpayer\'s tax debt may not be accurate (i.e., doubt as to liability).nThe taxpayer has insufficient assets and income to pay the amount due (i.e., doubt as to collectability).nBecause of the taxpayer\'s exceptional circumstances, paying the amount due would cause an economic hardship or would be unjust (i.e., to promote effective tax administration).nThe Form 656-B Booklet, page 3, explains there are two types of OIC payment terms that the IRS and the taxpayer may agree to:nnLump-sum cash requires 20% of the total offer amount to be paid with the offer and the remaining balance paid within five or fewer installments within 5 months from the date of notice of acceptance.nPeriodic payment requires the first payment with the offer and the remaining balance paid within 6 to 24 months, in accordance with the taxpayer’s proposed offer terms.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1591,11,'The IRS has selected Frances\' 2023 tax return for examination. The only item of inquiry in the IRS contact letter was for verification of charitable contributions. Frances\' tax return for 2021 was also examined to verify her charitable contributions, and no change was proposed to her tax liability. Which of the following statements is correct?','[\"If Frances advises the IRS representative that no change resulted in her tax return for 2021, the examination of her tax return for 2023 might be discontinued.\",\"If Frances advises the IRS representative that no change resulted in her tax return for 2021, the examination of her tax return for 2023 is automatically discontinued.\",\"If Frances advises the IRS representative that no change resulted in her tax return for 2021, the examination of her tax return for 2023 is automatically continued since it is only one occurrence.\",\"Frances should contact the Taxpayer\'s Advocacy Office to have this examination terminated.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight to the issue of repeat examinations. In particular, the IRS tries to avoid repeat examinations of the same items. If a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer should contact the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.nnSince the examination of Frances\' 2021 return for the same item is within the last 2 years and there were no changes, she should request that the current examination be discontinued.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1592,11,'Ruth\'s 2021 and 2022 returns were examined for investment expenses. Both examinations resulted in no change to the return as filed. Ruth was notified that her 2023 return was selected for examination for investment expenses. Which of the following statements is the best advice to give Ruth?','[\"Since Ruth has two prior no change audits on the same item, upon notifying the Internal Revenue Service, the examination should be discontinued.\",\"Since Ruth has two prior no change audits, upon notifying the Internal Revenue Service, the examination should be discontinued.\",\"Since Ruth\'s prior reviews were on the same item, the current examination should continue.\",\"Ruth can disregard the notice.\"]',0,'Publication 556, page 4, provides insight to the issue of repeat examinations. In particular, the IRS tries to avoid repeat examinations of the same items, but sometimes this happens. If a taxpayer\'s tax return was examined for the same items in either of the 2 previous years and no change was proposed to the taxpayer\'s tax liability, the taxpayer should contact the IRS as soon as possible to see if the examination should be discontinued.nnIn this case, Ruth should notify the Internal Revenue Service that she has had two no change audits on the same item to see if the examination should be discontinued, since this would be the 3rd year.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1593,11,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning a taxpayer that is unable to financially pay his or her tax liability?','[\"The IRS can temporarily delay the tax debt collection.\",\"The IRS can temporarily delay the interest accruing on the debt collection.\",\"The IRS can temporarily delay any penalties accruing on the debt collection.\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',0,'If a taxpayer cannot pay any of the amount due, they can request the IRS to delay collection until the taxpayer is able to pay. Prior to approving the request, the IRS may ask the taxpayer to complete a Collection Information Statement and provide proof of their financial status. However, the taxpayer should know that if the IRS does delay collecting the tax debt, the taxpayer\'s debt will increase because penalties and interest are charged until the full amount is paid.nnHence, the only correct response in this question is that the IRS can temporarily delay the tax debt collection.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1594,11,'How much time does a taxpayer have to file a petition with the Tax Court concerning the taxpayer\'s disagreement with the IRS?','[\"60 days from when the taxpayer receives the notice of deficiency from the IRS\",\"90 days from when the taxpayer receives the notice of deficiency from the IRS\",\"60 days from when the meeting between the taxpayer and the IRS ends\",\"90 days from when the meeting between the taxpayer and the IRS ends\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 5, provides that a taxpayer generally has 30 days from the date of the 30-day letter to tell the IRS whether he or she will accept or appeal the proposed changes.nnIf the taxpayer does not respond to the 30-day letter, or if the taxpayer later does not reach an agreement with an Appeals Officer, the IRS will send a 90-day letter, which is also known as a Notice of Deficiency. The taxpayer will have 90 days (150 days if it is addressed to a person outside the United States) from the date of this notice to file a petition with the Tax Court.nnIn addition, Publication 556, page 6, provides that if a taxpayer does not receive a notice of deficiency, the taxpayer cannot take his or her case to the Tax Court.nnIf, after the IRS mails the notice of deficiency, a taxpayer sends money without written instructions, it will be treated as a payment. In this case, the taxpayer is still able to petition the Tax Court.nIf the taxpayer sends money after receiving a notice of deficiency and has specified in writing that it is a “deposit in the nature of a cash bond,” the IRS would treat it as a deposit if the taxpayer sent it before either:nthe close of the 90-day or 150-day period for filing a petition with the Tax Court to appeal the deficiency ornthe date the Tax Court decision is final, if you have filed a petition.nHence, the taxpayer has 90 days for filing a petition with the Tax Court.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1595,11,'Brittany\'s 2021 return was selected for an examination. Information was requested to support claimed business expenses. Brittany failed to provide the Internal Revenue Service with any of the requested information because she felt the examination was an unwarranted invasion of her privacy. The Internal Revenue Service issued a Notice of Deficiency and Brittany filed a petition with the Tax Court. Which of the following statements is correct since the examination was started in 2023?','[\"The IRS will have the burden of proof in the Tax Court proceedings because the taxpayer claimed the examination was an unwarranted invasion of her privacy.\",\"The IRS will have the burden of proof in the Tax Court proceedings because business expenses are a protected area.\",\"Brittany will have the burden of proof in the Tax Court proceedings because she failed to provide the IRS with credible evidence relating to the issue.\",\"The taxpayer always has the burden of proof in the Tax Court proceedings.\"]',2,'Publication 556, page 9, provides information on burden of proof. For court proceedings resulting from examinations started after July 22, 1998, the IRS has the burden of proof for any factual issue if the taxpayer has introduced credible evidence relating to the issue. The taxpayer, however, also must have:nncomplied with all substantiation requirements of the Internal Revenue Code,nmaintained all records required by the Internal Revenue Code,ncooperated with all reasonable requests by the IRS for information regarding the preparation and related tax treatment of any item reported on the taxpayer\'s tax return, andnhad a net worth of $7 million or less and not more than 500 employees at the time the taxpayer\'s tax liability is contested in any court proceeding if the taxpayer\'s tax return is for a corporation, partnership, or trust.nSince Brittany has failed to provide the Internal Revenue Service with any of the requested information, the burden of proof remains with her.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1596,11,'Taxpayers can authorize tax payments using most major credit or debit cards via the Internet; this service generally is available through a service provider. Which of the following statements about this service is correct?','[\"The credit or debit card provided can charge only a flat fee for this service.\",\"The service provider should inform the taxpayer of the convenience fee before the tax return is filed.\",\"The credit or debit card payment can only be made when e-filing.\",\"Taxpayers that choose this service are not required to provide the credit or debit card numbers to the service provider.\"]',1,'Publication 1345, page 17, states that taxpayers may pay online at IRS.gov/payments, by phone or with the IRS2Go app using a major credit card (American Express® Card, Discover® Card, MasterCard®, or Visa® card). This service is available through credit card service providers. The service provider charges a convenience fee based on the amount of the tax payment. The software advises taxpayers of this fee during the transaction, and they can choose to end the transaction before the payment is completed and confirmed. The software provides a confirmation number at the end of the transaction. EROs should inform taxpayers of this option and advise them that fees may vary between service providers.nnThe best response to this question is the service provider should inform the taxpayer of the convenience fee before the tax return is filed.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1597,11,'To whom may a summons for information be issued by the Service to determine the taxpayer\'s financial situation?','[\"To a financial institution\",\"To a third-party record keeper\",\"Any person with information that may be relevant to the case\",\"All of the answer choices are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 594, page 7, the Service may serve a summons on the taxpayer, as the person responsible for the tax liability, to compel testimony, bring in books and records to prepare a tax return, or bring in documents and records to assist the Service in preparing a Form 433-A or 433-B (Collection Information Statement).nnIn addition, the Service may issue summons to a third party. If the Service is serving third-party summons to determine a taxpayer’s tax liability, the taxpayer will receive a notice to this effect. Some examples of who could be issued a third-party summons include financial institutions, record keepers, or any person with information that may be relevant to the taxpayer\'s case. The Service will not review the third-party information or receive testimony until the end of the 23rd day after the notice was given. IRC Section 7609 authorizes the Service to issue a third-party summons.nnThe taxpayer has the right to:nnpetition to reject (“quash”) the summons before the end of the 20th day after the date of the notice, ornpetition to intervene in a suit to enforce a summons to which the third party did not comply.nTherefore, all of the responses given in this problem are correct.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1598,11,'Which of the following statements is correct concerning the trust fund recovery penalty?','[\"The penalty may apply if federal income, Social Security, or Medicare taxes are not properly withheld,\",\"It may apply to the taxpayer if the unpaid taxes cannot be immediately collected from the employer or business.\",\"The \\u201caverage\\u201d failure-to-deposit penalty assessed by the IRS may be between 2% and 10%.\",\"All of the responses are correct.\"]',3,'Pursuant to Publication 15, page 31, the trust fund recovery penalty may apply if federal income, Social Security, or Medicare taxes that must be withheld are not withheld or are not deposited or paid to the U.S. Treasury. The penalty is the full amount (i.e., 100%) of the unpaid trust fund tax.nnThis penalty may apply to the taxpayer if these unpaid taxes can\'t be immediately collected from the employer or business.nnThe trust fund recovery penalty may be imposed on all persons who are determined by the IRS to be responsible for collecting, accounting for, and paying over these taxes, and who acted willfully in not doing so.nnIn addition, the “averaged” failure-to-deposit penalty may be assessed by the IRS. This penalty may range from 2% to 10% depending on circumstances. See Publication 15, page 30, for specifics.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19'),(1599,11,'After the issuance of a Statutory Notice of Deficiency, failure to timely file a petition with the Tax Court will result in which of the following?','[\"The Internal Revenue Service will issue a 30-day letter.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will assess the tax it says the taxpayer owes.\",\"The Internal Revenue Service will issue a 90-day letter.\",\"You will be required to post a deposit before being allowed to request an extension for time to file a petition.\"]',1,'Publication 556, page 4, provides that if a taxpayer disagrees with the IRS over its assessment of additional taxes owed, the taxpayer may request a meeting or telephone conference with the supervisor of the person who issued the findings. If the taxpayer still disagrees, the taxpayer can appeal the IRS\'s decision with the Appeals Office of the IRS. The Appeals Office is separate from—and independent of—the IRS office taking the action the taxpayer disagrees with.nnIf the taxpayer and the Appeals Office do not agree on some or all of the issues after the taxpayer\'s Appeals conference, or if the taxpayer skipped the Appeals system, the taxpayer may take his or her case to the U.S. Tax Court, the U.S. Court of Federal Claims, or the taxpayer\'s U.S. District Court.nnA taxpayer starts this process after the IRS issues a formal letter (known as a Notice of Deficiency) stating the amounts that the IRS believes the taxpayer owes. The taxpayer has 90 days from the mailing date of the Notice of Deficiency to file a petition with the Tax Court (or 150 days if the notice is addressed outside the United States). Failure to file timely results in the IRS assessing the tax that it says the taxpayer owes.',1,'2026-04-23 08:04:19');
